mutradif[3006]{id,mid,a,w,d,s,hw,aw,ay,ta}:
1,1,"P","أَسْكَنَ","أَسْكَنْتُ means to transport and settle in a different location. For example, in the Noble Quran, the account of Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) is mentioned as follows: أَسْكَنْتُ (37:14). Translation: O our Lord! I have settled my descendants in a valley where there is no cultivation.","«اَسْکَنَ» is used to resettle in another location.","Populate / Settle","اسکن","2:35-2:128-7:19-7:161-17:104-23:18-65:6",7
2,1,"P","آوى","«اٰوٰی» means to give someone a place to stay at one's own home, to grant refuge. Its original word is «اَوَی», which means to join and attach oneself to someone (transitive) in order to seek refuge from a danger, etc.\n\nAs mentioned in the Holy Quran regarding the story of the People of the Cave, they sat in a cave on a mountain out of fear of the oppressive polytheist government.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«اِذْ اَوَى الْفِتْيَةُ اِلَى الْكَهْفِ» (10 / 18)\nTranslation: When those young men took refuge in the cave.\n\nSimilarly, when Prophet Noah (peace be upon him) called his disbelieving son to believe and board the ship so he could be saved from drowning, his son said:\nThe Quran has described it as:\n«سَاٰوِيْٓ اِلٰي جَبَلٍ يَّعْصِمُنِيْ مِنَ الْمَاۗءِ» (43 / 11)\nTranslation: I will take refuge on a mountain; it will save me from the water.\n\nAnd in the chapter (of Actions), the meaning of 'iwa' specifically is to give someone a place to stay and settle them.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِيْنَ اٰمَنُوْا وَهَاجَرُوْا وَجٰهَدُوْا بِاَمْوَالِهِمْ وَاَنْفُسِهِمْ فِيْ سَبِيْلِ اللّٰهِ وَالَّذِيْنَ اٰوَوْا وَّنَــصَرُوْٓا اُولٰۗىِٕكَ بَعْضُهُمْ اَوْلِيَاۗءُ بَعْضٍ» (72 / 8)\nTranslation: Those who believed and emigrated and fought in the cause of Allah with their wealth and lives, and those who gave shelter and aid to the emigrants—they are allies of one another.","«اٰوٰی» is used to avoid danger and to take refuge in a safe place.","Populate / Settle","اوی","8:72-11:43-11:80-12:69-12:99-18:10-18:63-23:50-28:45-32:19",10
3,1,"P","بََوَّأَ","«بَوَّا» means to settle someone in a place agreeable to their nature and preference.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَلَقَدْ بَوَّاْنَا بَنِيْٓ اِسْرَاۗءِيْلَ مُبَوَّاَ صِدْقٍ وَّرَزَقْنٰھُمْ مِّنَ الطَّيِّبٰتِ» (93 / 10)  \nTranslation: And We granted the Children of Israel a noble abode and provided them with pure sustenance.","« بَوَّا» is used to settle in a suitable environment.","Populate / Settle","بوا","7:74-10:93-22:26",3
4,1,"P","تَبَوَّأَ","The root (origin) of «تَبَوَّا» is Baw. Two aspects are found in its meaning:  \n(1) return to the thing  \n(2) and being evenly distributed (م ۔ ل).  \nThis word is used when the climate and environment of a residential place are compatible and suitable for the nature of the dweller (مف), or when a person, for a particular purpose, chooses a residential place that is compatible and suitable for him.  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَكَذٰلِكَ مَكَّنَّا لِيُوْسُفَ فِي الْاَرْضِ ۚ يَتَبَوَّاُ مِنْهَا حَيْثُ يَشَاۗءُ» (56 / 12)  \nTranslation: And similarly, We granted Yusuf (AS) authority in the land (Egypt), so he could settle wherever he wished.  \n\nAnd similarly, in the Quran, Allah the Almighty addresses the Prophet (PBUH):  \n«وَاِذْ غَدَوْتَ مِنْ اَھْلِكَ تُبَوِّئُ الْمُؤْمِنِيْنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلْقِتَالِ» (121 / 3)  \nTranslation: And when you [O Prophet] left your home in the morning to assign the believers to their battle posts, [you did so] at the appropriate times and places.  \n\nThis means that He (the Prophet PBUH) would assign each individual to specific positions according to the time and place of the battle.","« تَبَوَّا» is used to inhabit a compatible and suitable environment.","Populate / Settle","تبوا","10:87-12:56-39:74-41:24-59:9",5
5,1,"P","ثَوَى","«ثَوَی» means to be buried. To settle in a place, to inhabit it.\n«ثَوَی الرَّجُل»: For a person to die (manjad) (from the lexicon of antonyms) and also to mean to make a place one's permanent residence (muf) From the time of one's ancestors, to have chosen to reside in a single location.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, Allah Almighty has addressed the Honorable Prophet ﷺ:\n«وَمَا كُنْتَ ثَاوِيًا فِيْٓ اَهْلِ مَدْيَنَ تَتْلُوْا عَلَيْهِمْ اٰيٰتِنَا» (45 / 28)\nTranslation: And you, [O Muhammad], were not among those who dwelled in Medina that they might recite Our verses to them repeatedly.\nNote: (Lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two entirely separate meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other).","«ثوَی» is used to stay on the land of ancestors.","Populate / Settle","ثوی","3:151-16:29-29:68-39:3239:60-39:72-40:76-41:24-47:12",9
6,1,"P","حَضَرَ ، بَدَا","«حَضَرَ» means to reside in a city. It is used to denote opting for urban habitation, whereas «بَدَا» is used for living in a rural area or jungle. The opposite of «حَضْرٌ» is «بَدْوٌ». (for example) The meaning of «بَدَا ، یَبْدُوْا،  بَدَاوَۃٌ» is to be an inhabitant of a village or a remote area. The literal meaning of «بَدَا» is also to be apparent, and it refers to a place of residence where, due to the absence of tall and lofty buildings, everything is visible and clearly observable. (figurative) From this root, «بَادِیَۃٌ» meaning desert, «بَادِیٌ» meaning desert dweller, and «بَدَوِیٌّ» meaning rustic are derived.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«ذٰلِكَ لِمَنْ لَّمْ يَكُنْ اَھْلُهٗ حَاضِرِي الْمَسْجِدِ الْحَرَامِ» (2 / 196)\nTranslation: This ruling is for the person whose family and dependents do not reside in Mecca.\n\nSimilarly, in the Noble Quran, Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) mentions Allah's favors with these words:\n«وَقَدْ اَحْسَنَ بِيْٓ اِذْ اَخْرَجَنِيْ مِنَ السِّجْنِ وَجَاۗءَ بِكُمْ مِّنَ الْبَدْوِ» (100 / 12)\nTranslation: And He (Allah) bestowed many favors upon me when He brought me out of the prison and brought you (all the household) from the village here.","«حَضَرَ» is used for choosing to reside in a city.  \nAnd «بَدَا» is used for residing in a village or forest.","Populate / Settle","حضر ، بدا","2:196-12:100",2
7,1,"P","خَلَدَ","«خَلَدَ» To reside in a place for a long period of time where no change (i.e., alteration) and corruption occur (def.).\nFor example: In the Quran, Allah the Most High addresses the people of Paradise and says:\n«وَلَھُمْ فِيْهَآ اَزْوَاجٌ مُّطَهَّرَةٌ وَّھُمْ فِيْهَا خٰلِدُوْنَ» (25 / 2)\nTranslation: And they will have therein pure spouses, and they will abide therein forever.","«خَلَدَ» To reside for a prolonged period in a place untouched by change or corruption.","Populate / Settle","خلد","2:25-2:39-2:81-2:82-2:162-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:15-3:88-3:107-3:116-3:136-3:198-4:13-4:14-4:57-4:93-4:122-4:169-5:80-5:85-5:119-6:128-7:20-7:36-7:42-9:17-9:22-9:63-9:68-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:26-10:27-10:52-11:23-11:107-11:108-13:5-14:23-16:29-18:108-20:76-20:101-20:120-21:8-21:34-21:99-21:102-23:11-23:103-25:15-25:16-25:69-25:76-26:129-29:58-31:9-32:14-33:65-39:72-39:73-40:76-41:28-43:71-43:74-46:14-47:15-48:5-56:17-57:12-58:17-58:22-59:17-64:9-64:10-65:11-72:23-76:19-98:6-98:8-104:3",84
8,1,"P","سَكَنَ","The word sukoon (stillness) is the opposite of idtarar (distress/restlessness) and movement. Therefore, when «سَکَنَ» is used in the sense of to inhabit/settle, its meaning is to come from another place and take up residence.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«يٰٓاٰدَمُ اسْكُنْ اَنْتَ وَزَوْجُكَ الْجَنَّةَ» (35:2)\nTranslation: O Adam! You and your wife, settle in Paradise.\n\nThus, the implication is that their creation occurred at a location other than Paradise.\n\nSimilarly, when Prophet Abraham brought Hagar and Ishmael to Mecca, he supplicated:\n«رَبَّنَآ اِنِّىْٓ اَسْكَنْتُ مِنْ ذُرِّيَّتِيْ» (37:14)\nTranslation: O our Lord! I have settled my offspring here.","«سَکَنَ» is used to denote settling in a place after arriving from somewhere else.","Populate / Settle","سکن","2:35-6:13-7:19-7:161-14:14-14:37-14:45-16:80-17:104-23:18-28:58-34:15-42:33-65:6",14
9,1,"P","عَاشَرَ","Its original root is «عَاشَرَ». It has two basic meanings.  \nThe first meaning is the number ten; the second meaning is mingling and interference (m l), i.e., to live together in mutual intimacy and to intervene. From this, the word «عَشِیْرَۃٌ» emerges, whose meaning is 'tribe', and «عَاشَرَ» means the state of a single clan or family living together in mutual intimacy.  \n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, men who have complaints against their wives are commanded:  \n«وَعَاشِرُوْھُنَّ بِالْمَعْرُوْفِ» (19 / 4)  \nTranslation: And live with them in kindness.","«عَاشَرَ» is used for living together with one's family.","Populate / Settle","عاشر","4:19",1
10,1,"P","عَمَرَ","The term «عَمَرَ» conveys meanings of constructing, increasing prosperity, and inhabiting barren and deserted land. According to Ibn al-Faris, its semantic scope also includes permanence (i.e., perpetuity) and long duration (m. l.). And 'age' is the duration during which the soul remains inhabited with the body.\n\nThe opposite of this is «خَرَبَ», which means to destroy places or fields, to ruin, to make desolate, and to strip of prosperity. For example: The Holy Prophet ﷺ, while describing the signs of the nearness of the Hour, mentioned among them: «مَسَاجِدُھَا عَامِرَۃٌ وَّھِیَ خَرَابٌ مِّنَ الْھُدٰی»\nMeaning that at that time, mosques will be physically inhabited but will be ruined in terms of guidance.\nAnd for example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا يَعْمُرُ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰهِ مَنْ اٰمَنَ بِاللّٰهِ وَالْيَوْمِ الْاٰخِرِ» (9 / 18)\nTranslation: Only those will frequent Allah's mosques who believe in Allah and the Last Day.\nSimilarly, at another place, the divine command states:\n«كَانُوْٓا اَشَدَّ مِنْهُمْ قُوَّةً وَّاَثَارُوا الْاَرْضَ وَعَمَرُوْهَآ اَكْثَرَ مِمَّا عَمَرُوْهَا» (9 / 30)\nTranslation: They (i.e., the previous nations) were mightier than them in strength and in numbers, and they tilled the earth and inhabited it more than they have inhabited it.","«عَمَرَ» is used for cultivating and settling land, constructing and inhabiting buildings, and enhancing prosperity.","Populate / Settle","عمر","9:17-9:18-11:61-28:45-30:9",5
11,1,"P","غَنِیَ بِالْمَکَانِ","«غَنِیَ بِالْمَکَانِ» means to reside in a place for an extended period with comfort and peace. It is as if one is independent of other locations. (muf)\n\nFor example, in the Quran, «الَّذِيْنَ كَذَّبُوْا شُعَيْبًا كَاَنْ لَّمْ يَغْنَوْا فِيْهَا» (92:7):\n\nTranslation: Those who rejected Shu'aib (peace be upon him) were destroyed so utterly that it was as if they had never been inhabited.","«غَنِیَ» is used for living with peace and comfort for a long time.","Populate / Settle","غنی بالمکان","7:92-11:68-11:95",3
12,2,"H","یَوْمُ الْاٰخِرَ","«یَوْمُ الْاٰخِرَ» The term 'یوم' does not refer to the ordinary day of this world—the 24-hour period or the time contrasted with night, as in 'day and night.' Rather, it signifies the long, unending duration of the Hereafter. For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated: «اِنَّ رَبَّکُمُ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ سِتَّۃِ اَیَّامٍ» (54 / 7) Translation: Indeed, your Lord is Allah, who created the heavens and the earth in six days. And this is clear. The concept of the present day, which comes into being with the existence of the sun, cannot even be conceived before the creation of the earth and the heavens.","«یَوْمُ الْاٰخِرَ» This refers to the Day of Judgment, when people will be raised for reckoning and recompense.","Hereafter","یوم الاخر","2:8-2:62-2:126-2:177-2:228-2:232-2:264-3:114-4:38-4:39-4:59-4:136-4:162-5:69-9:18-9:19-9:29-9:44-9:45-9:99-24:2-29:36-33:21-58:22-60:6-65:2",26
13,2,"H","یَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ","The term Al-Ba'th refers to coming to life from the graves for a specific purpose, since the beginning of that prolonged era of the Hereafter will commence with it; hence it is also called Al-Ba'th. For example, the Noble Quran states: «لَقَدۡ لَبِثۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡبَعۡثِ» (56:3). Translation: Indeed, you will remain in your graves until the «یَوْمُ الْبَعْث».","«یَوْمُ الْبَعْثِ» refers to the Day of Judgment, which is the day when all people will be resurrected.","Hereafter","الیوم البعث","30:56",1
14,2,"H","آخِرَۃ","«آخِرَۃ» means «دَارُالْبَقَا» (the eternal abode). ( م , م . منجد ) That is, after death, the body and soul will be reunited, and humans will be resurrected and granted an eternal, everlasting life wherein there will be no death. Furthermore, the righteous and the wicked will be admitted to Paradise or Hell in recompense for their respective deeds.\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ ھُمۡ یُوۡقِنُوۡنَ» (4/2)\nTranslation: And (the believing people) have firm belief in the Hereafter.\n\nHere, by Hereafter is meant precisely this kind of eternal life. In this sense, the terms used in the Noble Quran as antonyms for Hereafter are (عَاجِلَۃ, دنیا, اَدْنیٰ, اُوْلٰی).","«آخِرَۃ» is commonly used to refer to the Day of Resurrection, on which all human beings will be resurrected, judged according to their deeds, and granted eternal life.","Hereafter","آخرۃ","2:4-2:86-2:102-2:114-2:130-2:200-2:201-2:217-2:220-3:22-3:45-3:56-3:72-3:77-3:85-3:145-3:148-3:152-3:176-4:74-4:77-4:134-5:5-5:33-5:41-6:92-6:113-6:150-7:45-7:147-7:156-8:67-9:38-9:69-9:74-10:64-11:16-11:19-11:22-11:103-12:37-12:57-12:101-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:22-16:41-16:60-16:107-16:109-16:122-17:7-17:10-17:19-17:21-17:45-17:72-17:104-20:127-22:11-22:15-23:33-23:74-24:14-24:19-24:23-27:3-27:4-27:5-27:66-28:70-29:20-29:27-30:7-30:16-31:4-33:57-34:1-34:8-34:21-38:7-39:9-39:26-39:45-40:39-40:43-41:7-41:16-41:31-42:20-43:35-53:25-53:27-57:20-59:3-60:13-68:33-74:53-75:21-79:25-87:17-92:13-93:4",105
15,2,"H","دَارُالْاٰخِرَۃ","«دَارُالْاٰخِرَۃ» means a place of residence, i.e., a home. The plural of dar is diyar, and dur means distant. Its meaning is very extensive. For example, dar signifies home, mansion, region, homeland, country, and even, considering that the entire world is a place of residence for humans, it is dar al-dunya (the abode of this world). Its opposite is dar al-akhirah (the abode of the Hereafter). However, in the life of the Hereafter, every person will be given an abode, i.e., a place of residence, according to their deeds.\n\nFor instance, regarding the righteous, the Almighty Lord has declared:\n«وَلَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (30 / 16)\nTranslation: How excellent is the abode (Paradise) for the righteous.\n\nSimilarly, regarding the disbelievers, the Almighty Lord has declared:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَى الَّذِيۡنَ بَدَّلُوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰهِ كُفۡرًا وَّاَحَلُّوۡا قَوۡمَهُمۡ دَارَ الۡبَوَارِۙ‏ - جَهَـنَّمَ​ۚ يَصۡلَوۡنَهَا​ؕ وَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرَارُ‏» (29 - 28 / 14)\nTranslation: They have disbelieved in the favor of Allah and led their people to the home of destruction. It is the Fire; they will be burned therein, and what an evil abode it is.\n\n(The terms evil home and evil abode both refer to Hell.)","The term «دَارُالْاٰخِرَۃ» refers to the house whose fate will be determined on Judgment Day based on a person's good or bad deeds, and in which they will dwell eternally.","Hereafter","دارالاخرۃ","2:94-6:32-7:169-12:109-16:30-28:77-28:83-29:64-33:29",9
16,2,"H","دَارُالْاٰخِرَۃ","«دَارُالْقَرَار» literally means to remain firmly established in a place. Since the life of the Hereafter is eternal (never-ending) and perpetual (everlasting), it is therefore referred to as Dar al-Qarar. However, the word Dar al-Qarar is used in its positive connotations, and by Dar al-Qarar is meant the abode of the righteous, that is, Paradise.\n\nAnd for the eternal and never-ending life of the disbelievers, the Noble Quran has used the words « بِئْسَ الْقَرَار» in (Surah 14, verse 29). (The reference is to Hell).\n\nBy 'Yawm' (Day) is not meant the ordinary day of this world, which consists of 24 hours or which is spoken of in contrast to night, like day and night. Rather, what is meant by it is the long and never-ending era of the life of the Hereafter.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ رَبَّکُمُ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ سِتَّۃِ اَیَّامٍ» (54:7)\nTranslation: Indeed, your Lord is Allah, who created the heavens and the earth in six periods. And this is clear. The conception of a present-day, which is generated by the existence of the sun, cannot even be imagined before the creation of the earth and the heavens.","«دَارُالْقَرَار» refers to that excellent abode which Allah Almighty will grant to the believers in return for their righteous deeds, i.e., Paradise.","Hereafter","دارالقرار","40:39",1
17,3,"H","اٰدَمَ","The original word «اٰدَمَ» is «اَدَمْ», whose basic meanings are compatibility and harmony, i.e., having the same nature and temperament (m-l). And «اَدَام» refers to every compatible and harmonious thing (according to the exegesis). The evidence for this is the noble saying of the Prophet ﷺ, which he ﷺ addressed to Mu'awiyah ibn Shu'bah, may Allah be pleased with him, regarding the matter of sending a marriage proposal to a woman:\n«لَوْ نَظَرْتَ إِلَيْهَا فَإِنَّهُ أَحْرَى أَنْ يُؤْدَمَ بَيْنَكُمَا» meaning, If you look at her (i.e., your prospective wife) once, there is a greater chance of affection and harmony developing between you. (Sunan Nasa'i; Hadith No. 3237)\nBesides this evidence, several other proofs are also cited, but the correct evidence is the one mentioned above because it is also supported by the hadith.\nAdam: Abu al-Bashar is the name of Prophet Adam, peace be upon him. However, it can also be used for the progeny of Adam (according to the exegesis). Therefore, when Bani Adam (Children of Adam) is mentioned, it refers to all of humanity.\nMoreover, wherever the usage of Adam or Bani Adam occurs in the Noble Quran, it relates to the history of humankind.\nFor example: the birth of Adam from clay, the prostration of the angels to Adam, peace be upon him, and the honor of humankind as the best of creation, the covenant of 'Alast' (i.e., the promise that Allah took from Adam and his descendants in the realm of spirits), and Satan's misguidance of Adam and Bani Adam, and his dialogue with Allah, etc.","«اٰدَمَ» In common understanding, the first human is said to be Prophet Adam (peace be upon him). However, the word (Adam) is also used to mean 'of similar temperament and nature'.","human being","ادم","2:31-2:33-2:34-2:35-2:37-3:33-3:59-5:27-7:11-7:19-7:26-7:27-7:31-7:35-7:172-17:61-17:70-18:50-19:58-20:115-20:116-20:117-20:120-20:121-36:60",25
18,3,"H","اِنْس","«اِنْس» The plural form «اُنَاس» refers to groups or communities of humans that differ from one another due to tribe, family, or other reasons. For example, the Holy Quran states: «قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (60:2) Translation: Every group recognized its own drinking place. And (anasīyya) denotes a very large group of humans. For instance, Allah, the Most High, says: «خَلَقۡنَاۤ اَنۡعَامًا وَّ اَنَاسِیَّ  کَثِیۡرًا» (49:25) Translation: We created cattle and countless humans.","«اِنْس» When referring to the social aspect (i.e., way of life) of a human being, the terms *ins* and words derived from it are used. When referring to the historical aspect, *Adam* and *Bani Adam* are employed. And when referring to its natural and innate aspect, the word *bashar* is used.","Human being","انس","6:112-6:128-6:130-7:38-7:179-27:17-41:25-41:29-46:18-51:56-55:33-55:39-55:56-55:74-72:5-72:6",16
19,3,"H","بَشَرَ","The fundamental meanings of «بَشَرَ» are for something to manifest with its beauty and splendor (m.l.), whereas the meaning of 'uns' is merely to appear.\n\nAnd «اَلْبَشَرَۃَ» refers to the outer surface of a person's skin.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (29 / 74)\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch the skin and turn it black.\n\nAnd its plurals are « بَشَرٌ» and «اَبْشَارٌ». A person is called 'bushr' (human) because, compared to other animals, its skin is extremely pure, smooth, and appears clear due to wool, hair, etc. (m.f.).\n\nThe word 'bushr' is used for singular, plural, masculine, and feminine. However, if it is used for two people, «بَشَرَیْن» is used.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَنُؤۡمِنُ لِبَشَرَیۡنِ مِثۡلِنَا» (47 / 23)\nTranslation: Is it that we should believe in two men like ourselves?\n\nAnd the word 'bushr' is used when the intention is to mention a person's physical and material aspects, their bodily constitution, natural necessities, and weaknesses. As is clear from the aforementioned verse.\n\nAnd in contrast to 'bushr' is the word «مَلَک» (i.e., angel), which is free from material aspects, meaning external bodily and natural necessities. The disbelievers always raised this same objection: How can we believe in a human like ourselves, who is born and dies, eats and drinks, walks in the markets, and fulfills his needs just like we do? What special preference does he have that we should believe in him? But if there were an angel, who is free from those needs and necessities, then that would be a different matter.\n\nIn the following verses, Allah the Almighty has answered this very objection:\n«وَ مَا مَنَعَ النَّاسَ اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡۤا اِذۡ جَآءَہُمُ الۡہُدٰۤی اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ قَالُوۡۤا اَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ بَشَرًارَّسُوۡلًا .قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ یَّمۡشُوۡنَ مُطۡمَئِنِّیۡنَ لَنَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ  السَّمَآءِ  مَلَکًا  رَّسُوۡلًا»\n(95 - 94 / 17)\nTranslation: And when guidance came to the people, nothing prevented them from believing except that they said, Has Allah sent a human as a messenger? Say, [O Muhammad], If there were angels walking peacefully in the earth, We would have certainly sent down to them an angel as a messenger.","«بَشَرَ» is commonly used to refer to a human being, though it is also employed specifically for the outer surface of the skin.","Human being","بشر","3:47-3:79-5:18-6:91-11:27-12:31-14:10-14:11-15:28-15:33-16:103-17:93-17:94-18:110-19:17-19:20-19:26-21:3-21:34-22:72-23:24-23:33-23:34-23:47-25:54-26:154-26:186-30:20-36:15-38:71-41:6-42:51-54:24-64:6-74:25-74:29-74:31-74:36",38
20,4,"T","اِرْتَفَقَ","Its original word is «رَفَقَ». Mutual compatibility free from ill temperament and harshness, contentment, agreement, unity, friendship, and closeness are called 'rafq'. After that, whatever becomes a cause of comfort and contentment is also called 'rafq'. In this sense, «مِرْفَق» is also called such that through it support is taken, and a person feels at ease; and «مِرفَقَہ» is called a small pillow; and «اِرْ تِفَاق» is called such companionship that becomes a cause of comfort and compatibility; and «مَرْتَفَق» is called such a place where ease is also available and nothing causes disruption in that ease.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«نِعۡمَ الثَّوَابُ ؕ وَ حَسُنَتۡ  مُرۡتَفَقًا» (29 / 18)\nTranslation: (What an) excellent reward and (what a) good resting place!","«اِرْتَفَقَ» is used to denote a state of peace free from any obstruction or interference.","Tranquility","ارتفق","18:29-18:31",2
21,4,"T","سَبَتَ","«سَبَتَ» Its basic meaning is comfort and peace (M. L.), i.e., such rest after which comfort and tranquility are also attained (Muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا نَوۡمَکُمۡ سُبَاتًا» (9 / 78)\nTranslation: And We made sleep a means of rest for you.\n\nAnd medical science research shows that the cells of the body that are destroyed from working throughout the day are replenished during the state of sleep. This is the reason why after a full night's sleep, when a person wakes up, they feel refreshed and joyful. And this is the meaning of «سَبَتَ».","«سَبَتَ» Such peace after which one feels relief.","Tranquility","سبت","25:47-78:9",2
22,4,"T","سَكَنَ","«سَکَنَ» After movement and unrest, i.e., restlessness, the state of calm is called 'sukun' (م ل), and the word 'sukun' is used for both external and internal meanings. For example, for resting after physical fatigue.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُاللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِلَیۡلٍ تَسۡکُنُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (73 / 28)\nTranslation: And who is a god besides Allah who can give you shelter in the darkness of the night? While you are in a state of calm.\n\nAnd it is also used to attain tranquility from mental thoughts and reflections.\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ صَلِّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ؕ اِنَّ صَلٰوتَکَ سَکَنٌ لَّہُمۡ» (103 / 9)\nTranslation: And pray for their well-being, for indeed your prayer is a source of tranquility for them.","«سَکَنَ» is used for physical and mental comfort.","Tranquility","سکن","6:13-6:96-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:80-23:18-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33",13
23,5,"D","اَمَل","Such a desire and hope is termed as one whose fulfillment is possible yet difficult. Therefore, Ibn Faris has defined its meaning as «اَلتَّثَبُّت وَالْاِنْتِظَار». (م-ل) That is, to cling to the hope of a desire and await its completion, to remain eager to witness life's joys—just as a poet expressed to his friend in longing for loyalty, a couplet that truly conveys the meaning of «اَمَل»: Loyalty is a delusion, protracted hope is nothing.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «ذَرۡہُمۡ یَاۡکُلُوۡاوَ یَتَمَتَّعُوۡا وَ یُلۡہِہِمُ الۡاَمَلُ  فَسَوۡفَ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (3:15) Translation: (O Prophet!) Leave them to their state—they may eat and enjoy benefits, and (lengthy) hope keeps them occupied in this world. Soon they will come to know its outcome.","«اَمَل» a seemingly unexpected and long-delayed desire.","Desire","امل","15:3-18:46-47:25",3
24,5,"D","اُمْنِیَّۃ","A desire that has no firm foundation. To entertain thoughts based on mere conjecture and then to nurture that desire (i.e., the term is understood to refer to launching false and baseless hopes and expectations).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ یَّدۡخُلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ اِلَّا مَنۡ کَانَ ہُوۡدًا اَوۡ نَصٰرٰی ؕ تِلۡکَ اَمَانِیُّہُمۡ  ؕ قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2:111)\nTranslation: And they say, None will enter Paradise except a Jew or a Christian. These are their [mere] wishes. Say, [O Muhammad], Produce your proof if you should be truthful.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«وَمِنۡہُمۡ اُمِّیُّوۡنَ لَا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ اِلَّاۤ اَمَانِیَّ وَ اِنۡ ہُمۡ  اِلَّا یَظُنُّوۡنَ» (2:78)\nTranslation: And among them are those who are unlettered; they know nothing of the Scripture except [mere] wishes, and they assume nothing but conjecture.\n\nSome scholars have understood امانی (wishes/hopes) in this verse to refer to the narrations they had innovated into the religion or distorted. Mujahid interpreted «اِلَّا اَمَانِیَّ» as meaning «اِلَّا کَذِبًا» (i.e., 'he lied'), and some took «اَمَانِیّ» to mean reciting [the scripture] without understanding or contemplation (i.e., just as this opinion is supported by some other verses). And «تَمَنّٰی» means 'to speak falsely' while «تَمَنِیَ الرَّجُلْ» means 'he spoke falsely.' (M-Q)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمْ لِلْاِنْسَانِ مَا تَمَنّٰى٘ۖ» (24:53)\nTranslation: Does man think that he will be left without purpose?","«اُمْنِیَّۃ» is used for false and baseless desires (whereas a desire that has a valid foundation is « رَجَاء »).","Desire","امنیۃ","2:78-2:111-4:123-57:14",4
25,5,"D","وَدّ","«وَدّ» In its basic meanings, two things are found: (1) to love something, and (2) to desire its attainment. Then this word is sometimes used in both meanings and sometimes in only one meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (2:15)\nTranslation: At one time, the disbelievers will wish, If only we had been Muslims!\nIn this verse, both meanings are found.\nAt another place, the commandment of Allah the Most High is:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ  لَہُمُ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وُدًّا» (96:19)\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, Allah will instill their love (in the hearts of His creation).\nIn this verse, only the first meaning is found.\nAlso see desire.","«وَدّ» refers to the love and desire for anything.","Desire","ود","2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14",25
26,6,"S","بَرْزَخ","«بَرْزَخ» A barrier between two things is called a 'hā'il' (obstacle), but when there is sufficient breadth between those two things, that barrier is called Barzakh. (M-L) For example, the barrier between this world and the Hereafter, or the intermediate period between death and the Day of Resurrection, is called Barzakh. However, the condition of 'sufficient breadth' added by Ibn al-Faris is not correct, because the Noble Quran does not support it.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«مَرَجَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ ، بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا  یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (20 / 55)\nTranslation: He released two flowing seas that meet. Between them is a barrier which they do not transgress.\n\nHowever, it would be better to say 'sufficient difference' instead of 'sufficient open space'.\n\nBarzakh is essentially a third thing between two things that also serves as a barrier, but within this third thing, i.e., Barzakh, the characteristics of both things are present—whether one characteristic is greater than the other or they are equal. The state of the 'realm of Barzakh' is similar: for a believer, it becomes a place of comfort and tranquility in their grave, and for a disbeliever, that same grave becomes a place of punishment and affliction. However, this comfort or punishment is of a lower degree than the ultimate Hereafter comfort or punishment.\n\nAnd the intermediate Barzakh between two rivers works as follows: if one current in the sea is warm and the other is cold, then the water of this Barzakh will be moderate, i.e., intermediate. Similarly, if one side has sweet water and the other side has bitter and salty water, then the water of this Barzakh will possess an intermediate quality.","«بَرْزَخ» One refers to a third thing between two things, in which the characteristics of both are found either equally or to some extent, and which serves as an obstacle.","Shade","برزخ","23:100-25:53-55:20",3
27,6,"S","حِجْر","The general meaning of «حِجْر» is a stone that is hard and solid. Then, 'hajar' is used for anything that is hard and serves as a barrier or obstacle, capable of separating one thing from others. (Muf) According to Ibn Faris, its meaning is: «اَلْمُنِعَ وَالْاِحَاطَۃُ عَلَی الشَّیْء». (M-L) (i.e., the prevention and encirclement of something).\n\nTo protect a village, drawing a boundary around it, encircling it with stones, or surrounding it with a fort or enclosure—all these are included in the meaning of 'hajar'.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَرَوۡنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  لَا بُشۡرٰی یَوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ حِجۡرًا مَّحۡجُوۡرًا» (22 / 25)\nTranslation: On the Day they (the sinners) see the angels, no glad tidings will there be for the criminals that day, and they will say, It is forbidden and sealed off! (Jalandhari) And the Ottoman Tafsir translated it as: It is forbidden, let it be barred!\n\nThe word «حِجْرًا مَّحجُوْرًا» was used by the Arabs metaphorically when a calamity or an enemy's attack was imminent, just as we say, God forbid! So, the listener generally does not take it as an actual affliction. Then, the word 'hajar' is also used for an intellect that refuses to accept false and erroneous ideologies and nonsensical talk. Thus, such a cautious intellect, which takes its own safeguard, is also called 'hajar'.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n« ہَلۡ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ قَسَمٌ  لِّذِیۡ حِجۡرٍ» (5 / 89)\nTranslation: Indeed, these things are worthy of being sworn by for those of understanding.\n\nThen, the word 'hajar' is also used for things that are forbidden, unlawful, and prohibited (haram).\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا ہٰذِہٖۤ  اَنۡعَامٌ  وَّ حَرۡثٌ حِجۡرٌ ٭ۖ لَّا یَطۡعَمُہَاۤ اِلَّا مَنۡ نَّشَآءُ بِزَعۡمِہِمۡ» (138 / 6)\nTranslation: And they say, These cattle and crops are forbidden; none may eat them except whom we will, so they claim.","«حِجْر» is used as a barrier that separates one thing from others.","Shade","حجر","6:138-25:22-25:53",3
28,6,"S","حجز","They say that between two things, a third thing is placed as a barrier (hajiz) between them, and the word 'hajiz' also carries the meanings of 'cover' and 'screen'.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ جَعَلَ بَیۡنَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ حَاجِزًا» (61 / 27)\nTranslation: And who made the barrier (or screen) between the two rivers?\n\nThen the word 'hajiz' also comes to mean, when it intervenes between two things, to prevent one or to save the other.\n\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» (47 / 69)\nTranslation: Then none of you would have been there to act as a barrier and save us from it. (Jalandhariؒ)\n\nTafsir-e-Usmani has translated it as: Then none of you would have been there to save us from it.","«حَجَزَ» A barrier between two things that safeguards and protects one from the other.","shelter","حجز","27:61-69:47",2
29,6,"S","حَدّ","«حَدّ» refers to the ultimate limit or final boundary of anything that separates it from other things (M.R.). Essentially, its basic meaning encompasses the concepts of stop and boundary. Therefore, «حَدّ» is not a third entity; it is the final boundary of a single thing that does not allow it to merge with other things (M.F.). In our usage, the term Hudood-e-Arba'ah is commonly employed, which clarifies this meaning.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡصِ اللّٰہَ  وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ وَ یَتَعَدَّ حُدُوۡدَہٗ یُدۡخِلۡہُ نَارًا خَالِدًا فِیۡہَا» (14/4)\nTranslation: And whoever disobeys Allah and His Messenger and transgresses His limits «وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡصِ اللّٰہَ  وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ وَ یَتَعَدَّ حُدُوۡدَہٗ یُدۡخِلۡہُ نَارًا خَالِدًا فِیۡہَا»—Allah will cast him into the Fire, wherein he will abide forever.\nAlso, see veil and wall.","«حَدّ» refers to the extreme end or final boundary of something that prevents it from merging with other things.","Shelter","حد","2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1",9
30,7,"F","تَسْرِیْحُ","The word «تَسْرِيْحُ» is derived from «سَرَح», which means to take livestock (animals) out for grazing, and «اَسْرَحَ» means to send a camel or livestock out for grazing (manjad). Later, its application began to pertain to leaving livestock open in pastures (M.R).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ حِیۡنَ تُرِیۡحُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ  تَسۡرَحُوۡنَ» (6 / 16)\nTranslation: And when you bring them [your livestock] home in the evening and take them out to pasture in the morning, you are honored by them.\n\nThus, the fundamental meaning of «تَسْرِيْحُ» is to consider ease in dismissal, and the bond of restriction in it is not as strong as that found in the meaning of divorce. Moreover, the word «تَسْرِيْحُ» is general, while the word for divorce has become almost specific to women. However, if this explanation pertains to a woman, as in «تَسْرِيْحُ الْمَرَاۃ», then its meaning would be to consider ease in dismissal after divorcing a woman. (M.R)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلطَّلَاقُ مَرَّتٰنِ۪ فَاِمۡسَاکٌۢ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ اَوۡ تَسۡرِیۡحٌۢ بِاِحۡسَانٍ» (229 / 2)\nTranslation: Divorce is [only] twice. Then, either retain [her] in an acceptable manner or release her with kindness.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ  قُلۡ  لِّاَزۡوَاجِکَ اِنۡ  کُنۡـتُنَّ تُرِدۡنَ الۡحَیٰوۃَ  الدُّنۡیَا وَ زِیۡنَتَہَا فَتَعَالَیۡنَ اُمَتِّعۡکُنَّ وَ اُسَرِّحۡکُنَّ سَرَاحًا جَمِیۡلًا» (28 / 33)\nTranslation: O Prophet! Say to your wives, If you desire the life of this world and its adornment, then come, I will provide for you and give you a pleasant release.","Both «تَسْرِيْحُ» and «اَلطَّلَاق» are terms used for divorce or in a general sense. In the case of «اَلطَّلَاق», takhliyah (i.e., leaving alone) is a necessary condition, while irsal (i.e., sending to another place) is a partial condition. Whereas in «تَسْرِيْحُ», the mandatory aspect is irsal, meaning the husband must dismiss the wife from his home, all the while taking her ease and convenience into consideration.","Free","تسریح","2:229-16:6-33:28-33:49",4
31,7,"F","تَحْرِیْرًا","Its original «تَحْرِیْرًا» is «حُرّ», and two aspects are found in its meaning: (1) to be free, and (2) to be free from defects or flaws (m). The opposite of «حُرّ» is «عَبْد», meaning a slave. And «حَرَّرَ ، تَحْرِیْرًا» means to free a slave, implying this word is specifically designated for freeing a slave.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَمَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ» (92 / 4)\n\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer unintentionally, then (one) he must free a believing slave, and (two) pay blood money to the heirs of the slain.","The term «تَحْرِیْرًا» is specifically designated for freeing a slave.","Free","تحریر","4:92-5:89-58:3",3
32,7,"F","حُرّ","«حُرّ» meaning free (its opposite is 'abd' i.e., slave), meaning a person who is not anyone's slave.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» (178 / 2)\nTranslation: A free person for a free person, a slave for a slave, and a woman for a woman.","Free as opposed to a slave.","Free","حر","2:178-3:35",2
33,7,"F","سُدٰی","«سُدٰی النَّاقَۃ» meaning the she-camel took wide steps in her gait, and 'saadi' is the term for such a she-camel that takes wide, open steps in her gait (manjad), and «سُدٰی» meaning an untethered camel, one upon whom there is no restraint. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «اَیَحۡسَبُ  الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنۡ یُّتۡرَکَ سُدًی» (36 / 75) Translation: Does man think that he will be left uncontrolled? (Uthmani)","«سُدٰی» an unbridled camel without any restraint.","Free","سدی","75:36",1
34,7,"F","طَلَاق","«اَلطَّلَاق» In its lexical origin, the word talaq contains two meanings: (1) *takhliah*, meaning separation or isolation, and (2) *irsal*, meaning to send or let go. Its implication is that one takes back control and care from a living being who was under one's authority and then releases them. This term is generally used to free and release one's wife from the bonds of marriage. However, it is not necessary for both meanings to be present simultaneously.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَلطَّلَاقُ مَرَّتٰنِ» (229 / 2)\nTranslation: Divorce is twice.\n\nNow, it is evident that in a single or double divorce, the element of *takhliah* (separation) is present, but the element of *irsal* (formal release/dismissal) is not.\n\nSimilarly, the word talaq is also used for freeing a slave (though the Noble Quran does not provide an example of this). Here too, the condition of *takhliah* or relinquishing one's right exists, but there is neither a necessity nor a condition for *irsal*—meaning the formal act of release/dismissal.\n\nThis indicates that the essential condition in talaq is *takhliah* (separation/isolation). The condition of *irsal* (release/dismissal) is sometimes obligatory, as in the case of the third divorce, and at other times absent, as in the first or second divorce.","«اَلطَّلَاق» and «تَسْرِيْحُ» both are used for divorce in the context of a woman's separation or in a general sense. In «الطلاق», separation is essential, and dismissal is a partial condition, whereas in «تَسْرِیْح», mandatory dismissal is required, and that too while taking ease and convenience into consideration.","Free","طلاق","2:227-2:229",2
35,7,"F","مُحِصَن","The term «حَصَن» means fortress or refuge, and according to Ibn al-Faris, it encompasses three concepts: protection, enclosure, and refuge. Similarly, the concept of iḥṣān fundamentally embodies these same ideas. iḥṣān is of two types: one where freedom and its honor, by their very nature, serve as a fortress against slavery. The second is marriage, which also serves as a fortress to avoid immorality and to safeguard chastity and purity. In the Quran, this term has been used in both these meanings.\n\nIf محصن or محصنات is intended in the sense of عفیف or عفیفہ (chaste), then the ṣād can be pronounced with either a fatḥa or a kasra. However, if it follows حُرِّمَتْ, then the ṣād must be pronounced with a fatḥa only, and its meaning will be exclusively married (i.e., a married woman or a married man).\n\nFree men and women, in contrast to concubines and slaves, are largely free in protecting their chastity. Firstly, a concubine or slave had to go out for work, and due to their lower social status, they were more prone to or victims of immorality. Secondly, it was also the custom of that time that owners would force their concubines into prostitution merely for lustful gain. Therefore, Allah Almighty strictly forbade this abhorrent practice.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ  اِنۡ  اَرَدۡنَ تَحَصُّنًا لِّتَبۡتَغُوۡا عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا» (33:24). Translation: And do not compel your concubines to immorality if they wish to remain chaste, merely seeking worldly gain.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states: «وَمَنۡ لَّمۡ یَسۡتَطِعۡ مِنۡکُمۡ طَوۡلًا اَنۡ یَّنۡکِحَ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتِ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ فَمِنۡ مَّا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَتَیٰتِکُمُ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ» (25:4). Translation: And whoever among you cannot afford to marry free believing women, then marry the believing concubines that are in your possession.\n\nIn this verse, the term «مُحْصَنٰت» has been used for free and virgin women. Married women have even more means to protect their chastity. After marriage, the satisfaction of desire and the husband's protection serve as a strong fortress to safeguard the woman from immorality. In the following verse, the term «مُحْصَنٰت» clearly indicates the meaning of a married woman.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states: «وَّالۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (24:4). Translation: And married women are also forbidden to you, except the concubines that come into your possession.\n\nThus, the term «اِحْصَان» conveys the concept of being free in the protection of one's chastity.","«مُحْصِن» free and autonomous in safeguarding one's chastity and honor.","Free","محصن","4:24-4:25-5:5-24:4-24:23",5
36,8,"T","اِمْتَحَنَ","The term 'imtihan' denotes a trial that is conducted with gentleness rather than harshness, and which also encompasses the dimensions of leniency and breadth (M R). Moreover, often before such a trial, the one administering the test is also kept under education and training.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَاالَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا جَآءَکُمُ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ مُہٰجِرٰتٍ فَامۡتَحِنُوۡہُنَّ ؕ اَللّٰہُ  اَعۡلَمُ  بِاِیۡمَانِہِنَّ ۚ فَاِنۡ عَلِمۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ  مُؤۡمِنٰتٍ فَلَا تَرۡجِعُوۡہُنَّ  اِلَی  الۡکُفَّارِ»\n\nTranslation: O believers! When believing women come to you as emigrants, test them. And Allah is fully aware of their faith. So if you find them to be believers, do not send them back to the disbelievers.","«اِمْتَحَان» A trial in which there is gentleness instead of harshness, and it is a test of one's prior education and training.","Trial","امتحن","49:3-60:10",2
37,8,"T","بَلٰی","It is a trial in which hardship and severity are encountered. The author of al-Muntaha al-Arab explains its meaning as hardship (m. r.), and this trial can occur in both favorable and unfavorable circumstances.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَبَلَوۡنٰہُمۡ بِالۡحَسَنٰتِ وَ السَّیِّاٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» (168/7)\nTranslation: And We tested them with both ease and hardship, so that they might return [to Us].\n\nHowever, since trial involves distress, it is more frequently employed in the context of evil.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«وَلَنَبۡلُوَنَّکُمۡ بِشَیۡءٍ مِّنَ الۡخَوۡفِ وَ الۡجُوۡعِ وَ نَقۡصٍ مِّنَ الۡاَمۡوَالِ وَ الۡاَنۡفُسِ وَ الثَّمَرٰتِ ؕ وَ بَشِّرِ الصّٰبِرِیۡنَ» (155/2)\nTranslation: And We will surely test you with something of fear, hunger, and loss of wealth, lives, and fruits. But give good tidings to the patient.\n\nAnd «اِبْتَلیٰ» means to turn something upside down or to examine by altering circumstances.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ  اَمۡشَاجٍ ٭ۖ  نَّبۡتَلِیۡہِ» (3/76)\nTranslation: We created man from a mixed drop, which We continue to turn and change.\n\nThen «اِبْتَلَاء» generally occurs through an accidental incident—an event that others can also witness. (m. f.)\n\nSee the following verse:\n«وَاِذِ ابۡتَلٰۤی اِبۡرٰہٖمَ رَبُّہٗ بِکَلِمٰتٍ فَاَتَمَّہُنَّ» (124/2)\nTranslation: And [mention] when the Lord of Abraham, peace be upon him, tried him with certain commands, and he fulfilled them.\n\nAnd obviously, these commands were things such as leaving one's homeland, abandoning one's child in the wilderness, being prepared to sacrifice one's son, or entering the fire, etc., which all other people could witness.","«بَلَاء» and «اِبْتَلَاء» this is a severe test, and it generally occurs through events that others can also witness—that is, through incidents.","Trial","بلی","2:49-2:124-2:155-2:249-3:152-3:154-3:186-4:6-5:48-5:94-6:165-7:141-7:163-7:168-8:17-10:30-11:7-14:6-16:92-18:7-21:35-23:30-27:40-33:11-37:106-44:33-47:4-47:31-67:2-68:17-76:2-89:15-89:16",33
38,8,"T","فَتَنَ","The meaning of «فَتَنَ» is to melt gold and silver by placing them in a *kithiali* (a clay vessel shaped like a bowl for melting) and to burn them to ascertain impurities. (Munjid) Similar hardship is also encountered in this test.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«یَوۡمَ ہُمۡ عَلَی النَّارِ یُفۡتَنُوۡنَ» (13:51)  \nTranslation: They will be burned on that Day.  \n\nMoreover, the word «فِتْنَۃ» is often used in a negative sense. The meanings of *fitnah* include trial, sorrow, distress, disgrace, madness, lesson, punishment, and disease; it is employed in all these senses. (Munjid) Similarly, «فَتَّان» means an evil person, a thief, or Satan. (Munjid)  \n\nIn contrast, in *ibtila* (trial), a person's trial does not arise due to personal evil and malice. The distinction between the realm of *ibtila* and the realm of *fitnah* is entirely clear. In *ibtila*, the adverse aspect generally pertains to natural events, whereas in *fitnah*, the adverse aspect is often a person's own creation.  \n\nFor instance, the Quran declares:  \n«اِلَّا تَفۡعَلُوۡہُ تَکُنۡ فِتۡنَۃٌ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ فَسَادٌ کَبِیۡرٌ» (73:8)  \nTranslation: O believers! If you do not act thus, turmoil will spread in the land and great corruption will prevail.  \n\nThe difference between *ibtila* and *fitnah* is that in *fitnah*, the trial typically involves things a person loves and to which they are deeply attached. (M.R.)  \n\nFor example, the Quran says:  \n«وَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ  وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ  فِتۡنَۃٌ» (28:8)  \nTranslation: And know that your wealth and children are a great trial.  \n\nA strong proof of this lies in Surah Al-Baqarah, where, mentioning Harut and Marut, it is stated:  \n«وَ مَا یُعَلِّمٰنِ مِنۡ اَحَدٍ حَتّٰی یَقُوۡلَاۤ اِنَّمَا نَحۡنُ فِتۡنَۃٌ فَلَا تَکۡفُرۡ» (2:102)  \nTranslation: Those two did not teach magic to anyone until they would say, We are only a trial, so do not disbelieve.  \n\nThat disbelief was the demand for magic, in the desire for which those people were ensnared. This very desire has been termed *fitnah*.  \n\nNote: (*Kithiali*: a clay vessel shaped like a bowl for melting silver, gold, etc.)","«فَتَنَ» means trial or test, and this generally occurs through things to which people have a deep emotional attachment.","Trial","فتن","2:102-2:191-2:193-2:217-3:7-4:91-4:101-5:41-5:49-5:71-6:53-7:27-7:155-8:25-8:28-8:39-8:73-9:47-9:48-9:49-9:126-10:83-10:85-16:110-17:60-17:73-20:40-20:85-20:90-20:131-21:35-21:111-22:11-22:53-24:63-25:20-27:47-29:2-29:3-29:10-33:14-37:63-38:24-38:34-39:49-44:17-51:14-54:27-57:14-60:5-64:15-72:17-74:31-85:10",54
39,9,"E","ھَیِّن","«ھَیِّنٌ» has its substance in «ھون», which includes, besides ease, the aspect of gentleness (as noted by scholars), provided that this gentleness does not involve disrespect or dishonor. Rather, along with gentleness, serenity and dignity are included, and this attribute is praiseworthy.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «وَعِبَادُ  الرَّحۡمٰنِ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَمۡشُوۡنَ عَلَی الۡاَرۡضِ ہَوۡنًا» (25:63). Translation: And the servants of the Most Merciful are those who walk upon the earth modestly/humbly.\n\nAnd if this gentleness leads to belittling someone, then it becomes a matter of humiliation and disgrace, and this is a blameworthy act, for which the term «ھُوْن» is used.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «فَالۡیَوۡمَ تُجۡزَوۡنَ عَذَابَ الۡہُوۡنِ» (20:46). Translation: So today you will be punished with the torment of humiliation.\n\nTherefore, «ھَیِّنٌ» is an act that is completely insignificant (light) in comparison to the doer's power and capability, because in the meaning of its substance, alongside humility, the aspect of inferiority and humiliation is also included. That is, something utterly trivial and insignificant.\n\nThus, in Surah Maryam, it is mentioned that when the angel gave the news of the birth of a son to Maryam (Mary), she wondered and said, as the Noble Quran has described: «اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡ غُلٰمٌ وَّ لَمۡ یَمۡسَسۡنِیۡ  بَشَرٌ وَّ لَمۡ اَکُ بَغِیًّا ، قَالَ کَذٰلِکِ ۚ قَالَ رَبُّکِ ہُوَعَلَیَّ ہَیِّنٌ» (19:20-21). Translation: How can I have a son when no man has touched me, nor am I unchaste? The angel said, Just so. Your Lord says, It is easy for Me.","«ھَیِّنٌ» a matter or deed that is utterly insignificant when contrasted with the power and capability of the heedless.","Easy","ھین","19:9-19:21",2
40,9,"E","يَسِيرٌ","«يَسِيرٌ» Its material origin is «یُسْر» (ease and lightness), and «یَسِیْر» is the action that is performed with ease and facility. Its opposite is «عُسَیْر».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یَّفۡعَلۡ ذٰلِکَ عُدۡوَانًا وَّ ظُلۡمًا فَسَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِ نَارًا ؕ وَ کَانَ ذٰلِکَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ  یَسِیۡرًا» (4:30)\n\nTranslation: And whoever commits transgression and injustice, We will soon admit him into Hell. And that is ever easy for Allah.","«يَسِيرٌ» meaning ease, that is the work which is accomplished with ease and convenience.","Easy","یسیر","4:30-4:169-12:65-22:70-29:19-33:19-33:30-35:11-50:44-57:22-64:7-74:10-84:8",13
41,10,"H","سَمَاء","«سَمَاء» and «سَمُوْء» basically mean height, but there is no fixed limit to this height. The author of *Fiqh al-Lughah* has defined *samaa*: Anything that is above us and casts a shadow upon us is *samaa*. (F.L.)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَّ اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (2/22) Translation: And Allah sent down water from the sky (caused rain to fall). Here, by *samaa*, clouds are meant, which generally fly at an altitude of about one and a half miles above the earth's surface. The word *samaa* is used even for this modest altitude, and at another place, the divine command states: «اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ  الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ» (37/6) Translation: Indeed, We have adorned the sky of the world with the beauty of stars. Here, the intended height is as great as the distance at which stars shine, whether they are at hundreds of thousands of miles altitude like the moon, or tens of millions of miles like the sun, or billions of miles like Scorpio, etc.\n\nThe word «سَمَاء» is from the relative nouns, and its opposite is *ard* (earth). That is, every thing has its *matuh* (that which is beneath it); from that perspective, it is «سَمَاء». And that same thing, from the perspective of its *mafooq* (that which is above), is also «اَرْض» (meaning 'above'). Thus, it is as if a thing that from the perspective of its *matuh* is «سَمَاء», and that same thing from the perspective of its *mafooq* is *ard*.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «اَللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ سَبۡعَ  سَمٰوٰتٍ وَّ مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ مِثۡلَہُنَّ» (65/12) Translation: Allah is the One Who created seven heavens and earths of a similar nature. In this verse, these same meanings are found.\n\nThen, just as *samaa* is used in the meaning of height, *ard* (earth) is also used in meanings of lowliness. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ لَوۡ شِئۡنَا لَرَفَعۡنٰہُ بِہَا وَ لٰکِنَّہٗۤ اَخۡلَدَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ» (7/176) Translation: And if We had willed, We could have elevated him with these verses, but he inclined towards lowliness and followed his own desire.","«سَمَاء» its basic meaning is loftiness, but there is no limit to this loftiness.","Heaven","سماء","2:19-2:22-2:29-2:33-2:59-2:107-2:116-2:117-2:144-2:164-2:255-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:83-3:109-3:129-3:133-3:180-3:189-3:190-3:191-4:126-4:131-4:132-4:153-4:170-4:171-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:97-5:112-5:114-5:120-6:1-6:3-6:6-6:12-6:14-6:35-6:73-6:75-6:79-6:99-6:101-6:125-7:40-7:54-7:96-7:158-7:162-7:185-7:187-8:11-8:32-9:36-9:116-10:3-10:6-10:18-10:24-10:31-10:55-10:61-10:66-10:68-10:101-11:7-11:44-11:52-11:107-11:108-11:123-12:101-12:105-13:2-13:15-13:16-13:17-14:2-14:10-14:19-14:24-14:32-14:38-14:48-15:14-15:16-15:22-15:85-16:3-16:10-16:49-16:52-16:65-16:73-16:77-16:79-17:44-17:55-17:92-17:93-17:95-17:99-17:102-18:14-18:26-18:40-18:45-18:51-19:65-19:90-19:93-20:4-20:6-20:53-21:4-21:16-21:19-21:30-21:32-21:56-21:104-22:15-22:18-22:31-22:63-22:64-22:65-22:70-23:18-23:71-23:86-24:35-24:41-24:42-24:43-24:64-25:2-25:6-25:25-25:48-25:59-25:61-26:4-26:24-26:187-27:25-27:60-27:64-27:65-27:75-27:87-29:22-29:34-29:44-29:52-29:61-29:63-30:8-30:18-30:22-30:24-30:25-30:26-30:27-30:48-31:10-31:16-31:20-31:25-31:26-32:4-32:5-33:72-34:1-34:2-34:3-34:9-34:22-34:24-35:1-35:3-35:27-35:38-35:40-35:41-35:44-36:28-36:81-37:5-37:6-38:10-38:27-38:66-39:5-39:21-39:38-39:44-39:46-39:63-39:67-39:68-40:13-40:37-40:57-40:64-41:11-41:12-42:4-42:5-42:11-42:12-42:29-42:49-42:53-43:9-43:11-43:82-43:84-43:85-44:7-44:10-44:29-44:38-45:3-45:5-45:13-45:22-45:27-45:36-45:37-46:3-46:4-46:33-48:4-48:7-48:14-49:16-49:18-50:6-50:9-50:38-51:7-51:22-51:23-51:47-52:9-52:36-52:44-53:26-53:31-54:11-55:7-55:29-55:33-55:37-57:1-57:2-57:4-57:5-57:10-57:21-58:7-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-63:7-64:1-64:3-64:4-65:12-67:3-67:5-67:16-67:17-69:16-70:8-71:11-71:15-72:8-73:18-77:9-78:19-78:37-79:27-81:11-82:1-84:1-85:1-85:9-86:1-86:11-88:18-91:5",297
42,10,"S","فَلَک","The general meaning of «فَلَک» is understood as sky. However, in reality, the paths along which planets orbit or celestial bodies revolve in space are called *falak* (m.r. m.l. m.f).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ وَ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ  فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ»  (21:33)\n\nTranslation: And He it is Who created the night and the day, and the sun and the moon, all swimming along in their respective courses.\n\nThe reason these paths are termed «فَلَک» is that planets do not revolve in perfect circles in space; rather, under certain laws of motion, they adopt an elliptical shape. Subsequently, due to their ship-like appearance, they are referred to as «فَلَک». Such a ship is called «فُلْک» in Arabic.","«فَلَک» refers to the orbits (paths) of the planets.","Sky","فلک","21:33-36:40",2
43,11,"H","اِعْتَرٰی","«اِعْتَرٰی» means to be naked, and «اَعْرٰی» means to strip someone of their clothes and make them naked, and «اَعْرٰی فُلَانًا صَدِیْقَہ» means not helping a person and abandoning them, leaving them behind, and «عُرِیَ» means to feel cold due to fever and to shiver from fear, and «عُرْوًا» means coldness from fever (chills), and «اِعْتَرٰی» means to cause someone to experience such a condition. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «اِنۡ نَّقُوۡلُ  اِلَّا اعۡتَرٰىکَ بَعۡضُ اٰلِہَتِنَا بِسُوۡٓءٍ» (11/54) Translation: (The people of Hud said) We say that one of our gods has afflicted you (made you insane).","«اِعْتَرٰی» is used to afflict someone with a physical illness.","harm","اعتری","11:54",1
44,11,"H","تَخَبَّطَ","«خَبَطَ» meaning to drive someone mad by tormenting them (figurative), and Makhbūṭ meaning feeble-minded, i.e., a person whose intellect does not function properly. According to Arab belief, this was related to jinn and devils. Just as they used to call a madman insane too. That is, one upon whom jinn have descended and has made him insane. The difference between majnūn (insane) and makhbūṭ (feeble-minded) was only that a person who became ill due to a defect in intellect was called majnūn, while one upon whom this condition befell temporarily and transiently was called makhbūṭ.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ الرِّبٰوا لَا یَقُوۡمُوۡنَ اِلَّا کَمَا یَقُوۡمُ الَّذِیۡ یَتَخَبَّطُہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ مِنَ الۡمَسِّ» (2/275)\nTranslation: Those who consume usury will rise (from their graves) as if they were driven mad by the touch of the devils.","If the disease (illness) is related to the mind, it is called «تَخَبَّطَ». And if the disease (illness) is related to the body, then the term «اعترٰی» will be used.","Harm","تخبط","2:275",1
45,12,"F","اَطْفَأَ","«طَفَاْ» meaning the complete extinguishing of fire, becoming cold, and «اَطْفَاْ» meaning to extinguish fire. To blow out and extinguish a lamp (as in the dictionary). Then this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. For example, «اَطْفَأَ الْفِتْنَۃَ اَوِالْحَرْب», meaning to extinguish discord or battle (as in the dictionary).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  اَنۡ یُّطۡفِئُوۡا نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ» (9/32)\nTranslation: The disbelievers wish that they could extinguish Allah's light with their mouths.","«طَفَا» complete extinction of fire.","Fire","اطفا","5:64-9:32-61:8",3
46,12,"F","اَوْرٰی ( وری )","The meaning of «وَرٰی یَرِیْ» is the emission of a flame of fire. Wari al-zand is a metaphor meaning to draw out fire from a flint (intransitive) and (transitive, see page 288).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَالۡمُوۡرِیٰتِ قَدۡحًا» (2/100)\nTranslation: Then (by the horses) which strike sparks against stones.\n\nIn this verse, «قدَحَ» refers to striking a stone with a horseshoe (so that a spark is produced), and «آری» refers to the spark being produced. Subsequently, the word «اَوْرٰی» began to be used generally in the meanings of kindling fire, whether from vegetation, fuel, or any other thing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتُمُ النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ تُوۡرُوۡنَ ۔ ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ» (72-71/56)\nTranslation: So have you considered the fire which you kindle (from trees)? Did you create its trees or did We create them?","«اَوْرٰی» ignite","Fire","اوری ( وری )","56:71-100:2",2
47,12,"F","اَوْقَدَ","«وَقَدَ» means the blazing up of fire (munjad). Ibn Faris has stated its meanings «کَلِمَۃٌ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِشْتِعَالِ النَّار» (m l).\nAnd «اَوْقَدَ» comes in the meaning of lighting fire when flames begin to appear.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَوۡقِدۡ لِیۡ یٰہَامٰنُ عَلَی الطِّیۡنِ فَاجۡعَلۡ  لِّیۡ صَرۡحًا» (38/28)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) O Haman! Light a fire for me upon the clay (to bake the bricks) and then build for me a lofty tower.\n«اَوْقَدَ» is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَوۡقَدُوۡا  نَارًا لِّلۡحَرۡبِ اَطۡفَاَہَا اللّٰہُ» (64/5)\nTranslation: Whenever they (the Jews) kindle a fire for war, Allah extinguishes it.\nAnd «اِسْتَوْقَدَ» means to gather fuel, etc., and light a fire or lamp with great effort (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَثَلُہُمۡ کَمَثَلِ الَّذِی اسۡتَوۡقَدَ نَارًا ۚ  فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ» (17/2)\nTranslation: The example of those (hypocrites) is like that of a person who kindled a fire (in the dark night). When it illuminated what was around him, Allah took away their light.","«اَوْقَدَ» to kindle a fire.","Fire","اوقد","2:17-5:64-24:35-28:38-36:80-104:6",6
48,12,"F","تَلَظّٰی","«لَظٰی» refers to a fire that blazes but has no flame (F L 56), and «لَظَّی النَّار» means 'to kindle a fire' while «تَلَظّٰی» means 'for a fire to blaze intensely'.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«فَاَنۡذَرۡتُکُمۡ  نَارًا تَلَظّٰی» (14/92)  \nTranslation: Then I have warned you of a Fire that blazes.","When the fire is blazing fiercely, yet there is no flame.","Fire","تلظی","70:15-92:14",2
49,12,"F","جِذْوَۃٌ","An ember covered with ashes, its glow extinguished. For example: In the Quran it says: «اِنِّیۡۤ  اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ اَوۡ جَذۡوَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ» (29/28). Translation: I saw a fire; perhaps I can bring you some information about the path or a burning ember from there.","«جِذْوَۃٌ» a coal on which ash has fallen and whose glow has faded.","fire","جذوۃ","28:29",1
50,12,"F","حَرَّقَ","«حَرَقَ» and «حَرَّقَ بِالنَّار» mean setting on fire, and «اِحْتَرَقَ» means being reduced to ashes (meaning) (this is the final stage). For example, in the Quran: «قَالُوۡاحَرِّقُوۡہُ وَانۡصُرُوۡۤا اٰلِہَتَکُمۡ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ فٰعِلِیۡنَ» (68/21). Translation: Then the polytheists began to say, If you have (to take revenge from Abraham for your idols and) something to do, then burn Abraham and help your idols. At another instance, the divine decree is: «فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2/266). Translation: So suddenly, a fierce, fiery blast struck that garden, and it became (a heap of ashes).","«حَرَّقَ» to burn something to ashes.","Fire","حرق","20:97-21:68-29:24",3
51,12,"F","خَبَا","«خَبَا» means the flame becoming subdued or dying down, and a layer of ash settling over the embers or coal. (m.f.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا خَبَتۡ زِدۡنٰہُمۡ سَعِیۡرًا» (97/17)\nTranslation: When its fire is on the verge of dying out, We will flare it up even more intensely.","The extinction of the flame and the covering of ashes on the ember. This is an intermediate state.","Fire","خبا","17:97",1
52,12,"F","خَمَدَ","«خَمَدَ» refers to the state of a fire dying down where the flame has been extinguished but the embers remain glowing. As for «خَمِدَتِ الْحُمّٰی», it means the breaking of a fever's intensity, and «خُمُوْد» can also signify 'ember' and is metaphorically used to mean 'death' (see Majma' al-Bayan, vol. 9).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَانَتۡ  اِلَّا صَیۡحَۃً وَّاحِدَۃً  فَاِذَا ہُمۡ خٰمِدُوۡنَ» (36:29)\nTranslation: So it was only a single blast, and they suddenly became extinguished (or died).","«خَمَدَ» the flame of the fire dying out.","Fire","خمد","21:15-36:29",2
53,12,"F","سَجَّرَ","In «سَجَّرَ», the meaning of something being full and having mixture or turmoil within it is found (cf. M L). The meaning of «سَجَّرَ الْتَّنُّوْر» is to fill the furnace with fuel and heat it (cf. Munjid) so that the fire can blaze with full intensity. Also, «سَجْر» refers to the sound of thunder and flash of clouds (cf. Munjid).\n\nFor instance, in the Noble Quran: «وَ الۡبَحۡرِالۡمَسۡجُوۡرِ» (52/6) Translation: And the blazing sea. This implies that the sea is both full and boiling with turbulent waves.\n\nFor instance, in the Noble Quran: «فِی الۡحَمِیۡمِ ۬ ۙ ثُمَّ  فِی النَّارِ  یُسۡجَرُوۡنَ» (Surah No. 40, Ayah No. 72) Translation: These (disbelievers) will be thrown first into scalding water, then into the fire.\n\nNote: (Mukhalat: meaning mixture, friendship, blending, amalgamation)\n\nNote: (Talatam: the rising and clashing of intense waves, water surges, storm)","to stoke the flames «سَجَّرَ»","Fire","سجر","40:72-81:6",2
54,12,"F","سعّر ۔ سَعَرَ","The meaning of «سَعَّرَ» is the burning, blazing, and rising of fire. (M L) It is as if this is the next level after «وَقَدَ», and «سَقَرَ» means to blaze fire intensely (munjadd), while «سَعِیْر» means a blazing fire. For example: in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذَاالۡجَحِیۡمُ سُعِّرَتۡ» (81/12)\nTranslation: And when the Hellfire is set ablaze.","«سَعَّرَ» setting fire","Fire","سعر ۔ سعر","81:12",1
55,12,"F","شِھَابٌ","«شِھَابٌ» is the term for an ember that possesses brightness and flame, whether it is an ember of fire or found in space (mufrad), and its plural is «شُہُب».\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّاَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّشُہُبًا» (8/72)\nTranslation: (The jinn said) And that we have sought [to know] the heaven and found it guarded by stern guards and embers.","«شِھَابٌ» a flaming, glowing ember.","fire","شھاب","15:18-27:7-37:10-72:8-72:9",5
56,12,"F","شَوٰی ( یشوی )","«شَوٰی» Roasting meat in fire and meat that has been roasted is referred to as (munjad). This is the third degree (of hellfire).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ» ( 18/29 )\nTranslation: And if they call for relief, they will be relieved with water like scalding oil, which will roast [i.e., burn] their faces.","«شَوٰی» is used for meat roasted over fire.","Fire","شوی ( یشوی )","18:29-70:16",2
57,12,"F","صَھَرَ","«صَھَرَ» meaning to melt by heating fat, etc., and «صَھَارَۃ» meaning a melted substance. A piece of fat, the marrow of a bone, and «صَھُوْر» meaning one who melts, one who fries meat (mufannaj). Thus, «صَھَرَ» implies such intense heat as is required for melting substances, particularly for melting fat and for cooking meat.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُصَبُّ مِنۡ فَوۡقِ رُءُوۡسِہِمُ الۡحَمِیۡمُ ۔ یُصۡہَرُ  بِہٖ  مَا فِیۡ  بُطُوۡنِہِمۡ  وَ الۡجُلُوۡدُ» (22:19,20)\nTranslation: And scalding water will be poured over their heads, melting what is within their bellies and their skins.","«صَھَرَ» such a scorching fire that roasts meat and melts fat.","Fire","صھر","22:20",1
58,12,"F","قَبَسٌ","«قَبَسٌ» a requested ember or flame of fire. See details under 'to set fire'.","A sought-after burning coal or flame.","Fire","قبس","20:10-27:7",2
59,12,"F","قَبَسَ","«قَبَسَ» means a spark of fire taken from a flame (plural), and «قَبَس» means that flame taken from a great fire.  \nAnd «قَابِس» means one who seeks fire, and «قَبَسَہُ النَّار» means to bring fire for someone, and «اَقْبَسَ فُلَانًا» means to give fire to someone (Munjid).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِقَبَسٍ  اَوۡ  اَجِدُ  عَلَی النَّارِ  ہُدًی» (20:10)  \nTranslation: I have seen fire; perhaps I can bring you a spark from it or find a way to those who kindle fire.  \nIn this verse, the word «قَبَس» appears instead of «جَذْوَۃٌ مِنَ النَّار», and it is also used for the requested fire.  \nThen, the word «قَبَسَ» also comes to mean, besides fire, to light fire from fire, to obtain light from great light, and to acquire knowledge from great scholars. «قَبَسَ الْعِلْم» means to acquire knowledge, to benefit from knowledge, and «اِقْتَبَسَ مِنْہُ النَّارَ وَالنُّور وَالْعِلْم» means to obtain fire, light, or knowledge from someone (Munjid).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا انۡظُرُوۡنَا نَقۡتَبِسۡ مِنۡ نُّوۡرِکُمۡ» (57:13)  \nTranslation: Turn your gaze (of mercy) upon us so that we too may obtain light from your light.  \nAnd in our usage, the term for quotation means to take a part or piece from someone's scholarly writing or book and present it.","«قَبَسَ» to fight fire with fire","Fire","قبس","20:10-27:7",2
60,12,"F","قَدَحَ","«زَنَّدَ» means to strike fire (minjad), as though the term «قَدَحَ» is confined solely to the attempt and intention of eliciting fire.","«قَدَحَ» the initial attempt to set fire","Fire","قدح","100:2",1
61,12,"F","لَفَحَ","The meaning of «لَفَحَ» is to scorch or burn the face or skin with fire or hot wind (sing. Munjid). This causes the complexion to spoil, as if it were a second-degree burn. For example, the Noble Quran states: «تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» (23/104). Translation: The fire of Hell will scorch their faces, and they will be disfigured therein.","«لَفَحَ» refers to fire or hot wind scorching the face or skin, causing disfigurement.","Fire","لفح","23:104",1
62,12,"F","لَوَّحَ","«لَاحَ» refers specifically to the skin turning to a blackish hue. Whether this occurs due to fire, heat, the sun, thirst, or travel (i.e., *munjadd*), meaning fire or heat touching someone in such a way that their skin turns blackish. And «لَوَّحَ» means to heat something with fire (i.e., *munjadd*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (74/29)\nTranslation: The fire of Hell will scorch (their) skin, blackening it.","The skin turning black from the heat of fire or the sun's scorching rays.","Fire","لوح","74:29",1
63,12,"F","نَارٌ","The term «نَارٌ» is general. Whether fire is blazing, moving swiftly, or dying out, with flame or without, the word nar (fire) is applied to all of it. Whereas «لظٰی» refers to an intense, blazing fire that has no flame (Al-Khāliṣ min al-Lahāb, Fī 56).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی ۔ نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی» (70:15-16)\nTranslation: It (Hell) is a blazing fire, scalding [or peeling] the skin.","«نَارٌ» is used for all types of fire.","Fire","نار","2:17-2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:266-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:10-4:14-4:30-4:56-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:64-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:12-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-9:35-9:63-9:68-9:81-9:109-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-15:27-16:62-18:29-18:53-18:96-20:10-21:39-21:69-22:19-22:72-23:104-24:35-24:57-27:7-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-35:36-36:80-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-38:76-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:13-52:14-54:48-55:15-55:35-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:6-66:10-71:25-72:23-74:31-85:5-87:12-88:4-90:20-92:14-98:6-101:11-104:6-111:3",138
64,12,"F","نَضِجَ","«نَضِجَ» the scorching of meat by intense heat (example) in such a way that its parts begin to separate. (This is the fourth degree.)\nFor instance: In the Quran it is: «سَوۡفَ نُصۡلِیۡہِمۡ نَارًا ؕ کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا» (4/56)\nTranslation: We will soon admit them into the Fire. Then when their skins are scorched and burned, We will replace them with other skins.","« نَضِجَ» merely tenderizes the meat through the heat of the fire.","Fire","نضج","4:56",1
65,13,"I","اَدرٰی ( دری )","«اَدرٰی» means to acquire knowledge of something through a means, device, or some other thing. (muf) It is derived from «دَرِی» and is frequently used. «دِرَایَۃٌ» is transitive; upon it, «لَا ، مَا» or «اِنْ» (the negating particle), or «مَا» (the interrogative particle) always enters.\n\nFor example: The divine revelation states:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» (101/10,11)\nTranslation: And what will make you understand what the Blazing Fire is? (It is) the blazing Fire.\n\nFurther examples can be seen under the entry for to know (جاننا).\n\nNote: (مصدر: meaning to emanate or originate, i.e., the place of emergence or beginning, source, origin, foundation, spring, root. مصدر: It is a noun from which other verbs can be derived, but which itself is not derived from any verb.)","to explain something in a roundabout way","Informed","ادری ( دری )","10:16-10:90-21:109-21:111-46:9-69:3-69:26-72:25-74:27-77:14-82:17-82:18-83:8-83:19-86:2-90:12-97:2-101:3-101:10-104:5",20
66,13,"A","اَشْعَرْ","«اَشْعَرْ» is used to convey news.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَابۡعَثُوۡۤا اَحَدَکُمۡ بِوَرِقِکُمۡ ہٰذِہٖۤ  اِلَی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ اَیُّہَاۤ اَزۡکٰی طَعَامًا فَلۡیَاۡتِکُمۡ بِرِزۡقٍ مِّنۡہُ  وَ لۡـیَؔ‍‍‍تَلَطَّفۡ وَ لَا یُشۡعِرَنَّ بِکُمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/19)  \nTranslation: (The People of the Cave awoke after a long period and began to converse among themselves. They said, Send one of you to the city with this silver coin; let him find out which is the finest food and bring some back, and be gentle in your dealings, and do not let anyone know about you.)","«اَشْعَرْ» is used to convey information.","Aware","اشعر","6:109-18:19",2
67,13,"E","اَطْلَعَ","The basic meaning of «طَلَعَ» is to manifest and to come forth (m l), and «طَلَعَ الْکَوَاکِب» means the rising of planets, the sun, the moon, etc., and «اَطْلَع» means to make someone aware of the actual state (manjad).\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states: «وَ مَا کَانَ اللّٰہُ لِیُطۡلِعَکُمۡ عَلَی الۡغَیۡبِ وَ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ یَجۡتَبِیۡ مِنۡ رُّسُلِہٖ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (3/179). Translation: And it is not possible for Allah to make you aware of the unseen matters, but Allah chooses from His messengers whom He wills.","«اَطْلَع» to make someone aware of the reality of something.","Enlightened","اطلع","3:179-5:13-19:78",3
68,13,"I","اَظْھَرَ","«اَظْھَرَ» to disclose the hidden news.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا» ( 72/26 ) ’’\nTranslation: He is Allah, the Knower of the unseen, and He does not disclose His unseen to anyone.","To disclose the concealed news.","Informed","اظھر","66:3-72:26",2
69,13,"I","اَنْبَا  ،  نَبَّاَ","The fundamental meaning of «نَبَّاَ» is to come from one place to another, and «سَیْلٌ نَابیٌء» refers to a flood that reaches from one city to another (M.L.). Subsequently, based on this, the word *naba* began to be used in the meanings of news. The author of *Muntahi al-Arab* has written that the meanings of «اَنْبَا» are to give news and inform (M.L.). The difference between *khabar* (news) and *naba* is that *khabar* is general, while *naba* refers to news of a specific event that is also beneficial for the listener. Moreover, *naba* is related to news of the past, present, future, and even the trans-temporal—i.e., news after death and of resurrection—whereas the scope of *khabar* is limited only to the past and present. Thus, importance, benefit, and temporal breadth are the three things that distinguish «نَبَّاَ» from general news. Since «نَبَّاَ» also includes news of the future or prophecy, disbelievers consequently continued to call prophets soothsayers (*kahin*). Imam Raghib has also written in his definition of *naba* that it must be free from the possibility of falsehood, and from it, knowledge or beneficial conjecture should be obtained, as is attained from divine revelation and continuous news, etc. However, in our opinion, this condition is incorrect. Because the divine command states:\n\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49:6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, if there comes to you a disobedient one with news, then verify it.\n\nAnd it is evident that in the *naba* of a transgressor (*fasiq*), the possibility of falsehood exists—which is why Allah the Most High has commanded verification. Similarly, the news (*naba*) given by the hoopoe bird to Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him) did not result in knowledge or beneficial conjecture for him either (also see *khabar dana* – giving news).","To convey news of an important event and warn about it, when it pertains to the very being of the recipient, whether this news relates to the past, present, or future.","Informed","انبا ، نبا","2:31-2:33-3:15-3:44-3:49-5:14-5:27-5:48-5:60-5:105-6:5-6:34-6:60-6:67-6:105-6:108-6:143-6:159-6:164-7:101-7:175-9:64-9:70-9:94-9:105-10:18-10:23-10:53-10:71-11:49-11:100-11:120-12:15-12:36-12:37-12:45-12:102-13:33-14:9-15:49-15:51-18:13-18:78-18:103-20:99-22:72-24:64-26:6-26:69-26:221-27:22-28:3-28:66-29:8-31:15-31:23-33:20-34:7-35:14-38:21-38:67-38:88-39:7-41:50-49:6-53:36-54:4-54:28-58:6-58:7-62:8-64:5-64:7-66:3-75:13-78:2",76
70,13,"I","حَدَّثَ","«حَدَّثَ» means the occurrence of something, its coming into existence, or the emergence of something new (as per Manjad). According to Ibn al-Faris, it is «کَوْن الشَّیْء لَمْ یَکُنْ». Thus, it refers to the coming into existence or manifestation of something that did not previously exist (as per M. L.). And «حَدَّثَ» also means informing someone of a matter they did not previously know, or at least the informant believes it to be such.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا  ۚ ۖ  وَ اِذَا خَلَا بَعۡضُہُمۡ  اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ قَالُوۡۤا اَتُحَدِّثُوۡنَہُمۡ بِمَا فَتَحَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ لِیُحَآجُّوۡکُمۡ بِہٖ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکُمۡ» (2/76)\nTranslation: And when they (the Jews) meet the believers, they say, We have believed. But when they are alone with one another, they say, Do you inform them (the believers) of what Allah has revealed to you so that they may argue with you about it before your Lord?","«حَدَّثَ» tell us something new.","Informed","حدث","2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4",8
71,13,"A","خَبَرَ","«خَبَرَ» means to be acquainted with and informed about the reality and essence of something, and its other meaning «خبرالشیٔ» is to know something through experience, to experience, to test (manjada). It is evident from these that in comparison to 'ilm, khabar implies a clearer awareness. For instance, the Quran states: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  خَبِیۡرٌۢ   بِمَا تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (59/18) Translation: Indeed, Allah is aware of all your deeds.","When its verification with knowledge has also been completed, then it is used.","Aware","خبر","2:234-2:271-3:153-3:180-4:35-4:94-4:128-4:135-5:8-6:18-6:73-6:103-9:16-11:1-11:111-17:17-17:30-17:96-18:68-18:91-22:63-24:30-24:53-25:58-25:59-27:7-27:88-28:29-31:16-31:29-31:34-33:2-33:34-34:1-35:14-35:31-42:27-48:11-49:13-57:10-58:3-58:11-58:13-59:18-63:11-64:8-66:3-67:14-100:11",49
72,13,"I","دَلَّ","«دَلَّ» means to guide, to show the way, to indicate something, and to denote that by which knowledge and recognition of something are attained—such as words indicating their meanings. Or, for example, when something begins to move, a person understands that it is a living creature, as if its movement indicates the life of a living being (etc.). The word «دَلَّ» is used in both material and spiritual senses.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَمۡشِیۡۤ اُخۡتُکَ فَتَقُوۡلُ ہَلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ  عَلٰی مَنۡ  یَّکۡفُلُہٗ» (20/40)\nTranslation: And (O Moses) your sister went and said, Shall I direct you to a woman who will nurse him?\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا ہَلۡ اَدُلُّکُمۡ عَلٰی تِجَارَۃٍ  تُنۡجِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ عَذَابٍ اَلِیۡمٍ» (61/10)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, shall I guide you to a transaction that will save you from a painful punishment?","«دَلَّ» to guide. To point out the connection between things or to explain the path.","Informed","دل","20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-61:10",5
73,13,"A","شَعَرَ","«شَعْر» is termed bal (hair); therefore, «شَعَرَ» means acquiring knowledge as fine as hair (elaborate). To comprehend the subtleties and nuances of a matter, derive conclusions from circumstances, and reach the very depth of an issue is called «شَعْر». For example, the Quran states: «اَلَاۤ اِنَّہُمۡ ہُمُ الۡمُفۡسِدُوۡنَ وَ لٰکِنۡ لَّا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (2/12). Translation: Behold! These hypocrites are indeed corrupt in themselves, but they do not perceive it.","«شَعَرَ» understanding the intricacies and subtleties of a matter and reaching its very core.","Aware","شعر","2:9-2:12-2:154-3:69-6:26-6:109-6:123-7:95-12:15-12:107-16:21-16:26-16:45-18:19-23:56-26:113-26:202-27:18-27:50-27:65-28:9-28:11-29:53-39:25-39:55-43:66-49:2",27
74,13,"A","ظَھَرَ","The basic meanings of «ظَھَرَ» are two: (1) «قُوَّۃ» (2) to be manifest (apparent). Here it relates to the second meaning, the opposite of which is 'inner' (batin), so «ظَھَرَ» refers to knowledge that is obtained entirely from apparent circumstances and events.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَوِ الطِّفۡلِ الَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ  یَظۡہَرُوۡا عَلٰی عَوۡرٰتِ النِّسَآءِ» (24/31)\nTranslation: or from such boys (for whom there is no requirement for women to observe the veil) who have not yet become aware of the aspects of women's covering.","By this is meant knowledge that is derived entirely from apparent circumstances and events.","Aware","ظھر","2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26",27
75,13,"A","عَثَرَ","«عَثَرَ» Knowledge of such a matter that is acquired unintentionally through conversations (detailed).\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا» (5/107)\nTranslation: Then if it becomes known that both of them have committed sin (by lying).","«عَثَرَ» accidentally learning about something in the course of conversations.","Aware","عثر","5:107-18:21",2
76,13,"M","عَرَّفَ","The meaning of «عَرَفَ» is to contemplate the signs and effects of something and thereby realize or recognize it (مف). It is evident that in recognition, a person can sometimes err; therefore, the status of ma'rifat or 'irfan is lower than that of 'ilm, and the opposite of 'irfan is denial.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَعَرَفَہُمۡ  وَ ہُمۡ  لَہٗ  مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (12:58). Translation: Yusuf (AS) recognized them (his brothers), but they could not recognize him.\n\nFurthermore, «عَرَفَ» also means to perfume, and «عَرَّفَ» means to fragrance or to leave a scent behind (مف ۔ منجد). However, the general meaning of «عَرَّفَ» is to acquaint, introduce, or inform.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ یُدۡخِلُہُمُ  الۡجَنَّۃَ  عَرَّفَہَا  لَہُمۡ» (47:6). Translation: And He will admit them to Paradise, with which He has made them familiar.\n\nAnd Imam Raghib translated it as: And Allah the Exalted has filled Paradise with fragrance for them (مف).","«عَرَّفَ» to explain through signs and symbols.","Mindful","عرف","2:89-2:146-2:273-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:72-23:69-27:93-33:59-47:6-47:30-55:41-66:3-83:24",19
77,13,"A","عَلِمَ","«عَلِمَ» If awareness of the reality of something reaches the level of certainty, this awareness is termed knowledge, and its opposite is «جَھْل». For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمُوۡا لَمَنِ اشۡتَرٰىہُ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ» (2/102). Translation: And they knew that whoever purchases such things (i.e., sorcery and incantations, etc.) will have no share in the Hereafter.","to attain certainty about the truth of something","Aware","علم","2:60-2:65-2:102-2:187-2:235-7:160-8:23-8:66-12:21-12:37-24:41-45:9-48:18-48:27-50:4-56:62-60:10-73:20-81:14-82:5",20
78,13,"E","عَلَّمَ","«عَلَّمَ» is used in the sense of teaching someone knowledge.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«قُلۡ اَتُعَلِّمُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ بِدِیۡنِکُمۡ» (49:16)  \nTranslation: O Prophet! Tell them, Do you claim your piety before Allah?  \nBesides these, in this sense, the words «اَدْرٰی ، حَدَّثَ ، عَرَّفَ» and «اطلع ، اَنْبَاَ» or «نَبَّا» (Prophet) and «دَلَّ» have also been employed.","«عَلَّمَ» is used in the sense of teaching someone knowledge.","Enlightened","علم","49:16",1
79,14,"A","اَسْلَفَ","«سَلَفَ» means the passing or expiration of something or an action (M, A). For example: In Islamic jurisprudence, *bay'u-s-salaf* refers to a sale where the price is paid in full in advance. And *aslaf* refers to the generations that have passed in earlier times. The preceding ancestors (Munjid).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ» ( 4/23 )\nTranslation: But what has passed has passed.\n\nThen, other meanings of «سَلَفَ» also come to mean to move forward (M, L, Munjid). «سَلِیْف» means one who is ahead, one who moves forward. «اَسْلَاف» means the group of the predecessors (Munjid). And «اَسْلَفَ» means an action that occurred in past times.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہُنَالِکَ تَبۡلُوۡا کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ مَّاۤ  اَسۡلَفَتۡ» ( 10/30 )\nTranslation: (1) There, every soul will be tested regarding the deeds it sent ahead (for the Hereafter).\nTranslation: (2) There, He will fully inform them of what they used to do. (Hafiz Usmanؒ)","«اَسْلَفَ» is generally also used for the passing of a matter, i.e., for the Salaf, meaning the earlier forefathers.","Ahead","اسلف","2:275-4:22-4:23-5:95-8:38-10:30-43:56-69:24",8
80,14,"F","اَقْبَلَ","«اِقْبَال» and «اِسْتِقْبَال» both convey the meaning of turning one's face toward something and advancing toward it (muf), i.e., to move forward toward something.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» (68:30)\nTranslation: Then they began to blame each other face to face. (Jalandhari)\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ عَارِضًا مُّسۡتَقۡبِلَ اَوۡدِیَتِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا» (46:24)\nTranslation: Then when they saw it as a cloud advancing toward their valleys, they said, This is a cloud that will pour down rain upon us.","«اَقْبَلَ» is used to mean facing someone and being attentive to them.","Forward","اقبل","12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30",8
81,14,"F","بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ","«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ» (Its literal meaning is between the hands) but figuratively and idiomatically it means ahead or in front. And its opposite is «خَلَف». It is used as an adverb of time and place (i.e., in both senses of location and time). In the temporal sense, its meaning will be the people of that time or the people of that era, but generally, its meaning is taken as those who came after. For example: In the Holy Quran it is said: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/66) Translation: So We have made this story a lesson for the people of that time and for those who come after them. And in the spatial sense, its meaning is ahead or in front. For example: In the Holy Quran it is said: «لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (13/11) Translation: In front of them and behind them are guardians from Allah, who guard them by the command of Allah.","«بَیْنَ یَدَیْ ، بَیْنَ اَیْدِیْ» is generally used to describe time and era.","Forward","بین یدی ،  بین ایدی","2:66-2:97-2:255-3:3-3:50-5:46-5:48-6:92-7:17-7:57-10:37-12:111-13:11-19:64-20:110-21:28-22:76-25:48-27:63-34:9-34:12-34:31-34:46-35:31-36:9-36:45-41:14-41:25-41:42-46:21-46:30-49:1-57:12-58:12-58:13-61:6-66:8-72:27",38
82,14,"F","سَبَقَ","«سَبَقَ» means to advance, to be ahead, or to precede. «السَّبْقُ» refers to a condition imposed on those who advance, and sābiq (the one who precedes) means a horse that wins a race, while «سَبَّقَ» means to place a bet (according to Manjīd). Thus, the concept of advancing in a contest is found in «سبق».\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَ لِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59:10).  \nTranslation: O our Lord! Forgive us and our brothers who have preceded us in faith (all their sins).\n\nFurthermore, «اِسْتَبَقَ» means to strive to advance quickly (according to Manjīd) or to race ahead (as per Muf).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12:25).  \nTranslation: And they both raced to the door—Joseph ahead and the woman behind—and the woman seized his shirt from behind and tore it.","It conveys the meaning of advancing ahead of others in competition.","Forward","سبق","7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4",21
83,14,"F","قُبُل","«قُبْل» means the front part of everything that appears first. And its opposites are «دُبُر» and «دُبْر» (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَوۡ اَنَّنَا نَزَّلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ وَ کَلَّمَہُمُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ حَشَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ قُبُلًا مَّا کَانُوۡا لِیُؤۡمِنُوۡۤا» (6:111)\nTranslation: Even if We had sent down angels to them and the dead had spoken to them, and We had brought all things before them, still they would not have believed.\n\nAnd «قِبَل» also means power and might (Manjad). And «قِبَل» refers to the coming of something before which there is no power or ability to resist.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«بَاطِنُہٗ فِیۡہِ الرَّحۡمَۃُ وَ ظَاہِرُہٗ مِنۡ قِبَلِہِ الۡعَذَابُ» (57:13)\nTranslation: Inside this wall is mercy, and on its outside, facing it, is punishment.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«اَوۡ تَاۡتِیَ بِاللّٰہِ  وَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  قَبِیۡلًا» (17:92)\nTranslation: Or you bring Allah the Most High and the angels before us.","The meaning of «قُبُل» necessitates that two things be opposite each other or face-to-face. Whereas for «بَیْنَ یَدَی», whether in terms of time or place, it is not necessary for things to be opposite each other.","Forward","قبل","6:111-12:26-18:55-27:37-28:31-46:24-51:29-57:13",8
84,14,"F","قَدِمَ","The meaning of «قَدَمَ» is to move forward, to proceed on foot, and to go ahead of someone (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ» (11/98)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh) will lead his people on the Day of Resurrection and will lead them into the Hellfire.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَقْدَمَ» means to intend to move forward (i.e., to hasten) (muf), and its opposite is «اِسْتَاخَرَ» (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہُمۡ فَلَا یَسۡتَاۡخِرُوۡنَ سَاعَۃً وَّ لَا  یَسۡتَقۡدِمُوۡنَ» (10/49)\nTranslation: When their time comes, they cannot delay it by an hour nor hasten it.","In «قَدَمَ», the meaning of merely moving forward or advancing is found. In «سَبَقَ», the meaning of advancing in confrontation with others is found. In «اَقْبَلَ», the meaning of turning toward a person or thing and advancing is found.","Forward","قدم","7:34-10:2-10:49-11:98-15:24-16:61-25:23-34:30-38:60-38:61-49:1-58:12-58:13-74:37",14
85,14,"A","قَدَّمَ","The meaning of «قَدَّمَ» is to do a task before its required time, and its opposite is «اَخَّرَ», i.e., not doing a task at its appropriate time and delaying it (mufrad). And this appropriate time is death—meaning that before death, all the deeds a person has performed in their life are, as it were, sent forward for their eternal life in the Hereafter.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَنۡ یَّتَمَنَّوۡہُ اَبَدًۢا بِمَا قَدَّمَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (2:95)\nTranslation: And they will never wish for death because of the deeds their hands have sent forward.\n\nFurthermore, the word «قَدَّمَ» is also used to warn someone of the consequences of an action before they perform it.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ  لَا تَخۡتَصِمُوۡا لَدَیَّ وَ قَدۡ قَدَّمۡتُ اِلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡوَعِیۡدِ» (50:28)\nTranslation: Allah will say, 'Do not argue with Me. I had already sent you a warning beforehand.'\n\nAnd in «اَسْلَفَ», the same distinction exists as in «اِرْتَفَاع» and «عَمَق»: if one stands at the lower edge, that same distance is called height, but if one stands at the upper edge, that same distance is called depth or profundity. Similarly, the same act or matter that embodies the meaning of «قَدَّمَ» becomes sending forward from the perspective of opportunity. As Allah will say to the believers on the Day of Judgment:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا ہَنِیۡٓـئًۢا بِمَاۤ  اَسۡلَفۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَیَّامِ الۡخَالِیَۃِ» (69:24)\nTranslation: Eat and drink with pleasure for what you sent forward in past days.\n\nNow, if this same meaning is to be expressed in the present tense, it would be conveyed through «بِمَا قَدَّمَتْ اَیْدِیْکُمْ».","«قَدَّمَ» means to do something before its required time.","Ahead","قدم","2:95-2:110-2:223-3:182-4:62-5:80-8:51-18:57-22:10-26:76-28:47-30:36-36:12-42:48-48:2-50:28-59:18-62:7-73:20-75:13-78:40-82:5-89:24",23
86,15,"W","اَسْلِحَۃ","«اَسْلِحَۃْ» is a collective term for «سَلَاح», and it denotes any weapon with which war can be fought (for example). Essentially, this term is specific to martial weapons, whether they are knives, spears, and swords, or rifles and missiles.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَدَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ تَغۡفُلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَسۡلِحَتِکُمۡ وَ اَمۡتِعَتِکُمۡ» (4/102). Translation: The disbelievers indeed wish that you become neglectful of your arms and equipment.","«اَسْلِحَۃْ» all kinds of military equipment. A specific term for military equipment.","War","اسلحۃ","4:102",1
87,15,"W","اَوْزَار","«اَوْزَار» is plural, encompassing the meanings of burden, weapon, and tool. When «وِزْرُالْحَرْب» is used, it specifically denotes war instruments. (detailed) However, even the term «وِرْز» alone conveys the meaning of war weapons. «وَکَذَا اَلْوِزْر : اَلسَّلَاحُ وَالْجَمْعُ اَوْزَار ۔ م ل )» For example, the Quran states: «حَتّٰی تَضَعَ الۡحَرۡبُ اَوۡزَارَہَا» (47/4) Translation: Until the fighting (opposing party) lays down its weapons.","«اَوْزَار» means weapon. If the context is related to war, then they are instruments of war; otherwise, they are not.","War","اوزار","6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-47:4-53:38-94:2",11
88,15,"W","حِذْر","The primary meanings of «حِذْر» are to save, to be cautious, and to be vigilant (M.L.). This word is general in usage. If it is employed in the context of war, its meaning becomes defensive equipment for war. From this, the place of 'saving' can be understood, such as trenches, etc.; similarly, from shields to radar, all can be implied. That is, every thing and every measure through which saving and defense can be achieved is «حِذْر».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍاَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡاحِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: And there is no blame upon you if you put aside your arms when you are troubled by rain or you are ill, and take your precaution «حِذْر» with you. (Uthmani)\n\nIn this, the word «خُذُوْا» indicates that here «حِذْر» does not merely mean to be vigilant (as Fath Muhammad Sahib has written), but rather that defensive equipment must be kept with oneself at all times. This is so that the enemy does not see an opportunity and attempt to take advantage.","«حِذْر» If it is used in the context of war, it will mean defensive war equipment.","War","حذر","2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14",17
89,15,"W","شَوْکَۃ","«شَوْک» means a thorn (with), «درمثَاکَ» means to prick with a thorn, and «شَوْکَۃ» means a thorn, and its plural is «اَشْوَاک». Scorpion's sting. Weapons, speed, power, battle, awe, and «ذُوْشَوْکَۃ» means heavily armed. Armed and from «شَوْک», it is also evident that offensive weapons are meant, with which an attack can be made. (Manjad) For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ تَوَدُّوۡنَ اَنَّ غَیۡرَ ذَاتِ الشَّوۡکَۃِ تَکُوۡنُ لَکُمۡ» (8/7) Translation: And you wished that the unarmed caravan would fall into your hands.","«شَوْکَۃ» offensive weapons of war.","War","شوکۃ","8:7",1
90,16,"T","اَتٰی","«اَتٰی» refers to something that comes about as a result of another action or arrives effortlessly. For example, when milk is churned, butter rises to the top; that butter is called «اَتُوَّۃٌ», and a flood is called «اٰتِیّ». (Mufti F.)\n\nAnother distinction between «جَاءَ» and «اَتٰی» is that in «اَتٰی», unlike «جَاءَ», it is not necessary for the original action to have already occurred.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«اَتٰۤی اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ فَلَا تَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡہُ» (16:1)\nTranslation: God's command (i.e., the punishment as if it has arrived) has come, so (O disbelievers) do not hasten it.\nIn this verse, amr refers to the act of resurrection and recompense, which is yet to take place.","«اَتٰی» is described as coming as a result of another action or effortlessly.","to come","اتی","2:38-2:85-2:118-2:189-2:210-2:214-2:222-2:223-2:248-2:254-2:260-3:125-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:25-4:102-5:41-6:4-6:5-6:34-6:40-6:47-6:130-6:134-6:158-7:17-7:35-7:53-7:80-7:81-7:97-7:98-7:106-7:129-7:138-7:163-7:187-9:54-9:70-9:92-10:24-10:50-11:8-11:76-11:39-11:93-11:105-12:37-12:48-12:49-12:93-12:107-13:31-13:41-14:9-14:17-14:31-14:44-15:11-15:85-15:99-16:1-16:26-16:33-16:45-16:111-16:112-18:19-18:55-18:77-19:38-19:43-19:61-19:93-19:95-20:9-20:11-20:15-20:47-20:60-20:69-20:74-20:75-20:123-20:126-20:133-21:2-21:3-21:40-21:44-22:7-22:27-22:55-23:68-24:49-25:40-26:5-26:6-26:16-26:89-26:154-26:165-26:202-27:18-27:31-27:38-27:54-27:55-27:87-27:92-28:30-28:46-29:5-29:28-29:29-29:53-30:43-32:3-33:14-33:18-33:20-33:30-34:3-36:30-36:46-37:28-38:21-39:25-39:40-39:54-39:55-39:71-40:22-40:35-40:50-40:56-40:59-41:11-41:40-41:42-42:47-43:7-43:66-47:18-51:24-51:42-51:52-59:2-60:12-61:6-63:10-64:5-64:6-65:1-67:8-71:1-74:47-76:1-78:18-79:15-85:17-88:1-98:1",164
91,16,"T","تَعَال","«عَلَو» meaning loftiness and «تَعَال» meaning to call someone to a lofty station or a noble objective (trans.) It is used to call someone with respect, and only the imperative forms are employed:\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ تَعَالَوۡا اِلٰی کَلِمَۃٍ سَوَآءٍۢ  بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَکُمۡ اَلَّا نَعۡبُدَ اِلَّا اللّٰہَ» (3/64)\nTranslation: (O Prophet) say, O People of the Scripture, come to a word equitable between us and you—that we worship none but Allah...","«تَعَال» is used for a lofty purpose or to summon with reverence.","to come","تعال","3:61-3:64-3:167-4:61-5:104-6:151-33:28-63:5",8
92,16,"T","جَاءَ","«جَاءَ» is a common term for 'to come'. However, for its usage, it is necessary that the act of coming has actually been completed (perfective).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ جَآءُوۡۤ  اَبَاہُمۡ  عِشَآءً  یَّبۡکُوۡنَ» (12/16)\nTranslation: And they (the brothers of Prophet Yusuf, peace be upon him) came to their father at night, weeping.","For «جَاءَ» to mean to come, it is necessary that the act of coming has already actually occurred.","To come","جاء","2:87-2:89-2:92-2:101-2:120-2:145-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-2:275-3:19-3:61-3:81-3:86-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:43-4:62-4:64-4:83-4:90-4:153-4:170-4:174-5:6-5:15-5:19-5:32-5:42-5:48-5:61-5:70-5:84-6:5-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:43-6:54-6:61-6:104-6:109-6:124-6:157-6:160-7:4-7:5-7:34-7:37-7:43-7:53-7:63-7:69-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:113-7:116-7:126-7:131-7:143-8:19-9:48-9:90-9:128-10:13-10:22-10:47-10:49-10:57-10:74-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:93-10:94-10:97-10:108-11:12-11:40-11:58-11:66-11:69-11:74-11:76-11:77-11:78-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:120-12:16-12:19-12:50-12:58-12:96-13:37-14:9-15:61-15:67-16:61-16:113-17:5-17:7-17:81-17:94-17:101-17:104-18:55-18:98-19:43-20:72-23:27-23:44-23:68-23:70-23:99-24:39-25:29-26:41-26:206-27:28-27:13-27:36-27:42-27:84-27:89-27:90-28:20-28:25-28:36-28:37-28:48-28:84-28:85-29:10-29:31-29:33-29:39-29:53-29:68-30:9-30:47-33:9-33:10-33:19-34:32-34:43-34:49-35:25-35:37-35:42-35:45-36:13-36:20-37:37-37:84-38:4-39:32-39:33-39:59-39:71-39:73-40:25-40:28-40:29-40:34-40:66-40:78-40:83-41:14-41:20-41:41-42:14-43:29-43:30-43:38-43:47-43:53-43:63-44:13-44:17-45:17-46:7-47:18-49:6-50:2-50:5-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-53:23-54:4-54:41-57:14-58:8-59:10-60:1-60:10-60:12-61:6-63:1-63:11-67:9-69:9-71:4-79:34-80:2-80:8-80:33-89:22-98:4-110:1",216
93,16,"T","ھَلُمَّ","«ھَلُمَّ» is derived from *asma al-af'al*, meaning to call or summon someone repeatedly. This word is very rarely used.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ اللّٰہُ  الۡمُعَوِّقِیۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الۡقَآئِلِیۡنَ لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ   اِلَیۡنَا» (33:18)\nTranslation: Allah knows those among you who prevent others from fighting and say to their brothers, Come to us.\nNote: (*Asma al-af'al*: These are nouns that convey the meaning of a verb but do not accept the grammatical markers of a verb.)","«ھَلُمّ» is used for calling out repeatedly.","to come","ھلم","6:150-33:18",2
94,16,"T","ھَیْتَ","«ھَیْت» This word is actually used in the «اَتٰی» imperative mood, and its pronouns change from the separate pronoun forms. For example, «ھَیْتَ لَکَ ھَیْتَ لَکُمَا ، ھَیْتَ لَکُمْ ۔ وَ۔ وَقِس عَلیٰ ھٰذَا». According to Ibn Faris, «ھَیْتَ» originally signifies to cry out «کَلِمَۃٌ تُدَلٌ عَلَی الصَّیْحَۃِ». Some have also written that its meanings here include to come here, to come there, and to come quickly.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ غَلَّقَتِ الۡاَبۡوَابَ وَ قَالَتۡ ہَیۡتَ لَکَ» (12/23)  \nTranslation: That woman (Zulaikha) said, locking the doors, (Come) quickly, O Joseph!","«ھَیْت» is used to summon someone by shouting.","to come","ھیت","12:23",1
95,17,"E","بَصَر","«بَصَر» signifies both the physical eye and spiritual insight (detailed). Furthermore, «بَصَرَ» is applied in the senses of the act of physical seeing—i.e., looking and gazing—and then reflecting upon what is seen. Examples:\n\nExample (1): The Divine declaration states:\n«الۡحَقُّ فَاِذَا ہِیَ شَاخِصَۃٌ  اَبۡصَارُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (21:97)\nTranslation: And when the true promise of the Hour approaches, the disbelievers' eyes will remain wide open in horror.\n\nExample (2): Regarding gaze: The Divine declaration states:\n«فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50:22)\nTranslation: Now We have removed from you the veil, so your sight today is sharp.\n\nExample (3): Regarding spiritual insight: The Divine declaration states:\n«وَعَلٰۤی اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ غِشَاوَۃٌ» (2:7)\nTranslation: And upon their eyes is a covering.\n\nFrom the root بصر, there arise two verbal nouns (masdars): بصارة and بصیرت. بصارت applies to physical sight, and weakness in sight (ضعف بصارت) refers to the impairment of this physical vision. بصیرت signifies spiritual insight. A poet has thus clarified the distinction between بصیرت and بصارت:\n\nSeek from Allah a discerning heart as well,\nFor the light of the eye is not the light of the heart!\n\nNote: (مصدر: meaning 'source,' 'origin,' 'foundation,' 'spring,' 'root.' A مصدر is a noun from which other verbs can be derived, but which itself is not derived from any verb.)","«بَصَر» I also take into account the vision of the heart, in addition to the outer eye.","eye","بصر","2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9",82
96,17,"E","حُوْر","«حَورَتِ الْعَیْن» meaning the whiteness of the eye becomes intensely white and the blackness becomes deeply black. And to the extent that the whiteness in the eye's white and the blackness in the pupil's black increases, beauty increases proportionally. «اَحْوَرْ» and «حَوْرَاء» are the terms for the man and woman who are characterized by this trait, and their plural is «حُوْر» (pl. masc., pl. fem.). For example, the Noble Quran states: «حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی  الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72) Translation: (In Paradise) there will be houris, confined to tents. At another place, both these attributes of the eye are mentioned together: The declaration of Allah, the Most High, is: «وَ حُوۡرٌ عِیۡنٌ کَاَمۡثَالِ اللُّؤۡلُوءِ  الۡمَکۡنُوۡنِ» (56/22,23) Translation: And [there will be] women with large, black eyes, like hidden pearls.","«حُوْر» is used for white and black eyes; in common parlance, it refers to the women of Paradise.","eye","حور","44:54-52:20-55:72-56:22",4
97,17,"E","عَیْن","«عَیْن» is the well-known human organ with which one sees, and in the meaning of 'spring' (چشمہ), there are many points of correspondence between the two. The plural of this is «اَعْیُن اور عُیُوْن», but in the Quran, the plural of 'ayn (eye) most often appears as «اَعْیُن». And the plural of 'ayn in the meaning of 'spring' appears as «عُیُوْن». The word «عَیْن» is applied solely to the physical eye.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَالۡعَیۡنَ بِالۡعَیۡنِ» ( 5/45 )\nTranslation: Eye for an eye (is the prescribed retaliation).\n\nAnd in terms of attributes, two types of «عَیْن» are mentioned in the Quran:\n«عِیْن» and «حُوْر» are attributes of eyes: «عِین» (those with thick, large eyes) and «حُوْر» (those with intensely white and very black pupils).\n\nThe word «بَصَر» comes, besides the physical organ, to mean the faculty of sight (the act of seeing) and then the contemplation of what is seen.","The word «عَیْن» is used for the eye, which is the apparent organ of sight.","eye","عین","3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-36:66-40:19-43:71-52:48-54:14-54:37-90:8-102:7",35
98,17,"E","عِیْن","«عِیْن» means having big, large eyes. «اَعْیَن» is the term used for a man whose eyes are large and beautiful, and «عَیْنَاء» for a woman with similar eyes. The plural form for both «اَعْیَن» and «عَیْنَاء» is «عِیْنٌ». Since the eyes of a wild cow are also large and beautiful, it too is described with «اَعْیَن» and «عَیْنَاء» (abbreviation).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ عِنۡدَہُمۡ  قٰصِرٰتُ الطَّرۡفِ عِیۡنٌ» (37:48)\nTranslation: And there will be women with downcast eyes, and with large, beautiful eyes.","«عِین» having large, thick eyes.","Eye","عین","37:48-44:54-52:20-56:22",4
99,18,"A","تَاہَ","«تَاہَ» meaning to wander in confusion and distress; to roam about aimlessly in a state of misguidance. (Mufradat) And according to Ibn Faris, «جِنْسٌ مِّنَ الْحَیْرَۃ» refers to a specific type of perplexity, and «اَتِیَہ» means a barren, open plain where a traveler becomes lost.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/26)\nTranslation: God declared that their land would be forbidden to them (the Israelites) for forty years, and they would continue to wander aimlessly in the desert.","«تَاہَ» is used to wander down the paths of misguidance in a state of confusion and distress.","Astray","تاہ","5:26",1
100,18,"A","ھَامَ","«ھَامَ» meaning to wander in a frenzied state. The author of Manjad writes that its meaning is to love and to wander aimlessly, as is the case with people of that passionate disposition.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَالشُّعَرَآءُ  یَتَّبِعُہُمُ  الۡغَاوٗنَ ۔ اَلَمۡ تَرَاَنَّہُمۡ فِیۡ کُلِّ وَادٍ یَّہِیۡمُوۡنَ» (26:224)\nTranslation: And how many a misguided person has followed the poets. Do you not see that they wander aimlessly in every valley?","«ھَامَ» is used to express the restlessness of love and affection.","astray","ھام","26:225",1
101,19,"V","تَصْدِیَۃ","(Sadi') Clapping with both hands (Ma'l) and it includes all musical instruments and their accessories.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَمَا کَانَ صَلَاتُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ الۡبَیۡتِ اِلَّا مُکَآءً وَّ تَصۡدِیَۃً» (8/35)  \nTranslation: And their prayer at the House (Ka'bah) was nothing but whistling and clapping of hands.","A sound like a clap is called «تَصْدِیَۃ».","Voice","تصدیۃ","8:35",1
102,19,"V","تَغَیُّظ","«تَغَیُّظ» meaning the roaring and crackling sounds (metaphorically) arising from the intensity and fury of the Hellfire.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اِذَارَاَتۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ سَمِعُوۡا لَہَا تَغَیُّظًا وَّ زَفِیۡرًا» (25:12)  \nTranslation: When it (Hell) sees them from a distance, they will hear its raging (fury) and its roaring.","«تَغَیُّظ» is used to denote trembling and irritability in states of rage and anger.","Voice","تغیظ","3:119-3:134-9:15-9:120-22:15-25:12-33:25-48:29-67:8",9
103,19,"V","حَسِیْس","The sound of footsteps, the tread. A slight sound (mujad), the sound of fire crackling (cf. 2, 3).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«لَا یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ حَسِیۡسَہَا ۚ وَ ہُمۡ  فِیۡ مَا اشۡتَہَتۡ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ  خٰلِدُوۡنَ» (21/102)\nTranslation: They will not hear its sound, and they will remain forever in the pleasures of their souls. (Uthmani, may Allah have mercy on him)","«حَسِیْس» is used to denote a faint sound, like the soft patter of footsteps.","Voice","حسیس","21:102",1
104,19,"V","خُوَار","«خُوَار» bull. The sound of a cow or calf (F L 193)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اتَّخَذَ قَوۡمُ  مُوۡسٰی مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہٖ مِنۡ حُلِیِّہِمۡ عِجۡلًا جَسَدًا لَّہٗ خُوَارٌ» ( 7/148 )\nTranslation: And after Moses, the people of Moses made a calf from their ornaments, a mere body (idol) from which the sound of a bull was heard.","«خُوَار» is used for the sound of a calf.","Voice","خوار","7:48-20:88",2
105,19,"V","رِكْزًا","«رِکْز» a light and soft sound (f.l. 193) and according to some, a buzz. The buzzing of a fly.\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَکَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ؕ ہَلۡ تُحِسُّ مِنۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ  اَحَدٍ اَوۡ تَسۡمَعُ لَہُمۡ رِکۡزًا» (19/98)\nTranslation: And We have destroyed many a group before them. Do you see any of them now, or hear even a whisper of them?","«رِكْزًا» refers to a light sound like the buzzing of a fly.","Voice","رکز","19:98",1
106,19,"V","زَفِیْرٌ","«زَفَرَ» means to exhale a long breath, and «زَفِیْر» is the term for that sound when a donkey begins to bray; its initial sound, which gradually grows louder, is called zafir. (f.l. 34)","The initial sound of a donkey's crawling is called «زَفِیْر».","Voice","زفیر","11:106-21:100-25:12",3
107,19,"V","شَھِیْق","«شَھِیْق» is the term for the sound when a donkey ceases braying and its voice begins to lower from a high pitch. Zafir and Shahiq are opposites of each other.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ شَقُوۡا فَفِی النَّارِ لَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا زَفِیۡرٌ  وَّ شَہِیۡقٌ» (11:106)\n\nTranslation: So as for the wretched, they will be cast into Hell. There will be for them therein a [zafir] and a [shahiQ] (or sounds resembling these).\n\nThese sounds will either arise from the fire of Hell, which they will be forced to hear, or, due to the intensity of heat and thirst, such sounds will emerge from within them through their mouths.","«شَھِیْق» is the term for the extremely loud sound of a donkey's bray.","Voice","شھیق","11:106-67:7",2
108,19,"V","صَاخّۃ","«صَاخَّۃ» A harsh sound that deafens the ears—i.e., a sound that shatters the ears. An extremely loud noise and uproar.\nFor example:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الصَّآخَّۃُ» (80/33)\nTranslation: Then when it comes, that which will break the ears. (Uthmani)","«صَاخَّۃ» is used for a sharp, piercing, and loud voice.","Voice","صاخۃ","80:33",1
109,19,"V","صَدَّ","«یَصِدُّ صَدِیْدًا» the cry and shout, and the sound of screaming of a person when falling (F 192). However, this word appears in the Quran only in the meanings of screaming and shouting.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ» (43/57)\nTranslation: And when the case of the son of Maryam (Jesus) is mentioned, the people of your nation cry out loudly.","«صَدَّ» is used for screaming, shouting, or groaning.","Voice","صد","15:94-43:57",2
110,19,"V","صَرَخَ","«صَرَخَ» The sound of crying out in distress and panic. Cry for help (F L).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَہُمۡ یَصۡطَرِخُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا ۚ رَبَّنَاۤ اَخۡرِجۡنَا نَعۡمَلۡ صَالِحًا غَیۡرَ الَّذِیۡ کُنَّا نَعۡمَلُ» (35/37)\nTranslation: They will cry out in that Hellfire and say, Our Lord, take us out; then we will do righteous deeds, not what we used to do.","«صَرَخَ» is used for the sound of running in the context of an appeal.","Voice","صرخ","14:22-28:18-35:37",3
111,19,"V","صَلصَال","«صَلصَال» The sound of dry, baked clay pots striking each other. Originally this was «صَلَّال». A lam was changed to a sad. (mufradat) «اَلصَّلَالُ مِنَ الطِّیْن». Dry, ringing clay that sounds like iron (manjada) «صَلَّ الْمِسْمَارُ». Meaning: the sound produced by driving a nail or peg into something (mufradat).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26)\nTranslation: And We created man from an extract of dry, ringing clay.","«صَلْصَال» is used for the sound produced when earthen pots collide with each other.","Voice","صلصال","15:26-15:28-15:33-55:14",4
112,19,"V","صَوْت","«صَوْت» This Arabic term is used for all types of sounds, whether produced by speech or by the collision of objects. One definition of sawt is also given as: That which emerges from the mouth, if it does not consist of words and letters, is a sound. However, this definition is not reliable. (Al-Muhit)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَرۡفَعُوۡۤا اَصۡوَاتَکُمۡ  فَوۡقَ صَوۡتِ النَّبِیِّ» (49/2)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet.\n\nAnd it is evident that the speech of the Companions (may Allah be pleased with them) in the presence of the Prophet ﷺ was meaningful speech. Meaningless sounds did not occur.\n\nHowever, Ibn Faris has provided a comprehensive definition of sawt. He says «کُلُّ مَا وَتَرَفِیْ اُذُنِ سَامَعٍ». (L) Every thing that strikes the ear of the listener is a sound.\n\nIn the Quran, some sounds of living beings are mentioned and some of inanimate objects. We will mention them in the same order.\n\nSounds of living beings: «صَد ، صَرَخ ، ھَمَس ، حَسِیْس ، مُکَاء ( مَکُو ) تَصْدِیَۃ ، ضَبَح ، خُوَار ، زَفِیْر ، شَھِیْق ، لَھَث»","«صَوْت» is used for all kinds of sounds, whether light or loud, living or non-living, meaningful or meaningless.","Voice","صوت","17:64-31:19-49:2",3
113,19,"V","صَیْحَۃً","«صَیْحَۃً» means to shout or roar with a piercing, deafening voice. It refers to the sound of the trumpet-blast (ṣawr), a voice so intense that it causes hearts to tremble—a thunderous, explosive sound. In other words, whenever any voice becomes intense or forceful, every meaningless and loud sound is called «صَیْحَۃ» (Faqq al-Lughah, 26).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الصَّیۡحَۃُ  مُشۡرِقِیۡنَ . فَجَعَلۡنَا عَالِیَہَا سَافِلَہَا» (15:73,74)\n\nTranslation: So the cry seized them at sunrise, and We made the uppermost part of that city its lowermost, and We rained upon them stones of baked clay.","«صَیْحَۃً» is used for loud and meaningless voices.","Voice","صیحۃً","11:67-11:94-15:73-15:83-23:41-29:40-36:29-36:49-36:53-38:15-50:42-54:31-63:4",13
114,19,"V","ضَبَحَ","«ضَبَحَ» the sound of a horse's panting due to its fast running (verse 199)\nFor example: in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَالۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1)\nTranslation: By the chargers at dawn, panting.","The sound of panting while running is called «ضَبَحَ».","Voice","ضبح","100:1",1
115,19,"V","غَلْی","«غَلْی» the sound of a pot boiling and bubbling. the sound of bursting open. (fig.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ . کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44/45,46)\nTranslation: As if it were molten copper, it will burst open in their bellies like boiling water.","«غَلْی» is used for the sound of a handi boiling.","Voice","غلی","44:45-:44:46",3
116,19,"V","قارِعۃ","The meaning of «قَرَعَ» is to strike one thing upon another (muf), and «قَررَعَ الْبَابَ» means to knock a door (mansaj), i.e., when a sound is produced by striking one part against another, or by hand, or by something else. Regarding the Day of Judgment, Allah the Exalted has termed it «قَارِعَۃ», meaning that at that time sounds will be produced from things striking against each other. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَلۡقَارِعَۃُ مَا الۡقَارِعَۃُ» (101/1,2)\nTranslation: The one who knocks loudly. What is the one who knocks loudly?","«قَارِعَۃ» the sound of clattering","Voice","قارعۃ","13:31-69:4-101:1-101:2-101:3",5
117,19,"V","لَھَثَ","«لَھَثَ» The sound of a dog panting, which occurs due to heat or intense thirst, and it starts panting or barking with its tongue sticking out. (Mufradat, Manjad)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» ( 7/176 )\nTranslation: The example of that person is like a dog: if you burden him, he pants; and if you leave him, he still pants.\nIt is also used for sounds made by inanimate objects.","«لَھَثَ» refers to the sound of a dog panting or barking due to intense heat or thirst.","Voice","لھث","7:176",1
118,19,"V","مُکَآءً","«مُکَآءً» blowing a whistle (munjed) and encompassing all its musical melodies and rhythms.","«مُکَآءً» is used to produce a sound like a whistle from the mouth.","Voice","مکآءً","8:35",1
119,19,"V","ھَدّ","«ھَدّ» the sound of a building, wall, or pillar collapsing, etc., like a thunderous crash. (F L 194)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ تَخِرُّ الۡجِبَالُ ہَدًّا» (19/90)\nTranslation: It is imminent that from this [falsehood], the heavens will split apart, the earth will crack open, and the mountains will crumble and collapse.","«ھَدّ» is used for the sound of a building, wall, pillar, etc. falling.","Voice","ھد","19:90",1
120,19,"V","ھَمْس","«ھَمْس» is used for any sound produced by human movement, such as rustling or whispering (manjada). «اَلصَّوْتُ الْخَفِیِّ وَاَحَسّ» (m.l.) refers to any soft and perceptible sound from a human. For instance, the Quran states: «وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ فَلَا تَسۡمَعُ   اِلَّا ہَمۡسًا» (20/108) Translation: And all voices will be hushed before Allah, and you will not hear any sound except a faint whisper.","«ھَمْس» The slightest sound of any human movement is called.","Voice","ھمس","20:108",1
121,20,"S","اِسْتِدْراج","«دَرَجَۃ» refers to a staircase or ladder when one ascends upward. «ااِسْتِدْراج» means gradually and step by step bringing one thing closer to another (in a manner) so that it goes unnoticed. Thus, «ااِسْتِدْراج» implies that gradualness and step-by-step progression, along with gentleness, are essential in such matters.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَذَّبُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا سَنَسۡتَدۡرِجُہُمۡ مِّنۡ حَیۡثُ لَا  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (7:182)\nTranslation: And those who deny Our signs, We will gradually seize them with a seizure from where they perceive not. (Jalandhari). We will seize them gradually. (Usmani).","to gradually and gently approach something else","Slow","استدراج","7:182-68:44",2
122,20,"G","دَلّٰی ۔ دَلْوٌ","«دَلّٰی ۔ دَلْوٌ» means an empty bucket, «اَدْلیٰ» means lowering the empty bucket into a well to slowly reach water, and «دَلّٰی» means gradually completing a task and reaching the goal. (Detailed)\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَدَلّٰىہُمَا بِغُرُوۡرٍ» (7/22).\n\nTranslation: (The rejected Satan) deceived both (Adam and Eve) and drew them toward sin. (Jalandhari) / He enticed them through deception. (Osmani)","«دَلّٰی» is used gradually and gently to achieve one's purpose.","gradual","دلی ۔ دلو","7:22-:12:19",3
123,20,"S","رُخَاءً","«رُخَاءً» a wind so soft and gradual that it does not stir anything (manjada) — the gentle, slow movement of the wind.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَسَخَّرۡنَا لَہُ  الرِّیۡحَ تَجۡرِیۡ بِاَمۡرِہٖ رُخَآءً  حَیۡثُ  اَصَابَ» (38:36)\nTranslation: Then We subjected the wind to his command, so it blew gently and softly wherever he desired.","«رُخَاءً» The wind blows so softly and gently that it cannot stir anything.","slow","رخاءً","38:36",1
124,20,"S","رُوَیدا","«رُوَیْدا» has emerged from «اَلرَّوْد», and the original word for «اَرْوَدُ» is «مُصَغَّر», meaning 'to make small' or 'to diminish'. «اِمْشِ عَلَی الرَّوْد» means 'proceed gently'. And «سَارُوْا سَیْرًا رُوَیْدًا». It means to move with gentleness and gradually. And «اَرْوَدُ» also means one who practices gentleness and gradualness in their work. Furthermore, they say «اَلدَّھْرُ اَوْرَدُ ذُوْ غِیَرٍ», meaning time proceeds with its work slowly and imperceptibly. It does not let itself be noticed. They also say «رُوَیْدَ زَیْدًا». Grant Zaid respite (manjad), implying the meaning of «رُوَیْد» is to stretch a rope little by little, or to grant respite intermittently and gradually.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَمَہِّلِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  اَمۡہِلۡہُمۡ رُوَیۡدًا» (86/17)\nTranslation: So give the disbelievers a respite. Just a short while.","«رُوَیْدَا» gradually letting go of the rope so that they may reach their end.","Slow","رویدا","86:17",1
125,20,"G","عُرْفًا","«عُرْفًا» A gentle, slow-moving wind that brings tranquility and comfort. «العرْف» Meaning 'scent.' It is often used for fragrance. (Manjad) And such winds that generally move at a slow pace. The morning breeze. For instance, the Quran states: «وَ الۡمُرۡسَلٰتِ  عُرۡفًا» (77:1). Translation: By the gently blowing winds, comforting (to the hearts) (Ottoman).","«عُرْفًا» to glide with the gentleness of the wind, while also encompassing comfort and tranquility.","gradually","عرفًا","77:1",1
126,20,"S","یُسْر","«یُسْر» means ease and facility, and its opposite is «عُسْر», meaning tightness or constriction. The term «یُسْرًا» also denotes a state where a task is accomplished effortlessly and without any hitch or obstruction.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَالۡجٰرِیٰتِ  یُسۡرًا» (51/3)\nTranslation: Then (by the winds) that move gently (al-Jarari). Then the ships that sail with ease (Uthmani).\n\nThus, in this context, «یُسْر» does not refer to slowness of movement; rather, it means that despite moving at high speed, there is no jolt, shaking, swaying, or sound produced. Hence, it appears as if they are moving slowly and smoothly.","To accomplish a task effortlessly and without any resistance.","Slow","یسر","2:185-2:280-18:88-19:97-20:26-44:58-51:3-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-65:4-65:7-80:20-87:8-92:7-92:10-94:5-94:6",19
127,21,"T","غَلْی","The basic meanings of «غَلَا» are to exceed one's limit and to boil over, and from this «غَلَا الْقِدْر» means the boiling of a pot and «غَلَا السَّعْر» means the rising of prices. (For example)\n\nThe Quran states:\n«کَالۡمُہۡلِ  ۚ ۛ یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44:45-46)\nTranslation: Like molten copper, it will boil in their bellies as if boiling water were seething.","Due to heat, an obstructed substance boils over and rises above its original surface.","to boil","غلی","44:45-44:46",2
128,21,"T","فَارَ","The word «فَارَ» is also used for a pot boiling over, for water boiling from a spring, and for a fire blazing. However, this word will be used in a context where the boiling is rising rapidly and repeatedly, because the meaning of «اَلْفَوْر» is 'very quickly'. It is said «رَجَعَ مِنْ فَوْرَہٗ» that he returned very quickly, without delay. (Majid) The word 'fawara' (fountain) is also derived from this [root], wherein the water flows continuously.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ» (11/40)\nTranslation: Until Our command came and the oven began to boil over.","«فَارَ» Due to the intensity and haste in something, the continuity in its fervor remains established.","to boil","فار","11:40-23:27",2
129,21,"T","نَضَخَ","«نَضَخَ» A spring gushing forcefully from a water source (manjad), but in «نَضَخَ» the reason for gushing is the abundance and pressure of water, not heat, and «نَضَّاخ» is also called a torrential downpour. (manjad) And «عَیْنٌ نَضَّاخَۃٌ» is that spring which is gushing due to the abundance of water. (source) For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66) Translation: In both these gardens, two springs are flowing.","«نَضَخَ» the boiling of water due to its abundance and pressure.","to boil","نضخ","55:66",1
130,22,"S","اَزَّ","«اَزَّ» To incite someone toward evil in such a way that they remain unaware, and to uproot someone from their position.  \n«اَزِیْز» This term is also metaphorically used to describe the sound of a boiling pot, generally carrying a negative connotation.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اَنَّـاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ تَؤُزُّہُمۡ  اَزًّا» (19/83)  \nTranslation: Have you not seen that We have left the devils as companions to the disbelievers, so they continuously incite them?","«اَزَّ» to goad someone into evil in a manner that leaves them utterly unaware.","swelling","از","2:36-19:83",2
131,22,"R","اَمْت","«اَمْت» is the opposite of «عِوَجْ» (meaning lowliness), and «عِوَجْ» and «اَمْت» mean depressions and elevations, and «اَمْت» means a small hill. Ṭabah (a high place/mound) i.e., such a height and expanse wherein there is no order or arrangement.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَّا تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا وَّ لَاۤ اَمۡتًا» (20/107)\nTranslation: Wherein you will see no depression (lowliness) nor any elevation (hill).","«اَمْت» A small hill or mound that lacks any regularity in its height or extent.","Rising","امت","20:107",1
132,22,"E","جَرَمَ","«جَرَمَ» (it is a masdar) denotes sin and fault, and when this verb is employed, it signifies inciting someone toward a grave, life-threatening, or painful act. Lexicons do not affirm this meaning; however, translations such as those by Jalandhari, Osmani, and Tafheem-ul-Quran all corroborate the meaning we have presented.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَ لَا  یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوۡمٍ عَلٰۤی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا» (5/8). Translation: And let not the hatred of people prevent you from being just.\n\nNote: (Masdar: meaning 'to issue forth,' i.e., the place of emergence or beginning; source, origin, foundation, spring, root. Masdar: It is a noun from which other verbs can be derived, but it itself is not derived from any verb.)","«جَرَمَ» is used to encourage and incite sinful acts.","emergence","جرم","5:2-5:8-40:43",3
133,22,"E","حَدَب","«حَدَبَ الرَّجُل» means a person's tall stature, and «حَدَب» means tallness or loftiness. Metaphorically, it also refers to high, hard ground of that shape. A hill that is broader in expanse but lower in height, and this swelling or slope resembles tallness. «مُحَدَّب ضد مُجَوَّف» refers to such spectacles used for correcting weak distant and near vision, and «مُحَدَّب» the lens is also called thus because this glass bulges on both sides like a lentil seed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21/96). Translation: Until Ya'juj and Ma'juj are let loose, and they come rushing down from every elevation.","«حَدَب» is used for a tall man, and it also refers to a mound that is low in height but wide in spread.","Elevation","حدب","21:96",1
134,22,"A","حَرَضَ","The meaning of «حَرَضَ» is to become severely ill, emaciated, and near death (m. l, m q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85). Translation: (The sons of Jacob (peace be upon him) said to their father) They began to say, By Allah, if you continue to remember Joseph in this way, you will either become ill or lose your life.\n\nAnd «حَرَضَ» also means to encourage something whose non-doing leads to destruction and ruin. (m l) That is, to urge or create eagerness for an action such that if it is not performed, it becomes a cause of destruction and ruin.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ حَرِّضِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلَی الۡقِتَالِ ؕ اِنۡ یَّکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ عِشۡرُوۡنَ صٰبِرُوۡنَ یَغۡلِبُوۡا مِائَتَیۡنِ» (8/65). Translation: O Prophet (peace be upon him)! Encourage the Muslims to jihad. If there are twenty steadfast men among you, they will overcome two hundred disbelievers.","«حَرَضَ» means to be severely ill, emaciated, and near death.","Awakening","حرض","4:84-8:65-12:85",3
135,22,"E","حَضَّ ۔ حَثَّ","«حَضَّ ۔ حَثَّ» To urge someone to do something and accelerate the pace of work. To encourage good deeds. In essence, both «حَضَّ» and «حَثَّ» are used for urging. The word «حَضَّ ۔ حَثَّ» is used for driving or urging something (like an animal, etc.), while «حَضَّ» is used for all other matters.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُغۡشِی الَّیۡلَ النَّہَارَ یَطۡلُبُہٗ حَثِیۡثًا» (7:54)\nTranslation: He wraps the night over the day, and it pursues it rapidly.\n\nAnd «حَضَّ» is used for urging or encouraging other things.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَرَءَیۡتَ  الَّذِیۡ یُکَذِّبُ بِالدِّیۡنِ فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ وَ لَا یَحُضُّ عَلٰی طَعَامِ الۡمِسۡکِیۡنِ» (107:1-3)\nTranslation: Have you seen the one who denies the Recompense? That is the one who repulses the orphan and does not encourage feeding the poor.","«حَضَّ» is used to encourage other good deeds besides riding.\n«حَثَّ» is used to increase the speed of riding and similar activities.","Emergence","حض ۔ حث","7:54-18:56-69:34-107:3",4
136,22,"E","سَمْک","«سَمْک» means to elevate or make thick, and «سَمْک» is also used to mean a roof or the thickness of a roof. Moreover, the height and thickness of any elevated and thick thing (manjad) and «سَنَامٌ سَامِکٌ» meaning the high hump of a camel. (m q)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا  اَمِ  السَّمَآءُ ؕ بَنٰہَا رَفَعَ سَمۡکَہَا فَسَوّٰىہَا» (79/27,28)\nTranslation: Is your creation difficult or the creation of the sky? Allah created the sky. Then He raised its height, then He made it level. (Uthmaniؒ)","«سَمْک» thickening and elevating something, such as the height and thickness of a roof.","Emergence","سمک","79:28",1
137,22,"A","کَعَبْ","«کَعَبْ» meaning a swelling or protuberance. The term is also applied to anything that resembles a swelling on the foot. «کَعَبَتِ الْجَارِیَۃ» meaning a girl's breasts that have become prominent and enlarged. «کُعَب» meaning a woman's prominent breasts, and «کاعِب» refers to a woman whose breasts are elevated. Its plural is «کَوَاعِب», meaning young women (cf. singular).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ مَفَازًا حَدَآئِقَ وَ  اَعۡنَابًا وَّکَوَاعِبَ  اَتۡرَابًا» (78/31,32,33)\nTranslation: Indeed, for the righteous is attainment (i.e., Paradise), (wherein are) gardens and grapevines and full-breasted maidens of equal age.\n\nIf the spread (width) and elevation (height) are approximately equal, then it is «کَعَب» and «نَجَد»; the difference is only in quantity or measure. If the spread is greater and the elevation is less, then it is «حَدْب». If the spread is less and the elevation is greater, then it is «سَمک». And if there is no order or proportion between elevation and spread, then it is «اَمْت».","The term «کَعَبْ» refers to a protruding bone. In the Quran, this word is used for the ankle and for the houris with prominent breasts.","Awakening","کعب","78:33",1
138,22,"A","نَجْد","«نَجْد» denotes a hard, elevated tract of land devoid of trees, resembling a tall and large hill. It also signifies a small mountain and a valley, and is used for a path of ascending and descending. Furthermore, it is found to mean a woman's breasts (Manjad, etc.). The term «نَجْدَیْن» is metaphorically used for a woman's two breasts, as well as for the contrast between truth and falsehood, and beauty and ugliness (Muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ . فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» (90:10-11). Translation: And man has been shown both paths (of good and evil), yet he did not traverse the valley. In this context, some interpreters understand «نَجْدَیْن» to refer to both breasts, to which a child naturally clings and is nurtured (etc.).","«نَجْد» is used for land that is hard and elevated, with no trees or anything else growing on it.","Ascension","نجد","90:10",1
139,23,"T","اَحَلَّ","«اَحَلَّ» To cause someone to descend to a place. And this occurs as a result of an action of the one who descends. It occurs in both good and evil situations.\n\nFor example: For good, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوا الۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَذۡہَبَ عَنَّا الۡحَزَنَ ؕ اِنَّ  رَبَّنَا لَغَفُوۡرٌ  شَکُوۡرٌ ۔ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَحَلَّنَا  دَارَ الۡمُقَامَۃِ  مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (35/34,35)\nTranslation: They will say, All praise is for Allah who has removed from us all grief. Indeed, our Lord is Forgiving and Appreciative. Who, by His grace, has caused us to inhabit the eternal abode.\n\nAnd for evil, the Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ بَدَّلُوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ کُفۡرًا وَّاَحَلُّوۡا قَوۡمَہُمۡ دَارَالۡبَوَارِ» (14/28)\nTranslation: Have you not seen those who exchanged the favor of Allah for disbelief and led their people to the home of destruction?","The act of «اَحَلَّ» occurs as a result of some good or bad deed of the one receiving it.","to send down","احل","14:28-35:35",2
140,23,"T","اَنْزَلَ ، نَزَّل","«اَنْزَلَ ، نَزَّل» Some scholars are of the opinion that the word «اَنْزَلَ» is used to denote the complete descent of something in a single instance.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّاۤ  اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ  فِیۡ  لَیۡلَۃِ  الۡقَدۡرِ» (97:1)  \nTranslation: We have sent down the Quran on the Night of Decree.  \n\nAnd it is evident that the Quran was not revealed all at once in its entirety; rather, it was revealed in parts. The explanation for this is that the Quran was revealed in its complete form to the worldly heaven on the Night of Decree. Thereafter, according to the occasion and necessity, it was gradually revealed through revelation. The second explanation is the one which Fath Muhammad (may Allah have mercy on him) mentioned in his translation of this verse:  \nTranslation: We began to send down (the Quran) on the Night of Decree. And tanzil refers to sending something down gradually, in parts, or as needed.  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ نَزَّلَ الۡفُرۡقَانَ عَلٰی عَبۡدِہٖ» (25:1)  \nTranslation: Blessed is He who sent down the Quran upon His Servant.  \n\nThus, Imam Raghib also holds this view, stating: The spiritual difference between the two is that 'tanzil' implies sending something down gradually, in portions, and separately, while 'inzal' is a general term that can also be used for sending something down completely in one go. As though, according to the aforementioned Imam, 'tanzil' is used for gradual revelation, and 'inzal' is used for both gradual and instantaneous descent. However, the Quran does not support this distinction.  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ لَا نُزِّلَ عَلَیۡہِ الۡقُرۡاٰنُ جُمۡلَۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً» (25:33)  \nTranslation: And those who disbelieve say, 'Why was the Quran not revealed to him all at once?'  \n\nHere, the word «تنزیل» is used with the meaning of all at once.  \n\nAnd the reality is that both terms are so close in meaning that one can be used in place of the other without distinction. It is only due to the construction of the words and the clarification of the sentence that the Quran has employed one term or the other.","«اِنْزَال» and «تَنْزِیْل» are terms used for bringing something down. Inzal signifies a complete descent in a single instance, whereas Tanzil refers to the act of bringing down, whether it occurs all at once or gradually.","to send down","انزل ، نزل","2:4-2:22-2:23-2:41-2:57-2:59-2:90-2:91-2:97-2:99-2:102-2:105-2:136-2:159-2:164-2:170-2:174-2:176-2:185-2:213-2:231-2:285-3:3-3:4-3:7-3:53-3:65-3:72-3:84-3:93-3:124-3:151-3:154-3:199-4:47-4:60-4:61-4:105-4:113-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:162-4:166-4:174-5:44-5:45-5:47-5:48-5:49-5:59-5:64-5:66-5:67-5:68-5:81-5:83-5:101-5:104-5:112-5:114-5:115-6:7-6:8-6:37-6:81-6:91-6:92-6:93-6:99-6:111-6:114-6:155-6:156-6:157-7:2-7:3-7:26-7:33-7:57-7:71-7:157-7:160-7:196-8:11-8:41-9:26-9:40-9:64-9:86-9:97-9:124-9:127-10:20-10:24-10:59-10:94-11:12-11:14-12:2-12:40-13:1-13:7-13:17-13:19-13:27-13:36-13:37-14:1-14:32-15:6-15:8-15:9-15:21-15:22-15:90-16:2-16:10-16:24-16:30-16:44-16:64-16:65-16:89-16:101-16:102-17:82-17:93-17:95-17:102-17:105-17:106-18:1-18:45-19:64-20:2-20:53-20:80-20:113-21:10-21:50-22:5-22:16-22:63-22:71-23:18-23:24-23:29-24:1-24:34-24:43-24:46-25:1-25:6-25:7-25:21-25:25-25:32-25:48-26:4-26:198-27:60-28:24-28:87-29:34-29:46-29:47-29:50-29:51-29:63-30:24-30:35-30:49-31:10-31:21-31:34-33:26-34:6-35:27-36:15-36:28-38:8-38:29-39:2-39:6-39:21-39:23-39:41-39:55-40:13-41:14-41:39-42:15-42:17-42:27-42:28-43:11-43:31-44:3-45:5-46:30-47:2-47:9-47:20-47:26-48:4-48:18-48:26-50:9-53:23-56:69-57:9-57:25-58:5-59:21-64:8-65:5-65:10-67:9-76:23-78:14-97:1",222
141,23,"T","حَلَّ","The basic meaning of «حَلَّ» is to untie a knot, and its opposite is «عَقَدَ», meaning to tie a knot. «اَرْبابِ حَلّ وَ عَقْد» is a commonly understood term meaning owners of packing and unpacking. That is, this quality of packing and unpacking belongings is such that a traveler packs their belongings and sets out on a journey, and when they need to stop, they unpack their belongings. Therefore, the word «حَلَّ» also began to be used in the sense of settling or disembarking (for example), and just as a traveler, upon stopping at a place, unpacks their belongings, similarly the word «حَلَّ» also comes in the sense of the outcome or result of an action. It is said «مَنْ جَرَّبَ الْمُجَرَّبَ حَلَّتْ بِہٖ النَّدَامَۃ», meaning that when one who has been tested is tested again, shame descends upon them.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «مَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡہِ عَذَابٌ یُّخۡزِیۡہِ وَ یَحِلُّ عَلَیۡہِ عَذَابٌ مُّقِیۡمٌ» (39/40), which translates as: Upon whom will come that which will disgrace him, and upon whom will an everlasting punishment be inflicted?","«حَلَّ» is used for descending and staying at a place.","to send down","حل","11:39-14:28-20:27-20:81-20:86-35:35-39:40-90:2",8
142,23,"T","خَلَعَ","The basic meaning of «خَلَعَ» is to separate something that was previously included within it. (M.L.) The same meaning is also found in the word 'khula'—that a woman separates from her husband by returning the dowry, and divorce takes place.\n\nIn the Quran, this word has been used for the act of removing (taking off) shoes from the feet. For example: The Quran states:\n\n«اِنِّیۡۤ  اَنَا رَبُّکَ فَاخۡلَعۡ نَعۡلَیۡکَ ۚ اِنَّکَ بِالۡوَادِ الۡمُقَدَّسِ طُوًی» (20:12)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, I am your Lord, so remove your shoes. You are in the sacred valley of Tuwa.\n\nAnd regarding 'khula', there is this peculiar association: in ancient civilizations, women were metaphorically referred to as shoes for the feet.","«خَلَعَ» is used to separate something that was previously included in it.","to send down","خلع","20:12",1
143,23,"T","نَزَلَ","«نَزَلَ» Its well-known meaning is 'to descend'—that is, something coming down from a height (intransitive)—and this word is commonly used. Its antonym is also «صَعُوْد» and «عُرُوْج». For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ مَا یَنۡزِلُ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ وَمَا یَعۡرُجُ فِیۡہَا» (57:4) Translation: And whatever descends from the heavens and whatever ascends toward it. And «تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ» is also synonymous with «نَزَلَ بِہٖ». Both these words are used for the descent of angels and divine commands. For example, the Noble Quran states: «نَزَلَ بِہِ الرُّوۡحُ  الۡاَمِیۡنُ» (26:193) Translation: It was brought down by the trustworthy angel. At another instance, the sublime command of Allah states: « تَنَزَّلُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ وَ الرُّوۡحُ  فِیۡہَا بِاِذۡنِ رَبِّہِمۡ ۚ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  اَمۡرٍ» (97:4) Translation: During that night, the Spirit (Al-Amin) and the angels descend by their Lord's permission for every matter (of administration). But for satanic inspiration, only «تَنَزَّلَ بِہٖ» is used (intransitive). For example, the Noble Quran states: «ہَلۡ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ عَلٰی مَنۡ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلٰی کُلِّ اَفَّاکٍ اَثِیۡمٍ» (26:221-222) Translation: Shall I inform you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every lying sinner.","The word «نَزَلَ» is general. «تَنَزُّل» is used for divine revelation and commandments, as well as satanic inspirations and other such matters.","to reveal","نزل","17:105-26:193-26:210-26:221-26:222-34:2-37:177-41:30-57:4-57:16-65:12-97:4",12
144,23,"T","ھَبَطَ","«ھَبَطَ» To descend, fall, or emerge from something in a state of compulsion or constraint—such as a stone falling from a height (intransitive)—includes all meanings of coming out involuntarily, descending from one's rank or status, and moving from a higher to a lower place. Now consider some examples:\n\n(1) Regarding descending from a mount:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا وَ بَرَکٰتٍ عَلَیۡکَ» (11/48)\nTranslation: It was decreed: O Noah! Descend with peace and blessings from Us upon you.\n\n(2) Regarding descending from fear and anxiety:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ» (2/74)\nTranslation: And among them are those who, from the fear of Allah, fall prostrate.\n\n(3) Regarding emerging in a degraded or humbled state:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«فَاَزَلَّہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ عَنۡہَا فَاَخۡرَجَہُمَا مِمَّا کَانَا فِیۡہِ ۪ وَ قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ» (2/36)\nTranslation: Then Satan caused them both to slip from there and expelled them from the state in which they were. And We said: Descend, all of you, as enemies to one another.\n\nA poet has expressed this meaning in the following words:\nWe have heard of Adam's expulsion from Paradise,\nBut we emerged from your neighborhood utterly disgraced!","«ھَبَطَ» is used for descending, falling, or coming out from a place in a state of anger and helplessness.","to send down","ھبط","2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123",8
145,23,"T","وَضَعَ","The basic meanings of «وَضَعَ» are to place below (trans.). The word is also used in the sense of removing a burden and load, and in the context of pregnancy, it is the burden itself that is removed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94:2,3)\nTranslation: And We have removed from you a burden which weighed heavily on your back.\n\nThen this word began to be used generally for the act of removing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ» (24:58)\nTranslation: And when you lay aside your garments in the midday heat.","«وَضَعَ» is used to take something down and place it below.","to send down","وضع","3:36-18:49-39:69-46:15-55:7-55:10-94:2",7
146,24,"A","اِخْتَالَ","According to Ibn Faris, «خَیْل» means «یَدُلُّ عَلیٰ حَرَکَۃِ فِی تَلَوُّنٍ» (m. l.), i.e., that movement which changes its color every moment and every hour. «تَخَیُّلْ» means to imagine something, to be arrogant, and «اِخْتَال» means to walk with a swagger and to walk with arrogance. (Manjood) It is as if such a person's intellect is at a higher level than that of ordinary people, and this is the next level after «مَرَحَ».","«اِخْتَالَ» walking arrogantly and looking down on others.","Arrogance","اختال","4:36-31:18-57:23",3
147,24,"A","اَشَرَ : اَشِرٌ","«اَشَرَ» refers to a self-conceited person who boasts about his own greatness and speaks with exaggerated pride. Imam Raghb «اَلْاَشَر» explains its meaning as 'to rise exceedingly high,' indicating that it is even a higher degree than «مَرَحَ» and «اِخْتَال».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَیَعۡلَمُوۡنَ غَدًا مَّنِ الۡکَذَّابُ الۡاَشِرُ» (54/26)\nTranslation: They will come to know on that Day who the truly self-conceited liar is.","«اَشَرَ» is used for a self-conceited and flippant person.","Arrogance","اشر : اشر","54:25-54:26",2
148,24,"A","بَطَرَ","«بَطَرَ» being led astray due to the abundance of blessings, and according to Imam Raghib, «بَطَر» is a terror that befalls a person due to the misuse of prosperity, failing to uphold the rights of blessings, and the improper use of blessings. (m.f.) And according to Ibn Faris, the original meaning of «بَطَر» is to tear apart. That is, as if the abundance of blessings has torn someone's sight, and they do not care about anyone—thus, in the meaning of «بَطَر», there is also the abundance of blessings, ingratitude, and misuse present, and this is the next level after «فَرِحَ». For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ کَمۡ  اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍۭ  بَطِرَتۡ مَعِیۡشَتَہَا» (28/58) Translation: And We have destroyed many towns which were reveling in their prosperity.","To show ingratitude toward «بَطَرَ»'s blessings and to misuse them.","Arrogance","بطر","8:47-28:58",2
149,24,"A","تَکَبَّرَ","«تَکَبَّرَ» This is the highest degree of pride in which a person becomes a victim of arrogance—namely, pride, haughtiness, conceit, self-centeredness, and egotism—and considers himself superior to others and free from error. Moreover, his egotism reaches such an extent that he begins to deem others inferior and denies accepting the truth, as narrated in the hadith: «الْكِبَرُ بَطَرُ الْحَقِّ وَغَمْطُ النَّاس» (Al-Adab al-Mufrad by Bukhari). Translation: Pride is rejecting the truth and looking down upon people.\n\nFor instance, the Holy Quran states: «قَالَ فَاہۡبِطۡ مِنۡہَا فَمَا یَکُوۡنُ لَکَ اَنۡ تَتَکَبَّرَ فِیۡہَا» (7:13). Translation: Allah said to Satan, 'Get out of Paradise; you have no right to be arrogant here.'","«تَکَبَّرَ» The ultimate degree of arrogance: rejecting the truth and despising people.","Arrogance","تکبر","2:34-2:87-2:185-4:172-4:173-5:82-6:93-7:13-6:36-7:40-7:48-7:75-7:76-7:88-7:133-7:146-7:206-10:75-14:21-16:22-16:23-16:29-16:49-21:19-22:37-23:46-23:67-25:21-28:39-29:39-31:7-32:15-34:31-34:32-34:33-37:35-38:74-38:75-39:59-39:60-39:72-40:27-40:35-40:47-40:48-40:60-40:76-41:15-41:38-45:8-45:31-46:10-46:20-59:23-63:5-71:7-74:23",57
150,24,"A","تَمَطّٰی","«مُطَوَّ» meaning to walk with arms spread out in arrogance, pride, and haughtiness, showing indifference. To walk briskly with arrogance, arms outstretched (F L 178).\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَلَا صَدَّقَ وَلَا صَلّٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ کَذَّبَ وَتَوَلّٰی ثُمَّ ذَہَبَ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖ یَتَمَطّٰی» (75/31,32,33)\nTranslation: So he (the one heedless of the Hereafter) neither believed in the Word of Allah nor prayed, but denied and turned away. Then he went to his household in arrogance and pride.","«تَمَطّٰی» walking with a haughty strut, arms outstretched.","Arrogance","تمطی","75:33",1
151,24,"A","فَخَرَ","'Sheyki bagharna' means to boast about oneself and to mention a quality that one does not actually possess. For example, to look down upon others based on one's lineage or to boast about inherited wealth and property (abbr.). For instance, the Noble Quran states: «وَلَا تُصَعِّرۡخَدَّکَ لِلنَّاسِ وَلَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ کُلَّ مُخۡتَالٍ فَخُوۡرٍ» (21/18). Translation: And (out of arrogance) do not turn your cheek away from people nor walk in arrogance in the land, for Allah does not like any arrogant boaster. In this verse, Allah Almighty has mentioned the three blameworthy (i.e., evil) traits, namely «مَرَحَ ، اِخْتَال» and «فَخَرَ», in sequence.","«فَخَرَ» To involve oneself in matters that do not even exist.","Arrogance","فخر","4:36-11:10-31:18-57:23",4
152,24,"A","فَرِحَ","The term «فَرِحَ» is used in two ways: «فَرِحَ الْقَلْب اور فَرِحَ النَّفْس».\n«فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» means being sincerely grateful for a blessing, and this is a good characteristic.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ بِفَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ بِرَحۡمَتِہٖ فَبِذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَفۡرَحُوۡا ؕ ہُوَخَیۡرٌمِّمَّا یَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» (10:58)\nTranslation: Say, [the Book] has been revealed by the grace and mercy of Allah. So let people rejoice in it, and this is far better than what they amass.\nAnd «فَرِحَ النَّفْس» is a bad trait. That is, instead of being grateful for Allah's blessings, one starts to boast, becomes arrogant, and takes pride.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِذۡ  قَالَ لَہٗ قَوۡمُہٗ لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ» (28:76)\nTranslation: When his (Qarun's) people said to him, Do not boast. Indeed, Allah does not like those who boast.","«فَرِحَ» is used to express joy. It is also used both to express gratitude for Allah’s bounties and to boast over them in ingratitude.","Arrogance","فرح","3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23",21
153,24,"A","فَرِہَ","«فَرِہَ» means to be happy, to strut; and «فَرِہَ» also means to be skilled, experienced, light; and «فَارِہٌ» means agile and skillful, whose mastery is evident (manjada). Thus, «فَرِہَ» comes to express joy, pride, and boasting over one's own skill and art.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ بُیُوۡتًا فٰرِہِیۡنَ» (26/149)\nTranslation: And you carve out of the mountains, with [great] skill, houses to dwell in. (Jalandhari) Or you build ostentatious buildings. (Moududi)","«فَرِہَ» is used to attain mastery in one's art.","Arrogance","فرہ","26:149",1
154,24,"A","مَرَحَ","The meaning of «مَرَحَ» is to begin to frolic with joy, and «شِدّۃُ الْفَرْحِ» (ف ل 170) means to walk with swagger and pride.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَمۡشِ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَحًا ۚ اِنَّکَ  لَنۡ تَخۡرِقَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَنۡ تَبۡلُغَ الۡجِبَالَ طُوۡلًا» (17/37)\nTranslation: And do not walk upon the earth with arrogance and conceit; you will neither tear the earth apart nor reach the mountain-tops in height.","«مَرَحَ» to dance with joy and to strut with pride and grace.","arrogance (in the Islamic context, the sin of pride and haughtiness before Allah)","مرح","17:37-31:18-40:75",3
155,25,"I","اِخْتَلَقَ","«خَلَقَ» It means creating something from pre-existing material, whereas 'ikhtilaq' refers to a statement containing an element of truth into which falsehood is blended to render it smooth, polished, and pliable (m.l.)—a fabricated and self-contrived assertion. «اِخْتِرَاع» This term specifically denotes falsehood presented in a manner that makes it appear true. (Faq l 112)\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«مَا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِی الۡمِلَّۃِ  الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  ۚ ۖ اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ اِلَّا اخۡتِلَاقٌ» (38/7)\nTranslation: (The disbelievers said) We have never heard this in the previous religion. This is entirely a fabricated statement.","«اِخْتَلَقَ» A statement that contains a grain of truth, with the rest being pure fiction—a falsehood that appears true.","I am a created being.","اختلق","38:7",1
156,25,"I","اِفْتَرَاء","Its original word is «فَرِیَ». The meaning of «فَرِیَ» is to speak falsehood and to cause corruption (m. a).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَاَتَتۡ بِہٖ قَوۡمَہَا تَحۡمِلُہٗ ؕ قَالُوۡا یٰمَرۡیَمُ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتِ شَیۡئًا فَرِیًّا» (19/27)\n\nTranslation: Then she (Maryam, peace be upon her) brought him to her people while carrying him. They said, 'O Maryam! You have indeed brought a strange thing.' (Uthmani)\n\nFrom this verse, it is meant that Maryam has indeed incurred wrath and caused corruption.\n\nAnd «اِفْترٰی» refers to such a falsehood or accusation that is deliberately fabricated to cause corruption and disorder, i.e., slander (m.f).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَاِنۡ کَادُوۡا لَیَفۡتِنُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الَّذِیۡۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ لِتَفۡتَرِیَ عَلَیۡنَا غَیۡرَہٗ» (17/73)\n\nTranslation: And O Prophet! The revelation which We have sent to you, it was almost that these disbelievers would turn you away from it, so that you would fabricate something else in Our name.","«اِفْتَرَاء» Lying with the intent to cause corruption and disorder.","I am created.","افتراء","3:24-3:94-4:48-4:50-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:112-6:137-6:138-6:140-6:144-7:37-7:53-7:89-7:152-10:17-10:30-10:37-10:38-10:59-10:60-10:69-11:13-11:18-11:21-11:35-11:50-12:111-16:56-16:87-16:101-16:105-16:116-17:73-18:15-20:61-21:5-23:38-25:4-28:36-28:75-29:13-29:68-32:3-34:8-34:43-42:24-46:8-46:28-60:12-61:7",53
157,25,"I","تَقَوَّل","The term qawl (statement) refers to every utterance that comes from the mouth. And sometimes the term qawl is also applied to something that is still only in the heart.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ» (58:8)\nTranslation: And they say in their hearts, Why is not Allah punishing us for what we say?\n\nAnd the meaning of qawl can also denote uttering a falsehood and then attributing it to someone else (Manjada).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ تَقَوَّلَ عَلَیۡنَا بَعۡضَ الۡاَقَاوِیۡلِ . لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ الۡوَتِیۡنَ» (69:44-46)\nTranslation: And if he [i.e., the Prophet] had fabricated against Us some sayings, We would have seized him by the right hand; Then We would have cut from him the aorta.","«تَقَوَّل» to fabricate a lie oneself and then pin it on someone else.","I was deluded.","تقول","2:80-2:104-2:140-2:154-2:169-6:93-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:172-7:173-10:68-10:77-16:116-17:40-20:94-24:15-39:56-39:57-39:58-52:33-61:2-61:3-69:44-72:5",26
158,25,"I","خَرَصَ","«خَرَصَ» Relying solely on conjecture and speculation, and making estimates. «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃَ» refers to making an estimate based purely on conjecture—that this date palm will bear fruit. And «خَرَّاص» describes a person who often bases his actions on mere estimation and conjecture. (Majid) Such a person is generally untruthful and untrustworthy.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«قُتِلَ الۡخَرّٰصُوۡنَ» (51:10,11,12)  \nTranslation: Woe to those who guess blindly, lost in their ignorance. They ask, 'When will the Day of Recompense be?'","To rely solely on assumptions and guesses that have no basis in reality.","I fabricate.","خرص","6:116-6:148-10:66-43:20",4
159,26,"B","اَثَارَ","«ثَوْر ، ثَار» means 'to raise or lift something' (singular word), and the term «اَثَارَ» is used for lifting. When this word is used in reference to the earth, it signifies causing it to shake, i.e., lifting it upward. Generally, this term is employed for lifting winds and rivers.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ  سَحَابًا فَیَبۡسُطُہٗ فِی السَّمَآءِ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ وَ یَجۡعَلُہٗ کِسَفًا» (30/48)\nTranslation: Allah is the One who drives the winds, and they raise the clouds; then Allah spreads them in the sky as He wills and makes them layered.","«اَثَار» the raising of clouds by the winds","Burden","اثار","30:48-35:9",2
160,26,"B","اَقَلَّ","It is basically used in two meanings: (1) to be low or less, and (2) to be high or elevated. And «اَقَلَّ» means to lift and elevate something (as explained in Munjid). Furthermore, «اَقَلَّ ، اَثَارَ» is stronger and better. That is, to consider the heavy, rain-laden clouds as trivial and insignificant and then lift them (with ease). Thus, the following verse also clarifies this:\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ بُشۡرًۢا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡ رَحۡمَتِہٖ ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ اَقَلَّتۡ سَحَابًا ثِقَالًا سُقۡنٰہُ لِبَلَدٍ مَّیِّتٍ» (7:57)\n\nTranslation: And He it is who sends the winds as glad tidings ahead of His mercy (i.e., rain). Until, when they have lifted the heavy clouds, We drive them to a dead land.","«اَقَلَّ» the winds lift the burden of the clouds, regarding it as trivial and light.","Burden","اقل","7:57-9:38",2
161,26,"B","اِلْتَقَطَ","The meaning of «لَقَطَ» is to pick up something from the ground, and «اِلْتَقَطَ» refers to that item which has fallen on the earth and whose owner is unknown (source). From this, the term «اِلْتَقَطَ» is derived, meaning to pick up from the ground such a fallen item whose owner's identity is not known.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡا یُوۡسُفَ وَاَلۡقُوۡہُ فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ الۡجُبِّ یَلۡتَقِطۡہُ بَعۡضُ السَّیَّارَۃِ» (12/10)\nTranslation: (One of Yusuf's brothers) said, Do not kill Yusuf, but throw him into the bottom of a well. Some traveler will pick him up.","«اِلْتَقَطَ» is used to lift a fallen object.","Burden","التقط","12:10-28:8",2
162,26,"B","اَنْشَرَ","The basic meaning of «نَشَرَ» is to spread out, and its opposite is «طَوَی», meaning to fold or roll up. «نَشَرْتُ الْکِتَابَ» means I opened or spread out the book, and «طَوَیْتُہ» means I folded or closed the book (for example). For instance, in the Quran it is: «وَاِذَا الصُّحُفُ نُشِرَتۡ» (81:10) Translation: And when the records of deeds are spread out. And «نَشِرَ الْمَیِّتُ نشُوْرًا» means the resurrection of the dead (intransitive), and «وَاِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر» means to emerge from the graves only towards Allah. In it, the meanings of being alive, rising, and spreading are all found. From this, «اَنْشَرَ» is a transitive verb. For example, in the Quran it is: «ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ» (80:21-22) Translation: Then Allah gave death to man, then He buried him in the grave, then whenever He wills, He will raise him up. Note: (Transitive verb: This is the verb that requires an object in addition to the subject to complete its meaning.)","The term «اَنْشَرَ» is used to denote the raising of the dead from their graves and their dispersal on the Day of Judgment.","Burden","انشر","18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1",10
163,26,"B","اَنْشَزَ","The basic meanings of «نَشَزَ» are height, elevation, and prominence. Particularly when this elevation in something causes movement, excitement, fervor, speed, and intensity. (غ ق)\n\nThe meaning of «نَشْزَ الرَّجُل» is a sitting person standing up (منجد). From this, «اَنْشَزَ» is a transitive verb.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ انۡظُرۡاِلٰی حِمَارِکَ وَ لِنَجۡعَلَکَ اٰیَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ انۡظُرۡاِلَی الۡعِظَامِ کَیۡفَ نُنۡشِزُہَا ثُمَّ نَکۡسُوۡہَا لَحۡمًا» (2/259)\nTranslation: And look at your [companion] donkey, and We have willed to make you a model for the people, and look at the bones as well—how We raise them and bring them together. Then We clothe them with flesh. (Uthmaniؒ)\n\nHere, the usage of «اَنْشَزَ» signifies that movement and excitement were created in those bones. They began to join together and stood up, forming the structure of the donkey.\n\nNote: (Transitive verb: A verb that requires an object in addition to the subject to complete its meaning.)","«اَنْشَزَ» is used to generate motion to lift something.","Burden","انشز","2:259-58:11",2
164,26,"B","بَعَثَ","«بَعَثَ» Basically, it has two meanings: (1) to raise/revive, and (2) to send forth alone (sometimes). This word is sometimes used for both meanings simultaneously, and sometimes separately for only one meaning. It is said «بَعَثْتُ الْبَعِیْر», which means to raise a camel and set it free. Here, we are concerned with its first meaning. If this word is used in relation to the dead, both meanings are found in it. That is, to raise the dead to life and to march them toward the field of resurrection.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّاَنَّ السَّاعَۃَ اٰتِیَۃٌ لَّارَیۡبَ فِیۡہَا ۙ وَاَنَّ اللّٰہَ یَبۡعَثُ مَنۡ فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (22/7)\nTranslation: And the Hour is surely coming—there is no doubt about it—and Allah Almighty will surely raise to life those who are in the graves.\n\nThen this word was also used for raising from sleep (i.e., only in the first meaning). Because sleep itself is a light form of death.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَکَذٰلِکَ بَعَثۡنٰہُمۡ لِیَتَسَآءَلُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمۡ» (18/19)\nTranslation: And thus We raised them from sleep so that they might inquire of one another.","«بَعَثَ» is used for resurrecting the dead on the Day of Judgment.","Burden","بعث","2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7",27
165,26,"B","حَمَلَ","The term «حَمَلَ» is used for bearing a burden and is commonly employed in both material (i.e., carrying something like luggage, etc.) and spiritual (e.g., bearing the burden of sin) senses.\n\n(1) For material burden-bearing, whether external or internal, such as a woman carrying the weight of a child in her womb, or a tree carrying the weight of its fruit, or a cloud carrying the weight of its water. In short, this word is used in all contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7/189)\nTranslation: When a man approaches his wife, she becomes lightly pregnant and then she moves about with it.\n\n(2) For spiritual burden-bearing: For example, the divine declaration is:\n«وَعَنَتِ الۡوُجُوۡہُ لِلۡحَیِّ الۡقَیُّوۡمِ ؕ وَ قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ حَمَلَ ظُلۡمًا» (20/111)\nTranslation: And the living, established One will be faced by all, and he who bears the burden of injustice will be a failure.\n\nAnd «حَمَلَ عَلیٰ» means to place a burden upon someone, and «حَمَّلَ» comes in the sense of causing someone to bear a burden.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَلَا تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا» (2/286)\nTranslation: And do not place a burden upon us.","«حَمَلَ» is used to bear burdens, whether material or spiritual. This is common.","Burden","حمل","2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:176-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17",44
166,26,"B","لَقَحَ","«لَقَحَ» This word is specifically used for carrying an internal (i.e., unseen) burden. «لَقَحَۃُ النَّاقَۃ» means she-camel became pregnant (feminine). Then this word is also related to those winds which carry pollen from male trees and deposit it in female trees, or those winds that bear the burden of rain.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَاَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22)  \nTranslation: And We send the winds that carry the burden of water. Then We cause the rain to fall from the sky.","The term «لَقَحَ» is specifically used for the bearing of an inner burden (that is, one that does not manifest visibly).","Burden","لقح","15:22",1
167,26,"B","نَاءَ","The meaning of یَنَوء is to work hard and carry a burden with toil (م ۔ ن), and due to heaviness, to carry with difficulty (م ۔ ا).  \nFor example, the Holy Quran states:  \n«وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡکُنُوۡزِ مَاۤ اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ» (28:76)  \nTranslation: And We had granted him such abundant treasures that his keys were too heavy for even a group of strong men to carry.","«نَاءَ» a greater burden that can be borne with toil. To bear a burden with toil.","Burden","ناء","28:76",1
168,26,"B","وَزَرَ","When a person spreads out their cloth, places their burden on it, lifts it, and walks away, this is the correct meaning of «وَزَرَ». Therefore, «ذَنْب», i.e., sin, is called «وِزْر», meaning that person takes on the burden of the sins they have committed. (م ل) Thus, the usage of «وَزَرَ» generally comes to mean carrying the burden of sins.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6/31)\nTranslation: And they will be carrying their burdens (of sins) on their backs. See how evil is the burden they will carry!","Generally, «وَزَرَ» is used to denote bearing the burden of sin.","Burden","وزر","6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2",10
169,27,"T","اِنْبَعَثَ","The meaning of «بَعَثَ» is to rise for work. Due to its occurrence in «باب اِنْفِعَال», its meaning is that a person rises independently and sets out alone to accomplish an important objective.\n\nFor instance: The Quran states:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ ثَمُوۡدُ بِطَغۡوٰىہَاۤ اِذِ انۡۢبَعَثَ اَشۡقٰہَا» (91:11,12)\nTranslation: The people of Thamud denied [the truth] because of their rebellious arrogance. When a wretch arose from among them.","«اِنْبَعَثَ» to set off alone for some purpose.","To rise","انبعث","91:12",1
170,27,"T","قَامَ","«قَامَ» The act of a person rising from a sitting or lying position, or stopping while walking, applies to everyone. Generally, the term 'standing' is used.\n\nNow, consider the examples:\n\n(1) For example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَذۡکُرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ قِیٰمًا وَّقُعُوۡدًا» (3/191)\nTranslation: Those who remember God while standing and sitting.\n\n(2) For example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمُدَّثِّرُ قُمۡ فَاَنۡذِرۡ» (74/1,2)\nTranslation: O (Muhammad ﷺ), you who are wrapped in a garment, arise and warn.\n\n(3) For example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اَضَآءَ لَہُمۡ مَّشَوۡا فِیۡہِ٭ۙ وَاِذَاۤ اَظۡلَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ قَامُوۡا» (2/20)\nTranslation: When lightning flashes and illuminates them, they move within it, and when darkness falls, they stand still.","«قَامَ» to remain standing in any situation. This is common.","to be resurrected","قام","2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2",19
171,27,"T","نَشَرَ","«نَشَرَ» is used in two meanings: (1) for the dead to rise from their graves and spread forth «کَمَا مَرَّ»; (2) to rise and emerge.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَّلَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ مَوۡتًا وَّلَا حَیٰوۃً وَّلَا نُشُوۡرًا» (25:3)  \nTranslation: Neither is death within their power, nor life, nor (after death) rising again.  \nAt another place, the sublime command of Allah states:  \n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ لِبَاسًا وَّالنَّوۡمَ سُبَاتًا وَّ جَعَلَ النَّہَارَنُشُوۡرًا» (25:47)  \nTranslation: And He it is who made the night a covering for you, and sleep a rest, and appointed the day for rising again.","«نَشَرَ» is used in the sense of rising and spreading.","to rise","نشر","25:3-25:40-25:47-35:19-67:15",5
172,27,"T","نَشَزَ","«نَشَزَ» to rise due to some movement or impetus. «کَمَا مَرَّ»\nFor example: It is in the Holy Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ ۚ وَ  اِذَا قِیۡلَ انۡشُزُوۡا فَانۡشُزُوۡا» (58/11) Translation: O believers! When you are told to make room in the assemblies, then make room; Allah will grant you spaciousness. And when you are told to rise up, then rise up.","«نَشَزَ» is used to denote rising up on the basis of a movement (or initiative).","to rise","نشز","2:259-58:11",2
173,28,"P","اِستأذَنَ","«اَذِنَ» meaning permission or approval. «اِسْتأذَنَ» meaning to obtain permission or to seek permission for a task. «اِسْتَأذَنَ عَلَیْہِ» meaning to request permission to enter. (Munjad)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا یَسۡتَاۡذِنُکَ الَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَالۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِاَنۡ یُّجَاہِدُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِہِمۡ وَاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (9/44)\nTranslation: Those who believe in Allah and the Last Day would not ask your permission to remain behind. Rather, they desire to strive with their wealth and lives.","«اِستأذَنَ» to seek permission or approval for a task.","Permission","استاذن","9:44-9:45-9:83-9:86-9:93-24:58-24:59-24:62-33:13",9
174,28,"P","اِسْتَانَسَ","«اٰنَسَ» means to see something and know it. «اٰنس الصوت» means to hear a sound. «اٰنس النار» means to see fire. From this, «اِسْتَانَسَ» is derived. It means to make known, to create inclination; through one's word or action, to acquaint another person with oneself. For example, if a person stands at the door and calls the homeowner or knocks, then through that sound or act of knocking, the homeowner comes to know that so-and-so is at the door. Thus, the meaning of «اِسْتَاْنَسَ» is complete. For example: In the Quran it says: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَدۡخُلُوۡا بُیُوۡتًا غَیۡرَ  بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  حَتّٰی تَسۡتَاۡنِسُوۡا وَ تُسَلِّمُوۡا عَلٰۤی اَہۡلِہَا» (24/27) Translation: O you who believe! Do not enter houses other than your own without first seeking permission from the inhabitants and greeting them.","«اِسْتَانَسَ» To introduce others through one's own words or actions.  \nAnd permission is granted only through «اَذِنَ».  \nFor example: The divine command of Allah the Most High is:  \n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ» (9/43)  \nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ) May Allah forgive you. Why did you grant permission (to the hypocrites not to go to Jihad)?","Permission","استانس","24:27",1
175,29,"E","اَعْرَاب","«اَعْرَاب» The uncivilized, uneducated, rustic, wild, forest-dwelling, uncultured—those who possess neither proper speech nor a refined manner or etiquette for living life.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّنِفَاقًا وَّاَجۡدَرُاَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡاحُدُوۡدَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ» ( 9/97 )\nTranslation: The uncivilized are exceedingly severe in disbelief and hypocrisy. And they are precisely those who are incapable of comprehending the commandments which Allah has revealed to His Messenger.","«اَعْرَاب» Ill-mannered people who have no sense of conversational etiquette whatsoever.","Existence","اعراب","9:90-9:97-9:98-9:99-9:101-9:120-33:20-48:11-48:16-49:14",10
176,29,"E","عُتُلّ","«عَتَلَ» meaning to seize someone forcefully by the hair of their head and drag them (singular form). «عَتَلَہٗٓ اِلَی السِّجْن» meaning to drag him and throw into prison (famous saying).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47) Translation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.  \nAnd «عُتُلّ» meaning a harsh and ill-natured person (famous saying), harsh/stubborn (singular form).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «عُتُلٍّۭ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  زَنِیۡمٍ» (68/13) Translation: Harsh and additionally ill-natured.","«عُتُلّ» is used for stern and unyielding individuals.","Existence","عتل","44:47-68:13",2
177,29,"M","فَظّ","«فَظّ» means being harsh-tempered and bad-natured. «فَظُّ» refers to a rough, bad-tempered, and harsh-speaking person, one who is bitter-tongued. Its opposite is «لَیْن», which denotes softness in speech and temperament. For instance, the Quran states: «فَبِمَا رَحۡمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ لِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ ۚ وَلَوۡ کُنۡتَ فَظًّا غَلِیۡظَ الۡقَلۡبِ لَانۡفَضُّوۡا مِنۡ حَوۡلِکَ» (3/159). Translation: O Prophet ﷺ! This is a great mercy from Allah that you have been exceedingly gentle with these people; otherwise, had you been harsh-hearted, they would have all distanced themselves from you.","«فَظّ» ill-tempered and foul-mouthed.","Major ritual impurity","فظ","3:159",1
179,30,"S","بَغْتَۃً","«بَغْتَۃً» means the sudden appearance of something in such a way that its occurrence was not even imagined (lit.). The difference between «بَغْتَۃً» and «اِذْ» or «اِذَا» is that in «اِذَا», the later event has some connection or relation to the earlier event, whereas in «بَغْتَۃً», only a sudden or unexpected event is mentioned.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ  بَغۡتَۃً وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (7/95)\nTranslation: Then We seized them suddenly, and they had not even conceived of it.\n\nAt another place, the Almighty says:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا» (6/31)\nTranslation: Until when the Hour comes upon them suddenly, they will say, Alas for us for the negligence we showed regarding it (the Resurrection).","The sudden emergence of something like «بَغْتَۃً», whose appearance was not even anticipated.","Suddenly","بغتۃً","6:31-6:44-6:47-7:95-7:187-12:107-21:40-22:55-26:202-29:53-39:55-43:66-47:18",13
180,31,"G","نِعْمَ","«نِعْمَ» is a term of praise (i.e., an appreciative word) used for all kinds of commendation and admiration (muf), and its meanings are: Excellent! How wonderful! It is uttered when one is pleased with something good. According to Ibn Faris, its original sense is inclination and leaning (m-l), meaning when one's nature is inclined and drawn towards something upon seeing it, one says «نِعْمَ». Its opposite is «بِئْسَ», which is the word Zamm (i.e., evil and criticism) and is used for condemnation.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (16/30)\nTranslation: And excellent is the abode of the righteous.","«نِعْمَ» is a phrase of admiration (i.e., a praise phrase) that is recited as a form of praise for something good.","Good","نعم","2:271-3:136-3:173-4:58-8:40-13:24-16:30-18:31-22:78-29:58-37:75-38:30-38:44-39:74-51:48-77:23",16
181,31,"G","خَیْر","«خَیْر» is everything that is desirable. For example, justice, intellect, and wealth and riches are also called good (m. a). Its opposite is «شَر».\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِلَشَدِیۡدٌ» (100/8)\nTranslation: And indeed, man is ever greedy for wealth and riches.\n\nThat is, khair (good) refers to every good matter or righteous deed, and its plural is khairat (good deeds).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ» (3/114)\nTranslation: They believe in Allah and the Last Day, and they enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong, and they hasten to good deeds.\n\nThe word khair is not used only for a good matter or deed, but also for good people or things, and also for faith. In this context, its plural becomes akhyar (the best/goodest people).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ عِنۡدَنَا لَمِنَ الۡمُصۡطَفَیۡنَ الۡاَخۡیَارِ» (38/47)\nTranslation: They were indeed, in Our sight, among the chosen and the righteous.\n\nThus, the word khair is used for any good matter, deed, or person, and «نِعْمَ» is said upon seeing any good thing, expressing pleasure.\n\nThe following verse clarifies this point:\n«وَ لَدَارُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ ؕ وَ لَنِعۡمَ  دَارُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» (16/30)\nTranslation: And the home of the Hereafter is best for the righteous. How excellent is the home of the pious!","«خَیْر» is used for every good thing, deed, or good person.","Good","خیر","2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8",170
182,31,"G","حَسُنَ","«حَسُنَ» means pleasing and preferred (thing), and its opposite is «سَاءَ». Then this word is also used for apparent beauty and the glow of the face.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِنَّ خَیۡرٰتٌ حِسَانٌ» (55:70)\nTranslation: In them are good and beautiful women.\nIn this context, its opposite is «قَبُحَ». Besides this, this word is also used spiritually to denote excellence of character.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَحَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» (4:69)\nTranslation: And what excellent companionship that is!","«حَسُنَ» is used for pleasing and preferred matters, for both external and spiritual beauty and goodness.","Good","حسن","2:83-2:138-2:245-3:14-3:37-3:148-3:195-4:59-4:69-4:95-5:12-6:152-6:160-7:137-7:180-8:17-9:107-10:26-11:3-11:88-13:18-13:29-16:62-16:67-16:75-17:110-18:2-18:31-18:86-18:88-20:8-20:86-21:101-22:58-25:76-27:11-28:61-29:8-33:52-35:8-38:25-38:40-38:49-41:50-42:23-48:16-53:31-55:70-55:76-57:10-57:11-57:18-59:24-64:17-73:20-92:6-92:9",57
183,31,"G","اَمْثَل ، مُثْلیٰ","«مَثَلَ» means vivid, clear (m.) and «اَمْثَل» means exemplary, peerless, ideal. Best (m./f.).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ اَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً» (20/104)  \nTranslation: Then the best of the way (i.e., the wise and prudent) will say (Jalandhari).  \nAnd «مُثْلیٰ ، اَمْثَلُ» is feminine.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ یَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ  الۡمُثۡلٰی» (20/63)  \nTranslation: And put an end to your exemplary way of life.","«اَمْثَل ، مُثْلیٰ», meaning exemplary, best, ideal, and worthy of imitation.","Good","امثل ، مثلی","20:63-20:104",2
184,31,"G","جَمِیْلٌ","Its original word is jamal, which means external beauty, dignity and glory, splendor and majesty, and beauty (Faq 217).  \nFor example, in the Quran it says:  \n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ» (16/6)  \nTranslation: And there is grandeur for you in it.  \n\nAnd the meaning of «اَجْمَلَ فِی الْعَمَل» is to accomplish something in the best manner (M. Q), and the word jamil comes to mean choosing the better path. As Ya'qub (peace be upon him) said to his sons:  \n«بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ  جَمِیۡلٌ» (12/18)  \nTranslation: You have fabricated this from your own hearts. So patience is now the best course.  \n\nAnd in the Quran, when the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) said to his wives:  \n«اِنۡ  کُنۡـتُنَّ تُرِدۡنَ  الۡحَیٰوۃَ  الدُّنۡیَا وَ زِیۡنَتَہَا فَتَعَالَیۡنَ اُمَتِّعۡکُنَّ وَ اُسَرِّحۡکُنَّ سَرَاحًا جَمِیۡلًا» (33/28)  \nTranslation: If you desire the life of this world and its adornment, then come, I will provide for you and release you in a good manner.  \n\nLater, this word began to be used in the context of facial beauty as well. However, there is no example of this in the Quran.","«جَمِیْلٌ» is used for the good deeds and good character of any human being. In common usage, this word is also used for external beauty.","Good","جمیل","12:18-12:83-15:85-16:6-33:28-33:49-70:5-73:10",8
185,32,"S","نَکِرَ","«نَکِرَ» means to be unfamiliar with something. «نَکْرَۃ» is its opposite. «مَعْرفَۃ» is. And «اَنْکَرَ» means to deny. To be unfamiliar with someone and «تَنَاکَر» means to deliberately become unfamiliar with one another and to treat each other as strangers. And «نُکْر». A bad deed. An arduous task (manjad). And «مَنْکِر» means a bad deed, a bad thing, an unpleasant thing. It seems that in «نَکَرَ», two concepts are found: strangeness and aversion.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰۤ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ لَا تَصِلُ اِلَیۡہِ نَکِرَہُمۡ وَاَوۡجَسَ مِنۡہُمۡ خِیۡفَۃً» (11/70)\nTranslation: Then when Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) saw that their (the angels') hands were not reaching for the food, he felt fear in his heart, considering them strangers.","If strangeness is accompanied by displeasure, then «نَکِرَ» applies; if by pleasure, then «عَجَبَ»; and when there is neither displeasure nor pleasure, then «جُنُب» applies.","strange","نکر","11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8",7
186,32,"S","عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ","«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ» Such amazement is termed as that whose cause is unknown (detailed). Furthermore, «عَجَبَ» means 'to like' and «اَعْجَبَ» means 'to feel a pleasant sensation about something for which there is no hope or whose cause is unknown.' At times, this word is also used solely in the sense of pleasantness. Thus, within «عَجَبَ», two elements are discernible: strangeness and pleasantness.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «قَالُوۡۤا اَتَعۡجَبِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ رَحۡمَتُ اللّٰہِ وَ بَرَکٰتُہٗ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ» (11:73). Translation: The angels said to the wife of Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him), Do you wonder at God's power? O people of the house! May God's mercy and His blessings be upon you.","«عَجَبَ ۔ عَجَبٌ» is the term for a wonder whose cause is unknown.","stranger","عجب ۔ عجب","2:204-2:221-5:100-7:63-7:69-9:25-9:55-9:85-10:2-11:73-13:5-18:9-18:63-33:52-37:12-38:4-48:29-50:2-53:59-57:20-63:4-72:1",22
187,32,"S","جُنُب","«جَنْب» means side or turn, and «جُنُب» also means strange as well as impure. The word «جُنُب» is used uniformly for singular, dual, and plural—that is, for all—and for both men and women equally. (Manjad) This word appears in the Quran in both these meanings. When it occurs in the sense of strange, there is no implication of dislike or fondness associated with it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَالۡجَارِ ذِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡجَارِ الۡجُنُبِ وَ الصَّاحِبِ بِالۡجَنۡۢبِ» (4/36)\nTranslation: And treat well the close neighbors, the strange neighbors, and the companions of your side (those sitting beside you).\n\nAnd «جَنَبَ» means to turn aside and to be distant. The term junub (impure person) is also commanded to stay away from prayer and the mosque, etc., for this reason. Hence, it is called junub or junub.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَلَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43)\nTranslation: And the junub (should not approach prayer) until they bathe, except for the traveler on the road.","«جُنُب» has two meanings: one is used for a stranger, and the other is used for an impure person.","Stranger","جنب","4:36-4:43-5:6-10:12-28:11-39:56-87:11-92:17",8
188,33,"E","فَضْل","«فَضَّلَ» meaning the economy of something good and being more than the middle degree (excess), and «فُضُوْل» meaning something beyond necessity. Also, it refers to the spoils of war that remain after distribution. And «فَضُوْل» meaning one who bestows abundant favor, and «فَضْل» meaning kindness. Excess (manjad), and «فَضَّل» meaning to grant superiority or greatness to someone.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَنۡسَوُا الۡفَضۡلَ بَیۡنَکُمۡ» ( 2/237 )\nTranslation: And do not forget to do good to one another. (Uthmani)\n\nAnd «فَضَّلَ» meaning to give someone, out of kindness, something more than their rightful due.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تِلۡکَ الرُّسُلُ  فَضَّلۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» ( 2/253 )\nTranslation: Those are the prophets; We have given preference to some over others.","«فَضَّلَ» To grant someone a little extra out of kindness, considering their status.","Excellence","فضل","2:47-2:64-2:90-2:105-2:122-2:198-2:237-2:243-2:251-2:253-2:268-3:73-3:74-3:152-3:170-3:171-3:174-3:180-4:32-4:34-4:37-4:54-4:70-4:73-4:83-4:95-4:113-4:173-4:175-5:2-5:54-6:86-7:39-7:140-8:29-9:28-9:59-9:74-9:75-9:76-10:58-10:60-10:107-11:3-11:27-12:38-13:4-16:14-16:71-17:12-17:21-17:48-17:55-17:66-17:70-17:87-23:24-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:22-24:32-24:33-24:38-27:15-27:16-27:40-27:73-28:73-30:23-30:45-30:46-33:47-34:10-35:12-35:30-35:32-35:35-40:61-42:22-42:26-44:57-45:12-45:16-48:29-49:8-57:21-57:29-59:8-62:4-62:10-73:20",93
190,33,"E","اَنْعَمَ","«اَلنَّعْمَۃ» is termed as a good state of a person. And 'ni'mah' is any thing that fulfills a human need and can be a cause of their prosperity. This term is used for the genus, whether the blessing is small or great. And the words 'ni'mah' and 'in'am' are specific to humans.\n\n«اَنْعَمَ» means to do kindness, goodness, or benevolence. But «اَنْعَمَ عَلیٰ فَرَسِہ» will never occur (M. Q) and this word is not used for itself either. (FQ. L 158)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡ تَقُوۡلُ لِلَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِ وَاَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیۡہِ اَمۡسِکۡ عَلَیۡکَ زَوۡجَکَ» (33/37)\nTranslation: When you told the person—whom Allah had favored (Zaid bin Harithah) and whom you had also favored—'Keep your wife with you.' (Do not divorce her.)","«اَنْعَمَ» is employed to bestow favors upon others, excluding oneself.","Excellence (in worship); Grace (divine favor)","انعم","1:6-2:40-2:47-2:122-2:150-2:211-2:231-3:103-3:171-3:174-4:69-4:72-5:3-5:6-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:23-5:110-8:53-11:10-12:6-14:6-14:28-14:34-16:18-16:53-16:71-16:72-16:81-16:83-16:112-16:114-16:121-17:83-19:58-26:22-27:19-28:17-29:67-31:20-31:31-33:9-33:37-35:3-37:57-39:8-39:49-41:51-43:13-43:59-44:27-46:15-48:2-49:8-52:29-54:35-68:2-68:49-73:11-89:15-92:19-93:11",63
191,33,"E","اَحْسَنَ","«اَحْسَنَ» The meaning of ihsan is every virtuous and good deed, whether it pertains to oneself or to another (faq l 158). In the Hadith of Jibril (peace be upon him), it is narrated that Jibril (peace be upon him) asked the Prophet (peace be upon him), What is ihsan? So he (peace be upon him) replied: Ihsan is that you worship Allah as if you are seeing Him; and if that is not possible, then you should at least firmly believe that Allah is seeing you. The word ihsan is used for every good deed, whether small or great. As when Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him), while thanking Allah, said:\n«وَ قَدۡ اَحۡسَنَ  بِیۡۤ اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَنِیۡ مِنَ السِّجۡنِ وَ جَآءَ بِکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡبَدۡوِ» (12/100)\nTranslation: And He bestowed favor upon me by delivering me from prison and bringing you all from the countryside.","«اَحْسَنَ» is used for every good and virtuous deed, whether it relates to oneself or to others.","Excellence","احسن","2:83-2:178-2:195-2:229-3:172-4:36-4:59-4:62-4:86-4:125-5:50-5:93-6:151-6:152-6:154-7:145-9:100-9:121-10:26-11:7-12:3-12:23-12:100-16:30-16:90-16:96-16:97-16:125-17:7-17:23-17:34-17:35-17:53-18:7-18:30-19:73-19:74-23:14-23:96-24:38-25:24-25:33-28:77-29:7-29:46-32:7-37:125-39:10-39:18-39:23-39:35-39:55-40:64-41:33-41:34-46:15-46:16-53:31-55:60-64:3-65:11-67:2-95:4",63
192,34,"C","خِیَرَۃ","«خَیْر» meaning good and better, and «خِیَرَۃ» and «اِخْتَار» meaning to prefer, select, or choose a good option from among two or more things.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَمَا کَانَ لِمُؤۡمِنٍ وَّلَا مُؤۡمِنَۃٍ اِذَا قَضَی اللّٰہُ وَرَسُوۡلُہٗۤ اَمۡرًا اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ لَہُمُ الۡخِیَرَۃُ مِنۡ اَمۡرِہِمۡ» (33/36).  \nTranslation: It is not for a believing man or a believing woman to have any choice in a matter when Allah and His Messenger have already decided it.","«خِیَرَۃ» the option to choose one from two or more things.","Choice","خیرۃ","28:68-33:36",2
193,34,"D","مَلْک","«مِلْک» refers to every thing that is in someone's possession and over which no other person has the right to exercise control, and «مَلْک» and «مِلْک» are synonymous in this respect (i.e., «مَلْک» denotes that which one owns and has in one's possession). (And «مَلِک» is used for a king, meaning that the public property is under his possession and control, and he is its administrator.)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا مَاۤ اَخۡلَفۡنَا مَوۡعِدَکَ بِمَلۡکِنَا» (20/87)\nTranslation: The Children of Israel said to Prophet Moses, We did not break our promise to you of our own free will.\nMeaning: The Samiri deceived us, took the ornaments from us, and made the calf, which somehow gained such dominance over us that we no longer had the authority to exercise control over our own affairs.","«مَلْک» the authority to act upon something.","Divine Decree","ملک","2:246-2:247-4:3-4:24-4:25-4:36-5:17-5:25-5:41-5:76-7:188-10:31-10:49-12:43-12:50-12:54-12:72-12:76-13:16-16:71-16:73-17:56-17:100-18:79-19:87-20:87-20:89-20:114-23:6-23:88-23:116-24:31-24:33-24:58-24:61-25:3-29:17-30:28-33:50-33:52-33:55-34:22-34:42-35:13-39:43-43:86-46:8-48:11-59:23-60:4-62:1-70:30-72:21-78:37-82:19-114:2",56
194,34,"D","وَلَایۃ","«وَلَایَۃ» when pronounced with a *fatḥa* (zabar) on its waw, means to be in charge of or responsible for something. And «وِلَایَۃ» when pronounced with a *kasra* (zair) on its waw, means kingdom, sovereignty, or monarchy. (meaning) And «اَلْوَلَاء» means the inheritance one receives from a slave one has freed. (meaning) Furthermore, the word «وَلَایَۃ» is also used in the Quran in the meanings related to inheritance. When the bond of brotherhood (*mu'akhah*) was established between the early Muhajirs (emigrants) and the Ansar (helpers), they would also inherit from one another. However, later these rulings were abrogated, and only the actual blood relatives were designated as the rightful heirs. (Refer to Surah Al-Anfal 72-75) Also, in the Quran, «مَوْلیٰ اور مَوَالِی )» is used in the meanings of 'heir'.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/33)\nTranslation: And for those who leave behind neither parents nor children, We have appointed for every person among them as heirs...\n\nThus, the word «وَلَایَۃ» is used in a much broader sense than «مَلْک».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہُنَالِکَ الۡوَلَایَۃُ لِلّٰہِ الۡحَقِّ» (18/44)\nTranslation: (Thus it was made clear that) sovereignty belongs to Allah, the True (Al-Jalālayni).","«وَلَایَۃ» means having complete control over something.","Decree","ولایۃ","4:33-18:44-19:5",3
195,34,"D","اَمْکَنَ","Both «اَمْکَنَ» and «مَکَّنَ» mean to grant someone power or authority over a place, to give control, and to make capable (Munjid). From this, the meaning of 'place' is also derived, i.e., the location where something is kept or resides. And «اَمْکَنَ الْاَمْر» means to make something possible and easy (Munjid). Thus, it is observed that in «اَمْکَنَ», the concept of place or location is found along with authority.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ یُّرِیۡدُوۡا خِیَانَتَکَ فَقَدۡ خَانُوا اللّٰہَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاَمۡکَنَ مِنۡہُمۡ» (8/71)\nTranslation: If these people intend to betray you, they have already betrayed Allah before. So Allah has placed them in your grasp (Jalandhari). Thus, He caused them to be seized. (Uthmani)","«اَمْکَنَ» when the concept of place or location is also present in choice.","Discretion","امکن","8:71",1
196,34,"A","اِسْتَحَبَّ","«حُبّ» means love, and «اِسْتَحَبَّ» means choosing something that one's heart also covets.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡۤا اٰبَآءَکُمۡ وَ اِخۡوَانَکُمۡ اَوۡلِیَآءَ اِنِ اسۡتَحَبُّوا الۡکُفۡرَ عَلَی الۡاِیۡمَانِ» (9/23)  \nTranslation: O you who believe! If your parents and siblings choose disbelief over faith, do not befriend them.","«اِسْتَحَبَّ» to choose that which pleases the heart from among two or more things.","Authority","استحب","9:23-14:3-16:107-41:17",4
197,34,"O","تَحَرّٰی","«حَرْوٌ ، اَحْرٰی» means more worthy (م ق) and «تَحَرّٰی» means to seek what is more suitable and worthy. It refers to seeking the better of two things (from Manjad). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «فَمَنۡ اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا رَشَدًا» (72/14). Translation: And whoever becomes obedient, it is such people who have chosen the path of goodness.","«تَحَرّٰی» To choose and seek the more worthy and better of two things.","Option","تحری","72:14",1
198,35,"L","قرض","«قَرَضَ» means a loan, i.e., such a borrowing that a person takes from another person to fulfill his necessities. And according to Imam Raghib, it is wealth that is given to fulfill a need on the condition that it will be returned. (Maf) And the author of *al-Muntaha al-Arab* adds to this condition also that it is a loan for which no period has been specified for repayment. (M. A)\n\nBecause wherever the word *qard* (loan) has been used in the Holy Quran, the word «حَسَنَا» is often also mentioned with it, and this is also a condition of *Qard Hasanah* (benevolent loan).\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡعُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2/280)\nTranslation: And if the borrower is in difficulty, then grant him respite until a time of ease.\n\nAnd such a loan Allah the Almighty describes as *Qard Hasanah* (a good loan) and attributes to Himself taking it, even though it is given only to those in need.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یُقۡرِضُ اللّٰہَ  قَرۡضًا حَسَنًا فَیُضٰعِفَہٗ لَہٗ وَ لَہٗۤ اَجۡرٌ کَرِیۡمٌ» (57/11)\nTranslation: Who is it that would give Allah a good loan, so He will multiply it for him and have for him a noble reward (i.e., Paradise)?\n\nIn this sense, every *qard* (loan) is a *dayn* (debt), but not every *dayn* is a *qard*. (Fq. 140)","«قَرَضَ» refers to money taken for personal necessities with the condition of repayment after a specified period. Whereas in a benevolent loan (qard hasan), there is no fixed term.","Loan","قرض","2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20",9
199,35,"L","دین","«دَیْن» If a loan has a specified period, it is termed as *dayn* (debt).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282)  \nTranslation: O you who believe! When you contract a debt among yourselves for a fixed term, then write it down.  \n\nAnd by «دَیْن», all responsibilities of lending and borrowing are implied. The term is generally broader than *qard* (loan); it can be used for commercial purposes as well as personal needs. Consider this example: A person owes 5,000 rupees to others and is also owed 8,000 rupees. In this case, he is a *madyoon* (debtor) but not a *muqrid* (borrower). However, if he owes 8,000 rupees and is owed 5,000, then he is both a debtor and a borrower.  \n\nIf someone takes a *qard* (loan) for personal needs with a fixed repayment period, accepting the responsibility to repay at the specified time, then it is not merely a *qard* but a *dayn* (debt).","«دَیْن» If a loan has a fixed term, it is termed as debt.","Loan","دین","2:245-2:282-4:11-4:12-5:12-57:11-57:18-64:17-73:20",9
200,36,"I","اَرَادَ","«رَوْد» means to go to and fro in search of something (m. a.), and «اَرَادَ» means for the thought of doing something to arise in the heart (muf.), to desire it, and its opposite is «کَرِہَ» (faq. l. 103).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّمَاۤ اَمۡرُہٗۤ اِذَاۤ اَرَادَ شَیۡئًا اَنۡ یَّقُوۡلَ لَہٗ کُنۡ فَیَکُوۡنُ» ( 36/82 )\nTranslation: His way is that when He intends a thing, He says to it, Be, and it is.","For something to flit through one's heart.","Intention","اراد","2:26-2:228-2:233-5:17-9:46-12:25-13:11-17:19-17:103-18:82-21:70-22:22-25:62-28:19-32:20-33:17-33:50-36:82-37:98-39:4-39:38-48:11-72:10-74:31",24
201,36,"I","ھَمَّ","When an intention remains in the heart for some time and a person continually engages in contemplation and deliberation to give it practical form, it is termed as «ھَمَّ». For example, the Quran states: «اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ وَ ہَمُّوۡا بِاِخۡرَاجِ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (9:13). Translation: Why do you not fight a people who broke their oaths and intended to expel the Messenger? (Uthmani).","«ھَمَّ» to reflect upon the intentions that arise in the heart.","Intention","ھم","9:13-9:74",2
202,36,"I","عَزَمَ","When, after deliberation over one's intention, a decisive decision is made, it is called «عَزَمَ». In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «یَدُلُّ عَلَی الْعَزِیْمَۃِ وَالْقََطْعِ» (m. l.) means to form a firm intention and then resolve to fulfill it.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَشَاوِرۡہُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ ۚ فَاِذَا عَزَمۡتَ فَتَوَکَّلۡ عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (3/159)\n\nTranslation: And (O Prophet) consult with your companions regarding your matter. Then when you have resolved upon a course of action, put your trust in Allah.","After due consideration, to form a firm resolve.","Intention","عزم","2:227-2:235-3:159-3:186-20:115-31:17-42:43-46:35-47:21",9
203,36,"I","اَبْرَمَ","«بَرَمَ» means to combine two ropes and braid them, and «اَبْرَمَ» means to strengthen a matter, affair, or thing (M.L. M.A). Its opposite is «نَقَصَ». And «اَبْرَام» means to adopt measures, make a plan, and give final shape to a determination in order to put it into practice.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ اَبۡرَمُوۡۤا اَمۡرًا فَاِنَّا مُبۡرِمُوۡنَ» ( 43/79 )\nTranslation: Have they determined a matter? Then We [too] are determined.\n\nIn this verse, the reference is to the plot that the polytheists of Mecca had made to kill the Messenger of Allah (ﷺ). And Allah's plan was that He would save His Messenger from them.","Planning to fulfill one's resolve and intentions.","Intention","ابرم","43:79",1
204,36,"I","اَمَّ","«اَمَّ» meaning to intend a path or journey (M, A), and according to Imam Raghib, to be directed towards a straight purpose and not inclined towards anything else.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تُحِلُّوۡا شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ وَلَا الشَّہۡرَ الۡحَرَامَ وَلَا الۡہَدۡیَ وَلَا الۡقَلَآئِدَ وَلَاۤ آٰمِّیۡنَ الۡبَیۡتَ الۡحَرَامَ» (5/2)\nTranslation: O believers, do not violate the rites of God, nor the sacred month, nor the sacrificial animals, nor those with collars [garlands], nor those proceeding to the Sacred House [Kaaba] seeking bounty from their Lord and [His] approval.","«اَمَّ» To resolve to go straight to one's intended destination without paying attention to anything else.","Intention","ام","5:2",1
205,36,"I","تَیَمَّمْ","According to Sahib Mutla' al-Arab, this word originally was «تَاَمَّمَ», which is derived from «اَمَّ», and Ibn al-Faris considers its origin to be «تَمْ», meaning to do something intentionally or by mistake (e.g.). Apparently, this word is used for actions that do not require thought, reflection, or consultation; rather, the intended meaning is the resolve to comply with Shariah commands. In the Quran, this word has been used twice: once for 'amr' (command) and the second time for 'nahi' (prohibition).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n(1) «فَلَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (4/43)\nTranslation: Then if you do not find water, perform tayammum with clean earth. (Taqi Usmani)\nAnd if you do not find water, then intend clean earth. (Jona Garhi)\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n(2) «وَلَا تَیَمَّمُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنۡہُ تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ وَلَسۡتُمۡ بِاٰخِذِیۡہِ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تُغۡمِضُوۡا فِیۡہِ» (2/267)\nTranslation: And whatever you spend in the way of Allah, do not intend to give a bad and impure thing, so that if it were given to you, you would not even like to take it, unless you overlook it.","The intention to implement a shar'i ruling.","Intention","تیمم","2:267-4:43-5:6",3
206,36,"I","تَحَرّی","«حَرَّی» meaning 'deserving' and «تَحَرّٰی» meaning 'seeking the best path' (as per Manjaj), i.e., searching for the best path. And meaning 'seeking the more suitable and worthy one. Seeking the better one among two things.' (Manjaj)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَمَنۡ اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا رَشَدًا» (72/14)\nTranslation: Thus, those who became obedient chose the good path. (Uthmani (RA))","«تَحَرَّی» to resolve upon the best path.","Intention","تحری","72:14",1
207,37,"T","اَصَرَّ","«صَرَّ» means to tie and «صُرَّہ» refers to the pouch in which cash is tied up. «اَصَرَّ» means to firmly commit to sin or a bad deed and not turn back from it. (Mufradat) This word is mostly used for sin. (M. Q)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَکَانُوۡا یُصِرُّوۡنَ عَلَی الۡحِنۡثِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (56/46)\nTranslation: And they were firmly committed to great sin (polytheism).","«اَصَرّ» to persist in a bad deed or to remain attached to it.","to fly","اصر","3:135-45:8-56:46",3
208,37,"T","مَرَدَ","The basic meaning of «مَرَدَ» is for something to be devoid of what it should contain. «اَمْرَدُ» means a tree whose leaves have fallen, or a young person who either has not yet grown a beard or is beardless. And «مَارَدْ» refers to such devils among jinn or humans who are devoid of all kinds of goodness. Then this word began to be used for something bad that flies away, remaining empty of goodness (m.f.). For example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَ مِمَّنۡ حَوۡلَکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مُنٰفِقُوۡنَ  ؕ ۛوَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ ۛ ؔ مَرَدُوۡا عَلَی النِّفَاقِ» (9/101) Translation: And some of the Bedouins around you are hypocrites, and some of the people of Medina also, who persist in their hypocrisy.","«مَرَدَ» is something being devoid of that which ought to be inherent in its name.","to fly","مرد","9:101",1
209,37,"T","لَجَّ","«لَجَّ» means to argue due to opposition. To persist in enmity, i.e., to nurture hostility (minjadd). And «لَجَّۃً» means the depth of water, and «بَحْرٍ لُّجِیِّ» means the deep sea, and «اِلْتَجَّ الْبَحْر» means the agitation or storm of the sea, being turbulent (minjadd). Thus, the meaning of «لَجَّ» is found to imply going to extreme lengths in a bad deed.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَوۡ رَحِمۡنٰہُمۡ وَکَشَفۡنَا مَا بِہِمۡ مِّنۡ ضُرٍّلَّلَجُّوۡا فِیۡ طُغۡیَانِہِمۡ یَعۡمَہُوۡنَ» (23/75)\nTranslation: And if We show them mercy and remove the afflictions that are upon them, they would persist in their rebellion and wander blindly.","Nurturing enmity and taking it to extremes.","to fly","لج","23:75-67:21",2
210,38,"T","اَذْرٰی","«ذِرَءُ» means a fragment of speech (i.e., an incomplete statement), and «ذَرَاَتِ الرِّیْح» means the wind lifts scattered things and carries them away (source). «اَذْرٰی» means the wind scattering and dispersing light things. According to Ibn al-Faris, «ذَرْوُ» refers to things that fly in the wind and then separate, falling down (source).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran:\n«فَاخۡتَلَطَ بِہٖ نَبَاتُ الۡاَرۡضِ فَاَصۡبَحَ ہَشِیۡمًا تَذۡرُوۡہُ  الرِّیٰحُ» (18/45)\nTranslation: So it became green and lush, then it became scattered debris that the winds carry away.","«ذَرْوُ» is used to fly tiny things in the air.","to fly","اذری","18:45-51:1",2
211,38,"T","نَسَفَ","«نَسَفَ الْحَبَّ» To winnow grain with a winnowing basket, and «مِنْسَف» a winnowing basket and sieve, etc., with which grain is cleaned, and «نَسَفَ الرِّیْح» meaning to uproot something by the wind from its very foundation and scatter it (as in the root *f-n-d*), and meaning to crush mountains, etc., and scatter them in the wind (as in the root *k-w-t*).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡجِبَالِ فَقُلۡ یَنۡسِفُہَا رَبِّیۡ  نَسۡفًا» (20/105)\nTranslation: And they ask you about the mountains. Say, 'My Lord will blow them away and scatter them as dust.'","«نَسَفَ» to mix something thoroughly.","to fly","نسف","20:97-20:105-77:10",3
212,38,"T","طَارَ ، اِسْتَطَار","«اَلطَّائِر» refers to all winged creatures that move through space, and «طَارَ یَطِیْر» means the flight of a bird, while «طَیْر» is the plural form of «طَائِر».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَلَا طٰٓئِرٍ یَّطِیۡرُبِجَنَاحَیۡہِ» (6:38)\nTranslation: And there is no bird that flies with its two wings.\n\nAnd «غُبَارٌ مُّسْتَطَارٌ» means dust that scatters and disperses in the wind (muf), i.e., «اِسْتَطَار» signifies something scattering and dispersing in the air or space.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» (76:7)\nTranslation: And they fear a Day whose evil is widespread. (Al-'Uthmani)","«طَارَ» is used for flying birds.","to fly","طار ، استطار","6:38-76:7",2
213,39,"A","اَشَارَ","«اَشَارَ» meaning to convey something to someone through hand movements without opening one's mouth (f.l., 174).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَاَشَارَتۡ اِلَیۡہِ ؕ قَالُوۡا کَیۡفَ نُکَلِّمُ مَنۡ کَانَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ صَبِیًّا» (19/29)  \nTranslation: So Maryam (peace be upon her) gestured toward the child. They said, How can we speak to one who is but a baby in the cradle?","«اَشَارَ» is used to indicate by hand movement.","Allusion","اشار","19:29",1
214,39,"A","رَمَزَ","«رَمَزَ» refers to gesturing with the lips or emitting a slight sound (f l 174), and any speech that resembles a gesture is considered a symbol. For example, the Noble Quran states: «قَالَ اٰیَتُکَ اَلَّا تُکَلِّمَ النَّاسَ ثَلٰثَۃَ اَیَّامٍ اِلَّا رَمۡزًا» (3/41). Translation: Allah Almighty said: Your sign is that you will not be able to speak to the people for three days except by gesture.","«رَمَزَ» is used to indicate through lips or eyes.","Allusion","رمز","3:41",1
215,39,"H","تَغَامَز","«غَمْزُ» means to communicate through eyelashes and eyebrows (F L 174), and according to Ibn al-Faris, it means to make an animal move by tickling it with something (ML. Manjad). And «تَغَامَز» means pointing with the eyebrows to find fault with someone (MF).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا مَرُّوۡا بِہِمۡ یَتَغَامَزُوۡنَ» (83/30)\nTranslation: And when they passed by them, they gestured with disdain.","Conveying meaning through the hints of eyelashes and eyebrows.","Hint","تغامز","83:30",1
216,39,"I","عَرَّض","«عَرَضَ» means to present (a statement), and «عَرَّضَ» means to speak in hints and allusions. According to Imam Raghib, «عَرَضَ» in the sense of *ta‘rīḍ* means to speak in multifaceted statements (i.e., statements from which multiple meanings can emerge) that can be interpreted as true or false, and as apparent or hidden.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِیۡمَا عَرَّضۡتُمۡ بِہٖ مِنۡ خِطۡبَۃِ النِّسَآءِ» (2/235)\nTranslation: And (during the waiting period) if you convey a marriage proposal to women in allusive terms, there is no blame upon you.","«عَرَّضَ» does not refer literally, but rather the intended meaning is to understand through metaphorical implication.","indication","عرض","2:235",1
217,40,"O","تَبِعَ","«تَبِعَ» means to follow behind someone or to tread in their footsteps (masculine noun). It is used in both an external and an internal sense. Internally, it means to follow the guidance of the religion or to adopt the habits and character of a person.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ تَبِعَ ہُدَایَ فَلَا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَلَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (2/38)\nTranslation: Whoever follows My guidance will have no fear, nor will they grieve.\n\nAnd in the external sense, «اَتْبَعَ» is used for physically following behind someone.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَتۡبَعَہُمۡ فِرۡعَوۡنُ بِجُنُوۡدِہٖ» (20/78)\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh pursued them with his armies. (Hussainؒ)","«تَبِعَ» means to follow behind someone or to walk in their footsteps, and this usage applies both outwardly and inwardly.","Obedience","تبع","2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7",150
218,40,"O","اِقْتِدَا","«اِقْتِدَا» means to follow someone and act like them, and «اَقْدٰی» means to follow someone in the path of goodness and religion (as in the case of a follower who follows the Imam in prayer).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہَدَی اللّٰہُ  فَبِہُدٰىہُمُ اقۡتَدِہۡ» (6:90)  \nTranslation: These are the ones whom Allah has guided, so follow their guidance.  \n\nThe word اقتداء can also be used in a negative sense. «قُدْوَۃ» actually refers to a state where a person becomes subservient to another (as cited), and «قُدْوَۃ» can also mean a follower, guide, or leader.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّا وَجَدۡنَاۤ اٰبَآءَنَاعَلٰۤی اُمَّۃٍ وَّ اِنَّاعَلٰۤی اٰثٰرِہِمۡ مُّقۡتَدُوۡنَ» (43:23)  \nTranslation: Indeed, we found our forefathers following a certain way, and we are treading in their footsteps.","«اِقْتِدَا» meaning to follow in someone's footsteps and emulate their actions.","Obedience","اقتدا","6:90-43:23",2
219,40,"O","اُسْوَۃٌ ، قُدْوَۃٌ","«اُسْوَۃٌ» and «قُدْوَۃٌ» are very similar in meaning. They are used in the sense of an exemplary or followable state. The only difference is that «اُسْوَۃٌ» also encompasses the aspect of *mawasat*, meaning mutual compassion and empathy. Thus, «اُسْوَۃٌ» is such an example that can also provide solace. «اٰسِیْ» refers to one who applies a poultice, a physician, and one who makes peace (i.e., reconciles). (See Farahidi, Maqayis al-Lughah). Thus, the word «اُسْوَۃٌ» is more eloquent and expressive than «قُدْوَۃٌ».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ کَانَ لَکُمۡ  فِیۡ رَسُوۡلِ اللّٰہِ  اُسۡوَۃٌ حَسَنَۃٌ» (33:21)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, in the Messenger of Allah you have an excellent example for anyone whose hope is in Allah and the Last Day, and who remembers Allah often. (Taqi Usmani)\nYour best course is to follow the way of the Prophet. (Jalandhari)","«اُسْوَۃٌ» to follow an exemplary character with compassion.","Obedience","اسوۃ ، قدوۃ","33:21-60:4-60:6",3
220,40,"O","اَطَاعَ","«طَوْعَ» means happiness and contentment of the heart, and its opposite is «کَرْہٌ», which means aversion, hatred, and dislike. And «اَطَاعَ» refers to obedience that is carried out with joy.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَقَالَ لَہَا وَ لِلۡاَرۡضِ ائۡتِیَا طَوۡعًا اَوۡ کَرۡہًا ؕ قَالَتَاۤ اَتَیۡنَا طَآئِعِیۡنَ» (41/11)\nTranslation: Allah Almighty said to the heavens and the earth, Come willingly or unwillingly. They said, We come willingly.","«اَطَاعَ» to carry out someone's command with a happy heart.","Obedience","اطاع","2:184-3:83-3:168-4:64-4:80-4:81-13:15-24:53-40:18-41:11-43:54-47:21-81:21",13
221,40,"O","اِسْتَجَابَ","«اِسْتَجَابَ» is used in all these meanings: to answer, to accept, to obey, to take a command. The difference between obedience (اطاعت) and response/acceptance (استجابت) is that obedience is performed only by a subordinate, whereas response/acceptance can be performed by both a subordinate and a superior. If it is in relation to Allah, it means accepting the prayer of Allah's servant; and if it is in relation to a human, it means the human accepting Allah's command (Faqeeh al-Lughah, 184).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا اسۡتَجِیۡبُوۡا لِلّٰہِ وَ لِلرَّسُوۡلِ» (8/24)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, obey Allah and His Messenger.","«اِسْتَجَابَ» to accept the command and act upon it, to agree to the matter, and this is even possible for the elderly.","Obedience","استجاب","2:186-3:172-3:195-6:36-7:194-8:9-8:24-11:14-12:34-13:14-13:18-17:52-28:50-28:64-35:14-42:16-42:26-42:38-42:47-46:5",20
222,40,"O","اَسْلَمَ","«السَّلْم» means health and well-being (literal meaning), and it also means being protected from apparent and hidden afflictions (technical meaning). And «اَسْلَمَ» means to adopt obedience and to bow one's head in submission before God's commands and His pleasure, so that one may attain security and well-being from the punishment of the Hereafter (technical meaning).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ قَالَ لَہٗ رَبُّہٗۤ  اَسۡلِمۡ ۙ قَالَ اَسۡلَمۡتُ لِرَبِّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (2/131)\nTranslation: When his Lord said to Prophet Abraham, Submit, he said, I have submitted [as a Muslim] to the Lord of the worlds.","To bow one's head in submission before «اَسْلَمَ»'s pleasure.","Obedience","اسلم","2:112-2:131-3:20-3:83-4:65-4:125-5:44-6:14-6:71-22:34-27:44-37:103-39:54-40:66-49:14-49:17-72:14",17
223,40,"O","قَنَتَ","«قَنَتَ» meaning to stand in prayer with complete and perfect stillness and to exhibit humility and submission before Allah Almighty (Munjid); and according to Imam Raghib, it means to be wholly engrossed in worship and to turn attention away from others (Maf). Thus, qunoot is an obedience performed with full humility, submission, and concentration.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّقۡنُتۡ مِنۡکُنَّ لِلّٰہِ وَ رَسُوۡلِہٖ وَ تَعۡمَلۡ صَالِحًا نُّؤۡتِہَاۤ اَجۡرَہَا مَرَّتَیۡنِ» ( 33/31 )\nTranslation: And those of you who obey Allah and His Messenger and do righteous deeds - We will give them their reward doubly.","«قَنَتَ» Obedience in worship that also embodies humility and meekness.","Obedience","قنت","3:43-33:31",2
224,40,"O","ذَعَنَ","«ذَعَنَ» means to be obedient and compliant, and to follow cues and signals. «مِذْعَان» means one who readily becomes obedient (a munjid). And «نَاقَۃٌ مِّذْعَانٌ» refers to a submissive and obedient she-camel (a maf). Thus, «ذَعَنَ» also implies an aspect of humility and abasement alongside obedience.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّکُنۡ  لَّہُمُ الۡحَقُّ یَاۡتُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِ مُذۡعِنِیۡنَ» (24/49)\nTranslation: And if the truth were to come to them, they would follow it submissively.\n\nSome exegetes have translated «مُذْعِنِیْن» as «مُطِیْعِیْن و سَارِعِیْن». That is, if a matter were to go in their favor, they would rush to accept it (Faq l 209).","«ذَعَنَ» obeying someone for one's own interests.","Obedience","ذعن","24:49",1
225,41,"M","قَصْد","«قَصْد» and «اِقْتِصَاد» mean to adopt the middle path while avoiding excess and deficiency. The only difference is that «اِقْتِصَاد» is generally used in relation to expenditures and spending, whereas the word qasad (intention) is general.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ» (31:19)\nTranslation: And maintain moderation in your gait.\n\nAnd «قَصْدُ السَّبِیْل» refers to adopting the middle and moderate path while avoiding excess and deficiency, and this alone can be the straight path. Whereas all other paths will be inclined towards excess or deficiency, or crooked.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَعَلَی اللّٰہِ قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ» (16:9)\nTranslation: And Allah presents the straight path. And besides that, all paths are crooked.\n\nNote: (Excess and Deficiency: deficiency and excess, unbalanced state, more or less.\nExcess (Ifrat): Its meaning is to exceed the limit, to exaggerate in describing someone's status. The Noble Quran has termed it 'ghuluww' (extremism), and in Arabic it is also called 'tatarruf' (excessiveness).\nDeficiency (Tafrit): Its meaning is to do injustice to someone's status and lower them from their rightful rank.)","«قَصْد» To adopt the path of moderation by avoiding excess and deficiency in any action.","Moderation","قصد","9:42-16:9-31:19",3
226,41,"M","وَسْط","«وَسْط» is the middle of a single thing or the intermediate entity between two or more things. It is as if this term is more potent than 'qasad', and «وَسَطَ» means one who adopts the path of moderation and balance in every matter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ اُمَّۃً وَّسَطًا لِّتَکُوۡنُوۡا شُہَدَآءَ عَلَی النَّاسِ» (2/143)\nTranslation: And thus we have made you a moderate nation...","«وَسْط» is used to denote the middle of a single thing or the intermediary among two or more things.","Moderation","وسط","2:143-2:238",2
227,41,"T","تَقْوِیْم","«تَقْوِیْم» pertains to a single matter: that all aspects of excess and deficiency in it are eliminated. And it becomes balanced, proportionate, and moderate. In it, there remains no crookedness, deviation, or irregularity. (Faq 174)\n\n«قَوْمُ الشَّیءِ» means to determine and adjust something. «تَقْوِیْمُ الْبَدَان» is derived from it because it describes the length and width of cities. And «قَوَّمَ دَرْأَہٗ» means to straighten crookedness (Manjad).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡۤ  اَحۡسَنِ تَقۡوِیۡمٍ» (95/4)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, We have created man in the best of stature.","«تَقْوِیْم» to maintain moderation from every aspect in a single matter.","The golden mean","تقویم","95:4",1
228,42,"R","طَائر","«طَائِر» meaning bird, and «طَیْر» and «تَطَیَّرْ» and «اطَّیَّرَ» mean to take an omen from a bird, and then this word also began to be used in a negative sense.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«قَالُوۡا طَآئِرُکُمۡ مَّعَکُمۡ» (36:19)  \nTranslation: They said, Your evil omen is with yourselves.  \n\nAnd when a person performs an action, he no longer has any control over it. It is as if it flew away from his hands just as a bird flies away. From this perspective, human actions have also been metaphorically referred to as a bird.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ کُلَّ  اِنۡسَانٍ اَلۡزَمۡنٰہُ طٰٓئِرَہٗ  فِیۡ عُنُقِہٖ» (17:13)  \nTranslation: And every person's record of deeds is hung around his neck.","«طَائِر» meaning bird. Human deeds have also been metaphorically described as a bird. And when a person performs an action, thereafter they have no control over it. It is as if it has flown away from their hands just like a bird flies away.","Righteous deeds","طائر","6:38-7:131-17:13-27:47-36:19",5
229,42,"R","کتاب","«کَتَب» means writing and all forms of written records, whether a small note, a large scroll, a newspaper, or a thick book—this term applies to all of them. And human deeds are also being continuously recorded by the noble scribes. Therefore, the Record of Deeds is called a writing in this sense.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ نُخۡرِجُ لَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ کِتٰبًا  یَّلۡقٰىہُ  مَنۡشُوۡرًا» (17:13)\nTranslation: And We will bring forth the Book on the Day of Resurrection, which they will see laid open.","«کِتَاب» Every collection of written or printed pages is called a book.","Righteous deeds","کتاب","2:2-2:44-2:53-2:78-2:79-2:85-2:87-2:89-2:101-2:105-2:109-2:113-2:121-2:129-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:151-2:159-2:174-2:176-2:177-2:213-2:231-2:235-3:3-3:7-3:19-3:20-3:23-3:48-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:70-3:71-3:72-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:81-3:98-3:99-3:100-3:110-3:113-3:119-3:145-3:164-3:184-3:186-3:187-3:199-4:24-4:44-4:47-4:51-4:54-4:103-4:105-4:113-4:123-4:127-4:131-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:159-4:171-5:5-5:15-5:19-5:44-5:48-5:57-5:59-5:65-5:68-5:77-5:110-6:7-6:20-6:38-6:59-6:89-6:91-6:92-6:114-6:154-6:155-6:156-6:157-7:2-7:37-7:52-7:169-7:170-7:196-8:68-8:75-9:29-9:36-10:1-10:37-10:61-10:94-11:1-11:6-11:17-11:110-12:1-13:1-13:36-13:38-13:39-13:43-14:1-15:1-15:4-16:64-16:89-17:2-17:4-17:13-17:14-17:58-17:71-17:93-18:1-18:27-18:49-19:12-19:16-19:30-19:41-19:51-19:54-19:56-20:52-21:10-22:8-22:70-23:49-23:62-24:33-25:35-26:2-27:1-27:28-27:29-27:40-27:75-28:2-28:43-28:49-28:52-28:86-29:27-29:45-29:46-29:47-29:48-29:51-30:56-31:2-31:20-32:2-32:23-33:6-33:26-34:3-35:11-35:25-35:29-35:31-35:32-35:40-37:117-37:157-38:29-39:1-39:2-39:23-39:41-39:69-40:2-40:53-40:70-41:3-41:41-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:17-42:52-43:2-43:4-43:21-44:2-45:2-45:16-45:28-45:29-46:2-46:4-46:12-46:30-50:4-52:2-56:78-57:16-57:22-57:25-57:26-57:29-59:2-59:11-62:2-68:37-69:19-69:25-74:31-78:29-83:7-83:9-83:18-83:20-84:7-84:10-98:1-98:4-98:6",232
230,42,"D","قِطّ","«قِطّ» meaning the register of account, the decree, the written record of reckoning. The term Amaal Nama (Record of Deeds) is referred to as Qit in the Quran because it will be the very foundation for the reckoning of human deeds.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا عَجِّلۡ  لَّنَا قِطَّنَا قَبۡلَ یَوۡمِ  الۡحِسَابِ» (38:16)  \nTranslation: And they say, Our Lord, hasten for us our reckoning before the Day of Account.","«قِطّ» The register in which accounts are recorded.","Deeds","قط","38:16",1
231,42,"D","صُحُف","«صُحُف» (in its singular form) means a spread-out thing and anything upon which something is written. «صِحَافَۃ» means chronicling, and «اَصْحَفَ» means gathering scrolls or written leaves into a book, and «مُصْحَف» means book, with its plural being «مَصَاحِف» (manjud). The term sahifah (scroll) is used for the Book of Deeds in the sense that it will be in the form of large, spread-out pages.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا الصُّحُفُ نُشِرَتۡ» (81:10)\nTranslation: And when the records (of deeds) are opened.","compiling written papers into book form","Deeds","صحف","20:133-53:36-74:52-80:13-81:10-87:18-87:19-98:2",8
232,43,"A","وَیْلَ","«وَیْلَ» is a word of threat that, in its original sense, is used as a curse. And «وَیْلُ» (a noun) means the descent of evil and mischief, destruction, severe calamity (as cited), and «تَوَایَل» means to curse one another (as cited). The word «وَیْل» is used in negative connotations and is uttered at times of regret (m. r.), and when a person is afflicted with a calamity or distress, he expresses remorse with this word. Now, observe its examples:\n\n(1) Example at the time of calamity: The Almighty God has stated:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا» (36/52)\nTranslation: They will say, Alas! Who has awakened us from our sleeping places?\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty God has stated:\n«وَیۡلٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ  لِّلۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ» (77/15)\nTranslation: On that day, woe is for the deniers.\n\n(2) Example at the time of distress: The Almighty God has stated:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ ؕ قَالَ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤی اَعَجَزۡتُ اَنۡ  اَکُوۡنَ مِثۡلَ  ہٰذَا الۡغُرَابِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: So Allah sent a crow who began scratching the earth, to show him how to hide his brother's corpse. He said, Alas! I could not even be like this crow and hide my brother's body.","«وَیْلَ» is a phrase of regret that escapes a person's lips in times of distress and hardship.","Alas","ویل","2:79-5:31-11:72-14:2-18:49-19:37-20:61-21:14-21:18-21:46-21:97-25:28-28:80-36:52-37:20-38:27-39:22-41:6-43:65-45:7-46:17-51:60-52:11-68:31-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-83:1-83:10-104:1-107:4",38
233,43,"A","لَیْتَ","«لَیْتَ» The particle of wish (حرف تمنی) resembling a verb is used to express regret over a past shortcoming (i.e., if only, oh, that). It is also used for a wish whose fulfillment is impossible, such as «لَیْتَ الشَّبَابُ عَائِدًا» (If only youth could return).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ  کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا» (78/40)\nTranslation: And on the Day of Judgment, the disbeliever will say, If only I had been dust!\n\nNote: (Particles resembling verbs: These are particles that resemble verbs, and there are six of them: «إِنَّ، أَنَّ، کَأَنَّ، لٰـکِنَّ، لَیْتَ، لَعَلَّ»)\n\nParticle of wish (حرف تمنی): The word in which an expression of desire is found.","«لَیْتَ» is a word of longing and comes to express regret over past shortcomings.","Alas","لیت","4:73-6:27-18:42-19:23-25:27-25:28-28:79-33:66-36:26-43:38-69:25-69:27-78:40-89:24",14
234,43,"A","اَسَفٰی","«اَسَفَ» refers to the mixed and intertwined feelings of regret and sorrow. When anger befalls a weak person, it takes the form of rage and indignation; but when anger befalls someone towards a more powerful person, it turns into resentment and sorrow, becoming grief and regret. (Mafool 170)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ یٰۤاَسَفٰی عَلٰی یُوۡسُفَ وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ فَہُوَ کَظِیۡمٌ» (12/84)\n\nTranslation: And (Ya'qub عليه السلام) exclaimed, Alas, my sorrow over Yusuf! and his eyes turned white from the grief, and he was suppressing a grief that was overwhelming.","«اَسَفَ» refers to such sorrow and grief that exceeds human endurance.","Alas","اسفی","7:150-12:84-18:6-20:86-43:55",5
235,43,"A","آسٰی","«اَسٰی» meaning: to express regret and sorrow over an opportunity that slips away due to one's negligence or shortcoming (F L 170)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَلَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23)\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what you have missed nor exult over what has been given to you.","«اَسٰی» to lose a good opportunity due to one's own shortcomings, and then regret it.","Alas","آسی","7:93-57:23",2
236,44,"S","مَکَّنَ","«مَکَّنَ» meaning to grant power, to authorize, to empower (from Munjid); to attain position and rank. To stand firm on one's own feet and to be capable of something (from Muhit and Raghib), i.e., to grant someone authority and to bestow governance.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَلَّذِیۡنَ اِنۡ مَّکَّنّٰہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُاالزَّکٰوۃَ وَاَمَرُوۡا بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ نَہَوۡا عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» (22/41) Translation: These are the ones who, if We grant them authority in the land, will establish prayer, pay zakat, and enjoin good and forbid evil.","«مَکَّنَ» is generally used to grant someone authority, discretion, and governance.","Sovereignty","مکن","6:6-7:10-8:71-12:21-12:56-18:84-18:95-22:41-24:55-28:6-28:57-46:26",12
237,44,"A","اِسْتَخْلَفَ","«اِسْتَخْلَفَ» meaning to appoint someone as a successor or deputy (manjada, m, r), and «خَلَفَ» meaning to come after or to be someone's successor.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَعَدَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ لَیَسۡتَخۡلِفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (24/55)\nTranslation: Allah has promised those among you who believe and do righteous deeds that He will surely grant them succession [to authority] upon the earth just as He granted it to those before them and that He will surely establish for them their religion which He has chosen for them.\n\nThus, the word «اِسْتِخْلَاف» also implies that the present authority is in the hands of wrongdoers, and that those who believe in Allah and do good deeds will have this existing governance transformed and authority transferred to them.","«اِسْتَخْلَفَ» meaning to appoint someone as a successor or deputy.","Authority","استخلف","6:133-7:129-11:57-24:55-57:7",5
238,45,"P","اَقْرَرَ","«اِقْرَار» Its original root is «قَرَار», meaning to settle firmly in a place and to remain steadfast. And the meaning of «اَقْرَرَ» is to become firmly established on something (source: ref). And 'iqrar' generally pertains to a matter or promise that relates to the future, i.e., remaining steadfast and firm on a promise.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n\n«قَالَ ءَاَقۡرَرۡتُمۡ وَ اَخَذۡتُمۡ عَلٰی ذٰلِکُمۡ اِصۡرِیۡ ؕ قَالُوۡۤا اَقۡرَرۡنَا ؕ قَالَ فَاشۡہَدُوۡا وَ اَنَا مَعَکُمۡ مِّنَ الشّٰہِدِیۡنَ» (3/81)\n\nTranslation: Allah asked (after taking the covenant from the prophets), Have you affirmed and taken responsibility for this affirmation (i.e., made Me your guarantor)? They said, Yes! We have affirmed. Allah commanded, Then be witnesses of this covenant, and I will be a witness with you.","The meaning of «اِقْرَار» is to become firmly established upon something, and to remain steadfast upon a covenant or pledge.","Profession (of faith)","اقرر","2:84-3:81",2
239,45,"P","اِعْتَرَفَ","«عَرَفَ» means to recognize someone, and «اَعْتَرَفَ» means to confess one's crime and to be humiliated and abased (m. r.). It is as if the sinner is already aware and acquainted with his crime beforehand. When he himself confesses it, it is called an acknowledgment, and the crime in question pertains to the past, which he has confessed.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا  لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» (67/11)\nTranslation: So (the guilty ones) will confess their sins. So away with the people of Hellfire.","«اِعْتَرَفَ» confessing to a past crime.","Profession of faith.","اعترف","9:102-40:11-67:11",3
240,45,"D","شَھِدَ","«شَھِدَ» signifies testimony or shahadah. This testimony is of two kinds. The first is eyewitness testimony—a fact about which a person has absolute certainty and which he attests to before a judge. The second is the testimony of the heart, exemplified by the Shahadah. Every Muslim bears witness to it, even though they have not seen Allah, and apart from the Companions (may Allah be pleased with them), no other Muslim has seen the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) either. Moreover, when this heart-felt testimony pertains to oneself, it means to confess.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا شَہِدۡنَا عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِنَا وَ غَرَّتۡہُمُ الۡحَیٰوۃُ الدُّنۡیَا» (6/130)\nTranslation: They will say, Our Lord, we confess our sins, and those people were deluded by the life of this world.","«شَھِدَ» meaning testimony: the acknowledgment of a matter that pertains to oneself.","Declaration of faith","شھد","2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21",60
241,46,"A","اَحَد","«اَحَد» means The One or Unique. It is incomparable (from *manjad*). In this regard, this term is applied exclusively to the Essence of the Divine (Allah). For non-divine entities, the word «وَاحِد» (Wahid, meaning One in a numerical sense) is used (as cited in *Mufradat*). However, there are two instances where the word «اَحَد» appears as a synonym (radif) for Wahid (coming later in the text): (1) In cardinal numbers and their combinations, such as «اَحَدَ عَشَرَ ، اَحَدَھُمَ ، اَحَدٌ مِّنْکُم ، اَحَدُکُم ، یَوَمُ الْاَحَد» (three), etc. (2) In the form of negation, it is used only for beings possessing intellect, such as in «لَیْسَ فِی الدَّارِاَحَدٌ» (There is none in the house).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» (69:47)\nTranslation: Then not one of you would have been able to hinder Us.\n\nAnd the word Wahid is general. It is used uniformly for Allah the Almighty and for all others besides Him. And Ahad is one of the names of Allah, the meaning of which is The One. For instance, «ھُوَ اللہُ الْوَاحِدُ الْقَھَّارُ». But when we say «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ» (112:1),\nTranslation: Say, 'He is Allah, the One.'\n\nWe mean by this that He is Unique, Matchless, and Non-dual. And in these meanings, this term is specific to the Essence of the Divine.","«اَحَد» Unique and unparalleled, used in the sense of being exclusively for Allah, the Most High, or for a created being that has no equal.","Alone","احد","2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:4-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4",72
242,46,"A","وَحِیْد","«وَاحِد» and «وَحِیْد» are both terms used for something that is unique and singular in creation, having no equal. For example, «اَلشَّمْسُ وَاحِدَۃٌ» (the sun is one) or «فُلَانٌ وَاحِدُ عَصْرِہٖ» (so-and-so is alone in his livelihood). The word «وَحِیْد» is also used in these same meanings.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا» (74/11)\nTranslation: Let us deal with him who was created alone.\n\nThis verse relates to Walid ibn Mughirah, who at that time had no equal in offspring and in honor and wealth.","«وَحِیْد» is peerless and unparalleled; in those contexts, it is used for created beings.","alone","وحید","74:11",1
243,46,"A","فَرْد","«فَرَدَ» meaning alone, power, a single-heeled shoe (idiom). It is said.  \n«ھٰذَا شَیْءٌ فَرْدٌ» meaning this is a unique thing. (Monjad) and 'fard' refers to a thing that has no equal. This term is commonly derived from 'witr' (odd: opposite of even) and specifically from 'wahid' (one). Its singular form is 'mufrad,' and its plural is 'afrad,' meaning all separate.  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَزَکَرِیَّاۤ اِذۡ نَادٰی رَبَّہٗ رَبِّ لَا تَذَرۡنِیۡ فَرۡدًا وَّاَنۡتَ خَیۡرُالۡوٰرِثِیۡنَ» (21/89)  \nTranslation: And [mention] Zakariya, when he called his Lord, saying, My Lord! Do not leave me alone, and You are the best of inheritors.","«فَرَدَ» is used for a single individual.","Alone","فرد","19:80-19:95-21:89",3
244,46,"A","فُرَادٰی","«فرٰادٰی» is a plural form, the meaning of which is the one who goes alone. It is said that «جَاءُوْا فُرَادٰی» all came alone, all alone. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَقَدۡ جِئۡتُمُوۡنَا فُرَادٰی کَمَا خَلَقۡنٰکُمۡ  اَوَّلَ مَرَّۃٍ» (6/94)\n\nTranslation: And as We produced you the first time, so [now] you come alone to Us.","«فرٰادٰی» They say to those who depart one by one.","Alone","فرادی","6:94-34:46",2
245,47,"T","اِجْتَثَّ","«جَثّ» means to uproot from the very root, to eradicate, and «مَجَثَّہ» refers to the kind of uprooting tool used for grass, etc. (a spade or hoe). And «جَثِیْثَۃ» is the term for a date palm sapling that has been uprooted and replanted elsewhere. (Mufradat) And «اِجْتَثَّ» is also used in these same meanings. The word «جَثَّ» is used for uprooting grass, weeds, and small plants.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَمَثَلُ کَلِمَۃٍ خَبِیۡثَۃٍ کَشَجَرَۃٍ خَبِیۡثَۃِۣ اجۡتُثَّتۡ مِنۡ فَوۡقِ الۡاَرۡضِ مَا لَہَا مِنۡ قَرَارٍ» (14/26)\nTranslation: And the example of a wicked statement is like a wicked tree, uprooted from upon the earth; it has no stability.\n\nNote: (Uprooting/Eradication: meaning to annihilate and destroy something, to uproot by the root, to dig out the root, to cut off the lineage, to exterminate utterly).","«جَثَّ» is used for uprooting small plants and grass (i.e., removing them).","to uproot","اجتث","14:26",1
246,47,"T","اِنْقَعَر","The term «قَعَرَ» refers to the lower part of the depth and inner surface of something, while «اَقْعَرَ الْبِئْر» means to dig a well deeply, and «اَقْعَرَ الشَّجر» means to uproot a tree. According to Ibn al-Faris, it means uprooting something whose roots have penetrated deep into the ground (m, l). And the author of al-Muntaha al-Arbab interprets it as: after uprooting the tree, then throwing it onto the ground (m. a). Thus, the term «اَقْعَرَ» is used for the uprooting of such large trees whose roots have extended deep into the earth over a great distance, and «اِنْقَعَر» refers to when that action occurs or becomes manifest on that thing.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is: «تَنۡزِعُ  النَّاسَ ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ مُّنۡقَعِرٍ» (54/20)\nTranslation: It (the stormy wind) would uproot people as if they were uprooted palm tree roots.\n\nNote: (Uprooting: meaning to annihilate and destroy something, to demolish, to uproot from the roots, to dig up the roots, to cut off lineage, to utterly ruin).","«اِنْقَعَرَ» is used for uprooting large trees whose roots extend quite deep.","to uproot","انقعر","54:20",1
247,48,"T","جَمَعَ","The word «جَمَعَ» is used to gather together the various parts of one thing, or different things. These things may be animate or inanimate.\n\nFor example, for animate objects: The command of Allah, the Most High, is: «اَلَّذِیۡنَ  قَالَ لَہُمُ النَّاسُ  اِنَّ النَّاسَ قَدۡ جَمَعُوۡا لَکُمۡ» (3:173)\nTranslation: When those people came and reported that the disbelievers have gathered a great army against you.\n\nAnd for inanimate objects: The command of Allah, the Most High, is: «الَّذِیۡ جَمَعَ  مَالًا  وَّ عَدَّدَہٗ» (104:2)\nTranslation: He who gathered wealth and then continued to count it.\n\nThen the word جمع is also used for gathering external things. It is also used in a spiritual sense.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «فَتَوَلّٰی فِرۡعَوۡنُ فَجَمَعَ  کَیۡدَہٗ  ثُمَّ  اَتٰی» (20:60)\nTranslation: Then Pharaoh turned back, gathered all his schemes, then came. (Uthmani)","«جَمَعَ» The word jama is general. The term jama is used to denote the gathering together of either the various components of a single entity or distinct items.","Together","جمع","2:29-2:38-2:148-2:161-2:165-3:25-3:87-3:103-3:155-3:157-3:166-3:173-4:23-4:71-4:87-4:139-4:140-4:172-5:17-5:32-5:36-5:48-5:105-5:109-6:12-6:22-6:35-6:128-6:149-7:18-7:38-7:48-7:124-7:158-8:37-8:41-8:63-10:4-10:28-10:58-10:65-10:99-11:55-11:119-12:15-12:83-12:93-13:18-13:31-13:42-14:8-14:21-15:30-15:39-15:43-15:59-15:92-16:9-17:103-18:60-18:61-18:99-20:60-20:64-20:123-21:77-24:31-24:61-26:38-26:49-26:56-26:61-26:65-26:95-26:170-27:51-28:78-32:13-34:26-34:40-35:10-36:32-36:53-37:134-38:73-38:82-38:85-39:44-39:47-39:53-39:67-42:7-42:15-42:29-43:32-43:55-44:40-45:13-45:26-54:44-54:45-58:6-58:18-59:14-64:9-70:14-70:18-75:3-75:9-75:17-77:38-100:5-104:2",113
248,48,"G","اِجْتَمَعَ","The term «اِجْتَمَعَ» is used exclusively for the gathering of those possessing intellect, whether they are of the same kind or different kinds. For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡ لَّئِنِ اجۡتَمَعَتِ الۡاِنۡسُ وَ الۡجِنُّ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡا بِمِثۡلِ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ لَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ بِمِثۡلِہٖ» (17/88). Translation: Say, 'If all of mankind and the jinn were to gather together to produce something like this Quran, they would not be able to.'","«اِجْتَمَعَ» is used solely for gathering living creatures.","gathered","اجتمع","17:88-22:73-26:39",3
249,48,"T","حَشَرَ","The word is used for living beings, meaning to take people from their places to a specific location (singular), and Ibn al-Faris also confirms this meaning. He writes «اَلْحَشْرُ الْجَمْعُ مَعَ سَوْق» (as follows).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «فَحَشَرَ فَنَادٰی فَقَالَ اَنَا رَبُّکُمُ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (79/23,24) Translation: So Pharaoh gathered (the people) and called out. He began to say, I am your greatest lord.\n\nThen this word is sometimes also used in the meanings of «بَعَثَ» or «اَنْبِعَاث» (i.e.), meaning to give life to the dead or to take for a specific purpose. See the following example in the meaning of «بَعَثَ»:\n\nFor example: The Divine Command of Allah, the Most High, is: «قَالَ رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی وَ قَدۡ کُنۡتُ  بَصِیۡرًا» (20/125) Translation: He will say, My Lord! Why did You raise me up blind, while I used to see?\n\nAnd sometimes in the usage of this word, all the meanings of «تَجَمَّع ، سُوْق» and «بَعَث» are found. For example: In the Noble Quran it is: «وَ یَوۡمَ نُسَیِّرُ الۡجِبَالَ وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ بَارِزَۃً ۙ وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہُمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/47) Translation: And on the Day when We will move the mountains, and you will see the earth as a level plain, and We will gather them all together, not leaving anyone of them.","«حَشَرَ» denotes assembly, crowd, or throng, and is used to describe the act of gathering animals by raising them from their resting places to a single location.","Together","حشر","2:203-3:12-3:158-4:172-5:96-6:22-6:38-6:51-6:72-6:111-6:128-8:24-8:36-10:28-10:45-15:25-17:97-18:47-19:68-19:85-20:59-20:102-20:124-20:125-23:79-25:17-25:34-27:17-27:83-34:40-37:22-41:19-46:6-50:44-58:9-59:2-67:24-79:23-81:5",39
250,48,"G","اِدَّخَرَ","Its original root is «ذَخَر», the meaning of which is to stockpile edible items, i.e., food and drink items, for future needs. To store (transitive) and this storage is also carried out by many living beings besides humans. Ibn Faris writes two fundamental aspects in its meaning: to gather together and to preserve it (m. l), and «اِدَّخَرَ» also comes in this same meaning, and the gathered thing is called «ذخر» and «ذخیرہ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ بِمَا تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ وَمَا تَدَّخِرُوۡنَ ۙ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ» (3/49)\nTranslation: (Jesus, peace be upon him, said) And I inform you of what you eat and what you store up in your houses.","«اِدَّخَرَ» is used to gather necessities for the future.","Gathered together","ادخر","3:49",1
251,48,"T","خَزَنَ","The word ذخیرہ (treasury/store) is generally used for gathering food items. However, the term «خَزَنَ» is broader than this. It often refers to the accumulation of wealth and riches, which is «خَزَنْتُ الدَّرَاھِمَ», but its fundamental meaning emphasizes protection more than accumulation. It is said, «خَزَنْتُ السِّرَّ» (I have kept the secret/gathering secure) (peace be upon him), and a person who is the guardian of this gathered thing or wealth is called «خَازِنْ», and its plural form is «خَزَنَۃُ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا  فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ » (67/8)\nTranslation: When a group is thrown into it (Hell), its keepers (guardian wardens) will ask them, Did no warner come to you?\n\nAnd where any thing is gathered, that place is called «خِزَانَہ» and «خَزِیْنَہ», and its plural is «خَزَائِن». In the cited verse, the gathered things are the sinful people, the Hell-treasure, and the wardens or its guardians, i.e., the keepers.","«خَزَنَ» is used to safeguard gathered possessions.","Together","خزن","6:50-11:31-12:55-15:21-15:22-17:100-38:9-39:71-39:73-40:49-52:37-63:7-67:8",13
252,48,"T","وَسَقَ ۔ اِتسَقَ","The meaning of «وَسَقَ» is to gather and lift things (see: Majid, p. ‌م ل). And «اَوْسَقَ» means to load a burden on an animal. And «وَسَقْتُ الشَّیْءَ» means to gather the scattered parts of something. And «اِتَّسَقَ» means that all the parts of that thing have been gathered and it has become complete. (f)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّیۡلِ وَ مَا وَسَقَ وَ الۡقَمَرِ اِذَا اتَّسَقَ» (84/17,18)\n\nTranslation: And by the night and what it gathers, and by the moon when it becomes full.","«وَسَقَ» is used to gather components related to the same thing.","Together","وسق ۔ اتسق","84:17-84:18",2
253,48,"G","کَفَتَ","«کَفَتَ» meaning to gather something and take it into one's possession (trans.) to take hold of, to gather. And «کَفِیْت» meaning a provision container in which food and provisions are stored and kept. For example: «اَللّٰھُمَّ اکْفِہٖ». Or, O Allah, take it into Your custody (from *Manjad*).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَمۡ نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ  کِفَاتًا اَحۡیَآءً وَّاَمۡوَاتًا» (77/25,26)\nTranslation: Did We not make the earth a gatherer? (i.e., for the living and the dead).","«کَفَتَ» meaning to collect and take into possession, to gather up.","Gathered","کفت","77:25",1
254,48,"T","لَمَّ","It means to gather something and then arrange it or set it right (fig.).  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَتَاۡکُلُوۡنَ التُّرَاثَ اَکۡلًا لَّمًّا» (89/19)  \nTranslation: And you consume the inheritance, devouring it together.","«لَمَّ» collecting and improving it, that is, correcting it.","Together","لم","89:19",1
255,48,"G","حَصَّلَ ۔ التحصیل","«حَصَّلَ» means to extract the kernel and the essence from the shell (i.e., to separate). In the meaning of «حَصَّلَ», two things are understood: (1) to extract, (2) to gather. For example, the Quran states: «وَحُصِّلَ مَا فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (10:100). Translation: And the hidden things of the breasts will be brought to light. Its meaning is that whatever secrets are in the breasts will be extracted and gathered in such a manner as the kernel is separated from the shell.","«حَصَّلَ» to take out and collect.","Gathered","حصل ۔ التحصیل","100:10",1
256,48,"T","مثابۃ","«مَثابَۃ» is derived from the word 'ثوب', and its original meaning is the return of something to its original state. They say «ثَابَ فُلَانٌالیٰ دَارَہ». That is, so-and-so returned to his home, and «مَثابَۃ» refers to the place built at the mouth of a well for drawing water (muf). Because people would repeatedly return to such a place to drink water and take it away, and they would gather there. Therefore, it is called «مَثابَۃ». By the same analogy, Allah the Exalted has called the Honorable House of Allah «مَثابَۃ». Here, people come repeatedly to quench their spiritual thirst and gather.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا» (2/125)\nTranslation: And when We designated the House as a place of gathering and safety for the people.","The connotative and allusive meaning of «مَثَابَۃ» is found to be to gather. Its literal meaning is to keep coming repeatedly.","together","مثابۃ","2:125",1
257,49,"I","اِنْ","«اِنْ» is a conditional particle. It is used for the future tense. Its first clause is always conditional, and the second clause (the consequent) follows.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«اِنۡ تُعَذِّبۡہُمۡ فَاِنَّہُمۡ عِبَادُکَ» (5/118)  \nTranslation: If You punish them, they are Your servants.","«اِنْ» In Arabic grammar, this is called a conditional particle. It is used for the future tense.","If","ان","2:23-2:24-2:31-2:70-2:78-2:85-2:91-2:93-2:94-2:11-2:137-2:143-2:172-2:180-2:184-2:191-2:192-2:193-2:196-2:198-2:209-2:217-2:220-2:226-2:227-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:236-2:237-2:239-2:240-2:246-2:248-2:265-2:271-2:278-2:279-2:280-2:282-2:283-2:284-2:286-3:20-3:29-3:31-3:32-3:49-3:63-3:64-3:75-3:93-3:100-3:111-3:118-3:120-3:125-3:139-3:140-3:144-3:149-3:160-3:164-3:168-3:175-3:179-3:183-3:184-3:186-4:3-4:4-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:15-4:16-4:19-4:20-4:23-4:25-4:31-4:34-4:35-4:40-4:43-4:59-4:62-4:72-4:78-4:89-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:101-4:102-4:104-4:117-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:149-4:159-4:170-4:176-5:6-5:17-5:22-5:23-5:41-5:42-5:49-5:57-5:67-5:73-5:92-5:101-5:106-5:107-5:110-5:112-5:116-5:118-6:7-6:15-6:17-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:35-6:40-6:41-6:46-6:47-6:50-6:57-6:70-6:81-6:89-6:90-6:116-6:118-6:121-6:133-6:139-6:143-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:156-7:23-7:70-7:77-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:102-7:106-7:113-7:131-7:143-7:146-7:155-7:169-7:176-7:184-7:188-7:193-7:194-7:198-8:1-8:19-8:29-8:31-8:32-8:34-8:38-8:39-8:40-8:41-8:61-8:62-8:65-8:66-8:70-8:71-8:72-9:3-9:5-9:6-9:8-9:11-9:12-9:13-9:23-9:24-9:28-9:41-9:50-9:58-9:62-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:83-9:96-9:107-9:129-10:15-10:29-10:38-10:41-10:48-10:50-10:66-10:68-10:71-10:72-10:84-10:94-10:104-10:106-10:107-11:3-11:7-11:13-11:28-11:29-11:30-11:32-11:33-11:34-11:35-11:38-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:57-11:63-11:86-11:88-12:3-12:10-12:26-12:27-12:31-12:40-12:43-12:60-12:67-12:74-12:77-12:91-12:99-12:104-13:5-13:40-14:8-14:10-14:11-14:19-14:34-14:46-15:7-15:21-15:71-15:78-16:18-16:37-16:43-16:82-16:95-16:114-16:126-17:7-17:8-17:25-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:54-17:58-17:73-17:76-17:108-18:5-18:6-18:20-18:29-18:39-18:57-18:69-18:70-18:76-19:18-19:71-19:93-20:7-20:63-20:103-20:104-21:7-21:17-21:34-21:36-21:38-21:47-21:63-21:68-21:109-21:111-22:5-22:11-22:41-22:42-22:68-22:73-23:25-23:30-23:37-23:38-23:83-23:84-23:88-23:107-23:114-24:2-24:7-24:9-24:17-24:28-24:32-24:33-24:49-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:10-25:41-25:42-25:44-26:4-26:24-26:28-26:31-26:40-26:41-26:97-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:180-26:186-26:187-26:205-26:216-27:64-27:68-27:71-27:81-28:10-28:19-28:27-28:49-28:50-28:57-28:71-28:72-29:8-29:16-29:18-29:29-30:36-30:49-30:53-30:58-31:15-31:16-32:28-33:5-33:13-33:16-33:17-33:20-33:24-33:28-33:29-33:32-33:50-33:54-34:9-34:29-34:43-34:46-34:47-34:50-35:4-35:14-35:16-35:18-35:23-35:24-35:25-35:40-35:41-36:15-36:23-36:29-36:32-36:43-36:47-36:48-36:53-36:69-37:15-37:56-37:102-37:157-37:167-38:7-38:14-38:70-38:87-39:7-39:13-39:38-39:56-40:12-40:28-40:29-40:56-41:13-41:24-41:37-41:38-41:49-41:52-42:24-42:33-42:48-43:20-43:35-43:59-43:81-44:7-44:21-44:35-44:36-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:4-46:8-46:9-46:10-46:22-46:26-47:7-47:22-47:36-47:37-47:38-48:11-48:16-48:27-49:6-49:9-49:14-49:17-52:34-52:44-53:4-53:23-53:28-54:2-55:33-56:86-56:87-56:88-56:90-56:92-57:8-58:2-58:12-59:11-60:1-60:2-60:10-60:11-61:11-62:2-62:6-62:9-63:4-64:12-64:14-64:17-65:4-65:6-66:4-66:5-67:9-67:20-67:21-67:25-67:28-67:30-68:22-68:41-68:51-71:27-72:25-73:17-74:24-74:25-77:39-81:27-86:4-87:9-96:11-96:13",531
258,49,"I","اِمَّا","When « اِنْ ۔ مَا » appears as a conditional particle, it only conveys the meaning of «اِنْ». «مَا» is a particle of excess and is used solely for the rhetorical beauty, i.e., the embellishment of speech.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِمَّا یَبۡلُغَنَّ عِنۡدَکَ الۡکِبَرَ اَحَدُہُمَاۤ» (17/23)\nTranslation: If either of them (the parents) reaches old age in your presence.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«فَاِمَّا تَرَیِنَّ مِنَ الۡبَشَرِ اَحَدًا» (19/26)\nTranslation: So (O Maryam!) if you see any man.","In Arabic grammar, when «اِمَّا» occurs in the sense of if, it includes the redundant particle «مَا», which appears solely for emphasis.","If","اما","2:38-6:68-7:35-7:115-7:200-8:57-8:58-9:106-10:46-17:23-17:28-18:86-19:26-19:75-20:65-20:123-23:93-40:77-41:36-43:41-47:4-76:3",22
259,49,"I","لَوْ","«لَوْ» is a conditional particle, but its consequence clause is always subordinate to the condition (i.e., a condition is stipulated for the sake of an action), and the particle 'lam' (لام) is incorporated into the consequence.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:\n«لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ» (9/42)\nTranslation: If the spoils of war were near and the journey also short, then (O Prophet (peace be upon him)) these people would have followed you.\n\nAnd if «وَ» precedes «لَوْ», as in «وَلَو», it conveys the meaning of even if.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوۡجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ» (4/78)\nTranslation: Wherever you may be, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified towers.\n\nAnd by adding «لَا» after «لَوْ», the meaning of if not is produced.\n\nFor instance, the divine declaration states:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ لَکُنَّا مُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (34/31)\nTranslation: If you were not, then we would certainly have been believers.","«لَوْ» is bound by a condition of recompense (i.e., a condition stipulated in return for an action).","If","لو","2:20-2:64-2:96-2:102-2:103-2:109-2:251-2:165-2:167-2:220-2:221-2:253-3:30-3:69-3:91-3:110-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-3:168-4:9-4:39-4:42-4:46-4:64-4:66-4:78-4:82-4:83-4:89-4:90-4:102-4:113-4:129-4:135-5:36-5:48-5:65-5:66-5:81-5:100-5:106-6:7-6:8-6:9-6:27-6:28-6:30-6:35-6:58-6:88-6:93-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:137-6:148-6:149-6:152-6:157-7:43-7:96-7:100-7:155-7:176-7:188-8:8-8:19-8:23-8:31-8:42-8:43-8:50-8:63-8:68-9:32-9:33-9:42-9:46-9:47-9:57-9:59-9:81-9:113-10:11-10:16-10:19-10:42-10:43-10:54-10:82-10:97-10:99-11:80-11:91-11:110-11:118-12:17-12:24-12:94-12:103-13:18-13:31-14:21-15:2-15:7-15:14-16:9-16:35-16:41-16:61-16:93-17:42-17:74-17:88-17:95-17:100-18:18-18:58-18:77-18:109-20:129-20:134-21:17-21:22-21:39-21:99-22:40-22:73-23:24-23:71-23:75-23:114-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:35-25:42-25:45-25:51-25:77-26:102-26:113-26:198-28:10-28:47-28:64-28:82-29:41-29:53-29:64-31:27-32:12-32:13-33:14-33:20-33:52-34:14-34:31-34:51-35:14-35:18-35:45-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:57-37:143-37:168-39:4-39:26-39:47-39:57-39:58-40:14-41:14-41:44-41:45-42:8-42:14-42:21-42:27-43:20-43:33-43:60-46:11-47:4-47:21-47:30-48:22-48:25-49:5-49:7-56:65-56:70-56:76-58:22-59:3-59:9-59:21-60:2-61:8-61:9-67:10-68:9-68:33-68:49-69:44-70:11-71:4-75:15-102:5",214
260,50,"R","اَرْکَسَ","The meaning of «اَرْکَسَ» is to turn something upside down on its head (i.e., head down and feet up) or to reverse its front and back, making it inside out.  \n«اَرْکَسَ الثَّوبُ فِی الصَّبْغِ» means to dye cloth by turning it inside out in the dye.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَرۡکَسَہُمۡ بِمَا کَسَبُوۡا» (4/88)  \nTranslation: God has turned those (hypocrites) upside down because of their misdeeds.","To turn something upside down (i.e., with the head down and legs up).","Reverse","ارکس","4:88-4:91",2
261,50,"O","اِئْتَفَکَ","«اَفَکَ» means to turn someone to the correct direction (m. l.). And if someone is flipped to a direction other than the correct one, it is called «اِئْتَفَکَ» (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُؤۡتَفِکَۃَ  اَہۡوٰی» (53/53)\nTranslation: And He overturned the overturned towns.","«اِئْتَفَکَ» to prostrate facing a direction other than the qibla.","Opposite","ائتفک","9:70-53:53-69:9",3
262,50,"O","جَثَمَ","«جَثَمَ» A bird sitting chest-down on the ground and then clinging to it (Fall 186). Figuratively, it means a person lying prostrate on the ground.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الرَّجۡفَۃُ فَاَصۡبَحُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِہِمۡ  جٰثِمِیۡنَ» (7/78)\nTranslation: So the earthquake seized them, and they lay prostrate in their homes.","Prostration or adhering in that position.","Opposite","جثم","7:78-7:91-11:67-11:94-29:37",5
263,50,"O","کَبَّ","The meaning of «کَبَّ الْاِنَاءَ» is to turn a vessel upside down and place it (from 'munjad'), and the meaning of «کَبَّ فُلَانًا» is to throw someone face down (from 'muf').  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ مَنۡ جَآءَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ  فَکُبَّتۡ وُجُوۡہُہُمۡ  فِی النَّارِ» (27/90)  \nTranslation: And whoever brings an evil deed will be thrown face down into Hellfire.","«کَبَّ» to bring someone to their knees","Opposite","کب","26:94-27:90-67:22",3
264,50,"R","کَبْکَبَ","«کَبْکَبَ» involves verbal repetition that also intensifies its meanings, implying to throw something down from above into a pit.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «فَکُبۡکِبُوۡا فِیۡہَا  ہُمۡ  وَ الۡغَاوٗنَ» (26/94).  \nTranslation: So they and the misguided (i.e., the idols and idolaters) will be thrown upside down into the Hellfire.","«کَبْکَبَ» to topple headfirst into a pit/hole.","Reverse","کبکب","26:94",1
265,50,"O","قَلَّب","«تَقْلِیْبُ الشَّیء» means to turn something and return it from one state to another, and «قَلّب الثَّوْب» means to turn clothes inside out. «قلّب» is used in both material and spiritual senses.\n\nExample of its material usage:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«یَوۡمَ تُقَلَّبُ وُجُوۡہُہُمۡ فِی النَّارِ» (33:66)\nTranslation: On the Day when their faces will be turned in the Fire.\n\nExample of its spiritual usage:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«لَقَدِ ابۡتَغَوُا الۡفِتۡنَۃَ  مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ وَ قَلَّبُوۡا لَکَ الۡاُمُوۡرَ حَتّٰی جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ» (9:48)\nTranslation: They had already been intent on discord before and turned things upside down for you until the truth came.","«قَلّب» to reverse or completely overturn the state or condition of something.","opposite","قلب","2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:227-29:21-33:66-43:14-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9",27
266,50,"O","نَکَسَ ، نَکَّسَ","«نَکَسَ» meaning to reverse and «نَکَسَ رَأْسَہٗ» meaning to bow the head in humiliation or shame (this is used idiomatically), and «نَکِسَ الْمَرِیْض» meaning the patient falling ill again, and «اَلنُّکَاس» meaning the return of the disease and falling and not recovering, and then falling again with greater force than before, and «اَلنََکَس» meaning very old people, and «نَکَّسَ» meaning to turn upside down. «اِنْتَکَسَ» meaning to fall on one's head. To fall ill again. (as cited)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n\n«ثُمَّ  نُکِسُوۡا عَلٰی  رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ» (21/65) Translation: Then, feeling ashamed, he bowed his head.\n\nAt another place, the divine command is:\n\n«وَ مَنۡ نُّعَمِّرۡہُ  نُنَکِّسۡہُ  فِی الۡخَلۡقِ» (36/68) Translation: And whom We cause to grow old, We then return to the state of infancy.","«نَکَسَ» means to invert completely, i.e., placing the head down and the feet up. This is the worst possible state for any person.  \nAnd « نَکَّسَ » means to reverse or turn upside down.","Opposite","نکس ، نکس","21:65-36:68",2
267,51,"S","فَرَقَ","«فَرَقَ» means to split something apart and separate it into distinct parts. (Separate) Then that separated thing is called «فِرْق», and if those separate things are groups of people, they are called a faction. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ» (2/50) Translation: And when We split the sea apart for you. At another instance, the divine command states: «فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63) Translation: So the sea split, and each part became as if it were a massive mountain. Furthermore, «فَرَقَ» is also used metaphorically. That is, for two types of things that appear to be one but are fundamentally distinct, it is used in the sense of separating them. For example, the Quran states: «قَالَ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ  لَاۤ  اَمۡلِکُ اِلَّا نَفۡسِیۡ وَ اَخِیۡ فَافۡرُقۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الۡفٰسِقِیۡنَ» (5/25) Translation: Moses implored (God), 'O Lord! I have no control over anyone except myself and my brother, so separate between us and these rebellious people.' And «فَرَّقَ» means to separate from a group, to form a distinct faction. For example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ فَرَّقُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ  وَ کَانُوۡا  شِیَعًا» (6/159) Translation: Those who have made many paths in their religion and have become divided into numerous sects. (Jalandhari)","to tear something apart and separate it into pieces","Separate","فرق","2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-30:14-30:32-42:13-42:14-44:4-77:4-98:4",32
268,51,"S","فَتَقَ","The meaning of «فَتَقَ» is to create a large fissure in something and split it open, such as splitting open the musk pod (the pouch in which the musk deer stores musk). Or, to separate two joined things, and its opposite is «رَتَقَ», meaning something mixed up and intertwined. For example, the Quran states:\n«اَنَّ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ کَانَتَا رَتۡقًا فَفَتَقۡنٰہُمَا» (21/30)\nTranslation: The heavens and the earth were a single entity, so We split them apart.","To tear something open, or to separate mixed things.","Separate","فتق","21:30",1
269,51,"S","عَزَلَ","«عَزَلَ» To separate someone from their original work or purpose. To render idle. To set aside (as in M, Manj). The word 'mu'azzal' (deposed/removed) is also derived from this, referring to a person who has been removed from their work. And «عُزْلَت» comes in the meanings of 'corner of solitude'.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنِ ابۡتَغَیۡتَ مِمَّنۡ عَزَلۡتَ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکَ» (33:51)\nTranslation: And there is no blame upon you if you invite [to marriage] those [wives] you have divorced [and then take them back], should you wish to do so.","«عَزَلَ» to detach someone from their work.","Separate","عزل","11:42-33:51",2
270,51,"S","جَنَبَ","The basic meanings of «جَنَبَ» are two: (1) side/aspect, and (2) to be distant. The derived meaning of «جَنَبَ» is to save someone by keeping them distant from a calamity or affliction.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذۡ قَالَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمُ رَبِّ اجۡعَلۡ ہٰذَا الۡبَلَدَ اٰمِنًا وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ» (14/35)\n\nTranslation: And when Abraham prayed, My Lord, make this city a place of security and save me and my offspring from ever having to worship idols.","«جَنَبَ» to separate someone from a calamity.","Separate","جنب","14:35-87:11-92:17",3
271,51,"S","مَازَ","«مَازَ» means to separate one thing from another based on a notion of superiority and preference, and «مَا زَالشَّیء» means to give preference to a thing over other things. To give preference (manjīd).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَا کَانَ اللّٰہُ لِیَذَرَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ عَلٰی مَاۤ اَنۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ حَتّٰی یَمِیۡزَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنَ الطَّیِّبِ» (3/179)\nTranslation: O people! Until Allah separates the impure from the pure, He will never leave the believers in the state you are in.","«مَازَ» To separate or distinguish something from another based on superiority or preference.","separate","ماز","3:179-8:37",2
272,51,"S","زَیَّلَ","«زیَّلَ» means to remove something from its original place and separate it from others. «زَالَ عَنْ مَکَانِہٖ» means to remove something from its place, and «زَیَّل» means to remove someone from their place or to separate/disperse them (manjad). For example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «وَ یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُہُمۡ جَمِیۡعًا ثُمَّ نَقُوۡلُ لِلَّذِیۡنَ اَشۡرَکُوۡا مَکَانَکُمۡ اَنۡتُمۡ وَ شُرَکَآؤُکُمۡ ۚ فَزَیَّلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمۡ» (10/28). Translation: And on the Day We will gather them all together, then We will say to the polytheists, Remain you and your partners in your places. Then We will cause separation between them.","To isolate someone by moving or removing them from a place.","Separate","زیل","10:28",1
273,51,"S","تَفَرَّقَ","«تَفَرَّقَ» is the opposite of «تَجَمُّع». That is, to become separate and scattered, to split apart and divide (Manjada).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اعۡتَصِمُوۡا بِحَبۡلِ اللّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا وَّ لَا تَفَرَّقُوۡا» (3:103)\n\nTranslation: And hold firmly to the rope of Allah all together and do not become divided.","to separate and disperse from the group","Separate","تفرق","3:103-3:105-4:130-6:153-12:39-12:67-30:14-42:13-42:14-98:4",10
274,51,"S","اِعْتَزَلَ","«اِعْتَزَل» To dissociate oneself from something, whether from an action or a belief. That is, whether this dissociation is outward or spiritual, «اِعْتَزَلَ» is used in all situations.\n\nNow observe their examples:\n\nExample of dissociation from beliefs, i.e., spiritual dissociation:\n\nAllah, the Most High, says: «وَاِنۡ لَّمۡ تُؤۡمِنُوۡا لِیۡ فَاعۡتَزِلُوۡنِ» (44/21)\n\nTranslation: If you do not believe in me, then separate from me.\n\nExample of dissociation from an action, i.e., outward dissociation:\n\nAllah, the Most High, says: «فَاعۡتَزِلُوا النِّسَآءَ فِی الۡمَحِیۡضِ» (2/222)\n\nTranslation: So keep away from women during menstruation.","«اِعْتَزَل» to choose to distance oneself from an action, a belief, or people.","separate","اعتزل","2:222-4:90-4:91-18:16-19:48-19:49-44:21",7
275,51,"S","تَجَنَّبَ","«تَجَنَّبَ» To keep one's distance; to turn aside (from something).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَیَذَّکَّرُ مَنۡ یَّخۡشٰی وَ  یَتَجَنَّبُہَا الۡاَشۡقَی» (87:10-11)\nTranslation: He who fears (God) will take heed, but the wretched (one without fear) will turn aside.","To separate from something and move far away, «تَجَنَّبَ», in order to attain deliverance from calamity.","Separate","تجنب","87:11",1
276,51,"S","اِمْتَازَ","«اِمْتَازَ» The separation of the good from the bad, or the bad from the good, based on some merit or preference.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَامۡتَازُوا الۡیَوۡمَ اَیُّہَا الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» ( 36/59 )\nTranslation: And O criminals! Today you will be separated.\nApart from this, the following words are also used in the meanings of separation.\n«خَلَا ، خَلَو ، خَلَصَ ، فَصَلَ ، اِنْتَبَذَ ، نَبَذَ ، تَزَیَّلَ ، زَیَّلَ ، اور تَجَافٰی ، جَفَو»","«اِمْتَازَ» to be distinct from others based on a particular characteristic.","Separate","امتاز","36:59",1
277,51,"S","خَلَا","« خَلَاء ، یَخْلُو» refers to an empty space where there are no buildings, houses, or anything else. This term is used for both time and space. For example, «خَلَا الزَّمَان» means time has passed, and in terms of spatial capacity, «خَلَا الرَّجُل» means to meet someone in seclusion (privacy). (Maf Munajid)\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَاِذَا خَلَوۡا اِلٰی شَیٰطِیۡنِہِمۡ ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ» (2/14). Translation: And when they are alone with their devils, they say: 'Indeed, we are with you.' (Ottoman)","«خَلَا» to separate in order to meet in solitude.","Separate","خلا","2:14-2:76-2:214-3:119-10:102-24:34-33:38-33:62-35:24",9
278,51,"S","خَلَصَ","«خَلَصَ» is to purify something from a mixture and to separate that mixture from it, and its opposite is «خَلَطَ».\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا اسۡتَیۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡہُ خَلَصُوۡا نَجِیًّا» (12/80)\nTranslation: When they had lost hope in him, they retired in private to consult among themselves.\nThat is, they went away separately from others to a place where they could consult with one another.","«خَلَصَ» Separation from the original mixture and remaining pure.","Separate","خلص","2:139-4:146-7:29-10:22-12:24-12:54-12:80-15:40-19:51-29:65-31:32-37:40-37:74-37:128-37:160-37:169-38:46-38:83-39:2-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:65-98:5",24
279,51,"S","فَصَلَ","«فَصَلَ» The separation of two things in such a way that a distance comes between them (مف) and departing from a place.\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ  ۙ قَالَ  اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مُبۡتَلِیۡکُمۡ بِنَہَرٍ» (2/249)\nTranslation: So when Talut set out with the armies, he said to them, Indeed, Allah will test you with a river.","«فَصَلَ» To separate two things from each other in such a way that a distance is created between them.","Separate","فصل","2:249-6:65-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-17:12-30:28-41:3-41:44",20
280,51,"S","اِنْتَبَذَ","«نَبَذَ» means to discard something, considering it unworthy of attention (i.e., something that is forgettable and not deserving of regard). «اِنتَبَذَ» means to feel a sense of inferiority and consequently separate oneself from others.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاذۡکُرۡ فِی الۡکِتٰبِ مَرۡیَمَ ۘ اِذِ انۡتَبَذَتۡ مِنۡ اَہۡلِہَا مَکَانًا شَرۡقِیًّا» (19/16)\nTranslation: And mention in the Book (the story of) Mary. When she withdrew from her people to a place in the east.\n\nAt this point, the word «اِنتَبَذَ» was used for Maryam (peace be upon her) because, due to the pregnancy of Prophet Isa (peace be upon him), she had isolated herself from people to avoid their objections, curses, and reproach, seeking solitude.","«اِنْتَبَذَ» to separate from others due to a feeling of inferiority.","Separate","انتبذ","19:16-19:22",2
281,51,"S","تَزَیَّل","«زَالَ» means to remove something from its place (transitive). Similarly, «تَزَیَّلَ» means for something to leave its place and become displaced, to move away.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«لَوۡ تَزَیَّلُوۡا لَعَذَّبۡنَا الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ عَذَابًا اَلِیۡمًا» (48/25)  \nTranslation: And if they had dispersed, We would have punished those among them who disbelieved with a painful punishment.","«تَزَیَّلَ» to leave one's place and step aside to separate.","Separate","تزیل","48:25",1
282,51,"S","تَجَافٰی","«جَفْوَۃٌ» and «جَفَاءٌ» mean injustice, and «جَفَا یَجْفُوا» means not to settle in one place (najada). Consequently, «تَجَافٰی» means to change one's place due to instability or to remain separate from that place. For example, the Quran states: «تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا» (32/16). Translation: They stay away from their beds, and they call upon their Lord with fear and hope.","«تَجَافٰی» detachment from something due to restlessness.","separate","تجافی","32:16",1
283,52,"H","اَمَلَ","The discussion of «اَمَلَ» pertains to a desire and hope that, on the surface, seems unexpected and long-delayed in its occurrence. Thus, the concept of duration and waiting is also found in «اَمَل». In this sense, it conveys the meaning of maintaining hope.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡبٰقِیٰتُ الصّٰلِحٰتُ خَیۡرٌ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ ثَوَابًا وَّخَیۡرٌاَمَلًا» (18/46)\nTranslation: And the good deeds that remain are excellent in terms of reward with your Lord and far better in terms of hope.","«اَمَلَ» is used for a hope that is long-awaited and seemingly unexpected.","Hope","امل","15:3-18:46-47:25",3
284,52,"H","اَمْنٰی","«اَمْنِیَۃ» means false and vain desires, and «اَمَانِی» is its plural. This discussion has also passed through the meaning of to desire («اَمْنٰی»), and the word «اَمْنٰی» comes to mean instilling in someone such false and vain hopes.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ» (4:119)  \nTranslation: (Satan said) And I will certainly lead them astray and arouse false hopes in them.","«اَمْنٰی» is used to give false hopes.","Hope","امنی","4:119-22:52",2
285,52,"H","رجا","«رَجُو رَجَا» has two primary meanings: (1) edge/side, and (2) to hope (m. l.). Here, the second meaning is intended, and within it, the concept of duration and anticipation is found, similar to «اَمَلَ».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاٰخَرُوۡنَ مُرۡجَوۡنَ لِاَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (9:106)\nTranslation: And there are others whose affair is deferred until the command of Allah comes.\n\nHowever, «رَجَاء» refers to a hope where fulfillment is most likely (and its opposite is despair).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ ؕ اِنۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا تَاۡلَمُوۡنَ فَاِنَّہُمۡ یَاۡلَمُوۡنَ کَمَا تَاۡلَمُوۡنَ ۚ وَ تَرۡجُوۡنَ مِنَ اللّٰہِ مَا لَا یَرۡجُوۡنَ» (4:104)\nTranslation: And do not be weak in pursuit of the disbelievers. If you are suffering, they are suffering just as you are suffering, while you entertain from Allah hopes which they do not.","«رَجَا» is meant for such a hope whose fulfillment is probable, even if it is delayed.","Hope","رجا","2:218-4:104-9:106-10:7-10:11-10:15-11:62-17:28-17:57-18:110-24:60-25:21-25:40-28:86-29:5-29:36-33:21-35:29-39:9-45:14-60:6-71:13-78:27",23
286,53,"D","حَوَایَا","«حَوَایَا» refers to «حَوِیَّۃ», which means the intestines that coil like a snake. «حَیَّۃٌ» is the word for snake. «تَحْوِی الْحَیّۃ» refers to the coiling of the snake, and «حَاوِی». The one who recites the incantation for the snake is called (munjadd), and this is that intestine or gut which, while coiling, extends to the anus, i.e., reaches the back. (M. R)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«حَرَّمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ شُحُوۡمَہُمَاۤ اِلَّا مَا حَمَلَتۡ ظُہُوۡرُہُمَاۤ اَوِالۡحَوَایَاۤ اَوۡمَا اخۡتَلَطَ بِعَظۡمٍ» (6/146)\n\nTranslation: And We forbade them both (i.e., the cow and the goat) the fat, except what is on their backs, or the intestines, or what is mixed with bone.","«حَوَایَا» is used for these intestines that resemble a snake's coil.","Drawstring trousers","حوایا","6:146",1
287,53,"I","اَمْعَآء","«اَمْعَآء» is the plural of «معْیٌ». This word is general and is used for all types of intestines, both small and large. For example, in the Quran: «وَسُقُوۡا مَآءً حَمِیۡمًا فَقَطَّعَ اَمۡعَآءَہُمۡ» (47:15). Translation: And they will be given to drink boiling water which will tear their intestines into pieces.","«اَمْعَآء» is used for all kinds of small and large intestines.","Intestines.","امعآء","47:15",1
288,54,"A","اِنْتَظَرَ","«نَظَرَ» has two fundamental meanings: (1) *mu‘āyanah* (examination/observation), meaning to see something with the eyes, and (2) «تَاَمَّلِ الشَّیْء» (waiting/granting respite or time to someone). Here, the second meaning is intended. In the Holy Quran, «نَظِرَۃٌ» is used in this very sense.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2:280)\nTranslation: And if the debtor is in difficulty, then grant him respite until a time of ease.\n\nAnd «اِنْتَظَرَ» means to pass the time in anticipation of the fulfillment of a hope. This word is generally used for waiting, and in this respect, «نَظَرَۃ» and «اِنْتِظَار» are closely related in meaning. Furthermore, *intẓār* (waiting) is used for both good and evil, and in contexts of both doubt and certainty. (Faq l 58)\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ قُلۡ لِّلَّذِیۡنَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ اعۡمَلُوۡاعَلٰی مَکَانَتِکُمۡ ؕ اِنَّا عٰمِلُوۡنَ وَانۡتَظِرُوۡا ۚ اِنَّا مُنۡتَظِرُوۡنَ» (11:121-122)\nTranslation: And say to those who do not believe, 'Work in your place; indeed, we are working. And you will wait, and we will wait too.'","«اِنْتِظَار» refers to the period until a hope is fulfilled, and this term is general. It is used in both contexts of good and evil, as well as in situations involving doubt and certainty.","anticipation","انتظر","6:158-7:71-10:20-10:102-11:122-32:30-33:23",7
289,54,"W","اِرْتَقَبَ","«رَقَبَۃٌ» means neck, and «رَقَبَ» is used to denote watching over or guarding someone's neck (figurative). And «رِقْبَۃٌ» signifies caution, guardianship, protection, and fear (etymological). Therefore, «اِرْتَقَبَ» refers to a state of waiting wherein a person remains vigilant and cautious, mindful of others' movements and actions, and also of one's own protection.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «سَوۡفَ تَعۡلَمُوۡنَ ۙ مَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡہِ عَذَابٌ یُّخۡزِیۡہِ  وَ مَنۡ ہُوَ کَاذِبٌ ؕ وَ ارۡتَقِبُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡ  مَعَکُمۡ  رَقِیۡبٌ» (11/93). Translation: Soon you will know upon whom the humiliating torment will come and who is the liar! And you too wait; I too am waiting along with you.","«تَرَقُّب» means to wait and remain vigilant, to keep a sharp lookout. Generally, it comes for waiting during times of evil.","Waiting","ارتقب","4:1-5:117-11:93-28:18-28:21-44:10-44:59-50:18-54:27",9
290,54,"W","تَرَبُّص","«رَبَصَ» and «تَرَبُّص» are used with the same meaning, and this waiting is either for a specified period or for the occurrence or cessation of an event that is anticipated (muf). For example, waiting for the rise in prices of goods and the fall in their value. «تَرَبُّص بِسِلْعَۃٍ» means waiting for the devaluation of wealth (manjad). Similarly, waiting for a woman to complete her iddah (waiting period) is called «تَرَبُّص», and it also means waiting to gain greater benefit. (Faqih 59)\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قُلۡ ہَلۡ تَرَبَّصُوۡنَ بِنَاۤ اِلَّاۤ اِحۡدَی الۡحُسۡنَیَیۡنِ ؕ وَنَحۡنُ نَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمۡ اَنۡ یُّصِیۡبَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِعَذَابٍ مِّنۡ عِنۡدِہٖۤ اَوۡبِاَیۡدِیۡنَا ۫ ۖفَتَرَبَّصُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ مُّتَرَبِّصُوۡنَ» (9/52)\n\nTranslation: Say, You are waiting for us for one of two good things, while we are waiting for you that Allah will send down upon you a punishment from Himself or by our hands. So wait, we too are waiting with you.","«تَرَبُّص» the waiting period for a specified duration to gain further benefit.","Waiting","تربص","2:226-2:228-2:234-4:141-9:24-9:52-9:98-20:135-23:25-52:30-52:31-57:14",12
291,55,"F","منتھیٰ","«اَلنَّھِی» conveys the meaning of restraining or stopping, and «اِنْتَھٰی» is used to mean remaining or staying. «اَلْنِھَاءِ وَالنَّھَایَۃ» refers to the ultimate end or purpose (manshūd) of something, and «نَھَایَۃُ الدَّار» denotes the four walls of a house (m. q.). Moreover, «مُنْتَھٰی» is a noun of place. In terms of time or space, anything that reaches a point and stops there is its final limit, or «مُنْتَھٰی», or end.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «ثُمَّ  یُجۡزٰىہُ  الۡجَزَآءَ  الۡاَوۡفٰی وَ اَنَّ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ الۡمُنۡتَہٰی» (53:41-42). Translation: Then he will be given his full recompense, and indeed, your Lord is the place of return.","«مُنْتَھیٰ» is the place where a task is brought to completion; this is common.","Final outcome","منتھی","2:192-2:193-2:275-4:171-5:73-5:91-8:19-8:38-8:39-9:12-19:46-26:116-26:167-33:60-36:18-53:14-53:42-59:7-79:44-96:15",20
292,55,"F","صَارَ","Two fundamental meanings are associated with «صَیْر»: (1) return/reversion and (2) conclusion/end (m. l.). «َصْیرُالْاَمْر» refers to the final part of an action or its ultimate point. When a person's affair comes to an end, it is said «فُلَانٌ عَلیٰ صَیْرِ الْاَمْرِ» (manjad). Then, the meaning of «صَارَ» also includes transitioning from one state to another (manjad). Thus, the word «صَارَ» is also connected to the nature of an action. An action, in the manner and style it is occurring, will not adopt any other course, and the name of that final quality to which it arrives upon termination is «صَیْر». «مَصِیْر» denotes the place where a thing, after movement and transfer, arrives and comes to an end (muf).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  تَصِیۡرُ الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (42/53)\n\nTranslation: Remember that all matters will ultimately return to Allah.","The accomplishment of a task and the manner and method of its conclusion.","Final outcome","صار","2:126-2:285-3:28-3:162-4:97-4:115-5:18-8:16-9:73-14:30-22:48-22:72-24:42-24:57-25:15-31:14-35:18-40:3-42:15-42:53-48:6-50:43-57:15-58:8-60:4-64:3-64:10-66:9-67:6",29
293,55,"F","عَاقِبَۃ","«عَقَبَ» means to fly or to carry, and «عَقَّبْ» means to follow or come behind someone. «عَاقِبَۃ» signifies the end of all things, or the outcome/result of any matter (as in 'minjada'). Then, in the meaning of 'Aqib' (عقب), severity and hardship are also found. «عَاقَبَہٗ» also means to seize someone in return for their deeds. And «عِقَاب» is generally used for the recompense of a bad deed.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَجٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ» ( 40/5 )\nTranslation: And they disputed by way of vain argument to nullify the truth. So I seized them, and how [terrible] was My punishment.\n\nThus, the term 'Aqib' is not merely applied to the outcome of an action but also to its recompense.\n\nFor example: For good, the Divine Command states:\n«اِنَّ الۡاَرۡضَ لِلّٰہِ ۟ ۙ یُوۡرِثُہَا مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ ؕ وَ الۡعَاقِبَۃُ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ» ( 7/128 )\nTranslation: To Allah belongs the earth; He causes to inherit it whom He wills of His servants. And the [best] outcome is for the righteous.\n\nAnd for evil, the Divine Command states:\n«قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِکُمۡ سُنَنٌ ۙ فَسِیۡرُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡظُرُوۡا کَیۡفَ کَانَ عَاقِبَۃُ الۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ»\nTranslation: There have already passed before you many events. So travel through the land and observe how was the end of the deniers.","«عَاقِبَۃ» is used for the accomplishment of a task and its reward.","Final outcome","عاقبۃ","3:137-6:11-6:135-7:84-7:86-7:103-7:128-10:39-10:73-11:49-12:109-16:36-20:132-22:41-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:37-28:40-28:83-30:9-30:10-30:42-31:22-35:44-37:73-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-59:17-65:9",32
294,56,"E","خَرَصَ","The meaning of «خَرَصَ» is to proceed based solely on conjecture and estimation. «خَرَصَ النَّخْلَۃ» refers to this: to estimate merely by guesswork how much fruit will be on a date palm. And «خَرَّاص» is the term for a person who makes such an estimate (munjad), and «خَرَّاص» is also used to mean a liar (a great liar), because such a person speaks without knowledge or reality, and this is indeed the very foundation of falsehood.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَتَّبِعُوۡنَ اِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ اِنۡ اَنۡتُمۡ اِلَّا تَخۡرُصُوۡنَ» (6:148)\nTranslation: You follow nothing but conjecture, and you do nothing but lie.","«خَرَصَ» an estimate that is based on conjecture and assumption rather than knowledge and truth, and it is unreliable.","estimate","خرص","6:116-6:148-10:66-43:20",4
295,56,"E","قَدَّرَ","The meaning of «قَدَرَ» is to manage an affair, to prepare something, and to take care of it (Minajd). And «قَدَرْ» refers to those natural laws under which something comes into existence and is ordered (Maf). And this attribute is specific to Allah the Almighty, and it only occurs in good meanings (Faq al-157).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is:\n«اِنَّا کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلَقۡنٰہُ بِقَدَرٍ» (54/49)\nTranslation: We have created everything with a precise measure.\n\nAnd «قَدَّرَ» means to create something in that particular manner and train it as wisdom demands, and this term is general, and this measure can be good or bad (Faq al-157), as this matter is included in belief. «وَالْقَدْرِ خَیْرِہٖ وَشَرِّہٖ مِنَ اللہِ تَعَالیٰ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الشَّمۡسَ ضِیَآءً وَّ الۡقَمَرَ نُوۡرًا وَّ قَدَّرَہٗ  مَنَازِلَ  لِتَعۡلَمُوۡا عَدَدَ السِّنِیۡنَ وَ الۡحِسَابَ» (10/5)\nTranslation: He it is who made the sun radiant and the moon luminous, and determined phases for it so that you may know the number of years and calculation.","These are the natural laws that Allah, the Exalted, has established with His knowledge and wisdom, and they are firm evidence. And «قَدَّرَ» refers to an estimation based on such laws.","estimate","قدر","13:26-17:30-28:82-29:62-30:37-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-65:7-89:16",11
296,57,"I","خلال","«خَلَال» two things that have a mutual relationship within a certain space «خِلَال» also refers to the tool used for cleaning the gaps between teeth, as well as the act of cleaning that area. Similarly, during ablution, water is passed through the fingers of the hand and the beard's hair.\n\nFor example, regarding the hypocrites, the Divine decree states:\n«لَوۡ خَرَجُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ مَّا زَادُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا خَبَالًا وَّ لَا۠اَوۡضَعُوۡا خِلٰلَکُمۡ یَبۡغُوۡنَکُمُ الۡفِتۡنَۃَ» (9/47)\nTranslation: Had they gone forth among you, they would have only added disorder to you, and would have hurried about in your midst seeking to cause you sedition.","«خَلَال» The space between two such things that are mutually related. For example, the gap between teeth.","Inside","خلال","9:47-14:31-17:5-17:91-18:33-24:43-27:61-30:48",8
297,57,"I","باطن","The term battan refers to the belly, stomach, and the inner part of everything. The term «بَاطِن» specifically denotes the inner part, inner side, or interior of something (source: Manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَضُرِبَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ بِسُوۡرٍ لَّہٗ  بَابٌ ؕ بَاطِنُہٗ  فِیۡہِ الرَّحۡمَۃُ وَ ظَاہِرُہٗ  مِنۡ  قِبَلِہِ  الۡعَذَابُ» (57:13)\nTranslation: So a wall will be raised between them, with a gate in it. On the inner side (of it) there will be mercy, and on the outer side, facing it, will be punishment.\n\nBata'in: This is the plural of «بَطَانَۃ». It also refers to garments worn next to the skin, the inner covering, as well as a secret or mystery (source: Manjad). It is also used for a trusted, intimate friend.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مُتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلٰی فُرُشٍۭ بَطَآئِنُہَا مِنۡ اِسۡتَبۡرَقٍ» (55:54)\nTranslation: (The people of Paradise) will be reclining on cushions, the inner linings of which will be of rich brocade (silk).","«بَاطِن» the inside or inner part of something.","Inside","باطن","3:35-6:120-6:151-7:33-24:45-31:20-37:144-57:3-57:13",9
298,57,"I","جَوْف","«جَوِفَ» means to be hollow and «جَوَّف» means to hollow out. «جَوْف» refers to the stomach or inner part, and «جَوفَ الْبَیْت» to the inner part of a house, and «مُجَّوَف» to a hollow thing (manjada), as if in «جَوِفَ», where the concept of inner or internal part is found, there simultaneously the concept of hollowness, expanse, or void is also found. For example, the Quran states: «مَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ  لِرَجُلٍ مِّنۡ قَلۡبَیۡنِ فِیۡ جَوۡفِہٖ» (33:4). Translation: Allah has not placed two hearts within any person.","«جَوْف» the inner void of something.","Inside","جوف","33:4",1
299,58,"B","اَعْمٰی","«اَعْمٰی» meaning blind, visually impaired, one who is deprived of sight. Blindness of the eyes. (Fa 39)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ» (13/16)\nTranslation: Are the seeing and the blind equal?\nAlthough this term is generally applied to physical blindness of the eyes, it is occasionally also used for the blindness of the heart.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَاۤ اَنۡتَ بِہٰدِی الۡعُمۡیِ عَنۡ ضَلٰلَتِہِمۡ» (27/81)\nTranslation: And you cannot guide the blind away from error.","«اَعْمٰی» meaning blind.","Blind","اعمی","2:18-2:171-6:50-6:104-7:64-10:43-11:24-11:28-13:16-13:19-17:72-17:97-20:124-20:125-22:46-24:61-25:73-27:81-28:66-30:53-35:19-40:58-41:17-41:44-43:40-47:23-48:17-80:20",28
300,58,"B","اَکْمَہَ","«اَکْمَہَ» A person who is congenitally blind (for example).\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ تُبۡرِیُٔ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَ الۡاَبۡرَصَ بِاِذۡنِیۡ»\nTranslation: And [O Jesus], you used to cure the congenitally blind and the leprous by My command.","«اَکْمَہَ» is used for the congenitally blind.","blind","اکمہ","3:49-5:110",2
301,58,"B","عَمِہَ","«عَمْہٌ» meaning lack of insight, i.e., absence of insight (Manj), and meaning blindness of the heart (M Q), and meaning to be bewildered. To stray in misguidance (Manj), and due to bewilderment, to fall into hesitation and doubt (Mf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَسۡتَہۡزِئُ بِہِمۡ وَ یَمُدُّہُمۡ فِیۡ طُغۡیَانِہِمۡ یَعۡمَہُوۡنَ» (2/15)\nTranslation: Allah mocks at them and grants them respite so that they may persist in their arrogance, wandering astray. (Jalandhari). Their condition is that they are blind in their hearts. (Uthmani).","«عَمْہٌ» to become blind of the heart's eyes, to deliberately refuse to acknowledge the known truth.","Blind","عمہ","2:15-6:110-7:186-10:11-15:72-23:75-27:4",7
302,59,"J","قِسْط","The meaning of «قِسْط» is to fully pay someone their due, i.e., its basic meaning is to avoid oppression. (Lexicographically) In this sense, it is taken to mean to act justly. And its application pertains to doing justice in external, tangible matters. Therefore, the scales and measures for weighing are also called «قِسْط» (Fiqh 194).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُواالۡمِیۡزَانَ» (55:9)\nTranslation: And give full measure and do not be deficient in weight.\n\nThen, the word «قِسْط» is from the category of addad (words with opposite meanings) in lexicography. If «قَسَطَ یَقْسُطُ» is used, its meanings are as stated above; and if «قَسَطَ یَقْسِطُ» is used, its meanings would be to suppress someone's right, to act against the right, and to transgress the right. (Lexicographically). (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَمَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ فَکَانُوۡا لِجَہَنَّمَ حَطَبًا» (72:15)\nTranslation: And those who were unjust (oppressors) will become the fuel of Hell. (Uthmani)\n\nFurthermore, whether the payment of someone's right is in one lump sum or in several parts, the words «قِسْط» and «اَقْسَاط» are also used for it. Thus, the word «قِسْط» is used for both the whole and the part in giving rights. However, in these meanings, it is not used in the Quran. Rather, if the context is of actions (af'al), it will appear only in the meanings of to do justice.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَقۡسِطُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الۡمُقۡسِطِیۡنَ» (49:9)\nTranslation: And do justice, for Allah loves those who do justice.\n\nNote: In lexicography, addad refers to words that have two distinct meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other.","The term «قِسْط» is used to give someone their full due, whether all at once or in installments.","Justice","قسط","2:282-3:18-3:21-4:3-4:127-4:135-5:8-5:42-6:152-7:29-10:4-10:47-10:54-11:85-17:35-21:47-26:182-33:5-49:9-55:9-57:25-60:8-72:14-72:15",24
303,59,"J","عدل","In «عَدْل», two fundamental meanings are found: (1) to maintain balance and proportion, and (2) to give others their rights in an impartial manner (fiqh). And this hadith states: «بالعدل قامت السموت والارض». That is, the heavens and the earth are established on the support of justice. This means that in the planets of the universe, there exists such a degree of balance, proportion, and harmony that if even a slight deficiency or excess occurs in their attraction and movement, the earth and the heavens would collide with each other, and the universe would be instantly destroyed.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ فَسَوّٰىکَ فَعَدَلَکَ» (82:7)\nTranslation: Who created you and proportioned your limbs and made your stature moderate.\nThis verse is employed in the first sense, and justice pertains to all matters, both external and internal (fiqh 194).\n\nThen, from this perspective, this word is also used in the meanings of equality and compensation or recompense—the equality of two things with each other.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَفَّارَۃٌ  طَعَامُ مَسٰکِیۡنَ اَوۡ عَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ» (5:95)\nTranslation: Or expiation is the feeding of the poor, or fasting for an equal number of days, so that you may taste the penalty of your deed.\n\nCompensation, recompense, requital:\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّلَا یُقۡبَلُ مِنۡہَا شَفَاعَۃٌ وَّلَا یُؤۡخَذُ مِنۡہَا عَدۡلٌ» (2:48)\nTranslation: No intercession will be accepted, nor will any compensation be taken.\n\nAnd the second meaning of justice—giving others their rights—is what is under discussion here, which conveys the meaning of fairness.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِعۡدِلُوۡا ۟ ہُوَ  اَقۡرَبُ لِلتَّقۡوٰی» (5:8)\nTranslation: Be fair; that is nearer to piety.\n\nMoreover, in these senses, the word «عدل» is from the category of words with opposite meanings (ذوی الاضداد). If it originates from the context of «عَدِلَ یَعْدِلُ», then its meanings are to commit injustice or to act unfairly (Munjid).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالۡاَرۡضَ وَ جَعَلَ الظُّلُمٰتِ وَالنُّوۡرَ  ؕ ثُمَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِرَبِّہِمۡ یَعۡدِلُوۡنَ» (6:1)\nTranslation: All praise is for Allah alone, who created the heavens and the earth and made the darknesses and the light. Yet, the disbelievers consider others equal to their Lord.\n\nSince the word *‘adl* possesses a broad meaning, here the translation of «یَعْدِلُوْن» is also rendered as “considering equal to God” or “making counterparts to God.”\n\nNote: (Lughat al-Aḍdād refers to words that have two distinct meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«عَدْل» Granting another person their full right or providing compensation equal to its value is a practice common to both outward and inner affairs.","Justice","عدل","2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7",24
304,60,"D","اَبٰی","«اَبٰی» means to refuse to acknowledge something, to strictly forbid. It includes disobedience, not accepting, and rebelling. And «اَبٰی» also means to consider something detestable, i.e., disliked, to dislike something. Being displeased with something is also included. (from Munjid)\n\nFor example, in the Quran: «وَاِذۡ قُلۡنَا لِلۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ اسۡجُدُوۡا لِاٰدَمَ فَسَجَدُوۡۤا اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَکَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2/34). Translation: And when We commanded the angels to prostrate before Adam, they all fell prostrate except Satan. He refused and, becoming arrogant, became a disbeliever.","«اَبٰی» reject.","Denial","ابی","2:34-9:8-9:32-15:31-17:89-17:99-20:56-20:116-25:50",9
305,60,"R","اَنْکَر","«نَکَرَ» means not recognizing something, being unfamiliar with something or a matter (م ر) such a matter that the human heart does not accept and which seems strange and amazing, even if one cannot understand due to ignorance. (مف) And its opposite is «عَرَفَ», meaning to recognize something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَجَآءَ اِخۡوَۃُ یُوۡسُفَ فَدَخَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِ فَعَرَفَہُمۡ وَہُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (12/58)\nTranslation: And the brothers of Yusuf came to Yusuf. So he recognized them, but they did not recognize him.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah is:\n«وَہٰذَا ذِکۡرٌ مُّبٰرَکٌ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (21/50)\nTranslation: And this is a blessed admonition which We have revealed, so do you deny it?","«اَنْکَرَ» denial due to non-recognition.","Rejection","انکر","12:58-13:36-16:22-16:83-21:50-23:69-40:81",7
306,60,"D","جَحَدَ","«جَحَدَ» Meaning: to knowingly deny something after having knowledge of it (m. r.)—to verbally reject what the heart truly acknowledges.\n\nFor example: in the Holy Quran it is: «وَجَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ ظُلۡمًا وَّعُلُوًّا» (27/14) Translation: And they denied the signs with injustice and arrogance, even though their hearts were convinced of them.","to deny that in which one's heart has conviction","Denial","جحد","6:33-7:51-11:59-16:71-27:14-29:47-29:49-31:32-40:63-41:15-41:28-46:26",12
307,60,"D","کَفَرَ","«کَفَرَ» (not recognizing the truth) (m. r.) and its basic meanings are to cover something and veil it. A farmer is also called a disbeliever (manjidd) because he covers the seed in the soil. This word is also used in the Holy Quran in these senses.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57/20)\nTranslation: Like rain (by which crops grow and) farmers find their crops pleasing.\n\nThe opposite of disbelief is faith, and it is termed disbelief because it veils faith (m. l.).\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَیُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ» (18/37)\nTranslation: Then his companion, who was conversing with him, said: Have you become a disbeliever in Him who created you from dust? (Uthmani)\n\nMoreover, «کَفَرَ» also signifies the forgetting of favors. In this sense, its opposite is «شَکَرَ» (14/7).","To deny «کَفَرَ» while covering it up.","Disavowal","کفر","2:6-2:26-2:28-2:39-2:61-2:85-2:88-2:89-2:90-2:91-2:93-2:99-2:102-2:105-2:108-2:121-2:126-2:152-2:161-2:171-2:212-2:217-2:253-2:256-2:257-2:258-3:4-3:10-3:12-3:19-3:21-3:52-3:55-3:56-3:70-3:72-3:80-3:86-3:90-3:91-3:97-3:98-3:101-3:106-3:112-3:115-3:116-3:127-3:149-3:151-3:156-3:167-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:196-4:42-4:46-4:51-4:56-4:60-4:76-4:84-4:89-4:101-4:102-4:131-4:136-4:137-4:140-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:167-4:168-4:170-5:3-5:5-5:10-5:12-5:17-5:36-5:41-5:61-5:64-5:68-5:72-5:73-5:78-5:80-5:86-5:103-5:110-5:115-6:1-6:7-6:25-6:30-6:70-6:89-7:66-7:90-8:12-8:15-8:30-8:35-8:36-8:38-8:50-8:52-8:55-8:59-8:65-8:73-9:3-9:12-9:17-9:23-9:26-9:30-9:37-9:40-9:54-9:66-9:74-9:80-9:84-9:90-9:97-9:107-10:4-10:70-11:7-11:17-11:27-11:60-11:68-13:5-13:7-13:27-13:30-13:31-13:32-13:33-13:43-14:7-14:8-14:9-14:13-14:18-14:22-14:28-15:2-16:39-16:55-16:72-16:84-16:88-16:106-16:112-17:69-17:98-18:29-18:37-18:56-18:80-18:102-18:105-18:106-19:37-19:73-19:77-19:82-21:30-21:36-21:39-21:94-21:97-22:19-22:25-22:55-22:57-22:72-23:24-23:33-24:39-24:55-24:57-25:4-25:32-27:40-27:67-28:48-29:12-29:23-29:25-29:52-29:66-29:67-30:16-30:34-30:44-30:51-30:58-31:12-31:23-32:29-33:25-34:3-34:7-34:17-34:31-34:33-34:43-34:53-35:7-35:14-35:26-35:36-35:39-36:47-36:64-37:170-38:2-38:27-39:7-39:8-39:63-39:71-40:4-40:6-40:10-40:12-40:22-40:42-40:84-41:9-41:26-41:27-41:29-41:41-41:50-41:52-43:33-45:11-45:31-46:3-46:7-46:10-46:11-46:20-46:34-47:1-47:3-47:4-47:8-47:12-47:32-47:34-48:22-48:25-48:26-49:7-51:60-52:42-54:14-57:15-57:19-59:2-59:11-59:16-60:1-60:2-60:4-60:5-61:14-63:3-64:5-64:6-64:7-64:10-66:7-66:10-67:6-67:27-68:51-70:36-73:17-74:31-80:17-80:42-84:22-85:19-88:23-90:19-98:1-98:6",297
308,61,"F","اَصَابِع","«اَصَابِع» is the plural of «اَصْبِع». It refers to the part of the finger that has the nails. It is a combination of kham and jor (singular).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «یَجۡعَلُوۡنَ اَصَابِعَہُمۡ فِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ» (2/19).  \nTranslation: They put their fingers into their ears.\n\nAnd the term «بَنَان» is used specifically for the parts, whose singular form is «بَنَانَۃ».\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «بَلٰی قٰدِرِیۡنَ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ نُّسَوِّیَ بَنَانَہٗ» (75/4).  \nTranslation: Why not? And we are capable of restoring its every part.","«اَصَابِع» is used for the fingers.","fingers","اصابع","2:19-71:7",2
309,61,"F","اَنَامِل","«اَنَامِل» is the plural form of «اَنْمَلَۃٌ». It refers to the uppermost part of the finger and its sides (pl.).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَاِذَا خَلَوۡاعَضُّوۡاعَلَیۡکُمُ الۡاَنَامِلَ مِنَ الۡغَیۡظِ» (3:119)  \nTranslation: And when they separate, they bite their fingers out of rage against you.","«اَنَامِل» refers to the tips of the fingers where nails grow.","fingers","انامل","3:119",1
310,62,"T","استغشٰی","«غَشِی» means to cover one thing with another. And this word comes in the meaning of covering from above or placing a veil (m l).\nAnd «اِسْتَغْشٰی» means to wrap a cloth around oneself, and «غَوَاش» refers to every item that is wrapped. (7/41)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَاحِیۡنَ یَسۡتَغۡشُوۡنَ ثِیَابَہُمۡ ۙ یَعۡلَمُ مَا یُسِرُّوۡنَ وَ مَا یُعۡلِنُوۡنَ» (11/5)\nTranslation: Take heed! When they wrap themselves in their garments, He knows what they conceal and what they reveal. (Usmani)\nAnd this word, as it is used in its outward sense, is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاِنِّیۡ کُلَّمَا دَعَوۡتُہُمۡ  لِتَغۡفِرَلَہُمۡ جَعَلُوۡۤا اَصَابِعَہُمۡ فِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ وَاسۡتَغۡشَوۡا ثِیَابَہُمۡ وَاَصَرُّوۡا وَاسۡتَکۡبَرُوا اسۡتِکۡبَارًا» (71/7)\nTranslation: (Prophet Noah, peace be upon him, said) And when I call them to (repentance and) that You may forgive them, they place their fingers in their ears, wrap themselves in their garments, persist in arrogance, and act haughtily.","«اِسْتَغْشٰی» means to drape or wrap some cloth around oneself.","to don / to put on / to cover","استغشی","3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1",21
311,62,"T","اِدَّثَرَ","«اَلدِّثَار» This warm shawl or blanket is referred to as that which is worn over regular clothing or wrapped around while sleeping (manjadd). And every garment that is attached to the body is called «شَعَار», and the garment that is mixed with «شَعَار» is called «دِثَار» (f. l 19). And «اِدَّثَّرَ» means to take a shawl or blanket over regular clothing. And «دُثْورُالْقَلْب» means to be erased from the heart's memory, and «دَاثِر» means destruction and negligence (m. r). Thus, «اِدَّثَر» implies sleeping while covered in a garment in a state of negligence. For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمُدَّثِّرُ قُمۡ فَاَنۡذِرۡ» (74/1,2) Translation: O (Muhammad ﷺ) who is wrapped in a garment. Arise and warn.","«اِدَّثَر» To sleep while covered with a garment in a state of negligent sleep, or to wrap the garment with the intention of taking a deep sleep.","to drape","ادثر","74:1",1
312,62,"T","اِزَّمَّل","«زَمَّل» means to wrap oneself in garments. To conceal oneself within clothes, and «مُزَّمَّل» means one who is wrapped in garments. And «اِزْمَلّ» and «زُمَیْل» mean weak, cowardly, fearful (timid), and «زُمَّل» means feeble, frightened, and malevolent (corrupt). Thus, «مُزَمِّل» refers to the one who wraps himself in a garment due to some weakness, fear, or malevolence, and then lies down.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمُزَّمِّلُ قُمِ  الَّیۡلَ   اِلَّا  قَلِیۡلًا» ( 73/1 )\nTranslation: O you who wraps himself [in garments]. Arise and warn, and your Lord glorify.","«اِزَّمّل» to cover oneself with a garment out of fear, weakness, or malice.","to conceal","ازمل","73:1",1
313,63,"C","اَوْلَاد","«اَوْلَاد» is the plural of «وُلِد», meaning born child, and «اَوْلَاد» generally applies to sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and so on. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/11). Translation: Allah has ordained concerning your children that the share of a male is equal to that of two females.","«اَوْلَاد» sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and beyond.","Children","اولاد","2:233-3:10-3:116-4:11-6:137-6:140-6:151-8:28-9:55-9:69-9:85-17:31-17:64-34:35-34:37-57:20-58:17-60:3-60:12-63:9-64:14-64:15",22
314,63,"C","اَسْبَاط","«سِبْط» means the children's children (i.e., the second generation), but this term is more specifically reserved for grandsons/granddaughters. Just as for a grandson, «حَفِیْد» or «حَفْدَۃ» is used (see Munjid), and «اَسْبَاط» means the children of daughters, i.e., grandsons, granddaughters, and so on. Furthermore, the term Asbāt is generally used for the descendants of Prophet Isaac (peace be upon him) (see Munjid).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ تَقُوۡلُوۡنَ اِنَّ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ وَاِسۡمٰعِیۡلَ وَ اِسۡحٰقَ وَ یَعۡقُوۡبَ وَالۡاَسۡبَاطَ کَانُوۡا ہُوۡدًا اَوۡ نَصٰرٰی» (2/140)\n\nTranslation: (O Jews and Christians) Do you claim that Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and their descendants were Jews or Christians?","«اَسْبَاط» grandsons, granddaughters, and beyond.","Children","اسباط","2:136-2:140-3:84-4:163-7:160",5
315,63,"C","ذُرِیَّۃ","Some lexicographers derive it from «ذُرّ», meaning small ants (minjad), with «ذُرَّۃ» being its singular form, and «ذُرِّیَۃ» referring to small children (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَاَصَابَہُ الۡکِبَرُ وَلَہٗ ذُرِّیَّۃٌ ضُعَفَآءُ» (2:266). Translation: And he has attained old age, and he has young children.\n\nThen the application of this word began to encompass all offspring. Others derive it from «ذَرَاَ», meaning to sow in the earth (minjad). According to Ibn Faris, it refers to anything that can be sown and cultivated (m, l). This word is general for offspring, encompassing sons, daughters, grandsons, granddaughters, and all descendants. (F, L 206)\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «قَالَ اِنِّیۡ جَاعِلُکَ لِلنَّاسِ اِمَامًا  ؕ قَالَ وَمِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ  ؕ قَالَ لَا یَنَالُ عَہۡدِی الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (2:124). Translation: Allah said, 'I will make you a leader for the people.' He said, 'And my offspring?' Allah said, 'My covenant does not include the wrongdoers.'","«ذُرِیَّۃ» includes grandsons and granddaughters; it is used for all.","children","ذریۃ","2:124-2:128-2:266-3:34-3:36-3:38-4:9-6:84-6:87-6:133-7:172-7:173-10:83-13:23-13:38-14:37-14:40-17:3-17:62-18:50-19:58-25:74-29:27-36:41-37:77-37:113-40:8-46:15-52:21-57:26",30
316,63,"C","عَقِب","«عَقَب» means progeny, son, and grandson; «عَقَّبَ» means to follow behind; and «اَعْقَبَ» means to be a successor (as in 'minjad'). The usage of «عَقِبَ» applies to the offspring left behind after a person's death.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَجَعَلَہَا کَلِمَۃًۢ  بَاقِیَۃً فِیۡ عَقِبِہٖ» ( 43/28 )  \nTranslation: And (Prophet Ibrahim AS) left this same statement behind among his descendants.","After someone's death, their offspring can be referred to as «عَقِب», but not during their lifetime.","Children","عقب","43:28",1
317,63,"C","نَسْل","The lexical meanings of «نَسَلَ» are to run swiftly or to race from height to depth (Majid). For example, in the Quran, it is stated: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَمَاۡجُوۡجُ وَہُمۡ مِّنۡ کُلِّ حَدَبٍ یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21:96). Translation: Until Gog and Magog are let out, and they will be racing from every elevation.\n\nIts second meaning is that something separates from the body of a living being. And «نُسَالَہ» refers to the beard hairs that fall out or the feathers of birds that shed. And since offspring are also a part of the parents' body that separates from them, therefore offspring is termed as progeny (Muf.). Ibn al-Faris has also stated these two meanings (Lugh.).\n\n«نَسْل» refers to all the progenies of a specific person. Thus, this word is more general than offspring and «ذُرِّیَّت», etc. For example, in the Quran, it is stated: «وَ بَدَاَ خَلۡقَ الۡاِنۡسَانِ مِنۡ طِیۡنٍ ثُمَّ جَعَلَ نَسۡلَہٗ  مِنۡ سُلٰلَۃٍ مِّنۡ مَّآءٍ مَّہِیۡنٍ» (32:7-8). Translation: And He began the creation of man from clay. Then He made his progeny from an extract of insignificant water.","«نَسْل» All descendants of a person are considered his or her lineage.","Children","نسل","2:205-32:8",2
318,63,"C","حَفْدَۃ","«حَفَدَ» means showing agility in work (muf. manjad). This is also the intended meaning in the words of the Qunut supplication «وَاِلَیْکَ نَسْعٰی وَنَحْفِدُ». And «حَافِد» means one who performs service with speed, whether he is a stranger or a relative (muf). Both «حَافِد» and «حَفِیْد» also mean grandson (muf manjad). And the plural of «حَافِدْ» is «حَفْدَۃ». According to Imam Raghib, the term «حَفْدَۃ» applies to relatives on both sides—paternal and maternal—but «اُنَاث» is not included in it.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ اَزۡوَاجِکُمۡ بَنِیۡنَ وَ حَفَدَۃً» (16/72)\nTranslation: And for you are sons and grandsons born from your wives.","«حَفْدَۃ» applies to the father-in-law and children, as well as to relatives on both sides.","children","حفدۃ","16:72",1
319,63,"C","آل ، اَھْل","«اَھْل» and «آل», according to some lexicographers, are synonymous and both convey the meanings of relation or family. However, there are several differences between these two terms, for example:\n\nThe scope of «اَھْل» is limited in the sense that it includes only the members of one's household—namely, wife and children—whereas «آل» also includes those who share a mental harmony or consensus. For instance: «اَھْل» with reference to Pharaoh includes only his household members, while «آل» with reference to him includes, besides his household, his close associates and all people who are in agreement with him. Similarly, in Aal al-Nabi ﷺ, besides the Prophet's ﷺ relatives, it also includes those members of the Ummah who have a special connection with him in terms of knowledge and insight.\n\nFurthermore, the scope of «اَھْل» is wider than that of «اٰل» in the sense that its relation can also extend to those without intellect. For example, one can say Ahl al-Shahr (the people of the city) or Ahl al-Ard (the people of the land), but one cannot say Aal al-Balad or Aal al-Ard. Similarly, the construction is found in Ahl al-Madinah, Ahl al-Dhikr, Ahl al-Kitab, and Ahl al-Nar.\n\nThe relation denoted by «اٰل» is only toward a well-known personality. For example, one can say Aal Ibrahim or Aal Imran, but one cannot say Aal al-Khayyat (the family of the tailor). However, one can say Ahl al-Khayyat. In this case, it would mean the members of the tailor's household.","«اَھْل» Household members. Including the wife. Children and family members.\n«آل» Other relatives","children","آل ، اھل","2:49-2:50-2:248-3:11-3:33-4:54-7:130-7:141-8:52-8:54-12:6-14:6-15:59-15:61-19:6-27:56-28:8-34:13-40:28-40:45-40:46-54:34-54:41-2:105-2:109-3:69-3:72-3:75-3:110-3:113-3:199-4:123-4:153-4:159-5:47-5:65-7:96-7:97-7:98-9:101-11:73-12:109-15:67-16:43-18:77-20:40-21:7-28:12-28:45-29:31-29:34-29:46-33:26-33:33-38:64-57:29-59:2-59:7-59:11-74:56-98:1-98:6",62
320,64,"O","صَوْف","«صَوْفَ» refers to the wool sheared from the bodies of animals such as sheep and goats. (F L 30)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ اَصۡوَافِہَا وَاَوۡبَارِہَا وَاَشۡعَارِہَاۤ اَثَاثًا وَّمَتَاعًا اِلٰی حِیۡنٍ» (16/80)\nTranslation: And from their wool, fur, and hair, you make furnishings and goods for enjoyment that last for a time.","«صَوْفَ» Wool sheared from the bodies of animals such as sheep and goats.","oats","صوف","16:80",1
321,64,"W","عِھْن","Wool dyed in various colors is called... For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ تَکُوۡنُ السَّمَآءُ کَالۡمُہۡلِ وَ تَکُوۡنُ الۡجِبَالُ کَالۡعِہۡنِ» (70:8-9) Translation: On the Day when the sky will be like molten copper and the mountains like colored wool.","Wool dyed in various colors is called «عِھْن».","wool","عھن","70:9-101:5",2
322,65,"C","اِبِل","«اِبِل» is a generic noun used for all types of camels, both male and female. It does not have a dual or plural form, and from this word, the hump of the camel is also implied (singular).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «اَفَلَا یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَی الۡاِبِلِ کَیۡفَ خُلِقَتۡ» (88/17). Translation: Do these people not look at the camels, how they are wonderfully created?","«اِبِل» is a generic name used for all kinds of camels, both male and female.","camel","ابل","6:144-88:17",2
323,65,"C","بَعِیْر","«بَعِیْر» denotes a young and strong camel. It is a common noun applied to both male and female camels once they reach four years of age and become capable of bearing loads. (Mufradat 27)\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ الۡمَلِکِ وَلِمَنۡ جَآءَ بِہٖ حِمۡلُ بَعِیۡرٍوَّاَنَا بِہٖ زَعِیۡمٌ» (12/72)\nTranslation: They said, We have not found the king's drinking cup, and whoever brings it will be given a she-camel as a reward, and I will be its guarantor.","When a camel becomes capable of bearing burdens at four years old, it is called «بَعِیْر».","camel","بعیر","12:65-12:72",2
324,65,"C","جَمَل","«جَمَل» A male camel over five years old. A beautiful camel. (f.l 27) Its plural is «جِمَالَۃٌ».\nFor example: It is mentioned in the Quran:\n«اِنَّہَا تَرۡمِیۡ  بِشَرَرٍ کَالۡقَصۡرِ کَاَنَّہٗ جِمٰلَتٌ صُفۡرٌ» (77/32,33)\nTranslation: From it, sparks as huge as dark red or reddish-yellow camels fly out.","«جَمَل» A male camel over five years old. A handsome camel.","camel","جمل","7:40-77:33",2
325,65,"C","ھِیْم","«ھَام» is used in two meanings: (1) to wander in an ardent, lovesick, and frenzied manner, and (2) to be extremely thirsty. Here, the second meaning is under discussion. «ھَیَام» is a disease in camels wherein they become so thirsty that they are unable to walk (manjad). And «ھِیْم» refers to a camel that is exceedingly thirsty.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡحَمِیۡمِ فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ شُرۡبَ الۡہِیۡمِ» (56/54,55)\nTranslation: And you will drink scalding water, and you will drink it like thirsty camels drink.","«ھِیْم» a severely thirsty camel.","camel","ھیم","56:55",1
326,65,"C","رِکَاب","«رَکَب» means to ride, and «رِکاب» refers to the place where the feet of a rider rest. (In our usage, «رکاب» is employed in these same meanings.) Then this word began to be used for every rider and mount. (Manjad) In common parlance, the word raakib is specifically reserved for a camel rider (i.e., one who rides a camel), and its plurals are «رُکْبَان ، رَکَب» and «رُکُوْب» (muf). Furthermore, the term «رِکَاب» is also used for a herd of camels, just as the word kheel is used for a herd of horses. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ» (59:6)\nTranslation: For it, you neither spurred on horses nor camels.","«رِکَاب» is the term for the place where a rider rests their feet while mounted.","Camel","رکاب","11:41-11:42-16:8-18:71-29:65-36:42-40:79-43:12-59:6-84:19",10
327,65,"C","ضَامِر","«ضَمَرَ» means a smooth belly (i.e., lean and thin) with a beautiful body. And «ضَامِر» refers to every mount (horse or camel) that is swift-bodied due to exercise and training, not due to lack of food. And «مِضْمَار» is the term for the place where these animals are trained in exercise and conditioning. (M. R) Thus, «ضَامِر» denotes lean and long-bodied swift horses or camels, whether male or female. And since camel riding is common in Arabia, this term is more frequently applied to such camels.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ یَاۡتُوۡکَ رِجَالًا وَّعَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj; they will come to you on foot and on lean and thin camels coming from every distant path.","«ضَامِر» refers to a lean and swift camel, used for both males and females.","camel","ضامر","22:27",1
328,65,"C","بُدْنَ","«بُدْنَ» is the collective term for «بَدَنَۃٌ», which refers to those camels offered as sacrifices that are taken to the Sacred Mosque in Mecca to be slaughtered (M.R.). Alternatively, it refers to those taken to Mecca al-Mukarramah to be slaughtered (Minjaj, Muf). The term «بَدَنَۃ» is applied to both these animals due to their suitability in terms of body, i.e., because they are fat and robust. In common usage, however, it specifically denotes the sacrificial camel that is taken to Mecca to be slaughtered.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الۡبُدۡنَ جَعَلۡنٰہَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ  شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہِ» (22:36)\nTranslation: And the sacrificial camels have We made for you as symbols from Allah.\n\nAnd «شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہ» refers to those rites that are dedicated in the name of Allah.","«بُدْنَ» The sacrificial camels that are taken to the Kaaba sanctuary and slaughtered.","camel","بدن","22:36",1
329,65,"C","نَاقَۃ","«نَوْق» This she-camel is referred to as «نَوْق», meaning she has become capable of bearing offspring (Fath al-Bari, p. 17).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَیٰقَوۡمِ ہٰذِہٖ نَاقَۃُ اللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اٰیَۃً» (11/64)\nTranslation: And (Prophet Salih) said, O my people! This she-camel of Allah is a sign for you.","«نَاقَۃ» a she-camel that has become capable of direct milking.","camel","ناقۃ","7:73-7:77-11:64-17:59-26:155-54:27-91:13",7
330,65,"C","عِشَار","«عِشَار» is plural for «عَشْرَاءَ» and «عَشَرَ» means ten. «عَشْرَاء» refers to a she-camel that has been pregnant for ten months (M. R.) and such a she-camel was considered very precious, as she was expected to give birth soon.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ» (81:4)\nTranslation: And when the ten-month pregnant she-camels are abandoned.\n(Meaning: No one will bother to tend to such cherished things.)","«عِشَار» ten months pregnant she-camels.","Camel","عشار","34:45-81:4",2
331,65,"C","بُحَیْرَۃ","When a she-camel or goat gave birth to ten offspring, the Arabs would dedicate it for sacrifice to their idols, pierce its ears as a mark, and set it free to graze. No one was permitted to milk it, and upon its death, its meat was considered lawful for men but forbidden for women.","«بَحِیْرَۃ ، سَائِبَۃ ، وَصِیْلَۃ اور حَام» During the pre-Islamic era, under various stipulations, the animals offered as vows and sacrifices to idols were referred to.","camel","بحیرۃ","5:103",1
332,65,"C","سآئبۃ","«سَآئِبَۃ» They used to call those animals which, during the Era of Ignorance, people would set free in the name of their false deities, releasing them from being used for riding or carrying loads.","«سَآئِبَۃ» was the name given to those animals which, during the Era of Jahiliyyah, people would set free in the name of their false deities, releasing them from any use for riding or bearing burdens.","camel","سآئبۃ","5:103",1
333,65,"C","وَصِیْلۃ","«وَصِیْلۃ» They used to call that young she-camel one that gave birth to a female offspring the first time, and then also gave birth to a female the second time. Even in that case, when she gave birth to two female offspring consecutively and no male offspring was born in between, they would still dedicate it to idols.","«وَصِیْلۃ» (the she-camel that consistently bore female offspring and never a male)","camel","وصیلۃ","5:103",1
334,65,"C","حَام","«حَام» That Narāwint camel whose semen has produced ten offspring, and when it has completed such services, they would also set it aside in the name of idols, neither riding it nor loading it with burdens.\n\nNow, regarding such sacrifices, observe the divine command:\n\n«مَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ مِنۡۢ بَحِیۡرَۃٍ  وَّ لَا سَآئِبَۃٍ  وَّ لَا وَصِیۡلَۃٍ وَّ لَا حَامٍ ۙ وَّ لٰکِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یَفۡتَرُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ» (5/103)\n\nTranslation: Allah has not ordained any such thing as Bahirah, or Sa'ibah, or Wasilah, or Ham. Rather, the disbelievers fabricate falsehood against Allah.\n\nThe disbelievers had themselves prescribed these names and used to claim that this was the command of the law of Abraham (peace be upon him), and that through them, one attains nearness to Allah.","«حَام» a camel whose semen has produced at least ten offspring.","camel","حام","5:103",1
335,66,"ʿ","نُعَاس","This is the initial state of sleep, meaning drowsiness (p. 34). When, due to sleep, the senses become sluggish and its effect starts becoming apparent on the eyes, then it is called «نُعَاس».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ» (8/11).\nTranslation: When Allah gave you sleep as a cover from Himself for your reassurance.","«نُعَاس» is the term for the initial stage of sleep.","ʿUng","نعاس","3:154-8:11",2
336,66,"T","سِنَۃٌ","«سِنَۃٌ» Drowsiness: a state in which one begins to feel heaviness in the head and the head starts to nod. The next level of drowsiness. The intermediate state between drowsiness and sleep (p. 161).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَللّٰہُ لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَۚ اَلۡحَیُّ الۡقَیُّوۡمُ ۬ ۚ لَا تَاۡخُذُہٗ سِنَۃٌ وَّلَا نَوۡمٌ» (2/255)\nTranslation: There is no deity worthy of worship except Allah, the Ever-Living, the Sustainer of all existence. Neither drowsiness nor sleep overtakes Him.","«سِنَۃٌ» is an overwhelming drowsiness wherein one feels a heaviness in the head and the head begins to droop.","to doze","سنۃ","2:255-33:19",2
337,67,"F","حَطَبَ","Plant-based fuel. Worthless wood, thorns, and brambles that are only fit for burning.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَّامۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ الۡحَطَبِ» (111/4)  \nTranslation: And his wife [too] will carry firewood on her head.  \nAnd wood that is usable is called «خَشَب».","«حَطَبَ» plant-based fuel, worthless sticks that are only fit for burning.","fuel","حطب","72:15-111:4",2
338,67,"F","حَصَب","The meaning of «حَصَب» is stones, small pebbles, gravel, etc. And «حَاصِبْ» refers to the fierce and swift wind that sweeps up and carries pebbles and small stones (Munjid). Therefore, this word is used in the Holy Quran to mean a shower of stones (67:17). Moreover, «حَصَب» also means fuel (Munjid), referring to mineral fuels such as sulfur, potash, and other flammable substances. And stones, etc., meaning anything that ignites fire is «حَصَب» (F.L. 16).\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ وَ مَا تَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ حَصَبُ جَہَنَّمَ» (21:98)\nTranslation: O disbelievers, on that day, you and those you worship besides Allah will be the fuel of Hellfire.","«حَصَب» inorganic and mineral fuels, such as sulfur, potassium, and other combustible materials.","fuel","حصب","17:68-21:98-29:40-54:34-67:17",5
339,67,"F","وَقُوْد","«وَقَدَ» means to kindle a fire, and «وَقُوْد» refers to any fuel that burns by producing a flame (Fath al-Qadeer 31), whether it be wood, stone, or a human being. Sometimes the intensity of a fire reaches such an extreme that water, instead of extinguishing it, becomes a cause for its further ignition. In such a case, even water is included as fuel. Any type of fuel, while it is burning, is called «وَقُود», not before that.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاتَّقُوا النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ وَقُوۡدُہَا النَّاسُ وَ الۡحِجَارَۃُ» (2/24)\nTranslation: So fear the Fire whose fuel will be men and stones.","«وَقُوْد» is what burning fuel, of any kind, is called «وُقود».","fuel","وقود","2:24-3:10-66:6-85:5",4
340,69,"F","وَالِدٌ","The word «وَالِدٌ» is used exclusively for the father. Similarly, the word for mother is used only for the woman who has given birth to a child.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَّا یَجۡزِیۡ وَالِدٌ عَنۡ وَّلَدِہٖ وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَجَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا» (31:33)\nTranslation: Neither will the father be of any benefit to his son, nor will the son be of any benefit to his father.\n\nHowever, the term 'parents' applies to both the mother and the father.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَنِ اشۡکُرۡ لِیۡ وَ لِوَالِدَیۡکَ» (31:14)\nTranslation: And be grateful to Me and to your parents.","The term «وَالِدٌ» is used exclusively to mean father.","Father","والد","2:83-2:180-2:215-2:233-4:7-4:33-4:36-4:135-5:110-6:151-14:41-17:23-19:14-19:32-27:19-29:8-31:14-31:33-46:15-46:17-71:28-90:3",22
341,69,"F","اَبْ","The word «اَبْ» is used in a very broad sense. This word is employed for father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all the preceding generations. And for mother and father, «اَبْوَیْن» or «اَبْوَان» is used as the context requires.\n\nNow observe its examples:\n\n(1) For mother and father only:\n(It is the commandment of Allah, the Most High.)\n«وَ اَمَّا الۡغُلٰمُ فَکَانَ اَبَوٰہُ  مُؤۡمِنَیۡنِ» (18/80)\nTranslation: And the boy, his parents were both believers.\n\n(2) For several generations:\n(It is the commandment of Allah, the Most High.)\n«مَّا سَمِعۡنَا بِہٰذَا فِیۡۤ  اٰبَآئِنَا  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (23/24)\nTranslation: We have never heard of this from our forefathers.\n\nAnd these generational lines can be even more numerous.\nAs in (It is the commandment of Allah, the Most High.)\n«مِلَّۃَ اَبِیۡکُمۡ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ ؕ ہُوَ سَمّٰىکُمُ الۡمُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (22/78)\nTranslation: And (He has chosen for you) the religion of your father Abraham, and He named you Muslims before.\n\nIt should be noted that between the Noble Prophet ﷺ and Prophet Abraham ؑ, there is a distance of approximately 62 generations. In fact, even for Prophet Adam, who is the ultimate ancestor of humanity, the word «اَب» has been applied.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ اٰدَمَ لَا یَفۡتِنَنَّکُمُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ کَمَاۤ اَخۡرَجَ اَبَوَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/27)\nTranslation: O children of Adam, beware that Satan does not mislead you as he misled your parents from the Garden.\n\n«اَب» originally is «اَبَوَ» and it denotes providing nourishment and upbringing (M). Therefore, if one is addressing their father, the word «اَبّ» is generally used, as when Prophet Joseph ؑ said to his father:\nIt is the commandment of Allah, the Most High.\n«یٰۤاَبَتِ ہٰذَا تَاۡوِیۡلُ رُءۡیَایَ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ» (12/100)\nTranslation: O my father, this is the interpretation of my dream which I had in my childhood.\n\nFurthermore, the word «اَب» is sometimes used due to a specific characteristic, such as calling a host «اَبُوالْاضِیَاف» and a warrior «اَبُوالْحَرَب». In the Noble Quran, the word «ابولھب» was used for this very reason, because its color was radiant like a flame. Similarly, one is given a kunyah (patronymic) due to association and affection, such as Abu Hurairah and Abu Turab, etc.","«اَبْ» This term is used for ancestors, including father, grandfather, great-grandfather, and all preceding generations.","Father","اب","2:133-2:170-2:200-4:11-4:22-5:104-6:74-6:87-6:91-6:148-7:27-7:28-7:70-7:71-7:95-7:173-9:23-9:24-9:114-10:78-11:62-11:87-11:109-12:4-12:6-12:8-12:9-12:11-12:16-12:17-12:38-12:40-12:59-12:61-12:63-12:65-12:68-12:78-12:80-12:81-12:93-12:94-12:97-12:99-12:100-13:23-14:10-16:35-18:5-18:80-18:82-19:28-19:42-19:43-19:44-19:45-21:44-21:52-21:53-21:54-22:78-23:24-23:68-23:83-24:31-24:61-25:18-26:26-26:70-26:74-26:76-26:86-27:67-27:68-28:23-28:25-28:26-28:36-31:21-33:5-33:40-33:55-34:43-36:6-37:17-37:69-37:85-37:102-37:126-40:8-43:22-43:23-43:24-43:26-43:29-44:8-44:36-45:25-53:23-56:48-58:22-60:4-80:35-111:1",104
342,70,"B","تَبَارَک ۔ مُبَارَک","«مُبَارَک» In the meaning of *barakah* (blessing), it signifies the manifestation of divine goodness in something (muf). That is, when an action is performed, the expected benefit increases to the maximum; this is *barakah*, provided that the action or expectation possesses an aspect of goodness. And «بَرْکَۃْ» means increase, abundance (source). And that in which this aspect of goodness proves to be fruitful is *mubarak* (blessed).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَہٰذَا ذِکۡرٌمُّبٰرَکٌ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ» (21/50)\nTranslation: And this is a blessed Reminder which We have revealed.\n\nAnd *tabarak* means to take a good omen or good augury (source), but this word is generally specific to Allah the Almighty and comes for those good deeds which are exclusively His.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«تَبٰارَکَ الَّذِیۡ نَزَّلَ الۡفُرۡقَانَ (25/1)\nفَتَبٰارَکَ اللّٰہُ رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ (40/64)\nفَتَبٰارَکَ اللّٰہُ اَحۡسَنُ الۡخٰلِقِیۡنَ (23/14)\nتَبٰارَکَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ فِی السَّمَآءِ بُرُوۡجًا (25/61)\nتَبٰارَکَ الَّذِیۡ بِیَدِہِ الۡمُلۡکُ (67/1)» etc.","«مُبارک» Every thing in which there is an aspect of goodness and virtue, and which proves to be fruitful.\n«تبارک» The Essence of Allah Ta'ala is Most Blessed.","Blessed","تبارک ۔ مبرک","3:96-6:92-6:155-7:54-7:96-7:137-11:48-11:73-17:1-19:31-21:50-21:71-21:81-23:14-23:29-24:35-24:61-25:1-25:10-25:61-28:30-34:18-37:113-38:29-40:64-41:10-43:85-44:3-50:9-55:78-67:1",31
343,70,"M","اَیْمَن","«یَمِیْن» means the right hand and the right side, and «اَصْحٰبُ الْیَمِیْن» also denotes the right hand or those on the right, as well as the people of goodness and blessings (singular). «یَمَنَ یَیْمَنُ» means to be blessed or fortunate. «تَیَمُّن» signifies taking blessing or a good omen, while «مَیْمُون» means blessed (according to Majid), and in the view of Imam Raghib, «مَیْمُون» means fortunate. (singular) Just as prosperity is inherent in nature, so too is «اَیْمَن» that thing in whose very nature blessing has been ingrained.\n\nFor instance, the Holy Quran states: «فَلَمَّاۤ اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ» (28:30) Translation: Then when Moses (peace be upon him) arrived there, a voice called out to him from the blessed edge of the field.","«اَیْمَن» is inherent goodness and blessings. Felicity.","Most blessed","ایمن","19:52-20:80-28:30-56:8-90:18",5
344,70,"B","طیّب ، طوبٰی","«طَابَ» meaning something that pleases the heart, and «طَیَّب» meaning pure and lawful things, and «طِیْب» meaning fragrance. And «بَلْدَۃٌ طَیِّبَۃٌ» meaning a city of peace and blessings (Manjadd), and also «اَلْبَلَدُ الطَّیِّبُ» meaning blessed or fertile land (Muf).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَالۡبَلَدُ الطَّیِّبُ یَخۡرُجُ نَبَاتُہٗ بِاِذۡنِ رَبِّہٖ» (7/58)\nTranslation: And from the fertile land, vegetation emerges in abundance by the command of its Lord.\n\nAnd «طُوْبٰی» meaning envy, prosperity, goodness, and improvement (Manjadd). Thus, «طُوْبٰی» refers to such goodness and blessings that are also pleasing to the self.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ طُوۡبٰی لَہُمۡ وَحُسۡنُ مَاٰبٍ» (13/29)\nTranslation: For those who believe and do righteous deeds, for them is prosperity and an excellent place of return.","«طُوبی» a prosperity and blessing that delights the heart.","Blessed","طیب ، طوبی","2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-13:29-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12",43
345,71,"M","قَوْل","«قَوْل» Its plural forms are «اَقْوَال» and «اَلْجَمْعُ اَقَاوِیْل». Generally, it is understood that anything expressed by the tongue is a 'statement,' whether it be meaningless or meaningful. However, in the Noble Quran, this word has been used in three contexts: (1) For a statement that is uttered from the mouth, (2) For a statement that has not yet come out of the mouth but is still in the heart, and (3) It is also used for a doctrine or theory. Examples:\n\n(1) For a statement uttered from the mouth, the statement of Allah, the Most High is:\n«قَالَ قَآئِلٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ کَمۡ لَبِثۡتُمۡ» (18:19)\nTranslation: A speaker said, How long have you remained [here]?\n\n(2) For a statement in the heart, the statement of Allah, the Most High is:\n«وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ لَوۡلَا یُعَذِّبُنَا اللّٰہُ» (58:8)\nTranslation: And they say within themselves, If this is truly from Allah, then why does He not punish us?\n\n(3) For a doctrine or theory, the statement of Allah, the Most High is:\n«ذٰلِکَ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ ۚ قَوۡلَ الۡحَقِّ الَّذِیۡ  فِیۡہِ  یَمۡتَرُوۡنَ» (19:34)\nTranslation: That is Jesus, the son of Mary - a statement of truth about which they are in dispute.","«قَوْل» encompasses any matter, whether meaningless or meaningful, whether internal or ideological.","Matter","قول","2:8-2:26-2:58-2:59-2:68-2:69-2:71-2:79-2:80-2:83-2:102-2:104-2:113-2:117-2:118-2:136-2:140-2:142-2:154-2:169-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:214-2:235-2:263-3:7-3:16-3:47-3:64-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:124-3:147-3:154-3:167-3:181-4:5-4:8-4:9-4:43-4:46-4:51-4:63-4:73-4:75-4:78-4:81-4:94-4:108-4:148-4:150-4:155-4:156-4:157-4:171-5:19-5:41-5:52-5:53-5:63-5:73-5:83-5:109-5:116-6:22-6:25-6:33-6:50-6:53-6:73-6:93-6:105-6:112-6:148-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:53-7:105-7:161-7:162-7:169-7:172-7:173-7:205-8:49-9:30-9:40-9:49-9:50-9:61-9:65-9:124-10:18-10:20-10:28-10:31-10:38-10:48-10:65-10:68-10:77-11:7-11:8-11:10-11:12-11:13-11:18-11:31-11:35-11:40-11:53-11:54-11:91-12:66-12:81-13:5-13:7-13:10-13:27-13:33-13:43-14:27-14:44-15:97-16:27-16:32-16:40-16:86-16:103-16:116-17:16-17:23-17:28-17:40-17:42-17:43-17:47-17:51-17:53-17:108-18:5-18:22-18:23-18:42-18:49-18:52-18:88-18:93-19:26-19:34-19:35-19:66-19:79-19:80-20:7-20:28-20:40-20:44-20:47-20:89-20:94-20:97-20:104-20:109-20:130-21:4-21:27-21:38-21:46-21:110-22:24-22:30-22:40-23:27-23:68-23:70-23:85-23:87-23:89-23:109-24:15-24:26-24:47-24:51-25:17-25:19-25:22-25:27-25:65-25:74-26:16-26:203-26:226-27:19-27:49-27:71-27:82-27:85-28:28-28:47-28:51-28:62-28:63-28:65-28:74-28:82-29:2-29:10-29:46-29:55-29:61-29:63-30:58-31:25-32:3-32:13-32:28-33:4-33:12-33:13-33:32-33:37-33:66-33:70-34:29-34:31-34:40-34:42-36:7-36:48-36:58-36:70-36:76-36:82-37:31-37:36-37:52-37:151-37:167-38:17-38:84-39:18-39:38-39:56-39:57-39:58-40:28-40:44-40:47-40:68-41:25-41:33-41:50-42:24-42:44-43:9-43:13-43:87-44:34-46:8-46:11-46:17-46:18-47:20-47:21-47:30-48:11-48:15-49:2-49:14-50:18-50:29-50:30-52:33-50:39-50:45-51:8-52:30-52:33-52:44-54:2-54:8-54:44-56:47-57:13-58:1-58:2-58:8-59:10-59:11-60:4-61:2-61:3-63:4-63:7-63:8-63:10-66:8-67:13-67:25-68:51-69:19-69:25-69:40-69:41-69:42-69:44-72:4-72:5-73:5-73:10-74:25-74:31-75:10-78:40-79:10-81:19-81:25-86:13-89:15-89:16-89:24-90:6",327
346,71,"T","حَدِیْث","«حَدَثَ» means the emergence of something, the occurrence of an event, or the coming into existence of something new. Its opposite is «عَدَمَ». In the words of Ibn Faris, it is the coming into existence of something that did not exist before (m l). And in hadith, it refers to a new matter or theory that is related to common people and with which most people were previously unfamiliar.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا» (65/1)\nTranslation: Do you not know that Allah may bring about after that a new creation? (Othmani)\n\nFurthermore, the divine command states:\n«اَللّٰہُ نَزَّلَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡحَدِیۡثِ» (39/23)\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best of statements.\n\nHere, hadith refers to the Quran, and it is evident that according to the views and ideas of the people of that time, this was something new. Then, just as the term hadith is used for something new, it is also used for something old or an event that has generally been forgotten by people. In such a case, its meaning would be an old story or tale.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ» (23/44)\nTranslation: Whenever there came to them a messenger from Allah, they would deny him. So We seized them with destruction from the direction they did not expect, and We made them a subject of stories.","«حَدِیْث» A new matter. Something that common people are unaware of.","Thing","حدیث","4:42-4:78-4:87-4:140-6:68-7:185-12:6-12:21-12:101-12:111-18:6-20:9-23:44-31:6-33:53-34:19-39:23-45:6-51:24-52:34-53:59-56:81-66:3-68:44-77:50-79:15-85:17-88:1",28
347,71,"T","کَلِمَۃُ","The literal meaning of «کَلِمَۃُ» is meaningful speech—a statement that can be heard by the ears and whose meaning can be comprehended by the mind. In the words of Ibn Faris (under the root «نُطْقُ یُفْھَمُ»), it is defined as such. For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّہَا کَلِمَۃٌ ہُوَ قَآئِلُہَا» (23:100)\nTranslation: It will be a statement that the speaker will utter.\n\nHowever, when the word «کلمۃ» is attributed to the Essence of the Almighty, its meaning refers to the wonders of His power, the laws of nature, and Allah's creative works (as explained in *Tafhim al-Quran*). For example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُقَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ وَ لَوۡجِئۡنَا بِمِثۡلِہٖ مَدَدًا» (18:109)\nTranslation: Say, 'If the sea were ink for [writing] the words of my Lord, the sea would be exhausted before the words of my Lord were finished, even if We brought the like of it in addition.'\n\nAnd when the term Word is related from Allah to a human being, it refers to the divine commands and decrees. For example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنۡ حَقَّ عَلَیۡہِ کَلِمَۃُ الۡعَذَابِ ؕ اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» (39:19)\nTranslation: So is one against whom the decree of punishment is justified [equal to] one who is in the Fire? Will you rescue one who is destined for the Fire?","«کَلِمَۃُ» refers only to meaningful discourse—such as God's commandments and the wonders of His power, among other things.","thing","کلمۃ","2:37-2:75-2:124-3:39-3:45-3:64-4:46-4:171-5:13-5:41-6:34-6:115-7:137-7:144-7:158-8:7-9:6-9:40-9:74-10:19-10:33-10:64-10:82-10:96-11:110-11:119-14:24-14:26-18:5-18:27-18:109-20:129-23:100-31:27-35:10-37:171-39:19-39:71-40:6-41:45-42:14-42:21-42:24-43:28-48:15-48:26-66:12",47
348,71,"T","کَلَّمَ","«کَلَّمَ» means to be in conversation, to talk, or to converse (according to the lexicon). This term is generally used for brief conversations or for matters where a response can be given immediately upon hearing. Moreover, in «کَلَّمَ», it is not necessary for the conversation to be two-way; it can sometimes be one-sided.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَا یُکَلِّمُہُمُ اللّٰہُ وَلَا یَنۡظُرُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/77)\nTranslation: And Allah will not speak to them on the Day of Resurrection, nor will He look at them.","«کَلَّمَ» is a common term for conversation. It is generally used for brief and immediate dialogue.","Thing","کلم","2:118-2:174-2:253-3:41-3:46-3:77-4:164-5:110-6:111-7:143-7:148-11:105-12:54-13:31-19:10-19:26-19:29-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-42:51-78:38",24
349,71,"T","حَاوَرَ","Ibn Faris says that in «حَوْراً» there are basically two things: (1) referring back to a statement and (2) turning from one thing to another and then back to the second (M L). And Al-Munjid «حَارَ» writes that its meanings are to return and to be astonished. So it seems «حَاوَرَ» refers to conversation that is in the form of question and answer. And the listener must think and understand before giving the answer. Such conversation is generally lengthy. From this, the word muhawarah (proverb) is derived, which means that the saying is thought out and spoken, and also common, famous, and understandable.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is: «قَالَ لَہٗ صَاحِبُہٗ وَ ہُوَ یُحَاوِرُہٗۤ اَکَفَرۡتَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ مِنۡ تُرَابٍ ثُمَّ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ ثُمَّ سَوّٰىکَ رَجُلًا» (18/37) Translation: Then his companion who was conversing with him will say, Do you disbelieve in Him (God) who created you from dust, then from a sperm-drop, then fashioned you as a complete man?","«حَاوَرَ» A dialogue in the question-and-answer format that is conducted after careful thought and reflection and is extensive.","thing","حاور","18:34-18:37-58:1",3
350,71,"M","خَاطَب","«خَاطَبَ» also conveys the meanings of conversation or discussion and refers to the sermon, which is generally one-sided. The preacher, meaning the one who delivers the sermon, speaks with clarity (M Q), and sometimes it happens that the listener, by giving a brief reply, silences the one addressing them.\n\nThus, in the Quran, Allah Almighty addresses Prophet Noah (peace be upon him) saying:\n\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا وَ لَا تُخَاطِبۡنِیۡ فِی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا» (11/37)\nTranslation: And construct a ship under Our command and in Our presence, and do not speak to Us about the wrongdoers.\n\nIn another instance, Allah Almighty, while describing the attributes of His servants, says:\n\n«وَّاِذَا خَاطَبَہُمُ الۡجٰہِلُوۡنَ  قَالُوۡا سَلٰمًا» (25/63)\nTranslation: And when ignorant people address them with ignorant speech, they respond with words of peace.","«خَاطَبَ» This is generally a one-sided matter. Or, if the respondent prefers to answer or deems it necessary, then they should provide it.","Matter","خاطب","11:37-23:27-25:63",3
351,72,"M","سُلْطَان","The word «سُلْطَان» comes with three meanings:\n(1) Meaning evidence which holds the status of a proof or document. Authority. In these meanings, this word appears frequently in the Quran.\n(2) Sovereignty or kingship. In this meaning, it appears only in one instance.\n(3) Meaning 'kings' (plural). Its plural is 'sultans'. In these meanings, this word does not appear in the Quran, and the meaning of 'sultan' as 'king' is not literal from the lexical perspective; rather, it is a derivative meaning.\nWhen this word comes in the meanings of sovereignty or kingship, it refers to that territory which is under the control of a person, institution, or king, and over which he exercises his dominion.\nFor example: The Quran states that a disbeliever will say on the Day of Judgment:\n«مَاۤ اَغۡنٰی عَنِّیۡ مَالِیَہۡ ہَلَکَ عَنِّیۡ سُلۡطٰنِیَہۡ» (69/28,29)\nTranslation: Today my wealth is of no use to me at all. (Woe to me!) My sovereignty has also left me.","When the expression of authority and glory is intended, «سُلْطَان» is used. And when the expression of the vastness of territory is intended, «مُلْک» is used.","Monarchy","سلطان","3:151-4:90-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29",39
352,72,"M","مُلْک","The word «مُلک» carries a broader meaning than sovereignty. A specific region of the earth bounded by natural limits is also a ملک, and the entire surface of the earth is also a ملک.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلِ اللّٰہُمَّ مٰلِکَ الۡمُلۡکِ تُؤۡتِی الۡمُلۡکَ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ وَ تَنۡزِعُ الۡمُلۡکَ مِمَّنۡ تَشَآءُ» (3:26)\nTranslation: Say, 'O Allah, Owner of all sovereignty! You grant sovereignty to whom You will and strip it from whom You will.'\n\nIn this verse, the first ملک is in the sense of the entire surface of the earth, and the second is in the sense of a specific territory.\n\nFurthermore, the meanings of «مُلک» include ownership, sovereignty, and possession, while «مَلِک» means king. The plural forms of these two are «اَملَاک» and «مُلُوک» (source: Minaj). The word «مَلَکُوْت» also comes with an even broader meaning than «مُلک», signifying sovereignty over the heavens and the earth or the entire universe.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاتَّبَعُوۡا مَا تَتۡلُوا الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ عَلٰی مُلۡکِ سُلَیۡمٰنَ» (2:102)\nTranslation: And they followed what the devils used to recite during the reign of Sulaiman (Solomon).\n\n«فَسُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ بِیَدِہٖ مَلَکُوۡتُ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ وَّ اِلَیۡہِ  تُرۡجَعُوۡنَ» (83:36)\nTranslation: Exalted is He in whose hand is the dominion of all things, and to Him you will be returned.","«مُلک» is a specific area of land with defined borders and boundaries, and is also used to refer to all land surfaces.","Monarchy","ملک","2:102-2:107-2:247-2:248-2:251-2:258-3:26-3:189-4:53-4:54-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:120-6:73-6:75-7:158-7:185-9:116-12:101-17:111-20:120-22:56-23:88-24:42-25:2-25:26-27:23-35:13-36:83-38:10-38:20-38:35-39:6-39:44-40:16-40:29-42:49-43:51-43:85-45:27-48:14-57:2-57:5-64:1-67:1-76:20-85:9",48
353,73,"C","سحاب","«سَحَبْ» means to pull or drag, and its usage for clouds is common (f. l 454). All types of clouds are referred to as «سَحَاب»; however, this term specifically applies to clouds that winds lift and spread across the sky. Essentially, this is the primordial form of any cloud.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَاللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡۤ اَرۡسَلَ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا» (35:9). Translation: And Allah is the One who sends the winds and raises the clouds.","In common usage, «سَحَاب» is used for clouds.","Cloud","سحاب","2:164-7:57-13:12-24:40-24:43-27:88-30:48-35:9-52:44",9
354,73,"C","غَمَام","«غَمَّ» means to cover (manjad), and «غَمَام» is the cloud that becomes thick and dense in layers, blocking the sunlight from reaching the earth. (f.l 254) That is, it casts a shadow on the earth.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ ظَلَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡغَمَامَ وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡمَنَّ وَ السَّلۡوٰی» (2/57). Translation: And We have made a cloud to provide shade over you, and We sent down manna and quails for you.","When clouds become thick and shady, they are called «غَمَام».","cloud","غمام","2:57-2:210-7:160-25:25",4
355,73,"C","عَارِض","Then, when the clouds become dense and spread out and drizzle also begins, it is called «عَارِض» (f.l. 254). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا عَارِضٌ مُّمۡطِرُنَا ؕ بَلۡ ہُوَمَا اسۡتَعۡجَلۡتُمۡ بِہٖ ؕ رِیۡحٌ  فِیۡہَا عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (46/24). Translation: They began to say, This cloud will rain upon us. (No,) but this is the thing for which you were in haste—a wind bearing a painful punishment.","«عَارِض» A cloud that has started to rain.","Cloud","عارض","46:24",1
356,73,"C","مُعْصِرٰت","«عَصَرَ» means to wring out clothes and (to extract juice from fruits, etc.). It also refers to the extracted juice (m l). And «اَعْصَرَ الْقَوْم» means to send rain upon a people (munjad). And «مُعْصِرَات» is the plural of «مُعْصِرَۃٌ», i.e., clouds that are laden with water and are about to rain, clouds that are squeezing out [rain].\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَّاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡمُعۡصِرٰتِ مَآءً  ثَجَّاجًا» (78/14).\n\nTranslation: And We caused a torrential rain to fall from the squeezing clouds.","«مُعْصِرٰت» clouds full of water.","cloud","معصرت","78:14",1
357,73,"C","مُزْن","«مَزَنَ» meaning a water skin (i.e., a container for water) to fill with water, etc., and «اِبْنُ الْمُزْنَۃ». They call the moon that appears from the clouds (مف), and «مَزن» they call the white and shiny clouds (مف. فل 255), and «حَبُّ الْمُزْن» they call the hail (منجد), and «مُزْن» they call the rain-bearing cloud (منجد).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡزَلۡتُمُوۡہُ مِنَ الۡمُزۡنِ اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡزِلُوۡنَ» (56/69)\nTranslation: Have you seen the water that you bring down from the clouds, or do We bring it down?","«مُزْن» white gleaming clouds.","cloud","مزن","56:69",1
358,73,"C","صَیِّب","«صَیِّب» A severe, thunderous cloud (Fal 255), whereas Ibn Abbas intends by it a heavy downpour (M. L). According to Al-Munjid, any rain-bearing cloud is «صَیِّب».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ» (2/19)\nTranslation: Or like a rainstorm from the sky, wherein is darkness, thunder, and lightning.","«صَیِّب» is what a severe thundercloud is called.","Cloud","صیب","2:19",1
359,74,"B","مَرَّۃ","«مَرَّ» means to pass by a place (intransitive) and also the passage of time. In this sense, its meaning would be to pass once or to do something once. Its dual form is «مَرَّتَان» or «مَرَّتَیْن», and its plural forms are «مرّات» and «مَرَارًا» (meaning many times).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَوَلَا یَرَوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ یُفۡتَنُوۡنَ فِیۡ کُلِّ عَامٍ مَّرَّۃً اَوۡ مَرَّتَیۡنِ» ( 9/126 )\nTranslation: Do they not see that they are afflicted with some calamity once or twice every year?","«مَرَّۃ» is a common word for 'times' or 'occasions'.","Burden","مرۃ","6:94-6:110-8:56-9:13-9:80-9:83-9:126-17:7-17:51-18:48-20:37-36:79-41:21",13
360,74,"T","کَرَّۃً","«کَرَّ ، کَرَارًا» meaning (to attack an enemy). To break off. From this, the word «کَرّار» is famous, and *karr wa farr* refers to that war tactic which was famous among Arabs in a certain era. That is, to attack and then suddenly retreat and then break off again, and «کَرّ ۔ تکرارًا» meaning to do something repeatedly as before (manjada). And this is the subject under discussion. That is, to do something exactly as it was done before, to do it once again. And in the words of Ibn al-Faris, «رُجُوْع اِلَی الشَّی بَعْدَ مَرَّۃَ الْاُوْلٰی» (m l) means to do something again just as before (fq l), and «کَرَّۃً» means both an attack in battle once and also to do something again; it is used in both these meanings.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ رَدَدۡنَا لَکُمُ الۡکَرَّۃَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» ( 17/6 )\nTranslation: Then We gave you the upper hand over them for a second time.\nIn this verse, the word «کَرَّۃَ» is conveying both meanings, and the result «عَلیٰ» is manifesting the victory.\n\nAt another place, the sublime declaration of Allah is:\n«ثُمَّ ارۡجِعِ الۡبَصَرَکَرَّتَیۡنِ یَنۡقَلِبۡ اِلَیۡکَ الۡبَصَرُ خَاسِئًا وَّ ہُوَ حَسِیۡرٌ» ( 67/4 )\nTranslation: Then look again and yet again; your sight will return to you humbled and weary.\nWhen a poet recites his poetry, someone from the audience shouts the slogan *mukarrar* (مکرّر), which means recite that verse again, two or three times. This is the meaning of «کَرَّۃ», and according to Abu Hilal al-Askari, for doing something a second time or repeating it, *i'ada* (اعادہ) is used, and for doing something more than twice, «کرّر» is used (fq. l 27).","«کَرَّۃ» means once again and is used to perform the same task more than twice or to do it repeatedly.","time","کرۃً","2:167-17:6-26:102-39:58-67:4-79:12",6
361,74,"R","تَارَۃً","«تَارَۃً» Some lexicographers have brought it under «تَوْر» and others under «تَار». And its meaning is «اِعَادَۃً بَعْدَ مَرَّۃٍ» (m. q.) and with the meaning of time and once (m. r.), i.e., to do that work again at some time, once more. «فَعَلْتُ تَارَۃً ھَذَا اَو تَارَۃً ذَاکَ» means I have done this work sometimes and that (at times)—as if «تَارَۃً» is the repetition of such a work that was done at some time before.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «مِنۡہَا خَلَقۡنٰکُمۡ وَ فِیۡہَا نُعِیۡدُکُمۡ وَمِنۡہَا نُخۡرِجُکُمۡ تَارَۃً اُخۡرٰی» (20/55) Translation: From this (earth) We have created you, and into it We will return you, and from it We will extract you a second time.","«تَارَۃً» meaning to do again, at some time, what one has already done before.","Rain","تارۃً","17:69-20:55",2
362,75,"R","مَطَر","«مَطَر» is a general term for rain. Whether the rain is beneficial or harmful, whether it is water falling or something else, the word «مَطَر» can be used for all. And «اَمْطَرَ» means to send rain. For example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَاَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ مَّطَرًا ۚ فَسَآءَ مَطَرُالۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ» (26/173). Translation: And We sent upon them a torrential rain. It was a devastating rain upon those who had already been warned.","«مَطَر» is used for all types of rain. It is a masculine noun.","Rain","مطر","4:102--7:84-8:32-11:82-15:74-25:40-26:173-27:58-46:24",9
363,75,"R","مَآءَ","«مَآءَ» literally means water. «مِیَاہ» is used metaphorically to refer to rain.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَّاَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَاَخۡرَجَ بِہٖ مِنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ رِزۡقًا لَّکُمۡ» (2/22)  \nTranslation: And He sent down rain from the sky and brought forth for you from the earth every kind of fruit as sustenance.","«مَآءَ», meaning water, is used metaphorically to refer to rain.","rain","مآء","2:22-2:164-4:43-5:6-6:99-8:11-13:17-14:16-14:32-15:22-16:10-16:65-20:53-22:63-23:18-24:39-24:45-25:48-27:60-28:23-29:63-30:24-31:10-32:8-35:27-39:21-43:11-47:15-50:9-72:16-77:20-77:27-78:14-86:6",34
364,75,"R","طَلّ","The term «طَلّ» is used for both dew and light rain (as in Quran 2:265, etc.). For example: the Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ لَّمۡ یُصِبۡہَا وَابِلٌ فَطَلٌّ» (2/265)\nTranslation: Then if no rain falls, the drizzle is also sufficient.","«طَلّ» dew or frost","Rain","طل","2:265",1
365,75,"R","وَدْق","Continuous rainfall is termed «وَدْق» (f.l. 258). Such rain generally falls slowly and persists for a long duration.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  رُکَامًا فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ» (24:43)\n\nTranslation: Then He layers them layer upon layer, and you see the rain emerge from within them.","«وَدْق» gentle and steady rain.","Rain","ودق","24:43-30:48",2
366,75,"R","غَیْث","«غَیْث» is the rain that comes at its required time and in accordance with the need (F L 258. M L).  \nFor instance, the Quran states:  \n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57/20)  \nTranslation: Just as rain is such that from it crops grow and farmers find it pleasing.","«غَیْث» rainfall that comes when needed and in the measure required.","Rain","غیث","31:34-42:28-57:20",3
367,75,"R","مِدْرَارًا","«الدَّرّ» refers to milk and the abundance of milk, and «دَرُوْر» refers to a she-camel that gives milk in great abundance. From this, «مِدْرَارًا» is derived. The meaning of «عَیْنٌ مِدْرَارٌ» is an eye that sheds copious tears, and the meaning of «مِدْرَار» is a rain that falls heavily (manjad). And «مِدْرَار» is the rain in which there is an abundance of water.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یٰقَوۡمِ اسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡا رَبَّکُمۡ ثُمَّ تُوۡبُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِ یُرۡسِلِ السَّمَآءَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّدۡرَارًا» (11/52)\nTranslation: And, O my people, seek forgiveness from your Lord and then repent to Him. He will send down rain upon you in showers.","«مِدْرَار» is called torrential rain.","Rain","مدرارًا","6:6-11:52-71:11",3
368,75,"R","غَدَق","According to Ibn al-Faris, «غَدَق» is that rain which is both abundant in water and beneficial (م ل), and «غَدَقَۃٌ» means a sweet spring, and «غَدَقَ الْمَکَان» means a place becoming wet from rain, becoming verdant. And «غَدِق» means a green place (munjad). Thus, «غَدَق» refers to such rain that causes verdancy.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّاَنۡ لَّوِ اسۡتَقَامُوۡاعَلَی الطَّرِیۡقَۃِ لَاَسۡقَیۡنٰہُمۡ مَّآءً غَدَقًا» ( 72/16 )\nTranslation: And if these people had remained on the right path, We would have given them abundant water to drink.","«غَدَق» abundant and beneficial rain, i.e., rain that causes vegetation to grow.","rain","غدق","72:16",1
369,75,"R","صَیِّب","«صَیِّب» Such a heavy downpour is described as one in which the clouds are thundering loudly and lightning is flashing brilliantly (F L 255. M R). According to Ibn al-Faris, it refers to rain that falls in a concentrated, heavy manner (M L). In Punjabi, such a rain is called 'phanda'.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَصَیِّبٍ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فِیۡہِ ظُلُمٰتٌ وَّ رَعۡدٌ وَّ بَرۡقٌ» (2/19)\nTranslation: Or [it is] like a rainstorm from the sky, wherein is darkness, thunder, and lightning.","«صَیِّب» Heavy rain with large droplets.","rain","صیب","2:19",1
370,75,"R","وَابِل","The meaning of «وَبَل» is to strike continuously with a stick (manjad); in its meaning, severity and weight are found. Ibn Faris says that «وَبَل» denotes intensity and abundance in something. And «وَابِل» refers to a rain of severe type (m l). Thus, «وَابِل» is that rain which, due to the abundance of water and its own severity and swiftness, carries away debris (i.e., grass, twigs, rubbish). It is the final degree of rainfall.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۡدًا» (2/264)\n\nTranslation: Its example is like that of a [rock] upon which is a little soil, then a heavy rain strikes it and leaves it bare.","«وَابِل» a downpour that sweeps away all debris—grass, twigs, and litter.","Rain","وابل","2:264-2:265",2
371,76,"O","اِنْتَھٰی","«اَلنَّھْی» means to restrain or hold back, and «اِنْتَھٰی» signifies returning or ceasing. «النِّھَاءُ وَالنِّھَایَۃُ» denotes the outcome, termination, or ultimate limit of something (as in 'manjada'). For example, the Quran states: «فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا اَئِمَّۃَ الۡکُفۡرِ ۙ اِنَّہُمۡ لَاۤ اَیۡمَانَ لَہُمۡ لَعَلَّہُمۡ  یَنۡتَہُوۡنَ» (9:12). Translation: So fight the leaders of disbelief, for they are not truthful in their oaths. It would not be surprising if they were to desist.","The act of abstaining from an action in «انتھی» is largely optional, whereas in «اِنْفَکَّ» this act occurs in cases of necessity (compulsion, helplessness).","(One who) returns (to Allah); a falcon.","انتھی","2:192-2:193-2:275-4:171-5:73-5:91-8:19-8:38-8:39-9:12-19:46-26:116-26:167-33:60-36:18-53:14-53:42-59:7-96:15",19
372,76,"O","اِنَّفَکَ","«فَکّ» means to free someone from a bond.  \n«فَکُ الْاَسِیْر» means to release a captive.  \n«اِنْفِکَاک» means to separate oneself or to open.  \n«اِنْفِکَاکُ الْعَبْد» means the freeing of a slave.  \nAlso, «اِنْفَکَّ الْعَظْمُ» means the shoulder slipping out of its place due to weakness (dislocation). This implies that abstaining in «اِنْفِکَاک» is necessarily compulsory (i.e., by force), meaning to forcibly separate from the place where one was stuck.  \n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«لَمۡ یَکُنِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ مُنۡفَکِّیۡنَ حَتّٰی تَاۡتِیَہُمُ الۡبَیِّنَۃُ» (98/1)  \n\nTranslation: Those who are disbelievers—namely, the People of the Book and the polytheists—were not those who abstain (from disbelief) until clear evidence came to them.  \n\nAnd this clear evidence was the Prophethood and the dominance of Islam of the Honored Prophet ﷺ, which compelled them to abstain from disbelief and polytheism.","«اِنَّفَکَ» To free someone from a bond or to forcibly prevent someone from doing something.","Open","انفک","98:1",1
373,77,"A","جَنَاح","«جَنَاح» means 'bird's feather or wing.' The dual form «جَنَاحَیْن» is then metaphorically used for the two sides of anything as well. «جَنَاحَا الْعَسْکَر» means both wings of a bee or, similarly, both arms of a human. The word «جَنَاحَ» is used to denote the right or left side, aspect, or arm—in all contexts. Moreover, by 'arm' is meant the part from the shoulder to the fingertips.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ اضۡمُمۡ  اِلَیۡکَ جَنَاحَکَ مِنَ الرَّہۡبِ» (28/32)\nTranslation: And for protection from fear, draw your arm close to yourself.","«جَنَاح» refers to the arm, from the shoulder to the fingertips.","arm","جناح","6:38-15:88-17:24-20:22-26:215-28:32",6
374,77,"A","عَضُد","«عَضُدُ» refers to the part from the elbow to the shoulder (singular). And «عَضدْتُہٗ» means I struck it on the arm. Also, its meanings include I grabbed its arm and supported it. Therefore, this word, like «یَدْ», also comes in the metaphorical sense of helper (singular). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ مَا کُنۡتُ مُتَّخِذَ الۡمُضِلِّیۡنَ عَضُدًا» (18/51). Translation: And I was not one to make the misguiders helpers.","«عَضُدُ» refers to the area between the arm, shoulder, and elbow.","Arm","عضد","18:51-28:35",2
375,77,"A","ذِرَاع","«ذِرَاع» meaning from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger, and its translation is generally taken as hand. (Mufradat)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کَلۡبُہُمۡ بَاسِطٌ ذِرَاعَیۡہِ  بِالۡوَصِیۡدِ» (18:18)\nTranslation: And their dog was stretching its forepaws at the threshold.\n\nThus, the meaning of «ذِرَاع» in measurement is also taken as that length, from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger. This length is called a hand. Since a person's height and stature vary in different eras, the amount of this measurement has also varied. The author of Minhaj has stated it to be 50 to 70 centimeters, i.e., approximately 20 to 28 inches. Some translators have also translated it as gaz.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  فِیۡ سِلۡسِلَۃٍ  ذَرۡعُہَا سَبۡعُوۡنَ  ذِرَاعًا  فَاسۡلُکُوۡہُ» (69:32)\nTranslation: Then fasten him with a chain whose length is seventy hands.","«ذِرَاع» refers to the length from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger.","arm","ذراع","18:51-28:35",2
376,78,"G","جَنَّۃ","«جَنَّۃ» is derived from «جَنَّ», the meaning of which is to conceal and hide something from the senses. And «جَنّۃٌ» refers to a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees and greenery (muf). According to the author of Minjd, «جَنَّۃٌ» is a lush garden, whether earthly or celestial.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265)\nTranslation: (Their example is) like a garden on a high ground; upon which heavy rain falls and it yields double the fruit.","«جَنَّۃ» Such a garden is called one whose ground is not visible because of trees and greenery.","Garden","جنۃ","2:25-2:35-2:82-2:111-2:214-2:221-2:265-2:266-3:15-3:133-3:136-3:142-3:185-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-4:124-5:12-5:65-5:72-5:85-5:119-6:99-6:141-7:19-7:22-7:27-7:40-7:42-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:49-7:50-9:21-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:9-10:26-11:23-11:108-13:4-13:23-13:35-14:23-15:45-16:31-16:32-17:91-18:31-18:32-18:33-18:35-18:39-18:40-18:107-19:60-19:61-19:63-20:76-20:117-20:121-22:14-22:23-22:56-23:19-25:8-25:10-25:15-25:24-26:57-26:85-26:90-26:134-26:147-29:58-31:8-32:19-34:15-34:16-35:33-36:26-36:34-36:55-37:43-38:50-39:73-39:74-40:8-40:40-41:30-42:7-42:22-43:70-43:72-44:25-44:52-46:14-46:16-47:6-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-50:9-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:15-54:54-55:46-55:54-55:62-56:12-56:89-57:12-57:21-58:22-59:20-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:11-68:17-68:34-69:22-70:35-70:38-71:12-74:40-76:12-78:16-79:41-81:13-85:11-88:10-89:30-98:8",143
377,78,"G","حَدَآئِق","«حَدَآئِق» is the plural form of «حَدِیْقَۃ» and «حَدِیْقَۃ» is derived from «حَدَقَ». The meaning of «حَدَقَ» is to surround something from all sides. Therefore, «حَدِیْقَۃ» refers to a garden or orchard that has been enclosed by four walls for protection (Munjad). For instance, the Noble Quran mentions: «فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27:60). Translation: Then We caused a verdant garden to grow from that rain.","«حَدَآئِق» Such gardens or orchards, around which a four-walled enclosure has been built for protection, are called.","garden","حدآئق","27:60-78:32-80:30",3
378,78,"G","رَوْضَۃ","The plural of «رَوْضَۃ» is «رَوْضَات», and the word «رَوْض» indicates vastness and abundance (m. l.). The meaning of «رَوَّضَ الْمَطْرُالْاَرْضَ» is to make the earth into gardens and springtime due to rain, and «رَوْضَۃ» also refers to an ever-blooming garden (munjid). Thus, «رَوْضَہ» denotes a section or place within a garden that is particularly large and ever-blooming, and it is typically in such a place that structures like balconies or terraces are built.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ» (30:15)\nTranslation: So those who believed and did righteous deeds will be admitted to gardens (of Paradise).","The term refers to the spacious open area within a garden, where structures such as balconies or terraces are typically built.","Garden","روضۃ","30:15-42:22",2
379,79,"T","اَبْقٰی","The meaning of «بَقٰی» is for something to remain and endure forever (m. l.), and its opposites are «فَنٰی» and «ھَلَکَ». That is, the annihilation and destruction of something. And the meaning of «اَبْقٰی» is to keep something established and remaining.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «وَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰیوَاَنَّہٗۤ اَہۡلَکَ عَادَۨا الۡاُوۡلٰی وَثَمُوۡدَا۠ فَمَاۤ اَبۡقٰی» (53/50,51). Translation: And He destroyed the former people of 'Ad and Thamud as well, so that He did not leave anyone remaining.","«اَبْقٰی» To sustain the existence of something.","The Everlasting","ابقی","2:248-2:278-11:86-11:116-20:71-20:73-20:127-20:131-28:60-42:36-53:51-55:27-74:28-87:17",14
380,79,"E","اَثْبَتَ","The meaning of «ثَبَتَ» is for something to remain firm in its state, and its opposite is «زَالَ», which means for something to be displaced from its place, moving hither and thither. The meaning of «اَثْبَتَ» is to keep something firmly established and preserved in its original state (Mufradat).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ» (13:39)\nTranslation: Allah eliminates what He wills and retains what He wills. (Uthmani)","«اَثْبَتَ» to keep something in its original state and maintain it.","Everlasting","اثبت","2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7",12
381,79,"E","غَادَر","The meaning of «غَدَرَ» is to break a covenant and to break a promise (M. L). It also means to leave behind (M. R). And the meaning of «غَادَرَ» is to intentionally leave something out or not count it during the reckoning (Muf).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ یٰوَیۡلَتَنَا مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ اَحۡصٰہَا» (18/49)\nTranslation: And they will say, Woe to us! What sort of book is this that leaves neither a small thing nor a big thing unrecorded, but has recorded everything.","to spare one out of many","Everlasting","غادر","18:47-18:49",2
382,80,"H","شَعْر","«شَعْر» the hair of all living beings, including humans. This word is general in meaning, and its plural form is ash'ār. (Fil 98)","The hair of all living beings, including humans, is called «شَعْر».","Hair","شعر","16:80",1
383,80,"H","وَبْر","«وَبْر» the hair and fur of camels and birds streaming. Its plural is «اَوْبَار» (F 98)","The hair or fur of camels and birds is referred to as «وَبْر».","Hair","وبر","16:80",1
384,80,"H","صُوْف","«صُوْف» is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc. Its plural is «اَصْوَاف» (ف ل 98).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ اَصۡوَافِہَا وَاَوۡبَارِہَا وَاَشۡعَارِہَاۤ اَثَاثًا وَّمَتَاعًا اِلٰی حِیۡنٍ» (16/80)\nTranslation: And they used their wool, their fur, and their hair to produce household goods and items that bring you benefit for a time.","«صُوْف» is used for the wool and hair of sheep, goats, etc.","hair","صوف","16:80",1
385,81,"B","عَاقِر","In the original material of «عَاقِر», the meaning of inflicting a wound is found. For example, «اَلْکَلْبُ الْعَقُوْر» refers to the dog that cuts, and «عَقَرَ النَّخلَۃ» means to cut a date palm tree from its root.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَکَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَعَقَرُوۡہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So they denied the Prophet (peace be upon him) and cut off the she-camel's tendons.\n\nFurthermore, «اَلْعَقْر» also refers to one's last child, after whom there is no offspring (detailed). Thus, the word «عَاقِر» is used for a woman who previously had children but later, due to injury in the womb or cessation of menstruation or any other reason, stopped bearing children. Moreover, this term is used for both men and women.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِنِّیۡ خِفۡتُ الۡمَوَالِیَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِیۡ وَ کَانَتِ امۡرَاَتِیۡ عَاقِرًا فَہَبۡ لِیۡ مِنۡ لَّدُنۡکَ  وَلِیًّا» (19/5)\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya, peace be upon him, supplicated to Allah) saying, 'And I fear my brothers after me, and my wife is barren; so grant me from Yourself an heir.'","«عَاقِر» A woman who previously had children but has since stopped.","Barren","عاقر","3:40-19:5-19:8",3
386,81,"B","عَقِیْم","«عَقِیْم» is also used for both masculine and feminine, similar to «عَاقِر». «عَقِیْم» also refers to a patch of sand or earth that is barren (M. R.), and «رِیْحٌ عَقِیْمٌ» refers to a wind that is devoid of goodness.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَفِیْ عَادٍ اِذْ اَرْسَلْنَا عَلَیْهِمُ الرِّیْحَ الْعَقِیْمَۚ» (51/41)\nTranslation: Thus there has also come a warning to the people of 'Ad, when We sent against them the barren wind.\n\nFurthermore, «عَقِیْم» is a person whose reproductive material is absent or whose semen is dead (in common terms, a man lacking the ability to procreate). Similarly, «عَقِیْم» refers to a woman who does not accept male semen at all (M. R.). Thus, «عَقِیْم» is a man or woman who has had no offspring from the very beginning.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوۡ یُزَوِّجُہُمۡ ذُکۡرَانًا وَّاِنَاثًا ۚ وَیَجۡعَلُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ عَقِیۡمًا» (42/50)\nTranslation: Or He grants them both sons and daughters, and He makes whom He wills barren.","«عَقِیْم» refers to a woman who does not bear a child and a man from whose sperm pregnancy does not occur; the term sterile is used for both.","barren","عقیم","22:55-42:50-51:29-51:41",4
387,82,"T","رَبَطَ","«رَبَطَ» To bind firmly and «مِرْبَطُ» the rope etc. for tying animals, «مَرْبَطُ» the place for tying livestock, and «رَبَّاط» meaning the one who ties the rope, and «رَبَیْطَہ» meaning the tied animal, and «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ» is an idiom. Allah Almighty has bound his heart, i.e., He has granted his heart strength and bestowed patience upon it (Manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: Had We not fortified his (i.e., the mother of Moses') heart, he would have almost disclosed the matter.","«رَبَطَ» binding something with a rope, and «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلیٰ قَلْبِہٖ» Allah strengthening a person's heart and granting patience.","to tie","ربط","8:11-18:14-28:10",3
388,82,"T","شَدَّ","«شَدَّ الشَّیْء» meaning to tie something firmly, to strengthen. To tie firmly (Manajid).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ  اَثۡخَنۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ فَشُدُّواالۡوَثَاقَ» (47/4)\nTranslation: Then when you have overcome them, bind them firmly.","«شَدّ» to tie very securely","to bind","شد","10:88-20:31-28:35-38:20-47:4-66:6-76:28-78:12",8
389,82,"T","غُلّ","Its plural is «اَغْلَال». It refers to any thing with which a limb is tied and bound in the middle, and it also means a fetter. Metaphorically, «مَغْلُولُ الْیَد» is used for a stingy person, meaning his hands are bound from spending (i.e., he is tight-fisted). (mufradat)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَقَالَتِ الۡیَہُوۡدُ یَدُ اللّٰہِ مَغۡلُوۡلَۃٌ ؕ غُلَّتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ لُعِنُوۡا بِمَا قَالُوۡا ۘ بَلۡ یَدٰہُ مَبۡسُوۡطَتٰنِ ۙ یُنۡفِقُ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (5/64)\n\nTranslation: And the Jews say, The hand of Allah is chained (i.e., Allah is stingy). Chained are their own hands; and cursed they are for what they say. Nay, both His hands are widely outstretched, and He spends [from His bounty] as He wills.","«غُلّ» refers to a miserly person, meaning that his hands are tied from spending.","to tie / to bind","غل","5:64-12:23-17:29",3
390,83,"I","صَنَم","The plural of «صَنَم» is «اَصْنَام», meaning self-carved idols and statues made of silver, brass, or wood, etc., that could be transferred and traded. (lexical explanation) «صَنَّاعَۃُ الْاَصْنَام» refers to the art and profession of idol-selling. Prophet Ibrahim's (peace be upon him) father, Azar, used to practice this trade. And Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) supplicates to his Lord thus: For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ» (14/35) Translation: And (O Lord) keep me and my offspring away from worshipping idols.","«صَنَم» idols and statues carved from silver, brass, or wood.","Idol","صنم","6:74-7:138-14:35-21:57-26:71",5
391,83,"I","نُصُب","«نَصَبَ الشَّیْء» means to set up an idol facing a certain direction and to bury it in the ground. And «نَصِیْبٌ» is that stone which is buried to mark a path (as a guide). And «نَصِیْب» also refers to such a statue made of stone, iron, etc., which has been erected in a place for the purpose of worship. These statues are generally of prophets, saints, or elders, or kings. And such places where these statues are erected are called 'thaan'. And its plurals are «نُصُب» and «اَنْصَاب».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَمَا ذُبِحَ عَلَی النُّصُبِ وَ اَنۡ تَسۡتَقۡسِمُوۡا بِالۡاَزۡلَامِ» (5:3)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] animals sacrificed on stone altars [to idols], and those divided by divining arrows. (All this has been forbidden to you).","«نَصَب» statues buried in the ground.","Idol","نصب","5:3-70:43-88:19",3
392,83,"I","وَثْن","«وَثْن» is the plural of «اَوْثَان», referring to idols that remain fixed and established in their place. These are not carved or installed idols. Rather, in certain specific locations such as rocks, trees, stars, or rivers, etc., worship begins when people hold the belief that God's attributes are manifest there. The idolater is called «اَلْوَثَنِیٌّ» and such idolatry is called «اَلْوَثَنِیَّۃ» (Minjd). For example, the Quran states: «فَاجۡتَنِبُواالرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَاجۡتَنِبُوۡا قَوۡلَ الزُّوۡرِ» (22:30). Translation: So shun the filth of idols and shun false speech.","«وَثْن» The practice of believing that certain specific places—such as stones, trees, stars, or rivers—embody the attributes of God, and then beginning to worship them.","Idol","وثن","22:30-29:17-29:25",3
393,83,"I","جِبْت","«جِبْت» meaning idol, soothsayer, divination, and anything devoid of goodness. For example, magic and charms (m. r.)—this word is actually an umbrella term for superstitions, doubts, and myths. It encompasses everything: magic, charms, incantations, the influences of stars, talismans, amulets, inscriptions, and so forth.","«جِبْت» referring to idols, soothsaying, divination, and all such things that contain no good. For example, sorcery spells.","idol","جبت","4:51",1
394,83,"I","طَاغُوْت","«طَاغُوْت» meaning Lāt, ‘Uzzā, sorcerer, soothsayer, falsehood, idol, and worship of anything other than Allah, and rebellious (ref.). That is, taghut refers to every false and rebellious system or power that inclines people to obey its commands in opposition to Allah and is accepted as such.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡنَ اُوۡتُوۡا نَصِیۡبًا مِّنَ الۡکِتٰبِ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِالۡجِبۡتِ وَالطَّاغُوۡتِ» ( 4/51 )\nTranslation: Have you not seen those who were given a portion of the Scripture? They believe in the idol and the false deity.","«طَاغُوْت» refers to all false and rebellious systems or powers that oppose Allah's commands and are recognized as such.","Idol","طاغوت","2:256-2:257-4:51-4:60-4:76-5:60-16:36-37:30-38:55-39:17-51:53-52:32-68:31-69:5-78:22",15
395,84,"E","بَرْق","«بَرْق» refers to the dazzling or flashing lightning that blinds and stuns the eyes, and «بَرِقَ الْبَصَرُ» means the dazzling or blurring of eyesight.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» (2/20)  \nTranslation: It is as if the lightning were about to snatch away their sight.","«بَرْق» refers to the flashing or sparkling lightning.","Electricity","برق","2:19-2:20-13:12-24:43-30:24-75:7",6
396,84,"E","رَعْد","«رَعْد» Thunder and lightning. It is also the term for a cloud in which there is thunder and lightning (muf).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ یُسَبِّحُ الرَّعۡدُ بِحَمۡدِہٖ وَالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ مِنۡ خِیۡفَتِہٖ» (13:13)\nTranslation: And the thunder and the angels glorify and praise Him out of awe.","«رَعْد» refers to thunder lightning.","Electricity","رعد","2:19-13:13",2
397,84,"E","صَاعِقَۃ","«صَاعِقَۃ» refers to a striking thunderbolt from the sky that burns and utterly destroys. Therefore, its meaning is also taken to signify divine punishment or death.  \nImam Raghīb states that it denotes a terrifying explosion related to celestial bodies, while its counterpart, the word *ṣaqʿa*, is specific to terrestrial bodies; however, the meaning of both is essentially the same. (Mufradāt)  \nAl-Ṣāḥib al-Muntahī al-Adab explains its meaning as hurling a severe thunderbolt with fire from the sky, or as an intense sound that causes one to faint upon hearing it. (Maʿānī al-Qurʾān)  \nIn this context, «صَاعِقَۃ ، رَعْد» represents its most extreme form.  \nThe plural of «صَاعِقَۃ» is «صَوَاعِق».  \nFor example: The Noble Qurʾān states:  \n«وَیُرۡسِلُ الصَّوَاعِقَ فَیُصِیۡبُ بِہَا مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (13:13)  \nTranslation: And He sends down thunderbolts, and with them He strikes whom He wills.  \n\nNote: (Celestial bodies refer to actions performed through angels or divine names.)","«صَاعِقَۃ» the crackling lightning falling from the sky that burns and scorches.","Electricity","صاعقۃ","2:19-2:55-4:153-13:13-41:13-41:17-51:44",7
398,85,"T","وَقٰی","«وَقٰی» To deter someone from a bad deed and its punishment, thereby saving them from both. (explanatory)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ وَاَہۡلِیۡکُمۡ نَارًا» ( 66/6 )\nTranslation: O believers! Save yourselves and your families from the Fire of Hell.","«وَقٰی» To deter someone from a bad deed and its punishment, thereby saving them from both the deed and its consequence.","to save","وقی","66:6",1
399,85,"T","مَنَعَ","«مَنَعَ» means to restrain, and its opposite is «اَلْاِعْطَاء», which means to give something to someone (m. l). It also signifies to stand in the way, to become an obstacle, or to protect someone from a calamity or disaster.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ مَّانِعَتُہُمۡ حُصُوۡنُہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (59/2)\n\nTranslation: And those who thought that their fortresses would protect them from Allah's punishment.","to use «مَنَعَ» as a shield against calamity","to save","منع","2:114-4:141-7:12-9:54-12:63-17:59-17:94-18:55-20:92-21:43-38:75-59:2-107:7",13
400,85,"S","حَجَزَ","«حَجَز» originally means that a third thing comes between two things and, acting as a barrier, performs the function of a shield (m. l). And «حَجَز» means to shield or save one thing from another by interposing a barrier.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» ( 69/47 )\nTranslation: Then there is not among you any who would shield him from Us. (Uthmani)","To save by interposing «حَجَز».","Save","حجز","27:61-69:47",2
401,85,"T","اَحْصَنَ","The meanings of «حَصَنَ» are fortress or refuge. According to Ibn al-Faris, three fundamental aspects are found in its meanings: (1) protection, (2) enclosure, (3) refuge (e.g.). Therefore, these same aspects will be found in «اَحْصَنَ» as well—that is, to stop, to save, and to fully preserve.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَمَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ الَّتِیۡۤ اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا» ( 66/12 )  \nTranslation: And [the example of] Mary, the daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity.","«اَحْصَنَ» safeguarding oneself through vigilance and protection.","to save","احصن","4:24-4:25-5:5-21:91-24:4-24:23-59:14-66:12",8
402,85,"T","جَنَبَ","«جَنَب» has two basic meanings: (1) side/aspect, and (2) to ward off/remove. And «جَنَبَ» means to save someone by taking them away, thereby preserving them from a calamity or affliction.\n\nFor example: Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) supplicated before his Lord as follows:\n«وَّاجۡنُبۡنِیۡ وَ بَنِیَّ اَنۡ نَّعۡبُدَ الۡاَصۡنَامَ» (14/35)\nTranslation: And preserve me and my children from worshipping idols.","«جَنَب» to save someone from a calamity or disaster by taking them away.","to save","جنب","14:35-87:11-92:17",3
403,85,"T","عَصَم","«عَصَم» to keep something close or in one's protection to save it from a calamity that it might fall into. (m. l) In the words of Ibn Faris: «ع ۔ ص ۔ م» «کَلِمَۃٌ تَدُلُّ عَلَی الْاِمْسَاکِ وَالْمَنْعِ وَالْ مُلَازِمَۃِ مِنْ سُوْٓءِ مَا یَقَعُ فِیْہِ» (m. l)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَاالرَّسُوۡلُ بَلِّغۡ  مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ ؕ وَاِنۡ لَّمۡ تَفۡعَلۡ فَمَا بَلَّغۡتَ رِسَالَتَہٗ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ یَعۡصِمُکَ مِنَ النَّاسِ» (5/67)\nTranslation: O Prophet ﷺ! Convey to all people whatever revelations have been sent down to you from your Lord. If you do not, you will have failed in conveying God's message, and God will protect you from the people.\n\nIn another instance in the Quran, the son of Prophet Noah ﷺ responds to him:\n«سَاٰوِیۡۤ  اِلٰی جَبَلٍ یَّعۡصِمُنِیۡ  مِنَ الۡمَآءِ» (11/43)\nTranslation: I will take refuge on a mountain; it will save me from the floodwaters.","«عَصَم» to shield someone from harm or peril.","to save","عصم","5:67-11:43-12:32-33:17",4
404,85,"T","اِتَّقٰی","«اِتَّقٰی اور تَقْوٰی» To avoid the punishment of a bad deed, one must abstain from the evil act itself and its consequences, and adopt piety.  \nFor example: It is in the Noble Quran: «خُذُوۡا مَاۤ اٰتَیۡنٰکُمۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ وَّ اذۡکُرُوۡا مَا فِیۡہِ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/63)  \nTranslation: Hold firmly to what We have given you and remember what is in it, so that you may be saved.","«اِتَّقٰی اور تَقْوٰی» To abstain from bad deeds out of fear of their punishment.","to save","اتقی","2:2-2:21-2:24-2:41-2:48-2:63-2:66-2:103-2:123-2:177-2:179-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:189-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:206-2:212-2:223-2:224-2:231-2:233-2:237-2:241-2:278-2:281-2:282-2:283-3:15-3:28-3:50-3:76-3:102-3:115-3:120-3:123-3:125-3:130-3:131-3:133-3:138-3:172-3:179-3:186-3:198-3:200-4:1-4:9-4:77-4:128-4:129-4:131-5:2-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:11-5:27-5:35-5:46-5:57-5:65-5:88-5:93-5:96-5:100-5:108-5:112-6:32-6:51-6:69-6:72-6:153-6:155-7:26-7:35-7:63-7:65-7:96-7:128-7:156-7:164-7:169-7:171-7:201-8:1-8:25-8:29-8:34-8:56-8:69-9:4-9:7-9:36-9:44-9:108-9:109-9:115-9:119-9:123-10:6-10:31-10:63-11:49-11:78-12:57-12:90-12:109-13:35-15:45-15:69-16:2-16:30-16:31-16:52-16:81-16:128-19:13-19:18-19:63-19:72-19:85-19:97-20:113-20:132-21:48-22:1-22:32-22:37-23:23-23:32-23:52-23:87-24:34-24:52-25:15-25:74-26:11-26:90-26:106-26:108-26:110-26:124-26:126-26:131-26:132-26:142-26:144-26:150-26:161-26:163-26:177-26:179-26:184-27:53-28:83-29:16-30:31-31:33-33:1-33:32-33:37-33:55-33:70-36:45-37:124-38:28-38:49-39:10-39:16-39:20-39:24-39:28-39:33-39:57-39:61-39:73-40:9-41:18-43:35-43:63-43:67-44:51-45:19-47:15-47:17-47:36-48:26-49:1-49:3-49:10-49:12-49:13-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:32-54:54-57:28-58:9-59:7-59:18-60:11-64:16-65:1-65:2-65:4-65:5-65:10-68:34-69:48-71:3-73:17-74:56-77:41-78:31-91:8-92:5-92:17-96:12",223
405,85,"T","تَحَصَّنَ","To safeguard and protect something, thereby saving it. This term is generally used for the protection of one's chastity.  \nFor instance, the Quran states:  \n«وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ اِنۡ اَرَدۡنَ تَحَصُّنًا لِّتَبۡتَغُوۡا عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا» (24/33)  \nTranslation: And do not compel your slave girls, if they wish to remain chaste, to commit indecency in order to seek the benefits of worldly life.","«تَحَصَّنَ» to preserve and protect something, thereby saving it.","to save","تحصن","12:48-21:80-24:33",3
406,85,"T","اِجْتَنَبَ","«اِجْتَنَبَ» to avoid by keeping away from something or an action.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَاجۡتَنِبُوۡا قَوۡلَ الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30)\nTranslation: So avoid the impurity of idols and refrain from false speech.","«اِجْتَنَبَ» to shun something or an action.","to save","اجتنب","4:31-5:90-16:36-22:30-39:17-42:37-49:12-53:32",8
407,85,"T","اِسْتَعْصَمَ","«اِسْتَعْصَمَ» To safeguard from sin or harm, and to protect.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«ولَقَدۡ رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ فَاسۡتَعۡصَمَ» (12/32)  \nTranslation: (Zulaykha said) Indeed, I tried to seduce him, but he saved himself.  \n\nIn the aforementioned verse, besides the words mentioned, «حَذَرَ» and «تَعَفُّف» are also used in the Quran in the meaning of 'to save' or 'to protect'.","To safeguard from any sin or harm.","to save","استعصم","12:32",1
408,85,"T","حَذَرَ","«حَذَرَ» To be cautious and vigilant in order to safeguard against any anticipated danger (lit. fig. mean).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَاالَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنَّ مِنۡ اَزۡوَاجِکُمۡ وَاَوۡلَادِکُمۡ عَدُوًّا لَّکُمۡ فَاحۡذَرُوۡہُمۡ» ( 64/14 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Indeed, among your wives and your children are some who are your enemies. So beware of them.","«حَذَرَ» Be vigilant and guard against the impending danger.","to save","حذر","2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14",17
409,85,"T","تَعَفُّف","The meaning of «عَفَّ» is to abstain from haram or disliked actions and to remain chaste. And «تَعَفُّفَ» means to avoid haram deeds and remain chaste. (Minaj M.R.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ ۚ تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا» (2:273). Translation: Since they do not ask [for anything], those unaware consider them affluent. Their condition can be discerned from their faces.","Abstain from forbidden acts and remain chaste.","to save","تعفف","2:273-4:6-24:33-24:60",4
410,86,"B","اَجِنَّۃ","«اَجِنَّہ» is the plural form of «جَنِیْن». The child who is in the mother's womb is called «جَنِیْن». And «جَنَّ» means to cover something and conceal it (Fasl 90).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ اَجِنَّۃٌ فِیۡ بُطُوۡنِ اُمَّہٰتِکُمۡ» (53/32)\nTranslation: And when you were children in the wombs of your mothers.","«اَجِنَّہ» is the plural of «جَنِیْن». That child which is in the mother's womb is called «جَنِیْن».","boy","اجنۃ","53:32",1
411,86,"B","وَلِیْدًا","The literal meaning of «وَلَدُ» is newborn child, then this word began to be applied to children of young age (Maf, Fal 190).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا وَّلَبِثۡتَ فِیۡنَا مِنۡ عُمُرِکَ سِنِیۡنَ» (26/18)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said to Moses PBUH) Did we not raise you while you were a child, and you spent years of your life among us?\n\nAnd «وَلَدُ» and «مَوْلُود» are related not only to the child or its age but also to the act of its (birth) in contrast to «وَلَدُ». Whether it is of young age, mature, or elderly, in relation to its father, it is «وَلَدُ» and mawlood (born).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ اتَّقُوۡا رَبَّکُمۡ وَاخۡشَوۡا یَوۡمًا لَّا یَجۡزِیۡ وَالِدٌ عَنۡ وَّلَدِہٖ ۫ وَ لَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَجَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا» (31/33)\nTranslation: O people! Fear your Lord and be mindful of a Day when no father will be of any benefit to his child, nor will any child be of any benefit to his father.\n\nIn this sense, «وَلِیْدٌ ، مَوْلُوْدٌ ، وَلَدٌ» i.e., newborn child or suckling child also applies.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا تُضَآرَّ وَالِدَۃٌۢ بِوَلَدِہَا وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ لَّہٗ بِوَلَدِہٖ» (2/233)\nTranslation: Neither should the mother be harmed because of her child (in matters of breastfeeding), nor the father because of his child.\n\nAnd if the word «وَلَدُ» is related to age, it is generally applied to children around eight to ten years old who are capable of doing small chores and serving. Its plural form is «وِلْدَان». It is used for both masculine and feminine (Fal 93).\n\nAs stated by the Almighty in the Quran:\n«وَیَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ ۚ اِذَا رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ حَسِبۡتَہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤًا مَّنۡثُوۡرًا» (76/19)\nTranslation: And there will be boys serving them who will remain in the same state forever. When you look at them, you will think they are scattered pearls.","«وَلَدُ» a child up to the age of eight or ten years (with respect to the father, a person of any age is also called a child).","Boy","ولیدًا","2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-56:17-71:21-72:3-73:17-76:19-90:3-112:3",37
412,86,"B","طِفْل","«طَفِلَ» means soft and delicate, and «طَفْلَۃٌ» refers to a tender-bodied woman. According to this, as long as a child remains soft and delicate, he is «طِفْل» (masc.). However, it generally refers to children who have not yet reached puberty. Its plural is Atfal:\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا بَلَغَ الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24:59)\nTranslation: And when your children reach puberty, they should seek permission just as those before them (i.e., the elder adults) used to seek permission.\nThis verse makes it clear that after puberty, a child moves out of the category of childhood and enters the category of adulthood.","«طِفْل» minor child.","boy","طفل","22:5-24:31-24:59-40:67",4
413,86,"B","صَبِیٌّ","«صَبِیٌّ» is a child who is still in the age of ignorance and play (m. r.), and the term is more related to childish habits than to a specific age. If a boy, even after reaching maturity, remains foolish and indulges in play and amusement, he is still «صَبِیٌّ». «صَبِیٌّ» means a child characterized by childish habits and behaviors.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰیَحۡیٰی خُذِ الۡکِتٰبَ بِقُوَّۃٍ ؕ وَاٰتَیۡنٰہُ الۡحُکۡمَ صَبِیًّا» (19/12)\nTranslation: O Yahya (John)! Hold onto the Scripture with firmness. And We granted him wisdom while he was still a child (i.e., at an age when other children are occupied with play and amusement).","«صَبِیٌّ» an ignorant child who remains immersed in the habits and play of childhood.","Boy","صبی","19:12-19:29",2
414,86,"B","غُلَامٌ","«غُلَامٌ» refers to a child in whom sexual desires have been awakened (i.e., has reached puberty). Youth. And «اِغْتَلَمَ الْفَحْلُ غُلْمَۃً» refers to the dominance of the desire for intercourse in a male. And «غَلِیْم» refers to youth, and «اِغلَام» refers to masturbation. The plural of «غُلَام» is «غِلْمَۃٌ», and «غِلْمَانٌ» is derived from it. For example: The Quran states: «وَیَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ غِلۡمَانٌ لَّہُمۡ کَاَنَّہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (52/24). Translation: And youthful attendants (who will be like) hidden pearls, circulating around them.","«غُلَامٌ» The child who has reached puberty.","Boy","غلم","3:40-12:19-15:53-18:74-18:80-18:82-19:7-19:8-19:19-19:20-37:101-51:28-52:24",13
415,87,"T","دَحٰی ، طَحٰی","«دَحٰی اور طَحٰی» These two words are actually used with the same meaning; only the pronunciation differs. (Muf) refers to the vocabulary of different regions. In the Quran, both words are used only once each, and they appear with the same meaning. It is said «دَحَی الْمَطَرُ الْحَصٰی». «دَحَی الرَّجُل» means he traveled throughout the land (i.e., to distant places). Thus, «دَحٰی» and «طَحٰی» mean to spread far and wide or to extend to distant places.\n\nExample of «طَحٰی» in the Quran:\n(1) «وَ السَّمَآءِ وَ مَا بَنٰہَا وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ مَا طَحٰہَا» (91:5-6)\nTranslation: And by the sky and that which has built it, and by the earth and that which has spread it.\n\nSimilarly, example of «دَحٰی» in the Quran:\n(2) «وَالۡاَرۡضَ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ دَحٰىہَا» (79:30)\nTranslation: And after that, He spread the earth.\n\nModern research indicates that the meaning of «دَحٰی» encompasses the concept of sphericity. «اُدْحِیَّۃُ» means the place where ostrich eggs are laid in the sand (Manjad), and «اُدْحِیُ النَّعَام» means the place where ostrich eggs are laid in the sand (Muf), while «دَحْوَۃ» means ostrich egg. The word «دَحٰی» thus proves that the earth is round.","«دَحٰی اور طَحٰی» to take something far from its place and spread it out extensively.","to lay out (for prayer)","دحی ، طحی","79:30-91:6",2
416,87,"T","سَطَحَ","The basic meanings of «سَطَحَ» are to spread out and then level. «سَطَحَ الْبَیْتَ» refers to leveling the roof of a house, and «مَسْطَحْ» refers to the tools used for leveling. The upper part and roof of a building are called 'surface'. (Manjad) In the words of Imam Raghib, «اَلسَّطْحُ اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَاِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20). Translation: And (do they not look) at the earth, how it is spread out? (meaning its upper part has been made level).","«سَطَحَ» spread or lay out, and then smooth it.","to spread out (a prayer mat)","سطح","88:20",1
417,87,"T","فَرَشَ","«فَرَشَ» means to spread out a cloth, etc., to lay a bedding, and every such thing that is spread out is called «فرش» and «فِراش» (meaning to spread out). The fundamental meaning of farsh (فرش) is to spread something out, to make it wide and expansive (as per the lexicon). That is, to spread something out completely, and «فَرَشَ الدَّار» means to lay a carpet, to spread bricks and stones (as per the lexicon).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّالسَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\n\nTranslation: Who has made the earth a spread-out couch (or carpet) for you and the sky a canopy.","«فَرَشَ» to completely spread or lay out something and make it smooth.","to spread","فرش","2:22-6:142-51:48-55:54-56:34",5
418,87,"F","مَھَدَ","According to the scholar Munjid, just as the word «سَطَحَ» is used for spreading and smoothing out a roof, similarly «مَھَدَ» is used for smoothing out the earth (Munjid). However, «مَھْد» also refers to a mother's lap, which includes the aspect of training/upbringing. And the meaning of «مَھَدَ الْاَرْض» would be to spread out the earth in such a way that its inhabitants are also amply provided with the means of sustenance. This is also confirmed by the Noble Quran.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّمَہَّدۡتُّ لَہٗ  تَمۡہِیۡدًا ثُمَّ  یَطۡمَعُ اَنۡ اَزِیۡدَ» (74:14-15)\nTranslation: And I have bestowed upon him abundance of every [kind] of thing. But he is greedy that I give more.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَالۡاَرۡضَ فَرَشۡنٰہَا فَنِعۡمَ الۡمٰہِدُوۡنَ» (51:48)\nTranslation: And the earth We have spread out, and excellent is the preparer.\n\nThis verse also proves that within «مَھَدَ» there is more breadth than «فَرَشَ». That is, the preparation of the relevant means beyond the necessity.","Along with «مَھَدَ», also provide the training equipment.","furnace","مھد","3:46-5:110-19:29-20:53-30:44-43:10-74:14",7
419,88,"T","مِھَاد","«مَھَدَ» means spreading out and providing means of upbringing within it. As previously detailed, Allah Almighty has described the earth as «مِھَاد» from this perspective, since both these qualities are present in it. For example, the Quran states: «اَلَمۡ  نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ مِہٰدًا» (78/6). Translation: Did We not make the earth a spread-out place?","«مِھَاد» metaphorically and symbolically, the earth is described as providing for all creatures as a resting place, i.e., a bed, in addition to their sustenance.","to spread","مھاد","2:206-3:12-3:197-7:41-13:18-38:56-78:6",7
420,88,"T","فِرَاش","«فَرَشَ» means to spread out and to make level. «اَلْفَرَش» comes in the meanings of spreading a cloth according to its original meaning (mufradat). However, it also comes in the meanings of laying a floor of bricks or stones, as in «فَرَشَ الرَّجُلُ», the meanings of which include both spreading/spreading out and making a floor (mujam). And «فِرَاش» means to spread out or refers to a bedding, and metaphorically, it is used for each of the spouses (the husband and wife) (mufradat). As the Prophet ﷺ said: «اَلْوَلَدُ لِلْفِرَاشِ» and «لِلْعَاھِرِ الْحَجَر» (the child belongs to the husband, and the adulterer faces stoning). The Qur'an has also used this word in the meanings of 'earth' and in the meanings of 'bedding/spreading out'. And its plural is « فُرُشٍ».\n\nFor example: The Qur'an states:\n«مُتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلٰی فُرُشٍۭ بَطَآئِنُہَا مِنۡ اِسۡتَبۡرَقٍ» (55/54)\nTranslation: The people of Paradise will be reclining on carpets whose inner linings will be of rich brocade.","«فِرَاش» is generally used for a bed or bedding.","to spread","فراش","2:22-6:142-51:48-55:54-56:34",5
421,88,"T","مَضَاجِع","The plural of «مَضْجَعُ» is «مَضَاجِع». «ضَجَعَ» means to lie on one's side or to rest, to recline, or to relax. Whether drowsiness or sleep comes or does not come. The state of semi-sleep (m. q.) and «اَضْجَعَہٗ» means He made him sleep (munajjad), and «مَضْجَعُ » means a bed or bedding upon which one rests or sleeps.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا» (32:16)\nTranslation: They stay away from their beds and call upon their Lord with fear and hope.","«مَضْجَعُ» anything that a person can lean on to rest or sleep, be it a charpai, a bed, or any other object.","to spread","مضاجع","3:154-4:34-32:16",3
422,89,"S","بَخِلَ","«بَخِلَ» Do not refrain from spending even from your accumulated wealth in situations where expenditure is necessary. Stinginess is of two types: (1) Being stingy in fulfilling the rights of others or in spending in the way of Allah, i.e., in Allah's path; (2) Not spending even on one's legitimate necessities. Both types of stinginess are reprehensible—evil and detestable. Moreover, the term is general and can be applied to all forms of stinginess.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَبۡخَلُوۡنَ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبُخۡلِ وَیَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ ؕ وَاَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ عَذَابًا مُّہِیۡنًا» (4:37)\nTranslation: Who are stingy themselves and enjoin stinginess upon others, and conceal the wealth that Allah has granted them out of His bounty. And We have prepared a humiliating punishment for the ungrateful.","«بَخِلَ» Do not spend from your accumulated wealth even in places where spending is required.","Stinginess","بخل","3:180-4:37-9:76-47:37-47:38-57:24-92:8",7
423,89,"S","اَمْسَکَ","The meaning of «اَمْسَکَ» is to not let what one possesses slip from one's hand and to hold onto it; or to cling to something and protect it (m.f.). And «اِمْسَاک» means stinginess, and «مُمْسِک» also means a stingy person (m./f.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ اَنۡتُمۡ تَمۡلِکُوۡنَ خَزَآئِنَ رَحۡمَۃِ رَبِّیۡۤ اِذًالَّاَمۡسَکۡتُمۡ خَشۡیَۃَ الۡاِنۡفَاقِ» (17/100)\nTranslation: Say, 'If the treasures of my Lord's mercy were in your hands, you would withhold them for fear of spending.'","«اَمْسَکَ» means to withhold whatever one has, and it is also used in the sense of stinginess.","Stinginess","امسک","2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-16:59-16:79-17:100-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21",22
424,89,"M","اَوْعٰی","The meaning of «اَلْاِیْعَاء» is to take something (wealth, etc.) in a pouch and then close its mouth from above (i.e., to seal it). According to Al-Munjid, this term is used in all three senses: (1) to remember something, (2) to collect/gather, and (3) to hoard/be stingy. According to Ibn al-Faris, its basic meaning is solely to close the mouth. And «وِعَاء» refers to all such items whose mouth is closed or which are sealed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«تَدۡعُوۡا مَنۡ اَدۡبَرَوَ تَوَلّٰی وَ جَمَعَ فَاَوۡعٰی» (70/17,18)\nTranslation: It (Hell) will be called for those who turned away (from the truth) and turned their faces (in aversion), and hoarded (wealth) and kept it (confined).\n\nAnd «اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» (69/12), meaning ears that listen attentively and retain (what is heard). The intended meaning is a person who listens to something with full attention, then memorizes it perfectly, and does not allow any deficiency or excess in its words or meaning. As the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) said in his famous Farewell Sermon, which he delivered while mounted on his camel at the station of Mina:\nنَضَّرَ اللہُ عَبْدًا سَمِعَ مَقَالَتِیْ فَوَعَاھَا ثُمَّ اَدَّاھَا وَبَلَّغَھَا (Tirmidhi)\nTranslation: Allah will keep happy a slave who hears my speech, then retains it, then conveys it and reaches it to others.\n\nThus, the word «وعٰی» is general not only for wealth but for every preservable thing.","«اَوْعٰی» is employed to safeguard and sustain all things worthy of protection.","Miserliness","اوعی","69:12-70:18",2
425,89,"S","اَکْدٰی","«کُدْیَۃٌ» is referred to as hard ground. And the meaning of «حَفَرَ فَاَکْدٰی» is to dig until one reaches the hard ground (Tafsir Mazhari, vol. 262). When the context relates to spending wealth, the meaning of «اَکْدٰی» would be to spend a little and then withhold one's hand. Or it means to intend to spend but then stop.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡ تَوَلّٰی وَاَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا وَّاَکۡدٰی» (53:33,34)\nTranslation: Have you seen the one who turned away and gave a little, then withheld?","To stop after a little spending, or to intend not to complete.","Stinginess","اکدی","7:58-53:34",2
426,89,"S","اَقْتَرَ","The meaning of «قَتَرَ» is to spend very little. (muf) And «اِقْتَار» is the opposite of extravagance. That is, to spend less than necessary even on one's lawful necessities, and to be stingy. According to Sahib al-Muntahi al-Arab, its meaning is a person who has made maintenance (nafaqah) for his family and dependents very restricted. (m. r) Allah Almighty, while describing the attributes of His servants, says:\n\nThe divine command is:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا لَمۡ یُسۡرِفُوۡاوَلَمۡ یَقۡتُرُوۡا وَکَانَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ قَوَامًا» (25/67)\n\nTranslation: And those who, when they spend, are neither wasteful nor stingy, but hold a just balance between that [extremes].","«اَقْتَرَ» Being miserly in the maintenance and expenses of one's family, or also being stingy in spending on oneself.","Stinginess","اقتر","2:236-25:67",2
427,89,"S","ضَنَّ","«ضَنَّ» To be stingy in giving something cherished and prized. (i.e.)\n\nAnd «اَلضَّنَائِن» these are the things due to their intrinsic value that one withholds (for example),\n\nsuch as a wise person withholding his tried and tested remedy.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n\n«وَ مَا ہُوَ عَلَی الۡغَیۡبِ بِضَنِیۡنٍ» (81/24)\n\nTranslation: And he (the Noble Prophet ﷺ) is not stingy in revealing the hidden matters.","«ضَنَّ» to be stingy in giving something beloved or desirable.","Stinginess","ضن","20:124-81:24",2
428,89,"S","شُحَّ","The meaning of «شُحَّ» is to be stingy. To be greedy and covetous (Manj). When both stinginess and greed combine, it is called «شُحَّ» (Fal 33, M L), and its second name is *shiddat-e-hirs* (intense greed). Meaning: to remain constantly preoccupied with the thought of accumulating wealth and to be stingy in spending it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّوۡقَ شُحَّ نَفۡسِہٖ  فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ  الۡمُفۡلِحُوۡنَ» (59/9)\nTranslation: And whoever is saved from the greed of the self—it is they who will be successful.\n\nAnd the meaning of «شَحِیْحٌ» is a stingy and greedy person, and its plurals are «شِحَاحٌ» and «اَشِحَّۃٌ».\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَاِذَا ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when fear departs, they will assail you with sharp tongues, being stingy in wealth (Jalandhari) They are ever prone to hoard (Othmani).","When stinginess and greed come together, it is called «شُحَّ».","Stinginess","شح","4:128-33:19-59:9-64:16",4
429,89,"M","غُلَّ","The fundamental meaning of «غُلٌّ» is a form of betrayal where something not one's own property, but under one's control, is secretly taken and kept in one's possessions, such as taking something from the collectively owned spoils of war and appropriating it as one's own. And «غُلٌّ» also means a fetter, manacle, or chain—that is, anything used to bind someone's limbs together and secure them in the middle. Its plural is «غُلٌّ». By extension, «مَغْلُولُ الْیَد» is also used metaphorically for a miserly person whose hands are bound and who cannot spend anything.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَقَالَتِ الۡیَہُوۡدُ یَدُ اللّٰہِ مَغۡلُوۡلَۃٌ ؕ غُلَّتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (5/64)\nTranslation: And the Jews say, The hand of Allah is chained. Their own hands are chained.","«غُلٌّ» An Arabic idiom referring to the iron shackles on a prisoner's wrists or the iron collar around the neck. «مَغْلُولُ الْیَد» A stingy or miserly person who gives nothing to others.","Miserliness","غل","3:161-5:64-17:29",3
430,90,"W","شِقْوَۃ","Both «شِقْوَۃ» and «شِقَاوَۃ» mean misfortune, and their opposite is «سَعَادَۃ». And just as «سَعَادَۃ» is among the additional matters (i.e., supplementary attributes), similarly «شِقَاوَۃ» and «شِقْوَۃ» are also among the additional matters. And «شَقِی» is the person who is inherently wretched or ill-fated (abbr.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا غَلَبَتۡ عَلَیۡنَا شِقۡوَتُنَا وَ کُنَّا قَوۡمًا ضَآلِّیۡنَ» (23/106). Translation: The disbelievers will say, O our Lord! Our misfortune has overcome us, and we were led astray from the path.","«شِقْوَۃ» A person who is inherently unfortunate or ill-fated by nature, and for whom misfortune is his preordained lot.","Wretchedness","شقوۃ","11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15",9
431,90,"M","نَحُوْسَۃ","«نُحَاس» means both copper and a flame with a copper-like hue. And «نَحَسَ» means the sky turning red like copper, and this is a proverb for misfortune. And «نَحُسَ» and «نَحُوْسَۃ» signify a time of hardship and ill-fortune. The opposite of «نَحَس» is «سَعْد».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡۤ اَیَّامٍ نَّحِسَاتٍ» (41/16)\nTranslation: We sent upon them a fierce, cold wind during the days of misfortune.","a period of misfortune and hardship","misfortune","نحوسۃ","41:16-54:19",2
432,90,"M","طآئر","«طَارَ» means the flying of birds, etc., in the air, and «طَائِر» is the plural of «طَیْر», meaning bird. Since taking omens from birds was a common practice, therefore the word «طَائِر» also began to be used in the meanings of taking omens or auguries. This word is generally used in negative connotations. «اِطَّیَّرَ» and «تَطَیَّرَ» mean to take bad omens or evil auguries, and their opposites are «تَیَمَّنَ» and «تَبَرَّک». It is as if the original meaning of «طَائِر» is not misfortune itself, but rather taking misfortune as an omen.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا تَطَیَّرۡنَا بِکُمۡ» (36/18)\nTranslation: The disbelievers said to the messengers, We consider you to be ill-omened.\nSo those prophets replied:\n«قَالُوۡا طَآئِرُکُمۡ مَّعَکُمۡ» (36/19)\nTranslation: The prophet said, Your misfortune is with yourselves.","«طَائِر» To interpret someone's misfortune as an omen, or to see bad omens in their circumstances.","misfortune","طآئر","2:260-3:49-5:110-6:38-7:131-12:36-12:41-16:79-17:13-21:79-22:31-24:41-27:16-27:17-27:20-27:47-34:10-36:18-36:19-38:19-56:21-67:19-105:3",23
433,90,"W","شَئُوْم","«الشَّأمَۃَ الْمَشْئَمَۃ» means bad omen, lack of blessings, and the left side (i.e., the left side) (minjid). The left side is also considered a sign of bad omen. And shamat actually refers to such a bad omen that is expected as a result of one's own deeds. The phrase shamat-i-a'mal (consequence of deeds) is well-known, and «تَشَاءُم» means to take a bad omen, and its opposite is «تَیَمُّن». For example: In the Quran it says: «ثُمَّ کَانَ مِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالصَّبۡرِ وَتَوَاصَوۡا بِالۡمَرۡحَمَۃِ اُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَیۡمَنَۃِ وَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا ہُمۡ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَشۡئَمَۃِ» (90/17,18,19) Translation: Then he entered among those who believed and continued to exhort to patience and enjoin mercy upon people. These are the blessed ones. And those who did not accept Our verses, those are the wretched ones.","Such misfortune as is deserved as a consequence of one's own deeds.","Wretchedness","شئوم","56:9-90:19",2
434,90,"A","حُسُوْم","«اَلْحَسَمَ» means to cut something and erase its very name and mark, to annihilate it completely. And «حُسَام» means a sword. Then «حُسُومُ » is also used for such a calamity or punishment that erases even a person's name and mark (i.e., utterly destroys them).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاَمَّا عَادٌ فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍعَاتِیَۃٍ سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَبۡعَ لَیَالٍ وَّثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ اَعۡجَازُنَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ» (69:6,7)\nTranslation: As for 'Ad, they were destroyed by a fiercely raging wind, which God imposed on them for seven consecutive nights and eight consecutive days. So you would see the people lying prostrate, as if they were hollow trunks of palm trees.","Such a calamity that «حُسُوْم» wipes out.","Adversity","حسوم","69:7",1
435,91,"E","لَعَنَ","«لَعَنَ» means to expel or drive someone away due to displeasure. When attributed to Allah Almighty, it signifies being deprived of His mercy and guidance (Mufradat). It also means to revile, to turn away from goodness, and to curse (Majma' al-Bayan). The term is general and comprehensive for invoking evil upon someone.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لُعِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡۢ بَنِیۡۤ اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ عَلٰی لِسَانِ دَاوٗدَ وَعِیۡسَی ابۡنِ مَرۡیَمَ» (5:78)\nTranslation: Those among the Children of Israel who disbelieved were cursed by the tongue of David and Jesus, son of Mary.","«لَعَنَ» A curse seeking distance from God's mercy and guidance.","Evil supplication (prayer for harm)","لعن","2:88-2:89-2:159-2:161-3:61-3:87-4:46-4:47-4:52-4:93-4:118-5:13-5:60-5:64-5:78-7:38-7:44-9:68-11:18-11:60-11:99-13:25-15:35-24:7-24:23-28:42-29:25-33:57-33:64-33:68-38:78-40:52-47:23-48:6",34
436,91,"P","بَعِدَ ، بَعُدًا","«بُعْدًا» means to be distant, to be destroyed, to die. And «بُعْدًا» is a word of curse, meaning May Allah destroy him or distance him from His mercy (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «اَلَا بُعۡدًا لِّمَدۡیَنَ کَمَا بَعِدَتۡ ثَمُوۡدُ» (11/95)\nTranslation: Heed that upon Midian too is the same curse as was upon Thamud.","«بَعِدَ» a curse of being severed from mercy and ruin.","prayer for harm","بعد ، بعدًا","9:42-11:44-11:60-11:68-11:95-21:101-23:41-23:44-43:38",9
437,91,"E","سُحْقًا","«سَحَقَ» means to apply medicine or the like. And «اَسْحَقَ الثَّوْب» means the worn-out state of clothing. «اَسْحَقَہُ اللہ» means may Allah destroy him (masc.). Also, «سَحِقَ سُحْقًا» means to be distant and «اِسْتَحَقَ» means to remove (minjadd). Thus, this too is a word of cursing, and its meaning is separation from goodness, but it carries greater intensity than «بُعْدًا».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ ۚ فَسُحۡقًا لِّاَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» (67/11)\nTranslation: So they will confess their sins. Hence, for the inhabitants of Hell, there is remoteness from Allah's mercy (Jalandhari).","«سُحْقًا» is used for supplication. Its meaning conveys greater intensity than «بُعْدًا».","Evil prayer","سحقًا","67:11",1
438,91,"I","اِبْتَھَل","«اَبْھَلْتُ فُلَانًا» is used in the sense of leaving someone free in their opinion and intention, and «الْبَھْلُ وَالْاِبَتِھَالُ فِی الدُّعَاءِ» means to supplicate with complete freedom and humility in prayer (meaning). Then, since the verse of Mubahalah mentions the curse of Allah, the word Mubahalah became famous in the meaning of sending a curse upon one another. Thus, its usage also took on a negative connotation.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ نَبۡتَہِلۡ فَنَجۡعَلۡ لَّعۡنَتَ اللّٰہِ عَلَی الۡکٰذِبِیۡنَ» (3/61)\nTranslation: Then let us both turn in prayer to Allah and invoke His curse upon the liars.","«اِبْتِھَال» the two parties praying and supplicating with full freedom to curse each other.","imprecation","ابتھل","3:61",1
439,92,"U","مَسَخَ","«مَسَخَ» meaning to spoil or disfigure the form and appearance (sing.).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَوۡ نَشَآءُ لَمَسَخۡنٰہُمۡ عَلٰی مَکَانَتِہِمۡ فَمَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا مُضِیًّا وَّلَا یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» ( 36/67 )\nTranslation: If We willed, We could change their forms. Then they would not be able to move forward or backward.","«مَسَخَ» is used to spoil and corrupt good form and appearance.","Ugly","مسخ","36:67",1
440,92,"U","کَلَحَ","«کَلَحَۃ» refers to the mouth and the surrounding area, and «كَالِحُ» refers to a person whose lips are not closed but remain apart, and «کَلَحَ ، کَلَّحَ» means to curl one's lips (i.e., raising the nose and face in anger), and «اِکْلَوَّحَ» means to show teeth while curling one's lips (a snarl). According to the scholar of language, this is the extreme degree of lip-curling (see curling one's lips), wherein a person's appearance becomes distorted and, due to the exposed teeth, appears extremely hideous.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» (23/104)\nTranslation: The Fire will scorch their faces, and they will be disfigured therein.","«کَلَحَ» is used to describe a temporary marring of form due to illness, pain, or emotions.","Ugly","کلح","23:104",1
441,92,"R","قَبُحَ","«قَبُحَ» means to be of bad appearance, to be ill-favored. And «قَبِیْح» means bad, ill-favored, or of ugly form. The word «قَبُحَ» is also used in a spiritual sense, meaning the badness of a statement, action, or form (source: Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَیَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ» (28/42)\nTranslation: And they will be in a wretched state on the Day of Resurrection as well.\n\nIn this verse, «مَقْبُوحِیْن» conveys both meanings.","«قَبُحَ» means to be born misshapen in form and is also applied to negative traits.","repulsive in form","قبح","28:42",1
442,93,"E","زِنَا","«زِنَا» is a well-known term. That is, when a man commits illicit sexual acts with a non-woman, or a woman with someone other than her own husband, it is called zina (detailed).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوا الزِّنٰۤی اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا» ( 17/32 )\nTranslation: And do not approach adultery. Indeed, it is an abomination and an evil way.","«زِنَا» is a well-known term. It refers to non-male and non-female individuals engaging in indecent acts with one another.","Evil act","زنا","17:32-24:2-24:3",3
443,93,"E","بِغَاء","The meaning of «بَغِیَ» is to transgress, to disobey, to commit excess and oppression. And the meaning of «بَاغَتِ الْاَمَۃُ بِغَآءً» is committing adultery with a slave girl. And the meaning of «بَغِیّ» is an adulterous, promiscuous woman (manjada), meaning the word «بِغَاء» is either specific to the adultery of a slave girl or specific to a professional prostitute (kanjari), a woman notorious for committing adultery among people. The Quran supports both these meanings.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَلَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)\nTranslation: And do not compel your slave girls to prostitution.\n\nAt another place in the Quran, when addressing the Jews regarding Maryam (peace be upon her), it is stated:\n«یٰۤاُخۡتَ ہٰرُوۡنَ مَا کَانَ  اَبُوۡکِ امۡرَ اَ سَوۡءٍ وَّ مَا  کَانَتۡ  اُمُّکِ  بَغِیًّا» (19/28)\nTranslation: O sister of Harun, your father was not a man of evil character, nor was your mother a promiscuous woman.","«بِغَاء» The committing of adultery by a female slave, or making prostitution a profession for a free woman.","Evil-doing","بغاء","2:90-2:213-3:19-6:146-7:33-10:23-10:90-16:90-19:20-19:28-22:60-24:33-38:24-42:14-42:39-45:17-49:9-55:20",18
444,93,"S","سَافَحَ","The meaning of «سَفَحَ» is to shed blood or to let water flow, and the meaning of «سَافَحَ» is to commit adultery (from *Manjad*). In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «صَبَّ الْمَاء بِلَا عَقْدِ نِکَاحٍ» means committing adultery without the contract of marriage. Thus, the difference between adultery and «سَافَحَ» is that repetition is found in it. And the Noble Quran has confirmed this by using the word «مُسَافِحِیْن» in contrast to «مُحْصِنِیْن». Therefore, the meaning of «سَافَحَ» in our language is to keep as a concubine (i.e., a woman with whom one establishes a sexual relationship without marriage), and «مُسَافِح» refers to such a woman and a man who have open, public relations with each other. The word ashna (acquaintance) is also used today in this very sense.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ» (4/25)\nTranslation: So marry them with the permission of their owners and give them their dowry according to what is reasonable, provided they are chaste, neither promiscuous nor having secret paramours.","«سَافَحَ» to openly maintain illicit sexual relations between non-males and non-females.","Sinful act","سافح","4:24-4:25-5:5",3
445,93,"W","فَاحِشَۃ","«فَحَشَ» means any statement or action that exceeds bounds in ugliness (corruption) and evil (mufsadah). And «فَاحِشَۃٍ مُبَیِّنَۃ» refers to statements and actions that lead to adultery—that is, indecent acts and speech. And in these senses, this word is repeatedly used in the Quran, and for adultery, the word «فَاحِشَۃٍ مُبَیِّنَۃ» is employed.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ بِفَاحِشَۃٍ مُّبَیِّنَۃٍ» (4:19)\nTranslation: And with the intention that you might take back some of what you have given them, do not keep them (in their homes) unless they commit open lewdness.\n\nAnd the term fahishah is used for such lewdness or crime whose evidence is not yet available.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَالّٰتِیۡ یَاۡتِیۡنَ الۡفَاحِشَۃَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِکُمۡ فَاسۡتَشۡہِدُوۡا عَلَیۡہِنَّ اَرۡبَعَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» (4:15)\nTranslation: O believers! Among your women, those who commit lewdness, obtain testimony from four of your own.","«فَاحِشَۃ» is used for actions and words that lead one close to adultery. Or it refers to an accusation of adultery that requires evidence.","Wickedness","فاحشۃ","2:169-2:268-3:135-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:25-6:151-7:28-7:33-7:80-12:24-16:90-17:32-24:19-24:21-27:54-29:28-29:45-33:30-42:37-53:32-65:1",23
446,94,"S","بَدَّل","«بَدَلَ» is a well-known term. It means something in exchange for something else. And «بدَّل» refers to bringing another thing in place of something (in the singular sense), as though the original intention was for the first thing, but another thing took its place.","«بَدَّلَ» Replacing one thing with another by terminating the first.","Substitute","بدل","2:59-2:61-2:108-2:181-2:211-4:2-4:56-6:34-6:115-7:95-7:162-9:39-10:15-14:28-14:48-16:101-18:27-18:81-24:55-25:70-27:11-33:23-33:52-34:16-40:26-47:38-48:15-50:29-56:61-66:5-68:32-70:41-76:28",33
447,94,"S","حَوَّلَ","The meaning of «حَوَّل» is to remove something from its original place and place it elsewhere. And according to Ibn Faris, its meaning is «تَحَرُّک فَی دَوْر», i.e., to move in a circle. (M L) And the surroundings (i.e., the sides) of something are called its «حَوْل». It is as if in «حَوَّل», nothing is intended, but rather it moves from its original position.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا  ۚ وَ لَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَحۡوِیۡلًا» ( 35/43 )\nTranslation: They are not waiting for anything other than the way of the earlier peoples. So you will not find any change in Allah's way, nor will you find any alteration in it. (Ottoman)\nAnd Allah's way is that He destroys the guilty nations. In the above verse, change in Allah's way means that it can never happen. That rewards instead of punishment begin to befall a guilty nation, and alteration means that the crime belongs to one person, but its punishment is given to another.","The meaning of «حَوَّل» is to take something away from its original place and put it somewhere else.","substitute","حول","3:159-6:92-9:101-9:120-17:1-17:56-17:77-19:68-26:25-26:34-27:8-29:67-35:43-39:75-40:7-42:7-46:27",17
448,94,"S","غَیَّرَ","«غَیْر» means 'except'. «غیَّرَ» refers to a change in state or condition. «غَیَّرَ» implies that nothing is intended to be removed from its place; rather, a change occurs in that state or form.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُغَیِّرُ مَا بِقَوۡمٍ حَتّٰی یُغَیِّرُوۡا مَا بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (13:11)\nTranslation: Know that Allah will not change the condition of a people until they change what is within themselves.\n\nAnd a poet has rendered the translation of this verse thus:\nGod has not changed the condition of any people to this day,\nUnless they themselves have thought of changing their own condition.\n\nAt another instance, Satan responds to Allah the Almighty as follows:\n«وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاٰمُرَنَّہُمۡ فَلَیُبَتِّکُنَّ اٰذَانَ الۡاَنۡعَامِ وَ لَاٰمُرَنَّہُمۡ فَلَیُغَیِّرُنَّ خَلۡقَ اللّٰہِ» (4:119)\nTranslation: And I will mislead them and give them false hopes, and I will command them so they will slit the ears of cattle, and I will command them so they will change the creation of Allah.","«تَغْیِیْر» to bring about a change in the condition or form of something.","substitute","غیر","4:119-8:53-13:11-47:15",4
449,94,"S","حَرّف","The basic meaning of «حَرَف» is the edges or sides of something, and «حَرَّفَ» means to turn that edge (i.e., to alter or change). The plural of the letter 'harf' is 'huruf', and «حُرُوْفُ الْکَلَام» refers to the alphabetical letters. «تَحْرِیْفُ الْکَلَم» means that some words of a text are placed in a location other than their original one, without considering the context and sequence (i.e., the preceding and following text), which can yield a different meaning. And if words are replaced with other words, that constitutes alteration (taghyir). The Jews used to practice both of these actions.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَبِمَا نَقۡضِہِمۡ مِّیۡثَاقَہُمۡ لَعَنّٰہُمۡ وَ جَعَلۡنَا قُلُوۡبَہُمۡ قٰسِیَۃً ۚ یُحَرِّفُوۡنَ الۡکَلِمَ عَنۡ مَّوَاضِعِہٖ» (5:13)\nTranslation: So because of their breaking of the covenant, We cursed them and made their hearts hard. They alter the words (of the Scripture) from their proper places.\n\nAnd «تَحَرَّفَ» means to change the side or direction, and «تَحَرَّفَ عَنْہُ» means to incline toward someone and turn to one side (i.e., to show favoritism or bias).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّوَلِّہِمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ دُبُرَہٗۤ  اِلَّا مُتَحَرِّفًا لِّقِتَالٍ» (8:16)\nTranslation: And whoever turns his back to them on the day the armies meet, except for a tactical withdrawal or retreat to a fighting position, will have incurred the wrath of Allah.","«تَحْرِیْف» to alter any part of a continuous text or its meaning.","Substitute","حرف","2:75-4:46-5:13-5:41-8:16-22:11",6
450,94,"S","نَکَّرَ","«نَکَّرَ» two fundamental things are found: (1) strangeness/foreignness (اجنبیت) and (2) dislike/aversion (ناگواری). Denial (تنکیر) is the opposite of acknowledgment (تعریف), and denial (منکر) is the opposite of the acknowledged (معروف). Denial (تنکیر) means not to recognize someone, and acknowledgment (تعریف) means to recognize someone. Indefinite noun (اسم نکرہ) and definite noun (اسم معرفہ) are well-known terms. And denial (منکر) also means bad deeds, while acknowledgment (معروف) means good deeds. «نَکَّرَ» also means to make something indefinite (منجد) and to alter the form of something in such a way that it appears strange.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ نَـکِّرُوۡا لَہَا عَرۡشَہَا» (27/41)\nTranslation: Solomon (peace be upon him) said, Alter the appearance of her (Bilqis's) throne for her.","«نَکَّرَ» to transform.","substitute","نکر","27:41-",1
451,94,"R","دَاوَل","«اَلدَّوْلَۃ وَالدُّوْلَۃ» means to rotate and is the opposite of «دَالَ», which is «دَارَ». The words «دَوْر» and «دَائِرَۃ» are used to denote tight-handedness, adversity, and the rotation of days. «دَوْلَۃُ» refers to turning from bad days to days of prosperity. And «دَاوَل» means to exchange or rotate the days of prosperity (as in the concept of manjada). For example, the Quran states: «وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ» (3:140). Translation: And these are the days in which We rotate them among the people.","to transform and bring to a better state","Recompense","داول","3:140",1
452,95,"R","بَدَلَ","«بَدَلَ» means to bring one thing in place of another (transitive), and this can be less or more, good or bad, similar or otherwise. Apparently, this word is general for substitution. Here we limit ourselves to just two examples:\n\n(1) For instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَفَتَتَّخِذُوۡنَہٗ وَذُرِّیَّتَہٗۤ اَوۡلِیَآءَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِیۡ وَہُمۡ لَکُمۡ عَدُوٌّ ؕ بِئۡسَ لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ بَدَلًا» (18/50)\nTranslation: Do you take Satan and his progeny as friends instead of Me, while they are your enemies? What an evil exchange it is for the wrongdoers. (Jalandhri)\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n(2) «اِلَّا مَنۡ تَابَ وَاٰمَنَ وَعَمِلَ عَمَلًا صَالِحًا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ یُبَدِّلُ اللّٰہُ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ حَسَنٰتٍ» (25/70)\nTranslation: But whoever repents and believes and does righteous deeds, for such people, Allah will replace their sins with good deeds.","«بَدَلَ» is a general term for retaliation or recompense, whether it is less or more, good or bad.","Recompense","بدل","18:50-24:55-25:70-33:52-66:5-68:32",6
454,95,"R","عَدْل","«عَدْل» Balanced and proportionate compensation for the original thing, provided that this compensation is balanced and proportionate to the original thing. (See details under Doing Justice).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَّلَا یُقۡبَلُ مِنۡہَا شَفَاعَۃٌ وَّلَا یُؤۡخَذُ مِنۡہَا عَدۡلٌ» (2/48)  \nTranslation: Neither shall intercession be accepted from anyone, nor shall any compensation be accepted from anyone.","«عَدْل» The principle of balanced equality and proportionate recompense.","Retribution","عدل","2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7",24
455,95,"R","اَجْر","«اَجْر» and «اُجْرَۃ» is the compensation that has been predetermined by an earlier covenant or agreement, or which is announced at the time of need by «آجِر» (the one giving compensation), and «اَجِیْر» (the one receiving compensation) accepts it and begins the work. This is the compensation for work. And it is generally invoked for beneficial compensation. The word *ajr* (reward) is used for both divine and worldly compensation. However, the word *ujrat* (wage) is generally used for worldly compensation. And «اٰجِرْ» refers to the one who takes on work, and «اَجِیْر» to the one who performs the work, the servant or the one receiving compensation (pl.), and «اِسْتَاْجَرَ» means to employ someone as a laborer or servant. The usage of *ajr* in both divine and worldly contexts is mentioned in the Noble Quran.\n\nExample (1): The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَاَجۡرُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ خَیۡرٌ لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَکَانُوۡا یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (12/57)\nTranslation: And for those who believed and were ever fearing, the reward of the Hereafter is better.\n\nExample (2): The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ» (28/27)\nTranslation: He (Moses, peace be upon him) said, I wish to marry one of these two daughters of mine to you, on the condition that you serve me for eight years.","«اَجْر» fixed compensation. Remuneration for service.","Recompense","اجر","2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:136-3:171-3:172-3:179-3:199-4:40-4:67-4:74-4:95-4:100-4:114-4:146-4:162-5:9-6:90-7:113-7:170-8:28-9:22-9:120-10:72-11:11-11:29-11:51-11:115-12:56-12:57-12:90-12:104-16:41-16:96-16:97-17:9-18:2-18:30-18:77-25:57-26:41-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:25-28:26-28:27-28:54-29:27-29:58-33:29-33:31-33:35-33:44-34:47-35:7-36:11-36:21-38:86-39:10-39:35-39:74-41:8-42:23-42:40-48:10-48:16-48:29-49:3-52:40-57:7-57:11-57:18-57:19-57:27-64:15-65:5-67:12-68:3-68:46-73:20-84:25-95:6",87
456,95,"R","جَزَاء","«جَزَا» means to be sufficient and to suffice (m. l.), and *jazā wa badal* (recompense) is that which is not less in proportion to the deed, whether the deed and its recompense are good or bad. And in it, covenants or agreements and specification are not conditions.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا تُجۡزَوۡنَ  اِلَّا مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (37/39)\n\nTranslation: And you will be recompensed only for what you used to do.","«جَزَا» The recompense that is in no way diminished but is given in full.","Recompense","جزاء","2:85-2:191-3:87-3:136-4:93-5:29-5:33-5:38-5:85-5:95-9:26-9:82-9:95-10:27-12:25-12:74-12:75-17:63-17:98-18:88-18:106-20:76-25:15-32:17-34:37-39:34-41:28-42:40-46:14-53:41-54:14-55:60-56:24-59:17-76:9-76:12-76:22-78:26-78:36-98:8",40
457,95,"R","ثَوَاب","The fundamental meanings of «ثَوَاب» are to return and to come back, while «یَثُوْبُ اِلَیْہِ النَّاس» means a person whom people frequently visit. The Quran has employed this word in these very senses as well.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا» (2/125)\nTranslation: And when We designated the House [the Ka'bah] as a place of return for the people and [a place of] security.\n\nBy this analogy, the recompense a person receives for their deeds is called 'thawab' (reward) (Mufradat), even though its usage can apply to both good and evil. However, generally, it comes for the good reward of good deeds.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاٰتٰىہُمُ اللّٰہُ ثَوَابَ الدُّنۡیَا وَ حُسۡنَ ثَوَابِ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (3/148)\nTranslation: So Allah gave them the reward of this world and an excellent reward of the Hereafter.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«ہَلۡ  ثُوِّبَ الۡکُفَّارُ  مَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» (83/36)\nTranslation: So the disbelievers will be given in full their recompense.\n\nIn this verse, the word 'thawab' (reward) has been used ironically.","«ثَوَاب» meaning the good reward for good deeds.","Recompense","ثواب","2:103-2:125-3:145-3:148-3:153-3:195-4:134-5:60-5:85-18:31-18:44-18:46-19:76-28:80-48:18-83:36",16
458,95,"R","عِقَاب","The term is used to denote an evil recompense for evil deeds (see detailed explanation under 'Ending'). That is, it occurs in the meanings of punishment or torment. For example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «وَاتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّ اللّٰہَ شَدِیۡدُ الۡعِقَابِ» (2/196). Translation: And fear Allah and know that Allah is severe in retribution.","«عِقََاب» signifies the evil reward for evil deeds.","Retribution","عقاب","2:196-2:211-3:11-5:2-5:98-6:165-7:167-8:13-8:25-8:48-8:52-13:6-13:32-38:14-40:3-40:5-40:22-41:43-59:4-59:7",20
459,95,"R","کَفَّارَۃٌ","«کَفَرَ» means to conceal (see the detailed explanation under to deny), and «تَکْفِیْر» means concealing a sin. «کَفَّارَۃٌ» refers to the good deed performed in exchange for a sin, and the charity or fasting observed in this context is termed «کَفَّارَۃ».","That good deed which is performed as expiation in exchange for a sin.","Recompense","کفارۃ","5:45-5:89-5:95",3
460,95,"R","وَبَال","The fundamental meanings of «وَبَل» encompass the concepts of «شِدَّۃ» and «ثَقَل» (see مف ۔ منجد), and its meaning is to beat with a stick. The word 'Wabal' (وبال) is used for the severe punishment of a bad deed. This punishment may be received in this world or the Hereafter. However, it most often occurs in the form of worldly retribution or the recompense of deeds. Now, consider the examples:\n\nExample (1): Wabal in the form of Kaffarah (expiation):\nThe Divine Command states:\n«اَوۡ کَفَّارَۃٌ  طَعَامُ مَسٰکِیۡنَ اَوۡ عَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ» (5/95)\nTranslation: Or [make] expiation by feeding the poor or fasting for an equivalent number of days, so that he may taste the [consequence of] his deed.\n\nExample (2): The Divine Command states:\n«کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ قَرِیۡبًا ذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہِمۡ ۚ وَلَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (59/15)\nTranslation: Their state is like that of those who, not long before them, had tasted the consequence of their deeds. And for them is a painful punishment.","«وَبَال» in the form of a firm grip and punishment.","Retribution","وبال","5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9",4
461,95,"R","قِصَاص","«قِصَاص» means to give recompense for an action (manjada), and qisas generally pertains to human blood and its organs and limbs. An example of this has been discussed under section B of this title, but it is not necessary.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran, it is stated: «اَلشَّہۡرُالۡحَرَامُ بِالشَّہۡرِالۡحَرَامِ وَالۡحُرُمٰتُ قِصَاصٌ» (2/194) Translation: The month of respect is the counterpart of the month of respect, and matters of respect are mutual recompense.","Retribution for unjust killing and for limbs and organs.","Recompense","قصاص","2:178-2:179-2:194-5:45",4
462,95,"R","فِدْیَۃٌ","The meaning of «فِدْیَۃ» is to rescue someone from a calamity by giving wealth or compensation (according to the majority). According to the scholar Manj, it means to free someone from captivity by paying. And the amount given as compensation is termed «فِدْیَۃ». For example, the Quran states: «وَاِنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡکُمۡ اُسٰرٰی تُفٰدُوۡہُمۡ وَہُوَ مُحَرَّمٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِخۡرَاجُہُمۡ» (2:85). Translation: And if they come to you as captives, you would ransom them, even though it was forbidden for you to expel them.","«فِدْیَۃ» refers to the payment of a sum of money to free someone from trouble or captivity.","Retribution","فدیۃ","2:85-2:184-2:196-2:229-3:91-4:92-5:36-10:54-13:18-37:107-39:47-47:4-57:15-70:11",14
463,95,"R","دِیَۃٌ","«( وَدِی ) وَدَی یَدِیْ وَدْیًا وَدِیَۃً» means the payment of blood money by the killer or his heirs to the heirs of the victim. «اَوْدٰی» means the unlawful shedding of someone's blood. And «دِیَۃٌ» is the wealth that is given from the killer or his heirs in exchange for the victim's life (i.e., blood money).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» ( 4/92 )\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer by mistake, then (he must) free a believing slave and pay blood money to the family of the deceased, unless they remit it as a charity.","«دِیَۃٌ» The payment of blood money by the killer or his heirs to the heirs of the victim.","Recompense","دیۃ","4:92",1
464,95,"S","جَزٰی ۔ ثَوَّبَ","The Statement of Reward: The term بدلہ (recompense) has also passed for جزاء (reward) and for «اَثَاب» and «ثَوَّبَ».","«جَزَا» is to give full recompense for a deed.  \nAnd «ثَوَّبَ» is generally used for good recompense for good deeds.","Substitute","جزی ۔ ثوب","3:153-5:85-6:160-20:15-28:84-40:17-40:40-45:22-48:18-92:19",10
465,95,"R","عَذَّبَ","«عَذُبَ» means to abandon food due to severe thirst, and «عَذْب» means a sweet and pleasant drink or food, and «مَاءٌ عَذْبٌ» means cool and pleasant water, and «اَعْذَبْ» means to reach sweet water (ma' minjad). However, when this word is used in the context of «باب تفعیل», it departs from its primary meaning, and «عَذَّبَ» means to inflict severe hardship or punishment or torment. Abu Hala defines it as «اَلْاَ لَمَ الْمُسْتَقِرّ» (i.e., persistent and enduring pain). (Faq l 198)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَمَا کُنَّا مُعَذِّبِیۡنَ حَتّٰی نَبۡعَثَ رَسُوۡلًا» (17/15)\nTranslation: And We do not punish until We have sent a messenger.","«عَذَّبَ» is used for severe punishment.","Recompense","عذب","2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25",45
466,95,"R","دَانَ","The word «اَلدَّیْن» is used in a very broad sense. Briefly, it has four meanings: (1) complete sovereignty, (2) complete servitude and worship. For example, the Quran states: «اَلَا لِلّٰہِ الدِّیۡنُ الۡخَالِصُ» (39:3). Translation: Indeed, worship is for Allah alone. In this verse, both the concepts of sovereignty and servitude are present.\n\nThe third meaning is the law of reward and punishment. The fourth meaning is the granting of reward and punishment for good and bad deeds in accordance with that law. For example, the Quran states: «مٰلک یومِ الدین» (1:3). Translation: Master of the Day of Recompense. In this verse, the third and fourth meanings are found.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine declaration is: «فَلَوۡ لَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ غَیۡرَ مَدِیۡنِیۡنَ تَرۡجِعُوۡنَہَاۤ اِنۡ  کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (56:86-87). Translation: Then if you are free from the account, why do you not take back the soul when it is about to depart? If you are truthful.","«دَانَ» comes to highlight the aspects of the ruler and the ruled in reward and punishment.","Recompense","دان","1:3-2:132-2:193-2:217-2:256-3:19-3:24-3:73-3:83-3:85-4:46-4:125-4:146-4:171-5:3-5:54-5:57-5:77-6:70-6:137-6:159-6:161-7:29-7:51-8:39-8:49-8:72-9:11-9:12-9:29-9:33-9:36-9:122-10:22-10:104-10:105-12:40-12:76-15:35-16:52-22:78-24:2-24:25-24:55-26:82-29:65-30:30-30:32-30:43-31:32-33:5-37:20-37:53-38:78-39:2-39:3-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:26-40:65-42:13-42:21-48:28-49:16-51:6-51:12-56:56-56:86-60:8-60:9-61:9-70:26-74:46-82:9-82:15-82:17-82:18-83:11-95:7-98:5-107:1-109:6-110:2",84
467,95,"R","عَاقَبَ","The meaning of «عَقَب» is front and back, and «عَقَبَ» means to follow behind, while «عَاقِب» signifies to follow someone and hold them accountable and punish them (according to Manjad). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ عَاقَبۡتُمۡ فَعَاقِبُوۡا بِمِثۡلِ مَا عُوۡقِبۡتُمۡ بِہٖ» (16:126). The translation is: And if you retaliate, then retaliate to the same measure as you were harmed.","«عَاقَبَ» to pursue someone closely to exact retribution for their actions.","Recompense","عاقب","16:126-22:60-11:60",3
468,95,"R","اِنْتَقَمَ","«نَقَمَ» means to regard something as evil and to find fault with it (Mufradat).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَا نَقَمُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَمِیۡدِ» (85/8)\nTranslation: What they found most objectionable among the believers was that they believed in Allah.\n\nAnd «اِنْتَقَام» means to punish someone for their evil deeds, to exact retribution, or to deprive them of blessings. According to Abu Bilal al-Askari, the opposite of reward is retribution, and the meaning of retribution is the seizure or deprivation (of blessings) (Fiqh 199).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ ذُکِّرَ بِاٰیٰتِ رَبِّہٖ ثُمَّ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡہَا ؕ اِنَّا مِنَ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ مُنۡتَقِمُوۡنَ» (32/22)\nTranslation: And who is more unjust than one who, when reminded of the verses of his Lord, turns away from them? We will surely recompense the criminals.","«اِنْتَقَمَ» meaning to take revenge, to punish.","Retribution","انتقم","3:4-5:95-7:136-14:47-15:79-30:47-32:22-39:37-43:25-43:41-43:55-44:16",12
469,95,"R","اِنْتَصَرَ","The meaning of «نَصَرَ» is to help someone in removing oppression and excess (i.e., in a supportive, environmental sense), and the meaning of «اِنْتَصَرَ» is to take retribution against someone for committing oppression and excess, and to repel harm (i.e., to protect oneself from loss).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَصَابَہُمُ الۡبَغۡیُ ہُمۡ یَنۡتَصِرُوۡنَ» (42:39)\nTranslation: And when they are wronged, they simply retaliate.\n\nAt another instance, Prophet Noah (peace be upon him) supplicates to his Lord:\n«فَدَعَا رَبَّہٗۤ  اَنِّیۡ  مَغۡلُوۡبٌ  فَانۡتَصِرۡ» (54:10)\nTranslation: So he invoked his Lord, Indeed, I am overpowered, so take retribution.","«اِنْتَصَار» is to take retribution for an injustice and oppression, whether the oppressed person takes it themselves or another person takes it while assisting them.","Recompense","انتصر","18:43-26:93-26:227-28:81-42:39-42:41-47:4-51:45-54:10-54:44-55:35",11
470,96,"I","نَزَفَ","«نَزَفَ» meaning the gradual and step-by-step cessation of something. «نَزَفَ الْمَاءَ الْبِئْرَ» meaning to draw all the water from a well slowly, bit by bit, and «نُزِفَ الْمَآء» meaning the water gradually running out. Similarly, «نُزِفَ دَمْعَہٗ» meaning tears flowing from his eyes until they ceased or dried up. And «نُزِفَ الرَّجُلُ» meaning a person's intellect gradually and step-by-step diminishing or becoming impaired, regardless of the cause. (from Munjid)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَّا یُصَدَّعُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا وَلَا یُنۡزِفُوۡنَ» (56/19)\nTranslation: Neither will he have a headache nor will he speak nonsense. (Uthmani)","«نَزَفَ» refers to the gradual, step-by-step decline or derangement of a person's intellect.","Intoxicated / In a state of divine ecstasy (Sufi terminology)","نزف","37:47-56:19",2
471,96,"I","غَالَ","«غَوْل» refers to jinn and magicians who assume various forms. Terms like chalaawa (sorcery) and chureel (a female spirit or witch) are examples. «اَلْغَوْل» means intoxication or headache. «غَالَ» means to kill someone in such a way that no trace is left (i.e., secretly). Thus, the intoxication and frenzy implied by «غَوْل» are of a kind whose cause cannot be known.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا فِیۡہَا غَوۡلٌ وَّ لَا ہُمۡ عَنۡہَا یُنۡزَفُوۡنَ» (37:47)\nTranslation: Neither will they be caused to suffer any headache thereby, nor will they be intoxicated. (Usmani)","«غَوْل» refers to a state of such intoxication and frenzy whose cause cannot be known.","Intoxicated (often used in a mystical or spiritual context, implying divine ecstasy)","غال","37:47",1
472,96,"S","سَکَرَ","The term «سُکَر» is generally used in the context of intoxication and loss of reason caused by alcohol, and «سَکَر» refers to any intoxicating substance. That is, when intoxication from anything—whether due to overwhelming love or the agony of death—causes loss of reason, then «سکّر» is used. «سَکْرَاتُ الْمَوْت» is a well-known term. For example, the Noble Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَقۡرَبُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاَنۡتُمۡ سُکٰرٰی» (4/43). Translation: O you who believe! Do not approach prayer while you are intoxicated.","«سَکَرَ» an intoxication caused by wine. However, this term is also used in contexts of overwhelming love or terror.","Spiritually intoxicated","سکر","4:43-15:15-15:72-16:67-22:2-50:19",6
473,97,"E","بِئْسَ","«بِئْسَ» means 'evil' or 'bad'; it is a noun of dispraise (ذم), and it is a static verb (فعل ماضی جامد). It is used to condemn an abhorrent act or a bad statement. Its opposite is «نِعْمَ», which means 'good', 'excellent', 'how wonderful', and is used for all forms of praise.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَحَسۡبُہٗ جَہَنَّمُ ؕ وَ لَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ» (2/206)\nTranslation: So for such, the punishment is Hell, and evil is it as a resting place!\n\nNote: (A static verb is a verb that remains in only one form and is not conjugated, e.g., «نِعۡم», «عسی», etc.)","«بِئْسَ» is used to praise a disagreeable act or evil speech.","evil","بئس","2:90-2:93-2:102-2:126-2:206-3:12-3:151-3:162-3:187-3:197-5:62-5:63-5:79-5:80-7:150-8:16-9:73-11:98-11:99-13:18-14:29-16:29-18:29-18:50-22:13-22:72-24:57-38:56-38:60-39:72-40:76-43:38-49:11-57:15-58:8-62:5-64:10-66:9-67:6",39
474,97,"E","شَرّ","«شَرّ» is every thing which everyone detests or from which harm befalls, and its opposite «خَیْر» is desirable and approved for all. The word evil (شر) is used in meanings such as bad, evil, and trouble in all senses. And a spark (شرارہ) refers to a spark of fire, its plural being sparks (شرر).  \nAnd malice (شرارت) is every covert action through which harm can be caused to someone. And a bad person is called evil-doer (شریر), and its plural is «اَشْرَار».  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تَکۡرَہُوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ ۚ وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تُحِبُّوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ شَرٌّ لَّکُمۡ» (2/216)  \nTranslation: And perhaps you dislike a thing while it is good for you; and perhaps you like a thing while it is bad for you.  \nAt another place, the sublime command of Allah is:  \n«وَ قَالُوۡا مَا لَنَا لَا نَرٰی رِجَالًا کُنَّا نَعُدُّہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَشۡرَارِ» (38/62)  \nTranslation: And they will say, What is the matter with us that we do not see [here] men whom we used to count among the wicked?","«شَرّ» The word *sharr* (evil) is used in all senses to mean bad, evil, and harm. Everything from which everyone feels aversion or suffers harm.","Evil","شر","2:216-3:180-5:60-8:22-8:55-10:11-12:77-17:11-17:83-19:75-21:35-22:72-24:11-25:34-38:55-38:62-41:49-41:51-70:20-72:10-76:7-76:11-98:6-99:8-113:2-113:3-113:4-113:5-114:4",29
475,97,"E","سَاءَ","«سَاءَ» means to be ugly or repulsive (manjada), meaning to have an unsightly appearance or to be detestable. It applies to both external ugliness and spiritual corruption. Its opposite is «حَسُنَ». Similarly, «سَیِّئَات» means a bad deed, and its opposite is «حَسَنَات». Only the past and present (future) verb forms of «سَاءَ» are used.\n\n(1) For spiritual evil:\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ  مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6:31)\nTranslation: And they will bear their burdens on their backs. See what burdens they are bearing! How evil is that!\n\n(2) For external ugliness:\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَوۡہُ   زُلۡفَۃً  سِیۡٓئَتۡ وُجُوۡہُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (67:27)\nTranslation: So when they see the promise near, the faces of the disbelievers will become repulsive.\n\nAnd from «سَآءَ», the transitive verb «اَسَآءَ» means to corrupt, spoil, or make bad.\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah states:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  لِیَسُوۡٓءٗا  وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ» (17:7)\nTranslation: Then when the time for the other promise came, (We sent others) to disfigure your faces.\n\nAnd «سَوْء» means evil, bad, or corruption that exists within something. «اِمْرَأَسَوْءٍ» means a sinful person. And «سُوْءٓ» comes in the meanings of a fault, a bad deed, and evil. And «مُسِیْء» means one who does bad deeds, a sinner, or of evil character.\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ لَا الۡمُسِیۡٓءُ» (40:58)\nTranslation: And not equal are those who believe and do righteous deeds and the defiantly disobedient sinners.","«سَاءَ» signifies ugliness or unpleasantness, applicable to both external and internal aspects. Its opposite is «حَسُنَ».","Evil","ساء","2:49-2:81-2:169-2:271-3:30-3:120-3:174-3:193-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:22-4:31-4:38-4:78-4:79-4:85-4:97-4:110-4:115-4:123-4:148-4:149-5:12-5:65-5:66-6:31-6:54-6:136-6:157-6:160-7:73-7:95-7:131-7:141-7:153-7:165-7:167-7:168-7:177-7:188-8:29-9:9-9:37-9:98-9:102-10:27-11:10-11:54-11:64-11:78-11:114-12:24-12:25-12:51-12:53-13:6-13:11-13:18-13:21-13:22-13:25-14:6-16:25-16:27-16:28-16:34-16:45-16:59-16:60-16:94-16:119-17:7-17:32-17:38-18:29-19:28-20:22-20:101-21:74-21:77-23:96-25:40-25:66-25:70-26:156-26:173-27:5-27:11-27:12-27:46-27:58-27:62-27:90-28:32-28:54-28:84-29:4-29:7-30:10-30:36-33:17-35:8-35:10-35:43-37:177-39:24-39:47-39:48-39:51-39:61-40:9-40:37-40:40-40:45-40:52-40:58-41:34-41:46-42:25-42:40-42:48-45:15-45:21-45:33-46:16-47:2-47:14-48:5-48:6-48:12-53:31-58:15-60:2-63:2-64:9-65:5-66:8-67:27",139
476,97,"E","قَبَحَ","«قَبَحَ» signifies evil in speech, action, or appearance, and qabeeh means ugly or bad. The term badnama (generally) refers to the negativity of one's outward state. Similarly, «قَبِیْح» denotes a bad condition (muf), implying a bad form or appearance (generally). For instance, the Holy Quran states: «وَاَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً ۚ وَ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَقۡبُوۡحِیۡنَ» (28/42) Translation: And We have also cursed them in this world, and on the Day of Judgment, they will be among the wretched.","«قَبَحَ» means to be in a bad condition or of bad appearance. It is used to denote evil in speech, action, and form. Generally, it is employed in an outward or apparent sense.","Evil","قبح","28:42",1
477,97,"E","ذَمَّ","«ذَمَّ» means to commit evil. To find fault. «اَذَمَّ» means to consider insignificant and «تَذَمَّمَ» means to protect oneself from something and consider it shameful and disgraceful for oneself (as in 'munjad'), and «ذِمَام» means sanctity and honor, and «ذَمَّمَہٗ» meaning he greatly dishonored it. (M. Q) It seems that the word «ذَمَّ» is used for an act of fault-finding or dishonoring, the doing of which brings shame and disgrace upon the doer, and its opposite is «مَدَحَ».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنَا لَہٗ جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلٰىہَا مَذۡمُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» ( 17/18 )\nTranslation: Then We have prepared for him Hell, wherein he will enter humiliated and disgraced.","«ذَمَّ» to defame someone by highlighting their faults.","Evil","ذم","17:18-17:22-68:49",3
478,97,"E","عَتَبَ","«عَتَبَ» means to reproach or to censure. (This word is from the category of lexical opposites.) «عَاتِب» also means to reproach and to become angry, as well as to address someone with disdain. And «اَعْتَبَ» means to remove the cause of displeasure, while «اِسْتَعْبَبَ» means to satisfy someone or to reconcile with someone who is angry (i.e., to placate). Thus, «عِتَاب» refers to such sweet, gentle reproaches and admonitions whose ultimate purpose is to gain acceptance and agreement. Moreover, the use of reproach (عتاب) is also applicable when relationships of friendship and compassion are ruined. (See Fatḥ al-Qadīr, 39)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ یَّسۡتَعۡتِبُوۡا فَمَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمُعۡتَبِیۡنَ» (41:24)\nTranslation: If they wish to reconcile, then reconciliation with them will not be possible.\n\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two entirely separate meanings which are contrary and contradictory to each other.)","«عَتَبَ» To express wit in a gentle manner to dispel displeasure.","Evil","عتب","16:84-30:57-41:24-45:35",4
479,97,"E","لَامَ","«لَامَ» meaning: to consider an action bad and thus speak ill of the doer (even if the action itself is not bad), and meaning: to admonish someone based on the consequences of their action (e.g., in Fiqh 39). For example, the Quran states: «یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَلَا یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ» (5/54). Translation: Strive in the way of Allah and do not fear the blame of any blamer.","«لَامَ» to censure someone for their action and to warn them of its consequences.","evil","لام","5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2",11
480,97,"W","سَبَّ","«سَبّب» means to utter severe insults and obscene abuses (masculine), and «سَبَّبَ» means to give excessive insults (as cited).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«لَا تَسُبُّوا الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ فَیَسُبُّوا اللّٰہَ عَدۡوًۢا بِغَیۡرِعِلۡمٍ» (6/108)  \nTranslation: Do not insult those who invoke or worship besides Allah, lest they, out of ignorance, retaliate and begin to revile Allah.","«سَبّب» Using abusive, obscene, and grave language.","Wickedness","سب","6:108",1
481,97,"W","ثَرَّبَ","To reproach and scold someone for a bad deed (transitive).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَا تَثۡرِیۡبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡیَوۡمَ ؕ یَغۡفِرُ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (12/92)\nTranslation: (Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) said to his brothers) Today there will be no reproach upon you. May Allah also forgive you.","«ثَرَّبَ» to reproach someone for their bad deed and also to chide them.","Wickedness","ثرب","12:92",1
482,97,"E","نُکُر","In «نُکُر», two fundamental concepts are found: (1) strangeness/foreignness (اجنبیت) and (2) dislike/abhorrence (ناگواری). Furthermore, «اَنْکَرَ» also means to deny/reject, as well as to regard something as astonishing. And «مُنْکَر» refers to any matter that is disapproved of by general societal norms or that Sharia has deemed reprehensible. Meanwhile, «نُکُر» means an evil thing that is repulsive to everyone and appears bad.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَتَوَلَّ عَنۡہُمۡ ۘ یَوۡمَ یَدۡعُ الدَّاعِ اِلٰی شَیۡءٍ نُّکُرٍ» (54:6)\nTranslation: So turn away, [O Muhammad], from the disbelievers until the Day when the Caller will call them to a detestable matter.","Every such thing that is displeasing and disliked in the eyes of common people.","Evil","نکر","11:70-18:74-18:87-27:41-31:19-54:6-65:8",7
483,97,"E","نَقَمَ ، نَقِمَ","«نَقَمَ» means to consider something bad (transitive) and also means to regard as detestable, to find fault, to blame, or to punish (intransitive). As for «نِقْمَۃ», it refers to an unpleasant matter that some may dislike while others may not, whether this matter is actually unpleasant or not. Then they also resort to retaliation, and «نقمۃ» also signifies punishment, torment, or recompense.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is stated: «وَمَا نَقَمُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَمِیۡدِ» (85:8) Translation: (And what the disbelievers found most offensive was that the believers had faith in Allah, the Exalted in Might, the Praiseworthy.)","«نَقَمَ» something that a particular person finds offensive and cannot bear, even though in reality it is not bad.","Evil","نقم ، نقم","5:59-7:126-9:74-85:8",4
484,98,"E","عَدْل","Equality is termed in matters that involve measurement, weighing, or weight, or that can be perceived by the outward senses (detailed). Based on these outward senses, justice is also called fairness. For example, in the Quran it says: «اَوۡعَدۡلُ ذٰلِکَ صِیَامًا لِّیَذُوۡقَ وَبَالَ اَمۡرِہٖ» (5/95) Translation: Or let him fast for a similar number of days so that he may taste the consequences of his misdeed.","«عَدْل» Equality is said to apply to things that relate to measurement by dimensions, volume, or weight, or that can be perceived through the outward senses.","equal","عدل","2:48-2:123-2:282-4:3-4:58-4:129-4:135-5:8-5:95-5:106-6:1-6:70-6:115-6:150-6:152-7:159-7:181-16:76-16:90-27:60-42:15-49:9-65:2-82:7",24
485,98,"E","سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی","«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی» comes for the equality of state and condition (Detailed Fiqh, p. 128).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ءَاَنۡذَرۡتَہُمۡ اَمۡ لَمۡ تُنۡذِرۡہُمۡ» (2/6)\nTranslation: Whether you admonish them or not, it is all the same for those who disbelieve.\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ ۬ ۙ اَمۡ ہَلۡ تَسۡتَوِی الظُّلُمٰتُ وَ النُّوۡرُ» (13/16)\nTranslation: Can the blind and the seeing be equal? Or can the darkness and the light be equal?\nAnd «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» means to sit firmly upon something.\nAnd for equating a quantity or state, the word «سَوّٰی» is used. In the following verse, both these words appear together.\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ فَسَوّٰىکَ فَعَدَلَکَ» (82/7)\nTranslation: That Being who created you, then perfected your state, then made you proportioned and balanced.\nAnd the word «سَوّٰی» is also vast in meaning. It encompasses completing, equalizing, making correct and proper—everything is included.","«سَوَاء ، اَسْتَوٰی» is used to indicate exact equivalence with the state or quantity of anything.","Equal","سواء ، استوی","2:6-2:29-2:108-3:64-3:113-4:89-4:95-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:100-6:50-7:193-8:58-9:19-11:24-13:10-13:16-14:21-16:71-16:75-16:76-18:37-21:109-22:25-26:136-28:22-30:28-32:9-32:18-35:12-35:19-35:22-36:10-37:55-38:22-39:9-39:29-40:58-41:10-41:34-44:47-45:21-48:29-52:16-53:3-57:10-59:20-60:1-63:6-79:28-82:7-91:7-91:14",54
486,99,"D","ضَلّ","The meaning of «ضَلَّ» is for something to be lost and to go to the right of another (i.e., to be annihilated or merged), meaning to end one's own existence or to become completely absorbed into another existence.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا ضَلَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ءَ اِنَّا لَفِیۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (32:10)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers will say, When we are lost [ral mil] in the earth, will we then be created anew?\n\nSometimes this word also appears in the meanings of the mere termination, loss, or destruction of something's existence.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا ضَلُّوۡا عَنَّا وَ شَہِدُوۡا عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ اَنَّہُمۡ  کَانُوۡا کٰفِرِیۡنَ» (7:37)\nTranslation: They (the disbelievers) will say, Where have our partners gone? and they will confess that they were indeed disbelievers.\n\nAlthough the word «ضَلَّ» is general, as evident from the above examples. However, its usage generally pertains to losing one's way, and «ضَلَّ» means to cause to lose the correct path, to be unable to find it, and to wander in search of it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ وَجَدَکَ ضَآلًّا فَہَدٰی» (93:7)\nTranslation: And Allah found you lost, so He guided [you]. (Reported by Uthmani)\n\nAnd the meaning of «اَضَلَّ» generally is to cause someone to go astray, to lead them into error, and to make them take the wrong path. However, this word also appears in the meanings of destroying or ruining.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡا وَ صَدُّوۡا عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ  اَضَلَّ  اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ» (47:1)\nTranslation: Those who disbelieve and hinder [others] from the way of Allah - He will render their deeds void.\n\nSimilarly, at another place, the Divine decree states:\n«ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَرِہُوۡا مَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ فَاَحۡبَطَ اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ» (47:9)\nTranslation: That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered their deeds worthless.","«ضَلَّ» To be consumed in the service of others' rights, thereby negating one's own existence.","destroyed","ضل","1:7-2:16-2:26-2:108-2:175-2:198-2:282-3:69-3:90-3:164-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:113-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:143-4:167-4:176-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:105-6:24-6:39-6:56-6:74-6:77-6:94-6:116-6:117-6:119-6:125-6:140-6:144-7:30-7:37-7:38-7:53-7:60-7:61-7:149-7:155-7:178-7:179-7:186-9:37-9:115-10:30-10:32-10:88-10:108-11:21-12:8-12:30-12:95-13:14-13:27-13:33-14:3-14:18-14:27-14:30-14:36-15:56-16:25-16:36-16:37-16:87-16:93-16:125-17:15-17:67-17:72-17:97-18:17-18:51-18:104-19:38-19:75-20:52-20:79-20:85-20:92-20:123-21:54-22:4-22:9-22:12-23:106-25:17-25:29-25:34-25:42-25:44-26:20-26:86-26:97-26:99-27:81-27:92-28:15-28:50-28:75-28:85-30:29-30:53-31:6-31:11-32:10-33:36-33:67-34:8-34:24-34:50-35:8-36:24-36:47-36:62-37:69-37:71-38:26-39:8-39:22-39:23-39:36-39:37-39:41-40:25-40:33-40:34-40:50-40:74-41:29-41:48-41:52-42:18-42:44-42:46-43:40-45:23-46:5-46:28-46:32-50:27-53:2-53:30-54:24-54:47-56:51-56:92-60:1-62:2-67:9-67:29-68:7-68:26-71:24-71:27-74:31-83:32-93:7",163
487,99,"D","حَبِطَ","«حَبِطَ» means to be wasted, ruined, futile, or corrupted. «حَبَِطَ دَمُّ الْقَتِیْل» means the blood of a murdered person being shed in vain (manjad), i.e., an action not yielding results due to other factors. The nullification of good deeds because of bad deeds (and if bad deeds are nullified because of good deeds, that is called takfir). (Fiqh 196)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَشۡرَکُوۡا لَحَبِطَ عَنۡہُمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (6:88)\nTranslation: And if they had associated partners with Allah, all their deeds would have become futile.\n\nAnd «اَحْبَطَ» means to render futile, useless, ruin, or destroy.\nFor example: The Quran states:\nذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَرِہُوۡا مَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ فَاَحۡبَطَ اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ (47:9)\nTranslation: That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered their deeds fruitless.","«حَبِطَ» means that an action does not yield its result due to certain other factors. The loss of good deeds as a consequence of bad deeds.","Destroyed","حبط","2:217-3:22-5:5-5:53-6:88-7:147-9:17-9:69-11:16-18:105-33:19-39:65-47:9-47:28-47:32-49:2",16
488,99,"R","بَطَلَ","«بَطَلَ» refers to unjust and baseless actions, which are termed as «بَاطِل». The opposite of falsehood is truth. After thorough investigation, that in which no stability or permanence is found is false (according to the author). Furthermore, «بَطَلَ» also signifies something becoming wasted and fruitless due to ineffectiveness. For example, sinful conduct nullifies the benefit of treatment, or treatment eliminates the effects of the disease and terminates it.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَوَقَعَ الۡحَقُّ وَ بَطَلَ مَا کَانُوۡا یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (7:118)\nTranslation: Then truth was established, and what the Pharaohs used to do became false.\n\nAnd «اَبْطَلَ» means rendering an action ineffective and fruitless, the cause of which is another contrary act. For instance, the divine command declares:\n«لَا تُبۡطِلُوۡا صَدَقٰتِکُمۡ بِالۡمَنِّ وَالۡاَذٰی» (2:264)\nTranslation: Do not render your charities vain by reproach and injury.","«بَطَلَ» A contrary act that nullifies the preceding act.","Ruined","بطل","2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33",10
489,99,"D","اَضَاعَ","«اَضَاعَ» meaning to ruin, destroy, or waste, regardless of the reason.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran:  \n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا» (19/59)  \nTranslation: Then after them, there succeeded some corrupt successors who neglected prayer and pursued their desires. So they will soon receive the penalty of misguidance.","To ruin something for any reason.","Devastated","اضاع","19:59",1
490,100,"F","حَلُمَ","«حَلُمَ» means to be forbearing and courageous. This is a constant attribute that remains within the patient person at all times. That is, when he hears something unpleasant, or harm befalls him, or he is dishonored, or he hears something greatly pleasing, his nature should not experience any fluctuation, or if it does, it should be of a minor degree, and in any case, remain steadfast as before. This is a highly praiseworthy attribute. Abu Hala explains its meaning as «اِمھَال بِتَخِیْرِ الْعِقَابِ الْمُسْتَحَقٌ ( فق ل 165 )», i.e., granting respite by delaying punishment for the deserving (etc.).  \nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَبَشَّرۡنٰہُ  بِغُلٰمٍ  حَلِیۡمٍ» (37/101)  \nTranslation: We gave Abraham the good news of a forbearing son.","«حَلُمَ» To maintain composure during times of grief and anger, and to delay and grant respite to one who is deserving of punishment.","Forbearance","حلم","2:225-2:235-2:263-3:155-4:12-5:101-9:114-11:75-11:87-17:44-22:59-33:51-35:41-37:101-64:17",15
491,100,"F","صَبَرَ","The literal meaning of «اَلصَّبْر» is to restrain someone in a state of hardship (transitive), and the Messenger of Allah ﷺ defined «اَلصَّبْر» in this way: «اَلصَّبْرُ عِتْدَ الصَّدْمَۃِ الْاُوْلی» (Bukhari), meaning that upon the occurrence of a calamity, affliction, or unpleasant incident, one immediately restrains oneself from lamentation and restlessness and endures it patiently.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَالصّٰبِرِیۡنَ فِی الۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَالضَّرَّآءِ وَحِیۡنَ الۡبَاۡسِ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And those who are patient in adversity and hardship.","«صَبْرَ» To refrain from restlessness and to endure with fortitude during every kind of hardship, trial, and affliction.","Forbearance","صبر","2:45-2:61-2:153-2:175-2:250-3:120-3:125-3:186-3:200-4:25-6:34-7:87-7:126-7:128-7:137-8:46-10:109-11:11-11:49-11:115-12:18-12:83-12:90-13:22-13:24-14:12-14:21-16:42-16:96-16:110-16:126-16:127-18:28-18:67-18:68-18:72-18:75-18:78-18:82-20:130-23:111-25:20-25:42-25:75-28:54-29:59-30:60-31:17-32:24-38:6-38:17-40:55-40:77-41:24-41:35-42:43-46:35-49:5-50:39-52:16-52:48-68:48-70:5-73:10-74:7-76:12-76:24-90:17-103:3",69
492,100,"F","کَظَمَ","«کَظْم» refers to the windpipe, and «کَظَمَ السِّقَاء» means to fill a skin container (مشک) completely with water and then seal its mouth (figurative). «کَظِیْم» and «مَکْظُوْم» describe a person who is filled with grief or anger to the point of suffocation but does not express it, nor is he allowed to express it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ فَہُوَ کَظِیۡمٌ» (12/84)\nTranslation: And Ya'qub's eyes turned white from grief, and he was filled to the brim (with sorrow).\n\nIn another instance, regarding Prophet Yunus (peace be upon him), the Divine decree states:\n«اِذۡ نَادٰی وَہُوَ مَکۡظُوۡمٌ» (68/48)\nTranslation: When he called out, and he was seething with grief and anger.\n\nIn a third instance, while describing the attributes of the believers, it is stated:\n«وَالۡکٰظِمِیۡنَ الۡغَیۡظَ وَ الۡعَافِیۡنَ عَنِ النَّاسِ» (3/134)\nTranslation: And they are those who restrain anger and pardon people.","«کَظَمَ» No matter how intense grief and anger may be, suppress them and do not allow their expression.","Forbearance","کظم","3:134-12:84-16:58-40:18-43:17-68:48",6
493,101,"V","کَبِیْر ، اَکْبَرْ","In «كَبِيْر ، اَکْبَرْ», the fundamental meaning is simply 'greatness'. The opposite of 'kabīr' is 'ṣaghīr', and the opposite of 'akbar' is 'aṣghar'. These are comparative forms, meaning that every thing is 'kabīr' in comparison to things smaller than itself, and that same thing is 'ṣaghīr' in comparison to things greater than itself. The word 'kabīr' is fundamentally used for physical entities, whether that thing is great in age, in size, or in any other apparent attribute.\n\nFor example, for greatness in age: The divine command says: «قَالَ کَبِیۡرُہُمۡ اَلَمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّ اَبَاکُمۡ قَدۡ اَخَذَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مَّوۡثِقًا مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (12/80). Translation: The eldest among them (the brothers of Prophet Yusuf) said, 'Do you not know that your father had taken a covenant from you in the name of Allah?'\n\nAnd for greatness in size: The divine command says: «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ جُذٰذًا اِلَّا کَبِیۡرًا لَّہُمۡ» (21/58). Translation: Then Prophet Ibrahim broke the idols into pieces, except for the largest one.'\n\nHowever, later the words 'kabīr' and 'akbar' began to be used in a spiritual sense as well. For example, in the Quran it is said: «یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡخَمۡرِوَالۡمَیۡسِرِؕ قُلۡ فِیۡہِمَاۤ اِثۡمٌ کَبِیۡرٌ وَّمَنَافِعُ لِلنَّاسِ ۫ وَ اِثۡمُہُمَاۤ اَکۡبَرُ مِنۡ نَّفۡعِہِمَا» (2/219). Translation: O Prophet! People ask you about wine and gambling. Say, 'In them there is great harm and some benefit for people, but their harm is far greater than their benefit.'\n\nThe plural of «کَبِیْر» is «کُبَرَاء», and «اَکْبَر» is an intensive form meaning 'very great' or 'greatest'. It is used in both senses, and its plural is 'akābir'.","«کَبِیْر» is a general term for magnitude, typically used in reference to physical bodies and external attributes.","Venerable","کبیر ، اکبر","2:185-2:217-2:219-2:282-3:118-4:2-4:34-4:153-6:19-6:78-6:123-8:73-9:3-9:72-9:121-10:61-11:3-11:11-12:31-12:78-12:80-13:9-16:41-17:4-17:9-17:21-17:31-17:43-17:60-17:87-17:111-18:49-20:71-21:58-21:63-21:103-22:37-22:62-25:19-25:21-25:52-26:49-28:23-29:45-31:30-32:21-33:47-33:67-33:68-34:3-34:23-35:7-35:32-39:26-40:10-40:12-40:56-40:57-42:22-43:48-54:53-57:7-67:9-67:12-68:33-76:20-85:11-88:24",68
494,101,"G","عَظِیْم","«عَظِیْم» is the opposite of «حَقِیْر», and in the fundamental meaning of «اَعْظَمَ ، عَظْمٌ», the connotations of strength and intensity are also found alongside greatness. These spiritual attributes are sometimes found collectively and sometimes individually. Bone is also called «عَظْمٌ» due to its strength and intensity. (M.L.) The plural of both «عَظْم» and «عَظِیْم» is «عِظَام». The word «عَظِیْم» is also used in both forms: ajsam (bodies) and a'yan (entities/individuals, i.e., great persons or high ranks). (M.F.) And «اَعْظَمَ» is an elative name meaning 'very great and majestic' or 'the greatest and most majestic'. Now consider the examples:\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n(1) «وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» (2:7)\nTranslation: And for those disbelievers, there is a great punishment.\n(2) «فَسَبِّحۡ  بِاسۡمِ  رَبِّکَ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (56:96)\nTranslation: So continue to glorify the name of your Lord, the Majestic.\n\nIn a community, there can be many people who are «کَبِیْر» and «اَکْبَر», but «عَظِیْم» is only one. (F.Q. 150)","«عَظِیْم» in which greatness is found beyond strength and intensity. Just as the trivial is smaller than the smallest, the great is above the greater.","Great","عظیم","2:7-2:49-2:105-2:114-2:255-3:74-3:105-3:172-3:174-3:176-3:179-4:13-4:27-4:40-4:48-4:54-4:67-4:73-4:74-4:93-4:95-4:113-4:114-4:146-4:156-4:162-5:9-5:33-5:41-5:119-6:15-7:59-7:116-7:141-8:28-8:29-8:68-9:20-9:22-9:63-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:101-9:111-9:129-10:15-10:64-12:28-14:6-15:87-16:94-16:106-17:40-19:37-21:76-22:1-23:86-24:11-24:14-24:15-24:16-24:23-26:63-26:135-26:156-26:189-27:23-27:26-28:79-31:13-33:29-33:35-33:53-33:71-37:60-37:76-37:107-37:115-38:67-39:13-40:9-41:35-42:4-43:31-44:57-45:10-46:21-48:5-48:10-48:29-49:3-56:46-56:74-56:76-56:96-57:10-57:12-57:21-57:29-61:12-62:4-64:9-64:15-68:4-69:33-69:52-73:20-78:2-83:5",110
495,101,"G","ذُوالْجَلَال","«جَلَال» refers to greatness in status and rank. «ذُوْالْجَلَال» means «عَظِیمُ الْمَرْتَبَت», i.e., One of High Rank, and «جَلِیْل» means the One who creates magnificent, grand things (mufrad), and also means the Essence deserving praise due to His magnificent works (faqih, 150).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«تَبٰرَکَ اسۡمُ رَبِّکَ ذِی الۡجَلٰلِ وَالۡاِکۡرَامِ» (55:78)\nTranslation: Exalted is the name of your Lord, the Possessor of Greatness and Majesty. ('Uthmani)","«ذُوالْجَلَال» refers to greatness in honor and status, which is exclusively reserved for the blessed essence of Allah alone.","Great","ذوالجلال","55:27-55:78",2
496,101,"G","مَجِیْد","The meaning of «مَجِیْد» is to be exceedingly vast in grandeur and majesty (muf). And according to Ibn al-Faris: it is one who has reached the utmost degree in generosity, honor, and nobility (m. l). And «مَجِیْد» also means one who is supremely great in the sight of all people (m. q).\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states:\n«وَہُوَالۡغَفُوۡرُ الۡوَدُوۡدُ ذُوالۡعَرۡشِ الۡمَجِیۡدُ» (85:14,15)\nTranslation: And He is the Forgiving and the Loving. Owner of the Throne, the Most Exalted.","That Essence who has reached the ultimate degree in majesty, grandeur, grace, honor, and nobility.","Great","مجید","11:73-50:1-85:15-85:21",4
497,101,"V","کِبَر","«كِبْرُ» generally denotes old age. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَاَصَابَہُ الۡکِبَرُ وَلَہٗ ذُرِّیَّۃٌ ضُعَفَآءُ» (2/266) Translation: and he reaches old age and has young children.\n\nFurthermore, «کِبر» means greatness, glory, arrogance, and the display of one's own greatness is arrogance. This attribute is fitting and exclusive to Allah. For all others, it is blameworthy, i.e., evil. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنۡ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ  اِلَّا کِبۡرٌ» (40/56) Translation: There is nothing in their hearts except arrogance and pride.","«كِبْرُ» is used to denote seniority or to express one's status.","Venerable","کبر","2:266-3:40-4:6-10:78-14:39-15:54-17:23-19:8-45:37-74:3",10
498,101,"G","جَلَال","«جَلَالْ» denotes supreme greatness and the highest degree of honor and status, beyond which no further rank exists. The term «ذُوالجلال» is exclusively reserved for Allah Almighty. In contrast, «جَلِیْل» can also apply to other things. «جَلِیْل» refers to anything that is greater and more powerful in every respect.  \nExample: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«تَبٰرَکَ اسۡمُ رَبِّکَ ذِی الۡجَلٰلِ وَالۡاِکۡرَامِ» (55:78)  \nTranslation: Exalted is the name of your Lord, the Owner of Majesty and Honor.","The ultimate degree of honor and status.","Great","جلال","55:27-55:78",2
499,101,"G","جَدّ","«جَدّ» means divine grace and also fortune and destiny. «جُدِدْتُ» means one became fortunate and blessed. And «جَدَّ» also means to bestow someone with worldly wealth and status. «جَدّ» also means lineage (plural). «جَدّ» also means grandfathers (plural). And «اَجْدَاد» means good fortune, greatness, majesty, wealth, and sustenance. «فُلَانٌ ذُوْجَدٍّ» means that person is highly blessed (Manjad).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَّاَنَّہٗ تَعٰلٰی جَدُّ رَبِّنَا مَا اتَّخَذَ صَاحِبَۃً وَّلَا وَلَدًا» (72:3). Translation: And exalted is the glory of our Lord; He has neither spouse nor children.","«جَدّ» the divine grace that He bestows honor upon others as well.","Great","جد","72:3",1
500,102,"T","زَادَ ، اِزْدَادَ","«زَادَ» is the opposite of «نَقَص», meaning to increase and to cause increase. Both verbs are transitive and intransitive, appearing in both singular and plural forms. This is a general term for increase and augmentation, commonly used for adding to quantity and attributes. And «اَلزَّیَادَۃ» means that increase which is added after something is complete. Now observe their examples:\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ زَادَہٗ بَسۡطَۃً فِی الۡعِلۡمِ وَ الۡجِسۡمِ» (2/247)\nTranslation: And Allah had granted him (Talut) abundant knowledge and physical strength.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا تَغِیۡضُ الۡاَرۡحَامُ وَ  مَا تَزۡدَادُ» (13/8)\nTranslation: And (Allah knows) the wombs that shrink and expand.","«زَادَ» is used to add to the quantity and attributes of something after it is complete.","to increase","زاد ، ازداد","2:10-2:197-2:247-3:173-7:69-8:2-9:47-9:124-9:125-11:101-25:60-33:22-35:42-47:17-72:6",15
501,102,"T","کَثُرَ ، کَثَّرَ","Its opposite is «قلّ», meaning to be more in number and quantity.\n\nFor number:\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَدَّ کَثِیۡرٌ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ» (2/109)\nTranslation: Most of the People of the Book wish that...\n\nAnd for quantity, the Divine Command states:\n«مِمَّا قَلَّ مِنۡہُ اَوۡ کَثُرَ ؕ نَصِیۡبًا مَّفۡرُوۡضًا» (4/7)\nTranslation: From it (the inheritance), whether it is little or much, shares are prescribed.\n\nAnd «کَثّر» generally comes for addition in number.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاذۡکُرُوۡۤا اِذۡ کُنۡتُمۡ قَلِیۡلًا فَکَثَّرَکُمۡ» (7/86)\nTranslation: And remember when you were few, then He increased you.\n\nAnd «اَکْثَرَ» generally comes for addition in quantity.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَاَکۡثَرُوۡا فِیۡہَا الۡفَسَادَ» (89/12)\nTranslation: So they committed abundant corruption therein.","«کَثُرَ» is used to indicate an increase in number or quantity.","to increase","کثر ، کثر","2:100-2:243-3:110-4:7-4:12-5:59-5:100-5:103-6:37-6:111-6:116-6:128-7:17-7:86-7:102-7:131-7:187-7:188-8:19-8:34-9:8-9:25-9:69-10:36-10:55-10:60-11:17-11:32-12:21-12:38-12:40-12:68-12:103-12:106-13:1-16:38-16:75-16:83-16:101-17:6-17:89-18:34-18:54-21:24-23:70-25:44-25:50-26:8-26:67-26:103-26:121-26:139-26:158-26:174-26:190-26:223-27:61-27:73-27:76-28:13-28:57-28:78-29:63-30:6-30:9-30:30-30:42-31:25-34:28-34:35-34:36-34:41-36:7-37:71-39:29-39:49-40:57-40:59-40:61-40:82-41:4-43:78-44:39-45:26-49:4-52:47-58:7-74:6-89:12",89
502,102,"T","ضَاعَفَ","«ضِعْفٌ» means double, its opposite is «نِصْف». «ضَعَفَ الشَّيء» means as much as something and (whether this increase is in quantity or number). And «ضَعَّف» means to double, and «ضَاعَفَ» involves greater exaggeration.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاللّٰہُ یُضٰعِفُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ وَاسِعٌ عَلِیۡمٌ» (2/261)\nTranslation: And Allah increases it for whom He wills, and Allah is All-Sufficient and All-Knowing.","«ضَاعَفَ» is used to double or to increase even further.","to increase","ضاعف","2:245-2:261-3:130-4:40-11:20-25:69-33:30-57:11-57:18-64:17",10
503,102,"T","عَفَا","The general meaning of «عَفَا» is to forgive, however, its literal meaning is also to leave something in its state so that it may grow. «عَفَا اَلْشَعْر» means to let the hair grow so that it becomes long and increases. The Prophetic saying ﷺ states: «قَصُّوا الشَّوَارِبَ وَاعْفُوا اللُّحْیٰ», meaning Trim the mustache and let the beard grow. And this word is used in both transitive and intransitive forms.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ بَدَّلۡنَا مَکَانَ السَّیِّئَۃِ الۡحَسَنَۃَ حَتّٰی عَفَوۡا» (7/95)\nTranslation: Then We changed the adversity into ease until they grew (in wealth and offspring).\n\nAnd «عَفْو» also refers to something that is increased and is beyond what is necessary.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَیَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ مَا ذَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ ۬ ؕ قُلِ الۡعَفۡوَ»\nTranslation: They ask you what they should spend. Say, What is beyond your needs.","«عَفَا» Leave something as it is so that it grows.","to increase","عفا","2:219-7:95",2
504,102,"T","تَطَوُّع","«طَوْع» means to follow with heartfelt joy (mufradat), and the original meaning of «تَطَوُّع» is indeed to meticulously fulfill the command. However, in common usage, it refers to voluntary acts of goodness and worship performed out of personal desire, beyond obligatory duties. For example, voluntary prayers and optional charities, etc.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَعَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ یُطِیۡقُوۡنَہٗ فِدۡیَۃٌ طَعَامُ مِسۡکِیۡنٍ ؕ فَمَنۡ تَطَوَّعَ خَیۡرًا فَہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّہٗ» (2/184)\nTranslation: And whoever cannot fast [due to illness or travel] should feed a poor person as compensation. Then, whoever volunteers additional good deeds, it is better for them.","«تَطَوُّع» to voluntarily perform any good deed or give charity, etc.","to increase","تطوع","2:158-2:184-3:83-9:53-9:79-13:15-41:11",7
505,102,"T","نَافِلَۃً","«نَفْل» refers to an addition upon an obligation (mandatory act), and «اَنْفَال» refers to the spoils of war. The difference between «نَفْل» and «تَطَوُّع» is that «تَطَوُّع» also requires inner joy and eagerness, for example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَمِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً لَّکَ» (17/79)\nTranslation: And rise up at night for prayer, it is an additional merit for you.","«نَافِلَۃً» Voluntary acts of worship, such as: charity (sadaqah and khairat), Tahajjud prayer, voluntary prayers, fasting, etc.","to increase","نافلۃً","8:1-17:79-21:72",3
506,102,"T","اَرْبٰی","«رِبَا الْمَال» means an increase in wealth. And «رِبٰو» means interest. An additional increase on the principal without effort. «رِبَا الْفَرْس» means a horse's breath becoming swollen, and «رِبَا الْوَلْد» means a child's growth and subsequent education. And «اَرْبٰی» means to train something or to nurture and raise it. For example, in the Quran: «یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَیُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (2/276). Translation: Allah destroys interest and increases charities.","«اَرْبٰی» meaning to train or nurture something, or to raise and bring it up.","to increase","اربی","2:275-2:276-2:278-3:130-4:161-30:39",6
507,103,"S","قَرْیَۃ","«قَرْیَۃ» refers to every place where people gather and settle, whether it is a small town, a village, a settlement, or a city, and its inhabitants are «قُریٰ». And «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی» means a central town or city. The city of Mecca is also called «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی». And «قَرْیَۃ» can also mean a town and its residents, or the inhabitants of that place (pl.), for example: «وَسۡئَلِ الۡقَرۡیَۃَ الَّتِیۡ کُنَّا فِیۡہَا» (12/82) Translation: And ask the people of the town in which we resided.","«قَرْیَۃ» refers to a settlement (village or city) and its inhabitants—every place where people gather and settle.","Settlement","قریۃ","2:58-2:259-4:75-6:123-7:4-7:82-7:88-7:94-7:161-7:163-10:98-12:82-15:4-16:112-17:16-17:58-18:77-21:6-21:11-21:74-21:95-22:45-22:48-25:40-25:51-26:208-27:34-27:56-28:58-29:31-29:34-34:34-36:13-43:23-43:31-47:13-65:8",37
508,103,"S","بَدْوُ","«بَدْوُ» means village, rural area, or remote place. «بَدَا» means 'to appear,' and «بَدْوُ» refers to a place where, due to the absence of tall buildings, everything is visibly apparent (i.e., open). From this, «بَادِیَۃٌ» means desert, «بَادِیٌ» means desert dweller, and «بَدَوِیٌّ» means rustic or rural.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran, it is stated: «وَقَدۡ اَحۡسَنَ بِیۡۤ اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَنِیۡ مِنَ السِّجۡنِ وَجَآءَ بِکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡبَدۡوِ» (12/100). Translation: And He (Allah) bestowed favor upon me by taking me out of prison and bringing you here from the village.","«بَدْوُ» refers to rural areas or villages where, due to the absence of tall buildings, everything is distinctly visible.","Settlement","بدو","12:100",1
509,103,"I","اَعْرَابُ","«عَرَبِیٌّ» means a native of the land of Arabia, and «اَعْرَابِی» means a rural Arab. One who lives in the villages of the land of Arabia, and its plural is «اَعْرَاب», meaning Bedouin. Then, because villagers are generally ignorant and rustic, the word A'rab is also used in the meanings of rustic and ignorant.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَمِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مَنۡ یَّتَّخِذُ مَا یُنۡفِقُ مَغۡرَمًا» (9/98)  \nTranslation: And some of the Bedouin (rustic) are such that they consider whatever they spend as a loss.","«أَعْرَابُ» Arab villagers.","inhabited town","اعراب","9:90-9:97-9:98-9:99-9:101-9:120-33:20-48:11-48:16-49:14",10
510,104,"G","غَنَم","The term essentially means acquiring property that previously belonged to no one. Subsequently, this word began to be used for flocks of sheep that had wandered into someone's possession. Later, this term also started to apply to property obtained from the enemy after battle (spoils of war).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّمَا غَنِمۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ» (8/41)\nTranslation: And know that whatever you obtain as booty from the disbelievers...\n\nThen the usage of this word became specifically associated with stray flocks of sheep as well.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَدَاوٗدَ وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ اِذۡ نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And (recall) when David and Solomon were judging the case of a field in which some people's sheep had grazed at night and crushed it...","«غَنَم» is used only for herds of goats.","Goat","غنم","6:146-8:41-20:18-21:78",4
511,104,"G","مَعَزَ","«مَعَزَ» is used in the sense of separating goats from flocks. بکریاں (Bakriyan) is a plural form. بکری (Bakri) and بکرا (Bakra) are common for both genders, and its singular form is «مَاعِز». (Manjad)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مِنَ الضَّاۡنِ اثۡنَیۡنِ وَمِنَ الۡمَعۡزِاثۡنَیۡنِ» ( 6/143 )\nTranslation: Two from the sheep (flocks) and two from the goats.","«مَعَزَ» is used in the sense of separating goats from sheep.","Goat","معز","6:143",1
512,105,"T","اِنْبَثَّ","The meaning of «بَثَّ» is to scatter and spread far and wide (M. R.), and the meaning of «اِنْبَثَّ» is for something to disperse and spread in all directions to a great distance. In this, there is no element of intention from the thing that is spreading.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ  بُسَّتِ الۡجِبَالُ  بَسًّا فَکَانَتۡ ہَبَآءً  مُّنۡۢبَثًّا» (56/5,6)\nTranslation: And the mountains will break apart, becoming scattered dust. Then they will become dust and will fly around.","«اِنْبَثَّ» to scatter and spread far and wide. (This occurs without deliberate intention.)","to scatter","انبث","56:6",1
513,105,"T","اِنْتَشَرَ","The meaning of «نشر» is to spread and make famous (m. r.), and the meaning of «اِنْتَشَر» is for people to get up and leave from a gathering or assembly, each taking their own path.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«فَاِذَا قُضِیَتِ الصَّلٰوۃُ فَانۡتَشِرُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَابۡتَغُوۡا مِنۡ فَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (62/10)\nTranslation: Then when the prayer (Jumu'ah) is concluded, disperse and go your separate ways. And seek Allah's bounty (i.e., your livelihood).","«اِنْتَشَرَ» the dispersal of the gathering and each going their separate way (of their own accord).","to scatter","انتشر","30:20-33:53-54:7-62:10",4
514,105,"T","اِنْفَضَّ","«فَضَّ» means to break something in such a way that it becomes separated into distinct pieces. «اِنْفِضَاض» means that things like glass, etc., break into pieces and become separated (m. r.). Essentially, «اِنْفَضَّ» means that all the parts of something scatter and disperse.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاِذَا رَاَوۡا تِجَارَۃً اَوۡ لَہۡوَۨا انۡفَضُّوۡۤا اِلَیۡہَا وَتَرَکُوۡکَ قَآئِمًا» (62/11)\nTranslation: And when they see a transaction or a diversion, they rush to it and leave you standing [in prayer].","«اِنْفَضَّ» the gradual dispersion and scattering of all components of a thing.","to scatter","انفض","3:159-62:11-63:7",3
515,105,"T","اِنْتَثَرَ","«نَثَرَ» They say it for every thing that falls off and separates from something, scatters. And «اِنْتِشَار» they call it nose-scattering. (M R) Ibn Faris writes that the meaning of «نَثَر» is to throw down a scattered thing. In their own words, they also call «کلمۃ تَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِلْقَاءِ شَیْءٍ مُّتَفَرِّقٍ (م ۔ ل)» and «نَثَر» a non-verse expression (i.e., an expression in which there is no order or harmony). Moreover, «اِنْتَثَر» is used only for non-living things:\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡفَطَرَتۡ وَاِذَا الۡکَوَاکِبُ انۡتَثَرَتۡ» (82:1,2)\nTranslation: When the sky will crack open and the stars will scatter.","«اِنْتَثَرَ» to come apart and fall (used for inanimate objects)","to scatter","انتثر","82:2",1
516,105,"T","اِسْتَطَارَ","«طَارَ» means to fly in the air, like a winged creature or object, and «طَائِرُ» means a bird, its plural is «طَيْرٌ», and « اِسْتَطَار» means for something to rise high in the air and then spread and scatter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یُوۡفُوۡنَ بِالنَّذۡرِ وَیَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» (76:7)\nTranslation: They fulfill their vows and fear the Day whose evil is spreading.","«اِسْتَطَارَ» the scattering and spreading of something in space.","to scatter","استطار","76:7",1
517,106,"E","رَفَعَ","The meaning of «رَفَعَ» is to elevate. And if this action pertains to lifting and raising something from the ground, its opposite is «وَضَعَ». And if it pertains to raising the voice, its opposite is «خَفَضَ».\n\nFor example: For raising something, it appears in the Holy Quran:\n«وَاِذۡ یَرۡفَعُ  اِبۡرٰہٖمُ  الۡقَوَاعِدَ مِنَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَ اِسۡمٰعِیۡلُ» (2/127)\nTranslation: And when Abraham and Ishmael were raising the foundations of the House.\n\nAnd for raising the voice, it appears in the Holy Quran:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَرۡفَعُوۡۤا اَصۡوَاتَکُمۡ  فَوۡقَ صَوۡتِ النَّبِیِّ» (49/2)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not raise your voices above the voice of the Prophet.","«رَفَعَ» to raise something from the ground, to lift it up.","Exalted","رفع","2:63-2:93-2:127-2:253-4:154-4:158-6:83-6:165-7:176-12:76-12:100-13:2-19:57-24:36-35:10-43:32-49:2-55:7-58:11-79:28-88:18-94:4",22
518,106,"E","اَنْشَأ","«نَشَو» means the rising and elevation of something (m.l.). It also carries the meaning of nurturing and bringing something to maturity (m.f.). «نَشَاۃ» is used in the sense of 'to raise' or 'to elevate'. Here, the aspect of 'exaltation' or 'loftiness' of this word is under discussion. And «اَنْشَأ» means to create something, to raise it, and to bring it to maturity.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ یُرِیۡکُمُ  الۡبَرۡقَ خَوۡفًا وَّطَمَعًا وَّ یُنۡشِئُ السَّحَابَ الثِّقَالَ» (13/12)\nTranslation: He it is who shows you lightning, inspiring fear and hope, and brings forth the heavy clouds. (Jalandhari) He raises (Uthmani).","to create, to rear, and to elevate","Exalted","انشأ","2:259-6:6-6:83-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-13:12-21:11-21:21-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-25:3-25:40-25:47-28:45-29:20-35:9-36:79-43:11-43:18-44:35-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:15-67:23-88:22-",35
519,106,"E","عَلَا","«عَلَا» means to be high and its opposite is «سَفَلَ». This word is used for both jism-o-ayan (i.e., entities) and martabah (i.e., rank) in both contexts. That is, it is used for the elevation of a place as well as for the elevation of an entity's rank. Moreover, this word is used in both condemnatory (disparaging description) and commendatory (good description) forms. Now, consider the examples:\n\n(1) For the elevation of a place, in the Quran it is:\n«وَّرَفَعۡنٰہُ مَکَانًا عَلِیًّا» (19/57)\nTranslation: And We raised him (Idrees °) to a high place. (Jalandhari°) And We raised him to an elevated mansion. (Othmani°)\n\n(2) For the elevation of rank, in the Quran it is:\n«وَجَعَلۡنَا لَہُمۡ لِسَانَ صِدۡقٍ عَلِیًّا» (19/50)\nTranslation: And We raised for them (the Prophets °) a noble mention. (Jalandhari°) And We raised for them a true, elevated word. (Othmani°)\n\n(3) Example of the condemnatory form: In the Quran it is:\n«اِنَّ فِرۡعَوۡنَ عَلَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (28/4)\nTranslation: Indeed, Pharaoh had elevated himself in the land.","«عَلَا» is generally used, but it is employed specifically to denote the height of tall trees, especially date palms.","Exalted","علا","4:34-9:40-19:50-19:57-23:91-28:4",6
520,106,"E","بَسَقَ","«بَسَقَ» is used exclusively for tall and lofty trees, and especially for the tallness of date palms. (F L 43)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَالنَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ نَّضِیۡدٌ» ( 50/10 )\nTranslation: And tall date-palms, with layered (spadices).","«بَسَقَ» literally means 'to be tall'. It is used for tall and lofty trees, and especially for the tallness of the date palm.","Exalted","بسق","50:10",1
521,106,"E","شَمَخٌ","The word «شَمَخٌ» indicates something being large and elevated (m.l.). It is used for the height of mountains and lofty buildings (f.l 43) — exalted height. For example, the Quran states: «وَّجَعَلۡنَا فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ شٰمِخٰتٍ» (77/27)  \nTranslation: And We have placed on the earth lofty mountains.","«شَمَخٌ» is used to measure the height of mountains and tall buildings.","Exalted","شمخ","77:27",1
522,107,"T","جَعَلَ","The term «جَعَلَ» is commonly used for making or building, whether the work pertains to origination and creation or merely to arrangement, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: Who has made the earth a resting place for you and the sky a canopy.","«جَعَلَ» Its meanings are formed, but its usage is common, whether the act relates to creation and innovation or merely to arrangement and the like.","to make","جعل","2:19-2:22-2:30-2:66-2:125-126-2:128-2:143-2:224-2:259-2:260-3:41-3:61-3:126-3:156-3:176-4:5-4:15-4:19-4:33-4:75-4:90-4:91-4:141-4:144-5:6-5:13-5:20-5:48-5:60-5:97-5:103-6:1-6:6-6:9-6:25-6:39-6:91-6:96-6:97-6:100-6:107-6:112-6:122-6:123-6:124-6:125-6:136-6:165-7:10-7:27-7:47-7:69-7:74-7:138-7:143-7:150-7:189-7:190-8:10-8:29-8:37-9:19-9:40-10:5-10:14-10:24-10:59-10:67-10:73-10:85-10:87-10:100-11:82-11:118-12:15-12:55-12:62-12:70-12:100-13:3-13:16-13:33-13:38-14:30-14:35-14:37-14:40-15:16-15:20-15:74-15:91-15:96-16:56-16:57-16:62-16:72-16:78-16:80-16:81-16:91-16:93-16:124-17:2-17:6-17:8-17:12-17:18-17:22-17:29-17:33-17:39-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:80-17:99-18:1-18:7-18:32-18:48-18:52-18:57-18:59-18:90-18:94-18:95-18:96-18:98-19:6-19:7-19:10-19:21-19:24-19:30-19:31-19:32-19:49-19:50-19:96-20:29-20:53-20:58-21:8-21:15-21:30-21:31-21:32-21:34-21:58-21:70-21:72-21:73-21:91-22:25-22:34-22:36-22:53-22:67-22:78-23:13-23:41-23:44-23:50-23:94-24:40-24:43-24:63-25:10-25:20-25:23-25:31-25:35-25:37-25:45-25:47-25:53-25:54-25:61-25:62-25:74-26:21-26:29-26:84-26:85-27:34-27:61-27:62-27:86-28:4-28:5-28:35-28:38-28:41-28:71-28:72-28:73-28:83-29:10-29:15-29:27-29:67-30:21-30:48-30:54-32:8-32:9-32:23-32:24-33:4-34:18-34:19-34:33-35:11-35:39-36:8-36:9-36:27-36:34-36:80-37:63-37:77-37:98-37:158-38:5-38:26-38:28-39:6-39:8-39:21-40:61-40:64-40:79-41:9-41:10-41:29-41:44-42:8-42:11-42:50-42:52-43:3-43:10-43:12-43:15-43:19-43:28-43:33-43:45-43:56-43:59-43:60-45:18-45:21-45:23-46:26-48:26-48:27-49:13-50:26-51:42-51:51-56:36-56:65-56:70-56:73-56:82-57:7-57:26-57:27-57:28-59:10-60:5-60:7-65:2-65:3-65:4-65:7-67:5-67:15-67:23-68:35-68:50-69:12-71:7-71:12-71:16-71:19-72:25-73:17-74:12-74:31-75:39-76:2-77:21-77:25-77:27-78:6-78:9-78:10-78:11-78:13-87:5-90:8-105:2-105:5",305
523,107,"T","بَنٰی","«بَنٰی» meaning to build structures, etc. And «بُنْیَان» meaning building, wall, or any construction (fem.). And according to Ibn Faris, «بَنَاءَ الشَّیْ بِضَمٍّ بَعْضَہٗ اِلیٰ بَعْضٍ» (m. l.) (i.e., to build something in such a way that one part merges into another).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَالسَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ» (51/47)\nTranslation: And We have built the heaven with Our own hands, and We are its expanders.","«بَنٰی» meaning to build structures, etc.","to make","بنی","9:109-9:110-16:26-18:21-37:97-40:36-50:6-51:47-61:4-78:12",10
524,107,"T","صَنَعَ","«صَنَعَ» to make something beautiful with technical skill (lit.) and «صَنَّاع» refers to a skilled craftsman or artist, and «اِصْطَنَعَ» means to make something with technical skill and special attention (lit.).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا» (11/37)\nTranslation: And, O Nuh! construct the ship under Our eyes and with Our inspiration.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَاصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (20/41)\nTranslation: And I chose you for Myself.","To craft something with technical skill.","to create","صنع","5:14-5:63-7:137-11:16-11:37-11:38-13:31-16:112-18:104-20:39-20:41-20:69-21:80-23:27-24:30-27:88-29:45-35:8",18
525,107,"T","اِتَّخَذَ","«اَخَذَ» means to take, seize, or obtain something. When it governs two objects with «اِتَّخَذَ», it becomes a transitive verb with «جَعَلَ». (Grammatical note) In this usage, neither sequence nor creation is involved. Instead, it embodies continuity (i.e., the ongoing action of persisting).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَ الَّذِی اشۡتَرٰىہُ مِنۡ مِّصۡرَ لِامۡرَاَتِہٖۤ اَکۡرِمِیۡ مَثۡوٰىہُ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّنۡفَعَنَاۤ  اَوۡنَتَّخِذَہٗ وَلَدًا» (12/21)\n\nTranslation: And the one in Egypt who purchased him (Prophet Yusuf) said to his wife, Honor him greatly; perhaps he will benefit us, or we will adopt him as a son.","«اِتَّخَذَ» gives the meaning of forming by taking two objects transitively, and continuity (i.e., the continuous ongoing action) is evident in it.","to make","اتخذ","2:51-2:67-2:80-2:92-2:116-2:125-2:165-2:231-3:28-3:64-3:80-3:118-3:140-4:25-4:89-4:119-4:125-4:139-4:144-4:150-4:153-5:5-5:51-5:57-5:58-5:81-5:116-6:14-6:70-6:74-7:30-7:51-7:74-7:146-7:148-7:152-9:16-9:23-9:31-9:98-9:99-9:107-10:68-11:92-12:21-13:16-16:51-16:67-16:68-16:92-16:94-17:2-17:40-17:73-17:111-18:4-18:15-18:21-18:50-18:51-18:56-18:61-18:63-18:86-18:102-18:106-19:17-19:35-19:81-18:88-19:92-21:17-21:21-21:24-21:26-21:36-23:91-23:110-25:2-25:3-25:18-25:27-25:28-25:30-25:41-25:43-25:57-26:29-26:129-28:9-29:25-29:41-31:6-35:6-36:23-36:74-38:63-39:3-39:4-39:43-42:6-42:9-43:16-43:32-45:9-45:10-45:23-45:35-46:28-58:16-60:1-63:2-72:3-73:9-73:19-76:29-78:39",117
526,108,"C","غَلَّقَ","«غَلَقَ» means to lock or fasten, and its opposite is «فَکَّ», which means to release or untie (m. l.). «غَلْق» means a lock or bolt (manjada). And «غَلَّقَ الْبَاب» means to firmly lock a door, to install a latch, etc., or to make something secure.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَغَلَّقَتِ الۡاَبۡوَابَ وَ قَالَتۡ ہَیۡتَ لَکَ» (12/23)\nTranslation: And she (Zulaikha) certainly locked the doors and said, Come, Joseph.","«غَلَّقَ» is used for closing doors, gates, etc.","Closed","غلق","12:23",1
527,108,"C","وَصَدَ","This manner of sealing is described as one where nothing can escape from the sealed thing. In the words of Ibn Faris, the meanings of «اَلْوَصْدُ خَتْمُ شَیْءٍ اِلیٰ شَیْءٍ ( م ل )» and «اَوْصَدْتُ الْقِدْرَ» are: covering a pot so that steam does not escape (m. r.). And «اَوْصَدْتُ الْبَابَ» means closing a door. However, its application applies when no other window, door, skylight, or similar opening is open. For example: In the Holy Quran, it is stated: «عَلَیۡہِمۡ نَارٌمُّؤۡصَدَۃٌ» (90/20). Translation: These people will be shut in the fire.","«وَصَدَ» to seal something so that nothing can get out.","Closed","وصد","2:217-4:167-13:33-16:88-27:43-40:37-47:1-47:32-47:34-48:25",10
528,108,"C","قَصَرَ","«قَصَرَ» is used in two basic meanings. (1) Not reaching the extremity or goal of something. (2) «حَبَسَ» i.e., being closed or sealed (as commonly understood). Here the second meaning is under discussion. They say «قَصَرَ فِی بَیْتِہٖ» became confined or closed in one's home. For instance: In the Quran it is: «حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ» (55/72). Translation: Houris are in the tents that remain stationary (Ottmaniؒ).","«قَصَرَ» is used to mean being closed or sealed in a place.","Closed","قصر","7:74-22:45-25:10-55:72-77:32",5
529,108,"S","قَبَضَ","«قَبَضَ» means to hold something in a fist, and «قَبَضَۃٌ» (sing.) refers to the fist itself. Therefore, «قَبَضَ» is used in all the senses of constricting, reducing, tightening, and restraining.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمُنۡکَرِ وَیَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَیَقۡبِضُوۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ» (9/67)\nTranslation: (The hypocrites) are those who forbid evil and enjoin good, and (in spending for Allah's cause) they hold back their hands (from giving).","«قَبَضَ» to grasp something in one's fist and take it into one's possession.","sealed","قبض","2:245-9:67-20:96-25:46-39:67-67:19",6
530,109,"T","حَبَکَ","«حَبَّاک» means the weaver (one who makes cloth) and «حَبَکَ الثَّوْبَ» means he wove the cloth (masculine form) and «حَبَکَ حَابِکَ الثَّوْب» means to skillfully craft the weaver's cloth. Excellent crafting (minjad) and «حَبَک» also means 'pathway', and its plural is «حُبُک» (plural form).\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«وَالسَّمَآءِ ذَاتِ الۡحُبُکِ» (51/7)\nTranslation: And by the sky full of pathways.\n(i.e., a net of stars is spread across the sky) (Uthmani)\nAnd by the sky which contains pathways (Jalandhari)","«حَبَکَ» is used in the sense of building or fashioning something, such as weaving cloth, etc.","to build","حبک","51:7",1
531,109,"T","وَضَنَ","The original meaning of «وَضَنَ» is *zarbani* (i.e., embroidery with gold threads on cloth). And *isti'āratan* is used for something made firmly or robustly (as per lexical sources). «مَوضُون» means something made thin, or an object crafted from gold or silver (as noted in lexical sources).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«عَلٰی سُرُرٍ مَّوۡضُوۡنَۃٍ مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا مُتَقٰبِلِیۡنَ» (56:15-16)\nTranslation: (Upon thrones adorned with rubies, sapphires, and the like) they will be reclining, facing each other.","«وَضَنَ» is said to mean building something firmly.","To build","وضن","56:15",1
532,110,"B","ثَقَلَ","«ثَقَلَ» refers to a traveler's belongings, burden, weight, etc. (mujnad), and this term is generally used for material and sensory burdens. And the opposite of «ثَقِیْل» is 'khafif,' meaning light in weight. For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنۡفِرُوۡا خِفَافًا وَّ ثِقَالًا» (9:41)\nTranslation: Go forth, whether you are light or heavy.\nAnd the plural of «ثَقَل» is «اَثقَال».\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَتَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ» (16:7)\nTranslation: And they carry your loads to a land you could not have reached except with great hardship. Indeed, your Lord is Most Kind and Most Merciful.\nFurthermore, «ثَقِیْل», meaning heavy and burdensome things, is sometimes used in a spiritual sense as well.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا سَنُلۡقِیۡ عَلَیۡکَ قَوۡلًا ثَقِیۡلًا» (73:5)\nTranslation: Soon We will send down to you a heavy commandment.\nHere, «ثَقِیْل» refers to a matter, speech, or commandment that is extremely burdensome to one's innate nature, and acting upon it is an act of great courage.","Generally, it is used for a traveler's belongings and other heavy items.","Burden","ثقل","4:40-7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-10:61-13:12-16:7-21:47-23:102-29:13-31:16-34:3-34:22-35:18-52:40-55:31-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-99:7-99:8-101:6",25
533,110,"B","حَمْل","The term «حَمَلَ» denotes bearing a burden and carrying a load. And «حَمْل» denotes such a burden that a thing carries internally within itself, such as a child in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud (meaning).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7/189)\nTranslation: When a man approaches his wife, she becomes slightly pregnant, and she moves about with it.\n\nAnd «حِمْل» denotes such a burden that is physically placed on someone's back (meaning). However, according to the author of al-Muntahi al-Arb, the meaning of «حِمْل» is 'bar-i-sar' or 'bar-i-pusht' (reference), meaning the carrier; whatever maximum burden one can carry is the 'himl' for him. And this definition appears more correct. The Quran also supports this meaning:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ الۡمَلِکِ وَلِمَنۡ جَآءَ بِہٖ حِمۡلُ بَعِیۡرٍ وَّاَنَا بِہٖ زَعِیۡمٌ» (12/72)\nTranslation: They said, We are missing the king's measure, and whoever brings it will receive a camel's load (as reward), and I take responsibility for delivering it.","«حَمْل» refers to a burden that the bearer carries within itself, such as a fetus in the womb, fruit on a tree, or water in a cloud.","Burden","حمل","2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17",43
534,110,"B","وَقْر","The term «وَقْر» is used metaphorically in a spiritual sense. It is said that «فِیْ صَدْرِہٖ وَقْرٌ» has a burden of envy in his heart. (Munjid) Similarly, «فِیْ اُذُنِہٖ وَقْرٌ» means there is a burden in his ears, i.e., he suffers from heaviness of hearing or deafness and hears loudly. Some people also interpret «وَقْر» as earwax, but the first meaning is more eloquent. And interpreting it as earwax limits it.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّجَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ اَکِنَّۃً اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ وَفِیۡۤ اٰذَانِہِمۡ وَقۡرًا» (17:46)\nTranslation: And We have placed covers over their hearts so that they do not understand it, and [placed] heaviness in their ears.\n\nAnd the word «وِقْر» refers to that maximum degree of spiritual burden which is according to the carrier's ability and strength.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَالذّٰرِیٰتِ ذَرۡوًا فَالۡحٰمِلٰتِ  وِقۡرًا» (51:1-2)\nTranslation: By the scatterers scattering, and the carriers bearing a heavy load.","Generally, it comes as a spiritual burden. And «وِقر» is the maximum spiritual burden, commensurate with the strength of the one who bears it.","Burden","وقر","6:25-17:46-18:57-31:7-41:5-41:44-51:2",7
535,110,"B","وِزْر","Ibn Faris writes that when a person spreads out his garment, places his burden in it, and then carries it off, this is «وِزْر». And for this reason, «اَلْذَنْبُ» (sin) is called «وِزْر» (burden), meaning the burden of one's own deeds. Similarly, «وِزْر» is also used for weapons, and its plural is «اَوْزَار» (m. l). And the meanings of «اَوْزَرَ اِیْزَارًا» include hiding, taking, giving refuge, etc. (Manjad). And in the same way, the meanings of «وَزَرُ» also include taking refuge in a mountain, etc. (Muf). And the usage of «وِزْر» is often for the heaviness of sins.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ ؕ اَلَا سَآءَ مَا یَزِرُوۡنَ» (6/31)\nTranslation: And they will be carrying their burdens (of deeds) on their backs. See how evil is the burden they are carrying!","«وِزْر» is generally invoked for the burden of sins.","Burden","وزر","6:31-6:164-16:25-17:15-20:87-20:100-35:18-39:7-53:38-94:2",10
536,110,"B","اِصْر","«اَلْاِصْر» has two meanings: (1) to tie a knot, and (2) to forcibly seize or hold back something (mufradat, majma'). In this sense, the burden of adhering to one's covenant and fulfilling religious commands is «اِصْر». According to Ibn Faris, every contract, covenant, and relationship is «اِصْر» (majma').\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا وَلَا  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا» (2/286)\nTranslation: O our Lord! Do not impose upon us a burden like that which You imposed upon those before us.\n\nFurthermore, the application of «اِصْر» also extends to the obstacles encountered in choosing the path of truth, which arise due to the customs and traditions of a society.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَیَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ وَ الۡاَغۡلٰلَ الَّتِیۡ کَانَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (7/157)\nTranslation: He will remove from them their burden and the yokes that were upon them.","«اِصْر» meaning covenants and agreements, responsibilities of religious rulings, or bonds of customs and traditions.","Burden","اصر","2:286-3:81-7:157",3
537,110,"B","کَلٌّ","«کَلٌّ» signifies: needy, dependent, orphan, helpless, weak, and burden. (Manjad M. R. M. L.) And «کَلّ» refers to the responsibility of upbringing or the burden of maintenance and sustenance.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَحَدُہُمَاۤ اَبۡکَمُ لَا یَقۡدِرُعَلٰی شَیۡءٍ وَّہُوَ کَلٌّ عَلٰی مَوۡلٰىہُ ۙ اَیۡنَمَا یُوَجِّہۡہُّ لَایَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ» (16/76)\nTranslation: One of them is mute, powerless and incapable, having no strength over anything, and is a burden on his master. Wherever he sends him, he brings no good.","«کَلٌّ» comes to bear the burden of rearing a helpless and destitute orphan.","Burden","کل","16:76",1
538,110,"B","وَزْن ، مَوَازِیْن","«مَوَازِیْن» means a scale with which something is weighed and measured. And «وَزْن» is the weight that is placed on one pan of the scale for weighing. And mīzān means both the scale and the measure of weight, and its plural is «مَوَازِیْن» (singular and plural).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ  ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ» (101/6,7)\nTranslation: Then whoever's deeds weigh heavy will be in a pleasant abode.","«وَزْن ، مَوَازِیْن» the weight that is placed on the scale for weighing.","burden","وزن ، موازین","7:8-7:9-17:35-18:105-21:47-23:102-23:103-26:182-55:9-83:3-101:6-101:8",12
539,111,"A","ثَقُلَ","«ثَقُلَ» meaning something being heavy in the scale.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ  ثَقُلَتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَہُوَ فِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ» (101/6,7)\nTranslation: Then those whose deeds weigh heavy will be in a pleasant life.","«ثَقُلَ» meaning something becoming heavy in weight.","a tall camel","ثقل","7:8-7:57-7:187-7:189-9:41-13:12-16:7-23:102-29:13-35:18-52:40-68:46-73:5-76:27-99:2-101:6",16
540,111,"H","کَسَلَ","«کَسَلَ» the state of one's disposition becoming heavy and burdensome due to sloth, and «اَلْکَسْل» meaning to manifest heaviness (burden) in a matter where such heaviness is inappropriate (elaborated). For example: Regarding the hypocrites, the divine command states: «وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَ الصَّلٰوۃَ  اِلَّا وَ ہُمۡ کُسَالٰی» (9/54) Translation: And when they come to prayer, they come lazily and sluggishly.","«کَسَلَ» A heavy disposition resulting from laziness.","Heavy","کسل","4:142-9:54",2
541,111,"H","اٰد","«اٰدَ» meaning: the feeling of heaviness or burden in one's nature due to an excess of hardship or toil (intransitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَا یَئُوۡدُہٗ حِفۡظُہُمَا ۚ وَ ہُوَالۡعَلِیُّ الۡعَظِیۡمُ» (2/255)\nTranslation: And the protection of the heavens and the earth does not burden Allah the Exalted.","Overexertion due to excessive toil weighing down one's state.","heavy","اد","2:255",1
542,111,"H","کَبُر ، کَبِیْرَۃٌ","«کَبُرَ» The state of one's nature feeling burdened (heavy) due to considering a task difficult and onerous.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِنۡ کَانَ کَبُرَ عَلَیۡکَ اِعۡرَاضُہُمۡ» ( 6/35 )\nTranslation: And if the heedlessness of those [disbelievers] becomes burdensome to you...\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«وَاسۡتَعِیۡنُوۡا بِالصَّبۡرِ وَالصَّلٰوۃِ ؕ وَاِنَّہَا لَکَبِیۡرَۃٌ اِلَّا عَلَی الۡخٰشِعِیۡنَ» ( 2/45 )\nTranslation: And seek help through patience and prayer. Indeed, it is a weighty matter except for the humble.","The heaviness of heart resulting from considering a task difficult and burdensome.","Heavy","کبر ، کبیرۃ","2:45-2:143-10:71-17:51-18:5-20:23-24:11-40:35-42:13-44:16-53:18-61:3-74:35-79:20-79:34-87:12",16
543,112,"E","شَیْخ","«شَیْخ» means great. Whether it refers to someone advanced in age, or one who holds a high rank in knowledge, virtue, and status. (Munjid) The word Sheikh is essentially a term of respect. «شَیْخُ الْمِرْأَۃ» It is also used for a woman's husband, even if he is younger. However, in the Holy Quran, this word has been used specifically in the meaning of elderly in terms of age. (See: Shu'khu)\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لِتَبۡلُغُوۡۤا اَشُدَّکُمۡ ثُمَّ لِتَکُوۡنُوۡا شُیُوۡخًا» ( 40/67 )\nTranslation: Then you reach your youth... Then you become elderly.","«شَیْخ» means (old age); it is generally used for an elderly person. Additionally, it is also used to address someone possessing honor, respect, and knowledge.","Elder","شیخ","11:72-12:78-28:23-40:67",4
544,112,"E","شِیْب","«شَابَ» means to have white hair. They say «شَابَتْ رُءُوْسُ الْاٰکَام», meaning the peaks of the hills turned white with snow. And «اَشْیَب» means a white garment. «شِیْب» is its plural form. (Manjad) and «شَیْب» means old age (Muf). The scholar of linguistic jurisprudence considers it the middle stage between youth and old age and assigns it an age range of up to 30 to 40 years (F. L 91). In any case, «شِیْب» could refer to someone whose hair has already begun to turn white.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَکَیۡفَ تَتَّقُوۡنَ اِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ یَوۡمًا یَّجۡعَلُ الۡوِلۡدَانَ شِیۡبَۨا» (73:17)\nTranslation: If you were to disbelieve, how could you then be saved on a Day that will make children gray-haired?","«شِیْب» A person whose hair has begun to turn white.","Elderly person","شیب","19:4-30:54-73:17",3
545,112,"E","کَھَل","«کَھَل» means to reach middle age, and «کَھْل» refers to those between thirty and fifty years of age, while «کَاھَلَ الرَّجُل» means to marry (manjad). However, according to the scholar of language and jurisprudence, it is used for the middle age between forty and sixty years (f.l 9). In their own words, «ثُمَّ مَا دَامَ بَیْنَ الثَّلَاثِیْنَ وَالْاَرْبَعْیِنَ فَھُو شَابٌ ۔ ثُمَّ ھُوَ کَھْلٌ : اِلیٰ اَنْ یَسْتَوْفَی السِّتِّیْنَ». For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا» (3/46). Translation: And he (Jesus, son of Mary) will speak to people in the cradle and in maturity, equally in both states.","The term «کَھَل» is used for the middle age between forty and sixty years.","Elderly person","کھل","3:46-5:110",2
546,112,"E","عَجُوْز","«عَجُوْز» comes only for females, meaning an old woman whose childbearing has ceased. And «عَجُزَۃ» refers to someone's last child.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ  شَیۡخًا» (11/72).\n\nTranslation: She said, Alas! How can I have a child? I am certainly old, and my husband is also old.","«عَجُوْز» They call an old woman (this is used specifically for women).","elderly person","عجوز","11:72-26:171-37:135-51:29",4
547,112,"O","مُعَمَّر","«مُعَمَّر» meaning: one who attains a ripe old age, one who lives to a considerable age.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَمَا یُعَمَّرُ مِنۡ مُّعَمَّرٍ وَّلَا یُنۡقَصُ مِنۡ عُمُرِہٖۤ اِلَّا فِیۡ کِتٰبٍ» (35:11)\nTranslation: And no one is granted a long life unless We will it. Nor is anything shortened or lengthened for anyone, except that it is (already) recorded in a Book.","«مُعَمَّر» one who lives up to the age of sixty.","Old man","معمر","2:96-10:16-15:72-16:70-21:44-22:5-26:18-28:45-35:11-35:37-36:68",11
548,112,"E","عَوَان ، فَارِض","«عَانَ» means to be of middle age. It applies to humans, animals, women, and men alike. And «عَوَان» means middle-aged (specifically for a cow or bull), and «فَارِض» means an old cow or bull. Its opposite is «بِکْر», i.e., a young calf that has not yet reached maturity. (Figurative) It also means a virgin girl (in certain contexts).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ اِنَّہٗ یَقُوۡلُ اِنَّہَا بَقَرَۃٌ لَّا فَارِضٌ وَّلَا بِکۡرٌ  ؕ عَوَانٌۢ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ» (2/68)\n\nTranslation: Moses (peace be upon him) said, Your Lord says that it should be neither an old cow nor a young calf, but of middle age between the two.","The term «عَوَان» is used for humans, animals, men, and women—for all.  \nSpecifically for an old cow or bull, the term «فَارِض» is used.","elderly person","عوان ، فارض","2:68",1
549,113,"D","بَلَیَ","The weakening of a usable object due to it becoming old. «بَلَی الثَّوْب»: Clothes became old (intransitive); in Punjabi, this is expressed as 'henḍ jāna'. For example, in the Quran it is stated: «فَوَسۡوَسَ اِلَیۡہِ الشَّیۡطٰنُ قَالَ یٰۤـاٰدَمُ ہَلۡ اَدُلُّکَ عَلٰی شَجَرَۃِ الۡخُلۡدِ وَ مُلۡکٍ لَّا یَبۡلٰی» (20:120). Translation: Then Satan whispered into his mind and said, 'O Adam! Shall I inform you of a tree of eternal life and a kingdom that will never grow old?'","«بَلِیَ» to become worn out and old.","dilapidated","بلی","20:120",1
550,113,"D","وَھِیَ","«وَھِیَ» refers to the tearing or splitting of something's joint or seam (m.l.) «وَھْیَ الثَّوْبَ وَالْحَبْل», or the beginning to tear due to wear in cloth or rope (f.l 39) or the splitting of leather due to rot (m.l.). For example, in the Quran it says: «وَانۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ» (69/16). Translation: And the sky will split; indeed, it will be weak (and worn out) that day.","a loose joint in something","dilapidated","وھی","69:16",1
551,113,"R","رَمَّ","«رَمَّ» meaning capable of being repaired (due to decay) and «رَمَّ الْحَبْل» meaning the breaking of a rope. And «رَمَّ الْعَظْم». The bone becoming decayed and «رِمَّۃ» is said for an old bone that has become decayed and brittle (Fal 54) or then for an old piece of rope that has become separated (Manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَا تَذَرُ مِنۡ شَیۡءٍ اَتَتۡ عَلَیۡہِ اِلَّا جَعَلَتۡہُ کَالرَّمِیۡمِ» (51/42)\nTranslation: It (the calamitous wind) smote whatever it struck, leaving them like hollowed-out trunks of palm trees.","«رَمّ» to start breaking apart due to rot.","rotten","رم","36:78-51:42",2
552,113,"R","رَفَتَ","«رَفَتَ» meaning to break, to crush; and «رَفَتَ الْعَظْم» meaning bones becoming fragmented; and «اَلْرَفَات» meaning every broken thing. Rotten (decayed). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَقَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا وَّرُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا» (17/49). Translation: And they say, When we have died and our bones have become rotten and fragmented, will we then be raised up anew?","to crumble into fragments due to decay","rotten","رفت","17:49-17:98",2
553,113,"R","نَخِرَ","The meaning of «نَخِرَ» is to become rotten and crumbled (manjad). The meaning of «نَخِرَۃٌ» is for a bone to become rotten from within, hollow or empty, or to have holes in it. For example, in the Quran it says: «یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ ءَاِنَّا لَمَرۡدُوۡدُوۡنَ فِی الۡحَافِرَۃِ ءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا نَّخِرَۃً» (79/10-11). Translation: The disbelievers say, Shall we indeed be returned [to our former state]? When we have become hollow bones, shall we then be revived?","«نَخِرَ» (of bone) becoming hollow from within due to decay.","rotten","نخر","79:11",1
554,114,"T","لَفَظَ ، لَفِظَ","The meaning of «لَفَظَ» is to throw (from the mouth). «لُفَاظَۃٌ» refers to something thrown from the mouth or something wiped from a tray. The word also means a statement spoken from the mouth, and its plural is manjada [منجد]. «لَافِظ» refers to the millstone from which flour is thrown out (m. q.). The term generally means the expression of something by the tongue, even if it is only a single word.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مَا یَلۡفِظُ مِنۡ  قَوۡلٍ اِلَّا لَدَیۡہِ رَقِیۡبٌ عَتِیۡدٌ» (50/18)\nTranslation: No utterance occurs except that there is a guardian ready with it.","«لَفَظَ» Whatever one utters from the mouth is termed a word.","to speak","لفظ ، لفظ","50:18",1
555,114,"T","نَطَقَ","«نَطَقَ» means to speak in terms whose meanings can be understood. «اَلْمَالُ النَّاطِقُ وَالصَّامِت» refers to animals as speaking wealth, and to gold and silver as silent wealth. This is because animals are also capable of speech (nāṭiq) and understand each other's language. «مَنْطِقَ الطَّیْر» means the language of animals. However, this word is specifically used for humans. Logicians refer only to humans as speaking animals (ḥayawān nāṭiq), and they understand «نُطْقٌ» to mean the faculty of speech. (Aristotle was the first to call man a speaking animal, but etymologically, this term can be applied to all beings possessed of intellect.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَا یَنۡطِقُ عَنِ الۡہَوٰی اِنۡ ہُوَاِلَّا وَحۡیٌ یُّوۡحٰی» (53:3-4)\nTranslation: Nor does he speak from [his own] inclination. It is not but a revelation revealed.\n\nAnd regarding Prophet Sulaiman (peace be upon him), the Quran mentions:\nFor example, the Divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ عُلِّمۡنَا مَنۡطِقَ الطَّیۡرِ» (27:16)\nTranslation: O people, we have been taught the language of birds.\n\nThus, here «نَطَقَ» is used in relation to Prophet Sulaiman's (peace be upon him) comprehension and the birds' ability to speak.\n\nFurthermore, just as «نَطَقَ» has an apparent meaning referring to intelligible speech, it also has an inner meaning referring to comprehension, perception, or the language of state (ḥāl).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (45:29)\nTranslation: This, Our record, speaks the truth about you. Indeed, We were recording all that you were doing.","«نَطَقَ» means speaking in a way that is understandable, i.e., saying something whose meaning can be comprehended.","to speak","نطق","21:63-21:65-23:62-27:16-27:85-37:92-41:21-45:29-51:23-53:3-77:35",11
556,114,"T","فَصَحَ","The meaning of «فَصُحَ» is to purify something from all admixture and make it clean. And the meaning of «فَصَحَ اللَّبَن» is to remove the froth from the top of milk and thus clarify it. And «فَصَحَ الرَّجُل» is derived from this (i.e., taken from it), meaning that a person's speech is eloquent and his words are pure and free from idle and futile talk, and that he uses well-chosen, appropriate words.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَاَخِیۡ ہٰرُوۡنُ ہُوَاَفۡصَحُ مِنِّیۡ لِسَانًا فَاَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعِیَ رِدۡاً یُّصَدِّقُنِیۡۤ»\nTranslation: (Moses) said, My brother Aaron is more eloquent in speech than me, so send him with me as a helper to confirm me.","«فَصُحَ» To be eloquent in speech, straightforward and clear, free from ambiguity.","to speak","فصح","28:34",1
557,114,"T","اَعْرَبَ ۔ اَعْجَمَ","«اَلْاِعْرَاب» means to make something clear. And «اَعْرَبَ عَنْ نَفْسِہٖ» means he explained the matter thoroughly. «اَلْعَرَبِیُّ» also means one who explains clearly and (speaks) clear and eloquent language (Ma'fa). For example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ  قُرۡءٰنًا عَرَبِیًّا» ( 12/2 )\nTranslation: Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Quran, so that you may understand.\n\nAnd «اَلْعُجَمَۃ» means ambiguity and concealment. And «اَلْاَعْجَمُ» is what one calls a person whose language is not eloquent, even if it is Arabic. The Arabs used to consider themselves the masters of eloquent language and others as non-eloquent, and they used to call all non-Arabs «اَلْعَجْم». «اَلْعَجَمِیُّ» is derived from that. And they also call animals «عَجْمَاء» because they (cannot express the thoughts of their hearts) properly.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡ جَعَلۡنٰہُ قُرۡاٰنًا اَعۡجَمِیًّا لَّقَالُوۡا لَوۡلَا فُصِّلَتۡ اٰیٰتُہٗ ؕ ءَؔاَعۡجَمِیٌّ وَّعَرَبِیٌّ» ( 41/44 )\nTranslation: And if We had made it a non-Arabic Quran, they would have said, Why are its verses not explained in detail?","«اَعْرَب» Speaking with clarity.\n«اَعْجَمَ» Speaking vaguely and ambiguously, i.e., in a roundabout manner.","to speak","اعرب ۔ اعجم","12:2-13:37-16:103-20:113-26:195-26:198-39:28-41:3-41:44-42:7-43:3-46:12",12
558,114,"T","تَکَلَّمَ","«کَلَّمَ» means to speak or to talk, and «تَکَلَّم» means to utter or to bring speech to the lips.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ» (78/38)  \nTranslation: No soul will speak except with the permission of Allah, the Most High.","«تَکَلَّمَ» to utter a meaningful statement that another is hearing.","to speak","تکلم","3:41-5:110-11:105-19:10-23:108-24:16-27:82-30:35-36:65-78:38",10
559,114,"T","لَحِنَ","«لَحِنَ» means to turn away from the commonly used method and style, and «لحن القول» means to employ a different method, deviating from the prevailing mode of expression or style of speech. And «اَلْحَنُ» is also used for eloquent speech (m. q.) and for an eloquent or articulate person (muf). And «لَحَّنَ» means to recite with a melodious voice; the tone of David is famous for this. However, the primary meaning of «لَحَن» is the change of tone, such that with it, a single sentence can become positive, negative, or interrogative.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَلَتَعۡرِفَنَّہُمۡ  فِیۡ لَحۡنِ الۡقَوۡلِ» (47/30). Translation: And you will recognize them by their tone of speech.","«لَحِنَ» To adopt a different mode of discourse.","to speak","لحن","47:30",1
560,115,"T","اَسَالَ","The meaning of «سَالَ» is to flow (of liquid substances) or to gush out, and «سَیل» means flowing water, a flood, and «سَیَّال» means forcefully flowing (a torrent); moreover, every flowing thing is called «سَیَّال». And «اَسَالَ» means to cause something (that flows or is liquid) to flow.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12)\nTranslation: And We caused a spring of copper to flow for him (David, peace be upon him).","«اَسَالَ» to cause any flowing thing to flow.","to flow","اسال","13:17-34:12-34:16",3
561,115,"T","اَفَاض","The meaning of «فَاضَ ، فَیْض» is said to be for something to flow forth effortlessly or for water to gush out and flow from a place (m. l. - muf). «اَفَاضَ السَّیْل» means for water to be abundant and to flow out from the banks of a valley, and «فَاضَتْ عَیْنٰہُ» means that tears flowed effortlessly from his eyes. «اَفَاضَ» means to cause (water, etc.) to flow effortlessly. «اَفَاضَ اِنَاہُ» He filled his bucket to the brim so that the water began to spill over from the top; its essential meaning is to overflow.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَنَادٰۤی اَصۡحٰبُ النَّارِ اَصۡحٰبَ الۡجَنَّۃِ اَنۡ اَفِیۡضُوۡا عَلَیۡنَا مِنَ الۡمَآءِ» (7/50)\nTranslation: And the people of the Fire will cry out to the people of Paradise, 'Pour upon us some water or a little from what Allah has provided you.'","to begin flowing from the edge","to flow","افاض","5:83-7:50-9:92",3
562,115,"T","سَکَبَ","The meaning of «سَکَبَ» is to pour or flow (such as water, etc.). And «اَلسَّکْب» refers to continuous rain or rain with large, heavy drops. (Source: Manjad) That whose water flows out. And «اَلْاُسْکُوْب» means continuous pouring (from Manjad); thus, the concept of continuity or permanence along with the pouring or flowing of water, etc., is also found in «سَکَبَ». And «مَآءٍ مَّسْکُوْبٍ» means flowing water.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّظِلٍّ مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّمَآءٍ مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ» (56:31)\nTranslation: And prolonged shade and abundant water. (Uthmani)","«سَکَبَ» Pouring a flowing substance in such an amount that it begins to flow.","to flow","سکب","56:31",1
563,115,"T","سَفَکَ","«سَفَکَ» meaning 'to shed blood or water'. However, its usage is more commonly associated with bloodshed. And «سفّاک» refers to a bloodthirsty person (M. R).\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذۡ اَخَذۡنَا مِیۡثَاقَکُمۡ لَا تَسۡفِکُوۡنَ دِمَآءَکُمۡ» (2/84)\nTranslation: And when We took your covenant, 'You shall not shed each other's blood...'","«سَفَکَ» is commonly used for bloodletting.","to flow","سفک","2:30-2:84",2
564,115,"T","سَفَحَ","The meanings of «سَفَحَ» are also literally to flow blood or water (sing.) and also denote the rapid flowing and continuity of something that flows (Faq l 257). In the Quran, «دَمًا مَّسْفُوْحًا» appears in the sense of flowing blood. However, this word is generally used for illicitly flowing semen or water, or for committing adultery: «مُسَافِحٌ» means adulterous man and «مُسَافِحَۃ» means adulterous woman.\n\nFor example: The Quran states: «وَاُحِلَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِکُمۡ مُّحۡصِنِیۡنَ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحِیۡنَ» (4/24)\n\nTranslation: And all women are lawful for you besides those [prohibited ones]; so marry them with your wealth, provided that the intention behind marriage is to preserve chastity and not to satisfy lust.","«سَفَحَ» the rapid flow of something.","to flow; to float; to drift","سفح","4:24-4:25-5:5",3
565,115,"T","فَجَرَ","The original meaning of «فَجَرَ» is to burst forth something widely (muf). Its usage indicates expansiveness in relation to flowing things.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا»\nTranslation: (And the disbelievers will say, We will never believe in you until you cause a spring to gush forth from the earth for us.)\n\nFor flowing, «سَالَ» and «فَاضَ» have been mentioned above. Now observe their examples.\n\n(1) Example of «سَالَ»: For instance, the Quran states:\n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)\nTranslation: He sent down water from the sky, then the channels flowed according to their capacity.\n\n(2) Example of «فَاضَ»: For instance, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا سَمِعُوۡا مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» (5/83)\nTranslation: And when they hear the Book revealed to the Prophet (Muhammad ﷺ), you see their eyes overflowing with tears because they have recognized the truth.","«فَجَرَ» to flow over a vast and extensive area.","to flow","فجر","2:60-2:74-17:90-17:91-18:33-36:34-54:12-76:6-82:3",9
566,115,"T","جَرٰی","«جَرْیًا وَجِرْیَانًا» In terms of its original meaning, this word is used for flowing and moving of water and similar liquid substances (e.g.).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فِیۡہَا عَیۡنٌ جَارِیَۃٌ» (88/12)\nTranslation: In it (Paradise) is a spring gushing forth.\nThen this word began to be used for everything that flows or moves over vast distances or for extended periods. Thus, its usage became common in both temporal and spatial contexts. For instance, its usage for the movement of winds or the motion of the moon and sun is found in the Quran. Then its usage also occurs in a spiritual sense. For example, Sunnah al-Jariyah (the enduring Sunnah) is a well-known term.","«جَرٰی» means to flow or move over a long distance or for a long time.","to flow","جری","2:25-2:164-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:85-5:119-6:6-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-10:22-11:42-13:2-13:35-14:23-14:32-16:31-18:31-20:76-21:81-22:14-22:23-22:65-25:10-29:58-30:46-31:29-31:31-35:13-36:38-38:36-39:5-39:20-43:51-45:12-47:12-48:5-48:17-51:3-54:14-55:50-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-69:11-85:11-88:12-98:8",60
567,116,"E","العُذْر","«اَلْعُذْر» means to present a reason in order to dismiss an accusation. According to Imam Raghb, such an effort by which a person seeks to erase his sins is «عَذَرَ», whose meaning is to accept an excuse; «عَذَّرَ» means a minor pretext or stating a false, flimsy reason; and «اِعْتَذَرَ» means to present an excuse. Now, this excuse also has three types: the first type is «فِتْنَۃٌ».","«العُذْر» is employed to offer a justification for dismissing an accusation, and «مَعْذِرَۃٌ» is used to concoct a false pretext.","excuse","العذر","7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6",6
568,116,"P","فِتْنَۃٌ","«فِتْنَۃٌ» means that a person, by resorting to falsehood, denies that very accusation or sin. For this, the Quran has employed the word «فِتْنَۃٌ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ لَمۡ تَکُنۡ فِتۡنَتُہُمۡ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ قَالُوۡا وَاللّٰہِ رَبِّنَا مَا کُنَّا مُشۡرِکِیۡنَ» (6:23)\nTranslation: Then the outcome of their polytheism will be nothing but that they will say, By Allah, we were not polytheists.\n\nThe word 'fitnah' is also used for the purpose of testing, examining, and scrutinizing someone.","«فِتْنَۃٌ» A person, by resorting to falsehood, denies the accusation or even the sin.","Pretext","فتنۃ","6:23",1
569,116,"E","عُذْر","«عُذْر» A person may attempt to absolve himself of blame by presenting a false reason or a lie. Therefore, the Quran has employed the term «عَذَّرَ».  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ جَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ» (9/90)  \nTranslation: And some of the desert dwellers came to you, making excuses, seeking permission to be exempted (from Jihad).  \n\nIt is also possible that the excuse itself is originally valid and reasonable. For this, the words «عُذْر» and «مَعْذِرَۃٌ» appear in the Quran.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَاِذۡ قَالَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ لِمَ تَعِظُوۡنَ قَوۡمَۨا ۙ اللّٰہُ مُہۡلِکُہُمۡ اَوۡ مُعَذِّبُہُمۡ عَذَابًا شَدِیۡدًا ؕ قَالُوۡا مَعۡذِرَۃً اِلٰی رَبِّکُمۡ  وَلَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (7/164)  \nTranslation: And when a group among them said, Why do you advise a people whom Allah is [about] to destroy or to punish with a severe punishment? They said, To be free from blame before your Lord and perhaps they may fear Him.","To present an excuse for not doing a task, even if the excuse is true or false.","excuse","عذر","7:164-9:90-18:76-30:57-40:52-77:6",6
570,117,"C","بُھْتَان","The meaning of «بَھَتَ» is to be astonished and bewildered (intransitive), or to become silent and stunned due to surprise (transitive). And «بُھْتَان» is used for a matter which, when heard, causes people to lose their senses, leaving them astonished and dumbfounded, and they cannot believe that such a thing is even possible.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ قُلۡتُمۡ مَّا یَکُوۡنُ لَنَاۤ اَنۡ نَّتَکَلَّمَ بِہٰذَا ٭ۖ سُبۡحٰنَکَ ہٰذَا بُہۡتَانٌ عَظِیۡمٌ» (24/16)\n\nTranslation: And why did you not, when you heard it, say, 'It is not for us to utter such a thing. Exalted are You! This is a great slander.'","An accusation that throws people into a state of bewildered amazement.","Calumny","بھتان","2:258-4:20-4:112-4:156-21:40-24:16-33:58-60:12",8
571,117,"B","اِفْک","«اَفَکَ» means to turn something away from its correct direction (sing.).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَاۡفِکَنَا عَنۡ اٰلِہَتِنَا» (46/22)\nTranslation: They (the people of 'Ad) said, Have you come to turn us away from our gods?\nSimilarly, turning from truth to falsehood, or from truth to lies, or from good deeds to bad deeds is called «اِفْک». In the same sense, fabrication, false speech, and accusation are also termed «اِفْک». And «اَفَّاک», meaning false and fabricated speech, is used for one who fabricates and accuses. According to Abu Hala al-Askari, «اِفْک» is a lie connected to «فَاحِشَ اَلْقُبْح».\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَوۡلَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَالۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّقَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ اِفۡکٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (24/12)\nTranslation: When you heard it, why did the believing men and women not think good in their hearts and say, This is a clear fabrication?\nIt is as if the essence of «اِفْک» is that it is based on baseless talk and is such a great falsehood that it astounds sound intellect—it was indeed a calumny.","«اِفْک» Baseless accusations that twist the real issue into a fabricated story.","Baseless accusation","افک","7:17-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9",12
572,117,"F","اِفْتَرٰی","The meaning of «فَرِيْ» is to cut leather for sewing and repairing, and «اِفْتِرَاء» means to cut it for corrupting (singular). «فَرَیَ یَفْرِیُ» means to join a storm (as in Al-Munjid), and the word «اِفْتَرٰی» is used for both reform and corruption, but its usage is predominantly in the sense of corruption (singular). In the Quran, this word is employed in contexts of falsehood, shirk, and injustice. Moreover, «اِفْتِرَآءً» generally refers to fabricated beliefs that are artificially created and attributed to Allah.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنِ افۡتَرٰی عَلَی اللّٰہِ کَذِبًا» (6/93). Translation: And who is more unjust than he who invents a lie against Allah?\n\nAnd «فَرِیًّا» means to attribute a lie and false statement to someone (as in Al-Munjid).\n\nFor instance, the divine declaration is: «قَالُوۡا یٰمَرۡیَمُ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتِ  شَیۡئًا فَرِیًّا» (19/27). Translation: They said, 'O Mary! You have certainly committed a great sin.' (Tafheem ul Quran)","To fabricate a false creed and attribute it to Allah, or to hold a belief that foments corruption instead of reform.","false accusation","افتری","3:24-3:94-4:48-4:50-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:112-6:137-6:138-6:140-6:144-7:37-7:53-7:89-7:152-10:17-10:30-10:37-10:38-10:59-10:60-10:69-11:13-11:18-11:21-11:35-11:50-12:111-16:56-16:87-16:101-16:105-16:116-17:73-18:15-19:27-20:61-21:5-23:38-25:4-28:36-28:75-29:13-29:68-32:3-34:8-34:43-42:24-46:8-46:28-60:12-61:7",54
573,118,"T","ضَلَّ","The meaning of «ضَلّ» is that a thing is wasted and goes to the benefit of another (i.e., the purpose for which an action is performed does not yield the intended result, or one deviates from the correct path).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ ضَلَّ سَعۡیُہُمۡ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ یُحۡسِنُوۡنَ صُنۡعًا» (18:104)\nTranslation: Those are the ones whose efforts have been wasted in this world while they thought that they were acquiring good.\n\nFurthermore, the Divine Command states:\n«اَلَمۡ یَجۡعَلۡ کَیۡدَہُمۡ فِیۡ  تَضۡلِیۡلٍ» (2:105)\nTranslation: Or have their plans gone astray?\n\nAnd this deviation can be intentional (i.e., with knowledge and will) or involuntary (out of compulsion). If it is involuntary, meaning due to a lapse of control (forgetfulness), then its meaning would be 'to forget'—i.e., to forget a matter, an event, or a part of it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ لَّمۡ یَکُوۡنَا رَجُلَیۡنِ فَرَجُلٌ وَّامۡرَاَتٰنِ مِمَّنۡ تَرۡضَوۡنَ مِنَ الشُّہَدَآءِ اَنۡ تَضِلَّ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا فَتُذَکِّرَ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا الۡاُخۡرٰی» (2:282)\nTranslation: And if there are not two men [available], then a man and two women from those whom you accept as witnesses—so that if one of the women errs, then the other can remind her.\n\nIn this sense, the opposite of «ضَلَال» or «ضَلَالَۃٌ» can also be 'truth'.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَمَا ذَا بَعۡدَ الۡحَقِّ  اِلَّا الضَّلٰلُ» (10:32)\nTranslation: So is it other than the way of Allah they desire while to Him have submitted all those within the heavens and earth, willingly or by compulsion, and to Him they will be returned?\n\nAnd its opposite can also be 'guidance'.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ وَجَدَکَ ضَآلًّا فَہَدٰی» (93:7)\nTranslation: And He found you lost and guided [you].","«ضَلّ» straying from the straight path, whether by error or by design.","to laugh","ضل","1:7-2:16-2:26-2:108-2:175-2:198-2:282-3:69-3:90-3:164-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:113-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:143-4:167-4:176-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:105-6:24-6:39-6:56-6:74-6:77-6:94-6:116-6:117-6:119-6:125-6:140-6:144-7:30-7:37-7:38-7:53-7:60-7:61-7:149-7:155-7:178-7:179-7:186-9:37-9:115-10:30-10:32-10:88-10:108-11:21-12:8-12:30-12:95-13:14-13:27-13:33-14:3-14:18-14:27-14:30-14:36-15:56-16:25-16:36-16:37-16:87-16:93-16:125-17:15-17:67-17:72-17:97-18:17-18:51-18:104-19:38-19:75-20:52-20:79-20:85-20:92-20:123-21:54-22:4-22:9-22:12-23:106-25:17-25:29-25:34-25:42-25:44-26:20-26:86-26:97-26:99-27:81-27:92-28:15-28:50-28:75-28:85-30:29-30:53-31:6-31:11-32:10-33:36-33:67-34:8-34:24-34:50-35:8-36:24-36:47-36:62-37:69-37:71-38:26-39:8-39:22-39:23-39:36-39:37-39:41-40:25-40:33-40:34-40:50-40:74-41:29-41:48-41:52-42:18-42:44-42:46-43:40-45:23-46:5-46:28-46:32-50:27-53:2-53:30-54:24-54:47-56:51-56:92-60:1-62:2-67:9-67:29-68:7-68:26-71:24-71:27-74:31-83:32-93:7",163
574,118,"T","غَوٰی","The meaning of «غَوٰی» is to become entangled in a wrong action due to ignorance (m.r.) and then to become hopeless from the right path (m.r.), and its usage is only in religious matters. (Faqih 177)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَعَصٰۤی اٰدَمُ رَبَّہٗ فَغَوٰی» (20:121)\nTranslation: And (thus) Adam turned away from his Lord's command, and went astray.\n\nThe opposite of «اورغیّ» is «رُشْد». It means to proceed on the straight path and adopt righteous conduct. And 'Rashid' means guided.\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2:256)\nTranslation: Guidance is clearly distinct from misguidance.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«مَا ضَلَّ صَاحِبُکُمۡ وَمَا غَوٰی» (53:2)\nTranslation: Your companion (Muhammad ﷺ) has neither strayed nor gone astray.","«غَوٰی» due to ignorance, one gets entangled in a wrongful act.","to go astray","غوی","2:256-7:16-7:146-7:202-11:34-15:39-19:59-20:121-28:18-28:63-37:32-38:82-53:2",13
575,118,"T","تَاہَ","Such a vast, barren plain is called «تَاہَ ، تِیْہ ، تِیْھَاء», where a traveler becomes lost. And the meaning of «تَاہَ» is to wander in a state of confusion and disorientation (as in the dictionary).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ فَاِنَّہَا مُحَرَّمَۃٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً ۚ یَتِیۡہُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/26)\nTranslation: Allah said that the land has been forbidden to them for forty years, during which they will wander lost in the wilderness of the earth.","«تَاہَ» refers to a sandy plain in which a wanderer can get lost.","to go astray","تاہ","5:26",1
576,119,"T","فَرَّ","«فَرَّ» generally means to flee, either for a suspect or to escape from some kind of fear or danger. «فَرَّمِنَ الْحَرْبِ فِرَارًا» means to leave the battlefield or to escape from fighting. And «مَفَرّ» refers to a place where one can flee to take refuge. A fugitive is a suspect who has fled.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡفَعَکُمُ الۡفِرَارُ اِنۡ فَرَرۡتُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمَوۡتِ اَوِالۡقَتۡلِ وَاِذًا لَّا تُمَتَّعُوۡنَ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» ( 33/16 )\nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], If you should die or be killed, your fleeing will not benefit you in the least, and you will not be recompensed except for what you used to do.\n\nFurthermore, this word also comes in the meaning of racing swiftly. «اَلْفَرَّار» refers to one who races swiftly. And «مَفَرٌ مِّنَ الْخَیْل» refers to that swift-racing horse which is employed when fleeing (in battle). This word has also been used in the Noble Quran in these meanings.\n\nThe Divine Command states:\n«فَفِرُّوۡۤا اِلَی اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنِّیۡ لَکُمۡ  مِّنۡہُ نَذِیۡرٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» ( 51/50 )\nTranslation: So flee to Allah. Indeed, I am, to you, a clear warner from Him.\n\nIn this verse, both of the aforementioned meanings are found.","«فَرَّ» the escape of a culprit","to run","فر","18:18-26:21-33:13-33:16-51:50-62:8-71:6-74:51-75:10-80:34",10
577,119,"T","اَبَق","The word «اَبَق» is specifically used for a slave fleeing from his master's household, especially when there is no danger from the master toward him (cf. Maf. Manjd). Moreover, this word is also employed to denote choosing the path of evasion from one's responsibilities.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَاِنَّ یُوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ اِذۡاَبَقَ اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37:140)\n\nTranslation: And Jonah (peace be upon him) was also among the messengers when he fled and boarded a fully laden ship.\n\nIn this verse, the word «اَبَقَ» conveys all these meanings.","«اَبَق» fleeing from one's master or escaping from responsibilities.","to run","ابق","37:140",1
578,119,"T","زَھَقَ","«زَھَقَ» means to flee after being defeated. (M. R)  \n«زَھَقَتْ نَفْسُہٗ» means its soul departed. This word is from the category of 'addad' (words with opposite meanings).  \n«زَاهِقُ» means both very fat and also very thin and weak (manjad). Therefore,  \n«اَزْھَقَ» refers to something fleeing after being defeated, or becoming weak and emaciated.  \n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَقُلۡ جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ زَہَقَ الۡبَاطِلُ ؕ اِنَّ الۡبَاطِلَ کَانَ زَہُوۡقًا» (17/81)  \n\nTranslation: And say, Truth has come, and falsehood has vanished. Indeed, falsehood is bound to vanish. (Jalandhari ra)  \nAnd say, Has the truth come forth and the falsehood fled? Indeed, falsehood is bound to flee. (Osmani ra)  \n\nNote: (Lughat-i-Iaddad refers to words that have two separate meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«زَھَقَ» to flee weakened and defeated.","to run","زھق","17:81",1
579,119,"T","ھَرْبَ","«ھَرْبَ» refers to fleeing due to the risk of being caught oneself (as in a thief running when discovered during theft or stealing and taking away the goods). It is also used in the meanings of tax evasion («تَھْرِیْب») and smuggling («مُھَرِّبْ») (New Dictionary). For example: In the Quran it says: «وَّاَنَّا ظَنَنَّاۤ اَنۡ لَّنۡ نُّعۡجِزَاللّٰہَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَلَنۡ نُّعۡجِزَہٗ ہَرَبًا» (72/12). Translation: And that we have believed that we cannot escape God in the land, wherever we may be, nor can we weary Him by fleeing.","«ھَرْبَ» Fleeing the scene of the crime in such a manner as to avoid apprehension.","to run","ھرب","72:12",1
580,119,"T","اِسْتَنْفَرَ","The meaning of «نَفَرَ» is to go out for war, etc., and «اِسْتَنْفَرَ» refers to fleeing from something in terror. (m.f.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ حُمُرٌ مُّسۡتَنۡفِرَۃٌ فَرَّتۡ مِنۡ قَسۡوَرَۃٍ» (74/50,51)\n\nTranslation: As if they were donkeys that flee in terror from a lion.","«اِسْتَنْفَرَ» to flee in terror.","to run","استنفر","4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-74:50",7
581,119,"T","شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر","«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر» means a camel bolted and fled. And «شَرَّدَ» means to do such a deed that others do not do the like thereof (mufradat), and also means to scold, frighten, and drive away (mujam). Its meaning is, as it were, to treat someone in an exemplary manner so that others are driven away by it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِمَّا تَثۡقَفَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡحَرۡبِ فَشَرِّدۡ بِہِمۡ مَّنۡ خَلۡفَہُمۡ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَذَّکَّرُوۡنَ» (8:57)\nTranslation: So if you encounter them in battle, inflict upon them such a punishment that those behind them may take warning.","«شَرَّدَ الْبَعِیْر» A punishment so exemplary that others flee from it.","to run","شرد البعیر","8:57",1
582,120,"B","اِخوَۃٌ","«اِخوَۃٌ» means siblings. It is used to denote familial relations and includes all brothers and sisters (as cited in references like Al-Munjid and Mufradat). For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ کَانَ لَہٗۤ  اِخۡوَۃٌ» (4:11). The translation is: If the deceased also has brothers. However, in this verse, the term «اِخْوَۃٌ» applies to both brothers and sisters.","«اِخوَۃٌ» is used for both brother and sister.","Brother","اخوۃ","4:11-4:23-4:176-12:5-12:7-12:8-12:58-12:69-12:100-20:42-24:31-24:61-33:55-49:10",14
583,120,"B","اِخْوَانٌ","The word «اِخْوَانٌ» conveys the meaning of sincerity, friendship, and brotherhood.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ رَبَّنَا اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَلِاِخۡوَانِنَا الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59:10)  \nTranslation: And pray, 'O our Lord, forgive us and our brothers who preceded us in faith...'  \nAnd the divine command of Allah Most High is:  \n«اِنَّمَا الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ اِخۡوَۃٌ» (49:10)  \nTranslation: The believers are but brothers...  \nThis verse points to the fact that believers should not merely be connected by sincerity and friendship, but should regard one another with the bond of kinship brotherhood.","«اِخْوَانٌ» refers to brotherly relations and friendship.","Brother","اخوان","2:220-3:103-3:156-3:168-6:87-7:202-9:11-9:23-9:24-15:47-17:27-26:106-26:124-26:142-26:161-33:5-33:18-50:13-58:22-59:10-59:11",21
584,121,"T","مَلَاَ","The meaning of «مَلَاَ الاِنَاءَ» is to fill a vessel, and «مِلْءُ» is that quantity of something with which a vessel is filled (m ł manj).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَنۡ یُّقۡبَلَ مِنۡ اَحَدِہِمۡ مِّلۡءُ الۡاَرۡضِ ذَہَبًا وَّلَوِ افۡتَدٰی بِہٖ» (3:91)\nTranslation: (Even if) a disbeliever were to give gold filling the earth in exchange [for salvation], it would never be accepted.\n\nAnd «اِمْتَلَأَ» means the filling of something.\n\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«یَوۡمَ نَقُوۡلُ لِجَہَنَّمَ ہَلِ امۡتَلَاۡتِ وَ تَقُوۡلُ ہَلۡ مِنۡ مَّزِیۡدٍ» (50:30)\nTranslation: On that Day We will ask Hell, 'Have you been filled?' And it will reply, 'Is there any more?'","«مَلَاَ» to fill a vessel.","to fill","ملا","3:91-7:18-11:119-32:13-38:85-50:30",6
585,121,"T","دَھَقَ","«دَھَقَ» is used to fill a cup with some drink (F 65).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ مَفَازًا ، حَدَآئِقَ وَ اَعۡنَابًا ، وَّکَوَاعِبَ اَتۡرَابًا ، وَّ کَاۡسًا دِہَاقًا» (78/31,32,33,34)\nTranslation: Indeed, for the righteous is success—(namely) gardens and grapevines and companions of equal age, and overflowing cups.","«دَھَقَ» the filling of a cup with a beverage.","to fulfill","دھق","78:34",1
586,121,"T","شَحْنُ","«شَحْنُ» To fill a ship or boat with passengers and cargo (F L 69)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ اَبَقَ اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37/140)\nTranslation: When he (Prophet Yunus) reached the already fully laden ship as he fled.","«شَحْنُ» is used for cargo ships.","to fill","شحن","26:119-36:41-37:140",3
587,122,"H","جُوْع","«جُوْع» means the arising of the desire to eat and this is the initial stage of hunger (F L 161), and its opposite is «شَبَعَ» (being satisfied after eating). (M. L)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡۤ اَطۡعَمَہُمۡ مِّنۡ جُوۡعٍ ۬ ۙ وَّاٰمَنَہُمۡ مِّنۡ خَوۡفٍ» (106/4)\nTranslation: He who fed them from hunger and granted them security.","«جُوْع» The state in which a human feels the urge to eat, i.e., the state of hunger.","Hunger","جوع","2:155-16:112-20:118-88:7-106:4",5
588,122,"H","مَسْغَبَۃ","«سَغَبَ» means to be hungry, and «اَسْغَبَ» means a nation being afflicted with famine, and «سَغَابُ» is what hunger is called. And this is the second degree of hunger (p. 161).\nFor example: It is stated in the Quran:\n«اَوۡ اِطۡعٰمٌ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ ذِیۡ مَسۡغَبَۃٍ» (90/14)\nTranslation: Or feeding on a day of hunger.","The era of famine.","Hunger","مسغبۃ","90:14",1
589,122,"H","مَخْمَصَۃ","«خَمَصَہُ الْجُوْع» meaning to make someone's stomach lean due to hunger, and «مَخْمَصَۃ» meaning the emptiness of the stomach from eating. (Manjad) To become lean and weak due to lack of food and excessive labor, and the stomach sinking in (R. L). And this is the third degree of hunger (Fal 161).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ فِیۡ مَخۡمَصَۃٍ غَیۡرَ مُتَجَانِفٍ لِّاِثۡمٍ ۙ فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ غَفُوۡرٌرَّحِیۡمٌ» (5/3)\n\nTranslation: Yes, whoever is compelled by hunger (provided he is not inclined to sin) – then Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.","«مَخْمَصَۃ» being thin-bellied due to lack of food.","Hunger","مخمصۃ","5:3-9:120",2
590,122,"H","خَصَاصَۃ","«خَصَّ» means to be needy and destitute, and «خَصَاصَۃً» is a source/verb form, while «خُصَاصَۃ» comes in the meanings of 'little' and 'scarce' (as in the lexicon) — i.e., to reach the point of starvation due to destitution and need.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ یُؤۡثِرُوۡنَ عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ وَلَوۡ کَانَ بِہِمۡ خَصَاصَۃٌ» ( 59/9 )  \nTranslation: And they give preference to themselves, even if a state of poverty is prevailing over them.","«خَصَاصَۃ» to be reduced to starvation due to poverty and destitution.","Hunger","خصاصۃ","59:9",1
591,123,"T","نَسِیَ","The term بھولنا is general for forgetting, whether due to negligence, lack of self-control, or other reasons, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ضَرَبَ لَنَا مَثَلًا وَّ نَسِیَ خَلۡقَہٗ» (36:78)\nTranslation: And he began to cite examples for us, and forgot his own creation.\n\nAnd «اَنْسٰی» means to cause someone else to forget something.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَنۡسٰہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ ذِکۡرَ رَبِّہٖ» (12:42)\nTranslation: But Satan made him forget the mention of his master.","«نَسِیَ», meaning 'to forget', is commonly used, whatever the reason may be.","to forget","نسی","2:106-2:286-6:68-7:51-9:67-12:42-18:24-18:57-18:61-18:63-18:73-19:23-19:64-20:52-20:88-20:115-20:126-32:14-36:78-39:8-45:34-58:19-59:19-87:6",24
592,123,"T","سَھَا ( سَھْوًا )","«سَھَا» means distraction from an action due to negligence. The original meaning is that attention turns away from the primary task and shifts to something else. And «سَاھِی» means heedless and forgetful (not remembering) (M. R.). Sajdah-e-Sahu is a famous term. It means one intended to do a particular action but, due to forgetfulness, performed a different one.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ فِیۡ غَمۡرَۃٍ سَاہُوۡنَ» ( 51/11 )\nTranslation: Those who are oblivious in their heedlessness.","To forget due to negligence. Turning one's attention away and engaging in another activity instead of the primary task.","to forget","سھا ( سھوًا )","51:11-107:5",2
593,123,"T","ضَلَّ","«ضَلّ» Failure to retain (forgetting) something, an event, or a part of it due to a lapse in mindfulness or self-restraint.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَنۡ تَضِلَّ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا فَتُذَکِّرَ اِحۡدٰىہُمَا الۡاُخۡرٰی» (2/282)\nTranslation: If one of them (the two women) forgets, then the other should remind her.","«ضَلّ» meaning forgetting due to abandonment of retention (not remembering).","to forget","ضل","1:7-2:16-2:26-2:108-2:175-2:198-2:282-3:69-3:90-3:164-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:113-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:143-4:167-4:176-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:105-6:24-6:39-6:56-6:74-6:77-6:94-6:116-6:117-6:119-6:125-6:140-6:144-7:30-7:37-7:38-7:53-7:60-7:61-7:149-7:155-7:178-7:179-7:186-9:37-9:115-10:30-10:32-10:88-10:108-11:21-12:8-12:30-12:95-13:14-13:27-13:33-14:3-14:18-14:27-14:30-14:36-15:56-16:25-16:36-16:37-16:87-16:93-16:125-17:15-17:67-17:72-17:97-18:17-18:51-18:104-19:38-19:75-20:52-20:79-20:85-20:92-20:123-21:54-22:4-22:9-22:12-23:106-25:17-25:29-25:34-25:42-25:44-26:20-26:86-26:97-26:99-27:81-27:92-28:15-28:50-28:75-28:85-30:29-30:53-31:6-31:11-32:10-33:36-33:67-34:8-34:24-34:50-35:8-36:24-36:47-36:62-37:69-37:71-38:26-39:8-39:22-39:23-39:36-39:37-39:41-40:25-40:33-40:34-40:50-40:74-41:29-41:48-41:52-42:18-42:44-42:46-43:40-45:23-46:5-46:28-46:32-50:27-53:2-53:30-54:24-54:47-56:51-56:92-60:1-62:2-67:9-67:29-68:7-68:26-71:24-71:27-74:31-83:32-93:7",163
594,123,"T","ذَھَل","When the cause of forgetfulness is terror or such preoccupation that leads to grief and distress, it is termed «ذَھُوْل» (detailed). The meanings of «ذَھَلَ ، ذَھُوْلًا» are to be negligent, to forget, and «ذَھِلَ ذَھُوْلًا» means to be bewildered, astonished (source: Munjid). For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ تَرَوۡنَہَا تَذۡہَلُ کُلُّ مُرۡضِعَۃٍ عَمَّاۤ اَرۡضَعَتۡ وَتَضَعُ کُلُّ ذَاتِ حَمۡلٍ حَمۡلَہَا وَ تَرَی النَّاسَ سُکٰرٰی وَ مَا ہُمۡ بِسُکٰرٰی» (22:2). Translation: On the Day when you will see the earthquake of the Hour, every nursing mother will neglect her child, and every pregnant woman will miscarry, and you will see people as if they are drunk, while they are not drunk.","«ذَھَل» meaning to forget due to terror and distress.","to forget","ذھل","22:2",1
595,124,"T","شَوٰی","«شَوٰی» meaning to roast meat etc. in fire (as in the Quran).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَاِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ» (18/29)  \nTranslation: And if they cry out for help, they will be given water like molten brass, which will scald their faces.","«شَوٰی» meaning to roast and cook meat and the like over fire.","to roast","شوی","18:29-70:16",2
596,124,"T","حَنَذَ","«اَلْحَنَذَۃٌ» means severe heat, and «حَنِیْذ» also means hot water and roasted meat. And «حَنَذَتْہُ الشَّمْس» means to scorch someone with the sun. (Munjid) The original meaning of «حَنَذَ» is to expel dampness and moisture (i.e., wetness and humidity) through any source of heat. (Ma‘)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَا لَبِثَ اَنۡ جَآءَ بِعِجۡلٍ حَنِیۡذٍ» (11:69)\nTranslation: Not much time had passed when Ibrahim (AS) brought a roasted calf.","«حَنَذَ» meaning severe heat.","to roast","حنذ","11:69",1
597,125,"T","اَرْسَلَ","«اَرْسَلَ» means to send someone a message, letter (note), or command. (Manjidd) and «رَسُول» means a messenger or one who delivers a message, who can be from among humans or from among the angels.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَرۡجِہۡ وَاَخَاہُ وَاَرۡسِلۡ فِی الۡمَدَآئِنِ حٰشِرِیۡنَ» (7/111)\nTranslation: The courtiers of Pharaoh said to him, Delay the matter of Moses and his brother for a while, and send heralds to the cities.","«اَرْسَلَ» meaning to send a message to someone.","to send","ارسل","2:119-2:151-4:64-4:79-4:80-5:70-6:6-6:42-6:48-6:61-7:6-7:57-7:59-7:75-7:87-7:94-7:105-7:111-7:133-7:134-7:162-9:33-11:25-11:52-11:57-11:70-11:96-12:12-12:19-12:31-12:45-12:63-12:66-12:109-13:13-13:30-13:38-14:4-14:5-14:9-15:10-15:22-15:58-16:43-16:63-17:54-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:77-17:105-18:40-18:56-19:17-19:83-20:47-20:134-21:5-21:7-21:25-21:107-22:52-23:23-23:32-23:44-23:45-25:20-25:48-25:56-26:13-26:17-26:27-26:53-27:35-27:45-27:63-28:34-28:47-29:14-29:40-30:46-30:47-30:48-30:51-33:9-33:45-34:16-34:28-34:34-34:44-35:2-35:9-35:24-36:14-36:16-37:72-37:147-39:42-40:23-40:70-40:78-41:14-41:16-42:48-42:51-43:6-43:23-43:24-43:45-43:46-46:23-48:8-48:28-51:32-51:33-51:38-51:41-54:19-54:27-54:31-54:34-55:35-57:25-57:26-61:9-67:17-71:1-71:11-73:15-83:33-105:3",131
598,125,"T","بَعَثَ","«بَعَثَ» basically has two meanings: (1) to raise, to lift, and (2) to send alone. Then sometimes it is taken to have a single meaning. For example, in «بَعَثْتُ الْبَعِیْر» I lifted the camel and set it free. And when it is in the meaning of 'to send', it would mean to send for the completion of a purpose or mission.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: And Allah sent a crow who began to scrape the earth.\n\nAt another place, the command of the Almighty is:\n«ہُوَالَّذِیۡ بَعَثَ فِی الۡاُمِّیّٖنَ رَسُوۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ یَتۡلُوۡاعَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ وَیُزَکِّیۡہِمۡ» (62/2)\nTranslation: He it is Who has sent among the unlettered ones a Messenger from among themselves, who recites to them His verses and purifies them.","«بَعَثَ» means to send someone alone for the completion of a specific purpose.","to send","بعث","2:56-2:129-2:213-2:246-2:247-2:259-3:164-4:35-5:12-5:31-6:36-6:60-6:65-7:14-7:103-7:167-10:74-10:75-15:36-16:21-16:36-16:38-16:84-16:89-17:5-17:15-17:79-17:94-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-25:41-25:51-26:36-26:87-27:65-28:59-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-40:34-58:6-58:18-62:2-64:7-72:7-91:12",54
599,126,"C","وَصَفَ","The meaning of «وَصَفَ» is to describe the state or condition of someone (lit. to portray). To describe the form and definition of a thing, whether correct or incorrect; to depict. (fig.)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «قَالَ بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا ؕ فَصَبۡرٌ جَمِیۡلٌ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ الۡمُسۡتَعَانُ عَلٰی مَا تَصِفُوۡنَ» (12/18). Translation: Jacob (peace be upon him) said, No, rather you have invented this story from your own hearts. Patience is indeed best, and it is Allah from whom help is sought against what you describe.","«وَصَفَ» means to describe the circumstances of something.","Clear Exposition","وصف","6:100-6:139-12:18-12:77-16:62-16:116-21:18-21:22-21:112-23:91-23:96-37:159-37:180-43:82",14
600,126,"S","قَصَّ","The meaning of «قَصَّ» is to walk upon someone's footprints (mufradat).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated::\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18/64)\nTranslation: So they both returned while looking at their footprints.\nFrom this, «قَصَّ» also means to follow gradually, i.e., step by step (manjad), meaning to relate a matter or event that has been passed down through generations.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated::\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ بِمَاۤ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ» (12/3)\nTranslation: (O Prophet ﷺ) We relate to you an excellent story through this Quran which We have revealed to you.\nThen the application of this word also began to be used for relating general events and stories.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated::\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَہٗ وَقَصَّ عَلَیۡہِ الۡقَصَصَ ۙ قَالَ لَا تَخَفۡ ٝ۟ نَجَوۡتَ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (28/25)\nTranslation: When Moses came to Shuaib and related his event to him, he said, Do not fear; you have escaped from the wrongdoing people.","«قَصَّ» meaning to narrate any story or incident.","Statement","قص","3:62-4:164-6:57-6:130-7:7-7:35-7:101-7:176-11:100-11:120-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:13-18:64-20:99-27:76-28:25-40:78",20
601,126,"C","ضَرَبَ","«مَثَلًا» To state something in such a way that another matter becomes comprehensible. (Meaning) To present a parable or example. «ضَرْبُ الْمِثْل» is a well-known term.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:  \n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا» (2/26)  \nTranslation: Allah does not feel ashamed to set forth an example of a mosquito or something greater than it (for instance, a fly, a spider, etc.).","«ضَرَبَ ، مَثَلًا » means to state an example or proverb.","Clear statement","ضرب","2:26-13:17-14:24-14:25-14:45-16:74-16:75-16:76-16:112-17:48-18:32-18:45-22:73-24:35-25:9-25:39-29:43-30:28-30:58-36:13-36:78-39:27-39:29-43:17-43:57-43:58-47:3-59:21-66:10-66:11",30
602,126,"S","حَدَّثَ","The meaning of «حَدَثَ» is the coming into existence of something that was not previously present (m. l.), and «حَدَّثَ» means conveying a matter or news that ordinary people are unaware of.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَقَالَ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مَا لَہَا ، یَوۡمَئِذٍ تُحَدِّثُ اَخۡبَارَہَا» (99:3-4)\nTranslation: And man will say, What has happened to this earth? On that Day, it will recount its news.","meaning to state something in such a way that ordinary people remain unaware.","Statement","حدث","2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4",8
603,126,"S","بَیّن","«بَیَّنَ» is used in the meaning of eloquent speech (manjad) and «بَیِِّنَۃ» means evidence and proof. And «بَیَّنَ» implies presenting something with evidence. According to Ibn al-Faris, three fundamental elements are found in «بَیَّنْ»: (1) separation (iftiraq), (2) distance (bu'd), and (3) clarity (wuduh). That is, for something to be distinct and clear from another (m. l).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَذٰلِکَ یُبَیِّنُ اللّٰہُ اٰیٰتِہٖ لِلنَّاسِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/187)\nTranslation: Thus does Allah make clear His verses to the people so that they may become cautious. (Uthmaniؒ)\n\nAnd «تَبَیَّنَ» comes in the meanings of being clear and being separate/distinct.\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2/256)\nTranslation: Indeed, the path of guidance has become clearly distinct from the path of error.","«بَیَّنَ» to explain something with evidence.","Statement","بین","2:68-2:69-2:70-2:118-2:159-2:160-2:187-2:219-2:221-2:230-2:242-2:266-3:103-3:118-3:187-4:26-4:176-5:15-5:19-5:75-5:89-6:105-9:115-14:4-16:39-16:44-16:64-16:92-18:15-22:5-24:18-24:58-24:59-24:61-43:63-57:17",36
604,126,"S","صَرَّف","«صَرَّفَ» means to change something from one state to another, and «صَرَّفَ» also means to reiterate and explain a matter (i.e., to elucidate a subject by presenting it in various ways and highlighting its different aspects).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡفَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ» (6/65)\nTranslation: Observe how We present Our verses in diverse manners so that they may understand.","«صَرَّفَ» meaning to shed light on the different aspects of a matter.","Statement","صرف","3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29",26
605,126,"D","فَصَلَ","The meaning of «فَصَلَ» is that one thing is completely separate from another such that there is a distance between them, and the meaning of «فَصَّلَ» is to explain a matter by separating it into parts and presenting it in an ordered manner.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«وَکُلَّ شَیۡءٍ فَصَّلۡنٰہُ تَفۡصِیۡلًا» (17/12)\nTranslation: And We have detailed everything completely.","«فَصَلَ» means to state things in an organized and separate manner.","Declaration","فصل","2:249-6:55-6:97-6:98-6:114-6:119-6:126-7:32-7:52-7:133-7:174-9:11-10:5-10:24-11:1-12:94-13:2-17:12-22:17-30:28-32:25-37:21-38:20-41:3-41:44-42:21-44:40-60:3-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17-86:13",33
606,126,"S","فَسَّرَ","«اَلْفَسَر» means to explain the spiritual attribute of something (مف). Also, «فَسَرَ» means to clarify and explain the intended meaning. And «فَسَّرَ» means to remove the veil from something (م ۔ ل ۔ منجد), and this is generally done with two words. The word «اَیْ» clarifies the ambiguous (i.e., that matter whose meaning is not clear and is not understood), and the word «اَوْ» explains the meaning and intention. It also means to explain each word of a sentence individually while considering the context of revelation (فق ل 43).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says: «وَلَا یَاۡتُوۡنَکَ بِمَثَلٍ اِلَّا جِئۡنٰکَ بِالۡحَقِّ وَاَحۡسَنَ  تَفۡسِیۡرًا» (25/33). Translation: And whenever they bring you any unusual matter, We grant you the precise answer and a more detailed explanation.","«فَسَّرَ» Explanation of ambiguous and difficult passages.","Statement","فسر","25:33",1
607,127,"M","وَلَدُ","«وَلَدُ» is the term used for every child born to a mother. All three words are used for both masculine and feminine genders. Etymologically, the feminine form of «وَلِیْد» is «وَلِیْدَۃ». However, the word «وَلِیْدَۃ» does not appear in the Quran. If there is any difference among these three terms, it is that the word «وَلَدُ» is used for a person of any age. An elderly man is also his father's or mother's «وَلَدُ» just as he was at birth. And the word «وَلِیْد» is used from birth until before puberty.\n\nFor example: The Quran states that Pharaoh, addressing Moses (peace be upon him), said:\n«اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا» (26:18)\nTranslation: Did we not nurture you as a child among us?\n\nGenerally, the relation of مَوْلُوْد («مولود») is attributed to the father; attribution to the mother is less common. And «مولود» comes in the meanings of 'son.' Its application is also generally for a young child (as in 'manjad'), though it can also apply to an adult.\n\nAs the sublime declaration of Allah states:\n«وَلَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ ہُوَ جَازٍعَنۡ وَّالِدِہٖ شَیۡئًا» (31:33)\nTranslation: And a son will not benefit his father at all.","«وَلَدُ» the literal meaning is 'boy'.","My son","ولد","2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:15-19:33-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-56:17-58:2-71:21-72:3-73:17-76:19-90:3-112:3",40
608,127,"S","اِبْن ، بِنْت","«اِبْن» means son and its plural is «اَبْنَاء», while «بَنُوْن» is its diminutive form «بَنِی». And «بِنْت» means daughter, its plural is «بَنَات», and «اَبّ» and «اُمّ» are similar. These words are not used exclusively in the meaning of direct offspring; rather, their scope becomes broader. For example, Bani Adam (Children of Adam), Bani Ismail (Children of Ismail), etc., and the names of tribes are also derived from the name of their founding ancestor.\n\nThe second major difference between «اِبْن» and «بِنْت» is that the terms «اِبْن» and «بِنْت» are used to indicate lineage and relationship. For example, 'Isa ibn Maryam (Jesus, son of Mary), Maryam bint Imran (Mary, daughter of Imran), «بِنِیْ اِخْوَانِہِنَّ» and «بَنَاتُ الْاَخِ», etc. Whereas the terms of «وَلَد» are not used to denote lineage and relationship.\n\nAnd the third difference is that the terms «اِبْن» and «بِنْت» are also used as a *kunya* (honorific title). In a *kunya*, «اَبُو» and «اُمّ» are also included. In such cases, even a slight resemblance or connection is considered sufficient. For example, «اَبُوتُرَاب ، ابوھریرہ ، اُمُّ الْخَبَائِث» and (wine) «اُمُّ الْاَمَرَاض» (to seize), similarly «اِبْنُ الْوَقْت ۔ اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل ۔ اِبْنُ الْاَدْھَم ، بِنْتُ الْکَرَم» (grape) and «بنَاَتُ النَّعَش» (galaxy), etc., are used. The terms «وَلَد» and its derivatives are also not used for a *kunya*.","«اِبْن» meaning son and « بِنْت» meaning daughter.","son","ابن ، بنت","2:40-2:47-2:49-2:83-2:87-2:122-2:132-2:133-2:146-2:177-2:211-2:215-2:246-2:253-3:14-3:45-3:49-3:61-3:93-4:11-4:23-4:36-4:157-4:171-5:12-5:17-5:18-5:27-5:32-5:46-5:70-5:72-5:75-5:78-5:110-5:112-5:114-5:116-6:20-6:100-7:26-7:27-7:31-7:35-7:105-7:127-7:134-7:137-7:138-7:141-7:150-7:172-8:41-9:24-9:30-9:31-9:60-10:90-10:93-11:42-11:45-11:78-11:79-12:5-12:67-12:81-12:87-14:6-14:35-15:71-16:57-16:72-17:2-17:4-17:6-17:26-17:40-17:70-17:101-17:104-18:46-19:34-20:47-20:80-20:94-21:91-23:50-23:55-24:31-26:17-26:22-26:59-26:88-26:133-26:197-27:76-28:4-28:27-30:38-31:13-31:16-31:17-32:23-33:4-33:7-33:50-33:55-33:59-36:60-37:102-37:149-37:153-40:53-43:16-43:57-43:59-44:30-45:16-46:10-52:39-57:27-58:22-59:7-61:6-61:14-66:12-68:14-70:11-71:12-74:13-80:36",131
609,128,"T","جَلَسَ","«جَلَسَ» is commonly used in the sense of sitting down. Whether one sits up from a lying position, or comes from somewhere and sits, or sits after standing; and its opposite is «قَامَ». And «جَلْسٌ» means high and hard ground, while «جَلَسَ» means to place one's seat (i.e., one's presence) on a hard surface. The place of sitting is called «مَجْلِس». And those who sit together are also called «مَجْلِس»; its plural is «مَجَالِس». And «جَلْسَہ» is a verbal noun, meaning to sit once or the state of sitting. (Source: Mafhoom-ul-Quran, Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (58:11)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! When you are told, Make room in the assemblies, then make room; Allah will make room for you.","Sitting down after any movement, such as lying, standing, or walking.","to sit","جلس","58:11",1
610,128,"T","قَعَدَ","«قَعَدَ» is used in several meanings. For example: (1) To sit down from a standing position, and «قَعْدَۃ» is an intensive form. Meaning: to sit once, as one sits between the two prostrations. (Ref. Q)\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَا تَقۡعُدۡ بَعۡدَ الذِّکۡرٰی مَعَ الۡقَوۡمِ الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (6:68)\nTranslation: After remembering [Allah], do not sit with the wrongdoers.\n\n(2) Meaning: to remain sitting, to do no work. To turn away from the actual task.\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَجَآءَ الۡمُعَذِّرُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ لِیُؤۡذَنَ لَہُمۡ وَقَعَدَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَذَبُوا اللّٰہَ وَرَسُوۡلَہٗ» (9:90)\nTranslation: And among the desert dwellers, some people came to you seeking permission [to stay behind], saying, Allow us [to remain]. And those who lied to Allah and His Messenger remained [at home] sitting.\n\n(3) Meaning: to stand. «قَعَدَ» is from a word of opposite meanings (addad). And «قَعُوْدًا» means both 'sitting' and 'standing'. Similarly, «مَقْعَد» means both 'sitting' and 'place/station'. (Ref. R. Manjad)\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فِیۡ مَقۡعَدِ صِدۡقٍ عِنۡدَ مَلِیۡکٍ مُّقۡتَدِرٍ» (54:55)\nTranslation: The pious will be in gardens and rivers, in an honorable station (i.e., in a true, elevated place, in the court of the All-Powerful King, [the station of] Uthman).\n\n(4) Then, just as «قَعَدَ» comes in the meanings of 'sitting' or 'not doing work', it also comes in the meaning of 'sitting prepared for an action'. For example, «قَعَدَ لِلْحَرْبِ» means 'to sit prepared for battle'. (Ref. Q)\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاقۡتُلُواالۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ وَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَاحۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَاقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» (9:5)\nTranslation: Wherever you find the polytheists, kill them, capture them, and besiege them, and lie in wait for them at every place of ambush.\n\nAnd «قَعِیْدَہ» is the term for a woman who is the guardian and protector of the house and remains within it. Its plural (according to grammar) is «وَالۡقَوَاعِدُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ الّٰتِیۡ لَا یَرۡجُوۡنَ نِکَاحًا».\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَالۡقَوَاعِدُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ الّٰتِیۡ لَا یَرۡجُوۡنَ نِکَاحًا» (24:60)\nTranslation: And [as for] women who have no hope of marriage, [it is] those who remain sitting at home.\n\nNote: (Lughat-e-Aaddad refers to words that have two distinct meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other).","«قَعَدَ» meaning to sit.","to sit","قعد","2:127-3:168-3:191-4:103-4:140-6:68-7:16-7:86-9:5-9:46-9:81-9:83-9:90-16:26-17:22-17:29-24:60-54:55-72:9-85:6",20
611,128,"T","جَثَا یَجْثُوْا جَثْوًا ، جَثٰی یَجْثِیْ جَثِیًّا","«جَثَمَ» meaning to sit on the knees (singular) or to sit on both knees.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَتَرٰی کُلَّ اُمَّۃٍ جَاثِیَۃً» ( 45/28 )\nTranslation: And you will see every group seated on their knees.","«جَثَمَ» meaning to sit on the heels.","to sit","جثا یجثوا جثوًا ، جثی یجثی جثیًا","7:78-7:91-11:67-11:94-19:68-19:72-29:37-45:28",8
612,129,"S","سَقِیْم","The term «سَقِمَ» is also used to mean disease, illness, and incorrect speech (i.e., false statements) (mentioned). The word «سَقِمَ» is specific to physical illness (specific), and according to the scholar of linguistic jurisprudence, the first degree of illness is termed 'alālat'. When a patient's natural state is mildly deteriorated, they are described as 'alīl'; when the natural state worsens further, they are termed «سَقِیْم»; and when one becomes severely ill, they are called 'marīḍ' (fal 123).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «فَنَظَرَ نَظۡرَۃً فِی النُّجُوۡمِ ، فَقَالَ اِنِّیۡ سَقِیۡمٌ» (37:88-89).\n\nTranslation: Then Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) looked towards the stars and said, Indeed, I am ill.","«سَقِیْم» applies only to physical ailments and minor illnesses.","sick","سقیم","37:89-37:145",2
613,129,"S","مَرِیْض","«مَرِیْض» is a higher degree than «سَقِیْمٌ» in terms of disease. And «مَرَضُ الْمَوْت» refers to a disease that proves fatal. And the term «مرض» is used for both physical and cardiac (ailments).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ ۙ فَزَادَہُمُ اللّٰہُ مَرَضًا» (2/10) Translation: In their hearts was a disease (of disbelief). Allah increased their disease.\n\nAnd by cardiac diseases, vile morals such as cowardice, stinginess, hypocrisy, disbelief, etc., are meant.\n\nAnd the plural of «مَرِیْض» is «مَرْضٰی», and the plural of that is «اَمْرَاض».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «لَیۡسَ عَلَی الضُّعَفَآءِ وَلَا عَلَی الۡمَرۡضٰی وَلَاعَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ مَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ حَرَجٌ» (9/91) Translation: There is no blame upon the weak, nor upon the sick, nor upon those who have nothing to spend, that they be participants in jihad.","«مَرِیْض» is used for all types of patients—physical, cardiac, ordinary, or severe.","Sick","مریض","2:10-2:184-2:185-2:196-4:43-4:102-5:6-5:52-8:49-9:91-9:125-22:53-24:50-24:61-26:80-33:12-33:32-33:60-47:20-47:29-48:17-73:20-74:31",23
614,129,"S","حَرَضَ","«حَرَضَ» means to become emaciated and weak due to severe illness, and «اَحْرَضَہُ الْمَرَضَ اَوِ الْحُزْن» means that the illness or grief has wasted away (the patient). And «حَرَضَ» also means to become extremely emaciated and reach the point of death. (M. Q)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85)\nTranslation: The brothers said, By Allah, if you continue to remember Yusuf (AS) in this way, you will either become gravely ill or lose your lives.","«حَرَضَ» that patient who is emaciated, weak, and near death.","Sick","حرض","12:85",1
615,130,"W","زَوْج","«زَوْج» means a pair. Then, each one in the pair is the other's «زَوْج». The wife is the husband's «زَوْج», and the husband is the wife's «زَوْج».\n\nFor example: For women, it is in the Quran:\n«وَ قُلۡنَا یٰۤاٰدَمُ اسۡکُنۡ اَنۡتَ وَ زَوۡجُکَ الۡجَنَّۃَ» (2/35)\nTranslation: And We said, O Adam, dwell you and your wife (both) in Paradise...\n\nAnd for men, it is in the Quran:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)\nTranslation: O Prophet! When a woman comes to you with a complaint against her husband...\n\nAnd even when together, they remain «زَوْج».","«زَوْج» This word is used in the Arabic language for the wife.","wife","زوج","2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7",72
616,130,"W","حَلَائِل","The plural of «حَلَائِل» is «حَلِیْلَہ». It means a married woman or wife. And «حَلِیْلَۃٌ حَلِیْل» is its feminine form. For a man, «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» means 'wife,' and for a woman, «حَلِیْل» means 'husband.' The plural of both «حَلِیْل» and «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» is «حَلَائِل» (source: «حَلِیْل»). There is no example of «حَلِیْل» in the Quran, and the example for «حَلِیْلَۃٌ» is:\n\nThe divine declaration is:\n«وَ حَلَآئِلُ اَبۡنَآئِکُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَصۡلَابِکُمۡ» (4/23)\n\nTranslation: And also the wives of your adopted sons are forbidden to you.","«حَلَائِل» meaning the woman who is married to you.","wife","حلائل","4:23",1
617,130,"W","اِمْرَاَۃٌ","The term «اِمْرَاَۃٌ» refers to a general woman, and this word has also been used to mean 'wife'.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ مَثَلًا  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا امۡرَاَتَ نُوۡحٍ وَّامۡرَاَتَ لُوۡطٍ» (66:10)  \nTranslation: Allah has set forth an example for the disbelievers with the wives of Noah and Lot.","«اِمْرَاَۃٌ» refers to an ordinary woman, and this term is also used for a wife.","Wife","امراۃ","2:282-3:35-3:40-4:12-4:128-7:83-11:71-11:81-12:21-12:30-12:51-15:60-19:5-19:8-27:23-27:57-28:9-28:23-29:32-29:33-33:50-51:29-66:10-66:11-111:4",25
618,130,"W","نِسَاءٌ","«اِمْرَأَۃٌ» is a non-plural form meaning 'ordinary women.' This word has also been used for 'wives.'  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«یٰنِسَآءَ النَّبِیِّ لَسۡتُنَّ کَاَحَدٍ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (33/32)  \nTranslation: O wives of the Prophet, you are not like ordinary women.","The word «نِسَاءٌ» refers to a woman, and it is also used for wife.","Wife","نساء","2:49-2:187-2:222-2:223-2:226-2:231-2:232-2:235-2:236-3:14-3:42-3:61-4:1-4:3-4:4-4:7-4:11-4:15-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:32-4:34-4:43-4:75-4:98-4:127-4:129-4:176-5:6-7:81-7:127-7:141-14:6-24:31-24:60-27:55-28:4-33:30-33:32-33:52-33:55-33:59-40:25-48:25-49:11-58:2-58:3-65:1-65:4",51
619,130,"W","صَاحِبَۃ","«صَاحِب» means companion and friend. Its feminine form, «صَاحِبَۃ», is used in the sense of 'wife'. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ یَفِرُّالۡمَرۡءُ مِنۡ اَخِیۡہِ ، وَاُمِّہٖ وَاَبِیۡہِ ، وَصَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ بَنِیۡہِ» (80:34-36)\nTranslation: On that Day, man will flee from his brother, his mother, his father, his wife, and his son.","«صَاحِبَۃ» is used to respectfully address a woman, for example, it is also used for 'grandmother' and 'wife'.","wife","صاحبۃ","6:101-70:12-72:3-80:36",4
620,130,"W","اَھْل","«اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» refers to a person's kinsfolk or those who live in the same household. This term is also used for a person's close relatives. And sometimes «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means wife.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n\n«قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءً» (12/25)\n\nTranslation: (Zulaykha) said to her husband, So what would be the punishment for someone who intends evil against your wife?","One’s blood relatives or those who reside in the same place, where «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» also includes one’s wife.","wife","اھل","12:25",1
622,131,"I","ظَلَمَ","«ظَلَمَ» is primarily used in two ways: (1) to place something in an unlawful manner outside its original place, and (2) meaning darkness, which is the opposite of light and radiance. And «ظُلْمَتْ» means darkness, and its plural is «ظُلُمٰت», and the plural «اَلْجَمْعُ ظَّلَام» is also derived from it (as in the example).  \nIn the first meaning, the opposite of injustice is justice. And every statement of injustice, whether it pertains to the rights of Allah or the rights of His creation, is an act of oppression. And the usage of this word is general.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«یٰبُنَیَّ لَا تُشۡرِکۡ بِاللّٰہِ   ؕ ؔاِنَّ الشِّرۡکَ لَظُلۡمٌ  عَظِیۡمٌ» (31:13)  \nTranslation: O my son! Do not associate anything with Allah. Indeed, association (with Him) is a great injustice.  \nAt another place, the command of the Almighty states:  \n«لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ  الۡجَہۡرَ  بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ» (4:148)  \nTranslation: Allah does not like the public proclamation of evil, except by one who has been wronged.","«ظَلَمَ» every matter of injustice, whether it pertains to the rights of Allah or the rights of His creation.","Injustice","ظلم","2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1",128
623,131,"I","حَافَ","The basic meaning of «حَافَ» is bias or inclination («اَلْمَیْل») (for example), i.e., to lean toward one side when making a decision and not to be just. Then, the meanings of «حَافَ» also include diminishing or reducing something from its sides (source).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَمۡ یَخَافُوۡنَ اَنۡ یَّحِیۡفَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ رَسُوۡلُہٗ» (24/50)\nTranslation: Or do they fear that Allah and His Messenger will wrong them?","«حَافَ» to show partiality in fulfilling others' rights and to give less than due.","Injustice","حاف","24:50",1
624,131,"I","عَالَ","«عَالَ» means to oppress. «اَلْعَوْل» is used in relation to anything that burdens a person, causing them to be crushed under the load. Essentially, it signifies injustice by taking more than one's rightful share. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا» (4/3). Translation: And if you fear that you will not be able to treat all women equally, then one woman (is sufficient) or a slave girl whom you own. Thus you will avoid injustice.","«عَالَ» To commit such an injustice in which another's right is also violated and whose right has been suppressed, it will also weigh heavily upon him.","Injustice","عال","4:3",1
625,131,"I","ضَازَ","«ضَازَ» meaning to oppress, to deprive of rights. «ضَیْز» meaning crookedness, bias, and deviation. «قِسْمَۃٌ ضِیْزٰی» meaning deficient and oppressive division (manjad), i.e., when determining the rights of oneself and others, disregarding all demands of justice, practicing fraud.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَکُمُ الذَّکَرُ وَلَہُ الۡاُنۡثٰی ، تِلۡکَ اِذًا قِسۡمَۃٌ ضِیۡزٰی» (53/21,22)\nTranslation: (O polytheists!) For you, there are sons, but for Allah, daughters. This is indeed a most unjust division. (Tafheem ul Quran)","To engage in extreme disorder in the determination of rights «ضَازَ».","Injustice","ضاز","53:22",1
626,132,"I","رَغِبَ عَنْ","«رَغِبَ» signifies having inclination or desire for something, and if its recompense is from «عَن», then the implication of aversion from it arises. For instance: the Quran states: «وَمَنۡ یَّرۡغَبُ عَنۡ مِّلَّۃِ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ اِلَّا مَنۡ سَفِہَ نَفۡسَہٗ» (2/130) Translation: And who would turn away from Abraham's religion except he who makes himself a fool?","«رغِب َعَنْ» is a common term for indifference.","Indifference","رغب عن","2:130",1
627,132,"I","حَصُور","«حَصَرَ» means to encircle by constricting, and «حَصِر» means to become constricted and to cease. And «حَصُوْر» is the term for a person who abstains from women and does not incline toward them.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکَ بِیَحۡیٰی مُصَدِّقًۢا بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَ سَیِّدًا وَّ حَصُوۡرًا وَّ نَبِیًّا مِّنَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» ( 3/39 )\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah gives you glad tidings, O Zakariya, of a son whose name will be Yahya; he will confirm the Word of Allah (Jesus) and will be a leader among the righteous, and a chaste man, and a prophet from among the righteous.","«حَصُور» meaning a person who is disinterested in women.","Indifference","حصور","3:39",1
628,132,"D","زَاھِدٌ","«زَھَدَ» means to be disinterested or to abandon. And «زَھِیْد» means an insignificant thing, and «زَاھِدٌ فِیْ الشَّیْء» means one who becomes indifferent to something or accepts something trivial. For example: In the Quran: «وَشَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ ۚ وَکَانُوۡا فِیۡہِ مِنَ الزَّاہِدِیۡنَ» (12/20) Translation: And the brothers of Joseph sold Joseph (peace be upon him) for a small price, a few coins, and they had no regard for him in that matter.","«زَھَدَ» One who considers something contemptible and ordinary, and therefore remains disinterested or indifferent towards it.","Disinclination","زاھد","12:20",1
629,133,"D","تَبَرّأَ","«بَرِأَ» means to be saved from something detestable or painful (transitive). «بَرِءتُ مِنَ الْمَرَضِ» i.e., I became healthy. And «اَبْرِأُ الْمَرِیْض» i.e., to give cure to the patient (transitive).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاُبۡرِئُ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَالۡاَبۡرَصَ وَاُحۡیِ الۡمَوۡتٰی بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (3/49)\nTranslation: And I heal the blind and the leper by Allah's permission and bring the dead to life.\nAnd «بَرَاءَۃ» meaning aversion, severance of ties. Boycott. Faq l 113.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«بَرَآءَۃٌ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَرَسُوۡلِہٖۤ» (9/1)\nTranslation: A declaration of aversion from Allah and His Messenger.\nAnd «بَرَّأَ» means to save someone from a detestable or painful matter. To absolve or distance from blame and slander, etc.\nFor example: The declaration of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَمَاۤ اُبَرِّئُ نَفۡسِیۡ ۚ اِنَّ النَّفۡسَ لَاَمَّارَۃٌۢ بِالسُّوۡٓءِ» (12/53)\nTranslation: And I do not claim myself to be pure. Indeed, the soul (that incites man to evil) is ever prone to evil.\nAnd «تَبَرَّاَ» means to become averse oneself from a detestable or painful matter.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡ تَبَرَّاَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتُّبِعُوۡا مِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّبَعُوۡا وَرَاَوُاالۡعَذَابَ وَتَقَطَّعَتۡ بِہِمُ الۡاَسۡبَابُ» (2/166)\nTranslation: On that day, the leaders (of disbelief) will show aversion to their followers and they will see the punishment, and the ties between them will be cut off.","to be disgusted with anything that causes distress or trouble","Disgusted","تبرأ","2:166-2:167-6:19-6:78-8:48-9:1-9:3-9:114-10:41-11:35-11:54-12:53-26:216-28:63-33:69-43:26-54:43-59:16-60:4",19
630,133,"A","قَلٰی","To become averse to someone due to displeasure. The scholar of language and jurisprudence has placed it second after enmity. That is, the rank of «قلٰی» comes after بُغْض (enmity) (F. L. 166).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَا وَدَّعَکَ رَبُّکَ وَ مَا قَلٰی» (93:3)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ) your Lord has neither abandoned you nor become displeased with you. (Jalandhari)\nTranslation: Neither has your Lord forsaken you nor become averse to you. (Usmaniؒ)","«قلٰی» to become disgusted with someone due to anger.","Aversion","قلی","93:3",1
631,133,"W","مَقْت","«مَقْت» To become extremely angry and disgusted upon the commission of a vile act. And this is the next degree of «قَلٰی» (f l 166).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَلَا تَنۡکِحُوۡا مَا نَکَحَ اٰبَآؤُکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ فَاحِشَۃً وَّ مَقۡتًا ؕ وَسَآءَ سَبِیۡلًا» (4/22)\nTranslation: And do not marry those women whom your fathers have married, except what has already occurred (in the Jahiliyyah). Indeed, it was an extremely obscene and hateful practice, and a very evil custom. (Jalandhari)","«مَقْت» denotes strong aversion and revulsion toward an abominable (evil) deed.","weary","مقت","4:22-35:39-40:10-40:35-61:3",5
632,134,"I","اِنَّ ، اَنَّ","Both of these words enter the nominative case. «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ » appears at the beginning of a statement. For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ » (2/20)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is over all things competent. However, «اَنَّ» appears in the middle. For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَعۡلَمُ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  عَلٰی کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ قَدِیۡرٌ» (2/259)\nTranslation: I know that Allah is over all things competent.\n\nIt is essential to remember that after «قَالَ» and its derivatives, «اِنَّ» will also appear in the middle of a statement. For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اِنَّہٗ یَقُوۡلُ اِنَّہَا بَقَرَۃٌ» (2/68)\nTranslation: Moses (peace be upon him) said, Indeed, your Lord says that it is a cow.\n\nGrammatically, «اَنَّ» should come after «عَلِمَ» and «شَھِدَ» in the middle of a statement (as the above example also shows). However, in one instance in the Quran, «اِنَّ» was used after «عَلِمَ» and «شَھِدَ».\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«وَاللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  اِنَّکَ لَرَسُوۡلُہٗ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ یَشۡہَدُ اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ لَکٰذِبُوۡنَ» (63/1)\nTranslation: And Allah knows that you are His Messenger, and Allah bears witness that the hypocrites are liars.","Both «اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» and «اَنَّ» are used for emphasis and investigation, with «اِنَّ ، اَنَّ» appearing at the beginning of the statement and «اَنَّ» in the middle.","Indeed","ان ، ان","2:6-2:12-2:13-2:14-2:20-2:25-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:33-2:37-2:45-2:46-2:47-2:54-2:61-2:62-2:67-2:68-2:69-2:70-2:71-2:74-2:77-2:97-2:98-2:103-2:106-2:107-2:109-2:110-2:115-2:119-2:120-2:122-2:124-2:127-2:128-2:129-2:130-2:132-2:140-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:148-2:149-2:153-2:156-2:158-2:159-2:161-2:164-2:165-2:167-2:168-2:173-2:174-2:176-2:181-2:182-2:186-2:187-2:190-2:192-2:194-2:195-2:196-2:197-2:199-2:203-2:208-2:209-2:211-2:214-2:215-2:218-2:220-2:222-2:223-2:226-2:227-2:231-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:243-2:244-2:247-2:248-2:249-2:252-2:258-2:259-2:260-2:267-2:270-2:273-2:275-2:277-2:282-2:283-3:4-3:5-3:8-3:9-3:10-3:13-3:16-3:18-3:19-3:21-3:24-3:26-3:30-3:32-3:33-3:35-3:36-3:37-3:38-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:49-3:51-3:52-3:55-3:59-3:62-3:63-3:64-3:68-3:73-3:75-3:76-3:77-3:78-3:86-3:87-3:89-3:90-3:91-3:92-3:96-3:97-3:112-3:116-3:119-3:120-3:128-3:154-3:155-3:159-3:165-3:173-3:176-3:177-3:181-3:183-3:186-3:190-3:192-3:193-3:194-3:195-3:199-4:1-4:2-4:10-4:11-4:16-4:18-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:32-4:33-4:34-4:35-4:36-4:40-4:43-4:46-4:48-4:56-4:58-4:60-4:64-4:66-4:72-4:76-4:86-4:94-4:97-4:101-4:102-4:103-4:104-5:105-4:106-4:107-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:137-4:139-4:140-4:142-4:145-4:149-4:150-4:157-4:163-4:167-4:168-4:170-5:1-5:2-5:3-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:12-5:13-5:14-5:17-5:22-5:23-5:24-5:25-5:26-5:28-5:29-5:32-5:34-5:36-5:39-5:40-5:42-5:44-5:45-5:49-5:51-5:53-5:56-5:58-5:59-5:65-5:66-5:67-5:69-5:72-5:73-5:82-5:87-5:97-5:98-5:106-5:107-5:109-5:111-5:115-5:116-5:118-6:14-6:15-6:19-6:21-6:28-6:33-6:37-6:50-6:54-6:56-6:57-6:58-6:71-6:74-6:78-6:79-6:81-6:83-6:94-6:95-6:99-6:109-6:111-6:114-6:117-6:119-6:120-6:121-6:128-6:130-6:134-6:135-6:139-6:141-6:142-6:144-6:145-6:146-6:150-6:157-6:158-6:159-6:161-6:162-6:165-7:5-7:13-7:15-7:21-7:22-7:27-7:28-7:30-7:31-7:37-7:40-7:50-7:54-7:55-7:56-7:59-7:60-7:64-7:66-7:71-7:75-7:76-7:81-7:82-7:90-7:96-7:104-7:109-7:113-7:114-7:123-7:125-7:127-7:128-7:136-7:138-7:139-7:144-7:146-7:148-7:149-7:150-7:152-7:153-7:156-7:158-7:167-7:170-7:171-7:172-7:183-7:194-7:196-7:200-7:201-7:206-8:5-8:7-8:9-8:10-8:12-8:13-8:17-8:22-8:24-8:25-8:36-8:39-8:40-8:41-8:42-8:43-8:46-8:48-8:49-8:52-8:55-8:58-8:59-8:61-8:62-8:63-8:65-8:66-8:69-8:72-8:75-9:2-9:3-9:4-9:5-9:6-9:7-9:9-9:12-9:22-9:28-9:34-9:36-9:40-9:42-9:49-9:52-9:53-9:54-9:56-9:59-9:63-9:64-9:66-9:67-9:71-9:78-9:80-9:83-9:84-9:95-9:96-9:99-9:102-9:103-9:104-9:107-9:111-9:113-9:114-9:115-9:116-9:117-9:118-9:120-9:123-9:126-9:127-10:2-10:3-10:4-10:6-10:7-10:9-10:15-10:17-10:20-10:21-10:22-10:24-10:33-10:36-10:44-10:53-10:54-1