34-68:38-68:39-68:45-68:51-69:11-69:20-69:33-69:40-69:48-69:49-69:50-69:51-70:6-70:15-70:19-70:28-70:30-70:39-70:40-71:1-71:2-71:4-71:5-71:7-71:8-71:9-71:10-71:21-71:27-72:1-72:3-72:4-72:5-72:6-72:7-72:8-72:9-72:10-72:11-72:12-72:13-72:14-72:19-72:21-72:22-72:23-72:27-73:5-73:6-73:7-73:12-73:15-73:19-73:20-74:16-74:18-74:35-74:54-75:17-75:19-75:28-76:2-76:3-76:4-76:5-76:10-76:22-76:23-76:27-76:29-76:30-77:32-77:41-77:44-77:46-78:17-78:21-78:27-78:31-78:40-79:10-79:17-79:26-79:39-79:41-80:11-80:25-81:19-82:10-82:13-82:14-83:4-83:7-83:15-83:16-83:18-83:22-83:29-83:32-84:6-84:13-84:14-84:15-85:10-85:11-85:12-85:13-86:8-86:13-86:15-87:7-87:18-88:25-88:26-89:14-92:4-92:12-92:13-94:5-94:6-96:6-96:8-97:1-98:6-98:7-100:6-100:7-100:8-100:11-103:2-104:3-104:8-108:1-108:3-110:3",1605
633,134,"I","لَاجَرَمَ","There is a difference of opinion among scholars regarding the meaning of this word. Most translators render its meaning as undoubtedly or indeed. Al-Munjid writes its meaning as by Allah's oath. This word appears three times in the Quran, and each occurrence precedes «اَنَّ» (11/22, 16/23, 16/109), indicating that it serves as a point for further inquiry. Nevertheless, adopting Al-Munjid's interpretation of by Allah's oath is also correct and adds further emphasis.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَا جَرَمَ اَنَّہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمُ الۡاَخۡسَرُوۡنَ» (11/22)\nTranslation: Indeed, these people will be the greatest losers in the Hereafter.","In Arabic grammar, this word is used for additional emphasis and clarification.","Indeed","لاجرم","11:22-16:23-16:62-16:109-40:43",5
634,134,"I","قَدْ","When «قَدْ» is incorporated into a past tense verb, it also imparts the meaning of inquiry and brings it close to the present tense. In other words, it transforms the past tense into the recent past.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «قَدۡ سَمِعَ اللّٰہُ قَوۡلَ الَّتِیۡ» (58/1).\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has heard the statement of this woman.","«قَدْ» also conveys the meaning of investigation when combined with a past tense verb, and it also imparts a meaning close to the present tense. That is, it transforms the past tense verb into the recent past.","Indeed","قد","2:60-2:75-2:108-2:118-2:134-2:137-2:141-2:144-2:231-2:237-2:246-2:247-2:256-2:269-3:13-3:20-3:40-3:49-3:101-3:118-3:137-3:140-3:143-3:144-3:154-3:165-3:173-3:183-3:184-3:185-3:192-4:21-4:22-4:23-4:48-4:54-4:60-4:72-4:80-4:100-4:112-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:161-4:164-4:167-4:170-4:174-5:5-5:12-5:15-5:19-5:61-5:72-5:75-5:77-5:102-5:113-5:116-6:5-6:16-6:31-6:33-6:56-6:80-6:89-6:97-6:98-6:104-6:119-6:126-6:128-6:140-6:157-7:26-7:38-7:44-7:53-7:71-7:73-7:85-7:89-7:95-7:105-7:149-7:160-7:185-8:16-8:19-8:31-8:38-8:71-9:40-9:50-9:66-9:94-10:16-10:45-10:51-10:57-10:89-10:91-10:108-11:32-11:36-11:57-11:62-11:76-12:30-12:77-12:80-12:90-12:100-12:101-12:110-13:6-13:30-13:42-14:12-14:46-15:13-16:26-16:91-17:33-17:77-18:76-18:91-19:8-19:9-19:24-19:43-20:36-20:47-20:48-20:61-20:64-20:75-20:80-20:81-20:85-20:99-20:111-20:125-21:97-22:42-23:1-23:66-24:41-24:63-24:64-25:4-25:19-25:77-26:6-28:78-29:18-29:38-31:22-33:18-33:36-33:50-33:58-33:71-34:53-35:4-35:25-37:105-39:50-39:59-40:9-40:28-40:48-40:85-41:25-41:43-43:63-44:13-46:17-46:18-46:21-47:18-48:21-48:23-50:4-50:28-54:12-57:8-57:17-58:1-58:5-60:1-60:4-60:5-60:13-65:1-65:3-65:10-65:11-65:12-66:2-66:4-67:9-68:43-71:14-71:24-72:28-87:14-91:9-91:10",212
635,135,"T","فَرَغَ","«فَرَغَ» means to be empty, and its opposite is «شَغَلَ», which means to be occupied with some work. And «قَلْبُ فَارِغٌ» is a state in which there is no occupation (F L 70), meaning that courage or patience is lost and one becomes restless.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا ؕ اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ لَوۡلَاۤ اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: And the heart of Moses' mother became anxious. If We had not strengthened her heart, she would almost have disclosed him.","«فَرَغَ» A heart devoid of patience and tranquility.","to be anxious","فرغ","28:10",1
636,135,"T","جَزِعَ","«جَزِعَ» To begin expressing lamentation and complaint verbally due to impatience. And its opposite is «صَبَرَ». This term is applied when a person, instead of exercising patience in the face of hardship or affliction, also starts to verbally express grief and sorrow (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡنَاۤ اَجَزِعۡنَاۤ اَمۡ صَبَرۡنَا مَا لَنَا مِنۡ مَّحِیۡصٍ» (14:21)\nTranslation: It is all the same for us whether we remain restless or exercise patience; there is no escape for us. (Uthmani)","«جَزِعَ» to start wailing impatiently","to panic","جزع","14:21",1
637,135,"T","فَزَع","«فَزِعَ» means to be terror-stricken (m. l.), and according to Imam Raghib, this is a type of «جَزَعَ» (muf)—that is, when fear (ghabrahat) is also included along with «جَزَعَ», it becomes the quality of «فَزِعَ».\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَنۡ جَآءَ بِالۡحَسَنَۃِ فَلَہٗ خَیۡرٌمِّنۡہَا ۚ وَہُمۡ مِّنۡ فَزَعٍ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ اٰمِنُوۡنَ» (27/89)\nTranslation: Whoever comes with a good deed will have something better (prepared as reward), and such people will be free from fear on that Day.","such agitation that occurs due to the fear of something","to worry","فزع","21:103-27:87-27:89-34:23-34:51-38:22",6
638,135,"T","کَرُب","«کَرُبَ» A restlessness that includes sorrow (F. 170). Anxiety, turmoil, and distress.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَنُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَاَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (21/76)\nTranslation: And (remember) Noah, when he called upon Us before, so We accepted his prayer and saved him and his companions from a great distress.","A restlessness that also includes an element of sorrow.","to panic","کرب","6:64-21:76-37:36-37:115",4
639,135,"T","ھَلَعَ","«ھَلَعَ» the extreme state of impatience and, according to the scholar of language and jurisprudence, this is the extreme state of «جَزِعَ» (f.l. 48) — being despondent and impatient.  \nFor example: the Noble Quran states:  \n«اِنَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ خُلِقَ ہَلُوۡعًا اِذَا مَسَّہُ الشَّرُّ جَزُوۡعًا» (70:19-20)  \nTranslation: Indeed, mankind was created impatient: when evil touches him, he becomes fretful.","«ھَلَعَ» the extreme state of impatience.","to be flustered","ھلع","70:19",1
640,135,"T","اِضْطَرَّ","«ضَرَّ» and «ضُرَّ» mean to cause someone distress, to inflict harm. And «أَضَرَّ فُلاناً عَلَى الْأَمْرِ» means to compel someone to do something. And «اِضْطَرَّ» means to force someone, to make them needy (in dire need). As for «اِضْطَرَار», it refers to a state of restlessness in which a person's need becomes attached [to something].\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ غَیۡرَ بَاغٍ وَّلَا عَادٍ فَلَاۤ اِثۡمَ عَلَیۡہِ» (2/173)\nTranslation: But whoever is forced by necessity, neither desiring nor transgressing, there is no sin upon him. Indeed, Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.","«اِضْطَرَّ» to be anxious to fulfill a necessary need.","to panic","اضطر","2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24",8
641,135,"T","اِسْتَفَزَّ","The meaning of «فَزَّ» is to cause someone to lose their senses, to expel someone by subjecting them to panic. And «اِسْتَفَزَّ» comes in the meanings of causing restlessness and anxiety, (intensive form) and to humiliate.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاسۡتَفۡزِزۡ مَنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ بِصَوۡتِکَ» (17/64)\nTranslation: And strike with terror those whom you can strike with your voice.","«اِسْتَفَزَّ» to throw someone else into panic.","to feel agitated","استفز","17:64-17:76-17:103",3
642,136,"U","فَرَغَ","«فَرَغَ» means to be free from a task, and its opposite is «شَغَل». (Singular) i.e., a person being free after completing a specific task.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَاِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94:7,8)\nTranslation: So when you have finished [your duties], then stand up [for worship]. And to your Lord direct your longing.","«فَرَغَ» an interim period between the completion of one task and the start of another.","Useless","فرغ","55:31-94:7",2
643,136,"U","عَطَلَ","«عَطَلَ» means a laborer being idle or a woman being without jewelry (singular), and «عَطَّلَ» means to abandon someone as useless.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَاِذَا الۡعِشَارُعُطِّلَتۡ» (81/4)  \nTranslation: And when the she-camels, ten months pregnant, are left untended.","«عَطَلَ» inactivity that is neither within one's control nor of one's own accord.","Useless","عطل","22:45-81:4",2
644,137,"U","مَحْرُوْمُ","«مَحْرُوْمُ» is used to refer to someone who is unfortunate in terms of material provision. And *haram* is that thing from which one has been prohibited. This prohibition can sometimes be coercive (i.e., to allure or make submissive) and at other times compulsory or Shariah-compliant. And *mahrūm* is the person from whom the expanse of sustenance and prosperity has been withheld (source). The word *mahrūm* appears in the Quran approximately three times, and in every instance, it is used in the sense of being *constrained* or *in straitened circumstances*.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ حَقٌّ مَّعۡلُوۡمٌ . لِّلسَّآئِلِ وَالۡمَحۡرُوۡمِ» (70/24,25)\n\nTranslation: And in the wealth of those (the wealthy) is a right for the beggar and the deprived.","«مَحْرُوْمُ» is used for someone who is economically deprived or unfortunate. And it is used in all these meanings: prohibited, banned, denied, forbidden, prevented, unlawful, and impermissible.","Unfortunate","محروم","51:19-56:67-68:27-70:25",4
645,137,"U","شَقِیًّا","«شَقِی» is the opposite of «سَعِیْد». And «سَعِیْد» is a person who is innately virtuous and blessed. Similarly, «شَقِی» is a person who is innately deprived of that virtuous and blessed state.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّلَمۡ اَکُنۡۢ بِدُعَآئِکَ رَبِّ شَقِیًّا» (19/4)\nTranslation: (Prophet Zakariya peace be upon him said) And my Lord, in my supplication to You, I have never been deprived.","«شَقِیًّا» is used for ill-fated and wretched humans.","Unfortunate","شقیًا","11:105-11:106-19:4-19:32-19:48-23:106-87:11-91:12-92:15",9
646,138,"N","غَنِی","«غَنِی» is the attribute of being one who has no need of anyone else. And its opposite is *al-faqir* (the poor), meaning one who is in need and dependent. The word «غَنِی» often comes in the sense of being independent of wealth and possessions, and it is also used for a wealthy person. Its plural is «اَغْنِیَاء». That is, at minimum, one must possess enough wealth so that one is not in need of others in matters of livelihood (as per *al-Mufradat*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ» (2:273)\nTranslation: Because they are not asking insistently, an ignorant person would think them wealthy.","That «غَنِی» who has no need of anyone else.","needless","غنی","2:263-2:267-2:273-3:97-3:181-4:6-4:130-4:131-4:135-6:133-9:28-9:74-9:93-10:68-14:8-22:64-24:32-24:33-27:40-29:6-31:12-31:26-35:15-39:7-47:38-53:48-57:24-59:7-60:6-64:6-80:5-80:37-92:8-93:8-96:7",35
647,138,"S","صَمَد","«صَمَد» involves two fundamental aspects: (1) something being solid and strong, and (2) people from all directions having the intention and resolve to turn towards it (m. l. manjad)—that is, a being who is Himself in need of nothing, while all others are in need of Him.\n\n«غَنِی» differs from «صَمَد» in that «غَنِی» relates more to economic matters, whereas «صَمَد» is independent in all aspects, and others are in need of Him.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ ہُوَاللّٰہُ اَحَدٌ اَللّٰہُ الصَّمَدُ» (112:1,2)\nTranslation: Say, He is Allah, the One. Allah, the Eternal Refuge [the Self-Sufficient, the Needed by all].","«صَمَد» A being who is Self-Sufficient, not in need of anything, while all others are in need of It.","Self-sufficient","صمد","112:2",1
648,139,"I","لَغُوْ","«لَغٰی ، یَلْغُوا» means to speak without thought or reflection, and to engage in nonsense. And «لَغَی الطَیرُبَا صْواتِھا» refers to each bird uttering its own distinct chirps. The well-known word lagat (لغت) is derived from it, meaning a mixed or common language. And laghw (لغو) is used for all vain, foolish talk and for the bark of a dog. And «لَاغِیْۃ» means vain and obscene speech (Munjid). For example: The Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا لَغۡوًا اِلَّا سَلٰمًا» (19:62)\nTranslation: They will not hear any vain talk there, only peace, only peace.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَّا تَسۡمَعُ فِیۡہَا لَاغِیَۃً» (88:11)\nTranslation: They will not hear any nonsense therein. (Uthmani, may Allah have mercy on him)","«لَغُوْ» idle chatter and thoughtless uproar.","Idle talk","لغو","2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11",11
649,139,"F","ھَزْل","«ھَزَلَ» has essentially two meanings: (1) to be lean, thin, or weak; (2) «ھَزَلَ فِیْ کَلَامِہٖ», meaning to joke or engage in frivolity. «ھَزَالَۃٌ», meaning wit and good humor, is also associated with it (Munjid). Thus, «ھَزَلَ» apparently means to speak lightly or playfully, as in jest (Faqih, p. 211).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ لَقَوۡلٌ فَصۡلٌ وَّمَا ہُوَبِالۡہَزۡلِ» (86:13-14)\nTranslation: Indeed, this (Quran) is a decisive word. And it is not a jest.","«ھَزَلَ» to spend time laughing, joking, and having cheerful conversations.","Futile speech","ھزل","86:14",1
650,139,"I","نَزَفَ","The meaning of «نَزَفَ» is for something to end and be discontinued. (M. L) «نَزِفَ دَمُہٗ» means all his blood has drained out, and «نَزِیْف» refers to a person whose intellect has been taken away—senseless and intoxicated (M. L). «نَزَفَ الْمَاء» means gradually, i.e., slowly drawing water (Muf). Thus, «نَزَفَ» signifies those rambling, incoherent utterances that a wretched person makes due to the consumption of an intoxicant or for some other reason that causes a deficiency in reason and senses.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَیۡضَآءَ لَذَّۃٍ لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ ، لَا فِیۡہَا غَوۡلٌ وَّلَا ہُمۡ عَنۡہَا یُنۡزَفُوۡنَ» (37:46,47)\nTranslation: It will be white and extremely delicious to drink. Neither will there be a headache from it, nor will one be intoxicated by it.","«نَزَفَ» What kind of foolish ramblings does a person intoxicated with alcohol or drugs engage in?","Idle talk","نزف","37:47-56:19",2
651,140,"U","صَعِقَ","«صَعِقَ» refers to fainting due to terror and panic (cf. F, L 130), and «صَاعِقَہ» denotes the falling lightning or that terrifying explosion which originates from the upper bodies (i.e., from the direction of the heavens). (For details, see the entry on lightning.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ دَکًّا وَّخَرَّ مُوۡسٰی صَعِقًا» (7:143)\n\nTranslation: When his Lord manifested Himself upon the mountain, He rendered it level, and Moses fell unconscious.","«صَعِقَ» to become unconscious from a celestial incident.","unconscious","صعق","7:143-39:68-52:45",3
652,140,"U","سَکَرَ","Generally, «سَکَرَ» is used for intoxication from wine or intoxicating substances. And «سُکْر» refers to such a state where a person loses their reason and senses (intoxicated). For example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَجَآءَتۡ سَکۡرَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ بِالۡحَقِّ» (50/19) Translation: And the unconsciousness of death will befall to unveil the truth. For example, the divine command states: «وَمِنۡ ثَمَرٰتِ النَّخِیۡلِ وَالۡاَعۡنَابِ تَتَّخِذُوۡنَ مِنۡہُ سَکَرًا وَّرِزۡقًا حَسَنًا» (16/67) Translation: And from the fruits of the date-palm and grapevines, you also derive intoxicants and good provision. And «سَکِر» means to become intoxicated from wine, and the adjective is sakran. The feminine form is «سَکْرٰی» and its plural is «سُکٰرٰی» (minj).","Generally, «سَکَرَ» is used to induce unconsciousness, similar to the effect of wine or other intoxicants.","Unconscious","سکر","15:15-15:72-16:67-50:19",4
653,140,"U","غَمِرَ","The meaning of «غَمِرَ» is to be overcome by unconsciousness or a stupor, and the meaning of «غَمَرَاتُ الْمَوْت» is the agonies and hardships of death, during which a person's senses and faculties gradually fail (Munjid). «غَمَرَۃٌ» also refers to abundant water, the extent of which cannot be known. Ibn al-Faris writes that «غَمِرَ» also means the obscuration (i.e., ruin) of reason and intellect due to severe hardships and difficulties (M. L).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذِ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ فِیۡ غَمَرٰتِ الۡمَوۡتِ وَالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ بَاسِطُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (6:93)\nTranslation: And if only you could see the wrongdoers at the time when they are seized by the agonies of death, and the angels extend their hands towards them.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«بَلۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ فِیۡ غَمۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ ہٰذَا» (23:63)\nTranslation: No! Their hearts are stupefied from that. (Uthmani, may Allah have mercy on him)","«غَمِرَ» Unconsciousness due to calamities and hardships.","Unconscious","غمر","6:93-23:54-23:63-51:11",4
654,140,"U","صَرَع","«صَرَعَ» means death or «اُمُّ الصِبْیَان» is a well-known disease in which a person loses consciousness and falls to the ground. And «صَرَع» means falling to the ground due to restlessness and anxiety (F. L 130).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/7)\nTranslation: Then you will see that people have scattered in it (Uthmani).","«صَرَعَ» fainting and falling to the ground.","unconscious","صرع","69:7",1
655,140,"U","غَشِیَ","The meaning of «غَشَا» is to cover something and place a veil over it. And when a veil descends upon a person's intellect and their senses cease to function, that is also called 'ghashi' (stupefaction). Its cause may be terror, fear, or something else. And «مُغَشِّی» is the term used for a person who has become unconscious.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ الۡخَوۡفُ رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ تَدُوۡرُ اَعۡیُنُہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ یُغۡشٰی عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡمَوۡتِ» (33:19)\nTranslation: Then when the time of fear came, you saw them looking towards you, their eyes rolling as though they were overcome with the stupor of death.","«غَشِیَ» To become unconscious due to fear of something, illness, or any other reason.","unconscious","غشی","2:7-3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-45:23-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1",23
656,141,"N","عِنْد","«عِنْد» means near. It is used for both temporal (time) and spatial (place) contexts. «عِنْدَ الْمَکَان» means near a place or location, and «عِنْدَ الْلَیْل» means at night or near nightfall—slightly before or after sunset. (M. R.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَاعِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَمَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ» (16:96)\nTranslation: Whatever is at your disposal will perish, and whatever is with Allah will remain.\n\nSometimes «عِنْد» precedes «مِنْ» to provide additional emphasis. «مِنْ عِنْد» means from near, from the side.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡتُمۡ اَنّٰی ہٰذَا ؕ قُلۡ ہُوَ مِنۡ عِنۡدِ اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ» (3:165)\nTranslation: So you set out to see from where this calamity came. Say, 'It is from yourselves, due to your deeds.'\n\nFurthermore, when this «مِنْ» is included, it creates greater emphasis.","«عِنْد» meaning to be near, whether in terms of place or time.","Near","عند","2:54-2:62-2:76-2:79-2:80-2:89-2:94-2:101-2:103-2:109-2:110-2:112-2:140-2:191-2:198-2:217-2:255-2:262-2:274-2:277-2:282-3:7-3:14-3:15-3:19-3:37-3:59-3:73-3:78-3:126-3:156-3:163-3:165-3:169-3:195-3:198-3:199-4:78-4:81-4:82-4:94-4:134-4:139-5:43-5:52-5:60-6:2-6:50-6:57-6:58-6:59-6:109-6:124-6:127-6:148-7:29-7:31-7:131-7:134-7:157-7:187-7:206-8:4-8:10-8:22-8:28-8:32-8:35-8:55-9:7-9:19-9:20-9:22-9:36-9:52-9:99-10:2-10:18-10:68-10:76-11:28-11:31-11:83-12:17-12:42-12:60-12:79-13:8-13:39-13:43-14:37-14:46-15:21-16:95-16:96-17:23-17:38-18:46-18:65-18:86-19:55-19:76-19:78-19:87-20:52-21:19-21:84-22:30-22:47-23:117-24:13-24:15-24:39-24:61-27:40-27:47-28:27-28:37-28:48-28:49-28:60-28:78-29:17-29:50-30:39-31:34-32:12-33:5-33:53-33:63-33:69-34:23-34:31-34:37-35:39-37:48-37:168-38:9-38:25-38:40-38:47-38:52-39:31-39:34-40:25-40:35-40:83-41:38-41:50-41:52-42:16-42:22-42:36-43:35-43:49-43:85-44:5-46:10-46:23-47:16-48:5-49:3-49:13-50:4-51:34-52:37-52:41-53:14-53:15-53:35-54:35-54:55-57:19-61:3-62:11-63:7-64:15-66:11-67:26-68:34-68:47-73:20-81:20-92:19-98:8",185
657,141,"N","لَدَیْ ، لَدُنْ","«لَدَیْ ، لَدُنْ» Both words are identical. If «مِنْ» enters after «لَدَیْ», it changes to «لَدُنْ». For example, «مِنْ لَّدُنْکَ ، مِنْ لَّدُنَّا». If it comes without «مِنْ», then «لَدَیْ» is used. For example, «بِمَا لَدَیْھِمْ» or «لَدَا الْبَاب». This word is specific and extensive compared to «عِنْد» and indicates greater proximity (muf). Moreover, it also entails «تَمَکُّنْ» (i.e., the demand of desire). For instance: «لَدُنِّیْ مَالٌ» means If I had wealth with me... And «عِنْدِیْ مَالٌ» would mean that the wealth is in one's possession but is not present or immediately available (faq l 246).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّاَلۡفَیَا سَیِّدَہَا لَدَا الۡبَابِ» (12/25)\nTranslation: They both found the husband of Zulaikha at the door.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty states:\n«وَّاِذًالَّاٰتَیۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ لَّدُنَّـاۤ اَجۡرًا عَظِیۡمًا» (4/67)\nTranslation: And We will grant them a great reward from Our presence.","Before «لَدُنْ», «مِنْ» always comes, and this is used for the imminent.","Near","لدی ، لدن","12:25-40:18",2
658,141,"N","تِلْقَاء","«لَقِیَ یَلْقِیْ لِقَاءً» means the coming of something before something else, meeting, and «تِلْقَاء ، لِقَاء» is used in the meanings of opposite or facing. It is said that «جَلَسَ تِلْقَاءِیْ» means he sat before it or facing it. For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَلَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22) Translation: And when Moses turned his face toward Midian. And «تِلْقَاءَ نَفْس» means by itself, on its own. «فَعَلَ الْاَمْر مَنْ تلْقاءِ نَفْسِہٖ» He did the work by himself; no one helped him nor forced him. (Munjid) For example, the Noble Quran states: «قُلۡ مَا یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡۤ اَنۡ اُبَدِّلَہٗ مِنۡ تِلۡقَآیِٔ  نَفۡسِیۡ» (10/15) Translation: Say, it is not for me to change the Quran of my own accord.","«تِلْقَاء» to meet someone, to come face-to-face with, to coincidentally run into someone.","Near","تلقاء","7:47-10:15-21:103-28:22",4
659,141,"N","حَوْل","The basic meaning of «حَالَ» is change, movement, and transfer. And «حَوْلَ الشَّیْء» means the direction toward which something can be turned. (Muf.) Later, this word began to be used in the meanings of around something or near it. (Manj.) For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ» (2/17) Translation: Then when the fire lit the things around it, Allah extinguished the light of those people.","«حَوْل» to surround something or be in its vicinity.","Near","حول","2:17-3:159-6:92-8:24-9:101-9:120-17:1-19:68-26:25-26:34-27:8-29:67-39:75-40:7-42:7-46:27",16
660,142,"P","سُبْحَان","According to Ibn Faris, the fundamental meanings of the word «سَبَحَ» are two: (1) a form of worship, and (2) a form of running. (M. L.)\n\nImam Raghib, however, writes that the meaning of «سَبَحَ» is for something to swim or fly in water or air, or to pass through with swift movement. (Muf) «سَبَّاح» means a great swimmer/flyer. And «فَرَسٌ سَبُوْحٌ» refers to a horse that does not sway from side to side due to its speed in movement. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَہُوَالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الَّیۡلَ وَالنَّہَارَ وَالشَّمۡسَ وَالۡقَمَرَ ؕ کُلٌّ فِیۡ فَلَکٍ یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» (21:33)\nTranslation: And He it is Who created the night and the day, and the sun and the moon; all (i.e., the sun, the moon, and the stars) are swimming/flying in the celestial sphere.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَّالسّٰبِحٰتِ سَبۡحًا» (79:3)\nTranslation: And by those [angels] who swim/fly about (in the atmosphere) with swift motion.\n\nThen the usage of this word began to be applied to performing a task with speed and haste.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ لَکَ فِی النَّہَارِ سَبۡحًا طَوِیۡلًا» (73:7)\nTranslation: Indeed, during the day, you have lengthy occupations.","That essence which is free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and shortcomings, and that is only Allah.","Pure","سبحان","2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29",41
661,142,"P","سُبْحَان","«سُبْحَان» emanates from «سَبَح». Just as millions and millions of planets revolve at extremely high speeds in space originating from «غَفَر» to «غُفْرَان». Among them, there is neither vibration, nor oscillation, nor collision or impact. This clearly indicates that the governing entity controlling them, in its destiny, management, and administration, can only be a being of utmost firmness and free from all kinds of flaws or deficiencies. And this is the meaning of «سُبْحَان». Moreover, it is necessary that such a managing being, which administers the universe through its firm management, and if it so wills, can also introduce disruption and disorder into that administration. Therefore, the meaning of «سُبْحَان» is that being which is free from flaws and deficiencies, and is also the Absolute Sovereign over all, and holds complete control over all the entities of the universe.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَقَالُوااتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ وَلَدًا ۙ سُبۡحٰنَہٗ  ؕ بَلۡ لَّہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالۡاَرۡضِ  ؕ کُلٌّ لَّہٗ قٰنِتُوۡنَ» (2/116)\nTranslation: And these people assert that God has offspring. Exalted is He! Nay, whatsoever is in the heavens and the earth belongs to Him, and all are obedient to Him.\n\nAnd the coordinated and organized motion of the universe and all its entities bears witness that the governing being that administers them is a essence free from all kinds of flaws, deficiencies, and polytheism.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَبَّحَ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَمَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ وَہُوَالۡعَزِیۡزُالۡحَکِیۡمُ» (61/1)\nTranslation: Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth glorifies Him, and He is the Mighty, the Wise.\n\nThen, another aspect of this coherent and systematic functioning of the universe and all its entities is that its order, control, administration, and regularity—where even a moment's precedence is impossible in terms of delay—has no oscillation, no collision, and no impact. Upon witnessing all these things, man becomes immersed in a whirlpool of wonder, and involuntarily, his tongue begins to extol and praise the grandeur of this governing universe. Hence, the word «سُبْحَان» is also used at a juncture where the artistry and creation of the universe's Creator plunge man into a whirlpool of wonder. And generally, phrases like Glory be to Your Power are uttered on such occasions.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Glory be to the One Who took His servant by night from the Sacred Mosque (i.e., the Ka'bah) to the Farthest Mosque (i.e., Bayt al-Maqdis).\n\nAt this point, the use of Subhan is evidence that this journey was physical, not spiritual.","That «سُبْحَان» which is free from all imperfections.","Pure","سبحان","2:32-2:116-3:191-4:171-5:116-6:100-7:143-9:31-10:10-10:18-10:68-12:108-16:1-16:57-17:1-17:43-17:93-17:108-19:35-21:22-21:26-21:87-23:91-24:16-25:18-27:8-28:68-30:17-30:40-34:41-36:36-36:83-37:159-37:180-39:4-39:67-43:13-43:82-52:43-59:23-68:29",41
662,142,"P","قُدُّوْس","«قَدُسَ» means to be pure and immaculate (according to one interpretation), and according to the author of *Munjid*, it means to be pure and blessed.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ نَزَّلَہٗ رُوۡحُ الۡقُدُسِ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ بِالۡحَقِّ» (16:102)\nTranslation: (O Prophet!) Say, 'The Holy Spirit has brought it down with truth from your Lord...'\nHere, 'the Holy Spirit' refers to Gabriel (peace be upon him), who preserved Allah's word free from all mixture of impurity and filth and delivered it to the Prophets. That is why he is also called 'the Trustworthy Spirit' in another verse. And 'the Holy Land' refers to that pure and blessed land which became sanctified due to the birth and burial of Prophets and remained pure from the filth of polytheism because of their mission.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰقَوۡمِ ادۡخُلُوا الۡاَرۡضَ الۡمُقَدَّسَۃَ الَّتِیۡ کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ» (5:21)\nTranslation: (Moses) said, 'O my people! Enter the Holy Land (i.e., the land of Shaam), which Allah has assigned to you...'\nAnd «قُدُّوْس» is a name of Allah, the Most High, the meanings of which are: free from all imperfection and evil, and a Blessed and Sanctified Entity. (Munjid)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُسَبِّحُ لِلّٰہِ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡمَلِکِ الۡقُدُّوۡسِ الۡعَزِیۡزِالۡحَکِیۡمِ» (62:1)\nTranslation: Whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth glorifies Allah, the King, the Holy, the Almighty, the Wise.","«قُدُّوْس» The name of Allah, the Most High. A pure and blessed Entity or Station, free from polytheism and all other similar evils.","Pure","قدوس","2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-59:23-62:1-79:16",10
663,142,"P","زَکِیَّۃ","The meaning of «زَکٰی ، زُكُوًّا» is to grow, prosper, and be excellent. And «زَکّٰی» means to make something excellent, to improve it, and to advance it. And «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ» signifies self-praise or self-glorification.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُزَکُّوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ ہُوَاَعۡلَمُ بِمَنِ اتَّقٰی» (53:32)\nTranslation: Do not consider yourself pure. Indeed, Allah is fully aware of those who are pious. (Jalandhari)\nTranslation: So do not boast of your virtues; He knows well those who are saved. (Ottani)\n\nAnd «تَزْکِیَہ» is generally used for the nafs (self). And tazkiyah of the nafs means to cleanse the nafs from spiritual diseases, impurities, and bad morals, and to instill good qualities. (The scholar)\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ اَفۡلَحَ مَنۡ زَکّٰىہَا وَقَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ دَسّٰىہَا» (91:9-10)\nTranslation: Whoever purifies his nafs (i.e., soul) will succeed, and whoever tarnishes it with dust will be in loss.\n\nAnd the nafs zakiyyah is a person who is innocent and pure from all accusations.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ نَفۡسٍ ؕ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتَ شَیۡئًا نُّکۡرًا» (18:74)\nTranslation: (Moses pbuh said to Khidr) You have killed an innocent person without just cause. Indeed, you have done a terrible thing.","«زَکِیَّۃ» Purifying the self from evil traits and beautifying it.","pure","زکیۃ","2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18",26
664,142,"P","طُهُوْرُ","«طُهُوْرُ» refers to that which is pure and free from dirt, filth, and impurity; according to Imam Raghib, it is cleansed from perceptible impurity. The opposite of «طَھَرَ» is «دَنَسَ», meaning dirt, filth, and similar contaminants (m. l). For example, the Quran states: «وَسَقٰہُمۡ رَبُّہُمۡ شَرَابًا طَہُوۡرًا» (76:21). Translation: And their Lord will grant them a drink of the purest wine. Similarly, a woman's state of purity after menstruation or postpartum bleeding is also termed taharah. For example, the Quran declares: «فَاعۡتَزِلُوا النِّسَآءَ فِی الۡمَحِیۡضِ ۙ وَلَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» (2:222). Translation: So abstain from women during menstruation and do not intimate with them until they become pure. Furthermore, «طَھَّرَ» (the causative form) is employed to denote purification from both external and internal impurities. For instance, regarding the removal of external impurities, the divine command instructs: «وَرَبَّکَ فَکَبِّرۡ ۪وَثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ» (74:3-4). Translation: And exalt your Lord and keep your clothing pure. And for cleansing inner evils, the divine command proclaims: «اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ لِیُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمُ الرِّجۡسَ اَہۡلَ الۡبَیۡتِ وَیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ تَطۡہِیۡرًا» (33:33). Translation: O People of the Prophet's household! Allah desires to eliminate all impurity from you and purify you thoroughly, as purity is your rightful due.","to be pure and clean from impurities and filth","Pure","طھور","2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2",26
665,142,"P","طَیَّب","«طَابَ» means something that delights the heart, having a pleasant taste.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3)  \nTranslation: Then marry those women who please you. (Uthmani)  \n\nAnd «طِیْب» means fragrance (manjad), and «طِیِّبَۃ» refers to the happiness and pleasure of the heart (M. Q.), and «طَیِّب» refers to everything that is delightful, pure, and lawful (M.F.), and its opposite is «خَبِیْث».  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا کُلُوۡا مِنۡ طَیِّبٰتِ مَا رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ» (2/172)  \nTranslation: O believers! Eat the pure things that We have provided for you.  \n\nAnd «بَلَدَۃً طَٰیِّبَۃً» refers to a city that is clean, tidy, beautiful in appearance, has a clean environment, and is fertile.","«طَیَّب» A thing pure from external impurities, lawful and pleasant.","Pure","طیب","2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:3-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12",43
666,142,"P","مَحَصَ","«مَحَصَ» means to purify something from impurity, dirt, and adulteration. And «مَحَصَ الذَّھَبَ» means to purify gold by placing it in a crucible, melting it over fire, and removing all dross and alloy from it to make it pure (as explained in the lexicon).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَلِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَیَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (3/141)\nTranslation: So that Allah may purify the believers [of their sins] and make them sincere, and destroy the disbelievers.\n\nAt this point, Allah is addressing the practical weaknesses of the Muslims and guiding them toward improvement. Thus, the meaning implied by «مَحَّصَ» is to purify a person in their practical life from weaknesses and deficiencies.","«مَحَصَ» to purify something from both external and internal impurities and weaknesses.","Pure","محص","3:141-3:154",2
667,142,"P","زَکیّٰ","By «زَکیّٰ» is meant purifying the self from spiritual impurities, diseases, and bad morals.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«قَدْ اَفْلَحَ مَنْ تَزَكّٰى» (87:14)  \nTranslation: Indeed, he has attained success who purifies himself.","«زَکیّٰ» meaning to purify the self from bad morals.","Pure","زکی","2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18",26
668,142,"P","طَھَّرَ","The term «طَھَّرَ» encompasses not only the removal of physical impurities but also the purification of the heart from polytheism and satanic insinuations. These details have been elaborated in «طُهُوْرُ».","«طَھَّرَ» Purification from both external and internal impurities, as well as from polytheism and insidious whispers.","Pure","طھر","2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2",26
669,142,"P","صَفَا","«صَفَّا» means for something to be pure and free from all kinds of mixtures (intransitive), and «صَفّٰی» means to make something pure and clean (transitive). For example, honey is purified from wax and pollen.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَنۡہٰرٌ مِّنۡ عَسَلٍ مُّصَفًّی» ( 47/15 )\nTranslation: And (in Paradise) there will be rivers of clear, pure honey.","«صَفَّا» denotes being pure and free from any admixture.","Pure","صفا","47:15",1
670,142,"P","بَرَّاَ","«بَرِءَ» means to recover from illness, and «اَبْرَاَ» means to make healthy, and «بَرَّأَ» means to clear someone from blame or defect (i.e., to absolve someone from a crime) (manjīd. muf).  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«فَبَرَّاَہُ اللّٰہُ مِمَّا قَالُوۡا ؕ وَکَانَ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ وَجِیۡہًا» ( 33/69 )  \nTranslation: So Allah exalted Moses from the accusation of the people and proved him blameless, and he was honored in the sight of Allah.","To clear someone of slander or fault.","Pure","برا","33:69",1
671,143,"T","وَجَدَ","«وَجَدَ» is a word commonly used to mean 'to find' or 'to see' something, and it can be employed everywhere.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَ عَلَیۡہَا زَکَرِیَّا الۡمِحۡرَابَ ۙ وَجَدَ عِنۡدَہَا رِزۡقًا» (3:37)  \nTranslation: Whenever Zakariya (peace be upon him) would come to her (Maryam, peace be upon her) in the sanctuary, he would find provisions with her.","«وَجَدَ» to find or see something present.","to get","وجد","3:37-4:64-4:82-4:89-5:104-7:28-7:44-7:102-9:5-10:78-12:65-12:75-12:79-18:49-18:65-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-21:53-24:39-26:74-27:23-27:24-28:15-28:23-31:21-38:44-43:22-43:23-43:24-51:36-72:8-93:7-93:8",35
672,143,"T","ثَقَفَ","«ثَقَفَ» meaning to act with prudence and skill in obtaining something or performing a task (singular), and «ثَقَفَ» refers to an expert and master of warfare and conflict (composite). «ثَقِیْف» meaning wise (prudent) and alert, and «ثَقَافَتْ» meaning wisdom (prudence) and skill. «ثَقَفَ» also means to thoroughly know someone and gain victory over them (composite).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ ثَقِفۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ وَاَخۡرِجُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ حَیۡثُ اَخۡرَجُوۡکُمۡ» (2/191)\nTranslation: And kill them wherever you find them, and expel them from where they have expelled you.\n\nAt another instance, for exactly such a situation, the word «وَجَدَ» was used instead of «ثَقَفَ», which indicates the generality of «وَجَدَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ» (4/89)\nTranslation: So seize them and kill them wherever you find them.","«ثَقَفَ» to skillfully obtain something. And to capture desired individuals during war.","to get","ثقف","2:191-3:112-4:91-8:57-33:61-60:2",6
673,143,"T","اَلْفٰی","«لفو» means the removal of a veil from something and its becoming apparent (m. l.), and «اَلْفٰی» means something coming into knowledge spontaneously or something appearing.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ وَّ اَلۡفَیَا سَیِّدَہَا لَدَا الۡبَابِ» (12/25)\nTranslation: And they both ran towards the door, and she seized his shirt from behind and tore it from the back. And they both met the husband of the woman at the door.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا بَلۡ نَتَّبِعُ مَاۤ اَلۡفَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» (2/170)\nTranslation: They say, Rather, we will follow that upon which we found our fathers.\n\nIn this verse, the usage of «اَلْفٰی» is from the perspective that the matter was inherited by them from generation to generation. At another instance, in a completely similar context, the word «وَجَدَ» was used instead of «اَلْفٰی», which indicates generality.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا حَسۡبُنَا مَا وَجَدۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» (5/104)\nTranslation: They say, The way upon which we found our fathers is sufficient for us.","«اَلْفٰی» to find something by chance; to find something when the veil is lifted; to find something spontaneously.","to attain","الفی","2:170-12:25-37:69",3
674,143,"T","اَدْرَک","«دَرَکَ» and «دَرَجَ» are two names for the same thing. When ascending from bottom to top on stairs, it is «دَرَجَ» or «دَرَجَۃً». And when descending from top to bottom, it is «دَرَکَ». Therefore, the phrase «دَرَجَاتُ الْجَنَّۃ» and «دَرَکَاتُ النَّار» is used (detailed).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «اِنَّ الۡمُنٰفِقِیۡنَ فِی الدَّرۡکِ الۡاَسۡفَلِ مِنَ النَّارِ» (4/145)\nTranslation: Indeed, the hypocrites will be in the lowest depths of Hell.\n\nAnd the meaning of «اَدْرَکَ» is to gradually reach the extreme degree of something, or to attain something, or to reach something at its proper time. (detailed) «اَدْرَکَ الثَّمَرُ» means the ripening of fruit, and «اَدْرَکَ الْوَلَد» means the boy reaching puberty. (Manjad) And Ibn al-Faris explains its meaning as to catch up with or overtake something (i.e., to seize, grasp, or comprehend). (m. l) See further details in Gharana.\n\nFor example: The divine command is: «لَا تُدۡرِکُہُ الۡاَبۡصَارُ وَہُوَ یُدۡرِکُ الۡاَبۡصَارَ» (6/103)\nTranslation: Eyes cannot perceive Him, but He perceives the eyes. (Uthmani)","«اَدْرَکَ» meaning to reach the utmost limit of something and attain it.","to attain","ادرک","4:78-4:100-4:145-6:103-10:90-20:77-26:61-36:40",8
675,144,"W","حَمِیْم","«حَمِیْم» means the heating of water, and «حَمّٰی» refers to fever or steam (Minjad). And «حَمِیْم» is used for water that becomes intensely hot due to sunlight (in wells, etc.), sometimes becoming foul-smelling as well. The scholar of language and fiqh defines its meaning as extremely hot water.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیْنَ كَفَرُوْا لَهُمْ شَرَابٌ مِّنْ حَمِیْمٍ» (10/4)\nTranslation: And for those who disbelieved is a drink of scalding water.","«حَمِیْم» is what we call hot water.","Water","حمیم","6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25",19
676,144,"W","غَسَّاق","«غَسَّاق» is generally translated as pus or stagnant pus. However, the author of Fiqh-ul-Lughah and the author of Munjid both state that its meaning is cold and foul-smelling water (F L 260. Munjid). This meaning is also corroborated by the Holy Quran, as the words «حَمِیْم» and «غَسَّاق» are used twice in opposition to each other in the Quran.\n\nExample of «حَمِیْم»: The divine command is:\n«لَا یَذُوۡقُوۡنَ فِیۡہَا بَرۡدًا وَّلَا شَرَابًا اِلَّا حَمِیۡمًا وَّغَسَّاقًا» (78/24,25)\nTranslation: There, they will not taste any coolness, nor will there be any drink except boiling water and flowing pus. (Jalandhari)\n\nExample of «غَسَّاق»: The divine command is:\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ ہٰذَا ۙ فَلۡیَذُوۡقُوۡہُ حَمِیۡمٌ وَّغَسَّاقٌ» (38/56,57)\nTranslation: Hell, wherein they will enter, is an evil resting place. It is a place of scalding water and pus. So let them taste it. (Jalandhari)","«غَسَّاق» cold and foul-smelling water or pus.","Water","غساق","38:57-78:25",2
677,144,"W","اٰنٍ ۔ اٰنِیَۃٍ","The meaning of «اَنٰی» is to ripen or that its time is approaching. And «اٰنٍ» refers to extremely hot water that begins to boil.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَطُوۡفُوۡنَ بَیۡنَہَا وَ بَیۡنَ حَمِیۡمٍ اٰنٍ» (55/44)\nTranslation: They will circle between Hell and boiling hot water.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«تَصۡلٰی نَارًا حَامِیَۃً تُسۡقٰی مِنۡ عَیۡنٍ اٰنِیَۃٍ» (88/4,5)\nTranslation: They will enter a raging fire. They will be given water from a boiling spring to drink.","«اٰنٍ» meaning flowing water.","Water","انٍ ۔ انیۃٍ","55:44-88:5",2
678,144,"W","غَوْر","That water which is in the depths below the earth. (Fal 259) And the author of Munjid writes the meaning of «غَوْر» as water that is absorbed in the earth.","«غَوْر» meaning the water that exists beneath the earth.","Water","غور","18:41-67:30",2
679,144,"W","مَعِیْن","«مَعَنَ» means water flowing gently (manjad), and «مَعِیْن» is water that flows on the earth's surface (f l 259), not with the force and speed of a flood, but flowing with gentleness and ease (m . l).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (67/30)  \nTranslation: Say, 'Then have you considered: if your water were to dry up, who would bring you a spring of sweet water?'","«مَعِیْن» meaning water flowing gently on the surface of the earth.","Water","معین","23:50-37:45-56:18-67:30",4
680,144,"W","عَذْبٌ","«عَذْبٌ» Sweet, pleasant, and cool water that one longs to drink.","«عَذْبٌ» meaning cold and sweet water.","Water","عذب","25:53-35:12",2
681,144,"W","فُرَاتٌ","«فُرَاتٌ» means sea. It is also the name of a great river that flows into the Persian Gulf, and «فُرَاتَان» refers to the Tigris and Euphrates rivers. The meaning of «فَرَتِ الْمَاءِ» is for water to be very sweet and pleasant (manjad). Thus, the quality of «عَذْبٌ» is a characteristic of «فُرَاتٌ» when it is present in a sufficiently large quantity.","meaning cold and sweet water when it is abundant.","water","فرات","25:53-35:12-77:27",3
682,144,"W","مِلْحٌ","«مِلْحٌ» brackish water. Salty water, seawater, salt water (F. L 33)","«مِلْحٌ» Salty water is sea water.","Water","ملح","25:53-35:12",2
683,144,"W","اُجَاج","«اُجَاجٌ» meaning such water which is both salty and bitter (fl 33) very salty and hot water. Burning the chest (muf).\nFor instance, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ مَا یَسۡتَوِی الۡبَحۡرٰنِ ٭ۖ ہٰذَا عَذۡبٌ فُرَاتٌ سَآئِغٌ  شَرَابُہٗ  وَہٰذَا مِلۡحٌ اُجَاجٌ» (35/12)\nTranslation: 'And the two seas are not equal. This one is sweet, thirst-quenching, its water is pleasant. And this one is salty, bitter, brackish.'","«اُجَاجٌ» brackish and bitter water.","water","اجاج","25:53-35:12-56:70",3
684,144,"W","اَوْدِیَۃ","«وَادِی» is the plural. Actually, wadi originally refers to that broad valley which lies between mountains, as well as to the slope that is between mountains and in which water flows. (Muf) Due to its location between mountains, it is necessary for rivers and streams to flow through this valley. These are the very channels through which rainwater and meltwater from mountain snow flow. The word wadi is sometimes used solely in the sense of the wide middle plain, and at other times in the sense of rivers and streams.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)\nTranslation: He sent down rain from the sky, and then from it the rivers and streams flowed out according to their respective capacities.","«اَوْدِیَۃ» meaning a river or stream.","Water","اودیۃ","13:17-46:24",2
685,144,"W","عَیْن","«عَیْن» means spring. If water emerges from a mountain or the ground at a certain place and collects in a low-lying area, it is a spring. Springs can also be so large that rivers and streams begin to flow from them. Such a spring is called a lake in modern times, and its plural is «عُیُوْن».\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا بَلَغَ  مَغۡرِبَ الشَّمۡسِ وَجَدَہَا تَغۡرُبُ فِیۡ عَیۡنٍ حَمِئَۃٍ» (18/86)\nTranslation: When Dhul-Qarnayn reached the setting place of the sun, he found it setting in a spring of hot and fetid water.\n\nAnd according to historical research, this was the location where the Aegean Sea assumes the form of small streams. Here, the Quran has used the word «عَیْن» instead of «بَحْر», which is consistent with the lexical meaning of «عَیْن» (i.e., spring).","«عَیْن» spring, lake, etc.","Water","عین","2:60-7:160-15:45-18:86-26:57-26:134-26:147-34:12-36:34-44:25-44:52-51:15-54:12-55:50-55:66-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12",21
686,144,"W","اَنْھٰر","The plural of «نَھْر» is «اَنْھَار». That is, the large canal into which numerous streams from various directions merge for the flow of water. The term «نَھْر» is generally applied to such a major canal whose flow path humans construct through their own efforts according to their needs. Rivers are either drawn from some very large reservoir spring or lake situated between mountains, or from rivers.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«عَیۡنًا یَّشۡرَبُ بِہَا عِبَادُ اللّٰہِ یُفَجِّرُوۡنَہَا تَفۡجِیۡرًا» (76/6)\nTranslation: This will be a spring from which the servants of Allah will drink, and they will take out (small) streams from it to their own places.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/25)\nTranslation: Gardens beneath which rivers flow.","«نَھْر» is a well-known term. It refers to a large canal for the flow of water, into which many streams from various directions converge and merge.","Water","انھر","2:25-2:74-2:249-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:85-5:119-6:6-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-13:3-13:35-14:23-14:32-16:15-16:31-17:91-18:31-18:33-20:76-22:14-22:23-25:10-27:61-29:58-39:20-43:51-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-54:54-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-71:12-85:11-98:8",51
687,144,"W","سَرِیٌّ","In «سَرِیٌّ», two concepts are found: (1) moving at night, and (2) being small. «سَرِيَّةُ» means both a small army and a small boat. Its plural is «سَرَایَا». And «سَارِیَہ» means a small army that sets out at night. And «سَرِیٌّ» also means a small flowing river (manjad. f l 36).\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ سَرِیًّا» (19/24)\nTranslation: Your Lord has caused a spring to gush forth beneath you.","«سَرِیٌّ» meaning a small canal.","Water","سری","19:24",1
688,144,"W","یَمّ","The meaning of «یَمّ» is, according to most lexicographers, a very large reservoir of water; they write (river, sea) (Mufradat, Manjad). However, in our opinion, the term «یَمّ» is applied to that reservoir of water which is flowing towards a low-lying area, i.e., a river.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَنِ اقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی التَّابُوۡتِ فَاقۡذِفِیۡہِ فِی الۡیَمِّ فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ یَاۡخُذۡہُ عَدُوٌّ لِّیۡ وَ عَدُوٌّ لَّہٗ» ( 20/39 )\nTranslation: (We revealed to the mother of Musa, Suckle him; then when you fear for him, put him in a chest and cast the chest into the river...) (Sahih International)\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Exalted is:\n«وَ قَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ ۫ فَبَصُرَتۡ بِہٖ عَنۡ جُنُبٍ  وَّ ہُمۡ لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» ( 28/11 )\nTranslation: And the mother of Musa said to his sister, Follow him; so she watched him from a distance while they perceived not. (Sahih International)\n\nThese verses prove that «یَمّ» refers to that body of water which flows like a river, stream, or canal towards a low-lying area. And for this, in our language, the word 'river' is specific.","«یَمّ» a large reservoir of water that flows toward a depression.","water","یم","7:136-20:39-20:78-20:97-28:7-28:40-51:40",7
689,144,"W","بَحْر","«بَحْر» Its plural is «اَبْحُرْ». Lexicographers also state that the meaning of «بَحْر» is river or ocean. However, in contemporary usage, «بَحْر» refers to that large reservoir of water which accumulates in a low-lying area and continually receives water from all sides. Water accumulating in a low-lying area, if in a small quantity, is called a *joħṛ*; if in a larger quantity, a *jheel* (lake); if even larger, «بُحَیْرَہ»—meaning a small sea; and if in a very large quantity, it is called «بَحْر». In the Quran, the same word «بَحْر» has been used for both «بُحَیْرَہ» and «بَحْر».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (2/50)\nTranslation: And (O Children of Israel, remember) when We parted the sea for you and saved you, and drowned the people of Pharaoh.\nAnd historical research indicates that this sea was the *Bahr al-Qulzum* (Red Sea).\n\nThe water gathered in a sea is sometimes stagnant. Often, winds create waves in it and keep it in motion. Although this motion is not towards any low-lying area. Furthermore, within the gathered waters of the sea, there also flow rivers (with a downward slope/slope towards the depression), and sometimes two rivers flow together side by side. In these, one is warm water and the other cold. Or one is sweet water and the other bitter. And they do not mix with each other. Although this too is contrary to the natural property of water. And all of this occurs under the perfect power of Allah Almighty. Referring to this very fact, the Divine declaration states:\n«مَرَجَ  الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ بَیۡنَہُمَا بَرۡزَخٌ  لَّا  یَبۡغِیٰنِ» (55:19,20)\nTranslation: He has released the two seas, meeting together. Between them is a barrier so they do not transgress.\nIn this verse, the Quran has used the word «بَحْر» for the river. This is because such rivers flow within the sea.","The term «بَحْر» is used for the sea or river.","water","بحر","2:50-2:164-5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-7:138-7:163-10:22-10:90-14:32-16:14-17:66-17:67-17:70-18:60-18:61-18:63-18:79-18:109-20:77-22:65-24:40-25:53-26:63-27:61-27:63-30:41-31:27-31:31-35:12-42:32-44:24-45:12-52:6-55:19-55:24-81:6-82:3",39
690,144,"W","اِسْتَسْقٰی","«سَقٰی» means to give someone water to drink, and «اَسْقٰی» means to give water to another person for drinking. And «اِسْتَسْقٰی» means to ask for water to drink.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ» (2/60)\nTranslation: And when Moses, peace be upon him, asked for water for his people (from Allah), We said: Strike the rock with your staff.","«اِسْتَسْقٰی» meaning to ask for water to drink.","Water","استسقی","2:60-2:71-7:160-9:19-12:41-12:70-13:4-14:16-15:22-16:66-23:21-25:49-26:79-28:23-28:24-28:25-47:15-72:16-76:17-76:21-77:27-83:25-88:5-91:13",24
691,144,"W","اِسْتَغَاث","«غَیْث» This rain is referred to as that which occurs at the time of need and in accordance with the need (neither less nor more) (F L 258. M L). And «غَیْث» it is also used for the grass and vegetation that grows from this rain. (Munjid. M. Q). And «غَاثَ اللہُ الْبِلَاد» meaning: Allah Almighty sent rain upon the land. (Munjid). And «اِسْتِغَاث» meaning: To cry out for such rain or to ask for water in the manner of a cry.  \nFor example: It is stated in the Quran:  \n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ» (18/29)  \nTranslation: If they were to cry out for water, they would be given water like molten copper, scalding [their faces].","«اِسْتِغَاث» To cry out or supplicate for water.","Water","استغاث","8:9-18:29-28:15-46:17",4
692,145,"F","رِجْلٌ","The part from below the ankle down to the toes of the foot is referred to as such (singular), and its plural is «اَرْجُلٌ».\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اُرۡکُضۡ بِرِجۡلِکَ ۚ ہٰذَا مُغۡتَسَلٌۢ بَارِدٌ وَّ شَرَابٌ» (38/42)\nTranslation: (We said to Job) Strike the ground with your foot. This is a cool spring for bathing and a refreshing drink.\n\nAnd «رَجُلٌ» means 'man', and its plural is «رِجَالٌ». And if «رِجَالًا» is used as an adjective, its meaning will be 'on foot' (pedestrian), and its opposite is «رُکْبَانًا» (meaning 'mounted').\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ  فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ  رُکۡبَانًا» (2/239)\nTranslation: If you are in a state of fear, then pray on foot or mounted (in whatever condition you are in).","The area from just below the ankle to the toes is referred to as «رِجْلٌ».","foot","رجل","2:239-5:6-5:33-5:66-6:65-7:124-7:195-17:64-20:71-22:27-24:24-24:31-24:45-26:49-29:55-36:65-38:42-60:12",18
693,145,"F","قَدَمَ","The distance between the back and front feet while walking is called «قَدَمَ». Its plural is «اَقْدَام» (singular), and in English, the word FOOT is used for both «رِجْل» and «قَدَمَ». A foot is also a unit of measurement equal to 12 inches in length. Therefore, in modern Arabic, this unit of measurement is also called «قَدَمَ». The Arabic translation for forty feet is «اَرْبَعِیْنَ اَقْدَام» (Al-Qamus Al-Jadid). When «قَدَمَ» is used as a verb, it means to advance and move forward. As a noun, «قَدَمَ» is also used for «رِجْلٌ», meaning foot. Thus, the difference between «رِجْل» and «قَدَمَ» is exactly like that between «عَیْن» and «بَصَر», the details of which have been discussed in Eye.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یُعۡرَفُ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ فَیُؤۡخَذُ بِالنَّوَاصِیۡ وَ الۡاَقۡدَامِ» (55:41)\nTranslation: The sinners will be recognized by their faces and will be seized by the forelocks and feet.","«قَدَمَ» the part of the leg that rests on the ground.","Foot","قدم","16:94",1
694,146,"S","حَجَر","«حَجَرَ» means hard stone, and its plurals are «اَحْجَار» and «حِجَارَۃ» (singular).  \nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اِنَّ مِنَ الۡحِجَارَۃِ لَمَا یَتَفَجَّرُ مِنۡہُ الۡاَنۡہٰرُ » (2/74)  \nTranslation: And some stones are such that rivers gush forth from them.","«حَجَرَ» a hard and large stone.","Stone","حجر","2:24-2:60-2:74-7:160-8:32-11:82-15:74-17:50-51:33-66:6-105:4",11
695,146,"S","حَصْب","«حَصْب» means small stones, pebbles, and «حَاصِب» refers to that fierce and sharp wind which carries such pebbles. In the Quran, the word «حَاصِب» has been used for a rain of stones and pebbles.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَمۡ اَمِنۡتُمۡ مَّنۡ فِی السَّمَآءِ اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (67/17)\nTranslation: Or have you become secure from the One who is in the heaven that He will not send upon you a storm of stones?","«حَصْب» small pebbles and tiny little stones.","Stone","حصب","17:68-21:98-29:40-54:34-67:17",5
696,146,"S","سِجِّیْل","«سِجِّیْل» meaning pebbles. (Abbreviation: مف ۔ منجد) i.e., those pointed pebbles in which soil is also mixed, and from the soil, pebbles are being formed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا جَعَلۡنَا عَالِیَہَا سَافِلَہَا وَاَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا حِجَارَۃً  مِّنۡ سِجِّیۡلٍ ۬ ۙ مَّنۡضُوۡدٍ» (11/82)\nTranslation: So when Our command came, We turned that town upside down and rained upon it stones, layer upon layer.","«سِجِّیْل» sharp pebbles of earth.","stone","سجیل","11:82-15:74-105:4",3
697,147,"P","اٰخِر","«اٰخِر» is the final part or end of anything. And its opposite is «اَوَّلْ». Generality is found in this word. It is used as a temporal expression (i.e., its relation is towards time) (Manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُلَّۃٌ مِّنَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَ ثُلَّۃٌ مِّنَ الۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ» (56/39,40)\nTranslation: It is among many of the earlier people and among many of the later people.","«اٰخِر» the final part or end of anything.","previous","اخر","3:72-5:114-10:10-26:84-37:78-37:108-37:119-37:129-43:56-56:14-56:40-56:49-57:3-77:17",14
698,147,"P","خَلَفَ","«خَلَفَ» means to be a successor (deputy, representative) and the generation that comes after the same nation or group. And its opposite is «سَلَفَ». The word «خَلْف» is generally used in a negative sense, meaning unfit and unworthy generations, or na-khlaaf.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ غَیًّا» (19:59)\nTranslation: Then after them, some unfit successors arose who abandoned prayer and followed their desires. So they will soon receive the punishment of misguidance.\n\nAnd the opposite of «خَلْف» is also «بَیْنَ یَدَیْ» or «بَیْنَ اَیْدِی», and these words appear in both temporal (time) and spatial (place) contexts. In the temporal sense, «خَلْف» refers to the later people without any specific distinction.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَمَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2:66)\nTranslation: So We have made this story a lesson for the people of this era and for the later ones.\n\nBut in contrast to «بَیْنَ یَدَیْ», if «خَلْف» is used as a spatial preposition, its meaning is not later but behind.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَمِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (13:11)\nTranslation: Before it and behind it are guardians from Allah, who protect it by His command.","«خَلَفَ» meaning to be a successor (representative, deputy).","Previous","خلف","2:66-2:255-3:170-4:9-6:133-7:17-7:69-7:74-7:129-7:142-7:150-7:169-8:57-9:81-9:118-9:120-10:92-11:57-13:11-19:59-19:64-20:97-20:110-21:28-22:76-24:55-25:62-27:62-34:9-36:9-36:45-41:14-41:25-41:42-43:60-46:21-48:11-48:15-48:16-57:7-72:27",41
699,148,"T","نَدَمَ","«نَدَمَ» Regretting a bad deed one has committed is a common expression. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَعَسَی اللّٰہُ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ بِالۡفَتۡحِ اَوۡ اَمۡرٍ مِّنۡ عِنۡدِہٖ فَیُصۡبِحُوۡا عَلٰی  مَاۤ اَسَرُّوۡا فِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ نٰدِمِیۡنَ» (5/52) Translation: Thus, it is likely that God will bring victory or a command from Himself, and then they will regret what they had concealed in their hearts.","«نَدَمَ» To repent or feel remorse for a wrongful act.","to repent","ندم","5:31-5:52-23:40-26:157-49:6",5
700,148,"T","حَسِرَ","The author of *Fiqh al-Lughah* explains its meaning as «اَشَدُّ النَّدَامَۃ» (to be extremely regretful). (f.l.m) However, the author of *Al-Munjid* writes that the meanings of «حَسِرَ» and «حَسْرَۃ» are to regret. That is, «حَسْرۃ» refers to the expression of regret and remorse over one's own actions.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا ۙ وَ ہُمۡ یَحۡمِلُوۡنَ اَوۡزَارَہُمۡ عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہِمۡ» (6:31)\nTranslation: They will say, Alas, our regret over what we neglected concerning it! And their state will be that they will bear their burdens on their backs.","«حَسْرَۃ» utmost regret and its expression.","to repent","حسر","2:167-3:156-6:31-8:36-19:39-35:8-36:30-39:56-69:50",9
701,148,"T","سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ","This is an idiom that means to feel ashamed and humiliated before people when one's own statement or argument is proven wrong.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ لَمَّا سُقِطَ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ رَاَوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ ضَلُّوۡا» (7/149)  \nTranslation: And when they were filled with remorse and saw that they had gone astray.","«سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ» to be left with a sense of shame and regret upon recognizing the error in one's words or argument, feeling distressed.","to repent","سقط فی یدہٖ","7:149",1
702,149,"O","بَلِیَ ( یَبْلٰی بَلَاءً )","«بَلِیَ» refers to something becoming old and worn out from being in continuous use. «بَلَی الثَّوْب» means the state of clothing becoming old and worn out (manj. muf). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «قَالَ یٰۤـاٰدَمُ ہَلۡ اَدُلُّکَ عَلٰی شَجَرَۃِ الۡخُلۡدِ وَ مُلۡکٍ لَّا یَبۡلٰی» (20/120) Translation: Satan said, O Adam! Shall I inform you of the tree of eternal life and a kingdom that does not grow old? (Osmaniؒ)","«بَلِیَ» to become old from use.","Old","بلی ( یبلی بلاءً )","20:120",1
703,149,"O","قَدِیْم","«قَدِیْم» means ancient, of old times, old, and its opposite is «جَدِیْد» (meaning new). «قَدَمَ» means to advance, and «قَدُمَ» means to become old. (Munjid)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ اِنَّکَ لَفِیۡ ضَلٰلِکَ الۡقَدِیۡمِ» (12/95)\nTranslation: They said, By Allah, you are still in your old error.","«قَدِیْم» old, of old times, for ages.","Old","قدیم","12:95-36:39-46:11",3
704,149,"O","عَتِیْق","«اَلْعِتْقُ» The meaning of the root is: to be pure in origin, beauty, nobility, majesty. Ancient. (Majid) «عَتِیْق» That is the thing which, despite being ancient and old, suffers no decline in its nobility and majesty. It is for this reason that the Kaaba is called «بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق». For example, in the Holy Quran: «ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ وَلۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22/29) Translation: Then let the pilgrims cleanse themselves of impurity, fulfill their vows, and circumambulate the Ancient House (i.e., the House of Allah).","Despite its old age, «عَتِیْق» remains unchanged in honor and greatness.","Old","عتیق","22:29-22:33",2
705,150,"C","غِطَاء","«غِطَاء» refers to every thing that is placed to cover or lid something and covers it completely. (e.g.) such as the lid of a pot, and this term is generally applied to things that are open on one side; if something is placed on it to cover it completely, then it is «غِطَاء». For «غِطَاء», it is necessary that it be thick as well, so that by covering completely, it conceals (Fiqh, p. 238).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22)\nTranslation: So have We removed from you your covering, and your sight today is sharp.","«غِطَاء» covering something completely where one part is vacant.","Curtain","غطاء","18:101-50:22-79:29",3
706,150,"V","غِشَاوَۃ","«غَشِی» signifies covering something with such a thin layer that it remains somewhat visible. (Fiqh, p. 238) And this is generally derived from 'ghitā'. «غَشِی» also refers to the condition where the senses are veiled yet still respond. Similarly, this veil can also consist of clothing, darkness, etc. This term is used in both literal and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«خَتَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ وَعَلٰی سَمۡعِہِمۡ ؕ  وَعَلٰۤی اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ غِشَاوَۃٌ» (2/7)\nTranslation: God has sealed their hearts and ears, and a veil lies over their eyes.","To cover something with such a thin cloth that it is still somewhat visible.","veil","غشاوۃ","2:7-3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-45:23-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1",23
707,150,"P","غَلَفَ","«غَلَفَ» means to cover something completely from all sides so that it is entirely hidden. «غَلَّفْتُ السَّیْف» For example, I sheathed the sword (trans.). And «غِلَاف» is that in which something is concealed. Its plural is «غُلْف».\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا قُلُوۡبُنَا غُلۡفٌ ؕ بَلۡ لَّعَنَہُمُ اللّٰہُ بِکُفۡرِہِمۡ» (2/88)\nTranslation: And the Jews say, Our hearts are covered (i.e., not receptive). No, but Allah has cursed them for their disbelief.","«غَلَفَ» that which completely envelops something from all sides.","Partition","غلف","2:88-4:155",2
708,150,"C","اَکْمَام","«کَمَّ» means to conceal, and «کَمَّ الْبَعِیْر» means to put a cloth (a mend) on a camel's mouth. The word «کَمِّ» is used for the coverings of dates. Its plural is «اَکْمَام».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فِیۡہَا فَاکِہَۃٌ ۪ۙ  وَّ النَّخۡلُ  ذَاتُ الۡاَکۡمَامِ» (55/11)\n\nTranslation: In it there are fruit trees and date-palms whose fruits have coverings.","the layers above the fruits of the trees","Curtain","اکمام","41:47-55:11",2
709,150,"C","اَکِنَّۃً","«کَنَّ الشَّیْ» means to hide something in a secure place and protect it from the sun. And «کَنَّ فِیْ نَفْسِہٖ» means to conceal something within the heart (manjada), and this term refers to a place where protection or refuge is obtained. Its plural forms are «اَکْنَان» and «اَکِنَّۃ» is derived from it. Thus, this word is used in both literal and spiritual contexts.\n\nExample of literal usage:\nThe command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَاللّٰہُ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ  مِّمَّا خَلَقَ ظِلٰلًا وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ  مِّنَ  الۡجِبَالِ  اَکۡنَانًا» (16/81)\nTranslation: And Allah has made for you shades from the things He has created and has made for you caves in the mountains.\n\nExample of spiritual usage:\nThe command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا قُلُوۡبُنَا فِیۡۤ  اَکِنَّۃٍ  مِّمَّا تَدۡعُوۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِ» (41/5)\nTranslation: And they say, That to which you invite us is [covered] over our hearts.","«اَکِنَّۃ» protective coverings and spaces.","Curtain","اکنۃً","2:235-6:25-16:81-17:46-18:57-41:5",6
710,150,"C","سِتْرًا","«سَتَرَ» means to conceal and to veil. «سِتْر» also refers to a shield (منجد), and also to that which provides cover or performs the function of a veil (مف). «سُتْرَۃ» refers to the barrier that a worshipper places in front of themselves during prayer. «سُتْرَۃُ السَّطْح» is the term for the veil wall on a roof (منجد), implying that in «سَتَرَ» nothing is entirely concealed from view. Moreover, «سَتَرَ» does not necessarily pertain to another thing, whereas «حِجَاب» is associated with other things (فق 238).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَجَدَہَا تَطۡلُعُ عَلٰی قَوۡمٍ لَّمۡ نَجۡعَلۡ لَّہُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِہَا سِتۡرًا» (18:90). Translation: Until, when he reached the place where the sun rises, he found it rising upon a people for whom We had not made any veil.","«سِتْرا» means to hide and to cover.","Curtain","سترًا","18:90",1
711,150,"V","حَجَاب","The meaning of «حَجَبَ» is to prevent something from reaching a destination and to become an obstacle in between. And «حَاجِب» refers to a gatekeeper or sentinel (as in Mufradat al-Quran). The meaning of «حَجَبَ» is to place a veil between two things in such a way that one cannot see the other nor reach it. The commandments regarding the veil from women are referred to as the 'Verse of the Hijab'. The meaning of Hijab is that a sheet or any other garment should be lowered from the eyes to such an extent that a woman can see the path, but a person walking on the path cannot see her, nor can any man see her face or body, etc. Similarly, any screen or barrier that fulfills this purpose is a Hijab. In other words, Hijab is a veil between two things that makes it prohibited for one to see and reach the other.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا سَاَلۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ مَتَاعًا فَسۡئَلُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ حِجَابٍ» (33:53)\nTranslation: And when you ask [the wives of the Prophet] for something, ask them from behind a partition.","«حِجَاب» is a veil through which one thing cannot be seen from or reached by another.","Veil","حجاب","7:46-17:45-19:17-33:53-38:32-41:5-42:51",7
712,150,"C","عَوْرَۃ","«اَلْعَوَارُ وَالْعَوْرَۃُ» means to have a tear (in clothing) or a crack (in a building); to develop a rift or opening.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ بُیُوۡتَنَا عَوۡرَۃٌ  ؕ وَ مَا ہِیَ بِعَوۡرَۃٍ» (33:13)\nTranslation: That our houses are open (and exposed), although they were not open.\nMeaning there were no tears or rifts in those houses through which someone could intrude.\n\nAnd «عَوْرَۃ» means anything that causes a sense of shame (modesty). And metaphorically, it refers to a person's private parts, which are covered due to modesty. The places of nakedness (ster). (See: Majd, etc.)\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَوِالطِّفۡلِ الَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ یَظۡہَرُوۡا عَلٰی عَوۡرٰتِ النِّسَآءِ» (24:31)\nTranslation: Or those children who are not yet aware of the aspects of women's covering.\nAnd a woman is called such because it is obligatory for her to cover her entire body except her face and hands. And remaining without covering (ster) is considered a cause for shame and modesty. Thus, the word also implies a tear or rift, as well as the place of nakedness (ster), and the necessity to cover it with a veil. Then this word also came to be used in the meanings related to the veil itself.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثَلٰثُ عَوۡرٰتٍ لَّکُمۡ» (24:58)\nTranslation: These three times are your privacy (or times of seclusion).","«عَوْرَۃ» meaning cleft. The seventy stations and their veil.","Curtain","عورۃ","24:31-24:58-33:13",3
713,150,"V","سُرَادِق","«سُرَادِق» is a loanword from Persian (meaning it was adopted), signifying a curtain or covering (fem.). A loanword is a term that originally belongs to another language and is adapted into Arabic with slight modifications. In this context, «سُرَادِق» refers to walls made of thick fabric, canopies, awnings, or such tents that have no roof.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا» (18/29)\nTranslation: We have prepared for the wrongdoers a fire whose walls (or canopies) will surround them.\n\nNote: («مُعَرَّب»: A word that originally belongs to another language and has been made Arabic with slight modifications.)","«سُرَادِق» the central pole of the tent, the curtain surrounding the tent, the canopy.","Veil","سرادق","18:29",1
714,150,"V","اِستَتَر ۔ حَجَب","«اِستَتَر» is the term for that which conceals something. And the explanation and distinction between these two terms has been elaborated in «حِجَاب». Now observe their examples:\n\nExample of «اِستَتَر»: The Divine command states:\n«وَمَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَسۡتَتِرُوۡنَ اَنۡ یَّشۡہَدَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ سَمۡعُکُمۡ وَ لَاۤ  اَبۡصَارُکُمۡ وَ لَا جُلُوۡدُکُمۡ» ( 41/22 )\nTranslation: And you used not to cover (yourselves) out of fear of this (matter) that your ears and your eyes and your skins would bear witness against you.\n\nExample of «حَجَبَ»: The Divine command states:\n«کَلَّاۤ اِنَّہُمۡ عَنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ لَّمَحۡجُوۡبُوۡنَ» ( 83/15 )\nTranslation: Indeed, these people will be veiled from (the sight of) their Lord.","«اِستَتَر» is the term for that which conceals something. And «حَجَب» means to veil, to obstruct, or to act as a barrier.","Veil","استتر ۔ حجب","41:22-83:15",2
716,151,"G","اَنْبَتَ ۔ نَبَتَ","«اَنْبَتَ» means to grow, like grass or vegetables, etc. However, if a child is raised in such a way that their rate of growth and development is exceptionally faster than that of ordinary children, the Quran has also used the term «اَنْبَتَ» for it.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَتَقَبَّلَہَا رَبُّہَا بِقَبُوۡلٍ حَسَنٍ وَّاَنۡۢبَتَہَا نَبَاتًا حَسَنًا» (3/37)  \nTranslation: So her Lord accepted her with favor and caused her to grow in a good manner.","«اَنْبَتَ» to nurture in the best possible way, with due attention to food and other necessities.","Growth","انبت ۔ نبت","2:61-2:261-3:37-15:19-16:11-22:5-23:20-26:7-27:60-31:10-36:36-37:146-50:7-50:9-71:17-80:27",16
717,151,"N","اَنْشَاَ","The meaning of «نَشَاَ» is to come into existence, to be alive, and to reach maturity (Munjid); and «اَنْشَاَ» means to create someone and then nurture and raise them (Muf). «نَاشِیْ» refers to a young person, and «نَاشِئَةٌ» means to raise or elevate.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتُمُ النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ تُوۡرُوۡنَ ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ» (56:71-72)\nTranslation: So consider the fire that you kindle from trees. Did you create its tree, or are We the creators?\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«وَّ یُنۡشِئُ السَّحَابَ  الثِّقَالَ» (13:12)\nTranslation: And He (Allah) creates the heavy clouds (Jalandhari) and raises the heavy clouds (Uthmani).\n\nAnd «نَشَّا یُنَشِّئْ» from the form of taf'il has the meanings solely of nurturing and fostering (Munjid).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوَمَنۡ یُّنَشَّؤُا فِی الۡحِلۡیَۃِ  وَہُوَ فِی الۡخِصَامِ غَیۡرُ مُبِیۡنٍ» (43:18)\nTranslation: (Are the daughters of Allah) who are raised in ornaments and cannot argue clearly?","«نَشَّاَ» meaning to create, then to nurture and cause to grow.","Nurturing","انشا","6:6-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-21:11-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-28:45-29:20-36:79-43:18-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:23",23
719,151,"U","کَفَّلَ","«کَفَّل» meaning to foster someone and spend on them (Majma' al-Bayan) and meaning to be responsible for someone's financial support and guardianship (Mafatih al-Ghayb).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ لَدَیۡہِمۡ  اِذۡ  یُلۡقُوۡنَ اَقۡلَامَہُمۡ اَیُّہُمۡ یَکۡفُلُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/44)\nTranslation: And you [O Muhammad] were not with them when they cast their pens [to decide] which of them would take charge of Mary; but you were not with them when they disputed.","«کَفَّل» to become responsible for someone's upbringing and education.","Upbringing","کفل","3:37-3:44-16:91-20:40-28:12-38:23",6
720,152,"T","قَرَأَ","«قَرَأَ» is commonly used for reading and study. Whether one reads a text, a book, or even a single letter (faq l 48), and the Noble Quran is called the Quran because it is recited frequently and repeatedly, and the word 'Quran' itself contains an element of emphasis (mubalagha).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِہٖ ۙ فَیَقُوۡلُ ہَآؤُمُ اقۡرَءُوۡا کِتٰبِیَہۡ» (69:19)\nTranslation: So whoever is given his record in his right hand will say, Here, read my record!\n\nAnd «اَقْرَأَ» means to teach someone else to read.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَنُقۡرِئُکَ فَلَا تَنۡسٰۤی» (87:6)\nTranslation: We will surely teach you, so you will not forget.","«قَرَأَ» is commonly used for reading, whether little or much, whether it is a book, a letter, or the like.","to read","قرء","2:185-4:82-5:101-6:19-7:204-9:111-10:15-10:37-10:61-10:94-12:2-12:3-13:31-15:1-15:87-15:91-16:98-17:9-17:14-17:41-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:71-17:78-17:82-17:88-17:89-17:93-17:106-18:54-20:2-20:113-20:114-25:30-25:32-27:1-27:6-27:76-27:92-28:85-30:58-34:31-36:2-36:69-38:1-39:27-39:28-41:3-41:26-41:44-42:7-43:3-43:31-46:29-47:24-50:1-50:45-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-55:2-56:77-59:21-69:19-72:1-73:4-73:20-75:17-75:18-76:23-84:21-85:21-87:6-96:1-96:3",77
721,152,"T","تلٰی","«تَلٰی ، یَتْلُوْا ، تَلَاوَۃً» meaning to read a book or the Quran. And the word «تِلَاوَۃٌ» is specifically for reading divinely revealed books (Mufradat) because in it, one verse is followed by another, and the second by the third (Ma'ani al-Lughah). The application of *tilawat* does not apply to reading even a single letter or phrase of the divinely revealed books (Fiqh al-Lughah 48). For example, the Quran states:\n«اُتۡلُ مَاۤ اُوۡحِیَ اِلَیۡکَ مِنَ الۡکِتٰبِ» (29/45)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ) Recite what has been revealed to you from this Book.\nBut it seems that the lexicographers' specification of the word *tilawat* for reading divinely revealed books is a later development after the revelation of the Quran. Because the Quran itself has used this word for general reading, even for reading incantations and magical words.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاتَّبَعُوۡا مَا تَتۡلُوا الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ عَلٰی مُلۡکِ سُلَیۡمٰنَ» (2/102)\nTranslation: And they followed [instead] what the devils used to recite during the reign of Sulaiman (Solomon).","«تِلَاوَۃٌ» comes to read the revealed books or incantations.","to recite","تلی","2:44-2:102-2:113-2:121-2:129-2:151-2:252-3:58-3:93-3:101-3:108-3:113-3:164-4:127-5:1-5:27-6:151-7:175-8:2-8:31-10:15-10:16-10:61-10:71-11:17-13:30-17:107-18:27-18:83-19:58-19:73-22:30-22:72-23:66-23:105-25:32-26:69-27:92-28:3-28:45-28:53-28:59-29:45-29:48-29:51-31:7-33:34-34:43-35:29-39:71-45:6-45:8-45:25-45:31-46:7-62:2-65:11-68:15-73:4-83:13-98:2",61
722,152,"T","رَتَّلَ","«رَتِلَ» means the proper ordering and methodical arrangement of something (m. r.). And «رَتَّلَ» means to deliver speech with elegance and order (muf.). And «تَرْتِیْل» means good voice, i.e., reciting with a pleasant tone and paying attention to the articulation of letters, and reciting with measured pauses (minjazd.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ رَتِّلِ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  تَرۡتِیۡلًا» (73/4)\nTranslation: And recite the Quran with measured recitation (Jalandhari) and recite it clearly and distinctly (Osmani).","Recite with measured pacing and artistic embellishment.","To read","رتل","25:32-73:4",2
723,152,"T","دَرَسَ","«دَرَسَ» is used for regular learning, memorizing, and preserving it. Another meaning of «دَرَسَ» is to become worn-out, as in «دَرَسَ الثَّوْب», meaning a cloth that has become old and tattered, and «دَرَسَ الْعِلْم» means to focus on learning knowledge. (Majma') According to Imam Raghib, its meaning is to gain the effect of knowledge by preserving and controlling it. And since this can only be attained through continuous recitation, therefore «دَرَسَ» comes to mean continuous and regular recitation. (Mafatih)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«وَلٰکِنۡ کُوۡنُوۡا رَبّٰنِیّٖنَ بِمَا کُنۡتُمۡ تُعَلِّمُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ وَ بِمَا کُنۡتُمۡ  تَدۡرُسُوۡنَ» (3:79)\nTranslation: Rather, he will invite people only to this: O people! Become people of Allah, because you teach the Book of Allah to others and recite it yourselves.\n\nAnd «دَرَسَ ، دِرَاسَۃً» means to read and teach, and «دَارَسَ ، دِرَاسًا» means to read to each other and listen together, reciting in unison. (Majma')\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«اَنۡ تَقُوۡلُوۡۤا اِنَّمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ الۡکِتٰبُ عَلٰی طَآئِفَتَیۡنِ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا ۪ وَاِنۡ  کُنَّا عَنۡ دِرَاسَتِہِمۡ  لَغٰفِلِیۡنَ» (6:156)\nTranslation: So that you do not say, The Book was only sent down to two groups before us, and we were unaware of their reading and teaching.","«دَرَسَ» is used for systematic learning, memorization, and preservation.","to read","درس","3:79-6:105-6:156-7:169-34:44-68:37",6
724,152,"T","اَمْلٰی","«اَلْاِمْلَاءُ» is derived by lexicologists under two root meanings: (1) «اَمَلَّ یُمِلُّ اِمْلَاءً (ملل)» and (2) «اَمْلٰی یُمْلِیْ اِمْلَاءً (ملی)». In both forms, «اِمْلَاء» carries a single meaning, which is to cause to write or to have written (dictionary, etc.). Since the form of «اِمْلَاء» implies that one person speaks while another writes, therefore, in this sense, the word «تُمْلٰی» in the Quran is also used by some to mean reading aloud a written text.\n\nIn the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَقَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ  بُکۡرَۃً وَّاَصِیۡلًا» (25:5)\n\nTranslation: (1) And they say, These are the tales of the former peoples which he has compiled, and they are recited to him morning and evening. (Jalandhari)\nTranslation: (2) And they say, These are fabricated tales of the ancients which he has had written down, so they are dictated to him morning and evening. (Osmani)","Recite the written text aloud.","to read","املی","2:282-25:5",2
725,153,"A","حَبَّ ، حَبَّۃ","«حَبَّ» refers to grain (such as wheat, barley, etc.). And «حَبَّۃُ الْقَلْب» refers to the blackness of the heart. And «مَحَبَّة» means to regard something as good, to intend it in one's heart, to desire and will it, and to pursue its attainment with wisdom. (Detailed) (Fiqh, p. 99)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَیُحِبُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ  اَنۡ یَّاۡکُلَ لَحۡمَ اَخِیۡہِ مَیۡتًا فَکَرِہۡتُمُوۡہُ» (49/12)\nTranslation: Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother?","«حَبَّ» is the liking and desire for something, and the prudent pursuit of its attainment.","approval","حب ، حبۃ","2:165-2:177-2:190-2:195-2:205-2:216-2:222-2:276-3:14-3:31-3:32-3:57-3:76-3:92-3:119-3:134-3:140-3:146-3:148-3:152-3:159-3:188-4:36-4:107-4:148-5:13-5:18-5:42-5:54-5:64-5:87-5:93-6:76-6:141-7:31-7:55-7:79-8:58-9:4-9:7-9:24-9:108-12:8-12:30-12:33-14:3-16:23-16:107-20:39-22:38-24:19-24:22-28:56-28:76-28:77-30:45-31:18-38:32-41:17-42:40-49:7-49:9-49:12-57:23-59:9-60:8-61:4-61:13-75:20-76:8-76:27-89:20-100:8",73
726,153,"A","وَدَّ","«وَدَّ» means to love intensely (m. r.), and according to Imam Raghib, it means to love something and sometimes merely to desire its existence. This word is also used distinctly in both meanings (muf) and «وَدُوْد» signifies intense love. Moreover, this word is also employed in the meanings of merely liking something or desiring it.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَوَدُّ  الۡمُجۡرِمُ لَوۡ  یَفۡتَدِیۡ مِنۡ عَذَابِ یَوۡمِئِذٍۭ بِبَنِیۡہِ» (70/11)\nTranslation: On that day, the sinful man will wish that he could be ransomed by giving his son in exchange for the punishment of that day.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (15/2)\nTranslation: At times, the disbelievers will wish that they had been Muslims.","«وَدَّ» comes for the sake of utmost love or the desire to attain it.","Approval","ود","2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14",25
727,153,"L","اِرْتَضٰی","«رَضِیَ» means to be pleased and content with someone. And «اِرْتَضٰی» means to willingly accept something with heartfelt joy.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا اِلَّا مَنِ ارۡتَضٰی مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ» (72/26,27)\nTranslation: Allah does not reveal His knowledge of the unseen to anyone. However, to any messenger whom He is pleased with, He does reveal (the knowledge of the unseen).","«اِرْتَضٰی» to accept something with heartfelt pleasure.","liking / preference","ارتضی","21:28-24:55-72:27",3
728,153,"A","تَخَیَّر","«خَیْر» meaning goodness, virtue. And «تَخَیَّر» meaning to like something because of its attributes (qualities) among many things. For example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَ فَاکِہَۃٍ مِّمَّا یَتَخَیَّرُوۡنَ» (56/20) Translation: and fruits as they will like them.","Among many things, liking something due to its qualities.","Approval","تخیر","56:20-68:38",2
729,154,"I","دُعَا ، نِدَاء","«دُعَا ، نِدَاء» These two words are near-synonyms. «دُعَاء» is more specific than «نِدَاء». The following differences are observed between them:\n\n(1) The meaning of «دُعَاء» is merely 'to call', whereas «نِدَاء» generally comes for calling aloud. Because «نِدٰی» also carries meanings of a long distance (M. L). And «مُنَادِی» refers to the one who proclaims.\n\n(2) In «دُعَا», the speech must be meaningful, whereas «نِدَاء» can be both meaningful and meaningless—i.e., merely loud «نِدَاء» is possible, but «دُعَاء» is not. As if the word «نَدَاء» can also be used merely for shouting.\n\n(3) In «دُعَاء», addressing someone is necessary. But in «نِدَاء», mentioning the addressee's name is not necessary (sing.).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَمَثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡ یَنۡعِقُ بِمَا لَا یَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا دُعَآءً وَّ نِدَآءً» (2/171)\nTranslation: And those who disbelieve are like the one who shouts to that which hears nothing but a call and a voice.\n\nAnd the barking of a dog is called «نَعَقَ». In the above verse, «نِدَاء» implies merely shouting, and «دُعَاء» implies calling. And what appears in the Quran is this:\n«اِذۡ نَادٰی رَبَّہٗ نِدَآءً خَفِیًّا» (19/3)\nTranslation: When they called upon their Lord with a subdued voice.\nHere, the word «خَفِیًّا» is giving rise to the form of «اِِسْتِثْنَا».\n\nAnd the word «نِدَاء» has also appeared in the Quran in the meanings of Adhan (call to prayer).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا نُوۡدِیَ لِلصَّلٰوۃِ مِنۡ یَّوۡمِ الۡجُمُعَۃِ  فَاسۡعَوۡا اِلٰی ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (62/9)\nTranslation: Then hasten to the remembrance of Allah (i.e., prayer).\nThus, in this sense of «نِدَاء», the addressee's name is also not mentioned, and the conditions of loudness and long distance are also present.","«دُعَا» is to call upon Allah, to ask, to beseech; to address someone in a low, humble voice.  \nAnd «نِدَاء» is to call out loudly, and its application can also be to meaningless speech.","Invoke","دعا ، نداء","2:23-2:61-2:68-2:69-2:70-2:171-2:186-2:221-2:260-2:282-3:23-3:38-3:61-3:104-3:153-4:117-6:40-6:41-6:52-6:56-6:63-6:71-6:108-7:5-7:29-7:37-7:55-7:56-7:134-7:180-7:189-7:193-7:194-7:195-7:197-7:198-8:24-10:10-10:12-10:22-10:25-10:38-10:66-10:89-10:106-11:13-11:62-11:101-12:33-12:108-13:14-13:36-14:9-14:10-14:22-14:39-14:40-14:44-16:20-16:86-16:125-17:11-17:52-17:56-17:57-17:67-17:71-17:110-18:14-18:28-18:52-18:57-19:4-19:48-21:15-21:45-21:90-22:12-22:13-22:62-22:67-22:73-23:73-23:117-24:48-24:51-24:63-25:13-25:14-25:68-25:77-26:72-26:213-27:62-27:80-28:25-28:41-28:64-28:87-28:88-29:42-29:65-30:25-30:33-30:52-31:21-31:30-31:32-32:16-33:5-33:53-34:22-35:6-35:13-35:14-35:18-35:40-37:125-38:51-39:8-39:38-39:49-40:10-40:12-40:14-40:20-40:26-40:41-40:42-40:43-40:49-40:50-40:60-40:65-40:66-40:74-41:5-41:33-41:48-41:49-41:51-42:13-42:15-43:49-43:86-44:22-44:55-45:28-46:4-46:5-47:35-47:38-48:16-52:28-54:6-54:10-57:8-61:7-68:42-68:43-70:17-71:5-71:6-71:7-71:8-72:18-72:19-72:20-84:11-96:17-96:18",171
730,154,"T","اَذَّنَ","The meaning of «اَذَان» is to attract someone's attention with a loud voice and to call. In this manner, the voice can reach their ears. Thus, the words «اَذَان» and «تَاذِیْن» are more specific than the term 'نداء'. For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ اَذَّنَ مُؤَذِّنٌ اَیَّتُہَا الۡعِیۡرُ اِنَّکُمۡ لَسٰرِقُوۡنَ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then (when they had departed from the town), a crier cried out: 'O people of the caravan! Indeed, you are thieves.'","«اَذَان» and «تَاذِیْن» to call out loudly in order to attract someone's attention or summon them.","to call upon","اذن","2:279-7:44-7:167-9:3-12:70-14:7-21:109-22:27-41:47",9
731,154,"T","اِبْتَھَلَ","«بَھْل» refers to a specific form of separation and supplication. And «اِبْتِھَال» or «مُبَاھَلَہ» mean that two parties invoke a curse—i.e., pray for evil—upon one another. The meaning is that when two groups are in dispute over the truth or falsehood of a matter, and the disagreement does not seem to end through reasoning, both groups should pray in the court of Allah: O Allah, curse the one among us two who is lying.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَقُلۡ تَعَالَوۡا نَدۡعُ اَبۡنَآءَنَا وَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ نِسَآءَنَا وَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ وَ اَنۡفُسَنَا وَ اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ۟ ثُمَّ نَبۡتَہِلۡ فَنَجۡعَلۡ لَّعۡنَتَ اللّٰہِ عَلَی الۡکٰذِبِیۡنَ» (3:61)\nTranslation: Then say, 'Come, let us call upon our sons and your sons, our women and your women, ourselves and yourselves. Then let us supplicate earnestly and invoke the curse of Allah upon the liars.'","«اِبْتِھَال» is a specific type of supplication.","to call upon","ابتھل","3:61",1
732,154,"T","جَھَرَ","«جَھَرَ» means calling out in such a loud voice that those nearby can hear it. Its opposite is «اَسَرَّ», which means speaking in such a low voice that those nearby cannot hear it, such as when followers recite during prayer.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ تَجۡہَرۡ بِالۡقَوۡلِ فَاِنَّہٗ یَعۡلَمُ السِّرَّ وَاَخۡفٰی» (20/7)\nTranslation: If you call out while speaking, He knows even the hidden secrets and most concealed matters.","«جَھَرَ» to call out in such a loud voice that at least those nearby can hear.","to call upon","جھر","2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7",14
733,155,"T","اَخَذَ","«اَخَذَ» is a common term meaning to take hold of something or to encompass it (transitive). This word is used in both literal and spiritual contexts.\n\n**Literal sense example:** The Divine command states:\n«قَالَ یَبۡنَؤُمَّ  لَا تَاۡخُذۡ بِلِحۡیَتِیۡ  وَلَا بِرَاۡسِیۡ» (20/94)\nTranslation: (Aaron, peace be upon him, said to Moses, peace be upon him,) Do not take hold of my beard or my head hair.\n\n**Spiritual sense example:** The Divine command states:\n«خُذُوۡا مَاۤ اٰتَیۡنٰکُمۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ وَّ اسۡمَعُوۡا» (2/93)\nTranslation: And hold firmly to what We have given you, and hear.","«اَخَذَ» means to hold or grasp something; it is a common term used for catching.","to seize","اخذ","2:48-2:55-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:206-2:229-2:255-2:260-2:267-3:11-3:81-3:160-3:187-4:20-4:21-4:71-4:89-4:91-4:102-4:118-4:153-4:154-4:161-5:12-5:14-5:41-5:70-6:42-6:44-6:46-6:70-7:31-7:73-7:78-7:91-7:94-7:95-7:96-7:130-7:144-7:145-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:169-7:171-7:172-7:199-8:52-8:68-8:70-9:5-9:50-9:103-9:104-10:24-11:56-11:64-11:67-11:94-11:102-12:76-12:78-12:79-12:80-13:32-15:73-15:83-16:46-16:47-16:113-18:77-18:79-19:12-19:78-19:87-20:21-20:39-20:94-22:44-22:48-23:41-23:64-23:76-24:2-26:189-28:40-29:14-29:37-29:40-33:7-33:61-34:51-35:26-36:49-38:44-40:5-40:21-40:22-41:17-43:48-44:47-48:15-48:19-48:20-51:16-51:40-51:44-54:42-55:41-57:8-57:15-59:7-69:10-69:30-69:45-73:16-79:25",121
734,155,"T","بَطَشَ","«بَطَشَ» means to seize something with power and strength (m. l.) or to take something forcefully. (muf.) It denotes a harsh and firm grip, a tyrannical grasp, seizing with severity and awe (m. q.). «اَخَذَ» Like this word, it is also used in both apparent and spiritual senses.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَاِذَا بَطَشۡتُمۡ  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  جَبَّارِیۡنَ» (26/130)  \nTranslation: And when you seize (someone), you seize unjustly.","«بَطَشَ» a harsh and oppressive grip.","to seize","بطش","7:195-26:130-28:19-43:8-44:16-50:36-54:36-85:12",8
735,155,"T","تَنَاوَش","«نَاشَ» meaning to catch something from such a distance that one's hand can reach it. To seek (mand) and «تَنَاوَش» meaning to reach a desired thing. To have access.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَاَنّٰی لَہُمُ التَّنَاوُشُ مِنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ» (34/52)\nTranslation: And (now) how can their hand reach from such a distance (for faith)?","«تَنَاوَش» an attempt to catch something distant.","to seize","تناوش","34:52",1
736,155,"T","قَبَضَ","«قَبَضَ» means to grasp or take something in one's fist, and «قَبْضَۃ» means 'fist'.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«قَالَ بَصُرۡتُ بِمَا لَمۡ یَبۡصُرُوۡا بِہٖ فَقَبَضۡتُ قَبۡضَۃً  مِّنۡ اَثَرِالرَّسُوۡلِ» (20/96)  \nTranslation: (The Samiri) said, I saw something that others did not see, so I took a fistful from the footprint of the angel (i.e., dust from it).","To grasp something in one's fist.","to catch","قبض","2:245-9:67-20:96-25:46-39:67-67:19",6
737,155,"T","خَطَفَ","«خَطَفَ» To seize something and carry it off; to grab something hastily and run away (Fall 170). To snatch away (something) forcibly. For a bird (or similar) to snatch something away quickly. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّشۡرِکۡ بِاللّٰہِ فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ سَحِیۡقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: (And whoever associates partners with Allah,) it is as if he has fallen from the sky, and the birds snatch him away, or the wind carries him to a far-off place.","«خَطَفَ» to hastily snatch something and leave.","to seize","خطف","2:20-8:26-22:31-28:57-29:67-37:10",6
738,155,"T","سَطَاَ","«سَطَاَ» means to overpower someone by attacking them (Manjīd) and, according to Imam Raghīb, it means to seize firmly during an attack (Muf). And «سَطْوَۃ» means «اَلْبَطْشُ بِرَفْعِ الْیَدِ», i.e., to raise one's hand and seize forcefully, to strike (M. Q.).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا بَیِّنٰتٍ تَعۡرِفُ فِیۡ  وُجُوۡہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا الۡمُنۡکَرَ ؕ یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا» (22/72)\nTranslation: And when clear verses are recited to them (then their faces change and) you see on their faces clear signs of displeasure. It is about to happen that those who recite Our verses to them will attack them.","«سَطَاَ» grip as if attacking.","to seize","سطا","22:72",1
739,155,"T","اِعْتَصَمَ","«عَصَم» means to preserve and safeguard something (manjood), and «اِعْتَصَمَ» means to grasp firmly with both palms and clutch (Fall 174).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاعۡتَصِمُوۡا بِحَبۡلِ اللّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا وَّلَا تَفَرَّقُوۡا» (3/103)\nTranslation: And hold firmly, all together, to the rope of Allah (i.e., His guidance) and do not become divided.","«اِعْتَصَمَ» grasping something firmly with both palms.","to seize","اعتصم","3:101-3:103-4:146-4:175-22:78",5
740,155,"T","اِسْتَمْسَک","The meaning of «اَمْسَکَ» is: not letting something that is in hand slip away. To hold back. To cling. And «تَمَسَّک» and «اِسْتَمْسَک» mean: to hold firmly. To cling. To grasp firmly. (Source: Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِالطَّاغُوۡتِ وَ یُؤۡمِنۡۢ بِاللّٰہِ فَقَدِ اسۡتَمۡسَکَ بِالۡعُرۡوَۃِ الۡوُثۡقٰی» (2/256)\nTranslation: So whoever rejects false deities and believes in Allah has grasped the most trustworthy handhold.","To firmly hold onto that which is grasped or at hand.","to seize","استمسک","2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-11:113-16:59-16:79-17:100-19:45-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21",24
741,155,"T","دَرَکَ","«دَرَکَ» means to catch up with and seize something from behind (e.g.), and «دَرْک» also refers to the seabed and that rope which is tied to another rope to reach the bottom of the water (detailed). Thus, «دَرَکَ» conveys the meaning of taking something, catching up, or overtaking.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says: «لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» (36/40) Translation: Nor can the sun catch up with the moon.","to catch something from behind","to seize","درک","4:78-4:100-6:103-10:90-20:77-26:61-36:40",7
742,156,"R","وَزَر","«وَزَرَ» is also used to mean a mountain and a place of refuge (m. r.). According to Imam Raghib, it refers to a place of refuge within a mountain, such as a cave or grotto (muf).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«کَلَّا لَا وَزَرَ ، اِلٰى رَبِّكَ یَوْمَئِذِ اِ۟لْمُسْتَقَرُّؕ» (75:11-12)  \nTranslation: Indeed, on that Day, there will be no refuge except with your Lord.","«وَزَرَ» refers to a cave or grotto in a mountain, which can be used as a shelter.","Refuge","وزر","75:11",1
743,156,"R","مَوْئِلًا","«وَالَّۃ» is called the enclosure for camels and sheep/goats, and «اِستِیْئَال» means the gathering of camels (M. R.). According to Ibn Faris, it denotes gathering and implies protection and safety. As if «مَوْئِلًا» is such a self-constructed place designed to remain secure from theft, robbery, and other dangers.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«بَلۡ لَّہُمۡ مَّوۡعِدٌ  لَّنۡ یَّجِدُوۡا مِنۡ  دُوۡنِہٖ  مَوۡئِلًا» (18/58)\nTranslation: But for them is an appointed time, so that they will find no place of refuge from its punishment.","«مَوْئِلًا» a self-made refuge that has been built to stay safe from theft and other dangers.","Refuge","موئلًا","18:58",1
744,156,"R","اَکْنَان","«کَنَّ» means to hide something within a house and to protect it from the sun, etc. (Manjad), and «کِنّ» is that secure place where one can take refuge from the sun and rain (M. R), or any thing in which something can be hidden. And the plural of «کِنّ» is «اَکْنَان» and «اَکِنَّۃً» comes from it.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ  مِّنَ الۡجِبَالِ اَکۡنَانًا» (16/81)\nTranslation: And Allah has made for you in the mountains caves, and has made for you in the mountains places to hide. (Othmaniؒ)","«اَکْنَان» a secure place shielded from the sun, rain, and other elements.","Refuge","اکنان","16:81",1
745,156,"R","مَلْجَاَ","«لَجَا» means to take refuge in a fortress, etc. (manjad), and «لَجْاَ» also denotes a fortress. Its plural is «اَلْجَاء» (m. q.), and «مَلْجَاَ» means fortress or fort—a place where protection from the enemy is arranged.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ مَّلۡجَاٍ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ وَّ مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّکِیۡرٍ» (42/47).\n\nTranslation: On that day, there will be no place of refuge for you, nor will you be able to deny your sins.","«مَلْجَاَ» A fort or citadel where defense against the enemy is organized.","Refuge","ملجا","9:57-9:118-42:47",3
746,156,"R","مَحِیْص","«حَیْص» meaning tightness and hardship (m. r.) «حَیْص» and «بَیْص» are both words generally used together and are near-synonyms. Their meaning is that of a difficulty and distress from which there is no possibility of escape. And «مَحِیْص» is the place where one can find refuge from pain and calamity.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ مَاۡوٰىہُمۡ جَہَنَّمُ ۫ وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا  مَحِیۡصًا» (4/121)\nTranslation: Their abode will be Hell, and they will find no way to escape from it.","«مَحِیْص» a place of refuge from hardships and calamities.","Refuge","محیص","4:121-14:21-41:48-42:35-50:36",5
747,156,"R","مَفَازَۃ","«فَازَ» means to attain salvation. It signifies reaching a place of safety with well-being and security after being saved from calamities (muf). Therefore, the meanings of 'to die' and 'to be destroyed' also apply to «فَازَالرَّجُل» and «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل». This word originates from the category of 'dhawi al-idadad' (words with contradictory meanings) (m. l. m q).\n\nThus, a human being is saved from the worldly anxieties and hardships. And «مَفَازَۃ» is the place of peace and security where a human attains relief from difficulties and tranquility from distresses. It also means the place of destruction and its cause (munjad).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُنَجِّی اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا بِمَفَازَتِہِمۡ ۫ لَا یَمَسُّہُمُ السُّوۡٓءُ» ( 39/61 )\nTranslation: And those who are pious will be saved by Allah due to their (blessedness and) success, so no hardship will touch them.\n\nNote: (Dhawi al-idadad refers to words that have two separate meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«مَفَازَۃ» Attaining salvation from hardships and calamities, and reaching with well-being and safety such a place of protection where peace and security are also granted.","Refuge","مفازۃ","3:188-39:61-78:31",3
748,156,"R","مُلْتَحَدًا","«لَحَدَ» means to incline toward something or to be partial to it. It also means to look from the corner of one's eye.  \n«لَحْد» means a crevice or niche dug on one side of a grave.  \n«مُلْتَحَدًا» refers to a spot or place where one can take shelter by moving slightly sideways, forward, or backward.  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«قُلۡ اِنِّیۡ لَنۡ یُّجِیۡرَنِیۡ مِنَ اللّٰہِ اَحَدٌ  ۬ ۙ وَّ لَنۡ اَجِدَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖ مُلۡتَحَدًا» (72:22)  \nTranslation: Say, 'No one can protect me from Allah's punishment, and I do not see any refuge besides Him.'","«مُلْتَحِدًا» a place of refuge away from the scene of disaster.","Refuge","ملتحدًا","18:27-72:22",2
749,156,"R","اَجَار ، اِسْتِجَار","«جَارَ» means neighbor, fellow resident, supporter, and helper (masculine). «اِسْتِجَارَ» means to seek protection and refuge from an enemy as a form of support and aid, and to seek safety from its punishment. «اَجَارَ» means to take someone under protection from an enemy or to grant them refuge (masculine). For example: The Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ  اَحَدٌ مِّنَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ اسۡتَجَارَکَ فَاَجِرۡہُ حَتّٰی یَسۡمَعَ کَلٰمَ اللّٰہِ ثُمَّ اَبۡلِغۡہُ مَاۡمَنَہٗ» (9/6). Translation: If any polytheist seeks your protection, grant him protection so that he may hear the word of Allah, and then return him to his place of safety.","«اَجَارَ» is used for refuge and protection from the enemy.","Refuge","اجار ، استجار","4:36-8:48-9:6-23:88",4
750,156,"R","اَعَاذ ، اِسْتعَاذ","«عَوْذ» means place of refuge and «مَعَاذ» also means sanctuary as well as sorcery (source). That is, this refuge is from evil spirits, whether they be jinn, Satan, or sorcerers. And ta'wiz means amulet, incantation, blowing and sprinkling, and also those names and verses that are tied around the neck, etc., to ward off disease or any other affliction (source). And «اِسْتَعَاذ» means seeking refuge from the evil of such evil spirits or desiring protection, and «اَعَاذَ» means coming under refuge and remaining clinging (elaboration).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ اَعُوۡذُ بِاللّٰہِ اَنۡ اَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡجٰہِلِیۡنَ» (2/67)\nTranslation: Moses said, 'I seek refuge in Allah from being among the ignorant.'\n\nAt another instance, the command of the Almighty is:\n«وَ اِمَّا یَنۡزَغَنَّکَ مِنَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ نَزۡغٌ فَاسۡتَعِذۡ  بِاللّٰہِ» (7/200)\nTranslation: And if any whisper from Satan arises in your hearts, then seek refuge with Allah.","«اَعَاذَ» is used to seek refuge and protection from the evil of all wicked spirits.","Refuge","اعاذ ، استعاذ","2:67-7:200-11:47-12:23-12:79-16:98-19:18-23:97-23:98-40:56-41:36-72:6-113:1-114:1",14
751,157,"T","سَاَلَ","The basic meanings of «سَاَلَ» are two: (1) «اِسْتِفْسَار», meaning to ask, to inquire; (2) to ask for something and desire it in response. Here, the first meaning is under discussion. In the sense of «اِسْتِفْسَار», it is commonly used.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» (67/8)\nTranslation: Whenever a group is cast into Hell, its keepers will ask them, Did no warner come to you?","«سَاَلَ» is a common word for asking and questioning.","to ask","سال","2:61-2:108-2:119-2:134-2:141-2:186-2:189-2:215-2:217-2:219-2:220-2:222-2:273-4:32-4:153-5:4-5:101-5:102-6:90-7:6-7:163-7:187-8:1-8:12-9:65-10:72-10:94-11:29-11:46-11:47-11:51-12:50-12:82-12:104-14:34-15:92-16:43-16:56-16:93-17:85-17:101-18:70-18:76-18:83-20:105-20:132-21:7-21:13-21:23-21:63-23:72-23:113-25:57-25:59-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:78-29:13-29:61-29:63-31:25-33:8-33:20-33:53-33:63-34:25-34:47-36:21-38:86-39:38-42:23-43:9-43:19-43:44-43:45-43:87-47:36-47:37-51:12-52:40-55:29-55:39-60:10-67:8-68:46-70:1-70:10-75:6-79:42-102:8",93
752,157,"T","اِسْتَفْتَاء","«فتوٰی» and «فُتْیَا» refer to the answer to a difficult issue (muf), and «اِسْتَفْتَاء» means to seek a fatwa. To inquire about an Islamic ruling on a complex matter from a scholar, to seek advice or opinion on a difficult issue.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَسۡتَفۡتُوۡنَکَ ؕ قُلِ اللّٰہُ یُفۡتِیۡکُمۡ فِی الۡکَلٰلَۃِ» (4/176)\nTranslation: People ask you about Kalalah. Say, Allah Almighty has given this ruling regarding Kalalah.","«اِسْتَفْتَاء» to ask for a Shariah ruling on a difficult issue.","to ask","استفتاء","4:127-4:176-8:19-12:43-12:46-14:15-18:22-27:32-37:11-37:149",10
753,157,"T","اِسْتَنْبَاء","Such news is termed as that which is both significant and connected to the one asking or answering, whether it pertains to an event that has already occurred or one that is yet to happen. The terms *Nubuwwah* (prophethood) and *Nabi* (prophet) are derived from this concept. A *Nabi* is a being who, through revelation from Allah Almighty, receives such news and conveys it to people, regardless of whether that news relates to past times or future events. And «اِسْتَنْبَاء» means to acquire news, to investigate a report (Manjad).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَیَسۡتَنۡۢبِئُوۡنَکَ اَحَقٌّ ہُوَ  ؕ ؔ قُلۡ اِیۡ وَ رَبِّیۡۤ اِنَّہٗ لَحَقٌّ» (10/53)\nTranslation: They ask you, [O Muhammad], whether it [i.e., the Hour] is true. Say, Yes, by my Lord, indeed it is true.\n\nAnd according to Imam Raghib, «نَبَا» is that news in which the possibility of falsehood does not exist (Muf). However, this qualification does not seem correct.\n\nBecause the Divine Command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, if a wicked person brings you news, verify it.\n\nSimilarly, in the case of the hoopoe bird that «نَبَا» brought to Prophet Solomon. He had deemed its investigation necessary precisely because of the possibility of it being false.","«اِسْتَنْبَاء» to ask about important news.","to ask","استنباء","10:53-4:94-49:6",3
754,158,"E","کُلّ","«کُل» means all, entire, complete, and its opposite is «جُزْء». That is, the thing whose parts are all complete. Furthermore, the usage of «کُلّ» also encompasses all the complete parts of something. Essentially, it conveys the meaning of each one, everyone, everything. Now observe their examples:\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ  الۡمَوۡتِ» (29/57)\nTranslation: Every soul shall taste death.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ قَاتِلُوۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی لَا تَکُوۡنَ فِتۡنَۃٌ وَّ یَکُوۡنَ الدِّیۡنُ کُلُّہٗ  لِلّٰہِ» (8/39)\nTranslation: And (O Muslims) fight the disbelievers until there is no more fitnah, and the religion will be entirely for Allah.","«کُل» «جُز» is used in opposition to, meaning complete and whole—that thing whose components are all intact.","Everlastingness","کل","2:20-2:29-2:31-2:60-2:106-2:109-2:116-2:145-2:148-2:164-2:231-2:259-2:260-2:261-2:266-2:276-2:281-2:282-2:284-2:285-3:7-3:25-3:26-3:29-3:30-3:93-3:119-3:154-3:161-3:165-3:185-3:189-4:11-4:12-4:32-4:33-4:41-4:78-4:85-4:86-4:95-4:126-4:129-4:130-4:176-5:17-5:19-5:40-5:48-5:97-5:117-5:120-6:17-6:25-6:44-6:64-6:67-6:70-6:80-6:84-6:85-6:86-6:99-6:101-6:102-6:108-6:111-6:112-6:123-6:132-6:146-6:154-6:164-7:29-7:31-7:34-7:38-7:46-7:57-7:86-7:89-7:112-7:145-7:146-7:156-7:160-8:12-8:39-8:41-8:54-8:56-8:75-9:5-9:33-9:39-9:115-9:122-9:126-10:22-10:30-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:79-10:97-11:3-11:4-11:6-11:12-11:40-11:57-11:59-11:111-11:120-11:123-12:31-12:76-12:111-13:2-13:3-13:7-13:8-13:16-13:23-13:33-13:38-13:42-14:5-14:15-14:17-14:25-14:34-14:51-15:17-15:19-15:44-16:11-16:36-16:69-16:77-16:84-16:89-16:111-16:112-17:12-17:13-17:20-17:29-17:36-17:38-17:71-17:84-17:89-18:45-18:54-18:79-18:84-19:49-19:69-19:93-19:95-20:15-20:50-20:56-20:98-20:135-21:30-21:33-21:35-21:72-21:79-21:81-21:85-21:93-21:96-21:99-22:2-22:3-22:5-22:6-22:17-22:27-22:34-22:38-22:67-23:27-23:53-23:88-23:91-24:2-24:11-24:35-24:41-24:45-24:64-25:2-25:31-25:39-25:51-26:7-26:37-26:63-26:128-26:222-26:225-27:16-27:23-27:83-27:87-27:88-27:91-28:48-28:57-28:75-28:88-29:20-29:40-29:57-29:62-30:26-30:32-30:50-30:58-31:10-31:18-31:29-31:31-31:32-32:7-32:13-33:27-33:40-33:51-33:52-33:54-33:55-34:7-34:9-34:19-34:21-34:47-35:1-35:12-35:13-35:36-36:12-36:32-36:36-36:40-36:79-36:83-37:7-37:8-38:14-38:19-38:37-38:48-38:73-39:5-39:27-39:62-39:70-40:5-40:7-40:17-40:27-40:35-40:48-40:62-41:12-41:21-41:39-41:53-41:54-42:9-42:12-42:33-43:12-43:35-44:4-44:55-45:7-45:22-45:28-46:19-46:25-46:33-47:15-48:21-48:26-48:28-49:16-50:7-50:8-50:14-50:21-50:24-50:32-51:49-52:21-54:3-54:28-54:42-54:49-54:52-54:53-55:26-55:29-55:52-57:2-57:3-57:10-57:23-58:6-58:7-59:6-61:9-63:4-64:1-64:11-65:3-65:12-66:8-67:1-67:19-68:10-70:38-72:28-74:38-74:52-78:29-80:37-83:12-85:9-86:4-97:4-104:1",337
755,158,"A","کَامِلْ","«کَامِلْ» is the opposite of «نَاقِصْ». That is, a thing whose components are complete and whose attributes are perfect, meaning it fulfills its own purpose and objective (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَالۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And mothers should breastfeed their children for two full years.","«کَامِلْ» meaning complete, in which no deficiency or shortcoming remains, and it fulfills the purpose and objective. It is the opposite of incomplete.","All","کامل","2:196-2:233-16:25",3
756,158,"A","کَافَّۃً","«اَلْکِفَاف» refers to encompassing something entirely. And «کَافّ» is an active participle, and its feminine form is «کَافَّۃً». «جَآءَ النَّاسَ کَافَّۃً», meaning all people have come (manjad), this word is also more comprehensive (complete) than «کَامِلْ» because it encompasses not only parts but also all aspects of a whole. Now observe their examples:\n\nFor instance, in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً وَلَا تَتَّبِعُوۡا خُطُوٰتِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (2/208)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Enter into Islam completely and do not follow the footsteps of Satan.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَمَاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا» (34/28)\nTranslation: And [O Muhammad ﷺ] We have not sent you except as a bringer of glad tidings and a warner to all mankind.","«کَافَّۃً» is used to mean all the individuals of a group or all the aspects of a matter. It is also employed in the emphatic forms پورے کے پورے (pure ke pure) and سب کے سب (sab ke sab), which convey the sense of completely or entirely.","All","کافۃً","2:208-9:36-9:122-34:28",4
757,158,"A","سَلَمٌ","«سَلَمٌ» means correct, proper, and sound (m. r.). «اَلسَّلم» means to remain free from apparent and hidden faults and protected. And «سَلَمٌ» refers to a thing that is inherently correct and upon which no one else has any right (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا» (39/29)\n\nTranslation: Allah presents an example: of a slave man owned by many partners who dispute with each other, and another slave man who is entirely owned by one person. Can these two be equal in condition?","something that is correct in itself and over which no one else has any right.","All","سلم","39:29-68:43",2
758,158,"A","اَتَمَّ","«تَمَّ» or «تَمَامُ الشَّئ» refers to a thing reaching such a limit that thereafter no further external need remains. And its opposite is «نَقَصَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَتَمَّتۡ کَلِمَتُ رَبِّکَ صِدۡقًا وَّعَدۡلًا» (6/115)\nTranslation: And the words of your Lord are complete in truth and justice.\n\nAnd the meaning of «اَتَمّ» is to bring something imperfect or incomplete to the point of completion. Its usage generally pertains to completing a count, a quantity, or a duration.\n\n(1) For a count: For example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ اَتۡمَمۡتَ عَشۡرًا فَمِنۡ عِنۡدِکَ» (28/27)\nTranslation: And if you complete ten years, it will be (an act of favor) from you.\n\n(2) For a quantity: For example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَتۡمَمۡتُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ نِعۡمَتِیۡ» (5/3)\nTranslation: And I have completed My favors upon you.\n\n(3) For a duration: For example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ اَتِمُّوا الصِّیَامَ اِلَی الَّیۡلِ» (2/187)\nTranslation: Then complete the fast until the night.","«اَتَمّ» means completing something in such a way that no deficiency or shortfall remains, and it is used to fulfill a period, quantity, or count.","All","اتم","2:124-2:150-2:187-2:196-5:3-6:115-7:137-7:142-9:4-11:119-12:6-28:27-66:8",13
759,158,"P","اَکْمَلَ","«اَکْمَل ، کَامِل» means to commence an action for a specific purpose and then bring it to its point of completion, i.e., the purpose for which the action was initiated is fully achieved (transitive verb). Its opposite is «نَاقِص».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلۡیَوۡمَ اَکۡمَلۡتُ لَکُمۡ دِیۡنَکُمۡ وَاَتۡمَمۡتُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ نِعۡمَتِیۡ» ( 5/3 )\nTranslation: This day I have perfected for you your religion and completed My favor upon you and have approved for you Islam as religion.\n\nTo clearly distinguish between 'completion' (تمام) and 'perfection' (کمال), consider another example:\nThe Divine Command states:\n«وَالۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ لِمَنۡ اَرَادَ اَنۡ یُّتِمَّ الرَّضَاعَۃَ» ( 2/233 )\nTranslation: And mothers may breastfeed their children for two complete years for whoever wishes to complete the nursing period.\n\nIn this verse, the term «کَامِل» is used for completing the duration of «رَضَاعَتْ», and the term «تَمَام» is used for fulfilling the purpose of «رَضَاعَتْ».","«اَکْمَل» To complete something in such a manner that its purpose is fulfilled.","pouring forth","اکمل","2:185-2:196-2:233-5:3-16:25",5
760,158,"A","اَوْفٰی","The word «وَفٰی» comes to mean fulfilling a covenant, measurements and weights, life or a condition, and the payment of reward or wages. And its opposite is «عُذَر», meaning breach of trust (unfulfilled promise).\n\nNow observe their examples:\n\n(1) For example, regarding a covenant, the divine command is:\n«اَوۡفُوۡا بِعَہۡدِیۡۤ اُوۡفِ بِعَہۡدِکُمۡ» (2/40)\nTranslation: And fulfill the covenant which you have taken with Me, and I will fulfill the covenant which I have taken with you.\n\n(2) For measurements and weights, the divine command is:\n«فَاَوۡفُوا الۡکَیۡلَ وَالۡمِیۡزَانَ وَلَا تَبۡخَسُوا النَّاسَ اَشۡیَآءَہُمۡ» (7/85)\nTranslation: And give full measure and weight, and do not deprive people of their due.\n\n(3) For vows, pledges, and conditions, the divine command is:\n«وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ» (22/29)\nTranslation: And it is their duty to fulfill their vows.\n\n(4) For the payment of reward or wages, this chapter will come from «وَفّٰی». For example, the divine command is:\n«وَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَیُوَفِّیۡہِمۡ اُجُوۡرَہُمۡ» (3/57)\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds - We will surely give them their rewards in full.","«اَوْفٰی» comes to fulfill the covenant, the measure, the reward, the value, and life.","All","اوفی","2:40-2:177-2:272-2:281-3:25-3:55-3:57-3:76-3:161-3:185-3:193-4:15-4:97-4:173-5:1-5:117-6:60-6:61-6:152-7:37-7:85-7:126-8:50-8:60-9:111-10:46-10:104-11:15-11:85-11:109-11:111-12:59-12:88-12:101-13:20-13:40-16:28-16:32-16:70-16:91-16:111-17:34-17:35-17:63-22:5-22:29-24:25-24:39-26:181-32:11-35:30-39:10-39:42-39:70-40:67-40:77-46:19-47:27-48:10-53:37-53:41-76:7-78:26-83:2",64
761,158,"A","قَضٰی","When it is attributed to a human, its meaning is to become free after fulfilling one's responsibility. (Maf. M. Q) For example, in the Quran it is stated: «فَاِذَا قَضَیۡتُمۡ مَّنَاسِکَکُمۡ فَاذۡکُرُوا اللّٰہَ کَذِکۡرِکُمۡ اٰبَآءَکُمۡ» (2/200). Translation: Then when you have completed the rites of Hajj in Mina, remember Allah as you used to remember your forefathers. Similarly, in another instance, the command of Allah the Exalted is: «فَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ قَضٰی نَحۡبَہٗ وَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّنۡتَظِرُ» (33/23). Translation: Among them are some who have fulfilled their vows, and some who are still waiting.","When applied to a human, «قَضٰی» signifies being relieved of responsibility after fulfilling one's duty.","All","قضی","2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23",58
762,158,"E","اسبغ","The word «سَبَغَ» denotes the completeness and perfection of something (M. L.) and, according to Imam Raghib, it also conveys the meanings of expansiveness and ease. «سَابِغُ» refers to an open space (M.F.). The meaning of «اَسْبَغَ» is to fulfill a task in such a manner that no deficiency or shortcoming remains, and the intended purpose and goal are also fully achieved. This term is generally employed in the context of completing wudu and blessings.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَاَسۡبَغَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ نِعَمَہٗ ظَاہِرَۃً وَّبَاطِنَۃً» (31:20) Translation: And Allah has perfected for you His evident and hidden blessings.","«اَسْبَغَ» to carry out something in such a manner that nothing is left deficient in it, and its objective is also achieved in the best possible way.","Emanation","اسبغ","31:20",1
763,159,"G","لَبِسَ یَلْبَسُ","In the past tense, «لَبِسَ یَلْبَسُ» will have «ب» underneath (zair), and in the present tense (subjunctive/jussive) it will have (pish) above. It means to wear clothes or garments, and «لِبَاس» means one's own clothing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یُحَلَّوۡنَ فِیۡہَا مِنۡ اَسَاوِرَ مِنۡ ذَہَبٍ وَّلُؤۡلُؤًا ۚ وَ لِبَاسُہُمۡ فِیۡہَا حَرِیۡرٌ» ( 35/33 )\nTranslation: They will be adorned with bracelets of gold and pearls. And their garments therein will be of silk.","«لَبِسَ یَلْبَسُ» means a garment or clothing worn for one's own use, and that which is prepared for someone else is «کِسْوَۃ».","Garments","لبس یلبس","2:187-7:26-7:27-16:14-16:112-18:31-22:23-25:47-35:12-35:33-44:53-78:10",12
764,159,"C","کِسْوَۃ","«کَسَا ۔ یَکْسُوا» means to clothe someone else, and «کِسْوَۃ» means someone else's clothing or garment.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَعَلَی الۡمَوۡلُوۡدِ لَہٗ رِزۡقُہُنَّ وَ کِسۡوَتُہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/233)  \nTranslation: And the food and clothing of nursing mothers shall be the father's responsibility in accordance with custom.","«کِسْوَۃ» is used for someone else's clothing or garment.","Clothing","کسوۃ","2:233-2:259-4:5-5:89-23:14",5
765,160,"M","جَبَل","«جَبَل» is a common noun meaning mountain. This term applies to every type of mountain, whether small or large, high or low—it is used for all. Its plural form is جبال. (فل 266) For example, the Noble Quran states: «ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260) Translation: Then place each of their pieces on every mountain.","«جَبَل» is a proper noun, meaning mountain.","mountain","جبل","2:260-7:74-7:143-7:171-11:42-11:43-13:31-14:46-15:82-16:68-16:81-17:37-18:47-19:90-20:105-21:79-22:18-24:43-26:149-27:88-33:72-34:10-35:27-38:18-52:10-56:5-59:21-69:14-70:9-73:14-77:10-78:7-78:20-79:32-81:3-88:19-101:5",37
766,160,"M","رَوَاسِیَ","«رَسْوُ» means something that is gathered and solidified, firm and strong. «رَسَا السَّفِیْنَۃ» means a ship anchoring. And «مَرْسٰی» refers to a harbor (manjad), and «رَاسِیَ» also refers to that large pot which, due to its size, is installed in one place. (34/13) And raasiyatun means firm and strong mountains (m. r. manjad), and «رَوَاسِیَ» means a mountain range; this is generally used in the plural, meaning mountains spread far and wide.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ اَنۡ تَمِیۡدَ بِہِمۡ» (21/31)\nTranslation: And We have set firm mountains in the earth so that it may not shake the creation.","«رَوَاسِیَ» a strong and stable mountain. A mountain range.","Mountain","رواسی","13:3-15:19-16:15-21:31-27:61-31:10-34:13-41:10-50:7-77:27",10
767,160,"M","طَوْد","«طَوْد» A very large mountain, which is both tall and extensive in width (Surah Al-Fil 267). According to the author of *Al-Muntaha al-Arb*, the term is also used for very large sand dunes besides a large mountain (M. R).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ کَالطَّوۡدِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: Then the sea was parted, and each group became like a huge mountain.","«طَوْد» a great and lofty mountain or sand dune.","Mountain","طود","26:63",1
768,160,"M","صَخْرَۃ","«صَخْرَۃ» means a rock, a small hill, or a hard stone (pl.). In reality, «صَخْرَۃ» refers to a very large rock of considerable height. Ibn Faris writes its meaning as «حِجْرٌ عَظِیْم» (m. l).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ثَمُوۡدَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَابُوا الصَّخۡرَ بِالۡوَادِ» (89/9)\nTranslation: And what will explain to you what the state of the people of Thamud was? They carved out rocks in the valley.","«صَخْرَۃ» a small yet towering mountain, a massive, lofty boulder, and a cliff.","Mountain","صخرۃ","18:63-31:16-89:9",3
769,160,"M","اَعْلَام","«عَلَم» is the plural of «اَعْلَام». And the meanings of «عَلَم» include: sign, landmark, flag, lighthouse (minaret), and mountain—all these meanings are applicable. And «اَعْلَام» refers to anything that is elevated and prominent among its peers. For example: illustrious personalities, mountains, etc. If a context (qarinah) is found with «اَعْلَام» that indicates prominence, then its meaning will certainly be mountain.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَہُ الۡجَوَارِ الۡمُنۡشَئٰتُ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ کَالۡاَعۡلَامِ» (55/24)\nTranslation: And in His command are the ships which sail upon the sea like mountains standing high.","«اَعْلَام» is metaphorically used for the mountain; its original meaning is every thing that is elevated and distinguished from its peers.","mountain","اعلام","42:32-55:24",2
770,161,"T","عَرَفَ","«عَرَفَ» means to recognize something by reflecting upon its signs and effects. And its opposite is «نَکِرَ». The degree of «عَرَفَ» is lower than «عَلَّمَ» (detailed).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ جَآءَ اِخۡوَۃُ یُوۡسُفَ فَدَخَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِ فَعَرَفَہُمۡ وَہُمۡ لَہٗ مُنۡکِرُوۡنَ» (12/58). Translation: And when the brothers of Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) came from Canaan to Egypt to buy grain, they went to Yusuf (peace be upon him). He recognized them, but they could not recognize him.","«عَرَفَ» to identify something by its signs and traces.","to recognize","عرف","2:89-2:146-2:273-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:72-23:69-27:93-33:59-47:6-47:30-55:41-66:3-83:24",19
771,161,"T","تَوَسَّم","«وَسَمَ» meaning to mark/stamp. To stain/apply a mark (transitive) and meaning to engrave designs/patterns and carve etc. on the body (intransitive). And «وَسْمُ» and «وِسَامٌ» that with which a mark/stain is applied or color is applied. And «وَسِیْم» meaning beautiful (from Quranic usage). And «تَوَسَّمْ» meaning to describe something with insight, to seek a sign, to recognize (from Majid).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اِنَّ  فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ  لَاٰیٰتٍ  لِّلۡمُتَوَسِّمِیۡنَ» (15/75)\nTranslation: Indeed in this (story) are signs for those of insight!","«تَوَسَّم» To first become aware of the signs and indicators through one's own understanding and insight, and then to recognize them.","to recognize","توسم","2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16",8
772,162,"F","اَوَّل","«اَوَّل» means the first and its feminine form «اُوْلٰی» means the first (feminine). And «اوّل» is used in three ways:\n\n(1) In terms of numerical sequence: That is, the number before which there is no other number. In this sense, after *awwal* (i.e., the first) comes *thani* (i.e., the second), then *thalith* (i.e., the third), and so on.\n\n(2) In terms of giving order or a systematic process (i.e., doing or making something first). For example, «الاَسُّ اوّلا ثمَّ البناء» means a foundation will be laid first, then construction will follow.\n\n(3) In terms of temporal sequence (i.e., the order of time). In this sense, the opposite of *awwal* is «اٰخِرْ», meaning the last or previous.\n\nAnd «اُوْلٰی», meaning the first (i.e., the first world), is used only for numerical sequence (numbering). And the opposite of «اُوْلٰی» is «اٰخِرَت» (meaning the Hereafter or the afterlife).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَالۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ لَمَجۡمُوۡعُوۡنَ  ۙ اِلٰی مِیۡقَاتِ یَوۡمٍ مَّعۡلُوۡمٍ» (56:49,50)\nTranslation: Say, 'Both the first and the last will be gathered on an appointed day.'","«اَوَّل» is used in three ways: (1) in terms of numerical order, (2) in terms of arranging or systematic order (i.e., arranging or making something in a sequence first and then doing it), (3) in terms of chronological order (i.e., according to the sequence of time).  \nAnd «اُوْلٰی», meaning 'first,' is used only for numerical order (number).","First","اول","2:41-3:96-5:107-5:114-6:14-6:25-6:94-6:110-6:163-7:38-7:39-7:143-8:31-8:38-9:13-9:83-9:100-9:108-15:10-15:13-16:24-17:7-17:51-17:59-18:48-18:55-20:21-20:51-20:65-20:133-21:5-21:104-23:24-23:68-23:81-23:83-25:5-26:26-26:51-26:137-26:184-26:196-27:68-28:36-28:43-28:70-33:33-35:43-36:79-37:17-37:59-37:71-37:126-37:168-39:12-41:21-43:6-43:8-43:81-44:8-44:35-44:56-46:17-50:15-53:25-53:50-53:56-56:13-56:39-56:48-56:49-56:62-57:3-59:2-68:15-77:16-77:38-79:25-83:13-87:18-92:13-93:4",82
773,162,"F","سَبَقَ","Its original meaning is to advance oneself and leave others behind.","«سَبَقَ» means to move forward.\n«مَسْبُوْق» refers to one who remains behind or one who comes later.","First","سبق","7:80-8:59-8:68-9:100-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:129-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-23:61-29:4-29:28-29:39-35:32-36:40-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-56:10-57:21-59:10-79:4",28
774,162,"F","قَبْل","«قَبْل» is the opposite of «بَعَد». It is used for all types of precedence (temporal, spatial, sequential). However, in the Quran, this word is used only in the temporal sense of «تَقَدّم».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ وَمَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِکَ» (2/4)\n\nTranslation: And who believe in what has been revealed to you, [O Muhammad], and what was revealed before you.","«قَبْل» is used in all these meanings: ahead, before, previously, in front.","First","قبل","2:4-2:21-2:25-2:89-2:91-2:108-2:118-2:183-2:198-2:214-2:237-2:254-2:286-3:4-3:11-3:93-3:137-3:143-3:144-3:164-3:183-3:184-3:186-4:26-4:47-4:60-4:94-4:131-4:136-4:159-4:162-4:164-5:5-5:34-5:57-5:59-5:75-5:77-5:102-6:6-6:10-6:28-6:34-6:42-6:84-6:148-6:156-6:158-7:38-7:53-7:101-7:123-7:129-7:155-7:173-8:52-8:54-8:71-9:30-9:48-9:50-9:69-9:70-9:107-10:13-10:16-10:39-10:74-10:91-10:94-10:102-11:17-11:49-11:62-11:78-11:109-11:116-12:3-12:6-12:26-12:37-12:64-12:76-12:77-12:80-12:100-12:109-13:6-13:30-13:32-13:38-13:42-14:9-14:22-14:31-14:44-15:10-15:27-16:26-16:33-16:35-16:43-16:63-16:118-17:58-17:77-17:107-18:109-19:7-19:9-19:23-19:67-19:74-19:98-20:71-20:90-20:114-20:115-20:128-20:130-20:134-21:6-21:7-21:24-21:25-21:34-21:41-21:51-21:76-22:42-22:52-22:78-23:83-24:34-24:55-24:58-24:59-25:20-26:49-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:42-27:46-27:68-28:12-28:46-28:48-28:52-28:53-28:78-29:3-29:18-29:48-30:4-30:9-30:42-30:43-30:47-30:49-32:3-32:26-33:15-33:38-33:49-33:62-34:44-34:45-34:53-34:54-35:4-35:25-35:44-36:31-37:71-38:3-38:12-38:16-39:8-39:25-39:50-39:54-39:55-39:65-40:5-40:21-40:34-40:67-40:74-40:78-40:82-41:25-41:43-41:48-42:3-42:47-43:21-43:23-43:45-44:17-44:37-46:4-46:12-46:17-46:18-47:10-48:15-48:16-48:23-50:12-50:36-50:39-51:16-51:46-51:52-52:26-52:28-53:52-54:9-55:56-55:74-56:45-57:10-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:5-59:9-59:15-62:2-63:10-64:5-67:18-69:9-71:1",236
775,163,"A","جَنْب","«جَنْب» means side, aspect, turn, or position. «جَنْب» can also refer to any one side or aspect of something.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَاِذَا مَسَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ الضُّرُّ دَعَانَا لِجَنۡۢبِہٖۤ اَوۡ قَاعِدًا اَوۡ قَآئِمًا» (10:12)  \nTranslation: And when harm touches man, he lies on his side, sits, and stands (in every state) calling upon Us.  \n\nFurthermore, it can refer to something that is near or adjacent, such as «صاحِبِ بِالْجَنَب» meaning a companion who sits nearby, or «جَانِب» or «طَرَف», like «جَنْبِ الْحَائِط» meaning towards the wall (in the sense of proximity).  \n\nPrimarily, «جَنْب» is used in two meanings: (1) side, aspect; (2) to be distant (m. l.).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَالۡجَارِ الۡجُنُبِ وَ الصَّاحِبِ بِالۡجَنۡۢبِ وَ ابۡنِ السَّبِیۡلِ» (4:36)  \nTranslation: And the neighbor who is a stranger, and the companion by your side, and the traveler.  \n\nAnd «جَارِالْجَنْب» refers to a distant neighbor, while «صَاحِبِ بِالْجَنْب» means one who resides nearby. By extension, this word also appears in the sense of in relation to or concerning.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ» (39:56)  \nTranslation: Lest a person should say, Alas, my regret for what I neglected in relation to Allah.","«جَنْب» comes equally for the living and the non-living, for the near and the far.","Aspect","جنب","4:36-10:12-17:68-17:83-19:52-20:80-28:29-28:44-28:46-37:8-39:56-41:51",12
776,163,"F","جَنَاح","«جَنَاح» generally comes in the meaning of a feather. Its dual form is «جَنَاحَیْن» and its plural is «اَجْنِحَۃٌ». Then this word also began to be used for a human's arm, meaning the part from the shoulder to the palm (the upper arm). And «جَنَحَ» means to incline. If this inclination is toward good, then it is called «جَنَاح»; and if it is toward evil, then it is called «جُنَاح». (Muf) In the following verses, «جَنَاح» means only 'side' or 'arm', but its inclination is toward goodness.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ جَنَاحَکَ لِمَنِ اتَّبَعَکَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (26:215)\nTranslation: And lower your wing of mercy to the believers who follow you with humility.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Exalted is:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17:24)\nTranslation: And lower your wing of humility (or lower your arm in submission) for them (the parents). (Uthmani)\n\nAnd the word «جُنَاح» does not come for an inclination toward goodness; rather, it gives the meaning of inclination toward sin or toward it.","«جَنَاح» is used to refer to the aspect of living beings and to describe the quality of humility and modesty.","Facet","جناح","6:38-15:88-17:24-20:22-26:215-28:32",6
777,163,"F","عِطْف","«عَطَفَ» means to turn one side of something towards the other, to double. And Ataf refers to a two-layered cloth (Muf). And «عَطْف» also means crookedness and inclination (Manjada). And «عِطْفُ» means side and edge. And «عِطْفُ الرَّجُل» means both sides of a man. And «ثَنَا عِطْفِہٖ» means to turn away and to exceed. And «مَرَّثَانِیَ عِطْفِہٖ» means to walk with arrogance (Manjada). It seems that the word «عِطْف», when used in the sense of side, comes to describe a state of excess and arrogance.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «ثَانِیَ عِطۡفِہٖ لِیُضِلَّ عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (22/9) Translation: And (with arrogance) he turns aside to lead (people) astray from Allah's path.","«عِطْف» is used to describe the state of excess and arrogance.","Facet","عطف","22:9",1
778,164,"T","بَلَغَ","«بَلَغَ» meaning to reach the ultimate limit of a purpose, to reach the final limit (intransitive)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَابۡتَلُوا الۡیَتٰمٰی حَتّٰۤی اِذَا بَلَغُوا النِّکَاحَ» (4/6)\nTranslation: And continue to test the orphans until they reach the age of marriage.","to reach the ultimate or final limit of a purpose","to arrive","بلغ","2:196-2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-3:40-4:6-5:67-6:19-6:128-6:152-7:62-7:68-7:79-7:93-9:6-11:57-12:22-13:14-17:23-17:34-17:37-18:60-18:61-18:76-18:82-18:86-18:90-18:93-19:8-22:5-24:58-24:59-28:14-33:10-33:39-34:45-37:102-40:36-40:67-40:80-46:15-46:23-48:25-53:30-56:83-65:2-72:28-75:26",49
779,164,"T","اَصَابَ","The meaning of «صَوْب» refers to something descending and settling. And «اَلْصَوْب» also refers to rainfall. And «اَصَابَ» means to hit a target precisely, like an arrow. And «صَوَابُ» means correct and accurate. And its opposite is «خَطَا» (manjada). And «مُصِیْبَۃٌ» originally refers to something that hits the mark perfectly. Then, in common usage, the word 'calamity' began to be used predominantly in a negative sense.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ  ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَاِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» (2/156)\nTranslation: Who, when a calamity befalls them, say, 'Indeed, we belong to Allah, and to Him we will return.' (Uthmani)\n\nThus, «اَصَابَ» is applied to the constriction, calamity, and hardship that befall humans from God. Although its usage is mostly in a negative sense, it can also occur in a positive context.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ اَصَابَکُمۡ فَضۡلٌ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (4/73)\nTranslation: And if a favor from Allah comes to you... (Uthmani)","«اَصَابَ» from Allah, bringing hardship or goodness to humans.","to reach","اصاب","2:156-2:264-2:265-2:266-3:117-3:146-3:153-3:165-3:166-3:172-4:62-4:72-4:73-4:79-5:106-11:81-11:89-16:34-22:11-22:35-30:48-31:17-38:36-39:51-42:30-42:39-57:22-64:11",28
780,164,"T","نَالَ","«نَالَ» denotes reaching or acquiring that which a person desires (elaborate), or taking with both hands (Quran Majeed). «نَیْل» signifies purpose and intent, while «نَیْلَۃً» denotes the sought-after object (Manjad). For instance, the Noble Quran states: «لَنۡ تَنَالُوا الۡبِرَّ حَتّٰی تُنۡفِقُوۡا مِمَّا تُحِبُّوۡنَ» (3/92). Translation: Never will you attain goodness until you spend from what you love...","to reach that «نَالَ» and obtain what a human desires.","to reach","نال","2:124-3:92-5:94-7:37-7:49-7:152-9:74-9:120-22:37-33:25",10
781,164,"T","نَاوَشَ","«نَاشَ» means to seize something, to seek (manjad), and also means to consume. And «نَاشَ فُلَانًا» means to make haste to grasp his head and beard. And «نَالَ» and «نَاشَ» are nearly synonymous terms. That is, to stretch out the hand and seize or for the hand to reach something. The only difference is that «نَالَ» is used specifically for attaining something desirable, whereas «نَاشَ» is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا بِہٖ ۚ وَ اَنّٰی لَہُمُ التَّنَاوُشُ مِنۡ مَّکَانٍۭ بَعِیۡدٍ» (34/52)\nTranslation: And (seeing the punishment) they will say, We have now brought faith; how can their hands reach out for faith from such a far-off place?","«نَاوَشَ» to reach out and grasp something.","to reach","ناوش","34:52",1
782,164,"T","تَعَاطٰی ( عَطْو )","«تَعَاطٰی» signifies reaching and grasping a desired object. In the words of Ibn Faris, its meaning is « تَنَاوَلَ بِالْیَد » (moving the hand), and that which is obtained is «عَطَاء» and «عَطْیَہ». Furthermore, the meaning of «تَعَاطٰی» is to lay hands upon something over which one has no right; it connotes standing on the tips of one's fingers, raising the hand, and striving to seize an unjust object. (M. L) (M. Q)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَنَادَوۡا صَاحِبَہُمۡ  فَتَعَاطٰی فَعَقَرَ» (54:29)\nTranslation: So they called their companion, and he took the she-camel and slaughtered her.","To stretch one's hand toward something over which one has no right.","to reach","تعاطی ( عطو )","54:29",1
783,164,"T","وَصَل","«وَصَلَ» means to reach another thing and merge into it. For example, the diameter of a circle touches and connects with the circumference at both ends (fig.). Thus, its meanings include reaching, merging, and joining (Manjad. M.Q.). Then this word is used separately in all three meanings.\n\n(1) Example of the meaning to reach:\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰلُوۡطُ اِنَّا رُسُلُ رَبِّکَ  لَنۡ یَّصِلُوۡۤا اِلَیۡکَ» (11/81)\nTranslation: The angels said, O Lot! We are messengers from your Lord; it is impossible for them to reach you.\n\n(2) Example of the meanings to merge and to join:\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27)\nTranslation: And they sever the ties that Allah has commanded to be maintained.","to attain and unite with «وَصَلَ»","to reach","وصل","2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3",18
784,164,"T","اَفْضٰی","The meaning of «فَضَا» is an open and empty space between the earth and the sky. (meaning, meaning, word) And «مَقَامٍ فَاضٍ» is the term for such a place that is open, wide, and empty (manjada). And «اَفْضٰی اِلَیْہِ بِسِرِّہٖ» means to disclose a secret to someone. And «اَفْضٰی بِفُلَانٍ» means to take someone to an open field (manjada). And «اَفْضٰی اِلَی امْرَأَتِہٖ» is used figuratively to mean having intercourse with one's wife.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says: «وَ کَیۡفَ تَاۡخُذُوۡنَہٗ وَ قَدۡ  اَفۡضٰی بَعۡضُکُمۡ  اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (4/21) Translation: And how can you take back that (given right of dowry) and it has already reached among you from one to another (Uthmanؒ)?","Figuratively, «اَفْضٰی» is used in the meanings of a husband and wife being together or companionship.","to arrive","افضی","4:21",1
785,164,"T","مَسَّ","The original meaning of «مَسَّ» is for one thing to touch another. However, in translation, this word sometimes conveys the meaning of 'to reach' or 'to befall'.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ بَدَّلۡنَا مَکَانَ السَّیِّئَۃِ الۡحَسَنَۃَ حَتّٰی عَفَوۡا وَّ قَالُوۡا قَدۡ مَسَّ اٰبَآءَنَا الضَّرَّآءُ وَ السَّرَّآءُ» (7/95)\nTranslation: Then We replaced affliction with ease, until they grew numerous in wealth and offspring, and they said, Indeed, hardship and ease used to befall our forefathers.","The original meaning of «مَسَّ» is to touch. However, due to the need for translation, it is sometimes rendered as to reach.","to arrive","مس","2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-4:43-5:6-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21",58
786,164,"T","وَرَدَ","The literal meaning of «وَرَدَ» is for a person to arrive at a well or watering place in search of water to drink, and its opposite is «صَدَرَ». That is, to return after having taken water, drunk it, or quenched one's thirst (sing.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا وَرَدَ مَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ وَجَدَ عَلَیۡہِ اُمَّۃً مِّنَ النَّاسِ یَسۡقُوۡنَ» (28/23)\nTranslation: And when Moses reached the watering place of the people of Midian, he found there a group of people watering their flocks.","«وَرَدَ» to reach the water's edge or a well.","to arrive","ورد","21:99-28:23",2
787,164,"T","بَلَّغ","«بَلَّغَ» and «اَبْلَغَ» both denote the meaning of reaching an ultimate limit or conclusion regarding something or a message, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَحَدٌ مِّنَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ اسۡتَجَارَکَ فَاَجِرۡہُ حَتّٰی یَسۡمَعَ کَلٰمَ اللّٰہِ ثُمَّ اَبۡلِغۡہُ مَاۡمَنَہٗ» (9:6)\nTranslation: If any of the polytheists seeks your protection, then grant him protection so that he may hear the word of Allah, and then deliver him to his place of safety.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الرَّسُوۡلُ بَلِّغۡ  مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکَ  مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ» (5:67)\nTranslation: O Prophet! Convey to the people whatever has been revealed to you from your Lord.","«بَلَّغَ» is generally used for conveying messages.  \n«اَبْلَغَ» to convey any thing or message to the final limit or conclusion.","to arrive","بلغ","2:196-2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-3:40-4:6-5:67-6:19-6:128-6:152-7:62-7:68-7:79-7:93-9:6-11:57-12:22-13:14-17:23-17:34-17:37-18:60-18:61-18:76-18:82-18:86-18:90-18:93-19:8-22:5-24:58-24:59-28:14-33:10-33:39-34:45-37:102-40:36-40:67-40:80-46:15-46:23-48:25-53:30-56:83-65:2-72:28-75:26",49
788,164,"T","اَوْرَدَ","«اَوْرَدَ» meaning to bring another person to the brink (transitive).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ ؕ وَ بِئۡسَ الۡوِرۡدُ  الۡمَوۡرُوۡدُ» (11/98).\nTranslation: He (Pharaoh) will lead his people on the Day of Resurrection, going before them, and will bring them to Hell. What an evil brink they will be brought to!","«اَوْرَدَ» to take someone to the riverbank.","to arrive","اورد","11:98",1
789,164,"T","جَبَا","In the fundamental meanings of «جَبَا», two aspects are found: (1) to gather or collect something, and (2) then to convey it to another place. «جَبَتِ الْخِرَاجُ جَبَایَۃً» This phrase is used for the collection of kharaaj (land tax) and subsequently its remittance to the original location. For example: The Holy Quran states: «اَوَ لَمۡ نُمَکِّنۡ لَّہُمۡ حَرَمًا اٰمِنًا یُّجۡبٰۤی اِلَیۡہِ ثَمَرٰتُ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ» (28/57) Translation: Did We not grant them a place in the Haram, which is a sanctuary of security, where fruits of all kinds are brought?","«جَبَا» to gather something and bring it to another place.","to reach","جبا","28:57",1
790,164,"T","اَدْلٰی","«دَلْوُ» means an empty water bucket, and «اَدْلٰی» means lowering that empty bucket into the well to fill it, which gradually reaches the water. (مف)\n\nAnd the meaning of «اَدْلٰی اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» is to bring one's matter or dispute, etc., to another person for decision, and to use the means of kinship or intercession. (منجد)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَلَا تَاۡکُلُوۡۤا اَمۡوَالَکُمۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ بِالۡبَاطِلِ وَ تُدۡلُوۡا بِہَاۤ اِلَی الۡحُکَّامِ لِتَاۡکُلُوۡا فَرِیۡقًا مِّنۡ اَمۡوَالِ النَّاسِ بِالۡاِثۡمِ» (2/188)\nTranslation: And do not consume one another's wealth unjustly, and do not bring it (as a bribe) to the authorities, so that you may sinfully consume a portion of the people's wealth.","«اَدْلٰی اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» Delegating one's responsibilities to another person and relying on personal connections, bribes, and recommendations.","to reach","ادلی","2:188-7:22-12:19-20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-34:14-53:8-61:10",10
791,165,"T","خَرَقَ","The meaning is to tear something apart and ruin it; to smash to pieces; or to break in order to damage (fig.). And «خَرْقَہ» refers to rags of cloth, while «خَارِق» denotes an act contrary to custom (Munjid).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَانۡطَلَقَا ٝحَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ خَرَقَہَا ؕ قَالَ اَخَرَقۡتَہَا لِتُغۡرِقَ اَہۡلَہَا» (18:71).  \nTranslation: So both set out until when they boarded the ship, he (Khidr) tore it apart. Moses said, Did you tear it so that its passengers would drown?","«خَرَقَ» to tear something in order to damage or ruin it.","to tear","خرق","6:100-17:37-18:71",3
792,165,"T","قَدَّ","«قَدَّ» means to tear something lengthwise. And «قَدّ» refers to the length or stature of a human (plural). And «قَدِیْد» means the long strips of dried meat (plural; *manjad*).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12/25)\nTranslation: And they both ran towards the door, and she seized his shirt from behind and tore it.","«قَدَّ» meaning to split something lengthwise.","to tear","قد","12:25-12:26-12:27-12:28",4
793,165,"T","فَطَرَ","«فَطَرَ» means to tear something lengthwise so that a fissure appears in it; to split or cleave. In this sense, it also conveys the meanings of creating and bringing into existence. And «فُطُوْر» is the term for a fissure or cleft (as per Ma‘ani al-Qur'an).\n\nFor example, the Noble Qur'an states:\n«فَارۡجِعِ  الۡبَصَرَ ۙ ہَلۡ  تَرٰی مِنۡ فُطُوۡرٍ» ( 67/3 )\nTranslation: Look again and again: your vision will return to you humbled while it is fatigued. Do you see any rifts or fissures? (i.e., no fissure is visible in the flawless creation of the heavens).\n\nAt another place, the Divine declaration is:\n«فِطۡرَتَ اللّٰہِ  الَّتِیۡ فَطَرَ  النَّاسَ عَلَیۡہَا» ( 30/30 )\nTranslation:\n(1) [This is] the natural pattern (fitrah) upon which Allah has originated mankind. (i.e., adhere to the innate, pure disposition with which Allah created people).\n(2) That is the pattern of Allah (sunnat Allah) upon which He has originated (fatara) mankind. (Othmani)","«فَطَرَ» meaning to split and chip away.","to split open","فطر","6:14-6:79-11:51-12:101-14:10-17:51-19:90-20:72-21:56-30:30-35:1-36:22-39:46-42:5-42:11-43:27-67-3-73:18-82:1",18
794,165,"T","فَجَرَ","«فَجَرَ» means to rupture or split something on a wide scale. And «فَجْر» (at the time of bursting forth) is called *Fajr* (dawn) for this very reason, because it becomes visible across the entire horizon. And «فَجُور» means to boldly unveil the commands of religion. And from this, «فَاجِر» and «فُجَّار» are derived (free from ambiguity). And the meanings of «فَجَرَ» and «فَجَّرَ» also extend, in this sense, to causing water to flow or spread over a wide area.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ لَنَا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا» (17:90)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers said, We will never believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth for us from the earth.\n\nAnd the word «فَجَّر» comes specifically in the meaning of opening a path far and wide for the flow of water.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا» (18:33)\nTranslation: And We made a river flow between them.","«فَجَرَ» to tear something apart and scatter it on a wide scale.","to tear/rip","فجر","2:60-2:74-2:187-17:78-17:90-17:91-18:33-24:58-36:34-54:12-71:27-75:5-76:6-80:42-82:3-89:1-91:8-97:5",18
795,165,"T","مَخَرَ","«مَخَرَ» is used for the cutting and splitting of water. They say «مَخَرَ الْمَاءُ الْاَرْضَ» means to cut and split the water from the earth and to churn it. And «مَخَرَالسَّفِیْنَۃَ» means the boat cutting the water with its bow, splitting it, and producing sound. And «مَاخِر» refers to the boat that cuts the water and produces sound in it (M. R.). And the plural of «مَاخِر» is «مَوَاخِر».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡفُلۡکَ مَوَاخِرَ فِیۡہِ» (16/14)\nTranslation: And you see the boats cutting through the water in the sea.","«مَخَرَ» to break the ship's water, producing sound as well.","to split","مخر","16:14-35:12",2
796,165,"R","شقّ","«شَقَّ» to split open something hard. In the Quran, it is used for the splitting open of great and hard things like the sky, earth, moon, and rocks. For example, the Noble Quran states: «ثُمَّ شَقَقۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ شَقًّا» ( 80/26 ) Translation: Then We split the earth open.","«شَقَّ» to tear something hard.","rend","شق","2:74-19:90-25:25-50:44-54:1-55:37-69:16-80:26-84:1",9
797,165,"R","فَلَقَ ۔ فَرَقَ","«اَلْفَلَق» and «اَلّفَرَق» are both near-synonyms. And two fundamental aspects are found in both: (1) splitting and (2) separating. Furthermore, the middle part of the hair on the head, i.e., the parting, is also called «فَرْق» and «فِلْق». Therefore, in the Holy Quran, these words have been used with the same meaning.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«وَاِذۡ فَرَقۡنَا بِکُمُ الۡبَحۡرَ فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (2:50)\nTranslation: When We parted the sea for you, We saved you and drowned the people of Pharaoh.\n\nThe same event is described elsewhere as:\n«فَاَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ  الۡبَحۡرَ ؕ فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26:63)\nTranslation: At that time, We revealed to Moses, Strike the sea with your staff. So the sea split, and each section became like a huge mountain.\n\nHowever, there is a slight difference between the two, and that is that «فَلَقَ» is generally used when a part of something becomes separate, meaning the whole is divided into two parts. The term «فِلْق» is used for the parting on the head because it divides the hair into two equal parts. Moreover, «فِلْق» and «فِلْقَہ» refer to one part of a split thing that is in two parts. But the term «فَرَقَ» is general in this regard; its application extends to two and more than two parts.\n\nThe second difference is that «فَلَقَ» is generally applied to inanimate objects, while «فَرْق» is general. Its application is on both inanimate and animate entities, particularly on humans. A part separated from a group is called «فِرْق», and if this separated part is also large in number, it is called «فِرْقَہ». And in the case of a dispute or matter, «فَرِیْق».\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  فَالِقُ الۡحَبِّ وَ النَّوٰی» (6:95)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is the One Who splits the grain and the fruit pit. (Uthmani)\nThat is, the grain and the fruit pit split from the middle and separate, and a sprout emerges from them.\n\nSimilarly, «فَالِقُ الْاِصْبَاح» (6:96) is He by whose command the morning light splits open, (Taqi Uthmani). In this, the term «فَلَقَ» is appropriate from the perspective that the ray of morning is in the sky, just like the parting on the head.","«فَلَقَ» to split and separate an inanimate object into two parts.\n«فَرَقَ» to divide something into two or more parts (common).","rend","فلق ۔ فرق","2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:95-6:96-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-9:122-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-26:63-30:14-30-32-42:13-42:14-44:4-77:4-98:4-113:1",36
798,165,"T","مَزَّقَ","«مَزَّقَ» meaning to tear, scatter, or utterly destroy. «مَزَّقَ الثَّوْب» meaning to tear a garment. (manjada) As if in «مَزَّقَ», the intensity of the action is manifested (manjada).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَجَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ وَمَزَّقۡنٰہُمۡ کُلَّ مُمَزَّقٍ» (34/19)  \nTranslation: So We made their legends a reality, then tore them to pieces and utterly destroyed them.","«مَزَّق» shatter to pieces.","to tear","مزق","34:7-34:19",2
799,166,"T","اِنْفَطَر","«تَفَطَّرَ» and «اِنْفَطَر» mean to split or crack lengthwise within something. For example, in the Quran it is: «اِذَا السَّمَآءُ انۡفَطَرَتۡ» (82/1) Translation: When the sky cracks. Translation: When the sky splits (Usmani).","Splitting or cracking along the length from «تَفَطَّرَ » to «اِنْفَطَر» in something.","to split open","انفطر","73:18-82:1",2
800,166,"T","تفطّر ، اِنشَقَّ","The terms «تشفَّقَ» and «اِنشَقّ» refer to a hard object splitting into two pieces. For example, the Holy Quran states: «تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ» (19:90). Translation: It is as if the sky will almost burst apart and the earth split open because of it (the slander). At another instance, the Divine Command states: «وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَشَّقَّقُ فَیَخۡرُجُ مِنۡہُ الۡمَآءُ» (2:74). Translation: And some stones are such that they burst open, and water gushes forth from them.","«تشفَّقَ» and «اِنشَقّ» splitting a hard thing into two parts.","to split","تفطر ، انشق","19:90-42:5-54:1-55:37-69:16-84:1",6
801,166,"T","فلق ۔ اِنفَلَق","«اِنفَلَقَ» The splitting of something soft or small into two parts.\nFor example: The divine command of Allah, the Exalted, states:\n«فَاَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ  الۡبَحۡرَ ؕ فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: At that time, We revealed to Moses (peace be upon him): Strike the sea with your staff. So the sea split, and each part became as if it were a huge mountain.\n\n«فَلَقَ» To split an inanimate object into two parts and separate them.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  فَالِقُ الۡحَبِّ وَ النَّوٰی» (6/95)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is the One Who splits the grain and the pit. (Uthmani)","«اِنفَلَقَ» For a soft or small thing to split into two parts.\n«فَلَقَ» To tear an inanimate object into two pieces and separate them.","to burst","فلق ۔ انفلق","26:63-113:1",2
802,166,"T","صَدَع","«تَصَدَّعَ» denotes the splitting of something in such a way that it does not break into separate pieces (fissuring). According to Imam Raghb, it refers to the fissuring of solid bodies, such as iron, glass, etc. (muf) The term «صَدَّاع» is used for a headache that causes the head to split due to pain.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ الۡاَرۡضِ ذَاتِ الصَّدۡعِ» (86/12)\nTranslation: And by the earth which splits.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«لَّا یُصَدَّعُوۡنَ عَنۡہَا وَلَا یُنۡزِفُوۡنَ» (56/19)\nTranslation: There will be no headache from this (wine) nor will their intellects be impaired.\n\nAnd «تَصَدَّع» means for something to split and become many pieces. «تَصَدَّعَ الْقَوْم» means the scattering of a nation (fissuring).\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«لَوۡ اَنۡزَلۡنَا ہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ عَلٰی جَبَلٍ لَّرَاَیۡتَہٗ  خَاشِعًا مُّتَصَدِّعًا مِّنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ» (59/21)\nTranslation: If We had sent down this Quran upon a mountain, you would have seen it splitting apart out of fear of Allah.","«تَصَدَّعَ» to split into several parts.","to split","صدع","15:94-30:43-56:19-59:21-86:12",5
803,166,"T","تَمَیَّز","The meaning of «مَازَ ، مَیَّزَ» is to separate one thing from another on the basis of superiority. And the meanings of «اِمْتِاز» and «تَمَیَّز» are to be separate from others. And «تَمَیَّز» also means to be separate and then to split and break into pieces. «( م ۔ ق ) اور تَمَیَّزَ فُلَانٌ مِّنَ الْغَیْظ» is an idiom meaning that so-and-so burst with anger. (Source: Munjad)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تَکَادُ تَمَیَّزُ مِنَ الۡغَیۡظِ» (67/8)\nTranslation: It is almost as if Hell will burst with rage.","«تَمَیَّزَ» to erupt from inner fervor.","to split","تمیز","3:179-8:37-67:8",3
804,167,"T","دَارَ","To revolve in a circular motion; to rotate; to go around in circles; to experience the turning of time (the cycle of events) (ref.). And «دَائِرَہ» is a famous word. Its plural is «دَوَائِر», meaning the revolution of days, the afflictions and calamities of time (the cycle of events) (ref.). This word is used in a negative sense. The opposite of «دَوْرَۃ» is «دَوْلَۃً», which refers to a time of prosperity. (meaning)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ الۡخَوۡفُ رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ تَدُوۡرُ اَعۡیُنُہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ یُغۡشٰی عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡمَوۡتِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when the time of fear comes, you will see them looking at you. And their eyes will be turning as if someone is overcome by the dizziness of death.","to spin, to circle, to move in a circular path","to repent","دار","5:52-9:98-33:19-48:6",4
805,167,"T","طَافَ","«طَوْفَ» To encircle something (i.e., to go around another thing). And «مَطَاف» refers to the place of circling (majanad). For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17)\nTranslation: Young attendants who will remain in a constant state, circulating around them.","to go around something on all sides","to return","طاف","2:158-22:29-37:45-43:71-52:24-55:44-56:17-68:19-76:15-76:19",10
806,167,"T","حَارَ","«حَارَ» means to go around and return to the same place from where one started. According to Ibn Faris, its two fundamental meanings are: (1) returning/reverting, and (2) «اَنْ یَدُوْرَ الشَّئُ دَوَرًا» meaning to circle around something. «حَارَ الْمَاءِ فِی الْغَدِیْرِ» means the water in a pool began to swirl. And «مَحُوْر» refers to the wood around which a whirlwind spins, i.e., the pivot of a whirlwind.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّہٗ ظَنَّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّحُوۡرَ» (Surah 84, Verse 14)\nTranslation: He (the criminal) thought that he would never return (to God).","«حَارَ» to return to the original place after wandering.","to revert (from faith)","حار","84:14",1
807,167,"T","تَقَلَّبَ ، اِنْقَلَبَ","«قَلَبَ» is used in the sense of turning the direction or state. That is, to turn the upper part of something downwards or the inner part outwards (to invert), and in the words of Imam Raghīb, it means to change or turn from one state to another (to reverse). And «تَقَلَّبَ» and «اِنْقَلَاب» mean to return by oneself or to revert to the previous state.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«قَدۡ نَرٰی تَقَلُّبَ وَجۡہِکَ فِی السَّمَآءِ» (2/144) Translation: (O Muhammad ﷺ) We see you turning your face towards the heaven repeatedly.\n\nAnd the word «اِنْقَلَاب» is used in both good and bad contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ ارۡجِعِ  الۡبَصَرَ کَرَّتَیۡنِ  یَنۡقَلِبۡ اِلَیۡکَ الۡبَصَرُ خَاسِئًا وَّہُوَ حَسِیۡرٌ» (67/4) Translation: Then cast your glance repeatedly; the result will be that your sight will return to you, fatigued and defeated.\n\nAnd for evil or for returning from good, both idioms «اِنقلبَ علٰی عَقِبِہٖ» and «عَلٰی وَجْھہٖ» have been used.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«اَفَا۠ئِنۡ مَّاتَ اَوۡ قُتِلَ انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ عَلٰۤی اَعۡقَابِکُمۡ» (3/144) Translation: If Muhammad ﷺ were to die or be killed, would you then turn back on your heels? (Meaning: Would you become apostates?)\n\nAt another place, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَصَابَتۡہُ فِتۡنَۃُۨ  انۡقَلَبَ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ» (22/11) Translation: And if any calamity befalls him, he turns back on his face (i.e., in retreat).","to undergo a complete transformation from one state to its opposite","to return","تقلب ، انقلب","2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9",32
808,167,"T","نَکَصَ علٰی عَقِبِہٖ","«نَکَصَ» means to turn away. And «نَکَصَ عَنِ الْاَمْرِ» means to refrain from a task, to stop. And «نَکَصَ عَلٰی عَقِبِہٖ» means to turn back on one's heels, to turn away from a previous matter (m.), and its usage is exclusively for turning away from good deeds. (m.) Thus, this word is more specific than 'revolution' or 'change'.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَدۡ کَانَتۡ اٰیٰتِیۡ تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡکُمۡ فَکُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰۤی  اَعۡقَابِکُمۡ  تَنۡکِصُوۡنَ» (23/66)\nTranslation: My verses were recited to you, but you would turn back on your heels.","«نَکَصَ علٰی عَقِبِہٖ» turning away from good deeds.","To repent","نکص علی عقبہٖ","2:143-3:144-3:149-6:71-8:48-13:41-23:66-27:10-28:31-43:28",10
809,167,"R","اِنْصَرَف","The word «صَرَفَ» is more common than «نَکَبَ» (to be crooked). And «نَکِبَ» is used for complete change. Meaning: to reverse completely, to turn around. Whereas «صَرَفَ» is used in both senses: changing direction and complete change. «تَصْرِیْفِ الرِّیَاح» means to change the direction of the winds, even if this change is very slight.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says: «وَ اِذَا مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ  نَّظَرَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ ؕ ہَلۡ یَرٰىکُمۡ مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ ثُمَّ انۡصَرَفُوۡا» (9/127). Translation: And when any Surah is revealed, they begin to look at each other (and ask), Well, does anyone see you? Then they turn away.","«اِنْصَرَف» To change direction is a shift from one state to another, whether slight or significant.","Revert","انصرف","3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29",26
810,167,"T","وَلّٰی ، تَوَلّٰی","«وَلّٰی ، تَوَلّٰی » means to turn away, to avoid, and to distance oneself. And «وَلَّی الدُّبُر» means to turn one's back and leave, or in the sense of fleeing.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ  کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا» (27/10)\nTranslation: Then when Moses saw it as a moving snake, he turned back in retreat.\n\nOn another occasion, the divine command states:\n«فَتَوَلّٰی عَنۡہُمۡ وَ قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ لَقَدۡ اَبۡلَغۡتُکُمۡ رِسَالَۃَ رَبِّیۡ» (7/79)\nTranslation: Then Salih turned away from them in despair and said, O my people, I have certainly conveyed to you the message of Allah.","«وَلّٰی ، تَوَلّٰی » meaning to turn away, to avoid, and to go far away.","to repent","ولی ، تولی","2:64-2:83-2:144-2:148-2:205-3:23-3:82-3:111-4:80-4:115-5:92-7:79-7:93-8:16-9:3-9:25-10:72-12:84-18:18-20:48-20:60-24:47-27:10-28:24-28:31-31:7-33:15-47:22-48:16-51:39-53:29-53:33-54:45-59:12-64:12-70:17-75:32-80:1-88:23-92:16-96:13",41
811,167,"T","اِرْتَدَّ","The meaning of «رَدّ» is to not accept something and turn it back (i.e., reject it). Mardood (rejected) refers to that which is returned because it is unacceptable. And «اِرْتَدَّ» means to turn away from something out of dislike, to return, and «اِرْتَدَّ عَنْ دِیْنِہٖ» means to turn away from religion or to become an apostate.\n\nThe Quran states:\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18:64)\nTranslation: So they turned back, tracing their footsteps.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّرۡتَدِدۡ مِنۡکُمۡ عَنۡ دِیۡنِہٖ فَیَمُتۡ وَ ہُوَ کَافِرٌ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ حَبِطَتۡ اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ  فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (2:217)\nTranslation: And whoever among you turns back from his religion (becomes an apostate) and dies as a disbeliever—their deeds will become worthless in this world and the Hereafter.","to turn away from something deemed unacceptable, and to renounce one's faith.","to repent","ارتد","2:217-5:21-5:54-12:96-14:43-18:64-27:40-47:25",8
812,167,"T","اَدْبَرَ","«دُبُر» Its plural is «اَدْبَار», meaning 'back' or 'posterior'. Its antonym is «قَبْل», and «دَبَرَ فَلَانٌ» means 'so-and-so turned his back' (transitive), while «اَدْبَرَ» means 'to turn one's back and go away'.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ نَظَرَ ثُمَّ عَبَسَ وَبَسَرَ ثُمَّ  اَدۡبَرَ وَاسۡتَکۡبَرَ» (74:21-23)\nTranslation: Then he reflected, then he turned his face away and frowned. Then he turned his back and went away in pride.","«اَدْبَرَ» to turn one's back and go away, to turn away in rejection.","to repent","ادبر","3:111-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-15:65-17:46-33:15-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22",20
813,168,"T","اَقْلَبَ ۔ قَلَّبَ","This refers to a complete transformation from one state to another.  \nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«یُعَذِّبُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ وَ یَرۡحَمُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ ۚ وَ اِلَیۡہِ تُقۡلَبُوۡنَ» (29/21)  \nTranslation: He will punish whom He wills and show mercy to whom He wills. And to Him you will be returned. (Uthmani)  \n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:  \n«وَّ نُقَلِّبُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ» (18/18)  \nTranslation: And We turned them from side to side.","«تَقَلُّبَ» refers to a complete transformation from one state to another.","to turn away","اقلب ۔ قلب","2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9",32
814,168,"T","صَرَفَ","«صَرَفَ» is used in the literal sense of turning one's face. For example: it is mentioned in the Quran: «وَ اِذَا صُرِفَتۡ اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تِلۡقَآءَ اَصۡحٰبِ النَّارِ» (7/47) Translation: and when their eyes will be turned towards the people of Hell (Uthmani).","«صَرَفَ» is used to mean simply turning one's face.","to turn away","صرف","3:152-6:16-6:46-6:65-6:105-7:47-7:58-7:146-9:127-10:32-12:24-12:33-12:34-17:41-17:89-18:53-18:54-20:113-24:43-25:19-25:50-25:65-39:6-40:69-46:27-46:29",26
815,168,"T","وَلّٰی","turning away, disregarding, distancing oneself, and causing to turn away.\nFor example, it is in the Quran: «فَلَنُوَلِّیَنَّکَ قِبۡلَۃً  تَرۡضٰہَا» (2:144) Translation: So indeed, We will turn you toward the qibla you are pleased with.","«وَلّٰی» meaning to turn away, to turn one's face away, and to be distant.","to turn away","ولی","2:64-2:83-2:144-2:148-2:205-3:23-3:82-3:111-4:80-4:115-5:92-7:79-7:93-8:16-9:3-9:25-10:72-12:84-18:18-20:48-20:60-24:47-27:10-28:24-28:31-31:7-33:15-47:22-48:16-51:39-53:29-53:33-54:45-59:12-64:12-70:17-75:32-80:1-88:23-92:16-96:13",41
816,168,"T","ردّ","To return something due to its being unacceptable; to give back; to repel.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65).  \nTranslation: And when they opened their baggage, they found their capital returned to them.","To turn something away because it is unacceptable.","to turn away","رد","2:85-2:109-2:217-2:228-3:100-3:149-4:47-4:59-4:83-4:86-4:91-5:108-6:27-6:28-6:62-6:71-6:147-7:53-9:94-9:101-9:105-10:30-11:76-12:65-12:110-13:11-14:9-16:70-17:6-18:36-18:87-21:40-22:5-28:13-30:43-33:25-38:33-40:43-41:47-42:44-42:47-62:8-79:10-95:5",44
817,168,"T","لَفَتَ","«لَفَت» and «اِلتَفَتَ» mean to turn something to the right or left. And «اِلتَفَتَ» also means to pay attention, to turn and look, to turn one's face to look. (Majid)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَلۡفِتَنَا عَمَّا وَجَدۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ اٰبَآءَنَا» (10/78)\nTranslation: The courtiers of Pharaoh said, O Moses! Have you come to us to turn us away from that upon which we found our fathers?\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ لَا یَلۡتَفِتۡ مِنۡکُمۡ اَحَدٌ» (11/81)\nTranslation: Let none of you turn back!","«لَفَتَ» meaning to turn right or left.","to turn (to God)","لفت","10:78-11:81-15:65-75:29",4
818,168,"T","اَفَک","«اَفَکَ» means to turn away correctly and in the right direction (transitive), and «اِفْک» comes in the meaning of falsehood and slander.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَجِئۡتَنَا لِتَاۡفِکَنَا عَنۡ اٰلِہَتِنَا» (46/22)\nTranslation: They (the people of 'Ad) said, Have you come to us to turn us away from our gods?","«اَفَکَ» to divert from the correct path to the wrong one.","to turn away","افک","7:117-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9",12
819,169,"T","زَلَقَ","«زَلَقَ» means to slip. And its opposite is «ثَبَتَ». (M. L) «زَلَقَتِ الْقَدَمُ» means the foot slipped, and «زَلَقَ بَدَنٌ» means to cause slipperiness by applying oil, etc., to the body.  \nAnd «مَزْلَقُ » refers to a place where one might slip and not be able to plant one's feet firmly.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» (18/40)  \nTranslation: And send down upon your garden a calamity from the sky, so it becomes a smooth plain. (Meaning: so smooth that a person would slip.)  \nAnd «اَزْلَقَ» means to cause someone to slip through intimidation or deception. And «اَزْلَقَ بِبَصَرِہٖ» is an idiom meaning to glare at someone with anger and fierce eyes. (Manjad)  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ اِنۡ یَّکَادُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَیُزۡلِقُوۡنَکَ بِاَبۡصَارِہِمۡ» (68/51)  \nTranslation: And when the disbelievers hear the Reminder (the Quran), they would, as it were, look at you with the eyes of one intending to make you slip. (Meaning: they stare at you so intensely and intimidatingly that you might slip [in your resolve] out of fear.)","«زَلَقَ» means to slip up.","to slip","زلق","18:40-68:51",2
820,169,"T","زَلَّ","«زَلَّ» means to slip and to move from one's place. And its antonym is «رَسَخَ» (M. L). And according to some, its meanings are to slip and to fall (M. Q). And its antonym «ثَبَتَ» also occurs, and the Noble Quran also supports it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَکُمۡ  دَخَلًۢا بَیۡنَکُمۡ فَتَزِلَّ قَدَمٌۢ  بَعۡدَ ثُبُوۡتِہَا» (16/94)\nTranslation: And do not make your oaths a means of deception between yourselves, lest a foot slip after it has been firmly planted.\n\nAnd «اَزَلَّ» means to cause someone else to slip in such a way that they become uprooted from their place. And both «زَلَّ» and «اَزَلَّ» are used in both literal and metaphorical senses.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَزَلَّہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ عَنۡہَا فَاَخۡرَجَہُمَا مِمَّا کَانَا فِیۡہِ» (2/36)\nTranslation: Then Satan caused them both to slip from there and brought them out of the state in which they were.","«زَلَّ» stumble and slip or fall.","to slip","زل","2:36-2:209-3:155-16:94",4
821,169,"T","دَحَضَ ، اَدْحَضَ","«دَحَضَ» meaning anything that is prone to decline or slipping away (m. l.) and «دَحَضَ» meaning to slip like a slaughtered animal (m) and «دَحَضَ الرَّجُل» meaning a person's foot slipping or stumbling (muf) and «دَحَضَتِ الْحُجَّۃ» meaning a proof/argument becoming invalid (minj) and «اَدْحَضَ» meaning to cause someone to slip or stumble.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ یُجَادِلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ» (18/56)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers argue with falsehood to undermine the truth through that [falsehood].","«دَحَضَ» meaning to slip and become weak, to perish.","to slip","دحض ، ادحض","18:56-37:141-40:5",3
822,169,"T","ھَالَ","«ھَیْل» refers to the sliding of sand from the top to the bottom of a sandhill or mound. And «اَلْھَیْل» and «اَلْھَیَال» refer to fallen sand (according to Manjad).  \nFor example: In the Quran it says:  \n«وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73:14)  \nTranslation: And the mountains will become like sand dunes sliding.","to slide down from a pile of sand or the like","to slip","ھال","73:14",1
823,169,"T","رَاوَدَ","«رَوْد ، رَادَ» means to go around searching for something, to come and go. And «اَرَادَ» means for a thought to arise in the heart. And «رَاوَدَ» means to make someone share one's thoughts or intentions when there is no harmony, and this word is used to encourage evil and immorality. That is, to mislead and deceive someone into committing evil (fem.).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«قَالَ مَا خَطۡبُکُنَّ اِذۡ رَاوَدۡتُّنَّ یُوۡسُفَ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ» (12/51)\n\n1 - Translation: The ruler of Egypt asked the women, So what happened when you tried to incline Joseph toward yourselves?\n2 - Translation: The king said to the women, What is the truth of your matter when you seduced Joseph from the protection of his chastity? (Othmani)","«رَاوَدَ» to deliberately lead someone into sin.","to slip","راود","12:23-12:26-12:30-12:32-12:51-12:61-54:37",7
824,170,"F","ثَمَرَ","«ثَمَرَ» means fruit. This word is commonly used. It can apply to anything whether fresh or dried. Its plurals are «اَثْمَار» and «ثَمَرَات».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَخۡرَجَ بِہٖ مِنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ رِزۡقًا لَّکُمۡ» (2/22)\n\nTranslation: Then He brings forth from the earth its produce for you to eat. (Othmaniؒ)","«ثَمَرَ» is a general term for fruit.","Fruit","ثمر","2:22-2:25-2:126-2:155-2:266-6:99-6:141-7:57-7:130-13:3-14:32-14:37-16:11-16:67-16:69-18:34-18:42-28:57-35:27-36:35-41:47-47:15",22
825,170,"F","فَاکِھَۃ","«فَاکِھَۃ» refers to all fruits except dates, grapes, and pomegranates, and its plural is «فَوَاکِہَ» (M. L.). According to some scholars, all fruits, including grapes, but excluding dates and pomegranates, are «فَاکِھَۃ».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِمَا فَاکِہَۃٌ وَّ نَخۡلٌ وَّ رُمَّانٌ» (55:68)\nTranslation: In them are fruits and date-palms and pomegranates.\n\nThis indicates that dates and pomegranates are distinct from «فَاکِھَۃ», and some interpret «فَوَاکِہَ» as referring to dried fruits. The meaning of «فَکِہَ» is pleasant disposition, being cheerful and smiling. «فَکَّہَ» also means to feed someone fruit. To delight someone with sweet speech is also included (Manjad). Hence, according to Ibn Faris, «فَاکِھَۃ» is the fruit from which pleasure and delight are obtained. (M. L.) (And Allah knows best).","«فَاکِھَۃ» is used for other fruits besides dates and pomegranates, and according to some, for delicious fruits or dried fruits.","Fruit","فاکھۃ","36:57-38:51-43:73-44:55-52:22-55:11-55:52-55:68-56:20-56:32-80:31",11
826,170,"F","جَنِی","«جَنِی» Fresh fruit. Meaning fruit that is completely ripe and ready for picking. Whether it is still on the tree or has already been harvested. (muf)  \n«جَنِیَ» also means to pick fruit or to pluck fresh fruit. (manjad)  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَجَنَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ دَانٍ» ( 55/54 )  \nTranslation: And the fruits of both gardens will be hanging low (within easy reach).","«جَنِی» fresh fruits that have fallen or are still hanging on the tree.","Fruit","جنی","19:25-55:54",2
827,170,"F","اُکُل","«اُکُل» refers to every produce of trees and plants that becomes food for humans. According to Maf, the author of Al-Munjid, its meanings are fruit, food, and ample provision.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265). Translation: Their example is like a garden on elevated land; when a downpour strikes it, it yields double the fruit.","«اُکُل» The edible portion of a fruit-bearing tree or plant that serves as human food.","Fruit","اکل","2:265-6:141-13:4-13:35-14:25-18:33-34:16",7
828,170,"F","یَنَعَ","«یَنَعَ» refers to a fruit ripening fully and becoming ready. The ripe fruit is termed «یَانِعَۃٌ» or «مُوْنِعَۃٌ» (singular). For instance, the Quran states: «اُنۡظُرُوۡۤا اِلٰی ثَمَرِہٖۤ اِذَاۤ اَثۡمَرَ وَیَنۡعِہٖ» (6/99). Translation: Observe its fruit when it bears fruit, and also observe its ripening.","«یَنَعَ» to ripen.","fruit","ینع","6:99",1
829,170,"F","جَنَی","Lexically, it means to pick ripe fruits and to harvest them (as per dictionaries). However, in the Quran, this word has been used twice. It is employed for ripe fruits that are hanging on trees and are ready to fall.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَنَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ دَانٍ» (55:54)\nTranslation: And the fruits of the two gardens will be hanging low.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ  تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا» (19:25)\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards you; it will drop upon you fresh ripe dates.","«جَنَي » the ripening of fruit to the point where, if not harvested, it falls off the tree on its own, or the act of plucking and picking the fruit.","Fruit","جنی","19:25-55:54",2
830,171,"D","نَفَخَ","«نَفْخ» means the swelling of the belly and «مَنْفُوخ» is used for a large-bellied or fat man. And «نَفَخَ» means to blow air into a body (m. r.), and according to the author of al-Munjid, «نَفَخَ» only means to blow. And «مِنْفَاخُ» refers to a blacksmith's bellows.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it says: «فَاَنۡفُخُ فِیۡہِ فَیَکُوۡنُ طَیۡرًۢا بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (3/49). Translation: Then when I blow into it, it becomes a real bird by the command of Allah.","«نَفَخَ» Blow upon. Commonly used. And according to some, to blow into a body.","Divine breath","نفخ","3:49-5:110-6:73-15:29-18:96-18:99-20:102-21:91-23:101-27:87-32:9-36:51-38:72-39:68-50:20-66:12-69:13-78:18",18
831,171,"I","نَقَرَ","«نَقَرَ» means to blow into something that is meant to be blown into to produce sound. And «نَاقُوْر» refers to anything that is hollow and resonant from within, such as a drum, a trumpet, a horn, or any instrument that is blown into (detailed explanation).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا نُقِرَ فِی النَّاقُوۡرِ» (74/8)\nTranslation: So when the trumpet is blown.","«نَقَرَ» blowing into something that can be inflated or is hollow inside.","Inspiration","نقر","74:8",1
832,171,"D","نَفَثَ","«نَفَثَ» means to vomit. To expel a little (as in verse 190). To blow away or spit out after scattering, or to expel poison (metaphorically). And «نَفْثُ الدَّم» is the name of the disease in which some blood comes with the phlegm.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ  شَرِّ النَّفّٰثٰتِ فِی الۡعُقَدِ» (113/4)\nTranslation: And from the evil of those who blow (spells) on knots (O Allah, I seek refuge in You).","«نَفَثَ» to blow. The puff blown by the hookah-smoker.","Divine breath","نفث","113:4",1
833,171,"D","اَطْفَاَ","«طَفَئَتِ النَّار» means the extinguishing of fire. And «اَطْفَاَ» means extinguishing by blowing (transitive), and this same word is also used for extinguishing a lamp or light (cf. 133).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا نُوۡرَاللّٰہِ بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ» (61:8)\n\nTranslation: They desire to extinguish the light of God's guidance with their mouths (by blowing).","«اَطْفَاَ» means to blow out a lamp or extinguish a fire.","Divine breath","اطفا","5:64-9:32-61:8",3
834,172,"S","ذَرَأَ","«ذَرْءَ» refers to everything that is sown and cultivated (M. L.), and «ذَرَاَ الْاَرْض» means to sow seeds in the earth (Munjid). Lexicographers also write that Sahib-ul-Muntaha al-Ard signifies to create, increase, or spread (M. R.). The same meaning is implied by «ذُرِّیَّۃ», which applies to the offspring of both jinn and humans. The Noble Quran also supports the meanings of Sahib-ul-Muntaha al-Ard.\n\n(1) Example of the meaning to create:\nThe Divine declaration is:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ ذَرَاۡنَا لِجَہَنَّمَ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ» (7:179)\nTranslation: And We have certainly created many of the jinn and mankind for Hell.\n\n(2) Example of the meaning to spread or to increase:\nThe Divine declaration is:\n«قُلۡ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ ذَرَاَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ اِلَیۡہِ تُحۡشَرُوۡنَ» (67:24)\nTranslation: Say, 'It is He who has multiplied you throughout the earth, and to Him you will be gathered.'","«ذَرَاَ» meaning to create and spread.","Spread","ذرأ","6:136-7:179-16:13-23:79-67:24",5
835,172,"T","مَدّ","«مَدَّ» to stretch something out in length and extend it (meaning). For example, the meaning of «مَدّ» is to lengthen and spread.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَیۡفَ مَدَّ الظِّلَّ» (25/45)\nTranslation: Have you not considered your Lord, how He spreads out the shadow?","to spread and lengthen","to spread","مد","2:15-7:202-13:3-19:75-25:45-31:27-56:30-74:12-104:9",9
836,172,"S","دَحٰی ، طَحٰحٰی","«دَحٰی اور طَحٰی» These two are in fact the same word. The only difference is in pronunciation or regional dialect. And its meaning is to spread far and wide. Its detailed exposition has been covered.","«دَحٰی اور طَحٰی» spread far and wide.","Spread","دحی ، طححی","79:30-88:20-91:6",3
837,172,"T","نَشَرَ","The meaning of «نَشَرَ» is to spread something, to make some news famous (M.R), and its opposite «طَوَي» means to fold. One says «نَشَرَتُ الْکِتَابَ ثُمَّ طَوَیْتُہٗ» I opened the book and then closed it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُنَزِّلُ الۡغَیۡثَ مِنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ مَا قَنَطُوۡا وَ یَنۡشُرُ رَحۡمَتَہٗ» (42/28)\nTranslation: And He it is who sends down rain after people have despaired, and spreads His mercy (i.e., the blessings of rain).","«نَشَرَ» to exalt, spread, and publicize.","to spread","نشر","17:13-18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1",11
838,172,"T","بَسَطَ","The meaning of «بَسَطَ» is to open, spread, and expand something. And «بَسَاطُ» also means a wide earth, as well as vastness (muf). Its opposite is also «قَبَضَ» and «قَدَرَ».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اَللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ سَحَابًا فَیَبۡسُطُہٗ فِی السَّمَآءِ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (30/48)\n\nTranslation: It is Allah who sends the winds, and they raise the clouds. Then He spreads them in the sky as He wills.","«بَسَطَ» meaning to open, spread, and expand.","to spread","بسط","2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19",22
839,172,"T","بَثَّ","«بَثَّ» means scattered (i.e., dispersed, scattered, distressed). It also refers to a state of distress and intense grief. Thus, «بَثَّ» is used in senses related to spreading, such that the components of that thing are scattered, like dust or the moths of a candle.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ اتَّقُوۡا رَبَّکُمُ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ وَّ خَلَقَ مِنۡہَا زَوۡجَہَا وَ بَثَّ مِنۡہُمَا رِجَالًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ نِسَآءً» (4/1)\nTranslation: O people! Fear your Lord, who created you from a single soul, and created from it its mate, and dispersed from both of them many men and women.","«بَثَّ» to spread in such a way that its parts become scattered and dispersed.","to spread","بث","2:164-4:1-31:10-42:29-45:4-56:6-88:16-101:4",8
840,173,"T","نَبَذَ","«نَبَذَ» means to discard something considering it worthless and futile, or to cast it behind one's back heedlessly. (See Farahi, vol. 190)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوَ کُلَّمَا عٰہَدُوۡا عَہۡدًا نَّبَذَہٗ فَرِیۡقٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ» (2:100)\n\nTranslation: Whenever they make a solemn covenant, a faction among them casts it aside recklessly.","«نَبَذَ» to cast aside without regard.","to throw","نبذ","2:100-2:101-3:187-8:58-20:96-28:40-37:145-51:40-68:49-104:4",10
841,173,"T","طَرَحَ","«طَرَحَ» To discard something as worthless and throw it away; to hurl it far away, out of people's sight (intransitive). «رَاَیْتُہٗ مِنْ طَرْح» I saw it from a distance. And «طَرُوْحُ» a remote, distant place. And «طَرَحَ» refers to something that is thrown away, considered worthless.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اقۡتُلُوۡا یُوۡسُفَ اَوِ اطۡرَحُوۡہُ  اَرۡضًا یَّخۡلُ لَکُمۡ وَجۡہُ  اَبِیۡکُمۡ» (12:9)  \nTranslation: (The brothers of Yusuf said) Either kill Yusuf or cast him away to some distant land, then your father's attention will be solely towards you.","«طَرَحَ» to throw something away as worthless or trash.","to throw","طرح","12:9",1
842,173,"T","رَجَمَ","«رَجَمَ» To kill someone by throwing stones and pebbles at them; to stone to death (Fiqh 189).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ اِنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡا عَلَیۡکُمۡ یَرۡجُمُوۡکُمۡ اَوۡ یُعِیۡدُوۡکُمۡ فِیۡ مِلَّتِہِمۡ» (18/20)\nTranslation: If they gain power over you, they will stone you to death or compel you to revert to their religion.","«رَجَمَ» To throw stones or pebbles from a distance, or to kill by stoning. To stone (as a form of capital punishment).","to throw","رجم","11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20",6
843,173,"T","رَمٰی ، قذف","Both words «رَمٰی ، قَذَفَ» are close in meaning. Both mean to throw stones, rocks, etc., far away or to throw from a distance. (Note) The basic difference between them is that «رَمٰی» is generally used for throwing material objects.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ مَا رَمَیۡتَ اِذۡ رَمَیۡتَ وَ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ رَمٰی» (8:17)\nTranslation: And [O Muhammad ﷺ], when you threw the pebbles, you did not throw them, but Allah threw them.\n\nFrom this, the Shariah term «رَمِیَ الْجِمَار» is also used in this sense, meaning that the pilgrims throw pebbles at the Satan from a distance in Mina. And the word «قَذَفَ» is used metaphorically, such as the famous Shariah term *hadd al-qadf*, which refers to the prescribed punishment for accusing someone of adultery or slander. In this meaning, it appears in the Quran:\n\nFor example: The divine command says:\n«وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الرُّعۡبَ فَرِیۡقًا تَقۡتُلُوۡنَ وَ تَاۡسِرُوۡنَ فَرِیۡقًا» (33:26)\nTranslation: And Allah cast terror into their hearts, so you killed some of them and took others captive.\n\nHowever, later these two words began to be used synonymously. Thus, in the Quran, the term *rami* (throwing) is also used metaphorically.\n\nFor example: The divine command says:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّکۡسِبۡ خَطِیۡٓئَۃً اَوۡ اِثۡمًا ثُمَّ یَرۡمِ بِہٖ بَرِیۡٓـئًا فَقَدِ احۡتَمَلَ بُہۡتَانًا وَّ اِثۡمًا مُّبِیۡنًا» (4:112)\nTranslation: And whoever commits a fault or sin but then attributes it to an innocent person, he has borne [the burden of] falsehood and a clear sin.\n\nSimilarly, «قَذَفَ» is also used in the Quran for material objects.\n\nFor example: The divine command says:\n«وَ لٰکِنَّا حُمِّلۡنَاۤ اَوۡزَارًا مِّنۡ زِیۡنَۃِ الۡقَوۡمِ فَقَذَفۡنٰہَا» (20:87)\nTranslation: But they took out from our presence the ornament of the people of Pharaoh, so we cast it into the fire.","Both terms are similar in meaning. Their meanings involve throwing pebbles, stones, etc., from a distance or hurling them afar.","to throw","رمی ، قذف","4:12-8:17-20:39-20:87-21:18-33:26-34:48-34:53-37:8-59:2-77:32-105:4",12
844,173,"T","جَفَاَ","«اَلْجَفَاء» refers to the filth and debris that accumulates on both banks of a river valley, or the scum from a pot that, when it boils over, splatters everywhere. It is said «اَجْفَاْتِ الْقِدْرِزَ بَدَھَا», meaning the pot has thrown its boiling over.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَاَمَّا الزَّبَدُ فَیَذۡہَبُ جُفَآءً» (13:17)  \nTranslation: And the foam/scum goes away as worthless, while that which benefits people remains in the earth. (Meaning: The river throws it onto the banks, where it eventually dries up and accumulates.)","«جَفَاَ» The river casts its foam upon its banks, and the pot its boiling upon its rim.","to throw","جفا","13:17",1
845,174,"T","ظَمْاٰن","«ظَمَاَ» means to be thirsty. And «ظَمْاٌ» means thirst. And the word «ظَمْاٌ» is the next degree from «عَطْشَ» (meaning thirst) (Fasl 162). And «ظَمْاٰن» is the intensive form. The meaning is a person who is extremely restless due to thirst. Very thirsty.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39)\nTranslation: And those who disbelieved - their deeds are like a mirage in a desert which the thirsty one thinks is water.","«ظَمْاٰن» to be restless with thirst.","Thirsty","ظمان","9:120-20:119-24:39",3
846,174,"T","وِرْد","«وِرْد» means a thirsty person or a caravan that sets out in search of water (singular). «وَرَدَ» means reaching the water's edge to drink (12:90). «وِرْد» also means 'water's edge' (11:98). «مَوْرُوْد» also means 'water's edge.' The opposite of «وَرَدَ» is «صَدَرَ», meaning to return after drinking water.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَّ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا» (19:86). Translation: 'And we will drive the sinners to Hell, thirsty.'","«وِرْد» A person so thirsty who has set out in search of water.","thirsty","ورد","11:98-19:86",2
847,174,"T","ھِیْم","«اَلْھَیَام» meaning extreme thirst (M.L. 162), and «ھَامَ» meaning to be intensely thirsty (Manjad), and «هُيَامُ» is a disease of the camel in which the camel remains intensely thirsty. And «ھِیْم» is that intensely thirsty camel which is afflicted with a disease that does not quench its thirst.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡحَمِیۡمِ فَشٰرِبُوۡنَ شُرۡبَ الۡہِیۡمِ» (56/54,55)\nTranslation: And you will be given to drink of a gushing spring, and you will drink it as camels afflicted with the disease of thirst drink.","«ھِیْم» An unquenchable thirst.","Thirsty","ھیم","56:55",1
848,174,"T","لَھَثَ","«لَھَثَ» refers to panting and protruding the tongue due to extreme thirst. According to some, this term is also used to describe a combination of desperation (i.e., compulsion and helplessness) and thirst (Muf.). Furthermore, «لُھْثَۃٌ» denotes severe thirst, while «لُهَاثُ» refers to thirst arising from internal or stomach heat (Q. M.).\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» (7:176). Translation: Thus, its example is like that of a dog: if you burden it, it pants with its tongue out, and if you leave it alone, it still pants with its tongue out.","«لَھَثَ» tongue hanging out due to extreme thirst.","thirsty","لھث","7:176",1
849,175,"G","اَکْوَاب","The plural of «کُوْب» is «اَکْوَاب». And «کُوْب» refers to a cup or vessel that has no handle (like a glass, etc.). If it has a handle, it is called «کُوْز» (cf. 30). And if it has both a handle and a spout, it is called «إِبْرِيْق», and its plural is «اَبَارِیْق». Meaning a lota or jug, etc.","«كُوْبُ» a handleless cup.","Goblet","اکواب","43:71-56:18-76:15-88:14",4
850,175,"C","کَاْس","A cup filled with drink. A goblet. A brimming cup. And if it contains no drink, then it is «قَدَحَ». (p. 30) «کَاْس» generally refers to a cup filled with wine. And «کَاْس» also means wine (source: Munjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ ۔ بِاَکۡوَابٍ وَّ اَبَارِیۡقَ ۬ ۙ وَ کَاۡسٍ مِّنۡ مَّعِیۡنٍ ۔ لَّا یُصَدَّعُوْنَ عَنْهَا وَ لَا یُنْزِفُوْنَۙ» (56/18)\nTranslation: Immortal youths will circulate among them with goblets, pitchers, and a cup [of wine] from a flowing spring, wherein they will suffer no headache nor any intoxication.","a cup filled with drink «کَاْس»","cup","کاس","37:45-52:23-56:18-76:5-76:17-78:34",6
851,175,"C","سِقَایۃ","«سَقٰی» means to give water to drink or to present any beverage. And «سِقَایۃ» also refers to the one who gives water to drink and to the drinking vessel (masculine).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ  فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/70)  \nTranslation: When Joseph began to load his brothers' supplies, he placed his cup into his brother's baggage.","«سِقَایۃ» A cup or pitcher for drinking and serving water.","Cup","سقایۃ","9:19-12:70-76:21",3
852,175,"C","صُوَاع ، صِوَاع","«صُوَاعُ» is a cup, glass, or vessel for drinking water that is made of gold or silver. Its plural is «صِیْعَان» (munjad). If the glass or vessel is made of glass (qanchar), it is called «قَدَحَ»; if made of wood, «عُسْ»; if made of leather, «عَلْبَہ»; and if made of clay, «مِرْكَن». (Salaman Mansoor Puri, p. 174) (It should be clarified that this word «صَاعَ» does not derive from the meaning of 'measure' [paimana].)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ الۡمَلِکِ» (12/72)\nTranslation: They said, We cannot find the cup of the king [for drinking].","«صُوَاعُ» A cup or glass for drinking water, made of gold or silver.","cup","صواع ، صواع","12:72",1
853,176,"P","غِسْلِیْن","The meaning of «غَسَلَ» is to purify something with water and to remove dirt and impurities. And «غِسْل» refers to anything with which something is washed or cleaned (as per the dictionary). And «غِسْلِیْن» refers to dirty, filthy, and contaminated water or washing, and also to the washing of wounds that contains pus, blood, and dirt.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَّلَا طَعَامٌ اِلَّا مِنۡ غِسۡلِیۡنٍ لَّا یَاۡکُلُہٗۤ اِلَّا الۡخَاطِئُوۡنَ» (69/36)  \nTranslation: And he will have no food except pus, which no one will eat except the sinners.","«غِسْلِیْن» the water used for washing wounds, etc., or dirt and grime.","Pus","غسلین","69:36",1
854,176,"P","غَسَّاق","The translation of «غَسَّاق» is generally rendered as 'pus' or 'flowing pus'. «صاحبِ مُنْجِد» - «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ» and «صَاحِبِ مُنْتَہَی الْاَرَب» all indicate its meaning as cold and foul-smelling water. And «صاحبِ مَقَائِیْسُ الْلُغَۃ» has written its meaning as «مَا تَقْطُرُ مِنْ جُلُوْدِ اَھْلِ النَّارِ», meaning that which will drip drop by drop from the skins of the people of Hell. (M. L) In the Noble Quran, the word «غَسَّاق» has been used in two places in contrast to «حَمِیْم». This indicates that its meaning as cold and foul-smelling water is more appropriate. And Allah knows best. Now observe the examples:\n\nThe Divine Command states:\n«اِلَّا حَمِیۡمًا وَّغَسَّاقًا» ( 78/25 )\nTranslation:\n1 - But hot water and flowing pus (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - But hot water and flowing pus (Osmaniؒ)\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«ہٰذَا ۙ فَلۡیَذُوۡقُوۡہُ حَمِیۡمٌ  وَّ غَسَّاقٌ» ( 38/57 )\nTranslation:\n1 - This is the boiling, scalding water and pus; so taste it (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - This is it, so taste it: hot water and pus (Osmaniؒ)","«غَسَّاق» stagnant, cold water, or flowing pus.","Pus","غساق","38:57-78:25",2
855,176,"P","صَدِیْد","According to Imam Raghib, its meaning is pus that accumulates between flesh and skin. (Muf) And it has likely been defined in the sense of «صَدّ». Sahib-i-Munjid writes its meaning as mixed blood (pus mixed with blood), and this seems correct. And «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ» writes its meaning as the mixture of water and blood in a wound. (F, L 118)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مِّنۡ وَّرَآئِہٖ جَہَنَّمُ وَ یُسۡقٰی مِنۡ مَّآءٍ صَدِیۡدٍ» (14/16)\nTranslation: Behind him is Hell, and he will be given pus to drink.","«صَدِيد» blood, pus, putrid matter, discharge from a wound.","Pus","صدید","14:16",1
856,177,"B","ظَھَرَ","«ظَھَرَ» is the posterior external part of a living being from the lower back up to the neck, and its plural is «ظَھُور». For example, the Quran states: «وَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ وَرَآءَ ظَہۡرِہٖ» (84:10). Translation: And he whose record is given to him from behind his back.","«ظَھَرَ» the back of a living being, from the tailbone to the neck.","back (in the sense of turning one's back on something, often used in Islamic contexts to signify rejection or abandonment of faith or guidance)","ظھر","2:101-2:189-3:187-6:31-6:94-6:138-6:146-7:172-9:35-11:92-21:39-35:45-42:33-43:13-84:10-94:3",16
857,177,"B","دُبُر","«دُبُر» means a seat (of honor) and the rear part of everything. Its plural is «اَدْبَار» and its opposite is «قُبُل». «دُبُر» and «اَدْبَار» also come in the meanings of 'after' or 'behind'. For example, «دُبُرُ الصَّلوٰۃ» means 'after the prayer' and «اَدْبَارُ السُّجُوْد» means 'after the prostrations'.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَاتَّبِعۡ اَدۡبَارَہُمۡ» (15/65)\nTranslation: And follow them from behind.\n\nThus, the word «دُبُر» is used in a wider sense than «ظَھَرَ».\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«سَیُہۡزَمُ الۡجَمۡعُ وَ  یُوَلُّوۡنَ الدُّبُرَ» (54/45)\nTranslation: Soon will this party be routed, and they will turn their backs and flee.","«دُبُر» the seat of honor and the rear portion of all things.","back (often used metaphorically in Islamic contexts to mean 'turning one's back on' or 'rejecting', as in turning away from guidance)","دبر","3:11-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-12:25-12:27-12:28-15:65-17:46-21:57-27:10-27:80-28:31-30:52-33:15-37:90-40:33-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-54:45-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22",31
858,177,"B","صُلْب","«صَلَبَ الْعَظْم» means extracting fat from bone. And «صُلْب» refers to the fat and marrow of the spinal bone (the *mijnad*). Since this bone is located between the back and the chest, its translation is rendered as back or chest.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَّخۡرُجُ مِنۡۢ بَیۡنِ الصُّلۡبِ وَ التَّرَآئِبِ» (86:7)\nTranslation: That which lies between the backbone and the ribcage.","«صُلْب» spine, including the lumbar region and back.","back","صلب","86:7",1
859,178,"P","اِبْتِغَاء","«بَغٰی» means to search, to seek, to desire. And «اِبْتِغَاء» means to search for the desired thing and pursue it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4/104)\nTranslation: And do not be weak in pursuing the disbelievers.","To seek out and pursue.","pursuit","ابتغاء","2:187-2:198-2:207-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:85-4:24-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-6:35-6:114-9:48-13:17-13:22-16:14-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-45:12-48:29-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20",46
860,178,"F","قَصَّ","«قَصَّ» to follow closely behind, to go along trailing someone/something (abs.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَقَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ» (28/11)\nTranslation: And (the mother of Moses pbuh) said to his sister, Go and follow closely behind him.","to persistently follow, to continue trailing the sign","Follow","قص","18:64-28:11",2
861,178,"P","اَتْبَعَ","«اَتْبَعَ» to follow someone and overtake them. (sing.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ فَلَمَّا تَرَآءَ الۡجَمۡعٰنِ قَالَ اَصۡحٰبُ مُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَمُدۡرَکُوۡنَ» (26/60,61)\nTranslation: So they pursued them at sunrise. When the two armies came within sight of each other, the companions of Moses (peace be upon him) said, Indeed, we have been overtaken.","«اَتْبَعَ» to pursue and seize.","Pursuit","اتبع","2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7",150
862,179,"B","بَعْد","«بَعْدُ» means after or thereafter. This is a temporal adverb (manzil), and its opposite is «قَبْل», meaning before.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«ثُمَّ بَعَثۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَوۡتِکُمۡ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ» (2/56)  \nTranslation: Then after death had come upon you, We revived you again, so that you might be grateful.","«بَعْدُ» (in terms of time) a bygone era, a past period.","Behind","بعد","2:27-2:51-2:52-2:56-2:64-2:74-2:75-2:87-2:92-2:109-2:120-2:133-2:145-2:159-2:164-2:178-2:181-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:230-2:246-2:253-2:259-3:8-3:19-3:61-3:65-3:80-3:82-3:86-3:89-3:90-3:94-3:100-3:105-3:106-3:152-3:154-3:160-3:172-4:11-4:12-4:24-4:115-4:153-4:163-4:165-5:12-5:32-5:39-5:41-5:43-5:94-5:106-5:108-5:115-6:6-6:54-6:68-6:71-6:133-7:56-7:69-7:74-7:85-7:89-7:100-7:103-7:129-7:148-7:150-7:153-7:169-7:173-7:185-8:6-8:75-9:12-9:27-9:28-9:66-9:74-9:113-9:115-9:117-10:3-10:14-10:21-10:32-10:74-10:75-11:7-11:10-12:9-12:35-12:45-12:48-12:49-12:100-13:25-13:37-14:9-14:14-16:41-16:65-16:70-16:91-16:92-16:94-16:106-16:110-16:119-17:17-17:104-18:76-19:59-20:85-21:11-21:57-21:105-22:5-23:15-23:31-23:42-23:44-24:5-24:33-24:47-24:55-24:58-25:29-26:120-26:227-27:11-28:43-28:58-28:87-29:63-30:3-30:4-30:19-30:24-30:50-30:51-30:54-31:27-33:52-33:53-34:32-35:2-35:9-35:41-36:28-38:35-38:88-39:6-40:5-40:31-40:34-41:50-42:14-42:16-42:28-42:41-42:44-45:5-45:6-45:17-45:23-46:30-47:4-47:25-47:32-48:24-49:11-53:26-57:10-57:17-59:10-61:6-65:1-65:7-66:4-68:13-77:50-79:30-95:7-98:4",189
863,179,"B","اَدْبَار","«دُبْر» refers to the latter part of everything, and its opposite is «قُبل». It is also used consecutively as a temporal adverb, meaning immediately upon the completion of an action or right after it, such as: «دُبْرُ الصَّلوٰۃ» means 'after the prayer,' and its plural is «اَدْبَار».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ  وَاَدۡبَارَ السُّجُوۡدِ» (50:40)\nTranslation: And glorify Him during the night and after the prayer.\n\nAnd «اِدْبَار» means to turn one's back on something or to disappear.\n\nThus, at another instance, the Almighty states:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَسَبِّحۡہُ وَ اِدۡبَارَ النُّجُوۡمِ» (52:49)\nTranslation: And glorify Him during part of the night and at the decline of the stars.\n\nIn this verse, the eloquence lies in the fact that the meaning of «اَدْبَار» is also implied alongside «اِدْبَار».","«اَدْبَار» occurs immediately upon the completion of a task or right after, and its opposite is «قُبْل».","behind","ادبار","3:11-4:47-5:21-8:15-8:16-8:50-9:25-12:25-12:27-12:28-15:65-17:46-21:57-27:10-27:80-28:31-30:52-33:15-37:90-40:33-47:25-47:27-48:22-50:40-52:49-54:45-59:12-70:17-74:23-74:33-79:22",31
864,179,"B","خلْف","«خَلْف» means behind, and its opposite is «بَیْنَ یَدَیْن», which means in front (muf) or near. It is also used as both a temporal and spatial adverb. In its temporal sense, «بَیْنَ یَدَیْن» means present, while in its spatial sense, it means in front.\n\n**Example of temporal usage:**\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/66)\nTranslation: And We have made this story a lesson for the people of that time and for those who came after them.\n\n**Example of spatial usage:**\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«لَہٗ مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ مِنۡ اَمۡرِاللّٰہِ» (13/11)\nTranslation: There are guardians of Allah before him and behind him, who protect him by the command of Allah.","«خَلْف» means behind, and its opposite is «بَیْنَ یَدَیْن», meaning in front or near.","Behind","خلف","2:66-2:255-3:170-4:9-7:17-8:57-10:92-13:11-19:59-19:64-20:97-20:110-21:28-22:76-25:62-34:9-34:39-36:9-36:45-41:14-41:25-41:42-72:27",23
865,179,"B","وَرَآء","«وَرَآء» means 'ahead' or 'behind' (as per the lexicon of antonyms). It is both masculine and feminine (according to Munjid) and is used both as a temporal and spatial adverb. Now observe its examples:\n\n(1) Example of a spatial adverb meaning 'behind':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ» (49/4)\nTranslation: Those who call you from behind the chambers (from outside).\n\n(2) Example of a temporal adverb meaning 'behind':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ ۙ وَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ اِسۡحٰقَ یَعۡقُوۡبَ» (11/71)\nTranslation: So We gave him glad tidings of Isaac and of Jacob after Isaac.\n\n(3) Example of a spatial adverb meaning 'ahead':\nThe Almighty declares:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ غَصۡبًا» (18/79)\nTranslation: And ahead of them (in that direction) was a king who seized every ship by force.\n\nThis word is also sometimes used in the sense of 'besides' or 'except'.\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ» (23/7)\nTranslation: And those who seek besides them (others) are those who transgress the bounds set by Allah.\n\nAnd «وَرَآءَ الْاِنْسَان» means 'grandson'. As is also evident from example 2 above. Thus, «وَرَآء» signifies 'beyond', 'on this side or that side', 'here or there'. And it is both temporal and spatial. As clarified by the following verse:\n\nFor example: The Almighty declares:\n«فَاِذَا سَجَدُوۡا فَلۡیَکُوۡنُوۡا مِنۡ وَّرَآئِکُمۡ ۪ وَ لۡتَاۡتِ طَآئِفَۃٌ اُخۡرٰی لَمۡ یُصَلُّوۡا فَلۡیُصَلُّوۡا مَعَکَ» (4/102)\nTranslation: When they have performed the prostration, let them move away from you, then let another group who have not yet prayed (in their place) come forward and pray with you.","«وَرَآء» meaning ahead or behind, this side or that side, here or there.","Behind","ورآء","2:91-2:101-3:187-4:24-4:102-6:94-11:71-11:92-14:16-14:17-18:79-19:5-23:7-23:100-33:53-42:51-45:10-49:4-57:13-59:14-70:31-76:27-84:10-85:20",24
866,179,"B","خَلَفَ","«خَلَفَ» is the opposite of «سَلَفَ» and is used as a temporal term meaning to come afterwards, to take the place of, or to be a successor (as in *Munjid*). «خَلْفٌ» is generally used for unworthy and incompetent successors.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَاتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ غَیًّا» ( 19/59 )\nTranslation: Then, after them, succeeded «خَلَفَ» a generation who neglected prayer and pursued «خَلْفٌ» their lowly desires. So they will soon meet «خِلْفَۃً» (the consequence of) their evil deeds.\n\nAnd «خِلْفَۃً» means the coming and going of two things one after the other. The first follows the second, and the second follows the first; they continue to alternate in succession (as in *Munjid*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ خِلۡفَۃً» ( 25/62 )\nTranslation: And He it is who made the night and the day to follow «خِلْفَۃً» one another in succession.","«خَلَفَ» is used in all these meanings: those who come after, later generations, the past, offspring of elders, heir, children, successor, replacement.","Behind","خلف","6:133-7:69-7:74-7:129-7:142-7:150-7:169-11:57-19:59-24:55-27:62-43:60-46:21-57:7",14
867,179,"B","اَرْدَفَ","«رَدَفَ» means to ride behind someone, and «رِدْفٌ» refers to one rider coming after another (in sequence). It signifies the coming of one thing after another of the same kind. And «اَرْدَفَ» means to send consecutively after something, to form a chain. (It is a well-known recurring term).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ اَنِّیۡ مُمِدُّکُمۡ بِاَلۡفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  مُرۡدِفِیۡنَ» (8/9)\n\nTranslation: When you sought help from your Lord, He answered your prayer and said, I will assist you with a thousand angels coming one after another.","A continuous succession of similar things.","Behind","اردف","8:9-27:72",2
868,179,"B","تلٰی","«تَلٰی» meaning to come behind something repeatedly and to keep coming (intransitive). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَالشَّمۡسِ وَضُحٰہَا وَالۡقَمَرِ اِذَا تَلٰىہَا» (91/1,2) Translation: By the sun and its brightness, and by the moon when it follows (it).","«تَلٰی» persistently following behind something else.","behind","تلی","91:2",1
869,179,"B","اَخَّرَ","«تَاخِیْرًا» is the opposite of «تَقْدِیْم». It is used as a temporal adverb, meaning to leave behind or to put behind. Furthermore, this word is also used to mean delaying an action, and if it relates to someone else, it conveys the meaning of granting respite.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یُنَبَّؤُا الۡاِنۡسَانُ یَوۡمَئِذٍۭ بِمَا قَدَّمَ وَاَخَّرَ» (75:13)\nTranslation: On that Day, man will be informed of all the deeds he has sent forth and those he has left behind.","«اَخَّرَ» i.e., to cause someone to fall behind in terms of time.","behind","اخر","3:153-7:38-7:39-11:8-75:13-82:5",6
870,179,"B","خَلَّفَ","«خَلَّفَ» means to leave behind. This word is used when both temporal and spatial context are involved.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ عَلَی الثَّلٰثَۃِ الَّذِیۡنَ خُلِّفُوۡا» (9/118)\nTranslation:\n1. And upon those three also whose matter was postponed. (Jalandhari)\n2. And upon those persons who were held back. (Usmaniؒ)","«خَلَّفَ» Spatial adverb, meaning to leave someone behind, to be behind someone, to remain behind, to catch up with someone from behind.","behind","خلف","9:81-9:118-9:120-48:11-48:15-48:16-",6
871,179,"B","تَاَخَرَّ","«تَاَخَرَّ» to refrain from one's own intention and choice.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَنْ تَعَجَّلَ فِي يَوْمَيْنِ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَيْهِ وَمَنْ تَأَخَّرَ فَلَا إِثْمَ عَلَيْهِ» ( 2/203 )\nTranslation: And whoever hastens to leave in two days, it is no sin for him; and whoever stays longer, it is no sin for him.","«تَاَخَرَّ» to hold back from one's own volition and choice.","behind","تاخر","2:203-7:34-10:49-15:5-15:24-16:61-23:43-34:30-48:2-74:37",10
872,179,"B","خَالَفَ","«خَالَفَ» To lag behind due to deficiency or shortcoming (intransitive). Its second meaning is also 'to oppose'. And «خَالِفْ» refers to the one who lags behind due to one's own laziness or incompetence (intransitive). And «خَالِف» means foolish and one who remains seated after a person has departed (transitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّکُمۡ رَضِیۡتُمۡ بِالۡقُعُوۡدِ اَوَّلَ مَرَّۃٍ  فَاقۡعُدُوۡا مَعَ الۡخٰلِفِیۡنَ» ( 9/83 )\nTranslation: Since you were pleased with sitting back the first time, then remain seated with those who lag behind.\nAnd the feminine form of «خَالِفْ» is «خَالِفَۃٌ», and generally, it refers to a domestic woman who stays at home during jihad. And its plural form is «خَوَالِف» (intransitive). For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«رَضُوۡا بِاَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا مَعَ الۡخَوَالِفِ» ( 9/87 )\nTranslation: They are pleased to remain seated with those women who lag behind, staying in their homes.","«خَالَفَ» falling behind due to deficiency and shortcoming.","Behind","خالف","9:83-9:87-9:93",3
873,179,"B","غَبَرَ","«غَبَرَ» to lag behind due to falling short with one's companions.  \nFor example: As mentioned in the Noble Quran: «فَاَنۡجَیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗۤ  اِلَّا امۡرَاَتَہٗ  ۫ ۖکَانَتۡ مِنَ الۡغٰبِرِیۡنَ» (7:83)  \nTranslation: And We saved Lot and his household, except his wife; she was among those who lagged behind.","«غَبَرَ» being left behind due to falling short with one's companions.","Behind","غبر","7:83-15:60-26:171-27:57-29:32-29:33-37:135",7
874,179,"B","اَخَّرَ","«اَخَّرَ» means to delay beyond the appointed time or to grant respite (manjad or muf). This term is commonly used.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «وَلَنۡ یُّؤَخِّرَ اللّٰہُ  نَفۡسًا اِذَا جَآءَ اَجَلُہَا» (63/11) Translation: And when death comes to anyone, Allah never grants him respite.","to delay beyond the appointed time or to grant a respite.","Behind","اخر","4:77-11:104-14:10-14:42-14:44-16:61-17:62-35:45-63:11-71:4",10
875,179,"B","اَرْجٰی","«رَجَاء» is the term for an assumption in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (delight). Its opposite is «خَوْف». Moreover, «رَجَاء» and «خَوْف» are both interdependent (necessary for one another). When there is expectation (hope) of attaining a beloved thing, there will also be apprehension of its being lost. Similarly, in the opposite scenario, the apprehension of loss is accompanied by the hope of attainment as well. And «اَرْجٰی» means to push away something in which there is a possibility of attaining joy (happiness).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تُرۡجِیۡ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ مِنۡہُنَّ وَ تُـئۡوِیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکَ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ» (33/51)\nTranslation: You may put off whom you will of them, and you may take to yourself whom you will, and whom you desire of those whom you had previously set aside—there is no blame on you.","A delay that holds the promise of joy, undertaken in hope.","behind","ارجی","33:51",1
876,179,"B","اَرْجَہَ","The meaning of «رَجَہَ» is to hold something with one's teeth, and «اَرْجَہَ الْاَمْر» is to postpone a task (mansh). That is, «اَرْجَہَ» involves a delay arising from caution and strength, so that the expected results from that task can be achieved.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَرۡجِہۡ  وَاَخَاہُ وَاَرۡسِلۡ فِی الۡمَدَآئِنِ حٰشِرِیۡنَ» (7/111)\nTranslation: They said, Give them and their brother respite and send the gatherers to the cities.","«اَرْجَہَ» A delay in which caution is observed so that the work may be done correctly.","Behind","ارجہ","7:111-26:36",2
877,179,"B","نَسَأَ","«نَسَأَ» means to delay or postpone something. It is an idiom. «نَسَاَکَ اللہُ فِیْٓ اَجَلِکَ» means May Allah prolong your life (a common expression). «نَسِیْئَۃَ» also refers to delay and deferment, meaning to pay back money later in transactions like buying, selling, and lending. And «نَسِیْءُ», the Quran has used this word in the meanings of precedence and delay, and this indeed is its true meaning. That is, to rush in one matter and delay in another. The disbelievers of Mecca used to do this: they would shift the months of Hajj forward or backward to suit the seasons, so that fruits would ripen and become available, and the offerings at the Ka'bah could be paid with ease. Allah Almighty has declared this kind of advancing and postponing as disbelief.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«اِنَّمَا النَّسِیۡٓءُ زِیَادَۃٌ فِی الۡکُفۡرِ  یُضَلُّ بِہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یُحِلُّوۡنَہٗ عَامًا وَّ یُحَرِّمُوۡنَہٗ عَامًا» (9/37)\n\nTranslation: To move a sacred month forward or backward is an increase in disbelief, and through it the disbelievers are led astray. They make one year lawful and another unlawful.","«نَسَأَ» to be hasty in one thing and delayed in another.","Behind","نسأ","9:37",1
878,179,"B","اَتْبَعَ","«اَتْبَعَ» is used in both transitive and intransitive forms. When used intransitively, its meaning is 'to follow' or 'to pursue'.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ» (26:60)  \nTranslation: So the courtiers of Pharaoh pursued them (i.e., the Children of Israel) at sunrise.  \n\nAnd when used transitively, its meaning becomes 'to make follow' or 'to pursue something/someone'.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ اَتۡبَعۡنٰہُمۡ فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا لَعۡنَۃً» (28:42)  \nTranslation: And We caused a curse to follow them in this world.  \n\nNote:  \nIntransitive Verb: A verb is called intransitive when it completes the meaning of a sentence with only the subject (fa'il).  \nTransitive Verb: A verb is called transitive when it requires an object (maf'ul) in addition to the subject to complete its meaning.","«اَتْبَعَ» to follow, to accompany, to adhere, to be subordinate, to come after someone, or to be under someone's authority. It is used in all these meanings.","Behind","اتبع","2:38-2:102-2:120-2:143-2:145-2:166-2:167-2:168-2:170-2:208-2:262-2:263-3:7-3:20-3:31-3:53-3:55-3:68-3:73-3:95-3:162-3:167-3:174-4:27-4:83-4:115-4:125-4:135-5:16-5:48-5:49-5:77-6:50-6:56-6:106-6:116-6:142-6:148-6:150-6:153-6:155-7:3-7:18-7:90-7:142-7:157-7:158-7:175-7:176-7:193-7:203-8:64-9:42-9:100-9:117-10:15-10:35-10:36-10:66-10:89-10:90-10:109-11:27-11:59-11:60-11:97-11:99-11:116-12:38-12:108-13:37-14:21-14:36-14:44-15:18-15:42-15:65-16:123-17:47-17:63-18:28-18:66-18:70-18:85-18:89-18:92-19:43-19:59-20:16-20:47-20:78-20:90-20:93-20:108-20:123-20:134-22:3-23:44-23:71-24:21-25:8-26:40-26:52-26:60-26:111-26:215-26:224-28:35-28:42-28:47-28:49-28:50-28:57-29:12-30:29-31:15-31:21-33:2-34:20-36:11-36:20-36:21-37:10-38:26-38:85-39:18-39:55-40:7-40:38-40:47-42:15-43:61-44:23-45:18-46:9-47:3-47:14-47:16-47:28-48:15-52:21-53:23-53:28-54:3-54:24-57:27-71:21-75:18-77:17-79:7",150
879,179,"B","قَفٰی ، قَفّٰی","The term «اَلْقَفَاءُ» signifies blind imitation or following without knowledge.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ لَا تَقۡفُ مَا لَیۡسَ لَکَ بِہٖ عِلۡمٌ» (17/36)  \nTranslation: And do not pursue that of which you have no knowledge.\n\nThe term «قَفَا ۔ یَقْفُوْا» means to strike someone's back or to follow closely behind someone or something (figuratively).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ لَا تَقۡفُ مَا لَیۡسَ لَکَ بِہٖ عِلۡمٌ» (17/36)  \nTranslation: And do not pursue that of which you have no knowledge.\n\nThe term «قَفّٰی» means to persistently follow or attach something behind another in continuous succession (from which the word *qāfiyah* [rhyme] is derived; i.e., to follow in a way that maintains continuity).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ قَفَّیۡنَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہٖ بِالرُّسُلِ» (2/87)  \nTranslation: And We sent after them successive messengers.","«قَفٰی» to fall behind something and «قَفّٰی» to keep someone continuously lagging behind something.","behind","قفی ، قفی","2:87-5:46-17:36-57:27",4
880,179,"B","اَغْرٰی","«أَغْرَيَ» means to incite (urge) a dog or any hunting animal to chase the prey.  \nFor example, the Holy Quran states: «فَاَغۡرَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ» (5/14).  \nTranslation: Then We have instilled among them enmity and hatred. (Uthmani)","To hoist something like a cross and impose it upon others.","Behind","اغری","5:14-33:60",2
881,179,"B","اِتَّبَعَ ۔ اِلْتَفَتَ","«اِتَّبَعَ» means to follow behind someone, and «اِلْتَفَتَ» means to turn and look back—that is, to pay attention and look behind. And «لَفَتَ» means to turn something to the right or left. (For example) «الَتفات» is a well-known term. For instance, in the Quran it is stated: «فَاَسۡرِ بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ وَاتَّبِعۡ اَدۡبَارَہُمۡ وَ لَا یَلۡتَفِتۡ مِنۡکُمۡ اَحَدٌ» (15/65). Translation: So travel with your family in the latter part of the night, and follow right behind them, and let none of you turn back to look.","To follow someone and to turn and look; to pay attention and to look back.","Behind","اتبع ۔ التفت","10:78-11:81-15:65-75:29",4
882,179,"B","خَنَّسَ","The meaning of «خَنَّسَ ، خَنْس» is to retreat and shrink ('manjūd'), and to mean stepping back while walking straight ('mufrad'), to retreat stealthily or while hiding. (m. l.) And «خَانِسْ» means the one who retreats. Its plural is «خنَّس».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ» (81:15-16)  \nTranslation: By the stars when they retreat, and when they move forth, and when they vanish.\n\nAnd in «خَنَّاس» there is greater emphasis than «خَانِسْ». That is, one who has made retreating his habit or practice.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «مِنۡ شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ ۙ الۡخَنَّاسِ» (114:4)  \nTranslation: (O Allah, I seek refuge) from the evil of the whisperer who withdraws and hides.","To step back while walking straight ahead, or by averting one's gaze, or by slipping away discreetly.","Behind","خنس","81:15-114:4",2
883,180,"C","بَرَاَ","«بَرَأَ» means bringing something into existence from non-existence (absolute nothingness). (Minaj, Fiqh, p. 113). To create and invent.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَاقۡتُلُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ  ؕ ذٰلِکُمۡ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ عِنۡدَ بَارِئِکُمۡ» (2/54)  \nTranslation: And kill your own selves; that is better for you in the sight of your Creator.","«بَرَأَ» meaning: bringing something into existence from non-existence (the beginning) without any material (origin).","Created","برا","2:54-59:24",2
884,180,"C","بَدَع","«بَدَعَ» without a model or imitation, i.e., to create or bring into existence for the first time (muf). And Badi‘ means one who creates something unique (manjad).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«بَدِیۡعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (2/117)\nTranslation: He is the One who creates the heavens and the earth.","«بَدَعَ» to create something for the first time without a model or precedent.","Created","بدع","2:117-6:101-46:9",3
885,180,"C","فَطَرَ","The meaning of «فَطَرَ» is to fashion and create beautifully.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فِطۡرَتَ اللّٰہِ الَّتِیۡ فَطَرَ  النَّاسَ عَلَیۡہَا» (30:30)\nTranslation: So direct your face toward the religion, inclining to truth. [Adhere to] the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created [all] people.\nAt another instance, the command of the Almighty Allah is:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (35:1)\nTranslation: All praise is to Allah, Originator of the heavens and the earth.","«فَطَرَ» to sculpt into a fine shape.","Created","فطر","6:14-6:79-11:51-12:101-14:10-17:51-20:72-21:56-30:30-35:1-36:22-39:46-42:11-43:27-67-3",14
886,180,"C","خَلَقَ","The word «خَلَقَ» is used in multiple meanings. For example:\n\n(1) To estimate or prepare a design for making something (intransitive). This means the act of creation can also be mental, and its attribution can also be to other than Allah.\n\n(2) Sometimes it also occurs in the meaning of «خَلَقَ ، اِبْدَاع». In the Quran, just as «خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ» occurs, similarly «بَدِیْعُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَالْاَرْضِ» also occurs. In this case, its attribution to other than Allah is not possible.\n\n(3) The general meaning of «خَلَقَ» is that one thing is created from another. If the initial matter exists, another thing is originated from it.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n\n«خَلَقَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ وَّ خَلَقَ مِنۡہَا زَوۡجَہَا وَ بَثَّ مِنۡہُمَا رِجَالًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ نِسَآءً» (4/1)\n\nTranslation: You were created from a single person, and his mate was created from him. Then from both of them, He created many men and women and spread them on earth. (Uthmani)\n\nIn this case, its attribution to other than Allah is also possible. As Allah the Most High says regarding Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him):\n\n«وَاِذۡ تَخۡلُقُ مِنَ الطِّیۡنِ کَہَیۡئَۃِ الطَّیۡرِ» (5/110)\n\nTranslation: And when you created from clay the form of a bird. (Uthmani)\n\nFurthermore, in another verse, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n\n«فَتَبٰرَکَ اللّٰہُ  اَحۡسَنُ  الۡخٰلِقِیۡنَ» (23/14)\n\nTranslation:\n1 - So Allah, who is the best of creators, is Most Blessed. (Jalandhri)\n2 - The Best Creator. (Uthmani)","To create such a thing whose material already exists.","created","خلق","2:21-2:29-2:164-2:228-3:47-3:49-3:59-3:190-3:191-4:1-4:28-4:119-5:17-5:18-5:110-6:1-6:2-6:73-6:94-6:100-6:101-6:102-7:11-7:12-7:54-7:69-7:181-7:185-7:189-7:191-9:36-10:3-10:4-10:5-10:6-10:34-11:7-11:119-13:5-13:16-14:19-14:32-15:26-15:27-15:28-15:33-15:85-16:3-16:4-16:5-16:8-16:17-16:20-16:48-16:70-16:81-17:49-17:51-17:61-17:70-17:98-17:99-18:37-18:48-18:51-19:9-19:67-20:4-20:50-20:55-21:16-21:33-21:37-21:104-22:5-22:73-23:12-23:14-23:17-23:91-23:115-24:45-25:2-25:3-25:49-25:54-25:59-26:78-26:166-26:184-27:60-27:64-28:68-29:17-29:19-29:20-29:44-29:61-30:8-30:11-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:27-30:30-30:40-30:54-31:10-31:11-31:25-31:28-32:4-32:7-32:10-34:7-35:1-35:3-35:11-35:16-35:40-36:36-36:42-36:68-36:71-36:77-36:78-36:79-36:81-37:11-37:96-37:125-37:150-38:27-38:71-38:75-38:76-39:4-39:5-39:6-39:38-39:62-40:57-40:62-40:67-41:9-41:15-41:21-41:37-42:29-42:49-43:9-43:12-43:16-43:19-43:87-44:38-44:39-45:4-45:22-46:3-46:4-46:33-49:13-50:15-50:16-50:38-51:49-51:56-52:35-52:36-53:45-54:49-55:3-55:14-55:15-56:57-56:59-57:4-59:24-64:2-64:3-65:12-67:2-67:3-67:14-70:19-70:39-71:14-71:15-74:11-75:38-76:2-76:28-77:20-78:8-79:27-80:18-80:19-82:7-86:5-86:6-87:2-88:17-89:8-90:4-92:3-95:4-96:1-96:2-113:2",210
887,180,"C","اَنْشَاَ","«اَنْشَاَ» Its basic meanings are two: (1) to create something and (2) then to nurture and grow it (m. l. manjd). This word is used both separately for these two meanings and also jointly.\n\n(1) Example of the meaning of creation:\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is: «وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ» (6/98)\nTranslation: And He it is who created you from a single person.\n\n(2) Example of the meaning of nurturing:\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is: «اَوَ مَنۡ یُّنَشَّؤُا فِی الۡحِلۡیَۃِ» (43/18)\nTranslation: And has Allah [chosen] for Himself such offspring as are raised in adornment?\n\n(3) Example of the joint action of creating and growing:\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is: «ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ» (56/72)\nTranslation: Have you created this tree or are We the creators?","«اَنْشَاَ» meaning to create and to nurture.","Created","انشا","6:6-6:98-6:133-6:141-11:61-21:11-23:14-23:19-23:31-23:42-23:78-28:45-29:20-36:79-43:18-53:32-53:47-55:24-56:35-56:61-56:62-56:72-67:23",23
888,180,"C","ذَرَءَ","«ذَرَاَ» is used in two meanings: (1) to create, and (2) to spread/scatter. (M. R.) And this word is used separately in both meanings as well as in a combined sense. For example, the following verse pertains only to the meaning of creation:\n\nThe command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ ذَرَاۡنَا لِجَہَنَّمَ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ» ۰ ( 7/179 )\nTranslation: And indeed, We have created many of the jinn and mankind for Hell.\n\nAnd «ذَرَاَ» in the sense of sowing seeds in a field (manjad) and «ذَرَء» in the sense of everything that is sown and cultivated (M. L.)—it is as if, just as a seed is scattered and spread, so too does it come to mean spreading or scattering human beings upon the earth.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ ذَرَاَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ اِلَیۡہِ تُحۡشَرُوۡنَ» ( 67/24 )\nTranslation: Say, He is the One who has spread you upon the earth, and to Him you will be gathered.","«ذَرَاَ» meaning to create and to spread.","Created","ذرء","6:136-7:179-16:13-23:79-67:24",5
889,181,"B","عَرَضَ","«عَرَضَ» means to present, to bring forward (manjīd). And this term is generally used for non-rational entities (i.e., things that lack intellect), such as requests, petitions, messages, or other objects, and is generally used in a spiritual context. (m.f.)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا ثُمَّ عَرَضَہُمۡ عَلَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ» (2/31) Translation: And Allah taught Adam the names of all things, then He presented them before the angels.","«عَرَضَ» means to present or put forward, and it is used for non-rational entities, that is, things which lack intellect.","Before / In the presence of","عرض","2:31-11:18-18:48-18:100-33:72-38:31-40:46-42:45-46:20-46:34-69:18",11
890,181,"P","اَحْضَرَ","The meaning of «حَضَر» is to come forward, to present. And «اَحْضَرَ» means to present someone or bring forward, to make present, and in this, the existence and observation of the thing are necessary (m. l). It generally applies to those with intellect (i.e., those who possess reason). It is also used in a negative sense, such as presenting a criminal, and the word summoning connotes anger and wrath (fq l 77).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَوَ رَبِّکَ لَنَحۡشُرَنَّہُمۡ وَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ ثُمَّ لَنُحۡضِرَنَّہُمۡ  حَوۡلَ  جَہَنَّمَ  جِثِیًّا» (19/68)\nTranslation: By your Lord! We will gather them and the devils as well, then We will bring them all around Hell.","«اَحْضَرَ» means to present or bring forward something, to make it present, and its existence and observation are necessary in it.","Presenting","احضر","2:133-2:180-2:196-2:282-3:30-4:8-4:18-4:128-5:106-7:163-18:49-19:68-23:98-28:61-30:16-34:38-36:32-36:53-36:75-37:57-37:127-37:158-46:29-81:14",24
891,182,"F","جَبِین","One side of the forehead is called (munjad), and both sides of the forehead (the right and left) are referred to as «اَجْبِیَان».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا و تَلَّہٗ لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ» (37/103)\nTranslation: When both had accepted the command, the father laid his son down on his forehead.","to either the right or left side of the forehead","Forehead","جبین","37:103",1
892,182,"F","جَبِہَ","«جَبِہَ» means the width and beauty of the forehead (musnad). In fact, «جَبِہَ» refers to the front and middle part of the forehead that touches the ground during prostration. Its plural form is «جِبَاہ».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَتُکۡوٰی بِہَا جِبَاہُہُمۡ وَ جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ ظُہُوۡرُہُمۡ» (9/35)\nTranslation: The foreheads, sides, and backs of those misers will be branded.","«جَبِہَ» the middle part of the forehead.","Forehead","جبہ","9:35",1
893,182,"F","نَاصِیَۃ","«نَاصِیَۃ» denotes the forehead or the long hair of the forehead. (Munjad) is another term that is also applied to the forehead hair and the forehead itself. Its plural is «نَوَاصِی».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«یُعۡرَفُ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ فَیُؤۡخَذُ بِالنَّوَاصِیۡ وَ الۡاَقۡدَامِ» (55/41)\nTranslation: The sinners will be recognized by their faces, and then seized by the hair of their foreheads and their feet.","The forehead and its hair.","Forehead","ناصیۃ","11:56-55:41-96:15-96:16",4
894,183,"P","نبی ، رسول ، مرسل","«نَبِی» It is derived from «نَبَا», and its meaning is: one who receives news of the unseen from Allah Almighty through revelation. And prophethood (nubuwwah) is attributed to the Prophet (Nabi).  \nAnd the lexical meaning of Rasool (messenger) is simply a bearer of a message, which could be any person sent by someone. However, in the Shariah terminology, a Rasool is one who receives news of the unseen, commands, and revelations from Allah Almighty through inspiration and divine revelation, and then conveys that message to other people. Messengership (risalah) is attributed not to the messenger (Rasool) but to Allah Almighty. And a Rasool is only called a Mursal (one who is sent) when he actually delivers the message to others. Although a Rasool is considered a Rasool from the moment a message or letter is entrusted to him. (Faqih al-Lughah, p. 223)  \n\nSome people think there is no difference between a Nabi (prophet) and a Rasool (messenger), and that they are simply two aspects of the same coin. Their evidence is that those beings whom Allah Almighty called Nabi, He also called Rasool, or most of them. But the reality is that there is a clear difference between a Nabi and a Rasool. And the evidence for this difference is the following verse:  \n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ مَاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا مِنۡ قَبۡلِکَ مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ وَّ لَا نَبِیٍّ اِلَّاۤ  اِذَا تَمَنّٰۤی اَلۡقَی الشَّیۡطٰنُ فِیۡۤ اُمۡنِیَّتِہٖ» (22/52)  \nTranslation: And We did not send any messenger or prophet before you, but when he had a desire, Satan would cast [evil] into his desire.  \n\nFrom this verse, it is explicitly clear that Nabi and Rasool are two distinct technical terms, and the fundamental differences between them are as follows:  \n\n(1) Before a Rasool is sent, the news of his coming is given through previous prophets, who announce it. However, this is not necessarily the case for a Nabi.  \n\n(2) A Rasool brings a new Sharia (divine law) with him and establishes a new community (ummah), whereas a Nabi comes to reform the corrupted teachings of the previous Rasool and to reform the character of that same first community.  \n\n(3) The protection of a Rasool from the oppression and tyranny of people is the responsibility of Allah. Whereas the prophets (anbiya) were often killed unjustly.","«نَبِی» One who receives news of the unseen through revelation from Allah the Most High, and in accordance with it, reforms the previous teachings and the conduct of the earlier communities.\n«رَسُوْل» A prophet who is also a law-bearer, establishes a new community, and conveys Allah's message to others.\n«مُرْسَل» Meaning 'sent' or 'one who is sent'; that prophet who is the possessor of a scripture.","Prophet","نبی ، رسول ، مرسل","2:61-2:91-2:136-2:177-2:213-2:246-2:247-2:248-3:21-3:39-3:68-3:80-3:81-3:84-3:112-3:146-3:161-3:181-4:69-4:155-4:163-5:20-5:44-5:81-6:112-7:94-7:157-7:158-8:64-8:65-8:67-8:70-9:61-9:73-9:113-9:117-17:55-19:30-19:41-19:49-19:51-19:53-19:54-19:56-19:58-22:52-25:31-33:1-33:6-33:7-33:13-33:28-33:30-33:32-33:38-33:40-33:45-33:50-33:53-33:56-33:59-37:112-39:69-43:6-43:7-49:2-60:12-65:1-66:1-66:3-66:8-66:9-2:87-2:101-2:108-2:129-2:143-2:151-2:214-2:279-2:285-3:32-3:49-3:53-3:81-3:86-3:101-3:132-3:144-3:153-3:164-3:172-3:183-4:13-4:14-4:42-4:59-4:61-4:64-4:69-4:79-4:80-4:83-4:100-4:115-4:136-4:157-4:170-4:171-5:15-5:19-5:33-5:41-5:55-5:56-5:67-5:70-5:75-5:83-5:92-5:99-5:104-5:111-7:61-7:67-7:104-7:157-7:158-8:1-8:13-8:20-8:24-8:27-8:41-8:46-9:1-9:3-9:7-9:13-9:16-9:24-9:26-9:29-9:33-9:54-9:59-9:61-9:62-9:63-9:65-9:71-9:74-9:80-9:81-9:84-9:86-9:88-9:90-9:91-9:94-9:97-9:99-9:105-9:107-9:120-9:128-10:47-12:50-13:38-14:4-15:11-16:36-16:113-17:15-17:93-17:94-17:95-19:19-19:51-19:54-20:47-20:96-20:134-21:25-22:52-22:78-23:32-23:44-23:69-24:47-24:48-24:50-24:51-24:52-24:54-24:56-24:62-24:63-25:7-25:27-25:30-25:41-26:16-26:27-26:107-26:125-26:143-26:162-26:178-28:47-28:59-29:18-33:12-33:21-33:22-33:29-33:31-33:33-33:36-33:40-33:53-33:57-33:66-33:71-36:30-40:5-40:34-40:78-42:51-43:29-43:46-44:13-44:17-44:18-47:32-47:33-48:9-48:12-48:13-48:17-48:26-48:27-48:28-48:29-49:1-49:3-49:7-49:14-49:15-51:52-57:7-57:8-57:28-58:4-58:5-58:8-58:9-58:12-58:13-58:20-58:22-59:4-59:6-59:7-59:8-60:1-61:5-61:6-61:9-61:11-62:2-63:1-63:5-63:7-63:8-64:8-64:12-65:11-69:10-69:40-72:23-72:27-73:15-73:16-81:19-91:13-98:2",287
895,183,"M","مَلا ئِکۃ","The original material of «مَلاَ ئِکَۃ» is «لأک». «اَلَاکَۃُ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to convey the message to him. «اَلِکْنِیْ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means my conveying the message to him. And «مَلْأَکَ» and «مَلَک» mean the messenger angel (manjud). «مَلَک» also means angel. «( ج مَلٰئِکَۃ )» is also used as a legal term, and it does not specify that every «مَلَک» is necessarily a messenger. And the angel appointed by Allah to bring His message to the prophets and messengers is Jibril (peace be upon him), whom Allah the Almighty has also called by the titles of Ruh (Spirit) and Ruh al-Amin (the Trustworthy Spirit). However, other angels also perform the task of message delivery.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/45)\nTranslation: And when the angels said, O Mary! Indeed Allah gives you glad tidings of a word from Him, whose name will be the Messiah, 'Isa, son of Mary.","Angels, who are also bearers of messages.","Messenger of God","مَلا ئِکۃ","2:30-2:31-2:34-2:98-2:161-2:177-2:210-2:248-2:285-3:18-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:80-3:87-3:124-3:125-4:97-4:136-4:166-4:172-6:93-6:111-6:158-7:11-8:9-8:12-8:50-13:13-13:23-15:7-15:8-15:28-15:30-16:2-16:28-16:32-16:33-16:49-17:40-17:61-17:92-17:95-18:50-20:116-21:103-22:75-23:24-25:21-25:22-25:25-33:43-33:56-34:40-35:1-37:150-38:71-38:73-39:75-41:14-41:30-42:5-43:19-43:53-43:60-47:27-53:27-66:4-66:6-70:4-74:31-78:38-97:4",73
896,183,"M","سَاحِر","«سَاحِر» refers to one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the sciences of prophethood. When prophets and messengers were granted miracles by Allah Almighty—sometimes spontaneously, sometimes at the demand of disbelievers, and sometimes under extreme necessity—the disbelievers would immediately accuse them of being a magician.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ وَ انۡشَقَّ الۡقَمَرُ ، وَاِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَیَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54:1,2)\nTranslation: The Hour has drawn near, and the moon has split. And if the disbelievers see a sign, they turn away and say, This is persistent magic.\n\nHere, after describing the miracle of «اِنْشِقَاقِ قَمَر», the reality is immediately clarified: the disbelievers' habit is to falsely label a miracle as magic. Therefore, it is necessary to understand the difference between magic and a miracle. These differences are as follows:\n\n(1) In magic, the essence (reality) of things does not change; rather, a spell is cast over people's eyes, making them perceive something as something else. Regarding the magicians who confronted Moses:\nThe Almighty declared:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَلۡقَوۡا سَحَرُوۡۤا اَعۡیُنَ النَّاسِ وَاسۡتَرۡہَبُوۡہُمۡ وَجَآءُوۡ بِسِحۡرٍعَظِیۡمٍ» (7:116)\nTranslation: When the magicians threw their ropes and staffs, it seemed to the people's eyes as if they were moving swiftly, and they struck fear into the people and brought a great magic.\n\nWhereas in the case of a miracle, the very essence and reality of the thing changes. For instance, when Prophet Moses threw his staff, it became a snake, but upon being picked up, it returned to its original state.\n\n(2) In the case of a miracle, the newly created thing either remains in that state permanently, like the spring of Zamzam or the bursting forth of twelve springs, or it returns to its original state, like the splitting of the moon, the staff of Moses, or the radiant hand. A miracle cannot be destroyed or countered, whereas magic can be destroyed or countered. For example, the snakes created by the magicians were devoured by the staff (snake) of Prophet Moses.\n\n(The word 'miracle' does not appear in the Quran. Instead, the terms «اٰیَۃ ، اٰیَۃٌ بَیِّنَۃ ، مُبْصِرَۃ» and «بُرْھَان» are used. From the Quran's style of expression, context, and circumstances, it is immediately apparent whether a word is used in its common meaning or in the sense of a miracle. And sometimes, neither of these terms appears; the indication of a miracle is derived solely from the manner of description. For instance, in «سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی», the word «سُبْحَان» is used, which denotes wonder and amazement. This clearly indicates that the journey was spiritual, not physical, and it was a miracle.)\n\n(3) Magic is a skill acquired through rigorous practice and effort. But a miracle is a divinely granted (wahbi) occurrence, not attained through practice or effort. This is why the magicians who confronted Prophet Moses—who were at the pinnacle of the art of magic—realized that what Moses presented was beyond the realm of magical skill. Consequently, they immediately embraced faith.\n\n(4) The character and conduct of magicians is detestable and corrupt, and people live in fear of their evil. In contrast, the lives of prophets are extremely pure, and in this regard, they are held in honor and love among the people.","«سَاحِر», meaning one who acquires satanic sciences in opposition to the prophetic sciences.","Messenger","ساحر","7:109-7:112-10:2-10:77-10:79-20:63-20:69-26:34-38:4-40:24-43:49-51:39-51:52",13
897,183,"P","کَاھِن","«کَاہِن» Soothsayer, predictor, claimant to knowledge of the unseen, teller of future events, augur, diviner, astrologer, physiognomist—it is used in all these meanings. Since the Prophets (peace be upon them) also give news of events that will occur in the future, and soothsayers do as well. In this regard, the Prophets were also accused of being soothsayers.\n\n1 - The difference between the two is that the source (means of acquisition) of a Prophet's news is divine revelation, which cannot be proven false. For example, during the Prophetic era, the Romans were defeated, and divine revelation informed that they would become dominant again within a period of three to nine years. Although, apparently, there was no possibility of this happening. Yet, this prophecy was fulfilled. And the source (means of acquisition) of soothsaying is jinn and evil spirits. They hear some news from the highest heavens and mix truth with falsehood, passing it on to the soothsayers. Therefore, their news becomes erroneous at times and correct at others.\n\n2 - The second difference is that a woman can be a soothsayer but cannot be a Prophet. One hundred and twenty-four thousand messengers came, but no woman, not even Mary (peace be upon her), was a Prophet. Soothsayers, both men and women, were considered by people as having religious sanctity, and their pronouncements were taken as final. During the Prophetic era, Ibn Sayyad was such a soothsayer, whose mention exists in authentic hadiths. Even the ruling of diyah (blood money) for a human life versus a hundred camels was also established based on soothsaying, which Islam retained.\n\n(3) The function of a poet is that he presents the loftiness of his thoughts and the subtlety of his expression (the delicacy of his speech) in eloquent and metered language in such a way that it creates a sort of ecstatic feeling in the listener. Although the Noble Quran is pure from all such things. Yet, all the characteristics that are possible in the speech of a human being are found in it to the highest degree. It is due to this very similarity that the Prophet (peace and blessings be upon him) was also called a poet. The fundamental difference between a poet and a Prophet is that the field of a poet's imagination's flight is every good or bad aspect of life. The influence of the environment remains dominant on his nature. And since the majority of society is misguided, his imagination (thoughts) also soars along those very paths.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الشُّعَرَآءُ یَتَّبِعُہُمُ  الۡغَاوٗنَ ۔ اَلَمۡ  تَرَ اَنَّہُمۡ  فِیۡ کُلِّ وَادٍ یَّہِیۡمُوۡنَ» (224/ 26)\nTranslation: And only the misguided people follow the poets. Do you not see that they wander distracted in every valley?\n\nWhereas the field of a Prophet's imagination's flight is subordinate to divine revelation.\n\nAnd the second difference is that a poet's views change due to the maturity of age and intellect, experience, and practice. But whatever a Prophet says in the beginning and whatever he will say later, he will confirm it. Refuting these accusations of the disbelievers, Allah the Almighty has said:\nThe command of Allah the Almighty is:\n«وَّ مَا ہُوَ بِقَوۡلِ شَاعِرٍ ؕ قَلِیۡلًا  مَّا تُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ ۔ وَ لَا بِقَوۡلِ کَاہِنٍ ؕ قَلِیۡلًا مَّا تَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (41-42 / 69)\nTranslation: And it is not the word of a poet, little do you believe. Nor is it the word of a soothsayer; little do you remember.\n\nIt was because of these very disparagements that you were not taught poetry. Although you were «اَفْصَحُ الْعَربَ وَالْعَجَم». Despite all this, it is wrong to say that all poetry and all poets are reprehensible (bad). A poet's imagination can also see the path of righteousness (goodness and virtue). Thus, the Prophet (peace and blessings be upon him) greatly liked this pre-Islamic poem of Labid (may Allah be pleased with him) because this poem presents the interpretation of divine revelation itself:\n«اَلَا کُلُّ شَیْءٍ مَا خَلَا اللہَ بَاطِلٗ وَکُلُّ نَعِیْمٍ لَا مَحَالَۃَ زَائِلٗ» Know that besides Allah, everything is false and every blessing is undoubtedly transient.","«کَاہِن» is used in all these senses: fortuneteller, soothsayer, diviner, one who claims knowledge of the unseen, predictor of the future, augur, astrologer, or physiognomist.","Prophet","کاھن","52:29-69:42",2
898,183,"P","مَجْنُوْنٌ","«مَجْنُوْنٌ» meaning a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks incoherently. The Arabs used to call a crazy person 'majnun' because, in their view, when a jinn enters a human, it causes them to lose their senses and they begin to speak irrationally. Since the teachings of the prophets were not acceptable to society, the disbelievers also persistently addressed the prophets with the label of 'majnun'.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَذٰلِکَ مَاۤ اَتَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ اِلَّا قَالُوۡا سَاحِرٌ اَوۡمَجۡنُوۡنٌ» (51/52)\nTranslation: Similarly, never has there come to them a messenger before whom they did not call a sorcerer or a madman.\n\nThe fundamental difference between a prophet and a madman is that a prophet's call, although contrary to the intellect and customs of society, always remains steadfast upon himself, demonstrates it through action, and establishes the seal of verification upon his message through his pure character and conduct. Whereas a madman is devoid of all three of these qualities.","«مَجْنُوْنٌ» a person whose intellect is veiled and who speaks incoherent nonsense.","Prophet","مجنون","15:6-26:27-37:36-44:14-51:39-51:52-52:29-54:9-68:2-68:51-81:22",11
899,184,"T","شَرِبَ","«شَرِبَ» meaning water or any other drinkable thing to drink. (m.f.) The use of this word for 'to drink' is common. Sharab meaning any drink. «شِرْب ۔ شِرْبَۃ». A turn to drink or drinking once. And «مَشْرَب» meaning place of drinking. Ghat (manjdar).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«فَمَنۡ شَرِبَ مِنۡہُ فَلَیۡسَ مِنِّیۡ» (2/249)  \nTranslation: Whoever drinks water from it will not be with us.","«شَرِبَ» meaning water or any other drinkable thing.","to drink","شرب","2:60-2:93-2:187-2:249-7:31-7:160-16:66-19:26-23:33-26:155-36:73-37:46-47:15-52:19-54:28-56:54-56:55-56:68-69:24-76:5-76:6-77:43-83:28",23
900,184,"T","جَرَّعَ","«جَرَّعَ» means to drink in gulps (munjad), and «جُرْعَۃ» means a gulp, and «اِجْتَرَعَ» means to drink in one go (munjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَّتَجَرَّعُہٗ  وَلَا یَکَادُ یُسِیۡغُہٗ» (14/17)\nTranslation: He will drink it gulping, but will not be able to swallow it down.","«جَرَّعَ» to drink in gulps","to drink","جرع","14:17",1
901,184,"T","سَاغ","«سَاغ» refers to a drink that goes down the throat smoothly and easily (i.e., is gulped down), and «سَاغِیَۃ» denotes a delicious beverage or drink (i.e., a pleasant-tasting liquid). Its opposite is «غَصَّ», meaning something that does not easily pass down the throat and gets stuck.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«نُسۡقِیۡکُمۡ  مِّمَّا فِیۡ بُطُوۡنِہٖ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ  فَرۡثٍ وَّ دَمٍ لَّبَنًا خَالِصًا سَآئِغًا لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ» (16/66)\nTranslation: And indeed, in the livestock there is a lesson for you. We give you to drink from what is in their bellies—from between the digested food and blood—pure milk, palatable to the drinkers.","«سَاغ» Because the drink is tasty, one gulps it down hastily.","to drink","ساغ","14:17-16:66-35:12",3
902,185,"S","نَجْم","«نَجْم» basically comes with two meanings: (1) Non-vascular plants, i.e., shrubs and bushes. (2) Planets that rise and set. Its plural is *nujūm*. And *najm* is used as a generic noun.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ بِالنَّجۡمِ  ہُمۡ  یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ» (16/16)\nTranslation: And people find their way by the stars.","«نَجْم» to rise and become visible, as in the emergence of a star.","Star","نجم","6:97-7:54-16:12-16:16-22:18-37:88-52:49-53:1-55:6-56:75-77:8-81:2-86:3",13
903,185,"S","کَوَاکِب","«کَوْکِبَۃٌ» is the name of a large star (manjad), and «کَوْکَب» refers to every large star, whether it is a star or a planet (fa. la). Its plural is «کَوَاکِب». And «کَوْکَبَ الْجَدِیْد» means the glittering or shining of iron, to twinkle or glisten (manjad). Thus, «کَوکَب» refers to every star that is both large and luminous, radiant.\n\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّا زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ  الدُّنۡیَا بِزِیۡنَۃِۣ الۡکَوَاکِبِ» (37:6)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have adorned the lowest heaven with stars, [making them] a decoration.\n\nThe following stars are mentioned in the Quran:\n\n(1) «شِعْرٰی»: The name of a bright star that rises in the season of intense heat (muf). In distant pre-Islamic times, it was worshipped. (For further details, see page (1/5) of 'False Deities'). Allah the Almighty said to the polytheists:\n«وَاَنَّہٗ ہُوَ رَبُّ الشِّعۡرٰی» (53:49)\nTranslation: And that He is the Lord of Sirius (Sh'ara).\n\n(2) «خُنَّس ، خَنَسَ» means to move backward and shrink (manjad); moving forward but taking a step back (muf); retreating cautiously or stealthily (mal). «خَانِسْ» means 'one that moves backward', and «خُنَّس» is its plural. Thus, «خُنَّس» refers to those planets that, while moving straight, sometimes reverse their course. According to some, Venus, Jupiter, Saturn, Mars, and Mercury are these five planets (manjad), and for this reason, they are also called 'the five wandering ones' (khamsah mutahayyirah).\n\n(3) «جَوَار ، جَار ، جَوْرًا» means to deviate from the path (manjad). And «جَوَار» refers to those planets that maintain a straight course, occasionally changing direction slightly.\n\n(4) «کُنَّس ، کَنَّسَ» means to hide, to become invisible (mal). And «كِنَاسُ» refers to the shelter of a deer, and «کَانَس» to the deer that enters the shelter. The plural of «کَانَس» is «کُنَّس». That is, those planets that suddenly disappear while moving.\n\nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَاۤ اُقۡسِمُ  بِالۡخُنَّسِ الۡجَوَارِ الۡکُنَّسِ» (81:15-16)\nTranslation: So I swear by the stars that recede. And those that move [across the sky] and disappear.","«کَوَاکِب» is the term for every big star, whether it is a star or a planet.","Star","کواکب","6:76-12:4-24:35-37:6-82:2",5
904,186,"D","عَسْعَسَ","«عَسْعَسَ» meaning the twilight of the evening (a light darkness). As soon as the sun sets, the evening darkness envelops. Similarly, the light darkness (a light darkness) a little before sunrise (example). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا عَسۡعَسَ وَالصُّبۡحِ اِذَا تَنَفَّسَ» (81/17). Translation: And by the night when it envelops, and by the morning when it appears.","«عَسْعَسَ» meaning that as soon as the sun sets, the evening darkness envelops.","darkness","عسعس","81:17",1
905,186,"D","غَسَقَ","«غَسَقَ» meaning twilight, i.e., (the reddish glow that appears on the horizon at sunrise and sunset) the darkness following its disappearance. Early night. The initial part of the night (p. 34).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ  لِدُلُوۡکِ الشَّمۡسِ اِلٰی غَسَقِ الَّیۡلِ وَ قُرۡاٰنَ الۡفَجۡرِ» (17/78)\n\nTranslation: Perform the prayers (Dhuhr, Asr, Maghrib, and Isha) from sunset until the darkness of the night, and the morning prayer. (Jalandhari)","«غَسَقَ» the initial part of the night.","darkness","غسق","17:78-113:3",2
906,186,"D","اَغْطَشَ","«غَطَشَ» means the darkness of the night. And «غَطَشُ» means having weak or dim sight. Similarly, «غَطَاش» is also used for the darkness of the night and for weakness of sight (manjad), i.e., such darkness in which objects appear faint and blurry.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَغۡطَشَ لَیۡلَہَا وَ اَخۡرَجَ ضُحٰہَا» ( 79/29 )\nTranslation: And He made the night dark and brought forth the morning brightness.","«اَغْطَشَ» such darkness that things are not clearly visible.","darkness","اغطش","79:29",1
907,186,"D","وَقَبَ","«وَقْب» refers to a pit or hollow in a rock, and so on. And «وَقَبَ» means to enter such a pit and disappear. «وَقَبَ الشَّمْس» means the setting of the sun. And «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام» means such deep darkness that objects within it become invisible (i.e., vanish from sight).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَمِنۡ شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ اِذَا وَقَبَ» (113/3)\nTranslation: And from the evil of the dark night when it covers (O Allah, I seek refuge in You).","«وَقَبَ» Such darkness in which objects disappear.","Darkness","وقب","113:3",1
908,186,"D","سَجٰی","«سَجَی الْلَیْل» means the night being silent and deserted. And «سَجَی الْمَیِّتَ» refers to wrapping and covering a corpse with a sheet. «سَجَّ مَعَائِبِ اَخِیْکَ» means conceal your brother's faults (manjad). Essentially, this word carries the concept of both covering and being at peace. That is, so much of the night has passed that all people have fallen asleep and the darkness has completely enveloped everything.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَالضُّحٰی وَ الَّیۡلِ اِذَا سَجٰی» (93:1,2)\nTranslation: By the brightness of the sun and by the night when it envelops in darkness.","«سَجٰی» the stillness and darkness of the night.","Darkness","سجی","93:2",1
909,186,"D","اَظْلَمَ","«ظَلِمَ ، ظُلْمًا» and «اَظْلَمَ اللَّیْل» mean the darkness of the night (manjad) – enveloping darkness. This term is not specific to the night; rather, if the day becomes dark due to clouds or any other reason, this word can be applied. And «ظُلْمَۃْ» means darkness, its opposite is «نُوْر», and its plurals are «ظُلَم», «ظُلُم», «ظُلَمٰت», and «ظُلُمَات» (manjad). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ ؕ کُلَّمَاۤ اَضَآءَ لَہُمۡ مَّشَوۡا فِیۡہِ ٭ۙ وَ اِذَاۤ اَظۡلَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ قَامُوۡا» (2/20) Translation: It is almost that the lightning snatches away their sight. When it flashes and illuminates them, they proceed therein, and when it becomes dark, they stand still.","«ظُلْمٰت» is a general term for darkness, whether due to night or any other reason.","darkness","اظلم","2:17-2:19-2:20-2:257-5:16-6:1-6:39-6:59-6:63-6:97-6:122-10:27-13:16-14:1-14:5-21:87-24:40-27:63-33:43-35:20-36:37-39:6-57:9-65:11",24
910,187,"F","طَرِیّ","«طَرِیّ» meaning fresh. Its usage is for meat (ف ۔ ل 54). «طَرَاوَتٌ» meaning freshness.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنۡ کُلٍّ تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ لَحۡمًا طَرِیًّا وَّ تَسۡتَخۡرِجُوۡنَ حِلۡیَۃً تَلۡبَسُوۡنَہَا» (35/12)\nTranslation: And you eat fresh meat from every kind of sea, whether sweet or salty, and you extract ornaments which you wear.","«طَرِیّ», meaning tartar, is generally used for meat.","Fresh","طری","16:14-35:12",2
911,187,"N","رَطَبَ","«رَطَبَ» means fresh and ripe, and its opposite is «یَابِس», which means dried. However, in common usage, the word «رَطَبَ» is specifically associated with ripe and fresh dates (sing.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ  تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا» (19/25)\n\nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards you. Fresh, ripe dates will fall upon you.","«رَطَبَ» is used for fresh and ripe dates.","Newly revealed","رطب","6:59-19:25",2
912,187,"F","نَضْرَۃً","«نَضَرَ» means to be soft, fresh, and beautiful (from the root letters م, ل), and «نَضْرَۃً» refers to the beauty and splendor of complexion, the freshness and radiance of the face.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«فَوَقٰہُمُ  اللّٰہُ  شَرَّ ذٰلِکَ الۡیَوۡمِ وَلَقّٰہُمۡ نَضۡرَۃً  وَّ سُرُوۡرًا» (76:11)  \nTranslation: So Allah will protect them from the hardship of that Day and grant them freshness and joy.","«نَضْرَۃً» a radiant countenance and the purity of the atmosphere.","Fresh","نضرۃً","75:22-76:11-83:24",3
913,187,"F","نَاعِمَۃٌ","«نَاعِمَۃٌ» means a prosperous life. Prosperity (manjid) refers to the abundance of blessings and the radiance on faces due to well-being.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ نَّاعِمَۃٌ لِّسَعۡیِہَا رَاضِیَۃٌ» (88:8-9)\nTranslation: On that day, many faces will be radiant, joyful because of the reward for their deeds.","«نَاعِمَۃٌ» the face radiant with abundance of blessings and prosperity.","Fresh","ناعمۃ","88:8",1
915,188,"S","کَیْ","«کَیْ» meaning so that. It comes after a verb to state its purpose. In Arabic grammar, it is called the jussive particle (مضارع خفیف حرف ناصبہ), i.e., the particle that puts the verb in the subjunctive mood. Often, the lam jar (لام جارّہ) accompanies کَیْ, and this lam is frequently omitted.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n« كَيْ تَقَرَّ عَیۡنُہَا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنَ» (20/40)\nTranslation: so that her eyes may be cooled and she may not grieve.","«کَیْ» means so that or in order that. It follows a verb to express the purpose or intention of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called a *mudari' khafif harf nasb*—that is, a particle that places the following verb in the subjunctive mood. The particle *kay* (کے) is often accompanied by the preposition *lam* (لام), and this *lam* is frequently omitted.","so that","کی","20:33-20:40-28:13",3
916,188,"S","اَنْ","«اَنْ» is called a masdar particle in Arabic grammar because it combines with a verb to convey the meaning of a verbal noun.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it states:  \n«ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی  اَنۡ تَقَرَّ اَعۡیُنُہُنَّ» (33/51)  \nTranslation: In it there is hope that their eyes may remain cool.","In Arabic grammar, it is called a verbal noun because when combined with a verb, it imparts the meaning of a verbal noun.","so that","ان","2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7",488
917,188,"S","کَیْ لَا","«کَیْ لَا» meaning so that. It follows a verb to express the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is called the subjunctive particle, i.e., the particle that causes the accusative case (nasb) for the verb. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «كَيْ لَا یَکُوۡنَ دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (59/7). Translation: so that those among you who are rich, that wealth does not remain circulating in their hands.","«کَیْ لَا» means so that or in order to. It comes after the verb to state the verb's purpose. In Arabic grammar, it is called the subtle imperfect particle that accusativizes the verb, meaning the particle that puts the verb in the accusative case.","so that","کی لا","59:7",1
918,188,"S","لِکَیْلَا","«لِکَیْلَا» means so that or in order that. It follows a verb to express the purpose of that verb. In Arabic grammar, it is known as the subtle jussive particle (مضارع خفیف حرف ناصبہ), meaning the particle that places the verb in the subjunctive mood. لِکَیْ is commonly written in combination with the negative particle لَا as لِکَیْلَا.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ» (3:153)\nTranslation: so that you do not grieve over what your hands have lost.","«لِکَیْلَا» means in order to. It follows a verb to state that verb's purpose. In Arabic grammar, it is called the subtle imperfect accusative particle—that is, the particle which governs the accusative case. لِكَي is written combined with the negation لَا as لِكَيْلَا.","so that","لکیلا","3:153-16:70-22:5-33:37-33:50-57:23",6
919,188,"S","لِئَلَّا","«لِئَلَّا» meaning 'so that'. For example, the Noble Quran states: «لِئَلَّا یَکُوۡنَ  لِلنَّاسِ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حُجَّۃٌ» (2/150). Translation: so that no blame may be placed upon you among the people.","«لِئَلَّا» meaning so that.","so that","لئلا","2:150-4:165-57:29",3
920,189,"T","قِطْر","«قِطْر» is a specific term for molten copper (مف ۔ منجد).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12)\nTranslation: And We caused a spring of molten copper to flow for him (Solomon, peace be upon him).","«قِطْر» molten copper.","Tawbah (repentance)","قطر","14:50-18:96-34:12",3
921,189,"R","مُھْل","«مُھْل» meaning «فَلَذَات»: minerals that can be melted, such as gold, silver, iron, copper. Molten metals. Thin pitch (flowing sulfur). Poison. Pus (madaj). And «مُھْل» and «مُھْلَۃ» meaning yellowish fluid (pus, the corrupt matter of a wound or boil). That is, the thin yellowish discharge that comes out of a corpse. (madaj. m. q) Thus, «مُھْل» is also used for several other molten metals besides copper, as well as for any yellowish discharge (yellowish filth). Therefore, some scholars have also translated «مُھْل» as pus.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡا یُغَاثُوۡا بِمَآءٍ کَالۡمُہۡلِ یَشۡوِی الۡوُجُوۡہَ ؕ بِئۡسَ الشَّرَابُ» (18/29)\nTranslation: If they cry for water, they will be given scalding water like molten copper, which will burn their faces. What an evil drink!","«مُھْل», besides copper, some other molten metals, and every detestable molten alloy.","Repentance","مھل","18:29-44:45-70:8",3
922,190,"T","عَرَش","«عَرَش» is used for a royal throne. (F L 230)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» (12/100)\nTranslation: And Yusuf (AS) placed his parents on the throne.\nAnd «عَرْشَ الْبَیْت» refers to the roof of a house. And «عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» means to build a house of wood. That is, «عَرْشَ الْبَیْت» refers to such a roof which consists of beams, planks, etc.","«عَرَش» is used for the royal throne.","Throne","عرش","2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15",29
923,190,"T","اَرَآئِک","«اَرِیْکَہ» meaning a canopied couch or a four-poster bed with bolsters, or a throne (as in footnote 30), or comfortable cushioned thrones and seats. An adorned and decorated throne (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran: «مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا عَلَی الۡاَرَآئِکِ» (76/13) Translation: The people of Paradise will be seated on thrones with cushions in Paradise.","«اَرِیْکَہ» is used for the throne of the arch.","Throne","ارآئک","18:31-36:56-76:13-83:23-83:35",5
924,190,"T","سُرُر","«سَرِیْر» Its plural is «سُرُِر», meaning plank (bed), charpagh, throne (cf. F. 30). «سَرِیْر» refers to the charpagh on which a funeral bier is carried. According to Sahib Manjad, the term «سَرِیْر» is mostly used for a royal throne. And Imam Raghib explains its meaning as a throne that wealthy people have made for sitting with pomp. (detailed)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«عَلٰی سُرُرٍ مَّوۡضُوۡنَۃٍ مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا مُتَقٰبِلِیۡنَ» (56:15-16)\nTranslation: (On thrones) embedded with rubies and sapphires, leaning against each other face to face.\n\nAnd in «مَوْضُوْنَۃٍ», the word «وَضَنَ» derives from 'zarbani,' meaning to weave with threads of gold and silver (detailed). Thus, this verse can also be translated as: On thrones woven with threads of gold and silver.","«سَرِیْر» royal throne, royal cushion, or throne, etc.","throne","سرر","15:47-37:44-43:34-52:20-56:15-88:13",6
925,191,"T","زُبَرْ","«زُبَر» is the plural of «زُبْرَۃ». And «زُبْرَۃ» means iron plates. Chadar (pl. manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اٰتُوۡنِیۡ زُبَرَ الۡحَدِیۡدِ» ( 18/96 )\nTranslation: Bring me iron plates (large ones).","«زُبَر» is generally used for iron sheets and large beds.","Throne","زبر","3:184-16:44-18:96-26:196-35:25-54:43-54:52",7
926,191,"T","اَلْوَاح","«اَلْوَاح» Its singular form «لَوْح» means the board of a ship, etc.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُ عَلٰی ذَاتِ اَلۡوَاحٍ  وَّدُسُرٍ» (54/13)  \nTranslation: And We made Noah ride upon a ship which was made of planks and nails.  \n\nFurthermore, «لَوْح» also refers to a wooden plank or similar material upon which something is written (Mu‘jam).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ کَتَبۡنَا لَہٗ  فِی الۡاَلۡوَاحِ  مِنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ مَّوۡعِظَۃً» (7/145)  \nTranslation: And We wrote for Moses every matter of advice in the tablets.","«اَلْوَاح» is used for a wooden board or writing tablet.","Table","الواح","7:145-7:150-7:154-54:13-85:22",5
927,192,"P","دَبَّرَ","«دَبَّرَ» meaning to observe the outcome of an action, reflect upon it, and determine its path (detailed).\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّدَبِّرُ الۡاَمۡرَ ؕ فَسَیَقُوۡلُوۡنَ اللّٰہُ» (10/31)\nTranslation: And who manages the affairs of the world? They will hastily say: Allah!","«دَبَّرَ» contemplating with the outcome of an action in mind.","Planning/Management","دبر","4:82-10:3-10:31-13:2-23:68-32:5-38:29-47:24-79:5",9
928,192,"D","کَیْد","«کَیْد» secretly planning to accomplish something. Scheme or trick (figurative) and «کَیْدُ سَاحِرٍ» meaning sorcerer's tricks (figurative). If the purpose of such planning is righteous and good, then it is permissible and correct.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n« کَذٰلِکَ  کِدۡنَا لِیُوۡسُفَ» (12/76)\nTranslation: Thus did We plan for Joseph.\n\nAnd if the purpose is evil, then it is condemnable.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ کَانَ  لَکُمۡ  کَیۡدٌ  فَکِیۡدُوۡنِ» (77/39)\nTranslation: If you are given a scheme, then scheme against me.\n\n«مَکَرَ» Moreover, such acts are permissible when intended for good purposes but impermissible when intended for bad purposes. However, the term makar (deceit) is predominantly used in a negative sense.","A covert scheme that causes someone to encounter something detestable (bad). On a small scale, it is termed «مَکَر»; on a large scale, it is termed «کَیْد».","Deliberate planning","کید","3:120-4:76-7:183-7:195-8:18-11:55-12:5-12:28-12:33-12:34-12:50-12:52-12:76-20:60-20:64-20:69-21:57-21:70-22:15-37:98-40:25-40:37-52:42-52:46-68:45-77:39-86:15-86:16-105:2",29
929,192,"P","مَکَرَ","«مَکَرَ» means to employ trickery and deception to accomplish a task (M. L.) and, metaphorically, to cause someone to secretly encounter something detestable (F. Q. 214). This word generally appears with a negative connotation. «مَکَرَ» also signifies fraud and cunning (M. R.). Imam Raghib defines its meaning as diverting a person from their objective through excuses and pretexts (M.F.). If this word is attributed to Allah, it comes as a retaliatory course of action against the deceitful.\n\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«اَللہُ یَسْتَھْزِئُ بِھِمْ»\nTranslation: Allah also mocks them.\nAnd in the context of *mushākilat* (a literary device where a meaning is expressed through a word not originally coined for it but which is associated with it), this is permissible.\n\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«وَمَکَرُوۡا وَمَکَرَ اللّٰہُ ؕ وَاللّٰہُ خَیۡرُ الۡمٰکِرِیۡنَ» (3/54)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers plotted, and Allah [also] plotted [in response]; and Allah is the best of plotters.","«مَکَرَ» Deception is such a secret trick that hinders others from their work.","Planning","مکر","3:54-6:123-6:124-7:99-7:123-8:30-10:21-12:31-12:102-13:33-13:42-14:46-16:26-16:45-16:127-27:50-27:51-27:70-34:33-35:10-35:43-40:45-71:22",23
930,192,"P","حِیْلَۃ","«حُوَّل ، حَوْل» means strength, power, intelligence, and foresight. The power to control or manage, and its plural forms are «حِیَل» and «حِوَل» (as in 'manjad'). It also means deceit and trickery (m. q.). «حیلہ» actually refers to actions undertaken to gain benefit or avoid harm in such a way that one evades legal consequences. For example, before the year passes, gifting one's property to one's wife to avoid paying zakat, and then after some time, reclaiming that gift from her. This involves both cunning, deception, and strategy. Unlike «کَیْد», it is not a secret plot.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِلَّا الۡمُسۡتَضۡعَفِیۡنَ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ وَالنِّسَآءِ وَالۡوِلۡدَانِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ حِیۡلَۃً  وَّلَا  یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ سَبِیۡلًا» (4/98)\nTranslation: Yes, those men, women, and children who are helpless—neither possessing the power to devise a plan nor knowing the way.","To acquire control and power over someone through astuteness and cunning.","Planning","حیلۃ","4:98",1
931,193,"S","مِیْزَان","«مِیْزَان» A weighing instrument. This term is commonly used for an instrument that weighs something of equal weight. And each weight placed on the pan of a scale is also called a mīzān (balance/measure).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَّا تَطۡغَوۡا فِی الۡمِیۡزَانِ وَ اَقِیۡمُوا الۡوَزۡنَ بِالۡقِسۡطِ وَلَا تُخۡسِرُوا الۡمِیۡزَانَ» (55:8,9)\nTranslation: So that you do not commit fraud in the balance (by weighing). And establish weights in justice and do not make the measure deficient.","«مِیْزَان» the instrument for weighing, the scales upon which on the Day of Judgment, the deeds of human beings will be weighed, and according to which reward and punishment will be given.","Scale","میزان","6:152-7:85-11:84-11:85-42:17-55:7-55:8-55:9-57:25",9
932,193,"S","قِسْطَاس","«قِسْطَاس» is a word from the Roman lexicon that entered the Arabic language (F. L 286), and it refers to a scale that is extremely sensitive. (M. R) It is a scale in which one must even cut (the object being weighed) to check for any tilt.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ زِنُوۡا بِالۡقِسۡطَاسِ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمِ» (17:35)\n\nTranslation: And when you measure, measure with a straight scale.","«قِسْطَاس» This is what a highly sensitive scale is called.","scales","قسطاس","17:35-26:182",2
933,194,"T","نَحَتَ","«نَحَتَ» is used in the sense of carving or chiseling hard materials such as wood, stone, iron, etc. And «نُحَاتَۃُ» refers to shavings from wood or chips from stone that fall during carving. (Example)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَتَعۡبُدُوۡنَ  مَا تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ» (37/95)\nTranslation: Do you then worship that which you yourselves carve?\n\nAnd evidently, these idols were made from carved stone, wood, or metals.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَّ تَنۡحِتُوۡنَ الۡجِبَالَ بُیُوۡتًا» (7/74)\nTranslation: And you carve out of the mountains, homes.","«نَحَتَ» is used to carve or peel something.","to chisel","نحت","7:74-15:82-26:149-37:95",4
934,194,"T","جَابَ","«جَابَ» means to cut (transitive) and to make a hole or fissure (intransitive), and then to carve or shape it meticulously. Thus, the word «نَحَتَ» is suitable for delicate work, and «جَابَ» for heavy work.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ ثَمُوۡدَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَابُوا الصَّخۡرَ بِالۡوَادِ» (89:9)\nTranslation: And the Thamud who carved (and built houses) in the valley.","«جَابَ» is used in the meanings of cutting, splitting, and peeling. And it is associated with heavy work.","to carve","جاب","89:9",1
935,195,"C","قَضْب","«قَضْب» refers to vegetables or greens that are eaten fresh after being cut (manjid), and «صاحبِ مُفرَدَات» and «صَاحِبِ مُنْتَہَی الْاَرَب». In this context, fresh grass (i.e., animal feed) is also included. Moreover, the definition provided by the author of Tafsir-e-Muhammadi, citing «مَعَالِمُ التَّنزِیْل» regarding «قَضْب», appears more accurate. That is, every vegetable or green whose leaves are above ground (as animal feed) and whose useful part (for human consumption) is below ground. For example, carrots, radishes, turnips, etc.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَنْۢبَتْنَا فِيْهَا حَبًّا وَّعِنَبًا وَّقَضْبًا وَّ زَیۡتُوۡنًا وَّ نَخۡلًا» (80/29)\nTranslation: Then We have sown therein grain, and grapes and vegetables and olives and dates.","«قَضْب» that vegetable or green which is eaten after being freshly cut.","Cultivation","قضب","80:28",1
936,195,"C","بَقْل","According to Imam Raghib, such vegetables are those whose roots and branches do not survive the winters (detailed), and according to «صَاحِبِ مُنْتَہَی الْاَرَب», «بَقْل» refers to every vegetable and greens that grows from a seed, not from a root—like watermelon, etc. However, the correct understanding seems to be that the term «بَقْل» is general, encompassing all types of vegetables and greens. And «بَقّال» refers to a vegetable seller who sells all kinds of vegetables and greens.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَادۡعُ لَنَا رَبَّکَ یُخۡرِجۡ لَنَا مِمَّا تُنۡۢبِتُ الۡاَرۡضُ مِنۡۢ بَقۡلِہَا» (2/61)\nTranslation: So invoke your Lord to bring forth for us from the earth a vegetable that grows.","«بَقْل» all vegetables and greens that grow from seed rather than from root.","cultivation","بقل","2:61",1
937,196,"P","سَبَّحَ","«سَبَّحَ» meaning to recite tasbeeh. To say Subhan Allah or to mention Subhan Allah. To express through speech or state the attributes of that blessed Essence, who is free from all types of flaws, defects, and weaknesses. To positively mention His perfect qualities and to extol His praise. (For details, see Pure).","«سَبَّحَ» meaning to say tasbih. To remember Subhan Allah. To remember and extol the glorious attributes of Allah's blessed Essence and to praise Him.","Purity","سبح","2:30-3:41-7:206-13:13-15:98-17:44-19:11-20:33-20:130-21:20-21:79-24:36-24:41-25:58-32:15-33:42-37:143-37:166-38:18-39:75-40:7-40:55-41:38-42:5-48:9-50:39-50:40-52:48-52:49-56:74-56:96-57:1-59:1-59:24-61:1-62:1-64:1-68:28-69:52-76:26-87:1-110:3",42
938,196,"P","قَدَّسَ","«قُدُّوْس» Allah, the Most High, is the Entity who is not in need of anyone's partnership and is pure from the other impurities of shirk (associating partners with Allah). (See the detailed explanation under Purity). And «قَدّسَ» means mentioning the purity of the Essence of the Most High and negating all attributes that are not befitting for Allah Ta'ala.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ نَحۡنُ نُسَبِّحُ بِحَمۡدِکَ وَ نُقَدِّسُ لَکَ» (2/30)\nTranslation: (The angels said,) And we glorify You with praise and we sanctify You.","Negating evil and negative attributes while mentioning a being or thing.","Purity","قدس","2:30-2:87-2:253-5:21-5:110-16:102-20:12-79:16",8
939,196,"P","حَاشَ","«حَاشَ» is the word of exclamation (meaning: that which induces wonder and amazement). It is synonymous with «حَاشَا لِلّٰہِ ، سُبْحَانَ اللہ», but it is employed only in very restricted senses. This word conveys *tanzih* (i.e., the essence absolutely free from all flaws and deficiencies) and *istithna* (exception). It is not used in the sense of the exclamatory word «حَاشَ» either. For example: The Quran states:  \n«فَلَمَّا رَاَیۡنَہٗۤ  اَکۡبَرۡنَہٗ وَ قَطَّعۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُنَّ وَ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا ہٰذَا بَشَرًا ؕ اِنۡ  ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّا مَلَکٌ  کَرِیۡمٌ» (12:31)  \nTranslation: When those women saw Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him), a profound awe overcame them to such an extent that they cut their hands while slicing fruit and cried out spontaneously, Glory be to Allah! This is not a mortal; he is none but a noble angel.  \n\nAt another instance, the Almighty Lord declares:  \n«قَالَ مَا خَطۡبُکُنَّ اِذۡ رَاوَدۡتُّنَّ یُوۡسُفَ عَنۡ نَّفۡسِہٖ ؕ قُلۡنَ حَاشَ لِلّٰہِ مَا عَلِمۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءٍ» (12:51)  \nTranslation: The king summoned the women and said, What was your affair when you attempted to seduce Yusuf? They all replied, Far be it from Allah! We did not perceive any ill in him at all.  \n\nSometimes the word *kalla* is also used alongside *hasha*. «حَاشَ وَکَلَّا» is employed for emphatically denying an accusation, whether about oneself or another. This usage does not occur in the Quran. Thus, the dimension of emphatic denial is incorporated within «حَاشَ».","«حَاشَ» is an exclamatory word used in the sense of 'Subhan' (Glory be to God). It is employed to emphatically deny an accusation, whether against oneself or another.","Purity","حاش","12:31-12:51",2
940,197,"T","سَکِیْنَۃٌ","«سَکُون» refers to the pause after movement, which is called tranquility. This can be physical as well as mental or emotional. If it is mental or emotional, it is called «سَکِیْنَۃ». That is, the heart finds relief from thoughts and grief, and attains stability.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا ۚ فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ» (9:40)\nTranslation: When the Prophet would console his companion, saying, Do not grieve; indeed, Allah is with us, then Allah sent down His tranquility upon him.","The term «سَکِیْنَۃ» is employed for «سَکِیْنَۃٌ», meaning tranquility from grief and contemplative reflections.","Tranquility","سکینۃ","2:248-9:26-9:40-48:4-48:18-48:26",6
941,197,"T","اِطْمَئِنَّ","«اِطْمَئِنَّ» meaning to attain reassurance. After restlessness, anxiety, hesitation, and doubt, the soul finds tranquility (intransitive). The natural state of being content and at peace.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ اَوَ لَمۡ تُؤۡمِنۡ ؕ قَالَ بَلٰی وَ لٰکِنۡ لِّیَطۡمَئِنَّ قَلۡبِیۡ» (2/260)\nTranslation: He asked, Do you not believe? He replied, Yes, but I seek this so that my heart may be at peace. (Uthmaniؒ)","The word «اِطْمِیْنَان» appears in «اِطْمَئِنَّ» for deliverance from doubts.","Tranquility","اطمئن","2:260-3:126-4:103-5:113-8:10-10:7-13:28-16:106-16:112-17:95-22:11-89:27",12
942,198,"I","عَبَرَ","«عَبَرَ» means to cross a valley or river, and «عِبَارَۃَ الرُّؤْیَا» and «عَبَّرَ الرُّؤْیَا» mean to interpret a dream, and «عَبَّار» means the one who gives dreams (a soothsayer), and «اَلْعِبْرَۃ وَالْاِعْتِبَار» means to reach the seen results from something that has been seen. And interpretation means telling the outcome of a dream (detailed).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ لِلرُّءۡیَا تَعۡبُرُوۡنَ» (12/43)\nTranslation: If you are able to interpret dreams.","The words «عَبَرَ» and «تَعْبِیْر» are specifically used for explaining the interpretation of dreams.","Interpretation","عبر","3:13-12:43-12:111-16:66-23:21-24:44-79:26",7
943,198,"I","تَاَوَّلَ","«تَاوِیْل» means to return something to its ultimate end or outcome. This term is more specific than interpretation, because the meaning of interpretation is to state the absolute outcome of any matter, whether it be a dream or something else. Whereas the term 'interpretation' is specifically used to state the outcome of a dream. And according to «صاحبِ فُرُوْقُ الْلغَوِیَّہ», interpretation is only done for something ambiguous (Faq. p. 43).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالَ الۡاٰخَرُ اِنِّیۡۤ  اَرٰىنِیۡۤ  اَحۡمِلُ فَوۡقَ رَاۡسِیۡ خُبۡزًا تَاۡکُلُ الطَّیۡرُ مِنۡہُ ؕ نَبِّئۡنَا بِتَاۡوِیۡلِہٖ» (12/36)\n\nTranslation: The other said, I dreamt that I was carrying bread on my head, and birds were eating from it. So inform us of its interpretation!","« تَاَوَّلَ» is generally used to announce the outcome of an event or matter, particularly in the context of interpreting dreams.","Interpretation","تَاَوَّلَ","3:7-4:59-7:53-10:39-12:6-12:21-12:36-12:37-12:44-12:45-12:100-12:101-17:35-18:78-18:82",15
944,198,"I","اَفْتٰی","«اَفْتٰی» means to explain the solution to a difficult and complex problem. «فَتْوٰی» is a Shariah term, meaning to present a Shariah solution to a difficult and complex problem. The term 'بتلانا' means to inform or tell. And 'استفتاء' means to ask a scholar for the solution to a difficult and complex problem. In the Quran, the word «اَفْتٰی» is used only in the context of dream interpretation because the dream whose interpretation was sought was very complex and difficult.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡمَلَاُ  اَفۡتُوۡنِیۡ فِیۡ رُءۡیَایَ» (12/43)\nTranslation: The king of Egypt said, O my chiefs! Explain to me my dream.\nAnd those who were to interpret that complex dream dismissed it by saying,\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحۡلَامِ بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44)\nTranslation: These are confused dreams, and we do not know the interpretation of such dreams.\nThen the freed companion of Joseph (peace be upon him) said:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ» (12/46)\nTranslation: O Joseph, O truthful one! Explain to us the interpretation of the dream about the seven fat cows.","«اَفْتٰی» to present a solution to a difficult and complex problem, which also includes the interpretation of dreams.","Interpretation","افتی","4:127-4:176-12:43-12:46-27:32",5
945,199,"P","حَمْد","«مَدَح» is to mention someone's good qualities and virtues, provided those qualities are optional (i.e., chosen by the person). For example, if a person practices generosity, this act is optional. Praise given for it will be «حَمْد». However, if the qualities are involuntary (i.e., non-optional), such as a person being tall, handsome, or of noble lineage—wherein the person has no personal contribution—then praising these traits is called «مَدَح». Its opposite is «ذَمّ», which means mentioning faults or defects present in a person, whether they are optional or involuntary. Thus, the term حمد (praise) is specific to «مَدَح». «مَدَح» can apply to both optional and involuntary goodness, but حمد is exclusively used for optional acts.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ یُحِبُّوۡنَ اَنۡ یُّحۡمَدُوۡا بِمَا لَمۡ یَفۡعَلُوۡا» (3:188)\nTranslation: And they wish that you should approve of what they did not do.\n\nMoreover, the term «مَدَح» is inappropriate (unsuitable) for Allah Almighty, because all His actions are both beloved and optional.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ رَبِّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (1:1)\nTranslation: All praise is for Allah, Lord of the worlds.\n\nThe word مدح (commendation) does not appear anywhere in the Quran.","«مَدَح» means to praise someone by mentioning their good qualities, provided those qualities are acquired, and to be grateful for bounties and favors.","Praise","حمد","1:1-2:30-3:144-3:188-6:1-6:45-7:43-10:10-13:13-14:39-15:98-16:75-17:44-17:52-17:111-18:1-20:130-23:28-25:58-27:15-27:59-27:93-28:70-29:63-30:18-31:25-32:15-33:40-34:1-35:1-35:34-37:182-39:29-39:74-39:75-40:7-40:55-40:65-42:5-45:36-47:2-48:29-50:39-52:48-61:6-64:1-110:3",47
946,199,"D","شُکر","The term «شُکر» is used for the conception and expression of someone's favors and bounties (مف), and its opposite is «کُفْر». It means to forget someone's favor or to conceal a blessing and not let it be apparent. This is ingratitude toward favors or denial of blessings. It is also specific to «شُکْر ، حَمْد». For example, if we say that God Almighty has created the universe's system with such excellence, this is «حَمْد»; and if we say that it is God who feeds and gives us drink, this is «شُکْر».\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَئِنۡ شَکَرۡتُمۡ لَاَزِیۡدَنَّکُمۡ وَ لَئِنۡ کَفَرۡتُمۡ اِنَّ عَذَابِیۡ لَشَدِیۡدٌ» (14:7)\nTranslation: If you are grateful, I will increase you [in favor]; but if you deny, indeed, My punishment is severe.","«شُکر» Expressing gratitude is used to acknowledge kindness in the context of some favor or blessing.","Definition","شکر","2:52-2:56-2:152-2:172-2:185-2:243-3:123-4:147-5:6-5:89-7:10-7:58-8:26-10:60-12:38-14:7-14:37-16:14-16:78-16:114-22:36-23:78-27:19-27:40-27:73-28:73-29:17-30:46-31:12-31:14-32:9-34:13-34:15-35:12-36:35-36:73-39:7-40:61-45:12-46:15-54:35-56:70-67:23",43
947,200,"R","عَظَّم","The meanings of «عَظْم» also include 'to be great' and 'bone.' Thus, in «عَظْم», the concept of greatness accompanied by maturity, strength, or firmness is also found. And «عَظَّمَ» means to regard someone as great and honorable from the heart. It is used for both living and non-living things.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَمَنۡ یُّعَظِّمۡ شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ فَاِنَّہَا مِنۡ تَقۡوَی الۡقُلُوۡبِ» (22/32)\nTranslation: And whoever honors the symbols of Allah, it is from the piety of hearts.","«عَظَّم» is used to consider someone greater and more honorable than the heart, and this applies to all living and non-living things.","Reverence","عظم","6:146-19:4-22:30-22:32-65:5",5
948,200,"R","وَقّر","«وَقَّرَ» means seriousness and greatness (according to Munjid), and according to «صاحبِ مُفرَدَات», it signifies seriousness and forbearance (Muhit). Ibn Faris also records its meaning as «اَلْحِلْمُ وَالرَّزَانَۃ» (M. L.). Furthermore, «وَقَّرَ» denotes respecting the status of a person of high rank and refraining from any action contrary to that status. This term is used exclusively for humans.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «لِّتُؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ وَ رَسُوۡلِہٖ  وَ تُعَزِّرُوۡہُ وَ تُوَقِّرُوۡہُ» (48:9) Translation: So that you may believe in Allah and His Messenger, support him, and honor him.","«وَقَّرَ» Dignity means gravity and grandeur; to be dignified is to be serious and steadfast in temperament.","Reverence","وقر","48:9",1
949,201,"U","اِلٰی","In Arabic grammar, the preposition «اِلٰی» is used to indicate the extremity or limit of something. It can also attach to a pronoun. For example, «اِلَیْکمْ»—in this case, it will mean toward him—but «حتّٰی» can only govern a demonstrative noun (i.e., it can only be followed by a noun). It does not attach to a pronoun; it only attaches to a noun or a verb.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً» (2/55)\nTranslation: Until we see Allah face to face.","In Arabic grammar, «اِلٰی» is called a preposition. It is used to denote the extremity or limit of something.","until","الی","2:4-2:14-2:28-2:29-2:36-2:46-2:54-2:76-2:85-2:99-2:125-2:126-2:136-2:142-2:156-2:178-2:187-2:188-2:195-2:196-2:203-2:210-2:213-2:221-2:240-2:243-2:245-2:246-2:257-2:258-2:259-2:260-2:272-2:275-2:280-2:281-2:282-2:285-3:12-3:23-3:28-3:44-3:49-3:52-3:55-3:64-3:75-3:77-3:83-3:97-3:101-3:104-3:109-3:133-3:154-3:158-3:183-3:199-4:2-4:6-4:21-4:44-4:49-4:51-4:58-4:59-4:60-4:61-4:77-4:83-4:87-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:94-4:100-4:105-4:142-4:143-4:158-4:162-4:163-4:166-4:171-4:172-4:174-4:175-5:6-5:11-5:14-5:16-5:18-5:28-5:35-5:48-5:49-5:58-5:59-5:64-5:66-5:67-5:68-5:70-5:74-5:81-5:83-5:96-5:104-5:105-5:111-6:12-6:19-6:25-6:36-6:38-6:41-6:42-6:50-6:51-6:60-6:62-6:71-6:72-6:87-6:93-6:99-6:106-6:108-6:111-6:112-6:113-6:114-6:119-6:121-6:136-6:145-6:159-6:161-6:164-7:2-7:3-7:6-7:14-7:24-7:59-7:65-7:73-7:85-7:103-7:117-7:125-7:135-7:143-7:150-7:156-7:158-7:160-7:164-7:167-7:176-7:189-7:193-7:198-7:203-8:6-8:12-8:16-8:24-8:36-8:44-8:58-8:60-9:1-9:3-9:4-9:24-9:38-9:57-9:59-9:77-9:83-9:94-9:95-9:101-9:105-9:118-9:122-9:125-9:127-10:2-10:4-10:11-10:12-10:15-10:23-10:25-10:30-10:35-10:42-10:43-10:46-10:56-10:70-10:71-10:74-10:75-10:87-10:94-10:98-10:109-11:3-11:4-11:8-11:12-11:15-11:23-11:25-11:34-11:36-11:43-11:49-11:50-11:52-11:57-11:61-11:62-11:70-11:78-11:80-11:81-11:84-11:88-11:90-11:97-11:113-11:123-12:3-12:8-12:15-12:31-12:33-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:65-12:69-12:81-12:86-12:99-12:102-12:108-12:109-13:1-13:14-13:19-13:27-13:30-13:36-14:1-14:5-14:9-14:10-14:13-14:28-14:30-14:37-14:43-14:44-15:35-15:36-15:38-15:58-15:66-15:88-16:7-16:43-16:44-16:48-16:53-16:61-16:63-16:68-16:70-16:79-16:80-16:86-16:87-16:103-16:121-16:123-16:125-17:1-17:4-17:29-17:39-17:42-17:47-17:51-17:57-17:62-17:67-17:73-17:74-17:78-17:86-18:10-18:16-18:19-18:27-18:36-18:57-18:63-18:87-18:110-19:11-19:17-19:23-19:25-19:29-19:40-19:85-19:86-20:22-20:24-20:38-20:40-20:43-20:48-20:66-20:77-20:84-20:86-20:89-20:91-20:97-20:114-20:115-20:120-20:131-20:134-21:7-21:10-21:13-21:25-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:71-21:73-21:81-21:93-21:108-21:111-22:4-22:5-22:15-22:24-22:33-22:48-22:54-22:67-22:76-23:23-23:27-23:46-23:50-23:60-23:73-23:79-23:100-23:115-24:31-24:34-24:42-24:46-24:48-24:49-24:51-24:64-25:7-25:8-25:23-25:34-25:36-25:45-25:46-25:57-25:71-26:7-26:13-26:27-26:50-26:52-26:63-27:12-27:28-27:29-27:33-27:35-27:37-27:40-27:45-28:7-28:13-28:24-28:32-28:35-28:38-28:39-28:41-28:44-28:47-28:57-28:63-28:70-28:71-28:72-28:77-28:85-28:86-28:87-28:88-29:8-29:14-29:17-29:21-29:26-29:36-29:45-29:46-29:47-29:57-29:65-30:11-30:21-30:31-30:33-30:47-30:50-30:56-31:14-31:15-31:21-31:22-31:23-31:24-31:29-31:32-32:5-32:11-32:27-33:2-33:6-33:18-33:19-33:43-33:46-33:51-33:53-34:6-34:9-34:31-34:44-34:50-35:4-35:9-35:10-35:15-35:18-35:31-35:45-36:8-36:14-36:16-36:22-36:31-36:44-36:50-36:51-36:60-36:83-37:8-37:23-37:68-37:91-37:94-37:99-37:140-37:144-37:147-37:148-38:22-38:24-38:29-38:70-38:78-38:79-38:81-39:2-39:3-39:7-39:8-39:17-39:23-39:42-39:44-39:54-39:55-39:65-39:71-39:73-40:3-40:10-40:11-40:24-40:37-40:41-40:42-40:43-40:44-40:69-40:77-41:5-41:6-41:11-41:19-41:21-41:33-41:47-41:50-42:3-42:7-42:10-42:13-42:14-42:15-42:44-42:52-42:53-43:14-43:43-43:46-43:85-44:18-44:47-45:15-45:26-45:28-46:5-46:9-46:11-46:15-46:29-46:30-47:16-47:20-47:35-48:12-48:15-48:16-49:5-49:7-49:9-50:6-50:16-50:28-50:43-51:26-51:27-51:32-51:38-51:50-52:13-53:10-53:42-54:6-54:8-56:50-56:85-57:5-57:9-57:21-58:1-58:8-58:9-58:14-59:9-59:11-60:1-60:2-60:4-60:8-60:10-60:11-61:5-61:6-61:7-61:14-62:8-62:9-62:11-63:8-63:10-64:3-65:5-65:10-65:11-66:3-66:4-66:8-67:4-67:15-67:19-67:24-68:32-68:39-68:42-68:43-70:4-70:43-71:1-71:4-72:1-72:2-73:8-73:15-73:19-75:12-75:23-75:30-75:33-76:29-77:22-77:29-77:30-78:39-79:17-79:18-79:19-79:44-80:24-83:31-84:6-84:9-88:17-88:18-88:19-88:20-88:25-89:28-94:8-96:8",653
950,201,"U","حَتّٰی","In Arabic grammar, «حَتّٰی» is considered a preposition used to indicate the limit or end of something. And «حَتّٰی ، اِلٰی» is more eloquent; for example, with «حَتَّی الْاٰن» ('until then'), one can say [it], but one does not say «اِلی الْاٰن». The meaning of «اِلٰی» is taken only as 'until,' whereas «حَتّٰی» means 'up to here.' For instance: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ قٰتِلُوۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی لَا تَکُوۡنَ فِتۡنَۃٌ» Translation: And fight them until there is no more persecution.","«حَتّٰی» is known as a preposition in Arabic grammar. It is used to denote the limit or extremity of something.","until","حتی","2:55-2:102-2:109-2:120-2:187-2:191-2:193-2:196-2:214-2:217-2:221-2:222-2:230-2:235-3:92-3:152-3:179-3:183-4:6-4:15-4:18-4:43-4:65-4:89-4:140-5:22-5:68-6:25-6:31-6:34-6:44-6:61-6:68-6:124-6:148-6:152-7:37-7:38-7:40-7:57-7:87-7:95-8:39-8:53-8:67-8:72-9:6-9:24-9:29-9:43-9:48-9:115-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:88-10:90-10:93-10:97-10:99-10:109-11:40-12:35-12:66-12:80-12:85-12:110-13:11-13:31-15:99-17:15-17:34-17:90-17:93-18:60-18:70-18:71-18:74-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-18:96-19:75-20:91-21:15-21:44-21:96-22:55-23:25-23:54-23:64-23:77-23:99-23:110-24:27-24:28-24:33-24:39-24:62-25:18-26:201-27:18-27:32-27:84-28:23-28:59-34:23-36:39-37:174-37:178-38:32-39:71-39:73-40:34-41:20-41:53-43:29-43:38-43:83-46:15-47:4-47:16-47:31-49:5-49:9-51:43-52:45-57:14-60:4-63:7-65:6-70:42-72:24-74:47-97:5-98:1-102:2",138
951,202,"H","ضَرّ","«ضَرَّ» meaning harm. Any material or spiritual affliction or damage. And its opposite is «نَفَعَ». «ضَرَّ» and this harm or affliction can sometimes be good, like experiencing pain from bitter medicine (Faq l 162). For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ اَتَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مَا لَا یَمۡلِکُ لَکُمۡ ضَرًّا وَّلَا نَفۡعًا» (5/76)\nTranslation: Say, Why do you worship besides Allah that which holds no power to harm or benefit you?","«ضَرَّ» means harm or loss, any material or spiritual hardship or detriment. And its opposite, «نَفَعَ», means benefit.","Hardship","ضر","2:231-4:95-5:76-7:188-9:107-10:49-13:16-20:89-25:3-34:42-41:50-48:11-72:21",13
952,202,"D","ضُرّ","«ضُرّ» is found to denote exaggeration and is generally used for physical affliction. It is employed for misfortune, disease, wound, or other physical and mental ailments (see: فق ل 162), and it carries a negative connotation.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا مَسَّ الۡاِنۡسَانَ الضُّرُّ دَعَانَا لِجَنۡۢبِہٖۤ اَوۡ قَاعِدًا اَوۡ قَآئِمًا» (10/12)\nTranslation: And when affliction befalls man, he calls upon Us, whether lying down, sitting, or standing.","«ضُرّ» is used for physical pain and illness.","Divine commandment","ضر","2:102-3:111-3:120-3:144-3:176-3:177-4:113-5:42-5:105-6:17-6:71-9:39-10:12-10:18-10:106-10:107-11:57-12:88-16:53-16:54-17:56-17:67-21:66-21:83-21:84-22:12-22:13-23:75-25:55-26:73-30:33-36:23-39:8-39:38-39:49-47:32",36
953,202,"R","ضَرَّآء","«ضَرَّآء» a period of hardships and prosperity. Loss of life, wealth, or offspring, or famine (from the root letters م, ق) and its opposite, «نَعْمَاء», means prosperity. «ضَرَّآء» refers to visible afflictions that are apparent to others. (Faq l 163)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَسَّتۡہُمُ الۡبَاۡسَآءُ وَالضَّرَّآءُ وَ زُلۡزِلُوۡا حَتّٰی یَقُوۡلَ الرَّسُوۡلُ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مَعَہٗ مَتٰی نَصۡرُ اللّٰہِ» (2:214)\nTranslation: They were afflicted with illnesses and calamities, and they were shaken to such an extent that the Messenger and those who believed with him said, When will the help of Allah come?","«ضَرَّآء» is used for times of apparent difficulties and hardship.","Religious duty","ضرآء","2:214-2:177-3:134-6:42-7:94-7:95-10:21-11:10",8
954,202,"R","اَذًی","«اَذًی» is used to denote a light hardship. «اَلضُّرُّ الْیَسِیْر» (i.e., م ۔ ق) means a light hardship.\nFor example: the Noble Quran states:\n«لَنۡ یَّضُرُّوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّاۤ اَذًی» (3:111)\nTranslation: They will not cause you any harm except a slight inconvenience.\nThis light hardship can also be mental, such as causing someone emotional pain or speaking offensively.\nFor example: the Divine Command of Allah states:\n«وَ مِنۡہُمُ الَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡذُوۡنَ النَّبِیَّ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ ہُوَ اُذُنٌ» (9:61)\nTranslation: Among them are those who hurt the Prophet and say, He is all ears.\nThis hardship can also be physical, as in the Noble Quran where menstruation is referred to as «اَذًی», which is also translated as impurity or filth.","«اَذًی» is used for mild pain.","religious obligation","اذًی","2:196-2:222-2:262-2:263-2:264-3:111-3:186-4:102-9:61-33:57-33:58-61:5",12
955,202,"D","کُرْھًا","«کَرْھًا» means compulsory toil or urgent distress (fem.), i.e., being forced to undertake a burdensome task. Its opposite is «طَوْعًا», i.e., performing an action willingly or with pleasure.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حَمَلَتۡہُ اُمُّہٗ کُرۡہًا وَّ وَضَعَتۡہُ کُرۡہًا» (46/15)\nTranslation: His mother carried him in toil and gave birth to him in pain.","«کَرْھًا» is used for compulsory hardship.","Divine command","کرھًا","2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9",26
956,202,"T","مَعَرَّۃٌ","«اَلْعَرُّ وَالْعُرُّ» is the term for a skin disease that afflicts the entire body. By extension, «مَعَرَّۃٌ» is applied to all kinds of harm (muf) and, according to the author of *Manjad*, its meanings include sin, affliction, evil, fault, defect, and a bad thing. They write that it signifies hardship and abuse. Thus, this word has a broad meaning and is used for every type of pain, distress, and corruption.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَتُصِیۡبَکُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَرَّۃٌۢ  بِغَیۡرِ عِلۡمٍ» (48:25)\n\nTranslation: Then corruption befell you unwittingly on their account. (Translation of Shah 'Abdul Qadir [عثمانیؒ])","«مَعَرَّۃ» is used for all kinds of pain and corruption.","trial","معرۃ","48:25",1
957,202,"O","اٰذٰی","«اٰذٰی» is used for minor troubles, whether mental or physical. For example, the Quran states: «لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا کَالَّذِیۡنَ اٰذَوۡا مُوۡسٰی» (33:69). Translation: And be like those who afflicted Moses.","«اٰذٰی» is used for ordinary hardship, whether mental or physical.","Obligation","اذی","2:64-4:16-14:12-33:69",4
958,202,"H","ضَرَّ","«ضَرَّ» is used for great hardship and harm.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَاِنۡ تَصۡبِرُوۡا وَ تَتَّقُوۡا لَا یَضُرُّکُمۡ کَیۡدُہُمۡ شَیۡئًا» ( 3/120 )\nTranslation: And if you are patient and adopt Taqwa (God-consciousness/piety), their plot will not harm you at all.\nAnd «ضَارَّ ،  یُضَارُّ» means to cause pain to one another, to inflict harm, or to bring about hardship.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا تُضَآرَّ وَالِدَۃٌۢ بِوَلَدِہَا وَ لَا مَوۡلُوۡدٌ لَّہٗ بِوَلَدِہٖ» ( 2/233 )\nTranslation: Neither should the mother be made to suffer harm because of her child, nor the father because of his child.","«ضَرَّ» is used to cause great suffering and harm.","hardship","ضر","2:231-4:95-5:76-7:188-9:107-10:49-13:16-20:89-25:3-34:42-41:50-48:11-72:21",13
959,202,"D","کُرْہٌ","«اَکْرَہْ» means forced hardship. To force someone into hardship against their will or to compel someone to do something against their inclination.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)  \nTranslation: And do not compel your slave women into prostitution.  \n\nApart from these meanings, the words «کَلَّفَ ، شَقَّ ، سَامَ» and «عَنَتَ» also occur.","«اَکْرَہَ» is used for compulsory hardship.","Divine commandment","کرہ","2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9",26
960,202,"D","کَلَّفَ","«کَلَّفَ» meaning to demand more from something than its capacity and strength (transitive) or to command a difficult task (intransitive).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا» (2/286)  \nTranslation: God does not burden any person beyond their capacity.  \nHardship can be praiseworthy (good) or blameworthy (bad). Praiseworthy hardship is that which is undertaken because it is easy and one comes to love it. This constitutes the legitimate religious hardship. Blameworthy hardship is what is termed 'takalluf', implying an artificial burden or affectation.","«کَلَّفَ» meaning to take more from something than its status and capacity permit.","Divine decree","کلف","2:233-2:286-4:84-6:152-7:42-23:62-65:7",7
961,202,"H","شَقَّ","«شَقّ» can also mean to tear apart. And «شَقَّ یُشَقُّ» means to take from someone more work than their capacity or to subject them to toil and hardship (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَمَاۤ اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اَشُقَّ عَلَیۡکَ» (28:27)\nTranslation: And I do not wish to put you in hardship.","«مُشَقَّۃ» is used to exploit beyond one's strength.","hardship","شق","13:34-16:7-20:2-20:117-20:123-28:27",6
962,202,"T","عَنَتَ","«عَنَتَ» Such an affliction wherein there is a risk of perishing (i.e., severe) and meaning the most harmful or extreme hardship (i.e., intense).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا ؕ وَدُّوۡا مَا عَنِتُّمۡ» ( 3/118 )\nTranslation: O believers! Do not take anyone outside your faith as an intimate friend. They will not spare any effort to corrupt you and cause you trouble; they desire to inflict pain upon you in whatever way they can!\nAnd «اَعْنَتَ» meaning to plunge someone into such hardship.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَوۡ شَآءَ اللّٰہُ  لَاَعۡنَتَکُمۡ» ( 2/220 )\nTranslation: And if Allah had willed, He could have imposed hardship upon you.","«عَنَتَ» such distress that carries the risk of death.","Trial","عنت","2:220-3:118-9:128-49:7",4
963,202,"T","سَامَ","«سَامَ» means to cause someone pain or hardship, and ’’ «سَامَ خَسْفًا» ‘‘ is an idiom meaning to humiliate and disgrace someone (manjidd). The meaning derived from «سَامَ» is a type of hardship that also includes an element of humiliation and degradation.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَسُوۡمُوۡنَکُمۡ سُوۡٓءَ الۡعَذَابِ یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» (2/49)\nTranslation: They (used to) inflict great suffering upon you. They would kill your sons and let your daughters live.","«سَامَ» is used for such a hardship wherein the aspect of humiliation is included.","Trial","سام","2:49-7:141-14:6",3
964,203,"H","شَفٰی","«شِفَاء» means to be saved from illness; to attain safety. And «شَفٰی یَشْفِیْ» means to grant salvation from illness; to make healthy (transitive).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا مَرِضۡتُ فَہُوَ یَشۡفِیۡنِ» (26/80)\nTranslation: And when I am ill, it is You who cures me.\nAnd «شَفٰی» is used in the same way for physical ailments as it is for deliverance from spiritual ailments.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ یَشۡفِ صُدُوۡرَ قَوۡمٍ  مُّؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (9/14)\nTranslation: And He will cure the hearts of the believers.","«شَفٰی» to recover from an illness.","Healthy","شفی","9:14-10:57-16:69-17:82-26:80-41:44",6
965,203,"H","اَبْرَءَ","«بَرَءَ» means to loathe or feel disgust. And «بُرْءُ» means to be saved from an undesirable deed. And «رَجُلٌ بَزِیْءٌ» means a pure and sinless person. And «بَرَءَ مِنَ الْمَرْض» means to recover from illness, to be saved from disease. And «اَبْرَءَ الْمَرِیْض» means to heal a patient from their illness.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَاُبۡرِئُ الۡاَکۡمَہَ وَ الۡاَبۡرَصَ وَ اُحۡیِ الۡمَوۡتٰی بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (3/49)\nTranslation: And I heal the blind and the leper by Allah's command, and I give life to the dead.","«اَبْرَءَ» to deliver from a severe illness.","Healthy","ابرء","3:49-5:110",2
966,203,"S","اَفَاقَ","«اَفَاقَ» meaning the state of regaining consciousness from intoxication or unconsciousness, or returning from weakness to strength. (Mufradat) (M. Q.) According to «صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ», the word «اَفَاقَ» is used exclusively for regaining consciousness from a state of unconsciousness (F.L. 131).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا وَّ خَرَّ مُوۡسٰی صَعِقًا ۚ فَلَمَّاۤ  اَفَاقَ قَالَ سُبۡحٰنَکَ» (7/143)\nTranslation: When his Lord manifested upon the mountain (the manifestation of the lights of the Lord, Exalted and Sublime), He shattered the mountain into fragments, and Moses (peace be upon him) fell unconscious. When he regained his senses, he said, Glory be to You!","«اَفَاقَ» to regain consciousness.","Sound","افاق","7:143",1
967,204,"S","فَقْرُ","«فَقْرُ» signifies poverty, destitution, or extreme hardship. «فَقِرَ» and «فِقْرَۃٌ». The term refers to the joints of the backbone, with its plural being «فِقَار». «فِقْرَۃٌ» means backbone. Furthermore, «فَقْرٌ» is also used in the sense of backbone or breaking the waist; they say «فَقْرَتْہُ الدَّاھِیَۃُ». A calamity so severe befell him that it broke his waist bone (manjada), thus «فَقْر» denotes extreme, back-breaking poverty.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا فُقَرَآءَ یُغۡنِہِمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» (24/32). Translation: If they are poor, Allah will enrich them out of His grace.","«فَقْرُ» meaning poverty, destitution, and extreme penury.","Stinginess","فقر","2:268-2:271-2:273-9:60-24:32-35:15-47:38-59:8",8
968,204,"S","مَسْکَنَۃ","«مِسْکِیْن» refers to a person who is in a state equivalent to having none of life's basic necessities (F 65). According to some, a miskin is one who barely scrapes by yet possesses nothing—not even shelter. Lexicographers have disagreed on whether, economically, a faqir is weaker than a miskin. However, the Quran's manner of expression indicates that the faqir is indeed more needy and destitute.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا الصَّدَقٰتُ لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ» (9:60)\nTranslation: Charities (i.e., Zakat and alms) are the right of the faqir and the miskin.\nThe precedence of 'faqir' over 'miskin' in the above verse indicates that the faqir is more needy and destitute.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine decree states:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18:79)\nTranslation: And the ship belonged to poor people who worked on the sea.\nThis verse proves that a miskin can be an owner.","«مَسْکَنَت» barely make ends meet.","Stinginess","مسکنۃ","2:61-3:12",2
969,204,"S","عَیْلَۃً","«عَوْل» is everything that burdens a person and weighs them down. And «عَیَال» refers to those individuals whose living expenses become a burden upon them because they are responsible for providing for others (i.e., dependents). Thus, «عَیْلَۃ» signifies the poverty and need that arises due to having a family to support.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ عَیۡلَۃً فَسَوۡفَ یُغۡنِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖۤ» (9/28)\nTranslation: And if you fear poverty, then Allah will, if He wills, enrich you out of His bounty.","«عَیْلَۃً» meaning to be overwhelmed by the expenses of one's dependents.","Stinginess","عیلۃً","9:28",1
970,204,"P","اِمْلَاق","In actuality, the terms 'poverty' and 'destitution' are not used; rather, this term denotes the anxiety that one's existing wealth and assets might be squandered and completely depleted. It is said: 'Time has snatched away his wealth (manjad),' and «اَمْلَقَ» means the loss of existing wealth and property from one's grasp. For instance, the Noble Quran declares: «وَ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ خَشۡیَۃَ  اِمۡلَاقٍ» (17:31). Translation: 'And do not kill your children for fear of poverty.' This very meaning is also conveyed in another verse via «خَشْیْۃَ اِنْفَاق».","«اِمْلَاق» to live in constant fear of poverty.","Predestined scarcity","املاق","6:151-17:31",2
971,204,"M","قَتْر","«قَتْر» meaning need, poverty, and destitution.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ مَتِّعُوۡہُنَّ ۚ عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَعَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ» (2/236)\nTranslation: For those divorced women, there is an obligation (to give) something according to custom. That is, the wealthy should give according to their capacity and the poor according to their capability.\nBut the linguists define its meaning as to make nafaqah (maintenance) tight on one's family (m r, m q). That is, «مُقْتِر» refers to a person who is not actually poor but is stingy in spending on their family according to their status.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا لَمۡ یُسۡرِفُوۡا وَلَمۡ یَقۡتُرُوۡا وَکَانَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ قَوَامًا»\nTranslation: And those who, when they spend, are neither wasteful nor stingy, but maintain a balance, neither exceeding necessity nor falling short.","«قَتْر» Being stingy in spending on one's family.","Miserliness","قتر","2:236-25:67",2
972,204,"S","بَاْسَآء","«بَئِسَ یَبْئَسُ» means severe neediness, and «بَاسْ» means punishment, war, and hunger (scarcity), and «بَاْسَآءِ» generally refers to periods of financial difficulty and poverty. Its opposite is «سَرَّاء», meaning an era of prosperity and happiness. That is, «مُسَرَّۃٌ فِی الْیُسْر» and «بَاسَاء» denote an affliction that includes fear. (Faq l 163) For example, the Holy Quran states: « فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡبَآئِسَ الۡفَقِیۡرَ» (22:28) Translation: So you too may eat and feed the hungry poor. At another instance, the divine command is: «مَسَّتۡہُمُ الۡبَاۡسَآءُ وَ الضَّرَّآءُ وَ زُلۡزِلُوۡا» (2:214) Translation: Afflictions and calamities befell them, and they were shaken until... In this verse, «بَاْسَاء» refers to economic hardship, and «ضَرَّاء» refers to other afflictions and calamities.","«بَاْسَآءِ» the era of poverty and asceticism.","straitened circumstances","باسآء","2:177-2:214-6:42-7:94-22:28",5
973,204,"D","مَتْرَبَۃ","«تُرَاب» means dry soil, and «تَرِبَ الرَّجُل» means a person became so impoverished that he mixed with the dust.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اَوۡ اِطۡعٰمٌ فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ ذِیۡ مَسۡغَبَۃٍ یَّتِیۡمًا ذَا مَقۡرَبَۃٍ اَوۡ مِسۡکِیۡنًا ذَا مَتۡرَبَۃٍ» (90:14–16)  \nTranslation: Or to feed on a day of hunger, an orphan of near kin, or a poor person covered in dust.","«مَتْرَبَۃ» to be reduced to dust due to poverty.","Destitution","متربۃ","90:16",1
974,205,"C","عُسْر","«عُسْر» means tightness or a time of hardship—distress and trouble (for example), whether such tightness is economic or of any other kind. The use of this word is general, and its opposite is «یُسْر», meaning ease and prosperity. For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «اِنَّ مَعَ الۡعُسۡرِ  یُسۡرًا» (94:6). Translation: Indeed, with hardship comes ease.","«عُسْر» is used for times of hardship.","Constriction","عسر","2:185-2:280-9:117-18:73-54:8-65:7-92:10-94:5-94:6",9
975,205,"C","حَرَج","«حَرَج» meaning constriction of the heart. The heart feeling constrained due to illegitimate restrictions (f.l 54).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا جَعَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِی الدِّیۡنِ مِنۡ حَرَجٍ» (22/78)\nTranslation: And no constraint has been placed upon you in [any matter of] religion.","«حَرَج» is used for heart constriction and suffocation.","Constriction","حرج","4:65-5:6-6:125-7:2-9:91-22:78-24:61-33:37-33:38-33:50-48:17",11
976,205,"C","ضَنْک","«ضَنْک» meaning a constricted manner of living and narrowness in livelihood. (See 54) Restlessness and instability of the heart, remaining engrossed in thoughts. «ضَنَاکَۃ» meaning a constricted life (tightness).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ مَنۡ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِیۡ فَاِنَّ لَہٗ مَعِیۡشَۃً ضَنۡکًا» (124 / 20)  \nTranslation: And whoever turns away from My admonition, his life will become constricted.","«ضَنْک» is used for the hardships and troubles of life, or for weariness resulting from deep contemplation.","Constriction","ضنک","20:124",1
977,205,"C","ضَیْق","«ضَیْق» is used to denote the narrowness of space. (F L 54) And its opposite, «سَعَۃٌ», means spaciousness. (M L)  \nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «وَاِذَاۤ اُلۡقُوۡا مِنۡہَا مَکَانًا ضَیِّقًا» (25:13)  \nTranslation: And when they will be cast into a narrow compartment of Hell.  \n\nSometimes its opposite, «رَحُبَ», also occurs.  \nFor example, the Divine Command states: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا ضَاقَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡاَرۡضُ بِمَا رَحُبَتۡ» (9:118)  \nTranslation: Until the earth, despite its spaciousness, became constricted for them.  \n\nThen, sometimes the word «ضَیْق» is used in the sense of *harj*, meaning constriction of the heart. Thus, this is the figurative usage of «ضَیْق».  \nFor example, the Divine Command states: «وَ لَا تَکُ فِیۡ  ضَیۡقٍ مِّمَّا یَمۡکُرُوۡنَ» (16:127)  \nTranslation: And do not let your hearts be constrained by those who practice deceit.","«ضَیْق» is used due to space constraints.","Constriction","ضیق","6:125-9:25-9:118-11:77-15:97-16:127-25:13-26:13-27:70-29:33-65:6",11
978,205,"C","حَاجَۃ","«اَلْحَوْج» means need, necessity, and poverty. And «حَاجَ» means to be in need. And hājat means necessity. It is the feeling of tightness in the heart due to the non-fulfillment of some desire or need.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ حَاجَۃً  مِّمَّاۤ اُوۡتُوۡا» (59:9)\nTranslation: And whatever they are given, they do not feel any tightness in their breasts.","The lack and constraint that arise when a desire or need goes unfulfilled.","Constriction","حاجۃ","12:68-40:80-59:9",3
979,206,"C","ضَاقَ","«ضَاقَ» indicates the tightness of space.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذَاۤ اُلۡقُوۡا مِنۡہَا مَکَانًا ضَیِّقًا» (25:13)\nTranslation: And when they will be thrown into some narrow place of Hell.","«ضَاقَ» is used due to lack of space.","Constricted","ضاق","9:25-9:118-11:77-29:33",4
980,206,"C","قَدَرَ","The basic meaning of «قَدَرَ» is to assess something, to manage it, and to take care of it (manjad). However, when this word is associated with 'rizq' (sustenance), it signifies the scarcity of that sustenance, and its opposite is «بَسَطَ».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ وَیَقۡدِرُ لَہٗ» (29/62)\n\nTranslation: It is Allah who grants abundant sustenance to whichever of His servants He wills, and He makes it scarce for whichever He wills.","If «قَدَرَ» is associated with sustenance, it is used to denote a scarcity of sustenance.","Constricted","قدر","13:26-17:30-28:82-29:62-30:37-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-65:7-89:16",11
981,206,"D","قَبَضَ","«قَبَضَ» means to grasp something with the whole palm, to close it in a fist, and to contract (figurative). And «قَبْضَۃٌ» means the fist and the thing enclosed within it. Its opposite is «بَسَطَ». «قَبَضَ» is used when scarcity or reduction is made in something that was previously abundant, whether concerning sustenance or anything else. For example, the Quran states: «مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یُقۡرِضُ اللّٰہَ  قَرۡضًا حَسَنًا فَیُضٰعِفَہٗ لَہٗۤ اَضۡعَافًا کَثِیۡرَۃً ؕ وَ اللّٰہُ یَقۡبِضُ وَ یَبۡصُۜطُ» (2:245). Translation: There is someone who will give Allah a good loan, so He will multiply it for him many times, and Allah alone withholds and expands provision.","«قَبَضَ» meaning to hold something with the full palm.","Distress","قبض","2:245-9:67",2
982,206,"D","حَصِرَ","«حَصِرَ» means to feel constricted; to return home. And «حَصِرَ الرَّجُل» means to feel pressure upon one's heart, for the heart to shrink; to become constricted. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ یَصِلُوۡنَ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍۭ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ مِّیۡثَاقٌ اَوۡ جَآءُوۡکُمۡ حَصِرَتۡ صُدُوۡرُہُمۡ اَنۡ یُّقَاتِلُوۡکُمۡ اَوۡ یُقَاتِلُوۡا قَوۡمَہُمۡ» (4/90)\nTranslation: But those who make peace with people with whom you have a treaty, or those who come to you feeling their hearts constrained [by the thought] that they must fight you or fight their own people...","«حَصِرَ» (as a masdar) is used for the sinking and agitation of the heart.","Distressed","حصر","2:196-2:273-4:90-9:5",4
983,206,"T","حَفَا","The literal meaning of «حَفَا» is to exaggerate and insist in demanding something. (muf. m. q) And the meaning of «حَفِیُّ» is one who possesses complete knowledge about something, who exaggerates in showing respect, honor, and expressing joy, and who persistently inquires about someone's state and insists on asking questions. (manjad) Thus, from this exaggeration and insistence, the meaning of sometimes causing annoyance is derived.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنۡ یَّسۡئَلۡکُمُوۡہَا  فَیُحۡفِکُمۡ  تَبۡخَلُوۡا» (47:37)\nTranslation: And if he demands wealth from you and harasses you, then you become stingy.","«حَفَا» is used in the sense of harassing someone through excessive and persistent questioning.","tight, narrow, distressed","حفا","7:187-19:47-47:37",3
984,207,"T","نَکَثَ","«نَکَثَ» means to unravel or undo something that has been woven or knitted. And «نِکْث» refers to old tents or covers, etc., which are unraveled so that their threads can be respun. And «نَکَّاث» is the term for the one who unravels a woven or knitted thing. (Manj) Its usage is generally in the context of covenants, vows, and trade (commerce). That is, to break a covenant, to violate a promise (m. r).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ» (9:13)\nTranslation: Why should you not fight those who have broken their oaths?","«نَکَثَ» is used for breaking sales, oaths, and covenants, or for destroying something that has been built.","to break","نکث","7:135-9:12-9:13-16:92-43:50-48:10",6
985,207,"T","نَقَضَ","«نَقَضَ» means to scatter the threads of something, and its opposite is «اَبْرَم». That is, to make a matter firm and strong (muf), and this word is more common than «نَکَثَ». For example, «نَقَضَتُ الْبِنَاء» means to plaster a building. «اَلْعَظْمُ» means to break a bone. «اَلْعَقْدُ» means to untie a knot. Similarly, «نَقَضْتُ الْحَبْلَ» also conveys the meaning of lowering a rope. Then it is more eloquent (stronger) than «نَقَضَ ، نَکَثَ». And it is used for breaking that covenant or oath which has been firmly established.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَوۡفُوۡا بِعَہۡدِ اللّٰہِ اِذَا عٰہَدۡتُّمۡ وَ لَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡاَیۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡکِیۡدِہَا» (16/91)\nTranslation: And fulfill the covenant of Allah when you have taken a pledge, and do not break oaths after their confirmation.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَنۡقُضُوۡنَ عَہۡدَ  اللّٰہِ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مِیۡثَاقِہٖ» (2/27)\nTranslation: Those who break the covenant of Allah after its confirmation.","«نَقَضَ» is used for tearing something apart, scattering it, breaking firm pacts and oaths, or ruining things through trickery and pretexts.","to break","نقض","2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77",9
986,207,"T","اَنْقَضَ","The meaning of «اَنْقَضَ» is to break something in such a way that a cracking sound is heard (i.e., to cause something to creak). Then its application began to be used in various contexts as well. For example, «اَنْقَضَتِ الدُّجَاجَۃ» means the clucking sound a hen makes when laying an egg. «الادِیْم» means the creaking or crackling of leather. And «اَنْقَضَ اَصَابِعَہٗ» means the clicking of fingers. And «اَنْقَضَ الْحَمَلُ الظَّھْرَ» means to load so much weight on one's back that it begins to creak and becomes doubled over.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94/2,3)\nTranslation: And We have removed from you your burden which had broken your back.","«اَنْقَضَ» to break something in a manner that produces a crackling sound.","to break","انقض","94:3",1
987,207,"T","فَقَرَ","This word is more specific than «اَنْقَضَ». It comes only in the meaning of breaking the back. Whereas «اَنْقَضَ» is general. «اَلْفَقْرَۃُ» and «اَلْفِقْرَۃُ» refer to the vertebrae of the spinal cord which have a hole, and their plurals are «فِقَار» and «فِقْرَات». And «فَقَرَ الْخَرْزَ» means to pierce it for pearls. And «فَاقِرَۃٌ» refers to such a calamity that breaks the spinal cord. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍۭ بَاسِرَۃٌ تَظُنُّ  اَنۡ  یُّفۡعَلَ بِہَا فَاقِرَۃٌ» (75/24,25)\nTranslation: And how many faces will be (radiant and) sorrowful that day, thinking that a matter that will break their backs will be dealt with them. (Uthmaniؒ)","«فَقَرَ» is the specific term for breaking the spine.","to break","فقر","75:25",1
988,207,"T","جَذَّ","To shatter something hard into fragments (see detailed dissection).","«جَذَّ» to shatter something into pieces.","to break","جذ","11:108-21:58",2
989,208,"D","وَفَّقَ","«وَفْق» means compatibility and harmony between two things (noun), and «وَفَّقَ» means to make compatible. And «وَفَّقَ اللہ» means for Allah Almighty to align circumstances with a particular matter. For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنۡ یُّرِیۡدَاۤ  اِصۡلَاحًا یُّوَفِّقِ اللّٰہُ بَیۡنَہُمَا» (4/35)\nTranslation: If both of them desire reconciliation, Allah will create compatibility between them.","«وَفَّقَ اللہُ» Making Allah's circumstances suitable or favorable for some purpose.","Divine enablement","وفق","4:35",1
990,208,"D","اَوْزَعَ","«وَزَعَ» means to restrain. «وَزَعَ الْجَیْش» means to arrange troops in orderly ranks, and «وَزَّع» and «اَوْزَعَ» mean to divide. Pragandah (dispersed, scattered, or spread out) means to scatter (antonymic vocabulary). «اَوْزَعَ الشَّیْ» means to inspire, and «اِسْتَوْزَعَ اللہُ شُکْرَہ» means to seek from Allah the ability to be grateful (Manjad). «اَوْزَعَ اللہُ فُلَانًا» means Allah inspired so-and-so with gratitude (Muf).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ رَبِّ اَوۡزِعۡنِیۡۤ  اَنۡ اَشۡکُرَ نِعۡمَتَکَ الَّتِیۡۤ اَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیَّ وَ عَلٰی وَالِدَیَّ» (27:19) (46:15)\nTranslation: So he said, O my Lord, grant me the ability to be grateful for the favors You have bestowed upon me and upon my parents, and to perform righteous deeds that please You...\n\nNote: Antonymic vocabulary refers to words that have two distinct meanings that are opposite and contradictory to each other.","«اَوْزَعَ اللہُ» The divine preparation of a person's heart by Allah the Almighty, making it receptive and suitable for a particular purpose.","Divine enablement","اوزع","27:19-46:15",2
991,209,"T","طَبَقَ","«طِبَاق» To place one thing equal to another in such a way that they fit perfectly (detailed). To correspond.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ سَبۡعَ سَمٰوٰتٍ طِبَاقًا» ( 67/3 )\n\nTranslation:\n1 - He has built seven heavens, one above the other. (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - Who has built seven heavens, layer upon layer. (Osmaniؒ)","«طِبَاق» to place an equivalent item on top of another.","the lowest layer","طبق","67:3-71:15-84:19",3
992,209,"T","رَکَمَ","«رَکَمَ» means to heap (to pile up) without any order or arrangement, gathering things together by mixing them, placing them above and below or in front and behind. And «رُکَام» and «مَرْکُوْم» mean layer upon layer, for example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اَلَمۡ  تَرَ اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِیۡ سَحَابًا ثُمَّ  یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ  ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  رُکَامًا» (24/43) Translation: Do you not see that God is the One who drives the clouds? Then He gathers them together, then He layers them. At another instance, the divine command states: «لِیَمِیۡزَ اللّٰہُ الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنَ الطَّیِّبِ وَ یَجۡعَلَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ بَعۡضَہٗ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ فَیَرۡکُمَہٗ جَمِیۡعًا فَیَجۡعَلَہٗ فِیۡ جَہَنَّمَ ؕ» (8/37) Translation: That God may separate the impure (people) from the pure (people), and place one impure upon another, making a heap of them all, and throw that heap into Hell.","«رَکَمَ» To heap things up in a disorderly manner, upside down or front to back.","The lower garment (izar) / The hem or edge (in general context)","رکم","8:37-24:43-52:44",3
993,209,"L","تَرَاکِب","«رَکِبَ» meaning to ride. And «رَکِیْب» refers to the latter of two riders, or a rooted entity such as the bezel set in a ring (munj). And «تَرَاکِب» meaning to be layered in such a way that a specific order and arrangement is found among them. And «مُتَرَاکِب» meaning one mounted upon another, one riding atop the other.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَخۡرَجۡنَا مِنۡہُ خَضِرًا نُّخۡرِجُ مِنۡہُ حَبًّا مُّتَرَاکِبًا» (6/99)\nTranslation: Then We bring forth from it green sprigs, and from those sprigs We bring forth grains growing in pairs, intertwined (Jalandhari).","«تَرَاکِب» To arrange something in a systematic, orderly fashion—up and down, forward and backward—so that they are interconnected with one another.","lowest part","تراکب","6:99-84:19",2
994,209,"B","نَضِیۡدٌ","«نَضَدَ» means to select or place one thing upon another, to arrange. And «نَضَدُ» refers to selected or arranged household goods (manjad). And «تَنَضَّدَتِ الْاَسْنَان» means the orderly alignment of teeth (manjad). Thus, «نَضَدَ» is used to denote gathering something with propriety and order.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ النَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ  لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ  نَّضِیۡدٌ» (50:10)\nTranslation: And long dates whose stalks are strong. (i.e., the stalk of a date palm or similar, upon which the fruit or seed clusters are layered and tightly packed).","«نَضَدَ» To place and arrange items neatly up and down.","Bottom","نضید","50:10",1
995,209,"B","کِسَف","«کِسْفَۃٌ» means a porous piece of a body, such as a cloud or wool, etc., and its plural is «کِسْفٌ». And «کِسَفًا» refers to layering porous pieces upon one another, whether they are small or large (i.e., meaning hollow from within, empty, hollow, or spongy).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡ یُرۡسِلُ الرِّیٰحَ فَتُثِیۡرُ  سَحَابًا فَیَبۡسُطُہٗ فِی السَّمَآءِ کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ وَ یَجۡعَلُہٗ کِسَفًا» (30/48)\n\nTranslation: It is Allah who sends the winds, and they raise the clouds. Then Allah spreads them in the sky as He wills and makes them into layers.","«کِسَفَ» To place a hollow or porous object, such as cotton-like clouds, above and below.","Base","کسف","17:92-26:187-30:48-34:9-52:44",5
996,210,"T","سَئَمَ","To become weary or disgusted from remaining with something for a long time; to get fed up with something; to have one's heart turn away from something; to become satiated while performing a task. This is the initial state of fatigue.  \nFor example: In the Quran, «لَا یَسۡئَمُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِنۡ دُعَآءِ  الۡخَیۡرِ» (41/49).  \nTranslation: Man does not tire of praying for good.","to become weary of something","to become tired","سئم","2:282-41:38-41:49",3
997,210,"T","نَصِبَ","The literal meaning of «نَصِبَ» is 'to plant'. However, when it is used in the chapter (or context) of «عَلِمَ یَعْلَمُ», the meaning reverses, indicating that due to exhaustion, a person cannot keep their body straight and upright. (M. L) Therefore, «نَصِبَ» means 'to work hard', and 'fatigue resulting from labor'.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18:62)\nTranslation: When they had proceeded further, (Moses) said to his servant, Bring us our lunch. We have certainly become weary from this journey.","«نَصِبَ» extreme fatigue, leading to the body becoming emaciated.","to become tired","نصب","9:120-15:48-18:62-35:35-88:3-94:7",6
998,210,"T","لَغَبَ","«لَغَبَ» To become tired and weak due to excessive work or effort. To become incapable or helpless (for example).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ مَا بَیۡنَہُمَا فِیۡ سِتَّۃِ  اَیَّامٍ ٭ۖ وَّ مَا مَسَّنَا مِنۡ  لُّغُوۡبٍ» (50/38)\nTranslation: And We created the heavens and the earth and all that is within them in six days, and We experienced no fatigue whatsoever.","«لَغَبَ» becoming weak due to fatigue.","to become tired","لغب","35:35-50:38",2
999,210,"T","عَیَّ","«عَیَّ» means to be unable to do further work due to fatigue and to become incapacitated. «اَلْعَیُّ» and «اَلْعَیَّانُ» are called 'weary', and «دَاءٌ عَیَاءٌ» is called 'incurable disease' (Manjad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n« اَوَ لَمۡ یَرَوۡا اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَمۡ  یَعۡیَ بِخَلۡقِہِنَّ» (46/33)\nTranslation: Do they not see that Allah has created the heavens and the earth and has not become weary?","Being unable to work further due to exhaustion.","To get tired","عی","46:33-50:15",2
1000,210,"T","حَسَرَ","«حَسَر ، اَلْعَیَّ» is the next level, meaning to become utterly helpless due to exhaustion. (F L 110)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  ارۡجِعِ  الۡبَصَرَ کَرَّتَیۡنِ  یَنۡقَلِبۡ اِلَیۡکَ  الۡبَصَرُ خَاسِئًا وَّ ہُوَ حَسِیۡرٌ» (67/4)\nTranslation: Then look again and again; your sight will return to you humbled and fatigued.","«حَسَر» utterly exhausted due to fatigue.","to become tired","حسر","21:19-67:4",2
1001,210,"T","اٰدَ","The original meaning of «اٰدَ ، یَؤَدُّ» is to become crooked or bent due to heaviness and weight (morphological form), and in common usage, it means to become tired or exhausted because of heaviness.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n« وَسِعَ کُرۡسِیُّہُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ ۚ وَ لَا یَئُوۡدُہٗ حِفۡظُہُمَا ۚ وَ ہُوَ الۡعَلِیُّ الۡعَظِیۡمُ» (2/255)\n\nTranslation: His Kursi (Throne) encompasses the heavens and the earth, and their preservation does not burden Him in the least. And He is the Most High, the Most Great.","«اٰدَ» to become weary due to a heavy burden and weight.","to get tired","اد","2:255",1
1002,211,"S","سَكَنَ","«سَکَنَ» The cessation following any movement is called 'sukoon' (stillness). It is used in both literal and spiritual senses. Its opposite is movement and disturbance. (muf)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If God wills, He can calm the wind.","The term «سَکَنَ» is commonly used; we call the stillness that follows any movement 'sukun'.","Sitting (between the two prostrations in prayer)","سکن","2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-6:13-6:96-7:170-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:79-16:80-23:18-25:45-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33-",20
1003,211,"S","سَکَتَ","«سَکَتَ» meaning to become silent (lit. to be silent). To fall silent while speaking (fig.), to stop, to cease, and «سَکِیْت» and «سَاکُوْت» are terms used for a person who is habitually silent. And «سَکَتَ الْغَضَب» means the calming or subsiding of anger.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ» ( 7/154 )\nTranslation: And when the anger of Moses subsided... (Othmani)","«سَکَتَ» to stop short while speaking.","standing","سکت","7:154-17:100",2
1004,211,"T","رَھْوًا","«رَھَا ، یَرْھُوْا» meaning to proceed with gentle conduct, and «رَھَا الْبَحْرَ» meaning the sea becoming calm. (Munjad) refers to the subsiding of waves and ripples in water, and also to water gathered in a smooth, level place.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ اتۡرُکِ  الۡبَحۡرَ رَہۡوًا» (44:24)  \nTranslation: And leave the sea as a stagnant mass.","«رَھْوًا» is used to calm waves and surges on water.","to stop; to remain; (in Islamic context) to assume the standing position (in prayer)","رھوًا","44:24",1
1005,212,"A","قَلِیل","«قَلِیل» Its opposite is «کثیر». i.e., it is commonly used to denote 'less' in contrast to 'more'. It is used everywhere for quantity, weight, distance, duration, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَشۡتَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِیۡ ثَمَنًا قَلِیۡلًا» (2/41)\nTranslation: And do not sell My verses for a small price.","«قَلِیل» is used in reference to a small thing in comparison to every greater thing. Its usage is common.","A little while","قلیل","2:41-2:79-2:83-2:88-2:126-2:174-2:246-2:249-3:77-3:187-3:197-3:199-4:46-4:66-4:77-4:83-4:142-4:155-5:13-5:44-7:3-7:10-7:86-8:26-8:43-8:44-9:9-9:38-9:82-11:40-11:116-12:47-12:48-16:95-16:117-17:52-17:62-17:74-17:76-17:85-18:22-23:40-23:78-23:114-26:54-27:62-28:58-31:24-32:9-33:16-33:18-33:20-33:60-34:13-34:16-38:24-39:8-40:58-44:15-48:15-51:17-53:34-56:14-67:23-69:41-69:42-73:2-73:3-73:11-77:46",70
1006,212,"A","فَتِیل","«فَتَلَ» means to weave a rope, etc. And «فَتِیل» refers to a woven rope. Its feminine form is «فَتِیْلَۃٌ», which means that wick (fita) with which a lamp is lit. Furthermore, «فَتِیْلَۃٌ» also refers to that thin thread which is found in the fissure of a date seed (munjad), and from this word, a very small amount is also understood.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ لَا یُظۡلَمُوۡنَ فَتِیۡلًا» ( 4/49 )  \nTranslation: And no injustice will be done to them, even by a thread's breadth.","«فَتِیل» is used in small amounts.","A little","فتیل","4:49-4:77-17:71",3
1007,212,"A","نَقِیر","«نَقَرَ الطَّیْر» means the bird pecked. And «نَقَرَ الطَّیْرَ الْحَبْ» means the bird picked a seed. «مِنْقَارُ» refers to the beak, and «نَقِیْر» refers to the small, round mark found in a date seed. This is because its shape resembles a mark left by a bird's peck. Furthermore, «نَقِیْر» also denotes an extremely minuscule quantity.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اَمۡ لَہُمۡ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّنَ الۡمُلۡکِ فَاِذًا لَّا یُؤۡتُوۡنَ النَّاسَ نَقِیۡرًا» (4/53)  \nTranslation: So have they a share of the kingdom? If so, they would not give people even as much as the speck on a date seed.","It is said for a very small amount.","a little","نقیر","4:53-4:124",2
1008,212,"A","قِطْمِیْر","«قِطْمِیْر» a thin covering or membrane (qafas) over a date seed, and by this term is meant an extremely small amount, virtually nothing. It is an idiom: «مَآ اَصَبْتُ عَنْہُ قِطْمِیْرًا», meaning I gained nothing from it whatsoever.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ تَدۡعُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖ مَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ مِنۡ  قِطۡمِیۡرٍ» (35/13)\n\nTranslation: And those whom you invoke besides Him do not own even the thin covering over a date seed!","«قِطْمِیْر» so small an amount that it's virtually nonexistent.","A little","قطمیر","35:13",1
1009,212,"A","فَوَاق","«فَوَاق» The intermediate pause between two breastfeedings. It refers to the time between pressing the breasts and opening the hand (during feeding), and by it is meant a very short period or duration.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ مَا یَنۡظُرُ ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  اِلَّا صَیۡحَۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً مَّا لَہَا مِنۡ  فَوَاقٍ» (38:15)  \nTranslation: And these people are only waiting for a single mighty blast, which will not be followed by any pause.","«فَوَاق» comes for a very short period or interval.\nNote: In the same way, «خَرْدَل» (a grain of mustard seed) and «ذَرّۃ» are also used in the Quran to indicate an extremely small amount.","A little","فواق","38:15",1
1010,213,"R","ھَیَّئَ","«ھَاءَ ، یَھِیْئُ ، ھَیْئَۃً» refers to the perceptible state or condition of something (muf), and «ھَیَّاَ» means to conform, to correct, or to prepare (manjadd). That is, to prepare and correct the appropriate means for the accomplishment of a task.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَنۡشُرۡ لَکُمۡ رَبُّکُمۡ مِّنۡ رَّحۡمَتِہٖ وَیُہَیِّیٔۡ لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ  اَمۡرِکُمۡ  مِّرۡفَقًا» ( 18/16 )\nTranslation: Your Lord will expand His mercy for you and will prepare for you (the means of) ease in your affairs.","Making preparations for something by preparing its means accordingly and perfecting them.","Ready","ھیئ","18:10-18:16",2
1011,213,"R","اَعْتَدَ","«اَلْعَتَادُ» denotes that which is prepared for a specific purpose, while «عَتُدَ» means to be prepared or to be ready, and «اَعْتَدَ» means to prepare (as in the dictionary). For example, in the Quran, it is stated: «اِنَّـاۤ  اَعۡتَدۡنَا جَہَنَّمَ  لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ نُزُلًا» (18/102). Translation: We have prepared for the disbelievers a banquet of Hell.","to keep the preparatory equipment ready «عَتَدَ»","Ready","اعتد","4:18-4:37-4:151-4:161-12:31-17:10-18:29-18:102-25:11-25:37-33:31-48:13-67:5-76:4",14
1012,213,"R","اَعَدَّ","«اَعَدَّ» means to prepare. To present (manjid), i.e., to prepare each thing completely and stand it before (one). «عَدَّ» means to count and enumerate. And «اَعَدَّ» means to present each individual thing after completing its preparation. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاتَّقُوا النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ وَقُوۡدُہَا النَّاسُ وَ الۡحِجَارَۃُ  ۚ ۖ اُعِدَّتۡ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2/24)\nTranslation: Fear the Fire whose fuel will be men and stones, prepared for the disbelievers.\nMost lexicographers also include «اَعْتَدَ» under «عَدَدَ». According to Imam Raghib, «اَعْتَدْنَا» was originally «اَعْدَدْنَا». When the first (d) (t) changed, it became «اَعْتَدْنَا» (maf'ul). Thus, according to most lexicographers, the meanings of «اَعَدَّ» and «اَعْتَدَ» are the same.","«اَعَدَّ» Bring everything forward once it is fully completed.","Ready","اعد","2:24-3:131-3:133-4:93-4:102-8:60-9:46-9:89-9:100-33:8-33:29-33:35-33:44-33:57-33:64-48:6-57:21-58:15-65:10-76:31",20
1013,213,"P","جَھَزَّ","«جِھَاز» is the traveler's luggage that is prepared and kept ready. And «جَھَزَّ», meaning the loading and sending of prepared luggage (masc.), is typically used either in the context of preparing for the deceased. Tajheez wa takfeen is a well-known term. Or else for preparing a traveler's luggage.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then when Yusuf (Joseph) peace be upon him had prepared their baggage.","«جَھَّزَ» Preparing the belongings of a traveler or a deceased person.","Prepared","جھز","12:59-12:70",2
1014,214,"A","سَھْمٌ","«سَھْمٌ» is called the arrow used in divination, the arrow for casting lots, and also the common arrow. Its plurals are «سَھَام» and «سَاھَمَ», meaning to cast lots, and «تَسَاھَمَ» means to distribute something among themselves. «سَھْم» means the distributed portion, lot, or destiny (m. q.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَسَاہَمَ فَکَانَ مِنَ الۡمُدۡحَضِیۡنَ» (37/141)\nTranslation: Then they participated in the casting of lots, and they were overcome in the lots.","«سَھْمٌ» is also called the arrow for gambling, the arrow for casting lots, and the ordinary arrow.","Arrow","سھم","37:141",1
1015,214,"S","زَلَمُ","«زَلَمُ» arrows for divination, arrows for seeking omens, azlam. In pre-Islamic Arab ignorance, they used to determine their fate with arrows in this manner: they would write permission or prohibition on the arrows, throw them into a container, and then when someone sought counsel regarding themselves, they would reach in and draw an arrow. If it bore a command or permission, they would proceed with it; if it bore a prohibition, they would refrain from it and not do it. And its plural is «اَزْلَام». It is a small arrow that has neither feathers nor a head. Gambling arrows (m. q).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا الۡخَمۡرُ وَ الۡمَیۡسِرُ وَ الۡاَنۡصَابُ وَ الۡاَزۡلَامُ رِجۡسٌ مِّنۡ عَمَلِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ فَاجۡتَنِبُوۡہُ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تُفۡلِحُوۡنَ» ( 5/90 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, indeed, intoxicants, gambling, [sacrificing on] stone altars [to other than Allah], and divining arrows are but defilement from the work of Satan, so avoid them that you may be successful.","«زَلَمُ» featherless arrow, dice, gambling by means of arrows.","Sacrificial arrow","زلم","5:3-5:90",2
1016,214,"A","حَدِیْد ، حِدَاد ","Had means the ultimate boundary or limit of something that separates it from other things. And «حَدَّ السَّیْف والسِّکِین» means to sharpen a sword or knife. And «حَدِیْد» means both iron and sharp. «حَدِیْدُ الْفَھَم» means sharp in understanding (intelligent), and «حَدِیْدُ النَّظَر» means sharp-sighted.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«لَقَدۡ کُنۡتَ فِیۡ غَفۡلَۃٍ  مِّنۡ ہٰذَا فَکَشَفۡنَا عَنۡکَ غِطَآءَکَ فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22)\nTranslation: Indeed, you were heedless of this, but We have removed from you your veil, so your sight today is sharp.\n\nAnd «حَدِیْدُ الْلِسَان» means sharp-tongued, and the plural of «حَدِیْد» is «حَدَّاد».","«حَدِیْد» iron, steel, or similar metals, and an iron scabbard, and «حِدَاد » is used metaphorically to mean the sharpening of a sword or a knife.","Arrow","حدید ، حداد","17:50-18:96-22:21-33:19-34:10-50:22-57:25",7
1017,214,"A","سَلَقَ","«سَلَقَ» means to speak with the connotation of coercion and dominance (power). And «سَلَقَ الْلِسَان» means to run the tongue swiftly. (Minaj)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33:19)\nTranslation: Then when the (fear of) war is removed, they speak ill of you with tongues sharp and swift. And they are extremely greedy for wealth.","«سَلَقَ» is to overstep bounds with wrath (anger) and dominance (power).","Arrow","سلق","33:19",1
1018,215,"O","زَیْت","«زَیْت» is the term for the oil from the olive tree, and the fruit is called «زَیْتُونَۃٌ» (common saying). And «زَاتَ الطَّعَام» means adding olive oil to food or seasoning it with olive oil.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«یَّکَادُ زَیۡتُہَا یُضِیۡٓءُ وَ لَوۡ لَمۡ تَمۡسَسۡہُ نَارٌ» (24/35)\nTranslation: Its oil, even if fire does not touch it, is ready to burn.","«زَیْت» refers only to olive oil.\nAnd «دُھْن» refers to every type of oil, including olive oil.\nAnd «دِھَان» refers to the sediment or residue of any type of oil.","Oil","زیت","6:99-6:141-16:11-24:35-80:29-95:1",6
1019,215,"O","دُھْن","«دُھْن» denotes oil, grease, or fat. This term is general, applicable to any kind—whether plant-based or animal-based. And «دَھَنَ» and «اَدْھَنَ» mean deception and hypocrisy. Meanwhile, «تَدَھَّنَ» means to anoint with oil (from the root 'manjad'). For example, the Quran states: «وَ شَجَرَۃً  تَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ طُوۡرِ سَیۡنَآءَ تَنۡۢبُتُ بِالدُّہۡنِ» (23/20). Translation: And [it is] the tree that We have also created, which grows in the Sinai and yields oil.","«دُھْن» This word is used for oil and fat.","Oil","دھن","23:20",1
1020,215,"O","دِھَان","«دِھَان» meaning the dregs or sediment at the bottom of oil (i.e., the grime or any other substance settled beneath the oil). A slippery place. Varnish. Paint (mangeed).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا انۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ  فَکَانَتۡ وَرۡدَۃً کَالدِّہَانِ» (55/37)\nTranslation: Then when the sky splits open, it will become rose-colored like the dregs of oil.","«دِھَان» the gunk or residue (i.e., dirt, grime, or any other substance settled at the bottom of the oil)","oil","دھان","55:37",1
1021,216,"T","عَبَسَ","«عَبَسَ» means to frown or scowl. It refers to a furrow or line appearing between the two eyebrows on the forehead. It is used in all these meanings: roughness, cruelty, perversity, obstinacy, and harshness. This is the first degree (f l 139).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«عَبَسَ وَ تَوَلّٰۤی اَنۡ  جَآءَہُ  الۡاَعۡمٰی» (80/1)\nTranslation: (Muhammad Mustafa) He frowned and turned away when the blind man came to him.","the mark of «عَبَسَ» appearing on the forehead between the eyes.","Theory","عبس","74:22-80:1",2
1022,216,"T","کَلَحَ","«کَلَحَ» This is the next level of «عَبَسَ». It means that wrinkles appear on the face so that the features become distorted (F. 139). And according to some, it means moving the lips up and down in such a way that the teeth become visible and the face appears hideous. (M. Q)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تَلۡفَحُ وُجُوۡہَہُمُ النَّارُ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہَا کٰلِحُوۡنَ» (23/104)\nTranslation: Their faces will be scorched by the Fire, and they will be disfigured therein.","«کَلَحَ» wrinkles forming on the face to the point of distorting one's features.","Tawhid","کلح","23:104",1
1023,216,"R","بَسَرَ","«بَسَرَ» is the final degree of «عَبَسَ». When the act of raising the nose (i.e., the nose/mouth) reaches its extreme, it will be called «بَسَرَ». Sour-facedness (f. l 139). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «ثُمَّ  نَظَرَ ثُمَّ  عَبَسَ  وَ  بَسَرَ» (74:21-22). Translation: Then he looked again, then he raised his nose and made a face.","When the action of raising the nose and mouth reaches its extreme, it is termed «بَسَرَ».","ritual purity","بسر","74:22",1
1024,217,"S","جُزء","«جُزء» means a piece or a separated part of something. Its opposite is «کُلّ» and its plural is «اَجْزَاء». That is, the parts of something which, when combined, make that thing complete. And «جَزَءَ الشَّیْء» means dividing something into different parts. Taking one part (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260)\nTranslation: Then place each of their pieces on every mountain.","The parts of something from which it is completed.","Segment","جزء","2:260-15:44-43:15",3
1025,217,"P","قِطَعٌ","«قِطْعٌ» is a collective, meaning a separated part or piece of something. The term «قِطْعَہ» is also used for a collection of verses containing more than 4 but fewer than 10 lines, and it also applies to separate pieces of land, etc. (Munjid). For example, in the Quran:\n«وَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ قِطَعٌ مُّتَجٰوِرٰتٌ» (13/4)\nTranslation: And in the earth, there are various tracts that lie adjacent to one another.\nAnd if the word «قِطْعٌ» is attributed to the night, it refers to any one part of the night (Munjid), though some translators understand it to mean the last part of the night. The Divine command states:\n«فَاَسۡرِ بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/81)\nTranslation: So travel with your family in the latter part of the night.","«قِطْعَۃٌ» is used for parts or portions of land, verses, and the night.","Piece","قطع","10:27-11:81-13:4-15:65",4
1026,217,"P","بُقْعَۃ","«بُقْعَۃ» According to the author of Mizan al-Lughah, it is that part of the earth which is distinct from the surrounding parts (m. l).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ فِی الۡبُقۡعَۃِ  الۡمُبٰرَکَۃِ مِنَ الشَّجَرَۃِ» (28/30)\nTranslation: When he reached it, a voice came from a tree in a blessed spot on the right side of the field.","«بُقْعَۃ» that distinct portion of land.","piece","بقعۃ","28:30",1
1027,217,"E","کِسَف","«کِسَف» is the plural of «کِسْفَۃ». It means porous bodies, such as clouds or pieces of cotton (singular: «کِسْفَۃ»), which can easily separate and rejoin.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاَسۡقِطۡ عَلَیۡنَا کِسَفًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اِنۡ  کُنۡتَ مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (26:187)\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then bring down a piece from the sky.","«کِسَف» rarefied bodies, such as clouds, wool, or a piece of sky.","Excerpt","کسف","17:92-26:187-30:48-34:9-52:44",5
1028,217,"P","زُبُر","«زُبُر» is the plural form of «زُبْرَةُ». It means a large piece of iron, iron sheets, planks (minjadd). Then it applies to every thing that is spread out, whose thickness is less but width is greater. For example, paper sheets, book pages, scrolls, etc.\n\nFor example, in the Quran:  \n«اٰتُوۡنِیۡ زُبَرَ الۡحَدِیۡدِ» (18/96)  \nTranslation: Then bring to me large iron planks.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah is:  \n«وَ  اِنَّہٗ  لَفِیۡ  زُبُرِ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (26/196)  \nTranslation: And its account is written in the books of the earlier prophets.\n\n«زُبُر» has also been used metaphorically.  \nFor example, the command of Allah is:  \n«فَتَقَطَّعُوۡۤا  اَمۡرَہُمۡ بَیۡنَہُمۡ زُبُرًا» (23/53)  \n\nTranslations:  \n1. Then they separated their work among themselves, dividing it into distinct parts. (Jalandhari)  \n2. Then they broke their work into pieces. (Osmani)","«زُبُر» boards or sheets of iron, paper, etc.","piece","زبر","3:184-16:44-18:96-23:53-26:196-35:25-54:43-54:52",8
1029,217,"P","اِنْکَاث","«اِنْکَاث» refers to a folded blanket or tent, meaning something that is folded or wrapped up for the purpose of unravelling or unwinding it again. And «نَکَّاث» refers to the person who unravels or unwinds something that has been wound or wrapped. (The root implies 'to scatter' or 'to disperse'). Then, since in the act of unraveling, such things become damaged and torn into pieces, therefore «اِنْکَاث» also comes to mean those very pieces or fragments.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا  کَالَّتِیۡ نَقَضَتۡ غَزۡلَہَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ قُوَّۃٍ  اَنۡکَاثًا» (16/92)\nTranslation: And do not be like the woman who unravels the thread she has spun, after it has become strong.","processed cotton or wool pieces","Passage","انکاث","7:135-9:12-9:13-16:92-43:50-48:10",6
1030,217,"F","عَضِیْن","«اَلْعُضْو» and «اَلْعِضْو» mean a part of the body, and their plural is «اَعْضاء». And «عَضَا یَعْضُوا» means to cut into pieces. And «اَلْعِضَۃُ» means a piece, a faction. And its plurals are «عِضِیِن» and «عَضُوْن» (in Majid). And according to the author of *Muqayyas al-Lughah*, «عَضَنَ» means to cut something into pieces. And from it are derived «عُضْو» and «عِضْو». (M. L.) Pieces of meat. Booties.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ  جَعَلُوا  الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  عِضِیۡنَ» (15/91)\n\nTranslation:\n1 - That is, they cut the Quran into pieces (by accepting some parts and rejecting others) (Jalandhariؒ)\n2 - Those who have made the Quran into booties (Osmaniؒ)","«عَضِیْن» pieces of meat, boots.","Fragment","عضین","3:119-15:91",2
1031,217,"P","جُذَاذُ","«جَذَّ» means to cut, to break. And «جِذَّ» refers to small pieces of something that has been cut. Its plurals are «جُذَاذُ» and «جُذَّاذَات», meaning small pieces or fragments of a cut object. «جُذَاذَةُ مِنَ الْفِضَّۃ» means pieces of silver, and «جُذَاذ» also refers to gold droplets. (Manjada) apparently «جُذَاذ» is used for small pieces or fragments of precious metals.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «فَجَعَلَہُمۡ جُذٰذًا  اِلَّا کَبِیۡرًا  لَّہُمۡ  لَعَلَّہُمۡ اِلَیۡہِ  یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» (21/58). Translation: Then he shattered them (the idols) into fragments, except for the largest one, so that they might return to it.","«جُذَاذُ» fragments and pieces of precious metals.","piece","جذاذ","21:58",1
1032,217,"P","فِرْق","«فِرْق» means a broken or cut piece (cleft). It generally involves two parts: one that is cut and separated, and the other that remains after the cut. Also, «فَرْق» refers to the gap between the hair on the head (cleft), and «فَرَق» refers to the space between the two front teeth (cleft).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«فَانۡفَلَقَ فَکَانَ کُلُّ فِرۡقٍ  کَالطَّوۡدِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (26/63)\nTranslation: Then the sea parted, and each part became like a huge mountain.\n\n(For the difference between «فِرق» and «فِلق», see to split).","Generally, any one of the two parts of something.","piece","فرق","2:50-2:53-2:102-2:136-2:185-2:285-3:4-3:84-3:103-3:105-4:130-4:150-4:152-5:25-6:153-6:159-8:29-8:41-9:122-12:39-12:67-17:106-20:94-21:48-25:1-26:63-30:14-30:32-42:13-42:14-77:4-98:4",32
1033,217,"P","بَعْض","The usage of «بَعْض» is common. It is also used for a 'part' of a 'whole'.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا» (2:73)\nTranslation: Then We said, Strike the (slain cow's) piece with another.\n\nAnd if there is a collection of several things, it can also refer to an individual. Such as «بَعْضُ الْلَیَالِی», meaning 'one night among nights', or «بَعْضُ النَّاس», meaning 'a man'.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» (68:30)\nTranslation: Then they began to blame one another.\n\nMoreover, some usages are also spiritual in nature.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (43:63)\nTranslation: And I will explain to you some matters in which you differ.","«بَعْض» applies to the part in contrast to the whole, and to the individual or some individuals in contrast to the collective.","Piece","بعض","2:36-2:73-2:76-2:85-2:145-2:251-2:253-2:259-2:283-3:34-3:50-3:64-3:155-3:195-4:19-4:21-4:25-4:32-4:34-4:150-5:49-5:51-6:53-6:65-6:112-6:128-6:129-6:158-6:165-7:24-8:37-8:72-8:73-8:75-9:67-9:71-9:127-10:46-11:12-11:54-12:10-13:4-13:36-13:40-16:71-17:21-17:55-17:88-18:19-18:99-20:123-22:40-23:44-23:91-23:113-24:40-24:58-24:62-24:63-25:20-26:198-27:72-29:25-30:41-33:6-34:31-34:42-35:40-37:27-37:50-38:22-38:24-40:28-40:77-43:32-43:63-43:67-45:19-47:4-47:26-49:2-49:12-52:25-66:3-68:30-69:44",86
1034,218,"T","تَبَّ","The lexical meaning of «تَبّ» is to perish due to continuous loss and damage (intransitive), and in the Quran, the word «تَبَاب» is used in this sense. And «تَبَّ» is also a curse word. They say «تَبًّا لَکَ» means may God destroy you or may God ruin you. Similarly, «تَبَّتْ یَدَاہُ» means may both his hands be broken (from the root *najada*). For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «تَبَّتۡ یَدَاۤ  اَبِیۡ  لَہَبٍ وَّ  تَبَّ» (111/1). Translation: May Abu Lahab's hands be broken, and may he be ruined.","«تَبّ» is a supplicatory phrase with a negative connotation, meaning to curse someone for their ruin and destruction.","to break","تب","7:139-11:101-17:7-18:35-25:39-35:29-40:37-111:1",8
1035,218,"T","اِنْفَصَمَ","The breaking of something in such a way that its parts do not separate but remain connected. A line appearing. Hair coming. (Munjid)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «فَمَنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِالطَّاغُوۡتِ وَ یُؤۡمِنۡۢ بِاللّٰہِ فَقَدِ اسۡتَمۡسَکَ بِالۡعُرۡوَۃِ الۡوُثۡقٰی ٭ لَا انۡفِصَامَ  لَہَا» (2/256)\nTranslation: Guidance has become completely distinct from misguidance. So whoever rejects taghut and believes in Allah has grasped the firmest rope, which will never break.","«اِنْفِصَام» to break in such a manner that the two parts remain undivided.","to break","انفصم","2:256",1
1036,218,"T","اِنْقَضَّ","«نَقَضَ» meaning to break or collapse, and «اِنْقَضَّ» meaning the collapse of a building or wall, etc., to chip or to develop a crack. And «اَلنَّقْض» meaning a broken part of a building, etc. (a fissure) — for a wall, etc., to chip and develop a crack in it, and to break and lean to one side.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» ( 18/77 )\nTranslation: Then they saw a wall which was about to collapse (or lean). So he (Khizar) straighten it.","«اِنْقَضَّ» A crack or fissure appearing in a structure such as a building or wall.","to break","انقض","2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77-94:3",10
1037,218,"T","تَقَطَّعَ","«تَقَطَّعَ» To break or cut apart from something. It is used in both literal and spiritual senses.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ رَاَوُا  الۡعَذَابَ وَ تَقَطَّعَتۡ بِہِمُ الۡاَسۡبَابُ» (2/166)\nTranslation: They will see the (Divine) punishment and their mutual relations will be severed.","to break in such a way that its parts become separate","to break","تقطع","2:166-5:33-6:94-9:110-21:93-23:53-29:29-47:22",8
1038,219,"C","بَرَدَ","«بَرَدَ» means to become cold. And «بَرْد ۔ بُرُوْدَت» means coolness or coldness. And «بَرَد» means frost. «بُرِدَتِ الْاَرَض» means frost falling on the ground (manjad). And «بَارِدْ» means any cold thing.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اُرۡکُضۡ بِرِجۡلِکَ ۚ ہٰذَا مُغۡتَسَلٌۢ  بَارِدٌ وَّ  شَرَابٌ» (38/42)\nTranslation: (We said to Job, Strike the ground with your foot.) A spring gushed forth, cool for bathing and sweet for drinking.","«بَرَدَ» is generally said for coolness.","Cold","برد","21:69-24:43-38:42-56:44-78:24",5
1039,219,"C","قَرَّ","«قَرَّ الْیَوْم» meaning the cooling of the day. «یَوْمٌ قَرٌّ» meaning a cool day. «لَیْلَۃٌ قَرَّۃٌ» meaning a cool night. Then it is also used metaphorically. Such as «قَرَّتْ ( قُرَۃٌ وقُرَّۃٌ ) عَیْنُہٗ» meaning for someone's eyes to be cooled. The attainment of the heart's happiness and desire (see Majid) — as it were, that kind of coolness which is also pleasant — for this, the word «قَرَّ» is used.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَکُلِیۡ وَ اشۡرَبِیۡ وَ قَرِّیۡ عَیۡنًا» (19/26)\nTranslation: So (O Maryam) eat and drink, and cool your eyes.","«قَرَّ» denotes a coolness that is pleasant and a source of comfort and peace.","cold","قر","19:26-20:40-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:51",7
1040,220,"T","سَكَنَ","«سَکَنَ» comes after movement for pausing.","«سَکَنَ» the cessation of something after its movement.","to remain steadfast","سکن","2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-6:13-6:96-7:170-7:189-9:103-10:67-16:79-16:80-23:18-25:45-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:21-40:61-42:33-",20
1041,220,"T","رَکَدَ","«رَکَدَ» The state of a moving thing coming to a standstill by establishing its own support. (M. R)  \n«رَکَدَ الْمِیْزَان» Meaning: to become stationary by balancing evenly, like the scales of a balance.  \nAnd «رَکَدَ الَشَّمْس» Meaning: to appear stationary when the sun reaches its zenith.  \n\nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ فَیَظۡلَلۡنَ رَوَاکِدَ عَلٰی ظَہۡرِہٖ» (42/33)  \nTranslation: If Allah wills, He can still the wind, and the ships remain motionless upon its surface.","«رَکَدَ» The act of a moving thing establishing and stabilizing itself on its own support, thereby coming to a standstill.","to stop","رکد","42:33-53:34",2
1042,220,"T","جَمَدَ","«جَمَدَ» The complete lack of sensation and movement in inanimate objects. «جَمَدَ الْمَاء» Stagnant water becoming still and motionless. And «جَمَدَ الدَّمْ» meaning the drying up of blood. And «جَمْد» refers to water that has become still and stagnant.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡجِبَالَ تَحۡسَبُہَا جَامِدَۃً  وَّ  ہِیَ تَمُرُّ مَرَّ السَّحَابِ» ( 27:88 )\nTranslation: And you will see the mountains, thinking them solid, but they will pass away like the passing away of the clouds. [Sahih International]","«جَمَدَ» Jam Jana. The permanent steadfastness of inanimate objects.","to abide","جمد","27:88",1
1043,220,"T","رَھْوًا","«رَھْوًا» The calming or cessation of waves and turbulence on the surface of the sea (stilled). Another meaning is: an open space or passage between two elevations (m. r. maf).\n\nThis word appears in the Quran only once, and it conveys both meanings.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اتۡرُکِ  الۡبَحۡرَ رَہۡوًا» (44/24)\nTranslation: And leave the sea, stilled.","«رَھْوًا» The calmness of the water's surface, or an open space between two stable things.","to stop","رھوًا","44:24",1
1044,220,"T","قَرَّ","«قَرَّ» to settle firmly in a place (munjad) to remain steadfast.  \nFor example, the Holy Quran states: «وَ نُقِرُّ  فِی الۡاَرۡحَامِ مَا نَشَآءُ  اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی» (22:5)  \nTranslation: And those whom We will, We cause to remain in the womb for a predetermined term.","«قَرَّ» To place something in a specific location. To remain settled for a certain period of time.","to remain steadfast","قر","22:5",1
1045,220,"T","وَقَفَ","«وَقَفَ» To stand motionless and senseless (i.e., to pause briefly in the course of an action (as at a bus stand), or to be made to stand in such a way that the initial movement or action is expected thereafter). This word is used both transitively and intransitively.\n\nIntransitive example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذۡ  وُقِفُوۡا عَلٰی رَبِّہِمۡ» (6/30)\nTranslation: And if you could but see when they will be made to stand before their Lord.\n\nTransitive (meaning: to make stand):\nFor instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ قِفُوۡہُمۡ   اِنَّہُمۡ  مَّسۡئُوۡلُوۡنَ» (37/24)\nTranslation: And detain them, for they must be questioned.","«وَقَفَ» to take a short break while doing something.","to abide","وقف","2:87-5:46-6:27-6:30-34:31-37:24-57:27",7
1046,220,"T","لَبِثَ","«لَبِثَ» meaning to settle firmly in a place and establish permanently (intransitive). For example: In the Holy Quran: «وَ لَبِثُوۡا فِیۡ  کَہۡفِہِمۡ ثَلٰثَ مِائَۃٍ سِنِیۡنَ وَ ازۡدَادُوۡا  تِسۡعًا» (18/25) Translation: And they (the People of the Cave) remained in their cave for three hundred years and nine more (sleeping).","«لَبِثَ» is used to stay for a very long period.","to abide","لبث","2:259-10:16-10:45-11:69-12:42-17:52-17:76-18:12-18:19-18:25-18:26-20:40-20:103-20:104-23:112-23:113-23:114-26:18-29:14-30:55-30:56-33:14-34:14-37:144-46:35-79:46",26
1047,220,"T","مَکَثَ","to remain in anticipation of something (figurative, metaphorical).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَقَالَ  لِاَہۡلِہِ  امۡکُثُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا» (20/10)\nTranslation: Moses said to his family, Wait here, indeed I have seen a fire.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command of Allah states:\n«فَمَکَثَ غَیۡرَ بَعِیۡدٍ» (27/22)\nTranslation: Only a little while had passed.\n\nAt a third instance, the divine command of Allah states:\n«وَ قُرۡاٰنًا فَرَقۡنٰہُ لِتَقۡرَاَہٗ  عَلَی النَّاسِ عَلٰی  مُکۡثٍ» (17/106)\nTranslation: And We have sent down the Quran in portions so that you may recite it to people with gradual intervals.\n\nHowever, later this word departed from its original meaning and became synonymous with «لَبِثَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مَّاکِثِیۡنَ فِیۡہِ اَبَدًا» (18/3)\nTranslation: They will abide therein forever.","«مَکَثَ» is used to wait for something.","to settle","مکث","13:17-17:106-18:3-20:10-27:22-28:29-43:77",7
1048,220,"T","عَکَفَ","«عَکَفَ» means to turn toward something with reverence and remain attached to it (intransitive), and also means to seclude oneself, to reform oneself, and to keep oneself (away from sins) (transitive). That is, to stay and remain at a blessed place for worship.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ لَا تُبَاشِرُوۡہُنَّ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ عٰکِفُوۡنَ  ۙ فِی الۡمَسٰجِدِ» (2/187)\nTranslation: And when you are in i'tikaf in the mosques, do not approach women.","To reside at a blessed place for worship.\nNote: See «سَکَنَ ، خَلَدَ» etc. for 'to be inhabited.'","to stay","عکف","2:125-2:187-7:138-20:91-20:97-21:52-22:25-26:71",8
1049,221,"H","رَبْوَۃ","«رَبْوَۃ» means a high and elevated place with undulations (i.e., high and low terrain). «رَبَا ، یَرْبُوا» means to grow and flourish. And «رَبْوَۃً» refers to sandy, elevated ground that is typically lush and fertile.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n« کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265)  \nTranslation: *[It is] like a garden on a height; when rain falls upon it, it yields double the produce.*","«رَبْوَۃ» elevated and soft sandy terrain.","Hillock","ربوۃ","2:265-23:50",2
1050,221,"M","اَمْتًا","«اَمَتَ» Elevation (m. q.), small hill, small mound, lofty place (manjad).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«لَّا  تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا  وَّ  لَاۤ   اَمۡتًا» (20/107)\nTranslation: in which you will see no slopes or depressions, nor any hills or elevations.","«اَمَتَ» a small, irregular mound.","Mound","امتًا","20:107",1
1051,221,"H","حَدَبَ","The literal meaning of «حَدَبَ» is protrusion and bulging. Metaphorically, it also refers to elevated and hard terrain of that shape (i.e.), such as a hill that is wide in expanse but low in height. «مُحَدَّب» is the opposite of «مُجَوَّف», which are lenses used to correct near- and farsightedness. Moreover, «مُحَدَّب» (the lens) is also called «عَدْسَہ» because it bulges out on both sides, resembling the shape of millet grains.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21:96)\nTranslation: Until when Gog and Magog are let loose, and they swoop down from every elevated place.","«حَدَبَ» a mound that is broad and low.","Hillock","حدب","21:96",1
1052,221,"M","رِیَع","«رِیَعَ» refers to «رِیْعَۃ», meaning a high valley—habitable valleys situated between mountains (م ۔ ر). And «رِیْعَۃ» also signifies a high hill, the place from which water flows down from the valley's elevation, or a broad mountainous path (منجد). For example, the Quran states: «اَتَبۡنُوۡنَ بِکُلِّ رِیۡعٍ  اٰیَۃً  تَعۡبَثُوۡنَ» (26/128). Translation: Do you erect a memorial on every high place only to engage in futile acts?","«رِیَعَ» habitable valleys among the mountains.","mound","ریع","26:128",1
1053,221,"M","اَحْقَاف","«اَحْقَاف» refers to a sandhill. «حَقَفَ» means an irregular (uneven) sandhill (mound of sand). A long and winding sandhill, i.e., a sand ridge (manjad), and «اَحْقَاف» means sandhills. Sandy desert. The name of a sandy desert.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ  اَخَا عَادٍ ؕ اِذۡ  اَنۡذَرَ قَوۡمَہٗ بِالۡاَحۡقَافِ» (46/21)\nTranslation: And remember the brother of 'Ad, Hud, when he warned his people in the land of Al-Ahqaf.","«اَحْقَاف» a desert, i.e., long and winding sand dunes.","Mound","احقاف","46:21",1
1054,221,"T","نَجَد","«نَجَدَ» means high and hard land. It is also called a hill or a mound (manjad), and its meaning is a small mountain (manjad).  \nFor example, in the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» (90/10,11)  \nTranslation: And man was shown both paths (good and evil), but he did not traverse the steep path.","«نَجَدَ» the valley and the path of ascending and descending on it.","Tilah (طيلة)","نجد","90:10",1
1055,222,"C","عِوَجَ","«عِوَجَ» refers to the slant or incline of a vertical object, such as a wall or tree. And «اَعْوَج» means a person who walks with a limp. While «اَلْعَرْج» is the type of crookedness perceptible to the physical eye, and «اَلْعِوَج» is the crookedness discernible through intellect and insight (detailed). However, according to the following verse, this understanding does not seem correct. And Allah knows best!\n\nThe divine command states:\n«لَّا  تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا  وَّ  لَاۤ   اَمۡتًا» (20/107)\nTranslation: Wherein you will see no depression or elevation.\n\n«عِوَجَ» and «أَمْتُ» are contradictory terms, meaning high and low. These two words are synonymous or have the same meaning, often used interchangeably. (M. L.) In any case, «عِوَجَ» has a broad meaning. In physical objects, it denotes height, depth, and bends; in spiritual matters, it signifies complexity, entanglement, or ambiguity.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَلۡحَمۡدُ لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡزَلَ عَلٰی عَبۡدِہِ الۡکِتٰبَ  وَ لَمۡ  یَجۡعَلۡ  لَّہٗ عِوَجًا» (18/1)\nTranslation: All praise is due to Allah, who has sent down upon His Servant the Book and has not made therein any crookedness.","«عِوَجَ» refers to the slant or tilt of an upright object, such as the upper part of a wall or a tree. If used figuratively, it means complexity, entanglement, and ambiguity.","Crooked","عوج","3:99-7:45-7:86-11:19-14:3-18:1-20:107-20:108-39:28",9
1056,222,"D","زَیْغ","«زَاغَ» meaning to deviate from the path of truth. «زَاغَ الْبَصَر» meaning the fatigue of sight (in the context of looking intently) and, according to Imam Raghīb, the sight has erred and turned aside (in the sense of misjudgment). This word is generally used in a spiritual sense, and its meaning is a change in angle of vision or point of view, crookedness, and deviation.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ زَیۡغٌ فَیَتَّبِعُوۡنَ مَا تَشَابَہَ مِنۡہُ» ( 3/7 )\nTranslation: So those in whose hearts is deviation [i.e., inclination toward deviation] will pursue that which is unspecific.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«فَلَمَّا  زَاغُوۡۤا اَزَاغَ  اللّٰہُ قُلُوۡبَہُمۡ» ( 61/5 )\nTranslation: So when they deviated [from the right path], Allah caused their hearts to deviate [i.e., twisted them].","«زَیْغ» is used to introduce a slant in perspectives and viewpoints.","Deviant","زیغ","3:7-9:117-33:10-38:63-53:17-61:5",6
1057,222,"C","اَلْحَد","«لَحْد» meaning a grave and its side chamber. And «اَلْحَدَ» meaning to turn away to one side from the straight path. And «اَلْحَدَ السَّھْمُ الْھَدَفَ» meaning for an arrow's target to land on one side. And «اَلْحَدَ عَنِ الدِّیْن» meaning to cavil and raise objections in religious rulings and beliefs (i.e., to engage in theological dissent), and this heresy (ilhad) pertains to beliefs (Faq. p. 189). For example, doubting the essence and attributes of God or denying miracles.\n\nFor instance: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّرِدۡ  فِیۡہِ  بِاِلۡحَادٍۭ بِظُلۡمٍ  نُّذِقۡہُ  مِنۡ  عَذَابٍ  اَلِیۡمٍ» (22/25)\nTranslation: And whoever intends therein [the Sacred Mosque] to deviate in malice and disbelief, We shall make him taste a painful punishment.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ لِلّٰہِ الۡاَسۡمَآءُ الۡحُسۡنٰی فَادۡعُوۡہُ بِہَا ۪ وَ ذَرُوا الَّذِیۡنَ یُلۡحِدُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اَسۡمَآئِہٖ» (7/180)\nTranslation: And all the names of Allah are the most excellent, so invoke Him by them. And leave those who deviate [from the correct usage] in His names.","«اِلْحَاد» is used to denote crookedness in matters of God's essence, attributes, and beliefs.","Crooked","الحد","7:180-16:103-22:25-41:40",4
1058,222,"C","جَوْر","«جَارَ» means «مَیْل عَنِ الطَّرِیْق ( م ۔ ل )», i.e., to incline away from the path, and it also means to desist from the commands of the Shariah (manjada). And this crookedness (twistedness) is related to turning away from the commands of the Shariah and committing disobedience (fiqh 199). And «جَائِر» means inclined to one side, leaning towards excess.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ  قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ» (16/9)\n\nTranslation: And the straight path leads to Allah. And some paths are crooked (they do not lead to Him). (Jalandhari)","«جَوْر» is used for straying from the implementation of Shariah commands.","Crooked / Twisted / Deviant","جور","16:9",1
1059,222,"C","نَکَبَ","«نَکَبَ اْلاِنَاءَ»: meaning to tilt and spill whatever is in a vessel. And «نَکَبَتِ اَلرِّیْح» meaning the wind blowing sideways (manjadd). And «اَلْاَنْکَبْ»: (1) meaning having uneven shoulders, and (2) the camel that walks while bent (muf). And «اَلْاَنْکَب» meaning one who holds one shoulder higher than the other. Oppressive. Tyrannical (one who acts unjustly, merciless). And «نَکُب» its plural is «نُکُوْب» and «نَکَبَات». Meaning calamities (manjadd). So to speak, «نَکَبَ» such a slant and deviation is called, the result of which is a defect, injustice, or sin.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ عَنِ الصِّرَاطِ لَنٰکِبُوۡنَ» (23/74)\nTranslation: And those who do not believe in the Hereafter have deviated from the path (of truth). (Usmani)","«نَکْب» such deviation and inclination that leads to fault, injustice, and sin.","crooked","نکب","23:74",1
1060,223,"S","اِتَّکَاَ","«اَتْکَاَ» means to lean or rely on something for support. And «اَتْکَاَ عَلَی الشَّیْ» means to take support, to lean on. «تَوَکَّاَ عَلَی الْعَصَا» means he leaned on his staff, and «تَکَاَۃٌ» means that upon which one leans, e.g., a staff, sword, bow, etc. And «اِتَّکَاَ» means to sit while leaning (as in the context of a throne or seat).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مُّتَّکِئِیۡنَ  فِیۡہَا عَلَی الۡاَرَآئِکِ» (76/13)\nTranslation: They will be reclining on thrones in that Paradise.","«اِتَّکَاَ» comes to rely on anything.","Support","اتکا","18:31-36:56-38:51-43:34-52:20-55:54-55:76-56:16-76:13",9
1061,223,"M","اِرْتَفَقَ","«مِرْفَق» means to lean and any object upon which one leans for support. And «مِرْفَقَۃ» means a small pillow or cushion. And «اِرْتَفَقَ» means to lean on or rest upon. And «مُرْتَفَق» refers to a place where cushions are placed and all forms of comfort are available (as in the exegesis 'Manhad').\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«نِعۡمَ الثَّوَابُ ؕ وَ حَسُنَتۡ  مُرۡتَفَقًا» (18/31)\nTranslation: What an excellent reward and what a wonderful place of rest!","«اِرْتَفَقَ» comes only to lean on comfortable things.","Mindfulness of Allah","ارتفق","18:16-18:29-18:31",3
1062,224,"S","حَقَّ","«حَقَّ» means 'to be established' or 'to be obligatory' (as in Manjad), and its opposite is «بَطَلَ». «حَقٌّ» means 'an established statement,' 'truth,' or 'faithfulness,' and its opposite is «بَاطِل».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَفَسَقُوۡا فِیۡہَا فَحَقَّ عَلَیۡہَا الۡقَوۡلُ  فَدَمَّرۡنٰہَا  تَدۡمِیۡرًا» (17:16)\nTranslation: So they persisted in disobedience. Then the decree was established against that town, and We utterly destroyed it.","«حَقَّ» is used for truth and honesty.","Steadfast","حق","2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3",252
1063,224,"C","حَصْحَص","«حَصْحَص» A true matter that remains concealed due to some pressure, and then becomes clearly evident when the pressure is removed or ceases. (The manifestation of truth after it has been hidden.)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ الۡعَزِیۡزِ الۡئٰنَ حَصۡحَصَ الۡحَقُّ ۫ اَنَا رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ  نَّفۡسِہٖ» (12/51)\nTranslation: The wife of Al-Aziz said, Now the truth has come to light. Indeed, it was I who sought to seduce him...","Such a truth that remains concealed under pressure.","Constant","حصحص","12:51",1
1064,224,"C","ثَبَتَ","«ثَبَتَ» meaning to stand firm on something, to remain steadfast and resolute. And its opposite is «زَلَّ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا لَقِیۡتُمۡ فِئَۃً فَاثۡبُتُوۡا» (8/45) Translation: O you who believe! When you confront a disbelieving group, then stand firm.","«ثَبَتَ» to stand firm on something.","Constant","ثبت","2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:24-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7",13
1065,224,"S","اِسْتَقَام","«قَامَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to remain steadfast upon an action or matter. And «اَقَاَمَ الشَّئْ» means to make someone stand upright and straight. And «اِسْتَقَام» means to keep something established and ongoing, and to persist (in it). It also means to walk upon the straight path and remain firm upon it (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ قَالُوۡا رَبُّنَا اللّٰہُ  ثُمَّ اسۡتَقَامُوۡا فَلَا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وَ لَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (46/13)\nTranslation: As for those who say, Our Lord is Allah, and then remain steadfast—no fear will come upon them, nor will they grieve.","«اِسْتَقَام» To steadfastly adhere to what is right, remain firm, and consistently uphold it.","Steadfast","استقام","9:7-41:30-46:13-72:16",4
1066,224,"C","اِصْطَبَرَ","«صَابَرَ» and «صَبَرَ» mean restraining oneself from unlawful acts during times of hardship or distress. (مف) And its opposite is «جَزَعَ». And «صَبَرَ الدَّایَۃ» means keeping an animal tied without fodder. «صَابَرَ» also means encouraging another to remain steadfast and patient. (منجد) And «اِصْطَبِر» means making a habit of facing hardships with resilience, persisting in it, enduring.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اۡمُرۡ اَہۡلَکَ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ وَ اصۡطَبِرۡ عَلَیۡہَا» (20/132). Translation: Command your household to pray, then remain steadfast upon it.","«اِصْطَبَرَ» To face adversities with fortitude and make it a habit.","Constant","اصطبر","19:65-20:132-54:27",3
1067,224,"S","رَابَطَ","«رَبَطَ الْفَرَس» means to tether a horse for protection. And «رَبَاط» is that place where protective detachments are stationed. «رَبَاطَ الجَّیْش» means to assign the army to a place (muf). And «رَابَطَ الْجَّیْش» means to always keep the army encamped near the enemy's border. And «رَابَطَ اْلاَمْرَ» means to always take charge of a task (munajid). As if «رَابَطَ» is used for permanently assuming responsibility for a task that relates to the protection and strengthening of that task.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا اصۡبِرُوۡا وَ صَابِرُوۡا وَ رَابِطُوۡا» (3/200)\nTranslation: O believers! Be patient against the disbelievers. Adopt steadfastness and remain gathered (in the trenches) (Jalandhari).\nAnd for maintaining firmness, «ثَبَّتَ» is employed.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ کُلًّا نَّقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ مِنۡ اَنۡۢبَآءِ الرُّسُلِ مَا نُثَبِّتُ بِہٖ فُؤَادَکَ» (11/120)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ!) We relate to you all the accounts of the messengers so that your heart may be made firm.","«رَابَطَ» to remain steadfast on such a task whose firmness and protection are essential.","Steadfast","رابط","3:200-8:11-8:60-18:14-28:10",5
1068,225,"E","تَجَسَّس","«جَسّ» means to touch with the hand to ascertain or feel. And «جَسَّ بِعَیْنِہٖ» means to stare with a piercing or sharp gaze. And «جَسَّسَ» and «تَجَسَّس» mean to investigate (munjad), to search for someone's faults, to be on their trail. Generally, it is used in a negative sense. And «جَسِیْس» means spy (especially secretly).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَّ لَا تَجَسَّسُوۡا وَ لَا یَغۡتَبۡ بَّعۡضُکُمۡ بَعۡضًا» (49/12)\nTranslation: And do not spy or backbite one another.","«تَجَسَّس» generally carries a negative connotation, meaning to search for someone's faults and uncover them by any means possible.","Espionage","تجسس","49:12",1
1069,225,"E","سَمَّاع","«سَمِعَ» means to hear and «سَامِع» means the listener. And «سَمَّاع» means one who listens secretly for the purpose of spying. A spy (i.e., one who spies).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِقَوۡمٍ اٰخَرِیۡنَ ۙ  لَمۡ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ» (5/41)\nTranslation: They [the Jews] fabricate lies and thus become spies for those who have not yet come to you.","The person who eavesdrops to spy on something and then relays it to others.","Espionage","سماع","5:41-5:42-9:47",3
1070,226,"T","عَلِمَ","«عَلِمَ» means to perceive, know, or ascertain the reality of something (sing.).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (2/60)  \nTranslation: Every tribe had come to know the place for drawing their water.","«عَلِمَ» to know something accurately.","to know","علم","2:13-2:22-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:33-2:42-2:75-2:77-2:78-2:80-2:101-2:102-2:103-2:106-2:107-2:113-2:118-2:120-2:140-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:151-2:169-2:184-2:188-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:209-2:216-2:220-2:223-2:230-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:239-2:244-2:247-2:255-2:259-2:260-2:267-2:270-2:280-3:7-3:18-3:19-3:29-3:36-3:61-3:66-3:71-3:75-3:78-3:135-3:140-3:142-3:166-3:167-4:25-4:43-4:45-4:63-4:83-4:113-4:157-4:162-4:166-5:34-5:40-5:49-5:61-5:92-5:94-5:97-5:98-5:99-5:104-5:109-5:113-5:116-6:3-6:33-6:37-6:50-6:53-6:58-6:59-6:60-6:67-6:80-6:81-6:91-6:97-6:100-6:105-6:108-6:114-6:117-6:119-6:124-6:135-6:140-6:143-6:144-6:148-7:7-7:28-7:32-7:33-7:38-7:52-7:62-7:75-7:89-7:123-7:131-7:182-7:187-7:188-8:24-8:25-8:27-8:28-8:34-8:40-8:41-8:60-8:70-9:2-9:3-9:6-9:11-9:16-9:36-9:41-9:42-9:43-9:63-9:78-9:93-9:97-9:101-9:104-9:123-10:5-10:18-10:39-10:40-10:55-10:68-10:89-10:93-11:5-11:6-11:14-11:31-11:39-11:46-11:47-11:49-11:79-11:93-12:21-12:22-12:40-12:46-12:51-12:52-12:68-12:73-12:76-12:77-12:80-12:81-12:86-12:89-12:96-13:8-13:19-13:33-13:37-13:42-13:43-14:9-14:38-14:52-15:3-15:24-15:96-15:97-16:8-16:19-16:23-16:25-16:27-16:38-16:39-16:41-16:43-16:55-16:56-16:70-16:74-16:75-16:78-16:91-16:95-16:101-16:103-16:125-17:12-17:25-17:36-17:47-17:54-17:55-17:84-17:85-17:102-17:107-18:5-18:12-18:19-18:21-18:22-18:26-18:65-19:43-19:65-19:70-19:75-20:7-20:52-20:71-20:98-20:104-20:110-20:114-20:135-21:4-21:7-21:24-21:28-21:39-21:65-21:74-21:79-21:110-22:3-22:5-22:8-22:54-22:68-22:70-22:71-22:76-23:84-23:88-23:96-23:114-24:15-24:19-24:25-24:29-24:31-24:33-24:63-24:64-25:6-25:42-26:49-26:112-26:132-26:188-26:197-26:227-27:15-27:25-27:40-27:42-27:52-27:61-27:65-27:66-27:74-27:84-28:13-28:14-28:37-28:38-28:50-28:56-28:57-28:69-28:75-28:78-28:80-28:85-29:3-29:8-29:10-29:11-29:16-29:32-29:41-29:42-29:45-29:49-29:52-29:64-29:66-30:6-30:7-30:29-30:30-30:34-30:56-30:59-31:6-31:15-31:20-31:25-31:34-32:17-33:5-33:18-33:50-33:51-33:63-34:2-34:6-34:14-34:21-34:28-34:36-35:11-36:16-36:26-36:36-36:76-37:158-37:170-38:69-38:88-39:9-39:26-39:29-39:39-39:49-39:52-39:70-40:7-40:19-40:42-40:57-40:70-40:83-41:3-41:22-41:47-42:14-42:18-42:25-42:35-43:20-43:61-43:85-43:86-43:89-44:32-44:39-45:17-45:18-45:23-45:24-45:26-46:4-46:8-46:23-47:16-47:19-47:26-47:30-47:31-48:25-48:27-49:7-49:16-49:18-50:16-50:45-52:47-53:28-53:30-53:32-53:35-54:26-56:61-56:76-57:4-57:17-57:20-57:25-57:29-58:7-58:11-58:14-60:1-60:10-61:5-61:11-62:9-63:1-63:8-64:4-65:12-67:14-67:17-67:26-67:29-68:7-68:33-68:44-69:49-70:39-71:4-72:24-72:28-73:20-74:31-78:4-78:5-82:12-84:23-87:7-96:5-96:14-100:9-102:3-102:4-102:5",448
1071,226,"T","اَدْرٰی","«اَدْرٰی» means to know, to understand. To have knowledge of something through another thing, means, plan, or device (indirect). And this knowledge is deficient (weak) because it is obtained indirectly. Moreover, it always involves «لَا», «مَا», or «اِنْ», which are negative or interrogative particles.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n\n«قُلۡ  اِنۡ  اَدۡرِیۡۤ  اَقَرِیۡبٌ مَّا تُوۡعَدُوۡنَ اَمۡ  یَجۡعَلُ  لَہٗ  رَبِّیۡۤ   اَمَدًا» (72/25)\nTranslation: Say, I do not know whether the Day you are promised is near or whether my Lord has extended its term.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» (101/10,11)\nTranslation: And what will make you realize what the Crusher is? (It is) a blazing Fire.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the divine command states:\n\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ  لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ  یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  اَمۡرًا» (65/1)\nTranslation: Perhaps Allah will bring about after this a change of condition (Uthmani).","«اَدْرٰی» indirect, i.e., having knowledge of something through a means.","to know","ادری","4:11-10:16-21:109-21:111-31:34-33:63-42:17-42:52-45:32-46:9-65:1-69:3-69:26-72:10-72:25-74:27-77:14-80:3-82:17-82:18-83:8-83:19-86:2-90:12-97:2-101:3-101:10-104:5",28
1072,226,"T","اَحَسَّ","«اَحَسَّ» To reach or know something through the power of senses (intransitive). To come to know something through the five external senses, to perceive it; one can call it proximate knowledge (intransitive). For example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَحَسَّ عِیۡسٰی مِنۡہُمُ الۡکُفۡرَ» ( 3/52 ) Translation: Then when Isa (peace be upon him) came to know of the disbelief of the Children of Israel (Uthmani, may Allah have mercy on him).","knowledge of something through the external senses","to know","احس","3:52-21:12",2
1073,227,"T","جَانِب ، جَنْب","«جَانِب» means side, direction, corner, aspect, and its plural is «جَوَانِب» (directions and sides). These are six: right, left, front, back, up, down, north, east, south, west, etc. And side refers to the direction that is relevant to an action at the time it is performed (as in Fiqh 244).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ نَادَیۡنٰہُ مِنۡ جَانِبِ الطُّوۡرِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ  وَ قَرَّبۡنٰہُ  نَجِیًّا» (19/52)\nTranslation: And We called Moses from the right side of the Tur (Mount Sinai) and brought him near for conversation.","«جَانِب» the nearest side.","toward","جانب ، جنب","4:36-10:12-17:68-17:83-19:52-20:80-28:29-28:44-28:46-37:8-39:56-41:51",12
1074,227,"S","طَرْف","«طَرْف» means the ultimate limit or edge of something, and its plural form is «اَطْرَاف» (as cited in the lexical sources). The word «طَرْف» is not used for direction in Arabic, but its usage is common in Urdu. In the Quran, wherever this word appears, it conveys the meaning of an ultimate limit or edge, or alternatively, the limit of vision or for vision.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/114)\nTranslation: And establish prayer at the two ends of the day and during some hours of the night.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ مِنۡ طَرۡفٍ خَفِیٍّ» (42/45)\nTranslation: They will be looking down, subdued. (Jalandhari)","the final limit or edge of something","Side","طرف","3:127-11:114-13:41-20:130-21:44-42:45",6
1075,227,"T","وِجْھَۃٌ","«وَجْہٌ» meaning 'face'. And the direction facing something. «وَجْہُ النَّھَار» meaning the first part of the day. And «وَاجَہَ» meaning to be face to face (munjadan). And «وِجْھَۃٌ» that is the direction towards which one turns (muf), i.e., that specific direction and place towards which one faces for worship, etc. Qibla (Faq. l. 244)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  لِکُلٍّ وِّجۡہَۃٌ ہُوَ مُوَلِّیۡہَا» (2/148)\nTranslation: And for every community there is a direction (appointed) towards which they turn (during worship).","«وِجْھَۃ» the specific place and direction toward which one turns in worship.","toward","وجھۃ","2:112-2:115-2:144-2:148-2:149-2:150-2:272-3:20-4:125-5:108-6:52-6:79-10:105-12:9-12:93-12:96-13:22-16:58-18:28-22:11-28:22-28:88-30:30-30:38-30:39-30:43-31:22-39:24-43:17-51:29-55:27-67:22-76:9-92:20",34
1076,227,"T","شَطْر","«شَطْر» has two basic meanings. (1) «نِصْفُ الشَّئْ» means half of something. (2) «اَلْبُعْد وَالْمَوَاجِھَۃ» (lexical meaning) i.e., in «شَطْر», besides facing each other, distance is also necessary, whereas in «وِجْھَۃ» it is not necessary, meaning that even from a distant place, turning one's face toward a specific direction is sufficient.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ» (2/149). Translation: And wherever you go out (for prayer), turn your faces toward the Sacred Mosque.","«شَطْر» turning toward something from a distant position.","toward","شطر","2:144-2:149-2:150",3
1077,227,"A","تِلْقَائَ","«لَقِیَ» means to come before something and find it (singular, intensive form), and «تِلْقَاءِ ، لِقَاء» is a noun of place, meaning the place of meeting. As in «جَلَسَ تِلْقَاءَہٗ» he sat facing him. «فَعَلَ الْاَمْرُ مِنْ تِلْقَاءِ نَفْسِہٖ» he did that work of his own accord; no one forced him (intensive form).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«قُلۡ مَا یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡۤ اَنۡ اُبَدِّلَہٗ  مِنۡ تِلۡقَآیِٔ  نَفۡسِیۡ» (10/15)\nTranslation: Say, It is not for me to change it of my own accord.\nMeaning: I cannot change it by my own will.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ  تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22)\nTranslation: And when he turned his face towards Madyan.\nMeaning: towards the opposite or front side.","«تِلْقَائَ» facing, being opposite something.","Aspect","تلقائ","7:47-10:15-28:22",3
1078,227,"S","قِبَلَ","«قِبَلَ» also means confrontation, as well as one thing being before another.  \nIt is as if «قِبَل» is that side which appears before the eyes.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«لَیۡسَ الۡبِرَّ اَنۡ تُوَلُّوۡا وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ  قِبَلَ الۡمَشۡرِقِ وَ الۡمَغۡرِبِ وَ لٰکِنَّ الۡبِرَّ مَنۡ اٰمَنَ بِاللّٰہِ وَ الۡیَوۡمِ الۡاٰخِرِ» ( 2/177 )  \nTranslation: Righteousness is not that you turn your faces toward the east and the west, but righteousness is in one who believes in Allah and the Last Day.","What is visible ahead «قِبَلَ»","Side","قبل","2:142-2:143-2:144-2:145-2:177-6:111-10:87-12:26-12:71-18:55-27:37-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-46:24-51:29-52:25-57:13-68:30-70:36",21
1079,228,"W","اِذْ","«اِذْ» comes for the past tense, and after it either a full sentence follows or else the sentence is elliptical (omitted).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَالَ رَبُّکَ لِلۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ اِنِّیۡ جَاعِلٌ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ خَلِیۡفَۃً» ( 2/30 )\nTranslation: And when your Lord said to the angels, Indeed, I will make upon the earth a successive authority.","«اِذْ» comes to remind of a past event.","When","اذ","2:30-2:34-2:49-2:50-2:51-2:53-2:54-2:55-2:58-2:60-2:61-2:63-2:67-2:72-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:124-2:125-2:126-2:127-2:131-2:133-2:165-2:166-2:246-2:258-2:260-3:8-3:35-3:42-3:44-3:45-3:55-3:80-3:81-3:103-3:121-3:122-3:124-3:152-3:153-3:164-3:187-4:64-4:72-4:108-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:27-5:110-5:111-5:112-5:116-6:27-6:30-6:43-6:71-6:74-6:91-6:93-6:144-7:5-7:12-7:69-7:74-7:80-7:86-7:89-7:141-7:160-7:161-7:163-7:164-7:167-7:171-7:172-8:7-8:9-8:11-8:12-8:17-8:26-8:30-8:32-8:42-8:43-8:44-8:48-8:49-8:50-9:25-9:40-9:115-10:61-10:71-12:4-12:8-12:51-12:89-12:100-12:102-14:6-14:7-14:35-15:28-15:52-17:47-17:60-17:61-17:94-17:101-18:10-18:14-18:16-18:21-18:39-18:50-18:55-18:60-18:63-19:3-19:16-19:39-19:42-20:10-20:38-20:40-20:92-20:104-20:116-21:52-21:76-21:78-21:83-21:87-21:89-22:26-24:12-24:15-24:16-25:29-26:10-26:70-26:72-26:98-26:106-26:124-26:142-26:161-26:177-27:7-27:54-28:44-28:46-28:76-28:87-29:16-29:28-31:13-32:12-33:7-33:9-33:10-33:12-33:13-33:37-34:31-34:32-34:33-34:51-36:13-36:14-37:84-37:85-37:124-37:134-37:140-38:21-38:22-38:31-38:41-38:69-38:71-39:32-40:10-40:18-40:47-40:71-41:14-43:26-43:39-46:11-46:21-46:26-46:29-48:18-48:26-50:17-51:25-51:38-51:41-51:43-53:16-53:32-59:16-60:4-61:5-61:6-66:3-66:11-68:17-68:48-74:33-79:16-85:6-91:12",218
1080,228,"W","اِذَا","«اِذَا» This is called a temporal adverb in Arabic grammar, and it conveys the meaning of a condition. It often governs the past tense and transforms its meaning into that of the future.  \nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا» (2/14)  \nTranslation: And when these people meet the believers, they say, We have believed.  \nSimilarly, at another place, the divine command is: إِذَا جَاءَ رَمَضَانُ، فُتِحَتْ أبْوَاب الجَنَّةِ  \nTranslation: When Ramadan comes, the gates of Paradise are opened.  \nAt another place, the divine command is: «اِذَا الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» (81/1)  \nTranslation: When the sun will be folded up.  \nAnd sometimes, by adding nunation, the time is specified in the future, i.e., «اِذًا» at that time, in that situation, in that state.  \nFor example, in the Quran: «اِذًا لَّارۡتَابَ الۡمُبۡطِلُوۡنَ» (29/48)  \nTranslation: At that time, the people of falsehood will surely doubt.  \nAnd by adding this word even after «حِیْن», «حِیْنَئِذٍ» comes to mean at that time. And by adding it after «یَوْمَ», «یَوْمَئِذٍ» specifically means on that day. And all these are used as temporal adverbs in the future.  \nAnd sometimes, this also governs the imperfect verb.  \nNote: (Temporal adverb: an adverbial noun that conveys the meaning of time or period, e.g., morning, evening, today, tomorrow, month, week, century, etc.)","«اِذَا» is called an adverb of time in Arabic grammar, and it conveys the meaning of a condition. It often occurs with the past tense and transforms its meaning into that of the future.","when","اذا","2:11-2:13-2:14-2:20-2:76-2:91-2:117-2:145-2:156-2:170-2:177-2:180-2:186-2:196-2:205-2:206-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:282-3:25-3:47-3:119-3:135-3:152-3:156-4:6-4:8-4:18-4:41-4:58-4:61-4:62-4:67-4:77-4:83-4:86-4:94-4:101-4:102-4:140-4:142-5:2-5:5-5:6-5:58-5:61-5:83-5:89-5:93-5:104-5:105-5:106-5:107-6:25-6:31-6:44-6:54-6:56-6:61-6:68-6:99-6:109-6:124-6:141-6:152-7:28-7:37-7:38-7:47-7:57-7:90-7:135-7:201-7:203-7:204-8:2-8:15-8:24-8:31-8:45-9:38-9:58-9:86-9:91-9:92-9:94-9:95-9:118-9:122-9:124-9:127-10:12-10:15-10:21-10:22-10:23-10:24-10:49-10:51-10:90-10:106-11:31-11:40-11:102-12:14-12:62-12:79-12:110-13:11-15:8-16:24-16:40-16:53-16:54-16:58-16:85-16:86-16:91-16:101-17:16-17:35-17:42-17:45-17:46-17:67-17:73-17:75-17:76-17:83-17:100-17:107-18:14-18:17-18:20-18:24-18:57-18:71-18:74-18:77-18:86-18:90-18:93-18:96-19:35-19:58-19:73-19:75-21:12-21:36-22:72-21:45-21:96-22:35-22:52-23:34-23:35-23:64-23:77-23:91-23:99-24:39-24:40-24:48-24:51-24:59-24:62-25:12-25:13-25:41-25:60-25:63-25:67-25:72-25:73-26:20-26:42-26:80-26:130-27:18-27:34-27:62-27:80-27:82-27:84-28:53-28:55-29:48-29:65-30:20-30:25-30:33-30:36-30:48-30:52-31:7-31:21-31:32-32:15-33:16-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:53-34:7-34:23-34:43-36:24-36:45-36:47-36:82-37:13-37:14-37:35-39:8-39:45-39:49-39:71-39:73-40:12-40:34-41:20-41:51-42:29-42:37-42:39-42:48-43:13-43:17-43:38-43:47-43:50-43:57-45:9-45:25-45:32-46:6-46:7-46:15-47:4-47:16-47:18-47:27-48:15-53:1-53:22-53:46-54:24-56:1-56:4-56:83-58:8-58:9-58:11-58:12-60:10-60:12-62:9-62:11-63:1-63:4-63:5-63:11-65:1-67:7-68:15-70:20-70:21-71:4-72:24-74:34-75:26-76:19-76:20-76:28-77:9-77:10-77:11-77:48-79:12-80:22-81:1-81:2-81:3-81:4-81:5-81:6-81:7-81:8-81:10-81:11-81:12-81:13-81:17-81:18-82:1-82:2-82:3-82:4-83:2-83:3-83:13-83:30-83:31-83:32-84:1-84:3-84:18-84:21-89:4-89:15-89:16-89:21-91:2-91:3-91:4-92:1-92:2-92:11-93:2-96:10-99:1-100:9-110:1-113:3-113:5",326
1081,228,"W","لَمَّا","«لَمَّا» In Arabic grammar, this particle is called nāfīyah and is used for conditional clauses in the past tense. For example, in the Quran it is: «فَلَمَّاۤ  اَنۡ جَآءَ الۡبَشِیۡرُ» (12/96). Translation: So when the bearer of good news arrived.","In Arabic grammar, this particle is called a negating particle and is used in conditional sentences in the past tense.","when","لما","2:17-2:33-2:89-2:101-2:214-2:246-2:249-2:250-2:259-3:36-3:52-3:142-3:165-4:77-5:117-6:5-6:44-6:76-6:77-6:78-7:22-7:116-7:126-7:134-7:135-7:143-7:149-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:166-7:189-7:190-8:48-9:16-9:76-9:114-10:12-10:13-10:23-10:39-10:54-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:81-10:98-11:58-11:66-11:70-11:74-11:77-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:111-12:15-12:22-12:28-12:31-12:50-12:54-12:59-12:63-12:65-12:66-12:68-12:69-12:70-12:80-12:88-12:94-12:96-12:99-14:22-15:61-17:67-18:59-18:61-18:62-19:49-20:11-21:12-25:37-26:21-26:41-26:61-27:8-27:10-27:13-27:36-27:40-27:42-27:44-28:14-28:19-28:22-28:23-28:25-28:29-28:30-28:31-28:36-28:48-29:31-29:33-29:65-29:68-31:32-32:24-33:22-33:37-34:14-34:33-34:43-35:42-37:102-37:103-40:25-40:66-40:83-40:84-40:85-41:41-42:44-43:30-43:35-43:47-43:50-43:55-43:57-43:63-46:7-46:24-46:29-49:14-50:5-59:16-61:5-61:6-62:3-66:3-67:27-68:26-68:51-69:11-72:13-72:19-80:23",150
1082,228,"W","کُلَّمَا","«کُلَّمَا» is used to encompass various matters or actions. It conveys the meaning of whenever or at any time. In numerous contexts, it functions as a past temporal adverb to include all instances.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is: «اَفَکُلَّمَا جَآءَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلٌۢ بِمَا لَا تَہۡوٰۤی اَنۡفُسُکُمُ اسۡتَکۡبَرۡتُمۡ» (2/87) Translation: So whenever a Messenger came to you with that which your souls did not desire, you became arrogant.","«کُلَّمَا» is used to cover certain matters (work).","when","کلما","2:20-2:25-2:87-2:100-3:37-4:56-5:64-5:70-7:38-11:38-17:97-22:22-32:20-67:8-71:7",15
1083,229,"R","اَصْل","«اَصْل» means the foundation of something and the root of trees, plants, etc., and its opposite is «فَرْع», meaning a branch, and its plural is «اُصُول». (Mufradat, Manjad) And usool (principles) are also called the rules upon which a science is founded. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً  کَشَجَرَۃٍ  طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی  السَّمَآءِ» (14/24)\n\nTranslation: The example of a good word is like a good tree, whose root is firm (i.e., firmly holding to the earth) and whose branches are in the sky.","«اَصْل» is called for the roots of trees and plants.","Root","اصل","14:24-37:64-59:5",3
1084,229,"R","اَعْجَاز","«اَعْجَازُ النَّخْلِ» means the roots of the date palm tree (manjad). The tree's root branches out into multiple sections that become embedded in the ground. These root sections are referred to as «اَعْجَاز». For instance, the Quran states: «فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ» (69/7). Translation: Then you will see that nation scattered like the hollow roots of date palms.","«اَعْجَاز» the parts of a tree's root that are embedded in the soil.","Root","اعجاز","54:20-69:7",2
1085,229,"R","دَابِر","«دُبُر» meaning the back, the rear, or the last part of everything. And «دَابِر» meaning the end or ultimate of everything. And «قَطَعَ اللہُ دَابِرَھُمْ» meaning Allah will uproot their roots. (Manjad) And one meaning of «اِدْبَار» is ill omen, and its opposite is «اِقْبَال». And «دَابِر» essentially comes from the lingering or residual bad effects of something.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یُرِیۡدُ  اللّٰہُ  اَنۡ یُّحِقَّ الۡحَقَّ بِکَلِمٰتِہٖ وَ یَقۡطَعَ دَابِرَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (8/7)\nTranslation: Allah intended to establish the truth by His word and to uproot the roots of the disbelievers.\n\nNote: (To destroy. To uproot. To eradicate. To exterminate a lineage. To annihilate.)","«دَابِر» is used for uprooting. It is also referred to as the root or foundation of any defect or corruption.","Root","دابر","6:45-7:72-8:7-15:66",4
1086,230,"B","جِسْم","«جِسْم» Every material thing that possesses length (longitude), width (latitude), and depth (altitude) and has a body (form), whether living or non-living, and its plural is «اجسام». It means bulk, stature, being huge and large.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا رَاَیۡتَہُمۡ  تُعۡجِبُکَ اَجۡسَامُہُمۡ» (63/4)\nTranslation: And when you see them (the hypocrites), their bodies (and the proportion of their limbs) seem pleasing to you.","«جِسْم» Every material thing that has a body.","body","جسم","2:247-63:4",2
1087,230,"B","جَسَد","«جَسَد» is specific to the body, meaning the body of a living being in which the blood has dried up.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَخۡرَجَ لَہُمۡ عِجۡلًا جَسَدًا لَّہٗ خُوَارٌ» (20/88)\nTranslation: So Samiri made for them a calf—a mere body that lowed like a cow.\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ مَا جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ جَسَدًا لَّا یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ الطَّعَامَ  وَ مَا  کَانُوۡا  خٰلِدِیۡنَ» (21/8)\nTranslation: And We did not create the bodies of those messengers [in a way that they] would not eat food, nor were they to live forever.\nTherefore, a deceased human is referred to as a 'dust body' or 'elemental body'.","«جَسَد» specifically denotes a body, meaning the body of a living being in which the blood has dried up.","Body","جسد","7:148-20:88-21:8-38:34",4
1088,230,"B","بَدَن","«بَدَن» means a living body with flowing blood or one that has not yet dried.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَالۡیَوۡمَ نُنَجِّیۡکَ بِبَدَنِکَ  لِتَکُوۡنَ لِمَنۡ خَلۡفَکَ اٰیَۃً» (10/92)  \nTranslation: So today (O Pharaoh) We will rescue your body from the sea so that you may become a lesson for those who come after you.","«بَدَن» means a body of a living being in which blood is flowing or has not yet dried.","Body","بدن","10:92",1
1089,231,"T","وَثَقَ","«وَثَقَ» means to bind with a rope and to tie a knot. And «وَثَاق» and «وِثَاق» refer to the thing that binds or a rope, etc. (manjad). Also, «وَثْق» refers to the rope used for tying animals.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ اَثۡخَنۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ فَشُدُّوا الۡوَثَاقَ» (47/4)\nTranslation: When you have thoroughly defeated them, then bind firmly the prisoners.\n\nIn this verse, the inclusion of the word «شَدَّ» causes the meaning of «وَثَقَ» to become to bind firmly or to tie tightly.","«وَثَقَ» is tied only with rope, etc.","to bend","وثق","2:256-31:22-47:4-89:26",4
1090,231,"T","قَرَّنَ","«قَرَن» means to tie or bind one thing with another and to mix them. And «قَرَن» refers to the rope with which two or more camels are tied (mujd), and its meanings also include 'mixed with' (munjad). It is also used for a companion who is of the same age or sits with one (in the same gathering). And exaggeration (mubalaghah) is found in «قَرَّنَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ اٰخَرِیۡنَ مُقَرَّنِیۡنَ فِی الۡاَصۡفَادِ» (38/38)\nTranslation: And others too who were bound in chains.","«قَرَّنَ» A rope that is also connected to something else for added strength.","to bind","قرن","14:49-25:13-38:38-43:13",4
1091,232,"P","مَقَام","«قَامَ» means to stand. And «مَقَام» is used for the place of standing. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ اتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ مَّقَامِ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ مُصَلًّی» (2:125). Translation: And make the place where Prophet Abraham stood a place of prayer.\n\nAnd «مُقَام» is a mīmī masdar (a verbal noun with an added م) from «قَامَ», meaning to stand. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ  لِمَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ  رَبِّہٖ  جَنَّتٰنِ» (55:46). Translation: And for whoever fears the standing before his Lord, there will be two gardens.\n\nNote: A mīmī masdar is a type of masdar (verbal noun) that has an extra م at the beginning.","the place of standing","Place","مقام","2:125-3:97-5:107-10:71-14:14-17:79-19:73-25:66-25:76-26:58-27:39-33:13-35:35-37:164-44:26-44:51-55:46-79:40",18
1092,232,"P","مَکَان","A building or place constructed for living, a residence, a mansion. The term is also used for a place that overlays or covers a body. The dweller within it is referred to as «مَکِیْن» (intransitive), provided the term is employed in a spatial or locative sense.\n\nFor example: The divine command states: Pharaoh said to Moses (peace be upon him):\n«فَاجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَکَ مَوۡعِدًا  لَّا نُخۡلِفُہٗ  نَحۡنُ  وَ لَاۤ  اَنۡتَ  مَکَانًا  سُوًی» (20/58)\n\nTranslation: Appoint for us a fixed time between us and yourselves, which we will not violate, nor you, and let this contest take place in a level ground (a plain field).","«مَکَان» meaning place, location, spot.","Place","مکان","4:20-5:60-6:6-6:135-7:10-7:95-7:143-10:22-10:28-11:93-11:121-12:21-12:54-23:13-12:56-12:77-12:78-14:17-16:101-16:112-18:84-18:95-22:41-19:16-19:22-19:57-19:75-20:58-22:26-22:31-24:55-25:12-25:13-25:34-28:6-28:57-28:82-34:51-34:52-34:53-36:67-39:39-41:44-46:26-50:41-77:21-81:20",47
1093,232,"P","مَرَاغَم","«رَغِمَ» (verb) means to cling to dust or to become dusty. «رَغِمَ اَنْفُ فُلَانٍ» means that his nose becomes dusty or he is humiliated (an expression of anger). And «رَاغَمَ» means the attempt to humiliate one another and to argue. And «مَرَاغَم» refers to a place that is obtained through conflict and effort with others (sing.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّہَاجِرۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ یَجِدۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُرٰغَمًا کَثِیۡرًا وَّ سَعَۃً» (4/100)\nTranslation: And whoever emigrates for the cause of Allah will find on the earth many [places of] refuge and abundance.","[A place] acquired through disputes and effort.","Place","مراغم","4:100",1
1094,233,"S","جَلَاء","«جَلَا» meaning to clarify a matter (command). A clear and evident situation.  \n«جَلَا اَلْرَجُلُ عَنْ بَلَدِہٖ» to expel someone from their city or country. To make them a refugee.  \n«جَلَا النَّحْل» meaning to smoke out bees in order to extract honey.  \n«اَلْجَالِی» meaning those traveler people who leave their homeland (refugees).  \n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is said:  \n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَنۡ  کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمُ  الۡجَلَآءَ لَعَذَّبَہُمۡ  فِی الدُّنۡیَا» (59/3)  \nTranslation: And if Allah had decreed exile for them, He would have punished them in this world as well.","«جَلَاء» means to exile someone.","Scorched Native Land","جلاء","59:3",1
1095,233,"B","نَفٰی","«نَفٰی» means to cease to exist, or the denial of something's existence. Its opposite is «ثَبَتَ». And «مَنْفٰی» means to be annihilated, destroyed, or removed. «نَفٰی الْرَجُلُ مِنْ بَلَدِہٖ» means to expel someone from a city (exile). And «نَفٰی ، یَنْفُوا» means to imprison in a prison (detention), and it also conveys the meaning of throwing something out—such as a millstone discarding flour, or a boiling pot discarding its scum, or a flood discarding debris (m. q). And «اَلنِّفَایَۃ» refers to that discarded object which is thrown away (m. l). Thus, the meanings of helplessness and humiliation are also inherent in «نَفٰی ، یَنْفُوا».\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا جَزٰٓؤُا الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَارِبُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ وَ یَسۡعَوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَسَادًا اَنۡ یُّقَتَّلُوۡۤا اَوۡ یُصَلَّبُوۡۤا اَوۡ تُقَطَّعَ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلُہُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ اَوۡ یُنۡفَوۡا مِنَ  الۡاَرۡضِ» (5:33)\nTranslation: The punishment of those who wage war against Allah and His Messenger and strive to spread corruption in the land is none but that they be killed, or crucified, or have their hands and feet cut off on opposite sides, or be exiled from the land.","«نَفٰی» means to remove someone from humiliation and disgrace.","Burning Homeland","نفی","5:33",1
1096,234,"H","سَرِعَ","«سَرِعَ» Do not delay in doing whatever work you intend to do. Do not leave today's work for tomorrow. Do not be lazy. Complete tasks on time or even a little earlier. And this is a praiseworthy (good) trait, and its opposite is «بَطَأَ», which means delaying (due to laziness, etc.). And where rushing is better and correct, do it quickly (as per Fiqh, p. 168).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ لَہُمۡ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا کَسَبُوۡا ؕ وَ اللّٰہُ  سَرِیۡعُ  الۡحِسَابِ» (2/202)\nTranslation: These are the people for whom there is a share in their deeds (i.e., reward prepared), and Allah is swift in taking account and swift in giving reward.","«سَرِعَ» means to complete a task quickly, to hurry.","hurry","سرع","2:202-3:19-3:199-5:4-6:62-6:165-7:167-10:21-13:41-14:51-24:39-40:17",12
1097,234,"H","عَجِلَ","«عَجِلَ» To try to obtain something before its appointed time; to be hasty. And this is a blameworthy (evil) trait. To hasten where one should not hasten.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یَدۡعُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ بِالشَّرِّ دُعَآءَہٗ  بِالۡخَیۡرِ ؕ وَ کَانَ  الۡاِنۡسَانُ  عَجُوۡلًا» (17/11)\nTranslation: And man prays for evil as he prays for good, and man is ever hasty.\nAnd «اِسْتَعْجَل» meaning to seek something hastily or before its time.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَکَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ قَبۡلَ الۡحَسَنَۃِ وَ قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمُ الۡمَثُلٰتُ ؕ» (13/6)\nTranslation: And those who hasten for punishment from your Lord—indeed, the punishments of your Lord are not far from the wrongdoers.","«عَجِلَ» Rashness; the attempt to acquire something before its proper time so that it is not done correctly.","Hurry","عجل","2:203-6:57-6:58-7:150-10:11-10:50-10:51-13:6-16:1-17:11-17:18-18:58-19:84-20:83-20:84-20:114-21:37-22:47-26:204-27:46-27:72-29:53-29:54-37:176-38:16-42:18-46:24-46:35-48:20-51:14-51:59-75:16",32
1098,234,"Q","بَدَرَ","The time required to complete a task. To finish the task earlier by reducing that time.\n\nFor example: A blessed Hadith: «لَا تُبَادِ رُوْنِیْ بِالرُّکُوْعِ وَ السُّجُوْدِ»\nTranslation: Do not rush in performing ruku and sujud before me (the Imam). (Ahmad, Abu Dawud, Ibn Majah)\n\nAnd the sublime command of Allah is: «وَ لَا تَاۡکُلُوۡہَاۤ اِسۡرَافًا وَّ بِدَارًا» (4/6)\nTranslation: And do not consume the orphans' wealth more than necessary and before need.","To rush work by reducing the required time.","Quickly","بدر","4:6",1
1099,234,"Q","فَوْر","«فَارَ» means to boil and to rage. And «فَوْر» means very quickly. As in «رَجَعَ مِنْ فَوْرِہٖ», he returned very quickly without pause (manjada), meaning to do something immediately with fervor.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«بَلٰۤی ۙ اِنۡ  تَصۡبِرُوۡا وَ تَتَّقُوۡا وَ یَاۡتُوۡکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَوۡرِہِمۡ ہٰذَا یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ رَبُّکُمۡ بِخَمۡسَۃِ اٰلٰفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُسَوِّمِیۡنَ» (3/125)  \nTranslation: Yes, if you hold fast to your resolve and remain conscious of Allah, and the disbelievers come upon you in rage, suddenly, then your Lord will reinforce you with five thousand marked angels.","«فَوْر» to do something with zeal and zest.","Quickly","فور","3:125-11:40-23:27-67:7",4
1100,234,"Q","سَ ، سَوْف","«سَ» and «سَوْف», when incorporated into the imperfect tense, impart the meaning of haste. And they specify the imperfect as future. The only distinction between the two is that «س» is employed for the near future, and its meaning is understood as now.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«سَیَقُوۡلُ السُّفَہَآءُ» (2/142)\nTranslation: Fools will say this.\n\nAnd the time frame of «سَوْف» is longer than that of «س».\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«کَلَّا  سَوۡفَ تَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (102/3)\nTranslation: You will certainly not die soon.","«سَ» and «سَوْفَ» fall upon the subjunctive mood and impart to it the meaning of haste.","Quickly","س ، سوف","4:30-4:56-4:74-4:114-4:146-4:152-5:14-5:54-6:5-6:67-6:135-7:123-7:143-9:28-11:39-11:93-12:98-15:3-15:96-16:55-18:87-19:59-19:66-25:42-25:77-26:49-29:66-30:34-37:170-37:175-37:179-39:39-40:70-43:44-43:89-53:40-84:8-84:11-92:21-93:5-102:3-102:4",42
1101,235,"C","جَمْعُ","«جَمْعُ» refers to a gathering of people, an assembly in a place. This term is commonly used for a group, whether it is a small or large gathering, or of any kind.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n\n«سَیُہۡزَمُ الۡجَمۡعُ وَ  یُوَلُّوۡنَ الدُّبُرَ» (54/45)\nTranslation: Soon this group will be defeated, and these people will turn their backs and flee.\n\nAt another place, the command of the Almighty is:\n\n«وَ اِنَّا  لَجَمِیۡعٌ  حٰذِرُوۡنَ» (26/56)\nTranslation: And indeed, we are a great multitude, those who remain away from it.","A throng of people, the assembling of people in a place.","Congregation","جمع","2:29-2:38-2:148-2:161-2:165-3:25-3:87-3:103-3:155-3:157-3:166-3:173-4:23-4:71-4:87-4:139-4:140-4:172-5:17-5:32-5:36-5:48-5:105-5:109-6:12-6:22-6:35-6:128-6:149-7:18-7:38-7:48-7:124-7:158-8:37-8:41-8:63-10:4-10:28-10:58-10:65-10:99-11:55-11:119-12:15-12:83-12:93-13:18-13:31-13:42-14:8-14:21-15:30-15:39-15:43-15:59-15:92-16:9-17:103-18:60-18:61-18:99-20:60-20:64-20:123-21:77-24:31-24:61-26:38-26:49-26:56-26:61-26:65-26:95-26:170-27:51-28:78-32:13-34:26-34:40-35:10-36:32-36:53-37:134-38:73-38:82-38:85-39:44-39:47-39:53-39:67-42:7-42:15-42:29-43:32-43:55-44:40-45:13-45:26-54:44-54:45-58:6-58:18-59:14-64:9-70:14-70:18-75:3-75:9-75:17-77:38-100:5-104:2",113
1102,235,"C","رَھْط","«رَھْط» refers to a small group of young men from the same family, consisting of 3 to 10 individuals, with a leader also appointed. (F. 205) According to Imam Raghib, this number can extend up to forty. (Maf) Al-Munjid adds the condition that no woman is included among them. (Munjid) And if the reference is to the number itself, then it signifies individuals and persons. For example, «عِشْرُوْنَ رَھْطًا» means twenty persons. (Munjid)\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  تِسۡعَۃُ  رَہۡطٍ یُّفۡسِدُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا یُصۡلِحُوۡنَ» (27/48)\nTranslation: And in the city were nine persons who used to cause corruption in the land and did not amend [their ways].\n\nAt another instance, the divine command is:\n«قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ اَرَہۡطِیۡۤ اَعَزُّ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (11/92)\nTranslation: Shu'ayb (peace be upon him) said, O my people! Is the pressure of my brothers upon you greater than that of Allah?","A group of young people from a family, up to ten in number, with a leader.","Congregation","رھط","11:91-11:92-27:48",3
1103,235,"C","شِرْذِمَۃٌ","«شِرذِمۃ» a small group of weak, helpless, and destitute people. In terms of quantity, it is larger than «رَھْط» (p. 205), and «ثِیَابٌ شِرَازِمٌ» meaning old, torn rags (Manjad. Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ   لَشِرۡ  ذِمَۃٌ  قَلِیۡلُوۡنَ» (26:54)\nTranslation: Indeed, this group is very small in number.","«شِرذِمَۃ» a small group of weak, feeble, and helpless people.","Congregation","شرذمۃ","26:54",1
1104,235,"C","عُصْبَۃٌ","«عُصْبَۃٌ» A small group of strong and powerful people who are supporters and helpers of one another. (Muf) In terms of number, it is larger than «شِرذِمَۃ» (fn 205), but this statement of the grammarian does not seem correct. Because the Quran has used this term even for the ten brothers of Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالُوۡا  لَئِنۡ  اَکَلَہُ  الذِّئۡبُ وَ نَحۡنُ عُصۡبَۃٌ  اِنَّاۤ   اِذًا  لَّخٰسِرُوۡنَ» (12/14)\n\nTranslation: They (the brothers of Yusuf) said, If we were a strong group, even then the wolf would have eaten him. So we would indeed be great losers.","«عُصْبَۃٌ» a small but sturdy and powerful group who support and aid one another.","Congregation","عصبۃ","12:8-12:14-24:11-28:76",4
1105,235,"C","طَآئِفۃ","«طَآئِفۃ» are a group of people holding a particular opinion and religion. (manjad) In terms of numbers, they are greater than «عُصْبَۃٌ» (p. 205).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» (49/9)\nTranslation: And if two parties among the believers fall into conflict, then make peace between them.\nAnd some exegetes are of the view that the ruling of «طَآئِفَۃ» can also apply to an individual when he is acting as a party. And they cite this very verse as evidence.","«طَآئِفَۃٌ» people of one opinion and one religion.","Congregation","طآئفۃ","3:69-3:72-3:122-3:154-4:81-4:102-4:113-6:156-7:87-8:7-9:66-9:83-9:122-24:2-28:4-33:13-49:9-61:14-73:20",19
1106,235,"C","فئۃ","«فِئَۃَ» A group whose members turn to one another for cooperation (detailed). For example: «کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» ( 2/249 ). Translation: Often, a small group, by God's command, has secured victory over a larger group.","«فِئَۃَ» A mutually cooperative group.","Community","فئۃ","2:249-3:13-4:88-8:16-8:19-8:45-8:48-18:43-28:81",9
1107,235,"C","فِرقۃ","«فِرَقَۃَ» A group that has separated from a larger community. And «فِرْق» meaning a detached piece or segment of something (i.e., a part separated from the whole).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» ( 9/122 )\nTranslation: Then why is it that not from each group among you a party should go forth to learn religion and wisdom?\n\nIn this verse as well, the application of «طَآئفۃ» is intended for an individual.","A small group separated from a larger community.","Congregation","فرقۃ","9:122",1
1108,235,"C","ثُلَّۃٌ","«ثُلَّۃٌ» is also used to denote a heap (of things) and a flock of goats (مف), and it is also used for a group of humans (منجد) (as if its basis is a large quantity or number). They say «فُلَانٌ لَا یُفَرَّقُ بَیْنَ الثَّلَّۃَ وَالثُّلَّۃَ», meaning that so-and-so does not distinguish between flocks and groups of humans. And in terms of number, according to the expert in linguistic jurisprudence (صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ), the count of «ثُلَّۃٌ» is more than «طَآئِفَۃ» and less than «فِرَقَۃَ» (ف ل 205).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُلَّۃٌ  مِّنَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ وَ قَلِیۡلٌ  مِّنَ الۡاٰخِرِیۡنَ» (56:13-14)\nTranslation: They will be many among the earlier generations and few among the later ones.","«ثُلَّۃٌ» is used only for a large number.","Congregation","ثلۃ","56:13-56:39-56:40",3
1109,235,"C","زُمْرَۃٌ","According to the scholar of jurisprudence and language, «زُمْرَۃٌ ، ثُلَّۃٌ» refers to a large gathering (F L 205), and its plural is «زُمَر».  \nImam Raghib holds that «زُمْرَۃٌ» denotes a small gathering. And «شَاۃٌ زَمِرَۃٌ» means a sheep with little wool. «زَمِرٌ» is used for an ill-mannered person (Muf), and the Noble Quran also supports this meaning. That is, when a large group splits into smaller parties or detachments while moving about, these parties are called «زُمُر».  \n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ سِیۡقَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا رَبَّہُمۡ  اِلَی الۡجَنَّۃِ زُمَرًا» (39:73)  \n\nTranslation: And those who feared their Lord will be driven to Paradise in groups.","«زُمْرَۃٌ» small, scattered groups that migrated separately from a larger community.","congregation","زمرۃ","39:71-39:73",2
1110,235,"C","عِزِیْن","The plural of «اَلْعِزَۃ» is «عِزِیْن» and «عِزُوْن». And «اَلْعِزَۃُ» means a group of people of the same lineage (sing.), and «اَلْاِعْتِزَآءُ فِی الْحَرْبِ» means to mention one's lineage during a fight (sing.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَالِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا قِبَلَکَ مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ عَنِ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ عَنِ الشِّمَالِ عِزِیۡنَ» (70/36,37)\nTranslation: So what is the matter with the disbelievers that they rush towards you in haste, (and) from the right and from the left, in groups?","«عِزِیْن» people of the same lineage.","congregation","عزین","70:37",1
1111,235,"C","حِزْب","«حِزْب» refers to a group characterized by firmness and severity (mufrad), and «حِزْب» also means party, faction, battalion, weapon, a human army, and like-minded companions. Its plural forms are «اَحْزَاب» and «حَازَبَ». It means to join a party, to help, and to provide strength (manjad). It denotes people gathered under one banner (m. q.). Thus, the word «حِزْب» is also used in the meanings of a political party or an army and battalion, whose objective is to exert influence within a kingdom.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا رَاَ  الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ ۙ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا مَا وَعَدَنَا اللّٰہُ  وَ رَسُوۡلُہٗ» (33:22)\nTranslation: And when the believers saw the enemy forces, they said, This is what Allah and His Messenger had promised us.","«حِزْب» militia or political party—a group seeking to intervene in the affairs of the state.","Congregation","حزب","5:56-11:17-13:36-18:12-19:37-23:53-30:32-33:20-33:22-35:6-38:11-38:13-40:5-40:30-43:65-58:19-58:22",17
1112,235,"C","مَعْشَرُ","«عَشَرَ» means ten, and «عَشِیْرَۃ» refers to all family members who are from the father's side. In this sense, «مَعْشَرُ» refers to all individuals of a group whose purpose and objective are one, and among whom harmony and agreement are found (M.L.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» (55/33)\nTranslation: O company of jinn and humans! If you have the power to escape from the boundaries of the heavens and the earth, then break through.","«مَعْشَرُ» all members of a specific group who share mutual harmony and cohesion.","Congregation","معشر","6:128-6:130-55:33",3
1113,235,"C","ثَقَلَان","«ثِقْل» means burden, weight, or heaviness. And «ثَقِیْل» and «ثِقَال» mean heavy and weighty things. And «ثَقَلَان» refers to two major heavy groups—two principal categories, namely the jinn and humans (Minaj, F.L. 134).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«سَنَفۡرُغُ   لَکُمۡ  اَیُّہَ  الثَّقَلٰنِ» (55:31)\nO you two groups! We will soon turn our attention toward you.","«ثَقَلَان» two great creations: jinn and humans.","Congregation","ثقلان","55:31",1
1114,235,"C","اُمَّۃ","«اُمَّۃ» groups of the same kind (humans, animals, birds). Or people of the same faith who follow a single Imam.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ  دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا طٰٓئِرٍ یَّطِیۡرُ  بِجَنَاحَیۡہِ  اِلَّاۤ  اُمَمٌ  اَمۡثَالُکُمۡ» (6/38)\nTranslation: And there is not a thing that moves on the earth, nor a bird that flies with its wings, but are communities like you.\n\nAnd when this term is applied to humans, it refers to people of the same faith.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«کَانَ النَّاسُ اُمَّۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً» (2/213)\nTranslation: (Initially) all people had a single religion.\n\nAnd in common usage, «اُمَّۃ» refers to the community of such people of the same faith, which is formed by a prophet or messenger.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُنۡتُمۡ خَیۡرَ اُمَّۃٍ اُخۡرِجَتۡ لِلنَّاسِ» (3/110)\nTranslation: (O believers) you are the best community ever raised for mankind.\n\nAnd the word «اُمّۃ» has also been used in the Quran exclusively for Prophet Ibrahim (AS) as an individual. The reason is that Prophet Ibrahim (AS) single-handedly accomplished so much in proclaiming the truth that it equals what an entire community would achieve. And according to some, «اُمَّۃ» also means Imam, i.e., a guide or one who paves the way. (Jalandhari, Osmani).\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«اِنَّ  اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ کَانَ اُمَّۃً  قَانِتًا لِّلّٰہِ حَنِیۡفًا» (16/120)\nTranslation: Indeed, Ibrahim (AS) was an entire community, obedient to Allah, and he was not of those who associate partners with Him.","«اُمَّۃ» groups of similar kinds (humans, animals, birds). Or groups of like-minded people who follow a single imam.","congregation","امۃ","2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18",54
1115,235,"C","رَکْب","«رَکْب» means both a camel's hump and a caravan and a camel rider—this word is applied to all of them (sing.).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی وَ الرَّکۡبُ اَسۡفَلَ  مِنۡکُمۡ» (8/42)\nTranslation: When you were on the nearer side of the valley, and they were on the farther side, and the caravan was below you.","«رَکْب» the caravan of camels with ten or more riders.","Congregation","رکب","8:42",1
1116,235,"C","خَیْل","«خَیْل» means horses' necks (i.e., cavalry). Then, like «رَکْب», the word «خَیْل» is also applied to a horseman (meaning a Persian) (Majid, Mufradat), and it is also used for the collective of both horse and rider (Mufradat).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَعِدُّوۡا لَہُمۡ مَّا اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ قُوَّۃٍ وَّ مِنۡ رِّبَاطِ الۡخَیۡلِ تُرۡہِبُوۡنَ بِہٖ عَدُوَّ اللّٰہِ وَ عَدُوَّکُمۡ » (8/60)\nTranslation: And (O believers) prepare against them whatever you can of power and of «خَیْل» (cavalry), by which you may terrify the enemy of Allah and your enemy, and others besides them whom you do not know but whom Allah knows.","«خَیْل» is also used to refer to a caravan of horses, denoting the combined group of both horses and riders.","Congregation","خیل","3:14-8:60-16:8-59:6",4
1117,235,"C","غَنَم","«غَنَم» is the term used for a flock of goats. (m.f.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ  اِذۡ  نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ  الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And when Dawud and Sulaiman decided a case concerning a field in which the sheep of some people had grazed (and destroyed it) at night.","«غَنَم» is used for a herd of goats.","Congregation","غنم","6:146-20:18-21:78",3
1118,235,"C","ابابِیل","«اَبَابِیْل» means a flock of birds. And according to some, the term Ababil is applied to groups of birds, camels, and horses (m. q). However, if «طَیْرًا اَبَابِیْل» is used, its meaning will only be a flock of birds. Flocks. Swarms.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ اَرۡسَلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  طَیۡرًا  اَبَابِیۡلَ تَرۡمِیۡہِمۡ  بِحِجَارَۃٍ  مِّنۡ سِجِّیۡلٍ» (105/3,4)\nTranslation: And He sent against them birds in flocks, striking them with stones of baked clay.","«اَبَابِیْل» is used for birds' nests.","congregation","ابابیل","105:3",1
1119,236,"J","جِنّ","«اَلْجِنّ وَالْجِنَّۃ» The genus name. The major creation besides humans that is accountable under the Shariah. The hidden creation created from fire. The fiery creation. Jinn. Fairy. Demon, and «جَآنٌّ ۔» is the plural form of jinn.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا خَلَقۡتُ الۡجِنَّ وَ الۡاِنۡسَ  اِلَّا لِیَعۡبُدُوۡنِ» (51/56)\nTranslation: And I did not create the jinn and mankind except to worship Me.","Besides humans, «جِنّ» and other hidden, fiery creatures are mukallaf under Sharia.","jinn","جن","6:100-6:112-6:128-6:130-7:38-7:179-7:184-11:119-17:88-18:50-23:25-23:70-27:17-27:39-32:13-34:8-34:12-34:14-34:41-34:46-37:158-41:25-41:29-46:18-46:29-51:56-55:33-72:1-72:5-72:6-114:6",31
1120,236,"J","شَیْطٰن","«شَطَنَ» means to be distant. «شَطَنَ الرَّجُلُ» refers to a person being distant from the truth. And «شَیْطَان» is used for every rebellious and disobedient being that has become distant from the truth due to its arrogance and disobedience (among jinn). Among them, some are good and righteous, while others are evil, harmful, and ill-natured. The second type is called Satan (as in Surah Al-Hijr, verse 27). Then this term began to be applied to every arrogant and disobedient being, whether human, jinn, or any animal. Similarly, a snake is called «جِنّ» and «جَانّ» due to its characteristic of causing harm (as cited in 'Manjad'). For example, «شَیَاطِیْنُ الْعَرَب» refers to the rebellious and disobedient people of Arabia.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنَا لِکُلِّ نَبِیٍّ عَدُوًّا شَیٰطِیۡنَ الۡاِنۡسِ وَ  الۡجِنِّ» (6/112)\nTranslation: And similarly, We made for every prophet an enemy—devils from among humans and jinn.","«شَیْطَان», rebellious, and harmful jinn or human.","jinni","شیطن","2:14-2:36-2:102-2:168-2:208-2:268-2:275-3:36-3:155-3:175-4:38-4:60-4:76-4:83-4:117-4:119-4:120-5:90-5:91-6:43-6:68-6:71-6:112-6:121-6:142-7:20-7:22-7:27-7:30-7:175-7:200-7:201-8:11-8:48-12:5-12:42-12:100-14:22-15:17-16:63-16:98-17:27-17:53-17:64-18:63-19:44-19:45-19:68-19:83-20:120-21:82-22:3-22:52-22:53-23:97-24:21-25:29-26:210-26:221-27:24-28:15-29:38-31:21-35:6-36:60-37:7-37:65-38:37-38:41-41:36-43:36-43:62-47:25-58:10-58:19-59:16-67:5-81:25",78
1121,236,"J","مَارِد","When a devil reaches the extreme in its rebellion and causing harm, it is called «مَارِدْ» (Quran 15:135).  \nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ  حِفۡظًا مِّنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡطٰنٍ مَّارِدٍ» (37:7)  \nTranslation: And He protected from every rebellious devil.","The Satan who reaches the utmost limit in causing harm, mischief, and rebellion.","jinn","مارد","37:7",1
1122,236,"J","خَنَّاس","«خَنَسَ» means to retreat and shrink, and «خَانِس ، خُنَّس» refers to those stars that, while moving in a straight path, begin to move backward. For example: Saturn, Jupiter, and Mars, etc. «خَنَّاس» is an intensive form, meaning one who always retreats and then advances. By this, the tempting devil is meant, who constantly tempts in this manner to mislead humans at every moment, whether from jinn or humans. For instance, the Holy Quran states: «مِنۡ  شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ  ۬ ۙ الۡخَنَّاسِ . الَّذِیۡ یُوَسۡوِسُ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ النَّاسِ . مِنَ الۡجِنَّۃِ وَ النَّاسِ» (114:4-6). Translation: I seek refuge with the evil of the tempting devil who, upon hearing the name of God, retreats, and who casts evil suggestions into the hearts of people, whether they be from jinn or humans.","«خَنَّاس» the Satan who casts evil suggestions into the heart and mind.","jinn","خناس","114:4",1
1123,236,"J","عِفْرِیْت","«عِفْرِیْت» A very strong, powerful, and tall jinn. (F. L 135)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ عِفۡرِیۡتٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ اَنَا اٰتِیۡکَ بِہٖ قَبۡلَ  اَنۡ  تَقُوۡمَ مِنۡ مَّقَامِکَ» (27/39)\nTranslation: One mighty jinn said, I will bring it to you even before you rise from your place.","«عِفْرِیْت» an extremely strong, powerful, and tall giant.","Jinn","عفریت","27:39",1
1124,237,"P","جَنَّۃٌ","«جَنَّۃٌ» means 'garden'. Its plural is « جَنَّاتٌ ، جَنَّ», meaning 'to cover' or 'conceal'. «جَنَّۃٌ» refers to a garden whose ground is not visible due to trees or crops (detailed explanation).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَیَوَدُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ لَہٗ جَنَّۃٌ مِّنۡ نَّخِیۡلٍ وَّ اَعۡنَابٍ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Would any of you wish to have a garden of date-palms and grapevines?\n\nAnd the words «اَلْجَنَّۃ» and «جَنَّۃ» are used in many places in the Noble Quran for that garden where righteous and pious people will find their abode in the hereafter. Paradise. For example: The Majestic Lord says:\n«وَ بَشِّرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ اَنَّ لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (2/25)\nTranslation: And give glad tidings to those who believe and do righteous deeds that they will have gardens beneath which rivers flow.","«جَنَّۃٌ» meaning garden, commonly used for paradise.","Paradise","جنۃ","2:25-2:35-2:82-2:111-2:214-2:221-2:265-2:266-3:15-3:133-3:136-3:142-3:185-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-4:124-5:12-5:65-5:72-5:85-5:119-6:99-6:141-7:19-7:22-7:27-7:40-7:42-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:49-7:50-9:21-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:9-10:26-11:23-11:108-13:4-13:23-13:35-14:23-15:45-16:31-16:32-17:91-18:31-18:32-18:33-18:35-18:39-18:40-18:107-19:60-19:61-19:63-20:76-20:117-20:121-22:14-22:23-22:56-23:19-25:8-25:10-25:15-25:24-26:57-26:85-26:90-26:134-26:147-29:58-31:8-32:19-34:15-34:16-35:33-36:26-36:34-36:55-37:43-38:50-39:73-39:74-40:8-40:40-41:30-42:7-42:22-43:70-43:72-44:25-44:52-46:14-46:16-47:6-47:12-47:15-48:5-48:17-50:9-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:15-54:54-55:46-55:54-55:62-56:12-56:89-57:12-57:21-58:22-59:20-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:11-68:17-68:34-69:22-70:35-70:38-71:12-74:40-76:12-78:16-79:41-81:13-85:11-88:10-89:30-98:8",143
1125,237,"P","جَنّٰتُ عَدْنٍ","«عَدَنَ» meaning to settle in a place. To take up permanent residence and always remain in that place. As if «جَنّٰتُ عَدْنٍ» there will be gardens that endure for a long time. And the people of Paradise will dwell in them forever.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ  رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (98/8)\nTranslation: Their reward will be eternal gardens with their Lord, beneath which rivers flow.","«جَنّٰتُ عَدْنٍ» the Everlasting Gardens (meaning Paradise).","Paradise","جنت عدنٍ","9:72-13:23-16:31-18:31-19:61-20:76-35:33-38:50-40:8-61:12-98:8",11
1126,237,"P","جَنّٰتُ الْفِرْدَوْس","«فِرْدَوْس» meaning a green valley (Manjad) and «فردوس» meaning a garden situated between large rivers or canals, in which all kinds of fruits and flowers are present. It is as if «جَنّٰتُ الْفِرْدَوْس» refers to lush, densely shaded, and cool gardens, which are fragrant with the scent of flowers and in which all kinds of fruits are abundant. That part of Paradise for which the Noble Prophet (peace be upon him) taught Muslims to pray. «اَللّٰھُمَّ اِنِّیْ اَسْئَلُکَ الْجَنَّۃَ الْفِرْدَوْس» And in the Noble Quran, the commandment of Allah the Most High is: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ کَانَتۡ لَہُمۡ  جَنّٰتُ الۡفِرۡدَوۡسِ نُزُلًا» (18:107) Translation: Indeed, for those who have believed and done righteous deeds, the Gardens of Paradise will be their abode.","«جَنّٰتُ الْفِرْدَوْس» signifies the lush, densely shaded garden with cool breezes—meaning Paradise.","Paradise","جنت الفردوس","18:107-23:11",2
1127,237,"P","جَنّٰتُ النَّعِیْمِ","«نَعْم» meaning provisions of comfort, ease, luxurious living, and a pure life (م ۔ ل), implying that «جَنَّاتُ النَّعِیْم» are such gardens that, in addition to the inherent qualities of a garden, also contain other amenities for comfortable residence.  \nFor example, the Holy Quran states:  \n«اِنَّ  لِلۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ عِنۡدَ رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتِ النَّعِیۡمِ» (68/34)  \nTranslation: For the righteous are blessed gardens with their Lord.","Gardens that, beyond their inherent qualities, also feature other amenities for comfortable living.","Paradise","جنت النعیم","5:65-10:9-22:56-26:85-31:8-37:43-52:17-56:12-56:89-68:34-70:38",11
1128,238,"W","قِتَال","«قَتَل» meaning to kill someone. And «قِتَال» meaning a fight in which the intention is to kill each other. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِتَالُ وَ ہُوَ کُرۡہٌ لَّکُمۡ» (2/216) Translation: Fighting has been prescribed for you, though it is distasteful to you. And sometimes «قِتَال» means «مَقْتَل» or battlefield. The command of Allah is: «وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ» (3/121) Translation: And (remember) when you left your home in the morning to post the believers at their battle stations.","«قِتَال» to intentionally harm one another. War and battlefield.","War","قتال","2:216-2:217-2:246-3:121-3:167-4:77-8:16-8:65-33:25-47:20",10
1129,238,"W","حَرْب","«حَرَبَ» means to take back or seize. And «حَرْبَۃٌ» refers to a spear or lance (as per Munjid). «اَحْرَبَ الْحَرْب» means to incite fighting or to guide someone to loot the enemy's wealth (Munjid). The term «حَرْب» is used in a broader sense than «قِتَال». It encompasses not only fighting but also the concept of acquiring spoils of war. Furthermore, this term covers the entire duration of a conflict, including its causes, consequences, and the affected circumstances.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اَوۡقَدُوۡا  نَارًا لِّلۡحَرۡبِ اَطۡفَاَہَا اللّٰہُ» (5/64)\nTranslation: Whenever they kindle a fire for war, Allah extinguishes it. (Translation by Osmaniؒ)","«حَرْب» waging war and seizing spoils from the enemy.","War","حرب","2:279-5:64-8:57-47:4",4
1130,238,"W","زَحْف","«زَحَفَ» means to crawl or advance slowly on one's knees or belly. And «زَحَفَ الْعَسْکَرُ اِلَی الْعَدُوِّ» means, due to the multitude of an army, to advance gradually toward the enemy. And «اَلزَّحْفُ» refers to a large, advancing army (a massive force). The word (munjadd) is as if the literal meaning of «زَحْفًا» is not to fight or a battlefield, but rather the field of a massive army's gradual advance toward combat. When they become intermingled with each other (M. Q). And «زَحُوْف» and «زَھَافَات» refer to animals that crawl close to the ground or slither, such as snakes, etc.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِذَا لَقِیۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  زَحۡفًا  فَلَا  تُوَلُّوۡہُمُ  الۡاَدۡبَارَ» (8/15)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! When you encounter the disbelievers in battle, do not turn your backs to them.","«زَحْفًا» the slow and steady advance of a large army toward the battlefield.","War","زحف","8:15",1
1131,238,"W","بَأس","The fundamental meaning of «بَأس» is harshness, severity, strength, and aversion. (M.L. Maf.) Whether it is in economic matters, such as tight circumstances and poverty/famine. And generally, the word «بَأسَآء» is used for it, whether in the form of punishment or in battle. The author of 'Manjad' has written the meanings of «بَأس» as courage, bravery, strength, fear, and punishment. And when the word «بَأس» comes for war or the battlefield, it refers to the harshness, severity, and physical harm of fighting.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الصّٰبِرِیۡنَ فِی الۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ  وَ حِیۡنَ الۡبَاۡسِ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And those who remain steadfast in hardship and adversity and during the time of conflict/battle.","«بَأس» the hardships of war and physical injury.","War","بأس","2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14",26
1132,238,"W","جِھَاد","«جِھَاد» means to exert one's utmost effort in a task. And Jihad in the way of Allah is every effort that is made solely for the elevation of Allah's word, abandoning personal motives. And «جِھَاد» is a Shariah term whose application generally comes in the meaning of «جِھَاد بِالسَّیْف», i.e., fighting the disbelievers with the sole aim of elevating Allah's word and religion, abandoning personal motives.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states: «وَ اِذَاۤ اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ اَنۡ اٰمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ وَ جَاہِدُوۡا مَعَ رَسُوۡلِہِ اسۡتَاۡذَنَکَ اُولُوا الطَّوۡلِ مِنۡہُمۡ وَ قَالُوۡا ذَرۡنَا نَکُنۡ مَّعَ الۡقٰعِدِیۡنَ » (9/86). Translation: When a Surah is revealed commanding, 'Believe in Allah and fight alongside His Messenger,' then a group of the wealthy among them comes to you seeking permission, saying, 'Leave us to be among those who remain behind.'","«جِھَاد» Fighting solely for the exaltation of religion, abandoning personal motives and interests.","War","جھاد","2:218-3:142-4:95-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:24-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-47:31-49:15-60:1-61:11-66:9",30
1133,238,"W","غَزٰی","«غَزْوَۃٌ» refers to going out with the intention of fighting the enemy. And a ghazi is one who goes out with that intention. And its plurals are «غُزَاۃٌ» and «غُزٌّ». (Mufradat)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا کَالَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ قَالُوۡا لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ اِذَا ضَرَبُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ کَانُوۡا غُزًّی لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا عِنۡدَنَا مَا مَاتُوۡا وَ مَا قُتِلُوۡا» (3/156)\n\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Do not be like those who disbelieved and said about their brothers when they traveled in the land or fought in the cause of Allah, If they had been with us, they would not have died or been killed.","«غَزٰی» to mobilize for battle against the enemy with the intention of jihad.","War","غزی","3:156",1
1134,239,"T","وَضَعَ","The basic meaning of «وَضَعَ» is to place something down (sing.). «وَضَعْتُ الْحَمْل» means, I lowered the burden and placed it down. When the word «وَضَعَ» is used with «حَمَلَ» and its relation is to a female (matter), its meaning is to give birth to a child. The term wad'u haml (وضع حمل) is general and is also used for animals besides humans. And it is a temporary action.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا وَضَعَتۡہَا قَالَتۡ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ وَضَعۡتُہَاۤ  اُنۡثٰی» (3/36)\nTranslation: Then when she gave birth to a girl, she said, My Lord! Indeed, I have given birth to a female...\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ تَضَعُ کُلُّ ذَاتِ حَمۡلٍ حَمۡلَہَا» (22/2)\nTranslation: And every pregnant one will deliver her child.","«وَضَعَ» is used in the sense of unloading and placing below.","to enter","وضع","3:36-3:96-4:102-7:157-18:49-21:47-22:2-24:58-24:60-35:11-39:69-41:47-46:15-47:4-55:7-55:10-65:4-65:6-94:2",19
1135,239,"J","وَلَدَ","«وَلَدَ» generally pertains to human beings. And lineage is not temporal but eternal. A mother is forever the mother of her child (offspring), but she is not forever in a state of bearing pregnancy. Then, in «وَلَدَ», the meaning is not confined to merely giving birth (procreation), but also encompasses the upbringing (nurturing) of the child (the one being born). And «وَلَدَ الولد» means 'He raised the child' (i.e., provided its nurture and upbringing).\n\nFor example: The Quran states: Pharaoh, addressing Moses (peace be upon him), said:\n«قَالَ اَلَمۡ نُرَبِّکَ فِیۡنَا وَلِیۡدًا وَّ لَبِثۡتَ فِیۡنَا مِنۡ عُمُرِکَ سِنِیۡنَ» (26/18)\nTranslation: Pharaoh said, Did we not raise you among us as a child? And did you not spend many years of your life among us?","«وَلَدَ» is generally used for children.","Jinn","ولد","2:116-2:233-3:47-4:11-4:12-4:171-4:176-6:101-10:68-12:21-17:111-18:4-18:39-19:15-19:33-19:35-19:77-19:88-19:91-19:92-21:26-23:91-25:2-26:18-28:9-31:33-37:152-39:4-43:81-58:2-71:21-71:26-72:3-90:3-112:3",35
1136,240,"A","اَجَابَ","«اَجَابَ» is the opposite of «سَاَلَ». And «سَاَلَ» means to question, and it also includes asking for something and inquiring about something. Similarly, «اَجَابَ» also means to answer a question. And if something is requested, it also means to accept or give it. Here, answering a question is under discussion.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» ( 5/109 )\nTranslation: On that Day, Allah will gather the messengers together, then He will ask: What response did you receive?","«اَجَابَ» to answer a question","Answer","اجاب","5:109-28:65",2
1137,240,"A","رَجَعَ","The basic meaning of «رَجَعَ» is to turn back, return, or revert. And «اَلْرَجْعُ» (as a verbal noun) means to reply to a letter (Munjid). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِذۡہَبۡ بِّکِتٰبِیۡ ہٰذَا فَاَلۡقِہۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ ثُمَّ تَوَلَّ عَنۡہُمۡ فَانۡظُرۡ  مَا ذَا یَرۡجِعُوۡنَ» (27/28). Translation: Take my letter and deliver it to them, then withdraw, and see how they respond.","«رَجَعَ» reply to the letter","Answer","رجع","2:18-2:28-2:196-2:210-2:245-2:281-3:55-3:72-3:83-3:109-5:48-5:105-6:36-6:60-6:108-6:164-7:150-7:168-7:174-8:44-9:83-9:94-9:122-10:4-10:23-10:46-10:56-10:70-11:4-11:34-11:123-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:81-19:40-20:40-20:86-20:89-20:91-21:13-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:95-22:76-23:99-23:115-24:28-24:64-27:28-27:35-27:37-28:39-28:70-28:88-29:8-29:17-29:57-30:11-30:41-31:15-31:23-32:11-32:12-32:21-33:13-34:31-35:4-36:22-36:31-36:50-36:67-36:83-37:68-39:7-39:44-40:77-41:21-41:50-43:28-43:48-43:85-45:15-46:27-50:3-56:87-57:5-57:13-60:10-63:8-67:3-67:4-86:8-86:11-89:28-96:8",98
1138,240,"A","اَفْتٰی","«اَفْتٰی» means to provide an answer to a difficult and complex issue, whether the issue is religious or related to worldly matters. And «فتوٰی» is also a religious term meaning to seek the answer to a complex issue from a scholar. And «اِسْتِفْتَاء» means to request an answer for such an issue.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَسۡتَفۡتُوۡنَکَ ؕ قُلِ اللّٰہُ یُفۡتِیۡکُمۡ فِی الۡکَلٰلَۃِ» ( 4/176 )\nTranslation: People ask you for a ruling. Say, Allah gives you a ruling concerning kalalah.","«اَفْتٰی» to answer a difficult and complex issue. To issue a fatwa.","Answer","افتی","4:127-4:176-12:43-12:46-27:32",5
1139,241,"Y","حَلَمَ","«حُلُمًا» signifies a boy attaining puberty (i.e., reaching maturity), and «حُلُم» refers to having intercourse in a dream (wet dream). Thus, when a boy experiences his first seminal emission, this stage is termed «حُلُم» or the age of puberty—meaning the onset of youth.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذَا بَلَغَ  الۡاَطۡفَالُ مِنۡکُمُ الۡحُلُمَ فَلۡیَسۡتَاۡذِنُوۡا کَمَا اسۡتَاۡذَنَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ» (24:59).  \nTranslation: And when your boys reach maturity, they should seek permission [to enter], just as those before them [the elders] do.","«حَلَمَ» meaning a boy reaching adulthood, maturing.","youth","حلم","24:58-24:59",2
1140,241,"Y","اَشُدَّ","«اَشَدَّ» means reaching maturity in intellect or age (manjada), and this is approximately middle age—full youth, after which the signs of old age begin. For example, the Holy Quran states: «حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا بَلَغَ  اَشُدَّہٗ  وَ بَلَغَ  اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ سَنَۃً» (46/15), meaning: Until when he becomes fully grown and reaches forty years.","«اَشُدَّ» meaning to attain maturity in intellect or age.","Youth","اشد","6:152-12:22-17:34-18:82-22:5-28:14-40:67-46:15",8
1141,242,"P","زَوَّجَ","The meanings of «زَوَّجَ» are very extensive. «زَوْج» means (1) wife or female (woman, feminine), (2) husband or male (man, masculine), and (3) a husband and wife or male and female (masculine and feminine) together also constitute one pair. Moreover, the union of male and female or husband and wife is termed a pair. And contrary to «نَکَحَ», «زَوَّجَ» is also applied to everything in which the existence or consciousness of male and female is found, such as plants (i.e., things that grow from the earth—grass, shrubs, plants, vegetables, crops) and so forth.\n\nNow, the pair has two parts. One, the male entities, are referred to as «ذَکَر» (plural) «ذُکُوْر» and «ذُکْرَان»; the other, the female, are called «اُنْثٰی» (plural) «اُنَاث». Furthermore, for «زَوَّجَ», it is not necessary that their union be sexual; rather, the term is applied even when simply one male and one female are distinguished or set apart.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states: «یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ  لِمَنۡ  یَّشَآءُ   الذُّکُوۡرَ اَوۡ یُزَوِّجُہُمۡ ذُکۡرَانًا وَّ اِنَاثًا» (42:49-50) Translation: He grants whom He wills daughters, and whom He wills sons, or grants them both sons and daughters.","«زَوَّجَ» In a couple consisting of a man and a woman, each is called the spouse of the other.","Pair","زوج","2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7",72
1142,242,"P","شَفْعُ","«شَفْعُ» is applied to things in which the distinction between male and female is not made. And «شَفْعُ» means to pair one thing with another similar to it, and a paired thing is called «شَفْعٌ», while that with which no similar other thing exists is called «وَتْر». In numbers, those integers that are completely divisible by two, such as: two, four, six, eight, etc., are called «شَفْعُ» or «جُفْت». And the number that is not completely divisible by two is called watr or taq, such as: one, three, five, seven, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ الۡفَجۡرِ وَ  لَیَالٍ عَشۡرٍ وَّ الشَّفۡعِ وَ الۡوَتۡرِ» (89/1,2,3)\nTranslation: By the dawn and ten nights and the even and the odd.\n\nAnd «شَفَعَ» means to make a pair of such things. This word does not appear in the Quran. However, «شَفَعَ» does appear in the meanings of recommending or interceding.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مَنۡ ذَا الَّذِیۡ یَشۡفَعُ  عِنۡدَہٗۤ  اِلَّا بِاِذۡنِہٖ» (2/255)\nTranslation: Who is it that can intercede with Him except by His permission?","«شَفْعُ» meaning to mix one thing with another similar thing.","pair","شفع","89:3",1
1143,243,"T","وَصَلَ","«وَصَلَ» means to mix and to join. From the perspective of mixing, its opposite is «فَصَلَ». From the perspective of joining, its opposite is «قَطَعَ». The meaning of «وَصَلَ» is to blend one thing with another in such a way that they become inseparably connected. This word is used separately in both of these meanings. It is also employed in both literal and metaphorical contexts within the Quran.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27)\nTranslation: And they break the bond which Allah has commanded to be upheld.","«وَصَلَ» meaning to mix and join.","to join","وصل","2:27-13:21-13:25",3
1144,243,"T","خَصَفَ","«خَصَفْ» refers to that piece of leather (or form or die) on which leather is placed to cut the size for new shoes (muf). And «خَصَفَ» means shoemaking, repairing shoes. And «خَصَفَ الشَّیءُ عَلَی الشَّیء» means to join and stick one thing onto another (minjad). For example: In the Quran it is: «بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/22) Translation: So the private parts of Adam and Eve became visible to them. Then they began to sew leaves of Paradise together.","«خَصَفَ» meaning to join and to stick.","to join","خصف","7:22-20:121",2
1145,243,"T","رَصَّ","«رَصَّ» means to merge one thing with another, to adhere, to join (in the sense of 'minjad'), and also means to combine two things together (in the sense of 'muf'). Furthermore, «رَصَّهُ » means to plate with lead (i.e., to apply a coating on vessels, to whiten, to varnish, to polish). And «رَصَاص» means lead (minjad), i.e., the meaning of «رَصَّ» is to strengthen something by mixing it with a substance like a seasoning, etc.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» ( 61/4 )\nTranslation: Allah Almighty loves those who fight in His cause in solid ranks, as if they were a solid structure cemented together.","«رَصَّ» To combine two things and bind them with seasonings, etc.","to join","رص","61:4",1
1146,244,"W","حَیْثُ","«حَیْثُ» means (where, wherever) and is used for an ambiguous/vague location (i.e., hidden, concealed, unknown), and its interpretation and clarification come from the subsequent sentence.  \nFor example: In the Quran:  \n«وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ» (2/149)  \nTranslation: And wherever you go out from, turn your faces toward the Sacred Mosque (when praying).","«حَیْثُ» means (where, where)","where","حیث","2:35-2:58-2:144-2:149-2:150-2:191-2:199-2:222-4:89-4:91-6:124-7:19-7:27-7:161-7:182-9:5-12:56-12:68-15:65-16:26-16:45-20:69-38:36-39:25-39:74-59:2-65:3-65:6-68:44",29
1147,244,"W","حَیْثُمَا","«حَیْثُمَا» its meaning is (wherever). «مَا» is added only for breadth in meanings.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ مِنۡ حَیۡثُ خَرَجۡتَ فَوَلِّ وَجۡہَکَ شَطۡرَ» (2/149)  \nTranslation: And wherever you may be, turn your faces toward it (the Sacred Mosque).","«حَیْثُمَا» means 'wherever'.","where","حیثما","2:149",1
1148,244,"W","اَیْنَمَا","«اَیْن» means where. It is used to inquire about a location. And «اَیْنَمَا» means any place, such that «اَیْنَمَا» and «حَیْثُمَا» become synonymous. However, in «اَیْنَمَا», the meaning of condition is also found (in Munjad Maq).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَیۡنَمَا ثُقِفُوۡۤا اُخِذُوۡا وَ قُتِّلُوۡا  تَقۡتِیۡلًا» (33/61)\nTranslation: Wherever they are found, they will be seized and killed.","«اَیْنَمَا» meaning 'where.' It is used to ask questions about a place.","Where","اینما","2:115-2:148-3:112-4:78-6:22-7:37-16:27-16:76-19:31-26:92-28:62-28:74-33:61-40:73-41:47-57:4-58:7-75:10-81:26",19
1149,245,"T","زَجَرَ","To admonish someone in a raised voice. To rebuke. To chide. To scold. And «زَجْرَۃٌ», meaning a reprimand.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَالزّٰجِرٰتِ  زَجۡرًا» (37/2)\nTranslation: Then (I swear) by the reprimanding angels.","«زَجَرَ» to scold. to rebuke.","to admonish","زجر","37:2-37:19-79:13",3
1150,245,"T","اِزْدَجَرَ","«اِزْدَجَرَ» meaning to drive someone away by scolding or rebuking (singular). For example, in the Quran it is: «کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ فَکَذَّبُوۡا عَبۡدَنَا وَ قَالُوۡا مَجۡنُوۡنٌ وَّ ازۡدُجِرَ» (54/9) Translation: Before them, the people of Noah had also denied Our servant and, after calling him a madman, had driven him away with scolding.","«اِزْدَجَرَ» to forcefully expel, to drive out.","to admonish","ازدجر","54:4-54:9",2
1151,245,"T","نَھَرَ","«نَھَرَ» means the forceful flow of a liquid. And «نَھَرَ السَّائِل» means to push the liquid and to take strict action in pushing, scolding, and reprimanding. (Manjad) «اَلزَّجْرُ الْغَلِیْظ» (muf. f.l 188)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَمَّا السَّآئِلَ  فَلَا تَنۡہَرۡ» (93/10)\nTranslation: And do not push the liquid.","«نَھَرَ» to reprimand harshly.","to scold","نھر","17:23-93:10",2
1152,246,"T","جَنَحَ","«جَنَحَ» means to incline toward one side. «جَنَحَتِ السَّفِیْنَۃ» means the tilting of a ship to one side. And «جَنَاح» means a bird's wing, a person's side, and its dual form is «جَنَاحَیْن». «جَنَاحَ» means inclination toward goodness (virtue), and «جُنَاح» is used for inclination toward evil (sin).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ جَنَحُوۡا لِلسَّلۡمِ فَاجۡنَحۡ لَہَا» (8/61)\nTranslation: And if these people incline toward peace, then you too incline toward it.","«جَنَحَ» the natural inclination towards good deeds.","to bend","جنح","8:61",1
1153,246,"T","مَالَ","«اَلْمَیْل» means natural inclination, i.e., the nature's tendency. Raghbat (Munajjad) means the leaning of one's nature. To be naturally inclined towards something or someone.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَنۡ تَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡۤا اَنۡ تَعۡدِلُوۡا بَیۡنَ النِّسَآءِ وَ لَوۡ حَرَصۡتُمۡ فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ» (4/129)\nTranslation: And you will never be able to do justice between women, no matter how much you desire to. So do not incline entirely towards one.","«مَالَ» to have a natural inclination toward something.","to bow","مال","4:27-4:129",2
1154,246,"T","عَنَا یَعْنَوْا","«عَنَا» means to be humble or lowly. To be obedient. And «عَنَا یَعْنِیْ» means to endure hardship. And «عَنِیَ یَعْنٰی» means to become weary (exhausted). Thus, «عَنَا یَعْنِیْ» conveys the meaning of bowing down due to humiliation, weariness, or being overcome by hardship.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَنَتِ الۡوُجُوۡہُ  لِلۡحَیِّ الۡقَیُّوۡمِ» (20:111)\nTranslation: All faces will be humbly bowed before the Ever-Living, Ever-Enduring, and All-Governor Allah.","to bend over from exhaustion","to bend / to bow (in prayer)","عنا یعنوا","20:111",1
1155,246,"T","صَغَا یَصْفَوْا","«صَغَا» means to incline completely. «صَغَتِ النُّجُوْمُ وَالشَّمْسُ» means to incline toward the setting of the sun or stars (مف ۔ منجد), and «صَغَیْتُ الْاِنَاءَ» means to tilt a vessel so that something comes out, and «اَصْغٰیٓ اِلَیْہِ» means to start inclining one's ear or to lend an ear (م ۔ م).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِنۡ تَتُوۡبَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  فَقَدۡ صَغَتۡ قُلُوۡبُکُمَا» (66/4). Translation: (O wives of the Prophet) if you both repent to Allah, it is appropriate, for your hearts have inclined.","«صَغَا» is used for full or more tilt.","to bow","صغا یصفوا","6:113-66:4",2
1156,246,"T","رَکَنَ","«رُکن» means strength, dominance, fortress, and a firm ground. And «رَکَنَ» means to place one's trust in someone and to incline toward them from whom strength is acquired. (Majid)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَنۡ ثَبَّتۡنٰکَ لَقَدۡ کِدۡتَّ تَرۡکَنُ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  شَیۡئًا  قَلِیۡلًا» (17/74)\nTranslation: And if We had not strengthened you, you would have almost inclined toward them a little.","Inclining toward something to obtain strength or refuge.","to bow","رکن","11:80-11:113-17:74",3
1157,246,"T","مَادَ","«مَادَ» meaning: to tilt due to movement in something; to shake and lean in any direction (m. l) to move, to shake, to tremble (minjadd).  \n«مَادَتِ الغَّصْن» meaning: a branch that has tilted (minjadd).  \nFor example: It is stated in the Holy Quran:  \n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ اَنۡ  تَمِیۡدَ بِہِمۡ» (21/31)  \nTranslation: And We have placed firm mountains on the earth, lest it should sway with them...","to stagger or sway due to movement or weight","to incline","ماد","16:15-21:31-31:10",3
1158,246,"T","خَشَعَ","«خَشَعَ» refers to bowing or lowering oneself due to humility. It is a state of awe whose effects become apparent on each physical faculty. This generally applies to the lowering of the eyes, face, voice, and heart, and it also includes an element of reverent fear.\n\nFor example, regarding the voice, the Quran states:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ» (20/108)\nTranslation: And voices will be lowered before Allah.\n\nFor example, regarding the eyes, the Quran states:\n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ  ذِلَّۃٌ» (70/44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be downcast, and humiliation will cover them.","«خَشَعَ» Bowing in fear and humility, with its effect manifest in the limbs and faculties.","to bend","خشع","2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2",15
1159,246,"T","ذَلَّ","«ذَلَّ» meaning to bend due to force, oppression, and pressure. To be humiliated (intransitive), and its opposite is «عَزَّ». The spontaneous overcoming of natural intensity and harshness (intransitive).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ دَانِیَۃً  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ظِلٰلُہَا وَ ذُلِّلَتۡ قُطُوۡفُہَا تَذۡلِیۡلًا» (76:14)\nTranslation: They will be close to them (with fruit-bearing branches), and bunches of fruit will be hanging down, bent low.","«ذَلَّ» to incline due to pressure.","to incline","ذل","2:61-3:26-3:112-3:123-5:54-7:152-10:26-10:27-11:27-16:70-17:24-17:111-20:134-22:5-26:111-27:34-27:37-36:72-42:45-58:20-63:8-67:15-68:43-70:44-76:14",25
1160,246,"T","عَالَ","«عَول» means to commit injustice; to deviate from the straight path (manjadd). «اَلْعَوْل» is used for anything that overwhelms a person and crushes them under its burden (muf). It refers to a bias in which someone's rights are violated.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا فَوَاحِدَۃً اَوۡ مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَلَّا تَعُوۡلُوۡا» (4/3)  \nTranslation: If you fear that you will not be able to deal justly with all women, then one (woman) is sufficient. Or a slave woman whom you own. This (is) so that you do not deviate (to one side). (Othmaniؒ)","«عَالَ» An inclination that violates the rights of others.","to bow","عال","4:3-10:83-23:46-44:31",4
1161,246,"T","دَنٰی","«دَنٰی» means to be near, to be close. And if its relation is toward something elevated, it will convey the meaning of bending to be near.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ  جَنَا  الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ  دَانٍ» (55/54)  \nTranslation: And the ripe fruits of both gardens will be hanging low (i.e., will be close to the ground).","«دَنٰی» to incline and draw near.","to incline; to bend; to turn (toward)","دنی","2:282-4:3-5:108-6:99-30:3-33:51-33:59-53:8-53:9-55:54-69:23-73:20-76:14",13
1162,246,"T","جَنَفَ","«جَنَفَ» meaning to show bias, to take sides, to incline toward one party.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:  \n«فَمَنۡ خَافَ مِنۡ مُّوۡصٍ جَنَفًا اَوۡ اِثۡمًا» (2/182)  \nTranslation: Then whoever fears bias or injustice from the testator.","«جَنَفَ» to incline due to bias.","to bow","جنف","2:182",1
1163,246,"T","صَبَا","«صَبُو ، صَبِیٌّ» means child or small boy, and its plural forms are « صِبْیَان» and «صَبَا», which convey the meaning of being inclined toward childlike actions. And «تَصَبِّی» means to be inclined toward play (rational). Thus, «صَبَاءَ» refers to such an inclination that arises due to childhood.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran, Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) said: «وَ اِلَّا تَصۡرِفۡ عَنِّیۡ کَیۡدَہُنَّ اَصۡبُ  اِلَیۡہِنَّ» (12/33). Translation: O Allah, if You do not remove from me the deceit of these women, I will incline toward them.","«صَبَا» to incline toward childish and improper actions, to be prone to child-like behaviors.","to bow","صبا","12:33",1
1164,247,"T","خَفَضَ","«خَفَضَ» means to lower or humble, and its opposite «رَفَعَ» means to raise or exalt. «خَفَضَ» is used in both literal and spiritual senses. «خَافِضُ» and «رَافِعُ» are also names of the attributes of Allah Almighty.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24)\nTranslation: And lower yourself to them with humility out of affection.","«خَفَضَ» is used for lowering or reducing.","to bow","خفض","15:88-17:24-26:215-56:3",4
1165,247,"R","غَضَّ","«غَضَّ» is specifically for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice (e.g.). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «قُلۡ لِّلۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ یَغُضُّوۡا مِنۡ  اَبۡصَارِہِمۡ» (24/30) Translation: Tell the believing men to lower their gaze.","«غَضَّ» is used for lowering the gaze or reducing the voice.","ruku' (the bowing position in Islamic prayer)","غض","24:30-24:31-31:19-49:3",4
1166,247,"T","رَکَعَ","«رَکَعَ» meaning to bow the body, lower the head, and bend the waist. Figuratively, it means performing prayer. For example: In the Quran it says: «وَ  اِذَا قِیۡلَ لَہُمُ  ارۡکَعُوۡا  لَا  یَرۡکَعُوۡنَ» (77/48) Translation: And when it is said to them, Bow down (before Allah), they do not bow down.","«رَکَعَ» (Ruku') means to bend the back, lowering the body into the bowing position.","to bow","رکع","2:43-2:125-3:43-22:26-22:77-48:29-77:48",7
1167,247,"R","نَکَسَ","Nakasa means to turn upside down (invert). And «نَکَسَ رَأْسَہٗ» means to bow one's head. To be humbled. To lower one's head out of shame and remorse. And «تَنَکَّسَ الْعَلَم» means the flag being bowed (humbled). And «اِنْتَکَسَ» means to fall prostrate on one's face. And «نَکَسَ عَلٰی رَاْسِہٖ» is an idiom meaning to become speechless and lower one's head in shame.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  نُکِسُوۡا عَلٰی  رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ ۚ لَقَدۡ  عَلِمۡتَ مَا ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  یَنۡطِقُوۡنَ» (21:65)\nTranslation: Then, (out of shame,) he lowered his head. (Despite this, they began to say to Abraham, You know very well that these [idols] do not speak.)","نَکَسَ meaning to turn upside down (reverse).","Ruku","نکس","21:65-36:68",2
1168,248,"T","شَجَرَ","«شَجَرَ» To argue and dispute (detailed), to discuss, to differ in opinion (as cited) – to argue based on a difference of opinion while the parties agree on the fundamental principles, and the dispute is of a subsidiary nature (minor issues, trivial matters).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is: «فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی  یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ» (4/65) Translation: By your Lord! They will not believe until they make you a judge in their disputes.","«شَجَرَ» to disagree.","to dispute","شجر","4:65",1
1169,248,"T","تَنَازَعَ","«تَنَازَعَ» means to differ and pull to one's side (manjada), and «نَزَع» means to pull something from its place of residence, i.e., its abode; to stretch the pulling; to prolong a dispute (maf).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَاِنۡ تَنَازَعۡتُمۡ فِیۡ شَیۡءٍ فَرُدُّوۡہُ اِلَی اللّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (4/59)  \nTranslation: So if you differ in any matter, refer it to Allah and His Messenger.","«تَنَازَعَ» to drag out a disagreement.","to dispute","تنازع","3:152-4:59-8:43-8:46-18:21-20:62-52:23",7
1170,248,"T","حَاجَّ","«حَجَّ» meaning to prevail in an argument. And «حُجَّۃٌ» meaning argument. And «اِحْتَجَّ» meaning to present proof for one's claim (as in the dictionary). That is, «حَاجّ» refers to debating with evidence and refuting another's statement with proof.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ تَرَ اِلَی الَّذِیۡ حَآجَّ اِبۡرٰہٖمَ فِیۡ رَبِّہٖۤ» (2:258)\nTranslation: Have you not considered the one who argued with Abraham about his Lord...?","To argue on the basis of «حَاجَّ».","to argue / to dispute","حاج","2:76-2:139-2:258-3:20-3:61-3:65-3:66-3:73-6:80-40:47-42:16",11
1171,248,"T","جَدَلَ","To try to gain the upper hand over the other in conversation, to repeat unnecessarily (intransitive). And «جَدَلَ» means to push down and throw to the ground (transitive) and to argue in the form of question and answer (interrogative). According to the author of *Maqayis al-Lughah*, prolonging an argument gives it length (prolonged).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«یُجَادِلُوۡنَکَ فِی الۡحَقِّ بَعۡدَ مَا تَبَیَّنَ» (8/6)\nTranslation: They used to argue with you concerning the truth while it was evident.","«جَدَلَ» trying to gain dominance over each other in conversation.","to dispute","جدل","4:107-4:109-6:25-6:121-7:71-8:6-11:32-11:74-13:13-16:111-16:125-18:54-18:56-22:3-22:8-22:68-29:46-31:20-40:4-40:5-40:35-40:56-40:69-42:35-43:58-58:1",26
1172,248,"T","مَارَ","«مِرْیَۃ» means doubt and hesitation. And «مَارَ» means to argue about something whose acceptance is doubtful. (Example)\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَا کَذَبَ الۡفُؤَادُ ی مَا  رَاٰی اَفَتُمٰرُوۡنَہٗ  عَلٰی مَا یَرٰی» (53/11,12)\nTranslation: What he (Muhammad ﷺ) saw, his heart did not deny as false. Do you then argue with them about what they see?","To argue about «مَارَ» when one is hesitant to accept it.","to argue","مار","18:22-42:18-53:12-53:55-54:36",5
1173,248,"T","خَصْم","«خَصْم» means claimant. The plaintiff (the one making the claim) and the defendant (the one against whom the claim is made), or either one of them. The opposing party. Whether an individual or a group. Such a dispute or case in which the rights of the parties are under discussion. And «اَخْصَمَ» means to provide evidence against someone. To present proof (source: Minjd).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ» (38/21)\nTranslation: Have the news of those litigants reached you? (Jalandhari)\nAnd: And the news of the claimants has reached you. (Usmani ؒ)","«خَصْم» arguing with others based on a claim to something.","to dispute","خصم","2:204-3:44-22:19-26:96-27:45-36:49-38:21-38:22-38:69-39:31-43:18-43:58-50:28",13
1174,248,"T","لَدّ","«لَدّ» meaning «شدّۃ الخصومۃ» meaning a severe quarrel. (F. L 48) And «اَلَدّ» meaning a severely quarrelsome person. One who considers the words of others as suitable and worthy of attention, yet creates a clamor for his own argument.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یُشۡہِدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی مَا فِیۡ  قَلۡبِہٖ  ۙ وَ ہُوَ  اَلَدُّ  الۡخِصَامِ» (2/204)\nTranslation: And he makes Allah a witness against his inner conscience (the matter of the heart) while he is a severe quarrelsome person.","«لَدّ» meaning severe dispute.","to dispute","لد","2:204-19:97",2
1175,248,"T","تَشَاکَسَ","«اَلشِّکْس» means a person of bad character. And «تَشَاکَسَ» means to quarrel with one another due to bad character (metaphorically). And «شَکَسَ» means to be of harsh character and stingy (literally). Thus, «تَشَاکَسَ» essentially means, due to stinginess, sharp temperament, and bad character, to tug and pull with one another over one's respective rights.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ضَرَبَ اللّٰہُ  مَثَلًا رَّجُلًا فِیۡہِ  شُرَکَآءُ مُتَشٰکِسُوۡنَ وَ رَجُلًا سَلَمًا  لِّرَجُلٍ ؕ ہَلۡ  یَسۡتَوِیٰنِ مَثَلًا» (39:29)\nTranslation: Allah puts forth a parable: (Consider) a slave who is owned by many partners who dispute with one another, and (consider) another slave who is owned entirely by a single man. Can these two be equal in condition?","«تَشَاکَسَ» Quarreling with one another over one's rights due to ill nature and greed.","to argue","تشاکس","39:29",1
1176,249,"F","کِذْب","«کِذْب» refers to deliberately conveying false information (manjūd), the discordance (lack of conformity) between the heart and tongue (muf), or speaking against the truth. Its opposite is «صِدْق». For example, the Quran states: «وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ الۡکَذِبَ وَ ہُمۡ  یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (3:78) Translation: And they speak falsehood concerning Allah, while they know.","«کِذْب» falsehood.","Falsehood","کذب","3:75-3:78-3:94-4:50-5:41-5:42-5:70-5:103-6:21-6:24-6:93-6:144-7:37-7:89-10:60-10:69-11:18-12:18-12:110-16:105-16:116-18:5-18:15-20:61-23:38-29:68-34:8-39:32-39:60-42:24-53:11-56:2-58:14-61:7-72:5-78:35",36
1177,249,"L","بَاطِل","«بَاطِل» means every such thing which, upon investigation, is found to lack firmness and permanence. Unjust, baseless, futile, and frivolous talk (manjid) and its opposite is «حَقّ». It means truth, reality, and authenticity. Thus, the word bāṭil (falsehood) is used in a broad sense, one meaning of which is also a lie or falsehood.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لِمَ تَلۡبِسُوۡنَ الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» (3:71)\nTranslation: O People of the Book, why do you mix truth with falsehood?","«بَاطِل» The phrase unstable and baseless talk carries very broad connotations, one category of which is falsehood.","Lie","باطل","2:42-2:188-3:71-3:191-4:29-4:161-7:139-8:8-9:34-11:16-13:17-16:72-17:81-18:56-21:18-22:62-29:52-29:67-31:30-34:49-38:27-40:5-41:42-42:24-47:3",25
1178,249,"F","زُوْرُ","«زَوْرُ» means the slant and crookedness of the upper part of the chest. And «زُوْر» means falsehood against the truth and committing shirk (associating partners) with Allah (manjada). And «زَاوَرَ» means to deviate from the path of truth; to stray off the straight path.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ» (18/17)\nTranslation: And when the sun rose, you would see it [i.e., the shade] shrinking away from their cave to the right.\n\nAnd in contrast to «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر», the words «قَوْلًا سَدِیْدًا» appear in the Quran. That is, [a statement] in which there is no defect, ambiguity, confusion, or complexity. And «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر» is a [statement] in which these things, or any one of them, is present. And according to Abu Hala al-Askari, «زُوْر» is a falsehood that is fabricated and presented so that it appears good and correct. (Faql 34)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاجۡتَنِبُوا الرِّجۡسَ مِنَ الۡاَوۡثَانِ وَ اجۡتَنِبُوۡا  قَوۡلَ  الزُّوۡرِ» (22/30)\nTranslation: So avoid the filth of idols and avoid false speech.","«زُوْرُ» meaning falsehood against the truth and associating partners with Allah.","Falsehood","زور","18:17-22:30-25:4-25:72-58:2",5
1179,249,"F","اِفْک","«اَفَکَ» means to turn away from the original direction with malicious intent, i.e., to take a statement and completely twist its meaning. To fabricate lies. To accuse. To slander. And this is the worst type of lie. According to the scholar of linguistic distinctions (Ibn Faris), this specific lie relates to the accusation of a heinous, obscene act such as adultery (Furqan al-Lughawiyyah, 33).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«لَوۡ لَاۤ اِذۡ سَمِعۡتُمُوۡہُ  ظَنَّ الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتُ بِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ خَیۡرًا ۙ وَّ قَالُوۡا ہٰذَاۤ  اِفۡکٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (24/12)\n\nTranslation: Why did you not, when you heard it, think well of your fellow believers—men and women—and say, 'This is a clear calamity'?","«اِفْک» To twist something into something else with malicious intent, and it also involves slander.","falsehood","افک","7:117-24:11-24:12-25:4-26:45-29:17-34:43-37:151-46:11-46:22-46:28-51:9",12
1180,249,"F","کَذَبَ","«کَذَبَ» To deliberately give news contrary to the facts.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ  اِنۡ  کَانَ  قَمِیۡصُہٗ  قُدَّ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ فَکَذَبَتۡ  وَ ہُوَ  مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (12/27)\nTranslation: But if his shirt is torn from the back, then she has lied, and he is of the truthful.","«کَذَبَ» false statement or lying.","Falsehood","کذب","2:10-3:61-6:28-7:66-9:42-9:43-9:77-9:90-9:107-11:27-11:93-12:26-12:27-12:74-16:39-16:62-16:86-16:105-23:90-24:7-24:8-24:13-26:186-26:223-27:27-28:38-29:3-29:12-36:15-37:152-38:4-39:3-40:24-40:28-40:37-54:25-54:26-58:18-59:11-63:1-96:16",41
1181,249,"L","اَفَکَ","«اَفَکَ» To turn the direction of something; to distort a statement with malicious intent, turning it into something else, as mentioned above, and this is the worst kind of lie.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہَلۡ اُنَبِّئُکُمۡ عَلٰی مَنۡ تَنَزَّلُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ تَنَزَّلُ عَلٰی کُلِّ  اَفَّاکٍ  اَثِیۡمٍ» (26/221,222)\nTranslation: (Well) shall I tell you upon whom the devils descend? They descend upon every sinful liar.","«اَفَکَ» to falsely accuse someone; to slander someone.","Lie","افک","26:222-45:7",2
1182,249,"F","تَقَوَّلَ","«تَقَوَّل» To say something that has no basis in reality; to falsely attribute a lie to someone (mansuj/fabricated).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ تَقَوَّلَ عَلَیۡنَا بَعۡضَ الۡاَقَاوِیۡلِ لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ  بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ  لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ  الۡوَتِیۡنَ» (69/44,45,46)\nTranslation: If this Prophet were to invent any lies against Us, We would seize him by his right hand, then cut off his aorta.","«تَقَوَّل» To utter something that has no basis in reality; to falsely accuse someone.","falsehood","تقول","2:80-2:104-2:140-2:154-2:169-6:93-6:156-6:157-7:28-7:33-7:172-7:173-10:68-10:77-16:116-17:40-20:94-24:15-39:56-39:57-39:58-52:33-61:2-61:3-69:44-72:5",26
1183,250,"T","کَذَّبَ","«کَذّبَ» means to accuse someone of falsehood; it is a well-known term. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنۡ کَذَّبُوۡکَ فَقَدۡ کُذِّبَ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ» (3/184). Translation: So if they have denied you, then indeed before you, messengers were also denied.","«کَذّبَ» is used merely to deny something.","to deny","کذب","2:39-2:87-3:11-3:137-3:184-5:10-5:70-5:86-6:5-6:11-6:21-6:27-6:31-6:33-6:34-6:39-6:49-6:57-6:66-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:157-7:36-7:37-7:40-7:64-7:72-7:92-7:96-7:101-7:136-7:146-7:147-7:176-7:177-7:182-8:54-10:17-10:39-10:41-10:45-10:73-10:74-10:95-15:80-16:36-16:113-17:59-20:48-20:56-21:77-22:42-22:44-22:57-23:26-23:33-23:39-23:44-23:48-23:105-25:11-25:19-25:36-25:37-25:77-26:6-26:12-26:105-26:117-26:123-26:139-26:141-26:160-26:176-26:189-27:83-27:84-28:34-29:18-29:37-30:10-30:16-32:20-34:42-34:45-35:4-35:25-36:14-37:21-37:127-38:12-38:14-39:25-39:32-39:59-40:5-40:70-43:25-50:5-50:12-50:14-52:11-52:14-54:3-54:9-54:18-54:23-54:33-54:42-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:43-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77-56:51-56:82-56:92-57:19-62:5-64:10-67:9-67:18-68:8-68:44-69:4-69:49-73:11-74:46-75:32-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:29-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-78:28-79:21-82:9-83:10-83:11-83:12-83:17-84:22-91:11-91:14-92:9-92:16-95:7-96:13-107:1",183
1184,250,"T","اَبْطَلَ","«بَاطِل» means unjust and transient, and its opposite is «حَقْ». Just as truth (ḥaqq) has the meaning of truth itself, falsehood (bāṭil) likewise has the meaning of falsehood. Moreover, «اَبْطَلَ» refers to denying something on the basis of circumstances and events or proving it to be false.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «لِیُحِقَّ الۡحَقَّ وَ یُبۡطِلَ الۡبَاطِلَ وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ الۡمُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» (8:8). Translation: So that Allah may establish the truth and falsify the falsehood, even if the criminals (polytheists) dislike it.","«اَبْطَلَ» is used to disprove a claim or action using evidence, experiments, and observations.","to deny","ابطل","2:264-7:118-7:173-8:8-10:81-29:48-30:58-40:78-45:27-47:33",10
1185,251,"M","مَقَالِيد","«قَلَدَ» means to thin iron and to bend it or to bend it and make a clasp. And «قِلَادُ» or «اِقْليْدُ» refers to copper or bronze wire that is used in a necklace. And «قِلَادَةُ» refers to a necklace for the neck. «مِقلَد» refers to that iron key which is bent to fit into a lock and open it. Its plural is «مَقالِدُ» and «مَقَالِیْد». For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«لَہٗ  مَقَالِیۡدُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ  یَقۡدِرُ» ( 42/12 )\nTranslation: The keys of the heavens and the earth are in His possession. He grants abundant sustenance to whoever He wills and restricts it for whoever He wills.","«مَقَالِيد» is the plural of 'maqlid', meaning keys.","mace","مقالید","39:63-42:12",2
1186,251,"T","مَفاتِح","The meaning of «فَتَحَ» is to open or to remove restriction and complexity (intransitive). This word is used in all the following meanings: opening a door, unlocking, opening a path for water to flow, deciding a case, and conquering a land. The plural of «مِفْتَحٌ» is «مَفَاتِح», and it also means both 'key' and 'water channel'. (source: Manjad) The plural of «مِفْتَاحٌ» is « مَفَاتِيْحُ». (source: Manjad) This word is not used in the Holy Quran. Thus, the word «مَفَاتِحُ» is more specific than «مَقَالِیْد», which comes in the meanings of removing and opening all kinds of restrictions and obstacles.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ عِنۡدَہٗ مَفَاتِحُ الۡغَیۡبِ لَا  یَعۡلَمُہَاۤ  اِلَّا ہُوَ» ( 6/59 )\nTranslation: And with Him are the keys of the unseen; none knows them except Him.","«مَفاتِح» meaning keys, it is also used in the sense of opening something or removing obstacles and complexities from something.","Treasure","مفاتح","6:59-24:61-28:76",3
1187,252,"S","خُمُر","The term «خُمُر» is collective, meaning «خِمَار» (dupatta, veil, curtain). «خِمَار» refers to a small shawl or dupatta that can be used to cover the face, the sides, and the chest. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لۡیَضۡرِبۡنَ بِخُمُرِہِنَّ عَلٰی جُیُوۡبِہِنَّ» (24/31). Translation: And let believing women draw their veils over their bosoms.","«خُمُر» meaning shawl, two-piece veil, curtain.","Shawl","خمر","24:31",1
1188,252,"S","جَلَابِیْب","«جَلَابِیْب» is the plural form of «جِلْبَاب». Meaning a cloak or a shirt, and «جَلْبَبَ» means to wear a cloak or shirt (manjada). «جَلْبَاب» is actually that large cloak which can cover the entire body from head to foot.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ  قُلۡ  لِّاَزۡوَاجِکَ  وَ  بَنٰتِکَ وَ نِسَآءِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ یُدۡنِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہِنَّ مِنۡ جَلَابِیۡبِہِنَّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ اَدۡنٰۤی اَنۡ یُّعۡرَفۡنَ فَلَا  یُؤۡذَیۡنَ» (33/59)\nTranslation: O Prophet, tell your wives, your daughters, and the believing women to let their cloaks hang low so that they may be recognized and not be harmed.","«جَلَابِیْب» means chador or qamis.","shawl","جلابیب","33:59",1
1189,253,"R","مَرْعٰی","«رَعٰی» means the grazing of livestock. The word «مَرْعٰی» also comes in the meaning of a pasture. And it also refers to fresh grass or fodder (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» (87/4,5)\nTranslation: And who has made the pasture grow and then made it black stubble.","«مَرْعٰی» is referred to as fresh fodder.","Remedy","مرعی","79:31-87:4",2
1190,253,"R","اَبّ","«اَبّ» refers to fodder that is completely suitable for grazing and cutting (as fodder). According to Sahib Minhaj, this term applies to all kinds of fresh and dry fodder that serves as animal feed, such as sorghum, grass, hay, etc. Or it refers to fodder that can be stored (as stock). That which holds the position for humans that «فَاکِھَۃ» (fruit) holds, the same position «اَبّ» holds for livestock (animals). «فَاکِھَۃ» means fruit, whether fresh or dried. Similarly, «اَبّ» applies to fresh and dry fodder (as per certain lexicographers).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ  فَاکِہَۃً  وَّ اَبًّا مَّتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» (80:31,32)\nTranslation: And fruits and fodder (also produced from the earth) — all created for you and your livestock.","«اَبّ» such a remedy that is becoming dry.","Remedy","اب","80:31",1
1191,253,"D","عَصْف","«عَصْف» refers to the husks and outer coverings of grains (m. l), tori (fodder for animals), bhusa, etc. And «عصف ماکول» denotes that part or stump of fodder (the portion of a vegetable, crop, or leaf that remains attached to the branch) which animals leave behind after grazing. According to Sahib al-Munjid, they are the stalks of crops and the chopped straw. «عَصَفَ» means the swift blowing of wind, and «عَاصِفَہ» is termed a storm. Moreover, that wind which carries away grass, vegetation, and their stalks is also called «عَصْف».\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«فَجَعَلَہُمۡ کَعَصۡفٍ مَّاۡکُوۡلٍ» (105/5)\nTranslation: So He made them like chewed-up straw.","That portion of fodder which animals leave behind after grazing, i.e., leftover fodder.","Divine solution","عصف","55:12-77:2-105:5",3
1192,254,"M","اَھِلَّۃ","«اَھِلَّۃ» is a collection of «ھَلَال». And «ھَلَال» means the new moon, and «ھَلَّ» means the appearance of the crescent. And «اَھَلَّ» means to publicize or make something known. For example, when people see the new moon, they signal to each other, show it, and make it known.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَہِلَّۃِ  ؕ قُلۡ ہِیَ مَوَاقِیۡتُ لِلنَّاسِ وَ الۡحَجِّ» (2/189)\nTranslation: (O Prophet) people ask you about the new moon. Say, 'It is a means for people to determine appointed times and to know the time for Hajj.'","«اَھِلَّۃ» is the plural of «ھَلَال». It refers exclusively to the new moon or crescent moon. Specifically, the moon from the 26th day up to the third.","Moon","اھلۃ","2:189-6:77-6:96-7:54-10:5-12:4-13:2-14:33-16:12-21:33-22:18-25:61-29:61-31:29-35:13-36:39-36:40-39:5-41:37-54:1-55:5-71:16-74:32-75:8-75:9-84:18-91:2",27
1193,254,"T"," قَمَر","The Arabs had divided the moon into three parts based on its shapes. The period of the crescent is 7 days: three days after its appearance and four days before its appearance. From the 4th to the 12th, and then from the 19th to the 26th, it is called «قَمَر». And from the 13th to the 18th, a week is called «بَدْر». However, its common everyday name is «قَمَر». And every shape of the moon can be called «قَمَر».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الۡقَمَرَ قَدَّرۡنٰہُ  مَنَازِلَ حَتّٰی عَادَ کَالۡعُرۡجُوۡنِ  الۡقَدِیۡمِ» (36/39)\nTranslation: And We have appointed for the moon its mansions, until it becomes like a dried, old date-stalk.","You can call every shape of the moon «قَمَر».","The moon","قمر","2:189-6:77-6:96-7:54-10:5-12:4-13:2-14:33-16:12-21:33-22:18-25:61-29:61-31:29-35:13-36:39-36:40-39:5-41:37-54:1-55:5-71:16-74:32-75:8-75:9-84:18-91:2",27
1194,255,"T","شَآءَ","The original meaning of «شَآءَ» is «شَیْء», which means thing. And «شَیْء» is that which can be known and about which information can be given, and its plural is things (ashya') (Majma'; Muf). And «شِیْئَۃ» and «مَشِیْئَۃ» are nouns meaning intention or will (Majma'). Originally, the meaning of «مَشِیْئَۃ» pertains to the creation of something or attaining it. However, since it is Allah Almighty Who brings everything into existence and maintains its order, the term mashi'ah (will) is therefore used exclusively in the sense of the Divine Will.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَخۡلُقُ مَا یَشَآءُ ؕ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ الذُّکُوۡرَ» (42/49)\nTranslation: He creates what He wills; He grants daughters to whom He wills and grants sons to whom He wills.","«شَآءَ» A wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's decree and does not occur before or after its appointed time.","to want","شآء","2:20-2:70-2:90-2:105-2:142-2:212-2:213-2:220-2:247-2:251-2:253-2:255-2:261-2:269-2:272-2:284-3:6-3:13-3:26-3:27-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:73-3:74-3:129-3:179-4:48-4:49-4:90-4:116-4:133-5:17-5:18-5:40-5:48-5:54-5:64-6:35-6:39-6:41-6:80-6:83-6:88-6:107-6:111-6:112-6:128-6:133-6:137-6:138-6:148-6:149-7:89-7:100-7:128-7:155-7:156-7:188-8:31-9:15-9:27-9:28-10:16-10:25-10:49-10:99-10:107-11:33-11:87-11:107-11:108-11:118-12:56-12:76-12:99-12:100-12:110-13:13-13:26-13:27-13:31-13:39-14:4-14:11-14:19-14:27-16:2-16:9-16:31-16:35-16:93-17:18-17:30-17:54-18:24-18:29-18:39-18:69-21:9-22:5-22:18-23:24-24:21-24:35-24:38-24:43-24:45-24:46-25:10-25:16-25:45-25:57-26:4-27:87-28:27-28:56-28:68-28:82-29:21-29:62-30:5-30:37-30:48-30:54-33:24-33:51-34:9-34:13-34:36-34:39-35:1-35:8-35:16-35:22-36:43-36:47-36:66-36:67-37:102-39:4-39:23-39:34-39:52-39:68-39:74-40:15-41:14-42:8-42:12-42:13-42:19-42:22-42:27-42:29-42:33-42:49-42:50-42:51-42:52-43:20-43:60-47:4-47:30-48:14-48:25-48:27-50:35-53:26-56:65-56:70-57:21-57:29-59:6-62:4-73:19-74:31-74:37-74:55-74:56-76:29-76:30-76:31-78:39-80:12-80:22-81:28-81:29-82:8-87:7",190
1195,255,"T","اَرَادَ","There is also a distinction between Divine Decree (Mashi'at) and Divine Desire (Iradah). Divine Decree is such an intention that must come into existence in accordance with Allah's knowledge and predestination. For example, the blessed Hadith states: «مَا شَآءَ اللہُ کَانَ وَ مَا لَمْ یَشَآءُ لَمْ یَکُنْ» (Sunan Abi Dawud: Hadith No. 5075), meaning: Allah does whatever He wills, and He does not do what He does not will. Whereas Divine Desire does not necessarily entail its actual occurrence.\n\nSimilarly, the Noble Quran states: «یُرِیۡدُ اللّٰہُ بِکُمُ الۡیُسۡرَ وَ لَا یُرِیۡدُ بِکُمُ الۡعُسۡرَ» (2:185). Translation: Allah intends for you ease and does not intend for you hardship. In the same manner, at another place, the Divine command states: «وَ مَا اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ ظُلۡمًا  لِّلۡعِبَادِ» (40:31). Translation: And Allah does not intend to wrong the servants.\n\nAlthough it is evident that hardship, constriction, and injustice are found among people. This is because such things are necessitated by Divine Decree. When the term Iradah (Desire) is attributed to a human being, it refers to a wish or intention that is subordinate to Allah's predestination. For example, the Divine command states: «وَ مَا تَشَآءُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ  رَبُّ الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (81:29). Translation: And you do not will except what Allah wills, Lord of the worlds.\n\nWhereas a human's desire is free from this restriction; it can be contrary to Divine Decree. For instance, a person desires that death should not come to him. But this would be against Divine Decree, hence it cannot happen. For example, the Noble Quran states: «یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ  لِیُطۡفِئُوۡا  نُوۡرَ اللّٰہِ  بِاَفۡوَاہِہِمۡ وَ اللّٰہُ  مُتِمُّ  نُوۡرِہٖ  وَ لَوۡ  کَرِہَ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (61:8). Translation: They desire to extinguish the light of Allah with their mouths, but Allah will perfect His light, even if the disbelievers may dislike it.\n\nFurthermore, the clear difference between Desire and Decree is that desire can pertain to the past or future, but the time of Decree is not subject to being forward or backward (as stated by the Faqih, ref. 40).","«اَرَادَ» is a common type of desire or intention that may or may not be subordinate to the divine will, and its timing can be variable.","to want","اراد","2:26-2:108-2:185-2:228-2:233-2:253-3:108-3:152-3:176-4:26-4:27-4:28-4:35-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:91-4:134-4:144-4:150-5:1-5:6-5:17-5:29-5:37-5:49-5:91-5:113-6:52-7:110-8:7-8:62-8:67-8:71-9:32-9:46-9:55-9:85-10:107-11:15-11:34-11:79-11:88-11:107-12:25-13:11-14:10-17:18-17:19-17:103-18:28-18:77-18:82-20:63-21:70-22:14-22:16-22:22-23:24-25:62-26:35-28:5-28:19-28:27-28:79-28:83-30:38-30:39-32:20-33:13-33:17-33:33-33:50-34:43-35:10-36:82-37:86-37:98-38:6-39:4-39:38-40:31-42:20-48:11-48:15-51:57-52:42-61:8-72:10-74:31-74:52-75:5-76:9-85:16",94
1196,255,"T","اِشْتَھٰی","«اِشْتَھٰی» means the soul's inclination toward that which it naturally likes. Natural inclinations such as hunger, lust, greed, etc. (plural) and its opposite is «نَفَرَ». And the author of *Munjid* writes its meaning as: the desire for desirable things (*Munjid*), such desires in which intention is not involved (Faqih 98).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَدَّعُوۡنَ» (41/31)\nTranslation: And there you will be given whatever your soul desires and whatever you ask for will be made available to you.","the innate desire for cherished things","to want","اشتھی","16:57-21:102-34:54-41:31-43:71-52:22-56:21-77:42",8
1197,255,"T","بَغٰی","«بَغٰی» means desiring to exceed the bounds of moderation in seeking something (verbal noun). This trait can be praiseworthy (good), such as exceeding the obligatory acts by performing voluntary acts of worship. It can also be blameworthy (bad), such as inclining towards falsehood (wrong speech) by transgressing the truth.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«قَالُوۡا  یٰۤاَبَانَا مَا نَبۡغِیۡ ؕ ہٰذِہٖ  بِضَاعَتُنَا رُدَّتۡ اِلَیۡنَا» (12/65)\nTranslation: They said, O our father! What else could we desire? Our wealth has also been returned to us.\nAs if this wallet that emerged from the belongings of Yusuf's brothers—they had no right to it, yet it came to them.\n\nAnd «اِبْتَغٰی» means seeking something with effort (verbal noun). That is, exerting more than the necessary effort.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ  وَجۡہِ  رَبِّہِ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (92/20)\nTranslation: But he desires only the pleasure of his Lord, the Most High.","Exceeding the bounds of moderation in acquiring something.","to want","بغی","2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20",79
1198,255,"T","رَغِبَ","«رَغَبَ» means to desire something from the heart. And «مَرْغُوب» means that which pleases the heart, i.e., what the heart finds good. Whether this thing aligns with one's natural inclinations or not.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«عَسٰی رَبُّنَاۤ  اَنۡ یُّبۡدِلَنَا خَیۡرًا  مِّنۡہَاۤ  اِنَّاۤ اِلٰی  رَبِّنَا  رٰغِبُوۡنَ» (68/32)\nTranslation: Perhaps our Lord will grant us a better garden than this. Indeed, we turn to our Lord with longing.","«رَغَبَ» is to merely desire something, whether it conforms to natural inclinations or not.","to want","رغب","4:127-9:59-9:120-21:90-68:32-94:8",6
1199,256,"S","سَکَتَ","«سَکَتَ» to stop while speaking; to become silent; to become quiet. (M. L. Manjad) In this meaning, this word is not used in the Quran. However, it is used for the context of controlling anger.\n\nFor example: It is in the Quran:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ» (7/154)\nTranslation: And when the anger of Moses (peace be upon him) subsided.","To fall silent while talking.","Silent","سکت","7:154-17:100",2
1200,256,"S","صَمَت","«صَمَتَ» means to remain silent. To be taciturn or of a quiet disposition.\nFor example: The Prophetic saying is: «مَنْ صَمَتَ نَجَا» meaning: Whoever remains silent has attained salvation. The opposite of «صَمَتَ» is «نَطَقَ». And (mal samit) refers to cash and currency. Whereas mal natq refers to livestock. (Minaj)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«سَوَآءٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اَدَعَوۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ  اَمۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  صَامِتُوۡنَ» (7/193)\nTranslation: Call them or remain silent; both are equal for them.","«صَمَتَ» is the term used for someone of a quiet disposition or who is taciturn.","Silence","صمت","7:193",1
1201,256,"S","اَنْصَتَ","and «اَنْصَتَ» means to listen to others' words silently and attentively (manjada).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قُرِئَ الۡقُرۡاٰنُ فَاسۡتَمِعُوۡا لَہٗ وَ اَنۡصِتُوۡا  لَعَلَّکُمۡ  تُرۡحَمُوۡنَ» (7/204)\nTranslation: When the Quran is recited, listen to it attentively and remain silent so that you may be shown mercy.","«اَنْصَتَ» comes to listen silently to others.","Silent","انصت","7:204-46:29",2
1202,257,"L","مَصْبَاح","«صَبَحَ» means to be bright and shining, «صَبَحَ الشَّعْر» signifies hair being lustrous, and «صَبَح الْحَدِیْد» means iron being bright and shining. And «صَبِیْح» and «صَبْحَان» are used in beautiful meanings (manjad). Ibn Faris writes that the word «صَبَحَ» fundamentally denotes a red color. Morning is also called 'sabah' due to its redness. And the plural of «مِصْبَاح» is «مَصَابِیْح», meaning 'lamp'; it is also referred to as 'masabih' because of its redness (m l).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «مَثَلُ نُوۡرِہٖ کَمِشۡکٰوۃٍ  فِیۡہَا مِصۡبَاحٌ» (24:35). Translation: The example of His light is as if there were a niche containing a lamp.\n\nFurthermore, the word «مِصْبَاح» is also used in the Quran to describe bright stars. For instance, the divine command states: «وَ لَقَدۡ  زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِمَصَابِیۡحَ» (67:5). Translation: And We have adorned the nearest heaven with lamps (stars).","That is the one whose light is white-tinted.","lamp","مصباح","24:35-41:12-67:5",3
1203,257,"L","سِرَاج","Ibn al-Faris states that the word «سَرَج» connotes beauty, adornment, and splendor. And «سِرَاج» (lamp) is called «سِرَاج» due to its light and adornment. The horse's saddle is also called «سَرْجُ» because it is its adornment. It is said «سَرَّجَ وَجْھَہٗ» he adorned his face, and «سَرَّجَ شَعْرَہٗ» he groomed or braided his hair. (Source: Ibn al-Faris).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  بُرُوۡجًا وَّ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا سِرٰجًا وَّ قَمَرًا  مُّنِیۡرًا» (25:61)\nTranslation: (Allah) is the Most Blessed, who has placed constellations in the heavens and made therein a lamp («سِرَاج»)—a radiant sun—and a luminous moon.\n\nThe above lexical research, cited from Ibn al-Faris's *Maqayis al-Lughah*, is not supported by the Quran; rather, the matter appears contrary to it. The Quran has called the sun a *siraj* («سِرَاجًا وَّہَّاجًا», 78:13) and «سِرَاجًا وَّہَّاجًا» (35:13), even though its light tends toward redness, not whiteness. Similarly, the Quran has called the stars «مَصَاِبْیح», even though their light tends toward whiteness, not redness. Therefore, the reality is that: «سِرَاج» is that whose light tends toward redness, and «مِصْبَاح» is that whose light tends toward whiteness. And Allah knows best.","«سِرَاج» That is the one whose light is reddish.","Lamp","سراج","25:61-33:46-71:16-78:13",4
1204,258,"T","رَعٰی","«رَعٰی» means to graze an animal and to provide for its protection and care. And «رَاعِی» means a shepherd. A herdsman (one who performs the service of taking livestock to pastures and grazing them). And «مَرْعٰی» means both fodder and pasture (m.f.)—to save something from being wasted. And to remove causes of external dangers, and its opposite «اِھْمَال» means being without a shepherd (Faq 15).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ» (20/54)\nTranslation: Eat and graze your cattle.\n\nThe fundamental meaning of the word «رَعٰی» is training and care; therefore, its application can also be to human beings. Thus, a king is a shepherd, and the public is his flock.","«رَعٰی» meaning to graze an animal and to provide for its protection and care.","to graze","رعی","20:54-28:23",2
1205,258,"T","اَسَامَ","The basic meanings of «سَوْمَ» are two: (1) request/need, and (2) departure/movement. That is, to set out in search of something. «سَامَتُ الْاِبِل» means they went to a pasture for grazing camels. And «اَسَامَ» means to go for grazing (intransitive).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ مِنۡہُ  شَجَرٌ  فِیۡہِ تُسِیۡمُوۡنَ» (16/10)\nTranslation: And from it (the rain) you graze your livestock, and they (the trees) become lush and fresh for you.","«اَسَامَ» to take animals for grazing.","to graze","اسام","16:10",1
1206,259,"T","عَرَجَ","Two meanings are found for «عَرَجَ»: inclination and elevation (m.l.). «عَرَجَ» means to walk with a limp, and «اَعْرَج» refers to a limp person. And «عَرَجَ فِی السَّلَم» means to climb a ladder.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ فَتَحۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ بَابًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَظَلُّوۡا فِیۡہِ  یَعۡرُجُوۡنَ لَقَالُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا سُکِّرَتۡ اَبۡصَارُنَا» (15/14,15)\n\nTranslation: And even if We opened for them a gate from the heaven and they began to ascend through it, they would surely say, 'Our eyes have been dazzled.'","«عَرَجَ» is used for climbing intermittently.","to climb","عرج","15:14-32:5-34:2-57:4-70:4",5
1207,259,"T","رَقِیَ","«رَقِیَ» also means to sweep away and to ascend. This is done by exerting strength in accordance with one's capacity and power. Gradually, with a gentle pace, ascending (ascending), for example: «اِرْقِ عَلٰی ظِلْعِکَ» means climb according to your courage. Do not burden your soul beyond your strength. (As in Al-Munjid and Al-Mufradat) And as in: «رَقَیْتُ فی العلم و الشّرف» I have progressed in knowledge and honor (Fiqh 152). Thus, its usage is general. For instance, the Quran states: «اَوۡ تَرۡقٰی فِی السَّمَآءِ ؕ وَ لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لِرُقِیِّکَ حَتّٰی تُنَزِّلَ عَلَیۡنَا کِتٰبًا نَّقۡرَؤُہٗ» (17/93) Translation: Or ascend to the sky, and we will not believe your ascension until you bring a book that we can read.","«رَقِیَ» is used for climbing, depending on one's ability.","to ascend","رقی","17:93",1
1208,259,"T","صَعَدَ","Two fundamental aspects are found in the meaning of «صَعَدَ»: (1) loftiness, (2) hardship (m. l.) i.e., climbing to a high place with difficulty. And «صُعُوْد» denotes high and low places, and also the difficult paths to climb them. ‘Munjad’ refers to the difficult rising of something, like smoke rising. And «مصعد الکھر بائیہ» means lift (elevator) (muf). And «أَصْعَدَ» and «صَعَّدَ» mean ascending with time and difficulty.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَجۡعَلۡ صَدۡرَہٗ ضَیِّقًا حَرَجًا کَاَنَّمَا یَصَّعَّدُ فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/126)\nTranslation: It makes his breast tight and constricted. As if he is ascending into the sky.\n\nNote: The aforementioned three words «عَرَجَ ، رَقٰی» and «صَعَدَ» have «نَزَلَ» as their opposite.","«صَعَدَ» is used to climb up laboriously.","to ascend (or: to climb, to rise, to mount)","صعد","3:153-6:125-35:10-72:17",4
1209,259,"T","ظَھَرَ","«ظَھَرَ» meaning: to become manifest, to prevail, to climb, and to reach the top by ascending—whether via stairs or a wall, etc.—even if climbed without stairs.  \nFor example: in the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«فَمَا اسۡطَاعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡہُ  وَ مَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا  لَہٗ  نَقۡبًا» (18/97)  \nTranslation: Then neither could they scale it (the barrier), nor could they make a breach in it.  \nAt another instance, the Divine decree states:  \n«لِبُیُوۡتِہِمۡ سُقُفًا مِّنۡ فِضَّۃٍ  وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ» (43/33)  \nTranslation: We would have made for them roofs of silver and stairways upon which they would ascend.","«ظَھَرَ» is used to climb up to.","to ascend","ظھر","2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26",27
1210,259,"T","رَھَقَ","«رَھَقَ» means one thing climbing over another and covering it (involving an urgent quality). «رَھَّقَہُ الْاَمْر» means a matter has forcefully suppressed it (muf) i.e., has covered it. (m. l)\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» (80/40,41)\nTranslation: And how many faces will be covered with dust, and darkness will be overwhelming them.","«رَھَقَ» is used for another to climb on one thing and to suppress it.","to ascend","رھق","10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41",9
1211,259,"T","تَسَوَّر","«سُوْر» means a city of refuge or such a high wall that cannot be scaled to enter inside. And «سَارَ» means to climb upon a wall or to scale it, to leap over it. And «تَسَوَّرَ» also means to climb and scale a wall, as well as to wear a bracelet. «سِوَار ، سَوَار کی جمع «اَسَاوِرَ» and «اَسْوَرَۃٌ» are [terms] derived from bracelet (i.e., their root is related to bracelet).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ نَبَؤُا الۡخَصۡمِ ۘ اِذۡ  تَسَوَّرُوا  الۡمِحۡرَابَ» (38/21)\nTranslation: Have the news of those who disputed reached you when they scaled the wall?","«تَسَوَّرَ» is used for climbing over the wall or jumping over it.","to ascend","تسور","38:21",1
1212,260,"F","عَیْنٌ","«عَیْنٌ» means eye, and its plural appears in the Quran as «اَعْیُنْ». Then, in the sense that water flows from an eye, the mouth of a water skin is also called «عَیْنٌ». Similarly, that spring from which water flows is also called «عَیْنٌ». (Maf) And its plural appears in the Quran as «عُیُوْن».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ » (54/12)\nTranslation: And We made the earth gush forth springs, so the water gathered for what it was destined.\n\nAnd the term «عَیْن» can also be applied to lakes and rivers.","«عَیْنٌ» A flowing spring of water.","Fount","عین","2:60-3:13-5:45-5:83-7:116-7:160-7:179-7:195-8:44-9:92-11:31-11:37-12:84-15:45-15:88-18:28-18:86-18:101-19:26-20:39-20:40-20:131-21:61-23:27-23:50-25:74-26:57-26:134-26:147-26:34-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:19-33:51-34:12-36:66-37:45-37:48-40:19-43:71-44:25-44:52-44:54-51:15-52:20-52:48-54:12-54:14-54:37-55:50-55:66-56:18-56:22-67:30-76:6-76:18-77:41-83:28-88:5-88:12-90:8-102:7",63
1213,260,"S","یَنْبُوْع","«نَبَعَ» means water gushing forth from a spring, and «مَنْبَع» is the term for the place from which the water gushes forth. And «یَنْبُوع» refers to a spring from which water bubbles up (muf), and its plural form is يَنَابِیْع (yanābi'ī).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی تَفۡجُرَ  لَنَا مِنَ  الۡاَرۡضِ  یَنۡۢبُوۡعًا» ( 17/90 )\nTranslation: And they said, We will not believe you until you cause a spring to gush forth from the earth for us.","«یَنْبُوْع» a spring of water gushing from the earth.","Spring","ینبوع","17:90",1
1214,260,"E","سَرِیٌّ","«سَرِیٌّ» means a small stream. A flowing stream (as in F L 261 Munjid). Its plural forms are «اَسْرِیَۃٌ» and «سُرْیَان». It is also used for a small army or military unit, whose plural is «سرایا». And «ساریہ» means a small contingent that marches at night (Munjid), implying the concept of smallness. (Munjid)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ جَعَلَ  رَبُّکِ  تَحۡتَکِ  سَرِیًّا» (19/24)\nTranslation: Your Lord has caused a spring to gush forth beneath you.","«سَرِیٌّ» A flowing spring that takes the form of a small river.","Eyecup","سری","19:24",1
1215,260,"S","فَارَ","«فَارَ» means to boil and bubble (from najm), and «فَوْر» means to boil, to open, to bubble (m. l). «فَارَ الْقِدْر» means the boiling of a pot, «فَارَ الْمَاء» means the boiling of water, and «فَارَ الْعِرْق» means the agitation and restlessness of a vein (manjad). In «فَارَ», the imagery suggests water boiling and rising upward rather than flowing downward, especially when the water pressure below is higher and the opening is narrow. It is from this concept that the famous term fawwarah (fountain) originates.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَ اَمۡرُنَا وَ فَارَ التَّنُّوۡرُ» (11/40) Translation: until Our command came and the oven began to boil.","«فَارَ» to boil over.","Spring","فار","3:125-11:40-23:27-67:7",4
1216,260,"E","نَضَخَ","«نَضَخَ» means to gush forth forcefully from a spring. And «اِنْضَخَ» means to splash down. «نَضَّاخ» refers to a torrential downpour, and «مِنْضَخَة» refers to a sprinkling device (manjad). It is as if in this word, the concept of boiling and flowing is found instead of splashing upward with force.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ نَضَّاخَتٰنِ» (55/66)\nTranslation: In them (both gardens) are two springs gushing forth.","«نَضَخَ» the splashing and falling of water.","Eyecup","نضخ","56:66",1
1217,260,"F","اَنْبَجَسَ","«اَنْبَجَسَ» means something opening due to water, whether it is land, stone, or a mountain (m. l.). And according to the scholar of linguistic jurisprudence, the word «اَنْبَجَسَ» is specifically used for water gushing out and flowing from a mountain or rock (f. l. 259). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ  اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی مُوۡسٰۤی  اِذِ  اسۡتَسۡقٰىہُ قَوۡمُہٗۤ  اَنِ اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ ۚ فَانۡۢبَجَسَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَا عَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (7/160). Translation: And when Moses (peace be upon him)'s people asked him for water, We revealed to him: Strike the rock with your staff, then twelve springs gushed out from it.","«اَنْبَجَسَ» gushing forth from a spring when the outlet is constricted.","Fountain","انبجس","7:160",1
1218,260,"S","اِنْفَجَرَ","«اِنْفَجَرَ» and «اِنْبَجَسَ» are near-synonymous terms. In the Quran, both words have been used for the same context. The verse related to «اِنْفَجَرَ» is as follows: For example, the divine command states: «وَ اِذِ اسۡتَسۡقٰی مُوۡسٰی لِقَوۡمِہٖ فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ  ؕ فَانۡفَجَرَتۡ مِنۡہُ اثۡنَتَاعَشۡرَۃَ عَیۡنًا» (2/60). Translation: And when Moses, peace be upon him, asked for water for his people, We said, 'Strike the rock with your staff.' Then, twelve springs gushed forth from it.\n\nThe subtle difference between them is that when the mouth (opening) of a spring is not fully open and the water rises a little above it, the word «اِنْبَجَسَ» is used. When the mouth opens completely and the water flows out from the opening, the word «اِنْفَجَرَ» is used. The second difference is that «اِنْبَجَسَ» is specifically used for a spring gushing forth from a mountain or rocky terrain, whereas «اِنْفَجَرَ» is a general term. It can be used for both mountainous and flat terrain. During the flood of Prophet Noah, peace be upon him, the water burst forth from the general earth.\n\nFor example, the divine command states: «وَّ فَجَّرۡنَا الۡاَرۡضَ عُیُوۡنًا فَالۡتَقَی الۡمَآءُ عَلٰۤی  اَمۡرٍ  قَدۡ  قُدِرَ» (54/12). Translation: And We split the earth into springs. And thus all the water was gathered for the purpose which had been decreed.","«اِنْفَجَرَ» gush forth from a spring while the outflow spreads out wide.","Spring","انفجر","2:60-2:74-17:90-17:91-18:33-36:34-54:12-76:6-82:3",9
1219,260,"E","سَالَ","In «سَالَ», only the concept of water flowing is found, whether that water is from rain or a spring.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اَنۡزَلَ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ  مَآءً  فَسَالَتۡ اَوۡدِیَۃٌۢ بِقَدَرِہَا» (13/17)  \nTranslation: He sent down rain from the sky. Then channels flow out from it according to their respective measures.  \n\nSimilarly, in another instance, the divine command states:  \n«وَ اَسَلۡنَا لَہٗ  عَیۡنَ الۡقِطۡرِ» (34/12)  \nTranslation: And We made a spring of copper flow for Solomon.  \n\nFrom this, the word sayyal is used for anything that flows down like water. Thus, in «سَیْل», the concept of flowing forcefully downwards is found. And «سَیْل» is called seelab in Urdu.  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«فَاَعۡرَضُوۡا فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَیۡلَ الۡعَرِمِ» (34/16)  \nTranslation: They turned away (in disbelief), so We sent upon them a flood of overwhelming force.","Here, the concept is limited to the flow of water or any liquid.","Eyecup","سال","13:17-34:12-34:16",3
1220,260,"S","جَرٰی","«جَرٰی» means the flowing or running of water. This occurs when there is neither an excessive slope nor an excessive force of water. It refers to the ordinary flow of water, whether from a spring, a river, or a sea, for example. The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡہِمَا عَیۡنٰنِ  تَجۡرِیٰنِ» ( 55/50 )\nTranslation: In both of them are two springs, flowing.\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«لَہُمۡ جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» ( 2/25 )\nTranslation: For them are Gardens beneath which rivers flow.\nThe usage of «جَرٰی» is general and is employed in the Noble Quran not only for fluids (i.e., things that flow) but also for the movement of winds, the sun, the moon, and others. Furthermore, its usage is also metaphorical, such as the well-known phrase Sunnah jarīyah (continuous Sunnah). However, an example of this metaphorical usage is likely not found in the Quran. It is used in both temporal and spatial contexts, denoting continuity over distance or over time.","«جَرٰی» refers to water or any other substance flowing or traveling for an extended period or distance, deviating from its normal course.","Spring","جری","2:25-2:164-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:85-5:119-6:6-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-10:22-11:42-13:2-13:35-14:23-14:32-16:31-18:31-20:76-21:81-22:14-22:23-22:65-25:10-29:58-30:46-31:29-31:31-35:13-36:38-38:36-39:5-39:20-43:51-45:12-47:12-48:5-48:17-54:14-55:50-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-85:11-98:8",57
1221,260,"S","فَاضَ","In «فَیْض», two concepts are found: (1) abundance of something, (2) losing control due to that abundance. «فَاضَ السَّیْلُ» means water being in abundance and flowing out from above the riverbanks (manjada), and «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاء» means he filled the container so much that water started overflowing from the edges (OVERFLOW) (manjada. muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «تَرٰۤی اَعۡیُنَہُمۡ تَفِیۡضُ مِنَ  الدَّمۡعِ مِمَّا عَرَفُوۡا مِنَ الۡحَقِّ» (5/83) Translation: You see that tears flow from their eyes because they have recognized the truth. That is, the eyes become so filled with tears that the tears begin to flow.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states: «ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199) Translation: Then return from where the people have returned. Here, 'people' refers to the crowd, multitude, or abundance of people. Their abundance compels one to accompany them. And accompanying and returning with them is expressed by «اَفَاضَ». Similarly, it is also used for extreme enthusiasm in any work or matter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (10/61) Translation: When you are engaged in that work.","«فَاضَ» To begin to flow (of water or any other thing) due to mere abundance or excess. (OVER FLOW)","spring","فاض","2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8",6
1222,261,"T","مَشٰی","«مَشٰی» Meaning: to walk with the intention and purpose of moving from one place to another (transitive), to walk step by step. To walk, to move around. To walk at a normal pace. (see 176) This word is generally used for walking.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ قَالُوۡا مَالِ ہٰذَا الرَّسُوۡلِ یَاۡکُلُ الطَّعَامَ وَ یَمۡشِیۡ  فِی الۡاَسۡوَاقِ» (25/7) Translation: And the disbelievers say, 'What kind of messenger is this? He eats food and walks around in the marketplaces.'","«مَشٰی» To proceed in a customary manner. The word to walk is a general term for movement.","to walk","مشی","2:20-6:122-7:195-17:37-17:95-20:40-20:128-24:45-25:7-25:20-25:63-28:25-31:18-31:19-32:26-38:6-57:28-67:15-67:22-68:11",20
1223,261,"T","دَبَّ","«دَبّ» to walk with a slightly lighter gait than the usual manner «حَرَکَۃِ عَلَی الْاَرْضِ اَخَفُّ مِنَ الْمَشْیِ » (M. L) includes crawling, moving like a snake, or the child who is learning to walk on hands and feet (M. Q), and whatever moves and walks on the earth is «دَابَۃ». (M. L)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  رِزۡقُہَا» (11/6)\nTranslation: And there is no creature that moves on the earth but its provision is the responsibility of Allah.","Meaning to walk with a slightly light pace from «مَشٰی».","to walk","دب","2:164-6:38-8:22-8:55-11:6-11:56-16:49-16:61-22:18-24:45-27:82-29:60-31:10-34:14-35:28-35:45-42:29-45:4",18
1224,261,"T","اِنطَلَق","«طَلَقَ» means to free from a bond (transitive), and «اِنطَلَق» means to move after a pause (i.e., to rise and walk). To set out. To begin walking. To set out after a prisoner's release, or to initiate conversation after a period of silence.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَانۡطَلَقَا  ٝ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ» (18/71)\nTranslation: Then both of them set out until they boarded a ship.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا یَنۡطَلِقُ لِسَانِیۡ فَاَرۡسِلۡ  اِلٰی ہٰرُوۡنَ» (26/13)\nTranslation: (Moses (peace be upon him) submitted) And my tongue is not fluent, so send revelation to Aaron (peace be upon him) as well (to be my helper).","«اِنطَلَق» to set out and start walking.","to walk","انطلق","18:71-18:74-18:77-26:13-38:6-48:15-68:23-77:29-77:30",9
1225,261,"T","سَلَکَ","«سَلَک» is used in two meanings: (1) to follow a path steadfastly and not deviate from it (transitive) — to walk and proceed upon the path (intransitive).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ  کُلِیۡ مِنۡ کُلِّ الثَّمَرٰتِ فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16:69)\nTranslation: (O honeybee) eat from all [types of] fruits and follow the clear paths of your Lord.\n\nAnd (2) the second meaning is «نُفُوذَ الشَّیْء», which means to permeate one thing into another; to enter, to do, to fill.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (28:32)\nTranslation: And (O Moses) put your hand into your garment. It will emerge pure, without any blemish.","to continue along the paths","to proceed","سلک","15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42",12
1226,261,"T","سَرَبَ","«سَرَب» means to go downward or to descend. «سَرْب» means a hole or den of wild animals, an underground pit, basement, or prison. These are referred to as «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا». For example, the snake slithered into its hole (masc.).\n\nAs mentioned in the Quran: «فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18:61). Translation: So it (the fish) made its path in the sea like a tunnel.","To descend (downward) «سَرَبَ». To get bogged down.","to walk","سرب","18:61",1
1227,261,"T","سَرٰی ( یَسرِیْ )","«سَرٰی» means to travel at night, to journey during the night. And «اَلسَّارِیَۃ» means a small group that travels at night (pl.). In the Quran, this word does not appear in the meaning of 'traveling at night,' but rather in the sense of the night itself moving.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّیۡلِ  اِذَا یَسۡرِ» (89/4)\nTranslation: And by the night when it moves on.","walking at night","to walk","سری ( یسری )","89:4",1
1228,261,"T","دَأَبَ","«دَأَب» to persist in a task with equal effort and toil (as per Munjid) and to continue moving forward without interruption (abbr.)\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n\n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ» (14/33)\n\nTranslation: And He has made the sun and the moon subservient to you, each moving in its orbit.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command declares:\n\n«تَزۡرَعُوۡنَ سَبۡعَ سِنِیۡنَ دَاَبًا» (12/47)\n\nTranslation: You will cultivate for seven consecutive years.","«دَأَب» to continue walking without interruption.","to walk","دأب","12:47-14:33",2
1229,261,"T","مَضٰی","«مَضٰی» meaning to pass, to go away, and to become empty (m. q.). In «مَضٰی», either the concept of mere time or the passage of time is found, referring to past elapsed time, or it conveys the meaning of something moving along with time and passing away. «مَضٰی مَا مَضٰی» means what happened, happened; what passed, passed (minjad).\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَہۡلَکۡنَاۤ  اَشَدَّ مِنۡہُمۡ بَطۡشًا وَّ مَضٰی مَثَلُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (43/8)\nTranslation: So those who were powerful among them, We destroyed them, and the state of the previous people passed away.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command is:\n«حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60)\nTranslation: Until I reach the place where the two rivers meet, (I will not turn back) even if I go on for ages.\n\nHere, the word «مَضٰی» is used with reference to time, meaning: I will not turn back even if many years pass.","«مَضٰی» the passage of time or to proceed in accordance with time.","to walk","مضی","8:38-15:65-18:60-36:67-43:8",5
1230,261,"T","نَقَّبَ","«نَقَبَ» has two meanings: (1) to pierce through a wall or leather, and (2) to investigate news or reports. And «نَقَّبَ» means to patrol, to enter a country, and to investigate and examine conditions.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَنَقَّبُوۡا فِی الۡبِلَادِ ؕ ہَلۡ  مِنۡ  مَّحِیۡصٍ» (50/36)\nTranslation: They began to patrol the cities. Is there any place to flee for refuge?","«نَقَّب» to take on a tour.","to walk","نقب","18:97-50:36",2
1231,261,"T","سَارَ","«سَارَ» means to walk, to move about; to travel, to stroll, regardless of the purpose. A person who walks is called «سَائِر», and a group walking together is called «سَیَّارَۃ».\n\nThe Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ وَ سَارَ بِاَہۡلِہٖۤ» (28/29)\nTranslation: When Moses had completed the appointed term, he set out with his family.","«سَارَ» to walk around, to tour, to travel.","to walk","سار","12:19-13:10-28:29",3
1232,261,"T","قصَّ","The meaning of «قَصَّ» is to follow a trail, to proceed gradually from behind, and to continue following (masc.).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is: «وَ قَالَتۡ لِاُخۡتِہٖ قُصِّیۡہِ ۫ فَبَصُرَتۡ بِہٖ عَنۡ  جُنُبٍ  وَّ  ہُمۡ  لَا  یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (28/11)  \nTranslation: And Moses's mother said to his sister, Follow him from behind. So she observed him from a distance while they were unaware.","to follow closely behind","to walk","قص","18:64-28:11",2
1233,261,"T","رَجِلَ","«رَجِلَ» means to walk on foot. It is used when in a battle some are mounted and some are on foot. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ » (22/27). Translation: They will come to you on foot and also mounted on lean camels. At another place, the Almighty says: «فَاِنۡ خِفۡتُمۡ فَرِجَالًا اَوۡ رُکۡبَانًا» (2/239). Translation: And if you fear (the enemy), then pray while standing or while riding. And if there is no mount, then the word «مَشٰی» will come.","Walking on foot while some people are also riding.","to walk","رجل","2:239-17:64-22:27",3
1234,261,"T","سَاقَ","«سَاقَ» means to drive or herd, i.e., to urge forward from behind, as a herdsman drives cattle. (F L 187). In the Quranic context, the driver is referred to as «سَوَّاق» (Q. J). For example, the Quran states: «وَّ نَسُوۡقُ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ اِلٰی جَہَنَّمَ وِرۡدًا» (19/86). Translation: And we will drive the thirsty sinners toward Hell.","meaning to push someone from behind to make them move.","to walk","ساق","8:6-19:86-32:27-75:30",4
1235,261,"T","حَرَّکَ","«حَرَکَ» means to shake, to move; and «حَرَّکَ» means to shake something, to give motion, to move forward by pushing or to drive. For example, in the Quran it says: «لَا تُحَرِّکۡ بِہٖ لِسَانَکَ لِتَعۡجَلَ بِہٖ» (75/16). Translation: And (O Muhammad ﷺ! for the purpose of reciting the revelation) do not move your tongue hastily so that you may memorize it quickly.","«حَرَّک» to set in motion and shake.","to walk","حرک","75:16",1
1236,261,"T","اَزْجٰی","«اَزْجٰی» To urge gently. To drive with softness, and «مُزَجّٰی» meaning weak (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَمۡ  تَرَ  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ یُزۡجِیۡ سَحَابًا ثُمَّ  یُؤَلِّفُ بَیۡنَہٗ» (24:43)\nTranslation: Do you not see that it is Allah who drives the clouds, then He merges them together?","«اَزْجٰی» to walk slowly","to walk","ازجی","17:66-24:43",2
1237,261,"T","سَلَک","«سَلَک» has two meanings:\n(1) To walk/tread a specified path. It is used in both transitive and intransitive forms.\n(2) To cause something to permeate/penetrate another or to pass through (e.g., to spread).\nThis word has a special connection with path.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ مَہۡدًا وَّ سَلَکَ  لَکُمۡ  فِیۡہَا سُبُلًا» (20/53)\nTranslation: And He it is who has made the earth a spread for you and has laid out paths for you therein.","«سَلَک» to follow the way or to walk upon the path.","to walk","سلک","15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42",12
1238,261,"T","سَیَّر","«سَارَ» means to travel, to journey, to go on a trip. And «سَیَّر» means to cause to travel, to send on a journey, to dispatch on a trip.\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10/22)\nTranslation: He it is who causes you to travel on land and sea.","«سَیَّر» to show around, to operate.","to walk","سیر","6:11-10:22-12:109-13:31-16:36-18:47-22:46-27:69-29:20-30:9-30:42-34:18-35:44-40:21-40:82-47:10-52:10-78:20-81:3",19
1239,261,"T","اَسْرٰی","«سَرٰی ، یَسْرِیْ» means to travel at night. And «اَسْرٰی» means to cause to travel at night, to escort on a night journey, to accompany on a nocturnal trip.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَسۡرِ  بِاَہۡلِکَ بِقِطۡعٍ مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/81)\nTranslation: So travel with your family during a part of the night from your town.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Glory be to the One Who took His servant by night.","to walk at night, to take for a walk","to walk","اسری","11:81-15:65-17:1-20:77-26:52-44:23",6
1240,262,"T","نَعَقَ","«نَعَقَ» To shout at the top of one's lungs to call someone. For a crow to caw loudly and forcefully. For a shepherd to call his flock from a distance. (See: L 194)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا کَمَثَلِ الَّذِیۡ یَنۡعِقُ بِمَا لَا یَسۡمَعُ اِلَّا دُعَآءً  وَّ  نِدَآءً» (2/171)\n\nTranslation: The example of those who disbelieve is as though they are calling out to something that can hear nothing but shouting and noise (and understands nothing).","«نَعَقَ» to shout at the top of one's lungs","to shriek","نعق","2:171",1
1241,262,"T","صَدَّ","«یَصِدُّ» meaning to raise a clamor, to shout, to wail. And «صَدَّد» meaning to clap (from 'munajid').\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَمَّا ضُرِبَ ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ  مَثَلًا  اِذَا قَوۡمُکَ مِنۡہُ  یَصِدُّوۡنَ» (43/57)\nTranslation: And when the case of Jesus, the son of Mary, was cited, behold, your people did raise a clamor.","«صَدَّ» to make an unintentional commotion.","to scream","صد","15:94-43:57",2
1242,262,"T","جَئَرَ","«جَئَرَ» to grumble loudly; to wail (vehemently) — during panic, wild animals such as deer etc. forcefully emitting sounds and shrieking (intransitive).  \nFor example, in the Holy Quran it says:  \n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَخَذۡنَا مُتۡرَفِیۡہِمۡ بِالۡعَذَابِ اِذَا ہُمۡ  یَجۡئَرُوۡنَ» (23/64)  \nTranslation: Until when We seized those among them who were at ease, they cried out at that time. (Uthmani)","«جَئَرَ» To grumble in a loud voice due to anxiety.","to shriek","جئر","16:53-23:64-23:65",3
1243,262,"T","اِسْتَصْرَخَ","«صَرَخَ» means to scream and shout so that other people may come to one's aid. To cry for help. And «اَصْرَخَ» means to hear someone's cry for help and to respond by bringing assistance to them. And:\n«اِسْتَصْرَخَ» means to summon one's own assistance by shouting and crying out in front of those present.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» ( 28/18 )\nTranslation: Then that same man who had sought help the day before began to cry out to them.","«اِسْتَصْرَخَ» crying out and shouting for help.","to scream","استصرخ","14:22-28:18",2
1244,262,"T","صَرَّ","«صَرَ الرَّجُل» meaning to run or move with force (manjad) and «صَرَّۃ» meaning to scream or shriek (muf). For example: In the Quran it is: «فَاَقۡبَلَتِ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  فِیۡ صَرَّۃٍ  فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29). Translation: So his wife came forward, and in astonishment, she struck her hands together and said, Indeed, I am an old woman, and at the same time, barren.","«صَرَّ» to scream.","To shriek","صر","51:29",1
1245,263,"T","اَلْحَفَ","«لِحَاف» means a garment to cover oneself. It is a proverb: «اَلْحَفْتُہٗ فَالْتَحَفَ» I wrapped it in a blanket, so it became entangled. And «اِلْحَاف» means «اِلْحَاح», i.e., to cling and beg. (muf)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«تَعۡرِفُہُمۡ بِسِیۡمٰہُمۡ ۚ لَا یَسۡئَلُوۡنَ النَّاسَ اِلۡحَافًا» (2:273)\nTranslation: You will recognize them by their appearance (that they are in need but restrained by modesty) and they do not beg people importunately.","to seize or enfold it with «اَلْحَفَ» and prepare it for work.","to stick","الحف","2:273",1
1246,263,"T","لَزَبَ","«لَازِبْ» refers to that which becomes firmly established and adheres at a place (i.e., sticky). According to the scholar of fiqh and language, «لَازِبْ» means sticky and clayey soil (F L 268). In the Quran, this word has been used exclusively for soil/clay. Therefore, both meanings are corroborated.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37:11)\nTranslation: We have created them from sticky clay.","to cling due to the sticky and adhesive nature of something","to stick","لزب","37:11",1
1247,263,"T","لَزِمَ","Within «لَزِمَ», two aspects are found: namely, the meaning of something remaining or staying in one place for an extended period (transitive verb). According to this meaning, this word is translated into various terms in the Urdu language at different contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا کَلِمَۃٌ سَبَقَتۡ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ لَکَانَ لِزَامًا  وَّ  اَجَلٌ  مُّسَمًّی» (20/129)\nTranslation: And if a matter from your Lord had not already been decreed and a specified term not appointed, this (punishment) would have been sealed.","«لَزِمَ» To adhere or stick to something for an extended period.","to stick","لزم","20:129-25:77",2
1248,264,"R","بَزَغَ","«بَزَغَ» means the rising of the sun while its light is spreading. (Detailed) The terms for the light of the sun, moon, stars, or celestial bodies are used when they are rising. And «نُجُوْمٌ بَوَازِغٌ» refers to the rising stars.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَلَمَّا رَاَ الشَّمۡسَ بَازِغَۃً  قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ» (6/78)  \nTranslation: Then when he saw the sun rising in splendor, he said, This is my Lord.","«بَزَغَ» the stars, planets, moon, and sun sparkle at sunrise.","Radiance","بزغ","6:77-6:78",2
1249,264,"R","اَشْرَقَ","«شَرَقَ» means the unveiling or diffusion of light (m.l.) and «اَشْرَقَ» means to illuminate something by casting full light upon it so that it shines.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا» (39/69)\nTranslation: And the earth will shine with the light of its Lord.","«اَشْرَقَ» to fall upon and spread over something, and then illuminate it completely.","Radiance","اشرق","38:18-39:69",2
1250,264,"R","ثَقَبَ","«ثَقَبَ» The brightness of fire. The twinkling of a star. And «ثَقُب» being similar to fire in redness, i.e., being like fire (manjada). The complete penetration and passage of light (m. l). «ثَقَبَ» also means to pierce through something, and thāqib means so bright that its rays pierce through and pass beyond whatever they fall upon (muf). Thus, the concept of «ثَقَبَ» entails speed and a red, fiery light.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا مَنۡ خَطِفَ الۡخَطۡفَۃَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ  ثَاقِبٌ» (37:10)\nTranslation: But whoever snatches [a word] from the heavens will be pursued by a flaming meteor.","«ثَقَبَ» to pass through piercing red light.","Radiance","ثقب","37:10-86:3",2
1251,264,"S","سَنَا","«سَنَا» meaning the brilliant flash of lightning—a dazzling (blinding) light that takes away sight. For example, the Quran states: «یَکَادُ سَنَا بَرۡقِہٖ یَذۡہَبُ بِالۡاَبۡصَارِ» (24:43). Translation: And when the lightning flashes, it almost snatches away the sight.","«سَنَا» The light that casts the evil eye with its blinding dazzle.","Sparkle","سنا","24:43",1
1252,264,"R","دُرِیٌّ","Both concepts of brightness and excess are found in them. «سَیْفٌ دُرِیٌّ» means a sword with brilliance and sparkle. And «دَارٌّ» and «اَدْوَرُ» refer to a camel that gives a lot of milk. The word «مِدْرَارًا» carries the same meaning, and «دُرّ» denotes shining pearls. Sometimes both ideas are combined, as in «کَوکبٌ درّیّ», meaning a very bright and sparkling star—that is, extremely luminous and possessing great brilliance.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَاَنَّہَا کَوۡکَبٌ دُرِّیٌّ» (24/35)\nTranslation: As if it were a shining star.","«دُرِیّ» extremely radiant.","Radiance","دری","24:35",1
1253,265,"A","مَعْدُوْدَۃٌ","The meaning of «مَعْدُوْدَۃٌ» is 'a few, some'; 'less' in comparison to 'more'. For example, even hundreds are few compared to thousands.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12/20)\nTranslation: And the brothers of Joseph sold him for a few pieces of silver—a paltry sum.","«مَعْدُوْدَۃٌ» a few, fewer in comparison to many.","a few","معدودۃ","2:80-2:184-2:203-3:24-11:8-11:104-12:20",7
1254,265,"S","بِضْع","The intermediate numbers from three to ten can each be called «بِضْع» (f l 76. maf). Only the odd numbers from 3 to 9 are «بِضْع» (m. q). For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ غَلَبِہِمۡ سَیَغۡلِبُوۡنَ فِیۡ بِضۡعِ سِنِیۡنَ» (30/3,4)\nTranslation: And they (the Romans) will soon prevail after their defeat, within a few years.","Only the odd numbers from 3 to 9 are called «بِضْع».","Some","بضع","12:42-30:4",2
1255,265,"S","نَفَرٌ","«اَلنَّفَرُ» meaning many people as well as a group ranging from three to ten. «ثَلَاثَۃُ نَفَرٍ اَوْ اَنْفَازٍ» meaning three men (mentioned). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا» (72/1) Translation: (O Prophet! Say to the people) that revelation has come to me that a group of jinn listened (to this Book) and then said, We have heard a wondrous Quran.","The term «نَفَرٌ» denotes a group of three to nine individuals. It is applied to rational beings (those endowed with intellect and consciousness).","Some","نفر","18:34-46:29-72:1",3
1256,266,"T","اِخْتار","«خَیْر» refers to anything that is universally praised and desirable. «اِخْتار» signifies selecting the superior option from among many items of the same category.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ اخۡتَارَ مُوۡسٰی قَوۡمَہٗ سَبۡعِیۡنَ رَجُلًا لِّمِیۡقَاتِنَا» (7:155)  \nTranslation: And Moses chose from his people seventy men for the appointed time We had set.","to choose the better option from many «اِخْتار»","Tajweed","اختار","7:155-28:68",2
1257,266,"T","اِصْطَفٰی","«اَلصَّفَا» and «صَفْوُ» mean to be pure and clean (مف). «اَلصَّفِیُّ» and «اَلصَّفْوَۃ» are called a sincere friend (منجد), and «اِصْطَفٰی» means choosing something based on purity and the cleanliness of the self.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اصۡطَفٰۤی اٰدَمَ وَ نُوۡحًا وَّ اٰلَ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ  وَ اٰلَ عِمۡرٰنَ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (3/33)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah the Exalted has chosen Adam, Noah, the family of Abraham, and the family of Imran above all the worlds.","«اِصْطَفٰی» choosing something based on its purity.","Tajweed","اصطفی","2:130-2:132-2:247-3:33-3:42-7:144-22:75-27:59-35:32-37:153-38:47-39:4",12
1258,266,"R","اِجْتَبٰی","«جَبُو» has two meanings: (1) to gather something, and (2) then to take it somewhere. According to the words of Ibn Faris, «جَمْعُ الشَّیءُ وَالْتَجَمَّعُ» are «جَمْعُ الشَّیءُ وَالْتَجَمَّعُ» (m. l). Furthermore, the word «جَبُو» generally comes to mean collecting a tax (mal), which also includes bringing it to the treasury. And «مُجْبٰی» means kharaj—a levy imposed on non-Muslims in Islamic states.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُّجۡبٰۤی  اِلَیۡہِ  ثَمَرٰتُ  کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ» (28:57)\nTranslation: That is, every kind of fruit is brought forth (Othmani) and conveyed (Jalandhari).\n\nAnd the meaning of «اِجْتَبٰی» is to select something excellent and bring it close, to make it chosen and preferred.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ یَجۡتَبِیۡکَ رَبُّکَ وَ یُعَلِّمُکَ مِنۡ تَاۡوِیۡلِ الۡاَحَادِیۡثِ» (12:6)\nTranslation: And thus (O Joseph) Allah will choose you and teach you the interpretation of events.","«اِجْتَبٰی» to choose someone and make them one's confidant.","Recitation","اجتبی","3:179-6:87-7:203-12:6-16:121-19:58-20:122-22:78-42:13-68:50",10
1259,266,"T","اِسْتَخْلَصَ","«خَلَصَ» means to be free from any mixture or adulteration. To be pure. And «خَلَّص» means to make pure (exclusively). Its opposite is «خَلَطَ». Therefore, the meaning of «اِسْتَخْلَصَ» is to choose someone and to designate them exclusively for oneself.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَالَ الۡمَلِکُ ائۡتُوۡنِیۡ بِہٖۤ  اَسۡتَخۡلِصۡہُ لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (12/54)\nTranslation: The King of Egypt ordered, Bring Joseph to me. I will make him my exclusive confidant.","the selection of a person for a specific purpose","Tajweed","استخلص","2:139-4:146-7:29-10:22-12:24-12:54-12:80-15:40-19:51-29:65-31:32-37:40-37:74-37:128-37:160-37:169-38:46-38:83-39:2-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:65-98:5",24
1260,266,"B","اِصْطَنَعَ","The meaning of «صَنَعَ» is to create something with technical skill. And «اِصْطَنَعَ» means selecting a suitable person for a specific purpose and training them specially.  \nFor example, regarding Prophet Musa, the Divine decree states:  \n«وَ اصۡطَنَعۡتُکَ  لِنَفۡسِیۡ» (20/41)  \nTranslation: And (O Musa) I have chosen you for My work.","«اِصْطَنَعَ» To select someone for a specific purpose and train them in a suitable (appropriate) manner.","Blacksmith","اصطنع","20:41",1
1261,267,"F","وُحُوْش","«وُحُوْش» is the plural form of «وَحَشَ». And it is the opposite of «وَحَشْ ، اِنْس». Meaning creatures that are not familiar with humans, such as wild animals and predators, etc. (mufradat)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  اِذَا  الۡوُحُوۡشُ حُشِرَتۡ» (81:5)\nTranslation: And when the wild beasts are gathered together.","«وُحُوْش» wild animals, predators.","Flock","وحوش","81:5",1
1262,267,"C","بَھَائِم","«بَھَائِم» is the plural of «بَھِیْمَہ». And it applies to all other types of animals except wild ones (مف), whether terrestrial or aquatic. (منجد) However, its usage is more common for sheep, goats, and cows (منجد). «بَھِم» refers to the young of sheep and goats (مف). And another definition of «بَھِیْمَہ» is such animals (except predators) that lack the power of speech (منجد). And «بُھِم» refers to difficult work, and «اَبْھَمْ» to the mute (منجد).","«بَھَائِم» The term for grazing animals, excluding predators, typically refers to sheep, goats, and cattle.","cattle","بھائم","5:1-22:28-22:34",3
1263,267,"C","اَنعَام","«اَنعَام» is a plural term. Although its application also extends to animals other than predators, its usage is predominantly for the camel (see footnote 134), as for the Arabs, there was no blessing greater than the camel. In the Quran, the word *An'am* also appears in its singular form.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«مَّتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» (80:32)\nTranslation: This is all for you and your livestock.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ ارۡعَوۡا اَنۡعَامَکُمۡ» (20:54)\nTranslation: You and your livestock will eat thereof.\n\nHowever, the word «بَھِیْمَۃ» (in its singular form) frequently appears alongside the word *An'am*.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«مِّنۡۢ بَہِیۡمَۃِ الۡاَنۡعَامِ ۚ فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا  الۡبَآئِسَ الۡفَقِیۡرَ» (22:28)\nTranslation: Eat thereof and feed the poor and the needy.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«اُحِلَّتۡ لَکُمۡ بَہِیۡمَۃُ الۡاَنۡعَامِ  اِلَّا مَا یُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡکُمۡ» (5:1)\nTranslation: Grazing livestock have been made lawful for you, except what is recited to you.","«اَنعَام» is generally used to denote camels among non-predatory livestock.","cattle","انعام","3:14-4:119-5:1-6:136-6:138-6:139-6:142-7:179-10:24-16:5-16:66-16:80-20:54-22:28-22:30-22:34-23:21-25:44-25:49-26:133-32:27-35:28-36:71-39:6-40:79-42:11-43:12-47:12-79:33-80:32",30
1264,267,"M","اَلدَّوَّاب","«دَوَّاب» is a collective term «دَآبَۃ». And every creature that moves on the surface of the earth, whether it crawls on its belly like a serpent, etc., or walks on two feet like a human, or some types of monkeys, or four-footed [creatures] like wild animals, etc., whether used for riding or for carrying loads, masculine or feminine—for all of them, the word «دَابَّۃ» (dabbah) is generally applicable. However, its usage is specifically for horses, donkeys, and mules. (See p. 134) In the Quran, its usage is not specific but absolute.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ دَآبَّۃٍ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  رِزۡقُہَا» (11:6)\nTranslation: And there is no creature on the earth whose provision is not the responsibility of Allah.\n\nMoreover, before «اَرْض», the word «فِی» indicates that water-dwelling creatures and birds are also included in it.\nFor example: The Majestic Lord declares:\n«اِنَّ شَرَّ الدَّوَآبِّ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (8:55)\nTranslation: Indeed, the worst of living creatures in the sight of Allah are those who disbelieve.","«دَوَّاب» Every living creature that moves upon the earth.","milch cattle","الدواب","2:164-6:38-8:22-8:55-11:6-11:56-16:49-16:61-22:18-24:45-27:82-29:60-31:10-34:14-35:28-35:45-42:29-45:4",18
1265,268,"M","ھَشِیْم","«ھَشَمَ» means 'to cut'. And «ھَشِیْم» refers to cut dry grass (manjad), and by it is meant all kinds of plant chaff, straw, and husks.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«اِنَّاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ صَیۡحَۃً  وَّاحِدَۃً فَکَانُوۡا کَہَشِیۡمِ  الۡمُحۡتَظِرِ» (54/31)  \nTranslation: Then We sent upon them a single blast, and they became like the dry, broken stubble of a fence.","«ھَشِیْم» is dried, cut grass; the dry chopped fodder of all kinds of plants. Hay.","minutiae","ھشیم","18:45-54:31",2
1266,268,"S","حُطَام","«حَطَمَ» means to break, to twist. And «حَطُوْم» refers to such a violent and fierce wind that breaks and twists everything. And «حُطَام» denotes something that is broken, twisted, or reduced to fragments (minajd). This word is also used for something that is crushed and pulverized. To crush completely (intensive).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا» ( 39/21 )\nTranslation: Then Allah brings forth from the earth various kinds of vegetation. Then when they ripen, you see them turning yellow; then He makes them chaff.","«حُطَام» powdered dry plant products. That which is made by crushing and grinding.","Sustenance","حطام","27:18-39:21-56:65-57:20-104:4-104:5",6
1267,268,"R","غُثَآء","«غُثَآء» refers to dirt and filth trapped in the foam of floodwater, as well as rotten leaves from trees that are mixed in the foam (manjad). And «غَثِیَ الْکَلَام» means mixing falsehood and truth in speech. Moreover, «غُثَآء» is also used for straw, chaff, and dirt (muf). For example, the Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» (87:4-5). The translation is: He brought forth pasture from the earth, then made it black stubble.","«غُثَآء» straw and chaff, garbage and debris.","Residue","غثآء","23:41-87:5",2
1268,268,"R","ھَبَآء","Dust and particles that the wind carries around. Flying dust (fl 253). Fine particles of soil that are spread in the wind. And «اَلْھَبْوَۃٌ» refers to the whirlwinds of dust (Minjhad).\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  ہَبَآءً  مَّنۡثُوۡرًا» (25:23)\nTranslation: And whatever deeds they have done, We will turn them into flying dust.","«ھَبَآء» Dust, the flying particles of everything.","Residue","ھبآء","25:23-56:6",2
1269,268,"P","رُفَات","«رَفَتَ» means to break and crush (from *munajjad*), and «رُفَات» means a crushed thing, or rotten (from *munajjad*). This term is used when something becomes fragmented due to decay.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤاءَ اِذَا کُنَّا عِظَامًا  وَّ  رُفَاتًاءَ اِنَّا  لَمَبۡعُوۡثُوۡنَ  خَلۡقًا جَدِیۡدًا» (17/49)\n\nTranslation: And they say, When we are dead and have become decayed bones, will we indeed be resurrected as a new creation?","«رُفَات» the crumbling into fragments of something due to decay.","particle","رفات","17:49-17:98",2
1270,268,"R","بَسَّ","«بَسَّ» means to be reduced to fine particles or crumbs (intransitive). According to the author of *Muqaddimat al-Lughah*, its two fundamental meanings are: (1) to crumble something, and (2) to mix it with something else. Both of these meanings are corroborated by the Noble Quran.  \nFor example, the Divine Command states:  \n«وَّ  بُسَّتِ الۡجِبَالُ  بَسًّا فَکَانَتۡ ہَبَآءً  مُّنۡۢبَثًّا» (56:5-6)  \nTranslation: And the mountains will be crumbled to dust, so they will become floating dust.","«بَسَّ» (of a stone or any object) to be shattered into pieces.","Remnants","بس","56:5",1
1271,268,"D","دَکَّآء","The basic meanings of «دَکَّ» are two: (1) to crush or cut, and (2) then to level it smoothly (m.l.), meaning to crush something, break it into fine particles, and make it level with the ground (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when his Lord manifested Himself to the mountain, He crushed it to fine particles and made it like dust.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«قَالَ ہٰذَا رَحۡمَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّیۡ ۚ فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ جَعَلَہٗ دَکَّآءَ ۚ وَ کَانَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ حَقًّا» (18/98)\nTranslation: Dhul-Qarnayn said, This is a mercy from my Lord. Then when the time my Lord has promised comes, He will level it (the barrier) to the ground. And my Lord's promise is always true.","«دکّاء» to be reduced to ground level, scattered into pieces.","Dust","دکآء","7:143-18:98-89:21",3
1272,269,"T","سَرَق","«سَرَق» Stealing is a well-known term. It means secretly taking someone else's owned property from a secure place.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا» ( 5/38 )\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the thief, whether male or female.\nAnd «اِسْتَرَق» means to attempt theft. And «اِسْتَرَقُ السَّمْع» means to eavesdrop or secretly listen to conversations.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ اسۡتَرَقَ السَّمۡعَ فَاَتۡبَعَہٗ شِہَابٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» ( 15/18 )\nTranslation: Indeed, if a [evil] one intends to eavesdrop, he will be pursued by a brightly shooting star.","«سَرَق» stealing is generally understood.","theft","سرق","5:38-12:70-12:73-12:77-12:81-60:12",6
1273,269,"T","غَلَّ","«غَلَّ» means to secretly seize something and keep it among one's possessions (Majma‘ al-Bayan, vol. 3). This is, in essence, a blended form of theft and breach of trust. Therefore, this word is translated as both 'to steal' and 'to be treacherous.' For example, taking something from the shared war booty that does not fulfill the conditions of theft, etc.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3:161)\nTranslation: And whoever conceals it will come with it on the Day of Resurrection. (Uthmani).","«غَلَّ» the blended form of theft and treachery.","theft","غل","3:161",1
1274,270,"W","حَرَسَ","«حَرَسَ» means to take into protection, to guard, to keep watch over, or to supervise a suspect. According to Ibn Faris, two elements are found in «حَرَسَ»: (1) protection, and (2) a period of time (i.e., to supervise for a certain duration). And «حَرَسَ الْمَلِکْ» means a royal guard or a bodyguard (manjada).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا» (72:8)\nTranslation: And we [the jinn] have sought [to reach] the heaven but found it filled with mighty guards and meteors.","«حَرَسَ» a guard responsible for supervision and protection for a specified period.","watchman","حرس","72:8",1
1275,270,"S","رَصَد","«رَصَد» meaning to sit in ambush, to keep watch. And «مرصاد» meaning the place of sitting in ambush. And «رَاصِد» meaning the one sitting in ambush; its plural is «رُصَّد», and «رَصَد» is derived from it.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِلَّا مَنِ ارۡتَضٰی مِنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ فَاِنَّہٗ یَسۡلُکُ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ  وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ رَصَدًا» (72/27)\nTranslation: Yes, to whichever prophet He wills, He reveals the news of the unseen and places guards before him and behind him.","«رَصَد» a guard lying in wait for when the prey arrives, to seize it on the spot.","Security guard","رصد","9:5-9:107-72:9-72:27-78:21-89:14",6
1276,270,"W","مُعَقِّبْ","«عَقَّب» meaning to come behind, to walk behind (from manjada). And «مُعَقِّبَات» meaning those who walk behind; guardian; protector; watchman; guard.  \nFor example: In the Quran, «لَہٗ  مُعَقِّبٰتٌ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ یَدَیۡہِ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہٖ  یَحۡفَظُوۡنَہٗ  مِنۡ اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (13/11):  \nTranslation: They protect them under Allah’s command, both in front and behind.","«مُعَقِّبٰت» A constant companion and guardian who stays close to protect and shield from harm.","Watchman","معقب","13:11-13:41",2
1277,271,"A","غَابَ","The word «غَابَ» is general. «غَیْب» refers to something concealed. Anything that becomes invisible from sight, whether due to some reason or at some time (as per lexical sources), is thus described by this general term. Its opposite is «حَضَرَ». However, according to the scholar of linguistic jurisprudence, everything that is hidden from human knowledge and senses is considered 'gha'ib' (absent/concealed), though its concept can be formed in the heart (cf. 16).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَا مِنۡ غَآئِبَۃٍ  فِی السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ  اِلَّا  فِیۡ  کِتٰبٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (27/75)\nTranslation: And there is not a thing hidden within the earth or the heaven except that it is in a clear book.","«غَابَ» is beyond the scope of the five senses—that is, beyond control, power, and authority.","Absent","غاب","2:3-2:33-3:44-3:179-4:34-5:94-6:50-6:59-6:73-7:7-7:188-9:94-9:105-10:20-11:31-11:49-11:123-12:52-12:81-12:102-13:9-16:77-18:22-18:26-19:61-19:78-21:49-23:92-27:20-27:65-27:75-32:6-34:3-34:14-34:53-35:18-35:38-36:11-39:46-49:18-50:33-52:41-53:35-57:25-59:22-62:8-64:18-67:12-68:47-72:26-81:24-82:16",52
1278,271,"A","اَفَلَ","«اَفَلَ» is used for the setting or disappearance of celestial bodies (e.g., sun, moon, stars) (sing.).  \nFor example, in the Quran:  \n«فَلَمَّا رَاَ الۡقَمَرَ بَازِغًا قَالَ ہٰذَا رَبِّیۡ ۚ فَلَمَّاۤ اَفَلَ قَالَ لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ یَہۡدِنِیۡ رَبِّیۡ لَاَکُوۡنَنَّ مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ الضَّآلِّیۡنَ» (6:77)  \nTranslation: Then when he saw the moon appearing, he said, 'This is my Lord.' But when it set, he said, 'If my Lord does not guide me, I will surely be among the people astray.'","«اَفَلَ» is used for the disappearance or setting of celestial bodies (e.g., the sun, moon, stars).","Absent","افل","6:76-6:77-6:78",3
1279,271,"A","غَرَبَ","«غَرَبَ» This word is used for the sun's setting or disappearing, as «شَرَقَ» for rising, and in «طَلَعَ» all planets including the sun are included. For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ» (18/16) Translation: And when the sun rises, you will see that (the shade) contracts from the right side of their cave, and when it sets, it departs from them to the left.","«غَرَبَ» solar eclipse.","Absent","غرب","2:115-2:142-2:177-2:258-7:137-18:17-18:86-20:130-24:35-26:28-28:44-50:39-55:17-70:40-73:9",15
1280,271,"A","عَزَبَ","«عَزَبَ» To become invisible to the eyes due to moving far away. And «عَازَب» it is said about a man who goes far away from his family and dependents in search of grass (metaphorical). And «عَزَّب» meaning to remain absent for a long time (lexical).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَا یَعۡزُبُ عَنۡ رَّبِّکَ مِنۡ مِّثۡقَالِ  ذَرَّۃٍ» ( 10/61 )\nTranslation: And not even an atom's weight of anything can remain hidden from your Lord.","«عَزَبَ» to be absent due to having gone far away.","Absent","عزب","10:61-34:3",2
1281,271,"A","وَقَبَ","«وَقَبَ» means to disappear by descending into a pit. The idiom «وَقَبَتِ الشَّمْس» is used for the setting of the sun, and «وَقَبَ الظَّلَام» refers to darkness spreading. (مف) «اَلْوَقْب» means a stone pit where water collects. And «وَقَبَ» refers to entering the pit. (منجد)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنۡ  شَرِّ غَاسِقٍ  اِذَا وَقَبَ» (113/3)\nTranslation: And from the evil of the dark night when it spreads.","«وَقَبَ» descend into the pit and disappear.","Absent","وقب","113:3",1
1282,271,"A","بَطَنَ","«بَطَنَ» means the belly or the inner part of something. And since the inner part is completely hidden, therefore the usage of «بَطَنَ» is for something that is entirely concealed, and its opposite is «ظَھَرَ». (Example)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ» (7/33)\nTranslation: Say, My Lord has forbidden all kinds of indecencies, whether they are open or secret.","«بَطَنَ» to be completely hidden.","Absent","بطن","3:35-6:151-7:33-24:45-37:144",5
1283,271,"A","تَوَارَی","«وَرٰی» means to veil the truth. And «یَتوٰرٰی» means to hide and move about from others after being defeated by a reality (i.e., after a truth has overwhelmed one).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«یَتَوَارٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءِ مَا بُشِّرَ بِہٖ» (16/59)  \nTranslation: He hides and moves about from his people due to the distress caused by the news of [the birth of] a daughter.","«یَتوٰرٰی» fleeing from a truth while persistently hiding from others.","Absent","تواری","16:59-38:32",2
1284,271,"U","خَفِی","«خَفِی» is the opposite of «بَدَا» and «عَلَنَ». It means the state of a thing or matter being concealed from others. This term has a greater sense of generality than «غَابَ» (i.e., it refers to something remaining hidden whose very conception is impossible).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا  یَخۡفٰی عَلَیۡہِ شَیۡءٌ  فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (3:5)\nTranslation: Nothing in the earth or the heavens is hidden from Allah.","«خَفِی» is the concealment of something from others. This word is even more common than «غَابَ».","Unseen","خفی","2:271-2:284-3:5-3:29-3:118-3:154-4:108-4:149-5:15-6:28-6:63-6:91-7:55-11:5-13:10-14:38-19:3-20:7-20:15-24:31-27:25-32:17-33:37-33:54-40:16-40:19-41:40-42:45-60:1-69:18-87:7",31
1285,271,"A","کَنَّ","«کِنّ» means a cave in a secure place or inside a mountain where a person can take refuge. And the meanings of its plurals «اَکْنَان» and «اَکِنَّۃ» and «کَنَّ» are that something is hidden in a secure place beyond the reach of common people (Muf. Manjad).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:\n«کَاَنَّہُنَّ بَیۡضٌ مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (37/49)\nTranslation: They (the houris of Paradise) are like eggs kept in a secure place.","«کَنَّ» to hide in some safe place.","Absent","کن","37:49-52:24-56:23-56:78",4
1286,272,"T","کَتَمَ","«کَتَمَ» To deliberately conceal something in one's heart. (Faqih 237) This term is generally used for concealing the truth, faith, and testimony. Its opposite is «اَبْدَا». Now observe their examples:\n\nThe Divine Command states:\n(1) «وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ مِمَّنۡ کَتَمَ شَہَادَۃً عِنۡدَہٗ مِنَ اللّٰہِ» (2/140)\nTranslation: Who is more unjust than the one who conceals the testimony of Allah which he has (in the Book of Allah)?\n\nThe Divine Command states:\n(2) «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡتُمُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡبَیِّنٰتِ» (2/159)\nTranslation: Those who conceal Our revealed commandments.\n\nThe Divine Command states:\n(3) «وَ قَالَ رَجُلٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٌ ٭ۖ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ یَکۡتُمُ  اِیۡمَانَہٗۤ» (40/28)\nTranslation: And a believing man from among the people of Pharaoh, who used to conceal his faith, said...","«کَتَمَ» is generally used for knowingly and deliberately concealing testimony, faith, and the truth.","to hide","کتم","2:33-2:42-2:72-2:140-2:146-2:159-2:174-2:228-2:283-3:71-3:167-3:187-4:37-4:42-5:61-5:99-5:106-21:110-24:29-40:28",20
1287,272,"T","وَارٰی","«وَرٰی» is essentially used in two meanings: (1) to ignite fire or produce sparks; they say: «وَرِيَ الزَّنْدُ» he struck a flint to produce fire. And (2) to place a veil over a truth. Here, only the second meaning is under discussion.\n\nFor example, in the Quran: «فَوَسۡوَسَ لَہُمَا الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِیُبۡدِیَ لَہُمَا مَا وٗرِیَ عَنۡہُمَا مِنۡ سَوۡاٰتِہِمَا» (7/20)\nTranslation: Then Satan began to whisper to both of them so that he might reveal to them their private parts which were concealed from them.\n\nAnd the meaning of «وَارٰی یُوَارِیْ» is to conceal a truth by placing it behind a screen or cover, i.e., to make it hidden from others' sight (detailed).\n\nFor example, the divine saying: «فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that began to scratch the earth, to show him (Cain) how to conceal his brother's corpse.","«وَارٰی» is used to hide some truth from people.","to hide","واری","5:31-7:20-7:26-16:59-38:32",5
1288,272,"T","اَکَنَّ","«اَکَنَّ» In its material, two fundamental aspects are found: (1) concealment and (2) protection (m. l.). Or, put another way, this word is used for hiding something in a secure place for protection (f. l. 238), whether something is concealed in the heart or an object is hidden elsewhere. «کنّ» means a cave or a small hollow in a mountain where one can take refuge, and its plural is «اَکْنَان». And «اَکِنَّۃ» refers to such a screen, cover, or shelter behind which something cannot proceed or enter.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ  اَکِنَّۃً  اَنۡ یَّفۡقَہُوۡہُ» (6/25)\nTranslation: And We have placed covers over their hearts so that they cannot understand it.\n\nAnd the word «اَکَنَ» has been used in the Quran generally in a spiritual sense, and its opposite is «عَلَنَ».\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ فِیۡمَا عَرَّضۡتُمۡ بِہٖ مِنۡ خِطۡبَۃِ النِّسَآءِ اَوۡ اَکۡنَنۡتُمۡ فِیۡۤ  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ» (2/235)\nTranslation: Give the women their dowry graciously; but if they, of their own accord, remit any part of it to you, then you may make use of it with a good conscience. There is no blame on you if you marry them while you have concealed something in your hearts.\n\nAnd for this same secure place, the words «نُفُوس ، نَفْس ، صُدُوْر» and «قُلُوب» are generally used in the Quran.","«اَکَنَّ» is used to hide something in a secure location.","to hide","اکن","2:235-6:25-16:81-17:46-18:57-41:5",6
1289,272,"T","اَسَرَّ","The meaning of «سِرّ» is a secret matter, and its plural is «اَسْرَار». And «اَسَرَّ» means to conceal a secret matter in the heart, whether it is a reality or not. Rather, it is concealed merely for the sake of interest. Its opposite is also «جَھَرَ» and «عَلَنَ». And «سَارَّ» means to whisper or to talk about secrets with each other. (Munjid) In the Quran, this word has been used in both literal and spiritual senses.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» (12/19) Translation: He said, 'What a fortunate one! This is indeed a (very handsome) boy.' Then the caravan people considered him as merchandise and concealed him.\n\nAt another place, the divine command is: «وَ اِذۡ  اَسَرَّ النَّبِیُّ  اِلٰی  بَعۡضِ  اَزۡوَاجِہٖ حَدِیۡثًا» (66/3) Translation: And when the Prophet ﷺ confided a secret matter to one of his wives.","«اَسَرَّ» is used to conceal a confidential matter for beneficial reasons.","to hide","اسر","5:52-10:54-12:19-12:77-13:10-20:62-21:3-34:33-66:3-67:13-71:9",11
1290,272,"T","اَخْفٰی","Its usage is general. It applies whether a matter or thought is hidden in the heart, or a thing, in some other context, possesses some reality or benefit or not. It is used in both literal and spiritual senses, and its opposites are «بَدَا», «عَلَنَ», and «جَلٰی ، جَلَو». Moreover, spiritually, it is even more general than «سِرٌّ», because «سِرٌّ» is limited to the concealment of a matter, whereas «خَفِىّ» also includes imaginations (analogies, concepts) and insinuations. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَاِنَّہٗ یَعۡلَمُ السِّرَّ وَ اَخۡفٰی» (20:7). Translation: Indeed, He knows the hidden secrets and the most concealed matters.","«اَخْفٰی» is a secret matter which a person keeps concealed in his heart and never discloses it to others.","to hide","اخفی","20:7-20:15-32:17-60:1",4
1291,272,"T","خَبۡءَ","«خَبَأَ» means to keep something hidden. And «خَابَاَ» means to speak in riddles to someone, or to speak in a roundabout way, or to say something in a secretive manner. And «اِخْتَبَا لَہٗ خَبِیْئًا» means to ask someone about something while keeping it hidden from them (source). And «خَبۡءَ» means hidden and secret treasure (abbr.). «خَبۡءَ الْاَرْض» means the vegetation of the earth. The power of growth (i.e., the act of growing or cultivating). And «خَبۡءَ السَّمَاء» means rain. And «اَخْرَجَ خَبۡءَ السَّمَآءِ خَبۡءَ الْاَرْضِ» means the rain from the sky caused growth on the earth. It made things apparent and grew plants (source).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n\n«اَلَّا یَسۡجُدُوۡا  لِلّٰہِ الَّذِیۡ یُخۡرِجُ الۡخَبۡءَ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تُخۡفُوۡنَ  وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ» (27/25)\n\nTranslation: Why should they not prostrate to Allah, who reveals what is hidden in the heavens and the earth and knows what you conceal and what you reveal?","«خَبۡءَ» hidden and secret treasures.","to conceal","خبۡء","27:25",1
1292,273,"R","عَرْش","«عَرَشَ یَعْرِشُ» means to build a wooden structure; to lay wooden beams, such as rafters, on a building; and to train grapevines to climb, etc. And «عَرَش» has two basic meanings: (1) royal throne, (2) wooden beams used in a roof (manjad). This word is also used for the roof of a room, tent, canopy, and anything that provides shade (m. r.). In the Quran, this word is used in both meanings. Examples for the roof and its beams: For instance, the divine command says: «اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا» (2/259) Translation: Or like the one who passed by a town whose roofs had collapsed. And for the throne: The divine command says: «وَ رَفَعَ اَبَوَیۡہِ عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» 12/100 Translation: And they raised their parents to the throne.","«عَرْش» Laying a wooden roof on the house.","Roof","عرش","2:259-7:54-9:129-10:3-11:7-12:100-13:2-17:42-18:42-20:5-21:22-22:45-23:86-23:116-25:59-27:23-27:26-27:38-27:41-27:42-32:4-39:75-40:7-40:15-43:82-57:4-69:17-81:20-85:15",29
1293,273,"R","سَقْف","«سَقْف» the inner part of the ceiling that is visible from inside a room (ceiling) or the sky chamber (mar), plural «سُقَف».  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: «فَخَرَّ عَلَیۡہِمُ السَّقۡفُ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہِمۡ» (16/26)  \nTranslation: Then the ceiling fell upon them from above.","«سَقْف» the inner part of the ceiling that is visible from inside the room.","roof","سقف","16:26-21:32-43:33-52:5",4
1294,273,"R","بِنَآء","«بِنَآء» means construction, and one can refer to any built structure or any part of it as «بِنَآء», whether it is the foundation, a wall, the roof, or the entire building. Moreover, when the word «بِنَآء» is used in contrast to 'floor', its meaning will specifically be 'roof', because the word «بِنَآء» also denotes elevation or height in a construction (m. l.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الۡاَرۡضَ فِرَاشًا وَّ السَّمَآءَ بِنَآءً» (2/22)\nTranslation: [He is] the One Who has made the earth a floor for you and the sky a roof.","«بِنَآء» meaning a constructed building.","roof","بنآء","2:22-40:64",2
1295,274,"T","تَرَکَ","«تَرَکَ» This word is general. That is, to leave something, whether intentionally or unintentionally, optional or compulsory. It can be used in every context.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنۡ تَرَکَ خَیۡرَۨا  ۚ ۖ  الۡوَصِیَّۃُ لِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ» (2/180)\nTranslation: When death approaches any of you, if he leaves wealth, it is for parents and near relatives a duty (bequest).\n\nThis situation was compulsory. Now see an example of optional or intentional:\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ تَرَکۡنَا یُوۡسُفَ عِنۡدَ مَتَاعِنَا» (12/17)\nTranslation: And they said, We will certainly guard him and his brother, and we will leave him with our belongings.","«تَرَکَ» meaning to leave something.","to abandon","ترک","2:17-2:180-2:248-2:264-4:7-4:9-4:11-4:12-4:33-4:176-6:94-7:176-9:16-11:87-12:17-12:37-16:61-18:99-23:100-26:146-29:2-29:35-35:45-37:78-37:108-37:119-37:129-44:24-44:25-51:37-54:15-59:5-62:11-75:36",34
1296,274,"T","ھَجَرَ","«ھَجَرَ» is a term that denotes severing relations between one person and another or others. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اصۡبِرۡ عَلٰی مَا یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ وَ اہۡجُرۡہُمۡ ہَجۡرًا جَمِیۡلًا» (73/10) Translation: And bear patiently what the disbelievers say and part from them in a good manner.\n\nAnother form of severing ties with people is to abandon that region entirely. In this case, migration means leaving one's homeland. For example, the Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  ہَاجَرُوۡا وَ جٰہَدُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (2/218) Translation: And those who emigrated and fought in the way of Allah.","«ھَجَرَ» abandoning ties or one's homeland.","to abandon","ھجر","2:218-3:195-4:34-4:89-4:97-4:100-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:20-9:100-9:117-16:41-16:110-19:46-22:58-24:22-25:30-29:26-33:6-33:50-59:8-59:9-60:10-73:10-74:5",26
1297,274,"T","عَطَّلَ","«عَطَّلَ» To leave something idle or unused. To render a worker idle or unemployed. (Figurative) «تعطیل» Meaning the time of leave from work. And «مُعَطّل» This term is used for an employee who is still in service but has been stopped from working.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ  اِذَا الۡعِشَارُ عُطِّلَتۡ» ( 81/4 )  \nTranslation: And when the ten-month pregnant camels are left untended.  \nAnd «بِئْرٌ مُعَطَّلَۃٌ» This term refers to wells that are ruined, desolate, or uninhabited.","«عَطَّلَ» to leave someone idle.","To leave","عطل","22:45-81:4",2
1298,274,"T","خَلّٰی","«خَلَو ، خَلَا» means to be empty or void. It is used in both linguistic and spatial contexts.  \n«خَلَا اِلٰی بَعْض» means to meet someone in solitude.  \n«خَلّٰی» means to leave someone alone and separate oneself, i.e., to leave someone in an empty space. It conveys the meanings of granting freedom, not seizing, or not retaining. (Figuratively)  \n«خَلّٰی سَبِیْلًا» is an idiom used in the sense of not seizing or not retaining someone.  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَاِنۡ تَابُوۡا وَ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُا الزَّکٰوۃَ  فَخَلُّوۡا سَبِیۡلَہُمۡ» (9:5)  \nTranslation: Then if they (the hypocrites) repent, establish prayer, and give zakah, leave their way free. (i.e., do not seize them).","«خَلَّا سَبِیْلًا» to abandon someone's path; not to seize.","to leave / to abandon","خلی","2:14-2:76-2:141-2:214-3:119-3:137-3:144-5:75-7:38-9:5-9:118-10:102-12:9-13:6-13:30-15:13-24:34-33:38-33:62-35:24-40:85-41:25-46:17-46:18-46:21-48:23-84:4",27
1299,274,"T","یَذَرُ","«وَذَرَ» is a deficient verb. Its usage is limited to the present tense and imperative; the past tense is not employed. Its application occurs in two contexts:\n\n(1) To abandon something considering it insignificant (e.g., Quran).\nFor instance: The Quran states:\n«وَ ذَرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّخَذُوۡا دِیۡنَہُمۡ لَعِبًا وَّ لَہۡوًا» (6/70)\nTranslation: And leave those who have taken their religion as amusement and play (i.e., have no concern with them).\n\n(2) To not grant permission to someone to interfere or object regarding the performance of an action. Its equivalent in English is the word LET. And the meaning of «ذَرْنِیْ» would be (LET ME DO THIS).\n\nFor instance: The Quran states:\n«ذَرۡنِیۡ  وَ مَنۡ خَلَقۡتُ وَحِیۡدًا» (74/11)\nTranslation: Leave me and whom I have created alone.\nThe implication is: I know (what is best), and they (the created ones) know. Do not intervene in this matter.","to write off","to abandon","یذر","2:234-2:240-2:278-3:179-4:129-6:70-6:91-6:110-6:112-6:120-6:137-7:70-7:73-7:127-7:180-7:186-9:86-10:11-11:64-12:47-15:3-19:72-20:106-21:89-23:54-26:166-37:125-40:26-43:83-48:15-51:42-52:45-62:9-68:44-70:42-71:23-71:26-71:27-73:11-74:11-74:28-75:21-76:27",43
1300,274,"T","دَعْ","This is also an incomplete verb, of which only the present tense and imperative are used; the past tense does not occur. Its meaning is to leave something in a peaceful manner (trans.).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ دَعۡ  اَذٰىہُمۡ  وَ  تَوَکَّلۡ  عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (33:48)  \nTranslation: You leave their harm to Allah and put your trust in Allah!  \n\nAnd the meaning of «وَدَّعَ» is to bid farewell to a traveler or to dismiss someone with happiness, honor, and dignity (trans.), in which the aspect of separating oneself and leaving it is also found.  \nFor example, the divine command states:  \n«مَا وَدَّعَکَ رَبُّکَ وَ مَا قَلٰی» (93:3)  \nTranslation: Your Lord has neither abandoned you nor become angry with you.","«دَعْ» to let someone go peacefully.","to abandon","دع","33:48-93:3",2
1301,274,"T","غَادَرَ","The word «غَدَرَ» is used for breach of covenant and disloyalty. And غدار means disloyal and a breaker of covenant (masc.), and its opposite is «وَفٰی». And «غَادَرَ» means to abandon something due to a flaw occurring in it, or to leave it remaining (masc.).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ حَشَرۡنٰہُمۡ  فَلَمۡ  نُغَادِرۡ  مِنۡہُمۡ اَحَدًا» (18/47)\nTranslation: When We gather them, We will not leave any of them behind.\nMeaning: No person's deeds, whatever their nature, will be left unaccounted for.\n\nAt another place, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«مَالِ ہٰذَا الۡکِتٰبِ لَا یُغَادِرُ صَغِیۡرَۃً وَّ لَا کَبِیۡرَۃً  اِلَّاۤ  اَحۡصٰہَا» (18/49)\nTranslation: What a book it is! It has not left any of our deeds, small or great, without encompassing them.","to abandon someone due to a defect","to abandon","غادر","18:47-18:49",2
1302,275,"T","فَکَّ","«فَکّ» means to free something from someone's possession or to liberate it.  \n«فَکَّ الرَّھْن» means to free a pledged or pawned item.  \n«فَکَّ الْاَسِیْر» means to free a war captive. (Source: Munjid)  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» (90:12,13)  \nTranslation: And what will make you know what the steep path is? It is the freeing of a slave (from bondage).","«فَکّ» To take something out of someone's possession or to set it free.","to snatch","فک","90:13",1
1303,275,"T","اَنْقَذَ","«اَنْقَذَ» means to rescue, save, or deliver a person from calamity or punishment. (intransitive)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» ( 39/19 )\nTranslation: Can you rescue such a person who is in the Hellfire?\nAnd «اِسْتَنْفَذَ» means to snatch something away with full effort and desire.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ ؕ ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ» ( 22/73 )\nTranslation: And if a fly should snatch away something from them, they cannot even snatch it back from it. Such a supplicant is also powerless, and so is the one from whom the supplication is sought.","«اَنْقَذَ» comes to rescue someone from a calamity.","to snatch away","انقذ","3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19",5
1304,276,"T","مَسَّ","«مَسَّ» The affliction of something upon any part of the body (transitive). This word also appears in the Quran with this meaning.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَیُّوۡبَ اِذۡ نَادٰی رَبَّہٗۤ  اَنِّیۡ مَسَّنِیَ الضُّرُّ» (21/83)\nTranslation: And [mention] Job, when he called to his Lord, Indeed, adversity has touched me.\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَنۡ تَمَسَّنَا النَّارُ اِلَّاۤ اَیَّامًا مَّعۡدُوۡدَۃً» (2/80)\nTranslation: And they say, The Fire will not touch us except for a few days.","«مَسَّ» something adhering to a part of the body.","to touch","مس","2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-4:43-5:6-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21",58
1305,276,"T","لَمَسَ","«لَمَسَ» To touch or feel something with the hand or fingers. Whether the desired object is found or not (intransitive). This word is also used in the Quran in these meanings.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا» (72/8)\nTranslation: And (the jinn said) we touched the sky and found it filled with strong guards and meteors.","«لَمَسَ» to touch or feel something with the hand or fingers.","to touch","لمس","72:8",1
1306,276,"T","طَمَثَ","«طَمَثَ» means menstrual blood (verse 115), and «طَمَثَ یَطْمِثُ» also signifies a woman having her period (Manj) and a man removing the veil covering a woman's private parts (Muf). Apparently, this term is specific to the first instance of sexual intercourse (مباشرت) among the meanings of مجامعت (intercourse), and in the first two meanings, this word is not used in the Quran. Also, see to have intercourse (مجامعت کرنا).","«طَمَثَ» meaning menstrual blood.","to touch","طمث","55:56-55:74",2
1307,277,"S","سَلْب","To forcibly take something from someone (snatching), or to see something being snatched or taken away even if the one taking is weak. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ» (22/73). Translation: If a fly snatches something from them, they cannot retrieve it.","To take something by force from someone.","Snatched","سلب","22:73",1
1308,277,"S","غَصَبَ","«غَصَبَ» means to seize something unjustly, through oppression, excess, force, or deceit (manj). However, there is a separate word, «غَبَنَ», for deceitfully seizing or taking something (m. q). Therefore, the meaning of «غَصَبَ» as stated by Imam Raghib is more accurate. That is, for a powerful person to forcefully and unjustly take possession of a weaker person's property (muf).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ  وَرَآءَہُمۡ مَّلِکٌ یَّاۡخُذُ کُلَّ  سَفِیۡنَۃٍ  غَصۡبًا» (18/79)\nTranslation: And ahead of them was a king who used to seize every ship by force.","«غَصَبَ» the seizure of a weaker person's property by a powerful person through force.","Snatched","غصب","18:79",1
1309,277,"T","نَالَ","«نَیْل» meaning every thing that a person can grasp with their hand, and that is also desirable to them. Or any thing that is within their reach and power (muf). That is, to get hold of or obtain something.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ رَدَّ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِغَیۡظِہِمۡ  لَمۡ یَنَالُوۡا خَیۡرًا» (33:25)\nTranslation: And those who disbelieved - Allah turned them back in their anger; they gained no good.\n\nThen the meanings of this word expanded. And it began to be used in the sense of reaching or merely arriving.\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«لَا یَنَالُ عَہۡدِی الظّٰلِمِیۡنَ» (2:124)\nTranslation: My covenant will not reach the wrongdoers.\n\nAnd on the other hand, this expansion occurred such that the word began to be used in the sense of seizing.\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«وَ لَا یَنَالُوۡنَ مِنۡ عَدُوٍّ نَّیۡلًا» (9:120)\nTranslation: And they do not seize anything from the enemy.","To forcibly seize something desirable over which one has power and strength.","to snatch","نال","2:124-3:92-5:94-7:37-7:49-7:152-9:74-9:120-22:37-33:25",10
1310,277,"S","خَطِفَ","«خَطِفَ» To move swiftly or to snatch something away in a flash (transitive verb). To snatch. To seize abruptly.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» (2/20)\nTranslation: It is as though the lightning snatches away their sight.","«خَطِفَ» swift movement and quickly snatching something away, to snatch.","Snatched","خطف","2:20-8:26-22:31-28:57-29:67-37:10",6
1311,278,"N","حَاجَۃ","«اَلْحُوْج» meaning a state of need and poverty/famine (manjad). It is a necessity or desire whose non-fulfillment causes a sense of tightness and constriction in the heart.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مَا کَانَ یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ شَیۡءٍ اِلَّا حَاجَۃً فِیۡ نَفۡسِ یَعۡقُوۡبَ قَضٰہَا» (12/68)\nTranslation: And this plan of his (Yaqub's) could not avert the decree of Allah at all. It was merely a desire in the heart of Ya'qub which he fulfilled.\n\nAt another place, the command of the Most High is:\n«وَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ حَاجَۃً  مِّمَّاۤ اُوۡتُوۡا» (59/9)\nTranslation: And whatever they are given, they find no lingering desire or resentment in their hearts (Jalandhari).\nMeaning: Even with such little provision, they are patient and grateful, and they do not feel any tightness or constriction in their hearts.","«حَاجَۃ» a need whose non-fulfillment causes a feeling of constriction in the heart.","Need","حاجۃ","12:68-40:80-59:9",3
1312,278,"N","مَاٰرِب","«اَرْب ، اَرِب» and «اِرب» refer to a necessity that cannot be avoided and for which one must strive to fulfill. For example, the Quran states:\n«غَیۡرِ اُولِی الۡاِرۡبَۃِ مِنَ الرِّجَالِ» (24:31)\nTranslation: Meaning young male servants who do not yet have a need (for marriage).\n\nAnd «مَاٰرِب» is the plural of «مَارِبَۃ», which means the fulfillment of a need or necessity. For example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی» (20:18)\nTranslation: Moses said, This is my staff; I lean upon it and I use it to beat down leaves for my sheep, and I have other needs for it. (Meaning: It fulfills other needs for me as well).","Such needs that can be fulfilled.","need","مارب","20:18-24:31",2
1313,278,"N","وَطَر","«وَطَرَ» means (1) need. (2) conjugal relations, desire (masc.) and its plural is «اَوْطَار». In the Quran, it has been used only in the second meaning.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا» (33:37)  \nTranslation: Then when Zaid had fulfilled his need with her.","This word, «وَطَرَ», was employed in the Quran in the context of communal necessity, yet its semantic range is extensive.","Need","وطر","33:37",1
1314,279,"P","حَضَرَ","«حَضَرَ» is the opposite of «غَابَ». «حَضَرَ» means the coming into existence or appearance of something (sing.).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَلَمَّا حَضَرُوۡہُ قَالُوۡۤا  اَنۡصِتُوۡا» (46/29)  \nTranslation: So when the jinn came to him, they said to one another, Stay silent.","«حَضَرَ» meaning to exist, to be present.","Present","حضر","2:133-2:180-2:196-2:282-3:30-4:8-4:18-4:128-5:106-7:163-18:49-19:68-23:98-28:61-30:16-34:38-36:32-36:53-36:75-37:57-37:127-37:158-46:29-81:14",24
1315,279,"P","شَھِدَ","This word is used in many meanings, but the following two are relevant to the topic:\n(1) To be present.\nFor example: The divine command of Allah, the Most High, states:\n«اَمۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  اِنَاثًا  وَّ ہُمۡ شٰہِدُوۡنَ» (37/150)\nTranslation: Or did We make the angels females while they were present?\n(2) To be present and see something with one's own eyes, then to present it before a judge (as in footnote 30). This carries the meaning of testimony.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَاۡبَ الشُّہَدَآءُ اِذَا مَا دُعُوۡا» (2/282)\nTranslation: Do not refuse to be witnesses when they are called upon.","«شَھِدَ» to be present. to see and to state.","Present","شھد","2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21",60
1316,279,"P","عَتِیْد","The meaning of «عَتَدَ» is to be prepared. And «اَعْتَدَ» means to prepare. And «عَتِیْد» means something that is already prepared and present.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالَ قَرِیۡنُہٗ  ہٰذَا مَا لَدَیَّ عَتِیۡدٌ» (50/23)\nTranslation: And its companion (angel) will say, This (record) is present with me.\n\nSee to be prepared.","«عَتَدَ» To be prepared and available in advance.","Present","عتید","50:18-50:23",2
1317,280,"S","بَال","«بَال» means the present condition or state. This word is general in usage.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ  فَمَا  بَالُ  الۡقُرُوۡنِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی . قَالَ عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ» (20:51,52)\nTranslation: Pharaoh asked Prophet Moses (peace be upon him), What is the condition of the earlier nations? He replied, Their knowledge is with my Lord.","«بَال» is used for the current situation when asking questions.","State","بال","12:50-20:51",2
1318,280,"S","خَطْبُ","«خَطْبُ» State/condition of a matter, whether major or minor. Generally used for disapproved matters (manjad).\nThe Quran states:\n«قَالَ فَمَا خَطۡبُکُمۡ اَیُّہَا الۡمُرۡسَلُوۡنَ . قَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّاۤ  اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی قَوۡمٍ مُّجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (51/31,32)\nTranslation: Prophet Ibrahim (AS) said to the angels, What is your purpose? The angels replied, We have been sent to a guilty people.","«خَطْبُ» is used to inquire about something disliked or objectionable.","State","خطب","12:51-15:57-20:95-28:23-51:31",5
1319,280,"S","دَأب","«دَأب» meaning to proceed continuously; a permanent habit; patterns of behavior; conduct (m. l.)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«کَدَاۡبِ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (3/11)\nTranslation: (Their case is) like that of the people of Pharaoh.","«دَأب» refers to habits and conduct.","State","دأب","3:11-8:52-8:54-40:31",4
1320,280,"S","طَوْر","«طَوْر» means estimate, limit, form, state, condition. «اَلنَّاسُ اَطْوَارٌ» means humans of many types (varied). «تَطَوُّر» means to change from one state to another. Thus, «طَوْر» refers to such a state or form that is inclined to change after a period according to an estimate.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ  قَدۡ خَلَقَکُمۡ   اَطۡوَارًا» (71:14)  \nTranslation: And Allah has created you in various states.","It comes in one form, then in another.","State","طور","71:14",1
1321,281,"J","حَاکِم","«حَکَمَ» meaning «المنع عن الظلم» (m. l.), i.e., a judgment that prevents oppression and excess against another. And «حَکَّمَ» meaning to appoint someone as a just judge or ruler. And «تحاکم» meaning to bring one's case to a ruler for judgment. (Manjad) Thus, the ruler is the person who judges between people in their disputes and prevents the oppressor from committing oppression. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا حَکَمۡتُمۡ بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ اَنۡ تَحۡکُمُوۡا بِالۡعَدۡلِ» (4/58)\nTranslation: And (Allah commands you that) when you judge between people, you judge with justice.","«حَاکِمْ» meaning: one who judges justly and prevents injustice.","Judge","حاکم","4:60-7:87-10:109-11:45-12:80-95:8",6
1322,281,"S","اُولِی الْاَمْر","«اُولِی الْاَمْر» is the plural of «وَلِیُّ الْاَمْر». And «وَلّٰی» means to appoint someone as the ruler, governor, or king of a region. Thus, literally, this term is applied to the administrative apparatus of a nation's government. However, its application can also extend to judicial authorities.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اَطِیۡعُوا اللّٰہَ وَ اَطِیۡعُوا الرَّسُوۡلَ وَ اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (4:59)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Obey Allah and His Messenger ﷺ, and those among you who are in authority.","«اُولِی الْاَمْر» Lords of the government, the officials whose commands are followed.","Sovereign","اولی الامر","4:59-4:83",2
1323,281,"T","قَوَّام","«قَامَ» means to stand. And «اَقَامَ» means to straighten or stabilize something that is crooked. And «قَوَّمَ» means the determination and adjustment of a thing (i.e., making it equal and correct) (source: Majid). And «قَوَّام» or «قیَّم» is the term used for a person who is responsible for managing the affairs of an individual, institution, or system in a proper state, and for its protection and oversight, and for providing its necessities. (Quranic context)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ وَّ بِمَاۤ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِنۡ اَمۡوَالِہِمۡ» (4/34)\nTranslation: Men are guardians over women, because Allah has favored some of them over others, and because they spend from their wealth.","«قَوَّام» Every person who is accountable for the just administration of any individual, institution, or system.","The Judge (one of the names of Allah) / Ruler / Governor","قوام","4:34-4:135-5:8",3
1324,282,"E","جَاوَزَ","«جَاوَزَ» means to go beyond a specific or designated place (station), continuing along the path until passing it, and «جَوَّزَ الطَّرِیّق» refers to the middle of the path. (station)\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا ۫ لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18/62)\nTranslation: When both of them went beyond that place, Moses said to his servant, Bring food for us. This journey has caused us much fatigue.","«جَاوَزَ» to go beyond the designated place.","Excess","جاوز","2:249-7:138-10:90-18:62",4
1325,282,"E","اَسْرَفَ","«اَسْرَفَ» means to exceed the bounds of moderation in any matter; to disregard the prescribed limits while performing an action. The meaning of «سَرَفَ فِی الْاَمْر» is negligence or laziness in a task. Whereas «اَسْرَفَ» means to commit excess. (M. Q)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا  تُسۡرِفُوۡا» (7:31)\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not be extravagant.","to transgress the limits of moderation","extravagance","اسرف","5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34",19
1326,282,"E","بَغْيُ","«بَغْيُ» Exceeding the appropriate limit in seeking and obtaining something (in its singular sense), attempting to claim one's due slightly more than what is just, and proportionally suppressing the right of the other.\n\nFor example, the Quran says: «وَ اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (38/24) Translation: And most business partners wrong each other.","Transgressing limits to fulfill a desire.","extravagance","بغی","2:90-2:187-2:198-2:207-2:213-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:19-3:83-3:85-3:99-4:24-4:34-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-5:50-6:35-6:114-6:146-6:164-7:33-7:45-7:86-7:140-9:47-9:48-10:23-10:90-11:19-12:65-13:17-13:22-14:3-16:14-16:90-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-18:64-18:108-22:60-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:76-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-38:22-38:24-42:14-42:27-42:39-42:42-45:12-45:17-48:29-49:9-55:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20",79
1327,282,"E","عَدٰی ، اِعْتَدٰی","«عَدٰی اور اِعْتَدٰی» means transgressing the path of truth, not considering Allah's commands and limits (detailed and concise), and «عُدْوَان» means to initiate in oppression and transgression.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«تِلۡکَ حُدُوۡدُ اللّٰہِ فَلَا تَعۡتَدُوۡہَا» (2/229)\nTranslation: These are the limits (commands) of Allah. Do not exceed them.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«فَمَنِ اضۡطُرَّ غَیۡرَ بَاغٍ وَّ لَا عَادٍ فَلَاۤ اِثۡمَ عَلَیۡہِ» (2/173)\nTranslation: Then whoever is compelled, neither being disobedient nor transgressing the limit (necessity), there is no sin upon him.\n\nHere, «بَاغٍ» means that he is not actually so compelled that he would incline toward eating haram, but he considers himself to be in such a state of compulsion. And «عَادٍ» means that if a little haram can be avoided, then he starts eating more (i.e., he transgresses).","«عَدٰی اور اِعْتَدٰی» Transgressing the path of truth and the divine commandments.","extravagance","عدی ، اعتدی","2:61-2:65-2:173-2:178-2:190-2:194-2:229-2:231-3:112-5:2-5:78-5:87-5:94-5:107-6:119-6:145-7:55-9:10-10:74-16:115-23:7-26:166-50:25-68:12-70:31-83:12",26
1328,282,"W","فَرَطَ","«فَرَطَ» to precede, to get ahead, to hurry.  \n«فَرَطَ مِنْہُ الْقَول» to speak without thinking (rashly); this word is used for committing an excess or overstepping in haste.  \nAnd «فَرَّطَ» is used for deficiency or falling short (antonym).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اتَّبَعَ ہَوٰىہُ  وَ کَانَ   اَمۡرُہٗ   فُرُطًا» (18:28)  \nTranslation: And he followed his own desire, and his affair became excessive.","«فَرَطَ» to act rashly or impulsively beyond bounds.","wasteful extravagance","فرط","18:28-20:45",2
1329,282,"E","سَلَقَ","«سَلَقَ» To extend the hand or tongue (i.e., to transgress or overstep with one's hand or tongue). (Figurative) To come forward aggressively or presumptuously. To transgress against others with hand or tongue.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33:19)\nTranslation: Then when the fear (of battle) subsided, these hypocrites would speak about you with sharp tongues and harbor greed for wealth.","«سَلَقَ» to transgress against others with one's hand and tongue.","Excess","سلق","33:19",1
1330,282,"E","غَلَا","«غَلَا» means to be expensive.  \n«غَلَا السِّعْر» means prices rise.  \n«غَلَا السَّھَم» means to throw an arrow very far.  \n«غَلَا فِی الْاَمْرِ» means to exaggerate, to exceed limits, or in the context of extreme devotion, to surpass the due worth and status of someone (i.e., to adopt extremism).  \n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ لَا تَغۡلُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ وَ لَا تَقُوۡلُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡحَقَّ ؕ اِنَّمَا الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ رَسُوۡلُ اللّٰہِ وَ کَلِمَتُہٗ» (4/171)  \nTranslation: O People of the Book, do not exceed limits in your religion, and do not say about Allah except the truth. The Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary, was not Allah, nor His son, but he was the Messenger of Allah and His word (a glad tiding) which He bestowed upon Mary.","«غَلَا» To overstep bounds in someone's worth and status due to excessive devotion. To act with extremism.","Excess","غلا","4:171-5:77",2
1331,282,"E","شَطَطًا","«شَطَطًا» To exceed in exaggeration, to go far beyond the limit, to lie and to exaggerate therein (approximate meaning).\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «لَنۡ نَّدۡعُوَا۠ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہٖۤ  اِلٰـہًا لَّقَدۡ قُلۡنَاۤ  اِذًا  شَطَطًا» (18/14)\nTranslation: We will not call upon anyone other than Him (if we were to do so), then we would have said something far from reason.","«شَطَطًا» Exaggerating in falsehood to a degree that reason cannot accept.","Excess","شططًا","18:14-38:22-72:4",3
1332,283,"B","فَرَّطَ","The word «فَرَّطَ» originates from the lexicon of antonyms ( opposites ).  \nThe meaning of «فَرَطَ» is, as we have previously explained, to act rashly or hastily, to exceed the limit, or to commit excess.  \nAnd the meaning of «فَرَّطَ» is to fall behind or be deficient through rashness or haste, to fall short, or to be neglectful.  \n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«اَنۡ تَقُوۡلَ نَفۡسٌ یّٰحَسۡرَتٰی عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡتُّ فِیۡ جَنۡۢبِ اللّٰہِ» ( 39/56 )  \nTranslation: Lest a soul should say, Alas, my regret upon the negligence I showed towards Allah.  \n\nNote: (The lexicon of antonyms refers to words that have two distinct meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","The word «فَرَّطَ» comes to indicate improper execution or negligence in completing a task.","Boundary","فرط","6:31-6:38-6:61-12:80-39:56",5
1333,283,"B","قَصَرَ","«قَصَرَ» To reduce something within the prescribed limit or to fall short. «قَصَرَ السَّھْم» Meaning: not reaching the target of an arrow. «قَصَرَ الصَّلوٰۃ» Not performing the prayer in full, but rather shortening it. «قَصَّرَ الشَّعْر» Meaning: to cut off a portion of the hair, and «قَصُرَ» meaning: to be small (minj). From this, the words «قَصُور ، تَقْصِیْر» and «قَاصِر» are well-known in our language. For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (4/101)\nTranslation: There is no blame upon you if you shorten your prayer.","«قَصَرَ» is used to indicate a decrease in the quantity of something.","Boundary","قصر","4:101-7:202-48:27",3
1334,284,"F","حَرَامٌ","«حَرَامٌ» Those matters or things which the Shariah has strictly prohibited. In the words of the author of *al-Maqaayis al-Lughah*, its meaning is «اَلْمَنْعُ الشَّدِیْد». This term is general.  \nFor example, disobedience to parents is also haram. The meat of carnivorous animals is also haram. And usury (interest) is also haram. And Paradise is also haram for a polytheist. And its opposite is halal, i.e., those things whose general use is permitted.  \nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ الۡبَیۡعَ وَ حَرَّمَ الرِّبٰوا» (2/275)  \nTranslation: Allah has permitted trade (buying and selling) and has forbidden usury (interest).","such matters or things from which Sharia has strictly prohibited","Forbidden / Illicit","حرام","2:85-2:173-2:275-3:50-3:93-4:23-4:160-5:3-5:26-5:72-5:87-5:96-6:119-6:138-6:139-6:140-6:143-6:144-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:150-6:151-7:32-7:33-7:50-7:157-9:29-9:37-10:59-16:35-16:115-16:116-16:118-17:33-21:95-24:3-25:68-28:12-66:1",40
1335,284,"F","سُحْت","The term «سُحْت» is specific to earnings and wealth. Its meaning is sustenance that leads to shame and disgrace, such as the price of a pig or a dog, etc. (See 12) Wealth earned through illicit means. Illicit earnings, bribery, etc.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ اَکّٰلُوۡنَ لِلسُّحۡتِ» (5/42)\n\nTranslation: They are those who practice espionage (to spread falsehoods) and consume illicit gains (bribery).","«سُحْت» is used for unlawful and haram earnings.","Forbidden","سحت","5:42-5:62-5:63-",3
1336,285,"P","جُزْء","«جُزْء» is a part or piece of something, and its collection (components). It means those parts or pieces of something which, when combined, make that thing complete or constitute its composition (plural). For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ اجۡعَلۡ عَلٰی کُلِّ جَبَلٍ مِّنۡہُنَّ جُزۡءًا» (2/260)\nTranslation: Then place on each [mountain] one of them.","«جُزْء» a portion or fragment of something.","portion","جزء","2:260-15:44-43:15",3
1337,285,"A","زُلْف","«زُلْف» the initial part of the night or the first watches (f. l. 34). The basic meanings of «زُلْف» are order and proximity. The initial part of the night is called «زُلْف» because it is the closest and nearest part of the entire night.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11:114)\nTranslation: Establish prayer at the two ends of the day (morning and evening) and during the first hours of the night.","«زُلْف» the early part of the night.","allotted portion","زلف","11:114",1
1338,285,"A","حَظّ","«حَظّ» means a share of goodness and merit (M. A.) (Faqih 135) and also signifies wealth or prosperity. Blessing (Manjad). In the Quran, this term refers to the prescribed shares of inheritance, which are connected to goodness, merit, and wealth, as well as prosperity and blessing.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «فَلِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4/176). Translation: The share for a male shall be equal to the share of two females.","«حَظّ» a share of goodness, blessings, and wealth.","Allotted portion","حظ","3:176-4:11-4:176-5:13-5:14",5
1339,285,"S","خَلَاق","«خَلَاق» A specific portion of all goodness (M. R) — the greater portion of goodness (manifest) (Muf) (Fiqh 136) — meaning the excellence that a person attains through their character. This portion is connected to a person's deeds.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَمِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّقُوۡلُ رَبَّنَاۤ  اٰتِنَا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ مَا لَہٗ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  مِنۡ خَلَاقٍ» (2/200)  \nTranslation: Then among them are some who say, Our Lord, grant us in this world, — for such people there will be no share in the Hereafter.","That specific portion which is obtained as a result of one's character.","Share","خلاق","2:102-2:200-3:77-9:69",4
1340,285,"P","نَصِیْب","«نَصَب» means to bury something. And «نَصِیْب» means a stone buried as a landmark on the path. And by «نَصِیْب» is also meant that specific portion which is written in one's destiny (qismah), whether it pertains to something beloved or detested (makhruh) (according to Fiqh, 135).  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ ابۡتَغِ  فِیۡمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکَ اللّٰہُ  الدَّارَ الۡاٰخِرَۃَ  وَ لَا تَنۡسَ نَصِیۡبَکَ مِنَ الدُّنۡیَا» (28/77)  \nTranslation: And seek through what Allah has given you the [blessings of] the Hereafter, and do not forget your share of the world.","«نَصِیْب» That portion which is ordained, whether little or much.","portion (of the Quran)","نصیب","2:202-3:23-4:7-4:32-4:33-4:44-4:51-4:53-4:85-4:118-4:141-6:136-7:37-11:109-16:56-28:77-40:47-42:20",18
1341,285,"P","کِفْل","«کِفْل» means guarantee and security, and «کِفْل» also means a share and the obligatory recompense for an action, whether good or bad. And according to the scholar Ibn Manzar, it means double reward or double sin.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً حَسَنَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّنۡہَا ۚ وَ مَنۡ یَّشۡفَعۡ شَفَاعَۃً سَیِّئَۃً یَّکُنۡ لَّہٗ کِفۡلٌ مِّنۡہَا» (4:85)\nTranslation: Whoever recommends a good deed will have a share in it, and whoever recommends an evil deed will have a share in it.","«کِفْل» a share in return for a good or bad deed.","portion","کفل","4:85-57:28",2
1342,285,"S","بَعْض","«بَعْض» meaning part, piece. It can also be used for a part of a whole. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبُوۡہُ بِبَعۡضِہَا» ( 2/73 )\nTranslation: So we said, Strike the (slaughtered cow's) piece (part) with a piece of it.\nAnd if a whole is a collection of several distinct things, the word can also be used for an individual. Such as «بَعْضَ النَّاس» meaning some person, «بَعْضَ الَلَیَالِی» meaning one night among nights.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«بَعۡضُکُمۡ لِبَعۡضٍ عَدُوٌّ» ( 2/36 )\nTranslation: You are all enemies to one another.\nApart from this, the word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لِاُبَیِّنَ  لَکُمۡ بَعۡضَ الَّذِیۡ تَخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» ( 43/63 )\nTranslation: So that I may explain to you some of the matters in which you differ.","«بَعْض» a part of a complete thing, or one or some from among similar things.","share","بعض","2:36-2:73-2:76-2:85-2:145-2:251-2:253-2:259-2:283-3:34-3:50-3:64-3:155-3:195-4:19-4:21-4:25-4:32-4:34-4:150-5:49-5:51-6:53-6:65-6:112-6:128-6:129-6:158-6:165-7:24-8:37-8:72-8:73-8:75-9:67-9:71-9:127-10:46-11:12-11:54-12:10-13:4-13:36-13:40-16:71-17:21-17:55-17:88-18:19-18:99-20:123-22:40-23:44-23:91-23:113-24:40-24:58-24:62-24:63-25:20-26:198-27:72-29:25-30:41-33:6-34:31-34:42-35:40-37:27-37:50-38:22-38:24-40:28-40:77-43:32-43:63-43:67-45:19-47:4-47:26-49:2-49:12-52:25-66:3-68:30-69:44",86
1343,286,"P","حَفِظَ","«حَفِظَ» Its opposite is «اَضَاعَ». Meaning: to save from perishing and destruction (Munjid); to guard (M. R.); to attempt to safeguard something from external dangers (faq l 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65)\nTranslation: We will also protect our brother and bring an additional camel's load.","«حَفِظَ» to save something from being lost.","Protection","حفظ","2:238-2:255-4:34-5:44-5:89-6:61-6:92-9:112-12:12-12:63-12:64-12:65-12:81-13:11-15:9-15:17-21:82-23:5-23:9-24:30-24:31-33:35-37:7-41:12-70:29-70:34-82:10-83:33-86:4",29
1344,286,"P","رَعٰی","«رَعٰی» To protect something and to eliminate the causes of external threats. And «رَاعِیْ» meaning shepherd, guardian, and its opposite. «اِھْمَال» meaning the grazing of a flock without a shepherd (Faq l 15).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23/8)\nTranslation: Those who safeguard their trusts and their promises.","«رَعٰی» Ensuring protection and removing the sources of external dangers.","Protection","رعی","20:54-28:23",2
1345,286,"P","اَحْصَنَ","«حِصْن» means fortress or a secure place, and its plural is «حُصُوْن» (59/2). In «حَصَن», two fundamental concepts are found: «اَلْحِفْظُ وَالْحَیَاطَۃ» (m. l.), i.e., protection, enclosure, and according to Sahib Minhaj, its meaning is to be secured in a strong place. It also means a woman protecting her chastity.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَرۡیَمَ  ابۡنَتَ عِمۡرٰنَ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَحۡصَنَتۡ فَرۡجَہَا» (66/12)\nTranslation: And Maryam (peace be upon her), daughter of Imran, who guarded her chastity.\n\nIt also has another meaning of entering into marriage. Because marriage also performs the function of a fortress against immorality.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (4/24)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess [i.e., captives].","«اَحْصَنَ» to protect by means of a four-walled enclosure.","Protection","احصن","4:24-4:25-5:5-21:91-24:4-24:23-59:14-66:12",8
1346,286,"P","کَلَأَ","«کَلَأَ» means to keep one's gaze fixed upon something at all times and to preserve it. Essentially, it comprises two elements: (1) vigilance (muraqaba) and (2) steadfastness (sabt) [m.l.; m.f.]. It also signifies safeguarding something from inclining toward harm (faqil 169).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ مَنۡ یَّکۡلَؤُکُمۡ  بِالَّیۡلِ وَ النَّہَارِ مِنَ الرَّحۡمٰنِ» (21/42)\nTranslation: Ask them, Who protects you from God's punishment by night and by day?","to keep «کَلَأَ» safe and sound by safeguarding it","Protection","کلأ","21:42",1
1347,287,"S","صَدُقَۃ","«صَدُقَۃ» Its plural is «صَدُقٰت». «صَدَقَۃ» If the dal carries a zabar, then its meaning is sadaqah (charity), and if the dal carries a damma (pish), then its meaning is taken as haq mehar (the right of dowry), and «اَصْدَقَ الْاِبْنَۃَ» means to stipulate the daughter's right to mahr (stipulated). Although «صَدُقَۃ» itself comes in a broader sense meaning mahr. Mahr refers to the stipulated sum whose payment is obligatory, whereas «صُدَاق» refers to that sadaqah or expense upon which the marriage is based. Thus, in «صُدَاق», apart from mahr, nafaqah (maintenance) is also included (Fiqh 139).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتُوا النِّسَآءَ صَدُقٰتِہِنَّ نِحۡلَۃً» (4:4)\nTranslation: Give the women their due mahr willingly.\n\nDue to the stipulation of the right of mahr, it is called «فریضۃ», and due to being a compensation, it is called ujrah.","In «صَدُقَۃ», all the obligations of the woman, including the mahr, are included.","Seal of the Prophets","صدقۃ","4:4",1
1348,287,"S","اَجْر","«اَجْر» Its plural is «اُجُوْر», meaning reward or compensation settled between «اٰجِر» and «اَجِیْر». Because in marriage, the woman accepts the reward for her chastity as mahr, which is settled by mutual consent. Therefore, the word «اَجْر» is used metaphorically in the Quran for the right of mahr. For example: The Quran states: «وَ اٰتُوۡہُنَّ اُجُوۡرَہُنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (4:25). Translation: And give the women their mahr in a good manner.","«اَجْر» is used in all these meanings: wage, salary, wages, remuneration, reward, bonus, compensation, and divine reward.","Seal of Truth","اجر","4:24-4:25-5:5-33:50-60:10",5
1349,287,"S","فَرِیْضَۃ","«فَرْضَ» means to determine, to stipulate, to make obligatory. And «فَرِیْضَۃ» means the stipulated or determined portion (the assigned share). The word *fard* (obligation) is also metaphorically employed for *mahr* (dower) because the payment of *mahr* must be mutually agreed upon and stipulated at the time of marriage.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ وَ قَدۡ فَرَضۡتُمۡ لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً فَنِصۡفُ مَا فَرَضۡتُمۡ» (2/237)\n\nTranslation: And if you divorce them before you have touched them and you have already stipulated their *mahr*, then [pay] half of what you stipulated, unless they forgo or the one in whose hand is the marriage contract forgoes.","«فَرِیْضَۃ» meaning to decree, to determine, to make obligatory.","Seal upon the heart","فریضۃ","2:236-2:237-",2
1350,288,"C","اَمَرَ","«اَمْر» signifies meanings such as transaction, state, condition, and its plural is أمور. These meanings are not under discussion here. «اَمْر» in the sense of 'command' has the plural «اَوَامِر» and its opposite is «نَھِی». And «اَمَرَ» means to command, to send an order, and to give instructions. Whether this command is for a good deed or a bad one (apparently), the usage of this word is general; whether the command is given by a king or a ruler to a subordinate, or by an ordinary person to another person.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» (3:104)\nTranslation: They enjoin what is right and forbid what is wrong.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\nOn the Day of Judgment, the weak will say to the mighty:\n«اِذۡ  تَاۡمُرُوۡنَنَاۤ  اَنۡ نَّکۡفُرَ  بِاللّٰہِ  وَ  نَجۡعَلَ لَہٗۤ  اَنۡدَادًا» (34:33)\nTranslation: When you used to command us to disbelieve in Allah and associate partners with Him.","The term «اَمْر» is commonly used in the sense of issuing a command or decree.","Command","امر","2:27-2:44-2:67-2:93-2:109-2:169-2:222-2:268-3:21-3:80-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:152-4:37-4:47-4:58-4:60-4:114-5:52-5:117-6:14-6:71-6:163-7:12-7:28-7:29-7:54-7:77-7:110-7:145-7:150-7:157-7:199-9:24-9:31-9:48-9:67-9:71-9:106-10:24-10:72-10:104-11:40-11:43-11:58-11:59-11:66-11:73-11:76-11:82-11:87-11:94-11:97-11:101-11:112-12:40-12:68-13:11-13:21-13:25-13:36-14:32-16:1-16:2-16:12-16:33-16:76-16:90-17:16-17:85-18:50-18:69-18:88-19:55-19:64-20:90-20:93-20:132-21:27-21:73-21:81-22:41-22:65-23:27-24:21-24:53-24:63-25:60-26:35-26:151-27:33-27:91-28:44-30:4-30:25-30:46-31:17-32:24-33:37-33:38-34:12-34:33-38:36-39:11-39:12-39:64-40:15-40:66-40:78-41:12-42:15-42:52-44:5-45:12-46:25-47:21-49:9-51:44-52:32-54:50-57:14-57:24-65:1-65:5-65:8-65:12-66:6-80:23-82:19-96:12-98:5",132
1351,288,"C","اَذِنَ","«اَذِنَ» means to approve or permit. And when it means to command, then it refers to a command that is in accordance with the Divine Will (muf). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فِیۡ  بُیُوۡتٍ اَذِنَ اللّٰہُ  اَنۡ تُرۡفَعَ وَ یُذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (24/36). Translation: the houses regarding which Allah has commanded that they be elevated and His name be mentioned therein.","«اَذِنَ» A ruling that is required by divine will; otherwise, it means granting permission or approval.","Command","اذن","2:97-2:102-2:213-2:221-2:249-2:251-2:255-3:49-3:145-3:152-3:166-4:25-4:64-5:16-5:110-7:58-8:66-9:43-10:3-10:59-10:100-11:105-12:80-13:38-14:1-14:11-14:23-14:25-20:109-22:39-22:65-24:36-24:62-33:46-34:12-34:23-35:32-40:78-42:21-42:51-53:26-58:10-59:5-64:11-78:38-97:4",46
1352,288,"C","حَکَمَ","The meaning of «حُکْم» is to restrain or put a rein on something for the purpose of its correction. «حَکَمَۃُ الدَّابَۃ» means I reined the animal (transitive verb), and «حَکَمَ» means «مَنَعَ عَنِ الظُّلْم» (noun), i.e., a command or ruling that restrains someone from oppression and excess.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لۡیَحۡکُمۡ اَہۡلُ  الۡاِنۡجِیۡلِ بِمَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ فِیۡہِ ؕ وَ مَنۡ لَّمۡ یَحۡکُمۡ بِمَاۤ اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ  الۡفٰسِقُوۡنَ» ( 5/47 )\n\nTranslation: And let the People of the Gospel judge by what Allah has revealed therein. And whoever does not judge by what Allah has revealed - then it is those who are the defiantly disobedient.","«حُکْم» A ruling through which injustice is prevented.","Command","حکم","3:7-5:43-6:57-6:62-12:40-12:67-13:37-13:41-27:78-28:70-28:88-47:20-52:48-68:48-76:24",15
1353,288,"R","اَوْصٰی","«اَوْصٰی» means to take a covenant regarding something, to command, and to bequeath (Manjad). And when it is attributed to Allah, it refers to a decisive command.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَوۡصٰنِیۡ بِالصَّلٰوۃِ  وَ الزَّکٰوۃِ مَا دُمۡتُ  حَیًّا» (19:31)\nTranslation: And He has enjoined upon me prayer and zakah as long as I remain alive. (Uthmani)\n\nAt another instance, the command of the Exalted Lord is:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ ٭ لِلذَّکَرِ مِثۡلُ حَظِّ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (4:11)\nTranslation: Allah instructs you concerning your children: for the male, the share of two females. (Uthmani)","When «اَوْصٰی» is ascribed to Allah, it signifies an emphatic command.","ruling","اوصی","2:132-2:180-2:182-2:240-4:11-4:12-4:131-5:106-6:144-6:151-6:152-6:153-19:31-29:8-31:14-36:50-42:13-46:15",18
1354,289,"A","سَطَا","«سَطْوَۃٌ  بِہٖ وَعَلَیْہِ» meaning to overpower someone by attacking them. And «سَطَا الْفَرَس» meaning a horse running with long, bounding strides (a gallop). And «سَطَا» meaning to seize violently or to attack (a forceful grasp).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَکَادُوۡنَ یَسۡطُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ یَتۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ اٰیٰتِنَا» (22/72)\nTranslation: It seems as if those who recite Our verses to them will attack them immediately.","To intensify the assault and strive to overcome.","Attack","سطا","22:72",1
1355,289,"A","اَغَارَ","«غَوْرَ ، غَارَۃً وَّ اِغَارَۃً )» meaning to conquer/plunder. «اَغَارُ الْفَرْس» meaning horses galloping at dawn (munjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَالۡمُغِیۡرٰتِ صُبۡحًا» (100/3)\nTranslation: Then (by the horses) who plunder at dawn (Ottoman) strike fiercely (Jalandhari).","«اَغَار» to attack and to loot and plunder.","Attack","اغار","100:3",1
1356,290,"A","حَیْرَان","«حَیْرَان» is a general term. It refers to being in a state of doubt due to not finding the correct path (the path of goodness), regardless of the situation.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «کَالَّذِی اسۡتَہۡوَتۡہُ الشَّیٰطِیۡنُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ حَیۡرَانَ ۪ لَہٗۤ  اَصۡحٰبٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَہٗۤ  اِلَی الۡہُدَی ائۡتِنَا» (6:71).  \nTranslation: As though someone has been led astray by jinn in the wilderness and is bewildered, while some companions call him towards the path, saying, 'Come to us.'","«حَیْرَان» is used in all these meanings: flabbergasted, astonished, amazed, and dumbfounded.","Astonished","حیران","6:71",1
1357,290,"B","بَھِتَ","«بَھِتَ» To be suddenly stunned, dumbfounded, and bewildered due to astonishment; to lose consciousness and senses (as in the Quran). To remain amazed and perplexed. To be flabbergasted. «مَبْھُوت» The word is derived from this.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«فَبُہِتَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَرَ» (2/258)  \nTranslation: (Upon hearing this) the disbeliever was dumbfounded.  \nAt another instance, the divine command states:  \n«بَلۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ بَغۡتَۃً  فَتَبۡہَتُہُمۡ» (21/40)  \nTranslation: Rather, the Hour will come upon them unexpectedly, so it will deprive them of their senses.","«بَھِتَ» to be stunned into unconsciousness.","Bewildered","بھت","2:258-21:40",2
1358,290,"A","عَجِبَ","«اَلْعَجْب» refers to a state of bewilderment whose cause is unknown (intransitive), and «عَجِبَ» means to be amazed, to wonder.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«بَلۡ عَجِبُوۡۤا اَنۡ جَآءَہُمۡ مُّنۡذِرٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ» (50/2)\nTranslation: But those people were amazed that a warner had come to them from among themselves.","«عَجِبَ» to be amazed by something for no known reason.","Astonished","عجب","7:63-7:69-9:55-9:85-10:2-11:73-13:5-18:9-18:63-37:12-38:4-50:2-53:59-72:1",14
1359,291,"M","مَحِیْضٌ","«مَحِیْضٌ» is used to mean menstruation. It is a well-known term. And «مَحِیْضٌ» can also mean menstruation, the time of menstruation, and the place of menstruation (in the genitive case). «حَاضَتِ الْمِرْأَۃ» means that a woman has her menstruation.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡمَحِیۡضِ» (2/222)\nTranslation: People ask you, [O Muhammad], about menstruation.","«مَحِیْضٌ» is used in the sense of menstruation.","menstruation","محیض","2:222-65:4",2
1360,291,"M","قُرُوْء","«قُرُوْء» is a collective term for «قَرْءُ». It refers to a woman's «طھر», meaning entering the state of menstruation from a state of purity. Therefore, lexically, this word applies to both «طھر» and menstruation, and it is among the *lughat al-iddad* (lexical antonyms—words that have two distinct, opposite meanings).\n\nHowever, in accordance with the saying of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ, «اُقْعُدِیْ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ اَیَّامِ اَقْرَائِک» (She should abandon prayer during the days of her menstruation), its translation has been specifically restricted to mean *menstruation*.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُطَلَّقٰتُ یَتَرَبَّصۡنَ بِاَنۡفُسِہِنَّ ثَلٰثَۃَ قُرُوۡٓءٍ» (2/228)\nTranslation: Divorced women shall wait for three menstrual periods.","«قُرُوْء» is used in the meaning of a woman becoming pure from menstruation.","menstruation","قروء","2:228",1
1361,292,"H","بَعْل","«بَعْل» means husband; the plural for husband is «بَعُول», and a wife is called «بَعْل» and «بَعْلَۃ». And «بَاعَلَ» means to marry or establish kinship ties between one tribe and another (source: Munjid). From this, it is also known that this term is used when the husband and wife belong to different tribes. And Allah knows best. According to the scholar of *Furūq al-Lughawiyyah*, a person cannot be called «بَعْل» until cohabitation occurs. And this is argued through this Prophetic tradition ﷺ: «یوم اکل و شرب و یعال» (Fatḥ al-Bārī, Vol. 236). For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَتۡ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤیءَ اَلِدُ وَ اَنَا عَجُوۡزٌ وَّ ہٰذَا بَعۡلِیۡ  شَیۡخًا» (11:72)\nTranslation: She said, Woe is me! How shall I bear a child while I am an old woman, and my husband is an old man in decrepitude?","«بَعْل» the husband who has already had intercourse.","Husband","بعل","2:228-4:128-11:72-24:31",4
1362,292,"H","زَوْج","Its plural is 'azwaj', meaning 'pair'. Both husband and wife are each other's «زَوْج». Then each one of them is the other's «زَوْج». For the husband, the wife is «زَوْج», and for the wife, the husband is her «زَوْج».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)\nTranslation: Allah has heard the statement of the woman who was disputing with you, [O Prophet], concerning her husband.","«زَوْج» is general for both rational and non-rational beings. It also applies to both husbands and wives.","husband","زوج","2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7",72
1363,292,"H","سَیَّد","«سَیّد» means leader, master, owner. This term is used metaphorically for husband because in the family system, the husband holds a superior status. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَّ اَلۡفَیَا سَیِّدَہَا لَدَا الۡبَابِ» (12/25). Translation: And both (Joseph and Zulaikha) found Zulaikha's husband at the door.","«سَیّد» is used contextually in the meaning of 'husband'.","Husband","سید","3:39-12:25",2
1364,293,"N","خَبْر","Its plural is *akhbar*. It is a well-known term. It refers to an event of which a person has no knowledge, and about which he is informed through someone else—that is *khabar* (news). It also denotes knowledge of the surrounding circumstances.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n\n«قَالَ  لِاَہۡلِہِ  امۡکُثُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡۤ  اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِخَبَرٍ» (28:29)\nTranslation: Moses said to his family, Stay here; indeed, I have seen a fire. Perhaps I will bring you from there news or a burning brand from the fire to warm you.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n\n«قُلۡ لَّا تَعۡتَذِرُوۡا لَنۡ  نُّؤۡمِنَ  لَکُمۡ  قَدۡ نَبَّاَنَا اللّٰہُ مِنۡ  اَخۡبَارِکُمۡ» (9:94)\nTranslation: Say, Do not make excuses; we will not believe you. Allah has already informed us of your circumstances.","«خَبْر» The news that is connected to the listener's own essence and can influence them.","News","خبر","27:7-28:29",2
1365,293,"N","خُبْر","«خُبْر» Knowledge of the true nature of an event, experience, insight. It is said «صَدَّقَ الْخَبْرَ الْخُبْرَ ۔» that experience and observation have confirmed the news that was heard (manjd).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَیۡفَ تَصۡبِرُ  عَلٰی مَا لَمۡ تُحِطۡ بِہٖ خُبۡرًا» (18/68)\nTranslation: And how can you have patience for something which you do not comprehend?","«خُبْر» is used in all senses, including news, information, and notice.","News","خبر","18:68-18:91",2
1366,293,"N","نَبَاَ","News pertaining to an important matter, especially news that also pertains to the listener. And whether this news relates to a past event or to future circumstances. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49/6)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, if there comes to you a disobedient person with news, then verify it.","«نَبَاَ» to convey news regarding an important and significant matter.","News / Information","نبا","2:31-2:33-3:15-3:44-3:49-5:14-5:27-5:48-5:60-5:105-6:5-6:34-6:60-6:67-6:105-6:108-6:143-6:159-6:164-7:101-7:175-9:64-9:70-9:94-9:105-10:18-10:23-10:53-10:71-11:49-11:100-11:120-12:15-12:36-12:37-12:45-12:102-13:33-14:9-15:49-15:51-18:13-18:78-18:103-20:99-22:72-24:64-26:6-26:69-26:221-27:22-28:3-28:66-29:8-31:15-31:23-33:20-34:7-35:14-38:21-38:67-38:88-39:7-41:50-49:6-53:36-54:4-54:28-58:6-58:7-62:8-64:5-64:7-66:3-75:13-78:2",76
1367,294,"F","نَفَدَ","«نَفَدَ» means to cease to exist completely; annihilation (m. l.). Its opposite is «بَقِیَ».\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «مَا عِنۡدَکُمۡ یَنۡفَدُ وَ مَا عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ بَاقٍ» (16/96).\n\nTranslation: Whatever you have will perish, and whatever is with Allah will remain everlasting.","«نَفَدَ» means to cease to exist completely, to become non-existent. In it, the actual thing becomes non-existent or slips from one's grasp, whereas in «خَتَمَ» that thing remains in existence. However, in it no increase or decrease is possible.","Finality","نفد","16:96-18:109-31:27-38:54",4
1368,294,"E","خَتَمَ","«خَتَمَ» To seal something after its completion by closing it and affixing a seal, so that no deficiency or excess can occur in it (for example). ‘Ākhir al-amr’ and ‘khatm al-amal’ mean to be free from an affair or to complete a task, and ‘khatm al-kitāb’ means to have read the entire book (Munjid).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «مَا کَانَ مُحَمَّدٌ اَبَاۤ  اَحَدٍ مِّنۡ رِّجَالِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ رَّسُوۡلَ اللّٰہِ وَ خَاتَمَ  النَّبِیّٖنَ» (33:40). Translation: Muhammad ﷺ is not the father of any of your men, but he is the Messenger of Allah and the Seal of the Prophets (i.e., their Finisher).","«خَتَمَ» meaning seal, stamp.","end","ختم","2:7-6:46-33:40-36:65-42:24-45:23",6
1369,295,"S","غُلَام","«غُلَام» refers to a boy or child who has reached maturity and whose sexual desires have been awakened. «اِغْتَلَمَ الْفَحْلُ غُلْمَۃً» means the arising of fervor and dominance of desire in a male (i.e., sexual urge). And «غَلِیْم» refers to a youth. And «اَغْلَام» refers to masturbation. And the plural of «غُلَام» is «غِلْمَۃٌ» and «غِلْمَانٌ». From another perspective, «غُلَام» and «غِلْمَان» refer to those children who are kept in wealthy households for small menial tasks. In this context, either modest compensation is given to them, or their upbringing and training itself is their compensation. In this case, the term «غُلَام» could also apply to a completely immature child.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» (12/19)\nTranslation: The caravan members said, This is indeed a handsome young man, and we will take him as a treasure.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَ یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ غِلۡمَانٌ  لَّہُمۡ  کَاَنَّہُمۡ لُؤۡلُؤٌ  مَّکۡنُوۡنٌ» (52/24)\nTranslation: And youthful attendants will circulate among them, [as if they were] hidden pearls.","«غُلَام» young domestic servant.","Servant","غلام","3:40-12:19-15:53-18:74-18:80-18:82-19:7-19:8-19:19-19:20-37:101-51:28-52:24",13
1370,295,"W","فَتٰی","«فَتٰی» and «تَفَتّٰی» mean 'young' or 'youthful'. In terms of age, it refers to the period from being young up to reaching full maturity. Its plural is «فَتَیَان». Its feminine form is «فَتَاۃ», and its plural is also «فَتَیَان». In terms of service, the use of «فَتٰی» is very extensive. «فَتٰی» and «فتاۃ» also refer to a slave-girl and a male slave. It is applied to servants and employees, as well as to one's own fellow attendants. And «فِتْیَۃٌ» refers to a group of young people.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا جَاوَزَا قَالَ لِفَتٰىہُ اٰتِنَا غَدَآءَنَا» (18/62)\nTranslation: When they moved forward, Moses (peace be upon him) said to his young companion, 'Bring us food.'\nAnd this companion was Joshua, son of Nun, who was also a special disciple of Moses (peace be upon him) and his attendant.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ  قَالَ لِفِتۡیٰنِہِ اجۡعَلُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ فِیۡ رِحَالِہِمۡ» (12/62)\nTranslation: And Joseph said to his servants, 'Put their merchandise (for which they bought the grain) into their saddlebags.'\n\nAnd at a third instance, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)\nTranslation: And do not compel your slave-girls to prostitution.","«فَتٰی» young servant and doer.","Worshiper","فتی","12:30-18:60-18:62-21:60",4
1371,295,"S","سُخْرِیًّا","«سَخِرَ ، یَسْخَرُ» means to mock or ridicule. And «سَخَرَ ، یَسْخُرُ» and «سَخَّرَ» mean to force someone into obedience or subservience.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«سَخَّرَ لَکُمۡ مَّا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (31:20)\nTranslation: And whatever Allah has subjected [for your use] on the earth for you.\n\nAnd «سُخْرِیَّا» also signifies taking work from someone without any wage or salary (as cited), as well as service with compensation. However, the aspect of compulsion (coercion) is prominent in it. That is, being compelled by necessity to perform service or employment.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43:32)\nTranslation: And We have raised some of them above others in degrees, that some of them may take others in service.","«سُخْرِیًّا» is urgent, compelled, and comes to serve.","servant","سخریًا","2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7",24
1372,296,"C","خَبَالًا","«خَبَلَ» refers to the corruption or disorder of the limbs and organs (m. l.). They say «خَبَلَ الْحُزْنُ عَقْلَہٗ» grief has corrupted his intellect. «خَبَلَ الْحُبُّ عَقَلَہٗ» love has destroyed his reason (Manjad). That is, «خَبَال» such corruption is called that which befalls someone and causes anxiety and restlessness, like madness or that illness which has a constant effect (muf) a chronic disease.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3:118)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Do not take anyone other than yourselves (i.e., non-Muslims) as your confidants. These people will not hesitate to cause you corruption!","«خَبَال» a disorder affecting the limbs and joints. Chronic disease.","corruption","خبالًا","3:118-9:47",2
1373,296,"C","مَعَرَّۃٌ","«مَعَرَّۃٌ» is invoked upon all kinds of harm and loss. The meaning of «عَیَّرَ» is to be afflicted with itching or irritation. And «مَعَرَّۃ» is applied to all forms of pain, sorrow, corruption, hardship, and abuse (as per Majma' and Ibn al-Faris). According to Ibn al-Faris, «مَعَرَّۃ» refers to such pain and sorrow that befall a person as a result of some sin or inappropriate action.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَ لَوۡ لَا رِجَالٌ مُّؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ نِسَآءٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٰتٌ لَّمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡہُمۡ  اَنۡ  تَطَئُوۡہُمۡ فَتُصِیۡبَکُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَرَّۃٌۢ  بِغَیۡرِ عِلۡمٍ» (48/25). Translation: And if there were not some Muslim men and Muslim women (in Mecca) about whom you had no knowledge, that you would have trampled them, and thus you would have incurred loss unknowingly.","«مَعَرَّۃٌ» a corruption that arises from an improper act.","corruption, depravity, disorder","معرۃ","48:25",1
1374,296,"C","فَسَاد","«فَسَاد» Its opposite is reformation. Fasad (corruption/disorder) refers to a corruption that manifests when something exceeds or falls short of its proper limit, thereby disrupting its balance (detailed definition).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ» (30:41)\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared in the land and sea because of what people's evil deeds have earned.","«فَسَاد» the corruption arising from extremism within the bounds of moderation, the ruin of society.","corruption","فساد","2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12",47
1375,297,"C","خَرِبَ ، اَخْرَبَ","«خَرِبَ» means to become desolate, ruined, or destroyed (of a cultivated land or building). To become uninhabited.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ مَّنَعَ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰہِ اَنۡ یُّذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ وَ سَعٰی فِیۡ خَرَابِہَا» (2/114)\nTranslation: And who is more unjust than he who forbids the mention of Allah's name in His mosques and strives for their ruin?\n\nAnd «اَخْرَبَ ( ضد عَمَرَ )» means to make an inhabited place uninhabited, to demolish or destroy a structure, or to ruin and lay waste to cultivation. (Mufradat)\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ  الرُّعۡبَ یُخۡرِبُوۡنَ بُیُوۡتَہُمۡ  بِاَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ  وَ اَیۡدِی الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (59/2)\nTranslation: Allah instilled terror in the hearts of those Jews, so they began to destroy their homes with their own hands and the hands of the believers.","«خَرِبَ» to be laid waste; the ruin or destruction of a place, land, or farmland.","corrupt","خرب ، اخرب","2:114-59:2",2
1376,297,"C","فَسَدَ ، اَفْسَدَ","«فساد» means corruption (the opposite of reform). It refers to any act that is contrary to Islamic law, whether related to actions or beliefs. And «فَسَدَ» means for corruption to arise in something. And «اَفْسَدَ» means to spoil or corrupt.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reformation.","«فَسَدَ» meaning corruption. Corruption in actions and beliefs.\n«اَفْسَدَ» meaning greater corruption, more severe.","corrupt","فسد ، افسد","2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12",47
1377,297,"C","عَاب","«عیب» means that a thing's form or appearance has a defect or flaw within it (applies to singular), and «عَابَ» means to make something defective or to damage it. It applies to both living and non-living things. The term is used in all contexts, whether in speech or action (Fiqh 39).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ فَاَرَدۡتُّ اَنۡ اَعِیۡبَہَا» (18/79)\nTranslation: As for the ship, it belonged to poor people working at sea. I wished to damage it.","«عَاب» to inherently corrupt something.","corrupt","عاب","18:79",1
1378,297,"C","اَسَنَ","«اَسَنَ الْمَاءُ» means to change and become foul-smelling. And «اَسِنَ الرَّجُل» means to lose consciousness or become dizzy from entering a well containing rotten water (as in the metaphorical sense). Thus, the word «اَسَنَ» is used to describe water that is bad, changed, and foul-smelling.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فِیۡہَاۤ اَنۡہٰرٌ  مِّنۡ  مَّآءٍ غَیۡرِ اٰسِنٍ» ( 47/15 )\nTranslation: In it (Paradise) are rivers whose water will never become foul.","«اَسَنَ» is used to spoil water and make it foul-smelling.","corrupted","اسن","47:15",1
1379,297,"C","سَنَّ","«سِنّ» also means 'tooth' and 'age'. And «سُنَّۃ» means 'method' or 'custom', and «سَنَّ سُنَّۃ» means 'he established or instituted the method' (muf. manjd). It seems that in the word 'sanna', the concept of duration and continuity is found. And «مَسْنُوْن» is the term for something that becomes rotten and foul after a period has passed; however, this word is generally used for mud, etc.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran: «وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26) Translation: And We created man from clinking, rotten, decayed mud.","«سَنَّ» is used for items that deteriorate over time.","Corrupted","سن","15:26-15:28-15:33",3
1380,297,"C","سَنِہَ","«سَنِہَ» means to be very long-lasting. «سَنِہَ الطَّعَام وَالشَّرَاب» means to undergo change or alteration in one's food and drink; to spoil. And «تَسَنَّہَ الْخُبْزُ» means for bread to rot; to become foul-smelling (as mentioned).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«فَانۡظُرۡ اِلٰی طَعَامِکَ وَ شَرَابِکَ لَمۡ یَتَسَنَّہۡ» (2:259)\n\nTranslation: And look at your food and drink—they did not spoil over that period.","«سَنِہَ» is used to make food and drinks fragrant.","corrupt","سنہ","2:259",1
1381,298,"E","اَنْفَقَ","«اَنْفَقَ» is a general term for spending. Generally, it refers to spending wealth and resources. However, it encompasses the concept that wealth comes in from one side and spending continues from the other. «نَفَقَ» This is called a tunnel that has both ends open. And «نیفق السّراویل» refers to the lower hem of a pajama. And «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» means a wild mouse entered from one end of its belly and exited from the other. In Shariah terminology, hypocrisy refers to this manner: a person enters Islam through one path and exits from it through another path (detailed).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡفِقُوۡا مِنۡ مَّا  رَزَقۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَ  اَحَدَکُمُ  الۡمَوۡتُ» (63/10)\nTranslation: And spend from what We have provided you (in accordance with Allah's command) before death approaches any of you.\n\nSee «بُخْل» and «اَقْتَرَ» for stinginess. And see «اَسْرَفَ» and «بَذَّرَ» for extravagance.","«اَنْفَقَ» is a common term for spending.\n«بَخِلَ» Not to spend or to spend less even on permissible necessities.\n«اِقْتَرَ» To be stingy in the sustenance and maintenance of one's family.\n«اَسْرَفَ» To spend beyond necessity.\n«بَذَّر» To spend unnecessarily and wastefully.","expenditure","انفق","2:3-2:195-2:215-2:219-2:254-2:261-2:262-2:264-2:265-2:267-2:270-2:272-2:273-2:274-3:17-3:92-3:117-3:134-4:34-4:38-4:39-5:64-8:3-8:36-8:60-8:63-9:34-9:53-9:54-9:91-9:92-9:98-9:99-9:121-13:22-14:31-16:75-17:100-18:42-22:35-25:67-28:54-32:16-34:39-35:29-36:47-42:38-47:38-57:7-57:10-60:10-60:11-63:7-63:10-64:16-65:6-65:7",57
1382,298,"E","اَھْلَکَ","The original meaning of «اَھْلَکَ» is to destroy, ruin, or waste something. And when it is related to wealth and property, its meaning is to spend all of one's wealth in its entirety. And it is generally used for spending wealth in bad or worthless places.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا  لُّبَدًا» (90/6)\nTranslation: Man says, I have squandered so much wealth.","«اَھْلَکَ» Spending abundant wealth in condemnable and evil objectives.","Expenditure","اھلک","2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6",63
1383,299,"T","بَاعَ ، تَبَایَعَ","(Bai') means to buy and sell. That is, to exchange. This word is from the category of *contronyms* (words with two opposite meanings).\n\nThe word «اِبْتَاع» comes in meanings related to purchasing, but this word has not been used in the Quran. In common usage, «بَائِع» refers to the seller. And «بَایَع» means to make a contract. *Bai'ah* (pledging allegiance) also falls under this, as does mutual exchange. And «تَبَایَع» means to engage in mutual buying and selling or exchange.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اَشۡہِدُوۡۤا اِذَا تَبَایَعۡتُمۡ» (2/282)\nTranslation: And when you transact a debt, record it.\n\nNote: *Lughat-e-Iaddad* refers to words that have two entirely separate meanings, and these meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other.","«بَاعَ» refers to buying and selling when the intention is to fulfill personal necessity, and in common parlance, the one who sells is called the seller.","Trade","باع ، تبایع","2:254-2:275-2:282-9:111-14:31-24:37-48:10-48:18-60:12-62:9",10
1384,299,"B","شَرٰی","Like the word «شَرٰی», it is also from the category of words with opposite meanings (addad). It is used in both the meanings of purchasing and selling. However, the word «اِشْتَرٰی» is specific to the meaning of purchasing. And «مُشْتَرِی» refers to the buyer.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ اشۡتَرٰی مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ بِاَنَّ لَہُمُ الۡجَنَّۃَ» (9/111)\nTranslation: Allah has purchased from the believers their lives and their wealth in exchange for Paradise.\n\nNote: (Words of opposite meanings are those words that have two distinct meanings which are contrary and antithetical to each other).","Engaging in buying and selling when the intention is to fulfill personal necessities. However, «اِشْتَرٰی» is understood in the sense of purchasing.","Buying and selling","شری","2:16-2:41-2:79-2:86-2:90-2:102-2:174-2:175-3:77-3:177-3:187-3:199-4:44-4:74-5:44-5:106-9:9-9:111-12:20-12:21-16:95-31:6",22
1385,299,"B","تِجَارَۃ","The word «تَجَرَ» also comes in both meanings of buying and selling. However, in it, the primary intention is to gain profit, whereas in بيع و شراء (sale and purchase), the purpose is to fulfill some other objective.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ اشۡتَرَوُا الضَّلٰلَۃَ بِالۡہُدٰی ۪  فَمَا رَبِحَتۡ تِّجَارَتُہُمۡ» (2:16)\nTranslation: Those are the ones who have purchased error [in exchange] for guidance, so their transaction has brought them no profit, nor were they guided.","«تَجَرَ» buying and selling with the primary objective of making a profit.","buying and selling","تجارۃ","2:16-2:282-4:29-9:24-24:37-35:29-61:10-62:11",8
1386,300,"T","قِنْطَار","«قِنْطَار» A heavy amount of gold, silver, or cash, and its accumulation «قَنَاطِیْر». According to the scholar of jurisprudence and language, this amount is four thousand dinars or more, or twelve thousand awqiyah.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مَنۡ  اِنۡ تَاۡمَنۡہُ بِقِنۡطَارٍ یُّؤَدِّہٖۤ  اِلَیۡکَ» (3:75)  \nTranslation: Among the People of the Book, there are some who, if you entrust them with even a heap of wealth, will return it to you.","«قِنْطَار» a vast amount of wealth and riches.","treasury","قنطار","3:14-3:75-4:20",3
1387,300,"T","کَنْز","«کَنْز» Its gathering is «کُنُوز». Such accumulated wealth that is concealed from people, whether in the form of a buried treasure (buried in the ground) or through any other means. And according to Ibn al-Faris, any wealth that is concealed. And «کَنَزَ المال» means the gathering of wealth and buried (as in the Quran).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  وَ کَانَ تَحۡتَہٗ کَنۡزٌ لَّہُمَا» (18/82) Translation: And the wall belonged to two orphan boys in the city, beneath which lay a treasure for them.","«کَنْز» hidden accumulated wealth.","treasury","کنز","9:34-9:35-11:12-18:82-25:8",5
1388,300,"T","خَزَائِنُ","«خَزِیْن» Its plural form is «خَزَانَۃ». Meaning: accumulated, stored wealth—whether it be a warehouse, store, cash, or any other type of goods, whether concealed or apparent. And in «خَزَنَ», there are two fundamental aspects: (1) to gather/accumulate, and (2) to safeguard/protect. «خَزَنْتُ الْسِرّ» means I have safeguarded the secret (M. L.), and the guardian/protector of this accumulated wealth is called «خَازِن».\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ اجۡعَلۡنِیۡ عَلٰی خَزَآئِنِ الۡاَرۡضِ ۚ اِنِّیۡ  حَفِیۡظٌ  عَلِیۡمٌ» (12/55)\nTranslation: Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) said to the king of Egypt, Appoint me over the treasuries of the land. I will indeed be a vigilant guardian and knowledgeable.","«خَزَانَۃ» A store or reserve of some commodity or cash for which security arrangements are made.","Treasure","خزائن","6:50-11:31-12:55-15:21-17:100-38:9-52:37-63:7",8
1389,301,"D","یَبَسَ","Its opposite is «رَطَبَ». This term is general, meaning the cessation of water or moisture from something or a place, or the drying out of something. For instance, in the Quran, it is stated: «اَسۡرِ بِعِبَادِیۡ فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» (20:77). Translation: O Moses! Take My servants out by night, then strike for them a dry path through the sea.","The word «یَبَسَ» is commonly used to denote dryness.","Dry","یبس","20:77",1
1390,301,"D","ھَاجَ","«ھَاجَ» The natural demands of plants or due to lack of water, turning from green to yellow and drying up. Plants reaching full maturity and then becoming subject to decline when they ripen, turn yellow, and become ready for harvest (figurative), and «ھَاجَ النَّبَتُ» meaning the grass drying up. And «ھَاجَتُ الْاَرْض» meaning the grass on the earth beginning to dry. (M.L.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ یُخۡرِجُ بِہٖ زَرۡعًا مُّخۡتَلِفًا  اَلۡوَانُہٗ  ثُمَّ یَہِیۡجُ  فَتَرٰىہُ مُصۡفَرًّا ثُمَّ یَجۡعَلُہٗ  حُطَامًا» ( 39/21 )\nTranslation: Then (Allah) brings forth from the earth crops of various colors. Then they dry up, and you see them turning yellow; then He reduces them to fragments.","«ھَاجَ» Plants (things that grow from the earth), after maturing, naturally become dry and yellow.","dry","ھاج","39:21-57:20",2
1391,301,"D","ھَمَدَ","«ھَمَدَ» The drying up and becoming barren of land due to lack of water, or the drying and withering of vegetation (intransitive) «نَبَاتٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» meaning dried grass, and «اَرْضٌ ھَامِدَۃٌ» meaning dry and barren land (transitive).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ تَرَی الۡاَرۡضَ ہَامِدَۃً  فَاِذَاۤ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا الۡمَآءَ   اہۡتَزَّتۡ وَ  رَبَتۡ وَ  اَنۡۢبَتَتۡ مِنۡ  کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ  بَہِیۡجٍ» (22/5)\nTranslation: So you see the earth lifeless, but We send down rain upon it, and it stirs and swells and brings forth every kind of beautiful growth.","«ھَمَدَ» refers to plants drying up and withering due to either water scarcity or barren land.","Dry","ھمد","22:5",1
1392,301,"D","جُفَآءً","«جَفَا یَجْفُوْا» refers to throwing the foam or scum of a river onto the shore, or the foam from a boiling pot, etc., onto the edges (singular), and «جَفَأ» also denotes that useless and worthless chaff and straw which dries up and remains on the riverbank. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَاَمَّا الزَّبَدُ فَیَذۡہَبُ جُفَآءً ۚ وَ اَمَّا مَا یَنۡفَعُ النَّاسَ فَیَمۡکُثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (13/17) Translation: And the foam dries up and vanishes, while the water that benefits people remains in the earth.","The drying up of foam or garbage crust by the riverbank.","Dry","جفآءً","13:17",1
1393,301,"D","غَاضَ","«غَاضَ» means to decrease something or for it to diminish on its own (intransitive). It also means to reduce something or for it to be reduced. It can be used both transitively and intransitively.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اَللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ مَا تَحۡمِلُ کُلُّ اُنۡثٰی وَ مَا تَغِیۡضُ الۡاَرۡحَامُ وَ  مَا تَزۡدَادُ» (13:8)\nTranslation: Allah knows whatever burden any matter carries, and [He knows] any decrease or increase in the wombs.\n\nAnd when «غَاضَ» refers to water, its meaning is that the water dries up. And the earth absorbs it, causing the water level to subside (minjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» (11:44)\nTranslation: And it was commanded, O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease. And the water dried up.","«غَاضَ» drying up and diminishing, shrinking, water flowing downward.","dry","غاض","11:44-13:8",2
1394,302,"R","نَجَات","«نَجَات» means to escape from a sudden calamity, a difficult task, a disaster, or a punishment. And «اَنْجٰی» means to grant release to someone else. This word is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ  اَنۡجَیۡنٰکُمۡ مِّنۡ اٰلِ فِرۡعَوۡنَ» (7/141)\nTranslation: When We delivered you from the people of Pharaoh.\n\nAnd «نَجَات» means salvation, release, and deliverance (reference).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ یٰقَوۡمِ مَا لِیۡۤ  اَدۡعُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَی النَّجٰوۃِ وَ تَدۡعُوۡنَنِیۡۤ   اِلَی  النَّارِ» (40/41)\nTranslation: And, O my people, what is [the matter with] me? I invite you to salvation, while you invite me to the Fire.","The word «نَجَات» is general. It is used to mean being saved or rescued from confusion, sudden calamity, punishment, affliction, etc.","Release","نجات","2:49-2:50-6:63-6:64-7:64-7:72-7:83-7:89-7:141-7:165-10:22-10:23-10:73-10:92-10:103-11:58-11:66-11:94-11:116-12:45-12:110-14:6-17:67-19:72-20:40-20:80-21:9-21:71-21:74-21:76-21:88-23:28-26:65-26:119-26:170-27:53-27:57-29:15-29:24-29:32-29:65-31:32-37:76-37:115-37:134-39:61-40:41-41:18-44:30-54:34-61:10-70:14",52
1395,302,"S"," مَنَاص","The meaning of «نَوْص» includes doubt and finding relief by going somewhere (m. l). «نَاصَ فُلَانًا» means to escape from someone's grasp. «نَاصَ عَنْ قَرْنِہٖ» means to flee from one's opponent (manjada), and «مَنَاص» is an adverb of place. It is used in both spatial and temporal senses, meaning the time of relief and the place of relief.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran: «کَمۡ  اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ فَنَادَوۡا  وَّ  لَاتَ حِیۡنَ مَنَاصٍ» (38/3). Translation: We destroyed many communities before them, and when Our punishment seized them, they started crying for help. But there was no time for escape then.","To attain salvation by oneself.","Salvation","مناص","38:3",1
1396,302,"D","اَنْقَذَ","«اَنْقَذَ» To deliver someone from danger or destruction; to rescue and save (verbal noun).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تُنۡقِذُ مَنۡ فِی النَّارِ» (39/19)\nTranslation: So, can you [O Prophet] rescue someone who is in the Fire?","«اَنْقَذَ» This term is more specific than 'salvation.' It signifies being granted deliverance from danger, ruin, or punishment. See also 'to attain salvation.'","Deliverance","انقذ","3:103-22:73-36:23-36:43-39:19",5
1397,303,"C","بَرِیَّۃ","«بَرَء» proceeds from. Meaning: to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ». All creation. The entire universe—earth and heavens, other planets are also included in it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ ۙ اُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمۡ خَیۡرُ الۡبَرِیَّۃِ» (98/7). Translation: Those who believed and did righteous deeds are the best of all creation.","«بَرِیَّۃ» meaning to bring something from non-existence into existence. Therefore, everything that exists is included in «بَرِیَّۃ».","Creation","بریۃ","98:6-98:7",2
1398,303,"C","اَنَام","«اَنَام» is used for every type of creature present on Earth, whether living or inanimate.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَضَعَہَا لِلۡاَنَامِ» (55:10)  \nTranslation: And Allah has spread the Earth for all creation.  \n\nAnd «اَلْوَرٰی» means that creation which exists on Earth at a given time. It does not include past and future generations (singular), although this form of the word is not used in the Quran. Its plural is «وَرَایَا».","«اَنَام» is recited for every kind of creature on earth.","Created being","انام","55:10",1
1399,303,"C","جِبِلًّا","The plural of «جِبِلّۃٌ» is «جَبِلًّا». In terms of the greatness of a mountain or hill, its meaning is a very large gathering. (Munjid) For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ لَقَدۡ اَضَلَّ  مِنۡکُمۡ  جِبِلًّا کَثِیۡرًا» (36:62). Translation: Indeed, Satan has already misguided many of your creatures.","«جَبِلًّا» applies to a large segment of creation, denoting individuals who are accountable (bound by Sharia).","Creation","جبلًا","26:184-36:62",2
1400,304,"D","مَنَام","«مَنَام» means the state of sleep. And whatever a person sees in a dream is also «مَنَام», whether it has any reality or not.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«اِذۡ یُرِیۡکَہُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَنَامِکَ قَلِیۡلًا» (8/43)  \nTranslation: When Allah showed the disbelievers to you [O Prophet] in a dream in a small number.","The word «مَنَام» is commonly used for dream.","Dream","منام","8:43-30:23-37:102-39:42",4
1401,304,"D","رُءْیَا","«رَاٰی» meaning 'to see'. This term is also applied when one witnesses an event while asleep. For example, the Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰبُنَیَّ  لَا تَقۡصُصۡ رُءۡیَاکَ عَلٰۤی اِخۡوَتِکَ» (12/5)\nTranslation: Prophet Ya'qub (peace be upon him) said, O my dear son, do not relate this dream to your brothers.\nIt is also applied when one witnesses an event in a state of wakefulness. The event of Mi'raj, upon which the majority of scholars agree, occurred in a state of wakefulness.\nRegarding this, the Almighty has declared:\n«وَ مَا جَعَلۡنَا الرُّءۡیَا الَّتِیۡۤ  اَرَیۡنٰکَ اِلَّا فِتۡنَۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ» (17/60)\nTranslation: And We showed you this only as a trial for the people.\nHere, the words of «فِتۡنَۃٌ لِلنَّاس» also explicitly indicate that this event took place in the state of wakefulness.","Whether any event is seen in the state of sleep or wakefulness.","Dream","رءیا","12:5-12:43-12:100-17:60-37:105-48:27",6
1402,304,"D","اَحْلَام","«اَحْلَام» is the plural of «حُلُم». «حَلَمَ» means being young and mature. And «حُلْم» means the dream of youth. Foolish and frightening dreams (m. l. manjada).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ  الۡاَحۡلَامِ  بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44).\n\nTranslation: They (the dream interpreters) said to the king of Egypt, These are merely confused thoughts that have become jumbled. And we are not skilled at interpreting such dreams.","«اَحْلَام» incoherent, absurd, and frightening dreams.","dream","احلام","12:44-21:5",2
1403,305,"D","اَمْل ، اُمْنِیَّۃ","See «اَمَل» for making wishes and hopes.","«اَمَل» A desire for which a long period is required.\n«اُمْنِیَّۃ» A baseless and false desire.","desire","امل ، امنیۃ","2:78-2:111-4:123-15:3-18:46-47:25-57:14",7
1404,305,"D","ھَوٰی","«ھَوٰی» Its plural is «اَھْوَاء», meaning the desires of the self and the inclination toward them (muf). «ھَوٰی یَھْوِی» means to fall from above. And «اَلْمَھْوَاۃ» is what a pit is called. And «اَھَوَاء» refers to such desires that, by pursuing which, a person loses his worth and status (manjad). This word is generally used in a bad sense. In the words of Ibn Faris, «ھَوَی النَّفْسُ خَالٍ مِّنْ کُلِّ خَیْرٍ» means desires of the self that contain no good whatsoever.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ  الۡہَوٰی فَاِنَّ  الۡجَنَّۃَ  ہِیَ الۡمَاۡوٰی» (79/40,41)\nTranslation: And whoever feared to stand before his Lord and restrained his desires, then indeed, his abode will be Paradise.","«ھَوٰی» refers to the misuse of evil desires or natural desires.","desire","ھوی","2:87-4:135-5:70-38:26-53:3-53:23-79:40",7
1405,305,"D","شَھْوَۃ","«شَھْوَت» are the natural demands of a person's desires and his accumulation «شَھْوَات» of such desires toward which a person's nafs (lower self) is pulled (as in the example): such as hunger, thirst, greed for wealth, and sexual desire. Whether their use is good or bad. And a person's own will is not involved in them (Fakhr al-Din al-Razi, 98).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«زُیِّنَ لِلنَّاسِ حُبُّ الشَّہَوٰتِ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ وَ الۡبَنِیۡنَ وَ الۡقَنَاطِیۡرِ الۡمُقَنۡطَرَۃِ مِنَ الذَّہَبِ وَ الۡفِضَّۃِ وَ الۡخَیۡلِ الۡمُسَوَّمَۃِ وَ الۡاَنۡعَامِ وَ الۡحَرۡثِ» (3/14)\nTranslation: To people, the things they desire—namely women, sons, heaped-up piles of gold and silver, fine horses, cattle, and tilled land—appear adorned.\n\nAnd «شَھْوً یَشْھَو», meaning 'to be delicious' (as in the lexicon *Majd*), and the word «اِشْتَھَا» has become specific to the desire for food and drink, or hunger.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡۤ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَا تَدَّعُوۡنَ» (41/31)\nTranslation: And in Paradise, whatever you desire will be yours, and whatever you request will be present for you.","«شَھْوَت» the natural human desires.","Desire","شھوۃ","3:14-4:27-7:81-16:57-19:59-21:102-27:55-34:54-41:31-43:71-52:22-56:21-77:42",13
1406,305,"D","وَطَرَ","«وَطَر» The utmost desire and essential need (muf) of cohabitation, lust (m. q.). In the Quran, this word has been used specifically for sexual desire.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لِکَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ عَلَی  الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ حَرَجٌ  فِیۡۤ  اَزۡوَاجِ اَدۡعِیَآئِہِمۡ  اِذَا  قَضَوۡا  مِنۡہُنَّ  وَطَرًا» (33/37)\nTranslation: So that there should be no blame on the believers for marrying the wives of their adopted sons when they have already dissolved their marriage with them.","«وَطَر» an utmost desire and a vital necessity, particularly in mutual coexistence.","Desire","وطر","33:37",1
1407,306,"B","بَھِیْج","«بَھُیْجَ» means to be beautiful. And «اَبْھَجُ الْمَکَان» means for a place to be lush and verdant. And «بَھْجَۃ» means beauty, lushness, verdancy, joy, happiness, or an expression of joy (as in *munajid*). It is said that the word «بَھْجَۃ» generally comes for the beauty of plants—a beauty that delights the heart. And «بَھِیْج» means beautiful, flourishing, full of spring.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡۢبَتۡنَا فِیۡہَا مِنۡ کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ بَہِیۡجٍ» (50/7)\nTranslation: And We have caused to grow in the earth every kind of splendid thing.","«بَھْجَۃ» is generally applied for the beauty of plants.","Beautiful","بھیج","22:5-27:60-50:7",3
1408,306,"B","نَاضِرَۃ","«نَضَرَ» means to be fresh and radiant. And «نَضَرَ الْوَجْہ» means for a face to be soft, fresh, and beautiful. And «نَضْرَۃٌ» means beauty, splendor, blessing. And «نَاضِر» means beautiful, soft and delicate (used for plants as well). However, this word is mostly used for the beauty of a human face, which is due to freshness and softness.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ  نَّاضِرَۃٌ اِلٰی رَبِّہَا نَاظِرَۃٌ» (75/22,23)\nTranslation: On that day, many faces will be fresh and radiant, looking at their Lord.","«نَضْرَۃ» is frequently applied to enhance the beauty of the human face, a beauty that arises from freshness and softness.","Beautiful","ناضرۃ","75:22-76:11-83:24",3
1409,306,"B","حِسَان","«حَسُنَ» means 'to be beautiful'. And «حَسِیْن» is its feminine form, and «حَسَنَاء» is its plural. And «حُسْن» means 'beauty' or 'jamaal'. And «مَحَاسِن» means the beautiful parts of the body (manjad). For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فِیۡہِنَّ خَیۡرٰتٌ حِسَانٌ» (55:70)\nTranslation: In those (gardens) are women of good character and beautiful (form).","«حَسُنَ» is used to become favored and good-looking.","Beautiful","حسان","2:83-2:138-2:245-3:14-3:37-3:148-3:195-4:59-4:69-4:95-5:12-6:152-6:160-7:137-7:180-8:17-9:107-10:26-11:3-11:88-13:18-13:29-16:62-16:67-16:75-17:110-18:2-18:31-18:86-18:88-20:8-20:86-21:101-22:58-25:76-27:11-28:61-29:8-33:52-35:8-38:25-38:40-38:49-41:50-42:23-48:16-53:31-55:70-55:76-57:10-57:11-57:18-59:24-64:17-73:20-92:6-92:9",57
1410,307,"F","قُوْت","«قُوْت» meaning food, sustenance. The amount of food by which any living being can stay alive. Its plural is «اَقْوَات». And «قَاتَ یَقُوْتُ» means to feed (someone) food. And «اَقَات» means to give something from which one can obtain strength. They say «مَا لَہٗ قُووْتُ لَیْلَۃٍ»: he does not even have food for the night (m.f.). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ مِنۡ فَوۡقِہَا وَ بٰرَکَ فِیۡہَا وَ قَدَّرَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَقۡوَاتَہَا فِیۡۤ  اَرۡبَعَۃِ  اَیَّامٍ» (41/10). Translation: And He has placed in the earth firmly set mountains, rising above it, and He has blessed it and created therein its sustenance in balance, all in four days.","«قُوْت» the minimum amount of food required to keep a living being alive.","Food","قوت","41:10",1
1411,307,"F","رِزْق","«رِزْق» meaning sustenance. «رَزَقَ» meaning to provide sustenance. And «رُزِق». To receive sustenance, to be fortunate. And «مُرْزُرْق» meaning fortunate (Munjid). The usage of this word applies to both material and spiritual contexts. And «رِزْق» also means 'fortune' or 'destined portion'. «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» meaning 'knowledge was bestowed upon me'. And in a material sense, rizq is everything that reaches the stomach and becomes nourishment (Muf). And «رِزْق» also means 'rain' (Muf. Munjid).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  رِزۡقُکُمۡ» (51/22)\nTranslation: And your provision is in the heavens.\n\nThus, everything that directly or indirectly becomes a cause for spiritual or physical nourishment and training is considered rizq.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«قَالَ لَا یَاۡتِیۡکُمَا طَعَامٌ تُرۡزَقٰنِہٖۤ  اِلَّا نَبَّاۡتُکُمَا بِتَاۡوِیۡلِہٖ  قَبۡلَ اَنۡ یَّاۡتِیَکُمَا» (12/37)\nTranslation: Yusuf said, I will inform you of its interpretation before the food you are given reaches you.","Everything that serves as a means of spiritual or physical training, whether directly or indirectly.","Food","رزق","2:3-2:22-2:25-2:57-2:60-2:126-2:172-2:212-2:233-2:254-3:27-3:37-3:169-4:5-4:8-4:39-5:88-5:114-6:140-6:142-6:151-7:32-7:50-7:160-8:3-8:4-8:26-8:74-10:31-10:59-10:93-11:6-11:88-12:37-13:22-13:26-14:31-14:32-14:37-16:56-16:67-16:71-16:72-16:73-16:75-16:112-16:114-17:30-17:31-17:70-18:19-19:62-20:81-20:131-20:132-22:28-22:34-22:35-22:50-22:58-24:26-24:38-27:64-28:54-28:57-28:82-29:17-29:60-29:62-30:28-30:37-30:40-32:16-33:31-34:4-34:15-34:24-34:36-34:39-35:3-35:29-36:47-37:41-38:54-39:52-40:13-40:40-40:64-42:12-42:19-42:27-42:38-45:5-45:16-50:11-51:22-51:57-56:82-63:10-65:3-65:7-65:11-67:15-67:21-89:16",105
1412,307,"F","مَارَ","«مَیْر» means food, provisions. «مِیَرَۃ» means gathered provisions, and its plurals are «مَیْر», «مَارَ», and «اَمَارَ عَیَالُہٗ». «مَائِر» and «مَیَّار» mean one who brings provisions (manjid). Essentially, «مَیْر» refers to such edible items stored as reserves. For example: In the Quran, «وَ نَمِیۡرُ اَہۡلَنَا وَ نَحۡفَظُ اَخَانَا وَ نَزۡدَادُ کَیۡلَ  بَعِیۡرٍ» (12/65). Translation: And (on this occasion) we will bring grain for our family, protect our brother, and bring an additional camel's load.","«مَارَ» meaning to bring food for one's family and dependents, and «مَیْر» meaning grain or provisions stored for future use.","Food","مار","12:65",1
1413,308,"H","رَضِیَ","«رَضِیَ» is a well-known term meaning to be pleased or to express approval. Its opposite is «سَخَطَ», meaning to be displeased or to be angry (transitive verb).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ  عَنِ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  اِذۡ یُبَایِعُوۡنَکَ تَحۡتَ الشَّجَرَۃِ» (48/18)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah was pleased with the believers when they pledged allegiance to you under the tree.","It is used solely to express preference.","Happy","رضی","2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7",26
1414,308,"H","سَرَّ","«سَرّ» meaning to give delight, to be a source of heartfelt joy. To become happy in the heart itself. It is used both transitively and intransitively.\nFor example: In the Quran it is mentioned:\n«بَقَرَۃٌ صَفۡرَآءُ  ۙ فَاقِعٌ لَّوۡنُہَا تَسُرُّ النّٰظِرِیۡنَ» (2/69)\nTranslation: The color of that cow is deep yellow. It delights those who see it.","«سَرّ» to be overjoyed.","Happy","سر","2:69-76:11-84:9-84:13",4
1415,308,"H","بَھِجَ","«بَھِج» means to be happy and delighted. And «بَھُج» means to be beautiful (manjad), but this word is not used in the Quran for any human being. Rather, it is used for vegetables, fruits, and flowers. For example, «حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27/60) or «مِنۡ کُلِّ  زَوۡجٍۭ بَہِیۡجٍ» (50/7), and its meanings are taken as 'flourishing' or 'in full bloom'.","«بَھِج» encompasses joy, happiness, and beauty for all. It is also used for plants and flowers.","Happy","بھج","22:5-27:60-50:7",3
1416,308,"H","حَبَرَ","«حَبَرَ» means to make happy and delighted. And «حَبِرَ» means to be happy. And «حَبِرَ الْاَرْض» means to produce abundant vegetation from the earth; to be very green and lush. And «تَحَبَّر» means to be adorned; to be excellent (manjad). Thus, the meaning intended by «حَبَرَ» is a joy that arises from the cleanliness, excellence, and spring-like beauty of the surroundings.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ فَہُمۡ فِیۡ رَوۡضَۃٍ یُّحۡبَرُوۡنَ» (30:15)\nTranslation: So those who believed and did righteous deeds will be made happy in the gardens (of Paradise).","«حَبَرَ» The purity, beauty, and freshness of the environment bring joy to the heart.","Happy","حبر","30:15-43:70",2
1417,308,"H","اِسْتَبْشَرَ","«بَشَر» means to peel the skin, and «بَشْرَۃ» means the direction above the skin. «اِسْتَبْشِر» refers to joy whose effects become visible on the skin or face, such as raised eyebrows. When one feels happiness upon hearing good news or receiving something good, the term «اِسْتَبْشَرَ» is used. Meanwhile, «بَشَّرَ» means to give good news that makes another happy—that is, giving glad tidings.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَاسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡا بِبَیۡعِکُمُ الَّذِیۡ بَایَعۡتُمۡ بِہٖ» (9/111)\nTranslation: Rejoice in the transaction which you have made.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَ بَشَّرُوۡہُ  بِغُلٰمٍ  عَلِیۡمٍ» (51/28)\nTranslation: And (the angels) gave glad tidings to Abraham of a knowledgeable boy.","«اِسْتَبْشَرَ» to light up (with joy) upon receiving good news or something good.","Happy","استبشر","3:170-3:171-9:111-9:124-15:67-30:48-39:45-80:39",8
1418,308,"H","طَابَ","«طَاب» Such is the joy from which, apart from the heart, a person's senses also derive pleasure (m.f.). «طَیِّبٰت» meaning pure things and «طِیْب» meaning fragrance (manjida).\nFor instance, the Quran states: «فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4/3) Translation: Marry those women who please you.","A bliss in which even the senses partake.","Happy","طاب","4:3",1
1419,308,"H","فَرِحَ","Rejoicing upon the receipt of a blessing. And it has two types:\n\n«فَرِحَ الْقَلْب» When a person, upon receiving a fortune, rejoices and expresses gratitude to Allah. And this is a praiseworthy (commendable) trait.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَرِحِیۡنَ بِمَاۤ اٰتٰہُمُ اللّٰہُ مِنۡ فَضۡلِہٖ» ( 3/170 )\nTranslation: They are joyful for what Allah has granted them.\n\n«فَرِحَ النَّفْس» When a person, instead of expressing gratitude to Allah for a blessing received, begins to boast—meaning to celebrate joyfully [in a vain manner]. And this is a blameworthy (reprehensible) trait.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَلَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ اٰتٰىکُمۡ» ( 57/23 )\nTranslation: So that you may not grieve over what has escaped you, nor exult over what He has given you.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«لَا تَفۡرَحۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یُحِبُّ الۡفَرِحِیۡنَ» ( 28/76 )\nTranslation: Do not boast. Indeed, Allah does not like the boastful.","«فَرِحَ» to break into joyous celebration.","Happy","فرح","3:120-3:170-3:188-6:44-9:50-9:81-10:22-10:58-11:10-13:26-13:36-23:53-27:36-28:76-30:4-30:32-30:36-40:75-40:83-42:48-57:23",21
1420,308,"H","فَکِہَ","«فَکِہَ» To engage in cheerful banter. To be of a happy disposition and to laugh, making others laugh (Fal 145). «طَیِّبَ النَّفْس» Or joviality (M. L).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَاِذَا انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہِمُ انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ» (83/31)\nTranslation: And when they return to their homes, they would engage in cheerful banter.","«فَکِہَ» Engaging in pleasant gossip and having refined taste.","Happy","فکہ","83:31",1
1421,308,"H","اَشْمَتَ","«شَمِتَ» means to be happy about someone's calamity. And «اَشْمَتَ» means to be happy about another person's calamity. *Shamatata a'dda'* is a famous Arabic term which means to rejoice over an enemy's suffering.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَا تُشۡمِتۡ بِیَ الۡاَعۡدَآءَ» (7/150)\n\nTranslation: (Aaron, peace be upon him, said, O Moses, peace be upon him) do not give an opportunity for my enemies to rejoice.","«اَشْمَتَ» is an enemy's delight in another's distress.","Happy","اشمت","7:150",1
1422,308,"H","اَعْجَبَ","The attractiveness or pleasant appearance of something, accompanied by a sense of wonder due to the unknown cause (formal).","«اَعْجَبَ» To be so deeply joyful within oneself that there is also wonder, and the cause of it remains unknown—a blend of happiness and astonishment.","Happy","اعجب","2:204-2:221-5:100-9:25-33:52-48:29-57:20-63:4",8
1423,309,"P","سَرَّا","The meaning of «سَرَّآءِ» is a period passing with comfort and tranquility, without any scarcity in livelihood—a time of prosperity, peace, and well-being in which one finds contentment. Its opposite is «ضَرَّاء», which means a period of poverty and afflictions (Faqir 163).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ فِی السَّرَّآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ» (3/134)\nTranslation: Those who spend their wealth (in the way of Allah) during times of ease and hardship.","«سَرَّآءِ» a time that passes in peace and comfort, without any financial hardship.","Prosperity","سرا","3:134-7:95",2
1424,309,"P","نَعْمَآء","«نِعْمَت» means good condition, favor. And «نعمت» means comfort and ease (pl.). And «نِعْمَت» means benefit, grace, reward. And «نَعْمَت» means improvement, prosperity, wealth, livestock. And «نُعْمَۃ» means joy (of mind). And «نعمآء» is such a period of prosperity in which divine rewards are abundant. And those blessings become apparent to others as well (Faqir 163). Its opposite is «ضَرَّاء».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلَئِنۡ اَذَقۡنٰہُ نَعۡمَآءَ بَعۡدَ ضَرَّآءَ مَسَّتۡہُ  لَیَقُوۡلَنَّ ذَہَبَ السَّیِّاٰتُ عَنِّیۡ» (11:10)\nTranslation: And if We let him taste favor after hardship has touched him, he says (rejoicing), All hardships have departed from me.","«نُعْمَاء» abundance of blessings, comfort, and ease.","Prosperity","نعمآء","2:271-4:58-11:10",3
1425,309,"P","طُوْبٰی","«طَابَ» meaning to attain such joy that not only the heart but also a person's senses beyond the heart are overcome (m.f.) and «طَیِّب» meaning pure and «طِیْب» meaning fragrance (minjadd) and «طُوبٰی» meaning such prosperity in which the heart is also content and delighted.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَعَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ طُوۡبٰی لَہُمۡ  وَحُسۡنُ مَاٰبٍ» (13/29)\nTranslation: For those who believe and perform righteous deeds, there is prosperity and an excellent abode.","«طُوْبٰی» The prosperity that brings contentment to the heart as well.","Prosperity","طوبی","2:57-2:168-2:172-2:267-3:38-3:179-4:2-4:43-4:160-5:4-5:5-5:6-5:87-5:88-5:100-7:32-7:58-7:157-7:160-8:26-8:37-8:69-9:72-10:22-10:93-13:29-14:24-16:32-16:72-16:97-16:114-17:70-20:81-22:24-23:51-24:26-24:61-34:15-35:10-40:64-45:16-46:20-61:12",43
1426,310,"S","طَلَعَ","The lexical meaning of «طَلَعَ» is to appear and to come forth (m. l.). For stars, the terms rising and setting are well-known, and «طَلَعَ» is also used for a new cluster when it begins to appear from its sheath or the cavity of a date fruit (manjd). For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ النَّخۡلَ بٰسِقٰتٍ  لَّہَا طَلۡعٌ  نَّضِیۡدٌ» (50:10). Translation: And tall date-palms with clusters layered one upon another.","«طَلَعَ» refers to the stage when the fruit cluster becomes visible from the flower bud. And «قِطْف» refers to the state of becoming ripe and ready to be harvested. And «قِنْو» refers to the intermediate state. However, the application of «قِنْو» is specific only to the clusters of dates and grapes.","Segments","طلع","6:99-26:148-37:65-50:10",4
1427,310,"S","قُطُوْف","«قُطُوْف» means gathered, referring to «قِطْف». And «قِطْف» refers to such ripe fruits that are completely ready to be picked, a meaning confirmed by the Quran. Meanwhile, the author of *Majma' al-Bayan* defines its meaning as chosen fruits; a cluster of grapes when it is selected.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَہُوَفِیۡ عِیۡشَۃٍ رَّاضِیَۃٍ فِیۡ جَنَّۃٍ عَالِیَۃٍ قُطُوۡفُہَا دَانِیَۃٌ» (69:21-23)\nTranslation: He will be in a life of pleasure, in lofty gardens whose clusters will be hanging low.\n\nThis makes it clear that the fruit on the trees is, as it were, ripe and ready to be picked, yet still on the trees. For this, Allah the Exalted has used the word «قُطُوْف».","«قُطُوْف» a perfectly ripe fruit, ready to be harvested.","segments","قطوف","69:23-76:14",2
1428,310,"S","قِنْوَان","«قِنْوَان» is the plural form of «قِنْو». This term is specifically used for clusters of dates and grapes that are not yet ripe for harvesting.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَمِنَ النَّخۡلِ مِنۡ طَلۡعِہَا قِنۡوَانٌ دَانِیَۃٌ» (6:99)  \nTranslation: And [from] the tall date palms, having layers upon layers [of fruit clusters].","«قِنْوَان» clusters of grapes and dates that are not yet ready to be picked.","Segment","قنوان","6:99",1
1429,311,"B","خَانَ","«خَانَ» means to betray, and its opposite is trust. This betrayal occurs even in covenants and also in property held in trust. For instance, taking all or part of someone's wealth through deception and wrongful seizure under false pretenses. Similarly, the term applies to breaking a covenant and failing to uphold that covenant. Deceit (example). For instance: In the Quran it is stated: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَخُوۡنُوا اللّٰہَ وَالرَّسُوۡلَ وَتَخُوۡنُوۡۤا اَمٰنٰتِکُمۡ» (8/27) Translation: O you who believe! Do not betray the trust of Allah and His Messenger, nor betray your own trusts.","Betrayal of covenant and the violation of trust through deception, whereas in «غَلّ» the cause of betrayal is theft.","Breach of trust","خان","4:105-5:13-8:27-8:58-8:71-12:52-40:19-66:10",8
1430,311,"B","غَلَّ","«غَلَّ» means to take something stealthily into one's possession and then conceal it so that it cannot be seen (Munjid, m. r.). And 'ghulool' means to betray, to lock up, and to be stingy—all these meanings are applicable (Munjid). Thus, it seems that in «غَلَّ», besides betrayal, the element of theft is also included, or the means of that betrayal is theft.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is said: «وَمَا کَانَ لِنَبِیٍّ اَنۡ یَّغُلَّ ؕ وَمَنۡ یَّغۡلُلۡ یَاۡتِ بِمَا غَلَّ  یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/161). Translation: And it is never possible that a Prophet of Allah should betray. And on the Day of Resurrection, those who betrayed will be brought forth with what they betrayed (in the presence of Allah). (Jalandhari) And it is not for a Prophet to conceal (anything). Then whoever conceals will bring forth what he concealed on the Day of Resurrection. (Ottoman)","«غَلَّ» meaning to betray.","Breach of trust","غل","3:161",1
1431,312,"T","خِیَامٌ","«خِیَامٌ» (the plural of khaimah) is a well-known word. It refers to a canopy made of thick cloth or matting to provide shelter from sun and rain, which typically has a sloping roof rather than a flat one. And according to Sahib Munjid, it includes any curtained shelter that is not constructed from bricks, stones, or mud. And «خیم» also refers to the structures and howdahs carried by camels (as per Munjid). In the Quran, it is mentioned:\n«حُوۡرٌ مَّقۡصُوۡرٰتٌ فِی الۡخِیَامِ» (55:72)\nTranslation: Who remain stationed in tents.","«خِیَامٌ» meaning tent.","tent","خیام","55:72",1
1432,312,"T","ظُلَّۃٌ","«ظُلَّۃٌ» It is a canopy whose roof is a roof (i.e., a covering) but has no walls. «ظُلَّۃ» It is also called an umbrella, and «ظلیل» a shade-giving tree (manjad), and «ظِلّ» meaning shade and its plural «ظِلَال» and «ظِلًّا ظَلِیْلًا» meaning long and dense shade.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَاِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ» ( 7/171 )\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy.","«ظُلَّۃٌ» means 'shadow'.","The Sacred Tent (in Mecca)","ظلۃ","7:171-26:189",2
1433,312,"T","سُرَادِق","«سُرَادِق» is the plural form. «سَرْدَقَ» refers to a structure that has only walls, such as the canopies used on occasions like weddings. This word is of Persian origin but has been Arabized (i.e., a word originally from another language that has been slightly modified to become Arabic).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَعۡتَدۡنَا لِلظّٰلِمِیۡنَ نَارًا ۙ اَحَاطَ بِہِمۡ سُرَادِقُہَا» (18/29)\nTranslation: We have prepared for the wrongdoers a Hell encompassed by walls.","«سُرَادِق» meaning tent, shamiana, pandal.","Tent","سرادق","18:29",1
1434,313,"I","دَخَلَ","«دَخَل» is a well-known word meaning to enter, and its opposite, «خَرَجَ», means to exit. Its usage is common.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَدَخَلَ مَعَہُ السِّجۡنَ فَتَیٰنِ» (12/36)\nTranslation: And two young men entered the prison along with Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him).\n\nAnd for to cause to enter, «اَدْخَلَ» is used.\nFor example: The divine declaration states:\n«یُّدۡخِلُ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ فِیۡ رَحۡمَتِہٖ» (76/31)\nTranslation: Allah admits whom He wills into His mercy.","«دَخَل» entering, being inside, trying to enter.","inner","دخل","2:58-2:111-2:114-2:208-2:214-3:37-3:97-3:142-3:185-3:192-3:195-4:13-4:14-4:23-4:31-4:57-4:122-4:124-4:154-4:175-5:12-5:21-5:22-5:23-5:24-5:61-5:65-5:84-7:38-7:40-7:46-7:49-7:151-7:161-9:57-9:99-12:36-12:58-12:67-12:68-12:69-12:88-12:99-13:23-14:23-15:46-15:52-16:29-16:31-16:32-17:7-17:80-18:35-18:39-19:60-21:75-21:86-22:14-22:23-22:59-24:27-24:28-24:29-24:61-27:12-27:18-27:19-27:34-27:44-28:15-29:9-33:14-33:53-35:33-36:26-38:22-39:72-39:73-40:8-40:40-40:46-40:60-40:76-42:8-43:70-45:30-47:6-47:12-48:5-48:17-48:25-48:27-49:14-50:34-51:25-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:10-68:24-70:38-71:25-71:28-76:31-89:29-89:30-110:2",109
1435,313,"E","وَلَجَ","«اَلْوَلْوَج» refers to entering a narrow space (transitive) – to enter with difficulty, to squeeze in.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَلَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» (7/40)\nTranslation: They will not enter Paradise until a camel enters the eye of a needle.\nAnd «اَوْلَج» is used for causing to enter or squeeze into a narrow place.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یُوۡلِجُ الَّیۡلَ  فِی النَّہَارِ  وَ یُوۡلِجُ النَّہَارَ فِی الَّیۡلِ» (22/61)\nTranslation: Allah causes the night to enter the day and causes the day to enter the night.","«وَلَجَ» to enter a tight spot.","entering","ولج","3:27-7:40-22:61-31:29-34:2-35:13-57:4-57:6",8
1436,313,"E","صَلَی","The word «صَلَی» is specifically used for entering fire. It means to enter fire and to burn. For example, in the Quran it says: «جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ؕ وَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرَارُ» (14/29). Translation: They will enter Hell and it is a terrible place.\n\nAnd for causing someone to enter fire or to burn, «صَلّٰی» is used. For example, in the Quran it says: «خُذُوۡہُ فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ الۡجَحِیۡمَ صَلُّوۡہُ» (69/30,31). Translation: Seize him and shackle him with chains, then throw him into Hell.","«صَلَی» meaning 'to enter fire'.","entering","صلی","4:10-4:90-11:81-14:29-28:35-36:64-38:56-52:16-58:8-69:31-82:15-84:12-87:12-88:4-111:3",15
1437,313,"E","سَلَکَ","The word «سَلَکَ» is employed in multiple meanings and in both transitive and intransitive forms, and in all these meanings, the concept of 'entering' is found.  \nExamples:  \n(1) To thread or insert, such as threading a needle with thread.  \nFor example, the divine command states:  \n«کَذٰلِکَ سَلَکۡنٰہُ  فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِ الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (26/200)  \nTranslation: Thus, We have cast (or inserted) denial into the hearts of the criminals. (Jalandhari) / We have made it (the denial) penetrate (or sink into). (Uthmani)  \n\n(2) To put in, to insert, such as putting a hand into a collar.  \nFor example, the divine command states:  \n«اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِسُوۡٓءٍ» (28/32)  \nTranslation: And put your hand into your collar; it will emerge pure and without any stain.  \n\nNow, this same verse is mentioned in another place with «اُسْلُک» instead of «اَدْخِلْ».  \nFor example, the divine command states:  \n«وَاَدۡخِلۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ مِنۡ غَیۡرِ سُوۡٓءٍ» (27/12)  \nTranslation: And put your hand into your collar; it will emerge pure and without any stain.  \n\n(3) To proceed along a path.  \nFor example, in the Quran, Allah the Most High says to the honeybee:  \n«فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16/69)  \nTranslation: Then, follow the ways of your Lord submissively.  \nIn this verse, «اُسْلُکِیْ» has also been translated as «اُدْخُلِیْ» (M. Q.).  \n\nAlso, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«مَا سَلَکَکُمۡ  فِیۡ سَقَرَ» (74/42)  \nTranslation: What has caused you to enter the Hellfire?  \n\nKeeping all these clarifications in mind, the author of *Muntahi al-Arab* has stated the briefest meaning of «سَلَکَ» as: Kashidan chīzē dar chīzē — i.e., to draw one thing into another, or to extract one thing from within another. According to the author of *Munjid*, it means to place one thing inside another. And the author of *Maqāyīs al-Lughah* gives two fundamental meanings: (1) to proceed along a path, and (2) to insert one thing into another, to thread.","«سَلَکَ» to draw one thing into another or to insert it.","entering","سلک","15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42",12
1438,314,"J","خَزَنَ","«خَزَنَ» This term often comes in the context of accumulating wealth and property, such as in *khazanat al-darahim* (the treasury of coins). However, its fundamental meaning is more about preservation than accumulation. It is said *khazanat al-sirr* (I have preserved the secret). And the person who guards this accumulated thing or property is called «خَازِن». Its plural form is *khazanah*.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«کُلَّمَاۤ  اُلۡقِیَ فِیۡہَا  فَوۡجٌ سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» ( 67/8 )\nTranslation: Whenever a group is thrown into Hell, its keepers will ask them, Did no warner come to you?\n\nThe difference between «خَازِن» and «مُصَیْطِر» is the same as that between *hafiz* (guardian) and *raqib* (overseer).\nThe responsibility of «خَازِن» is merely to protect, to safeguard the stored items. Whereas the responsibility of «مُصَیْطِر» also includes their meticulous care and supervision, because they have authority and control over them.","«خَزَنَ» meaning guardian, protector.","Jail superintendent","خزنۃ","15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8",5
1439,314,"G","مُصَیْطِر","«مُصَیْطِر» Some linguists write this word with س instead of ص. In the Quran, it is written with ص, and a small س is written above it. Then some linguists have derived it under the root «سطر», while others under «سَیْطر». «سَیْطَرَ عَلٰی» means to prevail over someone and to be their guardian. And «سیطر» means a caretaker (one to whom a task has been entrusted) and an overseer.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ ؕ اِنَّمَاۤ اَنۡتَ مُذَکِّرٌ لَسۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  بِمُصَۜیۡطِرٍ» (88/21,22)\nTranslation: Admonish them; you are only a warner. You are not a guardian over them.\nThat is, you have no power over them to compel them to accept your message.","«مُصَیْطِر» meaning guardian, watchman, keeper.","Guardian","مصیطر","52:37-88:22",2
1440,315,"S","وَسَم","«وَسَم» means to mark or to brand, and also to engrave or carve designs on the body. «وَسَّم» means to dye, and «وَسَام» and «وَسَمَہ» refer to the substance with which a mark is made or dye is applied.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68:16). Translation: So We will soon mark his nose (like a camel's) with a stain.","«وَسَم» means engraving or carving on the body, digging mounds, etc.","Stain","وسم","2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16",8
1441,315,"S","کَوٰی یَکْوِیْ","«کَوٰی» Heating an iron or any other metal instrument in fire until it becomes red-hot, then placing it on the skin to brand it and burn that portion of the skin. And «کَاوِیَۃ» they call that instrument the one with which branding is done.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَّوۡمَ یُحۡمٰی عَلَیۡہَا فِیۡ نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ فَتُکۡوٰی بِہَا جِبَاہُہُمۡ وَ جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ ظُہُوۡرُہُمۡ» ( 9/35 )\nTranslation: On the Day when their (gold and silver) will be heated in the fire of Hell and their foreheads, flanks, and backs will be branded with it.","«کَوٰی» To brand or mark the skin with iron or another metal.\n«کَاوِیَۃ» The tool with which a mark is made is called a branding iron.","Seal of Prophethood (in Islamic tradition); brand; stain; mark; scar","کوی یکوی","9:35",1
1442,315,"S","شِیَۃ","«وَشِیَ» «وَشَیْتُ الشَّیْءُ وَشْیًا» means to apply a color that is contrary to the natural color of something. And «وَشْیۃ» and «شِیَۃ» mean a spot or mark of a color that is different from the color of the entire body (i.e., a blemish).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«مُسَلَّمَۃٌ لَّا شِیَۃَ فِیۡہَا» (2/71)  \nTranslation: It (the cow) should be entirely sound and without any blemish.","A spot or mark that is distinct from the body's overall color.","Stain","شیۃ","2:71",1
1443,316,"T","عِجَاف","«عِجَاف» is plural. «اَعْجِفْ» means to abandon food while still hungry (M. Q). And «عَجِفَ» means to become lean due to a reduction in fat (M. L), thus implying a'jaf — an animal that has become weak and emaciated due to a lack of sustenance.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ الۡمَلِکُ اِنِّیۡۤ  اَرٰی سَبۡعَ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ یَّاۡکُلُہُنَّ سَبۡعٌ عِجَافٌ» (12:43)\n\nTranslation: The king said, Indeed, I have seen [in a dream] seven fat cows being eaten by seven lean cows.","«اَعْجَفَ» the animal that becomes emaciated due to lack of food.","thin","عجاف","12:43-12:46",2
1444,316,"T","ضَامِر","«ضَمَر ، اَلْاَضْمَار» means the field or course for horse racing. The field for training horses. The extreme limit of the horse racing course. And the period (munjad) for training and exercising horses. And «ضَامِر» is that animal which becomes lean and thin-bodied not due to scarcity of food but because of the abundance of training and exercise. Swiftness of pace. So that it can get ahead in a race. In Arabic, the word «ضِامِر» has generally become specific to the camel, whether male or female.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj [pilgrimage]; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel, coming from every distant path.","«ضَامِر» is the one who, due to exertion and hardship, becomes thin, lean, and of a bony frame.","Thin","ضامر","22:27",1
1445,317,"L","طَالَ ( طُوْلًا )","«طَالَ» means to be long. «طُوْل» means length, and its opposite, «عَرَض», means width. «اَطَالَ» means to make long.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«اِنَّکَ  لَنۡ تَخۡرِقَ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَنۡ تَبۡلُغَ الۡجِبَالَ طُوۡلًا» (17/37)\nTranslation: Nor can you tear open the earth, nor can you reach the mountains in height.\n\nAnd «تَطَاوَلَ عَلَیْہِ الْعُمْر» means to increase in someone's age. Longevity of age (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«وَ لٰکِنَّاۤ  اَنۡشَاۡنَا قُرُوۡنًا فَتَطَاوَلَ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡعُمُرُ» (28/45)\nTranslation: But We have produced many generations among whom long ages have passed.","«طَالَ» overly long.","Lengthy","طال ( طولًا )","17:37-20:86-21:44-28:45-57:16-73:7-76:26",7
1446,317,"E","مَدّ","«مَدَّ» means to stretch out and extend. It refers to stretching something and extending it in such a way that the thing remains connected, i.e., rooted. (Intensive) And it also denotes duration, meaning the length of time. For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَلَمۡ  تَرَ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَیۡفَ مَدَّ  الظِّلَّ» (25/45)\nTranslation: Have you not considered your Lord (in His power) how He extends the shade?\nAnd in «مَدَّدَ», repetition of the word is for semantic emphasis. (If the speech is strengthened by an additional emphatic word other than the mentioned word in the sentence, it is called semantic emphasis). For example, the divine command states:\n«فِیۡ  عَمَدٍ  مُّمَدَّدَۃٍ» (104/9)\nTranslation: In long, long pillars.","to lengthen something by pulling it","Extended","مد","2:15-7:202-13:3-19:75-25:45-31:27-56:30-74:12-104:9",9
1447,317,"E","بَاعَدَ","«بَعُدَ» means to be distant. And «بَاعَدَ» means to increase the distance between two things.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «فَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا بٰعِدۡ بَیۡنَ  اَسۡفَارِنَا» (34/19).  \nTranslation: So they said: Our Lord, increase the distance between our journeys.","«بَاعَدَ» to increase and lengthen the distance between two things.","Eternal","باعد","34:19",1
1448,318,"D","تَصَدّٰی","«تَصَدّٰی» means to pursue something like an echo. To pay attention (intransitive). (An echo is the sound that returns after hitting a mountain or dome, etc.)\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «اَمَّا مَنِ اسۡتَغۡنٰی فَاَنۡتَ  لَہٗ  تَصَدّٰی» (80:5-6) Translation: He who does not pay attention, you pursue him.","to pursue something temporarily or situationally.","Degrees","تصدی","80:6",1
1449,318,"S","حَفَا (حَفَو)","«حَفَا» means to insistently demand or ask for something, or to remain persistently engaged in investigation and inquiry to ascertain the state of something. (Figuratively) the word «حَفَو» is used to denote being constantly after or pursuing something.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«لَا تَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا بَغۡتَۃً ؕ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ کَاَنَّکَ حَفِیٌّ عَنۡہَا» ( 7/187 )\nTranslation: The Hour will come upon you suddenly. These people ask you (O Prophet) about it as if you were persistently pursuing its knowledge (i.e., you are constantly after it).\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«سَاَسۡتَغۡفِرُ  لَکَ  رَبِّیۡ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  بِیۡ  حَفِیًّا» ( 19/47 )\nTranslation: (Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) said to his father) I will seek forgiveness for you from my Lord. Indeed, He is to me Most Kind.\n\nIn this verse, the original meaning of «حَفِیًّا» is One who is vigilant and attentive moment by moment, which is concisely translated as Most Kind or Ever-Merciful.","comes continuously in pursuit of something or to follow behind.","study cells","حفا ( حفو )","7:187-19:47-47:37",3
1450,319,"T","شَجَرَۃ ، شَجَر","«شَجَرَۃٌ» means a tree; its plural is «شَجَرْ». The term «شَجَرَۃٌ» can be applied to any plant that has a stem (whether it grows tall or spreads on the ground). Thus, the word «شَجَرَۃٌ» is general in meaning.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتُمُ النَّارَ الَّتِیۡ تُوۡرُوۡنَ ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَنۡشَاۡتُمۡ شَجَرَتَہَاۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الۡمُنۡشِئُوۡنَ» (56:71,72)\nTranslation: So have you considered the fire which you kindle? Is it you who have produced the tree thereof, or are We the producer?","«شَجَرَۃ» is common. It is applicable to all kinds of plants and trees that are woody.","tree","شجرۃ ، شجر","2:35-7:19-7:20-7:22-14:24-14:26-16:10-16:68-17:60-20:120-22:18-23:20-24:35-27:60-28:30-31:27-36:80-37:62-37:64-37:146-44:43-48:18-55:6-56:52-56:72",25
1451,319,"T","نَجْم","«نَجْم» also means 'star' and also means 'plants without stems,' i.e., rooted plants, etc. (mufrad). For example, in the Noble Quran: «وَّ النَّجۡمُ وَ الشَّجَرُ  یَسۡجُدٰنِ» (55/6). Translation: And the plants and trees are prostrating to Him (Allah).","«نَجْم» Trunkless trees, plants, and rooted shrubs.","tree","نجم","6:97-7:54-16:12-16:16-22:18-37:88-52:49-53:1-55:6-56:75-77:8-81:2-86:3",13
1452,319,"T","اَثْل","«اَثَلَ» means to take root in the earth. And «اَثْل» refers to every tree whose root is strong. Generally, this term is applied to the jhau tree (as cited in Maqayis al-Lughah and Lisan al-Arab). For example, the Quran states: «وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ  اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» (34:16). Translation: And We replaced both of their gardens with two other gardens, bearing bitter fruit and containing some jhau trees and a few berry bushes.","«اَثْل» plants with firm roots and a tree with spreading branches.","tree","اثل","34:16",1
1453,319,"T","یَقْطِیْن","«یَقْطِیْن» meaning every tree that has no trunk. (sing.) It is generally applied to climbing plants and specifically to the gourd plant. (Quranic) For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَ اَنۡۢبَتۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ شَجَرَۃً مِّنۡ یَّقۡطِیۡنٍ» (37/146) Translation: And We caused a gourd plant to grow over him (Prophet Jonah, peace be upon him).","«یَقْطِیْن» that plant which has no stem, such as the vines of cucumber, pumpkin, bottle gourd, etc.","tree","یقطین","37:146",1
1454,319,"T","ضَرِیْع","«ضَرِیْع» meaning thorny shrub or prickly bush (fem.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لَیۡسَ لَہُمۡ طَعَامٌ   اِلَّا مِنۡ ضَرِیۡعٍ» (88/6)\nTranslation: And they will have no food except from a thorny shrub.","«ضَرِیْع» thorny bushes.","Tree","ضریع","88:6",1
1455,319,"T","زَقُّوْم","«زَقُّوْم» refers to the Zaqqum tree, whose leaves are broad, thick, and thorny, and whose taste is extremely bitter.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  شَجَرَتَ الزَّقُّوۡمِ طَعَامُ  الۡاَثِیۡمِ» (44:43-44)\nTranslation: Indeed, the Zaqqum tree is the food of the sinners.","«زَقُّوْم» denotes a tree with broad, thick, and thorny leaves, and an intensely bitter taste.","tree","زقوم","37:62-44:43-56:52",3
1456,320,"C","صَوَاب","«صَوَاب» means correct, right, appropriate. (Lexically) its opposite is «خَطَا». And «صَابَ واَصَابَ السَّھْم» means an arrow hitting the right target. And «اِسْتِصْوَاب» means to find the correct opinion or action; to think correctly. And «صَوَیْب» and «مُصِیْب» mean having the right opinion; correct doer (lexically). And if an arrow hits the right target and stays there, it is called «مُصِیْبَۃٌ», which is applied to every painful accident (elaborated). «صَوَاب» generally relates to speech and opinion, and sometimes to action as well.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «لَّا یَتَکَلَّمُوۡنَ  اِلَّا مَنۡ اَذِنَ لَہُ الرَّحۡمٰنُ وَ  قَالَ صَوَابًا» (78/38). Translation: No person can speak except with the permission of Allah, the Most High, and he has spoken correctly.","«صَوَاب» refers to correctness that is connected to a person's statement or opinion, whereas truth is every thing or matter that is proven correct through experience and observation.","Correct","صواب","78:38",1
1457,320,"C","حَقّ","«حَقّ» meaning truth, veracity, reality, correct — i.e., every matter or thing that is proven correct after experience and observation. (adj.) Its opposite is «باطل».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» ( 41/53 )\nTranslation: We will soon show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that this [revelation or Quran] is entirely true.","«حَقّ» is used for truth, honesty.","Correct","حق","2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3",252
1458,320,"C","اَصْلَحَ","«اِصْلَاح» is the opposite of «فَسَاد», meaning corruption. And «اَصْلَحَ» means to correct corruption, to remove chaos and disorder, and to fix any corruption arising from excess or deficiency in something.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ اُرِیۡدُ اِلَّا الۡاِصۡلَاحَ مَا  اسۡتَطَعۡتُ» (11/88)\nTranslation: (Prophet Shu'aib, peace be upon him, said to his people) I only desire, as far as I am able, to reform your affairs.","«اَصْلَحَ» is used to correct moral and material corruption, and «سَوّٰی» is used to correct creative corruption.","Correct","اصلح","2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10",40
1459,320,"C","سَوّٰی","The meaning of «سَوٰی یَسْوِی» is the correct form or shape of something. And «سَوّٰی» means to correct, smooth, equalize, and straighten a matter or thing (as per Munjid). According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is «اَلْاِسْتِقَامَۃ وَالْاِعْتِدَال», which conveys exactly the same concept.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ فَسَوّٰی» (87:2)\nTranslation: Who created man and then proportioned him.","«سَوّٰی» means to correct, level, equalize, and straighten a task or object.","Correct","سوی","4:42-15:29-19:10-19:17-19:43-20:58-20:135-26:98-38:72-67:22-75:4-75:38-87:2",13
1460,321,"B","بَیْن","This word is a particle that indicates separation or distinction between two different things. And «بَانَ» means to be distant. Therefore, «بَیْن» is used for distance or separation between two things. According to Ibn al-Faris, three elements are found in «بَیْن»: (1) separation, (2) distance, (3) clarity (m. l), i.e., something being distinct and clear from another.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«بَیۡنَ السَّمَآءِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (2/164)\nTranslation: between the heavens and the earth.\n\nThen this word is used not only in a physical sense but also in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The divine command is:\n«فَاحۡکُمۡ  بَیۡنَنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (38/22)\nTranslation: Judge between us with truth!","This term is a letter that indicates separation or distinction between two different things.","between","بین","2:68-2:102-2:113-2:136-2:164-2:182-2:188-2:213-2:224-2:232-2:237-2:282-2:285-3:19-3:23-3:30-3:55-3:64-3:84-3:103-3:140-4:23-4:29-4:35-4:58-4:65-4:73-4:90-4:92-4:105-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:141-4:143-4:150-4:152-5:14-5:17-5:18-5:25-5:42-5:48-5:49-5:64-5:91-5:106-6:19-6:53-6:58-6:94-7:44-7:46-7:87-7:89-8:1-8:24-8:63-8:72-9:107-10:19-10:28-10:29-10:45-10:47-10:54-10:93-11:43-11:110-12:100-13:43-15:85-16:66-16:92-16:94-16:124-17:45-17:53-17:96-17:110-18:19-18:21-18:32-18:52-18:61-18:78-18:93-18:94-18:95-18:96-19:37-19:64-19:65-20:6-20:58-20:62-20:94-20:103-21:16-21:93-22:17-22:56-22:69-23:53-23:101-24:43-24:48-24:51-24:63-25:38-25:50-25:53-25:59-25:67-26:24-26:28-26:118-27:61-27:78-28:28-29:25-29:52-30:8-30:21-32:4-32:25-34:18-34:19-34:26-34:54-37:5-37:158-38:8-38:10-38:22-38:26-38:27-38:66-39:3-39:46-39:69-39:75-40:48-41:5-41:34-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:21-42:38-43:32-43:38-43:52-43:65-43:85-44:7-44:38-45:17-46:3-46:8-48:29-49:9-49:10-50:38-54:25-54:28-55:20-55:44-56:60-57:13-57:20-59:7-59:14-60:3-60:4-60:7-60:10-65:6-65:12-78:37-86:7",181
1461,321,"B","خِلٰل","«خِلٰل» refers to the space between two such things that are connected to each other. «اَلْخِلَال» also denotes the practice of cleaning the space between the teeth, as well as the act of cleaning that space itself. Similarly, during ablution, water is passed through the spaces between the fingers of the hand or the strands of the beard.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ  فَجَّرۡنَا خِلٰلَہُمَا نَہَرًا» (18/33)\nTranslation: And We placed a flowing river between the two gardens.\n\nThen this word is also used for the space between the separate parts of a single thing.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡوَدۡقَ یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡ خِلٰلِہٖ» (24/43)\nTranslation: Then you see rain droplets emerging from within it (the cloud).","«خِلٰل» refers to different components of a single entity or two such entities that share a mutual relationship.","Between","خلل","9:47-14:31-17:5-17:91-18:33-24:43-27:61-30:48",8
1462,321,"B","وَسْط","The midpoint of any entity, where the distance to both its sides is equal (literal), or if there are more items, then equal in number from both sides. Essentially, the point of balance between deficiency and excess is termed the middle. This term is then used in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: Protect the prayers, especially the middle prayer.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command is:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ اُمَّۃً وَّسَطًا» (2/143)\nTranslation: And thus we have made you a moderate nation.","the middle of something in terms of number, quantity, or distance","between","وسط","2:143-2:238",2
1463,321,"M","سَوَآء","«سَوَاء» Midst, central point. The exact middle of something that has length, width, and depth from all sides. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is steadfastness and balance between the two things. (M. L)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» ( 44/47 )\nTranslation: (It will be commanded,) Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.","«سَوَاء» the central point from every perspective.","Middle","سوآء","2:6-2:29-2:108-3:64-3:113-4:89-5:12-5:60-5:77-7:193-8:58-13:10-14:21-16:71-18:37-21:109-22:25-26:136-28:22-30:28-32:9-36:10-37:55-38:22-41:10-44:47-45:21-52:16-60:1-63:6-79:28-82:7-91:7-91:14",34
1464,321,"A","قَصْد","«قَصْد» means moderation. It is the path or way that lies between excess and deficiency—neither too much nor too little. For instance, generosity between extravagance and stinginess, or courage between recklessness and cowardice. And «قَصَدَ» and «اِقْتَصَدَ فِی الْنَفَقَۃ» mean to spend in moderation, avoiding both excess and deficiency (extremes or shortage) in expenditure. And «قَصَدَ السَّبِیْل» means to proceed straight on the path, not deviating to either side. (Abbr. Maf. Manjd)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ» (31:19)\nTranslation: And moderate your pace and lower your voice.","«قَصْد» the path of moderation, the middle way.","amidst","قصد","9:42-16:9-31:19",3
1465,322,"E","عَدُوّ","Its plural is «اَعْدَاء». An enemy who is malicious and nurtures hatred. One who contemplates evil and harm and takes pleasure in others' suffering. And its opposite is «صِدِّیْق» (f. l. 168).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ الشَّیۡطٰنَ لَکُمَا عَدُوٌّ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7:22)\nTranslation: Indeed, Satan is your open enemy, both of you (Adam and Eve)!\n\nAnd «عَدَاوَۃٌ» means enmity and ill-will. This constitutes the first degree of enmity. (f. l. 169) It also signifies retreating with the support of another. Its opposite is wilayah. (f. l. 106)","«عَدُوّ» meaning enemy.","enemy","عدو","2:36-2:97-2:98-2:168-2:208-3:103-4:45-4:92-4:101-5:14-5:64-5:82-5:91-6:112-6:142-7:22-7:24-7:129-7:150-8:60-9:83-9:114-9:120-12:5-17:53-18:50-20:39-20:80-20:117-20:123-25:31-26:77-28:8-28:15-28:19-35:6-36:60-41:19-41:28-41:34-43:62-43:67-46:6-60:1-60:2-60:4-61:14-63:4-64:14",49
1466,322,"E","بَغْضَاء","«بُغْض» means to detest something or someone. This is the second degree of enmity, and its opposite is «حُبّ». And «بُغْضَۃٌ» means intending to degrade or humiliate someone (Faqih 106).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (5/64)\nTranslation: And We have cast between them enmity and hatred until the Day of Resurrection.","«بَغْضَاء» meaning to detest something or someone.","enemy","بغضاء","3:118-5:14-5:64-5:91-60:4",5
1467,322,"E","شَانِیءَ","«شَنَأَ» means to bear enmity, to hold malice, to hate (as in the root word «شَنَأٰن»).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ لَا  یَجۡرِمَنَّکُمۡ شَنَاٰنُ قَوۡمٍ عَلٰۤی اَلَّا تَعۡدِلُوۡا» (5:8)  \nTranslation: Let not the hatred of a people prevent you from being just.  \n\nAnd «شَانِیء» refers to a person who is both malevolent (ill-wishing) and spiteful (envying). That is, one who bears both enmity and envy—the worst kind of enemy. This is the third degree of enmity. (F. L. 169)  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ» (108:3)  \nTranslation: Indeed, your enemy will be childless.","«شَانِیءَ» meaning to harbor enmity.","enemy","شانیء","5:2-5:8-108:3",3
1468,323,"S","دَعَا ( دعو )","The meaning of «دُعَاء» is to call or summon. However, this word is used in both meanings: to supplicate (make dua) and to curse. The difference is only that if its complement is «لَ», it comes in the meaning of supplication or a good prayer; and if it is «عَلٰی», it gives the meaning of cursing. For example, «دَعًا لَہٗ» means he supplicated for him (a good prayer). And «دَعَا عَلَیْہ» means he cursed him. (The use of this word for cursing is not found in the Quran).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ قُلۡتُمۡ یٰمُوۡسٰی لَنۡ نَّصۡبِرَ عَلٰی طَعَامٍ وَّاحِدٍ فَادۡعُ لَنَا رَبَّکَ یُخۡرِجۡ لَنَا مِمَّا تُنۡۢبِتُ الۡاَرۡضُ» (2/61)\nTranslation: And when you said, O Moses! We will never endure one [kind of] food. So call upon your Lord to bring forth for us from what the earth grows of its herbs, its cucumbers, its garlic, its lentils, and its onions.","«دُعَاء» is common for all kinds of supplication.","Supplication","دعا ( دعو )","2:23-2:61-2:68-2:69-2:70-2:171-2:186-2:221-2:260-2:282-3:23-3:38-3:61-3:104-3:153-4:117-6:40-6:41-6:52-6:56-6:63-6:71-6:108-7:5-7:29-7:37-7:55-7:56-7:134-7:180-7:189-7:193-7:194-7:195-7:197-7:198-8:24-10:10-10:12-10:22-10:25-10:38-10:66-10:89-10:106-11:13-11:62-11:101-12:33-12:108-13:14-13:36-14:9-14:10-14:22-14:39-14:40-14:44-16:20-16:86-16:125-17:11-17:52-17:56-17:57-17:67-17:71-17:110-18:14-18:28-18:52-18:57-19:4-19:48-21:15-21:45-21:90-22:12-22:13-22:62-22:67-22:73-23:73-23:117-24:48-24:51-24:63-25:13-25:14-25:68-25:77-26:72-26:213-27:62-27:80-28:25-28:41-28:64-28:87-28:88-29:42-29:65-30:25-30:33-30:52-31:21-31:30-31:32-32:16-33:5-33:53-34:22-35:6-35:13-35:14-35:18-35:40-37:125-38:51-39:8-39:38-39:49-40:10-40:12-40:14-40:20-40:26-40:41-40:42-40:43-40:49-40:50-40:60-40:65-40:66-40:74-41:5-41:33-41:48-41:49-41:51-42:13-42:15-43:49-43:86-44:22-44:55-45:28-46:4-46:5-47:35-47:38-48:16-52:28-54:6-54:10-57:8-61:7-68:42-68:43-70:17-71:5-71:6-71:7-71:8-72:18-72:19-72:20-84:11-96:17-96:18",171
1469,323,"S","سَلَّمَ","«سَلّم» also means to keep safe and to protect, to entrust, and to pray for safety. Then to say As-salamu alaykum.  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَاِذَا دَخَلۡتُمۡ بُیُوۡتًا فَسَلِّمُوۡا عَلٰۤی اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ» (24/61)  \nTranslation: And when you enter houses, greet your families with a greeting.","«سَلّم» to greet, send greetings, and pray for safety.","Supplication","سلم","4:94-5:14-6:54-7:46-8:43-10:10-11:48-11:69-13:24-14:23-15:46-15:52-16:32-19:15-19:33-19:47-19:62-20:47-21:69-24:27-24:61-25:63-25:75-27:59-28:55-33:44-33:56-33:58-37:79-37:109-37:120-37:130-37:181-39:73-43:89-50:34-51:25-56:26-56:91-97:5",40
1470,323,"S","حَیَّیَ","«حَیَّ» means to live. And «حَیَّیَ , تَحِیَّۃً » means to say to someone «حَیَّاکَ اللہ». That is, May Allah the Exalted prolong your life. Then the use of this word is general for all kinds of good supplications and for prayers of safety. It also occurs in the meanings of «سَلَّم» or «سَلَام». Thus, «سَلَّم» is specific, and «حَیَّ» is general (Faqih: 44). For example: In the Noble Quran it is: «وَ اِذَا حُیِّیۡتُمۡ بِتَحِیَّۃٍ فَحَیُّوۡا بِاَحۡسَنَ مِنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ رُدُّوۡہَا» (4/86). Translation: And when you are greeted with a greeting, greet in return with a better one or at least an equal one.","«حَیَّیَ» To supplicate for longevity.","Supplication","حیی","4:86",1
1471,323,"S","صَلّ ( صَلُّو )","«صلٰوۃ» is a religious term (specific word) whose meaning is prayer, which is a fundamental pillar of Islam, but its original meaning is to supplicate, to define, to praise, and to glorify. (e.g.)\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ صَلِّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ؕ اِنَّ صَلٰوتَکَ سَکَنٌ لَّہُمۡ» ( 9/103 )\nTranslation: And pray for their well-being, for your prayer is a source of comfort for them.\nAnd regarding «صَلّ», if it is from Allah Almighty, it refers to the descent of mercy, and if it is from a servant, it refers to the supplication for the descent of mercy.\nFor instance: The command of Allah Almighty is:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ وَ مَلٰٓئِکَتَہٗ  یُصَلُّوۡنَ عَلَی النَّبِیِّ ؕ یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا صَلُّوۡا عَلَیۡہِ  وَ سَلِّمُوۡا  تَسۡلِیۡمًا» ( 33/56 )\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah and His angels send blessings upon the Prophet. O you who have believed, you should also send blessings upon him and greet him with peace. (Uthmani)","«صَلّ» Invoking blessings (upon the Prophet). Sending salutations.","Supplication","صل ( صلو )","2:157-9:99-9:103-33:43-33:56",5
1472,324,"H","قَلْب","«قَلْب» meaning (heart) is a well-known organ. The source and center of soul and life, its plural is «قُلُوب». For intellect, understanding, thought, and reflection, Allah the Almighty has chosen the heart. That is, what modern medicine has attributed to the brain, the Quran has attributed to the heart.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَہُمۡ قُلُوۡبٌ لَّا یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ بِہَا» (7/179)\nTranslation: They have hearts, but they do not strive to understand with them.","«قَلْب» meaning (the heart), the source, wellspring, and center of intellect, understanding, and reflection—that is, the heart.","heart","قلب","2:7-2:10-2:74-2:88-2:93-2:97-2:118-2:204-2:225-2:260-2:283-3:7-3:8-3:103-3:126-3:151-3:154-3:156-3:159-3:167-4:63-4:155-5:13-5:41-5:52-5:113-6:25-6:43-6:46-7:100-7:101-7:179-8:2-8:10-8:11-8:12-8:24-8:49-8:63-8:70-9:8-9:15-9:45-9:60-9:64-9:77-9:87-9:93-9:110-9:117-9:125-9:127-10:74-10:88-13:28-15:12-16:22-16:106-16:108-17:46-18:14-18:28-18:57-21:3-22:32-22:35-22:46-22:53-22:54-23:60-23:63-24:37-24:50-26:89-26:194-26:200-28:10-30:59-33:4-33:5-33:10-33:12-33:26-33:32-33:51-33:53-33:60-34:23-37:84-39:22-39:23-39:45-40:18-40:35-41:5-42:24-45:23-47:16-47:20-47:24-47:29-48:4-48:11-48:12-48:18-48:26-49:3-49:7-49:14-50:33-50:37-57:16-57:27-58:22-59:2-59:10-59:14-61:5-63:3-64:11-66:4-74:31-79:8-83:14",124
1473,324,"H","فُؤَاد","Some scholars have stated that the distinction between «عَیْن» and «بَصَر» or between «اُذُن» and «سَمَع» is the same as the distinction between «قَلْب» and «فُؤَاد». As evidence for this, the following verse is cited, for example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ السَّمۡعَ وَ الۡبَصَرَ وَ الۡفُؤَادَ  کُلُّ  اُولٰٓئِکَ کَانَ  عَنۡہُ  مَسۡئُوۡلًا» (17:36)\nTranslation: Be sure that you will be questioned about your ears, eyes, and hearts.\n\nHowever, this is not the reality because Allah the Exalted has directly addressed the heart for the purpose of intellect, understanding, consciousness, and contemplation. The fact is that this organ, the heart, has multiple parts. Just as different parts of the brain house different faculties, similarly, specific parts of the heart are specialized for specific actions and emotions. According to medical science, «فؤاد» refers to the upper part of the heart that lies opposite the stomach.\n\nThe plural form «اَفْئِدَۃ ، فأد» is derived from «فُؤَاد». «فَأدُ الْلَحَم» means to roast meat on fire, and «لَحْمٌ فَئِیْدٌ» means meat roasted on fire. In the words of Ibn Faris, «اَلْفَأْدُ یَدُلُّ عَلٰی حَمًّی وَّشِدَّۃُ الْحَرَارَۃ ( م ل )» indicates heat and intense movement. Therefore, wherever the intensity of human emotions and their impact are mentioned, this term will be used.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ  اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا» (28:10)\nTranslation: And the heart of Moses' mother became empty [of all patience and resolve].\n\nAt another instance, the Divine decree states:\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ ۚ وَ اَفۡئِدَتُہُمۡ  ہَوَآءٌ» (14:43)\nTranslation: They will hurry forward with raised heads, their gazes not returning to them, and their hearts [will be] in the air [i.e., terrified and scattered].\n\nAnd the accountability that Allah the Exalted has mentioned regarding «فواد» will pertain to those very actions which a human commits under the intensity of emotions.","«فُؤَاد» the focal point of emotional intensity.","heart","فؤاد","11:120-17:36-25:32-28:10-53:11",5
1474,324,"H","صَدْر","«صَدْر» means 'chest', and its plural is «صُدُوْر». And the heart is located within the chest.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ لٰکِنۡ  تَعۡمَی الۡقُلُوۡبُ الَّتِیۡ فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (22/46). Translation: But those hearts become blind which are within the chests.\n\nTherefore, sometimes only «فِی الصُّدُوْر» is used to mean hearts (qulub), as in شِفَآءٌ لِّمَا فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ (10/57).\n\nNow since «صَدْر» is related to the container of space, therefore if the mention of the constriction or expansion of the heart is intended, then the word «صدر» will be used.\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states: «وَ لَقَدۡ نَعۡلَمُ اَنَّکَ یَضِیۡقُ صَدۡرُکَ بِمَا یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ» (15/97). Translation: And We know that your heart is constrained by what they say.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states: «اَلَمۡ نَشۡرَحۡ  لَکَ صَدۡرَکَ» (94/1). Translation: Did We not expand for you your chest?\n\nAnd «شرح صدر» or «انشراح صدر» is an idiom. When in some difficult and complex matter, a path of correctness (right thing) occurs in the heart, it is called «شرح صدر».\n\nThen for hiding something as well, since a container is required, therefore in the mention of concealing a secret, thoughts, and whispers, «صدر» will also be used. For example, the Noble Quran states: «یَعۡلَمُ خَآئِنَۃَ  الۡاَعۡیُنِ وَ مَا تُخۡفِی الصُّدُوۡرُ» (40/19). Translation: He knows the betrayal of the eyes, and what the hearts conceal.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states: «اِنَّ  اللّٰہَ عَلِیۡمٌۢ  بِذَاتِ الصُّدُوۡرِ» (5/7). Translation: Indeed, Allah is aware of what the hearts conceal.\n\nAt yet another instance, the Divine Command states: «الَّذِیۡ یُوَسۡوِسُ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ النَّاسِ» (114/5). Translation: He (Satan) casts evil suggestions into the hearts of people.","meaning chest","Heart","صدر","3:29-3:118-3:119-3:154-4:90-5:7-6:125-7:2-7:43-8:43-9:14-10:57-11:5-11:12-15:47-15:97-16:106-17:51-20:25-22:46-26:13-27:74-28:69-29:10-29:49-31:23-35:38-39:7-39:22-40:19-40:56-40:80-42:24-57:6-59:9-59:13-64:4-67:13-94:1-100:10-114:5",41
1475,324,"H","نَفْس","«نَفْس» spirit, life, soul, self—its plural is «نُفُوس». From it originates the source (starting point) of desires and the place of refuge. The heart that desires and rejoices is what is intended:\nAs far as concealing hidden matters and thoughts is concerned, this attribute is shared between «نُفُوس» and «صُدُوْر».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تُخۡفِیۡ فِیۡ نَفۡسِکَ مَا اللّٰہُ مُبۡدِیۡہِ» (33:37)\nTranslation: And you used to conceal in your hearts that which Allah was going to reveal.\nDesires are connected to the self (nafs), whether good or bad.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنۡ یَّتَّبِعُوۡنَ  اِلَّا الظَّنَّ وَ مَا تَہۡوَی الۡاَنۡفُسُ» (53:23)\nTranslation: These people are merely following conjectures and the desires of their own (evil) selves.\nHappiness is also connected to «نفس».\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4:4)\nTranslation: Then if they (the wives) remit any part of it to you of their own accord, you may accept it with pleasure and enjoyment.","«نَفْس» is the center of desires. It is used for happiness and concealing speech.","Heart","نفس","2:9-2:44-2:48-2:54-2:57-2:72-2:84-2:85-2:87-2:90-2:102-2:109-2:110-2:123-2:130-2:155-2:187-2:207-2:223-2:228-2:231-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:240-2:265-2:272-2:281-2:284-2:286-3:25-3:28-3:30-3:61-3:69-3:93-3:117-3:135-3:145-3:154-3:161-3:164-3:165-3:168-3:178-3:185-3:186-4:1-4:4-4:29-4:49-4:63-4:64-4:65-4:66-4:79-4:84-4:95-4:97-4:107-4:110-4:111-4:113-4:128-4:135-5:25-5:30-5:32-5:45-5:52-5:70-5:80-5:105-5:116-6:12-6:20-6:24-6:26-6:54-6:70-6:93-6:98-6:104-6:123-6:130-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:164-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:42-7:53-7:160-7:172-7:177-7:188-7:189-7:192-7:197-7:205-8:53-8:72-9:17-9:20-9:35-9:36-9:41-9:42-9:44-9:55-9:70-9:81-9:85-9:88-9:111-9:118-9:120-9:128-10:15-10:23-10:30-10:44-10:49-10:54-10:100-10:108-11:21-11:31-11:101-11:105-12:18-12:23-12:26-12:30-12:32-12:51-12:53-12:54-12:68-12:77-12:83-13:11-13:16-13:33-13:42-14:22-14:45-14:51-16:7-16:28-16:33-16:72-16:89-16:111-16:118-17:7-17:14-17:15-17:25-17:33-18:6-18:28-18:35-18:51-18:74-20:15-20:40-20:41-20:67-20:96-21:35-21:43-21:47-21:64-21:102-23:62-23:103-24:6-24:12-24:61-25:3-25:21-25:68-26:3-27:14-27:40-27:44-27:92-28:16-28:19-28:33-29:6-29:40-29:57-30:8-30:9-30:21-30:28-30:44-31:12-31:28-31:34-32:13-32:17-32:27-33:6-33:37-33:50-34:19-34:50-35:8-35:18-35:32-36:36-36:54-37:113-39:6-39:15-39:41-39:42-39:53-39:56-39:70-40:10-40:17-41:31-41:46-41:53-42:11-42:45-43:71-45:15-45:22-47:38-48:10-49:11-49:15-50:16-50:21-51:21-53:23-53:32-57:14-57:22-58:8-59:9-59:18-59:19-61:11-63:11-64:16-65:1-65:7-66:6-73:20-74:38-75:2-75:14-79:40-81:7-81:14-82:5-82:19-86:4-89:27-91:7",268
1476,324,"H","وَحْیٌ","The literal meaning of «وَحْیٌ» is merely 'hidden' and a swift indication. And «اَوْحٰی» means to swiftly indicate something hidden and unknown (abbr. m. l). Then there are several types of revelation. One type is that which relates to matters of conquest or subjugation. For example: The Noble Quran states: «وَ اَوۡحٰی فِیۡ کُلِّ سَمَآءٍ  اَمۡرَہَا» (41:12). Translation: Allah has revealed concerning it in every heaven.\n\nNatural guidance is also termed as revelation, such as a newborn baby instinctively turning towards its mother's breast. For example: The divine command states: «وَ اَوۡحٰی رَبُّکَ اِلَی النَّحۡلِ» (16:68). Translation: And your Lord inspired the honeybee.\n\nThus, revelation from Allah can occur upon inanimate objects, animals, and humans alike. And such revelation can also occur for a non-prophet. For example: The Noble Quran states: «وَ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی اُمِّ مُوۡسٰۤی اَنۡ  اَرۡضِعِیۡہِ» (28:7). Translation: And We inspired the mother of Moses.\n\nIn all these examples, the word 'revelation' is used in its literal sense. Furthermore, a human can also 'reveal' to another human in this sense. For example: The divine command states: «فَاَوۡحٰۤی  اِلَیۡہِمۡ اَنۡ سَبِّحُوۡا بُکۡرَۃً وَّ عَشِیًّا» (19:11). Translation: So Zakariya signaled to his people: 'Glorify Allah morning and evening.'\n\nEven Satan inspires such revelation to another. For example: The Noble Quran states: «وَ  اِنَّ الشَّیٰطِیۡنَ لَیُوۡحُوۡنَ اِلٰۤی اَوۡلِیٰٓئِہِمۡ لِیُجَادِلُوۡکُمۡ» (6:121). Translation: And Satan inspires his allies to dispute with you.\n\nThus, revelation can be Rahman (Allah's) and it can also be Shaytani (Satanic). Rahman revelation is always based on goodness, and any revelation that opposes Rahman revelation is Shaytani. In the terminology of Shariah, 'revelation' refers to that knowledge, commands, and news of the unseen which Allah sends to one of His chosen humans (a Prophet) for the guidance of the general people. Three forms of this are mentioned in the Noble Quran: (1) Allah directly places the thought in the heart, (2) He sends an angel to the Prophet, and (3) He speaks from behind a veil (as He did with Moses). However, the most common and general method is that Allah, through Jibril, places His message upon the hearts of the Prophets and Messengers, which then is conveyed through the Prophet's tongue. For example: The Noble Quran states: «قُلۡ مَنۡ کَانَ عَدُوًّا لِّجِبۡرِیۡلَ فَاِنَّہٗ نَزَّلَہٗ عَلٰی قَلۡبِکَ بِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (2:97). Translation: Say, 'Whoever is an enemy to Jibril—then indeed he has brought it down upon your heart by Allah's permission.'","«وحی ، اِلْھَام» and «اِلْقَاء» can also be from Allah, and they can also be from Satan, whereas «وَسْوَسَہ» and «ھَمْز» are solely from Satan.  \nRevelation (وحی) pertains to teachings, beliefs, rulings, and matters of the unseen. Inspiration (الہام) pertains solely to the doing or not doing of an action, and «اِلْقَاء» pertains solely to teaching.  \n«وَسْوَسَہ» refers only to the arrival of evil thoughts in the heart, whereas «ھَمَزَ» includes, along with evil thoughts, the incitement and urging from Satan.  \nEvery revelation, inspiration, or casting that conforms to the sacred texts is Rahmanī (from the Most Merciful), and if it does not conform, then it is Shayṭānī (from Satan).","Heart","وحی","3:44-4:163-5:111-6:19-6:50-6:93-6:106-6:112-6:121-6:145-7:117-7:160-7:203-8:12-10:2-10:15-10:87-10:109-11:12-11:36-11:37-11:49-12:3-12:15-12:102-12:109-13:30-14:13-16:43-16:68-16:123-17:39-17:73-17:86-18:27-18:110-19:11-20:13-20:38-20:48-20:77-20:114-21:7-21:25-21:45-21:73-21:108-23:27-26:52-26:63-28:7-29:45-33:2-34:50-35:31-38:70-39:65-41:6-41:12-42:3-42:7-42:13-42:51-42:52-43:43-46:9-53:4-53:10-72:1-99:5",70
1477,324,"H","اِلْھَام","«اِلْھَام» That which Allah, the Most High, casts into the heart of someone (meaning: understanding and insight granted). Bestowing success (manjood). Inspiration (ilham) can also be satanic, especially when it cannot be substantiated by any Quranic verse or legal text. Therefore, according to scholars (other than the Sufi class), inspiration is not considered a valid proof (m. m). The difference between revelation (wahy) and inspiration (ilham) is that inspiration is specific to those of sound intellect, whereas revelation is general. Secondly, inspiration relates to performing or refraining from a specific action, while the scope of revelation is much broader (m. m).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَلۡہَمَہَا فُجُوۡرَہَا وَ تَقۡوٰىہَا» (91:8)\nTranslation: Then He granted it (the soul) understanding of evil (to avoid) and piety (to adopt).","In common understanding, «اِلْھَام» refers to that which is cast into the heart by Allah.","Heart","الھام","91:8",1
1478,324,"H","اِلْقَاء","The literal meaning of «اِلْقَاء» is merely 'to cast'. And «اَلْقٰی عَلٰی» means 'to teach' (m. m).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ءَاُلۡقِیَ الذِّکۡرُ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡۢ  بَیۡنِنَا» (54/25)\nTranslation: Was it that this (Prophet) alone among us was to receive the admonition?\nAnd «تَلَقّٰی الشَّیْء مِنْہُ» means 'to learn', 'to acquire knowledge' (manjad).\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«فَتَلَقّٰۤی اٰدَمُ مِنۡ رَّبِّہٖ کَلِمٰتٍ» (2/37)\nTranslation: Then Adam learned some words from his Lord.\nThus, «اِلْقَاء» refers specifically to something cast into the heart that pertains to teaching and learning. Just as there is revelation and inspiration, there can also be satanic suggestion.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَیَنۡسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلۡقِی الشَّیۡطٰنُ» (22/52)\nTranslation: Then Allah removes the suggestion of Satan.","The literal meaning of «اِلْقَاء» is only to throw/pour.","Heart","القاء","2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4",66
1479,324,"H","وَسْوَاس","«وَسْوَاس» From a medical perspective, it is a disease that impairs the mind due to overwhelming madness, causing a person to utter idle talk that was neither in their heart before nor contains any goodness (m. m). And «وِسْوَاس» means the illness of delusion; evil or useless talk that enters the heart; and also means Satan inciting towards evil and continuously casting evil thoughts (muf). It also refers to the initial stage of insanity (f l 135). Thus, a whisper is every evil thought that arises in the heart or is cast by Satan, and its attribution is solely to Satan.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مِنۡ  شَرِّ الۡوَسۡوَاسِ ۙ  الۡخَنَّاسِ الَّذِیۡ یُوَسۡوِسُ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ النَّاسِ» (114/4,5)\nTranslation: (Say, O Allah! I seek refuge with You from) the evil of the retreating whisperer, who whispers [evil] into the breasts of mankind.","«وَسْوَاس» Satan whispers into the hearts of mankind.","heart","وسواس","7:20-20:120-50:16-114:4-114:5",5
1480,324,"H","ھَمَزَات","«ھَمَزَ یَدُلُّ عَلٰی ضَغْطٍ وَّعَصْرٍ» (م ۔ ل) means to snap, to prick, to press, and in the context of an animal's side or flank, to prod with a pointed stick, etc., so that it moves swiftly. In fact, the Punjabi phrase چوہنبڑ دینا (to prod like a thorn) is very apt for this meaning. That is, for Satan to implant an evil thought in someone's heart and then urge them on. The attribution of this word is solely to Satan.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قُلۡ رَّبِّ اَعُوۡذُ بِکَ مِنۡ ہَمَزٰتِ الشَّیٰطِیۡنِ» ( 23/97 )\nTranslation: And say, My Lord, I seek refuge in You from the incitements of the devils.","«ھَمَزَات» Satan planting evil and filthy thoughts in the heart.","Heart","ھمزات","23:97",1
1481,325,"E","دَلِیْل","«دَلَالَت» and «دَلِیْل» mean that guidance through which one attains knowledge and recognition. For example, a person sees movement in a living being and thus knows it is alive, or written words indicate their intended meanings. In common speech too, words are a means of expressing meaning and serve as evidence for that meaning (e.g.). And «دَلَّ» means to manifest, to inform, to guide, and to serve as a means of knowledge and recognition.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَمۡ  تَرَ اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَیۡفَ مَدَّ  الظِّلَّ ۚ وَ لَوۡ شَآءَ لَجَعَلَہٗ  سَاکِنًا ۚ ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنَا الشَّمۡسَ عَلَیۡہِ  دَلِیۡلًا» ( 25/45 )\nTranslation: Have you not seen how your Lord spreads the shadow? If He willed, He could have made it stationary. Then We made the sun a proof for it.\n\nThus, the lengthening and shortening of shadows, and the proportion between them, are mutual proofs. The shortening of shadows indicates the correct direction of the sun. Similarly, it can also indicate the times. And by observing the direction of the sun, the direction and length of the shadow can be estimated.","«دَلِیْل» Obtaining guidance from one thing in order to recognize another.","Evidence","دلیل","25:45",1
1482,325,"P","حُجّۃ","«حَاجَّ» means to argue and to prevail in an argument. And «اَلْمُحَاجَّۃٌ» is when one party refutes the other's argument (refutation). And «حُجَّۃ» is the term for such an argument: when a matter is accepted (musallam) by both parties, and then one party deduces a conclusion from it and presents evidence before the other (proof). Such evidence is called «حُجّۃ». For example, the disbelievers used to acknowledge that their Creator, Owner, and Sustainer is Allah Almighty. Then Allah Almighty says: Can the one who creates a human being from a mere drop of semen, and then causes him to pass through various stages of life and finally causes him to die, not then recreate him? Such an argument is called a *hujjah* (argument/proof).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تِلۡکَ حُجَّتُنَاۤ  اٰتَیۡنٰہَاۤ  اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ عَلٰی قَوۡمِہٖ» (6:83)\nTranslation: This was Our argument which We gave to Abraham against his people.","to adduce an argument as a corollary from an admitted premise","Proof","حجۃ","2:150-4:165-6:149-6:83-42:15-42:16-45:25",7
1483,325,"P","بَیِّنَۃ","«بَیِّنَۃ» A clear and evident matter. Proof. Some explanation of «بَیِّنَۃ» is also derived from this statement of the Noble Prophet ﷺ. He said: «اَلبَیِّنَۃُ عَلَی الْمُدَّعِیْ وَالْیَمِیْنُ عَلَی الْمُدَّعٰی عَلَیْہِ» (Bukhari) Meaning: Providing proof is the responsibility of the claimant, and if he fails to do so, then the oath is upon the accused.\n\nNow consider, for example: Zaid is owed some money by Bakr, and Bakr denies it. If Zaid possesses a document from Bakr that can prove this matter or assist in proving it, then this document is «بَیِّنَۃ». Similarly, if Zaid can prove it by presenting witnesses, that too is «بَیِّنَۃ». «بَیِّنَۃ» is evidence before which the opposing party is rendered speechless. The very existence of the Noble Quran is «بَیِّنَۃ». Despite engaging in debate, the disbelievers cannot present any argument against it. Likewise, its verses are also «بَیِّنٰت».\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُوَ اٰیٰتٌۢ بَیِّنٰتٌ فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِ الَّذِیۡنَ اُوۡتُوا الۡعِلۡمَ ؕ وَ مَا یَجۡحَدُ بِاٰیٰتِنَاۤ  اِلَّا الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ» (29/49)\nTranslation: Rather, these are clear verses, preserved in the hearts of those who have been given knowledge. And none rejects Our verses except the wrongdoers.\n\nIn this verse, the word «جَحْدُ» has been brought in to point to the fact that they acknowledge in their hearts that these are clear verses, even though they deny them with their tongues.","«بَیِّنَۃ» A clear and evident proof, one that can invalidate the claim of the opposing party.","Proof","بینۃ","2:87-2:92-2:99-2:159-2:185-2:209-2:211-2:213-2:253-3:86-3:97-3:105-3:183-3:184-4:19-4:153-5:32-5:110-6:57-6:157-7:73-7:85-7:101-7:105-8:42-9:70-10:13-10:15-10:74-11:17-11:28-11:53-11:63-11:88-14:9-16:44-17:101-19:73-20:72-20:133-22:16-22:72-24:1-24:34-24:46-28:36-29:35-29:39-29:49-30:9-30:47-33:30-34:43-35:25-40:22-40:28-40:34-40:50-40:66-40:83-43:63-45:17-45:25-46:7-47:14-57:9-57:25-58:5-61:6-64:6-65:1-65:11-98:1-98:4",74
1484,325,"P","بُرْھَان","«بَرَہَ» means white and bright. And «بُرْھَان» is a proof that is also clear and establishes the truth. Its confirmation also comes from the divine speech (the Quran). And according to some, «بُرْھَان» is derived from the Persian word «بُرَّان», meaning a sword with a sharp edge that cuts. And «بُرْھَان» refers to such a proof that ends a dispute (Faqih 55).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«تِلۡکَ اَمَانِیُّہُمۡ  ؕ قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2/111)\nTranslation: These (claims) are merely their idle fancies. Say, Then bring your proof if you are truthful.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«فَذٰنِکَ بُرۡہَانٰنِ مِنۡ رَّبِّکَ اِلٰی فِرۡعَوۡنَ وَ مَلَا۠ئِہٖ» (28/32)\nTranslation: These two signs (the staff of Moses and the radiant hand) are from your Lord. Go to Pharaoh and his chiefs with them.","«بُرْھَان» is evidence that is clear and factually proven, and is also supported by the divine word.","Proof","برھان","2:111-4:174-12:24-21:24-23:117-27:64-28:32-28:75",8
1485,325,"P","سُلْطَان","«سُلْطَان» means dominance, power, and authority (manju: a royal decree or an authoritative letter). A proof that is clearly established by divine revelation. A certificate. And the plural of «سُلْطَان» is «سَلَاطِیْن», meaning 'king', and this is a metaphorical meaning, not lexical. Nor has the Quran used this word in those meanings.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَتُجَادِلُوۡنَنِیۡ فِیۡۤ  اَسۡمَآءٍ سَمَّیۡتُمُوۡہَاۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ  وَ اٰبَآؤُکُمۡ مَّا نَزَّلَ اللّٰہُ بِہَا مِنۡ سُلۡطٰنٍ» (7:71)\nTranslation: Do you then dispute with me concerning names which you have named—you and your fathers—for which Allah has sent down no authority?","«سُلْطَان» a proof clearly established by divine revelation.","Proof","سلطان","3:151-4:91-4:144-4:153-6:81-7:33-7:71-10:68-11:96-12:40-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:42-16:99-16:100-17:33-17:65-17:80-18:15-22:71-23:45-27:21-28:35-30:35-34:21-37:30-37:156-40:23-40:35-40:56-44:19-51:38-52:38-53:23-55:33-59:6-69:29",38
1486,326,"W","نَھَار","«نَھَار» means day, and its opposite «لَیْل» means night. «نَھَار» refers to the time from sunrise to sunset. The day is divided into 12 hours (or 12 gharī), whose names are as follows.\n«اَلشُّرُوْق ، بُکُوْر ، غُدْوَۃ ، ضُحٰی ، ھَاجِرَۃ ، ظَھِیْرَۃ ، رَوَاح ، عَصْرُ ، قَصْرُ ، صَیْل ، عَشِیّ ، غُرُوْب» (Fal 292)\n(The mention of night and day together appears frequently in the Noble Quran).","«نَھَار» the time from sunrise to sunset.","world","نھار","2:164-2:274-3:27-3:72-3:190-6:13-6:60-7:54-10:6-10:24-10:45-10:50-10:67-11:114-13:3-13:10-14:33-16:12-17:12-20:130-21:20-21:33-21:42-22:61-23:80-24:44-25:47-25:62-27:86-28:72-28:73-30:23-31:29-34:33-35:13-36:37-36:40-39:5-40:61-41:37-41:38-45:5-46:35-57:6-71:5-73:7-73:20-78:11-91:3-92:2",50
1487,326,"D","یَوْم","«یَوْم» means day. It refers to the time from sunset to the sunset of the following day. The total of night and daytime is 24 hours. The plural of «یَوْم» is «اَیَّام». The reckoning of time and eras is based on «ایام».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ  یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ ثَلٰثَۃِ اَیَّامٍ فِی الۡحَجِّ وَ سَبۡعَۃٍ اِذَا  رَجَعۡتُمۡ» (2/196)\nTranslation: And whoever cannot afford the sacrifice, let him fast for three days during the Hajj days and seven when he returns.\n\nThis duration of «یَوْم» is for humanity. Its concept can only be conceived after the creation of the sun and the earth; otherwise, with Allah, the duration of «یَوْم» is a long era, even if this era, according to our reckoning, extends to hundreds of thousands of years.\n\nFor example: The Command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«قُلۡ  اَئِنَّکُمۡ  لَتَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ الۡاَرۡضَ فِیۡ یَوۡمَیۡنِ» (41/9)\nTranslation: Do you then deny [the existence of] that God who created the earth in two days?\n\nSimilarly, in the context of the creation of the earth and heavens, whenever «یَوْم» is mentioned, it refers to a long era.\n\nFor example: The Command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَ اِنَّ یَوۡمًا عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ  کَاَلۡفِ  سَنَۃٍ   مِّمَّا  تَعُدُّوۡنَ» (22/47)\nTranslation: And indeed, with your Lord, a day is equivalent to a thousand years of what you count.\n\nAt another instance, the Command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«تَعۡرُجُ  الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  وَ الرُّوۡحُ  اِلَیۡہِ  فِیۡ یَوۡمٍ کَانَ مِقۡدَارُہٗ  خَمۡسِیۡنَ اَلۡفَ سَنَۃٍ» (70/4)\nTranslation: To Him ascend the angels and the Spirit in a day the extent of which is fifty thousand years.\n\nSimilarly, the Day of Judgment, meaning the day of recompense and reward, will also be based on a long era, the duration of which has been mentioned in Hadiths as fifty thousand years.","«یَوْم» the total of day and night, i.e., 24 hours.","Day","یوم","2:48-2:85-2:113-2:123-2:174-2:203-2:212-2:254-2:259-2:281-3:9-3:25-3:30-3:55-3:77-3:106-3:155-3:161-3:166-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-5:109-5:119-6:12-6:15-6:22-6:73-6:128-6:130-6:141-6:158-7:14-7:32-7:51-7:53-7:59-7:163-7:167-7:172-8:41-9:3-9:25-9:35-9:36-9:77-9:108-10:15-10:28-10:45-10:60-10:93-11:3-11:8-11:26-11:60-11:77-11:84-11:98-11:99-11:103-11:105-14:18-14:31-14:41-14:42-14:44-14:48-15:36-15:38-16:25-16:27-16:80-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:111-16:124-17:13-17:52-17:58-17:62-17:71-17:97-18:19-18:47-18:52-18:105-19:15-19:33-19:37-19:38-19:39-19:85-19:95-20:59-20:100-20:101-20:102-20:104-20:124-21:47-21:103-21:104-22:2-22:9-22:17-22:47-22:55-22:69-23:16-23:100-23:113-24:24-24:37-24:64-25:17-25:22-25:25-25:26-25:27-25:69-26:38-26:87-26:88-26:135-26:155-26:156-26:189-27:83-27:87-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:62-28:65-28:71-28:72-28:74-29:13-29:25-29:55-30:12-30:14-30:43-30:55-31:33-32:5-32:14-32:25-32:29-33:44-33:66-34:30-34:40-35:14-37:144-38:79-38:81-39:13-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-39:71-40:15-40:16-40:18-40:30-40:32-40:33-40:46-40:49-40:51-40:52-41:9-41:12-41:19-41:40-41:47-42:7-42:45-42:47-43:65-43:83-44:10-44:16-44:41-45:17-45:26-45:27-45:34-46:5-46:20-46:21-46:34-46:35-50:20-50:30-50:34-50:41-50:42-50:44-51:13-51:60-52:9-52:13-52:45-52:46-54:6-54:8-54:19-54:48-55:29-56:50-57:12-57:13-58:6-58:7-58:18-60:3-62:9-64:9-66:8-68:39-68:42-70:4-70:8-70:42-70:43-73:14-73:17-74:9-75:1-75:6-76:7-76:10-76:27-77:12-77:35-78:18-78:38-78:40-79:6-79:35-79:46-80:34-82:19-83:5-83:6-86:9-90:14-101:4",262
1488,326,"D","اَلْیَوْم","«اَلْیَوْم» meaning today. And the duration of its time will be according to «نَھَار» and not according to «یَوْم», meaning it refers to the time from sunrise to sunset (the entire day). As in the case of Pharaoh's drowning, Allah the Almighty said:\n«فَالۡیَوۡمَ نُنَجِّیۡکَ بِبَدَنِکَ  لِتَکُوۡنَ لِمَنۡ خَلۡفَکَ اٰیَۃً» (10/92)\nTranslation: So today We will save your body from the sea so that you may be a sign for those who come after you.\nAnd the word «اَلْیَوْم» has been used in the Holy Quran in many places for the Day of Judgment as well.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is said:\n«قَالَ  کَذٰلِکَ اَتَتۡکَ اٰیٰتُنَا فَنَسِیۡتَہَا ۚ  وَکَذٰلِکَ  الۡیَوۡمَ  تُنۡسٰی» (20/126)\nTranslation: Allah will say, Just as you forgot Our signs today, so will We forget you.","«اَلْیَوْم» meaning the time from sunrise to sunset today.","Day (worldly life)","الیوم","2:249-5:3-5:5-6:93-7:51-8:48-10:92-11:43-12:54-12:92-16:27-16:63-17:14-19:26-19:38-20:64-20:126-23:65-23:111-25:14-34:42-36:54-36:55-36:59-36:64-36:65-37:26-40:16-40:17-40:29-43:39-43:68-45:28-45:34-45:35-46:20-50:22-57:12-57:15-66:7-68:24-69:35-70:44-76:11-78:39-83:34-85:2",47
1489,326,"D","یَوْمَئِذٍ","It is formed by the addition of «اِذْ» after «یَوْم». It comes to indicate a specific time, meaning 'that day' or 'the day' (masc.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it appears:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ مُّسۡفِرَۃٌ ضَاحِکَۃٌ  مُّسۡتَبۡشِرَۃٌ» (80:38-39)\nTranslation: How many faces will be radiant that day, joyful and cheerful.","«یَوْمَئِذٍ» meaning that day.","Day; (in Islamic context) worldly life","یومئذٍ","3:167-4:42-6:16-7:8-8:16-11:66-14:49-16:87-18:99-18:100-20:102-20:108-20:109-22:56-23:101-24:25-25:22-25:24-25:26-27:89-28:66-30:4-30:14-30:43-30:57-37:33-40:9-42:47-43:67-45:27-52:11-55:39-69:15-69:16-69:17-69:18-70:11-74:9-75:10-75:12-75:13-75:22-75:24-75:30-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-79:8-80:37-80:38-80:40-82:19-83:10-83:15-88:2-88:8-89:23-89:25-99:4-99:6-100:11-102:8",69
1490,327,"W","دُنْیَا","«دَنٰی» meaning to be near or to be close. This word is employed in contexts of place, time, rank, and in all senses implying proximity. According to Islamic belief, there are two lives: one is the present life, which is called *nasha'ah ula* (the first creation), and the other is the life after death, which is called *nasha'ah ukhra* or *thaniyah* (the second life). Since the present life is temporally closer, it is called *dunya* (the world), and its opposite is *akhirah* (the Hereafter). This very word is generally used for the present life.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ اشۡتَرَوُا الۡحَیٰوۃَ الدُّنۡیَا بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (2/86)\nTranslation: These are the people who have purchased the life of this world in exchange for the Hereafter.","«دُنْیَا» In common parlance, we call the planet on which we live 'the world'.","World","دنیا","2:85-2:86-2:114-2:130-2:200-2:201-2:204-2:212-2:217-2:220-3:14-3:22-3:45-3:56-3:117-3:145-3:148-3:152-3:185-4:74-4:77-4:94-4:109-4:134-5:33-5:41-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:130-7:32-7:51-7:152-7:156-8:42-8:67-9:38-9:55-9:69-9:74-9:85-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:64-10:70-10:88-10:98-11:15-11:60-12:101-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:30-16:41-16:107-16:122-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-20:72-20:131-22:9-22:11-22:15-23:33-23:37-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:33-28:42-28:60-28:61-28:77-28:79-29:25-29:27-29:64-30:7-31:15-31:33-33:28-33:57-35:5-37:6-39:10-39:26-40:39-40:43-40:51-41:12-41:16-41:31-42:20-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-59:3-67:5-79:38-87:16",111
1491,327,"W","اَدْنٰی","«اَدْنٰی» is also understood to convey the meaning of being lesser in rank or status, in addition to temporal proximity. The word «اَدْنٰی» is also used in the senses of «اَرْذَل» and insignificant (meaning). Its antonyms «اَعْلٰی» and «اُخْرٰی» are also found.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ وَّرِثُوا الۡکِتٰبَ یَاۡخُذُوۡنَ عَرَضَ ہٰذَا الۡاَدۡنٰی» (7/169)\nTranslation: Then after them succeeded «فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ وَّرِثُوا الۡکِتٰبَ یَاۡخُذُوۡنَ عَرَضَ ہٰذَا الۡاَدۡنٰی» generations who inherited the Book but adopted the mundane life of this world.","«اَدْنٰی» is used to convey meanings such as lowly, petty, and despicable.","World","ادنی","2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:9-58:7-73:20",12
1492,327,"W","عَاجِلَۃ","Its opposite is «اٰخِرَۃ». And «عِجْل» means haste and impulsiveness. And «عَاجِلَۃ» means that which comes quickly, the present, the immediate world and its adornments (figurative).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«کَلَّا بَلۡ  تُحِبُّوۡنَ الۡعَاجِلَۃَ وَ  تَذَرُوۡنَ  الۡاٰخِرَۃَ» (75:20-21)\nTranslation: Not so! Rather, you hold the world dear and abandon the Hereafter.","«عَاجِلَۃ» meaning hurry and haste.","World","عاجلۃ","17:18-75:20-76:27",3
1493,327,"W","اُوْلٰی","«اُوْلٰی» means the first. And its feminine form means the first (feminine). That is, the first or present life, and its opposite is the last and the Hereafter, meaning the last or the second life.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنَّ  لَنَا لَلۡاٰخِرَۃَ  وَ الۡاُوۡلٰی» (92/13)\nTranslation: And the Hereafter and the present life are Ours.","«اُوْلٰی» is used in all these meanings: first, previous, next, of earlier times, precedent, before, better, greater.","World","اولی","20:21-20:51-20:133-28:43-28:70-33:33-37:59-44:35-44:56-53:25-53:50-53:56-56:62-79:25-87:18-92:13-93:4",17
1494,328,"D","بَعِیْد","«بُعْد» is the opposite of «قُرْب», meaning distance. This distance may be in terms of space or time. Its usage is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنۡ  اَدۡرِیۡۤ  اَقَرِیۡبٌ اَمۡ بَعِیۡدٌ مَّا تُوۡعَدُوۡنَ» (21:109)\nTranslation: And I do not know whether that [punishment] which you are promised is near or distant.\n\nBeyond physical senses, its usage also comes in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ یُرِیۡدُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ اَنۡ یُّضِلَّہُمۡ ضَلٰلًۢا بَعِیۡدًا» (4:60)\nTranslation: Satan desires to lead them far astray from the path.","«بَعِیْد» Its use is common whether for time or for place.","Distant","بعید","2:176-3:30-4:60-4:116-4:136-4:167-11:83-11:89-14:3-14:18-21:109-22:12-22:53-25:12-27:22-34:8-34:52-34:53-41:44-41:52-42:18-50:3-50:27-50:31-70:6",25
1495,328,"F","سَحِیْق","«سَحَقَ» meaning to crush, to pound. «سَحِقَ» meaning to be distant. And «سُحْقًا» meaning distance from God's mercy. Curse. (as in Munjid) «سَحَقَ الرِّیْحُ الْاَرْضَ» to strip the earth bare due to fierce winds. And «سَحِیْق» meaning a distant place. This applies only to locations. (p. 29)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیۡقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: (The example of a polytheist is) like one who falls from the sky. Then either birds snatch him away, or the wind carries him to a distant place.","«سَحِیْق» signifies a distant place. This term is used exclusively for locations.","Far","سحیق","22:31",1
1496,328,"D","عَمِیْق","«عَمَقْ» meaning depth, and «عَمِیْق» meaning steep, and «فَجٍّ عَمِیْق» meaning a path of valleys and peaks, crooked and winding, complex and distant.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)  \nTranslation: They should come to you from distant and remote paths.","meaning the paths of valleys and peaks, distance and hardship.","Distant","عمیق","22:27",1
1497,328,"E","قَصِیًّا","«قَصِی ، قَصٰی» means to be distant. «اَقْصَا» and «قُصْوٰی» refer to an extremely distant thing (manjad), and «اَقْصَا» also means the far side, the opposite bank, or the extremity.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ جَآءَ رَجُلٌ مِّنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ یَسۡعٰی» (28/20)\nTranslation: And a person came running from the farthest edge of the city.\n\nThus, in «اَقْصَا» and «قَصِیًّا», the concept of direction is also found along with distance.\nFor example: The divine statement says:\n«فَحَمَلَتۡہُ  فَانۡتَبَذَتۡ بِہٖ مَکَانًا قَصِیًّا» (19/22)\nTranslation: So she conceived him and withdrew with him to a distant place.\n\nThat is, Maryam initially went to an eastern location, and then she went to a place even more distant than that.","«قَصِیًّا» a distance in which some conception of direction is also found (distance and direction). For to stay away, see to avoid/save oneself.","Era","قصیًا","8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20",5
1498,328,"D","بَعُدَ","«بُعْد» meaning to be distant. This word is commonly used. Distance, time, and rank—all types of separation are expressed with it. To set out and go to a faraway place (Faq l 11)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لٰکِنۡۢ بَعُدَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الشُّقَّۃُ» (9/42)\nTranslation: But the distance appeared far (lengthy) to them.\n\nAnd «بَاعَدَ» meaning to make distant/lengthen (verb form).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا بٰعِدۡ بَیۡنَ  اَسۡفَارِنَا» (34/19)\nTranslation: They said, Our Lord, lengthen our distances (or make our journeys longer).","«بُعْد» is common for all kinds of distances.","Distant","بعد","9:42-11:44-11:60-11:68-11:95-21:101-23:41-23:44-43:38",9
1499,328,"F","قَصَا ( یَقْصُوْا )","«قَصَا» means to be distant. It is used only as a locative adverb and conveys the meaning of being far from a specific place and its inhabitants. «اَقْصَی الْمَدِیْنَۃِ» means the farthest part of the city. Masjid Al-Aqsa means the distant mosque.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَحَمَلَتۡہُ  فَانۡتَبَذَتۡ بِہٖ مَکَانًا قَصِیًّا» (19/22)\nTranslation: So she conceived him and withdrew with him to a distant place.","«قَصَا» is used to maintain distance from the residents of a specific place.","far","قصا ( یقصوا )","8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20",5
1500,328,"D","نَائٰ","«نَایٰ» means to turn away. And «نَائِیَۃ» means to turn away and remain distant (m. r.) and to reach a distant place. (f. l. 11) It is used only for temporal adverbs. And according to the statement of Imam Raghib, it is to turn away from someone out of arrogance (muf). This word appears twice in the Quran, and in both instances, both meanings are supported. For example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ  اِذَاۤ   اَنۡعَمۡنَا عَلَی  الۡاِنۡسَانِ اَعۡرَضَ وَ نَاٰ بِجَانِبِہٖ» (17:83) Translation: And when We bestow Our favor upon man, he turns away and changes his side. For example: The divine command states: «وَ ہُمۡ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنۡہُ  وَ یَنۡئَوۡنَ عَنۡہُ ۚ وَ اِنۡ یُّہۡلِکُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ مَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (6:26) Translation: They hinder (others) from it and themselves remain distant. Thus, they destroy themselves, but they are unaware.","A temporal adverb used to avoid arrogance.","Distant","نائ","6:26-17:83-41:51",3
1501,328,"F","کَفَّرَ","«کَفَرَ» means to conceal. And «کُفْرَۃ» means the darkness of the night. And «کَفَّارَۃ» is the act through which a sin is covered. And when «کَفَّرَ» is directed toward Allah Almighty, it means to remove evils. And «کَفَّرَ» is related to *sayyi'at* (sins). Just as «غَفَرَ» is related to *dhunub* (sins).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ  اَنَّ  اَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ اتَّقَوۡا لَکَفَّرۡنَا عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ» (5/65)\nTranslation: And if the People of the Book had believed and been mindful of evil, We would surely have removed from them their evils.","«کَفَّرَ» (عَنْ) Allah Ta'ala's forgiveness of sins due to good deeds.","Far","کفر","2:271-3:193-3:195-4:31-5:12-5:45-5:65-5:89-5:95-8:29-29:7-39:35-47:2-48:5-64:9-65:5-66:8",17
1502,328,"D","قَضٰی","The literal meaning of «قَضٰی» is not to remove but rather, when it is attributed to a human, it means to fulfill a responsibility. For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی مُوۡسَی الۡاَجَلَ» (28/29)\nTranslation: When Moses (peace be upon him) had completed the appointed term.\nHowever, in the following verse, due to the idiomatic usage of the language, its meaning is taken as to remove. Because this too is part of the completion of a task. For example: The Divine command states:\n«ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ» (22/29)\nTranslation: Then let them remove the soiled garments and fulfill their vows.\nNote: (Tamāmah: That which completes something, or a supplementary article, chapter, or annotation related to an original work [such as a book or treatise] that is included as a completion.)","«قَضٰی» Performing an act as a concluding or supplementary measure after completing a major task.","Distant","قضی","2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23",58
1503,329,"T","سَرَعَ","«سَرَعَ» means not delaying in doing a task and doing it immediately (detailed), and in terms of speed, «سَرَعَ» refers only to moving quickly without any danger (ف ۔ ل 33). Its opposite is «بَطَاَ».\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states: «یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا» (70/43). Translation: On the Day they will emerge from the graves in haste.","«سَرَعَ» to move swiftly.","to run","سرع","6:62-10:21-50:44-70:43",4
1504,329,"T","سَعٰی","«سَعٰی» a pace between walking and running. «سَعْی» That is the pace one walks between Safa and Marwah (cf. 177). For example, the Quran states: «وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی» (36:20). Translation: And a man came running from the farthest edge of the city.","«سَعٰی» the intermediate gait between walking and running.","to run","سعی","2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8",14
1505,329,"T","زَفَّ","«زَفّ» the renowned manner of running. And according to Sahib Munjid, it is to run swiftly. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَرَاغَ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ضَرۡبًۢا بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ فَاَقۡبَلُوۡۤا  اِلَیۡہِ  یَزِفُّوۡنَ» (37/93,94) Translation: Then (Prophet Ibrahim ﷺ) began to strike them with his right hand, so they came running to him.","«زَفّ» to move briskly, to run.","to run","زف","37:94",1
1506,329,"T","رَکَضَ","«رَکَضَ» means to gallop. «رَکَضَ الرَّجُلُ دَآبَّتَہٗ» He spurred his mount to surge ahead (e.g., to gallop a horse). To race at full speed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اَحَسُّوۡا بَاۡسَنَاۤ  اِذَا ہُمۡ  مِّنۡہَا یَرۡکُضُوۡنَ» (21:12)\nTranslation: When they perceived Our punishment, they began to flee from it.","«رَکَضَ» to run non-stop.","to run","رکض","21:12-21:13-38:42",3
1507,329,"T","جَمَحَ","«جَمَحَ» to bolt (of a horse) — meaning a horse running at high speed with the rider losing control (Manjd).","«جَمَحَ» break loose.","to run","جمح","9:57",1
1508,329,"T","ھَرَعَ","«وَ جَآءَہٗ  قَوۡمُہٗ یُہۡرَعُوۡنَ  اِلَیۡہِ» (11/78)\nTranslation: And the people of Lot's city came rushing to them.","«ھَرَعَ» to rush headlong, to be overcome by emotions and run.","to run","ھرع","11:78-37:70",2
1509,329,"T","نَسَلَ","«نَسَلَ» To rush from heights to lowlands. According to Ibn Manzoor, it means to move swiftly and to cause to fall. And according to Ibn al-Faris, it means to gradually extract one thing from another (for example). However, this meaning is not the intended one in the following verse.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا  فُتِحَتۡ یَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ مَاۡجُوۡجُ وَ ہُمۡ  مِّنۡ  کُلِّ  حَدَبٍ  یَّنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (21/96)\nTranslation: Until when Gog and Magog are let loose, and they swoop down from every height.","«نَسَلَ» running downward from a high place.","to run","نسل","21:96-36:51",2
1510,329,"T","اَوْفَضَ","«وَفَضَ» means to run swiftly. And «اَلْوَفْضَۃ» means a leather quiver in which arrows are kept (a munjad). According to Imam Raghib, it also means to run as hunters run toward the trap of their prey.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ» (70:43)\nTranslation: As if they are running toward a target.","to run swiftly and cautiously, as a hunter runs toward his snare.","to run","اوفض","70:43",1
1511,329,"T","ھَطَعَ","«ھَطَعَ» Fixing their gaze on what lies ahead, they rush forward in obedience and submission (e.g.). For instance, the Noble Quran states: «مُّہۡطِعِیۡنَ  اِلَی الدَّاعِ ؕ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ  عَسِرٌ» (54:8) They will be running towards the caller, and the disbelievers will say, This is a hard day!","«ھَطَعَ» fixing one's gaze and running obediently.","to run","ھطع","14:43-54:8-70:36",3
1512,329,"T","ضَبَحَ","«ضَبَحَ» To run a horse at full gallop so that it starts panting.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1)\nTranslation: By the chargers at dawn, striking (the ground) with their hooves.","«ضَبَحَ» (the horse) running so fast that it starts panting.","to run","ضبح","100:1",1
1513,329,"T","سَبَقَ ، اِسْتَبَقَ","«سَبَقَ» means to get ahead, to advance in a contest, or to run. And «اِسْتَبَقَ» means to strive to surpass one another in a contest.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَحۡسَبَنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا سَبَقُوۡا ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ  لَا  یُعۡجِزُوۡنَ» (8:59)\nTranslation: And let not the disbelievers think that they have outstripped [Allah's plan]. They will never be able to frustrate [His will].\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ اسۡتَبَقَا الۡبَابَ وَ قَدَّتۡ قَمِیۡصَہٗ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ» (12:25)\nTranslation: And they both raced to the door, and she tore his shirt from the back. They both found her husband at the door.","To race in an effort to advance in the competition.","to run","سبق ، استبق","2:148-5:48-7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-12:17-12:25-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-36:66-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4",26
1514,330,"H","اَوْضَعَ","«وَضَعَ» means to bring something down, to humiliate, or to cause a fall from a rank. And «وَضَعَ» or «اَوْضَعَ الْبَعِیْر» means to run an camel with its head lowered, in a manner that has no good aspect (i.e., stubbornly or obstinately). And «اَوْضَعَ» means to run around here and there in order to stir up trouble and cause chaos.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَوۡ خَرَجُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ مَّا زَادُوۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا خَبَالًا وَّ لَا۠اَوۡضَعُوۡا خِلٰلَکُمۡ یَبۡغُوۡنَکُمُ الۡفِتۡنَۃَ» ( 9/47 )\nTranslation: If they had gone forth with you, they would not have added to you except disorder, and they would have hurried about in your midst, seeking to cause you trouble and discord.","«اَوْضَعَ» running around to cause corruption.","horse","اوضع","9:47",1
1515,330,"H","اَوْجَف","«وَجَفَ» to be restless. Anxiety. To be uneasy. And «قَلْبٌ وَّاجِفٌ» meaning a restless heart. (Plural) And «اَوْجَفَ» meaning (to race horses, etc.).  \nFor example: In the Quran it says:  \n«وَ مَاۤ  اَفَآءَ اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ  مِنۡہُمۡ فَمَاۤ اَوۡجَفۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ مِنۡ خَیۡلٍ وَّ لَا رِکَابٍ» (59/6)  \nTranslation: And whatever wealth Allah has bestowed upon His Messenger from the people of the towns—there is no share for you therein unless... (for it is not for you that you raced horses or camels).","to run swiftly due to restlessness","horse","اوجف","59:6",1
1516,331,"H","النّار","«نَار ، نُوْر» means fire. It is a well-known word. When the definite article «ال» is prefixed to it and there is no other distinguishing sign (indicator) for specification, then «اَلنَّار» refers to Hellfire.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ صَالُوا النَّارِ» (38:59)\nTranslation: Indeed, those people will enter Hell.","«النّار» meaning fire.","Hell","النار","2:24-2:39-2:80-2:81-2:126-2:167-2:174-2:175-2:201-2:217-2:221-2:257-2:275-3:10-3:16-3:24-3:103-3:116-3:131-3:151-3:183-3:185-3:191-3:192-4:145-5:29-5:37-5:72-6:27-6:128-7:36-7:38-7:44-7:47-7:50-8:14-9:17-10:8-10:27-11:16-11:17-11:98-11:106-11:113-13:5-13:17-13:35-14:30-14:50-16:62-18:53-20:10-21:39-22:72-23:104-24:57-27:8-27:90-28:29-28:41-29:24-29:25-32:20-33:66-34:42-38:27-38:59-38:61-38:64-39:8-39:16-39:19-40:6-40:41-40:43-40:46-40:47-40:49-40:72-41:19-41:24-41:28-41:40-45:34-46:20-46:34-47:12-47:15-51:13-52:14-54:48-56:71-57:15-58:17-59:3-59:17-59:20-64:10-66:10-74:31-85:5-87:12",102
1517,331,"H","جَھَنَّمَ","«جَھَنَّمَ» is a Persian loanword in Arabic (a term originally from another language, Arabized with slight modification). It means the abode of punishment – the house of retribution and torment (masc.). Lexicographers generally derive it from the root Jahm.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«جَہَنَّمَ ۚ یَصۡلَوۡنَہَا ۚ فَبِئۡسَ الۡمِہَادُ» (38/56)\nTranslation: Those who enter it will find it an evil resting place.","Colloquially, «جَھَنَّمَ» is used to refer to Hell.","Hell","جھنم","2:206-3:12-3:162-3:197-4:55-4:93-4:97-4:115-4:121-4:140-4:169-7:18-7:41-7:179-8:16-8:36-8:37-9:35-9:49-9:63-9:68-9:73-9:81-9:95-9:109-11:119-13:18-14:16-14:29-15:43-16:29-17:8-17:18-17:39-17:63-17:97-18:100-18:102-18:106-19:68-19:86-20:74-21:29-21:98-23:103-25:34-25:65-29:54-29:68-32:13-35:36-36:63-38:56-38:85-39:32-39:60-39:71-39:72-40:49-40:60-40:76-43:74-45:10-48:6-50:24-50:30-52:13-55:43-58:8-66:9-67:6-72:15-72:23-78:21-85:10-89:23-98:6",77
1518,331,"H","جَحِیْم","«جَحَمَ» meaning the fierce glare of a lion and a piercing gaze. And «جَحْم» meaning the fierce blazing of fire. And «جَحِیْم» meaning fiercely blazing fire (masculine), and «جَحِیْم» meaning fire blazing fiercely in a pit, a scorching hot place, or Hell (feminine).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it says:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47)\nTranslation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.","«جَحِیْم» meaning a fiercely blazing fire.","Hell","جحیم","2:119-5:10-5:86-9:113-22:51-26:91-37:23-37:55-37:64-37:68-37:97-37:163-40:7-44:47-44:56-52:18-56:94-57:19-69:31-73:12-79:36-79:39-81:12-82:14-83:16-102:6",26
1519,331,"H","سَقَر","«سَقَر» meaning intense heat that scorches the body.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا سَقَرُ لَا  تُبۡقِیۡ  وَ لَا  تَذَرُ لَوَّاحَۃٌ  لِّلۡبَشَرِ» (74/27,28,29)\nTranslation: And what will make you realize what Saqar is? It will neither spare nor leave [anyone], and it will burn and blacken [the body].","«سَقَر» meaning intense heat that scorches the body.","Hell","سقر","54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42",4
1520,331,"H","سَعِیْر","«سَعَرَ» means to ignite and intensify (a fire), and due to this very attribute, Hellfire is referred to as «سعیر». That is, a fire that blazes perpetually.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ سَیَصۡلَوۡنَ  سَعِیۡرًا» (4/10)\nTranslation: Soon they will enter a blazing fire.","«سَعِیْر» meaning a fire that is always flaring up.","Hell","سعیر","4:10-4:55-17:97-22:4-25:11-31:21-33:64-34:12-35:6-42:7-48:13-67:5-67:10-67:11-76:4-81:12-84:12",17
1521,331,"H","غَیّ","«غَوٰی» means to go astray and choose the wrong path. It is the next level after «ضَلَال». And «غَیّ» refers to misguidance that occurs due to a false creed (lexical), and «غَیّ» is also the name of a valley or layer of Hell into which such misguided people will be thrown.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَخَلَفَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِہِمۡ خَلۡفٌ اَضَاعُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اتَّبَعُوا الشَّہَوٰتِ فَسَوۡفَ یَلۡقَوۡنَ  غَیًّا» ( 19/59 )\nTranslation: Then, after them, succeeded [to them] a generation who lost the prayer and pursued their desires. So they will soon encounter the Ghayy.","«غَیّ» misguidance due to an incorrect creed.","Hell","غی","2:256-7:146-7:202-19:59-",4
1522,331,"H","ھَاوِیَۃ","«ھَوٰی یَھْوِیْ» refers to falling from a height to the ground. And «اُھْوِیَّۃ» refers to a deep well. And «اُھْوِیَّۃ» refers to a deep pit (mand). And «ھَاوِیَۃ» is the name of a deep pit in Hell.  \nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«فَاُمُّہٗ  ہَاوِیَۃٌ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» (101:9,10,11)  \nTranslation: Its place is Hawiyah. And do you know what Hawiyah is? It is a fierce, blazing fire.","«ھَاوِیَۃ» is the name of a deep pit of Hell.","Hell","ھاویۃ","101:9",1
1523,331,"H","اَلْحُطَمَۃ","«حَطَمَ» means to grind and scatter, to pound and throw. And «حُطَمَۃ» is the name of one of the layers of Hell. For example, the Holy Quran states: «وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا  الۡحُطَمَۃُ نَارُ اللّٰہِ الۡمُوۡقَدَۃُ» (104:5-6). Translation: And do you know what «وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا  الۡحُطَمَۃُ نَارُ اللّٰہِ الۡمُوۡقَدَۃُ» is? It is Allah's fiercely blazing fire.","«اَلْحُطَمَۃ» is the name of one level of Hell.","Hell","الحطمۃ","104:4-104:5",2
1524,331,"H","خَزْنَۃ","«خَزْنَۃ» is the collection of «خَازِن». And in «خَزَن», the concepts of two things are found: collection and protection. «خَازِن» means the one who protects collected wealth: a treasurer, guards of the Hellfire, sentries, or wardens.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«سَاَلَہُمۡ خَزَنَتُہَاۤ  اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ  نَذِیۡرٌ» (67/8)\nTranslation: The wardens of Hell will question them, Did no warner come to you?","The guards and sentinels of Hell are called «خَزْنَۃ».","Hell","خزنۃ","15:22-39:71-39:73-40:49-67:8",5
1525,331,"H","زَبَانِیَۃ","«زَبَانِیَۃ» are those harsh and fierce angels of Hell who will drive the inhabitants of Hell into it.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«فَلۡیَدۡعُ نَادِیَہٗ سَنَدۡعُ  الزَّبَانِیَۃَ» (96:18)  \nTranslation: Then summon your council of flatterers; We will summon the guards of Hell.","«زَبَانِیَۃ» Those are the stern and fierce angels of Hell who will thrust the people of the Fire into it.","Hell","زبانیۃ","96:18",1
1526,331,"H","مَالِک","«مَالِک» is the name of the chief of the keepers of Hell.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ نَادَوۡا یٰمٰلِکُ لِیَقۡضِ عَلَیۡنَا رَبُّکَ» (43:77)\nTranslation: And the inmates of Hell will cry out, O master! If only our Lord would grant us death!","«مَالِک» is the name of the chief guardian of Hell.","Hell","مالک","43:77",1
1527,332,"F","قَرِیْن","«اَلْقَرَن» is the rope with which two camels are tied. And « اَلْقِرْنَ» means equal, counterpart, rival in courage or knowledge. According to the definition (from Farahidi, 235), its application extends to all things, both living and inanimate. And «قِرْاٰنُ السَّعْدَیْن» means the conjunction of two fortunate stars in one zodiac sign. And in the words of Imam Raghib, «قَرِیْن» is a person who is of the same age as another or is his equal in bravery, strength, and other qualities. (Mufradat) This word is generally used in a negative sense. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ» (43:38)\nTranslation: Until, when he comes to Us, he will say, Oh, I wish there was between me and you a distance as great as that between the east and the west! What an evil companion you were!","«قَرِیْن» peer, contemporary, and coeval.","Friend","قرین","4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27",6
1528,332,"F","رَفِیْق","«اَلرِّفْق» signifies gentleness, the conduct of kindness, and that which is sought for aid. And «مِرْفَقَۃ» means a small pillow or cushion. And «رَفِیْق» means a compassionate companion, one who is soft-hearted, agreeable, and keeps close company. And «رَفَقَ» is the opposite of «عَنَفَ», meaning harshness and severity.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ ۚ وَ حَسُنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ رَفِیۡقًا» (4:69)\nTranslation: They will be with those upon whom Allah has bestowed His grace: the Prophets, the steadfast in truth, the martyrs, and the righteous. And excellent is such companionship.","A compassionate and tender-hearted friend.","Friend","رفیق","4:69",1
1529,332,"F","وَلِی","«اَلْوَلَاءِ» meaning love, friendship, closeness, relationship (singular forms) and kinship (abstract). And «وَلِی» meaning helper, protector, one who comes to aid in times of trouble.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اَللّٰہُ وَلِیُّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا ۙ یُخۡرِجُہُمۡ مِّنَ الظُّلُمٰتِ اِلَی النُّوۡرِ» (2/257)\nTranslation: Allah is the friend of the believers who brings them out of darkness into light.\nAnd «اَلْوَلَاء» meaning wilayah (guardianship), inheritance of the estate. And «مَوَالِی ( واحد مولی )» meaning heirs of the estate. For further details, see under the section on inheritance.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/33)\nTranslation: And for the parents and near relatives, We have appointed heirs.","Helper and Protector, Defender and Sustainer (Helper)","Friend","ولی","2:107-2:120-2:257-2:286-3:68-3:150-4:33-6:51-6:62-6:70-8:40-9:51-9:74-9:116-10:30-13:37-16:76-17:111-18:26-19:5-22:13-22:78-29:22-32:4-33:5-41:34-42:8-42:31-42:44-44:41-45:19-47:11-57:15-66:2-66:4",35
1530,332,"F","صَدِیْق","«صَدِیْق» A true and loyal friend. A steadfast friend who upholds friendship. And «صداقت» is to mutually agree on the support of sincere and selfless hearts (pure and unselfish love) (reference 98/236).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا عَلٰۤی  اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ اَنۡ تَاۡکُلُوۡا مِنۡۢ بُیُوۡتِکُمۡ  ۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔۔ اَوۡ صَدِیۡقِکُمۡ» (24/61)\nTranslation: There is no sin upon you if you eat from your own homes or from the home of a friend.\n\nAnd «صِدِّیْق» is an emphatic form. Meaning: a confidant and true friend.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یُوۡسُفُ اَیُّہَا الصِّدِّیۡقُ اَفۡتِنَا فِیۡ سَبۡعِ بَقَرٰتٍ سِمَانٍ یَّاۡکُلُہُنَّ سَبۡعٌ عِجَافٌ» (12/46)\nTranslation: O Joseph, O great truthful friend, tell us the interpretation of the dream where seven fat cows are being eaten by seven lean cows.","«صَدِیْق» A loyal friend, sincere in agreement.  \nAnd «صِدّیق» truthful, conscientious, and loyal in friendship.","Friend","صدیق","4:69-5:75-12:46-19:41-19:56-24:61-26:101-57:19",8
1531,332,"F","خَلِیْل","«خُلَّۃَ» and «خِلَال» mean the settling of friendship in the heart (sing.), firm and deep friendship. And «خَلِیْل» means a sincere and intimate friend, and its plural is «اَخِلَّاء».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اتَّخَذَ اللّٰہُ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ خَلِیۡلًا» (4/125)\nTranslation: And Allah the Most High took Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) as His friend.","«خَلِیْل» a true and deep friend with heartfelt love.","Friend","خلیل","4:125-17:73-25:28",3
1532,332,"F","حَمِیْم","«حَمِیْم» is primarily used in three meanings: (1) to be black, (2) to be hot, (3) to be near. For example, «حَمَّ» means 'to heat', «حَمَّ الظَّھِیْرَۃ» means 'the intense heat of midday' (manjad), and «حَمِیْم» means 'a friend who shows enthusiasm or a close friend'.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا یُّبَصَّرُوۡنَہُمۡ» (70:10-11) Translation: On that day, no friend will inquire about his friend, even though they will be facing each other (Jalandhari).","«حَمِیْم» Expressive of warmth.","Friend","حمیم","6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25",19
1533,332,"F","وَلِیْجَۃ","«وَلَجَ» means to enter. And «وَلِیْجَۃ» is a friend who intervenes in the affairs of others. Confiḍ ʿalayh (i.e., one in whom trust is placed). Its second meaning is a person who remains attached to another group (or faction). The nuance of both meanings is approximately the same.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا یَعۡلَمِ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ جٰہَدُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ وَ لَمۡ یَتَّخِذُوۡا مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا رَسُوۡلِہٖ وَ لَا الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ  وَلِیۡجَۃً» ( 9/16 )\nTranslation: Although Allah has not yet made known who among you will strive in jihad, and Allah does not take as a close confidant anyone besides His Messenger and the believers.","«وَلِیْجَۃ» A friend so confident that he even intervenes in some water-related matter.","Friend","ولیجۃ","9:16",1
1534,332,"F","بَطَانَۃ","«بَطَن» means the belly and the inner part of everything. And «بَطَانَۃ» means secret, the inner garment (i.e., the inner cloth), a person's family and special ones (elite), and by «بَطَانَۃ» is meant such a friend who is a confidant or one acquainted with inner matters.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118)\nTranslation: O believers, do not take anyone of a different religion as your confidant. These people do not refrain from seeking your corruption.","«بَطَانَۃ» confidant or keeper of secrets","Friend","بطانۃ","3:118",1
1535,332,"F","خَذُوْل","«خَذَل» means not helping someone and abandoning them. And «خَذُوْل» refers to such a friend who verbally upholds friendship but abandons when needed (hypocrite), a betrayer.  \nFor example: In the Quran, «وَ کَانَ الشَّیۡطٰنُ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ خَذُوۡلًا» (25/29) Translation: And Satan is a betrayer to man at the appointed time.","«خَذُوْل» the one who will be betrayed when the time comes.","Friend","خذول","3:160-17:22-25:29",3
1536,332,"F","اَخْدَان","«اَخْدَان» is a term that means companion, a person of loose morals, amorous, friend, acquaintance, sinner, one who maintains secret friendships, or one who fulfills sexual desires. It is used for both masculine and feminine.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مُحۡصَنٰتٍ غَیۡرَ مُسٰفِحٰتٍ وَّ لَا مُتَّخِذٰتِ اَخۡدَانٍ» (4/25)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] women who are chaste, neither committing open adultery nor taking secret lovers.","«اَخْدَان» acquaintance, companion, friend of evil.","Friend","اخدان","4:25-5:5",2
1537,332,"F","تَوَلّٰی","«تَوَلّٰی» is used in the sense of taking as a friend or ally.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡہِ  اَنَّہٗ  مَنۡ تَوَلَّاہُ  فَاَنَّہٗ یُضِلُّہٗ» (22/4)\nTranslation: It has been decided that whoever takes Satan as a friend will be led astray by him.","«تَوَلّٰی» is used to mean to make friends.","Friend","تولی","7:196-22:4",2
1538,333,"P","رَجِیْم","«رَجَم» means to throw stones or pebbles from a distance (figurative). It is used in both material and spiritual senses. And «رَجِیْم» means cursed, rejected.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  قَرَاۡتَ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  فَاسۡتَعِذۡ بِاللّٰہِ مِنَ  الشَّیۡطٰنِ  الرَّجِیۡمِ» (16:98)\nTranslation: When you recite the Quran, seek refuge with Allah from the accursed Satan.","«رَجِیْم» meaning rejected and accursed.","pushed","رجیم","3:36-15:17-15:34-16:98-38:77-81:25",6
1539,333,"P","دُحُوْر","The basic meanings of «دَحَرَ» are two: (1) to stone/curse (2) to expel (root: ر ج م) i.e., to drive someone out by stoning/cursing.\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is said:\n«دُحُوۡرًا  وَّ  لَہُمۡ  عَذَابٌ  وَّاصِبٌ» (37/9)\nTranslation: (These devils) are stoned/cursed and for them is a permanent punishment.\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«قَالَ اخۡرُجۡ مِنۡہَا مَذۡءُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» (7/18)\nTranslation: Allah said: Get out from here, disgraced and degraded.","«دَحُوْرًا» expelled and removed.","pushed","دحور","7:18-17:18-17:39-37:9",4
1540,333,"S","خَسَاَ","«خَاسِئ» meaning to curse a dog or a pig; to curse with contempt, regarding as vile and despicable.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ  اخۡسَئُوۡا فِیۡہَا وَ لَا  تُکَلِّمُوۡنِ» (23/108)\nTranslation: Allah will say, Remain in it (Hell) in humiliation, and do not speak to Me.","«خَاسِئ» rebuked due to being contemptible and degraded.","shove","خسا","2:65-7:166-23:108-67:4",4
1541,334,"B","اِنْکَدَرَ","«کَدَرٌ» means turbidity or dullness, and its opposite is «صَفَاءٌ». And «کُدْرَۃٌ» means the fading or dimming of color, becoming pale and light (in a transitive sense).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  اِذَا  النُّجُوۡمُ  انۡکَدَرَتۡ» (81/2)\nTranslation: And when the stars lose their light.","«اِنْکَدَرَ» is used for the fading and dulling of the color of something.","Blurry","انکدر","81:2",1
1542,334,"D","اَبْیَضَّ","«بَیَاض» means white, the opposite of «سَوَاد», which means black. And «بَیَاضُ الْعَیْن» means the white of the eye. And «اِبْیَضَّتْ عَیْنُہٗ» means his eye turned white or became blind. For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ فَہُوَ کَظِیۡمٌ» (12/84)\nTranslation: And from grief, Ya'qub's (peace be upon him) both eyes turned white. And he was filled with sorrow.","«اَبْیَضَّ عَیْنُہٗ» comes to cause blindness in the eye.","Dim","ابیض","2:187-3:106-3:107-7:108-12:84-20:22-26:33-27:12-28:32-35:27-37:46-37:49",12
1543,334,"F","عَمًی","«عَمِیَ» means blindness of the eye or heart. And «عَمِیَتِ الْاَخْبَارُ عَنْ فُلَانٍ» means having no knowledge or clue about a particular person. And «عَمَّی الْمَعْنٰی» means to conceal the meaning or intent (from the dictionary *Munjad*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ  لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اٰذَانِہِمۡ وَقۡرٌ  وَّ ہُوَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  عَمًی» ( 41/44 )\nTranslation: And for those who do not believe, there is a heaviness in their ears, and this Quran is obscure to them.","«عَمَی الْاَمْر» is used for the concealment or obscurity of a matter.","foggy","عمًی","2:18-2:171-6:50-6:104-7:64-10:43-11:24-11:28-13:16-13:19-17:72-17:97-20:124-20:125-22:46-24:61-25:73-27:81-28:66-30:53-35:19-40:58-41:17-41:44-43:40-47:23-48:17-80:20",28
1544,334,"F","غُمَّۃً","«غَمُّ» means to conceal something, and «غُمّٰی» means darkness and dust. And «غُمَام» means a cloud that covers the sunlight. And «غُمَّۃَ الْاَمْر» means that a matter is complicated and dubious (ambiguous).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَجۡمِعُوۡۤا اَمۡرَکُمۡ وَ شُرَکَآءَکُمۡ ثُمَّ لَا یَکُنۡ اَمۡرُکُمۡ عَلَیۡکُمۡ غُمَّۃً ثُمَّ اقۡضُوۡۤا اِلَیَّ وَ لَا تُنۡظِرُوۡنِ» (10/71)\nTranslation: You and your partners all together agree on a matter, then let it not remain concealed among you. Then, whatever you can do against me, do it, and do not give me any respite.","«غُمَّۃُ الْاَمْر» is used to keep a matter ambiguous. Also see 'دیکھنا' (manner of seeing).","Foggy","غمۃً","10:71",1
1545,335,"S","دُخَان","«دُخَان» means smoke. This is a well-known fact. However, Imam Raghib has specified that it refers to the smoke that emerges along with flames. (Maf) Even though smoke also emerges before the flame. And that too is «دُخَان».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  اسۡتَوٰۤی  اِلَی السَّمَآءِ وَ ہِیَ دُخَانٌ» ( 41/11 )\nTranslation: Then Allah turned towards the heaven. At that time, it was (merely) smoke.","«دُخَان» meaning smoke.","Smoke","دخان","41:11-44:10",2
1546,335,"S","نُحَاس","«نُحَاس» means copper. And fire whose color resembles that of copper. And smoke in which flames of a coppery hue are intertwined—for example, red and intensely hot smoke. When fire and smoke are mixed, this quality arises.\n\nFor instance, in the Holy Quran:\n«یُرۡسَلُ عَلَیۡکُمَا شُوَاظٌ مِّنۡ نَّارٍ ۙ وَّ نُحَاسٌ فَلَا  تَنۡتَصِرٰنِ» (55/35)\nTranslation: (O jinn and humans) flames of fire and smoke will be cast upon you. Then you will not be able to resist.","«نُحَاس» refers to the red smoke of fire that has a color like copper.","smoke","نحاس","55:35",1
1547,335,"S","یَحْمُوْم","One of the fundamental meanings of «حَمَّ» is also to be black (م ۔ ل), and «حُمَّۃ» denotes soot, ash, and everything consumed by fire (minjad). «یَحْمُوْم» refers to smoke that is both hot and thickly black. For example, the Quran states: «فِیۡ  سَمُوۡمٍ  وَّ  حَمِیۡمٍ وَّ ظِلٍّ  مِّنۡ  یَّحۡمُوۡمٍ» (56:42-43). Translation: They will be in scorching wind and scalding water, and under the shadows of black smoke.","«یَحْمُوْم» means thick black smoke.","Smoke","یحموم","56:43",1
1548,336,"S","شَمْس","«شَمْس» means both sitting in the sun and sunlight. «شَمَسَ یَوْمُنَا» means to be in the daytime sun, not cloudy, and «شَمَّسَ» means to keep someone in the sun. And when «شَمْس» refers to sunlight, it can be at any time. However, generally, it implies the intensity of the sun and its heat.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا یَرَوۡنَ فِیۡہَا شَمۡسًا وَّ  لَا  زَمۡہَرِیۡرًا» (76/13)\nTranslation: They (the people of Paradise) will not see the sun's intensity or severe cold.","«شَمْس» is also used to mean the sun and sunlight.","Sunlight","شمس","2:258-6:78-6:96-7:54-10:5-12:4-13:2-14:33-16:12-17:78-18:17-18:86-18:90-20:130-21:33-22:18-25:45-27:24-29:61-31:29-35:13-36:38-36:40-39:5-41:37-50:39-55:5-71:16-75:9-76:13-81:1-91:1",32
1549,336,"S","ضُحٰی","«ضُحٰی» means the time of the sun rising and the spreading of sunlight. This term applies to both the time of Fajr and the sunlight at that time (fig.). For example, in the Quran it says: «وَ اَغۡطَشَ لَیۡلَہَا وَ اَخۡرَجَ ضُحٰہَا» (79/29) Translation: And He made the night dark and (the day) brought forth daylight.","The sun's heat at mid-morning.","sunlight","ضحی","7:98-20:59-20:119-79:29-79:46-91:1-93:1",7
1550,336,"S","حَرّ","«حَرَّ» and «حَرَارَت» mean heat and the time of heat. Since the time of heat is connected to the intensity (of the heat) of the sun and sunshine, therefore the intense midday sun is also called «حَرّ», and the hot season as well.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَا تَنۡفِرُوۡا فِی الۡحَرِّ ؕ قُلۡ نَارُ جَہَنَّمَ اَشَدُّ حَرًّا» (9/81)\nTranslation: And they also began to say, Do not go out in the heat. Say to them, The fire of Hell is far more intense.","«حَرّ» the hot afternoon sun.","sunlight","حر","9:81-16:81",2
1551,336,"S","حَرُوْر","«حَرُوْر» is the opposite of «ظَلّ», meaning shade. «حَرُوْر» means warm wind, lo, tapish that arises due to intense sun heat (etc.). For example, the Holy Quran states: «وَ لَا الظُّلُمٰتُ وَ لَا  النُّوۡرُ وَ لَا الظِّلُّ  وَ لَا  الۡحَرُوۡرُ» (35/20,21). Translation: And neither can darkness and light be equal, nor shade and heat.","«حَرُوْر» the heat and fever generated by the sun's fierce intensity.","Sunlight","حرور","35:21",1
1552,337,"D","غَرَّ","«غَرَّ» means to take someone unawares and thereby achieve one's objective; to deceive; to entrap (transitive). And «غُرُوْر» and «مَتَاعُ الْغُرُوْر» mean «اَبَاطِیْلُ الدُّنْیَا» and «غُرُوْر» means to deceive, and «غَرُوْر» (with a fatḥa on the ghain) means 'deceiver'. And «غُرُوْر» also means every kind of delusion that causes harm to a person, such as making a thirsty person think he is satisfied (as in Surah Yusuf, 12:47).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ غَرَّتۡکُمُ الۡاَمَانِیُّ حَتّٰی جَآءَ  اَمۡرُ اللّٰہِ  وَ غَرَّکُمۡ بِاللّٰہِ الۡغَرُوۡرُ» (57:14)  \nTranslation: And your vain desires had deluded you until Allah's command came, and the Deceiver [Satan] had deluded you concerning Allah.","to deceive by exploiting heedlessness","Deception","غر","3:24-3:185-3:196-4:120-6:70-6:112-6:130-7:22-7:51-8:49-17:64-31:33-33:12-35:5-35:40-40:4-45:35-57:14-57:20-67:20-82:6",21
1553,337,"D","خَدَعَ","«خَدَعَ» To conceal the truth and keep others in darkness (m. l.) and, in meaning, to hide the correct path from someone so that they fall into an undesirable act (f. l. 214). To show something other than what is in the heart and thereby turn someone away from the thing they are inclined towards. To beguile (muf).\n\nAnd «طَرِیْقَ الْخُدُوٌع» refers to a path that sometimes appears and sometimes disappears.\n\nAnd the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said regarding «اَلْحَرْبُ خُدْعَۃٌ ‘‘» and «خُدْعَۃٌ»: Their meaning is not deception or fraud, but rather a military stratagem. Such as positioning the army in a way that makes it appear much larger than its actual number, or the retreat of an army so that the enemy can be encircled. It is as if through such tactics the opponent is kept in the dark while one achieves their objective. There is no element of deceit or fraud in it. And if the intention is good, it is permissible; otherwise, it is not.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُخٰدِعُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا ۚ وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ» (2:9)\nTranslation: The hypocrites seek to beguile Allah and the believers, but in reality, they beguile none but themselves.","Concealing the truth to achieve one's objective and deceiving the opponent.","Deception","خدع","2:9-4:142-8:62",3
1554,337,"D","خَانَ","«خَانَ» meaning to secretly break a covenant. And this word is specific for covenant, trust, and hypocrisy (treachery in religion) (muf). And «خَوَّان» is an intensive form, meaning a great deceiver, a great traitor.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  اِمَّا  تَخَافَنَّ مِنۡ قَوۡمٍ خِیَانَۃً  فَانۡۢبِذۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ عَلٰی سَوَآءٍ ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یُحِبُّ الۡخَآئِنِیۡنَ» (8/58)\nTranslation: And if you apprehend treachery from any people, then throw back their treaty to them in a fair manner. Indeed, Allah does not like the treacherous.","«خَانَ» covertly betraying covenants, trusts, and faith.","Deception","خان","4:105-5:13-8:27-8:58-8:71-12:52-40:19-66:10",8
1555,337,"D","خَذَلَ","«خَذَلَ» one who feigns friendship verbally and betrays when the time comes (see details under friend).","Betraying a friend in their time of need.","Deception","خذل","3:160-17:22-25:29",3
1556,337,"D","رَاغَ اِلٰی","«رَاغَ» means to incline toward someone stealthily. And «رَاغ عَلٰی» means to pounce upon someone (i.e., to attack with full force and resolve all at once), «رَوَاغ» means deceit and trickery, and «رَوَّاغ» means a deceiver. A great fraudster. A fox is also called «رَوَّاغ». And «رَاوَغَہٗ» means he deceived him and then threw him down (from 'manjad'). And according to Imam Raghīb, its meaning is to incline toward one side for the sake of a stratagem and plan (muf).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«فَرَاغَ  اِلٰۤی  اٰلِہَتِہِمۡ  فَقَالَ  اَلَا  تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ» (37/91)  \nTranslation: So Prophet Abraham (peace be upon him) went stealthily toward their idols and said, Why do you not eat?","«رَاغَ» To incline toward deceit and cunning. To be deceived.","Delusion","راغ الی","37:9137:93-51:26",3
1557,337,"D","خَتَرَ","«خَتَرَ» means to act with extreme treachery. And «تَخَتَّرَ» means to become weak and sluggish. (Majid) According to Imam Raghib, «اَلْخَتْر» refers to such treachery which is executed with such effort that a person becomes weak and their limbs become limp. (Mufradat) i.e., to continue persistently in deceiving and being treacherous.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا یَجۡحَدُ بِاٰیٰتِنَاۤ  اِلَّا  کُلُّ  خَتَّارٍ  کَفُوۡرٍ» ( 31/32 )\nTranslation: And they deny Our signs, those who are treacherous and ungrateful.","«خَتَرَ» to betray in the worst manner and to persist in doing so.","Deception","ختر","31:32",1
1558,338,"T","رَاٰی","«رَاٰی» is commonly used to mean perceiving something, whether through the eyes, or through contemplation, intellect and insight, or in terms of imagination and thought. It applies whether one is in a state of wakefulness or in a dream, and also carries the meaning of a final, contemplative glance. To see something with the eyes and perceive it.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اِنِّیۡ  رَاَیۡتُ اَحَدَعَشَرَ کَوۡکَبًا» (12:4)  \nTranslation: I saw eleven stars.  \nAnd to perceive something through contemplation and reflection.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اَرَءَیۡتَ  الَّذِیۡ یُکَذِّبُ بِالدِّیۡنِ» (107:1)  \nTranslation: Have you seen the one who denies the Recompense?","«رَاٰی» is used for contemplating upon a matter.","to see","رای","3:143-4:61-6:40-6:46-6:47-6:68-10:50-10:59-11:28-11:63-11:88-12:4-17:62-18:63-19:77-20:92-21:36-25:43-26:75-26:205-27:10-27:40-28:31-28:71-28:72-33:19-35:8-35:40-39:37:55-38-41:52-45:23-46:4-46:10-47:20-53:13-53:19-53:33-56:58-56:63-56:68-56:71-59:21-63:4-63:5-67:28-67:30-76:19-76:20-81:23-96:7-96:9-96:11-96:13-107:1-110:2",56
1559,338,"T","نَظَرَ","«نَظَرَ» to look, to see, so that something becomes visible, whether it appears or not. It is used in both senses.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ  اِذَا مَاۤ  اُنۡزِلَتۡ سُوۡرَۃٌ  نَّظَرَ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (9/127)  \nTranslation: And whenever a Surah is revealed, they begin to look at one another.  \nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:  \n«فَانۡظُرِیۡ مَاذَا تَاۡمُرِیۡنَ» (27/33)  \nTranslation: Then whichever of them you command, let him look upon its outcome.  \nHowever, the usage of 'nazar' generally pertains to seeing with the eyes.","The use of «نَظَرَ» is generally for glancing.","To see","نظر","2:50-2:55-2:104-2:162-2:210-2:259-2:280-3:77-3:88-3:137-3:143-4:46-4:50-5:75-6:8-6:11-6:24-6:46-6:65-6:99-6:158-7:14-7:15-7:53-7:84-7:86-7:103-7:129-7:143-7:185-7:195-7:198-8:6-9:127-10:14-10:39-10:43-10:71-10:73-10:101-11:55-12:109-15:8-15:36-15:37-16:33-16:36-16:85-17:21-17:48-18:19-20:97-21:40-22:15-25:9-26:203-27:14-27:27-27:28-27:33-27:41-27:51-27:69-28:40-29:20-30:9-30:42-30:50-32:29-33:19-35:43-35:44-36:49-37:19-37:73-37:88-37:102-38:15-38:79-38:80-39:68-40:21-40:82-42:45-43:25-43:66-44:29-47:10-47:18-47:20-50:6-51:44-56:84-57:13-59:18-74:21-78:40-80:24-83:23-83:35-86:5-88:17",102
1560,338,"T","بَصَرَ","The word «بَصَرَ» is used for gazing and for seeing with the heart's eye, but it is very rarely used for seeing with the physical eyes. For example, the Quran states: «وَ تَرٰىہُمۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَیۡکَ وَ ہُمۡ لَا یُبۡصِرُوۡنَ» (7:198). Translation: And you see them as if they are looking at you (with their eyes open), but in reality, they see nothing. In this verse, «رَاٰی ، نَظَرَ» and «بَصَرَ» both appear as synonyms. And the distinction between them also becomes clear. The word «رَاٰی» is used for thinking, «نَظَرَ» for seeing with the eyes, and «بَصَرَ» for seeing with the heart's eye. Moreover, the word «بَصُرَ» is even more specific than «بَصَرَ». For example, the Quran states: «قَالَ بَصُرۡتُ بِمَا لَمۡ یَبۡصُرُوۡا بِہٖ» (20:96). Translation: The Samari said: I have seen something which others did not see. Here, something refers to the idea that occurred to his mind, but which did not occur to the minds of others.","«بَصُرَ» is used to mean seeing with the eyes of the heart.","to see","بصر","2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9",82
1561,338,"T","اٰنس","The meaning is not to contemplate, not to see with the eyes, nor to see with the heart's eye, but rather to become familiar with something or to know it through its indications and signs. In the words of Imam Raghib, it is to become acquainted with something (transitive). However, according to the idiom of our language, its translation is taken as 'to see,' meaning to understand by seeing from afar or with a penetrating gaze.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَقَالَ  لِاَہۡلِہِ  امۡکُثُوۡۤا  اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا» (20/10)\nTranslation: Prophet Moses (peace be upon him) said to his family, 'Wait here; I have seen a fire.'\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«فَاِنۡ اٰنَسۡتُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ رُشۡدًا» (4/6)\nTranslation: If you see in them maturity of intellect.","«اٰنَسَ» to see, meaning to find out or to obtain.","to see","انس","4:6-20:10-27:7-28:29",4
1562,338,"T","زَارَ","«زَارَہٗ» means to go to meet someone (manajada) and to come to see and meet something. To visit (m. q.) and «زَوْر» means the upper part of the chest. And «زُرْتُ فَلَانًا» means I presented my chest before him or intended his chest, i.e., the meeting (m.f.). For example: in the Quran it is: «اَلۡہٰکُمُ  التَّکَاثُرُ حَتّٰی زُرۡتُمُ  الۡمَقَابِرَ» (102/1,2) Translation: Your desire for abundance (wealth) has made you neglectful until you went to see the graves.","«زَارَ» is used to go and see or visit.","to see","زار","102:2",1
1563,338,"T","شَخَصَ","«شَخَصَ» meaning the eyes becoming petrified, losing their light, and not blinking (Fl 103).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اقۡتَرَبَ الۡوَعۡدُ الۡحَقُّ فَاِذَا ہِیَ شَاخِصَۃٌ  اَبۡصَارُ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (21/97)  \nTranslation: And the true promise will draw near; at that time the eyes of the disbelievers will remain staring wide open.","«شَخَصَ» eyes turning to stone.","to see","شخص","14:42-21:97",2
1564,338,"T","لَمَحَ","«لَمَحَ» meaning: the swiftness of a glance; to quickly look at something; the blink of an eye (Fasl 102).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَمۡرُ السَّاعَۃِ  اِلَّا کَلَمۡحِ الۡبَصَرِ اَوۡ ہُوَ اَقۡرَبُ» (16/77)\nTranslation: And the coming of the Hour is like the blink of an eye, or even quicker.","«لَمَحَ» the blink of an eye","to see","لمح","16:77-54:50",2
1565,338,"T","ھَطَعَ","«ھَطَعَ» meaning, with their gazes fixed ahead, running forward.\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ» (14/43)\nTranslation: People will raise their heads (toward the field of Resurrection) and run. Their gazes will not be able to turn back toward them.","«ھَطَعَ» Fix your gaze straight ahead.","to see","ھطع","14:43-54:8-70:36",3
1566,338,"T","عَشَا ( عشو )","The basic meaning of «عَشَا» is that things are not clearly visible due to darkness. (m. l) And sometimes this word is also used simply for the time of darkness.\n\n«اَلْعِشَاء» means the time after evening. Weakness of night vision. The night meal. And «عَشِیَ یَعْشٰی عَشِیًّا و عِشَاوَۃً».\n\nMeaning not seeing at night. Being night-blind (night-blindness is an eye disease that causes inability to see at night). (minjad) And «عِشْوَۃ» means the flame that is visible from afar at night. (m. q)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡشُ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ نُقَیِّضۡ لَہٗ  شَیۡطٰنًا  فَہُوَ  لَہٗ  قَرِیۡنٌ» (43/36) Translation: And whoever turns away from the remembrance of God, We will appoint a devil as his companion.","«عَشَا» darkness, impaired night vision.","to see","عشا ( عشو )","3:41-6:52-12:16-18:28-19:11-19:62-24:58-30:18-38:18-38:31-40:46-40:55-43:36-79:46",14
1567,338,"T","اَغْمَضَ عَیْنَہٗ","«اَغْمَضَ» means to close one's eyes. And «اَغْمَضَ عَنِ الشَّیْ» means to overlook, to transgress (manjada), i.e., to pretend ignorance about something bad despite seeing or knowing it. For example: The Quran states: «وَ لَا تَیَمَّمُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنۡہُ تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ وَ لَسۡتُمۡ بِاٰخِذِیۡہِ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تُغۡمِضُوۡا فِیۡہِ» (2/267). Translation: And do not intend to spend evil and impure things in the way of Allah. And you yourselves would not be prepared to accept such a thing unless you overlook.","«اَغْمَضَ» to turn a blind eye.","to see","اغمض عینہٗ","2:267",1
1568,338,"T","زَاغَ","«زَاغَ البَصَر» meaning to deviate from the path of truth. And «زَاغَ الْبَصَرُ» meaning the eye becoming tired or straining (from looking), and according to Imam Raghīb, the gaze erred and turned aside. For example: in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«مَا زَاغَ الۡبَصَرُ  وَ مَا طَغٰی» (53/17)\nTranslation: (The Prophet's ﷺ) gaze did not turn aside nor exceed the limit.","«زَاغَ البَصَر» to let one's gaze wander.","To see","زاغ","33:10-38:63-53:17-61:5",4
1569,338,"T","بَرِقَ","«بَرِق» means dazzling lightning, and «بَرِقَ الْبَصَرُ» means the brightness or flash of lightning, or the blinding of the eye by a sharp light. For example: In the Quran it is: «فَاِذَا  بَرِقَ الۡبَصَرُ» (75/7) Translation: So when the eyes are dazzled.","«بَرِق» Dazzled by bright light.","to see","برق","2:19-2:20-13:12-24:43-30:24-75:7",6
1570,338,"T","اَرٰی یَرٰی","«رَاٰی» From the root Af'al, meaning to show to others. This word is also used in both material and spiritual contexts.\nMaterial aspect: For example: The Quran states:\n«اَرُوۡنِیۡ  مَاذَا خَلَقُوۡا مِنَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (46/4)\nTranslation: Then show me what these [false deities] have created in the earth.\nSpiritual aspect: For example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَنۡزَلۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ الۡکِتٰبَ بِالۡحَقِّ لِتَحۡکُمَ بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ بِمَاۤ اَرٰىکَ اللّٰہُ ؕ» (4/105)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have sent down to you the Book with the truth so that you may judge between the people by that which Allah has shown you.\n(Here, arā refers to both God-given insight and hidden revelation.)\nAnd «اٰرٰی ، یُرَاء ، رَاٰی» from the root Tafa'al means to show to one another.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی ۙ یُرَآءُوۡنَ النَّاسَ وَ لَا  یَذۡکُرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ  اِلَّا  قَلِیۡلًا» (4/142)\nTranslation: And when they stand for prayer, they stand lazily, showing off to the people and not remembering Allah except a little.\nAnd «رِیَاء» also carries this meaning, i.e., to show off, to make a display. To do an act whose very purpose is to show others.\nFor example: Allah, the Most High, says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ رِئَآءَ النَّاسِ» (4/38)\nTranslation: And [also] those who spend their wealth to show off to the people...","«اَرٰی» refers to both God-given insight and hidden revelation.\n«یَرٰی» meaning to show.","to show","اری یری","2:264-3:152-4:38-4:105-4:142-6:74-8:43-8:47-8:48-11:29-11:84-12:36-19:74-26:61-31:11-34:27-35:40-46:4-46:23-79:20-107:6",21
1571,338,"T","بَصَّرَ","«بَصَّرَ» To demonstrate in a way that enables another to recognize and understand; to acquaint with the circumstances and their effects (elaborated).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا یُّبَصَّرُوۡنَہُمۡ» (70/11)\n\nTranslation: No friend will ask about his friend, even though they will be facing each other.","«بَصَّرَ» to show in such a way that the other may recognize.","to show","بصر","70:11",1
1572,338,"T","تَبَرَّجَ","«بَرَجَ» means to be elevated or to appear. (A well-known term is burj.) And «تَبَرَّجْتُ الْمِرْأَۃ» means women displaying their beauty and charms to strangers. For example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33:33)\nTranslation: And stay in your homes and do not display yourselves as in the former days of ignorance.","«تَبَرُّج» comes to display splendor and adornment.","to show","تبرج","24:60-33:33",2
1573,340,"W","دِیْن","The word «دِیْن» has a very broad meaning. Briefly, it is used in four senses: (1) Allah Almighty's complete and perfect sovereignty, (2) humanity's complete servitude and worship, (3) the law of recompense and punishment, (4) the power to enforce that law of recompense and punishment. Then, sometimes this word occurs in only one meaning, and sometimes in more than one meaning.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَلَا لِلّٰہِ الدِّیۡنُ الۡخَالِصُ» (39:3). Translation: Indeed, pure worship is for Allah Almighty alone. In this verse, this word conveys all four meanings. Now, the requirement of religion is that Allah Almighty commands people regarding certain matters, forbids them from certain actions, and rewards or punishes those who comply or disobey. Thus, those commandments that remained unchanged from Adam to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) constitute the true religion, such as the prohibition of shirk, unlawful killing, theft, adultery, obscenities, etc., and the accountability in the Hereafter. And accepting these commandments of Allah Almighty and becoming obedient is called Islam.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ الدِّیۡنَ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ الۡاِسۡلَامُ» (3:19). Translation: Indeed, the religion in the sight of Allah is Islam (submission).","«دَیْن» Obey those divine commandments that remained unchanged from Prophet Adam to Prophet Muhammad.","Way of Life","دین","1:3-2:132-2:193-2:217-2:256-3:19-3:24-3:73-3:83-3:85-4:46-4:125-4:146-4:171-5:3-5:54-5:57-5:77-6:70-6:137-6:159-6:161-7:29-7:51-8:39-8:49-8:72-9:11-9:12-9:29-9:33-9:36-9:122-10:22-10:104-10:105-12:40-12:76-15:35-16:52-22:78-24:2-24:25-24:55-26:82-29:65-30:30-30:32-30:43-31:32-33:5-37:20-37:53-38:78-39:2-39:3-39:11-39:14-40:14-40:26-40:65-42:13-42:21-48:28-49:16-51:6-51:12-56:56-60:8-60:9-61:9-70:26-74:46-82:9-82:15-82:17-82:18-83:11-95:7-98:5-107:1-109:6-110:2",83
1574,340,"R","شَرِیْعَۃ","The literal meaning of «شَرَعَ» is to clearly define the path (detailed). And «شَرِیْعَۃ» refers to those commandments that continue to change according to the needs of the time and circumstances. For example, among the children of Prophet Adam (PBUH), marriage between siblings was permissible because it was an emergency (compulsory) matter, which was later forbidden in subsequent Sharias. In the marriage of Prophet Jacob, there were two real sisters, which were later forbidden in subsequent Sharias. Similarly, in that era, prostration of reverence was permissible, which was later forbidden. In previous Sharias, benefiting from wealth was impermissible, which was made permissible for the Muslim Ummah. In short, there are numerous such examples.\n\nThe difference between religion (Din) and Sharia was explained by the Messenger of Allah (PBUH) in these words: «اَلْاَنْبِیَاءٌ اِخْوَۃُ الْعَلَّاتِ اُمَّھَاتُھُمْ شَتّٰی وَ دِیْنُھُمْ وَاحِدٌ» (Agreed upon) All the prophets (PBUH) are paternal half-brothers (those brothers whose father is one but mothers are different). That is, their mothers (i.e., their Sharias) are different, and their religion (i.e., their father) is one.\n\nFor example: in the Noble Quran it is: «شَرَعَ  لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ» (42/13). Translation: He (Allah) has defined the path of religion for you.","«شَرِیْعَۃ» The divine commands that continue to change in accordance with the needs of the time.","Religion (way of life)","شریعۃ","5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48",4
1575,340,"R","مِلَّت","In religion (deen) and Sharia, all matters are mentioned in the divinely revealed scripture. The Prophet is foremost in adhering to those commandments himself. Simultaneously, by propagating these divine commandments, he forms a community of followers, binds them all to these commandments, and establishes the Islamic system called the Millat. The Millat is not merely the name of the commandments and decrees, but the name of the system in which the Prophet serves as the leader, his followers are commissioned, their constitution consists of the divine commandments (deen, Sharia), and obedience to the leader is made obligatory upon the community. Scholars often briefly translate Millat as deen, although deen is the same for all prophets, whereas Millat can be attributed only to a specific Prophet.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاتَّبِعُوۡا مِلَّۃَ  اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ حَنِیۡفًا» (3/95)\nTranslation: So follow the Millat of Ibrahim, who detached himself from all others and became solely devoted to Allah.","«مِلَّت» the system that a prophet establishes among his adherents in obedience to divine commandments.","Religion","ملت","2:120-2:130-2:135-3:95-4:125-6:161-7:88-7:89-12:37-12:38-14:13-16:123-18:20-22:78-38:7",15
1576,341,"T","اٰتٰی","«اٰتٰی» To give. To give something to someone. It is used in its well-known senses and its usage is common.\nFor example: In the Quran it is mentioned:\n«وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And he gave his wealth for the love of Allah.","«اٰتٰی» to give something to someone.","to give","اتی","2:43-2:53-2:63-2:83-2:87-2:93-2:110-2:121-2:146-2:177-2:200-2:201-2:211-2:229-2:233-2:251-2:253-2:258-2:265-2:277-3:81-3:148-3:170-3:180-3:194-4:2-4:4-4:19-4:20-4:24-4:25-4:33-4:37-4:54-4:67-4:77-4:153-4:163-5:5-5:12-5:20-5:46-5:48-6:20-6:83-6:89-6:114-6:141-6:154-6:165-7:38-7:144-7:171-7:175-7:189-7:190-9:5-9:11-9:18-9:59-9:75-9:76-10:88-11:28-11:63-11:110-12:22-12:31-12:66-12:101-13:36-14:34-15:81-15:87-16:55-16:122-17:2-17:26-17:55-17:59-17:101-18:10-18:33-18:62-18:65-18:84-18:96-19:12-19:30-20:99-21:48-21:51-21:74-21:79-21:84-22:41-22:78-23:49-23:60-24:33-24:56-25:35-27:7-27:15-27:36-27:39-27:40-28:14-28:29-28:43-28:52-28:76-28:77-29:27-29:47-29:66-30:34-30:38-30:39-31:12-32:13-32:23-33:33-33:50-33:51-33:68-34:10-34:44-34:45-35:40-37:117-38:20-40:53-41:45-43:21-44:33-45:16-45:17-47:17-51:16-52:18-57:23-57:27-58:13-59:7-60:10-60:11-65:6-65:7-73:20",150
1577,341,"T","اَعْطٰی","«اَعْطٰی» comes in two meanings. (1) To give something to someone purely as a favor or gift. (Ex.)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ رَبُّنَا الَّذِیۡۤ اَعۡطٰی کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلۡقَہٗ  ثُمَّ  ہَدٰی» ( 20/50 )\nTranslation: Prophet Moses (PBUH) said to Pharaoh, Our Lord is He who gave everything its form and nature, then guided [it].\nAnd the meaning of «اَعْطٰی» also includes being obedient and subservient, and serving (Munjid). Therefore, to give someone more in return for their service, effort, and obedience is also «اَعْطٰی». A gift, an award, given gladly and in excess of the effort or service.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ سُعِدُوۡا فَفِی الۡجَنَّۃِ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا مَا دَامَتِ السَّمٰوٰتُ وَ الۡاَرۡضُ  اِلَّا  مَا شَآءَ رَبُّکَ ؕ عَطَآءً غَیۡرَ  مَجۡذُوۡذٍ» ( 11/108 )\nTranslation: But those who are blessed with goodness will abide in Paradise as long as the heavens and earth endure, except what your Lord wills—that is a boundless bestowal.","«اَعْطٰی» is to give a greater reward for forgiveness, service, or hard work, and obedience.","to give","اعطی","9:29-9:58-11:108-17:20-20:50-38:39-53:34-78:36-92:5-93:5-108:1",11
1578,341,"T","اَدَاء","«اَدَاءٌ» means to give someone their full and complete right all at once. This word is generally used in the context of transactions such as trusts, loans, and taxes, etc.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ اَمِنَ بَعۡضُکُمۡ بَعۡضًا فَلۡیُؤَدِّ الَّذِی اؤۡتُمِنَ اَمَانَتَہٗ» (2/283)\n\nTranslation: And if one of you entrusts another, then the trustee should fulfill the trust to its owner.","The discharge of «اَدَاءٌ» rights and financial transactions.","to give","اداء","2:178-2:283",2
1579,341,"T","دِیَۃٌ","«وَدِیَ ، ودٰی ، یَدِیْ ، دِیَۃٌ» This term is specifically used for the payment of blood money.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَدِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖ» (4:92)\nTranslation: The heirs of the deceased will have to pay the blood money.","«دِیَۃ» to pay the diya.","to give","دیۃ","2:85-2:184-2:196-4:92-37:107-47:4-57:15",7
1580,341,"T","اَثَابَ","«اَثَابَ» is more prevalent than «اَعْطٰی». It is used for the recompense of all deeds, whether good or bad. However, this term is generally employed for the reward of good deeds. Moreover, it also carries a specific nuance, similar to «اَعْطٰی»: to give full compensation for a deed or a little more.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاَثَابَہُمُ اللّٰہُ بِمَا قَالُوۡا جَنّٰتٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ» (5/85)\nTranslation: So Allah rewarded them for what they said with gardens beneath which rivers flow.","«اَثَابَ» refers to giving the reward for any deed in excess of the actual compensation.","to give","اثاب","3:153-5:85-48:18",3
1581,341,"T","وَھْبَ","«وَھْبَ» Giving something to someone without any expectation of compensation or reward, and not anticipating any benefit or return in exchange.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَہَبُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  اِنَاثًا وَّ یَہَبُ  لِمَنۡ  یَّشَآءُ   الذُّکُوۡرَ» ( 42/49 )\nTranslation: Allah grants daughters to whom He wills, and grants sons to whom He wills.","«وَھْبَ» giving without compensation and not expecting any reward or benefit in return.","to grant","وھب","3:8-3:38-6:84-14:39-19:5-19:19-19:49-19:50-19:53-21:72-21:90-25:74-26:21-26:83-29:27-33:50-37:100-38:30-38:35-38:43-42:49",21
1582,341,"T","رَفَدَ","«رَفَدَ» means gift and help. In its meanings, two fundamental aspects are essentially found: giving something to a poor and needy person as a gift, giving a stipend, and stipend allocation. «رَفَادَہ» refers to the fund that the Quraysh used to collect for the assistance of poor pilgrims. «اَرْفَدَ» means allocating a gift for someone so that they continue to receive from that allocated amount (muf). And «رَفَدَ» also means stipend and assistance.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  اُتۡبِعُوۡا فِیۡ ہٰذِہٖ  لَعۡنَۃً وَّ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ؕ بِئۡسَ الرِّفۡدُ  الۡمَرۡفُوۡدُ» (11/99)\nTranslation: And in this world too, a curse was made to follow the people of Pharaoh, and it will continue to do so on the Day of Judgment. Evil is the reward that will continue to be given to them.","«رَفَدَ» Giving a stipend or the like as aid to a poor and destitute person.","to give\n\n(Note: In Islamic contexts, دین (Deen) refers to religion/faith, specifically Islam.)","رفد","11:99",1
1583,341,"T","دفع ( اِلٰی )","«دَفَعَ» means to ward off and remove external dangers and attacks in the protection and support of something (transitive). And when its recompense comes from «اِلٰی», it means to fulfill it, or to entrust or hand over someone's thing to them.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ اٰنَسۡتُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ رُشۡدًا فَادۡفَعُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِمۡ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ» (4/6)\nTranslation: Then if you observe in them sound judgment, entrust to them their wealth.","«دَفَعَ اِلٰی» means to pay or perform, or to entrust something to someone or hand it over.","to give","دفع ( الی )","4:6",1
1584,341,"T","ھَدِیَّۃ","«ھَدِیَّۃ» These are called gifts which we present to each other to foster harmonious relationships. And «مِھْدٰی» is the term for the item in which a gift is placed for presentation. For example: in the Quran it is: «فَمَاۤ  اٰتٰىنِۦَ اللّٰہُ خَیۡرٌ  مِّمَّاۤ   اٰتٰىکُمۡ  ۚ بَلۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  بِہَدِیَّتِکُمۡ  تَفۡرَحُوۡنَ» (27/36) Translation: (Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him) said) What Allah has given me is better than what you have given, so be pleased with your gift.","«ھَدِیَّۃ» Giving gifts to foster harmonious relationships.","to give","ھدیۃ","27:35",1
1585,341,"T","نَحَلَ","«نِحْلَۃً» means giving something to someone. «نَحَلَ الْمِرْاَۃ» denotes giving the woman her due mahr. And «نَحْل» signifies a gift or bestowal (manjad). And «اَلنَّحْلَۃ» and «اَلنِّحْلَۃ» refer to a gift that is given voluntarily. This is specific to hiba because every hiba can be termed nihlah, but not every nihlah can be termed hiba (detailed). For instance, the Quran states: «وَ اٰتُوا النِّسَآءَ صَدُقٰتِہِنَّ نِحۡلَۃً» (4/4). Translation: And give the women their mahr (and maintenance) gladly.","«نِحْلَۃً» To give something to someone as a gift willingly and happily.","to give","نحل","4:4",1
1586,342,"W","جِدَار","«جِدَار» means «جُدُر» and «جُدْرَان» comes from it. «جِدَار» is any one wall from the walls of a house or fortress. «جَدَرَ» means to be enclosed by walls (manjad), and in the words of Ibn al-Faris, «ھُوَ الْحَائِطُ » means the wall of an enclosed structure.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اَمَّا الۡجِدَارُ فَکَانَ لِغُلٰمَیۡنِ یَتِیۡمَیۡنِ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ» (18/82)  \nTranslation: And as for the wall, it belonged to two orphaned boys in the city.","«جِدَار» the wall of a place or enclosure.","Wall","جدار","18:77-18:82-59:14",3
1587,342,"W","سَدّ","«سَدّ» meaning barrier, obstruction. A large wall erected between two things that serves as a barrier and is itself constructed. And if this wall or barrier is natural, it is called «سُدّ» (plural). And «سَدَّ» meaning to seal a crack with stones. And «سِدَاد» is the term for that mixture with which crevices, holes, or cracks are filled. And «سُدَّۃ» in the terminology of physicians refers to the retention of corrupt matter becoming lodged in the intestines:\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَہَلۡ نَجۡعَلُ لَکَ خَرۡجًا عَلٰۤی اَنۡ  تَجۡعَلَ بَیۡنَنَا وَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ  سَدًّا» ( 18/94 )\nTranslation: (O Dhul-Qarnayn!) Shall we gather some wealth for you so that you may build a wall between us and them?","«سَدّ» a wall built between two things that serves as a barrier.","wall","سد","18:93-18:94-36:9",3
1588,342,"W","رَدْم","«رَدْم» This word is more specific than «سَدّ». That is, a wall or barrier whose all holes and cracks have been thoroughly sealed (i.e., a thick wall, a strong barrier). And «رَدَمَ» means to seal holes, cracks, or fissures. And «رَدْمَ الثَّوْب» means to patch or mend clothing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَعِیۡنُوۡنِیۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ  اَجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  رَدۡمًا» (18/95)\nTranslation: (Dhul-Qarnayn replied) Give me the means of strength (or manpower), and I will erect between you and them a strong barrier.","A wall or barrier of which all holes and cracks have been thoroughly sealed.","Wall","ردم","18:95",1
1589,342,"W","سُوْر","«سُوْر» is the high wall of a fortress, etc., which cannot be scaled. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «یَدُلُّ عَلٰی عُلُوِّ وَ اِرْتِفَاعِ (م ۔ ل)» means a high and elevated wall that cannot be scaled to enter inside. And this wall is not of a building but of a fortress's rampart or an enclosure. And «سُوْرَۃ اَلْمَدِیْنَۃ» is called 'the city of refuge' (detailed explanation).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَضُرِبَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ بِسُوۡرٍ لَّہٗ  بَابٌ» (57:13)\nTranslation: So a wall will be drawn between them, within which there will be a gate.","«سُوْر» the towering rampart of a fortress that cannot be scaled.","Wall","سور","38:21-57:13",2
1590,342,"W","بُنْیَان","«بَنٰی» means to construct or build, in such a way that all its parts are interlocked with one another. And «بُنْیَان» refers to every such construction that fulfills this condition, whether it is just a foundation, a wall, or an entire building.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» (61/4)\nTranslation: Allah Almighty loves those who fight in His cause in dense ranks, as if they were a solid structure.","«بُنْیَان» a wall or structure whose parts are firmly interlocked and rooted together.","wall","بنیان","9:109-9:110-16:26-18:21-37:97-61:4",6
1591,343,"E","مَجْنُوْنٌ","«جَنَّ» means to overwhelm and cover something, causing the senses to become veiled. (From *Manjad*.) And «مَجْنُوْن» refers to a person whose senses and faculties are constantly impaired. The Arabs used to call such a person 'majnun' because, in their conception, jinn would enter a human and drive them to madness. In this sense, its meaning would be: a person whom the jinn have driven mad; an afflicted person.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَذٰلِکَ مَاۤ  اَتَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ رَّسُوۡلٍ  اِلَّا  قَالُوۡا  سَاحِرٌ  اَوۡ مَجۡنُوۡنٌ» ( 51/52 )\nTranslation: Thus, there never came to them a messenger before him whom they did not deride as a sorcerer or a madman.\n\nAnd «جِنَّۃ» means both 'jinn' and 'madness'.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اِنۡ ہُوَ  اِلَّا رَجُلٌۢ بِہٖ جِنَّۃٌ» ( 23/25 )\nTranslation: Indeed, this man is afflicted (with madness).","«مَجْنُوْن» meaning mad, crazy, insane, afflicted.","Ecstatic","مجنون","15:6-26:27-37:36-44:14-51:39-51:52-52:29-54:9-68:2-68:51-81:22",11
1592,343,"M","خَبَطَ","«خَبَطَ» means to stun someone by beating them until they lose their senses (intransitive), and «مَخْبُوط» means deficient in intellect (i.e., a person whose intellect has become impaired). That is, whose intellect does not function properly. According to Arab scholars, this feat was also attributed to jinn and devils.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ الرِّبٰوا لَا یَقُوۡمُوۡنَ اِلَّا کَمَا یَقُوۡمُ الَّذِیۡ یَتَخَبَّطُہُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ مِنَ الۡمَسِّ» (2:275)\nTranslation: Those who consume interest will stand [on the Day of Resurrection] like someone driven to madness by the touch of a devil.\n\nThe difference between «خَبَط» and «جُنُوْن» is that «خَبَط» is a temporary and passing affliction, whereas «جُنُوْن» is a long-term condition.","«خَبَطَ» The impairment of the intellect and the occurrence of deficiency within it. And this impairment and deficiency is temporary in nature.","Madman; or lover (in the Sufi sense)","خبط","2:275",1
1593,343,"M","مَفْتُوْن","«فَتَنَ» means: to incite into fitna (chaos/trial), to seduce, to incline (towards evil), and to astonish/confuse. And «مَفْتُوْن» means mad and insane (munjadd). And «مَفْتُوْن» also refers to one whom the vicissitudes of time have rendered intellectually impaired (fatar al-aql) and deprived of senses (hawas bakhtha).  \nFor example, in the Quran:  \n«فَسَتُبۡصِرُ وَ یُبۡصِرُوۡنَ بِاَىیِّکُمُ  الۡمَفۡتُوۡنُ» (68:6)  \nTranslation: So soon you will see, and they (the disbelievers of Mecca) too will see, who among you is insane?","Madness born of the vicissitudes of time.","Madman; insane person. (Also used poetically to mean infatuated or possessed [by love/obsession]).","مفتون","68:6",1
1594,343,"M","سُعُر","«سَعَرَ» meaning the blazing of fire and the emergence of flames. Then, metaphorically, this word is also used in the meanings of inciting or being inflamed. «اِسْتَعَرَّ الِلصَّوْص» meaning bandits flared up. «اِسْتَعَرَّ الْحَرَب» fight flared up. And «مِسْعَرْ» refers to the wood used to kindle a fire (singular), and «سُعُر» denotes a madness wherein a person, upon something, immediately becomes inflamed and begins to do wrong, and his sound intellect does not function. Foolishness.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «فَقَالُوۡۤا اَبَشَرًا مِّنَّا وَاحِدًا نَّتَّبِعُہٗۤ ۙ اِنَّاۤ  اِذًا  لَّفِیۡ ضَلٰلٍ  وَّ  سُعُرٍ» (54/24) Translation: They said, Should we follow a man from among ourselves? Then indeed we would fall into error and madness.","The weakness born of an immediate flare-up of temperament.","Madman","سعر","54:24-54:47",2
1595,344,"T","اَلْقٰی","«لَقِیَ» means two opposing things coming face to face, or meeting. However, when we come to the chapter of verbs (bab al-af'al), its basic meaning changes. «اَلْقٰی» means to throw, place, or set something down in such a way that it becomes visible to others (transitive).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: So Moses threw down his staff, and at once it was a clear serpent.\nThe word «اَلْقٰی» is also used metaphorically.\nFor example: The Almighty God declares:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡتُ عَلَیۡکَ مَحَبَّۃً مِّنِّیۡ» (20/39)\nTranslation: And I cast upon you from Me a love.\nFurthermore, this word is also used for putting a matter into the heart, which is referred to as «اِلْقَاء». This discussion can be seen under putting a matter into the heart.","«اَلْقٰی» meaning to throw, toss, or place something in such a way that others can see it.","to cast","القی","2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4",66
1596,344,"T","سَلَکَ","The discussion on «سَلَکَ» concerning to enter has already been covered. Its basic meanings are to draw one thing into another or to place one thing inside another. In this sense, the word can sometimes mean to throw in or to cast. For example, in the Quran it is stated: «اُسۡلُکۡ یَدَکَ فِیۡ جَیۡبِکَ» (28/32). Translation: Put your hand into your bosom.","«سَلَکَ» to insert one thing into another.","to pour","سلک","15:12-16:69-20:53-23:27-26:200-28:32-39:21-69:32-71:20-72:17-72:27-74:42",12
1597,344,"T","نَبَذَ","The basic meaning of «نَبَذَ» is to throw something away without considering it worthy of attention, or to cast it behind one's back (see the discussion under 'pʰeːŋkna'). Its translation is also sometimes done as 'ḍālnā' (to throw/cast).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَنَبَذۡنٰہُ  بِالۡعَرَآءِ  وَ  ہُوَ  سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/145)\nTranslation: So We cast him onto a bare plain, and he was ill at that time.","«نَبَذَ» to disregard something as unworthy of attention.","to place","نبذ","2:100-2:101-3:187-8:58-20:96-28:40-37:145-51:40-68:49-104:4",10
1598,344,"T","قَذَفَ","«قَذَفَ» meaning to throw from a distance (this discussion is found under throwing), but in some places its translation is also done as to cast. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ  الرُّعۡبَ» (59/2)\nTranslation: And Allah cast terror into their hearts.","«قَذَفَ» to throw or cast with force or intensity.","to pour","قذف","20:39-20:87-21:18-33:26-34:48-34:53-37:8-59:2",8
1599,344,"T","اَفْرَغَ","«فَرَغَ» means to be free from a task, or to become empty as well. Its opposite is «شَغَل». And «اَفْرَغَ الدَّلْو» means to pour water from a jug and empty the jug (transitive), i.e., to gradually place or drop something.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ  اَفۡرِغۡ عَلَیۡنَا صَبۡرًا وَّ ثَبِّتۡ اَقۡدَامَنَا» (2/250)\nTranslation: Our Lord! Pour patience into our hearts and make our feet firm (in the battle).\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«قَالَ اٰتُوۡنِیۡۤ  اُفۡرِغۡ عَلَیۡہِ قِطۡرًا» (18/96)\nTranslation: Dhul-Qarnayn said, Bring me lumps of iron. Then, when he had filled the valley between the two mountain walls, he said, Blow (with bellows). Then when he had made it (the iron) glow like fire, he said, Bring me molten copper to pour over it.","«اَفْرَغَ» to pour or drop in the manner of water slowly seeping from a leather bag.","to put","افرغ","2:250-7:126-18:96",3
1600,344,"T","اَوْقَعَ","The fundamental meanings of «وَقَعَ» are twofold: (1) to be established, and (2) to fall down (transitive). As for «اَوْقَعَ», it signifies bringing something about—that is, to place something and then firmly consolidate it. For instance, the Quran states: «اِنَّمَا یُرِیۡدُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ اَنۡ  یُّوۡقِعَ  بَیۡنَکُمُ الۡعَدَاوَۃَ  وَ الۡبَغۡضَآءَ» (5:91). Translation: Satan seeks only to excite enmity and hatred among you.","to add something and then gather it","to cast","اوقع","4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7",19
1601,345,"T"," اَغْرَقَ","«غَرَقَ» means: a non-aquatic creature sinking to the bottom in water; to drown; to die by drowning in water. And «اَغْرَقَ» means: to cause someone to drown.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اَغۡرَقۡنَاۤ  اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ تَنۡظُرُوۡنَ» (2/50) Translation: And We drowned the people of Pharaoh, and you were looking on.","«اَغْرَقَ» to drown someone.","to immerse","اغرق","2:50-7:64-7:136-8:54-10:73-10:90-11:37-11:43-17:69-17:103-18:71-21:77-23:27-25:37-26:66-26:120-29:40-36:43-37:82-43:55-44:24-71:25-79:1",23
1602,345,"T","صَبَغَ","«صَبَغَ یَدَہٗ فِی الْمَاءِ» means to immerse one's hand in water, and «اَصْبَغْتُ بِالْخَلِّ» means I dipped bread in vinegar and ate it. «صَبَغَ الثَّوْب» means to dye clothes. To immerse clothes in colored water. «صِبْغ» means both color and seasoning. And «صِبْغَۃ» means color. «صَابِغْ» means a dyer. And «صَبَّاغ» means a clothes dyer. (Muf. Manjad) In the Quran, this word appears in both these meanings.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«صِبۡغَۃَ اللّٰہِ ۚ وَ مَنۡ اَحۡسَنُ مِنَ اللّٰہِ صِبۡغَۃً» ( 2/138 )\nTranslation: Color belongs to Allah alone, and who could have a better color (i.e., religion) than His?\n\nAt another place, the command of the Almighty is:\n«تَنۡۢبُتُ بِالدُّہۡنِ وَ صِبۡغٍ  لِّلۡاٰکِلِیۡنَ» ( 23/20 )\nTranslation: (This olive tree) grows producing oil, and it is a seasoning for those who eat.","«اَصْبَغَ» Dip the morsel in sauce or the cloth in colored water.","to drown","صبغ","2:138-23:20",2
1603,346,"T","خَافَ","«خَافَ» denotes the foreboding of an approaching threat based on circumstantial evidence (noun), and its antonym is peace, not fear. In other words, «خَافَ» generally pertains to the future.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «قَالُوۡا لَا تَخَفۡ  اِنَّاۤ  اُرۡسِلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰی  قَوۡمِ  لُوۡطٍ» (11/70)  \nTranslation: (The angels said to Prophet Abraham) “Have no fear; we are sent to the people of Lot.”","Apprehension about the impending danger.","to fear","خاف","2:38-2:62-2:112-2:155-2:182-2:229-2:239-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:170-3:175-4:3-4:9-4:34-4:35-4:83-4:101-4:128-5:23-5:28-5:54-5:69-5:94-5:108-6:15-6:48-6:51-6:80-6:81-7:35-7:49-7:56-7:59-8:26-8:48-8:58-9:28-10:15-10:62-10:83-11:3-11:26-11:70-11:84-11:103-12:13-13:12-13:21-14:14-16:47-16:50-16:112-17:57-17:60-19:5-19:45-20:21-20:45-20:46-20:68-20:77-20:112-24:37-24:50-24:55-26:12-26:14-26:21-26:135-27:10-28:7-28:25-28:31-28:33-28:34-29:33-30:24-30:28-32:16-33:19-38:22-39:13-39:16-39:36-40:26-40:30-40:32-41:30-43:68-46:13-46:21-48:27-50:45-51:28-51:37-55:46-59:16-72:13-74:53-76:7-76:10-79:40-91:15-106:4",105
1604,346,"T","خَشِیَ","«خَشِیَ» A fear that overcomes the heart due to someone's greatness or majesty (sing.). For example, it is in the Quran: «وَ لَا تَقۡتُلُوۡۤا  اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ  خَشۡیَۃَ  اِمۡلَاقٍ» (17/31) Translation: And do not kill your children for fear of poverty.","«خَشِیَ» to be awed by the greatness of something.","to fear","خشی","2:74-4:25-4:77-17:31-17:100-18:80-20:94-21:28-23:57-36:11-50:33-59:21-98:8",13
1605,346,"T","خَشَعَ","«خَشَعَ» refers to fear whose effects become apparent on organs and limbs besides the heart. The softening of the heart (metaphorically) is why this word is also used for «جَوَارَح».\n\nFor example, Allah says in the Quran:\n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ» (70:44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be downcast.\n\nAt another instance, Allah says:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ خَاشِعَۃٌ» (88:2)\nTranslation: Many faces will be humbled on that day (from fear).\n\nAt yet another instance, Allah says:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ» (20:108)\nTranslation: And voices will be stilled (due to fear).\n\nAt another place, Allah says:\n«اَلَمۡ یَاۡنِ  لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اَنۡ  تَخۡشَعَ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ  لِذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (57:16)\nTranslation: Has the time not yet come for the believers that their hearts should soften at the remembrance of Allah?","«خَشَعَ» A fear whose effects are felt even in the limbs and organs.","to fear","خشع","2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2",15
1606,346,"T","اِتَّقٰی","«تَقْوٰی» means fearing the consequences of one's actions. It involves inclining one's nature towards abandoning sins and performing good deeds (as cited). Its opposite is «عُدْوَان». And «اِتَّقٰی» means striving to avoid sins out of fear of their consequences, and adopting piety.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: « کَذٰلِکَ یُبَیِّنُ اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ لِلنَّاسِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ  یَتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/187). Translation: Thus, Allah makes His signs clear to people so that they may adopt piety (fear and avoid).","Abstaining from sins out of fear of the consequences.","to fear","اتقی","2:2-2:21-2:24-2:41-2:48-2:63-2:66-2:103-2:123-2:177-2:179-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:189-2:194-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:206-2:212-2:223-2:224-2:231-2:233-2:237-2:241-2:278-2:281-2:282-2:283-3:15-3:28-3:50-3:76-3:102-3:115-3:120-3:123-3:125-3:130-3:131-3:133-3:138-3:172-3:179-3:186-3:198-3:200-4:1-4:9-4:77-4:128-4:129-4:131-5:2-5:4-5:7-5:8-5:11-5:27-5:35-5:46-5:57-5:65-5:88-5:93-5:96-5:100-5:108-5:112-6:32-6:51-6:69-6:72-6:153-6:155-7:26-7:35-7:63-7:65-7:96-7:128-7:156-7:164-7:169-7:171-7:201-8:1-8:25-8:29-8:34-8:56-8:69-9:4-9:7-9:36-9:44-9:108-9:109-9:115-9:119-9:123-10:6-10:31-10:63-11:49-11:78-12:57-12:90-12:109-13:35-15:45-15:69-16:2-16:30-16:31-16:52-16:81-16:128-19:13-19:18-19:63-19:72-19:85-19:97-20:113-20:132-21:48-22:1-22:32-22:37-23:23-23:32-23:52-23:87-24:34-24:52-25:15-25:74-26:11-26:90-26:106-26:108-26:110-26:124-26:126-26:131-26:132-26:142-26:144-26:150-26:161-26:163-26:177-26:179-26:184-27:53-28:83-29:16-30:31-31:33-33:1-33:32-33:37-33:55-33:70-36:45-37:124-38:28-38:49-39:10-39:16-39:20-39:24-39:28-39:33-39:57-39:61-39:73-40:9-41:18-43:35-43:63-43:67-44:51-45:19-47:15-47:17-47:36-48:26-49:1-49:3-49:10-49:12-49:13-50:31-51:15-52:17-53:32-54:54-57:28-58:9-59:7-59:18-60:11-64:16-65:1-65:2-65:4-65:5-65:10-68:34-69:48-71:3-73:17-74:56-77:41-78:31-91:8-92:5-92:17-96:12",223
1607,346,"T","حَذَرَ","«حَذِرَ» means to avoid or stay away from something frightening (intransitive); to remain vigilant against any danger, to be cautious. To save (transitive). In «حَذِرَ», the danger is sometimes certain, sometimes probable. However, one can avoid this danger through caution (Faqih 200), such as an electrical transformer or naked wire.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said: «یَجۡعَلُوۡنَ اَصَابِعَہُمۡ فِیۡۤ  اٰذَانِہِمۡ مِّنَ الصَّوَاعِقِ حَذَرَ الۡمَوۡتِ» (2/19) Translation: They put their fingers in their ears due to the fear of death at the sound of thunder.\n\nAnd «حِذْر» comes to mean means of protection.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command says: «خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/71) Meaning: Take hold of your weapons. Or, through any other means, be mindful of your protection and safety.","«حَذِرَ» to avoid danger, to fear, and to remain cautious.","To fear (God)","حذر","2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14",17
1608,346,"T","رَاعَ","«رَاعَ» meaning to alarm/disturb and meaning to cause amazement (from najm) «رَوْعَ» meaning heart and «رَعْتُہٗ» meaning to frighten. To alarm. And «نَاقَۃٌ رَوْعَاء» meaning a fearful she-camel (fem.) and «اَلرَّوْع» refers to a state where a person is both amazed by an event and also perceives a hypothetical and imaginary danger, causing them to become alarmed. For example: in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبَ عَنۡ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ الرَّوۡعُ» (11/74)\nTranslation: Then when the fear of Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) began to subside.","«رَاعَ» to marvel and to fear fictitious and imaginary dangers.","to fear","راع","11:74",1
1609,346,"T","اَوْجَسَ","«وَجْسٌ» means to perceive a sound secretly (auditory). To feel fear from something heard. And «اَوْجَسَ» means to attempt to conceal one's fear. And not allowing signs of fear to appear on the face.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰۤ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ لَا تَصِلُ  اِلَیۡہِ  نَکِرَہُمۡ وَ اَوۡجَسَ مِنۡہُمۡ خِیۡفَۃً» (11/70)\nTranslation: When (Prophet Ibrahim عليه السلام) saw that their hands did not reach toward the food, he felt uneasy toward them and concealed his fear from them.","To fear secretly within oneself and try to conceal it.","to fear","اوجس","11:70-20:67-51:28",3
1610,346,"T","وَجَفَ","«وَجَفَ» means to be restless, anxious, and agitated; the heart pounds. It also means to fall from fear (manjada). In «وَجَفَ», two things are found: restlessness and fear, and because of these, the heart begins to pound. For example, in the Quran it is stated: «قُلُوۡبٌ یَّوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاجِفَۃٌ» (79/8). Translation: That Day, people's hearts will be fearful (Jalandhari). Hearts pounding (Usmani).","«وَجَفَ» A pounding heart from fear, accompanied by anxiety and restlessness.","to fear","وجف","79:8",1
1611,346,"T","وَجِلَ","«وَجِلَ» means to feel a quivering fear in the heart (intransitive), and also means for one's hair to stand on end (transitive). It signifies to become overwhelmed with fear, to grow old, and due to one's own inadequacy, to fear someone and be restless (Faqih, p. 202).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَا ذُکِرَ اللّٰہُ وَجِلَتۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ» (8/2)\nTranslation: The believers are those whose hearts tremble with awe when Allah is mentioned.","«وَجِلَ» to fear someone and be restless due to one's own shortcomings.","to fear","وجل","8:2-15:52-15:53-22:35-23:60",5
1612,346,"T","رَھَبَ","This is the term for such fear which also includes anxiety and caution. Its opposite is «رَغِبَ», and «رَاھِبْ» refers to people who fear Allah—the secluded and worshipful. From this derives «رَھْبَاِنیَۃ», meaning to abandon worldly pleasures (munjad), and also means «طول الخوف و استمرارہ» (faq l 200), i.e., to remain constantly fearful.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یُسٰرِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ وَ یَدۡعُوۡنَنَا رَغَبًا وَّ رَہَبًا» (21/90)\nTranslation: They used to race towards good deeds and call upon Us with hope and fear.","«رَھَبَ» Such a fear in which there is both caution and anxiety, and which is prolonged.","to fear","رھب","2:40-7:116-7:154-8:60-16:51-21:90-28:32-59:13",8
1613,346,"T","رَعَبَ","«رُعْب» denotes intensity of fear, terror. And «رُعْب» (in its verbal form) means to be filled with fear, to be overwhelmed by someone's dread.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «لَوِ اطَّلَعۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ لَوَلَّیۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ فِرَارًا  وَّ  لَمُلِئۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ  رُعۡبًا» (18/18). The translation is: If you were to glance at them, you would certainly turn back in flight and be overwhelmed with terror from them.","«رَعَبَ» intense fear and terror.","to fear","رعب","3:151-8:12-18:18-33:26-59:2",5
1614,346,"T","اَشْفَقَ","«شَفِقَ عَلٰی» means to wish well for someone. And «اَشْفَقَ» means to wish good for someone along with fearing harm coming to them (transitive) and means to be concerned with their reform and well-being. To be merciful. To be kind. And «شَفَقَۃ» means kindness. Mercy. Kindness accompanied by fear. And «اَشْفَقَ مِنْہُ» means to fear. To desire (منجد).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ وُضِعَ الۡکِتٰبُ فَتَرَی الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ مُشۡفِقِیۡنَ  مِمَّا فِیۡہِ» (18/49) Translation: And when the record of deeds is laid open, you will see the sinners trembling at what is written therein.","«اَشْفَقَ» along with well-wishing for someone, fearing hardships for them, and experiencing conflicting feelings of fear and compassion.","to fear","اشفق","18:49-21:28-21:49-23:57-33:72-42:18-42:22-52:26-58:13-70:27",10
1616,346,"T","اَنْذَرَ","«اِنْذَار» means to inform, to give news, and to warn of consequences (especially the consequences of deeds and the reckoning of the Day of Judgment). And this task is solely that of Allah and His Messengers. «نَذِیْر» means the warner. Its opposite is «بشیر», meaning the bringer of glad tidings. And «نَذِیْر» also means to warn by elucidating the aspects of warning. And «اِنْذَار» means to warn; indeed, «مُنْذِرْ» means the great favor of the warner (Fiqh 20).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ اَلَمۡ یَاۡتِکُمۡ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡکُمۡ یَقُصُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اٰیٰتِیۡ وَ یُنۡذِرُوۡنَکُمۡ لِقَآءَ یَوۡمِکُمۡ ہٰذَا ؕ» (6/130)\n\nTranslation: O assembly of jinn and mankind! Did there not come to you messengers from among you, who used to recite to you My verses and warn you of the meeting of this Day?","Warning the prophets and messengers about the consequences of their deeds and their reckoning.","to fear","انذر","2:6-2:119-2:213-4:165-5:19-6:19-6:48-6:51-6:92-6:130-7:2-7:63-7:69-7:184-7:188-9:122-10:2-10:73-10:101-11:2-11:12-11:25-13:7-14:44-14:52-15:89-16:2-17:105-18:2-18:4-18:56-19:39-19:97-21:45-22:49-25:1-25:7-25:51-25:56-26:115-26:173-26:194-26:208-26:214-27:58-27:92-28:46-29:50-32:3-33:45-34:28-34:34-34:44-34:46-35:18-35:23-35:24-35:37-35:42-36:6-36:10-36:11-36:70-37:72-37:73-37:177-38:4-38:65-38:70-39:71-40:15-40:18-41:4-41:13-42:7-43:23-44:3-46:3-46:9-46:12-46:21-46:29-48:8-50:2-51:50-51:51-53:56-54:5-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:23-54:30-54:33-54:36-54:37-54:39-54:41-67:8-67:9-67:17-67:26-71:1-71:2-74:2-74:36-76:7-77:6-78:40-79:45-92:14",111
1617,346,"T","اَوْعَدَ","The term «اَوْعَدَ» is general, meaning to give someone hope. However, *wa'eed* (وعید) refers to the consequence of a bad deed and its punishment—a threat. And «اَوْعَدَ» means to threaten, to frighten, to intimidate—whether verbally or by practically providing such means.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡعُدُوۡا بِکُلِّ صِرَاطٍ تُوۡعِدُوۡنَ وَ تَصُدُّوۡنَ عَنۡ  سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (7/86)\nTranslation: And do not sit on every path, threatening and frightening those who have believed in Allah, and hindering them from the way of Allah.","«اَوْعَدَ» to frighten, to threaten, to intimidate.","to fear","اوعد","6:134-7:86-11:17-11:81-14:14-15:43-18:48-18:58-18:59-19:75-20:58-20:59-20:86-20:87-20:97-20:113-21:103-21:109-23:36-23:93-26:206-36:63-38:53-41:30-43:83-46:16-46:35-50:14-50:20-50:28-50:32-50:45-51:5-51:22-51:60-54:46-70:42-70:44-72:24-72:25-77:7-",41
1618,347,"D","دَلْو","«دَلْو» A container for drawing water from a well, such as a bucket, pail, etc. (provided it is empty of water) (ف ل ۔ 32 )\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)\nTranslation: And a caravan came. They sent their water-drawer to the well. He let down his bucket (into the well).","And «دَلْو» a bucket that is completely empty.\nAnd «ذَنُوْب» a bucket that is completely filled with water.\nAnd «سِجْل» a bucket that has some water in it.","dole","دلو","12:19",1
1619,347,"B","ذنُوْب","«ذنُوْب» A vessel for drawing water, such as a bucket or pail, when it is filled with water (Fal 31).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِنَّ لِلَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا ذَنُوۡبًا مِّثۡلَ ذَنُوۡبِ اَصۡحٰبِہِمۡ» (51/59)\nTranslation: So the bucket of these wrongdoers has also become full, just as the bucket of their companions was filled.\nMeaning: Morally, these oppressors have also reached that same depth of degradation, and the measure of their existence has become brimful, just as it was for other wrongdoers like them.","«ذنُوْب» a vessel for drawing water.","Bucket","ذنوب","51:59",1
1620,347,"D","جُنّٓۃ","«جُنّٓۃ» meaning a shield. A shield is a well-known weapon of defense used to stop an attack by placing it in front of the enemy's strike, thereby protecting oneself. Its use occurs in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِتَّخَذُوۡۤا  اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ جُنَّۃً  فَصَدُّوۡا عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» ( 58/16 )\nTranslation: They have taken their oaths as a shield (to obstruct others) and have hindered (people) from the path of Allah.","«جُنّٓۃ» meaning 'shield', a weapon used for defense against attacks.","drum","جنٓۃ","58:16-63:2",2
1621,347,"V","عُرْضَۃً","«عَرَضَ» means to present. And «عُرْضَۃ» is every thing that can be placed in front as a shield, whether it is a shield or any other thing (M. Q). And «عُرْضَۃ» also means target. And «ھُوَ عُرْضَۃٌ لِلنَّاسِ» is that which has become a target of people's ridicule and sarcasm. And «ھُوَ عُرْضَۃٌ لِلْکَلَامِ» is that which is the target of objections (Manjad). It seems that «عُرْضَۃً» is used in a wider meaning than «جُنَّۃ».\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَجۡعَلُوا اللّٰہَ عُرۡضَۃً  لِّاَیۡمَانِکُمۡ» (2/224)\nTranslation: And do not make Allah the target of your oaths.","«عُرْضَۃً» is anything that functions as collateral.","Vessel","عرضۃً","2:224",1
1622,348,"T","جَنَّ","«جَنَّ» To cover something so that it becomes hidden from sight (transitive verb). Those creatures that remain hidden from sight, and «جَنِیْن» is what the child in the mother's womb is called.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا جَنَّ عَلَیۡہِ الَّیۡلُ  رَاٰ کَوۡکَبًا» ( 6/76 )\nTranslation: Then when the night covered them (with a veil of darkness), he (Prophet Ibrahim ﷺ) saw a star.","«جَنَّ» to cover and conceal from view.","To cover","جن","6:76",1
1623,348,"T","غَشِیَ","To cover one thing with another. (e.g.) In such a way that it is not completely lost. (detailed)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا غَشِیَہُمۡ مَّوۡجٌ کَالظُّلَلِ دَعَوُا اللّٰہَ مُخۡلِصِیۡنَ لَہُ الدِّیۡنَ» (31/32)\nTranslation: And when the waves, like awnings, cover them (from the sea or ocean), they call upon Allah, devoting their worship solely to Him.\n\nAnd «اَغشٰی ، غَشّٰی» and «تَغَشّٰی». All these are transitive with «غَشِیَ».\n\nNow consider some more examples.\n\nExample 1: The Divine Command states:\n«یُغۡشِی الَّیۡلَ النَّہَارَ» (13/3)\nTranslation: Allah is the One who clothes the night with the day.\n\nExample 2: The Divine Command states:\n«اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ» (8/11)\nTranslation: When drowsiness had overcome you.\n\nExample 3: The Divine Command states:\n«فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا» (7/189)\nTranslation: Then when the man has covered the woman (for intercourse).","to cover something without completely hiding it","to veil","غشی","3:154-7:54-7:189-8:11-10:27-11:5-13:3-14:50-20:78-24:40-29:55-31:32-33:19-36:9-44:11-47:20-53:16-53:54-71:7-91:4-92:1",21
1624,348,"T","رَھِقَ","«رَھَقَہُ الْاَمْر» means a matter has been suppressed or forced down by coercion and compulsion. And «رَھِقَ» and «اَرْھَقَ» both have the same meaning (muf), and «لَا اَرْھَقَ اللہُ» means May Allah not afflict you with hardship and toil (minjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (68/43)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be downcast, and humiliation will cover them.","«رَھَقَ» force, coercion, and oppression: to suppress or overwhelm one thing with another.","to veil","رھق","10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41",9
1625,349,"T","زَال ( زول ) زَالَتِ الشَّمْس","«زَوَال» means the setting of the sun. And «زَوَال» also means the sun setting from overhead. And the time of setting (munajid) is also used for something reaching its peak and then gradually descending. Its opposite is «عُرُوْج». And *zawāl* means something inclining and moving away from its correct direction (muf). And «زَالَ عَنْہُ مُلْکُہٗ» means its dominion has been removed (m. q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ  تَکُوۡنُوۡۤا اَقۡسَمۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلُ  مَا  لَکُمۡ  مِّنۡ  زَوَالٍ» (14/44)\nTranslation: Did you not use to take oaths before this that you would not decline?","«زَوَال» descend from a height.","to be bestowed (divine blessings)","زال ( زول ) زالت الشمس","14:44",1
1626,349,"T","دُلُوْک","«دَلَکَتِ الشَّمْسُ دُلُوْکًا» meaning to incline for sunset, and «اَلْدَلْک» meaning slackness (from prayer).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ  لِدُلُوۡکِ الشَّمۡسِ اِلٰی غَسَقِ  الَّیۡلِ وَ  قُرۡاٰنَ  الۡفَجۡرِ» (17/78)\nTranslation: Establish prayer from the declining of the sun until the darkness of the night and recite the Quran at dawn.","«دُلُوْک» meaning to set (like the sun).","to soften","دلوک","17:78",1
1627,350,"T","طَلَبَ","«طَلْب» meaning to desire, to want, to search (Manjad), and meaning to seek and strive to attain something (Maf). The term is employed in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَوۡ یُصۡبِحَ  مَآؤُہَا غَوۡرًا  فَلَنۡ تَسۡتَطِیۡعَ  لَہٗ  طَلَبًا» (18/41)\nTranslation: So that you would not find it, even if you searched for it.","«طَلْب» to seek or desire something.","to search","طلب","7:54-18:41-22:73",3
1628,350,"T","اِبْتَغٰی","Ibn al-Faris has essentially given two basic meanings for «بَغْی»: (1) «طَلَبَ الشَّیْ», meaning the desire for something; and (2) «جِنْس مِنَ الْفَسَاد», meaning a type of corruption, such as rebellion and sedition, etc. Meanwhile, Imam Raghb combines both of these and defines it as: to go slightly beyond the bounds of moderation in seeking something (mufradat), and «اِبْتَغَاء» is used for seeking something with effort/striving (mujarrad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/35)\nTranslation: So if you have power, then seek a tunnel in the earth or a ladder in the sky (to escape).","«اِبْتِغَاء» to try to search for something.","to search","ابتغی","2:187-2:198-2:207-2:265-2:272-3:7-3:85-4:24-4:94-4:104-4:114-4:139-5:2-5:35-6:35-6:114-9:48-13:17-13:22-16:14-17:12-17:28-17:42-17:57-17:66-17:110-23:7-24:33-28:55-28:73-28:77-29:17-30:23-30:46-33:51-35:12-45:12-48:29-57:27-59:8-60:1-62:10-66:1-70:31-73:20-92:20",46
1629,350,"T","تَحَسَّسَ","«اَحَسَّ» means to perceive. And «تَحَسَّسَ» means to employ all five senses fully in the search for something, i.e., to strive tirelessly in searching for a lost item. This is a commendable quality.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰبَنِیَّ اذۡہَبُوۡا فَتَحَسَّسُوۡا مِنۡ یُّوۡسُفَ وَ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/87)\nTranslation: (Prophet Jacob) said, O my sons, go and search for Joseph and his brother.","To employ the five senses in search of something that is external or related to outside circumstances.","to search","تحسس","12:87",1
1630,350,"T","تَجَسَّسَ","The meaning of «جَسَّ» is to ascertain the internal condition of a patient by feeling the pulse. This is distinct from «حَسَّ». For «حَسَّ» employs the five senses to discern external conditions, whereas «جَسَّ» refers to knowing internal states. The word spy (جاسوس) is derived from this (مف). And «تَجَسُّسْ» means to probe secrets, to spy, to engage in espionage, and to search for the faults and weaknesses of others, then to inform others about them. And this is a blameworthy (reprehensible) trait.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا تَجَسَّسُوۡا وَ لَا یَغۡتَبۡ بَّعۡضُکُمۡ بَعۡضًا» ( 49/12 )\nTranslation: And do not spy or backbite one another.","«تَجَسُّس» to pry into someone's faults and weaknesses, seeking them out and then spreading them to others.","to search","تجسس","49:12",1
1631,350,"T","اِلْتَمَسَ","«لَمَسَ» means to feel or grope for something with the hands or fingers. And «اَلْتَمَسَ» means to search for something by touching repeatedly. (Fa 171) To demand something repeatedly. To make continuous efforts in searching.\n\nFor example: It is stated in the Holy Quran:\n«قِیۡلَ ارۡجِعُوۡا وَرَآءَکُمۡ فَالۡتَمِسُوۡا نُوۡرًا» (57:13)\nTranslation: It will be said to them, Turn back and seek light there.","to persistently seek something","to search","التمس","57:13-72:8",2
1632,350,"T","جَاسَ","«جَاسَ» To go to extremes in seeking something. (Fatwa 171) To search for something with great greed. (Ma'ariful Quran)\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» (17/5) Translation: We have made against you Our servants given to might, who entered the cities.","«جَاسَ» to go to extremes in seeking something; to search with intense greed.","to search","جاس","17:5",1
1633,350,"T","بَعْثَرَ","«بَعْثَرَ» means to search out and extract. And «بَعْثَرَ الْمَتَاعَ» means to turn things upside down (munjad). The word «بُعْثِرَ» is actually formed from «بُعِثَ» and «عُثِرَ», combining the meanings of both verbs, i.e., to turn over and raise the dead (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ  اِذَا الۡقُبُوۡرُ بُعۡثِرَتۡ» (82:4)\nTranslation: And when the graves are turned upside down.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine declaration states:\n«اَفَلَا یَعۡلَمُ  اِذَا بُعۡثِرَ مَا فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (100:9)\nTranslation: Does he not know that when what is in the graves is brought out.","«بَعْثَرَ» to find something by turning things over.","to search","بعثر","82:4-100:9",2
1634,350,"T","تَحَرّٰی","«حَرُّو» or «حَرّٰی» and «اَلْاَحْرٰی» mean: more worthy, more suitable, better. And «تَحَرّٰی» means: to seek what is more suitable and worthy in usage; to seek the better of two things (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ اَنَّا مِنَّا  الۡمُسۡلِمُوۡنَ وَ مِنَّا الۡقٰسِطُوۡنَ ؕ فَمَنۡ  اَسۡلَمَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ تَحَرَّوۡا  رَشَدًا» (72:14)\nTranslation: And that among us are some who are obedient (to Allah) and some who are unjustly sinful. So those who obeyed have sought the best way [of guidance].","Seeking what is better and more suitable.","to search","تحری","72:14",1
1635,351,"T","ذَبَحَ","«ذَبَحَ» Slitting the throat of an animal in the prescribed Shariah manner and expelling the innate heat (i.e., the physical warmth upon which life is based) (pl.). For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَذَبَحُوۡہَا وَ مَا کَادُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» ( 2/71 )\nTranslation: So they slaughtered the cow, even though they were reluctant to do so.","«ذَبَحَ» to slaughter an animal according to the recognized Islamic method.","to slaughter","ذبح","2:49-2:67-2:71-5:3-14:6-27:21-28:4-37:102-37:107",9
1636,351,"T","ذَکّٰی","«ذَکّٰی» To slaughter an animal in such a way that its soul departs quickly and effortlessly (M. L.), and meaning to pronounce the takbir over a hunted animal and then leave it, and later slaughter it according to the specific Shariah method (Muf).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَکَلَ السَّبُعُ اِلَّا مَا ذَکَّیۡتُمۡ» (5:3)\nTranslation: ...and that which is killed by a predator, but that which you slaughter (before its death)...","«ذَکّٰی» Consideration of the animal's ease during slaughter.","to slaughter","ذکی","5:3",1
1637,351,"T","نَحَر","«نَحَرَ» means to strike the chest, to slaughter. And «نَحْر» means the upper part of the chest, and its plural is «نَحُوْر». And «اِنْتَحَرَ» means to commit suicide. And «یَوْمُ النَّحْر» means the day of sacrifice, i.e., the 10th of the month of Dhu al-Hijjah (Munjid). And «نَحَرَ» means to perform the sacrifice or to cut the throat or to engage in combat (M. Q); thus, the original meaning of «نَحْر» is to cut the throat, whether this occurs in the form of mere slaughter or sacrifice. Whether done with a spear or a knife, and whether the animal is slaughtered while standing or laid down.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَصَلِّ  لِرَبِّکَ وَ انۡحَرۡ» (108/2)\nTranslation: So pray to your Lord and sacrifice.","«نَحَرَ» Any form of throat-cutting, whether it is termed as slaughter, sacrifice, or any other manner.","to slaughter","نحر","108:2",1
1638,352,"M","سَبَب","«سَبَب» This refers to the rope used for climbing up and down date palms. Then, by that same analogy, anything that serves as a means to reach something else is called a cause (sabab). Furthermore, this term is also applied to a path and its related equipment.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ اٰتَیۡنٰہُ مِنۡ کُلِّ شَیۡءٍ سَبَبًا فَاَتۡبَعَ  سَبَبًا» (18/84)  \nTranslation: We had granted Dhul-Qarnayn every kind of resource, so he pursued a path.","That which serves as a means to reach something else.","means","سبب","2:166-18:84-18:85-18:89-18:92-22:15-38:10-40:36-40:37",9
1639,352,"M","وَسِیْلَۃ","«وَسَلَ» meaning to reach something with inclination (sing.), and «وَسَلَ اِلَی اللہ» meaning to attain proximity to Allah. And «اَلْوَاسَطَہ» and «اَلْوَسِیْلَۃ» meaning the means of proximity, degree, rank (from Munjid).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ابۡتَغُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِ الۡوَسِیۡلَۃَ وَ جَاہِدُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ» (5:35)\nTranslation: And continue to seek the means of their nearness and strive in its way.","«وَسِیْلَۃ» the means chosen for attaining nearness.","means","وسیلۃ","5:35-17:57",2
1640,353,"H","ذِلَّۃ","«ذِلَّۃ» meaning subordination (i.e., being defeated), weakness. Being crushed under force and power (lit. 'to be pressed down'), and its opposite «عِزّۃ» meaning superiority (i.e., dominance or power).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ضُرِبَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الذِّلَّۃُ  اَیۡنَ مَا ثُقِفُوۡۤا» (3/112)\nTranslation: Wherever they are found, humiliation has been decreed for them.","«ذِلَّۃ» The ruler who bows before the powerful but oppresses the weak and his subordinates.","humiliation","ذلۃ","2:61-3:112-7:152-10:26-10:27-68:43-70:44",7
1641,353,"H","صَغَار","«صَغَار» meaning the humiliation of becoming subservient after battle and its acknowledgment and confession (Fiqh 207). Enduring the humiliation of becoming a subject after being a ruler or free.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «سَیُصِیۡبُ الَّذِیۡنَ اَجۡرَمُوۡا صَغَارٌ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ» (6/124) Translation: And the sinners will be humiliated by Allah.","«صَغَار» The humiliation of being reduced after greatness, and the acknowledgment of it.","Humiliation","صغار","6:124",1
1642,353,"I","خِزْی","«خِزْی» meaning disgrace, shame; falling in the eyes of others due to one's bad deeds (intransitive). And if this is limited merely to oneself, it is called remorse (intransitive).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«لَقَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡتَ  اِلَیۡنَا رَسُوۡلًا فَنَتَّبِعَ اٰیٰتِکَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ  نَّذِلَّ  وَ  نَخۡزٰی» (20/134)\nTranslation: They will say, Our Lord! Why did You not send a messenger to us so that we could follow Your revelations and commands before we are humiliated and disgraced?","«خِزْی» to lose face.","Ignominy","خزی","2:85-2:114-5:33-5:41-9:63-10:98-11:66-16:27-22:9-39:26-41:16",11
1643,353,"A","ھُوْن","«ھُوْن» means disgrace, humiliation, ignominy (for the feminine form), abasement, and contempt (for the masculine form).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَتَوَارٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡمِ مِنۡ سُوۡٓءِ مَا بُشِّرَ بِہٖ ؕ اَیُمۡسِکُہٗ عَلٰی ہُوۡنٍ اَمۡ  یَدُسُّہٗ  فِی التُّرَابِ» (16:59)\nTranslation: He conceals himself from people because of the evil of the bad news he has heard. Should he keep her with contempt (or humiliation) or bury her in the ground? Unquestionably, evil is what they decide.\n\nAnd «ھَوْن» (with a *zabar* on the letter ha) means gentleness. And this is a praiseworthy (good) attribute.\nAs Allah the Most High says while describing the attributes of the believers:\n«وَ عِبَادُ  الرَّحۡمٰنِ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَمۡشُوۡنَ عَلَی الۡاَرۡضِ ہَوۡنًا» (25:63)\nTranslation: And the servants of the Most Merciful are those who walk upon the earth easily (with gentleness and humility).","To endure humiliation due to being deemed insignificant.","Abasement","ھون","6:93-16:59-25:63-41:17-46:20",5
1644,354,"H","اَذِلَّۃ","«اَذِلَّۃ» is the plural of dhaleel (ذلیل), and its opposite is «اَعِزَّۃ», which is the plural of «عَزِیْز». In our common understanding, the meaning of dhaleel is taken as vile, mean, and contemptible. And the meaning of «عَزِیْز» is taken as close relatives. Both of these meanings are lexically incorrect. In reality, the meaning of dhaleel is under authority (subjugated, powerless, weak). And the meaning of «عَزِیْز» is having authority over (i.e., to have power over someone, to use force, to establish dominance). Understanding the meaning of «ذَلِیْل» is impossible and difficult without contrasting it with «عَزِیْز». In the Quran, this word has been used in this very meaning. For example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» (3/123)\nTranslation: And Allah had already given you victory at Badr while you were weak.","«ذَلِیْل» generally describes a person as worthless, dishonorable, despicable, and weak.","humble","اذلۃ","3:123-5:54-27:34-27:37",4
1645,354,"A","مَھِیْن","«مَھَنَ» means humble, weak. And «مَھِیْن» means contemptible, dishonorable, degraded and humiliated (m. q.). And according to Imam Raghīb, «مَھِیْن» refers to a person over whom another human being has gained dominance, thereby disgracing and humiliating him. (muf)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَمۡ اَنَا خَیۡرٌ  مِّنۡ ہٰذَا الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ  مَہِیۡنٌ» (43/52)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) Am I not better than this contemptible man?","«مَھِیْن» meaning degraded, brought low in the eyes of others due to one's own evil deeds.","Abased","مھین","2:90-3:178-4:14-4:37-4:102-4:151-22:57-31:6-32:8-33:57-34:14-43:52-44:30-45:9-58:5-58:16-68:10-77:20",18
1646,354,"H","صَاغِرْ","«صِغْر» is the opposite of «کِبْر». And «صَغَارٌ» means humiliation. And «صَاغِر» means one who is forced into subjugation while possessing a secondary status, along with the madness of arrogance and humiliation, and who acknowledges and confesses it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«حَتّٰی یُعۡطُوا  الۡجِزۡیَۃَ  عَنۡ ‌یَّدٍ  وَّ ہُمۡ  صٰغِرُوۡنَ» (9:29)\nTranslation: (Fight them) until they are humiliated and pay the jizya with their own hands.","One who steps down from rulership to subjecthood and acknowledges this.","humiliated","صاغر","7:13-7:119-9:29-12:32-27:37",5
1647,354,"A","دَاخِر","In it, three things are found: humility, humiliation, and contempt. And 'dakhir' refers to one who, due to a deficiency in intellect and reason, accepts humiliation submissively by regarding it as insignificant. For example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ یَسۡتَکۡبِرُوۡنَ عَنۡ عِبَادَتِیۡ سَیَدۡخُلُوۡنَ جَہَنَّمَ دٰخِرِیۡنَ» (40/60) Translation: Those who turn away from My worship out of arrogance will enter Hell in a state of humiliation. At another instance, the command of the Most High is: «وَ یَوۡمَ یُنۡفَخُ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَفَزِعَ مَنۡ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ مَنۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اِلَّا مَنۡ شَآءَ  اللّٰہُ ؕ وَ  کُلٌّ   اَتَوۡہُ   دٰخِرِیۡنَ» (27/87) Translation: And on the Day when the Trumpet is blown, all those in the heavens and the earth will be terrified except those whom Allah wills, and all will come to Him in a state of helplessness.","«دَاخِر» to become someone's obedient and subservient in a humiliating manner due to lack of intellect.","Abased","داخر","16:48-27:87-37:18-40:60",4
1648,354,"A","اَرْاذَلَ","«رَذْل» is the plural of «اَرْذَلَ», meaning deserving of contempt or ugly (Minjd). «دُوْنَ مِنْ کُلِّ شَیْءٍ» (m.l.) and «اَرْذَل» mean cheap, deficient, or worthless (Minjd). It refers to people of such a lowly, worthless grade that others do not pay attention to them due to their insignificance (m.f.). For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَا نَرٰىکَ اتَّبَعَکَ اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ اَرَاذِلُنَا بَادِیَ الرَّاۡیِ» (11:27). Translation: And we see nothing but that those who follow you are people of weak intellect like us.","«اَرْذَلَ» vile, despicable, lowly, and utterly contemptible.","Abased","اراذل","11:27-16:70-22:5-26:111",4
1649,354,"A","أَسْفَل","«اَلسَّفْلَۃ» despicable people, such as «دُوْن» and «اَسْفَل», mean 'low' and 'contemptible' (pl.), and their opposite is «اَعْلٰی». For example, in the Quran it is: «نَجۡعَلۡہُمَا تَحۡتَ اَقۡدَامِنَا لِیَکُوۡنَا مِنَ الۡاَسۡفَلِیۡنَ» (41/29) Translation: We shall trample them underfoot so that they become humiliated.","low and despicable in comparison to the Exalted","Abased","أسفل","4:145-8:42-9:40-33:10-37:98-41:29-95:5",7
1650,354,"A","خَاسِئ","«خَسَاَ» has two meanings: (1) meaning the tiredness or weakening of the eyes, and (2) meaning «خَاسِئُ مِنَ الْخَنَازِیْرِ وَ الْکِلَاب» scolded dogs and pigs that are not permitted to be let loose among people (manjad). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَ لَقَدۡ عَلِمۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ اعۡتَدَوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ فِی السَّبۡتِ فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ» (2/65) Translation: And (O Jews! You know those who transgressed the Sabbath, so We said to them, Be apes, despised and humiliated.)","«خَاسِئ» utterly disgraced. Most degraded.","Abased","خاسئ","2:65-7:166-23:108-67:4",4
1651,354,"A","اَذَلَّ","«اَذَلَّ» is its opposite «اَعَزَّ». To subjugate someone (i.e., bring them under control). And in it, the aspect of being defeated is prominent (Faqih 208). Moreover, the Most High can make the lowly dominant. For example: the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تُعِزُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ وَ تُذِلُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ» (3:26)\nTranslation: (O Allah!) You grant honor to whom You will and subject to disgrace whom You will.","«اَذَلَّ» To make the inferior subservient to the Most High, or to humiliate.","Abased","اذل","3:26-58:20-63:8",3
1652,354,"A","اَھَانَ","«اَھَانَ» is the opposite of «اَکْرَمَ». That is, due to enmity, to consider someone insignificant or weak, or to do so. And to insult them. And to insult them, and even an equal person can do this. And also someone of higher status (Faqih 208).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ مَنۡ  یُّہِنِ اللّٰہُ  فَمَا لَہٗ  مِنۡ مُّکۡرِمٍ» (22/18)  \nTranslation: And there is no one who can grant honor to whom Allah disgraces.","«اَھَانَ» to insult and humiliate someone out of enmity, and even a person of equal status can do this.","Abased","اھان","22:18-25:69-89:16",3
1653,354,"A","اَخْزٰی","«اَخْزٰی» To humiliate and disgrace, wherein a person's own evil deeds are involved, and people are aware of them.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُخۡزِنَا یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/194)\nTranslation: O Allah! Do not disgrace us on the Day of Resurrection.","«اَخْزٰی» to humiliate someone due to their apparent physical flaw.","Abased","اخزی","3:192-3:194-9:2-9:14-11:39-11:78-11:93-15:69-16:27-20:134-26:87-39:40-41:16-59:5-66:8",15
1654,354,"A","فَضَحَ","«فَضَحَ» To expose someone's faults. To degrade someone in the eyes of others. To humiliate someone in front of others (manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ  اِنَّ ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ ضَیۡفِیۡ فَلَا تَفۡضَحُوۡنِ» (15/68)\nTranslation: Prophet Lut (peace be upon him) said, These people are my guests. Do not humiliate me in front of them.","«فَضَحَ» defaming someone by speaking ill of them, thereby lowering them in the eyes of others.","Abased","فضح","15:68",1
1655,354,"H","اَزْدَرٰی","«زَرٰی» to consider someone as extremely despicable and dishonorable, and «زُرِیُّ» the person who is so insignificant that they are not even counted (Quranic meaning). For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَّ لَاۤ  اَقُوۡلُ لِلَّذِیۡنَ تَزۡدَرِیۡۤ اَعۡیُنُکُمۡ  لَنۡ  یُّؤۡتِیَہُمُ  اللّٰہُ خَیۡرًا» (11/31). Translation: And I do not say that those whom you look at with disdain, Allah will not grant them good (wealth and property or the reward of good deeds).","to regard someone as utterly despicable and disgraceful","Humiliated","ازدری","11:31",1
1656,354,"H","کَبَتَ","«کَبَتَ» means to return with hardship and humiliation (transitive), and to mean to humiliate. To return. To turn back. To reject in anger. To destroy (from *Najd*). This word comes in the context of anger with the meanings of humiliating, degrading, and disgracing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَآدُّوۡنَ اللّٰہَ  وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ کُبِتُوۡا کَمَا کُبِتَ الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ  قَبۡلِہِمۡ» ( 58/5 )\nTranslation: Those who oppose Allah and His Messenger will be humiliated just as those before them were humiliated.","to humiliate and disgrace someone in a state of anger","Humiliated","کبت","3:127-58:5",2
1657,355,"R","ذِمَّۃ","«ذِمَّۃ» denotes a type of covenant—a pledge of loyalty, trust, protection, and responsibility—and is referred to as a covenant and pledge. «اَنْتَ فِیْ ذِمَّۃِ اللہِ» means you are under Allah's protection. And «ذِمِّی» or «اَھْلِ الذّمّۃ» refers to those non-Muslims who, under the covenant and pledge, reside in Dar al-Islam by paying jizya to the Muslims, thereby living under their protection and security. (mentioned) Sometimes this term is used solely to mean upholding the covenant and pledge and its responsibilities.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9:10) Translation: These people do not uphold any ties of kinship or covenant with a believer.","«ذِمَّۃ» refers to the responsibility of fulfilling covenants with others.","Responsibility","ذمۃ","9:8-9:10",2
1658,355,"T","نَحْب","«نَحْب» refers to a vow whose fulfillment becomes obligatory (mandatory). And «نَحَبَ الرَّجُل» means that a person has imposed something upon himself. Thus, «نَحْب» signifies a responsibility that a person has voluntarily made binding upon himself, whether it be the responsibility of a vow or that of a covenant.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ قَضٰی نَحۡبَہٗ  وَ مِنۡہُمۡ مَّنۡ یَّنۡتَظِرُ» (33:23)\nTranslation: Then among them are some who have fulfilled their pledge (to go for jihad) and some are still waiting.","The responsibility of fulfilling a self-imposed obligation is termed «نَحْب».","The accountability","نحب","33:23",1
1659,356,"N","لَیْل","«لَیْل» is a well-known term meaning night, and its opposite «نَھَار» means day. «لَیْل» refers to the period from sunset to sunrise. In the Quran, in many places, night and day or both together are mentioned. The night is divided into 12 hours or 12 watches. The names of these hours in sequence are: «شَفَقَ ، غَسَقَ ، عَتَمَہ ، دَقَّۃَ ، فَحَّمَہ ، زُلْفَۃ ، زَلْقَۃ ، بَھْرَۃ ، سَحَر ، فَجَر ، صَبَحَ ، صَبَاح» (Surah 2, verse 92).","«لَیْل» meaning night.","Night","لیل","2:51-2:164-2:187-2:274-3:27-3:113-3:190-6:13-6:60-6:76-6:96-7:54-7:142-10:6-10:24-10:27-10:67-11:81-11:114-13:3-13:10-14:33-15:65-16:12-17:1-17:12-17:78-17:79-20:130-21:20-21:33-21:42-22:61-23:80-24:44-25:47-25:62-27:86-28:71-28:72-28:73-30:23-31:29-34:33-35:13-36:37-36:40-37:138-39:5-39:9-40:61-41:37-41:38-44:3-44:23-45:5-50:40-51:17-52:49-57:6-71:5-73:2-73:6-73:20-74:33-76:26-78:10-79:29-81:17-84:17-89:4-91:4-92:1-93:2-97:1-97:2-97:3",77
1660,356,"N","بَیَاتًا","«بَاتَ» meaning to spend the night, to pass the night.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64)\nTranslation: And those who spend the night before their Lord in prostration and standing in prayer.\n\nAnd «بَیَاتًا» meaning during any part of the night, while sleeping, in a state of sleep.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ اِنۡ اَتٰىکُمۡ عَذَابُہٗ بَیَاتًا اَوۡ نَہَارًا» (10/50)\nTranslation: Say, Have you considered: if the punishment of Allah should come to you by night or by day...","«بَیَاتًا» meaning to spend the night.","Night","بیاتًا","7:4-7:97-10:50",3
1661,356,"N","بَاتَ","«بَاتَ» means to spend the night, to pass the night, and the place where one spends the night is the house (i.e., home). (m.l)\nFor instance, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یَبِیۡتُوۡنَ لِرَبِّہِمۡ سُجَّدًا وَّ قِیَامًا» (25/64)\nTranslation: And those who remain standing in prayer before their Lord, spending the nights in worship.","«بَاتَ» means spending the night, passing the night, and the place where one spends the night.","Night","بات","25:64",1
1662,356,"N","بَیَّت","«بَیَّت» meaning: To gather at home after some part of the night has passed and consult on a matter (e.g.).\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«اِذۡ  یُبَیِّتُوۡنَ مَا لَا یَرۡضٰی مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ» (4:108)\nTranslation: When they consult at night concerning matters He does not like.\nFor example: The Quran says:\n«قَالُوۡا تَقَاسَمُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ لَنُبَیِّتَنَّہٗ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ ثُمَّ لَنَقُوۡلَنَّ لِوَلِیِّہٖ مَا شَہِدۡنَا مَہۡلِکَ  اَہۡلِہٖ» (27:49)\nTranslation: They said, Swear by Allah that we will attack him and his household by night. Then we will say to his heir, 'We were not present at the destruction of his household.'","«بَیَّت» To gather at home after a portion of the night has passed in order to consult on a matter.","Night","بیت","4:81-4:108-27:49",3
1663,356,"N","اَسْرٰی","«اَسْرٰی» meaning: to take for a walk at night; to lead out; to take away.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ  اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» (17/1)\nTranslation: Glory be to the One Who took His servant by night from the Sacred Mosque to the Farthest Mosque.","«اَسْرٰی» meaning to stroll at night.","Night","اسری","11:81-15:65-17:1-20:77-26:52-44:23",6
1664,356,"N","طَرَقَ","«طَرِیْق» means path, and «طَارِقْ» means one who travels the path. But in common parlance, it particularly refers to a traveler who arrives at night. And «طَارِق» is called a star because it generally appears at night (in brief). For example, the Quran states: «وَ السَّمَآءِ  وَ الطَّارِقِ» (86:1) Translation: By the sky and the night comer. In this verse, «طَارِق» could refer to stars as well as the night-coming guest.","«طَرَقَ» meaning path.","Night","طرق","86:1-86:2",2
1665,356,"N","نَفَشَ","«نَفْشُ الْغَنَم» means to scatter at night for grazing without a shepherd. And «اَلنَّفْش» refers to those sheep that have scattered at night to graze without a shepherd (mufradat).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ  اِذۡ  نَفَشَتۡ فِیۡہِ غَنَمُ  الۡقَوۡمِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And remember David and Solomon, peace be upon them, when they were judging the case of the field—some people's sheep had grazed in it by night.","«نَفَشَ» refers to the goats that spread out to graze at night without a shepherd.","Night","نفش","21:78",1
1666,356,"N","تَھَجَّدَ","«ھَجَدَ» means both sleeping at night and waking up (this is from the category of *addad*—words that have two separate, opposite meanings).  \nAnd «ھَجَّدَ تَھَجَّدَ» means both sleeping at night and waking others up. Waking from sleep. Sleeping at night. Waking up at night to pray (Munjid).  \n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:  \n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً  لَّکَ» (17/79)  \nTranslation: And rise up at night to pray the Tahajjud—it will be an additional [reward] for you.","«تَھَجَّدَ» Performing voluntary prayers after waking up at night.","night","تھجد","17:79",1
1667,357,"P","طَرِیْق","The plural of «طَرِیْق» is «طَرَائِق». This word is used for all kinds of paths (see footnote 269). Its usage occurs in both material and spiritual contexts. An example of its material usage is:\n\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«فَاضۡرِبۡ لَہُمۡ طَرِیۡقًا فِی الۡبَحۡرِ یَبَسًا» (20:77)\nTranslation: (O Moses!) Strike the sea with your staff and make for them a dry path across it.\n\nAnd an example of its spiritual usage is:\n\nThe command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَ لَا  لِیَہۡدِیَہُمۡ  طَرِیۡقًا اِلَّا طَرِیۡقَ جَہَنَّمَ» (4:168)\nTranslation: And He will not show them any path except the path of Hell.","«طَرِیْق» is a common term for the path.","path","طریق","4:168-4:169-20:63-20:77-20:104-46:30-72:16",7
1668,357,"P","صِرَاط","The term for a long, sharp-edged sword is Munjad, and the path that will be built to cross over Hell, commonly known as the Sirat Bridge, is also described with the same attribute: it will be sharper than a sword and thinner than a hair. Thus, it is the path that must be traversed with extreme vigilance and caution, surrounded by many dangers. The name for this extreme vigilance and caution in crossing the path is Taqwa. The word Taqwa is used in both material and spiritual contexts. Spiritually, its meaning generally refers to the path of guidance. And according to Abu Halaal, Taqwa refers to the easy path (Faqat 246). And Allah knows best.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ» (1/5)\nTranslation: O Allah, guide us to the straight path.\n\nAnd a material usage example is the divine declaration:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡعُدُوۡا بِکُلِّ صِرَاطٍ تُوۡعِدُوۡنَ وَ تَصُدُّوۡنَ عَنۡ  سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (7/86)\nTranslation: And do not sit on every path, threatening and deterring those who believe in Allah from the way of Allah.","a path that must be traversed with caution","Path","صراط","1:5-1:6-2:142-2:213-3:51-3:101-4:68-4:175-5:16-6:39-6:87-6:126-6:153-6:161-7:16-7:86-10:25-11:56-14:1-15:41-16:76-16:121-19:36-19:43-20:135-22:24-22:54-23:73-23:74-24:46-34:6-36:4-36:61-36:66-37:23-37:118-38:22-42:52-42:53-43:43-43:61-43:64-48:2-48:20-67:22",45
1669,357,"P","سَبِیْل","«سَبِیْل» is every path on which one can travel with ease (singular). «اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل» means traveler and «عَابِرِی سَّبِیْل» (4:43) means wayfarer, and its plural is «سُبُل». And «سبیل» means open road. «اَسْبَلُ الطَّرِیْق» means the path being heavily trafficked. And «اَسْبَلُ الدَّمْعِ وَالْمَطَر» means tears or abundant rain falling. Thus, «سَبِیْل» refers to such a path where there is frequent coming and going (Manjad).\n\nFor example, in the Quran, Allah Almighty says through the honeybee: «فَاسۡلُکِیۡ سُبُلَ رَبِّکِ ذُلُلًا» (16:69) Translation: And travel upon the clear paths of your Lord.\n\nHere, «سُبُل» refers to that natural guidance which Allah Almighty has inherently established in everything and upon which one can traverse with ease. And all proceed uniformly. This word is also used in both spiritual and material contexts. The above example is of the spiritual context, and an example of the material context is this.\n\nThe divine command is: «وَ  اِنَّہَا لَبِسَبِیۡلٍ  مُّقِیۡمٍ» (15:76) Translation: And that (city. Lot's settlement) remains on the straight path until now.\n\nNow observe that Allah Almighty has used all three words—«طَرِیْق ، صِرَاط», «سَبِیْل», and «طَرِیْق»—in the Quran for this 'path of guidance.' «طَرِیْق» is general in the sense that its word is common, used for every path. «صِرَاط» is such that it is encompassed within the limits and constraints of commands and prohibitions. And «سَبِیْل» is such that when a person embarks upon this path with determination, the Sharia has taken into account all kinds of ease for him, and the number of individuals traversing it is also substantial.","«سَبِیْل» a path that can be traversed with ease and on which there is considerable traffic.","Path","سبیل","2:108-2:154-2:190-2:195-2:217-2:218-2:244-2:246-2:261-2:262-2:273-3:13-3:75-3:97-3:99-3:146-3:157-3:167-3:169-3:195-4:15-4:22-4:34-4:44-4:51-4:74-4:75-4:76-4:84-4:88-4:89-4:90-4:94-4:95-4:98-4:100-4:115-4:137-4:141-4:143-4:150-4:160-4:167-5:12-5:16-5:35-5:54-5:60-5:77-6:55-6:116-6:117-6:153-6:153-7:45-7:86-7:142-7:146-7:148-8:36-8:47-8:60-8:72-8:74-9:5-9:9-9:19-9:20-9:24-9:34-9:38-9:41-9:60-9:81-9:91-9:93-9:111-9:120-10:88-10:89-11:19-12:108-13:33-14:3-14:12-14:30-15:76-16:9-16:15-16:69-16:88-16:94-16:125-17:32-17:42-17:48-17:72-17:84-17:110-18:61-18:63-20:53-21:31-22:9-22:25-22:58-24:22-25:9-25:17-25:27-25:34-25:42-25:44-25:57-27:24-28:22-29:12-29:29-29:38-29:69-31:6-31:15-33:4-33:67-38:26-39:8-40:7-40:11-40:29-40:37-40:38-42:41-42:42-42:44-42:46-43:10-43:37-47:1-47:4-47:32-47:34-47:38-49:15-53:30-57:10-58:16-60:1-61:4-61:11-63:2-68:7-71:20-73:19-73:20-76:3-76:29-80:20",157
1670,357,"P","فَجّ","The expanse between two mountains is called «فَجَّۃٌ», the plain between two mountains is called «فَجْوَۃ», and that open path which passes through that plain and connects these two mountains is called «فَجَّ». The plural of «فَجّ» is «فِحَاج».\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَذِّنۡ فِی النَّاسِ بِالۡحَجِّ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ  رِجَالًا وَّ عَلٰی کُلِّ ضَامِرٍ یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: And proclaim to the people the Hajj [pilgrimage]; they will come to you on foot and on every lean camel; they will come from every distant path.","«فَجّ» the open central path between two mountains.","Path","فج","21:31-22:27-71:20",3
1671,357,"P","اِمَام","«اِمَام» has two meanings: (1) meaning predecessor or guide, and (2) meaning main road or highway. A large and open road (manjada).\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«فَانۡتَقَمۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ ۘ وَ اِنَّہُمَا لَبِاِمَامٍ مُّبِیۡنٍ» (15/79)\nTranslation: So We exacted retribution from them, and indeed, both towns are located on a main highway.","«اِمَام» highway, open road.","Path","امام","2:124-11:17-15:79-17:71-25:74-46:12",6
1672,357,"P","نَجْد","«نَجْد» has two meanings: (1) a valley or ravine, and (2) the path that ascends towards a height or descends from above (see 269). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ» (90/10). Translation: And We have shown man both paths, but he did not pass through the valley.","A path that ascends and descends a valley.","path","نجد","90:10",1
1673,357,"T","ھُدًی","«ھُدٰی» means guidance and path. If a lost and misguided person finds the correct path, it is called «ھُدًی». And its opposite is «ضَلٰلَۃ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اِنِّیۡۤ اٰنَسۡتُ نَارًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اٰتِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا بِقَبَسٍ  اَوۡ  اَجِدُ  عَلَی النَّارِ  ہُدًی» (20:10).\n\nTranslation: I have seen a fire, and I am going there so that I may bring you a torch from it or find guidance from those seated by the fire.","«ھُدٰی» When the lost and astray human finds the right path.","the Straight Path","ھدًی","2:2-2:5-2:16-2:26-2:38-2:97-2:120-2:142-2:143-2:159-2:175-2:185-2:198-2:213-2:258-2:264-2:272-3:4-3:8-3:73-3:86-3:96-3:101-3:138-4:26-4:51-4:68-4:115-4:137-4:168-4:175-5:16-5:44-5:46-5:51-5:67-5:108-6:35-6:71-6:77-6:80-6:84-6:87-6:88-6:90-6:91-6:125-6:144-6:149-6:154-6:157-6:161-7:30-7:43-7:52-7:100-7:148-7:154-7:155-7:159-7:178-7:181-7:193-7:198-7:203-9:19-9:24-9:33-9:37-9:80-9:109-9:115-10:9-10:25-10:35-10:43-10:57-12:52-12:111-13:27-13:31-14:4-14:12-14:21-16:9-16:36-16:37-16:64-16:89-16:93-16:102-16:104-16:107-16:121-17:2-17:9-17:84-17:94-17:97-18:13-18:17-18:24-18:55-18:57-19:43-19:58-19:76-20:10-20:47-20:50-20:79-20:122-20:123-20:128-21:73-22:4-22:8-22:16-22:24-22:37-22:67-24:35-24:46-26:62-26:78-27:2-27:63-27:77-28:22-28:37-28:43-28:49-28:50-28:56-28:57-28:85-29:69-30:29-31:3-31:5-31:20-32:13-32:23-32:24-32:26-33:4-34:6-34:24-34:32-35:8-35:42-37:23-37:99-37:118-38:22-39:3-39:18-39:23-39:37-39:57-40:28-40:29-40:38-40:53-40:54-41:17-41:44-42:13-42:52-43:24-43:27-43:40-45:11-45:20-45:23-46:10-46:30-47:5-47:17-47:25-47:32-48:2-48:20-48:28-49:17-53:23-61:5-61:7-61:9-62:5-63:6-64:6-64:11-67:22-72:2-72:13-74:31-76:3-79:19-87:3-90:10-92:12-93:7-96:11",204
1674,357,"P","سبب","Its plural is «اَسْبَاب». Meaning: means, rope, path (manjad) path, and the means, equipment for travel (plural) for determining it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ   اَتۡبَعَ سَبَبًا» (18/89)\nTranslation: Then Dhul-Qarnayn set out on another journey.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«وَ قَالَ فِرۡعَوۡنُ یٰہَامٰنُ ابۡنِ  لِیۡ صَرۡحًا لَّعَلِّیۡۤ  اَبۡلُغُ  الۡاَسۡبَابَ» (40/36)\nTranslation: And Pharaoh said, O Haman! Build for me a tower that I may reach the ways.","«سَبَبَ» a means to reach something or a path.","Path","سبب","2:166-18:84-18:85-18:89-18:92-22:15-38:10-40:36-40:37",9
1675,358,"P","سُنَّۃ","«سَنّ» means for something to be in vogue or prevailing, and to function correctly. It is used both transitively and intransitively.  \nFor example, in the Prophetic Hadith it is stated: «مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّۃً».  \nIt is used in both good and bad senses, and when attributed to Allah, it refers to the Divine Law or the Divine Way.  \nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is said:  \n«فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا» (35/43)  \nTranslation: They are not waiting for anything but the ways of the earlier people. So you will never find any change in Allah's way.","«سَنَّ» comes to establish every good and bad way. However, in Shariah terminology, «سُنَّۃْ» refers specifically to the actions and sayings of the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ.","Prevalent","سنۃ","8:38-15:13-17:77-18:55-33:38-33:62-35:43-40:85-48:23",9
1676,358,"I","شَرَعَ","«شَرَعَ» A clear and defined path. However, its application is specific to the divine commandments (Muf) and «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْمِ» meaning to legislate a law for a people. And Sharia means Islamic law, divine commandments, regulations (Manjd). «شَرَعَ» essentially refers to those laws in which Allah the Exalted continues to make changes according to the demands of the times (for further details, see Tariqah and Din).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«شَرَعَ  لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا وَصّٰی بِہٖ نُوۡحًا» (42/13)\nTranslation: He (Allah) has ordained for you the same religion (path) which He enjoined upon Noah.\n\nHowever, lexically, the attribution of this word can also be towards other than Allah and false deities,\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah is:\n«اَمۡ لَہُمۡ شُرَکٰٓؤُا شَرَعُوۡا  لَہُمۡ مِّنَ الدِّیۡنِ مَا لَمۡ یَاۡذَنۡۢ بِہِ اللّٰہُ» (42/21)\nTranslation: Do they have partners (in divinity) who have legislated for them a religion (path) which Allah has not authorized?","«شَرَعَ» Allah Ta'ala establishing a clear and defined path for His servants through the Messenger. From Prophet Adam (AS) to Prophet Muhammad (PBUH), changes continued to occur in it, but now this part of the religion has also become unalterable (that which cannot be changed). This is because the Prophet (PBUH) was the Khatam an-Nabiyyin (Seal of the Prophets), and the religion was also completed upon him.","in force","شرع","5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48",4
1677,358,"P","اِبْتَدَعَ","«اَلْاِبْدَاعُ» means to invent something without imitating or following anyone else. And «بِدْعَتْ» is every new custom or practice that is adopted into religion by considering it a part of faith, while having no evidence for it in the Shariah. And «اِبْتَدَعَ» means to introduce something new into the Shariah by giving it a ruling and status. And the Prophetic saying ﷺ is: Every innovation is misguidance, even if it is considered good by people.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ رَہۡبَانِیَّۃَۨ  ابۡتَدَعُوۡہَا مَا کَتَبۡنٰہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (57/27)\nTranslation: So they took the monasticism as a new way which was not ordained for them by Allah...","«اِبْتَدَعَ» Introducing into religion any custom or practice as part of the Sharia, for which there is no evidence in the Sharia itself.","prevalent","ابتدع","57:27",1
1678,359,"P","رَضِیَ","«رَضِیَ» is a well-known term meaning to be pleased with someone, to be happy, to show approval or fondness.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«رَضِیَ اللّٰہُ عَنۡہُمۡ وَ رَضُوۡا عَنۡہُ» (5/119) (98/8)\nTranslation: Allah Almighty was pleased with them (the noble Companions ؓ) and they were pleased with Allah Almighty.","«رَضِیَ» to be pleased, to be happy, is a common term.","Pleased","رضی","2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7",26
1679,359,"P","طَوَّعَ","«اَطَاعَ» meaning to carry out a command with joy and willingness in the heart. And «طَوَّع» meaning to reluctantly force one's heart to accept a detestable (reprehensible) act.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَطَوَّعَتۡ  لَہٗ نَفۡسُہٗ  قَتۡلَ اَخِیۡہِ» ( 5/30 )\nTranslation: So his soul prompted him to kill his brother.","«طَوَّعَ» to artificially persuade one's heart to accept something bad.","Pleased","طوع","2:158-2:184-3:83-5:30-9:53-9:79-13:15-41:11",8
1680,359,"C","اَعْتَبَ","«عَتَبَ» means to reproach someone, to be angry. And «اَعْتَبَ» means to remove the cause of anger, to appease someone who is upset (and this is from the category of *lughat al-addād*—words with two distinct, opposite meanings). And «عِتَاب» means the expression of anger (or resentment) due to breaking ties of friendship and compassion (Fiqh 39).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  اِنۡ یَّسۡتَعۡتِبُوۡا فَمَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡمُعۡتَبِیۡنَ» (41:24)\nTranslation: And if they were to seek reconciliation, they would not be reconciled. (Usmani)\n\n(*Lughat al-addād* refers to words that have two separate meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«اَعْتَبَ» to complain with the intention of appeasing the offended party.","Content","اعتب","16:84-30:57-41:24-45:35",4
1681,360,"S","دَرَجَۃ","«دَرَجَۃ» means superiority, excellence, rank, status. «دَرْج» is the opposite of «دَرْک». And these two words are two aspects of the same thing. If, on the steps of a staircase, one ascends towards the top, these same steps are called «دَرَجَات». And when considering descending downwards, these same steps are called «دَرَکَات». This is why the idioms «دَرَجَاتُ الْجَنَّۃ» and «دَرَکَاتُ النَّار» are used (in the plural form). And by 'degree' is meant such superiority and excellence that exists from one degree to another.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَہُنَّ مِثۡلُ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِنَّ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ  ۪ وَ لِلرِّجَالِ عَلَیۡہِنَّ دَرَجَۃٌ» (2/228)\nTranslation: And women have rights similar to those of men, according to what is customary (the rights of men over women). But men have a degree of excellence over women.","«دَرَجَۃ» a station of excellence and superiority.","Station","درجۃ","2:228-2:253-3:163-4:95-4:96-6:83-6:132-6:165-8:4-9:20-12:76-17:21-20:75-40:15-43:32-46:19-57:10-58:11",18
1682,360,"R","زُلْفٰی","«زُلْفٰی» meaning nearness in terms of honor, status, and rank. (lit.)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ لَہٗ عِنۡدَنَا لَزُلۡفٰی وَ حُسۡنَ مَاٰبٍ» ( 38/40 )\nTranslation: And indeed for him (Prophet Solomon) with Us is nearness and an excellent position.\n\nHowever, when this term becomes a chapter in the context of actions, it also conveys the meaning of nearness in distance.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ  اَزۡلَفۡنَا ثَمَّ   الۡاٰخَرِیۡنَ» ( 26/64 )\nTranslation: And We brought the other party also near to that place.","«زُلْفٰی» closeness in honor and status.","Rank","زلفی","26:64-26:90-34:37-38:25-38:40-39:3-50:31-67:27-81:13",9
1683,360,"S","قَرَّبَ","«قَرُبَ» means to draw near. And it refers to performing an action that serves as a means to attain nearness in rank. And «قُرْبَان» is that vow and offering through which the attainment of rank and degree is sought.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اتۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  نَبَاَ ابۡنَیۡ اٰدَمَ  بِالۡحَقِّ ۘ اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا» (5/27)\nTranslation: And recite to them, [O Muhammad], the story of the two sons of Adam with truth when they both offered a sacrifice...\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ السّٰبِقُوۡنَ  السّٰبِقُوۡنَ اُولٰٓئِکَ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (56/10,11)\nTranslation: And the forerunners, the forerunners – Those are the ones brought near [to Allah].","To make oneself an intimate by conferring rank «قَرَّبَ».","Spiritual rank","قرب","2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28",36
1684,360,"R","مَکَنَ","«مَکَنَ» means to be of high rank. And «مَکَان» means a place, a place of residence, or such a place that possesses a body. And «مَکَّنَ» means to grant someone authority, to bestow governance. And «مَکِیْن» also means an inhabitant of a place, as well as a person of high rank.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ  لَقَوۡلُ رَسُوۡلٍ  کَرِیۡمٍ ذِیۡ  قُوَّۃٍ  عِنۡدَ ذِی الۡعَرۡشِ مَکِیۡنٍ» (81:19-20)\nTranslation: This (Quran) is indeed the word of a noble messenger. Possessor of power, with a high rank with the Owner of the Throne.","«مَکَنَ» When rank is attained along with authority as well.","Rank","مکن","6:6-7:10-8:71-12:21-12:54-12:56-18:84-18:95-22:41-24:55-28:6-28:57-46:26",13
1685,361,"D","اَقْبَلَ","«قَبَلَ الْمَکَان» means to turn one's face toward a place. «قَابَل» means to be face to face or opposite each other. To place two things opposite each other. To confront. And «قَبَّل» means to kiss someone. And «اَقْبَل» means to turn one's face toward something or someone that is in front.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَقۡبَلَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ یَّتَلَاوَمُوۡنَ» ( 68/30 )\nTranslation: Then they turned toward each other and began to blame one another.","«قَبْل» comes only for facing something present, while «تَوَجَّہ» is general. That is, to face anything—far or near.","Divine Grace / Favor / (Quranic context)","اقبل","12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30",8
1686,361,"D","تَوَجَّہَ","«وَجْہ» means face or mouth. And «وَجَّہَ» means to send towards someone. And «تَوَجَّہَ اِلَیْہِ» means to be attentive, to turn, or to direct one's face towards that thing (manjad). For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ  تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ» (28/22). Translation: Then when Moses turned towards Madyan.","«تَوَجَّہَ» meaning to pay attention.","Direction","توجہ","28:22",1
1687,362,"L","نَکِدَ","«نَکِدَ» means «قَلِیْلُ الْخَیْر», which has little aspect of goodness and excellence. (M. Q.) And in the words of Imam Raghb, it is every thing that is obtained with great difficulty by its seeker. And «نَاقَۃَ نَکِدَاء» refers to that she-camel which gives little milk and milking her is also difficult. (M.F.) And «نَکَدَ» means to prevent someone from need, to deprive, or to give little. And «نَکِدَ الرَّجُل» means to be one who asks a lot and has little goodness. (Manjada) Thus, «نَکِدَ» is that thing which is hard to obtain, little in quantity, and has little goodness, i.e., little and worthless.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡ خَبُثَ لَا یَخۡرُجُ  اِلَّا نَکِدًا» (7/58) Translation: And from the land that is ruined, nothing comes out except a scant production.","«نَکِدَ» a thing that is difficult to obtain, scarce in quantity, and low in goodness.","Lazy","نکد","7:58",1
1688,362,"U","خَمْط","«خَمْط» meaning every bitter or sour thing. A small fruit from any tree. Any long-thorned tree (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ وَّ اَثۡلٍ وَّ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡ سِدۡرٍ قَلِیۡلٍ» (34/16)\nTranslation: And He made both their gardens like gardens bearing bitter fruit. In them were some thorny shrubs and a few berries.","«خَمْط», a bitter, sour, and foul-tasting thing.","Useless","خمط","34:16",1
1689,362,"D","دَاحِضَۃٌ","«دَحَضَ» meaning to thrash about like a slaughtered animal. And «دَحَضَ الْحُجَّۃ» meaning a proof becoming invalid and false. And «اَدْحَضَ» meaning to invalidate a proof. And «دَحْض» meaning to slip. A slipping place (minjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ یُحَآجُّوۡنَ فِی اللّٰہِ  مِنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ مَا اسۡتُجِیۡبَ لَہٗ  حُجَّتُہُمۡ  دَاحِضَۃٌ  عِنۡدَ رَبِّہِمۡ» (42/16)\n\nTranslation: And those who argue about Allah after it has been accepted by people, their argument is nullified before their Lord.","«دَاحِضَۃ» idle talk, frivolity, and falsehood.","Disbelief","داحضۃ","18:56-40:5-37:141-42:16",4
1690,362,"I","نَاقِصْ","«نَاقِصْ» meaning incomplete «دِرْھمٌ ناقصٌ» meaning light-weight dirhams (manjud) or deficient dirhams (m. q.) «نَقْص» meaning deficiency, fault, and loss also occur.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذۡنَاۤ  اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ بِالسِّنِیۡنَ وَ نَقۡصٍ مِّنَ الثَّمَرٰتِ» ( 7/130 )\nTranslation: And We afflicted the people of Pharaoh with years of famine and scarcity of produce, so that they might take heed.","«نَاقِصْ» a flawed item; incomplete.","Inert","ناقص","2:155-7:130-9:4-11:84-13:41-21:44-35:11-50:4-73:3",9
1691,362,"D","بَخْس","meaning deficient, inferior, lesser (munjad) and meaning a contemptible and deficient thing (muf). For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12/20) Translation: And the caravan people purchased Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) for a paltry sum, that is, for a few coins.","«بَخْس» cheap and trashy thing.","disbeliever","بخس","2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13",7
1692,362,"D","خَبِیْث","«خَبُثَ» means to be impure and unclean. To be worthless. To be useless. And «خَبِیْث» means filthy. Worthless. Detestable. Every corrupt and dirty thing. Its opposite is «طَیّب» (pure). For example: In the Quran it is said: «وَ لَا تَتَبَدَّلُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ بِالطَّیِّبِ» (4/2) Translation: And do not exchange the good and pure wealth of orphans with your filthy wealth!","filthy and impure or forbidden","Disbeliever","خبیث","2:267-3:179-4:2-5:100-7:58-7:157-8:37-14:26-21:74-24:26",10
1693,362,"D","اَدْنٰی","«اَدْنٰی» Its opposite, «اَعْلٰی», is that thing which is deficient or worthless in comparison to a good thing.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «قَالَ اَتَسۡتَبۡدِلُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ اَدۡنٰی بِالَّذِیۡ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ» (2:61)\n\nTranslation: Moses said, Why would you want to exchange excellent things for deficient ones instead?","«اَدْنٰی» that is inferior to something good.","Disbeliever","ادنی","2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:9-58:7-73:20",12
1694,362,"D","مَزْجٰۃ","« زَجُو ، زَجَا» and «اَزْجٰی» mean to drive away, repel, or return. «مُزْجٰی» its feminine form is «مُزْجَاۃ». It means something insignificant or worthless (manjada, m., q.), i.e., a thing that no one is willing to accept and is returned (m., q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡعَزِیۡزُ مَسَّنَا وَ اَہۡلَنَا الضُّرُّ وَ جِئۡنَا بِبِضَاعَۃٍ مُّزۡجٰىۃٍ فَاَوۡفِ لَنَا الۡکَیۡلَ» (12/88)\nTranslation: The brothers of Prophet Yusuf (AS) said, O noble one! We and our family are suffering from great distress. We have brought a scanty measure of money. So give us the full measure in return, and be charitable to us. Indeed, Allah rewards the charitable.","«مُزْجٰۃ» such filth that no one is willing to accept.","Disbelief","مزجۃ","12:88",1
1695,363,"R","حَبْل","Its plural is «حَبَال». Meaning: a rope and anything of that sort. «حَبْلُ الْوَرِیْد» means a main vein or a life vein. And «حَبَالَۃُ الْصَیَّاد» means a hunter's snare. There is generality in the usage of this word.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«فِیۡ  جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ» (111/5)  \nTranslation: Upon her (Abu Lahab's wife) will be a rope of palm fiber.","«حَبْل» is used for all types of rope.","rope","حبل","3:103-3:112-20:66-26:44-50:16-111:5",6
1696,363,"R","سَبَب","That rope with which one climbs a date palm tree (literal), and «سَبَب» also signifies 'path,' 'journey,' 'travel equipment,' and the rope used for securing travel gear, etc.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَنۡ کَانَ یَظُنُّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ یَّنۡصُرَہُ اللّٰہُ فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ فَلۡیَمۡدُدۡ بِسَبَبٍ اِلَی السَّمَآءِ ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡطَعۡ فَلۡیَنۡظُرۡ ہَلۡ یُذۡہِبَنَّ کَیۡدُہٗ مَا یَغِیۡظُ » (22:15)\nTranslation: Whoever thought that Allah would not support him [the Prophet] in this world and the Hereafter should let down a rope to the heaven and sever all ties, then let him see if his stratagem can dispel his distress.","«سَبَب» is used exclusively as a means of travel or climbing, serving as a route.","rope","سبب","2:166-18:84-18:85-18:89-18:92-22:15-38:10-40:36-40:37",9
1697,364,"R","اَقْرَبُوْنَ","«قَرُبَ» means to be near or close. And this word encompasses time, distance, rank, and kinship—in short, it holds a comprehensive meaning in every respect. «اَقْرَبَ» means more near, closer. And the words «اَقْرَبُوْنَ» or «اَقْرَبِیْن» or «ذَا قُرْبٰی» or «ذَوِی الْقُرْبٰی» become specific in meaning to close relatives. Relatives can be both distant and near. The near relatives are those for whom Allah the Exalted has appointed a share in inheritance. That is: sons, daughters, mother, father, husband, wife, sister, and brother.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/7)\nTranslation: There is a share for men as well in that wealth which parents and closest relatives have left behind.","«اَقْرَبُوْنَ» near relatives for whom a share is prescribed in inheritance.","relative","اقربون","2:83-2:177-2:180-2:215-3:45-4:7-4:8-4:33-4:36-4:135-5:106-6:152-8:41-9:113-16:90-17:26-24:22-26:214-30:38-35:18-42:23-59:7-90:15",23
1698,364,"R","نَسَبَ","«نَسَبَ یَنْسُبُ» means to state lineage and to discover lineage. And «اِسْتَنْسَبَ» means to state lineage, to ask about lineage. And «نَسَب» and «اَنْسَاب» mean kinship, relationship (from *manjad*). By lineage (*nasab*) is meant those relatives who are from the father's side, because lineage is traced through the father. It includes, besides «اَقْرَبُوْن», also paternal uncles, paternal aunts, and their offspring.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَلَاۤ  اَنۡسَابَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  یَوۡمَئِذٍ» (23/101)\nTranslation: Then when the Trumpet is blown, that Day there will be no kinship among them.\n\nAnd Imam Raghib states that the meaning of lineage (*nasab*) is written as relatives from either of the two parents (i.e., it includes relatives from the father's side as well as the mother's side—meaning *nanake* and *nannial*).","«نَسَبَ» paternal relatives","Relative","نسب","23:101-25:54-37:158",3
1699,364,"R","صِھْر","«صِھْر» means *sasraal*, i.e., the kinship relations that come into existence as a result of marriage. The husband's blood relatives are *sasraal* for the wife, and the wife's blood relatives are *sasraal* for the husband.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَ مِنَ الۡمَآءِ بَشَرًا فَجَعَلَہٗ  نَسَبًا وَّ صِہۡرًا» (25/54)\nTranslation: And He is the One Who created humans from water, then ordained for them [both] lineage [*nasabiyyah*] and marital relations [*sasraaliyyah*].","«صِھْر» meaning the one with the chain of narrators.","Relative","صھر","25:54",1
1700,364,"R","اُولُو الْاَرْحَام","«اُولُو الْاَرْحَام» Those related through the womb (uterine relatives). Their circle is very wide, including paternal and maternal aunts and uncles (but according to the science of inheritance, their rank comes after the [ARABIC_2] and the [ARABIC_3]).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَامِ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِبَعۡضٍ فِیۡ  کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ» (8:75)\nTranslation: And according to the command of Allah, the (uterine) relatives are more entitled (to the inheritance) than others.\n\nNote:\nScience of Inheritance ([ARABIC_4]): Refers to the knowledge through which one determines who will be an heir and who will not, and what portion of the estate each heir will receive.\n[ARABIC_2] (Dhawi al-Farudh): These are the statutory heirs whose share is predetermined, meaning there is absolutely no substitution or alteration among them.\n[ARABIC_3] (Asabah): This is the heir whose share is not specified in the estate. If he is alone, he takes the entire estate; if he is alongside a fixed-share heir, he takes the residue of the estate after the fixed share has been distributed.","«اُولُو الْاَرْحَام» refers to kin connected by mercy, and their circle is extremely wide.","relative","اولو الارحام","8:75-33:6",2
1701,364,"R","اِلَّ","The translation of «اِلَّ» is generally given as kinship or relationship, but etymologically, it means a covenant or pact made with relatives. «اِلَّ» also signifies covenant, agreement, neighbor (munasib), and «اِلَّ الرَّجُل» means «جَارَ بِہٖ», i.e., its name is made neighbor (m. q).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10). Translation: These people do not uphold kinship or covenant in favor of a believer.\n\nThe correct meaning of «ذِمَّۃ» is not merely a covenant but a covenant of security and protection. And «اِلَّ» means any kind of covenant or pact made with one's neighbors and relatives.","«اِلَّ» What became of the covenant with the relatives?","relative","ال","2:144-4:24-5:3-5:119-9:10-9:38-9:58-9:59-9:83-9:87-9:93-9:96-9:100-10:7-19:6-19:55-20:109-27:19-33:51-46:15-48:18-58:22-69:21-88:9-89:28-98:8-101:7",27
1702,365,"D","رِضْوَان ۔ مَرْضَاۃ","«رَضِیَ» is a well-known word meaning 'to be happy'. From it, «رِضْوَان ، رَضْوَان» and «مَرْضَاۃ» also come as verbal nouns. And they convey the meaning of satisfaction, pleasure, or approval (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَبۡتَغُوۡنَ فَضۡلًا مِّنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ وَ رِضۡوَانًا» ( 5/2 )\nTranslation: Those who seek the favor and pleasure of their Lord.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّبِیُّ  لِمَ  تُحَرِّمُ مَاۤ  اَحَلَّ اللّٰہُ  لَکَ ۚ تَبۡتَغِیۡ  مَرۡضَاتَ  اَزۡوَاجِکَ» ( 66/1 )\nTranslation: O Prophet ﷺ! Why do you prohibit what Allah has made lawful for you, seeking the pleasure of your wives?","«رِضْوَان اور مَرْضَاۃ» signifies mere consent, whereas «وَجْہ» also encompasses the dimension of attention alongside consent.","Divine Pleasure","رضوان ۔ مرضاۃ","2:207-2:265-3:15-3:162-3:174-4:114-5:2-5:16-9:21-9:72-9:109-47:28-48:29-57:20-57:27-59:8-60:1-66:1",18
1703,365,"D","وَجْہ","«وَجْہ» means face, direction, mouth, approval, and the foremost part of anything that appears first. «وَجْہُ النَّھَار» means the first part of the day (morning). When a person becomes displeased with someone, they turn their face away from them; and when they are pleased, they turn towards them and give them more attention. This is the meaning of «وَجْہ» in the sense of seeking approval—that is, to seek someone's pleasure by avoiding acts of displeasure and performing good deeds.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ اِلَّا ابۡتِغَآءَ وَجۡہِ اللّٰہِ» (2/272)\nTranslation: And whatever you spend, spend it for the sake of Allah's pleasure.","«وَجْہ» meaning face.","Divine Pleasure","وجہ","2:112-2:115-2:144-2:148-2:149-2:150-2:177-2:272-3:20-3:106-3:107-4:43-4:47-4:125-5:6-5:108-6:52-6:79-7:29-8:50-10:26-10:27-10:105-12:9-12:93-12:96-13:22-14:50-16:58-17:7-17:97-18:28-18:29-20:111-21:39-22:11-22:72-23:104-25:34-27:90-28:88-30:30-30:38-30:39-30:43-31:22-33:66-39:24-39:60-43:17-47:27-48:29-51:29-54:48-55:27-67:22-67:27-75:22-75:24-76:9-80:38-80:40-83:24-88:2-88:8-92:20",66
1704,366,"Y","رَغِبَ","«رَغِبَ» meaning to desire or to have. To harbor a sincere longing for the attainment of something and to strive for it (transitive).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «فَاِذَا  فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی  رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94:7-8). Translation: Then when you are free, strive and turn to your Lord with devotion.","«رَغِبَ» meaning to desire or to have a heartfelt longing for the attainment of something and to strive for it.","Yearning","رغب","4:127-9:59-9:120-21:90-68:32-94:8",6
1705,366,"E","تَنَافُس","«نَفِسَ» means to envy. And «نَفَّسَ فِی الْاَمْر» means to encourage someone to do a good deed. And «تَنَافُس» means to take pride mutually, to vie with one another in righteous deeds. To compete with the intention of surpassing one another (in good deeds) with a competitive spirit.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُسۡقَوۡنَ مِنۡ  رَّحِیۡقٍ مَّخۡتُوۡمٍ خِتٰمُہٗ  مِسۡکٌ ؕ وَ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ فَلۡیَتَنَافَسِ الۡمُتَنَافِسُوۡنَ» (83:25, 26)\nTranslation: They will be given a pure wine, sealed. Its seal will be musk, and those who desire it should desire it.","Competition in the eagerness to do good deeds is called «تَنَافُس».","earnest desire","تنافس","83:26",1
1706,367,"T","وَضَعَ","Its opposite is «رَفَعَ». Meaning: to lift something, to raise. And «وَضَعَ» means to place something down gently. The opposite of «رَفِیْع» is «وَضِیْع», meaning a person of no worth or status in society. And «وَضَع حَمَل» means to keep a burden down, whether outward or inward (inner).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ وَضَعۡنَا عَنۡکَ وِزۡرَکَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡقَضَ ظَہۡرَکَ» (94:2,3)\nTranslation: And We have certainly removed from you your burden which had weighed down your back.","«وَضَعَ» is general, whether someone sees the thing kept or not.","to keep","وضع","3:36-18:49-39:69-46:15-55:7-55:10-94:2",7
1707,367,"T","اَلْقٰی","The basic meaning of «اَلْقٰی» is to put or place. The difference between رکھنا (to place/put with care) and ڈالنا (to throw/put) is that رکھنا involves an element of gentleness and caution. If something is done recklessly or hastily, it is called پھینکنا (to throw). And ڈالنا is an intermediate state between these two. Therefore, whenever the element of gentleness and caution is present in «اَلْقٰی», it will also carry the meaning of رکھنا. Another characteristic of «اَلْقٰی» is that it refers to the placing or putting of something that can be seen by others, whereas this is not necessarily the case with «وَضَعَ».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَلۡقٰی فِی الۡاَرۡضِ رَوَاسِیَ» (16:15)\nTranslation: And He has placed firm mountains on the earth (Othmani).\nAnd He has placed (by creating) mountains on the earth (Jalandhari).","to put such an object down that others cannot see","to place","القی","2:37-3:44-4:90-4:91-4:94-4:171-5:64-7:115-7:107-7:116-7:117-7:120-7:150-8:12-10:80-10:81-12:10-12:93-12:96-15:19-16:15-16:28-16:86-16:87-17:39-20:20-20:39-20:65-20:66-20:69-20:70-20:87-22:52-22:53-25:8-25:13-26:32-26:43-26:44-26:45-26:46-26:223-27:6-27:10-27:28-27:29-28:7-28:31-28:86-31:10-37:97-38:34-40:15-41:35-41:40-43:53-50:7-50:24-50:26-50:37-54:25-60:1-67:7-67:8-75:15-84:4",66
1708,368,"C","لَوْن","«لَوْن» Natural colors such as black, white, green, red, yellow, blue, and others take their plural form in «اَلْوَان». For example, the Quran states: «وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا» (35/37). Translation: And in the mountains are streaks of white, red, and various colors.","«لَوْن» is called natural color.","Color","لون","16:13-16:69-30:22-35:27-35:28-39:21",6
1709,368,"C","صِبْغَۃ","«صَبَغَ» means to dye. To stain. And «صَبَّاغ» means a dyer (a profession). And the word «صَبَغَہ» is used in both material and spiritual senses. In the spiritual sense, its meaning is that an effect and imprint of one thing upon another human being is created. And «صَبَّغَ بِالْمَاءِ» means to baptize with water. And «تَصَبَّغْ فِیْ دِیْنِہٖ» means for the color of religion to be perfectly imprinted upon someone. To be firmly established in religion. (A dyer) The Quran states:\n«صِبۡغَۃَ اللّٰہِ ۚ وَ مَنۡ اَحۡسَنُ مِنَ اللّٰہِ صِبۡغَۃً» (2/138) The color belongs to Allah. And what color could be better than Allah's color?\nNote: (Baptism: It is a Christian religious ritual. Through this ritual, a non-Christian is made a Christian by either immersing them in dyed water or sprinkling water upon them).","«صِبْغَۃ» That is the color that applies itself, whether in a material or spiritual sense.","color","صبغۃ","2:138-23:20",2
1710,369,"L","اَنَارَ","«نُوْر» means light that reveals things (manifesting), that is, the spreading light which aids in seeing objects (detailed). «نُوْر» is used in both material and spiritual contexts.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«اَفَمَنۡ شَرَحَ اللّٰہُ صَدۡرَہٗ  لِلۡاِسۡلَامِ  فَہُوَ عَلٰی نُوۡرٍ مِّنۡ رَّبِّہٖ» (39:22)  \nTranslation: Is he whose breast Allah has opened for Islam and who is upon light from his Lord?  \nIn this verse, light signifies both the guidance of the path and the light of the heart.  \nLight is of three types:  \n(1) The light of luminous objects, such as the sun, moon, stars, and lamps, without which a person cannot see visible things.  \n(2) The light of the eye, without which the light of luminous objects is useless.  \n(3) The light of revelation or religion, without which a person cannot benefit from the light of guidance, just as one cannot see visible things without the eye. Similarly, for those blind of heart, divine teachings become ineffective.  \nThe word light is also sometimes used in the sense of «مُنَوَّر». For instance, some scholars translate the following verse as:  \n«اَللّٰہُ  نُوۡرُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (24:35)  \nTranslation: Allah is the one who illuminates or enlightens the heavens and the earth.  \nIn our view, translating «نُوْر» as «نُوْر» is preferable, as it encompasses all types of light and is more eloquent than «مُنَوَّر».","«مُنِیْر» a light that is bright and radiant yet generates no heat or redness.","Light","انار","2:17-2:257-3:184-4:174-5:15-5:16-5:44-5:46-6:1-6:91-6:122-7:157-9:32-10:5-13:16-14:1-14:5-22:8-24:35-24:40-25:61-31:20-33:43-33:46-35:20-35:25-39:22-39:69-42:52-57:9-57:12-57:13-57:19-57:28-61:8-64:8-65:11-66:8-71:16",39
1711,369,"L","ضِیَاء ۔ نار","The essence of «ضَوء» and «نُوْر» is the same, that is «ن و ر». Noor is that light which possesses illumination and brightness but lacks heat, intensity, and redness in color. If there is also illumination along with a predominant element of heat, intensity, and redness, then it is «نَار». Moreover, the word «اَلنَّار» often comes in the sense of «نَارِ جَھَنَّم».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«اِنَّہُمۡ صَالُوا النَّارِ» (38:59)  \nTranslation: Indeed, those people will enter Hell.\n\n«ضِیَاء» is specific in contrast to Noor, and Noor is general. In other words, «ضِیَاء» is also a type of light that includes heat, intensity, and redness. And in the words of the author of *Al-Furqan al-Lughawiyyah*, «ضِیَاء» is that light whose components permeate the air and whiten it, and its application is to the sunlight during the day (faqih 256).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الشَّمۡسَ ضِیَآءً وَّ الۡقَمَرَ نُوۡرًا» (10:5)  \nTranslation: He is Allah, the One who made the sun a radiant light (*dhiya'*) and the moon a light (*noor*).\n\nThe word *dhiya'* is also used for the light of fire and a lamp, besides the sun.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:  \n«مَثَلُہُمۡ کَمَثَلِ الَّذِی اسۡتَوۡقَدَ نَارًا ۚ  فَلَمَّاۤ اَضَآءَتۡ مَا حَوۡلَہٗ ذَہَبَ اللّٰہُ بِنُوۡرِہِمۡ» (2:17)  \nTranslation: The example of those people is like that of a person who kindled a fire in the dark night. Then when the fire illuminated the surrounding things, Allah took away their light.\n\nAnd the word *noor* is used for the light of the moon and stars, as mentioned in the above verse.\n\nMoreover, Allah the Most High has described the Messenger of Allah ﷺ as سِرَاجًا مُّنِیْرًا (33:46), which indicates that he ﷺ did not contain the element of heat and intensity.","«ضِیَاء» when the element of light is less and heat and intensity are more.","Light","ضیاء ۔ نار","2:17-2:20-10:5-20:22-21:48-26:33-27:12-28:32-28:71-37:46",10
1712,369,"L","جَلَّی","«جَلَو ، جَلَا» means to appear, to be manifest, to become evident, and to make something manifest and evident. Jali script is a famous term that carries these same meanings. It is commonly referred to as being written with a thick pen.\n\nAnd «جَلّٰی» means to become manifest or appear prominently as something bright and illuminated, and to illuminate.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ النَّہَارِ  اِذَا  جَلّٰىہَا» (91/3)\nTranslation: And by the day when it reveals it.\n\nAnd «جَلْوَۃ» means to adorn a woman and present her to her husband. And «اِسْتَجْلٰی» means for a bride to be adorned and go before her husband. And «اَلْاَجْلٰی» means radiant, clear, and beautiful-faced (munjad). And «تَجَلّٰی» means the excellent manifestation of a radiant and beautiful thing (munjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when his Lord manifested upon the mountain, (by the Tajalli of Divine Lights) He leveled it to the ground.","«جَلّی» the radiant and evident nature of something beautiful.","Light","جلی","7:143-7:187-91:3-92:2",4
1713,369,"L","وَھَّجَ","«اَلْوَھْجَ» meaning the blaze of fire. The blaze of the sun or fire. Heat and splendor (Munjid).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ  بَنَیۡنَا فَوۡقَکُمۡ  سَبۡعًا شِدَادًا وَّ  جَعَلۡنَا سِرَاجًا وَّہَّاجًا» (78:12,13)\nTranslation: And He has built above you seven strong (heavens) and made a luminous lamp (the sun).","«وَھْج» a light of intense heat, fierce glow, and deep redness.","Light","وھج","78:13",1
1714,369,"L","اَشْرَقَ","«اَلْاِشْرَاق» is a well-known term. It refers to the time after sunrise and the ensuing light. And «اَشْرَقَتِ الشَّمْسُ» means the sun rising and becoming brightly illuminated.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا» (39:69)  \nTranslation: And the earth will shine brightly with the light of its Lord.","the light of the forenoon","Light","اشرق","38:18-39:69",2
1715,369,"L","اَسْفَرَ","«سَفَرَ» means (a woman's) face unveiling, lifting the veil (manjad). And «سَفَرَ عَنِ الْوَجْہ» face unveiling (muf). «اَسْفَرَ الْوَجْہُ» means face shining. Being beautiful. And «اَسْفَرَ الصُّبْح» morning's brightness (manjad) morning light. Dawn's first light.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّیۡلِ  اِذۡ  اَدۡبَرَ وَ  الصُّبۡحِ  اِذَاۤ   اَسۡفَرَ» (74/34)\nTranslation: And when the night turns away, and when the morning brightens.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command of the Exalted states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ مُّسۡفِرَۃٌ ضَاحِکَۃٌ  مُّسۡتَبۡشِرَۃٌ» (80/38)\nTranslation: How many faces will be radiant that day, smiling and joyful.","«سَفْرَ» the morning light, the radiance of dawn, and the glow and beauty of the face.","light","اسفر","74:34-80:38",2
1716,369,"L","اَبْصَرَ","«بَصَرَ» means 'to see.' And «مُبْصِر» means 'so bright that all things become easily visible.' (Detailed) For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ لِتَسۡکُنُوۡا فِیۡہِ وَ النَّہَارَ  مُبۡصِرًا» (10/67) Translation: He is the One who made the night for your rest, and made the day bright.","«مُبْصِر», so bright that everything can be seen easily in its light.","Light","ابصر","6:104-7:201-10:67-17:12-17:59-18:26-19:38-27:13-27:86-32:12-37:175-37:179-40:61",13
1717,370,"F","صَائِم","«صَوْم» is the plural of «صِیَام», meaning 'fasting', and «صَامَ» means 'to observe fasting'. That is, from suhoor to iftar, abstaining from eating, drinking, and certain other actions in accordance with Islamic rulings. And «صَائِم» means 'the one who fasts'. For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ الصَّآئِمِیۡنَ وَ الصّٰٓئِمٰتِ» (33/35). Translation: 'And the men who fast and the women who fast.'","The one who fasts is called «صَائِم».","Faster","صائم","33:35",1
1718,370,"F","سَائِح","«سَیْح ، اَلسَّاحَۃ» means an open space and the courtyard of a house. And «سَاحَ» means to travel and tour, to wander in open land, and to travel to distant places.  \nAnd «سَاحَ» means to observe fasting and to adhere to all its rulings, i.e., besides abstaining from food and drink, also avoiding sins of the limbs such as the eyes, ears, tongue, etc. (figurative). And according to Minj, «سَائِح» refers to a fasting person who stays in the mosque (Minj).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اَلتَّآئِبُوۡنَ الۡعٰبِدُوۡنَ الۡحٰمِدُوۡنَ السَّآئِحُوۡنَ» (9:112)  \nTranslation: Those who repent, those who worship, those who praise, and those who fast.","«سَائِح» A fasting person is one who, besides abstaining from food and drink, also observes the other obligatory restrictions.","faster","سائح","9:112-66:5",2
1719,371,"T","مَنَعَ","«مَنَعَ» is primarily used in two meanings:\n(1) To not give (the opposite of granting/giving) – to withhold; to be stingy. And «مَنَّاع» means a stingy person (masc.).\n(2) To restrain someone with one's hand or tongue; to not allow someone to do something; to deprive; to prevent (from doing something).\n\nExample: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ مَّنَعَ مَسٰجِدَ اللّٰہِ اَنۡ یُّذۡکَرَ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُہٗ» (2/114)\nTranslation: And who is more unjust than he who prevents the mention of Allah's name from being celebrated in His mosques?","to restrain one's hand or tongue","to restrain","منع","2:114-4:141-7:12-9:54-12:63-17:59-17:94-18:55-20:92-21:43-38:75-59:2-107:7",13
1720,371,"T","نَھٰی","The term «اَلنَّھْی» is generally used to denote the prevention or restraint from evils or vices.  \nFor example: The Quran states: «وَ اَمَّا مَنۡ خَافَ مَقَامَ رَبِّہٖ وَ نَہَی النَّفۡسَ عَنِ  الۡہَوٰی» (79/40)  \nTranslation: Then whoever fears standing before his Lord and restrains himself from the desires of the self.","«نَھٰی» to prevent evil.","to withhold","نھی","3:104-3:110-3:114-4:31-4:161-6:26-6:28-7:165-7:166-9:67-9:71-11:116-16:90-22:41-29:45-58:8-79:40-96:9",18
1721,371,"T","عَوَّقَ","«اَلْعَوْق وَالْعُوْق» means a useless person. One who prevents people from good deeds (munjad) and «عَوَّقَ» comes in the meanings of (one who prevents from good deeds). For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ اللّٰہُ  الۡمُعَوِّقِیۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الۡقَآئِلِیۡنَ لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ   اِلَیۡنَا» (33/18). Translation: Allah Almighty knows well those among you who prevent people (from jihad, etc.) and say, 'Come to us.'","Deterring from virtuous or good deeds.","to stop","عوق","33:18",1
1722,371,"T","عَضَلَ","«عَضَلَ» means to cause hardship, to prohibit (manj); to strictly prevent (muf). «عَضُلَہ» means muscle. And «عَضَّلَ» means to cause hardship in reaching, to obstruct in obtaining the desired goal (manj). This word is generally used by a man to prevent a woman from marriage, to cause her distress and trouble, so that some benefit may be gained from this action.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَعۡضُلُوۡہُنَّ لِتَذۡہَبُوۡا بِبَعۡضِ مَاۤ اٰتَیۡتُمُوۡہُنَّ» (4/19)\nTranslation: And do not hold them back on the pretext of taking back some of what you have given them (as mahr).","To keep someone from something in order to gain some benefit.","to forbid","عضل","2:232-4:19",2
1723,371,"T","اَمْسَکَ","«اَمْسَکَ» to hold onto something firmly and protect it (transitive). This term is generally used when something is already in one's possession and one does not allow it to slip from one's hand. It also conveys the meaning of stinginess in «مُمِسْک».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَمۡسِکُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ اَوۡ سَرِّحُوۡہُنَّ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ» (2/231)\nTranslation: So either retain them (the divorced women) in an acceptable manner or release them in an acceptable manner.","Do not let what you have slip from your grasp.","to prevent","امسک","2:231-2:256-4:15-5:4-7:170-16:59-16:79-17:100-22:65-31:22-33:37-35:2-35:41-38:39-39:38-39:42-43:21-43:43-60:10-65:2-67:19-67:21",22
1724,371,"T","صَدَّ","«صَدَّ» meaning to stop, to remove, to prevent. And «صَدَّ عَنْ» meaning to turn away, to incline (manjada), to stop with gentle treatment (vol. 188), turning away and deviation. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «المیل اِلٰی اَحَدِ الْجَانِبَیْن وَ عَدَلَ عَنْہُ ( م ل ) اور صَدّٓ» means «مَنَعَ عَنْ قَصْدِ الشَّیْءُ خَاصَۃٌ» (vol. 92), i.e., to stop someone from their intention and resolve. Thus, the word «صَدّ» comes to mean stopping someone from their purpose with a gentle policy.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ تَذُوۡقُوا السُّوۡٓءَ بِمَا صَدَدۡتُّمۡ  عَنۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (16/94). Translation: So now taste the penalty for what you used to hinder from the way of Allah.","«صَدَّ» Gradually deter someone from their intention through gentle conduct.","to restrain","صد","2:217-3:99-4:55-4:61-4:160-4:167-5:2-5:91-7:45-7:86-8:34-8:36-8:47-9:34-11:19-13:33-14:3-14:10-16:94-20:16-22:25-27:24-27:43-28:87-29:38-34:32-34:43-40:37-43:37-43:62-47:1-47:32-47:34-48:25-58:16-63:2-63:5",37
1725,371,"T","اَحْصَرَ","«اَحْصَرَ» means to encircle, to besiege, to surround, or to constrict someone's place. And «حِصَار» means fortress. And «حَاصَرَ» means to encircle and block aid, i.e., (military assistance) to prevent. (Manjad)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ الَّذِیۡنَ اُحۡصِرُوۡا فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ لَا یَسۡتَطِیۡعُوۡنَ ضَرۡبًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (2/273) Translation: That (expenditure) is for the poor who are restricted in the way of Allah and cannot travel in the land.","«اَحْصَرَ» to encircle and restrain, and to constrict.","to stop","احصر","2:196-2:273-4:90-9:5",4
1726,371,"T","حَظَرَ","«حَظَرَ» means to encircle something for its protection or to enclose it within a boundary.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ مَا  کَانَ عَطَـآءُ  رَبِّکَ  مَحۡظُوۡرًا» (17/20)  \nTranslation: And your Lord's grace is not withheld from anyone.","«حَظَرَ» to stop by erecting a barrier.","to stop","حظر","17:20",1
1727,371,"T","عَکَفَ","«عَکَفَ» meaning: to focus on something with reverence and remain attached to it; to remain closed, to keep stopped, to be imprisoned. For example, in the Holy Quran it is said: «عَنِ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ  وَ الۡہَدۡیَ مَعۡکُوۡفًا اَنۡ یَّبۡلُغَ مَحِلَّہٗ» (48/25) Translation: These are the ones who disbelieved and barred you from the Sacred Mosque, and also prevented the sacrificial animals from reaching their designated place.","«عَکَفَ» to voluntarily abstain out of reverence.","to stop","عکف","2:125-2:187-7:138-20:91-20:97-21:52-22:25-26:71",8
1728,371,"T","کَفَّ","«کَفّ» means palm and «کَفَّ» means to stop a strike aimed at the palm. It also carries the meanings of to repel, save, stop (transitive). Subsequently, this word began to be used in the sense of merely stopping a strike or providing protection.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذۡ ہَمَّ قَوۡمٌ اَنۡ یَّبۡسُطُوۡۤا اِلَیۡکُمۡ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ فَکَفَّ اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ عَنۡکُمۡ» (5:11)\nTranslation: When a people intended to strike at you, Allah the Most High restrained their hands from you.","«کَفَّ» to stop or repel an attack.","to restrain","کف","4:77-4:91-5:11-21:39-48:24",5
1729,371,"T","ثَبَّطَ","«ثَبَّطَ» means delaying a task, not doing it, remaining inactive regarding it, and implies procrastination and laziness. «اَثْبَطَہُ الْمَرْض» refers to an illness clinging to someone and not leaving them (manjad), and «ثَبَّطَہُ الْمَرْض» means being prevented by illness (manjad) from accomplishing any task due to delay or laziness.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ لَوۡ  اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا  لَہٗ  عُدَّۃً وَّ لٰکِنۡ  کَرِہَ  اللّٰہُ  انۡۢبِعَاثَہُمۡ  فَثَبَّطَہُمۡ» (9/46) Translation: Had they intended to go forth, they would have made some preparation for it. But Allah was not pleased with their going forth, so He hindered them (due to their own laziness).","«ثَبَّطَ» to stop and hinder due to laziness and delay.","to stop/hold back","ثبط","9:46",1
1730,371,"T","ذَادَ","«ذَادَ» means: to push away, to repel, to prevent from approaching, or to keep back (from the root م-ن-ج). And «ذَوَّدَ عَنْ حَسْبِہٖ» means: to protect and support someone's self (from the same root).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَ  وَجَدَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِہِمُ  امۡرَاَتَیۡنِ تَذُوۡدٰنِ» (28/23).  \nTranslation: And Moses, peace be upon him, saw that behind them were two women who were standing, holding back their sheep.","To repel «ذَادَ» and prevent it from drawing near, and to keep it restrained.","to stop","ذاد","28:23",1
1731,371,"T","وَزَعَ","«وَزَعَ» meaning to restrain, to prohibit. And «وَزَعَ الْجَیْش» meaning to arrange the army into organized ranks. And «اَلْاَوْزَع» meaning groups or divisions. Its singular is not «اَلْوَزْعَۃُ». And its plural is «وَازِعُ», meaning the helpers and protectors of the king (munjid). Thus, the word «وَزَعَ» comes in the meanings of restraint and arrangement for the purpose of organization.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ حُشِرَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ  مِنَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  وَ الطَّیۡرِ  فَہُمۡ  یُوۡزَعُوۡنَ» (27:17)\nTranslation: And armies of jinn, humans, and birds were gathered for Solomon, and they were organized into ranks.","«وَزَعَ» to stop in order to arrange and organize.","to restrain","وزع","27:17-27:83-41:19",3
1732,371,"T","حَبَسَ","«حَبَسَ» means to confine, to protect completely, to prohibit (manj), and to prevent someone from rising. (muf)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ» ( 5/106 )\nTranslation: So detain both of them after the 'Asr prayer.","«حَبَسَ» Preventing from standing, preventing from departing.","to stop","حبس","5:106-11:8",2
1733,371,"T","حِجْرًا","«حَجَرَ» is a metaphor for a hard stone, and «حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» is an idiom. It denotes an insurmountable obstacle that cannot be removed. In pre-Islamic times, it was customary that when someone who instilled fear of harm approached, they would say «حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» (meaning we seek refuge with you), and the enemy would remain silent. The Quran has also employed this idiom, for example: In the Quran, it is stated: «یَوۡمَ یَرَوۡنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  لَا بُشۡرٰی یَوۡمَئِذٍ لِّلۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ حِجۡرًا مَّحۡجُوۡرًا» (25/22). Translation: On the day they see the angels, there will be no good news for the sinners, and they will say, God willing, you are restrained (and sealed off), O Jalandhari.","«حِجْرًا مَّھْجُوْرًا» is used metaphorically to mean seeking refuge from loss and damage.","to stop","حجرًا","6:138-25:22-25:53",3
1734,371,"T","اِنْتَھٰی","«اِنْتَھٰی» to stop. to return. to choose to adhere to prohibitions and then to abandon them.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یَصُدَّکُمۡ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ وَ عَنِ الصَّلٰوۃِ ۚ فَہَلۡ اَنۡتُمۡ مُّنۡتَہُوۡنَ» (5/91)\nTranslation: and (so that Satan may hinder you from the remembrance of Allah and from prayer) through wine and gambling. Then will you return?","«اِنْتَھٰی» Abstain from reprehensible acts and prohibitions.","to restrain","انتھی","2:192-2:193-2:275-4:171-5:73-5:91-8:19-8:38-8:39-9:12-19:46-26:116-26:167-33:60-36:18-53:14-53:42-59:7-96:15",19
1735,371,"T","اَکْدٰی","«اَلْکُدْیَۃ» means hard and solid ground, or a hard rock. And «حَفَرَ فَاکْدٰی» means reaching hard ground while digging a pit (muf). And «کَدّٰی» means to ask or to seek forgiveness. And «سَاَلَہٗ فَاَکْدٰی» implies that when he asked, he found it like hard ground and gave nothing (minjad), as if this word conveys the meaning of stopping after a little spending. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَعۡطٰی قَلِیۡلًا  وَّ  اَکۡدٰی» (53/34) Translation: He gave a little then stopped (withheld his hand).","«اَکْدٰی» the hardening and stiffening of the heart due to spending wealth.","to stop","اکدی","7:58-53:34",2
1736,371,"T","اِشْمَاَزّ","«شَمَزَ» means to detest something hateful. And «اِشْمَاَزَّ» means to become constricted or heart-constricted. (Munjid)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  اِذَا ذُکِرَ اللّٰہُ  وَحۡدَہُ  اشۡمَاَزَّتۡ قُلُوۡبُ الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (39/45)\nTranslation: And when Allah alone is mentioned, the hearts of those who do not believe in the Hereafter become constricted.","«اِشْمَاَزَّ» to be deterred by something unpleasant.","to prevent","اشماز","39:45",1
1737,371,"T","قَلَعَ","«قَلَعَ» means to abandon or leave something; to leave and to cease (i.e., to stop). It also denotes abruptly discontinuing an ongoing action. For example, the Quran states: «وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ وَ یٰسَمَآءُ اَقۡلِعِیۡ وَ غِیۡضَ الۡمَآءُ» (11:44). Translation: And it was commanded, 'O earth, swallow your water, and O sky, cease,' and the water subsided.","«قَلَعَ» to abruptly stop a task that has already been started.","to stop; to hold back; to restrain","قلع","11:44",1
1738,372,"T","حَطَمَ","«حَطَمَ» meaning to break or crush.  \nAnd «حَطُوْم» refers to a fierce, violent wind that smashes and crushes everything.  \nAnd «حُطَام» denotes something that has been crushed, pulverized, or fragmented (minjad). This word is used for crushing something into tiny pieces (muf). To crush completely. To grind. To pulverize.  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«قَالَتۡ نَمۡلَۃٌ  یّٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّمۡلُ ادۡخُلُوۡا مَسٰکِنَکُمۡ ۚ لَا یَحۡطِمَنَّکُمۡ  سُلَیۡمٰنُ  وَ جُنُوۡدُہٗ ۙ وَ ہُمۡ  لَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (27/18)  \nTranslation: An ant said, O ants! Enter your dwellings, so that Solomon and his army do not crush you while you are unaware.","«حَطَمَ» to crush and pulverize, or to break and smash.","to crush","حطم","27:18",1
1739,372,"T","وَطَاَ","«وَطَا» has two meanings: (1) «وَطَا» means to trample underfoot, to crush (in Punjabi, 'lataarna' [لتاڑنا]). (The word 'wati' [وطی] also appears in meanings related to coitus.) Although these meanings do not appear in the Quran.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رِجَالٌ مُّؤۡمِنُوۡنَ وَ نِسَآءٌ  مُّؤۡمِنٰتٌ لَّمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡہُمۡ  اَنۡ  تَطَئُوۡہُمۡ فَتُصِیۡبَکُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَرَّۃٌۢ  بِغَیۡرِ عِلۡمٍ» (48/25)\nTranslation: And if it were not for the believing men and believing women whom you did not know, if you had trampled them [underfoot], you would have harmed them unknowingly.\n\nAnd the second meaning of «وَطَا» is to endure severe hardship, to suffer great distress (in 'Manjad' [منجد]).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ نَاشِئَۃَ الَّیۡلِ  ہِیَ اَشَدُّ وَطۡاً  وَّ  اَقۡوَمُ قِیۡلًا» (73/6)\nTranslation: Indeed, rising at night is hard, but it is more suitable for recitation and more effective for speech. (Jalandhari) It means severe trampling/crushing. (Osmani)","«وَطَا» to trample or crush underfoot.","to crush","وطا","9:120-33:27-48:25-73:6",4
1740,373,"L","زَھْرَۃ","«زَھْرَۃ» beauty, glitter and shine. Tinkling. And «زَھْرَۃُ الدُّنْیَا» meaning the world's superficial glitter and glamour (munajjad). This word is generally used for the fleeting allurements and colors of this unstable world.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ  اِلٰی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ زَہۡرَۃَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا» (20/131)\nTranslation: And do not let your eyes be diverted towards the worldly glitter and glamour which We have provided for various people as a means of enjoyment in the life of this world.","The word «زَھْرَۃ» is used for the external beauty and adornment of the plants of the world.","Luster","زھرۃ","20:131",1
1741,373,"S","نَضْرَۃً","«نَضْرَۃ» The radiance, beauty, and freshness of the face. Handsome (Munjid. m. l). Although lexically its usage is correct for both faces and plants, however, in the Holy Quran, this word has been used only for the radiance of the face wherever it occurs. For instance, the Holy Quran states: «وُجُوۡہٌ   یَّوۡمَئِذٍ  نَّاضِرَۃٌ اِلٰی رَبِّہَا نَاظِرَۃٌ» (75/22,23) Translation: On that day many faces will be resplendent, gazing at their Lord.","«نَضْرَۃ» is used for the adornment of the face.","Splendor","نضرۃً","75:22-76:11-83:24",3
1742,373,"L","بَھْجَۃ","«بَھْجَۃ» refers to everything that pleases the heart, and its fundamental meaning is delight or joy. According to Khaleel, it is associated with the good color and freshness of something (Faqih 216). It also applies to humans, but it is more frequently used for the freshness, verdancy, and lushness of plants, especially when they are in full spring bloom.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً ۚ فَاَنۡۢبَتۡنَا بِہٖ حَدَآئِقَ ذَاتَ بَہۡجَۃٍ» (27/60)\nTranslation: And who sends down water from the sky? Then We bring forth thereby gardens of verdant greenery.","«بَھْجَۃ» comes for the beauty of plants.","luster","بھجۃ","22:5-27:60-50:7",3
1743,374,"S","سَرَاب","«سَرَاب» is the sand which, at noon in a desert wilderness, appears like water due to the intensity of the sun's heat. Any drinkable thing is called «شَرَاب». And that which apparently looks like wine but in reality is not a drinkable thing is called «سَرَاب» (metaphorical). Then, metaphorically, its usage applies to every unreal thing. And generally, the usage of this term applies to that vast expanse of sand which, when seen from a distance at an angle in the sunlight, appears as shimmering water.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39)\nTranslation: Like a mirage in a desert which a thirsty man thinks is water.","«سَرَاب» The sand that, at noon in the wilderness, seems like water due to the harsh sunlight.","sand","سراب","24:39-78:20",2
1744,374,"S","کَثِیْب","«کَثِیْب» a long, broad sand dune (fn. 272)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ تَرۡجُفُ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ الۡجِبَالُ وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73/14)\nTranslation: On the Day when the earth and the mountains shall quake, and the mountains shall become like heaps of slipping sand.","a mound of shifting, slipping sand","sand","کثیب","73:14",1
1745,374,"S","اَحْقَاف","Ahqaf is the plural form, meaning a field consisting of several sand dunes; and Majid, meaning a vast field of sand stretching over hundreds of miles (the desert), and also referring to the inhabited region of western Yemen that was the center of the people of 'Ad (peace be upon them).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ  اَخَا عَادٍ ؕ اِذۡ  اَنۡذَرَ قَوۡمَہٗ بِالۡاَحۡقَافِ» (46/21)\nTranslation: And remember the brother of the people of 'Ad, Hud, when he warned his people in the land of Ahqaf.","A vast plain comprising many sand dunes.","Sand","احقاف","46:21",1
1746,375,"A","عَفَو","Two fundamental meanings are associated with «عَفَا»: (1) to leave or abandon something, and (2) to increase. «عَفَا الشَّعْر» means 'he left the hair so that it may grow longer.' The Prophetic saying states: «قَصُّوا الشَّوَارِبَ وَاعْفُو اللُّحٰی», meaning 'Trim your mustaches and leave your beards (or let them grow).' And «عَفَا الشَّیْ» means 'to increase.' «اَلْعَفْو» means 'excess' or 'superfluous.' «عَفْو مِنَ الْمَال» means 'expenditure' or 'wealth beyond necessity, the giving of which is not difficult'（manjūd）. For example, the Quran states: «وَ یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ مَا ذَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ  ۬ ؕ قُلِ الۡعَفۡوَ» (2/219). Translation: 'And people ask you what they should spend. Say, 'What is beyond your needs.''","«عَفْو» An excess beyond necessity. Spending from current income in such a way that something remains saved; preserving something from the capital when spending it.","Additional","عفو","2:219-7:95",2
1747,375,"A","نَافِلَۃ","«نَفَلَ» means to give as a gift. And «اَنْفَلَ» means to give as spoils of war. And «نَفْل» refers to every action that is beyond obligations and necessities (manj). Voluntary acts of worship (nafl ibadat) are those performed beyond the obligatory and Sunnah acts, purely voluntarily, whether it be prayer, charity, fasting, or Hajj and Umrah.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً  لَّکَ» (17/79) Translation: And perform the Tahajjud prayer during some part of the night. This additional (prayer) is only for you.\n\nIt is as if this additional prayer was obligatory upon him by this ruling, whereas for others it is a voluntary act of worship.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states: «وَ وَہَبۡنَا لَہٗۤ  اِسۡحٰقَ ؕ وَ یَعۡقُوۡبَ  نَافِلَۃً» (21/72) Translation: And We granted Prophet Abraham Isaac. And beyond that, Jacob also (for whom he had not even prayed).","«نَفْل» Voluntary acts of worship that go beyond the obligatory duties.","Additional","نافلۃ","17:79-21:72",2
1748,375,"E","ضِعْف","«ضِعْف» means as much as there is, and more, double.  \nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«اِذًا لَّاَذَقۡنٰکَ ضِعۡفَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ وَ ضِعۡفَ الۡمَمَاتِ ثُمَّ لَا تَجِدُ لَکَ عَلَیۡنَا نَصِیۡرًا » (17/75)  \nTranslation: And if that had happened, We would have given you double punishment in this world and after death, then you would have found no helper against Us.  \nAnd the plural of «ضِعْف» is «ضِعْفَیْن», which is used for additional emphasis.  \nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265)  \nTranslation: Its example is that of a garden on a high ground upon which heavy rain falls, so it yields double the fruit.  \nAnd «ضَاعَفَ» means to increase something greatly.  \nFor example: the Divine Command of Allah, the Most High, is:  \n«وَ اللّٰہُ یُضٰعِفُ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (2/261)  \nTranslation: And Allah multiplies [the reward] for whom He wills.","«ضِعْف» implies the amount that exists and more.  \nAlso see increase and cause to increase.","excess","ضعف","2:265-7:38-17:75-30:39-33:30-33:68-34:37-38:61",8
1749,376,"B","اَکْرَہَ","«کَرِہَ» means to dislike something, to hate. And «اَکْرَہَ» means to force someone into an action they do not wish to do. Thus, its meaning encompasses two fundamental aspects: aversion and compulsion.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«لَاۤ اِکۡرَاہَ فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (2/256)\nTranslation: There is no compulsion in religion (i.e., in accepting Islam).\n\nFurthermore, the command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ  اِنۡ  اَرَدۡنَ تَحَصُّنًا لِّتَبۡتَغُوۡا عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا» (24/33)\nTranslation: Do not force your female slaves (or those under your care) into immorality/prostitution if they wish to remain chaste, merely for the worldly benefit of a few.","«اِکْرَاہ» in the heart's aversion and compulsion.","by force","اکرہ","2:216-2:256-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9",27
1750,376,"B","جَبَرَ","«جَبَرَ» Two fundamental aspects are also inherent in its meanings: (1) coercion, and (2) reformation. That is, to reform something through force and pressure. «جَبَرَ الْعَظْم» meaning to set a broken bone straight, and «جَبَرَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» to compel someone to do something. Allah Almighty, while describing His attributes, states:\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n\n«الۡعَزِیۡزُ  الۡجَبَّارُ  الۡمُتَکَبِّرُ» (59/23)\n\nTranslation: (Allah Almighty) is the All-Prevailing, the Almighty, and the Most Great.\n\nThereafter, this term is sometimes used in the sense of pure coercion.\n\nFor example: The divine command is:\n\n«وَ  اِذَا  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  بَطَشۡتُمۡ  جَبَّارِیۡنَ» (26/130)\n\nTranslation: And when you seize [someone], seize them unjustly.","«جَبَرَ» to force or pressure someone into correcting something.","by force","جبر","5:22-11:59-14:15-19:14-19:32-26:130-28:19-40:35-50:45-59:23",10
1751,376,"F","قَھَرَ","«قَھْر» Two fundamental principles are essentially evident: (1) dominance, and (2) humiliation—meaning to dominate over someone and to humiliate the defeated. The oppression of a powerful (strong) person over a weak one. For example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَاَمَّا  الۡیَتِیۡمَ  فَلَا تَقۡہَرۡ وَ اَمَّا السَّآئِلَ  فَلَا تَنۡہَرۡ» ( 93/9،10 )\nTranslation: Do not oppress any orphan, nor drive away any beggar.","The terms «قَھْر» convey the meanings of force and pressure.","forcibly","قھر","6:18-6:61-7:127-12:39-13:16-14:48-38:65-39:4-40:16-93:9",10
1752,376,"F","سَخَّرَ","«سَخَرَ» means to mock or ridicule. And «سَخَّرَ» has two fundamental aspects: (1) coercion, and (2) purposeful direction—that is, to forcefully bring something toward a specific purpose. To compel something into service. To be bound by a command. In this, there is no role for anyone's will or preference. This term is generally used for matters concerning the subjugation of the cosmos.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ ۚ  وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ» (14/33)\nTranslation: And He has made the sun and the moon subservient for you, both constantly pursuing their courses. And (similarly) He has made the day and the night subservient for you.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَ رَفَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ فَوۡقَ بَعۡضٍ دَرَجٰتٍ لِّیَتَّخِذَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ بَعۡضًا سُخۡرِیًّا» (43/32)\nTranslation: And they have been given degrees above one another so that they may be of service to each other.","to force something toward a purpose","Forcibly","سخر","2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7",24
1753,376,"B","رَھِقَ","«رَھِقَ» means one thing climbing over another and covering it (transitive), and «رَھِقَہُ الْاَمْر» means a matter has forcibly suppressed it (compelled), as if «رَھِقَ» encompasses two elements: (1) forcefulness, (2) climbing to cover or conceal.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ ذِلَّۃٌ» (68:43)  \nTranslation: Their eyes will be downcast, and humiliation will overwhelm them.","«رَھِقَ» The meaning of covering or concealing force and names is found.","by force","رھق","10:26-10:27-18:73-68:43-70:44-72:6-72:13-74:17-80:41",9
1754,377,"W","قُرْحٌ","«قُرْحٌ» meaning pinholes, sores, itching, wounds, and their plurals. This can occur due to internal effects as well as external ones. Referring to sores and the resulting wounds (ulcers), and subsequently the pain and discomfort arising from those wounds, «قُرْحٌ» is also applied (figuratively). «قُرُوْح» actually denotes wounds whose impact is confined to the skin, whether the skin is blistered, scratched, or has sores/blisters.\n\nFor instance: The Holy Quran states: «اِنۡ یَّمۡسَسۡکُمۡ قَرۡحٌ فَقَدۡ مَسَّ الۡقَوۡمَ قَرۡحٌ مِّثۡلُہٗ» (3/140) Translation: If you have been wounded, then those [disbelieving] people have also been wounded similarly.","«قُرْحٌ» A wound whose effect is limited to the skin.","wound","قرح","3:140-3:172",2
1755,377,"W","جُرُوْح","«جُرُوْح» is the plural of «جُرْحٌ», meaning 'ghao' (wound), a deep wound. And «جَرَّاح» means 'sirjan' (creator), one who tears open wounds (mandaj). And «جَوَارِح» is the plural of «جَارِحَۃ», meaning animals or birds that hunt by inflicting deep wounds and then leave the prey. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ السِّنَّ بِالسِّنِّ ۙ وَ الۡجُرُوۡحَ قِصَاصٌ» (5/45). Translation: And the recompense for a tooth is a tooth, and for wounds is their equivalent.","«جُرْحٌ» denotes deep wounds. For earthquake, see tremble.","Wound","جروح","5:45",1
1756,378,"T","دَھْر","«دَھْر» is the time of the universe, the duration of the world. From the moment the universe began until its end time (muf), and Ibn al-Farsi states that the meaning is found in «دَھَرَ» and «قَھَر», and «دَھْر»—that is, this name for time—is because it passes over all things and prevails over them (m. l). Moreover, «دَھْر» is connected to the divine will. The Prophetic Hadith ﷺ says «لَا تَسُبُّوا الدَّھْرَ فَاِنَّ اللہَ ھُوَ الدَّھْر», meaning: Do not speak ill of time (dahr), for Allah Himself is Dahr. A person who neither affirms God nor His attributes is called a heretic or a Dahriyyah. Their belief is that time is eternal and everlasting, and there is no life after this. The philosophy of Dahriyyah is well-known.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ہَلۡ  اَتٰی عَلَی الۡاِنۡسَانِ حِیۡنٌ مِّنَ الدَّہۡرِ  لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ شَیۡئًا مَّذۡکُوۡرًا» (76/1)\nTranslation: There was a time when man was not even a thing worth mentioning.\nThat is, there was a period in time when man had no name or sign whatsoever.","«دَھْر» the time from the creation of the universe to its end.","Time","دھر","45:24-76:1",2
1757,378,"T","عَصْر","Two meanings are found for «عَصْر»: (1) the last part of the day; (2) night and day, era, time (stages, masculine, plural), i.e., from when day and night came into existence and as long as they will exist. However, in our opinion, this meaning or definition is debatable. And the meaning of «عَصْر» should be the period from the creation of the human species until the Day of Judgment. The reason for this is that Allah describes «عَصْر» as a witness (testimony) upon the human species. And when humanity did not even exist, how can there be testimony? And Allah knows best what is correct!\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «وَ الۡعَصۡرِ اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ لَفِیۡ خُسۡرٍ» (103/1).  \nTranslation: By time, indeed mankind is in loss.  \nAnd it is evident that night and day came into existence long before the creation of Adam.\n\n«دَھْر» and, according to the above explanation of «عَصْر», these words should not be pluralized. However, in lexicographical books, the plural of «دَھْر» is «دُھُوْر» and the plural of «عَصْر» is «عُصُوْر». This is because in common usage, «دَھر» and «عَصْر» are understood to mean merely a long period of time.","«عَصْر» the time from the creation of humanity until the Day of Judgment.","Time","عصر","103:1",1
1758,378,"T","قَرْن","«قَرْن» means a period of a hundred years. It refers to the people of one era, one nation after another nation, one generation and its period (manzad). Thus, «قَرْن» can be applied to one or two eras and the people of that time, just as the word «قَرْیَۃ» is used for a settlement and its inhabitants, with its plural being «قُرُوْن». In the Quran, this word has generally been used for the people of a particular era.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ  فَمَا  بَالُ  الۡقُرُوۡنِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (20/51)\nTranslation: Pharaoh asked Moses, What is the condition of the earlier nations?","«قَرْن» means a period of a hundred years. It refers to the people of an era, one nation succeeding another, and a generation along with its timeframe.","time","قرن","6:6-10:13-11:116-17:17-19:74-19:98-20:51-20:128-23:31-23:42-25:38-28:43-28:45-28:78-32:26-36:31-38:3-46:17-50:36",19
1759,378,"T","حُقْبَۃ","«حُقْبَۃ» a period of 80 years or more. Long duration, indefinite period (muf), and its plural is also «حُقُب» and «اَحْقَاب». Meaning 'for ages'. And according to the author of Al-Furūq al-Lughawiyyah, this word is derived (emerges) from «حَقِیْبَۃ». And «حَقِیْبَۃ» refers to that leather bag in which a rider keeps his belongings and places them along with his mount. Therefore, «حَقَب» is not a part of time but a type of container. That is, the period in which actions and affairs are carried out (Faqīh 224).\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60)\nTranslation: Until I reach the confluence of the two rivers, or I continue traveling for ages.","«حُقْبَۃ» a long period of 80 years or more.","Time","حقبۃ","18:60",1
1760,378,"T","رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن","«رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» refers to the events of time, which are generally used in a negative sense. Additionally, in the Quran, a metaphor «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» meaning the rotation of time has also been employed. It denotes the events of time that are typically used in a negative context, i.e., awaiting calamities—both earthly and heavenly—to befall someone (also see the rotation of days). For example, the Quran states: «اَمۡ  یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ  شَاعِرٌ  نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ  رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ» (52/30). Translation: Or the disbelievers say, He is but a poet; we await for him the calamities of time.","«رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» refers to events of time, which are generally used in a negative sense.","Time","ریب المنون","52:30",1
1761,379,"E","بَرّ","That part of the earth which is dry and is inhabited, or can be inhabited, by humans or other land animals. And this part constitutes one-quarter of the earth's total surface area.","«بَرّ» meaning that part of the land which is dry.","Earth","بر","5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-10:22-17:67-17:68-17:70-27:63-29:65-30:41-31:32",12
1762,379,"E","بَحْر","That part of the Earth which is underwater, meaning the area covered by seas. This area is three times larger than the dry land area. In this part, only aquatic creatures can live, and the term sea also includes rivers that flow over land. For example, the Quran states: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یُسَیِّرُکُمۡ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (10:22)  \nTranslation: He it is Who grants you the ability to travel on land and sea.  \nThe various types of dry land mentioned in the Quran are those for which the terms «جُرُز ، سھُوْل ، سَاھِرَۃ ، صَعِیْد ، قِیْعَۃ ( قوع ) صَفْصَف ، عَرَاء ( عری ) زَلَق ، صَفْوَان ، ( صفو ) فَجْوَۃ ( فج ) صَلْدًا ، سَاحَۃ ( سیح ) رَبْوَۃ ( ربو ) ، نَجْد ، رِیْع ، وَادِی ، مَوَاطِن اور جُدَد» appear.","«بَحْر» The part of the earth that is underwater, i.e., the part on which the seas lie.","Earth","بحر","2:50-2:164-5:96-6:59-6:63-6:97-7:138-7:163-10:22-10:90-14:32-16:14-17:66-17:67-17:70-18:60-18:61-18:63-18:79-18:109-20:77-22:65-24:40-25:53-26:63-27:61-27:63-30:41-31:27-31:31-35:12-42:32-44:24-45:12-52:6-55:19-55:24-81:6-82:3",39
1763,379,"E","جُرُز","«جَرَزَ» meaning 'to cut' and «سَیْفٌ جِرَازٌ» meaning 'the cutting sword' (m. l.) and «اَرْضُ الْجُرْز» meaning dry, barren, and uncultivable land. Such land where rainfall is very scarce (f. l. 70, 266). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «اَوَ لَمۡ یَرَوۡا اَنَّا نَسُوۡقُ الۡمَآءَ  اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ الۡجُرُزِ فَنُخۡرِجُ  بِہٖ زَرۡعًا تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡہُ  اَنۡعَامُہُمۡ وَ اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (32/27) Translation: Do they not see that We cause water to flow to barren land, then bring forth crops from it, which their cattle as well as they themselves consume?","«جُرُز» meaning dry and barren land.","earth","جرز","18:8-32:27",2
1764,379,"E","سُھُوْل","«سَھُوْل» is a collection of «سھل»'s soft and smooth land. Field areas (manjada). For instance, the Noble Quran states: «تَتَّخِذُوۡنَ مِنۡ سُہُوۡلِہَا قُصُوۡرًا» (7:74). Translation: You build palaces on soft ground.","«سَھُوْل» meaning soft earth.","Earth","سھول","7:74",1
1765,379,"E","سَاھِرَۃ","«سَاھِرَۃ» means earth or surface of the earth (i.e., a place of frequent activity). For example, the Quran states: «فَاِنَّمَا ہِیَ زَجۡرَۃٌ   وَّاحِدَۃٌ فَاِذَا  ہُمۡ  بِالسَّاہِرَۃِ» (79:14). Translation: It will be but a single blast, after which they will all (the dead) immediately rise to the surface of the earth.","«سَاھِرَۃ» the face of the earth or the surface of the earth.","Earth","ساھرۃ","79:14",1
1766,379,"T","صَعِیْد","«صَعَدَ» means to ascend. And «صَعِیْد» means the upper part of the earth. The upper part and the dust/soil present on it that rises up (singular) on every flat ground «صَعْد» (verse 16) and means «وَجْہُ الْاَرْض» the soil and dust etc. on top of the earth (for example).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6) Translation: Then if you do not find water, perform tayammum with clean soil.","«صَعِیْد» the dust carried by the wind.","the earth","صعید","4:43-5:6-18:8-18:40",4
1767,379,"E","قَیْعَۃً","«قَیْعَۃً» and «قَاعًا ( قوع )» meaning open field (m. l).\nFor example: in the Noble Quran it is:\n«اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ کَسَرَابٍۭ بِقِیۡعَۃٍ یَّحۡسَبُہُ الظَّمۡاٰنُ مَآءً» (24/39)\nTranslation: Their deeds are like a mirage in a desert which the thirsty one mistakes for water.","«قَیْعَۃً» meaning 'open field'.","Earth","قیعۃً","24:39",1
1768,379,"E","صَفْصَفَ","«صَفْصَفَ» meaning level and even field (fl 264).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is said:  \n«فَیَذَرُہَا  قَاعًا صَفۡصَفًا لَّا  تَرٰی  فِیۡہَا عِوَجًا  وَّ  لَاۤ   اَمۡتًا» (20/106,107)  \nTranslation: Then He will make the earth an open and even field in which you will see no unevenness (depression) nor any elevation (height).","«صَفْصَفَ» meaning an even and level plain.","Earth","صفصف","20:106",1
1769,379,"E","عَرَاء","«عَرَا» means to be naked. And «عَرَاء» refers to a field where there is no cover (i.e., a small desert). (fl 26)\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«فَنَبَذۡنٰہُ  بِالۡعَرَآءِ  وَ  ہُوَ  سَقِیۡمٌ» (37/145)\nTranslation: Then We cast him (Prophet Jonah, peace be upon him) onto a barren field while he was ill.","«عَرَاء» a barren field with no shade.","earth","عراء","37:145-68:49",2
1770,379,"E","زَلَقَ","«زَلَقَ» means to slip. And «صَعِیْدًا زَلَقًا» means slippery ground, where a person may slip.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَعَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ اَنۡ یُّؤۡتِیَنِ خَیۡرًا مِّنۡ جَنَّتِکَ وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتُصۡبِحَ صَعِیۡدًا زَلَقًا» (18/40)\nTranslation: Then there is not far off for me from my Lord that He would give me something better than your garden and would send upon it a heavenly punishment, so it becomes a smooth, empty plain.","«زَلَقَ» a smooth, slippery plain.","Earth","زلق","18:40-68:51",2
1771,379,"E","صَفْوَان","meaning a small smooth rock, salt, or rocky ground.","«صَفْوَان» a smooth-surfaced small rock.","earth","صفوان","2:264",1
1772,379,"E","صَلْدًا","«صَلْدًا» meaning solid and smooth stone. «رَاْسٌ صَلْدٌ» meaning bald head and «صَلْدٌ» meaning dry stone (page 45).  \nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:  \n«فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ صَفۡوَانٍ عَلَیۡہِ تُرَابٌ فَاَصَابَہٗ وَابِلٌ فَتَرَکَہٗ صَلۡدًا» (2/264)  \nTranslation: The example of this wealth is like a rock upon which there is a little soil, then a heavy rain strikes it and leaves it bare.","Smooth and dry stones.","earth","صلدًا","2:264",1
1773,379,"E","فَجْوَۃ","«فَجْوَۃ» An open field between two mountains. A valley. And the path that passes through that field is called «فَجّ» (manjad, m l).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡ فَجۡوَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ» (18/17)\nTranslation: And you would see that when the sun rises, it emerges to the right of their cave, keeping clear of it, and when it sets, it passes to the left, just grazing it. And they are in an open field.","«فَجْوَۃ» the middle ground between two mountains","Earth","فجوۃ","21:31-22:27-71:20",3
1774,379,"E","سَاحَۃ","Open space attached to or near houses: courtyard, courtyard, parks, etc., and gathering places.  \nFor example, in the Quran it says:  \n«اَفَبِعَذَابِنَا یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَ فَاِذَا نَزَلَ بِسَاحَتِہِمۡ فَسَآءَ صَبَاحُ الۡمُنۡذَرِیۡنَ» (37/176,177)  \nTranslation: So do they hasten Our punishment? When it descends into their courtyards, those who had been warned will have a terrible morning.","an open space adjacent to or near houses","earth","ساحۃ","37:177",1
1775,379,"E","رَبْوَۃ","«رَبَا» meaning to increase, to flourish and thrive. And «رَبْوَۃ» meaning elevated, fertile ground (as in Surah Al-Baqarah 266), land that is slightly higher than the ordinary surface and is fertile.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«کَمَثَلِ جَنَّۃٍۭ بِرَبۡوَۃٍ اَصَابَہَا وَابِلٌ فَاٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا ضِعۡفَیۡنِ» (2/265)  \nTranslation: Its example is like a garden on a high place. If it receives heavy rain, it yields double the produce.","[Slightly elevated and fertile land above the common surface level.","Earth","ربوۃ","2:265-23:50",2
1776,379,"L","نَجَد","«نَجْد» meaning valley. It is a high and hard place above the general ground level (F L 267. Muf). Najd also refers to the path that ascends or descends a valley.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ» (90/10)\nTranslation: And We showed him the two valleys (Ottoman). And And We showed him both paths (Jalandhari).","«نَجْد» valley, elevated, and hard ground.","Land","نجد","90:10",1
1777,379,"E","رِیْع","«رِیْع» is a collection of «رِیْعَۃٌ». Such land is that which is elevated and hard (Fayd al-Bari 267).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اَتَبۡنُوۡنَ بِکُلِّ رِیۡعٍ  اٰیَۃً  تَعۡبَثُوۡنَ» (26:128)  \nTranslation: Do you erect on every high place a monument for vain sport?","«رِیْع» somewhat elevated above the general surface.","earth","ریع","26:128",1
1778,379,"E","وَادِی","«وَادِی» Its plural is «اَوْدِیَۃ». It refers to a sloping area situated between mountains. It is vast and spacious. The water from rain, etc., that flows down the mountains also enters it. Then, the stream flowing within that valley is also called a valley. (Definition)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ  اِنِّیۡۤ  اَسۡکَنۡتُ مِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ بِوَادٍ غَیۡرِ  ذِیۡ  زَرۡعٍ» (14/37)\nTranslation: Our Lord! I have settled some of my descendants in an uncultivated valley.","«وَادِی» an open and spacious place enclosed between the mountains where water flows.","Earth","وادی","9:121-13:17-14:37-20:12-26:225-27:18-28:30-46:24-79:16-89:9",10
1779,379,"E","مَوَاطِن","«وَطَنَ» means iqamat, which is to choose a place of residence. And «وَطْن» means the dwelling place of a human being, i.e., the place where one lives, whether one was born there or not. And «مَوَاطِن» is the plural of «مَوْطِن», meaning homeland. And «مِیْطَان» is the term for the place from which horses are sent out for a raid or expedition. (Manjad)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡ مَوَاطِنَ کَثِیۡرَۃٍ» ( 9/25 )\nTranslation: Allah the Almighty granted you victory in many battlefields.","«مَوَاطِن» battlefield.","earth","مواطن","9:25",1
1780,379,"E","جُدَد","«جَدَّ» means something new or cutting something.  \n«جَادَّۃ» means highway, a road's bend, and  \n«جَدَد» means smooth and hard ground.  \nAnd «جُدَّۃ» means a sign of the way and its plural, while «جُدَد» means is.  \n(Manjad) refers to «جُدَّہ», such pieces of hard, smooth ground that appear clearly separate and cut.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیۡبُ سُوۡدٌ» (35:27)  \nTranslation: And in the mountains too are such pieces that are of various colors—white and red, and black as well.","«جُدَد» means a distinct piece of «جُدَّۃ»'s hard and flat land.","Earth","جدد","35:27",1
1781,379,"E","دَکَّ","In its meanings, two basic things are found: (1) to cut, (2) to level. (i.e., to cut something and reduce it to fragments, making it level with the ground's surface).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when the Lord of Moses appeared on the mountain, He leveled it by shattering it.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«اِذَا دُکَّتِ الۡاَرۡضُ دَکًّا دَکًّا» (89/21)\nTranslation: When the earth will be leveled by being cut into pieces (Uthmani).","«دَکَّ» to hack and slash inanimate objects and make them prostrate on the ground.","Earth","دک","7:143-18:98-89:21",3
1782,379,"E","دَمْدَمَ","«دَمْدَمُ الشَّیْء» means to sink something into the earth. And «دَمْدَمَ اللہُ عَلَیْھِمْ» means Allah Almighty destroyed them (munjad). And «دَیْمُوْمَۃ» means desert, sandy desert (muf). For example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«فَدَمۡدَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  رَبُّہُمۡ بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ  فَسَوّٰىہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So Allah sent punishment upon them because of their sins and annihilated them completely.","«دَمْدَمَ» to utterly destroy through punishment.","Earth","دمدم","91:14",1
1783,380,"C","سَلَاسِل","«سَلَاسِل» is a gathering or collection. «سِلْسِلَہ» means to pull one thing from another, like sheathing a sword in its scabbard. And «سَلَّ» means a chain, where one link emerges from the next (mufrad). And «ثُمَّ  فِیۡ سِلۡسِلَۃٍ  ذَرۡعُہَا سَبۡعُوۡنَ  ذِرَاعًا  فَاسۡلُکُوۡہُ» means the continuity or connection of one thing with another, i.e., proceeding while being linked.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ  فِیۡ سِلۡسِلَۃٍ  ذَرۡعُہَا سَبۡعُوۡنَ  ذِرَاعًا  فَاسۡلُکُوۡہُ» (69/32)\nTranslation: Then fasten them with a chain, the length of which is seventy cubits.","«سَلَاسِل» is a well-known term for chain.","Chains","سلاسل","40:71-69:32-76:4",3
1784,380,"C","اَصْفَاد","«اَصْفَاد» is plural, and «صَفَد» and «صِفَاد» mean an iron collar or chain with which captives are shackled. (Singular) And «صَفَدَ» means to bind, to imprison. And «اَصْفَدَ» means to imprison. (Compiled)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ اٰخَرِیۡنَ مُقَرَّنِیۡنَ فِی الۡاَصۡفَادِ» (38/38)\nTranslation: And [also] the other jinn were bound in chains.","«اَصْفَاد» meaning 'collar' or 'chain'.","Chains","اصفاد","14:49-38:38",2
1785,380,"C","اَنْکَال","«اَنْکَال» is the plural of «نَکْل». «نَکْل» refers to chains for animals and iron bits that keep them under control (sing.). «نَکَال» denotes such an exemplary punishment that causes one to be ensnared. And «نَکَّلَ» means to subject someone to an exemplary punishment, or to put chains on someone's feet, or to give a bit (rein).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  لَدَیۡنَاۤ  اَنۡکَالًا وَّ  جَحِیۡمًا وَّ طَعَامًا ذَا غُصَّۃٍ  وَّ عَذَابًا  اَلِیۡمًا» (73:12)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have chains and a blazing fire. And choking food and a painful punishment.","Bridle, shackles, and fetters.","Chains","انکال","73:12",1
1786,380,"C","اَغْلَال","«اَغْلَال» is the plural of «غُلّ», and its plural «غُلُوْل» is also used. And «غُلّ» refers to anything with which a person's limbs are tied and bound together (plural), and its application includes handcuffs, chains, and collars alike. And «غَلَّ» means to put on handcuffs or collars (intensive form), and chains are associated with all of these. For example: the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ  اَعۡتَدۡنَا  لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ سَلٰسِلَا۠ وَ اَغۡلٰلًا  وَّ  سَعِیۡرًا» (76:4)\nTranslation: We have prepared for the disbelievers chains and collars and a blazing fire.","«اَغْلَال» is general and occurs in all meanings, whether it refers to handcuffs, chains, or a collar.","Chains","اغلال","5:64-7:157-12:23-13:5-17:29-34:33-36:8-40:71-76:4",9
1787,381,"A","اَحْیَا","«اَحْیَا» means to give life to the dead, and its opposite, «اَمَاتَ», means death. «حَیِیَ» means to live, to remain alive. It is a well-known word.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کَذٰلِکَ یُحۡیِ اللّٰہُ  الۡمَوۡتٰی  ۙ وَ یُرِیۡکُمۡ اٰیٰتِہٖ» (2:73)\nTranslation: Thus does Allah give life to the dead and show you His signs that you may understand.","«اَحْیَا» to revive any deceased person. It is commonly used.","Alive","احیا","2:28-2:73-2:154-2:164-2:243-2:258-2:259-2:260-3:49-3:156-3:169-5:32-6:122-7:158-8:24-9:116-10:56-15:23-16:21-16:65-22:6-22:66-23:37-23:80-25:49-26:81-29:63-30:19-30:24-30:40-30:50-35:9-35:22-36:12-36:33-36:78-36:79-40:11-40:68-41:39-42:9-44:8-45:5-45:26-46:33-50:11-50:43-53:44-57:2-57:17-75:40-77:26-87:13",53
1788,381,"A","بَعَثَ","«بَعَثَ» Basically, it has two meanings: (1) to lift, to raise; (2) to send forth alone. And when this word is used in relation to the dead who are in their graves, its meaning will be to revive them in their graves and raise them up, and to lead them towards the Field of Resurrection (Mahshar).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\nTranslation: And indeed, the Hour is coming - there is no doubt about it - and indeed, Allah will gather all people together (from) the graves.","«بَعَثَ» to give life to and raise the dead from their graves.","Alive","بعث","2:56-2:259-6:36-6:60-7:14-15:36-16:21-16:38-18:12-18:19-19:15-19:33-22:5-22:7-23:16-23:100-26:87-27:65-30:56-31:28-36:52-37:144-38:79-58:6-58:18-64:7-72:7",27
1789,381,"A","اَنْشَرَ","The fundamental meaning of «نَشَرَ» is to spread, and its opposites, «طَوَی» and «نَشَرَ الْمَیِّتَ نَشُوْرًا», signify the resurrection of the dead. In «اِلَیْہِ النُّشُوْر», three meanings are found: to live, to rise, and to spread. That is, people will come to life and disperse towards it. Furthermore, «اَنْشَرَ» means to revive and cause to spread in the field of Mahshar.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  اَمَاتَہٗ  فَاَقۡبَرَہٗ ثُمَّ  اِذَا شَآءَ  اَنۡشَرَہٗ» (80:21-22)\nTranslation: Then Allah caused that human to die, then buried him in the grave. Then whenever He wills, He will raise him up.","to give life, to raise, and to spread","Alive","انشر","18:16-21:21-42:28-43:11-44:35-74:52-77:3-80:22-81:10-94:1",10
1790,381,"A","حَیِیَ","«حَیِیَ» means to live, to exist. And «حَیٰوۃ» means life. This word possesses a very broad meaning. Animals are certainly living, but contemporary research suggests that even inanimate things possess a form of life. For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ ہِیَ  اِلَّا حَیَاتُنَا الدُّنۡیَا نَمُوۡتُ وَ نَحۡیَا وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِمَبۡعُوۡثِیۡنَ» (23/37)\nTranslation: (The disbelievers) say, There is only our worldly life; we die and live here, and we shall not be raised again.","«حَیِیَ» the death of every living thing.","Alive","حیی","2:85-2:86-2:96-2:179-2:204-2:212-2:255-3:2-3:14-3:27-3:117-3:185-4:74-4:94-4:109-6:29-6:32-6:70-6:95-6:130-6:162-7:25-7:32-7:51-7:152-8:42-9:38-9:55-10:7-10:23-10:24-10:31-10:64-10:88-10:98-11:15-13:26-13:34-14:3-14:27-16:97-16:107-17:75-18:28-18:45-18:46-18:104-19:15-19:31-19:33-19:66-20:72-20:74-20:97-20:111-20:131-21:30-23:33-23:37-24:33-25:3-25:58-28:60-28:61-28:79-29:25-29:64-30:7-30:19-31:33-33:28-35:5-36:70-39:26-40:39-40:51-40:65-41:16-41:31-42:36-43:32-43:35-45:21-45:24-45:35-46:20-47:36-53:29-57:20-67:2-79:38-87:16-89:24",93
1791,381,"A","عَاشَ","«عَاشَ» means to live. And «عَیْش» refers to the life that is found in animals, i.e., the term is used for a living being that can sustain itself by eating and drinking. Essentially, this term «حَیِیَ» is specific, and «مَعِیْشَت اسکی جمع «مَعَائِش» means provisions for life (m.f.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10)\nTranslation: And We have made the earth a resting place for you and provided therein means of livelihood for you.","The life of such a living being whose existence depends on eating and drinking.","Alive","عاش","7:10-15:20-79:11",3
1792,381,"A","اِسْتِحْیَا","«اِسْتِحْیَاء» also signifies feeling shame and keeping or leaving alive (manjad). This word will be used when someone is being beaten in a confrontation. The Divine Command is:\n«یُذَبِّحُوۡنَ اَبۡنَآءَکُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیُوۡنَ نِسَآءَکُمۡ» (2/49)\nTranslation: (O people of Pharaoh) you used to kill your sons and let your daughters live.\nFrom «حَیِیَ», the source «حیوۃ» is also derived. And «حَیَاء» (also meaning shame).","«اِسْتِحْیَاء» to spare someone's life.","Alive","استحیا","2:49-7:127-7:141-14:6-28:4-40:25",6
1793,382,"A","زِیْنَۃ","«زِیْنَت» means to adorn, to beautify, to make attractive. The term 'zeenat' (adornment/beauty) is well-known and commonly used. It is employed in both material and spiritual contexts. Similarly, it is used for both bodily and external adornment. Now, consider the following examples:\n\n(1) Example of External Adornment:\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَخَرَجَ عَلٰی قَوۡمِہٖ فِیۡ زِیۡنَتِہٖ» (28/79)\nTranslation: So Qarun came out before his people in his splendor.\n\n(2) Example of Bodily Adornment:\nFor instance: The divine command states:\n«قُلۡ مَنۡ حَرَّمَ زِیۡنَۃَ اللّٰہِ الَّتِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ لِعِبَادِہٖ» (7/32)\nTranslation: Ask them: Who has forbidden the beautiful things of Allah which He has produced for His servants and the good things of His providing?\n\n(3) Example of Spiritual Adornment:\nFor instance: The Quran states:\n«وَ زَیَّنَ لَہُمُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ  مَا  کَانُوۡا  یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (6/43)\nTranslation: And whatever [evil] they used to do, Satan made it seem fair to them.","«زِیْنَت» is commonly used for decoration and adornment.","Adornment","زینۃ","7:31-7:32-10:24-10:80-11:15-16:8-18:7-18:28-18:46-20:59-20:87-24:31-24:60-28:60-28:79-33:28-37:6-57:20",18
1794,382,"A","زُخْرُف","«زُخْرُف» has two meanings: The first meaning is external, artificial adornment and the beauty that comes from superficial embellishment. «زُخْرُفَ الْکَلَام» means to adorn speech with falsehood (manjad).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یُوۡحِیۡ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ زُخۡرُفَ الۡقَوۡلِ غُرُوۡرًا» (6/112)\nTranslation: (Satan) would cast into [the hearts of] one another suggestions to deceive [people] through adorned speech.\nAnd the second meaning is the various colors and forms of plants (manjad), their springtime and prime.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ اَخَذَتِ الۡاَرۡضُ زُخۡرُفَہَا» (10/24)\nTranslation: Until the earth has become adorned with its splendor and beauty.","«زُخْرُف» means artificial and apparent adornment.","Adornment","زخرف","6:112-10:24-17:93-43:35",4
1795,382,"A","رِیْش","«رِیْشُ الطَّائِر» meaning the feathers of birds, particularly the feathers of hawks (muf), and «رَیَّاش» meaning one who attaches feathers to arrows (manjadd). Since birds' feathers serve as a covering (like clothing), this word began to be used metaphorically (in a temporary sense) for splendid, luxurious garments. Clothes of adornment.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا» (7/26)\nTranslation: O children of Adam! We have sent down upon you clothing to cover your private parts and as an adornment for your bodies.","«رِیْش» luxurious clothing and adornment obtained through embellishment.","adornment","ریش","7:26",1
1796,382,"A","زَھْرَۃ","«زُھْرَۃ» meaning beauty, splendor, glitter (in the context of music), and «زَھْرَۃَ الدُّنْیا» meaning the outward glitter and splendor of the world (in the context of music). This term is generally applied to the transient beauties and attractions of this fleeting world.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ  اِلٰی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ زَہۡرَۃَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ  الدُّنۡیَا» (20/131)\nTranslation: And do not let your eyes be diverted by that which We have given some of them to enjoy—the splendor of the worldly life—so that We may test them thereby.","«زُھْرَۃ» is used for the deceptions and charms of the world.","Adornment","زھرۃ","20:131",1
1797,382,"A","جَمَال","«جَمَال» This word is used in all three contexts: (1) external beauty, (2) goodness of character, and (3) the adornment and beauty of the surroundings (as mentioned in fiqh, 217). In the Quran, this word «مُؤَخَّرُ الذِّکْر» has been employed in both meanings. Etymologically, its primary meaning is goodness in actions, morals, and outward conduct. Later, its usage also began to encompass external beauty.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا جَمَالٌ حِیۡنَ تُرِیۡحُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ  تَسۡرَحُوۡنَ» (16:6)\nTranslation: And when you bring them home from pasture in the evening and take them out to graze in the morning, there is beauty in it for you.","«جَمَال» External beauty, goodness of character, and the adornment and decoration of the environment are all employed in various ways.","Adornment","جمال","16:6",1
1798,383,"C","صَاحِب","«صَاحِب» refers to one who remains alongside for an extended period, whether this companionship is with a human or an animal, and whether it is temporal or spatial (muf). According to Ibn al-Faris, two elements are found in «صَحَبَ»: (1) «مَقَارِنَۃ» and (2) «مَقَارِبَۃ», meaning a companion and being close or staying together (m. l). The plural of «صَاحِب» is «اَصْحَاب», and its feminine form is «صَاحِبَۃ». According to Sahib al-Furqan al-Lughawiyyah, the usage of this word is specific to humans (fql 235).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡ ہُمَا فِی الۡغَارِ اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» (9/40)\n\nTranslation: When the two (the Prophet ﷺ and Abu Bakr) were in the cave and he (the Prophet ﷺ) was saying to his companion (Abu Bakr), Do not grieve; indeed, our God is with us.","«صَاحِب» long-standing companion.","Companion","صاحب","2:39-2:81-2:82-2:119-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:116-4:36-4:47-5:10-5:29-5:86-6:71-6:101-7:36-7:42-7:44-7:46-7:47-7:48-7:50-7:184-9:40-9:70-9:113-10:26-10:27-11:23-12:39-12:41-13:5-15:78-15:80-18:9-18:34-18:37-18:76-20:135-22:44-22:51-25:24-25:38-26:61-26:176-29:15-31:15-34:46-35:6-36:13-36:55-38:13-39:8-40:6-40:43-46:14-46:16-50:12-51:59-53:2-54:29-56:8-56:9-56:27-56:38-56:41-56:90-56:91-57:19-58:17-59:20-60:13-64:10-67:10-67:11-68:17-68:48-70:12-72:3-74:31-74:39-80:36-81:22-85:4-90:18-90:19-105:1",87
1799,383,"C","عَشِیْرَۃ","«عَشِیْر» refers to the group of kinsfolk related through one's father. The men of a family. And «عَاشَرَ» means to live together and spend time collectively, as the members of a single family do. And «عَشِیْر» refers to every person who lives together, whether he is a relative or a stranger (m.f.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَدۡعُوۡا لَمَنۡ ضَرُّہٗۤ  اَقۡرَبُ مِنۡ نَّفۡعِہٖ ؕ لَبِئۡسَ  الۡمَوۡلٰی  وَ  لَبِئۡسَ  الۡعَشِیۡرُ» ( 22/13 )\nTranslation: They invoke those whose harm is closer than their benefit. What an evil protector and what an evil associate!","«عَشِیْر» that person who lives together as though they were one family.","Companion","عشیرۃ","4:19-9:24-22:13-26:214-58:22",5
1800,383,"C","قَرِيْنُ","«قَرِيْنُ» meaning contemporary. And every person who is equal in bravery, strength, or other qualities, and its usage is also applicable to non-living things. For details, see 'friend'.","«قَرِيْنُ» meaning a peer of equal rank and age.","Companion","قرین","4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27",6
1801,383,"C","اَزْوَاج","«زَوْج» means a pair; both husband and wife are «زَوْج» for each other, and together they are also «زَوْج». Its plural form is «اَزْوَاج». This word has also been used in the Holy Quran at one place in the meanings of companion or of the same kind (i.e., people who are alike or associated with one another). (For details, see the explanation under different).  \nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«اُحۡشُرُوا الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا وَ اَزۡوَاجَہُمۡ وَ مَا  کَانُوۡا  یَعۡبُدُوۡنَ» (37:22)  \nTranslation: Gather together those who did wrong, and their companions, and those whom they used to worship besides Allah.","«اَزْوَاج» meaning people of the same kind. Those whose habits and customs are compatible with each other.","Companion","ازواج","2:25-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:12-4:57-6:139-6:143-9:24-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:131-23:6-24:6-25:74-26:166-30:21-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-43:12-43:70-56:7-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-78:8",47
1802,384,"Y","عَام","«عَام» Its plural form is «عَوَام», which refers to a year characterized by expansion and abundance (i.e., a year of goodness and well-being).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ  یَاۡتِیۡ مِنۡۢ  بَعۡدِ ذٰلِکَ  عَامٌ فِیۡہِ یُغَاثُ  النَّاسُ  وَ فِیۡہِ  یَعۡصِرُوۡنَ» (12/49)\nTranslation: Then will come after that a year in which people will have abundant rain, and in which they will press (olives and grapes).\n\nAnd in this same sense, the word «عَام» is also used as a supplication. On the occasion of Eid, instead of saying Eid Mubarak, the Arabs say «اَنْتُمْ وَّکُلَّ عَامٍ بِخَیْرٍ», which means: May your year pass with goodness and well-being.","«عَام» Year of goodness and well-being.","year","عام","2:259-9:28-9:37-9:126-12:49-29:14",6
1803,384,"Y","سَنَۃَ","The plural of «سَنَۃ» is «سِنِیْن», meaning year of hardship. This same term is used for years of hardship, drought, and famine (pl.). For instance, the Quran states: «وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذۡنَاۤ  اٰلَ فِرۡعَوۡنَ بِالسِّنِیۡنَ» (7:130). Translation: And We afflicted the people of Pharaoh with years of famine.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah Almighty is: «فَلَبِثَ فِیۡہِمۡ  اَلۡفَ سَنَۃٍ  اِلَّا خَمۡسِیۡنَ عَامًا» (29:14). Translation: And Noah remained among his people for a thousand years minus fifty years.\n\nOut of these, the nine hundred and fifty years that passed in opposition and hardship with Noah's people are denoted by the word «سِنِیْن». The fifty years before his prophethood, during which there was no conflict or distress, are referred to with the word general.\n\nThe word «سَنَۃ» is employed in keeping track of calendars, time, and eras, indicating that prosperous periods are generally fewer than times of scarcity, hardship, and trouble.\n\nFor example, the Quran declares: «ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ الشَّمۡسَ ضِیَآءً وَّ الۡقَمَرَ نُوۡرًا وَّ قَدَّرَہٗ  مَنَازِلَ  لِتَعۡلَمُوۡا عَدَدَ السِّنِیۡنَ وَ الۡحِسَابَ» (10:5). Translation: It is He who made the sun a [source of] light and the moon a light and determined for it phases, that you may know the number of years and calculation.","«سَنَۃ» meaning the year of drought and famine.","Year","سنۃ","2:96-5:26-7:130-10:5-12:42-12:47-17:12-18:11-18:25-20:40-22:47-23:112-26:18-26:205-29:14-30:4-32:5-46:15-70:4",19
1804,384,"Y","حَوْل","«حَالَ» its plural is «حَالَات», meaning to change from one state to another. «حالات الدھر» means the revolutions of days, the vicissitudes of time. And «حَالَ الْحَوْل» means the passage of a year's duration (manjada). And «حَوْل» means a full cycle of the year, i.e., the period from a specific date in one year to the same date in the following year. Zakat is also paid according to the reckoning of «حَوْل». And in matters of nursing and divorce, the reckoning is also based on « حَوْل».\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّصِیَّۃً  لِّاَزۡوَاجِہِمۡ مَّتَاعًا اِلَی الۡحَوۡلِ غَیۡرَ  اِخۡرَاجٍ» (2/240)\nTranslation: He (the deceased husband) should make a will in favor of his wives that they be provided for for a year and not be evicted from the home.","«حَوْل» A full annual cycle, either from a specific date or based on lunar calculation.","Year","حول","2:233-2:240",2
1805,384,"Y","حِجَج","«حِجَج» is plural, and «حَجَّۃٌ» and «حَجَّ» mean to come and go repeatedly. The term for having frequent comings and goings (a repetitive form) is a repetitive noun derived from «حَجَّۃٌ ، حَجّ» (i.e., once a year). And since Hajj occurs once a year, the year is therefore called Hajj (l, m, q). In the early centuries (i.e., the time of the companions), there was no regular calendar and calculation of days, months, and years. Therefore, ordinary people used to count years by the Hajj.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says: «اِنِّیۡۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُنۡکِحَکَ اِحۡدَی ابۡنَتَیَّ ہٰتَیۡنِ عَلٰۤی اَنۡ تَاۡجُرَنِیۡ ثَمٰنِیَ حِجَجٍ» (28/27)  \nTranslation: I wish that you marry one of these two daughters of mine, provided that you work for me for eight years.","«حِجَج» the approximate method of counting years.","Year","حجج","28:27",1
1806,385,"S","عَرَض","«عَرْض» signifies every such thing that is impermanent and weak (sing.), and «عَرَض» denotes every thing from the world's belongings (ch. 16). When the intention is to highlight the instability and non-permanence of the world and its possessions, the word «عَرَض» is used, referring to the world and its trivial, lowly kinds of benefits, wealth, and effects.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ لَا تَقُوۡلُوۡا لِمَنۡ اَلۡقٰۤی اِلَیۡکُمُ السَّلٰمَ لَسۡتَ مُؤۡمِنًا ۚ تَبۡتَغُوۡنَ عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا ۫ فَعِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ مَغَانِمُ کَثِیۡرَۃٌ» (4/94).  \nTranslation: And whoever greets you, do not say to him, You are not a believer, out of the desire to obtain the goods of worldly life. For Allah has great treasures of spoils.","«عَرْض» This word is used to indicate the instability (transience) of the world and its trappings.","Sustenance","عرض","4:94-7:169-8:67-9:42-24:33",5
1807,385,"T","مَتَاع","«مَتَاع» Its plural is «اَمْتِعَۃ» and «مَتَعَ». It means to derive benefit for a long period (transitory), and «مَتَاع» refers to every useful thing or every portion of a thing from which benefit can be derived. To derive benefit from worldly possessions. This word is used when the aspect of worldly possessions and deriving benefit from them is intended to be highlighted.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُسۡتَقَرٌّ  وَّ مَتَاعٌ اِلٰی  حِیۡنٍ» (2/36)\nTranslation: And for you therein is a fixed term of residence and [the provision of] means of livelihood.","every such thing from which benefit is derived","things","متاع","2:36-2:236-2:240-2:241-3:14-3:185-3:197-4:77-5:96-7:24-9:38-10:23-10:70-11:3-12:17-12:65-12:79-13:17-13:26-16:80-16:117-21:111-24:29-28:60-28:61-33:53-36:44-40:39-42:36-43:35-56:73-57:20-79:33-80:32",34
1808,385,"W","اَثَاث","«اَثَاث» is plural, but it is generally used in the plural form; for instance, «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت» is a well-known word. It refers to household items that are in use, such as utensils, charpai, clothing, furniture, and so forth. All these things are included under «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت». Furthermore, this word also came to be used for many superfluous types of goods. It is also used to mean a shop and a warehouse (muf). Additionally, animals or slaves that are owned and for personal use are also included in «اَثَاثُ الْبَیْت», such as a horse, cow, camel, etc. (m. q). For example, the Quran states: «وَ کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا قَبۡلَہُمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ ہُمۡ اَحۡسَنُ  اَثَاثًا  وَّ رِءۡیًا» (19/74). Translation: We had already destroyed generations before them who were superior to them in material possessions and outward appearance.","«اَثَاث» meaning a room for storing miscellaneous household essentials.","worldly goods","اثاث","16:80-19:74",2
1809,385,"T","رَحْل","«رَحْل» means to saddle a camel (with a pack saddle) and also means to migrate or to ride. Additionally, «رَحْل» signifies the luggage that accompanies one on a journey (manjad). The word «رَحَلَ» is used for setting out on a journey (m. l.). The Prophetic saying ﷺ states: «لَا تَشَدُّوا الرِّحَالَ اِلاَّ لِثَلٰثَۃِ مَسَاجِدٍ» meaning, Do not saddle your camels for any destination (for the purpose of visiting and seeking reward) except for the three mosques: the Sacred Mosque, the Prophet's Mosque ﷺ, and the Al-Aqsa Mosque.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran mentions: «جَعَلَ السِّقَایَۃَ  فِیۡ رَحۡلِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12:70). Translation: Prophet Yusuf  placed the water-drawing vessel in his brother's luggage.","«رَحْل» accompanying luggage","things","رحل","12:70-12:75-106:2",3
1810,385,"T","وِعَاء","The terms «اَوْعِیَۃ» and «وَعٰی» refer to storing something in a basket or similar container and sealing it from the top. Additionally, «اَوْعِیَۃ» denotes the items placed in a vessel that is then closed or locked (detailed).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ ثُمَّ اسۡتَخۡرَجَہَا مِنۡ وِّعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/76)  \nTranslation: So Joseph began by searching the bags of his brothers before the bag of his full brother, then he brought out the cup from his full brother's bag.","«وِعَاء» every such item that is sealed or locked.","Things","وعاء","12:76",1
1811,385,"G","جَھَاز","«جَھَّزَ» means to prepare, load, and also send (trans.) and «جَھَاز» is the provisions that a traveler prepares and takes along when embarking on a journey. And «تَجْھِیْز» is the provisions prepared for the deceased before burial. And «جَھِیْز» is the provisions given by parents to a daughter at the time of her departure for marriage.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا جَہَّزَہُمۡ بِجَہَازِہِمۡ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then when Yusuf (Joseph) (peace be upon him) prepared the provisions for his brothers.","«جَھَاز» is the provisions that a traveler prepares and keeps ready when embarking on a journey.","goods","جھاز","12:59-12:70",2
1812,385,"G","زَاد","«زَادَ» means 'excess' or 'more than needed' (masc.). And the word «زَاد» generally pertains to the road. 'Zad-e-rah' refers to the expenses incurred during travel, the cost of the journey, and food and drink provisions. And «اَلْمُزَادَة» means a water skin used during travel. And «مِزْوَدَةٌ» means a provision bag. And «تَزَوَّدَ» also means to take provisions for the journey (manjada).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَزَوَّدُوۡا فَاِنَّ خَیۡرَ الزَّادِ التَّقۡوٰی» (2/197)\nTranslation: And take provisions with you. Indeed, the best provision is piety.","«زَاد» travel provisions for food and drink","Goods","زاد","2:197",1
1813,385,"T","اَسْلِحَۃ","«اَسْلِحَۃ» is a collective noun «سِلَاح»). This word is related to war or battle. It means implements of war, weapons and instruments of combat, the arms of fighting. And it is used for every such thing with which one fights, resists, or defends. (m.f.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلۡتَقُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّعَکَ وَ لۡیَاۡخُذُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَہُمۡ» (4/102)\nTranslation: A group of them should stand with you [in prayer], holding their weapons.","«اَسْلِحَۃ» war machinery.","things","اسلحۃ","4:102",1
1814,385,"G","عُدَّۃ","«عُدَّۃ» is a collective form meaning to prepare for «عُدَد» and «عَدَّ». «اَعَدَّ» and «اَعْتَدَ» mean to keep prepared or to maintain readiness, and «عُدَّۃٌ» means equipment or gear related to preparation. Since this word appears in the Quran in the context of war preparations, its meaning encompasses all types of preparation and associated gear.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ  اَرَادُوا الۡخُرُوۡجَ لَاَعَدُّوۡا  لَہٗ  عُدَّۃً» (9:46)\nTranslation: If they (the hypocrites) had truly intended to march forth (to the battlefield), they would have made some preparations for it.","«عُدَّۃ» war preparation and all related equipment and preparations.","Goods","عدۃ","9:46",1
1815,385,"T","نَعْمَۃ","«نَعَم» meaning prosperity and a favored passage (m. l.), and «نَعْمَۃٌ» meaning the equipment or furnishings for a life of luxury and comfort (muf).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ  نَعۡمَۃٍ  کَانُوۡا فِیۡہَا  فٰکِہِیۡنَ» (44:27)\nTranslation: And the furnishings of the affluence in which they used to indulge.","«نِعْمَۃ» meaning prosperity, comfort, wealth, luxury, and peace.","things","نعمۃ","44:27-73:11",2
1816,385,"L","رِیْشًا","«رِیْشُ الظَّائِر» meaning the wings and feathers of a bird. And «ریّاش» meaning one who attaches feathers (fletching) to arrows (munajjad), since the feathers of birds are like a covering or garment, therefore the word «رِیْشًا» is used for the luxurious clothing and adornment of a human. Means of decoration and embellishment.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا» ( 7/26 )\nTranslation: O children of Adam, We have bestowed upon you clothing that covers your private parts and (also serves as) adornment.","«رِیْش» is used for luxurious clothing and its adornment.","luggage","ریشًا","7:26",1
1817,385,"G","بِضَاعَۃً","«بِضَاعَۃ» refers to a substantial portion of wealth set aside for trade (i.e., goods for sale, merchandise). It also denotes the capital or principal funds specifically allocated for commercial purposes.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰبُشۡرٰی ہٰذَا غُلٰمٌ ؕ وَ اَسَرُّوۡہُ بِضَاعَۃً» (12/19)\nTranslation: The water carrier said, What excellent fortune! This is indeed a handsome boy. Then they hid him, considering him as [merchandise to be sold].","«بِضَاعَۃ» meaning merchandise.","Goods","بضاعۃً","12:19-12:62-12:65-12:88",4
1818,385,"B","مَاعُوْن","«اَلْمَعَنُ» means a useful thing. And «مَاعُوْن» refers to every such item that comes into common use. Utensils for use. Small and big things for use in the house. For example, kalahri, handiya, or other household items (manjad).\n\nFor example: in the Quran it is: «الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  یُرَآءُوۡنَ وَ یَمۡنَعُوۡنَ الۡمَاعُوۡنَ» (107/7) Translation: And those who show off yet do not lend utensils.","«مَاعُوْن» small everyday household items.","belongings","ماعون","107:7",1
1819,385,"G","حِذْر","«حَذَرَ» meaning cautious and vigilant (lit.) and «حِذْر» refers to all equipment that serves for protection and safety. Hence, during wartime, any equipment used for protection from attack is «حِذْر». For instance, the Quran states: «وَ لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِنۡ کَانَ بِکُمۡ اَذًی مِّنۡ مَّطَرٍ اَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَنۡ تَضَعُوۡۤا اَسۡلِحَتَکُمۡ ۚ وَ خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ» (4/102)  \nTranslation: And there is no blame upon you if you are afflicted by rain or if you are ill, so lay down your weapons and take your protective gear with you.","«حِذْر» provisions for one's salvation.","Goods","حذر","2:19-2:235-2:243-3:28-3:30-4:71-4:102-5:41-5:49-5:92-9:64-9:122-24:63-28:6-39:9-63:4-64:14",17
1820,385,"T","مَعَایِش","«مَعَایِش» is gathered; «مَعِیْشَۃٌ» means provisions for life. «عَاش» means to live, to exist. And all that provision which is for maintaining or sustaining life, such as food, grains, water, provisions, etc. That will be called 'معایِش'.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says: «وَ لَقَدۡ مَکَّنّٰکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ جَعَلۡنَا لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا مَعَایِشَ» (7/10) Translation: And We have made for you dwellings in the earth and provided for you the sustenance of life.","«مَعَایِش» all that equipment which is necessary to maintain or sustain life.","things","معایِش","7:10-15:20-79:11",3
1821,386,"I","اَقْبَلَ","«قَبَلَ الْمَکَان» meaning to turn toward a place. And «قَابَل» meaning two things being face to face or opposite, to compete. And «قَبَّلَ» meaning to give a kiss. And «اَقْبَلَ» meaning to turn toward someone and be in front of them or to come to them. To face. To come from the front (source: Munjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is mentioned:\n«قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  مَّا ذَا  تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ» (12/71)\nTranslation: And turning toward them, they said, What is it that you have lost?","«اَقْبَلَ» meaning to turn one's face towards someone/something and be before them or come before them.","in front","اقبل","12:71-28:31-37:27-37:50-37:94-51:29-52:25-68:30",8
1822,386,"I","بَرَزَ","«بَرْز» means space or an open field. And «بَرَزَ» means to come out into the open field (active form), and also means to become manifest after obscurity or hiddenness (passive form).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ بَرَزُوۡا لِلّٰہِ جَمِیۡعًا» ( 14/21 )\nTranslation: And (on the Day of Judgment) all people shall be gathered in the open field before Allah.","«بَرَزَ» meaning to come out into the open field.","In front","برز","2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36",7
1823,387,"S","حَیَّۃٌ","«حَیَّۃٌ» is a generic term. It refers to all kinds of snakes. It is used for both masculine and feminine (Fall 160). And according to the author of Al-Munjid, «حَیَّۃٌ» means the snake that strikes with its coils. And «حَوَایَا» refers to those intestines that are coiled like a snake. And «تَحَوُّی الْحَیَّۃٌ» means the coiling of a snake. And «حَاوِی» refers to the one who recites incantations over a snake (munajid). Both these meanings seem correct because every snake, in general, is one that strikes with its coils. And probably for this very reason, it is called «حَیَّۃٌ».\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«قَالَ  اَلۡقِہَا یٰمُوۡسٰی فَاَلۡقٰہَا فَاِذَا ہِیَ حَیَّۃٌ  تَسۡعٰی» (20/19,20)\nTranslation: Allah the Most High said, O Moses, throw down your staff on the ground. So Moses threw it down, and suddenly it became a swift-moving snake.","«حَیَّۃٌ» is used for all kinds of snakes.","Snake","حیۃ","20:20",1
1824,387,"S","جَآنّ","«جَآنّ» meaning jinn, devils, and fairies. Mighty and sturdy in form. And every jinn that takes the shape of a snake (plural), as is also mentioned in a hadith. And Maulana Shabbir Ahmad Usmani (may Allah have mercy on him) has translated it as the serpentine movement — meaning a swift, white, and slender snake.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ  کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا  وَّ لَمۡ  یُعَقِّبۡ» (27/10)\nTranslation: When Moses saw it, it seemed to him as if it was a snake, so he turned and fled, and did not look back.","«جَآنّ» is used for slender and long snakes.","Snake","جآن","15:27-27:10-28:31-55:15-55:39-55:56-55:74",7
1825,387,"S","ثَعْبَانٌ","«ثَعْبَانٌ» meaning dragon; a very large serpent (cf. 40, 160).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: Moses threw down his staff, and suddenly it became a serpent.\nNow observe that Allah Almighty used three different terms for serpent in the single incident of the staff turning into a serpent: «حَیَّۃ ، جَانّ», «ثَعْبَان», and «حَیَّۃٌ». «حَیَّۃ» is used because every type of serpent can be called by that term. «جَانّ» refers to the initial state of the staff becoming a serpent, while «ثَعْبَان» refers to its second and final state. And all of this occurred in quick succession.","The dragon is called «ثَعْبَانٌ».","Snake","ثعبان","7:107-26:32",2
1826,388,"E","کُلّ","«کُلّ» means all or the entire, and its opposite is «جُزْء». It is used when referring to a collective sum of several units (such as numbers from one to nine, or decades in numerical terms). Then, this word is also used for each individual part, meaning each one, every person, every thing.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» (17:84)\nTranslation: Say: Every person is acting according to his own manner.\n\nAnd it is also used on this sum of several units, where its meaning would be all or the entire.\nFor example: The divine declaration is:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا» (2:31)\nTranslation: And Allah taught Adam the names of all things.","«کُلّ» meaning both each one and all.","Eternal / Self-Subsistent","کل","2:20-2:29-2:31-2:60-2:106-2:109-2:116-2:145-2:148-2:164-2:231-2:259-2:260-2:261-2:266-2:276-2:281-2:282-2:284-2:285-3:7-3:25-3:26-3:29-3:30-3:93-3:119-3:154-3:161-3:165-3:185-3:189-4:11-4:12-4:32-4:33-4:41-4:78-4:85-4:86-4:95-4:126-4:129-4:130-4:176-5:17-5:19-5:40-5:48-5:97-5:117-5:120-6:17-6:25-6:44-6:64-6:67-6:70-6:80-6:84-6:85-6:86-6:99-6:101-6:102-6:108-6:111-6:112-6:123-6:132-6:146-6:154-6:164-7:29-7:31-7:34-7:38-7:46-7:57-7:86-7:89-7:112-7:145-7:146-7:156-7:160-8:12-8:39-8:41-8:54-8:56-8:75-9:5-9:33-9:39-9:115-9:122-9:126-10:22-10:30-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:79-10:97-11:3-11:4-11:6-11:12-11:40-11:57-11:59-11:111-11:120-11:123-12:31-12:76-12:111-13:2-13:3-13:7-13:8-13:16-13:23-13:33-13:38-13:42-14:5-14:15-14:17-14:25-14:34-14:51-15:17-15:19-15:44-16:11-16:36-16:69-16:77-16:84-16:89-16:111-16:112-17:12-17:13-17:20-17:29-17:36-17:38-17:71-17:84-17:89-18:45-18:54-18:79-18:84-19:49-19:69-19:93-19:95-20:15-20:50-20:56-20:98-20:135-21:30-21:33-21:35-21:72-21:79-21:81-21:85-21:93-21:96-21:99-22:2-22:3-22:5-22:6-22:17-22:27-22:34-22:38-22:67-23:27-23:53-23:88-23:91-24:2-24:11-24:35-24:41-24:45-24:64-25:2-25:31-25:39-25:51-26:7-26:37-26:63-26:128-26:222-26:225-27:16-27:23-27:83-27:87-27:88-27:91-28:48-28:57-28:75-28:88-29:20-29:40-29:57-29:62-30:26-30:32-30:50-30:58-31:10-31:18-31:29-31:31-31:32-32:7-32:13-33:27-33:40-33:51-33:52-33:54-33:55-34:7-34:9-34:19-34:21-34:47-35:1-35:12-35:13-35:36-36:12-36:32-36:36-36:40-36:79-36:83-37:7-37:8-38:14-38:19-38:37-38:48-38:73-39:5-39:27-39:62-39:70-40:5-40:7-40:17-40:27-40:35-40:48-40:62-41:12-41:21-41:39-41:53-41:54-42:9-42:12-42:33-43:12-43:35-44:4-44:55-45:7-45:22-45:28-46:19-46:25-46:33-47:15-48:21-48:26-48:28-49:16-50:7-50:8-50:14-50:21-50:24-50:32-51:49-52:21-54:3-54:28-54:42-54:49-54:52-54:53-55:26-55:29-55:52-57:2-57:3-57:10-57:23-58:6-58:7-59:6-61:9-63:4-64:1-64:11-65:3-65:12-66:8-67:1-67:19-68:10-70:38-72:28-74:38-74:52-78:29-80:37-83:12-85:9-86:4-97:4-104:1",337
1827,388,"A","کَافَّۃ","«اَلْکَفَافُ» refers to the entire circumference or scope of something. «کَافَّ» is an active participle, and «کَافَّۃٌ» is its feminine form (مف). Its usage occurs in two ways:\n\n(1) When «کُلّ» denotes a collection of many units, it applies to that entire collective group. In this sense, it is stronger and more complete than «کُلّ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنٰکَ  اِلَّا کَآفَّۃً  لِّلنَّاسِ بَشِیۡرًا وَّ نَذِیۡرًا» ( 34/28 )\nTranslation: And (O Muhammad ﷺ) We have sent you as a bringer of glad tidings and a warner for all people.\n\n(2) When «کُلّ» refers to a single unit, it comes to encompass all its constituent parts. In this sense, it is stronger than complete (کامل).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا ادۡخُلُوۡا فِی السِّلۡمِ  کَآفَّۃً» ( 2/208 )\nTranslation: O you who believe! Enter into religion completely (or in its entirety).\n\nIn this verse, the word «کَافَّۃ» conveys both meanings: entirely (سارے کے سارے) and completely (پورے کے پورے).","«کَافَّۃ» denotes the whole of the whole and the all of the all. This is even more powerful than «کُلّ» and than perfection.","All","کافۃ","2:208-9:36-9:122-34:28",4
1828,388,"G","اَجْمَعُوْن","«جَمَعَ» means to gather or assemble. And «اَجْمَعَ» means to collectively perform an action. And «اَجْمَعَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to reach a unanimous agreement on a matter.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» (12:15)  \nTranslation: Then when the brothers of Yusuf took him, they all agreed to throw him into a deep well.  \n\nAnd «اَجْمَعُوْن» means to do something together, all gathered or assembled at the same time.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَسَجَدَ  الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  کُلُّہُمۡ  اَجۡمَعُوۡنَ» (15:30)  \nTranslation: Then all the angels prostrated together (before Adam).","«اَجْمَعُوْن» to unite and agree together for a common purpose.","Glory be to","اجمعون","3:157-3:173-4:23-10:58-10:71-12:15-12:102-15:30-20:64-26:95-38:73-43:32",12
1829,389,"R","اَکْفَلَ ۔ کَفَّل","«کَفَلَ» means to be responsible for someone's sustenance and care, to be a guarantor. And «اَکْفَلَ» and «کَفَّلَ» mean entrusting the responsibility of care and upbringing to another, making someone a guarantor, giving in guardianship (manjd. muf).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is said: «اِنَّ  ہٰذَاۤ  اَخِیۡ ۟ لَہٗ  تِسۡعٌ وَّ تِسۡعُوۡنَ نَعۡجَۃً  وَّ لِیَ نَعۡجَۃٌ  وَّاحِدَۃٌ ۟ فَقَالَ اَکۡفِلۡنِیۡہَا وَ عَزَّنِیۡ  فِی الۡخِطَابِ» (38/23) Translation: This is my brother. He has ninety-nine sheep and I have only one. He says, Hand that over to me too, and he prevails over me in speech.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states: «فَتَقَبَّلَہَا رَبُّہَا بِقَبُوۡلٍ حَسَنٍ وَّ اَنۡۢبَتَہَا نَبَاتًا حَسَنًا ۙ وَّ  کَفَّلَہَا زَکَرِیَّا» (3/37) Translation: So the Lord accepted him with favor and raised him well and entrusted his upbringing to Prophet Zakariya (peace be upon him).","«کَفَّلَ» Entrusting the responsibility of someone's training to another person.","References","اکفل ۔ کفل","3:37-3:44-20:40-28:12-38:23",5
1830,389,"R","وَکَّلَ","«وَکَلَ» means to trust someone else in one's own matter (m. l.) and «وَکَّلَ» means to entrust one's matter to another by placing trust in them, appointing them as one's lawyer or agent (muf. manjd).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ یَتَوَفّٰىکُمۡ مَّلَکُ الۡمَوۡتِ الَّذِیۡ وُکِّلَ بِکُمۡ» (32/11)\nTranslation: Say, The angel of death, who has been appointed over you by Us, will take your souls.","«وَکَّل» to entrust one's affairs to someone based on trust.","References","وکل","6:89-32:11",2
1831,389,"R","دَفَعَ ( اِلٰی )","«دَفَعَ اِلٰی» means to hand over someone's property to them; to deliver it to them.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ اٰنَسۡتُمۡ مِّنۡہُمۡ رُشۡدًا فَادۡفَعُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِمۡ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ» (4/6)\nTranslation: Then if you observe in them (those orphans under your guardianship) sound judgment, hand over their property to them.","To hand over «دَفَعَ اِلٰی» someone's property to them.","references","دفع ( الی )","4:6",1
1832,389,"R","سَلَّمَ","«سَلِمَ» means to be saved from defect and calamity (Quranic meaning), and «سَلَّمَ» also means to say Salam and to save from harm. And «سَلَّمَہٗ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to entrust something to someone, and «سَلَّمہُ الشَّیْءَ فَتَسَلَّمَہٗ» means for someone to entrust something to another and for that person to accept it (as if for the purpose of avoiding trouble and entrusting something), so «سَلَّمَ» is used in contexts of avoiding harm and entrustment.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is said:\n«وَ اِنۡ اَرَدۡتُّمۡ اَنۡ تَسۡتَرۡضِعُوۡۤا اَوۡلَادَکُمۡ فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِذَا سَلَّمۡتُمۡ مَّاۤ  اٰتَیۡتُمۡ  بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And if you wish to wean your children, there is no blame on you, provided you hand over to the nursing mothers their due compensation according to the customary practice.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ  اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92)\nTranslation: And hand over the blood money to the heirs of the slain, unless they remit it as a charity.","«سَلَّمَ» entrusting something to someone to avoid hardship or trouble.","References","سلم","2:233-31:22",2
1833,389,"R","فَوَّضَ","«فَوَّضَ» means to entrust one's work to someone. And «تَفْوِیْضًا اِلَیْہِ الْاَمْر» means to delegate a task to someone and appoint them as a ruler (source: Manjad).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اُفَوِّضُ اَمۡرِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ» (40/44)\nTranslation: And I entrust my affair to Allah.","«فَوَّضَ» entrusting someone with the authority over a matter and appointing them as the decision-maker.","References","فوض","40:44",1
1834,389,"R","اِسْتَوْدَعَ","«وَدَعَ» meaning to leave. And «اَوْدَعَ الشَّیْ» meaning to keep something as a trust. And «وَدَّعَ» meaning to grant leave to a traveler. And «اِسْتَوْدَعَ فُلَانًا شَیْئًا» meaning to keep something with someone as a trust, as if this entrustment is in the capacity of a trust. (Munjid)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَنۡشَاَکُمۡ مِّنۡ نَّفۡسٍ وَّاحِدَۃٍ  فَمُسۡتَقَرٌّ وَّ مُسۡتَوۡدَعٌ» (6/98)\nTranslation: And He it is who created you from a single person, then for you is a place of residence (the world) and a place of entrustment (the grave).\nMeaning: You are kept alive in the world for a period, then after being buried in the earth, you are entrusted to Allah (Jalandhari).","«اِسْتَوْدَعَ» to entrust something to someone as a trust.","References","استودع","6:98-11:6",2
1835,390,"T","صِدْق","«صَدَقَ» means to speak truthfully. Its opposite is «کَذَب», that is, not saying anything contrary to fact. It is a well-known term.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ اَظۡلَمُ  مِمَّنۡ  کَذَبَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ وَ  کَذَّبَ بِالصِّدۡقِ اِذۡ جَآءَہٗ» (39:32)\n\nTranslation: Who is more unjust than the one who lies against Allah and denies the truth when it comes to him?","«صِدْق» meaning to speak the truth.","Truth","صدق","2:41-2:89-2:91-2:79-2:101-2:177-3:3-3:39-3:50-3:81-3:95-3:152-4:47-4:87-4:122-5:46-5:48-5:113-5:119-6:92-6:115-9:43-10:2-10:93-12:26-17:80-19:50-21:9-26:84-27:27-28:34-29:3-33:8-33:22-33:23-33:24-34:20-35:31-36:52-37:37-37:52-37:105-39:32-39:33-39:74-46:12-46:16-46:30-47:21-48:27-54:55-56:57-61:6-66:12-70:26-75:31-92:6",57
1836,390,"T","حَقّ","«حَقّ» is the opposite of «بَاطِل». «حَقّ» is every matter or thing that is proven true and correct after experience and observation. Truth. Reality (sing.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» (41/53)\n\nTranslation: We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves until it becomes clear to them that this [the revelation of the Quran] is indeed the truth.","«حَقّ» is used for truth and honesty.","Truth","حق","2:26-2:42-2:61-2:71-2:91-2:109-2:119-2:121-2:144-2:146-2:147-2:149-2:176-2:180-2:213-2:236-2:241-2:252-2:282-3:3-3:21-3:60-3:62-3:71-3:86-3:102-3:108-3:112-3:154-3:181-4:105-4:122-4:151-4:155-4:170-4:171-5:27-5:48-5:77-5:83-5:84-5:107-5:116-6:5-6:30-6:57-6:62-6:66-6:73-6:91-6:93-6:114-6:141-6:151-7:8-7:30-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:53-7:89-7:105-7:118-7:146-7:159-7:169-7:181-8:4-8:5-8:6-8:7-8:8-8:32-8:74-9:29-9:33-9:48-9:111-10:4-10:5-10:23-10:30-10:32-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:53-10:55-10:76-10:77-10:82-10:94-10:96-10:103-10:108-11:17-11:45-11:79-11:120-12:51-12:100-13:1-13:14-13:17-13:19-14:19-14:22-15:8-15:55-15:64-15:85-16:3-16:36-16:38-16:102-17:16-17:26-17:33-17:81-17:105-18:13-18:21-18:29-18:44-18:56-18:98-19:34-20:114-21:18-21:24-21:55-21:97-21:112-22:6-22:18-22:40-22:54-22:62-22:74-22:78-23:41-23:62-23:70-23:71-23:90-23:116-24:25-24:49-25:26-25:33-25:68-27:79-28:3-28:13-28:39-28:48-28:53-28:63-28:75-29:44-29:68-30:8-30:38-30:47-30:60-31:9-31:30-31:33-32:3-32:13-33:4-33:53-34:6-34:23-34:26-34:43-34:48-34:49-35:5-35:24-35:31-36:7-36:70-37:31-37:37-38:14-38:22-38:26-38:64-38:84-39:2-39:5-39:19-39:41-39:67-39:69-39:71-39:75-40:5-40:6-40:20-40:25-40:55-40:75-40:77-40:78-41:15-41:25-41:53-42:17-42:18-42:24-42:42-43:29-43:30-43:78-43:86-44:39-45:6-45:22-45:29-45:32-46:3-46:7-46:17-46:18-46:20-46:30-46:34-47:2-47:3-48:27-48:28-50:5-50:14-50:19-50:42-51:19-51:23-53:28-56:95-57:16-57:27-60:1-61:9-64:3-69:51-70:24-78:39-84:2-84:5-103:3",252
1837,391,"S","اَشَقّ","«شَقَّ الْاَمْر» means the difficulty of a task. And «شَقَّ عَلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to impose hardship on someone (to afflict). And the word «اَشَقَّ» generally refers to a hardship that exceeds one's strength or capacity. A suffering that is beyond endurance. Becoming a matter of life and death.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَعَذَابُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ اَشَقُّ» (13/34)\nTranslation: And the punishment of the Hereafter is far more severe.","«اَشَقّ» Such unbearable suffering.","Severe","اشق","13:34-28:27",2
1838,391,"S","اَشَدّ","«اَشَدُّ» meaning extremely strong and powerful, very harsh, and «قُوَّۃً فِیْ شَیْءٍ» meaning something being inherently powerful and hard in itself. Being severe in strength, power, and force. Overwhelming. It is used for the body, strength, and punishment.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«یُرَدُّوۡنَ اِلٰۤی اَشَدِّ الۡعَذَابِ» ( 2/85 )\nTranslation: They will be returned to a more severe punishment.","The inherent hardness of something.","Severe","اشد","2:74-2:85-2:165-2:191-2:200-4:66-4:77-4:84-5:82-9:69-9:81-9:97-19:69-20:71-20:127-28:78-30:9-35:44-37:11-40:21-40:46-40:82-41:15-43:8-47:13-48:29-50:36-59:13-73:6-79:27",30
1839,391,"S","اَدْھٰی","«دَھِیَ» means to afflict someone with a calamity. And «دَاھِیَۃٌ» means a severe calamity, a grave matter (munjad). And «دَھِیَ» also means for one thing to reach another in an unpleasant way or to plunge into calamity. And «دَوَاھِیَ الدَّھْر» means the accidents of time (m. l). And «اَدْھٰی» means severe in terms of calamities and difficulties.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ السَّاعَۃُ اَدۡہٰی  وَ  اَمَرُّ» (54/46)\nTranslation: And that Hour (the Hereafter) is severe and bitter.","«اَدْھٰی» to be severe in terms of calamities and difficulties.","Severe","ادھی","54:46",1
1840,391,"S","رَابِیَۃ","«رَبَا ، رَبْوًا» means to increase, grow, flourish, or become more, and «رَابِیَۃ» means that which continually increases.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَعَصَوۡا  رَسُوۡلَ  رَبِّہِمۡ  فَاَخَذَہُمۡ  اَخۡذَۃً  رَّابِیَۃً» (69:10)  \nTranslation: The people of 'Ad defied the command of their Lord's messenger, so He seized them with a severe punishment.","«رَابِیَۃ» The Ever-Increasing.","Severe","رابیۃ","69:10",1
1841,391,"S","عَصِیْب","«عَصَبَ» I find two aspects: (1) the connection and association of one thing with another; (2) severity. «عَصَبَہ» Its plural is «اَعْصَاب», meaning 'backbone' or 'strength,' and «عُصْبَۃ» also refers to a strong group whose number is ten or more, and who are connected, associated, and united with one another—hence, the group is powerful and strong (as in the example). For instance, the brothers of Prophet Yusuf (peace be upon him) said to their father: «وَنَحْنُ عُصْبَۃً» (12:14), meaning, Indeed, we are a powerful group. And «تَعَصُّبْ» refers to the severity of a theory or belief, meaning that even after knowing the truth, a person does not accept it. And «عَصِیْب» is something that is both severe and devoid of goodness and well-being.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَتۡ رُسُلُنَا لُوۡطًا سِیۡٓءَ بِہِمۡ وَ ضَاقَ بِہِمۡ ذَرۡعًا وَّ قَالَ ہٰذَا یَوۡمٌ عَصِیۡبٌ» (11:77)\n\nTranslation: When Our sent messengers reached the people of Lot, they caused him great distress, and his heart constricted with grief, and he said, This is a day of extreme hardship.","«عَصِیْب» severe and devoid of goodness.","Severe","عصیب","11:77",1
1842,391,"S","قَمْطَرِیْر","«قَمْطَرِیْر» meaning that which makes hearts extremely restless, agitated, and distressed (مف)  \n«قِمْطَر» refers to the wood used for stretching the feet of criminals and for administering punishment (م ۔ ق)  \nand «قَمْطَرِیْر» meaning severe evil or intense days (مُنْجِد)  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«اِنَّا نَخَافُ مِنۡ رَّبِّنَا یَوۡمًا عَبُوۡسًا قَمۡطَرِیۡرًا» (76/10)  \nTranslation: We have a looming fear from our Lord of a Day when faces will be utterly transformed.","«قَمْطَرِیْر» severe in terms of evil.","Severe","قمطریر","76:10",1
1843,391,"S","قَاسِیَۃ","The word «قَسْوَۃ» denotes intensity and harshness (M. al-L). «قَسَا» means to be hard and solid (Munjid). «حَجَرٌ قَاسٍ» means a hard stone. And «اَلْقَسْوَۃ» means to be hard-hearted (Mufradat). Thus, the word «قَسْوَۃ» generally comes to mean the hardness of the heart, hard-heartedness, and being devoid of tender and merciful feelings. It is said that «اَلذَّنْبُ مُسْقَاۃٌ لِّلْقَلْبِ» is what hardens the heart (Munjid).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ  لِّلۡقٰسِیَۃِ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ مِّنۡ ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (39/22)\nTranslation: Woe to those whose hearts are hardening against the remembrance of Allah.","«قَاسِیَۃ» the hardness or stone-heartedness of the heart.","Severe","قاسیۃ","5:13-22:53-39:22",3
1844,391,"S","غَلِیْظ","«غَلَظَ» means to be thick or coarse, dense, hard, rough, or uneven. And «غَلَظَ الرَّجُل» means for a man to be irritable, bad-tempered, and harsh in speech (manjad). And «غَلِیْظ» is the opposite of «لِیْنٌ», which means softness. And «غَلِیْظُ الْقَلْب» refers to a person who is both hard-hearted and bad-tempered, and its plural is «غِلَاظٌ».\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«عَلَیۡہَا مَلٰٓئِکَۃٌ  غِلَاظٌ شِدَادٌ لَّا یَعۡصُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ مَاۤ  اَمَرَہُمۡ» (66:6)\nTranslation: Stern and harsh angels are appointed over Hellfire, and they do not disobey any command given to them by Allah.","«غَلِیْظ» means hard-hearted and quick-tempered.","Severe","غلیظ","3:159-4:21-4:154-9:73-11:58-14:17-31:24-33:7-41:50-48:29-66:9",11
1845,391,"S","عَرِمَ","«عُرَامَہ» meaning the intensity and harshness of temperament, the effect of which is manifest in a person's actions. And «عُرَامُ الْجَیْش» meaning the intensity, speed, and multitude of an army (military context).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ سَیۡلَ الۡعَرِمِ» (34/16)\nTranslation: So We unleashed upon them a torrent of might.","«عَرِم» refers to a negative innate quality whose effects manifest in a person's actions.","Severe","عرم","34:16",1
1846,392,"H","قَسْوَۃ ۔ غِلْظَۃ","«قَسْوَۃ» and «غِلْظَۃ» have been discussed previously. «قَسْوَۃ» refers to the hardness or stubbornness of the heart. For example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ قَسَتۡ قُلُوۡبُکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ ذٰلِکَ فَہِیَ کَالۡحِجَارَۃِ اَوۡ اَشَدُّ قَسۡوَۃً» (2/74)\nTranslation: Then after that, your hearts became hard. They were like stones, or even harder.\n\nWhereas «غِلْظَۃ» denotes a combination of hardness and harshness (ill-temper) when the term is attributed to the heart. For example, the Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَاتِلُوا الَّذِیۡنَ یَلُوۡنَکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡکُفَّارِ وَ لۡیَجِدُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ  غِلۡظَۃً» (9/123)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, fight those near you of the disbelievers, and let them find in you firmness.","the hardness of heart, «غِلْظَۃ» stone-heartedness, and ill-temper","hardship","قسوۃ ۔ غلظۃ","2:74-6:43-9:123-57:16",4
1847,392,"A","بَأسَاء","In «بَؤُسَ», the meanings of hardship and constriction are found, whether due to warfare or hunger. The word «بَأس» has also been used in the Noble Quran in the meanings of battle, for example: «وَحِیْنَ الْبَاْس» (2:177); in the meanings of punishment, for example: «اِذْجَآءَ ھُمْ بَاْسُنَا» (6:43); and in the meanings of affliction, for example: «بَأسًا شَدِیْدًا» (18:2). In all these instances, the meanings of constriction are found. Furthermore, «بَأسَآء» refers to a prolonged period of constriction and hardship, whether it be economic deprivation and destitution or the severity of warfare.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی  اُمَمٍ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ فَاَخَذۡنٰہُمۡ بِالۡبَاۡسَآءِ وَ الضَّرَّآءِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَضَرَّعُوۡنَ» (6:42)\n\nTranslation: And We sent many messengers to nations before you. Then (due to their disobedience), We seized them with hardships and afflictions so that they might humble themselves.","«بَأسَاء» an era of hardship and scarcity.","Adversity","بأساء","2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14",26
1848,392,"H","کَبَد","The word «کَبَد» carries the connotation of severity and strength (M. L.), while «تَکَبَّد» and «کَابَد» mean to endure hardship (Manjad). «فِیْ کَبَد» is used metaphorically and expresses human nature. When a desire arises in a person's heart, they endure various forms of pain and suffering (hardship) to fulfill it. If it remains unfulfilled, several other desires emerge. Then, the person prepares to fulfill them and endure more pain and suffering, and thus their entire life passes.\n\nAllah the Almighty has expressed this same reality as:\n«لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡ  کَبَدٍ» (90/4)\nTranslation: We have made man a creature of enduring hardship.\n\nNote: In medical science and wisdom, the liver (jigar) is also called *kabd*.","«کَبَد» The human nature that endures hardships throughout life.","hardship","کبد","90:4",1
1849,393,"H","اَقْمَحَ","«اَقْمَحَ» One may raise their head in such a manner, but have their gaze lowered. And «اَقْمَحَ الْبَعِیْر» when a camel, after drinking its fill of water, raises its head but keeps its eyes down, that state is described as such (F L 186). And when a person wishes to look down but, due to some compulsion, cannot lower their head, that too is called «اَقْمَحَ الرَّجُلُ وَغَضَّ بَصَرُہٗ» (M. Q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنَا فِیۡۤ  اَعۡنَاقِہِمۡ  اَغۡلٰلًا فَہِیَ  اِلَی  الۡاَذۡقَانِ فَہُمۡ  مُّقۡمَحُوۡنَ» (36:8)\nTranslation: We have placed collars around their necks, so they are forced to raise their heads only up to their chins.","«اَقْمَحَ» He raised his head, but his gaze was downcast.","Head","اقمح","36:8",1
1850,393,"H","اَقْنَعَ","«اَقْنَعَ» meaning to raise the voice or head. To elevate. And «مُقْنِع» meaning one who raises their head to look (from 'manjada' [a place of looking/observation]).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مُہۡطِعِیۡنَ مُقۡنِعِیۡ رُءُوۡسِہِمۡ لَا یَرۡتَدُّ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  طَرۡفُہُمۡ ۚ وَ اَفۡئِدَتُہُمۡ  ہَوَآءٌ» ( 14/43 )\nTranslation: They will be running with their heads raised (towards the gathering place of the Resurrection). Their eyes will not be able to return towards them, and their hearts (overcome with terror) will be in a state of agitation.","«اَقْنَعَ» with the head raised and the gaze directed forward or upward.","head (also: top, chief, beginning)","اقنع","14:43",1
1851,393,"H","عَلَا یَعْلَوْا عُلُوًّا","«عَلَا» to rise, to exalt oneself (in arrogance) «عُلْو» is its opposite «سُفْل». This word is general, but it is mostly used in a negative sense. It can be used in both material and spiritual contexts. In contrast, «عَلِیَ یَعْلَی» generally carries a positive connotation (m.f.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ فِرۡعَوۡنَ عَلَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ» (28/4)\nTranslation: Pharaoh had exalted himself in the land.","«عَلَا» meaning to rise or lift one's head in a rebellious manner.","Head; chief; leader; summit; top; beginning; source.","علا یعلوا علوًا","3:139-17:4-17:43-27:14-27:31-28:4-28:83-44:19",8
1852,394,"L","سَیِّد","«سَادَ» meaning to be noble, great, the leader of a people, or to surpass others in honor and dignity (source). «سَوَادَ» means a large community, and «سَیّد» refers to the leader of that large community. And since it is necessary for a leader to be cultured, every noble person can also be called Sayyid. And for the same reason, master and husband are also called «سَیِّد» (abbr.). Its plural forms are «سَادَت» and «سَادَات». This word is used with positive connotations.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَاۤ  اِنَّاۤ  اَطَعۡنَا سَادَتَنَا وَ کُبَرَآءَنَا  فَاَضَلُّوۡنَا السَّبِیۡلَا» (33/67)  \nTranslation: They will say, Our Lord! We obeyed our leaders and elders, so they led us astray from the path.","«سَیِّد» the leader of a large group (in a positive sense).","Leader","سید","3:39-12:25-33:67",3
1853,394,"L","مَلَأ","«مَلَا» means to fill and «مَلَأ» means that group which is gathered upon a matter (command). And (it is a state) that fills the eyes with apparent beauty and splendor, and fills the souls (hearts) with awe (muf). And its leader is one who turns eyes with arrogance and chests with awe (muq). And in common parlance, «مَلَا» refers to those official royal courtiers who, by virtue of royal influence and authority, remain dominant over people.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ الۡمَلَاُ الَّذِیۡنَ اسۡتَکۡبَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَوۡمِہٖ لَنُخۡرِجَنَّکَ یٰشُعَیۡبُ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مَعَکَ مِنۡ قَرۡیَتِنَاۤ» (7:88)\nTranslation: The arrogant chiefs of his people said, O Shu'ayb, we will surely expel you and those who believe with you from our city.","The government's courtiers and those who have cast their net over the nation.","Leader","ملأ","7:60-7:66-7:75-7:88-7:90-7:109-7:127-10:88-11:27-11:38-12:43-23:24-23:33-27:29-27:32-27:38-28:20-28:38-38:6",19
1854,394,"L","رَھْط","«رَھْط» refers to a small group of people from a tribe, numbering less than ten and containing no women. The leader of such a group is also called «رَھْط» (muf), and this term is generally used in a derogatory sense. «رَھْط» also denotes the rag or cloth that a woman uses specifically during her menstrual period. From this, the proverb «ھُوَ اَذَلُّ مِنَ الرَّھْط» is derived, meaning he is even more degraded than a menstrual cloth. Furthermore, when the word «رَھْط» is attached to a number, it refers to individuals or persons. For example, «عِشْرُوْن رَھْطًا» means twenty persons (manjada).\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَ کَانَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  تِسۡعَۃُ  رَہۡطٍ یُّفۡسِدُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَا یُصۡلِحُوۡنَ» (27/48). Translation: And in that city were nine leaders who spread corruption in the land and did not promote reform.","«رَھْط» a small clique from the same tribe, a gang of miscreants, and its leader.","Leader","رھط","11:91-11:92-27:48",3
1855,394,"C","اَئِمَّۃ","«اَئِمَّۃ» is a collective term. «اِمَام» refers to a person, book, or saying that is followed, whether it be a person, their sayings, or a book, whether it be on the truth or falsehood. (In the context of) a human, it generally comes to mean a religious leader or the prayer leader (imam) of the congregation. Now, observe its examples:\n\nExample (1) A Book of Guidance, for instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   اِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36:12)\nTranslation: And We have recorded everything in a clear Book.\n\nExample (2) An Imam of Guidance: For instance, the command of Allah, the Most High, states:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ  اَئِمَّۃً  یَّہۡدُوۡنَ  بِاَمۡرِنَا لَمَّا صَبَرُوۡا» (32:24)\nTranslation: And among them, We appointed leaders who guided by Our command.\n\nExample (3) An Imam of Disbelief: For instance, the command of Allah, the Most High, states:\n«فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا اَئِمَّۃَ الۡکُفۡرِ ۙ اِنَّہُمۡ لَاۤ اَیۡمَانَ لَہُمۡ» (9:12)\nTranslation: Fight the leaders of disbelief. Their oaths are of no account.","«اَئِمَّۃ» is the plural of «اِمَام», meaning a leader whose example is followed, whether good or bad.","Commander","ائمۃ","9:12-21:73-28:5-28:41-32:24",5
1856,394,"L","نَقِیْب","«نَقَبَ» signifies making a hole in the wall; tunneling.  \n«نَقَبَ عَنِ الْاَخْبَار» signifies investigating news.  \n«نَاقَبَ» signifies taking pride in one's own deeds.  \n«نَاقِبْ» signifies one who knows the conditions of a nation, and  \n«مَنْقَبَتْ» signifies praise and commendation.  \nNoble deed and «نَقِیْب» signifies one who knows the conditions of the people; the leader of the nation; a notable; the witness and guarantor of the people (singular. enumerated). This word is also used in positive connotations.  \n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ لَقَدۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ بَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ ۚ وَ بَعَثۡنَا مِنۡہُمُ اثۡنَیۡ عَشَرَ نَقِیۡبًا» (5/12)  \nTranslation: And Allah took a firm covenant from the Children of Israel, and We appointed among them twelve leaders.","The chief or head of a tribe or group, a responsible individual who represents them; a leader, a sheikh.","Leader","نقیب","5:12",1
1857,395,"C","شِتَآء","«شِتَآء» means the cold season, its opposite is «صَیْف» which means the hot season, and «شَتْوِیّ» means the rain of winter (manjad).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«لِاِیۡلٰفِ قُرَیۡشٍ اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/1,2)\nTranslation: Because the people of Quraysh are accustomed. That is, they are accustomed to traveling (to Yemen and Syria) in the cold and hot seasons.","«شِتَآء» winter season.","Cold","شتآء","106:2",1
1858,395,"C","صِرّ","«صُرَّ الْبَنَات» refers to the death of plants due to cold wind (manjad), and «صِرّ» refers to severe, numbing cold.  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran: «کَمَثَلِ رِیۡحٍ فِیۡہَا صِرٌّ اَصَابَتۡ حَرۡثَ قَوۡمٍ ظَلَمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ فَاَہۡلَکَتۡہُ» (3/117)  \nTranslation: Its example is like a wind laden with severe cold, striking a people who wronged themselves, and utterly destroying them.","«صِرّ» meaning severe cold.","cold","صر","3:117",1
1859,395,"C","صَرْ صَر","«صَرْ صَر» signifies a severe, cold, and fierce wind that produces sound; a howling, bitter wind. For instance, the Quran states: «وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ  فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ» (69/6). Translation: The people of 'Ad were utterly destroyed by a fierce, cold wind.","«صَرْ صَر» meaning a harsh, cold, and swift wind that also produces sound.","cold","صر صر","41:16-54:19-69:6",3
1860,395,"C","نَفْحَۃ","«نَفَحَ» meaning the blowing of wind in coldness, or the blowing of cold wind. And *nafḥah* is a feminine noun, meaning a single gust of cool wind. Its opposite is «لَفْحَۃ», meaning a gust of hot wind.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: And even if a slight whiff of your Lord's punishment touches them.","«نَفْحَۃ» a cool breeze or gust.","Cold","نفحۃ","21:46",1
1861,395,"C","زَمْھَرِیْر","«اِزْمَھَرَّالْیَوْم» means the day being intensely cold. And «زَمْھَرِیْر» means severe cold as well as that layer where the intensity of cold exists (manjadd).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَا یَرَوۡنَ فِیۡہَا شَمۡسًا وَّ  لَا  زَمۡہَرِیۡرًا» (76:13)\nTranslation: They will not see there the intensity of the sun nor the severity of cold.","«زَمْھَرِیْر» an extremely cold layer or severe cold.","coldness","زمھریر","76:13",1
1862,396,"R","طَغٰی","«طَغٰی» means exceeding the bounds in disobedience; being extremely rebellious. And «طَغَا الْمَاء» means water rising high and overflowing its banks; the coming of a flood (majid). «طَاغِیَۃ» means an excessive punishment, a flood, or a mighty thunderstorm. And «طَاغُوْت» refers to anything for which servitude is chosen besides Allah (whether a system or a personality). Thus, in the concept of 'taghut' (transgression), besides overstepping limits, dominance and tyranny are also found (as per Fazlur Rahman, p. 190).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ  لَیَطۡغٰۤی اَنۡ  رَّاٰہُ  اسۡتَغۡنٰی» (96:6)\nTranslation: Indeed, man is openly rebellious, because he considers himself self-sufficient.","«طَغٰی» to overstep someone's boundaries.","rebellion","طغی","20:24-20:43-20:45-53:17-53:52-69:11-79:17-79:37-96:6",9
1863,396,"R","عَتَا","«عُتُوّ یَدُلُّ عَلیٰ اِسْتِکْبَارًا» refers to such rebellion that stems from pride, where a human, deeming themselves great, rebels against Allah's command. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «بَلۡ لَّجُّوۡا فِیۡ عُتُوٍّ  وَّ نُفُوۡرٍ» (67:21). Translation: Rather, these people have gone far in rebellion and hatred.","«عَتَا» a rebellion born of arrogance.","rebellion","عتا","7:77-7:166-25:21-51:44-67:21",5
1864,396,"R","عَلَا","«عَلَا» means to be elevated, to prevail, to be arrogant (haughty), and—due to gaining dominance and authority—to adopt rebellion and raise one's head.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«لَتُفۡسِدُنَّ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مَرَّتَیۡنِ  وَ لَتَعۡلُنَّ  عُلُوًّا کَبِیۡرًا» (17/4)  \nTranslation: You will cause corruption in the land twice and will commit great arrogance.","To adopt arrogance upon attaining dominance and authority.","rebellion","علا","3:139-17:4-17:43-27:14-27:31-28:4-28:83-44:19",8
1865,396,"R","مَرَدَ","«مَرَدَ» means disobedient and rebellious. Surpassing one's peers (manjada), as if the rebellion implied by «مَرَدَ» is such that one surpasses others. For example: In the Noble Quran: «اِنۡ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ  اِلَّا شَیۡطٰنًا مَّرِیۡدًا» (4:117) Translation: And if they call, they call Satan the rebellious.","to be rebellious, then break free from it and soar.","rebellion","مرد","4:117-9:101-22:3",3
1866,397,"T","تَخَافَتَ","«خَفَتَ» means to lower one's voice. And «تَخَافَتَ» means to speak in a low voice. (Mindaj) Whispering among themselves, even if someone hears it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَّتَخَافَتُوۡنَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  اِنۡ لَّبِثۡتُمۡ اِلَّا عَشۡرًا» (20:103)\nTranslation: They will speak to each other in a low voice, You remained [in the world] only ten days.","to mutter in a low, indistinct voice","The Whispered Secret","تخافت","20:103-68:23",2
1867,397,"S","تَنَاجٰی","«نَجْوٰی ، نَجَاَ» means to whisper. To engage in secret conversations.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّمَا  النَّجۡوٰی مِنَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ  لِیَحۡزُنَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اٰمَنُوۡا» (58/10)\nTranslation: (The disbelievers') whispers are from Satan (his incitements) so that the believers may be distressed by them.\nAt another place, the divine command of the Almighty states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِذَا تَنَاجَیۡتُمۡ فَلَا تَتَنَاجَوۡا بِالۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ وَ مَعۡصِیَتِ الرَّسُوۡلِ وَ تَنَاجَوۡا بِالۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی» (58/9)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! When you converse in secret, do not engage in sin, transgression, and disobedience to the Messenger, but rather speak of righteousness and piety.","«نَجْوٰی» meaning to whisper; to talk confidentially.","Satanic whisper (waswasah)","تناجی","4:114-9:78-17:47-20:62-21:3-43:80-58:7-58:8-58:9-58:10-58:12-58:13",12
1868,398,"S","نَفَق","«نَفَق» A path that is open on both sides. A tunnel (like in FL 30) made by cutting through a mountain, from below, for a railway or traffic route. «نَیْفَقُ السَّرَاوِیْل» meaning the hem of a pajama, and «نَافِقَاءَ الْیَرْبُوْع» meaning the burrow of a wild mouse, which has two openings. And «نَافَقَ الْیَرْبُوْعُ وَ نَفَقَ» meaning a mouse entered the burrow through one opening and exited through the other.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» ( 6/35 )\nTranslation: So if you have the power, then find a tunnel in the earth or a ladder (to ascend) into the sky.","a tunnel with two openings","Subterranean passage","نفق","6:35",1
1869,398,"S","سَرَب","A tunnel that has only one entrance. And «سَرَبَ» meaning to crawl along equally (F L 30). And «اِنْسَرَبَتِ الْحَیَّۃُ اِلٰی جُحْرِھَا» meaning a snake entering its hole [by crawling].\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا بَلَغَا مَجۡمَعَ بَیۡنِہِمَا نَسِیَا حُوۡتَہُمَا فَاتَّخَذَ سَبِیۡلَہٗ  فِی الۡبَحۡرِ  سَرَبًا» (18/61)\nTranslation: So when they reached the meeting point of the two rivers, they forgot their fish, and it [the fish] made its way into the river as if it were a tunnel.","«سَرَب» a tunnel with a single entrance/exit.","subterranean passage","سرب","18:61",1
1870,399,"L","کَسَلَ","«کَسَلَ» A state of heaviness, lethargy, or sluggishness in one's nature due to lack of eagerness or listlessness. To be lazy, indolent, or to remain in a state of laxity and weakness (verbal noun).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی» (4/142)\nTranslation: And when they (the hypocrites) stand up for prayer, they stand up lazily and half-heartedly.","To become negligent due to heedlessness.","Lazy","کسل","4:142-9:54",2
1871,399,"S","وَھَنَ","«وَھَنَ» Sluggishness due to physical or moral weakness (intransitive)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4/104)\nTranslation: And do not be sluggish in pursuing the disbelieving people.","«وَھَنَ» to become sluggish due to physical or moral weakness.","Slothful","وھن","3:139-3:146-4:104-47:35-8:18-19:4-29:41-31:14",8
1872,399,"S","وَنٰی","«وَنٰی» meaning to fall short, be careless, or lazy (from 'manjada')—not to strive for something despite having the power and ability to do it.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡہَبۡ اَنۡتَ وَ اَخُوۡکَ بِاٰیٰتِیۡ وَ لَا تَنِیَا فِیۡ  ذِکۡرِیۡ» (20/42)\nTranslation: O Musa! You and your brother go with My signs, and do not be neglectful in remembering Me.","To slacken due to heedlessness «وَنٰی».","Slothful (in religious duties); negligent. (Also generally: lazy, sluggish).","ونی","20:42",1
1873,399,"N","اِسْتَحْسَرَ","«حَسَرَ» means to become tired. And «حَسَرَ الْبَصَرَ» means the tiredness of sight, the weakening of vision. And «حَسِیْر» means exhausted (mandah); as if «حَسَرَ» is used for becoming sluggish due to tiredness, to become bored.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ مَنۡ عِنۡدَہٗ  لَا یَسۡتَکۡبِرُوۡنَ عَنۡ عِبَادَتِہٖ وَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡسِرُوۡنَ» (21/19). Translation: And those (angels) who are with Him do not disdain His worship nor do they become weary.","«اِسْتَحْسَرَ» to become lazy due to fatigue.","Negligent","استحسر","21:19",1
1874,399,"L","بَطَّاَ","«اَلْبَطْؤُ» meaning to delay in moving and to be sluggish.  \n«اِبْطَاءٌ» meaning slow pace, sluggishness, laziness.  \n«بَطَّاَ» meaning to be extremely sluggish and to delay (intensive form).  \n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ اِنَّ مِنۡکُمۡ لَمَنۡ لَّیُبَطِّئَنَّ» (4/72)  \nTranslation: And among you are some who lag behind (intentionally).","Slothfulness or habitual laziness, followed by procrastination.","Lazy","بطا","4:72",1
1875,400,"J","سَفَرَ","«سَفَرَ» means to leave one's place of residence and to cover distance. This term is general, applicable to any journey regardless of purpose.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran, it states:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ مَّرۡضٰۤی اَوۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ» (4/43)\nTranslation: If you are ill or on a journey.","«سَفَرَ» is a common term for travel.","Journey","سفر","2:184-2:185-2:283-4:43-5:6-9:42-18:62",7
1876,400,"J","سَاحَ","«سَاحَ الْمَاءَ» meaning the wandering of water, and «سَاحَۃ» meaning a spacious place, «سَاحَۃُ الدَّار» meaning the courtyard of a house. An open space adjacent to or near the home (open), and «سَاحَ» meaning to wander and travel in an open space. Sightseeing and travel, whether purely for recreation or for some other purpose.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَسِیۡحُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَرۡبَعَۃَ  اَشۡہُرٍ» ( 9/2 )\nTranslation: So, O polytheists! Travel freely in the land for four months.","«سَاحَ» journeying in diverse directions across a vast area, for tourism and sightseeing.","Journey","ساح","9:2",1
1877,400,"J","ظَعَنَ","«ظَعَنَ» meaning to migrate. To move from one place to another. To relocate (transitive verb).  \n«ظَعَان» meaning the rope for securing a camel's saddle (howdah).  \n«ظُعُوْن» meaning a beast of burden (a camel that carries goods from one place to another).  \n«ظَعِیْنَہ» meaning a howdah (camel's saddle). And the woman who often resides in travel and a howdah.  \n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ جُلُوۡدِ الۡاَنۡعَامِ بُیُوۡتًا تَسۡتَخِفُّوۡنَہَا یَوۡمَ ظَعۡنِکُمۡ وَ یَوۡمَ اِقَامَتِکُمۡ» (16:80)  \nTranslation: And He has made for you from the hides of cattle dwellings which you find light on your travel days and your days of residence.","«ظَعَنَ» to relocate as part of a migration.","Journey","ظعن","16:80",1
1878,400,"J","نَفَرَ","«اَلنَّفِیْر» A group of fewer than ten people. People who march toward battle. And «اَلنَّفِیْرُ الْعَام» meaning the public rising up against the enemy (mujahid), and «نَفَرَ» meaning to go forth to confront the enemy on a campaign or in war.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71) Translation: Then you (toward the battlefield) whether you go forth in small groups or all together.","«نَفَرَ» to go out for a mission or to confront an enemy.","Journey","نفر","4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-46:29-18:34-46:29-72:1",10
1879,400,"J","ضَرَبَ فِیْ الْاَرْضِ","«ضَرَبَ فِیْ الْاَرْض» Literally means to set foot on the ground. It is used idiomatically for travel, and generally for a journey that is both distant and undertaken with a purpose. For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اٰخَرُوۡنَ  یَضۡرِبُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ  یَبۡتَغُوۡنَ مِنۡ فَضۡلِ اللّٰہِ» (73/20)\nTranslation: And some others travel through the land in search of God's bounty (i.e., livelihood).","to travel with the intention of reaching a distant place","Journey","ضرب فی الارض","2:273-3:156-4:101-5:106-73:20",5
1880,400,"J","رَحَلَ","«اَلرَّحْل» means a saddle, a howdah (a seat for riding on an animal), a place to stay, a resting place, or luggage that accompanies one on a journey. And «رَحَل» means to load a saddle or howdah onto a camel or any animal; to ride; to migrate; to set out on a journey (transitive/intransitive).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/2)\nTranslation: (This is) to accustom them (the Quraysh) to the winter and summer journeys.","«رَحَلَ» to migrate. to set out on a journey.","Journey","رحل","12:70-12:75-106:2",3
1881,401,"T","شَعَرَ","«اَلشَّعْر» meaning hair and «شَعَرَ» meaning to acquire knowledge as fine as a hair (intransitive), i.e., to grasp the intricacies and subtleties of a matter.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ وَ مَا یَشۡعُرُوۡنَ» (2/9)  \nTranslation: And (these hypocrites, in reality) do not give anyone else a false step, and they do not understand (this fact).","to understand the subtlety and delicacy of a matter","to understand","شعر","2:9-2:12-2:154-3:69-6:26-6:109-6:123-7:95-12:15-12:107-16:21-16:26-16:45-18:19-23:56-26:113-26:202-27:18-27:50-27:65-28:9-28:11-29:53-39:25-39:55-43:66-49:2",27
1882,401,"T","فَھَمَ","«اَلْفَھْم» is the name of that mental faculty through which a person derives matters with refinement and excellence. And «فَھَمَ» means to understand something thoroughly (muf) and to grasp meanings immediately upon hearing speech (faq l 69). And «سَرِیْعُ الْفَھْم» means one who understands a matter instantly. And «سَیِّءُ اَلْفَھَم» means dull-minded (faq l 69). And «فَھَّم» means to make another comprehend the reality of something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ کُنَّا  لِحُکۡمِہِمۡ  شٰہِدِیۡنَ فَفَہَّمۡنٰہَا سُلَیۡمٰنَ» (21/78,79)\nTranslation: And we were present when they were judging, so we gave Solomon the matter in a way he understood completely.","To understand the meanings and implications of a transaction.","to understand","فھم","21:79",1
1883,401,"T","فَقَہَ","«اَلْفِقْہُ» is the knowledge through which one reaches from the present world to the knowledge of the unseen. (Definition) Finding solutions to current matters by keeping precedents, examples, and rulings in mind.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ کَیۡفَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡنَ» (6/65)\nTranslation: Behold! How We expound the Signs in diverse ways, so that they may understand.\n«تَفَقُّہ» Meaning: To develop understanding and insight in a matter, and to reach the depth of the issue.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (9/122)\nTranslation: Why should not then a company from every section of them go forth, so that they may grow in religious understanding?","«فَقَہَ» by considering existing examples to derive solutions for similar problems.","to understand","فقہ","4:78-6:25-6:65-6:98-7:179-8:65-9:81-9:87-9:122-9:127-11:91-17:44-17:46-18:57-18:93-20:28-48:15-59:13-63:3-63:7",20
1884,401,"T","عَقَلَ","«عَقَلَ» means to be understanding and discerning, and to be capable of recognizing errors (Munjid). And «عَقَلَ» also means to restrain and forbid. And «عِقَال» refers to the hobble (a rope) used to tether a camel's leg. And «اَلْمَعْقِل» means a place of refuge, such as a mountain or fortress wherein one seeks shelter (Muf). Thus, the function of reason is to distinguish between benefit and harm, to adopt measures for avoiding harmful things (Faqih, p. 65), and to remain ever-prepared for attaining beneficial matters and accepting knowledge. Then, it engages in reflection and deliberation (Muf).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَتَاۡمُرُوۡنَ النَّاسَ بِالۡبِرِّ وَ تَنۡسَوۡنَ اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ تَتۡلُوۡنَ الۡکِتٰبَ ؕ اَفَلَا تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ» (2/44)\nTranslation: Is it logical that you bid others to do righteous deeds while forgetting your own selves, even though you recite the Scripture? Do you not then understand?","«عَقَلَ» To understand one's benefit and harm, and then to devise a plan to either adopt or abandon it.","To understand","عقل","2:44-2:73-2:75-2:76-2:164-2:170-2:171-2:242-3:65-3:118-5:58-5:103-6:32-6:151-7:169-8:22-10:16-10:42-10:100-11:51-12:2-12:109-13:4-16:12-16:67-21:10-21:67-22:46-23:80-24:61-25:44-26:28-28:60-29:35-29:43-29:63-30:24-30:28-36:62-36:68-37:138-39:43-40:67-43:3-45:5-49:4-57:17-59:14-67:10",49
1885,402,"T","سَمِعَ","«سَمِعَ» means to hear a word or sound with the ears, and «اَلسَّمْع» also denotes the faculty of hearing as well as the ear itself.  \nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«قَدۡ سَمِعَ  اللّٰہُ  قَوۡلَ  الَّتِیۡ تُجَادِلُکَ فِیۡ زَوۡجِہَا» (58/1)  \nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has heard the statement of the woman who was disputing with you concerning her husband.","«سَمِعَ» to hear any sound or voice.","To hear","سمع","2:7-2:20-2:75-2:93-2:104-2:171-2:181-2:285-3:181-3:186-3:193-4:46-4:140-5:7-5:83-5:108-6:36-6:46-7:100-7:179-7:195-7:198-8:20-8:21-8:23-8:31-9:6-10:31-10:67-11:20-12:31-15:18-16:65-16:78-16:108-17:36-18:26-18:101-19:38-19:42-19:62-19:98-20:46-20:108-21:45-21:60-21:100-21:102-22:46-23:24-23:78-24:12-24:16-24:51-25:12-25:44-26:72-26:212-26:223-28:36-28:55-28:71-30:23-31:7-32:9-32:12-32:26-35:14-36:25-37:8-38:7-41:4-41:20-41:22-41:26-43:80-45:8-45:23-46:26-46:30-50:37-50:42-56:25-58:1-63:4-64:16-67:7-67:10-67:23-68:51-72:1-72:9-72:13-78:35-88:11",95
1886,402,"T","سَمَّاع","«سَامِع» means the Hearer. And «سَمَّاع» means the Spy. It refers to a person who eavesdrops for the purpose of spying.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِلۡکَذِبِ سَمّٰعُوۡنَ لِقَوۡمٍ اٰخَرِیۡنَ ۙ  لَمۡ  یَاۡتُوۡکَ» ( 5/41 )\n\nTranslation: They spy to fabricate falsehoods and act as spies for those who do not come to you.","«سَمَّاع» eavesdropping for spying.","to hear / to listen","سماع","5:41-5:42-9:47",3
1887,402,"T","اَسْمَعَ","«اَسْمَعَ» means to convey something to another.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّکَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الۡمَوۡتٰی وَ لَا تُسۡمِعُ الصُّمَّ الدُّعَآءَ اِذَا وَلَّوۡا مُدۡبِرِیۡنَ» (27:80)\nTranslation: There is no doubt that you (O Prophet) cannot make the dead hear (the message), nor the deaf, even if they turn their backs and flee; you can hear the sound.","«اَسْمَعَ» to convey something to another person.","to hear","اسمع","4:46-8:23-10:42-27:80-27:81-30:52-30:53-35:22-43:40-",9
1888,402,"T","اِسْتَمَعَ","«اِسْتَمَعَ» meaning to listen attentively, to strain one's ears to hear, to make an effort to hear a word or sound when it is not clearly audible (as per the lexicon).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«قُلۡ  اُوۡحِیَ  اِلَیَّ  اَنَّہُ  اسۡتَمَعَ  نَفَرٌ مِّنَ الۡجِنِّ فَقَالُوۡۤا  اِنَّا سَمِعۡنَا قُرۡاٰنًا عَجَبًا» (72:1)  \nTranslation: Say, [O Muhammad], It has been revealed to me that a company of the jinn listened and said, 'We have heard a wondrous Quran.'","«اِسْتَمَعَ» to listen attentively and try to hear any sounds or words.","to hear / to listen","استمع","6:25-7:204-10:42-17:47-20:13-21:2-22:73-26:15-26:25-39:18-46:29-47:16-50:41-52:38-72:1-72:9",16
1889,402,"T","اَذِنَ","«اَذِنَ» Attentive and focused listening (detailed) to the discourse in order to implement the directive.\n\nFor example: The Holy Quran states: «وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84/2) Translation: And they lend an ear to the command of their Lord, and this is most fitting for them.","«اَذِنَ» lend an attentive ear.","to hear","اذن","84:2-84:5",2
1890,402,"T","اٰذَنَ","«اٰذَنَ» means to inform someone and warn them, to make them aware (Manjad al-Mufradat). For example, in the Quran it says: «وَ یَوۡمَ  یُنَادِیۡہِمۡ  اَیۡنَ شُرَکَآءِیۡ ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اٰذَنّٰکَ ۙ مَا مِنَّا مِنۡ شَہِیۡدٍ» (41/47). Translation: And on the Day when Allah will call them and say, Where are My partners? they will say, We have informed you that today there is no one among us to bear witness.","«اٰذَنَ» to hear and then warn someone.","to hear","اذن","2:279-7:44-7:167-12:70-14:7-22:27",6
1891,403,"T","اِصْلَاحُ","«اِصْلَاحُ»'s opposite is «اَفْسَدَ». «اِصْلَاحُ» means to rectify corruption and disorder. Its usage is widespread in every material and spiritual respect.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n« کَفَّرَ عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ  وَ اَصۡلَحَ بَالَہُمۡ» (47/2)  \nTranslation: (Allah) has removed their sins from them and set their state right.  \nAt another instance, the divine command states:  \n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)  \nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reformation.","The word «اِصْلَاحُ» is used for rectifying and correcting all kinds of corruption.","to arrange / to organize / to set up","اصلح","2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10",40
1892,403,"T","زَکّٰی","The literal meaning of «زَکوٰ ، زَکٰی» and «زَکّٰی» is increase and growth in cultivation, etc. And «زَکِیْ مَالَہٗ» means to pay the zakat of wealth. And «زَکّٰی نَفْسَہٗ» means to make one's own mouth sweet (manjad), but Shariah has used the word «تَزْکِیَہ» in the meanings of purification and reformation. And tazkiyah nafs means to purify the nafs (self) from vile morals (bad morals) and to add good morals.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is: «قَدۡ  اَفۡلَحَ  مَنۡ  زَکّٰىہَا وَ  قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ  دَسّٰىہَا» (91:9-10) Translation: He who has purified his nafs (i.e., his soul) has achieved his goal, and he who has buried it in dust has remained in loss.","The word «زَکّٰی» is used for correcting the corruption of the self and then adding superior ethics to it.","to arrange","زکی","2:129-2:151-2:174-2:232-3:77-3:164-4:49-9:103-18:19-18:74-18:81-19:13-19:19-20:76-24:21-24:28-24:30-35:18-53:32-62:2-79:18-80:3-80:7-87:14-91:9-92:18",26
1893,404,"H","رَکَبَ","«رَکَبَ» means to ride on something, such as the back of an animal, a boat, etc. And «رِکَاب» means a ride, or the mount (e.g., a camel for riding). And «رَاکِب» means a rider. Generally, it is used for a camel rider (one who rides a camel). And «رَکْب» means a caravan of camel riders.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا رَکِبَا فِی السَّفِیۡنَۃِ خَرَقَہَا» (18/71)\nTranslation: Until they both boarded a ship, and he (Khidr, peace be upon him) scuttled it.","«رَکَبَ» to ride on anything that can be ridden.","Horsemen","رکب","2:239-8:42-11:41-11:42-16:8-18:71-29:65-36:42-40:79-43:12",10
1894,404,"T","اِسْتَوٰی ( عَلٰی )","«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» meaning to stabilize, settle, or take a firm position after mounting; to sit firmly and securely.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِتَسۡتَوٗا عَلٰی ظُہُوۡرِہٖ  ثُمَّ تَذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَۃَ  رَبِّکُمۡ  اِذَا اسۡتَوَیۡتُمۡ عَلَیۡہِ» (43:13)\nTranslation: So that you may mount them and, when you have settled firmly upon them, remember the favor of your Lord.","To sit firmly after mounting «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی».","The Horseman (AS)","استوی ( علی )","7:54-10:3-13:2-20:5-25:59-32:4-43:13-48:29-57:4",9
1895,404,"T","حَمَلَ","The basic meaning of «حَمَلَ» is to bear a burden, and «اَحْمَلَ» means to help in bearing a burden. Then, when this burden is a human and it is necessary to load him onto an animal or a riding beast, the word «حَمَلَ» itself is used in the meanings of to ride.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قُلۡتَ لَاۤ  اَجِدُ مَاۤ  اَحۡمِلُکُمۡ  عَلَیۡہِ» (9/92)\nTranslation: They came to you so that you might provide them with mounts to ride, and you said, I do not have anything on which I can mount you.","The meaning of «حَمَلَ» is to bear a burden and to carry, and «حَمَلَ عَلٰی» means to mount or ride.","The Rider","حمل","2:248-2:286-6:31-6:146-7:176-7:189-9:92-11:40-12:36-12:72-13:8-16:7-16:25-17:3-17:70-19:22-19:27-19:58-20:87-20:100-20:101-20:111-22:2-23:22-24:54-29:12-29:13-29:60-31:14-33:72-35:11-35:18-36:41-40:7-40:80-41:47-46:15-54:13-62:5-65:4-65:6-69:11-69:14-69:17",44
1896,405,"E","اِلَّا","«اِلَّا» means but or except. It is an exception word. In this case, it can form a negative sentence (exception).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«لَاۤ اِلٰہَ اِلَّا ہُوَ الرَّحۡمٰنُ  الرَّحِیۡمُ» (2/163)\nTranslation: None is worthy of worship except the Most Merciful, the Bestower of Mercy.\nBesides this, this word also conveys the meaning of «حَصَر».\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ مَا یَخۡدَعُوۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ» (2/9)\nTranslation: And they do not deceive except themselves.\n\n1- Note: By exception is meant that a general word appearing at the beginning of a statement, which includes certain things, is excluded from its ruling by «اِلّا» or similar words like «سَوَی ، غَیْرَ، لَیْسَ ، عَدَا ، خَلَا ، حَاشَا».\n2- Note: (Hasr) In Arabic terminology, it means to establish a ruling for one specific thing and negate it for all others. This is also called restriction or exclusive specification.\n3- Note: An indefinite noun (ism nakirah) is a noun that is used for all things of a single type without specification.","«اِلَّا» with the exception derives the benefit of restriction.","except","الا","2:9-2:26-2:32-2:34-2:45-2:78-2:80-2:83-2:85-2:99-2:102-2:111-2:114-2:130-2:132-2:143-2:150-2:160-2:163-2:171-2:174-2:193-2:210-2:213-2:229-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:246-2:249-2:255-2:267-2:269-2:272-2:275-2:282-2:286-3:2-3:6-3:7-3:18-3:19-3:24-3:28-3:41-3:62-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:73-3:75-3:89-3:93-3:102-3:102-3:111-3:112-3:126-3:135-3:144-3:145-3:147-3:185-4:19-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:43-4:46-4:62-4:64-4:66-4:83-4:84-4:87-4:90-4:92-4:98-4:113-4:114-4:117-4:120-4:142-4:146-4:148-4:155-4:157-4:159-4:169-4:171-5:1-5:3-5:13-5:25-5:34-5:59-5:73-5:75-5:99-5:110-5:117-6:4-6:7-6:17-6:23-6:25-6:26-6:29-6:32-6:38-6:47-6:48-6:50-6:57-6:59-6:80-6:90-6:102-6:106-6:111-6:116-6:119-6:123-6:128-6:138-6:145-6:146-6:148-6:151-6:152-6:158-6:160-6:164-7:5-7:11-7:20-7:42-7:53-7:58-7:82-7:83-7:89-7:94-7:99-7:105-7:126-7:147-7:155-7:158-7:169-7:184-7:187-7:188-8:10-8:16-8:31-8:34-8:35-8:72-8:73-9:4-9:7-9:8-9:10-9:18-9:31-9:32-9:38-9:39-9:40-9:47-9:51-9:52-9:54-9:74-9:79-9:107-9:110-9:114-9:118-9:120-9:121-9:129-10:3-10:5-10:15-10:19-10:32-10:35-10:36-10:45-10:49-10:52-10:61-10:66-10:72-10:83-10:90-10:98-10:100-10:102-10:107-11:2-11:6-11:7-11:11-11:14-11:16-11:26-11:27-11:29-11:36-11:40-11:43-11:47-11:50-11:51-11:54-11:56-11:81-11:88-11:104-11:105-11:107-11:108-11:109-11:116-11:119-12:25-12:31-12:33-12:37-12:40-12:47-12:48-12:53-12:64-12:66-12:67-12:68-12:76-12:79-12:81-12:87-12:104-12:106-12:109-13:14-13:26-13:30-13:38-14:4-14:9-14:10-14:11-14:22-15:4-15:8-15:11-15:18-15:21-15:31-15:40-15:42-15:56-15:59-15:60-15:85-16:2-16:7-16:33-16:35-16:43-16:64-16:77-16:79-16:106-16:127-17:23-17:33-17:34-17:41-17:44-17:47-17:52-17:58-17:59-17:60-17:61-17:62-17:64-17:67-17:76-17:82-17:85-17:87-17:89-17:93-17:94-17:99-17:102-17:105-18:5-18:16-18:22-18:24-18:39-18:49-18:50-18:55-18:56-18:63-19:60-19:62-19:64-19:71-19:87-19:93-20:3-20:8-20:14-20:98-20:103-20:104-20:108-20:109-20:116-21:2-21:3-21:7-21:22-21:25-21:28-21:36-21:58-21:87-21:107-22:30-20:40-22:52-22:65-23:6-23:24-23:25-23:27-23:33-23:37-23:38-23:62-23:83-23:114-23:116-24:3-24:5-24:6-24:31-24:54-25:4-25:8-25:20-25:33-25:41-25:44-25:50-25:56-25:57-25:68-25:70-26:5-26:77-26:89-26:99-26:109-26:113-26:115-26:127-26:137-26:145-26:154-26:164-26:171-26:180-26:186-26:208-26:227-27:11-27:26-27:56-27:57-27:65-27:68-27:75-27:81-27:87-27:90-28:19-28:36-28:58-28:59-28:70-28:80-28:84-28:86-28:88-29:14-29:18-29:24-29:29-29:32-29:33-29:43-29:46-29:47-29:49-29:64-30:8-30:53-30:58-31:28-31:32-33:6-33:12-33:13-33:14-33:16-33:18-33:20-33:22-33:39-33:52-33:53-33:60-34:3-34:14-34:17-34:20-34:21-34:23-34:28-34:33-34:34-34:37-34:43-34:46-34:47-35:3-35:11-35:23-35:24-35:39-35:40-35:42-35:43-36:15-36:17-36:29-36:30-36:44-36:46-36:47-36:49-36:53-36:54-36:69-37:10-37:15-37:35-37:39-37:40-37:59-37:74-37:128-37:135-37:160-37:163-37:164-38:7-38:14-38:15-38:24-38:65-38:70-38:74-38:83-38:87-39:3-39:6-39:68-40:3-40:4-40:13-40:25-40:29-40:37-40:40-40:50-40:56-40:62-40:65-40:78-41:14-41:35-41:43-41:47-42:14-42:23-42:48-42:51-43:7-43:20-43:23-43:27-43:48-43:58-43:59-43:66-43:67-43:86-44:8-44:35-44:39-44:42-44:56-45:17-45:24-45:25-45:32-46:3-46:9-46:17-46:21-46:25-46:35-47:18-47:19-48:15-50:18-51:42-51:52-51:56-53:4-53:23-53:26-53:28-53:29-53:32-53:39-54:34-54:50-55:33-55:60-56:26-56:79-57:20-57:22-57:27-58:2-58:7-58:10-59:14-59:22-59:23-60:4-64:11-64:13-65:1-65:7-67:9-67:19-67:20-68:52-69:36-69:37-70:22-70:30-71:6-71:21-71:24-71:27-71:28-72:23-72:27-73:2-73:9-74:24-74:25-74:31-74:39-74:56-76:30-78:25-78:30-78:38-79:46-81:27-81:29-83:12-84:25-85:8-87:7-88:6-88:23-92:15-92:20-95:6-98:4-98:5-103:3",609
1897,405,"E","غَیْر","The word «غَیْر» sometimes comes only for negation. For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ ہُوَ فِی الۡخِصَامِ  غَیۡرُ  مُبِیۡنٍ» (43/18) Translation: And they could not even clarify the matter during the dispute. And sometimes it comes for exception. In this case, it can become a negative attribute (مف). For example: The divine command states: «ہَلۡ مِنۡ خَالِقٍ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ» (35/3) Translation: Is there any other creator besides Allah?","In «غَیْر», the meaning of negation is also found alongside exception.","Except","غیر","1:7-2:59-2:173-2:230-2:240-3:83-3:85-3:154-4:12-4:24-4:25-4:46-4:56-4:81-4:82-4:95-4:115-4:140-5:1-5:3-5:5-5:77-5:106-6:14-6:40-6:46-6:68-6:93-6:99-6:114-6:141-6:145-6:164-7:53-7:59-7:65-7:73-7:85-7:140-7:162-8:7-9:2-9:3-9:39-10:15-11:46-11:50-11:57-11:61-11:63-11:65-11:76-11:84-11:101-11:108-11:109-13:4-14:37-14:48-16:21-16:52-16:115-17:73-20:22-22:5-22:31-23:6-23:23-23:32-24:27-24:29-24:31-24:60-26:29-27:12-27:22-28:32-28:38-28:71-28:72-30:55-33:53-35:3-35:37-39:28-39:64-41:8-43:18-47:15-47:38-50:31-51:36-52:35-52:43-56:86-68:3-70:28-70:30-74:10-84:25-95:6",101
1898,405,"E","دُوْن","«دَان» means to be mean or stingy, and to be weak. «دُوْن» means low, inferior, or lesser in worth and status. It also means contemptible, a worthless thing (manjad), and «دُوْن» can also mean to be incapable or deficient in something (muf). Furthermore, when «دُوْن» conveys the meaning of 'except' (sawā), it also carries the nuance of inferiority and weakness.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ» (3:118)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Do not reveal your secrets to anyone except your own people.\nIn this verse, the expression of the inferiority of other religious communities, apart from the Muslims, is intended.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَغۡفِرُ اَنۡ یُّشۡرَکَ بِہٖ وَ یَغۡفِرُ  مَا دُوۡنَ ذٰلِکَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (4:48)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah does not forgive association with Him, but He forgives anything else of whom He wills.\nHere, the sins referred to are those of a lesser degree than shirk (association).\n\nSimilarly, the Divine command states:\n«مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ وَّلِیٍّ وَّ لَا نَصِیۡرٍ» (2:107)\nTranslation: You have no protector or helper besides Allah.\nIn this verse as well, «دُوْن» (besides) imparts the meaning of 'except' along with the connotation of inferiority.","In «دُوْن», the meaning of reduction with exception is found.","except","دون","2:23-2:94-2:107-2:165-3:28-3:64-3:79-3:118-4:48-4:116-4:117-4:119-4:123-4:139-4:144-4:173-5:76-5:116-6:51-6:56-6:70-6:71-6:108-7:3-7:30-7:37-7:81-7:168-7:194-7:197-7:205-8:60-9:16-9:31-9:116-10:18-10:37-10:38-10:66-10:104-10:106-11:13-11:20-11:55-11:101-11:113-12:40-13:11-13:14-13:16-16:20-16:35-16:73-16:86-17:2-17:56-17:97-18:14-18:15-18:26-18:27-18:43-18:50-18:58-18:93-18:102-19:17-19:48-19:49-19:81-21:24-21:29-21:43-21:66-21:67-21:82-21:98-22:12-22:62-22:71-22:73-23:63-25:3-25:17-25:18-25:55-26:93-27:24-27:43-27:55-28:23-28:81-29:17-29:22-29:25-29:41-29:42-31:11-31:30-32:4-32:21-33:17-33:50-34:22-34:41-35:13-35:40-36:23-36:74-37:23-37:86-39:3-39:15-39:36-39:38-39:43-39:45-40:20-40:66-40:74-42:6-42:9-42:31-42:46-43:45-43:86-45:10-46:4-46:5-46:28-46:32-48:27-52:47-53:58-55:62-60:4-62:6-67:20-71:25-72:11-72:22",141
1899,405,"E","وَرَاء","«وَرَاء» is a word of *al-ghaṭāṭ al-aḍdād* (words with opposite meanings). Its meanings include 'ahead' and 'behind', 'this side' and 'that side', 'here' and 'there'. By this same consideration, it can also convey the meaning of 'except' or 'apart from'. That is, other than all those directions or things.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَنِ ابۡتَغٰی وَرَآءَ ذٰلِکَ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡعٰدُوۡنَ» (23/7)\nTranslation: So whoever desires other than that, then those are the ones who transgress the bounds.\n\nIts meaning is: Whoever seeks, besides the commands of Allah, something in this direction or that, ahead or behind, is an erroneous person.\n\nNote: *Al-ghaṭāṭ al-aḍdād* refers to words that have two separate meanings, and those meanings are contrary and opposite to each other.","«وَرَاء» serves as an exception that extends to all sides.","Except","وراء","2:91-2:101-3:187-4:24-4:102-6:94-11:71-11:92-14:16-14:17-18:79-19:5-23:7-23:100-33:53-42:51-45:10-49:4-57:13-59:14-70:31-76:27-84:10-85:20",24
1900,405,"E","اِسْتَثْنَاء ( ثنی )","«اِسْتَثْنَاء» means excluding something from a general ruling (specific). For this purpose, «اِلَّا» is used, but in Shariah terminology, it means considering something subject to the will of Allah and thus excluding it from the general ruling.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَقُوۡلَنَّ لِشَایۡءٍ  اِنِّیۡ  فَاعِلٌ ذٰلِکَ غَدًا اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّشَآءَ اللّٰہُ» (18/23)\nTranslation: And do not say regarding any matter, 'I will do it tomorrow,' except (by saying 'if Allah wills') i.e., if Allah wills, (I will do it).\n\nAnd the word «اِسْتَثْنَاء» is used instead of saying «اِنْ شَاءَ اللہ».\n\nFor example: The divine declaration states:\n«اِذۡ  اَقۡسَمُوۡا لَیَصۡرِمُنَّہَا مُصۡبِحِیۡنَ وَ لَا  یَسۡتَثۡنُوۡنَ» (68/17/18)\nTranslation: When they swore and said, 'We will cut the fruit of the garden in the morning.' And they did not say 'Insha'Allah'.","By saying God willing to exclude something from a general ruling.","Except","استثناء ( ثنی )","68:18",1
1901,406,"G","نَامَ","«نَامَ» meaning sleep is a well-known word and commonly used (cf. 292). Sleep is also a type of death in which the soul separates from the body and roams about, and the functionality of the five senses diminishes greatly because they become sluggish. During this, a person's fatigue is removed. And due to mental and physical peace, he attains comfort and tranquility. «نَوْم» meaning sleep and «مَنَام» meaning the state of sleep. The state of sleep.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَفَاَمِنَ اَہۡلُ الۡقُرٰۤی اَنۡ  یَّاۡتِیَہُمۡ  بَاۡسُنَا بَیَاتًا  وَّ ہُمۡ  نَآئِمُوۡنَ» (7:97)\nTranslation: Did the people of the town become secure that Our punishment would not come to them at night while they were asleep?","«نَامَ» meaning (sleep) to sleep, is a common word for sleeping.","gold","نام","2:255-7:97-8:43-25:47-30:23-37:102-39:42-68:19-78:9",9
1902,406,"G","ھَجَعَ","«ھَجَعَ» meaning heedless sleep (Fall 161) sleeping while selling horses. To become unaware of the world and its contents while sleeping, and some attribute the meaning of صاحبِ مُنْجِد «اَلْھَجَعَۃ» to light sleep in the first part of the night, but this does not seem correct because they themselves define «اَلْھُجَعُ» as heedless, foolish, and one who sleeps a lot (munajid). Moreover, this is not supported by the Quran either. Therefore, the meaning according to the scholar of linguistic jurisprudence (صَاحِبِ فِقْہُ الْلُغَۃ) appears to be correct. However, the word «ھَجُوْع» is specific (exclusive) to sleep at night, just as sleep during the day is called qailulah (M Q).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«کَانُوۡا  قَلِیۡلًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ مَا یَہۡجَعُوۡنَ وَ  بِالۡاَسۡحَارِ ہُمۡ  یَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ» (51:17,18)\nTranslation: They used to sleep but a little of the night, and in the hours of early dawn they used to ask for forgiveness.","«ھَجَعَ» profound and heedless sleep.","Gold","ھجع","51:17",1
1903,406,"G","رَقَدَ","«رَقَدَ» means a long sleep (Fath al-Bari 161). «اَلرُِّقَاد» means a pleasant and light sleep (Mafatih), and «اَلرُّقَدَۃُ» and «اَلْيَرْقُوْدُ » mean one who sleeps a lot, and «اَلرُّقُوْد» means one who is always sleeping (Munajid). From all these statements, it is understood that «رَقَدَ» is a sleep that is long, pleasant, and light. That is, a person wakes up at the slightest sound.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَحۡسَبُہُمۡ اَیۡقَاظًا وَّ ہُمۡ رُقُوۡدٌ» (18:18)\nTranslation: And you would think them awake, while they were asleep.","«رَقَدَ» long, light sleep.","Gold","رقد","18:18",1
1904,406,"G","قَالَ","«یَقِیْلُ قَیْلًا وَ قَیْلُوْلَۃً» sleeping in the afternoon; resting (taking ease) during the day (Fal 292)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ اَہۡلَکۡنٰہَا فَجَآءَہَا بَاۡسُنَا  بَیَاتًا  اَوۡ  ہُمۡ  قَآئِلُوۡنَ» ( 7/4 )\nTranslation: And how many towns We have destroyed while they were asleep at night or resting in the afternoon.","«قَالَ» to take an afternoon nap.","Gold","قال","7:4",1
1905,406,"G","ضَجَعَ","«ضَجَعَ» to lie on one's side or turn, to rest, whether drowsiness or sleep comes or does not come (manjud). A state of half-sleep. And «مَضَاجِع» meaning to spread out, bed, and «اَضْجَعَہ» meaning to spread it. (M. Q.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«تَتَجَافٰی جُنُوۡبُہُمۡ عَنِ الۡمَضَاجِعِ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ خَوۡفًا وَّ طَمَعًا» (32/16)\nTranslation: They keep their sides away from their beds and call upon their Lord with fear and hope.","«ضَجَعَ» to lie on one's side for sleeping, whether sleep comes or not.","Gold","ضجع","3:154-4:34-32:16",3
1906,406,"G","تَھَجَّدَ","«هُجُوْد» means both sleeping and waking during the night; sometimes sleeping, sometimes waking (this word is from the category of antonyms). And spending the night while alternating between sleep and wakefulness. And «ھَجَّدَ» means praying at night after waking up (Manjad). For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنَ الَّیۡلِ فَتَہَجَّدۡ بِہٖ نَافِلَۃً  لَّکَ» (17/79)\nTranslation: And perform the Tahajjud prayer during a part of the night, as an additional act of worship for you.","«تَھَجَّدَ» To wake up at night for the Tahajjud prayer and similar acts of worship, to pray at night, to perform Tahajjud.","gold","تھجد","17:79",1
1907,407,"I","اَسْوَد","«اَسْوَد» means black, and its opposite «اَبْیْضَ» means white. «اَسْوَد» is used in its well-known meanings and is commonly employed. Its plural is «سُوْد», and its feminine form is «سَوْدَاء».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ لَکُمُ الۡخَیۡطُ الۡاَبۡیَضُ مِنَ الۡخَیۡطِ الۡاَسۡوَدِ  مِنَ الۡفَجۡرِ» (2/187)\nTranslation: And eat and drink until the white thread of dawn becomes distinct to you from the black thread.","«اَسْوَد» means black color.","ink","اسود","2:187-3:106-16:58",3
1908,407,"I","غَرَابِیْب","«غُرَاب» means 'kaww' (a type of crow); its plural is «غِرْبَان». And «غِرْبِیْب» means 'very black like a crow'; its plural is «غَرَابِیْب» (sing.). And «غُرْبِیْب» means a person who dyes (hair) black with henna; its plural is «غَرَابِیْب» (coll.).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ جُدَدٌۢ  بِیۡضٌ وَّ حُمۡرٌ  مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہَا وَ غَرَابِیۡبُ سُوۡدٌ» ( 35/27 )\nTranslation: And among the mountains are streaks white and red, of varying colors and black.","«غَرَابِیْب» meaning extremely black.","Ink","غرابیب","35:27",1
1909,407,"I","اَحْوٰی","«اَحْوٰی» is a blackish-green or blackish-reddish hue (munjad). These words appear in the Noble Quran as «غُثَآءً اَحْوٰی». «غُثَآء» refers to the twigs, leaves, and scum that get caught in the foam, which the river then washes ashore. And when this scum and debris is continually trampled underfoot, its color turns to a blackish hue, which is called «اَحْوٰی».\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَخۡرَجَ  الۡمَرۡعٰی فَجَعَلَہٗ  غُثَآءً  اَحۡوٰی» (87:4,5)\nTranslation: And who produced green vegetation, then made it blackened stubble.","«اَحْوٰی» meaning a black color tinged with green.","Ink","احوی","87:5",1
1910,407,"I","اَدْھَم","«دَھَمَ» means something being covered in darkness. And «اَلدُّھْمَۃ» means blackness. «دَھَّمَتِ النَّارُ الْقِدْرَ» The fire blackened the pot.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«مُدۡہَآ  مَّتٰنِ» (55/64)\nTranslation: Both gardens will be of deep green, as if they were dark (or black).","«اَدْھَم» denoting a deep green with a blackish tint.","ink","ادھم","55:64",1
1911,407,"I","قَتَرَۃ","«قَتَرَ النَّار» بمعنی آگ کا دھواں دینا (منجد) اور «قَتَرَۃ» بمعنی دھوئیں جیسے رنگ والا گردوغبار ، سیاہی ۔\nمثلاً : قرآن کریم میں ہے :\n«وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» ( 80/40،41 )\nترجمہ : اور آج کے دن کتنے منہ ہوں گے جن پر گرد پڑ رہی ہو گی ( اور ) سیاہی چڑھ رہی ہو گی ۔","«قَتَرَۃ» meaning smoke-colored.","Ink","قترۃ","10:26-80:41",2
1912,407,"I","مِدَاد","«مَدَدْتُ الدَّوَاۃ» means to put ink or light in a pen. And «مِدَادَ» is the ink or light (singular) with which one writes.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«قُلۡ لَّوۡ کَانَ الۡبَحۡرُ مِدَادًا لِّکَلِمٰتِ رَبِّیۡ لَنَفِدَ الۡبَحۡرُ  قَبۡلَ اَنۡ تَنۡفَدَ کَلِمٰتُ رَبِّیۡ» (18/109)\nTranslation: (O Prophet, say to the people) Say: If the sea were ink for writing the Words of my Lord, the Words of my Lord would never be exhausted, even if the sea were to dry up first.","«مِدَاد» means ink and the light used for writing.","Ink","مداد","18:109",1
1913,408,"S","مُسْتَقِیْم","«مُسْتَقِیْم» is that which is both straight and also balanced and moderate. And «قَامَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to remain firm and steadfast upon something. And «اَقَامَ الشَّیْ» means to make something stand upright and straight.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ زِنُوۡا بِالۡقِسۡطَاسِ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمِ» (17/35)\nTranslation: And weigh with a straight balance.\n\nBecause if the rod of the balance, which is already straight, does not remain parallel to the horizontal line, then the weighing itself will not be balanced, even though the rod is, after all, straight and remains straight, whether one pan is tilted downwards or not. So here, by 'straight' is meant straight in the vertical sense, i.e., it should also remain parallel. And according to geometric science, the shortest distance between two points or two locations is called a straight line. Thus, the 'Sirat al-Mustaqim' (Straight Path) is that path which is straight and in which there is no kind of sway, flexibility, or deviation—meaning it is free from excess and deficiency (shortage and surplus).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, we have been taught this supplication:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ» (1/5)\nTranslation: Our Lord, guide us to the straight path.","«مُسْتَقِیْم» balanced, moderate, and upright.","straight","مستقیم","1:5-2:142-2:213-3:51-3:101-4:68-4:175-5:16-6:39-6:87-6:126-6:153-6:161-7:16-9:7-10:25-10:89-11:56-15:41-16:76-16:121-17:35-19:36-22:54-22:67-23:73-24:46-26:182-36:4-36:61-37:118-41:6-42:52-43:43-43:61-43:64-46:30-48:2-48:20-67:22-81:28",41
1914,408,"S","سَوٰی ۔ سَوِیّ","«سَوِیَ یَسْوِی» means the correctness of something. And «سَوّٰی» means to make something correct and even/smooth. And «سَوِیَ» means even, correct, and sound/healthy.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا» (19/17)\nTranslation: Then the angel appeared before Maryam (peace be upon her) in the form of a sound and perfectly shaped man.\n\nAnd «صِرَاطًا سَوِیًّا» also refers to a path that is correct, even, and straight—without any elevation, depression, or crookedness.\n\nFor example: The Divine command states:\n«فَاتَّبِعۡنِیۡۤ  اَہۡدِکَ صِرَاطًا سَوِیًّا» (19/43)\nTranslation: (Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) said to his father) Follow me; I will guide you to a straight path.\n\nThe word «سَوَاء» also comes with meanings of equality. If this equality is in terms of distance or number from both sides, then the word for 'middle' will be used. But if equality in every respect is intended, then the word «سَوَاء» is used, as if its meaning is the central point or the very middle.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47)\nTranslation: (It will be commanded) Seize him and drag him into the middle of Hell.\n\nAnd the meaning of «سَوَآءَ السَّبِیْل» is a path that, while leaving all kinds of error, disbelief, and misguidance on its sides, emerges straight from the middle.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَمَّا تَوَجَّہَ  تِلۡقَآءَ مَدۡیَنَ قَالَ عَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ   اَنۡ  یَّہۡدِیَنِیۡ  سَوَآءَ  السَّبِیۡلِ» (28/22)\nTranslation: When Prophet Musa (peace be upon him) turned his face towards Madyan, he said, I hope that my Lord will guide me to the straight path.","«سَوَیّ» smooth, straight, and correct.\n«سَوَاء» the straight path that passes through the middle.","Straight","سوی ۔ سوی","4:42-15:29-19:10-19:17-19:43-20:58-20:135-26:98-38:72-67:22-75:4-75:38-87:2",13
1915,408,"S","قَصْد","«قَصْد» refers to the legitimate use of something with proper intention. For example, if a person can bathe using one bucket of water and uses exactly that amount, it is *qasad* (intentional and appropriate use). If he uses more, it is *israf* (extravagance), and if he uses less than a bucket, it is *bukhl* (stinginess). To consider this balance in every matter and make it a habit is called *iqtisad* (moderation/frugality).\n\nNow, looking at it from a spiritual perspective: in every situation, neither extreme leniency nor extreme severity can achieve the desired objective. Determining how much firmness or leniency is required to attain the goal is the function of Shariah.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَی اللّٰہِ  قَصۡدُ السَّبِیۡلِ وَ مِنۡہَا جَآئِرٌ» (16:9)\nTranslation: And to show the straight path is the responsibility of Allah alone, apart from that, all other paths are crooked.\n\n«قَصْد»: Its meaning is not correctly conveyed by the phrase 'moderate and balanced' either. Therefore, its meaning is taken as 'straight' (or 'correct').","«قَصْد» The One who correctly determines values and the straight path, free from excess and deficiency.","Straight","قصد","9:42-16:9-31:19",3
1916,408,"U","سَدِیْدًا","«سَدُّ » means a barrier, a rampart, or a wall erected between two things. And «سُدٌّ» means to seal a crack or fissure with stones. And «سِدَاد» is the term for the substance with which a rift or fissure is filled. And «قَوْلاً سَدِیْدًا» is that which contains no obstacle, defect, corruption, or any complexity and deceit. It is correct, proper, true, and straight. Its opposite is «قَوْلَ الزُّوْر», which has a much broader meaning than falsehood.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلۡیَتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لۡیَقُوۡلُوۡا قَوۡلًا سَدِیۡدًا» (4/9)\nTranslation: So let them fear Allah and set things right (or speak justly).","«سَدِیْدًا» is a path that is free from all obstacles, strong, clear, and straight.","Upright","سدیدًا","4:9-33:70",2
1917,409,"L","سُلَّم","This word is commonly found in the terms ma'araj or mi'raj. Although the word «سُلَّم» is used for a staircase leading to a roof made of bricks and stones in a building, and for a wooden staircase. However, «سُلَّم» can refer to anything that serves as a means to reach a high place. And its plurals are «سَلاَلِمُ» and «سَلَالِیْم». And «اَدْرَاجُ السُّلَم» means the pole or support of a staircase (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَاِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتَ اَنۡ تَبۡتَغِیَ نَفَقًا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ اَوۡ  سُلَّمًا فِی السَّمَآءِ» (6/35). Translation: So if you have the strength, then find a tunnel in the earth, or a staircase in the sky (search for it).","«سُلَّم» meaning ladder, staircase.","ladder","سلم","6:35-52:38",2
1918,409,"L","مَعَارِج","The plural of «مِعْرَاج» is «عَرَجَ», meaning to limp while walking. And «اَعْرَج» means limp, «عَرَجَ فِی السُّلم» means to climb a ladder. And «مِعْرَاج» means a place to climb (manjada), thus the word «مِعْرَاج» is more specific than «سُلَّم». In it, the concept of reaching a high place via a ladder is found, whereas «سُلَّم» merely refers to the ladder itself. For example: In the Quran, it is: «وَّ مَعَارِجَ عَلَیۡہَا یَظۡہَرُوۡنَ» (43:33) Translation: And ladders too, on which they climb.","«مَعَارِج» meaning the place to climb.","ladder","معارج","43:33-70:3",2
1919,410,"T","تَعَلَّمَ","«عَلِمَ» means to know or to discover the reality of something. And «عَلَّمَ» means to inform someone abundantly and repeatedly, that is, to teach. And «تَعَلَّمَ» means to gradually accept the effect of a piece of news, to learn continuously, to learn (transitive).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا» ( 2/31 )\nTranslation: And Allah taught Adam the names of all things.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«فَیَتَعَلَّمُوۡنَ مِنۡہُمَا مَا یُفَرِّقُوۡنَ بِہٖ بَیۡنَ الۡمَرۡءِ  وَ زَوۡجِہٖ» ( 2/102 )\nTranslation: And they used to learn from them what would cause separation between a man and his wife.","«تَعَلَّم» means to learn oneself and «عَلَّمَ» means to teach someone.","to learn","تعلم","2:31-2:32-2:102-2:129-2:151-2:251-2:282-3:48-3:79-3:164-4:113-5:4-5:110-6:91-12:6-12:21-12:68-12:101-16:103-18:65-18:66-20:71-21:80-26:49-27:16-36:69-44:14-53:5-55:2-55:4-62:2-96:4-96:5",33
1920,410,"T","تَلَقّٰی","«لَقِیَ» means to meet, encounter, find, see, and «تَلَقّٰی» means to receive/accept (someone). «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْءُ مِنْہُ» is used in the sense of learning from someone (from manjad), and «تَلَقّٰی» also means to cast into the heart and learning from that. For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَتَلَقّٰۤی اٰدَمُ مِنۡ رَّبِّہٖ کَلِمٰتٍ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡہِ» (2/37). Translation: Thus Adam (peace be upon him) learned some words from his Lord, so Allah Almighty accepted his repentance.","«تَلَقّٰی» to learn something through recitation.","to learn","تلقی","2:37-7:115-17:39-20:65-27:6-60:1",6
1921,410,"T","کَلَّبَ","«کَلْب» means dog. And «کَلَّبَ الْکَلْب» means teaching and training a dog to hunt. And «مُکَلِّب» and «کَلَّاب» are terms used for a person who teaches or trains for hunting. Then «کَلَّب» is used not only for training dogs but also for other hunting animals, birds, etc.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَا عَلَّمۡتُمۡ مِّنَ الۡجَوَارِحِ مُکَلِّبِیۡنَ تُعَلِّمُوۡنَہُنَّ» (5/4)\n\nTranslation: And for you is lawful the game that your trained hunting animals catch.","«کَلَّب» To teach and train hunting animals in the art of hunting.","to learn","کلب","5:4",1
1922,411,"H","فَرَعَ","«فَرَعَ» means branch, its opposite is «اصل», which means root. The plural of «فَرَعَ» is «فُرُوْع», meaning (tree) twigs. And Imam Raghib says that anything whose upper part emerges from a root is called «فَرَعُ الشَّجَر» (mufrad). For example, the Quran states:\n«مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً  کَشَجَرَۃٍ  طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی  السَّمَآءِ» (14/24)\nTranslation: The example of a pure word is like that of a pure tree, whose roots are firm in the earth and whose branches reach into the sky.\nThis term is used in both material and spiritual senses. Frooci issues refer to matters that are based upon another matter (the original) and are analogized from it. However, no example of this usage appears in the Quran.","«فَرَعَ» is whatever emerges from a thing apart from its original essence; that is its «فَرَع».","Horn","فرع","14:24",1
1923,411,"B","شُعَب","The plural of «شُعْبَۃ» is «شَعْب», and its meaning essentially encompasses two fundamental aspects: (1) *iftiraq* (separation, i.e., becoming distinct) and (2) *ijma* (gathering, i.e., coming together). However, this is not a case of linguistic opposites; rather, the term applies to anything that, upon further development, divides into multiple parts (m. l). For example, «تَشَعَّبُ النَّھْر» (meaning a river) from which numerous branches flow out, or like the fingers on a hand, and «شَعْبُ» (meaning) a large tribe (manjad).\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنۡطَلِقُوۡۤا  اِلٰی ظِلٍّ  ذِیۡ ثَلٰثِ شُعَبٍ» (77/30)\nTranslation: Towards a shadow that has three branches. (i.e., one that later splits into three parts.)","«شُعْبَہ» to divide something into several parts in such a way that the connection to the original remains intact.","Branch","شعب","77:30",1
1924,411,"B","اَفْنَان","«اَفْنَان» is the plural of «فَنَن», and «فَنَن» means the very thick and long branch of a tree, while «شَجَرَۃٌ فَنَانٌ» means a tree with very thick and long branches (sing. & pl.).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ذَوَاتَاۤ   اَفۡنَانٍ» (55:48)\nTranslation: Both trees have massive branches.","«اَفْنَان» meaning boughs and branches.","Branch","افنان","55:48",1
1925,412,"T","رَوَاح","«رَوَاح» Zawal-e-Aftab, meaning the time after Zuhr (afternoon prayer), begins. «رَوَاح» means the latter part of the day, and its opposite is «غُدُوّ» or «غُدْوَۃ», meaning the morning time (cf. 292). «اَلْغُدُوُّ وَ الرَّوَاح» is used for the coming and going of the first and latter parts of the day.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لِسُلَیۡمٰنَ الرِّیۡحَ غُدُوُّہَا شَہۡرٌ وَّ رَوَاحُہَا شَہۡرٌ» (34/12)\n\nTranslation: And for Solomon, We subjected the wind, blowing vigorously; its journey in the first part of the day was the distance of a month's travel, and similarly in the latter part of the day.","«رَوَاح» refers to the time period from after the sun's decline until sunset.","the Levant (historical Syria)","رواح","34:12",1
1926,412,"T","اَصِیْلًا","The plural of «اَصِیْلًا» is «اٰصَال». «اَصِیْلًا» refers to the time after afternoon, i.e., the evening. Its opposite is «بُکْرَۃ», meaning the time of morning (F L 292).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اذۡکُرِ اسۡمَ  رَبِّکَ بُکۡرَۃً  وَّ اَصِیۡلًا» (76/25)\nTranslation: And glorify the name of your Lord morning and evening.","«اَصِیْلًا» The time after Asr is called.","The Levant","اصیلًا","7:205-13:15-24:36-25:5-33:42-48:9-76:25",7
1927,412,"S","عَشِیًّا","The time of «عَشِی» begins before sunset, and its opposite is «اِشْرَاق»; its opposite «غُدُوّ» also occurs, and «بُکْرَۃ» as well.\n\nNow consider their examples:\n\nExample 1 - The command of Allah the Exalted is:\n«اَلنَّارُ یُعۡرَضُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا غُدُوًّا وَّ عَشِیًّا» (40/46)\nTranslation: They are presented to the Fire morning and evening.\n\nExample 2 - The command of Allah the Exalted is:\n«وَ لَا تَطۡرُدِ الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ بِالۡغَدٰوۃِ  وَ الۡعَشِیِّ  یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ وَجۡہَہٗ» (6/52)\nTranslation: And do not drive away those who invoke their Lord morning and evening, seeking His countenance alone.\n\nExample 3 - The command of Allah the Exalted is:\n«وَ اذۡکُرۡ رَّبَّکَ کَثِیۡرًا وَّ سَبِّحۡ بِالۡعَشِیِّ وَ الۡاِبۡکَارِ » (3/41)\nTranslation: And remember your Lord abundantly and glorify Him morning and evening.\n\nThe time for the Isha prayer, which is specified and fixed, extends from the onset of night's darkness until midnight.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«مِنۡ قَبۡلِ صَلٰوۃِ  الۡفَجۡرِ وَ حِیۡنَ تَضَعُوۡنَ ثِیَابَکُمۡ مِّنَ الظَّہِیۡرَۃِ وَ مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ صَلٰوۃِ الۡعِشَآءِ   ۟ ؕ ثَلٰثُ عَوۡرٰتٍ لَّکُمۡ» (24/58)\nTranslation: [These are] three times of privacy for you: before the dawn prayer, when you put aside your clothing at midday, and after the Isha prayer.\n\nThe term «اَمْسَا ( مسو )» is used for the evening.","«عَشِیًّا» The time for Isha prayer is from after Maghrib until complete darkness.","Syria","عشیًا","3:41-6:52-12:16-18:28-19:11-19:62-24:58-30:18-38:18-38:31-40:46-40:55-43:36-79:46",14
1928,412,"T","اَمْسَاَ","«مَسَا» means the time of evening. And «اَمْسَاَ» means to do evening, to enter the evening, or to do some work in the evening. Its opposite is «اَصْبَحَ». That is, morning, to do morning, to enter the morning, or to do some work in the morning.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَسُبۡحٰنَ اللّٰہِ  حِیۡنَ تُمۡسُوۡنَ وَ حِیۡنَ تُصۡبِحُوۡنَ» (30/17)\nTranslation: So remember Allah when you do evening and when you do morning.","«اَمْسَاَ» meaning to combine.","The Levant (historical Syria region)","امسا","30:17",1
1929,413,"M","عَسٰی","«عَسٰی» is among the verbs of proximity and is static (i.e., a word that is not derived from another word) and is used only for the past tense; it does not occur for the present/future tense. It is employed for predominant hope in desirable matters and for fear in undesirable matters (Manjad).\n\nFor predominant hope in a desirable matter:\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«عَسٰی رَبِّیۡۤ   اَنۡ  یَّہۡدِیَنِیۡ  سَوَآءَ  السَّبِیۡلِ» (28/22)\nTranslation: I hope that my Lord will guide me to the straight path.\n\nAnd for fear in an undesirable matter:\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«فَہَلۡ  عَسَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ تَوَلَّیۡتُمۡ  اَنۡ تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی  الۡاَرۡضِ وَ تُقَطِّعُوۡۤا  اَرۡحَامَکُمۡ» (47/22)\nTranslation: (O hypocrites!) It is not surprising to you that if you attain authority, you will spread corruption in the land and sever your ties of kinship.\n\nNote: Verbs of proximity are those verbs that make the predicate (khabar) akin to a noun (ism).","Hope comes to the aid of the conqueror.","maybe","عسی","2:216-2:246-4:19-4:84-4:99-5:52-7:129-7:185-9:18-9:102-12:21-12:83-17:8-17:51-17:79-18:24-18:40-19:48-27:72-28:9-28:22-28:67-47:22-49:11-60:7-66:5-66:8-68:32",28
1930,413,"P","لَعَلَّ","«لَعَلَّ» This is a particle resembling a verb. It is used only to express a strong possibility.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَا یُدۡرِیۡکَ لَعَلَّ  السَّاعَۃَ   تَکُوۡنُ  قَرِیۡبًا» ( 33/63 )\nTranslation: How do you know? Perhaps the Hour is near.\n\nAnd when it is attributed to Allah the Most High, its meaning becomes that of obligation (necessity).\nFor example: The command of Allah the Most High is:\n«لَا تَدۡرِیۡ  لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ  یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  اَمۡرًا» ( 65/1 )\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will afterward bring about a matter.\n\nNote: (Particles resembling verbs: These are particles that resemble verbs. When they enter a nominal sentence, they put the subject (mubtada') in the accusative case and the predicate (khabar) in the nominative case. There are six of them.) «إن . أن. كان . لكن ، ليت . لعل»","«لَعَلَّ» comes to enable dominance.","Perhaps","لعل","2:21-2:52-2:53-2:56-2:63-2:73-2:150-2:179-2:183-2:185-2:186-2:187-2:189-2:219-2:221-2:242-2:266-3:72-3:103-3:123-3:130-3:132-3:200-5:6-5:35-5:89-5:90-5:100-6:42-6:51-6:65-6:69-6:151-6:152-6:153-6:154-6:155-7:26-7:57-7:63-7:69-7:94-7:130-7:158-7:164-7:168-7:171-7:174-7:176-7:204-8:26-8:45-8:57-9:12-9:122-11:12-12:2-12:46-12:62-13:2-14:25-14:37-16:14-16:15-16:44-16:78-16:81-16:90-18:6-20:44-20:113-20:130-21:13-21:31-21:58-21:61-21:111-22:36-22:77-23:49-23:100-24:1-24:27-24:31-24:56-24:61-26:3-26:40-26:129-27:7-27:46-28:29-28:38-28:43-28:46-28:51-28:73-30:41-30:46-32:3-32:21-33:63-35:12-36:45-36:74-39:27-39:28-40:36-40:67-41:26-42:17-43:3-43:10-43:28-43:48-44:58-45:12-46:27-49:10-51:49-57:17-59:21-62:10-65:1-80:3",125
1931,414,"W","خَمْر","«خَمْر» This word is used for wine. «خَمَرَ» means to cover. And the plural of «خِمَار» is «خُمُر», meaning a veil or dupatta with which one can cover the face, etc. Wine is also called «خَمْر» because it covers and destroys intellect and senses.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّمَا الۡخَمۡرُ وَ الۡمَیۡسِرُ وَ الۡاَنۡصَابُ وَ الۡاَزۡلَامُ رِجۡسٌ مِّنۡ  عَمَلِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (5/90)\nTranslation: Wine, gambling, idols, and divining arrows are all abominations and works of Satan.","«خَمْر» is a general term for all intoxicating drinks that impair reason and senses.","wine","خمر","2:219-5:90-5:91-12:36-12:41-47:15",6
1932,414,"W","مَعِیْن","«مَعَنَ الْمَاءَ» means water flowing slowly and gradually to the surface of the earth, and «مَعَنَ النَّظْر فِی الْاَمْر» means to ponder deeply to the very essence of a matter (munjad). And «مَعِیْن» refers to water that is pleasant-tasting, sweet, and clear/transparent.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» ( 67/30 )\nTranslation: So have you considered if your water were to sink deep into the earth, who then could bring you flowing water?\n\nHowever, in the following verse, the word «کَاْس» (a filled cup) changes the meaning of «مَعِیْن» to mean an intoxicating drink. Such a drink that is pure from the defects of «خَمْر». Because the word «کاس» generally comes for a filled cup and also for wine.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وِلۡدَانٌ مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ - بِاَکۡوَابٍ وَّ اَبَارِیۡقَ  ۬ ۙ وَ کَاۡسٍ مِّنۡ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (18-17 /56)\nTranslation: Young men who will serve them forever, with cups and ewers and a cup from a flowing spring.","«مَعِیْن» a delicious and delightful wine, free from all harm, which will be found in Paradise.","Wine","معین","23:50-37:45-56:18-67:30",4
1933,414,"W","رَحِیْقٍ","«رَحِیْق» meaning pure, clear, and fragrant wine (verse 56) that contains no mixture, impurities, or particles whatsoever.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یُسۡقَوۡنَ مِنۡ  رَّحِیۡقٍ مَّخۡتُوۡمٍ خِتٰمُہٗ  مِسۡکٌ» (83/25,26)\nTranslation: They will be given to drink a cup [of wine] that is pure and clear, sealed with musk.","«رَحِیْق» The finest, most fragrant wine, free from all harm, which will be found in Paradise.","wine","رحیقٍ","83:25",1
1934,415,"T","اِسْتِحْیَاءَ","«حَیِیَ یَحْیٰی حَیٰوۃً» means 'to be alive.' And «حَیَّ یَحَیُّ حَیًّاء» means 'to feel shame' and 'to shame.' Both derive from «اِسْتِحْیَاء» in Form IV (Istif'al). The two meanings—'to leave someone alive' and 'to feel shame from someone'—are both used in the Quran. It is employed in both material and spiritual senses.\n\nExample of material usage: The divine declaration states:\n«فَجَآءَتۡہُ  اِحۡدٰىہُمَا تَمۡشِیۡ عَلَی اسۡتِحۡیَآءٍ» (28/25)\nTranslation: Then one of the two women came walking shyly and hesitantly.\n\nExample of spiritual usage: The divine declaration states:\n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا مَّا بَعُوۡضَۃً فَمَا فَوۡقَہَا» (2/26)\nTranslation: Allah does not feel any hesitation in citing the example of a mosquito or something even smaller.","«اِسْتِحْیَاءَ» meaning to make someone feel ashamed because of modesty.","to be ashamed","استحیاء","2:26-28:25-33:53",3
1935,415,"T","اِسْتِنْکَفَ","«نَکِفَ» means to raise one's nose in arrogance. And «اِسْتَنْکَفَ» means to consider something as a cause of shame and disgrace out of arrogance (منجد). For example, the Holy Quran states: «لَنۡ یَّسۡتَنۡکِفَ الۡمَسِیۡحُ اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ عَبۡدًا لِّلّٰہِ» (4/172) Translation: The Messiah does not deem it disgraceful to be a servant of Allah.","A reprehensible trait is to feel hesitation and shame out of arrogance, and to consider something disgraceful.","to commit shirk","استنکف","4:172-4:173",2
1936,416,"S","بَدَاَ","«بَدَاَ» has two meanings: (1) to initiate something, to begin, to start; and (2) to do something before others. And when it is attributed to Allah Almighty, its meaning is to create for the first time (its opposite is *'aud*, meaning to do the same action again).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَبَدَاَ بِاَوۡعِیَتِہِمۡ قَبۡلَ وِعَآءِ اَخِیۡہِ» (12/76)\nTranslation: Then Yusuf (peace be upon him) began to search the belongings of his brothers before (searching) the belongings of his full brother.\n\nIn this verse, both meanings of «بَدَاَ» are found. One meaning is that the search began with the belongings of the other brothers. The other meaning is that he chose to search the belongings of the other brothers before searching the belongings of his full brother.\n\nFurthermore, the Divine declaration states:\n«اِنَّہٗ  ہُوَ  یُبۡدِئُ وَ یُعِیۡدُ» (85/13)\nTranslation: He it is Who originates the creation, then He will reproduce it.","«بَدَاَ» to begin a task.","Start","بدا","2:117-6:101-7:29-9:13-10:4-10:34-12:76-21:104-27:64-29:19-29:20-30:11-30:27-32:7-34:49-85:13",16
1937,416,"S","طَفِقَ","«طَفِقَ» is an incomplete verb that requires another verb to accompany it (in its basic form). It is used in affirmative (positive) sentences and means to begin.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7:22)\nTranslation: And both (Adam and Eve) began to cover themselves with the leaves of Paradise.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ» (38:33)\nTranslation: So Solomon began to pass his hand over the legs and necks of the horses. (Or: he started passing his hand over them.)\n\nNote: Incomplete verb: It is a verb that does not indicate the completion of an action or make a statement complete until another noun or adjective is added to it besides the subject.","«طَفِقَ» is an incomplete verb, meaning the primary action is actually performed by something else. It combines with that entity to convey the meaning of the initiation of the action.","Start","طفق","7:22-20:121-38:33",3
1938,417,"S","فَرْج","The plural of «فَرْج» is «فُرُوْج», and the concept of spaciousness is inherent in «فَرْج». «فَرَجَ» means to open, make spacious, clear (manjada), and «فَرْج» means the expanse between two things or two parts of one thing. And «فَرْجُ الطَّرِیْق» means the middle part of a path. A crack in a wall is also called «فَرْج», and the space between two legs is also «فَرْج». Then, metaphorically, the word «فَرْج» is also used for private parts (sharamgah). And due to frequent usage, it began to be understood in its literal sense (m.f.). For example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِفُرُوۡجِہِمۡ حٰفِظُوۡنَ» (23/5). Translation: And those who guard their private parts.","the open space (private area) between two things «فَرْج»","State of disgrace","فرج","21:91-23:5-24:30-24:31-33:35-66:12-70:29",7
1939,417,"A","سَوْءَۃَ","«سَوْء ، سُوْء» means every thing that is evil from an intellectual or Shariah perspective or appears ugly to look at. In this sense, if a person's private parts are naked, it is called «سَوْءَۃَ». And the term «سَوْءَۃَ» is not applied only to the private area but also to all parts of the private parts, such as a woman's body and breasts, etc., if they are exposed.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ  قَدۡ  اَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لِبَاسًا یُّوَارِیۡ سَوۡاٰتِکُمۡ وَ رِیۡشًا» (7/26)\nTranslation: O children of Adam! We have bestowed upon you clothing that covers your private parts and serves as adornment for the body.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَاقَا الشَّجَرَۃَ بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا» (7/22)\nTranslation: When they ate from the tree, their private parts became exposed.\n\nThen, in the same sense, the word «سَوْءَۃَ» has also been used for a human corpse, because after some time, if it is not buried, it becomes a repulsive sight.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow that was scratching the ground to show him how to cover the corpse of his brother.","«سَوْءَۃَ» The parts that must be covered, if they are exposed, and every thing whose exposure is disgraceful.","Abode of shame","سوءۃ","5:31-7:20-7:22-7:26-7:27-20:121",6
1940,418,"A","خَلِیْط","«خَلَطَ» means to mix one thing into another, its opposite. «خَلَصَ» means pure, unadulterated, and clear. «اَلْخَلْط» means one who mixes and associates with people. «خَلِیْط» refers to those people whose affair is united. And «اَلْخُلْطَۃ» is called partnership (musharakah). In terminological meanings, «خَلِیْط» means partial partners (shuraka' juz'i), i.e., partners who have some arrangements that are communal and some that are separate. For example, both Zaid and Bakr have separate herds which are their own private property, but for their protection they have rented a shared location, or they pay a shared wage to a herdsman. Such partners «خَلَیْط» are called (according to authentic Hadiths, zakat is due on the shared property of such «خُلَطَاء»).\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ کَثِیۡرًا مِّنَ الۡخُلَطَآءِ لَیَبۡغِیۡ  بَعۡضُہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (38/24)\nTranslation: Most partners transgress against one another.","«خَلِیْط» associate partners, that is, those people whose dealings are unified.","associate","خلیط","9:102-38:24",2
1941,418,"A","شَرِیْک","«شَرِیْک» means a partnership that cannot be separated from one another. Partnership can be material as well as spiritual. The material kind is, for example, when two people are partners in a business and their responsibilities are such that if either one leaves, the business cannot be started or continued. In this same sense, the divine declaration is:\n«وَّ لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  شَرِیۡکٌ فِی الۡمُلۡکِ  وَ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ لَّہٗ  وَلِیٌّ  مِّنَ الذُّلِّ» (17/111)\nTranslation: And there is no partner in His dominion, nor is He weak or in need of a helper.\nAnd the spiritual partnership is like that between a human and an animal in terms of animality. This is an essential partnership. Allah is also pure from this, as is made clear in many verses of the Quran.","«شَرِیْک» one who fully participates in a single task.","associate","شریک","6:163-17:111-25:2",3
1942,418,"A","اَنْدَادًا","«نِدّ» means to intensely detest and flee. And «نَادَّہٗ» means he opposed it (M. Q) and also means to be a partner or associate in an essence or nature (Muf). Thus, «نِدّ» does not imply partnership but rather the status of an adversary or rival. That is, all attributes or some of them are also found in others. Example. (In the dictionary of antonyms) it also means opponent and rival, as well as example and likeness (K. Z).\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَا تَجۡعَلُوۡا لِلّٰہِ اَنۡدَادًا وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ تَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (2/22)\nTranslation: So do not make any partner for Allah, while you know.","The term «نَدّ» refers to one who is a partner, adversary, or counterpart in essence and substance.","associate","اندادًا","2:22-2:165-14:30-34:33-39:8-41:9",6
1943,419,"F","لَھَب","«لَھَب» means the movement and rising of fire, and also means the flames of fire rising (m. l.). Shuala (flame) is used in its well-known meanings and is the common word for flame.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«سَیَصۡلٰی نَارًا ذَاتَ  لَہَبٍ» (111/3)  \nTranslation: Soon he will enter the fire of flames.","«لَھَب» is a common word, meaning the flame of fire.","Flame","لھب","77:31-111:3",2
1944,419,"F","شُوَاظ ۔ نُحَاس","«شُوَاظ» refers to a flame in which there is no mixture of smoke (pure). If there is a mixture of smoke, it is called «نُحَاس». Provided that if the mixture of smoke is less and the fire is more, then since its color becomes like copper, it is called «نُحَاس», meaning copper.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یُرۡسَلُ عَلَیۡکُمَا شُوَاظٌ مِّنۡ نَّارٍ  ۙ وَّ نُحَاسٌ فَلَا  تَنۡتَصِرٰنِ» (55:35)\n\nTranslation: A flame of fire and copper-colored smoke will be poured upon you, and you will not be able to protect yourselves.","«شُوَاظ» A flame without smoke.\n«نُحَاس» A flame with a mixture of smoke, yet the fire predominates.","Flame","شواظ ۔ نحاس","55:35",1
1945,419,"F","مَارِج","«مَارِج» The uppermost, hottest part of a flame that is purified from smoke, the tip of the fire (fl 58).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  خَلَقَ  الۡجَآنَّ مِنۡ مَّارِجٍ  مِّنۡ نَّارٍ» (55/15)\nTranslation: And the jinn were created from the flame of fire.","the hottest part at the tip of the flame «مَارِج»","Flame","مارج","55:15",1
1946,419,"F","شَرَر","«شَرَر» Small fragments that break off and fly away from a large flame. Sparks, sparkles, fiery particles (pl.)\nFor example, in the Quran: «اِنَّہَا  تَرۡمِیۡ  بِشَرَرٍ  کَالۡقَصۡرِ» (77/32) Translation: That (Hell) will hurl up enormous sparks.","«شَرَر» Tiny little sparks breaking off and flying from a flame.","Flame","شرر","77:32",1
1947,420,"D","شَکّ","Two theories being considered equal in the mind when there is no evidence to prefer one over the other. Essentially, the basis of doubt is ignorance or insufficient knowledge (detailed). For example, the Holy Quran states: «اَفِی اللّٰہِ شَکٌّ فَاطِرِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (14/10) Translation: Do you have doubts about Allah, who created the heavens and the earth?","«شَکّ» One cannot give preference to either of the two theories based on inferior knowledge.","doubt","شک","4:157-10:94-10:104-11:62-11:110-14:9-14:10-27:66-34:21-34:54-38:8-40:34-41:45-42:14-44:9",15
1948,420,"D","شَبَّہَ","«شَبَّہَ» means that two or more things are so similar to each other in appearance or characteristics that a correct distinction between them cannot be made, and this occurs in terms of color or attributes (m. l.).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» (4/157)\nTranslation: And they did not kill Jesus, nor did they crucify him, but it appeared so to them. And those who differ therein are full of doubts.\n\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«اِنَّ الۡبَقَرَ تَشٰبَہَ عَلَیۡنَا» (2/70)\nTranslation: Indeed, we have doubts about this cow (it has become dubious to us).","«شَبَّہَ» meaning that two or more things are so similar to each other that one cannot correctly distinguish between them.","Doubt","شبہ","2:25-2:70-2:118-3:7-4:157-6:99-6:141-13:16-39:23",9
1949,420,"D","مِرْیَۃ","The term «مِرْیَۃ» essentially carries two fundamental meanings: (1) the acceptance of a reality or doctrine, and (2) persisting in casting doubt upon that reality. Consequently, this word is also used in the sense of arguing, and such arguments are fundamentally based on these very matters of doubt.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَبِاَیِّ  اٰلَآءِ  رَبِّکَ  تَتَمَارٰی» (53/55)\nTranslation: So, O human, about which of your Lord’s favors will you dispute?\n\nAnd «مِرْیَۃ» refers to the doubts generated by people concerning the truth.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«فَلَا تَکُنۡ فِیۡ مِرۡیَۃٍ  مِّنۡ لِّقَآئِہٖ» (32/23)\nTranslation: So do not remain in doubt about the meeting with your Lord.","«مِرْیَۃ» To cast doubt on an accepted (acknowledged) truth by associating it with speculative or suspicious matters.","Doubt","مریۃ","11:109-22:55-32:23-41:54",4
1950,420,"D","مَرِیْج","«مَرَجَ» means the merging of two theories. And «غُصْنٌ مَّرِیْجٌ» refers to intertwined branches (muf), meaning to be disordered (munjazd) — the matter being mixed up and complicated. And «مَرَجَ» also signifies the coming and going of a thought and restlessness (be-chain) (m. l) — as if this word is a combination of doubt and agitation.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلۡ کَذَّبُوۡا بِالۡحَقِّ لَمَّا جَآءَہُمۡ فَہُمۡ  فِیۡۤ اَمۡرٍ  مَّرِیۡجٍ» (50:5)\nTranslation: When the truth came to them, they denied it; so they became entangled in confusion.","«مَرِیْج» Thoughts alternate—first one, then another, then the first again—leaving one in a state of doubt.","Doubt","مریج","50:5",1
1951,420,"D","لَبْس","«لَبَسَ» means mixing and interference (i.e., one thing joining with another and one being included within the other) (m. l.), that is, to thoroughly blend two things together and to insert one into another. Such as mixing falsehood into truth and blending some truth into falsehood, thereby rendering reality so dubious that one cannot distinguish between truth and falsehood. Those who become entangled in such doubt and suspicion are termed «لَبْس». This term is also employed in contexts of rejection and in rhetorical forms (as per Fiqh 249).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (50/15)\nTranslation: Rather, they are in doubt concerning the new creation.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command proclaims:\n«وَ لَا تَلۡبِسُوا الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» (2/42)\nTranslation: Do not mix truth with falsehood.","«لَبْس» To mix two theories in such a way that one cannot even distinguish between them.","Doubt","لبس","2:42-3:71-6:9-6:65-6:82-6:137-50:15",7
1952,420,"D","رَیْب","«رَیْب» is a doubt that also includes the element of restlessness (disquietude). «رَیْبُ الدَّھْر» denotes the passage of time, the events of time, and «رَیْبُ الْمَنُوْن» signifies the dangers of life (e.g.). «رَیْب» is a doubt that causes disquietude, hesitation, and uneasiness. It is said «دَعْ مَا یُرِیْبَکَ اِلٰی مَا لَا یُرِیْبَکَ», meaning: abandon that which engenders doubt and anxiety in the heart, and choose that in which there is no doubt or anxiety. «رَیْبَۃ» means sorrow and regret. Disturbance (disquietude) (e.g.). For instance, the Quran states: «اِنَّہُمۡ لَفِیۡ شَکٍّ  مِّنۡہُ  مُرِیۡبٍ» (41/45) Translation: They are in such doubt that does not allow them to attain peace. At another place, the Divine Commandment declares: «ذٰلِکَ  الۡکِتٰبُ لَا رَیۡبَ فِیْہِ» (2-2) Translation: This is a book in which there is no doubt (and no danger).","«رَیْب» A doubt that involves agitation, restlessness, and hesitation.","Doubt","ریب","2:2-2:23-3:9-3:25-4:87-6:12-9:45-9:110-10:37-17:99-18:21-22:5-22:7-32:2-40:59-42:7-45:26-45:32",18
1953,421,"F","ھَیْئَۃ","«ھَیْئَت» refers to the initial form and appearance of a thing, whether perceptible (known through one of the five senses) or rational (known through reason) (i.e., whether physically existent or merely mental). And «ھَیْئَۃ» and «ھِیْئَۃ» mean the state, condition, or form of a thing (source: Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَنِّیۡۤ  اَخۡلُقُ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ الطِّیۡنِ کَہَیۡئَۃِ الطَّیۡرِ» (3/49)\nTranslation: I will create for you from clay the form of a bird.","«ھَیْئَت» is called the primordial form and appearance of something.","Form / Appearance (in Islamic/Quranic contexts, often referring to divine manifestation or theophany)","ھیئۃ","3:49-5:110",2
1954,421,"F","شَکْل","«مُشَاکِلَۃ» means to resemble in form and appearance (plural), and ashkāl refers to a complexity in a matter where various intermingling forms appear. And mushkil (difficult) is used for such a complex affair. And «شَکَلَ الْاَمْر» means to be suspect or dubious. And «شَکْل» means resemblance, similarity, likeness, or analogy. Ashkāl also means pearls or silver ornaments that resemble one another. (Source: Manjad)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ اٰخَرُ  مِنۡ شَکۡلِہٖۤ  اَزۡوَاجٌ» (38:58)\nTranslation: And there are many other punishments of a similar kind.","«شَکْل» things that are similar in form and appearance.","Form","شکل","38:58",1
1955,421,"F","صُوْرَت","«صُوْرَت» meaning the external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized and distinguished from other things (detailed). For example: In the Quran: «فِیۡۤ  اَیِّ صُوۡرَۃٍ  مَّا شَآءَ  رَکَّبَکَ» (82/8) Translation: Then Allah, the Exalted, formed you as He willed.","«صُوْرَت» the external features of a material thing by which it can be recognized and distinguished from other things.","Form","صورت","82:8",1
1956,421,"F","تَمْثَال","«تَمْثَال» and «تَمَاثِیْل ، مَثُلَ» mean to adopt the form and shape of another thing and to stand upright. And «مُمَثَّل» is that which is made according to a sample (model). And «تَمَثَّلَ» means to take on the form of someone, to assume someone's likeness (figurative). And «تَمْثَال» means an image, a picture, or a representation of something (figurative).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «اِذۡ قَالَ لِاَبِیۡہِ وَ قَوۡمِہٖ مَا ہٰذِہِ التَّمَاثِیۡلُ  الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ  لَہَا  عٰکِفُوۡنَ» (21/52)\nTranslation: When Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him) said to his father and his people: What are these idols that you sit in seclusion before?","A copy, image, figure, statue, etc., of something original.","Form","تمثال","21:52-34:13",2
1957,421,"F","صَوَّرَ","«صَوَّرَ» meaning to draw a picture; to form a shape (Munjid). This word is generally applied to living things, and forming the shapes of living things is a special attribute of Allah Almighty.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«ہُوَ  الَّذِیۡ یُصَوِّرُکُمۡ  فِی الۡاَرۡحَامِ  کَیۡفَ یَشَآءُ» (3/6)  \nTranslation: He it is Who fashions you in the wombs as He wills.","«صَوَّرَ» meaning to paint a picture, to create a vivid image.","Form (in the sense of divine manifestation or appearance)","صور","3:6-7:11-40:64-64:3",4
1958,421,"O","خَلَّقَ","«خَلَّقَ» The initial design and patterning before the completion of form upon matter.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated: «ثُمَّ مِنۡ مُّضۡغَۃٍ مُّخَلَّقَۃٍ» (22/5) Translation: Then from that plant, whose structure can be both complete and incomplete.","«خَلَّقَ» to create an initial design.","Outward form","خلق","2:21-2:29-2:164-2:228-3:47-3:49-3:59-3:190-3:191-4:1-4:28-4:119-5:17-5:18-5:110-6:1-6:2-6:73-6:94-6:100-6:101-6:102-7:11-7:12-7:54-7:69-7:181-7:185-7:189-7:191-9:36-10:3-10:4-10:5-10:6-10:34-11:7-11:119-13:5-13:16-14:19-14:32-15:26-15:27-15:28-15:33-15:85-16:3-16:4-16:5-16:8-16:17-16:20-16:48-16:70-16:81-17:49-17:51-17:61-17:70-17:98-17:99-18:37-18:48-18:51-19:9-19:67-20:4-20:50-20:55-21:16-21:33-21:37-21:104-22:5-22:73-23:12-23:14-23:17-23:91-23:115-24:45-25:2-25:3-25:49-25:54-25:59-26:78-26:166-26:184-27:60-27:64-28:68-29:17-29:19-29:20-29:44-29:61-30:8-30:11-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:27-30:30-30:40-30:54-31:10-31:11-31:25-31:28-32:4-32:7-32:10-34:7-35:1-35:3-35:11-35:16-35:40-36:36-36:42-36:68-36:71-36:77-36:78-36:79-36:81-37:11-37:96-37:125-37:150-38:27-38:71-38:75-38:76-39:4-39:5-39:6-39:38-39:62-40:57-40:62-40:67-41:9-41:15-41:21-41:37-42:29-42:49-43:9-43:12-43:16-43:19-43:87-44:38-44:39-45:4-45:22-46:3-46:4-46:33-49:13-50:15-50:16-50:38-51:49-51:56-52:35-52:36-53:45-54:49-55:3-55:14-55:15-56:57-56:59-57:4-59:24-64:2-64:3-65:12-67:2-67:3-67:14-70:19-70:39-71:14-71:15-74:11-75:38-76:2-76:28-77:20-78:8-79:27-80:18-80:19-82:7-86:5-86:6-87:2-88:17-89:8-90:4-92:3-95:4-96:1-96:2-113:2",210
1959,421,"F","تَمَثَّلَ","«تَمَثَّلَ» meaning: to change one's form and appearance to become like that of another; to assume a shape.  \nFor example: In the Quran it says:  \n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا» (19/17)  \nTranslation: We sent Our angel to Mary, and he appeared before her in the form of a perfect man.","«تَمَثَّلَ» meaning to take on a form.","Form","تمثل","19:17",1
1960,422,"C","فُطُوْر","«فَطَرَ» means to tear or split something lengthwise (i.e., along its length). And «اِنْفَطَر» means to graze or skim lightly. (Ottoman) Thus, «فُطُوْر» refers to a fissure or cleft whose width is very small compared to its length. Terms: rent, fissure, crack.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَارۡجِعِ  الۡبَصَرَ ۙ ہَلۡ  تَرٰی مِنۡ فُطُوۡرٍ» (67:3)\nTranslation: Raise your gaze (toward the heaven). Do you see any rent or fissure?","«فُطُوْر» is a long fissure that is formed when something splits or tears.","cleft","فطور","67:3",1
1961,422,"C","فُرُوْج","The concept of spaciousness is found in the meaning of «فَرْج», not of splitting or tearing. «فَرَجَ» means to open, to make spacious, to lay open (Munjid). «فَرَجَ» means the expanse and space between two things or between two parts of the same thing. And «فَرَجَ الطَّرِیْق» means the middle part of a path (Munjid, Muf). A hole or fissure, whether congenital or occurring later.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَفَلَمۡ  یَنۡظُرُوۡۤا  اِلَی السَّمَآءِ  فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَیۡفَ بَنَیۡنٰہَا وَ زَیَّنّٰہَا وَ مَا لَہَا مِنۡ فُرُوۡجٍ» ( 50/6 )\nTranslation: Do they not look at the heaven above them – how We have built it and adorned it, and where there are no fissures?","The term «فُرُوْج» refers exclusively to the open space in the middle, whether this cleft is congenital or acquired later.","cleft","فروج","50:6",1
1962,423,"C","مَدِیْنَۃ","«مَدَن» means to reside, to live in a city. And «تَمَدَّن» means to be civilized and refined (manjad). And «مَدِیْنَۃ» refers to every such city where people live together under principles and rules. The plural is «مَدَائِن». For example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی» (36/20). Translation: And from the outer side of the city, a man came running.","«مَدِیْنَۃ» A city where people live by established principles and rules.","City","مدینۃ","7:123-9:101-9:120-12:30-15:67-18:19-18:82-27:48-28:15-28:18-28:20-33:60-36:20-63:8",14
1963,423,"C","بَلَد","«بَلَد» Its plural is «بِلاَد». Every place that has defined boundaries and is inhabited by people (sing.).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«لَاۤ  اُقۡسِمُ  بِہٰذَا الۡبَلَدِ» (90/1)  \nTranslation: I swear by this city (Makkah Al-Mukarramah).","The city whose boundaries have been demarcated.","city","بلد","2:126-7:57-7:58-14:35-16:7-25:49-27:91-34:15-35:9-43:11-50:11-90:1-90:2-95:3",14
1964,423,"C","مِصْر","Its plural form is «مُصُوْر». Meaning: boundary. It is said: So-and-so purchased that house up to its boundaries. And «مِصْر» also means: a taxable tract of land (land from which revenue and tribute are taken), a district (whose boundaries are defined), and according to some, «مِصْر» is a city where spoils of war and charity are distributed (m. l). And according to some, it is a city with a fortified wall (a city with four walls). Moreover, «مِصْر» is also the name of a country:\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is mentioned:\n«اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ» (2/61)\nTranslation: Go out to the city, you will find what you seek.","«مِصْر» a city that has been fortified and has a fortified wall.","City","مصر","2:61-10:87-12:21-12:99-43:51",5
1965,423,"C","دِیَار","«دِیَار» is the plural form of «دَار», and its plural «دُوْر» is also used. «دُوْر» means something being surrounded on all sides, and «دَار» means home, dwelling. And «دَیْر» means the place of residence of a devout worshipper. And «دَار» has a very broad meaning in terms of residence, which can apply to a town, a city, a country, or the entire world. «دَارُ الْحَرْب» means the land of an enemy, «دَارُ الْقَرَار» means the Hereafter, «دَارُ الدُّنْیَا» means the home of this world. The entire world. And «دَارَان» or «دَارَیْن» means this world or the Hereafter.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ اُوۡلٰىہُمَا بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» ( 17/5 )\nTranslation: Then when the first of the two appointed times came, We sent against you some of Our servants, mighty in war, who penetrated the innermost parts of your homes.","The application of «دِیَار» can also extend to a house, a village, a town, a city, a country, and the entire world.","City","دیار","2:84-2:85-2:243-2:246-3:195-4:66-8:47-11:67-11:94-17:5-22:40-33:27-59:2-59:8-60:8-60:9",16
1966,423,"C","قَرْیَۃ","The plural of «قَرْیَۃ» is «قُرٰی». It has two meanings: (1) a town/settlement, and (2) the people living in that town. This word is used in different contexts, both individually and collectively—referring to any settlement, whether large or small, a village or a city. Its application encompasses all of them. However, according to the author of Manjad, its usage is specifically restricted to large towns (Manjad). For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَاَیِّنۡ  مِّنۡ  قَرۡیَۃٍ  عَتَتۡ عَنۡ اَمۡرِ رَبِّہَا وَ رُسُلِہٖ» (65:8)\nTranslation: And many a town (i.e., its inhabitants) rebelled against the command of their Lord and His messengers.\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«تِلۡکَ الۡقُرٰۤی اَہۡلَکۡنٰہُمۡ  لَمَّا ظَلَمُوۡا» (18:59)\nTranslation: Those towns (now in ruins) — when they wronged, We destroyed them completely.","A big city or town and its residents.","City","قریۃ","2:58-2:259-4:75-6:123-7:4-7:82-7:88-7:94-7:161-7:163-10:98-12:82-15:4-16:112-17:16-17:58-18:77-21:6-21:11-21:74-21:95-22:45-22:48-25:40-25:51-26:208-27:34-27:56-28:58-29:31-29:34-34:34-36:13-43:23-43:31-47:13-65:8",37
1967,424,"G","زُجَاجَۃ","«زُجَاجَۃ» means glass (GLASS). Crystal. It is a well-known term. A piece of glass or a glass vessel is used by everyone. «اَلزُّجَاجِی» means a seller of glass. And for example: In the Quran it is: «اَلۡمِصۡبَاحُ فِیۡ زُجَاجَۃٍ ؕ اَلزُّجَاجَۃُ کَاَنَّہَا کَوۡکَبٌ دُرِّیٌّ» (24/35) Translation: That lamp is in a niche. And that niche is (transparent) as if it were a shining star.","«زُجَاجَۃ» meaning glass, crystal, that is transparent.","glass","زجاجۃ","24:35",1
1968,424,"G","قَوَارِیْر","«قَوَارِیْر» refers to «قَارُوْرَہ », meaning any drinking vessel (for beverages) or a container for dates or dried fruits (a glass vessel). In the terminology of physicians, it denotes that glass vessel (bottle) which a doctor or physician uses to examine a patient's urine. And «قَارُوْرَہ» refers to every such glass that has been crafted for a specific purpose, whether it is for viewing faces, or colored for the adornment of buildings, or used in the making of glass vessels. For instance: In the Noble Quran, it is mentioned: «وَ یُطَافُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  بِاٰنِیَۃٍ  مِّنۡ  فِضَّۃٍ وَّ اَکۡوَابٍ کَانَتۡ قَؔوَارِیۡرَا۠» (76/15) Translation: And there will be circulated among them vessels of silver and cups which are of glass.","«قَوَارِیْر» is the glass that is made for a specific purpose. Glass products, even if they are floral and colorful, are included under this definition.","Glass","قواریر","27:44-76:15-76:16",3
1969,425,"C","مَحَّصَ","«مَحَّصَ» To purify something in which adulteration has become entrenched. In material substances, its application is to separate compounds. For example, «مَحَّصَ الذَّھْب» meaning to place gold in a cupel to remove the adulteration and impurities of other metals. And in a spiritual sense, its application is to afflict someone with trials and tribulations to make them pure and clean.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لِیُمَحِّصَ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ یَمۡحَقَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (3/141)\nTranslation: So that Allah may purify the believers [through trials] and destroy the disbelievers.\n\nNote: (A cupel (کٹھالی) is that small cup in which gold and silver are placed and melted.)","«مَحَّصَ» to clean something that is made by combining several things, and where the mixture has become deeply embedded.","Clear","محص","3:141-3:154",2
1970,425,"C","طَھَرَ","Its opposite, «دَنَسَ», means impurity. «طَھَّرَ» means the removal of impurity. And «طَھُوْر» means being free from impurity and filth; clean, clear, and transparent.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً  طَہُوۡرًا» (25/48)\nTranslation: And We sent down pure water from the sky.","«طَھَّرَ» removing physical impurities with water and the like.","Clear","طھر","2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2",26
1971,425,"C","صَفَّا","«صَفّا» To purify things like these from impurities and admixture in a way that is possible without a chemical process. That is, for a mixture—such as purifying honey from wax and pollen, or heating saline water to separate the water and salt.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَنۡہٰرٌ مِّنۡ عَسَلٍ مُّصَفًّی» ( 47/15 )\nTranslation: And there are rivers of pure honey.","Purifying such things from dirt and impurities, which can be separated without chemical processes.","Clear","صفا","47:15",1
1972,425,"C","مَسَحَ","«مَسَحَ» meaning to pass the hand over something to remove the dirt and impurities around it. To wipe, to clean.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَطَفِقَ مَسۡحًۢا بِالسُّوۡقِ وَ الۡاَعۡنَاقِ» (38:33)\nTranslation: So Solomon began to wipe the necks and hindquarters of the horses to clean away the dirt.\n\nAnd in the legal (shar'i) terminology, the meaning of *masah* (wiping) is to apply clean earth or water to a place first, and then to wipe it to make it clean.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا فَامۡسَحُوۡا بِوُجُوۡہِکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡہُ» (5:6)\nTranslation: So seek clean earth, and then wipe your faces and hands with it.","«مَسَحَ» Wiping away dust and dirt, sweeping, and cleaning.","Clear","مسح","4:43-5:6-38:33",3
1973,426,"P","صَبَرَ","«صَبْر» means to endure any hardship or harm that befalls one, and not to display restlessness, impatience, weeping, or lamentation.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَصَبَرُوۡا عَلٰی مَا کُذِّبُوۡا وَ اُوۡذُوۡا حَتّٰۤی اَتٰہُمۡ  نَصۡرُنَا» (6/34)\nTranslation: So those messengers endured the denial and the harm inflicted upon them until Our help came to them.","«صَبْر» to endure when calamities and difficulties strike.","Patience","صبر","2:45-2:61-2:153-2:175-2:250-3:120-3:125-3:186-3:200-4:25-6:34-7:87-7:126-7:128-7:137-8:46-10:109-11:11-11:49-11:115-12:18-12:83-12:90-13:22-13:24-14:12-14:21-16:42-16:96-16:110-16:126-16:127-18:28-18:67-18:68-18:72-18:75-18:78-18:82-20:130-23:111-25:20-25:42-25:75-28:54-29:59-30:60-31:17-32:24-38:6-38:17-40:55-40:77-41:24-41:35-42:43-46:35-49:5-50:39-52:16-52:48-68:48-70:5-73:10-74:7-76:12-76:24-90:17-103:3",69
1974,426,"P","قَانِع","«قاَنِع» means contentment, i.e., being patient with whatever portion one receives (manjīd), and «قَنَاعَت» means being satisfied with a small amount related to life's necessities (muf), being patient and grateful for a little, and not complaining in front of anyone (muf).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَاِذَا وَجَبَتۡ جُنُوۡبُہَا فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36)  \nTranslation: Then when (after being slaughtered) they fall on their sides, eat from them yourselves and also feed the needy who are seated with patience.","«قاَنِع» is one who is content, self-sufficient, patient and grateful, exercising patience and gratitude upon whatever portion comes.","Patience","قانع","22:36",1
1975,427,"P","صُلْح","«اَلْاِصْلَاح» is the opposite of *fasad* (corruption/strife), meaning *bagāṛ* (disorder/damage). And «اَصْلَحَ» means to correct that disorder. And «صُلْح» refers to the mutual agreement between two parties among whom prior corruption, dispute, or fighting exists.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» ( 49/9 )\nTranslation: And if two parties among the believers fall into a fight, then make peace between them.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ اِنِ امۡرَاَۃٌ خَافَتۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡلِہَا نُشُوۡزًا اَوۡ اِعۡرَاضًا فَلَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡہِمَاۤ  اَنۡ یُّصۡلِحَا بَیۡنَہُمَا صُلۡحًا ؕ وَ الصُّلۡحُ  خَیۡرٌ» ( 4/128 )\nTranslation: And if a woman fears from her husband contempt or evasion, there is no blame on them if they arrange a settlement between them—and settlement is best.","«صُلْح» refers to the mutual agreement between the parties after a dispute.","Peace","صلح","2:11-2:160-2:182-2:220-2:224-2:228-3:89-4:16-4:35-4:114-4:128-4:129-4:146-5:39-6:48-6:54-7:35-7:56-7:85-11:88-17:142-7:170-8:1-10:81-11:117-13:23-16:119-21:90-24:5-26:152-27:48-28:19-33:71-40:8-42:40-46:15-47:2-47:5-49:9-49:10",40
1976,427,"T","سَلَم","«اَلسَّلْم» means safety, well-being, and obedience. «سَلَم» means to be saved, to be secure. And «سَلَم» also refers to a peacemaker (muslih) and to such a treaty or peace that occurs even before a fight or dispute arises. To obey.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:\n«فَاِنِ اعۡتَزَلُوۡکُمۡ فَلَمۡ یُقَاتِلُوۡکُمۡ  وَ اَلۡقَوۡا اِلَیۡکُمُ السَّلَمَ ۙ فَمَا جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبِیۡلًا» (4/90)\nTranslation: Then if they withdraw from you and do not fight you and offer you peace, then Allah has not made for you a cause [for fighting] against them.","«سَلَم» such a treaty or peace that is concluded even before any fighting or dispute arises.","Truce","سلم","4:90-4:91-8:61-16:28-16:87-47:35",6
1977,428,"G","کَفِیْل","«کَفَلَ» means to be responsible for someone's sustenance and maintenance as well as their care and guardianship. To act as a surety (in the passive form). The meanings of taking bail for a criminal are also found in «کَفِیْل».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ لَدَیۡہِمۡ  اِذۡ  یُلۡقُوۡنَ اَقۡلَامَہُمۡ اَیُّہُمۡ یَکۡفُلُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/44)\nTranslation: And you were not with them when they cast their pens (as lots) to determine which of them would be the guardian of Maryam.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَ قَدۡ جَعَلۡتُمُ اللّٰہَ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  کَفِیۡلًا» (16/91)\nTranslation: And indeed you have already taken upon yourselves a surety from Allah.","«کَفِیْل» a guarantor who is responsible for sustenance, maintenance, and guardianship.","Guarantor","کفیل","3:37-3:44-16:91-20:40-28:12-38:23",6
1978,428,"G","زَعِیْم","«زُعَامَۃ» meaning leadership, headship, leadership, leader ship, command «زَعِیْم» is the person who is responsible or a guarantor for something on behalf of the government.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«قَالُوۡا نَفۡقِدُ صُوَاعَ  الۡمَلِکِ  وَ لِمَنۡ  جَآءَ بِہٖ  حِمۡلُ  بَعِیۡرٍ  وَّ اَنَا  بِہٖ  زَعِیۡمٌ» (12/72)  \nTranslation: He (the king's cup-bearer) said: We have not found the king's measuring bowl, and he who will bring it (back) will have a camel's load (as reward), and I will be responsible for it (ensuring the reward is given).","The «زَعِیْم»—the guarantor designated by the government to bear responsibility for a matter.","guarantor","زعیم","12:72-68:40",2
1979,429,"P","طَاقَت","«طَاقَت» is a well-known word and its usage is common. It means courage, power (POWER), which is required for any task (capacity).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تُحَمِّلۡنَا مَا لَا طَاقَۃَ لَنَا بِہٖ» (2/286)\nTranslation: O our Lord! Do not impose upon us that which we have no power to bear.","«طَاقَت» is a general term. It denotes the amount of strength required for any task.","Power","طاقت","2:249-2:286",2
1980,429,"P","قُوَّۃ","«قُوَّۃ» means force (zur), referring to the inherent capability and potential found within something (muf). Its opposite is «ضُعْف», which means weakness (kamzori) (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ مَفَاتِحَہٗ  لَتَنُوۡٓاُ بِالۡعُصۡبَۃِ  اُولِی الۡقُوَّۃِ» (28/76)\nTranslation: The keys to that (Qarun's treasure) were carried by a group of strong men with great difficulty.","«قُوَّۃ» the inherent aptitude and capability that exists within something.","Power","قوۃ","2:63-2:93-2:165-7:145-7:171-8:60-9:69-11:52-11:80-16:92-18:39-18:95-19:12-27:33-28:76-28:78-30:9-30:54-35:44-40:21-40:82-41:15-47:13-51:58-81:20-86:10",26
1981,429,"P","مِرَّۃ","«مِرَّۃ» means intensity, the permanent state of something, power, strength. (According to Manjad) intensity and determination (Q. J.) and «ذُوْمِرَّۃ» is an idiom meaning strong and powerful, energetic, greatly forceful. And «مَرِیْر» means a twisted rope (masc.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«عَلَّمَہٗ  شَدِیۡدُ الۡقُوٰی ذُوۡ مِرَّۃٍ ؕ  فَاسۡتَوٰی» (53:5-6)\nTranslation: They were taught by one possessing mighty power (an angel), who is the bearer of strength, so he appeared before them.","«مِرَّۃ» meaning intensity. The permanent state of something. Strength. Firmness.","Power","مرۃ","53:6",1
1982,429,"P","رُکْن","«رُکْن» refers to a member of any community, association, or organization—an individual belonging to a group. It also carries the meaning of pillar and is used in contexts denoting fortress, support, aid, or protection.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«قَالَ لَوۡ اَنَّ لِیۡ بِکُمۡ قُوَّۃً  اَوۡ اٰوِیۡۤ اِلٰی رُکۡنٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ» (11/80)  \nTranslation: (Lut) said, Oh, if only I had the strength to resist you or could take refuge in a mighty fortress!","«رُکْن» A member of a group, community, or organization; an individual belonging to a collective.","Power","رکن","11:80-11:113-17:74",3
1983,429,"P","مَحُلَ","«مَحُل» means to devise an evil scheme against someone with force and severity (Mafhoom, Manjad). As if in the meaning of «مَحْل», two things are found: «قُوَّۃ» and «حِیْلَۃ». That is, to seize and capture someone severely through cunning and planning. And «مَحْل» means: deception, cunning, enmity, severity, famine, severe hunger (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ہُمۡ  یُجَادِلُوۡنَ فِی اللّٰہِ ۚ وَ ہُوَ  شَدِیۡدُ الۡمِحَالِ» (13:13)\nTranslation: And they argue about Allah while He is exceedingly Powerful (Jalandhari). And His grasp is severe (Othmani).","«مَحُل» To plot evil against someone with force and severity.","Power","محل","13:13",1
1984,429,"P","اَطَاق","«اَطَاق» means having the courage and strength for a task. It is a well-known term.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ یُطِیۡقُوۡنَہٗ فِدۡیَۃٌ طَعَامُ مِسۡکِیۡنٍ» (2/184)\nTranslation: And those who have the strength to fast (but do not) should instead feed the needy.","To have power over something.","Power","اطاق","2:184",1
1985,429,"P","اِسْتِطَاعَ","«اِسْتِطَاعَ الْاَمْر» means to possess the power for something, to be worthy (eligible), and to denote the presence of all necessary means and resources required to accomplish a task (muf). Power is confined solely to one's inherent self, whereas ability extends to other means and resources beyond personal strength. For instance, in the context of Hajj, such as financial expenditure, transportation, the safety of the route, and provision for one's family, etc.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لِلّٰہِ عَلَی النَّاسِ حِجُّ الۡبَیۡتِ مَنِ اسۡتَطَاعَ اِلَیۡہِ سَبِیۡلًا» (3/97)\nTranslation: And among the people are those who have the ability to reach it (the House); upon them is the obligation of Hajj for the sake of Allah.\n\nTherefore, «اِسْتِطَاعَ» is understood to mean possessing power and strength, having capability, or being able to undertake something.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَا اسۡطَاعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّظۡہَرُوۡہُ  وَ مَا اسۡتَطَاعُوۡا  لَہٗ  نَقۡبًا» (18/97)\nTranslation: Then they had no power to climb over it, nor could they breach it.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«اِذۡ  قَالَ الۡحَوَارِیُّوۡنَ یٰعِیۡسَی ابۡنَ  مَرۡیَمَ ہَلۡ یَسۡتَطِیۡعُ رَبُّکَ اَنۡ یُّنَزِّلَ عَلَیۡنَا مَآئِدَۃً مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ» (5/112)\nTranslation: And [mention] when the disciples said, O Jesus, son of Mary, can your Lord send down to us a table from the heaven?","«اِسْتِطَاعَ» meaning to possess the strength or power for a task.","Power","استطاع","2:217-2:273-2:282-3:97-4:25-4:98-4:129-5:112-6:35-7:192-7:197-8:60-9:42-10:38-11:13-11:20-11:88-16:73-17:48-17:64-18:41-18:67-18:72-18:75-18:78-18:97-18:101-21:40-21:43-25:9-25:19-26:211-36:50-36:67-36:75-51:45-55:33-58:4-64:16-68:42",40
1986,430,"M","طَرِیْقَۃ","«طَرِیْقَۃ» signifies habit, condition, or religion (mindset). Every such nation and religion is referred to as «طَرِیْق»—that which a person adopts for performing any action, be it good or bad. For example, the Quran states: «وَ یَذۡہَبَا بِطَرِیۡقَتِکُمُ  الۡمُثۡلٰی» (20:63) Translation: And those two (Moses and Aaron) will destroy your cherished religion. At another instance, the Divine command states: «اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ اَمۡثَلُہُمۡ طَرِیۡقَۃً اِنۡ لَّبِثۡتُمۡ اِلَّا یَوۡمًا» (20:104) Translation: Then the one among them who has the best way of life will say, 'You remained only a day.' Thus, in Shariah terminology, طریقہ denotes the customs and habits that people have elevated to the status of religious emblems.","«طَرِیْقَۃ» those customs and traditions which a person comes to regard as religious matters.","Method","طریقۃ","20:63-20:104-72:16",3
1987,430,"P","سُنَّۃ","«سَنَّ» means for something to be in continuous operation and to run its proper course (m. l.). It is used both transitively and intransitively. «جیسے مَنْ سَنَّ سُنَّۃً» refers to whoever institutes a matter (a method, custom, or regulation). When attributed to Allah the Almighty, it signifies the divine law (generally referred to as the law of nature). For example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَّا سُنَّتَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ ۚ فَلَنۡ تَجِدَ لِسُنَّتِ اللّٰہِ تَبۡدِیۡلًا» (35/43) Translation: They do not await except the ways of the former peoples. So you will not find any change in the course of Allah. (Uthmani). And when the word *Sunnah* is mentioned alone, it generally refers to the way established by the Messenger of Allah ﷺ, and its plural is «سُنَن», i.e., the *Sunnah* of the Messenger ﷺ.","«سُنَّۃ» The divine laws that operate throughout the universe, or the method by which branding an ox causes it to start moving.","Path","سنۃ","8:38-15:13-17:77-18:55-33:38-33:62-35:43-40:85-48:23",9
1988,430,"M","اُمَّۃ","«اُمَّۃ» The term *Ummah* is used for a group of people who share the same creed or ideology (plural). Then this term is also applied to that creed or ideology upon which people become united, whether that creed or ideology is correct or incorrect.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا وَجَدۡنَاۤ  اٰبَآءَنَا عَلٰۤی  اُمَّۃٍ  وَّ اِنَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثٰرِہِمۡ  مُّقۡتَدُوۡنَ» ( 43/23 )\nTranslation: Indeed, we found our forefathers upon a certain path, and we are following in their footsteps.","«اُمَّۃ» the ideology or creed of a like-minded community and its adherents.","Method","امۃ","2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18",54
1989,430,"M","شَرِیْعَۃ","«شَرَع» means for something to appear or become manifest by being raised or elevated. «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیْرُ عُنُقَہٗ» The camel raised its neck in such a way that it became distinctly visible (M. L). And «شَرَعَ لِلْقَوْم» means to establish a law for a people. And «شَرِیْعَۃ» is used in the meanings of Islamic law, divine commands, code (manjd), and Islamic Sharia and Islamic laws. And «شَرِیْعَۃ» also means a clear and defined path, but its application is specific to divine commands (Muf). In our view, Imam Raghib's definition or meaning is more correct, i.e., the word Sharia does not mean Islamic law but rather the commands of Allah. Because the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said: The religion (deen) of all the prophets and messengers is one, but the Sharia changes with the times. The status of religion is like that of a father, and the status of Sharia is like that of a mother. He ﷺ said: We prophets have the same father, but different mothers. Thus, religion consists of immutable (unchangeable) divine commands that have remained the same since the creation of Adam, such as belief in the unseen, belief in Allah, His angels, and His books, and the law of reward and punishment, etc., and the commands of prayer, fasting, zakat, and hudud and ta'zirat, etc. The commands of Sharia should be understood like this: the number of prayers, their rak'ahs, and their method of performance. The Sharia of every prophet or messenger who was given a Sharia was different, but the religion remained one.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ جَعَلۡنٰکَ عَلٰی شَرِیۡعَۃٍ  مِّنَ الۡاَمۡرِ» (45:18)\nTranslation: Then We established you [O Muhammad] on a clear path of religion.\nThis verse makes it clear that a separate Sharia was given to you.","«شَرِیْعَۃ» Divine laws that change according to necessity and circumstances.","Method","شریعۃ","5:48-42:13-42:21-45:48",4
1990,430,"M","مِنْھَاج","«نَھَجَ الْاَمْرُ وَ الطَّرِیْق» means a clear path or way (manjīd), and «مِنْھَاج» means a clear methodology (mīfāq), i.e., the procedure for fulfilling religious obligations. This method is also revealed to the prophets by Allah alone, as proven by authentic Hadith that Angel Jibril (peace be upon him) came to the Prophet (peace and blessings be upon him) for two consecutive days to teach the five daily prayers—on the first day at the earliest time and on the second day at the latest time—and clarified that prayer could be performed at any time between these two extremes. This is the *minhāj* (methodology). Thus, the very name «مِنْھَاج» signifies the breadth and clarity of the Shariah (faq l 11).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡکُمۡ شِرۡعَۃً وَّ مِنۡہَاجًا» (5/48)\n\nTranslation: For each of you We have appointed a divine law and a clear way.","«مِنْھَاج» The method of implementing Shariah rulings: clarity and scope.","Method","منھاج","5:48",1
1991,430,"M","مَنْسَکَ","«نَسَکَ» means to become a worshipper, to become an ascetic. And «نَسَکَ لِلّٰہِ» means to sacrifice for the sake of Allah (mankind). The term «مَنْسَک» is more specific than «مِنْھَاج» and refers only to that method which is related to acts of worship.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«لِکُلِّ اُمَّۃٍ جَعَلۡنَا مَنۡسَکًا ہُمۡ نَاسِکُوۡہُ» (22/67)\nTranslation: For every community We have appointed a whole system of worship which they follow.\n\nThe term «مَنَسَک» has generally become specific to the rites and rulings of Hajj and their performance. *Manasik al-Hajj* means the places, rules, and methods of performing the acts of Hajj. And «نُسُک» is the term for the sacrifice offered during the Hajj.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَنۡ کَانَ مِنۡکُمۡ مَّرِیۡضًا اَوۡ بِہٖۤ اَذًی مِّنۡ رَّاۡسِہٖ فَفِدۡیَۃٌ مِّنۡ صِیَامٍ اَوۡ صَدَقَۃٍ اَوۡ نُسُکٍ» (2/196)\nTranslation: Then whoever among you is ill or has an ailment in his head (and must shave his head), he must make an expiation by fasting, or giving charity, or offering a sacrifice.","«مَنْسَک» the acts of worship, and particularly the rites and rulings of Hajj.","Method","منسک","2:128-2:200-22:34-22:67",4
1992,430,"M","شَاکِلَۃ","«شَکَلَ» means to be suspicious or doubtful. And «شَکُلَ الدَّایَۃ» means to tie an animal's legs (the rope used to bind the front and hind legs of an animal) (manjad). And «اَلنَّاسُ اَشْکَالٌ وَّ اُلَّافٌ» means people who are similar to each other and affectionate (mutual resemblance and affection). Thus, in terms of form, two meanings are found: resemblance in appearance (doubt and suspicion) and binding/restriction. And «شَاکِلَۃ» is that specific manner or method which a person adopts based on the inclination or predisposition of their nature. As the Prophet ﷺ said: «کُلٌّ مُّیَسَّرٌ لِّمَا خُلِقَ لَہٗ» meaning: Each person is facilitated what they were created for. Its example should be understood like this: a person prefers open, general charity with the intention that others are also encouraged to do so, and showing off is not intended. But another person prefers to give charity in a way that not even a neighbor hears about it. Now, both these methods are permissible and correct. The action itself is essentially the same, but the manner of its performance differs for each, according to their own personal preference and choice (of what is most suitable). This is «شَاکِلَۃ».\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ کُلٌّ یَّعۡمَلُ عَلٰی شَاکِلَتِہٖ» (17/84)\nTranslation: Say, 'Each person acts according to their own manner.' (Uthmani)","«شَاکِلَۃ» due to someone's individual inclination, their conduct.","method","شاکلۃ","17:84",1
1993,430,"P","مَعْرُوْف","«مَعْرُوْف» means goodness, virtue, and its opposite is «مُنْکَر», which means anything that is disapproved of or forbidden by Sharia, evil, a bad thing, a bad deed. «عُرْف» means to recognize. And *ma'ruf* (customary practice) refers to any practice, local custom, or tradition that is well-known and considered good in society, regardless of whether Sharia provides specific guidance regarding it or not. Examples include sitting respectfully before elders and addressing them with ji or aap (terms of respect). Such practices have no specific ruling in Sharia, but they are indeed good. This is *ma'ruf*.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لِلۡمُطَلَّقٰتِ مَتَاعٌۢ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ» (2/241)\nTranslation: And divorced women must also be provided with maintenance according to the customary practice.","«مَعْرُوْف» meaning goodness and virtue; a custom or tradition that is socially acceptable and not religiously prohibited.","Path","معروف","2:178-2:180-2:228-2:229-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:241-2:263-3:104-3:110-3:114-4:5-4:6-4:8-4:19-4:25-4:114-7:157-9:67-9:71-9:112-22:41-24:53-31:15-31:17-33:6-33:32-47:21-60:12-65:2-65:6",36
1994,430,"M","خُلُق","«خَلْق ، خِلْقَت» refers to a form and appearance that is recognized and understood through sight. «خُلْق» pertains to the inner faculties (i.e., mental and spiritual powers that are not outwardly tangible—the powers of the inner self, intellectual capabilities) and in the sense of habits and traits related to insight (intellect, understanding, consciousness). (Mufradat) «خُلْق» and «خُلُق» mean nature, character, innate disposition (fitrah) or that habit and manner which has become deeply ingrained with one's nature. Its plural is «اَخْلَاق».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنۡ  ہٰذَاۤ   اِلَّا  خُلُقُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (26:137)\nTranslation: These are merely the practices of the former people.","«خُلُق» habits or ways that have become second nature.","Method  \nWay  \nPath  \nSufi order (when referring to a specific spiritual path)","خلق","26:137-68:4",2
1995,431,"C","طَعَنَ","«طَعَنَ» Meaning: to wound with a spear, horn, or any other sharp and pointed object (transitive). Then this word is used concerning a person or to say something about him that pierces like a spear, i.e., to mention someone's flaw in such a way that it becomes extremely offensive (transitive).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ  اِنۡ نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ  مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ عَہۡدِہِمۡ وَ طَعَنُوۡا فِیۡ دِیۡنِکُمۡ  فَقَاتِلُوۡۤا اَئِمَّۃَ الۡکُفۡرِ» ( 9/12 )\nTranslation: If they break their oaths after making a covenant and taunt you about your religion, then fight the leaders of disbelief.","«طَعَنَ» To mention a person's fault or weakness in a manner that pierces them like a thorn.","carping","طعن","4:46-9:12",2
1996,431,"T","لَمَزَ","«لَمَزَ» meaning to find fault or to criticize. To persistently search for someone's faults and for that purpose to speak ill of them (muf) so as to discover some weak point about them. Then to make sarcastic remarks or to deride them. And also meaning to unjustly accuse someone of their actions (faq 39).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَلۡمِزُوۡنَ الۡمُطَّوِّعِیۡنَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ فِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (9/79)\nTranslation: And those who, from among the believers, find fault with those who give charity generously.","«لَمَزَ» is used in all these meanings: to defame, to accuse, to level a charge, to disgrace, to taunt.","taunt","لمز","9:58-9:79-49:11-104:1",4
1997,431,"T","ھَمَزَ","«ھَمَزَ» meaning to backbite, to slander, to engage in malicious talk. And «ھَامَز» meaning a great fault-finder. And «ھَمَّاز» meaning one who finds faults and engages in mockery, insults, and revilement. And «ھَمَزَاتِ الشَّیٰطِیْن» meaning Satan's instigation and whispers. And «ھَامِز» meaning one who commits evil through gestures of the eyes and hands while backbiting. And «ھَمَزَ» meaning gestured with the eye, cut, struck, and backbit. And «ھَمَزَ الْفَرَس» meaning one who applied the spur to the horse.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہَمَّازٍ مَّشَّآءٍۭ  بِنَمِیۡمٍ» (68/11)\nTranslation: One who makes sarcastic gestures and goes about spreading malicious whispers.","To employ sarcasm through indirect allusion.","taunt","ھمز","68:11-104:1",2
1998,432,"C","طَوَّقَ","«طَوَّقَ» refers to anything that has assumed a circular shape (M. L) and also means a neck ornament. Any encircling object. And its plural is «اَطْوَاق». (Manjad) Thus, tauq means a neck collar, a neck ornament, a neck noose. An iron ring placed around the neck, which can be used by anyone, and «اِطَّوَّقَ الْحَیَّۃ» means to coil like a snake. And «طَوَّقَ» means to put a collar on someone (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«سَیُطَوَّقُوۡنَ مَا بَخِلُوۡا بِہٖ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3/180)\nTranslation: The wealth in which they hoard will be made into a collar and hung around their necks on the Day of Judgment.","«طَوَّقَ» a necklace, a neck ornament, a neck pendant, or an iron bangle worn around the neck; all of these can be used by everyone.","collar","طوق","3:180",1
1999,432,"O","غُلّ","«غُلّ» is its plural. «اَغْلَال». This word is more common than 'collar'. «غُلّ» refers to anything used to bind a person's limbs and secure them in place (muf), and its application includes handcuffs, chains, and collars. «غَلَّ» means 'to put on handcuffs or a collar' (manjada).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ  فَغُلُّوۡہُ ثُمَّ  الۡجَحِیۡمَ  صَلُّوۡہُ» (69:30-31)\nTranslation: (It will be commanded,) 'Seize him and fetter him. Then throw him into the Blazing Fire.'","«غُلّ» meaning to put on handcuffs or a chain.","Orbit","غل","5:64-7:157-12:23-13:5-17:29-34:33-36:8-40:71-76:4",9
2000,433,"A","طَمَعَ","«طَمَعَ» refers to the arising of strong hope in the heart for something (e.g., to hold strong hope).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَّ مَہَّدۡتُّ لَہٗ  تَمۡہِیۡدًا ثُمَّ  یَطۡمَعُ اَنۡ اَزِیۡدَ» (74:14,15)  \nTranslation: And I have granted him abundance in every way. Yet he desires that I give even more.","To harbor a strong hope in the heart for something.","Avarice","طمع","2:75-5:84-7:46-7:56-13:12-26:51-26:82-30:24-32:16-33:32-70:38-74:15",12
2001,433,"G","حِرْص","«حِرْص» refers to intense desire or greed for something, whether it is for one's own benefit or for the benefit of another. (Synonym: Covetousness). For example, the Quran states:\n«اِنۡ تَحۡرِصۡ عَلٰی ہُدٰىہُمۡ فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ یُّضِلُّ» (16:37)\nTranslation: O Prophet, if you are eager for these people to be guided, then know that Allah does not guide those whom He leaves astray due to their obstinacy, and they will have no helper.","When greed or desire for something intensifies, it is called «حِرْص».","Greed","حرص","2:96-4:129-9:128-12:103-16:37",5
2002,433,"G","شُحّ","«شُحَّ» means to be stingy and greedy. And «اَلشِّیْح» and «اَلشِّحَاح» mean miserly, greedy (intense). As if «شَحَّ» encompasses two traits simultaneously: (1) the greed for acquiring wealth, and (2) stinginess, miserliness in spending it. And this is the worst characteristic (elaborated).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  ذَہَبَ الۡخَوۡفُ سَلَقُوۡکُمۡ بِاَلۡسِنَۃٍ حِدَادٍ  اَشِحَّۃً عَلَی الۡخَیۡرِ» (33/19)\nTranslation: Then when the danger is past, they speak to you with sharp tongues in their greed for wealth.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّوۡقَ شُحَّ نَفۡسِہٖ  فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ  الۡمُفۡلِحُوۡنَ» (59/9)\nTranslation: And whoever is saved from his own greed, it is they who will be successful.","«شُحَّ» When greed for wealth is accompanied by an increase in stinginess.","Greed","شح","4:128-33:19-59:9-64:16",4
2003,434,"P","عَبَرَ","The fundamental meaning of «عَبَرَ» is to cross through water, whether by swimming or by means of a mount or a bridge. And «عَبْرُ النَّھْر» refers to the riverbank from which one can descend to cross the river. And «عَبَرَ الْعَیْن» means the flowing of tears. And «اَلْعَبَرَات» (plural) means tears (singular). Subsequently, its application expanded to encompass any path, whether it contains water or not.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4:43). Translation: And do not approach prayer while in a state of janabah until you have bathed, except for the traveler on the road who, if he cannot find water, may perform tayammum for prayer.","The term «عَبَرَ» is used exclusively for traversing a path, particularly water. The term «قَطَعَ» is general, employed for settling matters and crossing land parcels (such as land, agricultural fields, farms, etc.).","Path","عبر","4:43",1
2004,434,"T","قَطَعَ","The basic meaning of «قَطَعَ» is to cut and separate. And «قَطَعَ النَّھْر» means to cross a river. «قَطَعَ السَّبِیْل» means banditry (i.e., robbing travelers). And «قَطَعَ الْوَادِی» means to traverse a valley. And «قَطَعَ الْاَمْر» means to program something in order to complete a task. Thus, this word is also more common than «عَبَرَ» in the meanings of 'to determine a path'.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ لَا یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ وَادِیًا اِلَّا کُتِبَ لَہُمۡ» (9/121)\nTranslation: And they do not traverse any valley, but it is recorded in their record of deeds.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty states:\n«مَا کُنۡتُ قَاطِعَۃً  اَمۡرًا حَتّٰی تَشۡہَدُوۡنِ» (27/32)\nTranslation: I do not decide any matter until you are present.","The basic meaning of «قَطَعَ» is to cut and to separate.","the Straight Path","قطع","2:27-3:127-5:38-6:45-7:72-8:7-9:121-13:25-22:15-29:29-59:5-69:46",12
2005,435,"M","ظَھَرَ","«ظَھْر» means the back or the exterior part of anything that can be seen with the eyes, and its opposite is «بَطَن», which means the belly or the inner part of anything that cannot be seen with the eyes (muf). And «ظَھَرَ» means for something to become visible, to manifest, to appear, and to prevail.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ اَیۡدِی  النَّاسِ» (30/41)\nTranslation: Because of the (evil) deeds of people, corruption has appeared in the land and sea.\n\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor example: Allah, the Most High, says:\n«قُلۡ  اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ رَبِّیَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ مَا ظَہَرَ  مِنۡہَا وَ  مَا بَطَنَ» (7/33)\nTranslation: Say, My Lord has forbidden only indecent acts, whether they are committed openly or in secret.","«ظَھَرَ» To appear in such a way that it can be seen with the eyes. This term is general.","Manifest","ظھر","2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26",27
2006,435,"A","جَھَرَ","«جَھَرَ» is to do something in such a manner that others come to know of it. Its opposite is «اَسرَّ», which means to conceal. (Mu‘jam)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذۡ قُلۡتُمۡ یٰمُوۡسٰی لَنۡ نُّؤۡمِنَ لَکَ حَتّٰی نَرَی اللّٰہَ جَہۡرَۃً» (2:55)\nTranslation: And [recall] when you said, O Moses, we will never believe you until we see Allah outright.\n\nHowever, this term is generally used for making the voice apparent and for announcement (m. l.). *Jahri* prayer is that in which the Imam recites the Quran aloud, i.e., the prayers of Fajr, Maghrib, and Isha. And *sirri* is that in which the Imam also recites in such a low voice that others cannot hear it. «جَھَرَ» is to say something in such a way that others hear it (m. q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا یُحِبُّ اللّٰہُ  الۡجَہۡرَ  بِالسُّوۡٓءِ مِنَ الۡقَوۡلِ اِلَّا مَنۡ ظُلِمَ» (4:148)\nTranslation: Allah does not like the public utterance of evil except by one who has been wronged.","To announce something in such a manner, or to perform an action in such a way that others become aware of it.","Apparent","جھر","2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7",14
2007,435,"A","بَدَا","«بَدَا» meaning that something becomes manifest or evident in a prominent manner, and no intention or design of anyone is involved in it. (Ref. 237)  \nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:  \n«بَلۡ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مَّا کَانُوۡا یُخۡفُوۡنَ مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ» (6/28)  \nTranslation: Rather, all that they used to conceal before has become manifest.  \n\nOn another occasion, the divine command of Allah, the Most High, is:  \n«بَدَتۡ لَہُمَا سَوۡاٰتُہُمَا وَ طَفِقَا یَخۡصِفٰنِ عَلَیۡہِمَا مِنۡ وَّرَقِ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (7/22)  \nTranslation: So when the private parts of both of them (Adam and Eve) became apparent, they began to cover themselves with the leaves of Paradise.  \n\nThen this word is also used in a spiritual sense. For example, the divine command is:  \n«ثُمَّ بَدَا لَہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَا رَاَوُا الۡاٰیٰتِ لَیَسۡجُنُنَّہٗ حَتّٰی حِیۡنٍ» (12/35)  \nTranslation: Even after seeing these signs, it occurred to those people in their minds to imprison Joseph (peace be upon him) for a while.","«بَدَا» Something becoming apparent without intention, which one tries to conceal.","Apparent","بدا","3:118-6:28-7:22-12:35-20:121-39:47-39:48-45:33-60:4",9
2008,435,"M","عَثَرَ","«عَثَرَ» means 'to slip and fall' (metaphorically). The usage of «عَثَرَ» in the sense of something becoming apparent will occur when a person, while attempting to hide something by lying, accidentally utters a truth from their mouth, thereby revealing the reality.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ عُثِرَ عَلٰۤی اَنَّہُمَا اسۡتَحَقَّاۤ اِثۡمًا» (5:107)\nTranslation: Then if it becomes known that both of them have committed sin (by lying).","In the course of conversation, the actual truth gets revealed.","manifest","عثر","5:107-18:21",2
2009,435,"A","تَبَیَّنَ ، اِسْتِبَانَ","«بَانَ» means to appear separate and distinct from something else, and to be clear (m.l.). Thus, its meaning encompasses three concepts: (1) افتراق (i.e., separation), (2) بُعْد (i.e., distance), (3) وُضُوح (i.e., luminous, apparent, and clear) (m.l.). And «تَبَیَّن» is also used in these same meanings.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is stated: «قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2/256). Translation: Guidance (clearly manifest and) has become distinct from misguidance.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states: «وَ لِتَسۡتَبِیۡنَ سَبِیۡلُ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (6/55). Translation: And so that the path of the sinners may become clear.","«تَبَیَّنَ» meaning that something is distinct and clearly apparent from something else.  \n«اِسْتِبَانَ» a statement through which meanings become clear.","apparent","تبین ، استبان","2:109-2:187-2:256-2:259-3:187-4:115-6:55-8:6-9:43-9:113-9:114-14:45-16:44-16:64-29:38-34:14-37:117-41:53-47:25-47:32",20
2010,435,"A","حَصْحَص","When a matter remains concealed due to some pressure and then becomes manifest after the pressure is lifted, the word «حَصْحَص» will be used.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ الۡعَزِیۡزِ الۡئٰنَ حَصۡحَصَ الۡحَقُّ ۫ اَنَا رَاوَدۡتُّہٗ عَنۡ  نَّفۡسِہٖ» (12/51)\n\nTranslation: The wife of the Aziz of Egypt said, Now the truth has become manifest and clear. I had indeed tried to seduce Yusuf (peace be upon him).","«حَصْحَص» such a matter that remains concealed due to some pressure and becomes apparent once that pressure is lifted.","Apparent","حصحص","12:51",1
2011,435,"E","تَجَّلّٰی","«تَجَّلّٰٰی» the clear and beautiful manifestation of something (see details under 'to be radiant')\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا تَجَلّٰی رَبُّہٗ  لِلۡجَبَلِ جَعَلَہٗ  دَکًّا» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when his Lord manifested on the mountain, He shattered it by His radiance.","the appearance or manifestation of something bright and beautiful","Evident","تجلی","7:143-7:187-91:3-92:2",4
2012,435,"A","شُرَّعًا","«شَرَعَ» meaning to come into view or become apparent by rising or protruding. It is said «شَرَعَ الْبَعِیْرُ عُنُقَہٗ», i.e., the camel raised its neck in such a way that it became distinctly visible. (M L)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِذۡ تَاۡتِیۡہِمۡ حِیۡتَانُہُمۡ یَوۡمَ سَبۡتِہِمۡ شُرَّعًا» (7/163)\nTranslation: While on their Sabbath, their fish would come into view prominently before them.","«شُرَّعًا» to emerge.","Apparent","شرعًا","7:163",1
2013,435,"E","اَظْھَرَ","«اَظْھَرَ» meaning to manifest. Very clear, extremely, and very obvious.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«عٰلِمُ الۡغَیۡبِ فَلَا یُظۡہِرُ عَلٰی غَیۡبِہٖۤ اَحَدًا» (72/26)  \nTranslation: He does not reveal His unseen to anyone.","to manifest the meaning of «اَظْھَرَ»","Evident (in Islamic contexts, often contrasted with باطن/inner)","اظھر","66:3-72:26",2
2014,435,"M","اَبْدَا","«اَبْدَا» meaning to manifest/reveal.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَعۡلَمُ مَا تُبۡدُوۡنَ وَ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَکۡتُمُوۡنَ» (2/33)\nTranslation: And I know very well what you reveal and what you conceal.","«اَبْدَا» meaning to explain.","Manifest","ابدا","2:33-2:271-2:284-3:29-3:154-4:149-5:99-5:101-6:91-7:20-12:77-24:29-24:31-28:10-33:37-33:54",16
2015,435,"A","اَعْثَرَ","«اَعْثَرَ» meaning to make clear, to inform, to make aware.\nFor example: In the Quran, it states:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ اَعۡثَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ لِیَعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّ وَعۡدَ اللّٰہِ حَقٌّ» (18/21)\nTranslation: And thus We made it clear to them so that they may know that Allah's promise is true.","«اَعْثَرَ» meaning to make evident, to acquaint, to inform.","Apparent","اعثر","18:21",1
2016,435,"E","جَھَرَ","«جَھَرَ» meaning: to manifest.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَسِرُّوۡا  قَوۡلَکُمۡ  اَوِ اجۡہَرُوۡا بِہٖ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  عَلِیۡمٌۢ  بِذَاتِ الصُّدُوۡرِ» ( 67/13 )\nTranslation: Whether you keep your speech secret or reveal it, He is fully aware of what is in the hearts.","«جَھَرَ» meaning to show.","Evident","جھر","2:55-4:148-4:153-6:3-6:47-7:205-13:10-16:75-17:110-20:7-21:110-49:2-67:13-87:7",14
2017,435,"M","اَعْلَنَ","«اَعْلَنَ» means 'to manifest' or 'to make evident'. Its opposite is «اَسَرَّ». Its usage is for expressing meanings, i.e., for making something evident; it is very rarely used for physical objects (mujarrad) and does not necessarily require a loud voice (faq lam 237).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ یَعۡلَمُ  مَا تُسِرُّوۡنَ وَ مَا  تُعۡلِنُوۡنَ» (16/19)\nTranslation: And Allah knows what you conceal and what you manifest.\n\nFor 'manifest', the words «ظَاھِر ، عَلَانِیَۃ» and «شُرَّعًا» also appear. The details have been discussed above.","«اَعْلَنَ» meaning to manifest.","Manifest","اعلن","2:77-2:274-11:5-13:22-14:31-14:38-16:19-16:23-27:25-27:74-28:69-35:29-36:76-60:1-64:4-71:9",16
2018,436,"H","عَجَزَ","«عِجْز» is the state of being incapable of performing an action, lacking the ability or strength to carry it out (see 214), and its opposite is «عِجْز» (power/ability).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰوَیۡلَتٰۤی اَعَجَزۡتُ اَنۡ  اَکُوۡنَ مِثۡلَ  ہٰذَا الۡغُرَابِ» (5:31)\nTranslation: He said, Alas! How could I not have been like this crow and buried the corpse?","To be incapable of doing anything.","Helpless","عجز","5:31-6:134-8:59-9:2-9:3-10:53-11:20-11:33-16:46-24:57-29:22-35:44-39:51-42:31-46:32-72:12",16
2019,436,"H","عَیَّ","«عَیَّ» means to become exhausted while working and be unable to complete it, or to lack the strength to repeat the same work, or to be unable to do it properly (Munjid). And «دَاءٌ عِیَاءٌ» refers to an incurable disease (Muf). «عَیَاءُ» is less than incapacity (Munjid), because previously the capacity to work was present.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اَفَعَیِیۡنَا بِالۡخَلۡقِ الۡاَوَّلِ ؕ بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (50/15)  \nTranslation: Did We become weary by creating the first time? (No,) but these people are in doubt about the new creation.","«عَیَّ» unable to continue or restart work due to fatigue.","Helpless","عی","46:33-50:15",2
2020,436,"P","اِسْتَکَان فلَانٌ","«اِسْتَکَان فلَانٌ» meaning: So-and-so expressed humility. It is as if he stopped (muf) and was overwhelmed in confrontation. And meaning: to act humbly. To be obedient (submissive) (manjada).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَمَا وَہَنُوۡا لِمَاۤ اَصَابَہُمۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ مَا ضَعُفُوۡا وَ مَا اسۡتَکَانُوۡا» (3/146)\nTranslation: So whatever hardships befell them in the way of Allah, they did not lose heart nor were they overwhelmed by the disbelievers.","«اِسْتَکَان» to be humbled in competition and to manifest humility.","Powerless","استکان فلان","3:146-23:76",2
2021,437,"U","اَخْبَتَ","«خَبْت» refers to low-lying and soft ground. And «اَخْبَتَ الرَّجُل» means the intention of a person to go to such soft ground or to descend there. Afterwards, this word began to be used in the meanings of gentleness and humility (مف), meaning to turn to Allah with tranquility and contentment (فق 208).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ اَخۡبَتُوۡۤا اِلٰی رَبِّہِمۡ ۙ اُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡجَنَّۃِ» (11/23)\nTranslation: Those who believe and do righteous deeds and humble themselves before their Lord – it is they who will be the companions of Paradise.","Softness and humility of the heart (one who practices humility).","utter dependence on Allah","اخبت","11:23-17:97-22:34-22:54",4
2022,437,"H","خَشَعَ","«خُشُوْع» This refers to fear whose effect extends from the heart to the limbs and faculties, causing the eyes and voice to become subdued. (See details under to fear). Hence, this term is used in both senses: to fear and to be humble. The outward indication of the heart's tenderness is that the eyes and voice are lowered. For example, the Quran states:\n\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡ اَہۡلِ  الۡکِتٰبِ لَمَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنُ بِاللّٰہِ وَ مَاۤ اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡکُمۡ وَ مَاۤ  اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡہِمۡ خٰشِعِیۡنَ  لِلّٰہِ» (3/199)\n\nTranslation: And among the People of the Book there are those who believe in Allah and in what has been revealed to you, and in what was revealed to them, and they humble themselves before Allah.","Adopting humility out of the fear of God.","humility","خشع","2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2",15
2023,437,"H","خَضَعَ","«خَضَعَ» means to be obedient and compliant. «خُضُوْع» means submissive, obedient, adherent to commands, subordinate, very humble (sing.). And «خَاضِع» means humble. And «رَجُلٌ خَضِیْعٌ» refers to a person who is unconcerned with disgrace (sing. and pl.). In khudāʿ, the concept of humility is prominent, whereas in khushūʿ, fear and its effects on limbs and faculties are evident.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِنۡ نَّشَاۡ نُنَزِّلۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اٰیَۃً فَظَلَّتۡ اَعۡنَاقُہُمۡ  لَہَا خٰضِعِیۡنَ» (26/4) Translation: If We willed, We could send down a sign to them from the heaven, and then their necks would bow before it.","«خَضَعَ» meaning to be obedient and compliant to someone.","Humility","خضع","26:4",1
2024,437,"H","تَضَرَّعَ","«تَضَرُّع» means to be humble. To approach quietly (in a state of humility). Its meaning encompasses both the attributes of *khushoo'* (reverence) and *khudoo'* (submissiveness). When the heart's softness, tenderness, and sense of helplessness and humility increase, the word «تَضَرُّع» is used. It means to whimper, i.e., to cry softly and quietly before Allah, expressing one's humility and lowliness.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَوۡلَاۤ  اِذۡ جَآءَہُمۡ بَاۡسُنَا تَضَرَّعُوۡا وَ لٰکِنۡ  قَسَتۡ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ» (6:43)\nTranslation: Then why did they not humbly supplicate when Our punishment came to them? But their hearts had become hard.","The collective term for khushu' and khudhu' refers to the state where the heart's softness, tenderness, and humility intensify, at which point the word «تَضَرُّع» is employed.","Humility (before God)","تضرع","6:42-6:43-6:63-7:55-7:205-23:76",6
2025,438,"T","عَالِمْ","«عَالِم» means one who possesses knowledge or one who understands the reality of a thing. It is a well-known and commonly used word. Its plural is «عُلَمَاء». «عَلَّام» and «عَلِیْم» are forms of emphasis (exaggeration). «عَلَّام» means one who possesses exceedingly abundant knowledge, and «عَلِیْم» means the Knower of all things.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّمَا یَخۡشَی اللّٰہَ مِنۡ عِبَادِہِ  الۡعُلَمٰٓؤُا» (35/28)\nTranslation: Among the servants of Allah, only those who have knowledge fear Him.","«عَالِم» is the knower, the possessor of knowledge—common, whether educated or uneducated.","This world","عالم","6:73-9:94-9:105-13:9-21:51-21:81-23:92-26:197-29:43-30:22-32:6-34:3-35:28-35:38-39:46-59:22-62:8-64:18-72:26",19
2026,438,"W","اَحْبَار","«اَحْبَار» refers to «حِبْر» and «حَبْر». It means ink as well, and it also refers to the written script—that which is written is also «حِبْر», such as (the pen, ink, writing instrument, etc.). And whatever is written is also «حِبْر». The terms «حِبْر» and «حَبْر» are also used for the writer and the reader. And «اَحْبَار» also refers to those who read and write, or the literate people (i.e., those who read and write). The application of «اَحْبَار» in the Quran is upon both the literate people of the Jews and the Christians.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِتَّخَذُوۡۤا اَحۡبَارَہُمۡ وَ رُہۡبَانَہُمۡ اَرۡبَابًا مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (9:31)\nTranslation: They have taken their rabbis and their monks as lords besides Allah.","«اَحْبَار» the educated and the literati.","world","احبار","5:44-5:63-9:31-9:34",4
2027,438,"W","قِسِّیْسِیْن","«قَسَّی الشَّیْ» means to seek or search for something. And «قَسِیْسَۃٌ» means to become a monk or a priest (source: Minj). «قِسِّیْسِیْن» is the plural of «قَسُّ». It means Christian teachers or priests. The rank of «قَسُّ» is between «اُسْقُف» and «شَمَّاس» (source: Minj).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَتَجِدَنَّ  اَقۡرَبَہُمۡ مَّوَدَّۃً  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوا الَّذِیۡنَ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا نَصٰرٰی ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّ مِنۡہُمۡ قِسِّیۡسِیۡنَ وَ رُہۡبَانًا» (5:82)\nTranslation: And you will find, in terms of friendship, those who claim to be Christians to be the closest to the believers. That is because among them are scholars and monks.\n\nNote: «اُسْقُف» is a high priest, the religious leader of the Christians. «شَمَّاس» is a servant of the church whose rank is lower than that of a priest.","«قِسِّیْسِیْن» Christian religious teachers and instructors.","World","قسیسین","5:82",1
2028,439,"W","صَوَامِع","«صَوَامِع» is the plural of «صَوْمِعَہ». It means khanqah, i.e., places of worship for spiritual guides.","«صَوَامِع» monasteries and churches.","Worship","صوامع","22:40",1
2029,439,"W","بِیَعٌ","The term «بِیَعٌ» refers to the Christian place of worship known as «بیعۃ».","«بِیَعٌ» the Christians' place of worship.","Worship","بیع","22:40",1
2030,439,"W","صَلَوٰت","«صَلَوٰت» is the plural form of «صَلَاۃ». The synagogues of the Jews. The synagogues of the Jews are also called «کَنَائِس», which is the plural of «کَنِیْسَہ» (see 275). However, for the Jewish place of worship, the Quran has used the term «صَلٰوۃ» instead of «کَنِیْسَہ», which is the well-known form for worship.","«صَلَوٰت» Jewish place of worship.","Worship","صلوت","22:40",1
2031,439,"W","مَسَاجِد","«مَسَاجِد» is a collective noun meaning 'place of prostration'. This same word is used for the places of worship of Muslims.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ وَّ صَلَوٰتٌ وَّ مَسٰجِدُ یُذۡکَرُ فِیۡہَا اسۡمُ اللّٰہِ کَثِیۡرًا» (22/40)  \nTranslation: And if Allah did not check one set of people by means of another, monasteries, churches, synagogues, and mosques—in which the name of Allah is commemorated in abundant measure—would surely have been pulled down.","«مَسَاجِد» Muslim place of worship.","Worship","مساجد","2:114-2:187-9:17-9:18-22:40-72:18",6
2032,440,"P","عَذَاب","«عَذَبَ الرَّجُل» meaning he abandoned food and sleep due to extreme thirst. And a person who abandons food and sleep in this manner is called «عَاذِبٌ و عَذُوْبٌ». And «عَذَاب» means to cause severe hardship—this hardship may be through physical punishment or mental. And the meaning of 'ta'dhib' (عذاب) is to flog. And according to some, it only means to beat or to punish.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ ۢ  ۬ ۙ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡذِبُوۡنَ» (2/10)\nTranslation: And a painful punishment will be theirs because of their lying.","«عَذَاب» pain, punishment, and recompense for evil deeds. It is common.","Punishment","عذاب","2:7-2:10-2:49-2:85-2:86-2:90-2:96-2:104-2:114-2:126-2:162-2:165-2:166-2:174-2:175-2:178-2:201-3:4-3:16-3:21-3:56-3:77-3:88-3:91-3:105-3:106-3:176-3:177-3:178-3:181-3:188-3:191-4:14-4:18-4:25-4:37-4:56-4:93-4:102-4:138-4:147-4:151-4:161-4:173-5:33-5:36-5:37-5:41-5:73-5:80-5:94-5:115-6:15-6:30-6:40-6:47-6:49-6:65-6:70-6:93-6:124-6:157-7:38-7:39-7:59-7:73-7:141-7:156-7:164-7:165-7:167-8:14-8:32-8:35-8:50-8:68-9:3-9:34-9:39-9:52-9:61-9:68-9:74-9:79-9:90-9:101-10:4-10:15-10:50-10:52-10:54-10:70-10:88-10:97-10:98-11:3-11:8-11:20-11:26-11:39-11:48-11:58-11:64-11:76-11:84-11:93-11:103-12:25-12:107-13:34-14:2-14:6-14:7-14:17-14:21-14:22-14:44-15:50-16:26-16:45-16:63-16:85-16:88-16:94-16:104-16:106-16:113-16:117-17:10-17:57-17:58-18:55-18:58-18:87-19:45-19:75-19:79-20:48-20:61-20:71-20:127-20:134-21:46-22:2-22:4-22:9-22:18-22:22-22:25-22:47-22:55-22:57-23:64-23:76-23:77-24:2-24:8-24:11-24:14-24:19-24:23-24:63-25:19-25:37-25:42-25:65-25:69-26:135-26:156-26:158-26:189-26:201-26:204-27:5-27:21-28:64-29:10-29:23-29:29-29:53-29:54-29:55-30:16-31:6-31:7-31:21-31:24-32:14-32:20-32:21-33:8-33:30-33:57-33:68-34:5-34:8-34:12-34:14-34:33-34:38-34:42-34:46-35:7-35:10-35:36-36:18-37:9-37:33-37:38-37:176-38:8-38:26-38:41-38:61-39:13-39:19-39:24-39:25-39:26-39:40-39:47-39:54-39:55-39:58-39:71-40:7-40:45-40:46-40:49-41:16-41:17-41:27-41:50-42:16-42:21-42:26-42:42-42:44-42:45-43:39-43:48-43:50-43:65-43:74-44:11-44:12-44:15-44:30-44:48-44:56-45:8-45:9-45:10-45:11-46:20-46:21-46:24-46:31-46:34-48:16-48:17-48:25-50:26-51:37-52:7-52:18-52:27-52:47-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:37-54:38-54:39-57:13-57:20-58:4-58:5-58:15-58:16-59:3-59:15-61:10-64:5-65:8-65:10-67:5-67:6-67:28-68:33-70:1-70:11-70:27-70:28-71:1-72:17-73:13-76:31-78:30-78:40-84:24-85:10-88:24-89:13-89:25",306
2033,440,"P","عِقَاب","«عَقَب» meaning the back part of the foot or the heel. And 'عاقبت' meaning the outcome or end of all things. And «عَقَبَہٗ» meaning he followed behind it or pursued it (passive). And the terms «عِقَاب ، عَقُوْبَۃ» and «مُعَاقبَۃ» are applied in the context of recompense for evil human deeds, and it denotes the inevitable result, i.e., the outcome of that evil deed.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جٰدَلُوۡا بِالۡبَاطِلِ لِیُدۡحِضُوۡا بِہِ الۡحَقَّ فَاَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۟ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ عِقَابِ» ( 40/5 )\nTranslation: And they argued falsely to suppress the truth thereby. So the consequence was that I seized them. Now (see) how severe was My punishment.","«عِقَاب» What is the result of an evil deed and its inevitable consequence?","Punishment","عقاب","2:196-2:211-3:11-5:2-5:98-6:165-7:167-8:13-8:25-8:48-8:52-13:6-13:32-38:14-40:3-40:5-40:22-41:43-59:4-59:7",20
2034,440,"P","بَأس","«بَأس» or « بَؤُسَ», in its meanings, conveys the concept of constriction and severity. (M. L) In the Quran, this word has been used in three meanings: war, punishment, and calamity. And in all three, the concept of constriction and severity is present. If it is used in the meanings of punishment or penalty, it will come in the meaning of severe punishment.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَوۡلَاۤ  اِذۡ جَآءَہُمۡ بَاۡسُنَا تَضَرَّعُوۡا» (6/43)\nTranslation: Then why did they not cry out when Our punishment came upon them?","«بَأس» a punishment that is both severe and constricting.","Punishment","بأس","2:177-2:214-4:84-6:42-6:43-6:147-6:148-7:4-7:5-7:94-7:97-7:98-12:110-16:81-17:5-18:2-21:12-21:80-27:33-33:18-40:29-40:84-40:85-48:16-57:25-59:14",26
2035,440,"P","نَکِیْر","The opposite of recognition is astonishment (a matter of wonder, something strange or extraordinary). Alienation and «نُکْر» mean unpleasant, indecent, and irrational things. «مُنْکَر» refers to actions in which Allah's pleasure is not found. «نَكُرَ الأَمْرُ» means something becoming extremely difficult (example). «نَکِیْر» is used in all senses: an unpleasant thing, denial, and punishment. When it means punishment, it refers to an unexpected and severe punishment.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «وَ کُذِّبَ مُوۡسٰی فَاَمۡلَیۡتُ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ ثُمَّ  اَخَذۡتُہُمۡ ۚ فَکَیۡفَ کَانَ نَکِیۡرِ» (22/44). Translation: And Moses was denied, but I continued to grant respite to the disbelievers. Then when I seized them, see how severe My punishment was.","«نَکِیْر» a severe, unbearable, and unexpected punishment.","Punishment","نکیر","22:44-34:45-35:26-42:47-67:18",5
2036,440,"P","نَکَال","«نَکْل» means an iron fetter. A rein (bit) and muhar (i.e., a rope tied in a chain), and anything by which a person is made to be bound and compelled to move. Its plural is «اَنْکَال». And «نَکَّلَ» means to put chains on someone and to give an exemplary punishment to someone. And «نَکَال» means an exemplary punishment so severe that others take a lesson from witnessing it (i.e., a deterrent punishment).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا نَکَالًا مِّنَ  اللّٰہِ» ( 5/38 )\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male thief and the female thief. That is the recompense for what they have earned, and an exemplary punishment from Allah.","«نَکَال» exemplary punishment.","punishment","نکال","2:66-5:38-79:25",3
2037,440,"P","وَبَال","«وَبْل» conveys the meaning of weight (i.e., heaviness) and severity. «اَلْوَبَلُ» and «اَلْوَابِلُ» refer to rain that has thick and heavy droplets (mef). «وَبْلُ بِالْعَصَا» means struck with a stick and struck repeatedly. «وَبِیْل» denotes the stick used for washing clothes (m. q.). «وَبَال» signifies a punishment or recompense that is both severe and excessive.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states: «اَلَمۡ  یَاۡتِکُمۡ نَبَؤُا  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلُ ۫ فَذَاقُوۡا وَبَالَ  اَمۡرِہِمۡ وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ  اَلِیۡمٌ» (64/5). Translation: Have you not received the news of the disbelievers who came before you? They tasted the consequences of their deeds, and there is a painful torment (in store) for them.","«وَبَال» severe and continuous punishment.","punishment","وبال","5:95-59:15-64:5-65:9",4
2038,440,"P","مَثُلٰت","«مَثَل» Two meanings are found in it: (1) to compare a thing to its counterpart, and (2) the pattern according to which something is made. And «اَلْمُثلَۃ» means to establish an exemplary punishment so that others may refrain from committing crimes (m. l), and also means to cut off the nose and ears or other limbs after killing (m q), and its plural is «مَثُلٰت». And «مَثُلَ» means for the image of something to reappear before one's eyes. And «مَثُل» means a punishment which, when remembered, causes its image to reappear before one's eyes—an exemplary punishment.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَسۡتَعۡجِلُوۡنَکَ بِالسَّیِّئَۃِ قَبۡلَ الۡحَسَنَۃِ وَ قَدۡ خَلَتۡ مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمُ الۡمَثُلٰتُ» (13/6)\nTranslation: And these people are hastening to ask for evil (punishment) instead of good, even though many exemplary punishments have already passed before them.","«مَثُلٰت» such a memorable punishment that its image begins to flash before one's eyes.","Punishment","مثلت","13:6",1
2039,440,"P","عَذَّبَ","«عَذَّبَ» Punishment for sin from Allah Almighty.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَنۡ  کَتَبَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمُ  الۡجَلَآءَ لَعَذَّبَہُمۡ  فِی الدُّنۡیَا ؕ وَ لَہُمۡ  فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ عَذَابُ النَّارِ» ( 59/3 )\nTranslation: And if Allah had not decreed exile for them, He would have punished them in this world, and in the Hereafter, the punishment of the Fire is prepared for them.","The punishment from Allah the Almighty for sin.","Punishment","عذب","2:284-3:56-3:128-3:129-4:173-5:18-5:40-5:115-5:118-7:164-8:33-8:34-9:14-9:26-9:39-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:85-9:101-9:106-17:15-17:54-17:58-18:86-18:87-20:47-26:138-26:213-27:21-29:21-33:24-33:73-34:35-37:59-48:6-48:14-48:16-48:17-48:25-58:8-59:3-65:8-88:24-89:25",45
2040,440,"P","نَکَّلَ","«نَکَّلَ» Punishment from Allah Almighty for sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ اَشَدُّ  بَاۡسًا وَّ اَشَدُّ تَنۡکِیۡلًا» ( 4/84 )\nTranslation: And Allah is Severe in penalty and [also] in retribution.","«نَکَّلَ» - Punishment for sin from Allah the Almighty.","Punishment","نکل","4:84",1
2041,440,"P","حُسْبَان","«حُسْبَان» meaning to count, to enumerate; and also meaning a small arrow (a projectile), and according to Imam Raghib, it refers to anything that is accounted for and then recompensed accordingly, while some scholars understand it to mean fire and punishment (Mufradat), and according to Ibn Faris, it also means to hurl small, scattered arrows and embers (M. L.). This meaning is derived from the following verse of the Quran, indicating a punishment that burns up crops and the like, turning them to ashes—whether it be a punishment of fire or of embers.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» ( 18/40 )\nTranslation: And send down upon your garden a calamity from the sky, so that it becomes a smooth, barren plain. (Jalandhari)","«حُسْبَان» the punishment of fire or burning that scorches plants and reduces them to ashes.","Punishment","حسبان","6:96-18:40-55:5",3
2042,440,"P","حَاصِبْ","«حَصَبَ الْمَکَان» means to pave a floor with pebbles. And «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْسُ» means a horse running so fast that pebbles fly into the air from its hooves (M. Q). «اَرْضٌ حَصِیَۃٌ» means pebble-strewn ground and a valley. «مُحَصَّبْ» refers to that valley from which pilgrims pick up pebbles. And «حَاصِب» means such a fierce and violent wind that hurls stones and pebbles into the air, and also a cloud that brings hail (Munajid. M Q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ اَمِنۡتُمۡ مَّنۡ فِی السَّمَآءِ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» ( 67/17 )\nTranslation: Are you then secure that He who is in the heaven will not send against you a storm of pebbles?","«حَاصِبْ» a fierce and sharp wind containing pebbles.","Punishment","حاصب","17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17",4
2043,440,"P","صَیْحَۃً","«صَاحَ» means to shout loudly, to scream or cry out. «صَائِحَۃ» means a gathering, the screaming or crying of mourners. And «صَیْحَۃ» refers to such a thunderous voice that makes people start screaming (muf).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ  الصَّیۡحَۃُ  مُشۡرِقِیۡنَ» (15/73)  \nTranslation: So the cry seized them at sunrise.","«صَیْحَۃ» a voice so thunderous that people begin to scream and shout.","Punishment","صیحۃً","11:67-11:94-15:73-15:83-23:41-29:40-36:29-36:49-36:53-38:15-50:42-54:31-63:4",13
2044,440,"P","رِجْز","«رِجْز» embodies the fundamental concept of agitation, meaning restlessness and excitement (m.l.). Rallying poems are those poems recited during wartime to incite excitement (i.e., swiftness, intensity, force, and dominance). And «رِجْز» is that punishment which makes the heart restless and uneasy.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ» (2:59)  \nTranslation: So We sent down upon the wrongdoers a punishment from the sky because of their transgression.","An unsettling punishment.","Punishment","رجز","2:59-7:134-7:135-7:162-29:34-34:5-45:11",7
2045,440,"P","رَجْف","«رَجَف» meaning severe restlessness and agitation (masc. pl.)\n«رَجَفَتِ الْاَرْض» meaning an earthquake occurring in the earth; to start shaking.\n«بَحْرٌ رَجَافٌ» meaning turbulent, i.e., a raging sea (منجد)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاَخَذَتۡہُمُ الرَّجۡفَۃُ فَاَصۡبَحُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِہِمۡ  جٰثِمِیۡنَ» (7/78)\nTranslation: So the earthquake seized them, and they lay overturned in their homes.","«رَجَف» the earthquake and its terror, severe restlessness and anxiety.","Punishment","رجف","7:78-7:91-7:155-29:37-73:14-79:6",6
2046,440,"P","خَسَفَ","«خَسَفَ الْقَمَر» means the darkening of the moon (i.e., the moon becoming dim due to an eclipse). And «خَسَفَ الْعَیْن» means the eye becoming fixed or sitting in its socket. And «خَسَفَ فُلَانًا» means to force someone into a state of humiliation and disgrace. And «خَسَفَ فِی الْاَرْض» means to cause to sink into the earth (to be swallowed up). In «خَسَف», two concepts are found: (1) to drown/submerge, and (2) humiliation and disgrace (lit. m. l.), i.e., to force something or someone to drown/submerge.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَخَسَفۡنَا بِہٖ وَ بِدَارِہِ  الۡاَرۡضَ» (28/81)\nTranslation: So We caused the earth to swallow up him and his home.","«خَسَف» To submerge something either forcefully or under duress.","Punishment","خسف","16:45-17:68-28:81-28:82-29:40-34:9-67:16-75:8",8
2047,441,"D","اَعَزَّ","«اَعَزّ» means to bestow honor, and its opposite, «اَذَلَّ», means to humiliate. «عِزّ» fundamentally means supremacy (i.e., being autonomous and not under anyone's authority). And «ذِلّ» means subordination (i.e., being under someone's authority). And «عِزَّت» refers to a state that safeguards a person from being defeated (detailed). For example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَ تُعِزُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ وَ تُذِلُّ مَنۡ تَشَآءُ ؕ بِیَدِکَ الۡخَیۡرُ» (3/26). Translation: O Allah! You grant honor to whom You will and humiliate whom You will; all good is in Your hands.","The term «اَعَزّ» is general. It means to bestow honor, to protect someone from another's guardianship, and to make them independent.","Dignity","اعز","2:206-3:26-4:139-10:65-11:92-18:34-19:81-26:44-27:34-35:10-37:180-38:82-63:8",13
2048,441,"H","اَکْرَمَ","«کَرَم» refers to an honor that is inherent in something due to its very nature or its qualities (M. L.). Moreover, a person cannot be described as generous until their generosity has been manifested (Maf). And «اِکْرَام» means to benefit someone in such a way that no sense of shame or embarrassment is caused to them. And it is the most noble and exalted (Maf). And when the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ emphasized «اِکَرَامُ الضَّیْف» (the honoring of guests), it means that one should serve them with humility (i.e., being considerate of their needs) and regard them as honored.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«کَلَّا بَلۡ  لَّا تُکۡرِمُوۡنَ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (89/17)\nTranslation: Nay, but you do not honor the orphan (Jalandhari). You do not show respect (Othmani).","«اِکْرَام» to honor someone.","Honor","اکرم","12:21-49:13-55:27-55:78-82:11-89:15-89:17-96:3",8
2049,441,"H","کرّم ، کرم","«تَکْرِیْم» indicates an honor that is inherent in the very essence of a thing.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ کَرَّمۡنَا بَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُمۡ  فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (17/70)\nTranslation: And We have honored the children of Adam and carried them on land and sea.","«تَکْرِیْم» to bestow honor upon someone based on their intrinsic qualities or personal essence.","honor","کرم ، کرم","4:31-8:4-8:74-12:31-17:23-17:62-17:70-21:26-22:18-22:50-23:116-24:26-26:7-26:58-27:29-27:40-31:10-33:31-33:44-34:4-36:11-36:27-44:17-44:26-44:49-51:24-56:44-56:77-57:11-57:18-69:40-70:35-80:13-81:19-82:6",35
2050,442,"I","حِجْر","«حِجْر» meaning stone. And meaning any solid and hard thing that provides shelter, and meaning intellect. And «حَجَرَ» meaning to encircle something to secure it and prevent others from intruding. And «عَقْل» is named after «حِجْر» because it also prevents anything harmful (M. L.). And «حِجْر» meaning obstacle, prohibition, intellect (from Minjaj). And «ذِیْ حِجْر» meaning possessor of intellect, wise, or one having intellect. (For detailed explanation, see under  shelter.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ہَلۡ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ قَسَمٌ  لِّذِیۡ حِجۡرٍ» (89/5)\nTranslation: Are these (the four mentioned matters) not worthy of oaths in the sight of the wise?","the intellect that safeguards against harm","Intellect","حجر","6:138-25:22-25:53",3
2051,442,"I","عَقْل","«عَقَلَ» means to possess understanding and be capable of recognizing errors (manjada). It also signifies to restrain and prohibit. «عِقَال» refers to the hobble used to tie a camel's foot (muf). Essentially, the function of reason is to distinguish between benefit and harm, to adopt measures to avoid detrimental matters (faq, p. 65), and to remain constantly prepared for beneficial things and the acceptance of knowledge. Then one should reflect (muf).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ قَالُوۡا  لَوۡ  کُنَّا نَسۡمَعُ  اَوۡ نَعۡقِلُ مَا کُنَّا فِیۡۤ   اَصۡحٰبِ السَّعِیۡرِ» (67:10). Translation: And they will say, If only we had listened or understood, we would not have been among the inhabitants of the Blaze.","That intellect which saves from harm and devises means to choose beneficial things.","Intellect","عقل","2:44-2:73-2:75-2:76-2:164-2:170-2:171-2:242-3:65-3:118-5:58-5:103-6:32-6:151-7:169-8:22-10:16-10:42-10:100-11:51-12:2-12:109-13:4-16:12-16:67-21:10-21:67-22:46-23:80-24:61-25:44-26:28-28:60-29:35-29:43-29:63-30:24-30:28-36:62-36:68-37:138-39:43-40:67-43:3-45:5-49:4-57:17-59:14-67:10",49
2052,442,"I","حِلْم","«حَلُمَ» means to forgive and to be forbearing. And «حَلِیْم» means having a patient temperament and being forbearing. And «حِلْم» means seriousness and forbearance—that is, maintaining such control over one's nature that it does not flare up even in times of anger. Its collective form is «اَحْلاَم». (The exegete) explains that «حِلْم» is that faculty which controls one's nature and prevents it from becoming inflamed, i.e., from flaring up.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَمۡ  تَاۡمُرُہُمۡ  اَحۡلَامُہُمۡ  بِہٰذَاۤ   اَمۡ  ہُمۡ قَوۡمٌ  طَاغُوۡنَ» (52/32)\nTranslation: Do their minds command them to this, or are they indeed a rebellious people?","«حِلْم» An intellect that maintains control over one's nature and does not allow it to become agitated.","Intellect","حلم","2:225-2:235-2:263-3:155-4:12-5:101-9:114-11:75-11:87-17:44-22:59-33:51-35:41-37:101-52:32-64:17",16
2053,442,"I","اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب","«اَلْبَاب» is a collection of «لُبّ». And «لُبّ» means the summary, the pure part of something (as in verse 66). And «لَبِیْب» means wise, intelligent. And «اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب» refers to those people who, upon hearing something, can extract its summary—people of quick understanding.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ فِیۡ  ذٰلِکَ لَذِکۡرٰی لِاُولِی الۡاَلۡبَابِ» (39/21)\nTranslation: Indeed, in these examples, there is a lesson for those of understanding.","«اُولِی الْاَلْبَاب» Intelligent and quick-witted people. Those who grasp the essence of a discussion.","Intellect","اولی الالباب","2:179-2:197-2:269-3:7-3:190-5:100-12:111-13:19-14:52-38:29-38:43-39:9-39:18-39:21-40:54-65:10",16
2054,442,"D","اُولِی الْاَبْصَار","«بَصُرَ» also means to see with the eye, and to see with the eye of the heart (i.e., the heart's eye). (For details, see 'to see'). And «اُولِی الْاَبْصَار» means people of insight. Those who reflect and ponder, whether they be quick-witted or not.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاعۡتَبِرُوۡا یٰۤاُولِی الۡاَبۡصَارِ» (59/2)\nTranslation: O you who possess eyes of insight! Take heed.","«اُولِی الْاَبْصَار» those who reflect.","Discernment","اولی الابصار","3:13-24:44-59:2",3
2055,442,"I","اُولِی النُّھٰی","«نُھٰی» means to reach the extreme limit of something (م ۔ ل), and «نَھُوَ یَنْھُوْا» means to be extremely intelligent, perfect in intellect, and «نُھٰی» is the plural of «نُھْیَہ». And «اُولِی النُّھٰی» means possessing foresight, people of good judgment, experienced (منجد). For example: In the Quran it says: «اِنَّ  فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ لَاٰیٰتٍ  لِّاُولِی  النُّہٰی» (20/54) Translation: Indeed, in these (matters) are abundant signs for those who understand.","«اُولِی النُّھٰی» Those of keen insight who reach the depth of matters.","Intellect","اولی النھی","20:54-20:128",2
2056,442,"I","اِسْتَفَزَّ","«فَزَّ» means: to triumph through deception; to bewilder; to cause to panic and expel.  \n«اِسْتَفْز» means: to agitate; to consider insignificant; to deem contemptible; to drive out from home (expel).  \n«اِسْتَفَزَّ» means: to throw into turmoil; to cause loss of reason (sing. Quranic).  \n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «فَاَرَادَ  اَنۡ یَّسۡتَفِزَّہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَرۡضِ» (17/103). Translation: Pharaoh desired to expel the Children of Israel from the land (Egypt) by bewildering them.","«اِسْتَفِزّ» to confound someone by causing them distress and agitation, or by deceiving them to the point of impairing their intellect.","Intellect","استفز","17:64-17:76-17:103",3
2057,442,"I","اِسْتَخَفَّ","«خَفَّ» means 'to be light'. «خَفِیْف» means 'light' and its opposite. «ثَقِیْل» means 'heavy in weight' and «خَفَّفَ» means 'to make light'. And «اِسْتَخَفَّ» means 'to consider light', to deem ignorant, to remove from truth and righteousness (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاسۡتَخَفَّ قَوۡمَہٗ  فَاَطَاعُوۡہُ» (43/54)\nTranslation: So he (Pharaoh) persuaded his people, and they obeyed him.","To humiliate and degrade someone to the point of destroying their intellect.","Intellect","استخف","43:54",1
2058,443,"W","اُنْثٰی","«اُنْثٰی» means feminine (as opposed to masculine or male). This term applies to the feminine gender of all living beings. And similarly, when the human species is mentioned, it refers to woman.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِصَاصُ فِی الۡقَتۡلٰی ؕ اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» (2/178)\nTranslation: Retaliation has been prescribed for you: free for free, slave for slave, and woman for woman.","«اُنْثٰی» This term is used for 'woman' whenever a living female is mentioned, whether in reference to males and females or to the human species.","Woman","انثی","2:178-3:36-3:195-4:11-4:124-4:176-6:143-6:144-13:8-16:58-16:97-35:11-40:40-41:47-49:13-53:21-53:27-53:45-75:39-92:3",20
2059,443,"W","اِمْرَاَۃ","«اِمْرَأَۃ»: «اِمْرَءٌ» or «مَرْءٌ» is used in contrast. It means any person, any man. This word is applied when a man or woman reaches the age of marriage. (F. L 17) The dual form of «اِمْرَأۃ» is «اِمْرَاَتَان», and the plural is «نِسَاء» or «نِسْوَۃ».\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«وَ اِنِ امۡرَاَۃٌ خَافَتۡ مِنۡۢ بَعۡلِہَا نُشُوۡزًا» (4/128)\nTranslation: If a woman fears from her husband [discontent or ill-treatment]...\n\n«نِسَاء» is its opposite, «رِجَال», which is the plural of «اِمْرَءٌ». And the plural of «اِمْرَاَۃٌ» is «نِسَاءٌ» and «نِسْوَۃٌ». Men are referred to as «رَجُل» when the aspect of their strength is intended to be emphasized. (See details in Adam. Insaan)\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡخَرۡ قَوۡمٌ مِّنۡ قَوۡمٍ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا خَیۡرًا مِّنۡہُمۡ وَ لَا نِسَآءٌ  مِّنۡ  نِّسَآءٍ» (49/11)\nTranslation: Let no people mock another people; perhaps they may be better than them, nor should women mock women.\n\n«نِسْوَۃٌ» refers to those women who are connected to a specific matter.\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«قَالَ ارۡجِعۡ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ فَسۡئَلۡہُ مَا بَالُ النِّسۡوَۃِ  الّٰتِیۡ قَطَّعۡنَ اَیۡدِیَہُنَّ» (12/50)\nTranslation: So when the messengers came to them, Yusuf said: Return to your master and ask him, What is the case of the women who cut their hands?","«اِمْرَأَۃَ» is the feminine form of «مَرْءٌ» and «اِمْرَءٌ». A woman who has reached the age of marriage is called by this term, and its plural form is «نِسَاء». And «نِسْوَۃ» refers to a group of women pertaining to a specific matter.","woman","امراۃ","2:282-3:35-3:40-4:12-4:128-7:83-11:71-11:81-12:21-12:30-12:51-15:60-19:5-19:8-27:23-27:57-28:9-28:23-29:32-29:33-33:50-51:29-66:10-66:11-111:4",25
2060,444,"C","وَعْد","«وَعَدَ» means to promise; to give hope regarding something. It is a well-known word (m. l.) and it is unilateral. And «اَخْلَفَ الْوَعْد» means to fail to fulfill a promise.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ لَمَّا قُضِیَ الۡاَمۡرُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ وَعَدَکُمۡ وَعۡدَ الۡحَقِّ وَ وَعَدۡتُّکُمۡ فَاَخۡلَفۡتُکُمۡ» (14/22)\nTranslation: And when the matter [i.e., judgment] is decided, Satan will say, Indeed, Allah had promised you a true promise, and I promised you, but I failed you.","«وَعَدَ» When someone is given hope, it is called a promise.","Covenant","وعد","3:152-3:194-4:95-4:122-5:9-6:134-7:44-7:86-9:68-9:72-9:77-9:111-9:114-10:4-10:48-10:55-11:17-11:45-11:65-11:81-13:31-13:35-14:22-14:47-15:43-16:38-17:5-17:7-17:64-17:104-17:108-18:21-18:48-18:58-18:59-18:98-19:54-19:61-19:75-20:58-20:59-20:86-20:87-20:97-21:9-21:38-21:97-21:103-21:104-21:109-22:47-22:72-23:36-23:83-23:93-24:55-25:15-25:16-26:206-27:68-27:71-28:13-28:61-30:6-30:60-31:9-31:33-33:12-33:22-34:29-35:5-36:48-36:52-36:63-38:53-39:20-39:74-40:8-40:55-40:77-41:30-43:42-43:83-45:32-46:16-46:17-46:35-47:15-48:20-48:29-50:32-51:5-51:22-51:60-54:46-57:10-67:25-70:42-70:44-72:24-72:25-73:18-77:7",103
2061,444,"C","وَعِیْد","«وَعِیْد» is a promise based on evil and related to bad outcomes. Threat. Intimidation. (meaning)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَذَکِّرۡ بِالۡقُرۡاٰنِ مَنۡ یَّخَافُ وَعِیۡدِ» (50/45)\nTranslation: Therefore, continue to admonish every person who fears My threat through the Quran.\n«مَوْعِدَۃ : مَوْعِدًا» All these words originate from «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ» and «وَعَدَ یَعِدُ وَعْدًا وَعِدَۃً وَ مَوْعِدًا وَ مَوْعِدَۃً» and their meaning is promise or to promise. (Manj) And they have been used in the Quran in these meanings.\n«مِیْعَاد»: It is a noun of time. In its temporal form, it means the time of the promise, and in its spatial form, it means the place of the promise.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ لَوۡ  تَوَاعَدۡتُّمۡ  لَاخۡتَلَفۡتُمۡ  فِی الۡمِیۡعٰدِ» (8/42)\nTranslation: And if you (for battle) had made a mutual agreement among yourselves, then there would have been precedence and delay in the appointed time (of gathering).\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ اِنَّکَ جَامِعُ النَّاسِ لِیَوۡمٍ لَّا رَیۡبَ فِیۡہِ ؕ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ  لَا یُخۡلِفُ الۡمِیۡعَادَ» (3/9)\nTranslation: O our Lord! Indeed, You will gather the people on a Day about which there is no doubt; indeed, Allah does not fail in His promise.","«وَعِیْد» If a promise pertains to an adverse outcome, it is termed a threat. The time or place specified for a promise is called its term. This is generally unilateral.","Covenant","وعید","14:14-20:113-50:14-50:20-50:28-50:45",6
2062,444,"C","عَھِدَ","«عَھْد» means to continuously protect and take care of something; to acknowledge. (Figurative) To protect and fulfill. (Majid) And «عَھْد» also means fidelity, friendship, trust, responsibility, and will. And «وَلِی العَھَد» means the king's heir (Majid). Some lexicographers hold that a covenant is a bilateral promise, while others maintain it is a promise made with a condition (Faqir 43).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَوۡفُوۡا بِالۡعَہۡدِ ۚ اِنَّ  الۡعَہۡدَ  کَانَ  مَسۡئُوۡلًا» (17:34)\nTranslation: And fulfill the covenant. Indeed, the covenant will be questioned about.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«اَوۡفُوۡا بِعَہۡدِیۡۤ اُوۡفِ بِعَہۡدِکُمۡ» (2:40)\nTranslation: Fulfill My covenant, and I will fulfill your covenant.","«عَھْد» A commitment that is also safeguarded, with its fulfillment kept in mind at all times; it can be either bilateral or conditional.","Covenant","عھد","2:27-2:40-2:80-2:100-2:124-2:125-2:177-3:76-3:77-3:183-6:152-7:102-7:134-8:56-9:4-9:7-9:12-9:111-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:95-17:34-19:78-19:87-20:86-20:115-23:8-33:15-36:60-43:49-70:32",32
2063,444,"C","ذِمَّۃ","«ذِمَّہ» is essentially a type of covenant—namely, a covenant of fidelity. It also carries the meanings of protection (aman), the responsibility of safeguarding, and a pledge to grant someone refuge. The people of the covenant (ahl al-dhimma) are those who have been granted protection in exchange for the jizya tax.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ  یَّظۡہَرُوۡا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡا فِیۡکُمۡ  اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9:8)\nTranslation: If they gain the upper hand over you, they would respect neither kinship nor covenant.","«ذِمَّۃ» is essentially a type of covenant—the covenant of granting refuge.","Covenant","ذمۃ","9:8-9:10",2
2064,444,"C","اِصْر","«اَصَرَ» meaning to tie a knot in something, and to forcibly stop it (e.g.).  \n«اِصْر» meaning binding, heavy burden, shackles of customs and traditions, limits of Sharia, restrictions, great responsibility. It seems that in this word, the concepts of covenant, burden, and confinement are present.  \n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ یَضَعُ عَنۡہُمۡ اِصۡرَہُمۡ» (7/157)  \nTranslation: The Prophet removes from them the burden (of customs and traditions).  \n\nAt another instance, the Almighty God states:  \n«رَبَّنَا وَ لَا  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡنَاۤ  اِصۡرًا کَمَا حَمَلۡتَہٗ عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ مِنۡ قَبۡلِنَا» (2/286)  \nTranslation: Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden (the limits and restrictions of Sharia) like that which You imposed on those before us.","«اِصْر» a covenant that is burdensome or difficult due to obligation, whether customary or Sharia.","Covenant","اصر","2:286-3:81-7:157",3
2065,444,"C","مِیْثَاق","This is the rope or chain with which something is tied tightly. And «مِیْثَاق» is that covenant or pledge which has been made firm (i.e., strong and solid) or, in written form, has bound the parties to the agreement.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ یَصِلُوۡنَ اِلٰی قَوۡمٍۭ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ مِّیۡثَاقٌ» (4/90)\nTranslation: But those who have allied themselves with a people among whom there is a treaty (of peace) with you.","When a covenant is made stronger through writing or repetition, it becomes a «مِیْثَاق».","Covenant","میثاق","2:27-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-3:81-3:187-4:21-4:90-4:92-4:154-4:155-5:7-5:12-5:13-5:14-5:70-7:169-8:72-13:20-13:25-33:7-57:8",23
2066,444,"C","عُقُوْد","«عَقَدَ» means to tie a knot. And «عُقْدَۃ» means to tie a knot firmly, and its plural is «عُقَد». It is also used in a physical sense.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ  شَرِّ النَّفّٰثٰتِ فِی الۡعُقَدِ» (113/4)\nTranslation: And (I seek refuge) from the evil of those who blow knots (i.e., sorcerers).\nAnd it is used in a spiritual sense as well, such as «عَقْدُ الْبَیْع ، عَقْدُ النِّکَاح» and «عَقْدُ الْعَھْد». Its meaning is to strengthen a covenant so firmly that it is as if a knot has been tied. And according to Ibn al-Faris, 'Aqd (contract/covenant) denotes intensity and firmness (i.e., a covenant stronger than even a 'Mithaq'—solemn pledge).\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اَوۡفُوۡا بِالۡعُقُوۡدِ» (5/1)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, fulfill your pledges.\n«عَقْد» is also very often made stronger than oaths. Sometimes through the repetition of a pledge, and sometimes through writing.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ عَقَدَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ فَاٰتُوۡہُمۡ نَصِیۡبَہُمۡ» (4/33)\nTranslation: And give to those whom you have pledged (their due shares).","«عَقْد» To strengthen a covenant by inscribing it, repeating it, and taking an oath, making it more firm, solid, and certain—and this makes it stronger than the covenant itself.","Covenant","عقود","2:235-2:237-4:33-5:1-5:89-20:27-113:4",7
2067,445,"C","غَار","«غَوْر» is also used for subterranean land and for depth. «غَارَ الرَّجُل» means a person descended into the subterranean land. And «غَارَ الْمَاءُ» means water went underground. «غَوْر» means deep. Deep thought. And «غَار» means such a subterranean place or depth where a person can take refuge, whether it is in a mountain or underground.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «اِذۡ ہُمَا فِی الۡغَارِ اِذۡ یَقُوۡلُ لِصَاحِبِہٖ لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: When both of them (the Messenger of Allah and Abu Bakr) were in the cave and when the Messenger of Allah ﷺ was saying to his companion, Do not grieve. Indeed, Allah is with us.\n\nAnd «مَغَار ، غَوْر» is a noun of place (spatial) that comes in the meanings of cave. Its plural is «مَغَارَات».\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «لَوۡ  یَجِدُوۡنَ مَلۡجَاً  اَوۡ مَغٰرٰتٍ اَوۡ  مُدَّخَلًا لَّوَلَّوۡا  اِلَیۡہِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَجۡمَحُوۡنَ» (9/57)\nTranslation: If the hypocrites find any place of refuge (such as a fortress) or a cave or any place to burrow into, they will turn and run towards it, pulling ropes.","«غَار» in the mountains, a place where a human can take refuge.","Cave","غار","9:40-9:57",2
2068,445,"C","کَھْف","«کَھُوْف» is the plural of «کَھْف». And «کَھْف» is more specific than cave. «کَھْف» refers to such a cave or cavern that is in a mountain and is large (for example). If it is small, it will be called a cave (م ق).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبۡتَ اَنَّ  اَصۡحٰبَ الۡکَہۡفِ وَ الرَّقِیۡمِ ۙ کَانُوۡا  مِنۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا  عَجَبًا» (18:9)\nTranslation: Do you think that the Cave and the Raqim were among Our signs as a wonder?\n(Meaning: When We have already created and shown many greater signs than this, then how is the story of the People of the Cave so strange and amazing?)","«کَھْف» refers to a cave or cavern that is located within a mountain and is larger than a standard cave.","cave","کھف","18:9-18:10-18:11-18:16-18:17-18:25",6
2069,446,"H","غَفَلَ","«غَفَل» meaning to abandon a task, whether intentionally or unintentionally (m. l). To be unaware of the knowledge (i.e., recognition) of facts. (muf) To not do a required action due to laziness or forgetfulness. And a heedless person can be heedless regarding their own actions or essence, as well as regarding others (fq l 78).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا اللّٰہُ بِغَافِلٍ عَمَّا تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (2/140)\nTranslation: And Allah is not heedless of what you do.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«وَدَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ تَغۡفُلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَسۡلِحَتِکُمۡ وَ اَمۡتِعَتِکُمۡ فَیَمِیۡلُوۡنَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مَّیۡلَۃً وَّاحِدَۃً» (4/102)\nTranslation: The disbelievers wish that you should be heedless of your weapons and equipment so they can launch a sudden attack upon you.\n\nAnd «اَغْفَلَ» means to divert someone's attention elsewhere, thereby making them heedless or preventing them from doing something.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَا تُطِعۡ مَنۡ  اَغۡفَلۡنَا قَلۡبَہٗ عَنۡ  ذِکۡرِنَا» (18/28)\nTranslation: And do not follow one whose heart We have made heedless of Our remembrance.","«غَفَل» Failing to act due to forgetfulness or laziness, or neglecting someone else's work.","Heedless","غفل","2:74-2:85-2:140-2:144-2:149-3:99-4:102-6:131-6:132-6:156-7:136-7:146-7:172-7:179-7:205-10:7-10:29-10:92-11:123-12:3-12:13-14:42-16:108-18:28-19:39-21:1-21:97-23:17-24:23-27:93-28:15-30:7-36:6-46:5-50:22",35
2070,446,"N","سَھٰی","«سَھٰی» means 'to forget' and 'the heart turning away to another direction.' And «سَھْو» means 'gentleness' and 'calmness' (tranquility). «سَھْو» actually refers to the act that occurs due to forgetfulness. If no intention is involved in it, it is excusable. For example, a madman swearing. And if it is done with intention, it is subject to punishment and accountability. (Mujtahid) 'Sujud al-Sahw' is a well-known term, meaning the prostration performed as compensation for deficiencies or additions in the acts of prayer due to the heart turning away (from concentration). And this term does not apply to the actions of others. (Fiqh 78)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ  لِّلۡمُصَلِّیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ عَنۡ صَلَاتِہِمۡ سَاہُوۡنَ» (107:4,5)\nTranslation: So woe to those who pray but are heedless of their prayer.","«سَھٰی» Due to forgetfulness, performing a different task instead of the original one, or altering it by addition or subtraction. This is not related to external factors.","negligent","سھی","51:11-107:5",2
2071,446,"N","سَمَدَ","«سَمَد» means to stand in amazement, to be stunned or dumbfounded; and «سَمَدَ فِی الْعَمْل» means to be occupied with some work; and «سَمَّدَ» means to engage someone in play or sport (majnid). Thus, «سَمَدَ» is used metaphorically for the state of becoming engrossed in play and amusement, thereby neglecting the real purpose and work at hand.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَضۡحَکُوۡنَ  وَ لَا  تَبۡکُوۡنَ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ  سٰمِدُوۡنَ فَاسۡجُدُوۡا لِلّٰہِ  وَ اعۡبُدُوۡا» (53:60, 61, 62)\nTranslation: And you laugh and do not weep, while you are engaged in vain play? So prostrate before Allah and worship Him.","«سَمَد» falling into heedlessness and becoming preoccupied with play and amusement instead of attending to the real work.","negligent","سمد","53:61",1
2072,446,"H","اَلْھٰی","They refer to everything that distracts a person from their true intention (e.g.) and «لَھَا یَلْھُو» means 'to play', 'to be enthusiastic'. And in «لَھٰی» and «اَلْھٰی», the cause of diverting thoughts is not negligence but rather other futile activities.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated: «اَلۡہٰکُمُ  التَّکَاثُرُ» (102/1)\n\nTranslation: (O people) the abundance (craving for wealth) has made you heedless (of Allah's remembrance).","When attention deviates from the main task, the reason is play and diversion or other engagements, not forgetfulness.","Heedless","الھی","4:135-6:32-6:70-7:51-21:17-29:64-31:6-38:26-47:36-53:3-57:20-62:11-79:40-102:1",14
2073,447,"V","ظَھَرَ","Two fundamental meanings are inherent in the word «ظَھَرَ»: (1) to appear, to become manifest, to become evident. (2) strength, power. This word is then used in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«ظَہَرَ الۡفَسَادُ فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» ( 30/41 )\nTranslation: Corruption has appeared in the land and sea.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«حَتّٰی جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ ظَہَرَ  اَمۡرُ  اللّٰہِ» ( 9/48 )\nTranslation: Until the truth came and the command of Allah prevailed.\n\nThus, the meaning of «ظَھَرَ» signifies the manifestation of something along with strength and power.\n\nAnd for the phrase to overcome or to prevail, the word «اَظْھَرَ» is used.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَرۡسَلَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ  بِالۡہُدٰی وَ دِیۡنِ الۡحَقِّ لِیُظۡہِرَہٗ عَلَی الدِّیۡنِ کُلِّہٖ» ( 9/33 )\nTranslation: He it is Who has sent His Messenger with guidance and the true religion to make it prevail over all religions.","«ظَھَرَ» meaning to come forth with strength, to emerge, (as) rising power.","Victorious/Dominant","ظھر","2:85-6:120-6:151-7:33-9:8-9:33-9:48-13:33-18:20-18:22-18:97-24:31-30:7-30:18-30:41-31:20-34:18-40:26-40:29-43:33-48:28-57:3-57:13-61:9-61:14-66:3-72:26",27
2074,447,"P","عَزَّ","«عَزَّ» means to be ruled and subdued. «ذَلَّ» means to be superior, i.e., autonomous. And just as in today's rural setting, the landlord class is superior (powerful) and the lowly or laboring people are subordinate and weak under them. This is the correct meaning of «عَزِیْز» and «ذَلِیْل».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَالَ اَکۡفِلۡنِیۡہَا وَ عَزَّنِیۡ  فِی الۡخِطَابِ» (38/23)\nTranslation: And I have only one ewe, but he says, Give it to me, and he presses me strongly in speech.","«عَزَّ» meaning to be powerful, dominant, and strong.","Prevailing","عز","38:23",1
2075,447,"V","غَلَبَ","«غَلَبَ» conveys the meaning of power, coercion, and intensity (m l), i.e., to achieve superiority and dominance through force of arm; to conquer. And maghlub (overcome) refers to one who is compelled and overpowered by force and strength.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» (2/249)  \nTranslation: Many times it occurred that a small group, by the command of Allah, overcame a much larger host.","to attain supremacy by might","Victorious, Prevailing, Conquering, Predominant","غلب","2:249-3:12-3:160-4:74-5:23-5:56-7:113-7:119-8:36-8:48-8:65-8:66-12:21-18:21-21:44-23:106-26:40-26:41-26:44-28:35-30:2-30:3-37:116-37:173-41:26-54:10-58:21",27
2076,447,"P","اِسْتَعْلٰی","«عَلٰی یَعْلو» means to be elevated. And «اِستعْلٰی» means to desire elevation—the demand to attain superiority and dominance. And «تَعِلّیْ» means to boast. These «تَعَلّی» and «استعلی» are generally used in negative connotations. And «عَلَا یَعْلُوْا» is used in both good and bad contexts. And «عَلِیَ یَعْلٰی» is used in a good sense (muf).  \nFor example, in the Quran it is: «فَاَجۡمِعُوۡا کَیۡدَکُمۡ  ثُمَّ  ائۡتُوۡا  صَفًّا ۚ وَ  قَدۡ  اَفۡلَحَ  الۡیَوۡمَ  مَنِ  اسۡتَعۡلٰی» (20/64).  \nTranslation: (Pharaoh said) So gather the [magic] equipment, then come in ranks. Today, whoever prevails will be successful.","«اِسْتَعْلٰی» meaning to desire elevation; to seek to attain superiority and dominance.","Prevailing","استعلی","20:64",1
2077,447,"P","قَھَرَ","Two fundamental meanings are associated with «قَھْر»: (1) to prevail/overcome, and (2) to subdue/humiliate the defeated. The term 'to suppress' (م ۔ ل) is also used. Subsequently, this word is employed separately in both meanings.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ سَنُقَتِّلُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ نَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ ۚ وَ اِنَّا فَوۡقَہُمۡ  قٰہِرُوۡنَ» (7/127)\nTranslation: Pharaoh said, We will kill their sons and let their daughters live, and indeed, we are dominant over them.\n\nIn this verse, the word 'qahr' conveys both meanings. Whereas in the following verse, only the meaning of 'to subdue' is implied.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَمَّا  الۡیَتِیۡمَ  فَلَا تَقۡہَرۡ وَ اَمَّا السَّآئِلَ  فَلَا تَنۡہَرۡ» (93/9,10)\nTranslation: So do not oppress the orphan, nor repulse the beggar.","To dominate and humiliate, to oppress the weak.","Prevailing","قھر","6:18-6:61-7:127-12:39-13:16-14:48-38:65-39:4-40:16-93:9",10
2078,448,"D","غَبَرَۃٌ","«غَبَرَۃ» meaning dust and airborne particles. For example, in the Holy Quran: «وَ وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ عَلَیۡہَا غَبَرَۃٌ تَرۡہَقُہَا قَتَرَۃٌ» (80/40,41). Translation: On that day, many faces will be covered in dust, with darkness overwhelming them.","«غَبَرَۃ» are the dust particles that become visible to the eye.","Dust","غبرۃ","80:40",1
2079,448,"D","نَقْعًا","«نَقْعَا» meaning trailing dust or debris. This is the dust and dirt that fast-moving vehicles leave behind them. Due to the heaviness of the soil particles, they gradually settle back onto the ground.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَثَرۡنَ بِہٖ نَقۡعًا فَوَسَطۡنَ بِہٖ جَمۡعًا» (100/4,5)\nTranslation: Then (by the horses) that raise dust, then (by the horses) that plunge into the midst of the enemy's ranks.","«نَقْعَا» the heavy particles of dust and dirt that any fast-moving vehicle leaves behind.","dust","نقعًا","100:4",1
2080,448,"D","ھَبَاءً","«ھَبْوَۃ» refers to fine dust particles (m. l.), i.e., extremely fine particles of soil that are perpetually present in the air and invisible. For example, the Quran states: «وَ قَدِمۡنَاۤ اِلٰی مَا عَمِلُوۡا مِنۡ عَمَلٍ فَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  ہَبَآءً  مَّنۡثُوۡرًا» (25/23). Translation: And whatever deeds they have done, We will draw them towards it, and We will turn them into scattered dust.","«ھَبَاءً» are those fine particles of dust that remain scattered in the air at all times and are not visible.","dust","ھباءً","25:23-56:6",2
2081,449,"A","سَخَطَ","«سَخَطَ» signifies acting against one's will, and «سَخْط» signifies displeasure. This is the first level of anger. (Fa 169) And this always occurs from the elder to the younger. This can be said as «سَخَطَ الْاَمِیْر عَلَی الْحَاجِب», but «سَخَطَ الْحَاجِبِ عَلَی الْاَمِیْر» is not used. (Faq 106)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنِ اتَّبَعَ رِضۡوَانَ اللّٰہِ کَمَنۡۢ بَآءَ بِسَخَطٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (3/162)\n\nTranslation: Can the one who follows the pleasure of Allah ever be like the one who earns His anger?","«سَخَطَ» means displeasure or dislike; this is the first stage of anger, and it always happens from a superior to an inferior.","anger","سخط","3:162-5:80-9:58",3
2082,449,"A","غَیْظ","«غَیْظ» is a type of anger that quickens the circulation of blood in a person and is the second degree of rage (cf. 169). However, no retaliatory action should be taken, nor has it been taken. And «غَیْظ» can also relate to one's own self (cf. 06).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡکٰظِمِیۡنَ الۡغَیۡظَ وَ الۡعَافِیۡنَ عَنِ النَّاسِ» (3/134)\nTranslation: And those who restrain anger and pardon people.","«غَیْظ» A state of anger that quickens a person's blood circulation; this is the second degree of anger, and wrath can also turn upon oneself.","Anger","غیظ","3:119-3:134-9:15-9:120-22:15-25:12-33:25-48:29-67:8",9
2083,449,"A","غَضَبٌ","«غَضَبٌ» According to the scholar of fiqh and language, this term is general and is used for every type of anger. (F L 169) But this definition does not seem correct. The definition of anger given by the Messenger of Allah ﷺ is as follows:\n«اِتَّقُوْا مِنْ الْغَضَبِ فَاِنَّہٗ جُمْرَۃٌ تُوْقَدُ فِیْ قَلْبِ ابْنِ اٰدَمَ اَلَمْ تَرَوْا اِلَی انْتِفَاخِ اَوْدَاجِہٖ وَجُمْرَۃِ عَیْنَیْہِ»\nTranslation: Avoid anger, for it is a spark of fire that burns in the heart of the son of Adam. Do you not see that the veins of such a person swell and his eyes turn red?\nAnd it is evident that this state occurs when anger overwhelms a person and he descends to seeking revenge. And Ibn al-Faris has given its meaning as «اَشَدّْ السَّخَط», meaning extreme displeasure. (M L) And the author of al-Munjid has written the meaning of «غَضِبَ» as to bear rancor, to become angry. (al-Munjid) And with the meaning of «اِرَادَۃُ الضَّرْر لِلْمَغْضُوْبِ عَلَیْہِ ۔» and «غَضْب», it always comes from the other, meaning it can be from a junior to a senior and also from a senior to a junior. (F Q L 106)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّحۡلِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ غَضَبِیۡ فَقَدۡ ہَوٰی» (20/81)\nTranslation: And the one upon whom My wrath descended was destroyed.","«غَضَبٌ» When a person, driven by anger, descends upon revenge—whether the offense is small or great—it is not connected to their own self, but to the self of another.","anger","غضب","1:7-2:61-2:90-3:112-4:93-5:60-7:71-7:150-7:152-7:154-8:16-16:106-20:81-20:86-24:9-42:16-42:37-48:6-58:14-60:13",20
2084,449,"A","حَرْد","«حَرِْد» means to be angry with someone. And «حَرَدَ» means to forbid (prohibit). «حَرْد» means overwhelmed by anger (i.e., in a fit of rage) to swiftly attack someone or to seek an opportunity to attack (Fal 169). «حَرْد» is actually not the name of any state of anger but rather the quality of that opportunistic or vengeful action which a person carries out while overcome with fury and rage. And according to Abu Hala, the meaning of «حَرْد» is to distance oneself from the person one is angry with (i.e., the one at whom one is angry) and to see the matter through to its conclusion. (Faq l 106)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَّ  غَدَوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡدٍ   قٰدِرِیۡنَ» (68/25)  \nTranslation: They arrived there in the morning, hastening as if they were capable of treading the land.","«حَرْد» The nature of retaliatory actions due to anger—swiftly pouncing or attacking from a distance—and scheming (i.e., devising a plan to cause damage or harm).","Anger","حرد","68:25",1
2085,449,"A","اَسْخَطَ","«اَسْخَط» meaning to displease. The details have already been discussed above.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمُ  اتَّبَعُوۡا مَاۤ  اَسۡخَطَ اللّٰہَ وَ کَرِہُوۡا  رِضۡوَانَہٗ» (47/28)\nTranslation: This is because they pursued what angered Allah and disliked what pleased Him.","«اَسْخَط» meaning to anger.","anger","اسخط","47:28",1
2086,449,"A","غَاظ","«غَاظَ» meaning to anger. The detail has already been mentioned above.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا یَطَئُوۡنَ مَوۡطِئًا یَّغِیۡظُ الۡکُفَّارَ» ( 9/120 )\nTranslation: And they do not tread on any place that would anger the disbelievers.","«غَاظَ» means to instill anger.","Anger","غاظ","9:120-22:15-48:29",3
2087,449,"A","اٰسَفَ","«اَلْاَسْف»: A type of anger that arises from regret and sorrow (grief). If the anger is directed at someone weaker, it takes the form of rage and fury. And if it is directed at someone stronger, it remains internal, manifesting as grief and sorrow within (as explained). And «اَسَفَ» means the loss of something and feeling regret over it. Also, «اٰسف» means to make someone angry; to cause grief (as defined).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ  اٰسَفُوۡنَا انۡتَقَمۡنَا مِنۡہُمۡ» (43/55)\nTranslation: Then when they made Us angry, We took retribution from them.","«اٰسَفَ» comes to incite anger in the powerful and to afflict the weak with grief and sorrow.","Anger","اسف","7:150-12:84-18:6-20:86-43:55",5
2088,450,"S","غَمَّ","The basic meaning of «غَمَّ» is to cover and conceal. «غُمّٰی» means dust and darkness, and «غَمَام» means clouds that cover the sunlight. And «غم» means restlessness, sorrow, pain (i.e., distress and affliction).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«ثُمَّ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الۡغَمِّ اَمَنَۃً نُّعَاسًا یَّغۡشٰی طَآئِفَۃً مِّنۡکُمۡ» (3/154)\nTranslation: Then after grief and sorrow, Allah the Most High sent down tranquility upon you, (meaning) sleep that overcame a group among you.","«غَمّ» is used in all these meanings: sorrow, grief, restlessness, pain, and regret.","Sorrow","غم","3:153-3:154-20:40-21:88-22:22",5
2089,450,"S","حُزْن","«حُزْن» means grief, and its opposite «فَرَح» means happiness. «حُزْن» refers to a state of anxiety regarding a matter. This expresses the distressed (anxious) state of a human. When no remedy for anxiety is found, it assumes the form of grief. Moreover, «حُزَن» also denotes calamities. Therefore, the grief that befalls due to a calamity is termed «حُزْن». For instance, the Holy Quran states: «وَ ابۡیَضَّتۡ عَیۡنٰہُ مِنَ الۡحُزۡنِ» (12/84). Translation: And both his (Jacob's) eyes became blind due to grief.","«حُزْن» A grief whose cause is some incurable calamity.","Sorrow","حزن","3:176-5:41-6:33-10:65-12:13-12:84-12:86-21:103-31:23-36:76-58:10",11
2090,450,"S","بَثَّ","«بَثّ» meaning «شِدَّۃُ الْحُزْن» (Fussilat 48): Intense grief. Regret. The kind of grief that consumes a person from within. A prolonged period of sorrow and anguish.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ اِنَّمَاۤ اَشۡکُوۡا بَثِّیۡ وَ حُزۡنِیۡۤ اِلَی اللّٰہِ » (12/86)\nTranslation: Ya'qub (Jacob) said: I only complain of my distress and sorrow to Allah.","«بَثّ» - the intensity of grief; a sorrow that consumes a person from within.","sorrow","بث","12:86",1
2091,450,"G","حَزَنَ","«حَزَنَ» meaning to grieve, to sorrow (detailed and has passed over).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«لَا تَحۡزَنۡ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ مَعَنَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: Do not grieve. Indeed, Allah is with us.","«حَزَنَ» to feel grief or sorrow due to some accident or calamity.","Grief","حزن","2:38-2:62-2:112-2:262-2:274-2:277-3:139-3:153-3:170-5:69-6:48-7:35-7:49-9:40-9:92-10:62-15:88-16:127-19:24-20:40-27:70-28:7-28:8-28:13-29:33-33:51-35:34-39:61-41:30-43:68-46:13-",31
2092,450,"G","اٰسٰی","«اٰسٰی» meaning to grieve over the loss of something (intransitive).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَ لَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23)\nTranslation: So that you do not grieve over what has escaped you, nor boast over what He has given you.","«اٰسٰی» To grieve over what has already slipped from one's hands.","grief","اسی","7:93-57:23",2
2093,450,"G","اَبْلَسَ","«اَبْلَسَ» meaning to be grieved due to intense despair (transitive verb) and meaning to be unaware. To be grieved and broken-hearted (from 'manjada') i.e., such grief that befalls one due to having despaired completely of something. And Satan (Iblis) was also called 'Ablis' because he despaired of God's mercy and was broken and defeated in spirit.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یُّنَزَّلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِہٖ لَمُبۡلِسِیۡنَ» (30/49)\nTranslation: And before the rain fell, they were in despair.","«اَبْلَسَ» Grief arising from disappointment in a task.","grief","ابلس","6:44-23:77-30:12-30:49-43:75",5
2094,450,"D","اِبْتَئَسَ","«بِئْس» conveys the meanings of hardship and aversion (intransitive), and «اِبْتَئَسَ» means to find something disagreeable and to grieve over it (transitive). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ اُوۡحِیَ  اِلٰی نُوۡحٍ اَنَّہٗ  لَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنَ مِنۡ قَوۡمِکَ اِلَّا مَنۡ قَدۡ اٰمَنَ فَلَا تَبۡتَئِسۡ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡعَلُوۡنَ» (11/36). Translation: And it was revealed to Noah that from now on, none of your people will believe except those who have already believed. So do not grieve over what they do.","«اِبْتَئَسَ» to be afflicted with grief due to another's objectionable and intolerable deed.","Deep sorrow","ابتئس","11:36-12:69",2
2095,451,"C","تَفَکَّرَ","«اَلْفِکْرَۃ»: The faculty that leads knowledge to the known is called (muf). And «تَفَکّر» means to think, to contemplate. To deliberate (munjad) means to reflect on the various aspects of a matter. «فِکْر ، اَفْکَر ، فَکَّر» and «تَفَکَّر» are all near-synonyms. «فِکْر» means 'thought' and its plural is «اَفْکَار». (munjad) also means to reflect on the evidence in a matter. (Fiqh 58)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says: «کَذٰلِکَ یُبَیِّنُ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمُ الۡاٰیٰتِ لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَتَفَکَّرُوۡنَ» (2/219) Translation: Thus Allah makes His signs clear to you so that you may contemplate.","«تَفَکّر» to ponder over the different aspects and arguments of a matter.","Contemplation","تفکر","2:219-2:266-3:191-6:50-7:176-7:184-10:24-13:3-16:11-16:44-16:69-30:8-30:21-34:46-39:42-45:13-59:21",17
2096,451,"R","تَدَبُّر","«دُبْر» refers to the back, rear, or posterior part of something. And «اَدْبَر» means to turn one's back (turning away). While «تَدَبُّر» means to ponder over the completion or outcome of a matter; to reflect upon the results, then formulate a plan of action accordingly. And this very concept is termed as Tadbir (planning).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَفَلَمۡ  یَدَّبَّرُوا الۡقَوۡلَ اَمۡ  جَآءَہُمۡ  مَّا لَمۡ یَاۡتِ  اٰبَآءَہُمُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (23/68)\nTranslation: Have they not reflected upon this discourse, or has there come to them something that did not come to their forefathers?","«تَدَبّر» to oversee the outcome of a matter and to devise a plan of action for it.","Reflection","تدبر","4:82-10:3-10:31-13:2-23:68-32:5-38:29-47:24-79:5",9
2097,451,"C","تَفَقُّہ","«اَلفِقْہ» means to exert effort to reach knowledge from absence to presence (intransitive): to find something and thereby gain knowledge of it. Then this knowledge became specific to Shariah (transitive). Every scholar who understands the reality of what is lawful and unlawful is a jurist (faqih), and «تَفَقُّہ» refers to this: by contemplating several known things or rulings, one arrives at the ruling for an issue for which no explicit text exists. To form an understanding.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (9/122)\nTranslation: Then why is it that not a small group from every faction among them should have devoted themselves to gaining a deep understanding in religion?","«تَفَقّہ» Reflecting upon known matters to develop understanding and thereby finding solutions to analogous problems.","Contemplation","تفقہ","4:78-6:25-6:65-6:98-7:179-8:65-9:81-9:87-9:122-9:127-11:91-17:44-17:46-18:57-18:93-20:28-48:15-59:13-63:3-63:7",20
2098,451,"C","اِدَّکَرَ","«ذَکَرَ» means to remember something, to preserve it. And «ذَکَّر» means to remind someone of something in such a way that they may derive advice from it. And «اِدَّکَرَ» means to bring something to mind oneself, to reflect upon it (M. R). To pay attention and ponder over it so that one may derive advice for oneself.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ یَسَّرۡنَا الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  لِلذِّکۡرِ  فَہَلۡ مِنۡ مُّدَّکِرٍ» ( 54/17 )\nTranslation: And indeed, We have made the Quran easy to remember. So is there any who will remember?","Recalling a matter, reflecting upon it, and then deriving admonition from it.","Contemplation","ادکر","12:45-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51",7
2099,451,"C","اِسْتَنْبَط","«اِسْتَنْبَط» refers to the water drawn for the first time after digging a well, which is called «نَبْط». And «نَبْط» means drawing water from the bottom of the well. And «اِسْتَنْبَاط» is used in the sense of extraction (istikhraj), while «اِسْتَنْبَط» means to reveal after concealment, to extract by choice, to innovate, or for a jurist to derive something from their own understanding and reasoning (minj). «اِسْتَنْبَاط» is in fact a type of ijtihad or tafaqquh wherein one reflects deeply within known knowledge, reaches its essence, and derives subsidiary issues or outcomes from it.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ لَوۡ رَدُّوۡہُ  اِلَی الرَّسُوۡلِ وَ اِلٰۤی اُولِی الۡاَمۡرِ مِنۡہُمۡ لَعَلِمَہُ الَّذِیۡنَ یَسۡتَنۡۢبِطُوۡنَہٗ مِنۡہُمۡ» (4:83) Translation: And if they had referred the matter to their Prophet or their chiefs, they would have verified it.","«اِسْتَنْبَط» To contemplate established knowledge and thereby extract subsidiary (derived) issues or derive results.","contemplation / deliberation / profound reflection","استنبط","4:83",1
2100,452,"B","نَفَعَ","«نَفَع» means to receive something good or a part of it; to be beneficial. (See root letters: م, ل). Its opposite is «ضَرَر», meaning hardship or loss. Its usage is common.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«قُلۡ  اَفَاتَّخَذۡتُمۡ  مِّنۡ  دُوۡنِہٖۤ  اَوۡلِیَآءَ  لَا یَمۡلِکُوۡنَ لِاَنۡفُسِہِمۡ نَفۡعًا وَّ لَا ضَرًّا» (13/16)\nTranslation: Why have you taken besides Allah protectors who do not possess any power for benefit or harm?","«نَفَع» to be granted a share of goodness. Its opposite is «ضَرَر».","Benefit","نفع","2:102-2:123-2:164-2:219-4:11-5:76-5:119-6:71-6:158-7:188-10:18-10:49-10:98-10:106-11:34-12:21-13:16-13:17-16:5-20:89-20:109-21:66-22:12-22:13-22:28-22:33-23:21-25:3-25:55-26:73-26:88-28:9-30:57-32:29-33:16-34:23-34:42-36:73-40:52-40:80-40:85-43:39-48:11-51:55-57:25-60:3-74:48-80:4-87:9",49
2101,452,"B","مَتَّعَ","«مَتَاع» means every thing from the provisions of life from which a human or any living being derives benefit to sustain its life. And its plurals are «أَمْتِعَة» and «مَتَّع». Meaning to derive benefit from such provisions.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَخۡرَجَ  مِنۡہَا مَآءَہَا وَ  مَرۡعٰہَا وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا مَتَاعًا  لَّکُمۡ  وَ  لِاَنۡعَامِکُمۡ» (79/31,32,33)\nTranslation: He has brought forth water from the earth and grown vegetation and placed firm mountains on it—all for your benefit and that of your livestock.\n\nAnd «مَتَّعَ» means to provide someone with such provisions from which they can derive benefit. To confer benefit.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ مَتِّعُوۡہُنَّ ۚ عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَ عَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ» (2/236)\nTranslation: But give them a provision—the wealthy according to his means and the poor according to his means—an obligation upon the righteous.\n\nAnd «تَمَتَّعَ» means to derive benefit for oneself. To enjoy.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ» (11/65)\nTranslation: Enjoy yourselves in your homes for three days.","«مَتَّعَ» To benefit from all things that any living being, including humans, relies on for survival.","Benefit","متع","2:126-2:196-2:236-4:24-6:128-9:69-10:98-11:3-11:48-11:65-14:30-15:3-15:88-16:55-20:131-21:44-25:18-26:205-26:207-28:61-29:66-30:34-31:24-33:16-33:28-33:49-37:148-39:8-43:29-46:20-47:12-51:43-77:46",33
2102,452,"B","رَبِحَ","«رَبِحَ» is the profit that is gained from buying and selling (i.e., profit in trade goods). And its opposite is «خَسِرَ», meaning loss.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَا رَبِحَتۡ تِّجَارَتُہُمۡ وَ مَا کَانُوۡا مُہۡتَدِیۡنَ» (2/16)\nTranslation: So their trade did not bring them any profit, nor were they guided.","to profit from trade goods","Benefit","ربح","2:16",1
2103,452,"B","مَاٰرِب","«اَرْب» means a severe need without which one cannot subsist, and effort is made to obtain it (mufradat). It also signifies need, necessity, and extremity (manjada). And «مَارِب ، مَارِبَۃ ، مَارَبَہ» and «مَارُبَۃ» mean need and its completion. And its plural is «مَارَب». And it also refers to the thing through which that need is fulfilled.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ وَ لِیَ فِیۡہَا مَاٰرِبُ  اُخۡرٰی» (20:18)\nTranslation: Moses said, This is my staff; I lean on it and I use it to beat down leaves for my sheep, and I have other uses for it.","«مَاٰرِب» necessities and the means for their fulfillment.","Benefit","مارب","20:18-24:31",2
2104,453,"C","فَتَحَ","«فَتْح» means to remove obstruction and complexity from something (intransitive). This word is used in all meanings such as to open, to decide, and to grant victory. Its opposite is «اِغْلَاق». When this word is used in the context of confronting an enemy for «فَتَح», its meaning is a clear and evident victory after which the enemy has no doubt regarding their defeat. Its opposite is «ھَزِیْمَت», meaning defeat, retreat.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذَا  جَآءَ  نَصۡرُ اللّٰہِ  وَ  الۡفَتۡحُ وَ  رَاَیۡتَ النَّاسَ یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ فِیۡ  دِیۡنِ اللّٰہِ  اَفۡوَاجًا» (110:1,2)\nTranslation: When the help of Allah came and victory was attained, you saw the people entering the religion of Allah in multitudes.","The word «فَتْح» is used solely to denote supremacy.","Conquest","فتح","2:89-4:141-5:52-48:1-48:18-48:27-57:10-61:13-110:1",9
2105,453,"C","اَظْفَرَ","«ظَفَر» means human or animal nails. And «ظَفَرَ فُلَانٌ» means so-and-so has driven his nails into it, or has achieved a victory (masc.). And «اَظْفَرَ» means to grant such a victory that nails are driven into the enemy's chest. That is, victory and, thereafter, dominance over the enemy. In the words of Ibn al-Farisi, «یَدُلُّ عَلَی الْقَھْرِ وَ الْفَوْزِ وَ الْغَلَبَۃِ ».\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ کَفَّ  اَیۡدِیَہُمۡ  عَنۡکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ عَنۡہُمۡ بِبَطۡنِ مَکَّۃَ  مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  اَظۡفَرَکُمۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (48/24)\n\nTranslation: And He is the One Who, after granting you victory over them (the disbelievers), restrained their hands from you and your hands from them in the sacred territory of Mecca.","«اَظْفَرَ» a victory so complete that nails pierce the enemy's chest—that is, victory followed by dominance over the enemy.","Conquest","اظفر","48:24",1
2106,454,"P","مَیْسَرَۃ","«یُسْر» means ease, and its opposite «عُسْر» means hardship. «مَیْسَرَۃ» means the time of ease—a time when a person can manage their livelihood comfortably from a financial perspective.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2/280)  \nTranslation: And if the debtor is in hardship, then grant him respite until a time of ease.","«مَیْسَرَۃ» ease after hardship.","prosperity","میسرۃ","2:280",1
2107,454,"A","طَوْل","«طُوْل» means length, extension, and (the length of) time. The term «طَوْل» is used to denote favor and grace that is not merely temporary (permanent), and it also signifies sustenance, expenses, and the expenditures of livelihood—bounty, forgiveness, independence (etc.). For example, the Holy Quran states: «وَ مَنۡ لَّمۡ یَسۡتَطِعۡ مِنۡکُمۡ طَوۡلًا اَنۡ یَّنۡکِحَ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتِ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ فَمِنۡ مَّا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ مِّنۡ فَتَیٰتِکُمُ الۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ » (4/25) Translation: Those among you who cannot afford to marry free Muslim women may marry those Muslim slave women whom you own. And «اُوْلُوا الطَّوْل» refers to those who can easily manage their time and resources (9/86).","To be the guarantor of the passage of time.","Abundance","طول","4:25-9:86-40:3",3
2108,454,"A","بَسْطَۃ","«بَسَطَ» means to open and spread. And its opposites are also «قَبْض» and «قَدْر». And «بَسْطَۃً» means spaciousness (of place), abundance, and plenty (metaphorical), whether this abundance is in wealth and property or in any other thing. This word is used in all ways, both materially and spiritually.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ زَادَہٗ بَسۡطَۃً فِی الۡعِلۡمِ وَ الۡجِسۡمِ» (2/247)\nTranslation: Allah has chosen them over you by giving them superiority and has granted them greater expanse in knowledge and physique.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ مِنۡ عِبَادِہٖ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ  لَہٗ» (29/62)\nTranslation: Allah alone expands the provision for whichever of His servants He wills and restricts it for whichever He wills.","Whether there is abundance and spaciousness in something.","Abundance","بسطۃ","2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19",22
2109,454,"A","سَعَۃً","«وَسِعَ» means to have expanse and capacity in something. And «اَلْوُسْعُ» means abundance of sustenance, richness. (M. L) And the opposite of «وُسْعَۃ» is also «ضِیْق» and «عُسْر» as well (M. L). And «سَعَۃَ» is used for abundance of sustenance. And «اُولُوا السَّعَۃ» means those people who, beyond their daily expenses, can save something from their income and have the capacity to give charities and alms.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ لَا یَاۡتَلِ اُولُوا الۡفَضۡلِ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ السَّعَۃِ  اَنۡ یُّؤۡتُوۡۤا  اُولِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ» (24/22) Translation: And those among you who are affluent and possess wealth should not swear that they will not give to relatives, the poor, and those who emigrate in the cause of Allah.","«اُولُوا السَّعَۃ» Such people who, beyond their basic sustenance and needs, can save something from their income and have the means to give in charity and perform good deeds.","Abundance","سعۃً","2:247-4:130-24:22-65:7",4
2110,454,"P","رَحِبَ ، رَحُبَ","«رَحُب» means the openness or spaciousness of a place. It is used solely to denote spatial expanse. The state of a place or location being open/spacious, and its opposite is «ضَاقَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ ضَاقَتۡ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡاَرۡضُ بِمَا رَحُبَتۡ» (9:25)\nTranslation: And the earth, despite its spaciousness, became constricted for them.\n\nAnd the word «مَرْحَبْ» is used in the context of supplication, meaning welcome. For a curse, they say «لَا مَرْحَبًا», meaning May you have no space or opportunity.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا مَرۡحَبًۢا بِہِمۡ ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ صَالُوا النَّارِ» (38:59)\nTranslation: Curse them! They will also enter the Hellfire.","«رَحُب» is used solely to create extra space.","Prosperity","رحب ، رحب","9:25-9:118-38:59-38:60",4
2111,454,"A","وَسِعَ","«وَسِعَ» applies to both place and condition. Meaning: spaciousness, expansiveness, breadth, capacity (CAPACITY). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَسِعَ کُرۡسِیُّہُ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ» (2/255) Translation: The heavens and the earth are encompassed in His Throne. Also, the Divine saying is: «لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا» (2/286) Translation: Allah does not burden any soul beyond its capacity. And «اَوْسَعَ» means to be very wealthy. And «اَوْسَعَ الْمَوْضَعَ» means to make the space wide (munjad). For example: The Divine saying is: «وَ السَّمَآءَ  بَنَیۡنٰہَا بِاَیۡىدٍ وَّ اِنَّا لَمُوۡسِعُوۡنَ» (51/47) Translation: We have built the heaven with Our own hands and, indeed, We are the Expanders.","«وَسِعَ» applies to both spatial capacity and conditional state, regardless of the context. And «اَوْسَعَ» means to expand a place.","Abundance","وسع","2:115-2:233-2:236-2:247-2:255-2:261-2:268-2:286-3:73-4:97-4:100-4:130-5:54-6:80-6:147-6:152-7:42-7:89-7:156-20:98-23:62-24:32-29:56-39:10-40:7-51:47-53:32",27
2112,454,"A","تَفَسَّحَ","«فَسَحَ» means to spread one's feet/step widely. And «تَفَسَّحَ فِی الْمَجْلِس» means to make space in a gathering. That is, to sit in such an open manner that space becomes available for others (to sit).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا یَفۡسَحِ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ» (58/11)  \nTranslation: When it is said to you, Make room in the assemblies, then make room; Allah will make room for you.","«تَفَسَّحَ» to sit in such a way that space becomes available for others.","Abundance","تفسح","58:11",1
2113,455,"A","مَلَک","«مَلَک» is the singular form, and «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is its plural. Its root is «لأک», which means to convey a message. «اَلْاَکَۃُ اِلٰی فُلَانٍ» means to convey a message to someone. And «اَلِکْنِیْ» means to deliver a message from me. And «مَلَأک» and «مَلَک» mean a messenger angel (manjūd). And «مَلَک» is used as a term for an angel in the legislative sense, and this specification is not necessarily that it must be a messenger. Angels are commissioned by Allah Almighty for the administration of the universe. The angel of clouds, the angel of death, the angels of Paradise and Hell—for all of them, the words «مَلَک» and «مَلٰئِکَۃ» are used, even though they are not messengers. And sometimes, when a message from Allah Almighty occurs in the form of a hidden call or a caller from the unseen (i.e., one calling from the unseen), the plural form «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is used instead of «مَلَک».\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3/45)\nTranslation: And when the angels said, O Mary! Allah gives you glad tidings of a word from Him, whose name will be the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary.\n\nWhy the plural form «مَلٰئِکَۃ» was used at this instance or similar instances instead of the singular «مَلَک» is beyond human comprehension.","«مَلَک», the angel who delivers the message.","angel","ملک","2:30-2:31-2:34-2:98-2:102-2:161-2:177-2:210-2:248-2:285-3:18-3:39-3:42-3:45-3:80-3:87-3:124-3:125-4:97-4:136-4:166-4:172-6:8-6:9-6:50-6:93-6:111-6:158-7:11-7:20-8:9-8:12-8:50-11:12-11:31-12:31-13:13-13:23-15:7-15:8-15:28-15:30-16:2-16:28-16:32-16:33-16:49-17:40-17:61-17:92-17:95-18:50-20:116-21:103-22:75-23:24-25:7-25:21-25:22-25:25-32:11-33:43-33:56-34:40-35:1-37:150-38:71-38:73-39:75-41:14-41:30-42:5-43:19-43:53-43:60-47:27-53:26-53:27-66:4-66:6-69:17-70:4-74:31-78:38-89:22-97:4",86
2114,455,"A","رُوْح","Just as knowledge of the soul's true nature has been given to humans in very limited measure, comprehending the meanings of the spirit is also beyond human capacity. The term spirit (روح) has been used in the Quran to mean mercy, as well as revelation and the Quran, and also to mean angel. The angel specifically commissioned by Allah Almighty to deliver messages to the prophets is named Jibril. Allah Almighty has addressed him by the titles of the Spirit (روح), the Trusted Spirit (روح الامین), and the Noble Messenger (رسول کریم). And the angel who came to Maryam (peace be upon her) and delivered Allah's message in human form is referred to as the Spirit in Surah Maryam, and in Surah Al-Imran, instead of «مَلَک», the term «مَلٰئِکَۃ» is used. The interpreters are of the opinion that this spirit was Jibril. This is possible and also permissible. Maryam (peace be upon her) was not a prophetess. Nevertheless, Jibril (peace be upon him) or some other angel or angels came to her. Allah's message was delivered, and He conversed with her. This message was specifically related to Maryam's own self. To convey it to others was out of the question; the message had no connection whatsoever with others in matters necessary for prophethood and messengership.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہَا رُوۡحَنَا فَتَمَثَّلَ لَہَا بَشَرًا سَوِیًّا» (19/17)\nTranslation: We sent to Maryam Our angel, who appeared before her in the form of a perfect man.","The angel who is commissioned by Allah Almighty to deliver messages to the prophets.","angel","روح","2:87-2:253-4:171-5:110-15:29-16:2-16:102-17:85-19:17-21:91-26:193-32:9-38:72-40:15-42:52-58:22-66:12-70:4-78:38-97:4",20
2115,456,"D","بُعْد","«بَعِد» and «بَعُد» mean to be distant. The original meaning of «بُعْد» is also distant. However, this word is also used in the senses of distance and curse, particularly in the context of evil supplication. When used as a spatial adverb, it conveys the meaning of separation or distance.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَنَا قَالَ یٰلَیۡتَ بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَکَ بُعۡدَ الۡمَشۡرِقَیۡنِ فَبِئۡسَ الۡقَرِیۡنُ» (43:38)\n\nTranslation: Until, when such a person comes to us, he will say to his satanic companion, I wish there were the distance of east and west between me and you, for you were a terrible companion.","«بُعْد» is used to denote distance and difference.","Difference","بعد","9:42-11:44-11:60-11:68-11:95-21:101-23:41-23:44-43:38",9
2116,456,"D","تَفَاوُت","«تَفَاوُت» meaning difference, disparity, deficiency, and excess. And its opposite is «اِسْتَوَاء», meaning uniformity, equality, or being equal. And «اِسْتَوَاء فَاتَ الْاَمْر» meaning the time of a task slipping from one's grasp and being irretrievable. And «تَفَاوَتَ الشَّیْئَیْن» meaning two things being different, separate, and incompatible; this word always carries negative connotations. And «فَات» meaning something being so far from a person that acquiring it becomes difficult. And «تَفَاوُت» also means two things having different attributes, as if each attribute negates the other.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«مَا تَرٰی فِیۡ  خَلۡقِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ مِنۡ  تَفٰوُتٍ» (67:3)\nTranslation: You will not see any disparity in the creation of the Most Merciful.\nMeaning all things in the universe are in perfect compatibility and harmony.","Difference arising from the distinct attributes of two things; incompatibility.","Difference","تفاوت","67:3",1
2117,457,"S","فِرْقَۃَ","«فَرَقَ» meaning to separate, to split. And «فِرْق» meaning a separated part (26/63). And «فِرْقَۃ» meaning a group of numerous and like-minded people separated from a larger community or faction (i.e., a distinct faction or sect). For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَوۡ لَا نَفَرَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فِرۡقَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ طَآئِفَۃٌ  لِّیَتَفَقَّہُوۡا فِی الدِّیۡنِ» (9/122)\nTranslation: So why should not a party (or group) from every larger community among them separate (to strive in the cause of Allah), so that those who remain behind may gain understanding in religion by their teaching?","A separate group of people distinct from a large crowd.","sect","فرقۃ","9:122",1
2118,457,"S","فَرِیْق","«فِرْقَۃ» and «فَرِیْق» are approximately synonymous. The usage of «فَرِیْق» occurs when there is another party present or mentioned in opposition to it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَرِیۡقٌ فِی الۡجَنَّۃِ  وَ فَرِیۡقٌ فِی السَّعِیۡرِ» (42:7)\nTranslation: One party will be in Paradise and the other in Hell.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«اَیُّ الۡفَرِیۡقَیۡنِ خَیۡرٌ  مَّقَامًا وَّ اَحۡسَنُ نَدِیًّا» (19:73)\nTranslation: Of the two parties, whose residence is better and whose assemblies are more excellent?","The sect to which another sect exists or is mentioned in opposition.","Sect","فریق","2:75-2:85-2:87-2:100-2:101-2:146-2:188-3:23-3:78-3:100-4:77-5:70-6:81-7:30-8:5-9:107-9:117-11:24-16:54-19:73-23:109-24:47-24:48-27:45-30:33-33:13-33:26-34:20-42:7",29
2119,457,"S","طَائِفَۃ","«طَائِفَۃ» is a term that, according to some people of opinion and religion (mufassirin), can be applied even to the smallest group or a single individual. As certain interpreters state regarding this verse. The Divine directive says:\n«وَ اِنۡ طَآئِفَتٰنِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ اقۡتَتَلُوۡا فَاَصۡلِحُوۡا بَیۡنَہُمَا» ( 49/9 )\nTranslation: If two parties from among the believers fall into conflict, then make peace between them.\nIn this verse, the word «طَائِفَۃ» has been applied to a single individual.","«طَائِفَۃ» a small group of like-minded people of the same faith.","Sect","طائفۃ","3:69-3:72-3:122-3:154-4:81-4:102-4:113-6:156-7:87-8:7-9:66-9:83-9:122-24:2-28:4-33:13-49:9-61:14-73:20",19
2120,457,"S","زُمَر","«زُمَر» is the plural of «زُمْرَہ», meaning 'group'. When a large congregation or army divides into small groups or squads for movement, such groups are called «زُمُر» (see details under 'Congregation'). For example, in the Quran: «وَ سِیۡقَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّقَوۡا رَبَّہُمۡ  اِلَی الۡجَنَّۃِ زُمَرًا» (39/73). Translation: And the righteous will be taken to Paradise in groups.","«زُمَر» meaning small groups or teams.","Sect","زمر","39:71-39:73",2
2121,457,"S","شِیْعَۃ","«شِیْعَۃ» meaning party, faction, political group. The people from whom an individual derives strength and who remain spread around him (muf) are someone's followers and helpers (munjad). The foundation of such a party or faction is usually a difference in belief.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَوَجَدَ فِیۡہَا رَجُلَیۡنِ یَقۡتَتِلٰنِ ٭۫ ہٰذَا مِنۡ شِیۡعَتِہٖ وَ ہٰذَا مِنۡ عَدُوِّہٖ» (28/15)\nTranslation: Then Moses (peace be upon him) saw in the city two men fighting, one from his own party and the other from the party of his enemy (Pharaoh).\n\nThe plural of «شِیْعَۃ» is also «شِیَعًا» and «اَشْیَاعَ». «اَشْیَاع» means people who possess similar habits and customs, whether they are from the past or present. Those of the same kind.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ حِیۡلَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَ مَا یَشۡتَہُوۡنَ کَمَا فُعِلَ بِاَشۡیَاعِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلُ» (34/54)\nTranslation: And a barrier will be placed between them and what they desire, just as was done with their predecessors of the same kind.","«شِیْعَۃ» A party or faction based on differences in creed.","Sect","شیعۃ","6:65-6:159-15:10-19:69-28:4-28:15-30:32-34:54-37:87-54:51",10
2122,457,"S","اُنَاس","«اُنَاس» groups formed by division (i.e., based on capability and competence) or separate groups belonging to different tribes (some consider no difference between «نَاس» and «اُنَاس»).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (2/60)  \nTranslation: Each group recognized its own watering place.","«اُنَاس» distinct groups affiliated with different tribes.","Sect","اناس","2:60-7:82-7:160-17:71-27:56",5
2123,458,"H","اِسْتَجَاب","«جَابَ» means to carve stone. And «اَجَابَ» means referring to speech, i.e., answering a question. And «سَئَلَ» also comes in two meanings: (1) to inquire about something, (2) to request or demand something. Therefore, «اَجَابَ» also comes in both meanings: (1) in the sense of answering a question.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ یَجۡمَعُ اللّٰہُ الرُّسُلَ فَیَقُوۡلُ مَا ذَاۤ اُجِبۡتُمۡ» (5/109)\nTranslation: On the Day when Allah will gather the messengers, He will then ask them, What response did you receive?\n\n(2) And in the context of requesting something, it would mean to accept in that case.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«اَمَّنۡ یُّجِیۡبُ الۡمُضۡطَرَّ اِذَا دَعَاہُ» (27/62)\nTranslation: Who accepts the supplication of the distressed when he calls upon Him?\n\nAnd «اِسْتِجَاب» means to accept supplication, i.e., to fulfill the need of the caller or grant the plea, especially when invoked.\nFor example: The divine declaration of the Exalted is:\n«وَ نُوۡحًا اِذۡ نَادٰی مِنۡ قَبۡلُ فَاسۡتَجَبۡنَا لَہٗ فَنَجَّیۡنٰہُ وَ اَہۡلَہٗ مِنَ الۡکَرۡبِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (21/76)\nTranslation: Remember Noah when he called out before, and We accepted his supplication and saved him and his family from the great distress.","«اِسْتَجَاب» a prayer which Allah, the Most High, grants the honor of acceptance.","Heartfelt plea","استجاب","2:186-3:172-3:195-6:36-7:194-8:9-8:24-11:14-12:34-13:14-13:18-17:52-28:50-28:64-35:14-42:16-42:26-42:38-42:47-46:5",20
2124,458,"D","اَصْرَخَ","«صَرَخَ» means to scream, to cry out so that someone may hear the cry. And «صَرِیْخ» means for the cry to reach (36/43). And «اَصْرَخَ» also carries the same meaning. For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated: «فَلَا تَلُوۡمُوۡنِیۡ وَ لُوۡمُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَکُمۡ ؕ مَاۤ  اَنَا بِمُصۡرِخِکُمۡ وَ مَاۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ بِمُصۡرِخِیَّ» (14/22). Translation: Satan will say to his followers, Do not blame me, but blame yourselves. I cannot be your helper, nor can you be mine.","«اَصْرَخَ» To bring aid to those who cry out and shout in times of calamity.","Desperate cry","اصرخ","14:22-28:18-35:37",3
2125,458,"D","استغاث","«غَاثَ» means to aid or assist someone in times of difficulty (m. l.). And «غَیْث» refers to the rain that occurs both timely and as required. Furthermore, the meaning of «اِسْتِغَاث» also includes praying to God for such rain, as well as seeking aid and help from God or another ruler during times of hardship. Istighatha is a well-known term, meaning to complain of injustice or oppression before a ruler or a court.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ» (8/9)\nTranslation: When you cried out to your Lord for help, He heard your cry.","«اِسْتِغَاث» When an appeal to Allah or a de facto ruler is presented, the term 'istighatha' is used.","Desperate cry","استغاث","8:9-18:29-28:15-46:17",4
2126,458,"D","اِسْتَصْرَخ","«اِسْتَصْرَخ» means to cry out and make one's plea heard to the common people, seeking their assistance.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18)\nTranslation: So at that time, the man who had sought help from Moses (AS) the previous day began to cry out before them again.","When the public is summoned through proclamation, the term «اِسْتَصْرَخ» will be used.","Desperate plea","استصرخ","14:22-28:18",2
2127,459,"M","اَفْسَدَ","«فَسَدَ» means to spoil or ruin something. And «اَفْسَدَ» means to corrupt something and cause its ruin. «فَسَاد» is the opposite of «اِصْلَاح». The term «فَسَاد» is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reformation.","The application of «اَفْسَدَ» can occur even upon a single act of causing corruption. And when «فَسَاد» takes the form of a habit, «عَاثَ» will follow. Moreover, the real issue in «نَزَغَ» is interference, whether it be in one matter or many. Then, spread corruption among them.","Mischief","افسد","2:11-2:12-2:27-2:30-2:60-2:205-2:220-2:251-3:63-5:32-5:33-5:64-7:56-7:74-7:85-7:86-7:103-7:127-7:142-8:73-10:40-10:81-10:91-11:85-11:116-12:73-13:25-16:88-17:4-18:94-21:22-23:71-26:152-26:183-27:14-27:34-27:48-28:4-28:77-28:83-29:30-29:36-30:41-38:28-40:26-47:22-89:12",47
2128,459,"C","عَثَا","«عَثَا» or «عَاث» means to spread corruption, to cause disorder and corruption.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ لَا تَعۡثَوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُفۡسِدِیۡنَ» (2/60)  \nTranslation: And do not spread corruption in the land.  \n\nSome linguists have written the root of «تَعْثَوْا» as «ع ث ی», meaning «عَثِیَ یَعْثٰی عَثِیًّا» (mufrad). This pertains to mental and intellectual corruption, such as the dissemination of false beliefs and ideologies through literature or speeches. Others have written its root as «ع ی ث», meaning «عَاثَ یَعِیْثُ عَثِیًّا» (mufrad), which indicates physical or material corruption (m l), such as committing injustice and oppression against someone. In both cases, the negative form «لَا تَعْثَوْا» is used.","«عَثَا» meaning to cause corruption.","Corruption","عثا","2:60-7:74-11:85-26:183-29:36",5
2129,459,"C","نَزَغَ","«نَزَغَ» means to cause corruption between two things (M.L.) and to create a dispute. To instigate. To spoil. To incite a fight. To sow enmity (M.Q.) and to mean to spoil a matter and interfere in it (Muf) or to cause corruption by interfering and creating discord.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ اَنۡ  نَّزَغَ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  بَیۡنِیۡ وَ بَیۡنَ اِخۡوَتِیۡ» (12/100)\nTranslation: After that, Satan had caused discord between me and my brothers.","«نَزَغَ» meaning to sow discord between two things.","Corruption","نزغ","7:200-12:100-17:53-41:36",4
2130,460,"W","اَلْغٰی","«لَغَا» meaning to speak without thought or reflection; foolish talk (munjad) and meaning to chirp like birds. And similarly, repeatedly mentioning something (M. Q). And «اَلْغٰی» means to chatter and jabber in such a way that the listener's words are drowned out in the noise, so that others also cannot hear.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَا تَسۡمَعُوۡا لِہٰذَا الۡقُرۡاٰنِ وَ الۡغَوۡا فِیۡہِ  لَعَلَّکُمۡ تَغۡلِبُوۡنَ» (41/26)\nTranslation: And the disbelievers said, Do not listen to this Quran and make noise while it is being recited, so that you may prevail.","«اَلْغٰی» To whisper in such a way that others cannot hear.","Wasteful","الغی","2:225-5:89-19:62-23:3-25:72-28:55-41:26-52:23-56:25-78:35-88:11",11
2131,460,"W","خَاض","«خَاض» meaning to immerse oneself. «خَاضَ فِی الْمَاءِ» to plunge into water. «خَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْث» to be engrossed in conversations (or tasks) and to mean entering between things (m. l.), i.e., to be completely absorbed in talks or works. In the Quran, this term is primarily used to denote remaining engaged in idle or futile talks or activities (muf).\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا  رَاَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَخُوۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اٰیٰتِنَا فَاَعۡرِضۡ عَنۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی یَخُوۡضُوۡا فِیۡ حَدِیۡثٍ غَیۡرِہٖ» (6/68)\nTranslation: When you see those who engage in idle gossip about Our verses, turn away from them until they become preoccupied with another matter.","to become involved in idle talk or futile actions","Wasteful","خاض","4:140-6:68-6:91-9:65-9:69-43:83-52:12-70:42-74:45",9
2132,460,"F","فَکِہَ","«فَکِہَ» meaning to engage in cheerful banter. To laugh and make others laugh (Fall 145). And «فَکَاھَۃ» meaning pleasant talks (source). And «تَفَکَّہَ بِعِرْضِ فَلَانٍ» meaning to take pleasure in backbiting someone (source), to derive enjoyment from gossip.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا  انۡقَلَبُوۡۤا  اِلٰۤی  اَہۡلِہِمُ  انۡقَلَبُوۡا فَکِہِیۡنَ» (83/31)\nTranslation: And when they return to their homes, they return jesting.","«فَکِہَ» A jest that brings delight, cheerful banter.","Futile","فکہ","83:31",1
2133,460,"W","سَمَرَ","«سَمَر» Narrating stories and tales before sleeping at night. Talks before sleeping. Storytelling (detailed/brief).","Telling stories and tales at night before going to sleep.","Wasteful","سمر","23:67",1
2134,460,"S","ھَجَرَ یَھْجُرُ","«ھَجَر» To speak nonsense. To babble. (masc.) «ھِجْر» Meaning inappropriate speech. Evil talk. Nonsensical babbling (collected). To mutter in sleep or illness (m. q.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«مُسۡتَکۡبِرِیۡنَ ٭ۖ بِہٖ سٰمِرًا تَہۡجُرُوۡنَ» (23/67)\nTranslation: They used to rebel, engage in stories, and speak nonsense.","«ھَجَر» to mutter in sleep or illness and talk nonsense.","Supererogatory","ھجر یھجر","23:67",1
2135,460,"W","اَسْرَفَ","«سَرَفَ» and «اَسْرَفَ» mean to exceed the limits of moderation (excessive), and its usage pertains to spending more than necessary in wealth or food and drink. And the limit of moderation is that which pertains to something permissible (i.e., something allowed in Sharia) or lawful. Thus, the meaning of *israf* (extravagance) is to spend beyond necessity in permissible acts. For example: the Noble Quran states:\n«کُلُوۡا وَ اشۡرَبُوۡا وَ لَا  تُسۡرِفُوۡا» (7/31)\nTranslation: Eat and drink, but do not be excessive.","«اَسْرَفَ» is used for wasteful spending in permissible matters.","Wasteful","اسرف","5:32-6:141-7:31-7:81-10:12-10:83-17:33-20:127-21:9-25:67-26:151-36:19-39:53-40:28-40:34-40:43-43:5-44:31-51:34",19
2136,460,"P","بَذَّرَ","«بِذْر» and «بَذَرَ» mean seed. And «بَذَّرَ» means scattering seed. So just as seed is scattered in the earth, similarly, if wealth is scattered, it is called «تَبْذِیْر» (meaning). It implies that whether the need is legitimate or not, spending wealth extravagantly on it is called «تَبْذِیْر» (meaning). And this act is even worse than extravagance. For example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «وَ لَا  تُبَذِّرۡ  تَبۡذِیۡرًا اِنَّ الۡمُبَذِّرِیۡنَ کَانُوۡۤا اِخۡوَانَ الشَّیٰطِیۡنِ» (17/26,27). Translation: And do not squander in extravagance. Verily, the squanderers are the brothers of the devils.","«بَذَّرَ» to misappropriate and squander wealth.","Prodigal","بذر","17:26-17:27",2
2137,460,"U","فَضَّلَ","«فَضْل» means the state of something good exceeding its due balance and moderate degree. And «فَضَّلَ» means granting someone, out of kindness, more than their rightful share in something good.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰبَنِیۡۤ  اِسۡرَآءِیۡلَ اذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَتِیَ الَّتِیۡۤ  اَنۡعَمۡتُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ وَ اَنِّیۡ فَضَّلۡتُکُمۡ عَلَی الۡعٰلَمِیۡنَ» (2/122)\nTranslation: O Children of Israel! Remember My favor which I bestowed upon you and that I preferred you over the worlds.","The abundance of something good.","unfounded","فضل","2:47-2:64-2:90-2:105-2:122-2:198-2:237-2:243-2:251-2:253-2:268-3:73-3:74-3:152-3:170-3:171-3:174-3:180-4:32-4:34-4:37-4:54-4:70-4:73-4:83-4:95-4:113-4:173-4:175-5:2-5:54-6:86-7:39-7:140-8:29-9:28-9:59-9:74-9:75-9:76-10:58-10:60-10:107-11:3-11:27-12:38-13:4-16:14-16:71-17:12-17:21-17:48-17:55-17:66-17:70-17:87-23:24-24:10-24:14-24:20-24:21-24:22-24:32-24:33-24:38-27:15-27:16-27:40-27:73-28:73-30:23-30:45-30:46-33:47-34:10-35:12-35:30-35:32-35:35-40:61-42:22-42:26-44:57-45:12-45:16-48:29-49:8-57:21-57:29-59:8-62:4-62:10-73:20",93
2138,460,"S","کَرَّمَ","«کَرَم» denotes an honor that is intrinsic to something or arises from its inherent nature. And «کَرَّمَ» signifies the act of instilling the essence of excellence into something. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَقَدۡ کَرَّمۡنَا بَنِیۡۤ  اٰدَمَ وَ حَمَلۡنٰہُمۡ  فِی الۡبَرِّ وَ الۡبَحۡرِ» (17/70). Translation: And We have bestowed honor upon the children of Adam and have carried them upon the land and sea.","To infuse excellence into something.","Surplus","کرم","12:21-17:62-17:70-21:26-22:18-36:27-37:42-49:13-51:24-70:35-80:13-89:15-89:17-96:3",14
2139,461,"D","فَتَحَ","«فَتَحَ» means to remove restrictions and complexities (intransitive). Its opposite is «اِغْلَاق», which means confinement and restriction (transitive). And «فَتَحَ» also means to grant victory and to judge. Such a judgment wherein a distinction is made between right and wrong, complexity is removed, and neither party is left with any doubt or suspicion.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«رَبَّنَا افۡتَحۡ بَیۡنَنَا وَ بَیۡنَ قَوۡمِنَا بِالۡحَقِّ» (7:89)\nTranslation: Our Lord! Judge between us and our people with justice.","«فَتَحَ» A judgment that distinguishes between truth and falsehood, removes complications, and leaves no party in doubt or suspicion.","Decision","فتح","7:89-8:19-14:15-26:118-32:28-32:29-34:26",7
2140,461,"D","فَصَلَ","«فَصَلَ» means to distinguish one thing from another (to differentiate) and its separation from it (m. l.). Thus, «فَصَلَ» is specific in contrast to fath. In fath, only differentiation is found, whereas in «فَصَلَ», both differentiation and separation are found, and this differentiation and separation can sometimes occur even in a single thing, such as a chapter of a book. Similarly, fath's relation is sometimes with one thing and sometimes with multiple things. (f. l. 113)\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (77/38). Translation: This is the Day of Decision. We have gathered you and all the earlier generations together.","«فَصَلَ» is to distinguish one thing from another and its separation from it.","Decision","فصل","37:21-44:40-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17",6
2141,461,"D","حَکَمَ","«حَکَمَ» meaning «مَنَعَ عَنِ الظُّلْم» (m. l.) a ruling that prevents oppression and excess. And meaning «مَنَعَ عَنِ الْخَصُومَۃ» (f. l. 156), i.e., a command to refrain from fighting and disputes.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ دَاوٗدَ  وَ سُلَیۡمٰنَ  اِذۡ یَحۡکُمٰنِ فِی الۡحَرۡثِ» (21/78)\nTranslation: And (listen to) the story of David and Solomon when they judged concerning a field.","«حَکَمَ» A ruling that prevents someone from excess and takes measures to correct it.","Decision","حکم","2:113-2:213-3:23-3:55-4:58-4:105-4:141-5:1-5:42-5:43-5:44-5:45-5:47-5:48-5:49-5:50-5:95-6:136-7:87-10:35-10:109-12:80-16:59-16:124-21:78-21:112-22:56-22:69-24:48-24:51-29:4-37:154-38:22-38:26-39:3-39:46-40:12-40:48-42:10-45:21-60:10-68:36-68:39",43
2142,461,"J","قَضٰی","«یَقْضِیْ قَضْیًا وَ قَضَاءً وَ قَضِیَّۃً» means (1) to be free from a task; to have completed it. And (2) to make the final decision between the two parties (DECISION). The term Qaazi is employed in relation to a decision when the authority to enforce that decision is also present. Qaazi is a well-known term.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَا وَ رَبِّکَ لَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ حَتّٰی  یُحَکِّمُوۡکَ فِیۡمَا شَجَرَ  بَیۡنَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  لَا  یَجِدُوۡا فِیۡۤ  اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَرَجًا  مِّمَّا قَضَیۡتَ» (4/65)\nTranslation: By your Lord, they will not be true believers until they make you a judge in their disputes and then find no resentment in their hearts regarding your judgment, and submit fully.","The final and definitive decision of the person who possesses the power to enforce this command.","Judgment","قضی","2:117-2:200-2:210-3:47-4:65-4:103-6:2-6:8-6:58-6:60-8:42-8:44-10:11-10:19-10:47-10:54-10:71-10:93-11:44-11:110-12:41-12:68-14:22-15:66-17:4-17:23-19:21-19:35-19:39-19:71-20:72-20:114-22:29-27:78-28:15-28:28-28:29-28:44-33:23-33:36-33:37-34:14-35:36-39:42-39:69-39:75-40:20-40:68-40:78-41:12-41:45-42:14-42:21-43:77-45:17-46:29-62:10-80:23",58
2143,461,"D","حَتَمَ","«حَتَمَ» means: to decide, to strengthen, to decree something, and to make obligatory. «حَاتِم» means: judge, arbiter, ruler, and magistrate. «حَتَمَ الْحَاتِمُ کَذَا» The ruler gave the decree about that matter. «ھٰذا وَلَدٌ حَتَمٌ» means: This is the boy in whose lineage there is no doubt (clear). «حَتْم» means: Qaza wa Qadr (decree and predestination); as if «حَتْم» is the term for the decree that is final and unalterable (Faqih 187).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ اِنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ  اِلَّا وَارِدُہَا ۚ کَانَ عَلٰی رَبِّکَ حَتۡمًا مَّقۡضِیًّا» (19/71) Translation: And there is not one of you but will pass over it (Hell). This is a decree and predetermined by your Lord.","«حَتَمَ» is the decisive and unalterable decision, the decree of Divine will.","Decision","حتم","19:71",1
2144,462,"C","قَدَرَ","«قَدَر ، قَدِر ( قدرًا ، قُدْرَۃً ) قدر» means to devise a plan or manage an affair.  \n«قَدَرَ الرِّزْق» means to distribute sustenance, to restrict provision, and  \n«قَدَرَ عَلَی الشَّیْء» means to have power over something, to gain control. (Source: Manjad)  \n\nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ ذَاالنُّوۡنِ  اِذۡ ذَّہَبَ مُغَاضِبًا فَظَنَّ اَنۡ لَّنۡ نَّقۡدِرَ عَلَیۡہِ» (21/87)  \nTranslation: And the man of the fish (Prophet Yunus) when he went away in anger, thinking that We would not have power over him.","«قَدَرَ عَلٰی» to have power, to gain control; this usage is common.","Control","قدر","2:236-2:264-5:34-13:17-14:18-16:75-16:76-21:87-48:21-57:29-90:5",11
2145,462,"G","اَقْرَنَ","«قَرَنَ» means to combine one thing with another; to bind. And «قَرْن» is the term for the rope with which two camels are tied (muf). «اَقْرَنَ» means to gather two things into one, and «اَقْرَنَ لِلْاَمْر» means to possess the power of something and be capable over it. Whereas the meaning of «اَقْرَنَ عَلَیْہِ» is to become incapable of something (manjada). So to speak, the concept of gaining control over the accompanying thing is found in «اَقْرَنَ».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ سَخَّرَ لَنَا ہٰذَا  وَ مَا کُنَّا لَہٗ  مُقۡرِنِیۡنَ» (43:13)\nTranslation: Glory is to the One Who granted us this mount; otherwise, we would not have had the strength to control it.","«اَقْرَنَ» the power to gain control over the accompanying thing.","Grasp","اقرن","14:49-25:13-38:38-43:13",4
2146,462,"S","اِسْتَحْوَذَ","«حَاذَ الدَّآبَّۃ» means to urge an animal forward (majd), and «حَوَّذَ» means speed, swiftness, and lightness in an affair (m. l.), and «حَاذَ» means to urge with force. And «اِسْتَحْوَذ» means to dominate someone and urge them forcefully. They say «اِسْتَحْوَذَا الْعِیْرُ عَلَی الْاَتَانِ», i.e., a donkey climbing onto the back of another donkey and pressing it down from both sides (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِسۡتَحۡوَذَ  عَلَیۡہِمُ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  فَاَنۡسٰہُمۡ ذِکۡرَ  اللّٰہِ» ( 58/19 )\nTranslation: Satan has gained mastery over them and made them forget the remembrance of Allah.","«اِسْتَحْوَذ» to gain control over someone through force and harshness.","Seizure","استحوذ","4:141-58:19",2
2147,462,"M","اِحْتَنَکَ","«حُنْک» means tālū (a rein or rope). And «اِحْتَنَکَ الْفَرْس» means to put a rope or rein in a horse's mouth. And «اَلْحُنُک» is also used for a person whom time has made experienced (mujtahid). Thus, «اِحْتَنَک» means to gain control over someone through intellect and experience.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَئِنۡ اَخَّرۡتَنِ اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ لَاَحۡتَنِکَنَّ ذُرِّیَّتَہٗۤ  اِلَّا  قَلِیۡلًا» ( 17/62 )\nTranslation: (Satan said to Allah) If You grant me respite until the Day of Resurrection, I will mislead all but a few of his (Adam's) progeny. (Othmani)","«اِحْتَنَک» to gain mastery through intellect and deliberation.","Mastery","احتنک","17:62",1
2148,463,"C","سَیَّارَۃ","«سَارَ» means to move about or travel. And «سَیَّارَۃ» means anything that moves or travels continuously, or keeps moving (this is an intensive form). Celestial bodies are also called «سَیَّارَات». In common usage, «سَیَّارَۃ» refers to a group that travels together, like fellow travelers or a caravan. Caravan (pl.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)\nTranslation: And a caravan came. They sent their water-drawer, who let down his bucket (into the well).","«سَیَّارَۃ» refers to a group, caravan, or fellow travelers who journey together. This term is general.","caravan","سیارۃ","5:96-12:10-12:19",3
2149,463,"C","عِیْر","«عِیْر» Every caravan that carries grain is included—the people and camels transporting food supplies are all part of it (Muf). According to the scholar of jurisprudence and language, this term applies even if the caravan consists of camels, horses, or donkeys (F L 16). The caravan of the Hamyar tribe is also called «عِیْر» (M. Q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ اَذَّنَ مُؤَذِّنٌ اَیَّتُہَا الۡعِیۡرُ اِنَّکُمۡ لَسٰرِقُوۡنَ» (12/70)\nTranslation: Then a crier called out, O people of the caravan! Indeed, you are thieves.","«عِیْر» grain-carrying caravan.","caravan","عیر","12:70-12:82-12:94",3
2150,463,"C","رَکْب","«رَکَبَ» means to ride and «رِکَاب» means riding. And «رَاکِب» means rider. However, in common usage, the word «رَاکِب» has become specific to a camel rider (singular), and the plurals of «رَاکِب» are «رَکْب ، رُکْبَان» and «رُکُوْب» (plural). And «رَکْبُ» means cavalry or camel caravan.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی وَ الرَّکۡبُ اَسۡفَلَ  مِنۡکُمۡ» (8/42)\n\nTranslation: When you (from Medina) were at the near pass and the disbelievers at the far pass, and the caravan was below you (had descended).","Camel-mounted or horse-mounted caravan.","caravan","رکب","8:42",1
2151,464,"G","قَبْر","«قَبْر» means the place where a deceased person is buried in the earth. It is a well-known word, and its plural is «قُبُوْر». The word maqbara (مقبرہ) is also used in the same sense, and its plural is maqabir (مقابر), for example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُصَلِّ عَلٰۤی اَحَدٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ مَّاتَ اَبَدًا وَّ لَا تَقُمۡ عَلٰی قَبۡرِہٖ» (9:84)\nTranslation: And never perform the funeral prayer for any of them when he dies, nor stand at his grave [for supplication].","«قَبْر» is a common type of grave, whether its markers are present or not.","grave","قبر","9:84-22:7-35:22-60:13-80:21-82:4-100:9",7
2152,464,"G","مَرْقَد","«رَقَدَ» means a light and long sleep. And «مَرْقَد» means a place to rest for a long sleep; a resting place; a sleeping place. This word is used metaphorically for the grave because the disbelievers will describe the hardships of the grave as restful in comparison to the hardships of the Day of Judgment.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«قَالُوۡا یٰوَیۡلَنَا مَنۡۢ بَعَثَنَا مِنۡ مَّرۡقَدِنَا» (36/52)  \nTranslation: The disbelievers will say, Oh, woe to us! Who has raised us from our sleeping places?","«مَرْقَد» meaning sleeping place, place to sleep, resting place. (Figuratively) it is used for grave, tomb.","grave","مرقد","36:52",1
2153,464,"G","جَدَث","Although scholars of language have not made a clear distinction between «جَدَث» and «قَبْر», study of the Quran reveals that the word 'qabr' (grave) is general, whereas «جَدَث» refers to a grave whose markers have also vanished. Moreover, it sometimes happens that a body is consumed by a wild animal. At other times, if a human drowns in the sea, sea creatures consume it. Hindus cremate their dead and float the ashes in the Ganges. Whatever the case, when the particles of that body, while transferring, ultimately merge into the earth, that is its «جَدَث». And its plural is «اَجْدَاث». In the Quran, this word appears twice, and both times it is used in contexts where the very concept of grave markers is impossible.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ» (70:43)\nTranslation: On that Day they will rush from the graves as if they were rushing toward a (hunter's) lure.\n\nThis verse mentions «یَوْمُ النُّشُوْر» when all markers of graves will have vanished. Another verse also presents a similar scene.\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«وَ نُفِخَ فِی الصُّوۡرِ فَاِذَا ہُمۡ مِّنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ  اِلٰی  رَبِّہِمۡ  یَنۡسِلُوۡنَ» (36:51)\nTranslation: And when the Trumpet is blown a second time, they will rush from their graves toward their Lord.","Specifically, a grave like «جَدَث» that has no markers.","Grave","جدث","36:51-54:7-70:43",3
2154,465,"A","قَبِلَ","«قَبُوْلًا» means to accept something willingly and with pleasure. According to Munjid and the scholars of linguistic nuances, this term is used exclusively for actions (Faq l 184). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَّ لَا تَقۡبَلُوۡا لَہُمۡ شَہَادَۃً  اَبَدًا» (24/4). Translation: And do not ever accept their testimony.","«قَبِل» to accept something willingly and with pleasure.","Acceptance","قبل","2:48-2:123-3:85-3:91-9:104-42:25",6
2155,465,"A","تَقَبَّلَ","«تَقَبَّلَ» and «قَبِلَ» are nearly synonymous. The difference is only that «تَقَبَّل» is used for accepting something that requires compensation (i.e., exchange or price), such as gifts, etc., while «قَبِل» is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِذۡ  قَالَتِ امۡرَاَتُ عِمۡرٰنَ رَبِّ اِنِّیۡ نَذَرۡتُ لَکَ مَا فِیۡ بَطۡنِیۡ مُحَرَّرًا فَتَقَبَّلۡ مِنِّیۡ» ( 3/35 )\nTranslation: When the wife of Imran said, My Lord, I vow to You what is in my womb, to keep it entirely free for Your service, so accept this from me. Indeed, You are the All-Hearing, the All-Knowing.","«تَقَبَّل» meaning 'to accept'.","Acceptance","تقبل","2:127-3:35-3:37-3:90-5:27-5:36-9:53-9:54-14:40-24:4",10
2156,465,"A","اَجَاب","The use of «اِسْتِجَاب» is generally for the acceptance of prayer (see Faryad Rasi), meaning that accepting a prayer and then granting the supplicant's request is also included within «اِسْتِجَاب».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَمَّنۡ یُّجِیۡبُ الۡمُضۡطَرَّ اِذَا دَعَاہُ» (27:62)\nTranslation: Who responds to the distressed when he calls upon Him?\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ قَالَ رَبُّکُمُ  ادۡعُوۡنِیۡۤ   اَسۡتَجِبۡ لَکُمۡ» (40:60)\nTranslation: And your Lord has said, Call upon Me; I will respond to you.","«اِسْتجَاب» generally comes for the acceptance of prayer and then for the receiving of reward.","Acceptance","اجاب","3:172-3:195-8:9-12:34-13:18-14:22-21:76-21:84-21:88-21:90-35:14-40:60-42:38",13
2157,466,"F","شُعُوْب","«شُعُوْب» the offspring of a single man, and then the offspring of that offspring, and so on. Eventually, it evolves into a singular entity. In Arabic, this is called «شَعْب», and «شُعَب» (branch) is also used for it; its plural is «شُعُوب». Fundamentally, two meanings are found for «شَعْب»: (1) *infirāq* (separation), and (2) *ijtimāʿ* (gathering). That is, something that eventually divides into many parts, yet its origin and foundation remain one, and it also represents a gathering (م ۔ ل).","«شُعُوْب» refers to lineages, such as the children of a man and then the children of those children, which over time become a single lineage.","Family","شعوب","49:13",1
2158,466,"F","قَبَائِل","«قَبَائِل» is a collective term. «قَبِیْلَہ» means brotherhood or community. Now, this entity or *sha'b* (nation) is further divided into many smaller parts called tribes (*qabeel*), which maintain connections among themselves. «قَبَائِلُ الرَّأس» refers to the bones of the head that are connected and joined together (the skull). In our language, we call this a brotherhood or community (*biraadari*).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنٰکُمۡ شُعُوۡبًا وَّ قَبَآئِلَ لِتَعَارَفُوۡا ؕ اِنَّ  اَکۡرَمَکُمۡ  عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ  اَتۡقٰکُمۡ» (49:13)\nTranslation: And We have made you into nations and tribes so that you may know one another. Indeed, the most noble of you in the sight of Allah is the most righteous of you.\n\nNote: (By 'tribes' is meant a group of people who, while residing within a state, follow a distinct way of life. They have their own specific laws and customs. They reside in their own designated areas and are not bound by the state's laws. The number of tribes worldwide is approximately 150 million, which constitutes about 40% of the world's population.)","«قَبَائِل» meaning brotherhood. Groups, nations, and numerous collectives of men from the same generation or lineage.","Family","قبائل","49:13",1
2159,466,"F","فَصِیْلَۃ","«فَصِیْلَۃ» meaning family, clan, one's own household, members of a single home, household, a small tribe comprising one's wife, sons, daughters, siblings, parents, etc. (cf. 206)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَوَدُّ  الۡمُجۡرِمُ لَوۡ  یَفۡتَدِیۡ مِنۡ عَذَابِ یَوۡمِئِذٍۭ بِبَنِیۡہِ وَ صَاحِبَتِہٖ وَ اَخِیۡہِ وَ فَصِیۡلَتِہِ الَّتِیۡ تُـئۡوِیۡہِ» (70:11,12,13)\nTranslation: The criminal will wish that he could ransom himself, even with his sons, his wife, his brother, or the entire family he lived with.","«فَصِیْلَۃ» meaning family or clan.","Family","فصیلۃ","70:13",1
2160,466,"F","رَھْط","«رَھْط» a small group of young men from a tribe, whose number ranges from 3 to 9 and which includes no women (Fall 205). Such a group is also called «رَھْط», and its leader is also (referred to as such) (see also leader). According to the author of *Al-Munjid*, if a number is added to «رَھْط», it refers to individuals and persons, e.g., «خَمْسَۃُ رَھْطٍ» means five people (*Munjid*).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ یٰقَوۡمِ اَرَہۡطِیۡۤ اَعَزُّ  عَلَیۡکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» (11/92)\nTranslation: Shu'aib (AS) said, O my people! Is the pressure of my brothers upon you greater than that of Allah?","«رَھْط» A small group of young people from a tribe, numbering between 3 and 9.","Family","رھط","11:91-11:92-27:48",3
2161,466,"F","عَشِیْرَۃ","«عَشَرَ» means to live together in close association (the root letters are م ل). And «عَشِیْرَۃ» refers to that small tribe which consists only of male relatives, such as sons, daughters, paternal uncles, paternal aunts, etc. (Fayl 206).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡ عَشِیۡرَتَکَ  الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ» (26/214)\n\nTranslation: And warn your nearest kinsfolk.","«عَشِیْرَۃ» is a small clan consisting of the close relatives on the man's side.","Family","عشیرۃ","4:19-9:24-22:13-26:214-58:22",5
2162,466,"F","اَسْبَاط","«سِبْط» refers to the descendants of one's descendants, such as grandsons and great-grandsons (plural), but this term is predominantly specific to descendants through daughters (i.e., nephews and nieces). Similarly, «حَفِيْد» is used for grandsons (people), and when this term is attributed to the Jews, it signifies a tribe (people). According to the linguist, the status of a tribe within Banu Ishmael is the same as the status of «سِبْط» within Banu Isaac. (ف ل 25) In the Quran, the word «اَسْبَاط» appears in reference to the tribes of Banu Isaac. For example: In the Quran it is: «وَ قَطَّعۡنٰہُمُ اثۡنَتَیۡ عَشۡرَۃَ  اَسۡبَاطًا اُمَمًا» (7/160) Translation: And We divided the Children of Israel into twelve tribes and then made them into large communities.","«اَسْبَاط» nephews, nieces, etc., and if this word is attributed to the Jews, then it will refer to a tribe.","Family","اسباط","2:136-2:140-3:84-4:163-7:160",5
2163,467,"K","قَتَلَ","The term «قَتَل» is general, meaning to kill, to separate the soul from the body, whether by beheading or by any other means. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَاِنۡ تَوَلَّوۡا فَخُذُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡتُلُوۡہُمۡ حَیۡثُ وَجَدۡتُّمُوۡہُمۡ» (4/89). Translation: Then if they turn back, seize them and kill them wherever you find them.","The word «قَتَل» is commonly used to mean killing someone.","Killing","قتل","2:54-2:61-2:72-2:85-2:87-2:91-2:154-2:178-2:191-2:217-2:251-3:21-3:112-3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:181-3:183-3:195-4:29-4:66-4:74-4:89-4:91-4:92-4:93-4:155-4:157-5:27-5:28-5:30-5:32-5:33-5:70-5:95-6:137-6:140-6:151-7:127-7:141-7:150-8:17-8:30-9:5-9:111-12:9-12:10-17:31-17:33-18:74-20:40-22:58-25:68-26:14-28:9-28:19-28:20-28:33-29:24-33:16-33:26-33:61-40:25-40:26-40:28-47:4-51:10-60:12-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4",77
2164,467,"M","سَفَکَ","«سَفَکَ» meaning blood or water flowing, and «سَفُوْک» meaning a liar. And «سَفَّاک» meaning a bloodshedder. (sing.) This word is generally used to mean killing someone unlawfully.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَتَجۡعَلُ فِیۡہَا مَنۡ یُّفۡسِدُ فِیۡہَا وَ یَسۡفِکُ الدِّمَآءَ» (2:30)\nTranslation: The angels said to Allah Almighty: Will You place upon the earth a vicegerent who will spread corruption and shed blood unjustly?","«سَفَکَ» unjust killing.","Murder","سفک","2:30-2:84",2
2165,467,"M","حَسَّ","«حَسّ» means to uproot something from its very roots (manjad), and «حَسَّ» means «شِدَّۃُ الْقَتَل» (F 48). Thus, the meaning of «حَسَّ» is to strike repeatedly in such a way that the enemy's root is completely cut off.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ صَدَقَکُمُ اللّٰہُ وَعۡدَہٗۤ  اِذۡ تَحُسُّوۡنَہُمۡ بِاِذۡنِہٖ» (3/152)\nTranslation: And Allah fulfilled His promise to you when you were destroying them by His permission, until when you weakened and began to dispute about the command and disobeyed after He had shown you what you love...","«حَسّ» meaning to strike repeatedly and to uproot the enemy completely.","Murder","حس","3:152",1
2166,467,"K","اَثْخَنَ","«ثَخَنَ» means to lift something in order to estimate its weight (m l), and «ثَخُنَ» means to be thick and hard, and «اَثْخَنَ فِیْ الْاَرْض» means to go beyond the limit in bleeding during killing (manjad). Thus, the concept of severity is found in «اَثْخَنَ» during the act of killing. It also applies to mass killing, i.e., killing without restraint.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِذَا  لَقِیۡتُمُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فَضَرۡبَ الرِّقَابِ ؕ حَتّٰۤی  اِذَاۤ  اَثۡخَنۡتُمُوۡہُمۡ فَشُدُّوا الۡوَثَاقَ» (47/4)\nTranslation: When you encounter the disbelievers in battle, strike their necks until you have inflicted upon them a severe slaughter. Then bind them firmly and take them captive.","«اَثْخَنَ» to kill without restraint and to continue killing as much as possible.","Killing","اثخن","8:67-47:4",2
2167,468,"S","قَدَمَ","«قَدَمَ» is the plural of «اَقْدَام», meaning foot, leg, a well-known human organ. The difference between «قَدَم» and «رِجْل» is the same as that between «بَصَر» and «عَیْن», i.e., «قَدَمَ» is used both for the foot itself and for the act of placing the foot forward. In this sense, the application of «قَدَم» is not limited to the foot alone but extends to the entire part below the knee. (Also see foot)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَتَزِلَّ قَدَمٌۢ  بَعۡدَ ثُبُوۡتِہَا» (16/94)\nTranslation: In this way, after your foot has firmly settled, you will slip/stumble.","«قَدَم» human organ i.e. feet","Step","قدم","2:95-2:110-2:223-3:182-4:62-5:80-7:34-8:51-10:49-11:98-15:24-16:61-16:94-18:57-22:10-26:76-28:47-30:36-34:30-36:12-38:60-38:61-42:48-48:2-49:1-50:28-59:18-62:7-73:20-74:37-75:13-78:40-82:5:89:24",35
2168,468,"S","خُطُوَۃ","«خُطُوَۃ» Its plural is «خُطُوَات», meaning the intermediate distance between two steps, and meaning to advance beyond something by crossing it (m. l.), and «خُطُوَات لَازِمَہ» meaning necessary measures (manjada), as if the meaning of «خُطُوَات» is steps, advancement, and it also refers to the entire path. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «ۖوَّ لَا تَتَّبِعُوۡا خُطُوٰتِ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (2/168) Translation: And do not follow the footsteps of Satan.","The midpoint between two feet. And «خُطُوَات» meaning steps (STEPS).","spiritual rank","خطوۃ","2:168-2:208-6:142-24:21",4
2169,468,"S","اَثَر","«اَثَر» Its plural is «اٰثَار», meaning the remaining sign. Footprint (for example) and «اٰثَار» meaning the marks of the feet. Left-behind marks. Path marks. Also see sign and ancient traces meaning the marks and signs of old times.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «قَالَ ذٰلِکَ مَا کُنَّا نَبۡغِ ٭ۖ فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18/64)\nTranslation: Prophet Musa (pbuh) said to his companion Prophet Yusha (pbuh), Indeed we were in search of that very thing, then both of them turned back on their footsteps.","«اَثَر» Footprint. Guidepost.","Step","اثر","5:46-18:6-18:64-20:84-20:96-30:50-36:12-37:70-40:21-40:82-43:22-43:23-46:4-48:29-57:27-100:4",16
2170,469,"D","قَرَّ","«قَرَّ» means to settle or remain in one place. And «قَرَّ» also means to become cool. The relationship between these two meanings is that coldness or coolness, like its opposite heat, also seeks stillness, just as heat seeks movement (as explained).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33/33)\nTranslation: And stay in your homes, and do not display adornment and decoration as was done in the times of earlier ignorance.","«قَرَّ» to settle and establish oneself.","Decree","قر","19:26-20:40-25:74-28:9-28:13-32:17-33:33-33:51",8
2171,469,"R","اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی","The meaning of «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is to mount or ride something, then to settle or sit firmly upon it (see to mount). The fundamental difference between «قَرَّ» and «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is that «اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» is used to denote taking a position after transitioning from one state to another.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اسۡتَوَتۡ عَلَی الۡجُوۡدِیِّ» (11:44)\nTranslation: Meaning the ship of Noah (which was floating on the floodwaters) finally came to rest on Mount Judi.\n\nFurthermore, the Divine Command states:\n«فَاِذَا اسۡتَوَیۡتَ اَنۡتَ وَ مَنۡ مَّعَکَ عَلَی الۡفُلۡکِ» (23:28)\nTranslation: (O Noah!) When you and your companions are seated in the ship.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«ثُمَّ اسۡتَوٰی عَلَی الۡعَرۡشِ» (7:54)\nTranslation: Then He established Himself upon the Throne.","«اِسْتَوٰی عَلٰی» comes to transition from one state to another.","Ruling","استوی علی","2:29-7:54-10:3-11:44-13:2-20:5-23:28-25:59-32:4-41:11-43:13-48:29-57:4",13
2172,470,"Q","قُرْاٰن","«قَرَءَ» refers to a book that is recited repeatedly, abundantly, and always.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«قٓ ۟ ۚ  وَ الۡقُرۡاٰنِ  الۡمَجِیۡدِ » (50/1)  \nTranslation: Qaf. By the Glorious Quran.","«قُرْاٰن» The book that is recited repeatedly, abundantly, and always. (meaning the Noble Quran).","Quran","قران","2:185-4:82-5:101-6:19-7:204-9:111-10:15-10:37-10:61-12:2-12:3-13:31-15:1-15:87-15:91-16:98-17:9-17:41-17:45-17:46-17:60-17:78-17:82-17:88-17:89-17:106-18:54-20:2-20:113-20:114-25:30-25:32-27:1-27:6-27:76-27:92-28:85-30:58-34:31-36:2-36:69-38:1-39:27-39:28-41:3-41:26-41:44-42:7-43:3-43:31-46:29-47:24-50:1-50:45-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-55:2-56:77-59:21-72:1-73:4-73:20-75:17-75:18-76:23-84:21-85:21",69
2173,470,"Q","فُرْقَان","«فَرَقَ» means to separate or to distinguish. It is an intensive form derived from to separate and to distinguish. That is, a book that discerns and differentiates between truth and falsehood in every single aspect.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«تَبٰرَکَ الَّذِیۡ نَزَّلَ الۡفُرۡقَانَ عَلٰی عَبۡدِہٖ» (25/1)\nTranslation: Blessed is He who sent down the Quran upon His Servant...","«فُرْقَان» a book that distinguishes between truth and falsehood.","Quran","فرقان","2:53-2:185-3:4-8:29-8:41-21:48-25:1",7
2174,470,"Q","ذِکْر","«ذِکْر» and «تَذْکِرَۃ»: «ذَکَرَ» is the opposite of «نَسِیَ», which means to forget. And «ذَکَرَ» means to remember and to come to mind, which is contrary to forgetting. The Quran is called «ذِکْر» because it reminds humans of their innate call to goodness—that is, natural inclinations—and also of the covenant «اَلَسْت». Hence, it is also an admonition. And in the same sense, «تَذْکِرَۃ» also signifies both admonition and remembrance. Furthermore, a ticket for some conveyance, such as a train, airplane, etc., is termed «تَذْکَرَۃ». Certificates and passports are also referred to as «تَذْکَرَۃ» (Q. J).\n\nFor example, the Holy Quran states:\n«ءَ اُنۡزِلَ عَلَیۡہِ الذِّکۡرُ مِنۡۢ بَیۡنِنَا» (38/8)\nTranslation: Has the admonition (the Book) been sent down upon only one of us?\n\nAnd the command of the Almighty is:\n«اِنَّ  ہٰذِہٖ  تَذۡکِرَۃٌ» (73/19)\nTranslation: Indeed, this Quran is an admonition.","«ذِکْر» meaning 'to remember' and 'to recall'.","Quran","ذکر","2:114-2:221-2:269-2:282-3:7-3:58-5:13-5:14-5:91-6:44-6:68-6:69-6:70-6:80-6:90-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:126-6:138-6:152-7:2-7:3-7:26-7:57-7:63-7:69-7:130-7:165-7:201-8:2-8:57-9:126-10:3-11:24-11:30-11:114-11:120-12:42-12:104-13:19-13:28-14:5-14:25-14:52-15:6-15:9-16:13-16:17-16:43-16:44-16:90-17:41-17:46-18:28-18:57-18:70-18:83-18:101-19:2-20:3-20:14-20:34-20:42-20:44-20:99-20:113-20:124-21:2-21:7-21:10-21:24-21:42-21:48-21:50-21:84-21:105-22:35-23:71-23:85-23:110-24:1-24:27-24:37-25:18-25:29-25:50-25:62-25:73-26:5-26:209-26:227-27:62-28:43-28:46-28:51-29:45-29:51-32:4-32:15-32:22-33:34-33:41-35:37-36:11-36:19-36:69-37:3-37:13-37:155-37:168-38:1-38:8-38:29-38:32-38:43-38:46-38:49-38:87-39:9-39:21-39:22-39:23-39:27-39:45-40:13-40:54-40:58-41:41-43:5-43:36-43:44-44:13-44:58-45:23-47:18-47:20-50:8-50:37-50:45-51:49-51:55-52:29-53:29-54:17-54:22-54:25-54:32-54:40-56:62-56:73-57:16-58:19-62:9-63:9-65:10-68:51-68:52-69:12-69:42-69:48-72:17-73:19-74:31-74:49-74:54-74:55-74:56-76:29-77:5-79:43-80:4-80:11-80:12-81:27-87:9-87:10-88:21-89:23-94:4-79:35",181
2175,470,"Q","کِتَابٌ مُّبِیْنٌ","«بَانَ» means to be distant and separate. In «بین», three aspects are found: (1) *iftiraq*, meaning separation; (2) *bu'd*, meaning distance; and (3) *wuduh*, meaning clarity and manifestation. And «بَیَّنَ» means to explain something openly. Kitaab-e-Mubeen refers to a book in which every matter related to guidance is explained with full clarity and elaboration—the Clear and Luminous Book, i.e., the Noble Quran.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ  مِّنَ اللّٰہِ  نُوۡرٌ وَّ کِتٰبٌ مُّبِیۡنٌ» (5:15)\nTranslation: Indeed, there has come to you from Allah a light (guidance) and a clear book.","«کِتَابٌ مُّبِیْنٌ», the Clear and Luminous Book—the Noble Quran.","Quran","کتاب مبین","5:15-6:59-10:61-11:6-12:1-26:2-27:1-27:75-28:2-34:3-43:2-44:2",12
2176,470,"Q","حَدِیْث","«حَدَثَ» signifies the emergence of something new. Its opposite is «عَدَم», meaning non-existence or disappearance. And «حَدِیْث» refers to anything that did not exist before and appears anew—something new.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ  یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ  اَمۡرًا» (65:1)\nTranslation: Perhaps Allah will thereafter bring about a new matter.\n\nThen the application of the Hadith extends to every matter that previously existed but has faded from people's minds over time. If it is revived anew, the Hadith will apply to it as well—a new matter. The Quran is referred to as Hadith in these very senses.\n\nFor example: the Divine declaration states:\n«اَللّٰہُ  نَزَّلَ  اَحۡسَنَ الۡحَدِیۡثِ» (39:23)\nTranslation: Allah has sent down the best statement.","«حَدِیْث» meaning the emergence of something new.","Quran","حدیث","4:42-4:78-4:87-4:140-6:68-7:185-12:6-12:21-12:101-12:111-18:6-20:9-23:44-31:6-33:53-34:19-39:23-45:6-51:24-52:34-53:59-56:81-66:3-68:44-77:50-79:15-85:17-88:1",28
2177,471,"S","بُدْن","«بُدْن» is the plural of «بُدْنَہ». And «بَدَن» refers to the body of any living creature, provided its blood has not dried. (Vol. 115) And «بَدَنَ» and «بَدَّن» mean to be fat. And «بُدْن» also refers to the sacrificial camels that are brought to Mecca to be slaughtered (detailed). Sacrificial animals are also called «بُدْن» due to the suitability of their bodies and fatness (detailed).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ الۡبُدۡنَ جَعَلۡنٰہَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ  شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہِ» (22/36)\nTranslation: And We have made the sacrificial camels among the signs of Allah for you.","«بُدْن» camels that are slaughtered during Hajj.","Sacrifice (Qurbani)","بدن","22:36",1
2178,471,"S","نُسُک","The word «نَسَک» denotes worship and seeking closeness to Allah. «نَاسِک» means 'ascetic,' and «نَسِیْکَہ» refers to the sacrificial animal offered to seek closeness to Allah (M.S.). And «نُسُک» is the plural of «نَسِیْکَہ». Then this word generally became associated with Hajj. «مَنَاسِکِ حَجّ» means the pillars and rulings of Hajj, and also the places where these rulings are implemented. Similarly, by «نُسُک» is meant those sacrificial animals that are slaughtered at the location of Mina during the days of Tashriq.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ کَانَ مِنۡکُمۡ مَّرِیۡضًا اَوۡ بِہٖۤ اَذًی مِّنۡ رَّاۡسِہٖ فَفِدۡیَۃٌ مِّنۡ صِیَامٍ اَوۡ صَدَقَۃٍ اَوۡ نُسُکٍ» (2/196)\nTranslation: Then if any of you is ill or has an ailment in his scalp (and has to shave his head before the sacrifice), then he must either fast for three days, or give charity, or offer a sacrifice.","«نُسُک» all such animals of every kind that are slaughtered in Mina.","sacrifice","نسک","2:196-6:162",2
2179,471,"S","ھَدْی","«ھَدْی» is the plural of «ھَدْیَۃٌ». It refers to the sacrificial animal that is sent to the Sacred House of Allah for slaughter, whether it is a camel, cow, or sheep, and whether it is male or female (Munjid). For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ لَا تَحۡلِقُوۡا رُءُوۡسَکُمۡ حَتّٰی یَبۡلُغَ الۡہَدۡیُ  مَحِلَّہٗ» (2/196). Translation: And do not shave your heads until the sacrificial animal reaches its place.","«ھَدْی» are the sacrificial animals that pilgrims bring along for slaughter.","sacrifice","ھدی","2:196-5:2-5:95-5:97-48:25",5
2180,471,"S","قَلَائِد","«قَلَائِد» is a collective term. It means to put a garland around someone's neck. And «قَلَادَۃ» means a garland (a necklace). Then «قَلَادَۃ» is also used for a sacrificial animal on which a garland or a band has been tied around its neck as a mark of dedication. Whether it is related to Hajj or to fulfilling a vow.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تُحِلُّوۡا شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا الشَّہۡرَ الۡحَرَامَ وَ لَا الۡہَدۡیَ وَ لَا الۡقَلَآئِدَ» ( 5/2 )\nTranslation: O you who have believed, do not violate the rites of Allah or the sacred month or the sacrificial animals or the garlanded animals, or those coming to the Sacred House seeking bounty from their Lord and [seeking] His approval.","«قَلَائِد» sacrificial animals with a strap placed around their necks.","sacrifice","قلائد","5:2-5:97",2
2181,472,"O","قَسَمَ","«قَسَمَ» means to divide or distribute, and also to take an oath. And «قَسْم» means a suspicion arising in the heart that later reaches the level of certainty (source). And «قُسَامَت» are the oaths given in exchange for blood by people of a suspicious tribe to their saints (source). Thus, the word oath is used to remove doubt in a matter, and its usage occurs in the case of a dispute (Faqih 42).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ  اِنَّہٗ  لَقَسَمٌ  لَّوۡ  تَعۡلَمُوۡنَ عَظِیۡمٌ» (56/76)\nTranslation: And this is a great oath, if you only knew.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ قَاسَمَہُمَاۤ  اِنِّیۡ لَکُمَا لَمِنَ النّٰصِحِیۡنَ» (7/21)\nTranslation: And Satan swore before both Adam and his wife, saying, I am indeed your sincere advisor.","«قَسَم» is used to remove doubt.","Oath","قسم","5:53-5:106-5:107-6:109-7:21-7:49-14:44-16:38-24:53-27:49-30:55-35:42-56:75-56:76-68:17-69:38-70:40-75:1-75:2-81:15-84:16-89:5-90:1",23
2182,472,"O","یَمِیْن","«یَمِیْن» comes in the meaning of taking an oath.\nThe Prophetic saying ﷺ is: «اَلْبَیِّنَۃُ عَلَی الْمُدَّعِیْ وَ الْیَمِیْنُ عَلَی الْمُدَّعٰی عَلَیْہ» Sunan Tirmidhi: Hadith No. 1341\nTranslation: Abdullah ibn Amr (may Allah be pleased with them both) reported that the Messenger of Allah (peace and blessings be upon him) said in his sermon: The burden of proof is on the claimant, and the oath is on the one who denies (the claim).\nThat is, presenting evidence is the responsibility of the claimant (the one making the claim), and if he cannot do so, then the defendant (the one against whom the claim is made) takes the oath.\nAnd «یَمِیْن» also comes in the meaning of the right hand. It was the custom of the Arabs that when they wanted to strengthen or confirm a promise with an oath, the person taking the oath would place his right hand over the other person's hand. Therefore, the word «یَمِیْن» began to be used for an oath. And its plural is «اَیْمَان» (muf). The word «یَمِیْن» for oath is borrowed (i.e., taken on loan) (Faqih 43).\nThen sometimes, the Arabs would also place hand over hand and take an oath merely to add emphasis in speech, but it had no connection to reality. Allah the Almighty has declared such oaths as vain and forgivable. And an oath that is in fact based on reality is called «یَمِیْن مُنْعَقِدَۃ», which is accountable.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«لَا  یُؤَاخِذُکُمُ  اللّٰہُ بِاللَّغۡوِ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡمَانِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ یُّؤَاخِذُکُمۡ  بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ قُلُوۡبُکُمۡ» (2/225)\nTranslation: Allah will not hold you accountable for what is unintentional in your oaths, but He will hold you accountable for what your hearts have intended.","The word «یَمِیْن» is used for taking oaths, for dispelling accusations, and for reinforcing and strengthening covenants and pledges.","Oath","یمین","2:224-2:225-3:77-5:53-5:89-5:108-6:109-9:12-9:13-16:38-16:91-16:92-16:94-24:53-35:42-58:16-63:2-66:2-68:39",19
2183,472,"O","حَلْف","«حَلَفَ» means to remain steadfast on a matter (i.e., to be firm). An oath of allegiance. It is an oath to remain steadfast on the covenant of rectitude, i.e., reformation. And the allied tribes were those who took oaths to support each other in peace and war. Thus, the oath carries the meanings of ending a previous quarrel and establishing relations of loyalty. (Fakhr al-Din al-Razi, 42) For example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ سَیَحۡلِفُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ لَوِ اسۡتَطَعۡنَا لَخَرَجۡنَا مَعَکُمۡ» (9/43)\nTranslation: And now they will swear by Allah that if they had the power, they would surely have gone forth with you.","«حَلَفَ» to pledge to remain steadfast on something.","Oath","حلف","4:62-5:89-9:42-9:56-9:62-9:74-9:95-9:96-9:107-58:14-58:18",11
2184,472,"O","اَلِیَّۃ","«اَلَا ( یَاْلُوْا اَلْوًا )» has essentially two meanings: (1) To fall short or be negligent in performing a task, and to delay it. For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118)\nTranslation: They will not bear any shortcoming in your corruption.\n(2) To take an oath. And «اَلِیَّۃً» means an oath. An oath that causes hardship and shortcoming for the one taking it (Mufradat), and according to Ibn al-Faris, it is an oath not to do a good deed (Maqayis).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا یَاۡتَلِ اُولُوا الۡفَضۡلِ مِنۡکُمۡ وَ السَّعَۃِ  اَنۡ یُّؤۡتُوۡۤا  اُولِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ» (24/22)\nTranslation: And those of you who are affluent and possess wealth should not take such an oath that they will not give to relatives, the needy, and those who emigrate in the cause of Allah.","It is used to avoid completing a good deed.","Oath","الیۃ","24:22",1
2185,472,"O","اِیْلَا","«اٰلٰی یُؤْلُوْا اِیْلَاءً»: An oath to separate from one's wife and sever marital relations (i.e., the oath of īlāʾ). In pre-Islamic times, people used to greatly distress and harass their wives through such oaths. Sharia closed the door to this evil by stipulating a maximum waiting period of four months.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡلُوۡنَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِہِمۡ تَرَبُّصُ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَشۡہُرٍ» (2/226)\nTranslation: Those who swear to abstain from their wives must wait for four months.","«اِیْلَا» taking an oath of separation from one's wife.","Oath","ایلا","2:226",1
2186,472,"O","نَکَثَ","«نَکَثَ» is a common and well-known term for breaking an oath. Breaking the oath of a contract, sale, covenant, etc. (manjīd). For example, in the Quran it is: «اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ» (9/13). Translation: Will you not fight those who have broken their oaths?","«نَکَثَ» is a common and well-known phrase for breaking an oath.","Oath","نکث","7:135-9:12-9:13-16:92-43:50-48:10",6
2187,472,"O","نَقَضَ","«نَقَضَ» means destruction. «نَقْضَ الْبَنَاء» means to demolish a building. «نَقَضَ الْحَبْل» means to untie the rope's knot. «نَقَّضَ الْعَھْد وَ الْاَمْر» means to corrupt a firm covenant through pretexts and excuses after its establishment. And «نَقَّضَ الْاَمْن» means to spread disorder, to corrupt peace (manjad). Apparently, the word «نَقَّضَ» is used in a much broader sense than «نَکَثَ» (also see 'to break').\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡاَیۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡکِیۡدِہَا» (16/91)\nTranslation: And do not break the oaths after you have made them firm.","«نَقَضَ» Rendering oaths ineffective and void through deception and pretexts.","Oath","نقض","2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77",9
2188,472,"O","حَنِثَ","«حِنْث» meaning false and untrue oath, and also sin. Disobedience (masc.) and «حَنِثَ فِی الْیَمِیْن» meaning to violate an oath (transitive), i.e., not doing that for which one has taken an oath.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ خُذۡ بِیَدِکَ ضِغۡثًا  فَاضۡرِبۡ بِّہٖ وَ لَا تَحۡنَثۡ» (38/44)\nTranslation: (We said to Job,) Take in your hand a twig and strike with it, and do not break your oath. (Fulfill the oath.)","«حَنِث» To break an oath regarding an action one has sworn to perform or not perform.","Oath","حنث","38:44-56:46",2
2189,473,"F","حُصُوْن","«حُصُوْن» refers to «حِصْن», a fortress that is enclosed and where arrangements for protection and shelter are made. And every such place where safety can be ensured is called that. (e.g.) Fortresses where there are also battlements, so that one can take shelter there, ensure one's own protection, and also confront the enemy.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ ظَنُّوۡۤا  اَنَّہُمۡ  مَّانِعَتُہُمۡ حُصُوۡنُہُمۡ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ» ( 59/2 )\nTranslation: And the Jews were certain that their fortresses would protect them from Allah (His punishment).","«حُصُوْن» meaning fortress, secure place. «حِصْن» a fortress that is fortified and in which provisions for protection and refuge are made.","Fort","حصون","59:2",1
2190,473,"F","صَیَاصِی","«صَیَاصِی» is the plural of «صِیْصِیَہ», meaning every such thing through which one can protect oneself. A cow's horns are also called «صِیْصِیَہ» because it protects itself with them (sing.) meaning 'places of protection' or 'forts'. Any fortress-like thing. The war forts of the Jews.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ اَنۡزَلَ الَّذِیۡنَ ظَاہَرُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مِنۡ صَیَاصِیۡہِمۡ وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الرُّعۡبَ» (33:26)\n\nTranslation: And from the People of the Book, those who had supported the polytheists of Mecca, Allah brought them down from their fortresses and cast terror into their hearts.","«صَیَاصِی» signifies fortresses, sanctuaries. Any such place from which one can seek protection and safety.","Fort","صیاصی","33:26",1
2191,473,"F","بُرُوْج","«بُرُوْج» is the plural form of «بُرْج», meaning 'to appear' or 'to be elevated'. And «بَرَّج» means 'to build a tower'. And «بُرْج» means any tall structure like a dome, fortress, palace dome, etc. (manjad). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوۡجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ» (4/78). Translation: Death will overtake you wherever you may be, even if you are in fortified towers.","«بُرُوْج» a lofty, strong, and domed structure.","Fortress","بروج","4:78-15:16-25:61-85:1",4
2192,473,"F","مَحَارِیْب","«مَحَارِیْب» denotes a gathering, meaning the beginning part of a house, the head of a council, the place where people assemble, and «مِحْرَاب» meaning warrior, fighter, and brave (mujāhid). It also refers to any place where war strategies or equipment are prepared or where fighting can occur. Hence, it also carries the meaning of fortress (see fortress). For example, the Quran states: «یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ لَہٗ  مَا یَشَآءُ  مِنۡ مَّحَارِیۡبَ وَ تَمَاثِیۡلَ» (34:13). Translation: Those which were built for Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him) as he desired—fortresses and statues.","«مَحَارِیْب» such places where war-related matters are decided and are also secure.","Fort","محاریب","3:37-3:39-19:11-34:13-38:21",5
2193,474,"T","قَمِیْص","«قَمِیْص» means garment, shirt. For example, in the Noble Quran: «وَ اِنۡ  کَانَ  قَمِیۡصُہٗ  قُدَّ مِنۡ دُبُرٍ فَکَذَبَتۡ» (12:27). Translation: And if the shirt of Yusuf (AS) was torn from the back, then Zulaikha has lied.","«قَمِیْص», meaning clothing or a shirt.","tunic","قمیص","12:18-12:25-12:26-12:27-12:28-12:93",6
2194,474,"T","سَرَابِیْل","«سَرَابِیْل» is the plural of «سریال». The terms 'qamees' and 'pajama' are both used for it. And according to the author of Al-Munjid, 'qamees' or any garment worn (is termed 'munjid'). For example, in the Quran, it is stated: «وَّ جَعَلَ لَکُمۡ سَرَابِیۡلَ تَقِیۡکُمُ  الۡحَرَّ» (16/81). Translation: And Allah has made for you garments that protect you from the heat.","«سَرَابِیْل» qamis or whatever clothing should be worn.","tunic","سرابیل","14:50-16:81",2
2195,475,"S","اَیَّدَ","«اَلْاَیَّد» means severe strength (sing.) and «اَیَّدَ» means to fully assist someone and provide strength, support. For example: In the Quran it is: «فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ وَ اَیَّدَہٗ  بِجُنُوۡدٍ لَّمۡ تَرَوۡہَا» (9:40) Translation: Then Allah sent down tranquility upon the Prophet ﷺ and strengthened him with armies that you did not see.","«اَیَّدَ» To help someone by granting them full strength.","Strength","اید","2:87-2:253-5:110-8:26-8:62-9:40-38:17-58:22-61:14",9
2196,475,"S","اٰزَرَ","«اَلْاِزْر» denotes a root buttress. And «اَلْاِزَار» (means) sheet, buttress, curtain, wall buttress (that mound of soil built against a wall to reinforce it). And «اٰزَرَ الْبَنَات» denotes the intertwining of plants. And «اَزَّرَ» denotes to strengthen someone, to impart strength (Munajjad). As if the word «اٰزَرَ» is used for inherently imparting strength to something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کَزَرۡعٍ اَخۡرَجَ شَطۡئَہٗ فَاٰزَرَہٗ فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ لِیَغِیۡظَ بِہِمُ الۡکُفَّارَ» (48/29)\nTranslation: Like a plant that brings forth its sprout, then strengthens it, then it grows thick, then stands upright on its stem in such a manner that the cultivators are pleased with it. Thus, Allah enrages the disbelievers with their progress.","«اٰزَرَ» : By imparting strength to something from one's own essence, to fortify it.","Strength / Power","ازر","48:29",1
2197,475,"S","عَزَّزَ","«عَزَّ» means honor, and its opposite is «ذَلَّ», meaning humiliation. And «عَزَّ» also means supremacy, i.e., not being subordinate to anyone. And «اَعَزَّ» means to grant someone honor. And «عَزَّزَ» means to give such strength or assistance to a subordinate person that they become honored in society and attain respect. And 'izzat (honor) refers to a state that protects a person from being subjugated or overpowered (etc.).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ  اثۡنَیۡنِ  فَکَذَّبُوۡہُمَا فَعَزَّزۡنَا بِثَالِثٍ» ( 36/14 )\nTranslation: When We sent two (prophets) to them, they denied them. Then We strengthened them with a third.","«عَزَّزَ» to empower a subordinate (matāhat) to the extent that they are no longer a subordinate.","Strength","عزز","36:14",1
2198,476,"R","قِیَامَۃ","«قِیَامَۃ» meaning the one that is inevitably established. A day or era that will be established to fulfill the demands of truth and justice. It is due to the different states and distinctions of this era that the Quran mentions various names for the Day of Judgment.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ ؕ وَ اِنَّمَا تُوَفَّوۡنَ اُجُوۡرَکُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ» (3:185)  \nTranslation: Every soul shall taste the bitterness of death, and on the Day of Judgment you will be recompensed fully for your deeds.","«قِیَامَۃ» meaning the one who remains steadfast in all circumstances.","Resurrection","قیامۃ","2:85-2:113-2:174-2:212-3:55-3:77-3:161-3:180-3:185-3:194-4:87-4:109-4:141-4:159-5:14-5:36-5:64-6:12-7:32-7:167-7:172-10:60-10:93-11:60-11:98-11:99-16:25-16:27-16:92-16:124-17:13-17:58-17:62-17:97-18:105-19:95-20:100-20:101-20:124-21:47-22:9-22:17-22:69-23:16-25:69-28:41-28:42-28:61-28:71-28:72-29:13-29:25-32:25-35:14-39:15-39:24-39:31-39:47-39:60-39:67-41:40-42:45-45:17-45:26-46:5-58:7-60:3-68:39-75:1-75:6",70
2199,476,"R","اَلسَّاعَۃ","«سَاعَۃ» means clock. And «اَلسَّاعَۃ» means a specific clock. In the Noble Quran, «اَلسَّاعَۃ» generally refers to the clock (or time) when the trumpet will be blown for the first time (on Judgment Day).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً  قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا» (6:31)\nTranslation: Until, when the Hour (of Judgment) comes upon them unexpectedly, they will say, Oh, woe to us for having neglected it! (i.e., the Hour).","«اَلسَّاعَۃ» specific hour, moment, time.","Resurrection","الساعۃ","6:31-6:40-7:187-12:107-15:85-16:77-18:21-18:36-19:75-20:15-21:49-22:1-22:7-22:55-25:11-30:12-30:14-30:55-31:34-33:63-34:3-40:46-40:59-41:47-41:50-42:17-42:18-43:61-43:66-43:85-45:27-45:32-47:18-54:1-54:46-79:42",36
2200,476,"R","یَوْمُ الدِّیْن","The Day or era in which every individual will be given the reward or punishment for their good or evil deeds. The Day of Recompense. The Day of Judgment. Resurrection.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ» (1/3)\nTranslation: He is the Master of the Day of Recompense.","«یَوْمُ الدِّیْن» The Day of Recompense for deeds.","Resurrection (or Day of Judgment)","یوم الدین","1:3-15:35-26:82-37:20-38:78-51:12-56:56-70:26-74:46-82:15-82:17-82:18-83:11",13
2201,476,"R","یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج","The Day of emerging from the graves. With the second blowing of the trumpet, the dead will come to life and stand up, emerging from their graves.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَّوۡمَ  یَسۡمَعُوۡنَ الصَّیۡحَۃَ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ یَوۡمُ  الۡخُرُوۡجِ» ( 50/42 )\nTranslation: On the Day they will hear the true call, it will be a Day of emerging from the graves.","«یَوْمُ الْخُرُوْج» Day of Resurrection","Resurrection","یوم الخروج","50:42",1
2202,476,"R","یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب","«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب» The Day of Reckoning and Account. And the task of taking this account will be the sole responsibility of Allah, the Most High.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» ( 89/25,26 )\nTranslation: Indeed, they will return to Us, and then it is for Us to call them to account.\nAt another place, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا رَبَّنَا عَجِّلۡ  لَّنَا قِطَّنَا قَبۡلَ یَوۡمِ  الۡحِسَابِ» ( 38/16 )\nTranslation: And they say, Our Lord, hasten for us our account before the Day of Reckoning.","«یَوْمُ الْحِسَاب» The Day of Reckoning when people's deeds will be accounted for.","Resurrection","یوم الحساب","38:16-38:26-38:53-40:27",4
2203,476,"D","یَوْمُ الْفَصْل","«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل» The Day of Separation. The day when believers and disbelievers will be distinguished. And this will occur after the judgment is decreed. The people of Paradise and the people of Hell will be set apart.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«ہٰذَا یَوۡمُ الۡفَصۡلِ ۚ جَمَعۡنٰکُمۡ وَ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (77/38)  \nTranslation: This is the Day of Decision; We have gathered you and your forefathers together.","«یَوْمُ الْفَصْل» The Day when Believers and Disbelievers will be separated.","Day of Judgment","یوم الفصل","37:21-44:40-77:13-77:14-77:38-78:17",6
2204,476,"R","غَاشِیَۃ","«غَشِی» refers to a state in which a person's senses and consciousness are completely lost. And «غَاشِیَۃ» means that thing whose awe and majesty will overwhelm everyone. That which causes the loss of senses and consciousness.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ہَلۡ  اَتٰىکَ حَدِیۡثُ  الۡغَاشِیَۃِ» (88/1)\nTranslation: Has there come to you the news of the Overwhelming Event (i.e., the Day of Judgment)?","«غَاشِیَۃ» meaning to cover something by casting the shadow of one thing over another.","Resurrection","غاشیۃ","12:107-88:1",2
2205,476,"R","اَلْوَاقِعَۃ","meaning that which is bound to happen or that which is inevitable.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«اِذَا وَقَعَتِ الۡوَاقِعَۃُ لَیۡسَ  لِوَقۡعَتِہَا  کَاذِبَۃٌ» (56:1,2)  \nTranslation: When the inevitable Hour (of Judgment) arrives, there will be no falsehood about its coming.","«اَلْوَاقِعَۃ» that is about to occur.","Resurrection","الواقعۃ","56:1-69:15",2
2206,476,"R","اَلْحَاقَّۃ","«حَقَّ» meaning necessary and established (from 'munjad'), and «حَاقَّۃ» meaning that whose existence is demanded by truth; a permanent reality.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡحَآقَّۃُ» (69/3)  \nTranslation: And what will make you realize what the inevitable reality is?","«اَلْحَاقَّۃ» whose establishment is a requirement of truth.","Resurrection","الحاقۃ","69:1-69:2-69:3",3
2207,476,"D","صَآخَّۃ","«صَآخَّۃ» refers to a sound that deafens (m. l.), a harsh and piercing sound that causes the ears to burst open. This quality will occur at the time of the first Blast of the Trumpet.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ الصَّآخَّۃُ» (80/33)\nTranslation: So when the Deafening Blast (of the Resurrection) comes.","«صَآخَّۃ» refers to a sound that deafens the ears.","Day of Judgment","صآخۃ","80:33",1
2208,476,"R","اٰزِفَۃ","The meaning of time becoming short is understood (as in the example), as we say that the time for the train's departure has become short. And «اٰزِفَۃ» means 'about to arrive soon.' For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡہُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡاٰزِفَۃِ» (40/18)\nTranslation: And warn them of the Day that is drawing near.","«اٰزِفَۃ» meaning imminent.","Resurrection","ازفۃ","40:18-53:57",2
2209,476,"D","قَارِعَۃ","«قَرَعَ» means to strike one thing upon another in such a way that a sound is produced. And «قَرَعَ الْبَاب» means he knocked on the door. And «قَارِعَۃ» means the one that rattles or clatters. And according to Ibn al-Faris, anything that descends upon a person with intensity is «قَارِعَۃ» (m. l.). The Divine command is:\n«وَ  مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡقَارِعَۃُ» (101/3) And what will make you realize what the Rattling One is?","«قَارِعَۃ» meaning to strike one thing upon another in such a way that sound is produced.","Day of Judgment","قارعۃ","13:31-69:4-101:1-101:2-101:3",5
2210,476,"D","طَآمَّۃُ الْکُبْرٰی","«اَلطَّمُّ» means a sea filled with water. And «طَمَّ» means the filling of something. «طَمَّ الْبِئْرَ» He filled the well with soil. And «طَامَّۃ» means an affliction that encompasses all other calamities.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«فَاِذَا جَآءَتِ  الطَّآمَّۃُ  الۡکُبۡرٰی» ( 79/34 )  \nTranslation: Then when the great calamity comes.  \nFor the meaning of to stand/resume, see to become inhabited and to remain.","A calamity that overwhelms all other afflictions.","Day of Judgment","طآمۃ الکبری","79:34",1
2211,477,"I","سِجْن","«سِجْن» meaning prison or jail. It is a well-known term. A place where people sentenced by a court are kept in confinement.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«فَلَبِثَ فِی السِّجۡنِ بِضۡعَ سِنِیۡنَ» (12/42)  \nTranslation: Then Yusuf (Joseph) remained in the prison for several years.","«سِجْن» meaning prison, jail.","Imprisonment","سجن","12:33-12:35-12:36-12:39-12:41-12:42-12:100",7
2212,477,"I","حَصِیْر","«حَصَرَ» means to encircle something from all sides. To besiege. To surround. And «حَصِیْر» means a place of confinement for someone.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا جَہَنَّمَ لِلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  حَصِیۡرًا» (17/8)  \nTranslation: And We have made Hell a prison for the disbelievers.","«حَصِیْر» meaning to encompass.","Imprisonment","حصیر","17:8",1
2213,477,"B","حَبَسَ","«حَبَسَ» meaning to prevent someone from rising (transitive) and «حَبَسَ الشَّیْ» meaning to fully protect something. And «مَحْبَسَۃ» meaning prison. Also the seclusion of devotees and ascetics. «حَابَسَ» meaning to keep someone stopped. To keep in custody (transitive). Also «حَبَسَ» meaning «مَنَعَ عَنِ التَّصَرُّف» (faq l 93) i.e., to prevent someone from disposing of their property. And «مَحْبَس» meaning police stations where the accused are kept in custody during investigation at the police station (police).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«تَحۡبِسُوۡنَہُمَا مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ الصَّلٰوۃِ  فَیُقۡسِمٰنِ بِاللّٰہِ» (5/106)\nTranslation: Detain these two witnesses after the (Asr) prayer and make them swear by Allah.","Prohibiting someone from managing their property and needs.","Bond","حبس","5:106-11:8",2
2214,477,"I","اَثْبَتَ","«اَثْبَتَ» means to bind someone with chains (manjada), i.e., to tie someone up, restrict their movement, and keep them in custody. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ اِذۡ یَمۡکُرُ بِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لِیُثۡبِتُوۡکَ اَوۡ یَقۡتُلُوۡکَ اَوۡ یُخۡرِجُوۡکَ» (8/30) Translation: And O Muhammad ﷺ! Remember when the disbelievers were plotting against you, intending to imprison you, kill you, or expel you (from your homeland).","to take into custody after binding them","Imprisonment","اثبت","8:30",1
2215,477,"C","اَسَرَ","The meaning of «اَسَرَ» is also to tie someone with a rope (cf.). The difference between «اَسَرَ» and «اَثْبَتَ» is that «اَسَرَ» refers specifically to capturing someone during wartime. «اَسِیْر» means war captive, and its plurals are «اَسْرٰی» and «اُسَارٰی».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتُوۡکُمۡ اُسٰرٰی تُفٰدُوۡہُمۡ  وَ ہُوَ مُحَرَّمٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ اِخۡرَاجُہُمۡ» (2:85)\nTranslation: And if they come to you as captives, you ransom them, even though their expulsion was forbidden for you.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«فَرِیۡقًا تَقۡتُلُوۡنَ وَ تَاۡسِرُوۡنَ فَرِیۡقًا» (33:26)\nTranslation: You were killing some and capturing others.","To take someone prisoner during wartime.","Confinement","اسر","2:85-8:67-8:70-33:26-",4
2216,477,"I","سَجَنَ","«سَجَنَ» Imprisonment as a punitive measure after the establishment of a crime; sending someone to jail; a judge imposing imprisonment as a sentence for an offense.\n\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالَتۡ مَا جَزَآءُ مَنۡ اَرَادَ بِاَہۡلِکَ سُوۡٓءًا اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یُّسۡجَنَ اَوۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (12/25) Translation: Zulaikha said (to her husband), What is the punishment for someone who intends evil against your wife? It is that he should be imprisoned or subjected to a painful punishment.","«سَجَنَ» The court's sentencing of a criminal to imprisonment.","Imprisonment","سجن","12:25-12:32-",2
2217,478,"T","حَصَدَ","«حَصَد» means the cutting of a dry and ripe crop (verse 211), and «حَصِیْد» means the harvested farmland. And «مِحْصَدُ» means the standing crop, and «حَصِيْدَةُ» means the roots left behind after harvesting the crop, which the sickle does not reach. (A Punjabi idiom) (M. Q. Majid). Thus, the word «حَصَدَ» is generally used for harvesting with a sickle.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَمَا حَصَدۡتُّمۡ  فَذَرُوۡہُ  فِیۡ  سُنۡۢبُلِہٖۤ» (12/47)\nTranslation: So leave the grain you harvest in its ears (i.e., do not thresh it immediately).","«حَصَد» harvesting the ripe crop.","to cut","حصد","12:47",1
2218,478,"T","صَرَمَ","To cut branches of trees, etc., with a sharp instrument. «صَارِم» meaning sword and «صَرُمَ» meaning to cut with a sword. And «صَرُوْم» meaning the cutting sword (singular and accusative). For example, in the Quran it is: «اِنَّا  بَلَوۡنٰہُمۡ کَمَا بَلَوۡنَاۤ  اَصۡحٰبَ الۡجَنَّۃِ ۚ اِذۡ  اَقۡسَمُوۡا لَیَصۡرِمُنَّہَا مُصۡبِحِیۡنَ» (68/17) Translation: We tested them as We tested the owners of the garden. When they swore that they would cut down the garden in the morning.","«صَرَمَ» to cut clusters of fruit with a sharp-edged tool.","to cut","صرم","68:17",1
2219,478,"T","قَطَعَ","«قَطَعَ» meaning to cut something and separate a part of it (masc.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَا قَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  لِّیۡنَۃٍ اَوۡ تَرَکۡتُمُوۡہَا قَآئِمَۃً عَلٰۤی اُصُوۡلِہَا فَبِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» ( 59/5 )\nTranslation: Whatever palm trees you cut down or left standing on their roots, it was by Allah's command.","To cut off anything.","to slaughter (an animal for sacrifice)","قطع","2:27-3:127-5:38-6:45-7:72-8:7-9:121-13:25-22:15-29:29-59:5-69:46",12
2220,478,"T","قَطَّعَ","«قَطَّعَ» means to cut something into pieces, to make small pieces.\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«وَ سُقُوۡا مَآءً حَمِیۡمًا فَقَطَّعَ  اَمۡعَآءَہُمۡ» (47/15)\nTranslation: And they will be given to drink boiling water which will cut their intestines into pieces.","to cut «قَطَّعَ» into pieces","to cut","قطع","7:124-7:160-7:168-12:31-12:50-13:31-20:71-22:19-26:49-47:15",10
2221,478,"T","بَتَرَ","This term is specifically used for cutting off an animal's tail, and metaphorically, it means ‘maktu’ an-nasl’ or ‘la-walad,’ i.e., one who has no offspring, or one whose good mention does not endure (detailed). For example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ شَانِئَکَ ہُوَ الۡاَبۡتَرُ» (108/3) Translation: Indeed, your enemy is the one without heirs and without name or legacy.","«بَتَرَ» cutting off the tail of an animal. To be of cut-off progeny (i.e., one whose lineage has been severed).","to cut","بتر","108:3",1
2222,478,"T","بَتْک","According to Khalil, «بَتْک» refers to the severing of ties (cutting off the ears). (م ۔ ل) Whereas, according to Imam Raghib, its meaning is to slit the ears of animals or to cut off other limbs, hair, etc. (مف) In the days of pre-Islamic ignorance, people used to perform such acts as a sign of vows and offerings.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ لَاُضِلَّنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاُمَنِّیَنَّہُمۡ وَ لَاٰمُرَنَّہُمۡ فَلَیُبَتِّکُنَّ اٰذَانَ الۡاَنۡعَامِ» (4/119)\nTranslation: (Satan said) I will surely mislead the children of Adam. I will grant them alluring dreams, and I will command them that they slit the ears of cattle.","«بَتْک» cutting or tearing the ear or similar.","to cut","بتک","4:119",1
2223,478,"T","عَضَّ","«عَضَّ» to bite a living being with one's teeth ( f. l 110 )\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ  یَوۡمَ یَعَضُّ الظَّالِمُ عَلٰی  یَدَیۡہِ یَقُوۡلُ یٰلَیۡتَنِی اتَّخَذۡتُ مَعَ الرَّسُوۡلِ سَبِیۡلًا» (25/27)\nTranslation: And on the day when the wrongdoer will bite his own hands and will say, Alas! I had chosen my path along with the Messenger.","«عَضَّ» meaning to cut with the teeth.","to cut","عض","3:119-25:27",2
2224,478,"T","خَضَدَ","«خَضَدَ الشَّجَرَ» To cut or break off the thorns of a thorny tree and thus make it smooth; to render it free of thorns.  \nFor example, in the Quran:  \n«فِیۡ  سِدۡرٍ مَّخۡضُوۡدٍ» (56/28)  \nTranslation: (They will enjoy) in thornless sidr trees.","«خَضَدَ» pruning and cleaning the tree's thorn.","to cut","خضد","56:28",1
2225,478,"T","جَذَّ","The original meaning of «جَذَّ» is to cut or break something hard into fragments. And «اَلْجِذّ» means a small piece of something that has been cut, and «جُدَاد» or «جُداذ» means a cut piece, like a piece of gold. And «اذات» means fine fragments or pieces of something cut (cf. Munjid). These meanings are how the word is used in the Quran.\n\n«فَجَعَلَہُمۡ جُذٰذًا» (21/58)\nTranslation: Then he broke them all to pieces.\n\nLater, this word began to be used in the meanings of cutting or breaking.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«عَطَآءً غَیۡرَ  مَجۡذُوۡذٍ» (11/108)\nTranslation: This is the bounty of Allah which He grants to whom He wills, and it is never exhausted.","«جَذَّ» to cut something hard into pieces.","to cut","جذ","11:108-21:58",2
2226,478,"T","عَقَرَ","«عَقَر» the meaning of inflicting a wound is found (M.L.) «اَلْکَلْبُ الْعَقُوْر» meaning: a cutting dog. And «عَقَرَ النَّخْلَۃ» meaning: to cut down a date palm tree from the root. (Munjid)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَکَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَعَقَرُوۡہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So they denied Prophet Salih and hamstrung the she-camel.","making a surgical incision","to cut","عقر","7:77-11:65-26:157-54:29-91:14",5
2227,478,"T","تَقَطَّعَ","«تَقَطَّع» To become severed or separated by cutting or breaking.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡ  تَبَرَّاَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتُّبِعُوۡا مِنَ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّبَعُوۡا  وَ رَاَوُا  الۡعَذَابَ وَ تَقَطَّعَتۡ بِہِمُ الۡاَسۡبَابُ» (2/166)\nTranslation: On that Day, the leaders (of disbelief) will renounce their followers, and both will see the punishment, and all their ties between them will be cut off.","«تَقَطَّع» meaning to be severed.","to slaughter (an animal for sacrifice)","تقطع","2:166-5:33-6:94-9:110-21:93-23:53-29:29-47:22",8
2229,479,"P","رَقّ","«رَقَّ» means to be thin and soft. And «رِقَّت» refers to the softness of the heart, and its opposite is «قساوت», meaning hard-heartedness. And «رَقّ» is everything that is thin and soft, such as a tree's leaf, a membrane, thin leather, or paper (muf); thus, this word carries a general meaning. «رَقّ» and «وَرْق» are synonymous, and its plural is «اَوْرَاق».  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ کِتٰبٍ مَّسۡطُوۡرٍ فِیۡ  رَقٍّ مَّنۡشُوۡرٍ» (52:2-3)  \nTranslation: And by the Book which is written in spread-open leaves.","«رَقّ» Every thin and soft thing on which writing can be done, whether it is blank or already written upon.","paper","رق","52:3",1
2230,479,"P","قِرْطَاس","«قِرْطَاس» meaning a written letter or scroll (manshūd), whether it consists of several pages or leaves (m. q.). Qurtas abiad is a famous term. It also means a clear and complete report published on an important issue. «قِرْطَاس» In fact, it also refers to that early form of paper in roll form which was invented by the Egyptians; such paper was available at the time of the revelation of the Quran, but it was very rare.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ نَزَّلۡنَا عَلَیۡکَ کِتٰبًا فِیۡ قِرۡطَاسٍ فَلَمَسُوۡہُ بِاَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (6/7)\nTranslation: And if We had sent down to you a book written on paper, and they had touched it with their hands...","«قِرْطَاس» The preliminary draft form of written documents or existing paper.","paper","قرطاس","6:7",1
2231,480,"S","کَفٰی","«کَفٰی» means to be sufficient. To suffice for something and to be independent of others. Sometimes a preposition is also added to the subject of «کَفٰی». For example, «کَفٰی بِاللہِ شَھِیْدَا», meaning the testimony of Allah is so sufficient and complete that it makes one independent of the testimony of anyone else (Manjad). And «کَفَایَۃ» is that thing which is sufficient and makes one independent of others. And «مَکَافَات» means to recompense with an equal favor or with something even more (Manjad). The word «کَفٰی» essentially carries the meaning of giving a full, complete recompense for a thing and even giving something extra beyond that.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَفَی اللّٰہُ  الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ الۡقِتَالَ ؕ وَ کَانَ  اللّٰہُ   قَوِیًّا عَزِیۡزًا» (33:25)\nTranslation: And Allah was sufficient for the believers in the battle, and Allah is Ever-Mighty, Ever-Exalted.\n\nA word with a meaning very close to «کَفٰی» is «حَسْب». These two words are so close in meaning that one is used effortlessly in place of the other.\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\nحَسۡبُہٗ جَہَنَّم (2:206)\nTranslation: So Hell is sufficient for him.\nMoreover, the Divine Command states:\nوَ کَفٰی  بِجَہَنَّم (4:55)\nTranslation: And the burning of Hell is sufficient.\n\nThe only difference is that if the overall aspect is kept in view, «کَفٰی» is used. And if each individual aspect is considered, «حَسْب» is used.\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَفٰی بِاللّٰہِ حَسِیۡبًا» (4:6)\nTranslation: In reality, Allah alone is sufficient as the reckoner.","«کَفٰی» meaning to be sufficient; to suffice for something; and to be independent of others.","Sufficient","کفی","2:137-3:124-4:6-4:45-4:50-4:55-4:70-4:79-4:81-4:132-4:166-4:171-10:29-13:43-15:95-17:14-17:17-17:65-17:96-21:47-25:31-25:58-29:51-29:52-33:3-33:25-33:39-33:48-46:8-48:28",30
2232,480,"S","حَسْب","«حَسَبَ» means to calculate, count, enumerate, and then to keep its account. Moreover, «حَسَبَ» is a verb meaning to keep account of each thing individually and record its equivalent. Urdu has no specific word for this concept. Therefore, its translation is rendered as 'kafi'. However, in Punjabi, there is a term for it: 'ایچی بیچی' (meaning 'keeping account'), which conveys this meaning. That is, this matter or this work is sufficient for each of our individual needs and requirements. In other words, the word «حَسْب» is stronger than «کَفٰی». For example, the Quran states: «حَسۡبُنَا اللّٰہُ وَ نِعۡمَ الۡوَکِیۡلُ» (3/173). Translation: Allah is sufficient for us, and He is the best disposer of affairs.","«حَسْب» meaning to calculate, count, enumerate, then to keep its record.","Sufficient","حسب","2:206-3:173-5:104-8:62-8:64-9:59-9:68-9:129-39:38-58:8-65:3",11
2233,481,"D","جَزَا یَجْزِیْ جَزَاءً","Two meanings are found for «جَزَا ، یَجْزِیْ ، جَزَاءً»: (1) To give full recompense for an action and then to free or save someone. (2) To become a substitute for an action; for something to come to pass.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمًا لَّا تَجۡزِیۡ نَفۡسٌ عَنۡ نَّفۡسٍ شَیۡئًا» (2/48)\nTranslation: On that Day, no one will avail another anything.\n\nAnd an example of giving recompense to save:\nThe sublime command of Allah is:\n«اِنِّیۡ جَزَیۡتُہُمُ  الۡیَوۡمَ  بِمَا صَبَرُوۡۤا ۙ اَنَّہُمۡ  ہُمُ  الۡفَآئِزُوۡنَ» (23/111)\nTranslation: Today I have rewarded them for their patience. Indeed, they have succeeded.","«جَزَاء» is to give full recompense for something, then to free or save it.","Deed","جزا یجزی جزاءً","2:48-2:85-2:123-2:191-3:87-3:136-3:144-3:145-4:93-5:29-5:33-5:38-5:85-5:95-6:84-6:138-6:139-6:146-6:157-7:40-7:41-7:152-9:26-9:82-9:95-9:121-10:4-10:13-10:27-12:22-12:25-12:74-12:75-12:88-14:51-16:31-16:96-16:97-17:63-17:98-18:88-18:106-20:76-20:127-21:29-23:111-24:38-25:15-28:14-28:25-29:7-30:45-31:33-32:17-33:24-34:4-34:17-34:37-35:36-37:80-37:105-37:110-37:121-37:131-39:34-39:35-41:27-41:28-42:40-45:14-46:14-46:25-53:31-53:41-54:14-54:35-55:60-56:24-59:17-76:9-76:12-76:22-77:44-78:26-78:36-98:8",86
2234,481,"D","اَغْنٰی","«اَغْنٰی» The state of something being sufficient and beneficial to the extent that the need and necessity for another thing no longer exists. (m.f.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَاۤ  اَغۡنٰی عَنِّیۡ  مَالِیَہۡ ہَلَکَ عَنِّیۡ  سُلۡطٰنِیَہۡ» (69/28,29)\nTranslation: My wealth availed me nothing. My kingdom has departed from me.","«اَغْنٰی» to be of use and benefit.","Deed","اغنی","7:48-11:101-12:67-15:84-26:207-39:50-40:82-46:26-69:28-111:2",10
2235,481,"D","فَعَلَ","«فِعْل» Every action that results from an effective cause. It applies to all [actions], whether the doer has intention or not, and whether it has a material existence or not. Its plural is «افعال» (lexical) and «فَعْلَۃً» means to do something once.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ فَعَلۡتَ فَعۡلَتَکَ الَّتِیۡ فَعَلۡتَ وَ اَنۡتَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (26:19)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said to Moses) And you did another thing (the killing of the Egyptian). You seem to be ungrateful.\nSee, in this verse, the killing mentioned happened unintentionally from Moses.\nAnd for an action done with intention:\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«فَافۡعَلُوۡا مَا تُؤۡمَرُوۡنَ» (2:68)\nTranslation: So do what you are commanded.","An act that is either committed intentionally or occurs unintentionally.","Deeds","فعل","2:24-2:68-2:71-2:85-2:197-2:215-2:231-2:234-2:240-2:253-2:279-2:282-3:28-3:40-3:115-3:135-3:188-4:25-4:30-4:66-4:114-4:127-4:147-5:67-5:79-6:112-6:137-6:159-7:28-7:155-7:173-8:73-10:36-10:46-10:106-11:36-11:87-12:32-12:89-14:27-14:45-16:33-16:35-16:50-16:91-18:82-21:23-21:59-21:62-21:63-21:73-22:14-22:18-22:77-24:41-25:68-26:19-26:20-26:74-26:226-27:34-27:88-30:40-33:6-34:54-37:34-37:102-39:70-42:25-46:9-49:6-54:52-58:13-60:1-61:2-61:3-63:9-66:6-75:25-77:18-82:12-83:36-85:7-89:6-105:1",85
2236,481,"D","عَمِلَ","Every intentional act committed by a living being, whether good or bad. Its plural form is «اَعْمَال». The term «عَمَل» is also used to denote labor or wages. For example, the Quran states: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79). Translation: And the ship belonged to some poor people who earned their living at sea.","That action which is done intentionally to fulfill some purpose.","Deed","عمل","2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3",309
2237,481,"D","صَنَعَ","«صَنَعَ» To execute a task with artistic craftsmanship. It is more specific than «عَمَلَ» and is not used for animals (masc.), and «صَنَّاع» means craftsman—an expert in one's work.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اصۡنَعِ الۡفُلۡکَ بِاَعۡیُنِنَا وَ وَحۡیِنَا» (11/37)\nTranslation: O Noah! Build the Ark under Our eyes and in accordance with the guidance of Our revelation.","«صَنَعَ» to execute with technical proficiency.","deed","صنع","5:14-5:63-7:137-11:16-11:37-11:38-13:31-16:112-18:104-20:39-20:41-20:69-21:80-23:27-24:30-27:88-29:45-35:8",18
2238,481,"W","صَدَعَ","«صَدَعَ» means to undertake a task (manjīd) — to carry out an action while enduring hardships. And «صَدَعَ بِالْحَقّ» means to openly declare the truth. And «صَدَعَ الشَّیْ» means to split something but not separate it (manjīd). For example, the Quran states: «فَاصۡدَعۡ بِمَا تُؤۡمَرُ وَ اَعۡرِضۡ عَنِ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ» (15/94). Translation: So fulfill what has been commanded to you from Allah, and do not heed the polytheists.","«صَدَعَ» to get something done despite difficulties.","Work","صدع","15:94-30:43-56:19-59:21-86:12",5
2239,481,"W","جَرَحَ","«جُرْحُ» means 'wound'; its plural is «جُرُوْح». And «جَرَحَ» means 'to inflict a wound'. «جَرَحَ بِالِلّسَان» means 'to wound someone with the tongue', 'to cause harm with speech', 'to mention someone's faults and defects'. And «جَرَحَ الشَّھَادَۃ» means 'to invalidate testimony' (Majid). When this verb is used in the sense of performing an action, it is generally used in a negative sense. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ یَتَوَفّٰىکُمۡ بِالَّیۡلِ وَ یَعۡلَمُ مَا جَرَحۡتُمۡ بِالنَّہَارِ» (6/60)\nTranslation: And He it is who takes your souls by night (while you sleep) and knows what you do during the day.\nAnd «اِجْتَرَحَ» specifically comes in the meaning of 'to commit' i.e., in the sense of performing an action (Majid). «اِجْتَرَحَ الْاِثْم» he committed a sin.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَمۡ  حَسِبَ الَّذِیۡنَ اجۡتَرَحُوا  السَّیِّاٰتِ اَنۡ نَّجۡعَلَہُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ» (45/21)\nTranslation: Do those who commit evil deeds think that We will treat them the same as those who believe and do righteous deeds?","«جَرَحَ» is generally used to do evil deeds.","Work","جرح","6:60",1
2240,481,"W","تَعَمَّدَ","«عَمَدَ» means to intend and resolve upon something. And «عَمَد» means pillars; its plural is «عِمَاد». And «عَمُوْد» refers to the wood upon which a tent is erected. And «تَعَمَّدَ» means to do something knowingly, i.e., to deliberately do an act about which one has prior knowledge that it is evil, and its opposite is «سَھْو». (m.f.)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّقۡتُلۡ مُؤۡمِنًا مُّتَعَمِّدًا فَجَزَآؤُہٗ جَہَنَّمُ خٰلِدًا فِیۡہَا» (4/93)\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer intentionally, his recompense is Hell, wherein he will abide eternally.","«تَعَمَّدَ» to jeopardize one's life and property for some evil act.","Work","تعمد","4:93-5:95-33:5",3
2241,481,"D","اَمْر","«اَمْر» means work, state, matter, speech, or command, whether verbal or practical. Its plural is «اُمُوْر». This word is even more general than 'action' (فعل) because its application extends to sayings as well as actions. Furthermore, it also applies to matters or affairs that pertain to the Divine Will (مشیت الٰہی) and Divine Decree (تقدیر الٰہی).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مَا کُنۡتُ قَاطِعَۃً  اَمۡرًا حَتّٰی تَشۡہَدُوۡنِ» (27/32)\nTranslation: (The Queen of Sheba said to the chiefs) I will not decide any matter until you are present (and advise me).\n\nIn this verse, the word 'أمر' conveys the meanings of work, speech, and matter simultaneously, and the matter (کام) has no existence even in terms of speech or action.\n\nFurthermore, «اَمْر» also carries the meaning of 'command'. In this sense, its plural is «اَوَامِرْ» and its opposite is «نَوَاھِی». And when «اَمْر» appears as a verb, its meaning is not 'to do' but rather 'to command'.","This term «اَمْر» is even more general than the verb, because its application extends to utterances as well as actions.","Divine decree","امر","2:117-2:210-2:275-3:47-3:109-3:128-3:147-3:154-3:159-3:186-4:83-5:95-6:8-6:58-6:159-8:42-8:43-8:44-9:48-9:50-10:3-10:31-10:71-11:44-11:123-12:15-12:18-12:21-12:41-12:83-12:102-13:2-13:31-14:22-15:66-16:77-18:10-18:16-18:21-18:28-18:73-18:82-19:21-19:35-19:39-20:26-20:32-20:62-21:93-22:41-22:67-22:76-23:53-24:62-27:32-27:33-31:17-31:22-32:5-33:36-35:4-36:82-40:44-40:68-42:38-42:43-42:53-43:79-44:4-45:17-45:18-47:26-49:7-50:5-51:4-54:3-54:12-57:5-59:15-64:5-65:3-65:4-65:9-79:5-97:4",85
2242,481,"D","شَاْن","«شَاْن» The collection of its «شُؤُوْن» means great matters, situations, transactions, and states. And «مِنْ شَانِہٖ کَذَا» means to act in a manner that is inherent to its very nature and disposition (i.e., 'shan' refers to performing actions that are worthy of one's status or appropriate to the situation).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَسۡئَلُہٗ مَنۡ فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ ؕ کُلَّ یَوۡمٍ ہُوَ فِیۡ شَاۡنٍ» (55/29)\nTranslation: All that is in the heavens and the earth seeks from Him (their needs), and He is in a state of dignity every day.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«فَاِذَا اسۡتَاۡذَنُوۡکَ لِبَعۡضِ شَاۡنِہِمۡ فَاۡذَنۡ  لِّمَنۡ شِئۡتَ مِنۡہُمۡ» (24/62)\nTranslation: When they ask you, O Prophet, for permission to do something, then grant permission to whomever you wish among them.","«شَاْن» to perform deeds that are worthy of one's dignity or appropriate to one's circumstances.","Deeds","شان","24:62-55:29",2
2243,482,"S","اَفْلَحَ","Three meanings are found for «فَلَحَ»: (1) to split, (2) success, (3) survival (continuance). And «فَلَّاح» means a farmer who tills the land to sow seeds. He achieves success when the crop ripens and, by benefiting from it, attains his goal. And «اَفْلَحَ» means to be successful, to reach one's goal which comes as a result of one's own actions and efforts. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَدۡ  اَفۡلَحَ  الۡمُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  فِیۡ صَلَاتِہِمۡ خٰشِعُوۡنَ» (23/1,2)\nTranslation: Undoubtedly, the believers will attain success, those who are humble in their prayers.","«اَفْلَح» meaning to be successful, such success that comes as a result of one's own actions and hard work.","Successful","افلح","20:64-23:1-87:14-91:9",4
2244,482,"S","فَازَ","«فَازَ» means to be saved from a calamity and, at the same time, to reach a beloved object or goal (Faqih 273), and also to attain goodness with safety and well-being (Mufradat).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» (3/185)\nTranslation: Whoever is kept away from the Fire (Hell) and is admitted to Paradise, has attained his goal.\n\n«فَازَ»: This word originates from the category of 'addad' (antonymous words). «فَاز» also means to be successful and to be saved, as well as to be destroyed or to die. «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل» means 'the person died.' And «مَفَازَۃٌ» also means the cause or place of success, as well as the cause or place of destruction or ruin (Munjid). As in the previously cited verse, it is used here in the meanings of the place or cause of destruction. However, generally, this word comes in the meanings of being successful by being saved from a calamity and by attaining the desired object or goal.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یّٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتُ مَعَہُمۡ فَاَفُوۡزَ فَوۡزًا عَظِیۡمًا» (4/73)\nTranslation: The hypocrite will say, 'If only I had been with them, I would have attained a great success (Uthmani).'\n\nNote: (Lughat Addad refers to words that have two separate meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other).","«فَازَ» To escape a calamity and simultaneously reach a cherished goal.","Successful","فاز","3:185-4:13-4:73-5:119-6:16-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:64-33:71-37:60-40:9-44:57-45:30-48:5-57:12-61:12-64:9-85:11",20
2245,483,"T","زَلْزَلَ","«زَلَّ» meaning the slipping of a foot. And «زَلْزَل» involves verbal repetition which indicates conceptual repetition, i.e., slipping here and there repeatedly (interpretive meaning). And «زَلْزَلَۃ» means earthquake: the earth being shaken, moving, and trembling (fa 172). This term is specifically used for earthquake.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذَا  زُلۡزِلَتِ الۡاَرۡضُ  زِلۡزَالَہَا» (99/1)\nTranslation: When the earth is shaken with «اِذَا  زُلۡزِلَتِ الۡاَرۡضُ  زِلۡزَالَہَا».","«زَلْزَلَ ، رَجَّ» and «رَجَفَ» are all generally used for earthquake. «زَلْزَل» is common; «رَجَّ» refers to the initial quality and «رَجَفَ» to the severe quality. And «مَارَ» refers to vibration and shaking due to rapid movement in anything.","to tremble","زلزل","2:214-22:1-33:11-99:1",4
2246,483,"T","رَجّ","«رَجّ» To cause something to move; to give a jolt or shake (intransitive). This is the initial stage of an earthquake (Fasl 60).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذَا  رُجَّتِ الۡاَرۡضُ  رَجًّا» (56/4)\nTranslation: When the earth begins to shake due to the earthquake.","«رَجّ» to move something, to jolt it.","to tremble","رج","56:4",1
2247,483,"T","رَجَفَ","The basic meaning of «رَجَفَ» is severe turmoil (m. l). «بَحْرٌ رَجَّافٌ» means a turbulent sea.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَّ الۡمُرۡجِفُوۡنَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ» (33:60)  \nTranslation: And those who spread panic in Medina (i.e., those who stir waves of unrest).  \n\nAnd when it is attributed to the earth, it signifies severe jolts—the intense nature of an earthquake (fl 60).  \nFor example, the Divine declaration states:  \n«یَوۡمَ تَرۡجُفُ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ الۡجِبَالُ وَ کَانَتِ الۡجِبَالُ  کَثِیۡبًا مَّہِیۡلًا» (73:14)  \nTranslation: On the Day when the earth and the mountains shall shake, and the mountains become like heaps of sand slipping away.","«رَجَفَ» to be restless and unsettled, agitated due to fear.","to tremble","رجف","7:78-7:91-7:155-29:37-73:14-79:6",6
2248,483,"T","مَارَ","In «مَارَ», the basic concept is movement and swiftness. «اَلنَّاقَۃُ تَمُوْرُ فِیْ سَیْرِھَا» meaning a camel moving swiftly, raising dust (muf), and «مَوْر» meaning to become dust and fly in the wind (fl 31), and «مَارَ الشَّیء» something shaking back and forth and trembling due to swiftness, losing balance (manj). For example: In the Holy Quran, it is stated: «یَّوۡمَ تَمُوۡرُ السَّمَآءُ  مَوۡرًا» (52/9). Translation: On the Day when the heaven will tremble convulsively.","«مَارَ» to vibrate due to rapid movement.","to tremble","مار","52:9-67:16",2
2249,484,"W","اَیَّان","«اَیَّان» A time comes to ask about the timing of an event (e.g.)\nFor instance: The Quran states:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ السَّاعَۃِ  اَیَّانَ مُرۡسٰہَا» (79/42)\nTranslation: (O Prophet!) They ask you about the Hour, when it will come to pass.","«اَیَّان» is used to ask about the timing of something.","when","ایان","7:187-16:21-27:65-51:12-75:6-79:42",6
2250,484,"W","مَتٰی","«مَتٰی» also conveys the meaning of a condition, in addition to time (e.g., Quran).\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«مَتٰی ہٰذَا الۡفَتۡحُ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (32/28)\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then when will this victory be?\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«مَتٰی ہٰذَا الۡوَعۡدُ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (36/48)\nTranslation: If you are truthful, then when will this promise be fulfilled?","«مَتٰی» This word is used in Arabic grammar for conditional and interrogative purposes.","when","متی","2:214-10:48-17:51-21:38-27:71-32:28-34:29-36:48-67:25",9
2251,485,"B","کِتَاب","«کِتَاب» Every written thing—a scroll, a record of deeds, and in common usage, a book—its compilation is «کُتُب».  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«اِذۡہَبۡ بِّکِتٰبِیۡ ہٰذَا» (27/28)  \nTranslation: Take my scroll with you.","«کِتَاب» Every written thing is a book in the well-known meanings.","Book","کتاب","2:2-2:44-2:53-2:78-2:79-2:85-2:87-2:89-2:101-2:105-2:109-2:113-2:121-2:129-2:144-2:145-2:146-2:151-2:159-2:174-2:176-2:177-2:213-2:231-2:235-3:3-3:7-3:19-3:20-3:23-3:48-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:70-3:71-3:72-3:75-3:78-3:79-3:81-3:98-3:99-3:100-3:110-3:113-3:119-3:145-3:164-3:184-3:186-3:187-3:199-4:24-4:44-4:47-4:51-4:54-4:103-4:105-4:113-4:123-4:127-4:131-4:136-4:140-4:153-4:159-4:171-5:5-5:15-5:19-5:44-5:48-5:57-5:59-5:65-5:68-5:77-5:110-6:7-6:20-6:38-6:59-6:89-6:91-6:92-6:114-6:154-6:155-6:156-6:157-7:2-7:37-7:52-7:169-7:170-7:196-8:68-8:75-9:29-9:36-10:1-10:37-10:61-10:94-11:1-11:6-11:17-11:110-12:1-13:1-13:36-13:38-13:39-13:43-14:1-15:1-15:4-16:64-16:89-17:2-17:4-17:13-17:14-17:58-17:71-17:93-18:1-18:27-18:49-19:12-19:16-19:30-19:41-19:51-19:54-19:56-20:52-21:10-22:8-22:70-23:49-23:62-24:33-25:35-26:2-27:1-27:28-27:29-27:40-27:75-28:2-28:43-28:49-28:52-28:86-29:27-29:45-29:46-29:47-29:48-29:51-30:56-31:2-31:20-32:2-32:23-33:6-33:26-34:3-35:11-35:25-35:29-35:31-35:32-35:40-37:117-37:157-38:29-39:1-39:2-39:23-39:41-39:69-40:2-40:53-40:70-41:3-41:41-41:45-42:14-42:15-42:17-42:52-43:2-43:4-43:21-44:2-45:2-45:16-45:28-45:29-46:2-46:4-46:12-46:30-50:4-52:2-56:78-57:16-57:22-57:25-57:26-57:29-59:2-59:11-62:2-68:37-69:19-69:25-74:31-78:29-83:7-83:9-83:18-83:20-84:7-84:10-98:1-98:4-98:6",232
2252,485,"B","اَسْفَار","«اَسْفَار» is a collection of «سِفْر», and «سِفْر» means the great book. One of the components of the Torah is a part (manjūd), and «سُفْر» means to open or to unveil something. And «سِفْر» means a book that unveils the truths (as in Mafātīḥ al-Lughah, p. 241)—the Torah's great explanations and interpretations.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «یَحۡمِلُوۡہَا کَمَثَلِ  الۡحِمَارِ یَحۡمِلُ اَسۡفَارًا» (62:5). Translation: Those upon whom the responsibility of the Torah was placed, but they failed to uphold it—their example is like that of a donkey bearing heavy loads of books.","«اَسْفَار» voluminous works (of the Torah) — commentaries and interpretations.","Book","اسفار","62:5",1
2253,485,"B","سِجِل","«سِجِل» meaning the register of contracts. It is the register in which commands are recorded and preserved, which the judge keeps with him. Judicial record. (Source)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ نَطۡوِی السَّمَآءَ کَطَیِّ السِّجِلِّ لِلۡکُتُبِ» (21/104)\nTranslation: On the day when We will fold the sky just as one rolls up a scroll.","The register for writing and preserving legal rulings, which the judge keeps in his possession.","Book","سجل","21:104",1
2254,485,"B","نُسْخَۃ","«نَسَخَ» means to erase or to abrogate. And «نَسَخَ الْکِتَاب» means to copy a book word for word. And «نُسْخَۃ» is also used for that from which a copy is made, and also for that which has been copied (M. Q). Every manuscript is a book, but not every book is a manuscript (F. L. 240).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ فِیۡ نُسۡخَتِہَا ہُدًی وَّ رَحۡمَۃٌ  لِّلَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِرَبِّہِمۡ یَرۡہَبُوۡنَ» (7:154)\n\nTranslation: And in the inscribed scroll (the Torah) there was guidance and mercy for those who feared their Lord.","The transmitted book or the book from which transmission is made.","Book","نسخۃ","7:154-45:29",2
2255,485,"B","زُبُر","«زُبْرَۃ» means a large iron plate or sheet; its plural is «زُبَر». And «زَبَرَ الْکِتَاب» means to write a book in thick script. And «زِبْر», although it is a verbal noun (masdar), also occurs in noun meanings and conveys the meaning of 'book'; its plural is «زُبُر». And «زَبُوْر» is that inspired book which was revealed to Prophet David (peace be upon him). And «مِزْبَر» means 'pen' (see: مف، منجد). And «زُبَرَ» means to write on stone. And its basic meaning is thickness, i.e., bulkiness (see: Fiqh, vol. 240).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنَّہٗ  لَفِیۡ  زُبُرِ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (26:196)\nTranslation: And its news is already [written] in the scriptures of the earlier [prophets].","«زُبُر» books written in bold letters.","Book","زبر","3:184-16:44-18:96-26:196-35:25-54:43-54:52",7
2256,485,"B","صُحُف","«صُحُف» is a collection of «صَحِیْفَۃ». And «صَحِیْفَۃ» means a spread-out thing on which something is written (muf), and «صَحِیْفَۃ» also means written paper, leaf. And «صِحَافَۃ» means newspaper writing, and «اَصْحَفَ» means compiling scriptures or written leaves into the form of a book. And «مُصْحَف» its collection is «مَصَاحِف», meaning book, volume (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:\n«اِنَّ ہٰذَا  لَفِی الصُّحُفِ الۡاُوۡلٰی صُحُفِ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ وَ مُوۡسٰی» (87/18,19)\nTranslation: This matter is certainly recorded in the earlier (heavenly) scriptures as well—in the scriptures of Abraham and Moses.","«صُحُف» those written pages which can be compiled into book form.","Book","صحف","20:133-53:36-74:52-80:13-81:10-87:18-87:19-98:2",8
2257,486,"C","زَاوَرَ","«قَوْلُ الزُّوْر» meaning deceptive and false speech, a lie and incorrect statement.\nFor example: In the Quran Karim it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیْنَ لَا یَشْهَدُوْنَ الزُّوْرَۙ» (25/72)\nTranslation: And those who do not bear false witness.\nAnd «اَزْوَر» refers to a person in whose heart there is crookedness (perversity). And «بِئْرٌ زَوْرَاءَ» means a well whose digging involves crookedness. And «زَاوَرَ» means to be crooked or to emerge crooked.","to go awry","Child","زاور","18:17",1
2258,486,"C","قَرَضَ","«قَرَضَ» meaning to cut and emerge by cutting. «قَرَضَ الْمَکَان» meaning he emerged scattered from that place, and «قَرَضَ فِی السَّیْر» meaning to turn aside here and there while moving (from the original path).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ تَرَی الشَّمۡسَ  اِذَا طَلَعَتۡ  تَّزٰوَرُ عَنۡ کَہۡفِہِمۡ ذَاتَ الۡیَمِیۡنِ وَ اِذَا غَرَبَتۡ تَّقۡرِضُہُمۡ ذَاتَ الشِّمَالِ» ( 18/17 )\nTranslation: And when the sun rose, you would see it shifting away from their cave to the right, and when it set, it would deviate from them to the left.","To evade someone and then return to the straight path.","Child. (Alternatively: to escape/save)","قرض","18:17",1
2259,486,"C","حَادَ","«حَادَ» means to turn away from the straight path and run far away ( مف ۔ م ل ) to change direction. For example, in the Quran it is: «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَکۡرَۃُ  الۡمَوۡتِ بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ ذٰلِکَ مَا کُنۡتَ مِنۡہُ  تَحِیۡدُ» (50:19) translation: And the truth-revealing state of death's unconsciousness has befallen (O human), this is the very state from which you used to flee.","To cut and run far away, and then not return to the straight path.","child","حاد","9:63-22:25-50:19-58:5-58:20-58:22",6
2260,487,"H","کَمْ","Kam (كم) is an indefinite numeral used for inquiring about duration or quantity. It means how much, how many, or how many (feminine) when used interrogatively.\n\nFor example, in the Quran: «قَالَ کَمۡ لَبِثۡتَ» (2/259).  \nTranslation: Allah said, How long have you remained?\n\nNote: Kam has two types: (1) Kam interrogative (كَمْ استفہامیہ) and (2) Kam informative (كَمْ خبریہ).\n\nKam interrogative: That which is used to ask about a number. For example: «کَمْ رَجُلاً عِنْدَکَ؟» (How many men are with you?).\n\nKam informative: That which is used to state a number. For example: «کَمْ کُتُب دَرَسْتُ» (I have read many books).","This word is called both interrogative and declarative in Arabic grammar.","How many","کم","2:211-2:249-2:259-6:6-7:4-17:17-18:19-19:74-19:98-20:128-21:11-23:112-26:7-28:58-32:26-36:31-38:3-43:6-44:25-50:36-53:26",21
2261,487,"H","کَاَیٍّ یا کَاَیِّنْ","«کَمْ» and «کَاَیِّن» are near-synonyms. The only difference between them is that the concept of abundance or multitude is also found in «کَاَیِّن». Meaning: how many, how much, i.e., many, numerous. And it does not appear in an interrogative (questioning) sense.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَاَیِّنۡ مِّنۡ اٰیَۃٍ  فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ یَمُرُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا» (12/105)\nTranslation: And there are many (numerous) signs in the heavens and the earth which they pass by.\n\nFor crookedness, see crooked and to be crooked. For side or turn, see aspect.","The term «کَاَیٍّ یا کَاَیِّنْ» is synonymous with *khabariyah* in Arabic grammar. The difference is that *khabariyah* can appear both with and without *min*, whereas «کَاَیٍّ» generally appears with *min*.","How many","کایٍ یا کاین","3:146-12:105-22:45-22:48-29:60-47:13-65:8",7
2262,488,"T","بَحَثَ","«بَحَثَ» to dig. to scratch. to search for something under the soil (Fasl 171. Mal l)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَبَعَثَ اللّٰہُ غُرَابًا یَّبۡحَثُ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ لِیُرِیَہٗ کَیۡفَ یُوَارِیۡ سَوۡءَۃَ اَخِیۡہِ» (5/31)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent a crow who began to dig the ground (with its beak) to show Cain how to bury his brother (Abel).","to dig underground","to do","بحث","5:31",1
2263,488,"T","بَعْثَرَ","According to Imam Raghib, the word «بُعْثِرَ» is composed of «بُعِثَ» and «اُثِیْرَ». It means to turn graves upside down and to raise the dead (مف), and «بَعْثَرَ الْمَتَاع» means to turn things around, to reverse (منجد). «بَعثَرَہٗ» was examined and investigated. It was brought out and made manifest (م ۔ ق). For example, in the Quran it is stated: «اَفَلَا یَعۡلَمُ  اِذَا بُعۡثِرَ مَا فِی الۡقُبُوۡرِ» (100/9). Translation: Does he not know that when the contents of the graves are scattered? (Ottoman).","«بَعْثَرَ» to extract or produce something through striving.","to do","بعثر","82:4-100:9",2
2264,489,"B","اَمَرَّ","«مَرَّ ، مَرَارَۃ» means bitter. «مُرٌّ» means bitter. And «اَمَرَّ» means very bitter (from 'manjad'). For example: In the Quran it says: «بَلِ السَّاعَۃُ  مَوۡعِدُہُمۡ وَ السَّاعَۃُ اَدۡہٰی  وَ  اَمَرُّ» (54/46). Translation: Their appointed time has come, and the Hour is extremely severe and intensely bitter.","«اَمَرُّ» pure bitter and intensely bitter.","Bitter","امر","54:46",1
2265,489,"B","اُجَاج","«اُجَاج» means very salty and bitter water. And «اَجَّ الْمَاءَ» means to make water bitter or brackish (manjad).  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لَوۡ نَشَآءُ  جَعَلۡنٰہُ  اُجَاجًا فَلَوۡ لَا تَشۡکُرُوۡنَ» (56/70)  \nTranslation: If We will, We can make this water salty. Then why are you not grateful?","«اُجَاج» bitter and salty (brackish) water.","Bitter","اجاج","25:53-35:12-56:70",3
2266,489,"B","خَمْط","«خَمْط» meaning bitter and sour, and every thorny and bitter tree (Manjad, etc.).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ بِجَنَّتَیۡہِمۡ جَنَّتَیۡنِ ذَوَاتَیۡ  اُکُلٍ خَمۡطٍ» (34/16)  \nTranslation: And We replaced their two gardens with two other gardens whose fruits were bitter.","«خَمْط» bitter and sour (astringent) unpleasant.","bitter","خمط","34:16",1
2267,490,"F","زُرَّاع","«زُرَّاع» is the plural of «زَارِع», meaning a farmer or agriculturist. Its usage is common.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«کَزَرۡعٍ  اَخۡرَجَ  شَطۡئَہٗ  فَاٰزَرَہٗ  فَاسۡتَغۡلَظَ فَاسۡتَوٰی عَلٰی سُوۡقِہٖ یُعۡجِبُ الزُّرَّاعَ» (48:29)  \nTranslation: Like a farmer who has sown his seed, so it sprouts and grows thick, then stands firm on its stem, delighting the farmers.","«زُرَّاع» farmer or cultivator.","Farmer","زراع","48:29-56:64",2
2268,490,"F","کُفَّار","«کُفَّار» is the plural of «کَافِر». And «کُفْر» means to hide something. «کَافِر» comes with several meanings: (1) a denier of God, (2) an ungrateful person (denier of God's blessings), (3) one who conceals the truth, one who remains hidden, staying apart and distant from people. It also refers to: earth, plants, farmer, (manjad), and «اَلْکَفْرُ» means land far from people, countryside (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«کَمَثَلِ غَیۡثٍ اَعۡجَبَ الۡکُفَّارَ نَبَاتُہٗ» (57:20)\nTranslation: Like rain, (with which crops grow and) the farmers' crops appear good.","«کُفَّار» is the term used in common parlance for those who deny the truth.","Farmer","کفار","57:20",1
2269,491,"B","جَارِیَۃ","«جَرٰی یَجْرِیْ» means to move and flow. It is used for things that move like water and wind. By this same association, a ship is called «جَارِیَۃ»; its plural is «جَوَار» (masc.), and it refers to a sailing ship that moves in accordance with the direction and flow of wind and water.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَہُ  الۡجَوَارِ الۡمُنۡشَئٰتُ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ کَالۡاَعۡلَامِ» (55/24)\nTranslation: The towering ships, which are like mountains in the sea, are of that same type.","The ship is referred to as «جَارِیَۃ» in terms of its sailing.  \nThe ship is referred to as «سَفِیْنَۃ» in terms of being smooth and comfortable.  \nThe ship is referred to as «فُلْک» in terms of being ship-shaped.","boat","جاریۃ","42:32-55:24-69:11-81:16-88:12",5
2270,491,"B","سَفِیْنَۃ","«سَفَنَ» meaning to peel and to make soft. And «سَفَنُ» meaning a tool for carving, hollowing, and smoothing. And «سَفِیْن» meaning an axe for splitting wood. And «مِسْفن» meaning tools for carving. And «سَفَانَۃ» meaning the profession of shipbuilding. And «سَفِیْنَۃ» meaning a ship, a boat. (manj) That is, «سَفِیْنَۃ» refers to a boat that is made smooth, even, and comfortable through carving and planing.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18:79)\nTranslation: That boat belonged to poor people who earned their living (by rowing boats) in the sea.","«سَفِیْنَۃ» meaning ship, boat.","boat","سفینۃ","18:71-18:79-29:15",3
2271,491,"B","فُلْک","The word «فُلْک» implies something being round, spinning, and revolving (m. l). «فَلْکٌ مِّنَ الْبَحْر» means the whirlpool of a river or sea, where water gathers from all sides and begins to spin. And «فَلَک» means an orbit, the path of the revolving planets. «اَلْفَلْکَۃ» means anything that is elevated, prominent, and round (manjada). Thus, in relation to the act of spinning continuously, a ship is called «فُلْک» (its plural form is not used). In the Quran, the word «فُلْک» is often accompanied by «مَشْحُوْن». And «شَخَن» means to load cargo onto a ship and fill it. And «اَلشَّحْنَۃ» means that with which a ship is filled (manjada). Hence, «فُلْک» refers to a ship that serves both to carry passengers and transport cargo.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ یُوۡنُسَ لَمِنَ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ . اِذۡ  اَبَقَ  اِلَی الۡفُلۡکِ الۡمَشۡحُوۡنِ» (37/139,140)\nTranslation: And Yunus ( Jonah) was also among the prophets when he fled and boarded a fully laden ship.","«فُلْک» a boat that also carries cargo in addition to passengers.","boat","فلک","2:164-7:64-10:22-10:73-11:37-11:38-14:32-16:14-17:66-22:65-23:22-23:27-23:28-26:119-29:65-30:46-31:31-35:12-36:41-37:140-40:80-43:12-45:12",23
2272,492,"K","کَعْبَۃ","«کَعْبَۃ» refers to anything that is cube-shaped. Hence, the Ka'bah is called so because its length, width, and height are all equal. A square or cubical structure (F L 16).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«یَحۡکُمُ بِہٖ ذَوَا عَدۡلٍ مِّنۡکُمۡ ہَدۡیًۢا بٰلِغَ الۡکَعۡبَۃِ» (5/95)  \nTranslation: Let them appoint two reliable persons to offer the sacrifice and bring it to the Ka'bah.","«کَعْبَۃ» meaning every thing that is constructed in the shape of a cube.","Ka'bah","کعبۃ","5:95-5:97",2
2273,492,"K","اَلْبَیْت","«اَلْبَیْت» The Specific House. The Noble House of Allah.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «اِذۡ جَعَلۡنَا الۡبَیۡتَ مَثَابَۃً لِّلنَّاسِ وَ اَمۡنًا» (2/125)\nTranslation: When We appointed the House (Kaaba) as a place of assembly for people and as a sanctuary.","The specific noble House of Allah.","Ka'bah","البیت","2:125-2:127-2:158-3:97-5:2-5:97-8:35-22:26-52:4-106:3",10
2274,492,"K","بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق","«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق» meaning ancient house. «عَتِیْق» refers to something that is old, noble, and dignified, and in which there is no deficiency (for example): In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22:29). Translation: And people should perform Tawaf of the Ancient House.","«بَیْتُ الْعَتِیْق» meaning the ancient house, referring to Masjid al-Haram.","Ka'bah","بیت العتیق","22:29-22:33",2
2275,492,"T","حَرَم","Two meanings are associated with «حَرَم». (1) «اَلْمَنْعُ الشَّدِیْد» haram refers to those things whose use has been strictly forbidden by Shariah, and its opposite is halal, meaning that which has no restriction on its use. (2) And «حَرَم» and «حَرَام» mean respectable, dignified, and worthy of honor.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «اَوَ لَمۡ نُمَکِّنۡ لَّہُمۡ حَرَمًا اٰمِنًا» (28:57). Translation: Did We not grant them a place in the Haram, which is an abode of security?","The items whose use has been strictly forbidden by Sharia.","the Kaaba","حرم","28:57-29:67",2
2276,492,"K","بَیْتُ الْحَرَام ۔ بَیْتُ الْمُحَرَّم","«بَیْتُ الْحَرَام» a house worthy of respect and honor.\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَاۤ  آٰمِّیۡنَ الۡبَیۡتَ الۡحَرَامَ» (5/2)\nTranslation: And neither those who intend [to perform] the Sacred House.\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«رَبَّنَاۤ اِنِّیۡۤ  اَسۡکَنۡتُ مِنۡ ذُرِّیَّتِیۡ بِوَادٍ غَیۡرِ  ذِیۡ  زَرۡعٍ عِنۡدَ  بَیۡتِکَ  الۡمُحَرَّمِ» (14/37)\nTranslation: O my Lord! I have settled some of my descendants in an uncultivated valley near Your honored House.","«بَیْتُ الْحَرَام» The house worthy of respect and honor, meaning the Sacred Kaaba of Allah.","Ka'bah","بیت الحرام ۔ بیت المحرم","5:2-5:97-14:37",3
2277,492,"K","مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام","«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام» A mosque worthy of honor and respect. The Noble House of Allah.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡۤ  اَسۡرٰی بِعَبۡدِہٖ لَیۡلًا مِّنَ الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡحَرَامِ  اِلَی الۡمَسۡجِدِ الۡاَقۡصَا» ( 17/1 )\nTranslation: Glory be to the One Who took His servant by night from the Sacred Mosque to the Farthest Mosque.","«مَسْجِدُ الْحَرَام» is a mosque worthy of respect and honor. The Noble House of Allah.","Ka'bah","مسجد الحرام","2:144-2:149-2:150-2:191-2:196-2:217-5:2-8:34-9:7-9:19-9:28-17:1-22:25-48:25-48:27",15
2278,493,"T","اَمْس","The day before today is the day that has passed: the bygone yesterday (YESTERDAY). And if it is in the 'Arabi' state (i.e., with Arabic vowel marks), then «اَلْاَمْس» means one of the past days (manjada), and idiomatically, pronouncing the word «اَمْس» also implies the recent past.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا الَّذِی اسۡتَنۡصَرَہٗ  بِالۡاَمۡسِ یَسۡتَصۡرِخُہٗ» (28/18)\nTranslation: Meanwhile, he saw that the person who had sought help from them yesterday was again calling out to them for aid.\n\nIn this verse, «اَمْس» refers to the bygone day (yesterday). And in the following verse, the recent past is implied.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا حَصِیۡدًا  کَاَنۡ لَّمۡ تَغۡنَ بِالۡاَمۡسِ» (10/24)\nTranslation: So We struck it down, making it like a place where no settlement had existed the day before.","meaning any day from among the past days","Tomorrow","امس","10:24-28:18-28:19-28:82",4
2279,493,"T","غَدْ","«غَدْ» means the coming day or tomorrow. The word tomorrow also conveys meanings similar to «اَمْس», referring to both the upcoming day and the near future.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ» (12/12)\nTranslation: (O father) send him [Yusuf (Joseph)] with us tomorrow so that he may eat good fruits and play and roam about.\n\nIn this verse, «غَدًا» is used in the meaning of the coming tomorrow.\n\nSimilarly, at another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ لۡتَنۡظُرۡ  نَفۡسٌ مَّا قَدَّمَتۡ لِغَدٍ» (59/18)\nTranslation: And let every person see what they have sent ahead for tomorrow.\n\nIn this verse, the word «غَدْ» does not merely denote the near future but also signifies the meaning of the Hereafter, which, according to the Quran, is imminent.","«غَدْ», meaning the next day.","Tomorrow","غد","3:121-6:52-7:205-12:12-13:15-18:23-18:28-24:36-31:34-34:12-40:46-54:26-59:18-68:22-68:25",15
2280,494,"L","ظَلَمَ","«ظَلَمَ» means to place something in a location other than its original, rightful place. Its opposite is «عَدْل». That is, anything that goes against justice and fairness is considered injustice. Thus, the scope of the word injustice is very broad. It applies to any deficiency or excess in anything, regardless of how small or large the amount may be. Furthermore, this term is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کِلۡتَا الۡجَنَّتَیۡنِ اٰتَتۡ اُکُلَہَا وَ لَمۡ تَظۡلِمۡ مِّنۡہُ  شَیۡئًا» (18:33)\nTranslation: Both gardens yielded their fruits in full and did not withhold anything.","«ظَلَمَ» is used in a broad sense and applies to all kinds of scarcity and surplus.","less","ظلم","2:54-2:57-2:59-2:150-2:165-2:231-2:272-2:279-2:281-3:25-3:108-3:117-3:135-3:161-4:10-4:30-4:40-4:49-4:64-4:77-4:110-4:124-4:148-4:153-4:160-4:168-5:39-6:21-6:45-6:82-6:93-6:131-6:144-6:157-6:160-7:9-7:23-7:37-7:103-7:160-7:162-7:165-7:177-8:25-8:60-9:36-9:70-10:13-10:17-10:44-10:47-10:52-10:54-11:18-11:37-11:67-11:94-11:101-11:113-11:116-11:117-13:6-14:44-14:45-16:33-16:41-16:61-16:85-16:111-16:118-17:59-17:71-18:15-18:33-18:49-18:57-18:59-18:87-19:60-20:111-20:112-21:3-21:47-22:25-22:39-23:27-23:62-25:4-25:19-26:227-27:11-27:14-27:44-27:52-27:85-28:16-29:40-29:46-29:68-30:9-30:29-30:57-31:13-32:22-34:19-34:42-36:54-37:22-38:24-39:32-39:47-39:51-39:69-40:17-40:31-42:41-42:42-43:39-43:65-43:76-45:22-46:12-46:19-51:59-52:47-53:52-61:7-65:1",128
2281,494,"F","اَلَا","«اَلَا» Meaning: to fall short; to not do something as it should be done; to leave a deficiency (grammatical: maf'ul, ma'ul).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تَتَّخِذُوۡا بِطَانَۃً مِّنۡ دُوۡنِکُمۡ لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118) Translation: O believers! Do not take those outside your faith (non-Muslims) as confidants. They spare no effort to corrupt you.","«اَلَا» negligence or dereliction in performing a task.","Few","الا","3:118",1
2282,494,"L","قَصَرَ","«قَصَرَ» Not doing a task to the desired extent. And in the words of Imam Raghib, not reaching the length or ultimate limit of something (i.e., not fulfilling the stipulated quantity or count). Doing less. Making it shorter.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا ضَرَبۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ فَلَیۡسَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ جُنَاحٌ اَنۡ تَقۡصُرُوۡا مِنَ الصَّلٰوۃِ» (4/101)\nTranslation: And when you travel through the land, there is no blame upon you for shortening the prayer.","«قَصَرَ» Do not overdo any work; practice moderation in it.","Less","قصر","4:101-7:202-48:27",3
2283,494,"F","اَلَتَ","«اَلَتَ» meaning to deduct from someone's due (manjdan) from wages. Not giving full recompense for work or giving it late. «اَلْقَصْر وَ اِبْطَاء» (m. q)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«مَاۤ  اَلَتۡنٰہُمۡ  مِّنۡ عَمَلِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ» (52/21)\nTranslation: We did not diminish anything from their deeds.","«اَلَتَ» means to give less than what is due in terms of reward or wages, or to delay giving it.","few","الت","52:21",1
2284,494,"L","ھَضَمَ","«ھَضَمَ» means to crush something soft, to squeeze, to press out, and to reduce it. It also means to suppress the rights of the weak, to usurp. And «ھَضِیْم» means soft and delicate as well (26/48), and easy to digest (m.q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡمَلۡ مِنَ الصّٰلِحٰتِ وَ ہُوَ مُؤۡمِنٌ فَلَا یَخٰفُ ظُلۡمًا وَّ لَا ہَضۡمًا» (20/112)\nTranslation: And whoever does good deeds and is a believer, will have no fear of injustice or deprivation.","«ھَضَمَ» meaning to crush something soft, to squeeze, to press out, to reduce it, and to suppress the right of the weak.","Less","ھضم","20:112-26:148",2
2285,494,"L","فَتَرَ","«فَتَرَ» means to become weak in something; for example, due to continuous work or exhaustion, a decrease in speed occurs or one stops.  \nFor example: in the Quran it is:  \n«اِنَّ  الۡمُجۡرِمِیۡنَ فِیۡ عَذَابِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدُوۡنَ لَا یُفَتَّرُ عَنۡہُمۡ» (43:74-75)  \nTranslation: The criminals will remain forever in the punishment of Hell, which will not be lightened for them.","«فَتَرَ» deficiency occurring due to weakness.","Less","فتر","21:20-43:75",2
2286,494,"L","قَلَّ","Fundamentally, it has two meanings: (1) to be elevated, and (2) to be decreased. Here, the second meaning is under discussion—that is, to be decreased in number or quantity. And its opposite is «کَثُرَ», meaning 'more' or 'to increase.' For example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنۡ تَرَنِ  اَنَا  اَقَلَّ  مِنۡکَ  مَالًا  وَّ  وَلَدًا» (18:39)\nTranslation: If you see me as lesser in wealth and offspring.","«قَلَّ» to reduce in number or quantity.","Less","قل","18:39",1
2287,494,"L","طَفَّفَ","«طَفِیْف» means something insignificant or trivial. And «طَفَّفَ» means to give slightly less when filling a measure, or to use a slightly smaller measure. (Detailed)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَیۡلٌ   لِّلۡمُطَفِّفِیۡنَ الَّذِیۡنَ  اِذَا  اکۡتَالُوۡا عَلَی النَّاسِ یَسۡتَوۡفُوۡنَ» (83:1,2)\nTranslation: Woe to those who give less [than due], who, when they take a measure from people, take in full. But if they give by measure or weight to them, they cause loss.","The measuring standard should be either of modest size or only partially filled.","Less","طفف","83:1",1
2288,494,"L","خَسِرَ","«خَسِرَ» means a deficiency occurring in the capital (masc.). This term is generally specific to trade. To incur a loss. To bear a loss. And its opposite is «رَمِجَ». And «خَسَرَ الِمْيزَان» means to reduce in weight while suppressing someone's right.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا کَالُوۡہُمۡ  اَوۡ وَّزَنُوۡہُمۡ  یُخۡسِرُوۡنَ» (83/3)\nTranslation: And when they give them by measure or by weight, they give them less than what is due.","«خَسِرَ» to incur loss in trade.","less","خسر","4:119-6:12-6:20-6:31-6:140-7:9-7:53-10:45-11:21-11:22-18:103-21:70-22:11-23:103-26:181-27:5-39:15-40:78-40:85-42:45-45:27-55:9-65:9-83:3-103:2",25
2289,494,"L","نَقَضَ","«نَقَضَ» means to decrease or reduce, and its opposite is «زَادَ», meaning increase. And the opposite of «نُقْصَان» is «زِیَادَۃ». This word is more common than «خَسِرَ». Every loss is damage, but not every damage is a loss.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«نِّصۡفَہٗۤ  اَوِ انۡقُصۡ  مِنۡہُ  قَلِیۡلًا . اَوۡ زِدۡ  عَلَیۡہِ  وَ رَتِّلِ الۡقُرۡاٰنَ  تَرۡتِیۡلًا» (73:3,4)\nTranslation: Half the night, or a little less or a little more. And recite the Quran with measured recitation.","«نَقَضَ» is used to denote reduction or diminution in all kinds of matters.","less","نقص","2:155-7:130-9:4-11:84-13:41-21:44-35:11-50:4-73:3",9
2290,494,"F","بَخَسَ","«بَخْس» meaning deficient, inferior, less (in weight or measure). And «بَخَسَ» meaning to give something deficient or less in exchange, or to give a small amount.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ شَرَوۡہُ بِثَمَنٍۭ بَخۡسٍ دَرَاہِمَ مَعۡدُوۡدَۃٍ» (12:20)\nTranslation: And they sold Joseph (peace be upon him) for a trivial price, i.e., a few coins.\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَ لَا تَبۡخَسُوا النَّاسَ اَشۡیَآءَہُمۡ» (7:85)\nTranslation: And do not give people less than what is due to them of their things.","«بَخَسَ» Giving less instead of full in return for something good.","Few","بخس","2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13",7
2291,494,"L","فَرَّطَ","«فَرَّط» means to fall short, to lag behind the limit of moderation, or to diminish it (see details under to exceed the limit and to diminish). «فَرَّط» is from the category of antonymous lexical pairs.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰحَسۡرَتَنَا عَلٰی مَا فَرَّطۡنَا فِیۡہَا» (6/31)\nTranslation: Until, when the Hour suddenly overtakes them, they will say, Oh, woe to us for how we used to fall short regarding the Hour.\n\nNote: (Antonymous lexical pairs are words that have two separate meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«فَرَّط» to fall short of the limit of moderation, to be deficient.","Less","فرط","6:31-6:38-6:61-12:80-39:56",5
2292,494,"L","وَتَرَ","«وَتَرَ» meaning to wrong or oppress. «اَلْوَتْر» and «اَلْوِتْر» meaning to take revenge or to wrong in taking revenge (from *Munajid*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اللّٰہُ  مَعَکُمۡ  وَ لَنۡ یَّتِرَکُمۡ   اَعۡمَالَکُمۡ» (47:35)\nTranslation: And Allah is with you; it is impossible that He would let your deeds go to waste.","«وَتَرَ» shortchanging or withholding in giving or taking.","Less","وتر","47:35",1
2293,495,"E","عَمِلَ","«عَمِلَ» Every deed that a person intends is an action. And since earning is also an action, the term is used in that sense as well.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79) Translation: The ship belonged to some poor people who worked at sea.","«عَمِلَ», meaning 'to work,' is commonly used and also conveys the sense of 'to earn.'","earnings","عمل","2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3",309
2294,495,"E","کَسَبَ","The term 'earning' or 'to earn' is more specific than 'action'. It means to gain profit or to do something for the sake of good fortune. Whether this work is for oneself or for others, and whether this earning is good or bad, lawful or unlawful. And «کَاسِبْ» means one who labors for wages, a professional.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ السَّارِقُ وَ السَّارِقَۃُ فَاقۡطَعُوۡۤا اَیۡدِیَہُمَا جَزَآءًۢ بِمَا کَسَبَا» (5:38)\nTranslation: Cut off the hands of the male thief and the female thief. That is the recompense for what they have earned.","«کَسَبَ» To undertake any work for the purpose of gaining benefit, whether for oneself or for others.","earnings","کسب","2:79-2:81-2:134-2:141-2:202-2:225-2:264-2:267-2:281-2:286-3:25-3:155-3:161-4:88-4:111-4:112-5:38-6:3-6:70-6:120-6:129-6:158-6:164-7:39-7:96-9:82-9:95-10:8-10:27-10:52-13:33-13:42-14:18-14:51-15:84-18:58-30:41-31:34-35:45-36:65-39:24-39:48-39:50-39:51-40:17-40:82-41:17-42:22-42:30-42:34-45:10-45:14-45:22-52:21-74:38-83:14-111:2",57
2295,495,"E","اِکْتَسَب","That is an action which a person undertakes while keeping only their own interests in mind (benefit).\n\nFor example: the Noble Quran states:\n«لِلرِّجَالِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبُوۡا ؕ وَ لِلنِّسَآءِ نَصِیۡبٌ مِّمَّا اکۡتَسَبۡنَ» (4/32)\nTranslation: Men will be rewarded for the deeds they have done, and women for the deeds they have done.","«اِکْتَسَب» to do any work for one's own benefit or profit.","Earnings","اکتسب","2:286-4:32-24:11-33:58",4
2296,495,"E","اِقْتَرَفَ","«قَرَفَ» means to remove the scab of a wound. And «اِقْتَرَف» means to commit a sin or to earn through illicit means. It is an idiom that «اَلْاِعْتِرَافُ یَزِیْلُ الْاِقْتِرَاف» means confession (of a crime). Confession eliminates the crime (figuratively). Thus, «اِقْتَرَاف» is used for sinful and criminal acts. For example, in the Holy Quran: «اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یَکۡسِبُوۡنَ الۡاِثۡمَ  سَیُجۡزَوۡنَ بِمَا کَانُوۡا  یَقۡتَرِفُوۡنَ» (6/120) Translation: Those who commit sins will soon receive the punishment for their deeds.","«اِقْتَرَفَ» Engaging in illegitimate acts, acquiring wealth through illicit means.","Earnings","اقترف","6:113-6:120-9:24-42:23",4
2297,496,"R","حُجْرَۃ","«حُجْرَۃ» means room. Its plural is «حُجْرَات». It can also mean dining room (masc.). So to speak, «حُجْرَۃ» is that small room from which the entire household's affairs are managed. For example, in the Quran: «اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ یُنَادُوۡنَکَ مِنۡ وَّرَآءِ الۡحُجُرٰتِ» (49:4). Translation: Those who call you from outside the chambers.","«حُجْرَۃ» means room.","Room","حجرۃ","49:4",1
2298,496,"R","غُرْفَۃ","«غُرْفَۃ» meaning 'mansion' (manzil) and «غُرَف» and «غُرَفَات» meaning the levels and degrees of Paradise (muf), implying a structure more elevated than a room and a lofty chamber.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اُولٰٓئِکَ یُجۡزَوۡنَ الۡغُرۡفَۃَ  بِمَا صَبَرُوۡا» (25:75)  \nTranslation: Those possessing these qualities will be granted lofty mansions as a reward for their patience (Jalandhari).","«غُرْفَۃ» meaning balakhana.","room","غرفۃ","25:75-29:58-34:37-39:20",4
2299,497,"W","ضَعِیْف","«ضَعِیْف» means weak or elderly. It is a well-known term. Its antonyms are «قَوِی», meaning strong. And «ضَعْف» and «ضُعْف» mean weakness; their plurals are «ضُعَفَاء» and «ضِعَاف».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ کَانَ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِ الۡحَقُّ سَفِیۡہًا اَوۡ ضَعِیۡفًا» (2/282)\nTranslation: Then if the borrower is of weak intellect or weak.","«ضَعِیْف» meaning weak, old; deficient in strength and power.","weak","ضعیف","2:266-2:282-3:146-4:28-4:75-4:76-4:97-4:98-4:127-7:75-7:137-7:150-8:26-8:66-9:91-11:91-14:21-19:75-22:73-28:4-28:5-30:54-34:31-34:32-34:33-40:47-72:24",27
2300,497,"F","وَاھِیَۃ","«وَھِیَ» means to become weak due to old age, such as clothes becoming worn-out (Fal 29). And «وَھِیَ» also means something becoming loose, its fastenings becoming loose (M. L.). This word is generally used for clothes, ropes, etc. (Fal 29). And «اَلْوَھْی» means leather getting holes (M. L.). Thus, this word is used for something becoming worn-out, weak, and tearing due to old age and weakness. The Punjabi word Bhaga correctly conveys this meaning. For example: In the Quran, it is said: «وَ انۡشَقَّتِ السَّمَآءُ  فَہِیَ یَوۡمَئِذٍ وَّاہِیَۃٌ» (69/16). Translation: And the sky will crack; it will have become weak by that day.","Weakened by decay.","Feeble","واھیۃ","69:16",1
2301,497,"W","اَوْھَنَ","«وَھَنَ» means to be weak, to become weak and sluggish due to a lack of strength. When used in a physical context, it refers to the weakness of a bone or a hard object; when used in a moral context, it refers to the weakness of an affair or moral deficiency (F 29). And «وَھَنَ» means to become weak and sluggish due to the absence of strength (M. L).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ  اَوۡہَنَ الۡبُیُوۡتِ لَبَیۡتُ الۡعَنۡکَبُوۡتِ» (29/41)\nTranslation: Indeed, the weakest of homes is the home of the spider.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا تَہِنُوۡا فِی ابۡتِغَآءِ الۡقَوۡمِ» (4/104)\nTranslation: Do not show weakness in pursuing the disbelievers.","meaning to weaken","Weak","اوھن","3:139-3:146-4:104-47:35-8:18-19:4-29:41-31:14",8
2302,497,"W","اَذِلَّۃ","«اَذِلَّۃ» is the plural of «ذَلِیْل», meaning subordinate. Inferior in honor and status. People holding a second-class position in society. Its opposite is «عَزِیْز», meaning dominant, powerful, authoritative, capable.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» (3:123)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah aided you at Badr while you were weak.\n\nTo weaken: The terms «اِسْتَضْعَفَ» for making and keeping weak, and «اَوْھَنَ» for weakening, are used in the Quran.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«اَنَّ اللّٰہَ  مُوۡہِنُ کَیۡدِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (8:18)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah will weaken the plots of the disbelievers.","«اَذِلَّۃ» defeated, helpless, weak, and destitute people.","weak","اذلۃ","3:123-5:54-27:34-27:37",4
2303,498,"S","طَرْف","«طَرْف» means the ultimate limit of everything, the corner, the edge of a cubic object, the pointed side, the sight, or the direction (manjid). Its plural is «اَطْرَاف».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ» (11/114)\nTranslation: And establish prayer at both ends of the day (morning and evening).","«طَرْف» the ultimate end of all things.","side","طرف","3:127-11:114-13:41-20:130-21:44",5
2304,498,"E","حَدّ","«حَدَّ السِّکِّیْن» means sharpening a knife. And «حَدُّ السَّیْف» means the edge of a sword. And «حَدّ» means the barrier between two things. «حَدَّ الْمَکَان» He established the limit of the house. From this comes the concept of the limits of the four directions (arba'ah), meaning the boundaries on all four sides. Thus, a limit is the extreme and final edge of something that separates it from other things. And «حُدُوْدُ اللہ» means the commands of Allah, transgressing which is a cause of sin.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ یَّتَعَدَّ حُدُوۡدَ اللّٰہِ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الظّٰلِمُوۡنَ» ( 2/229 )\nTranslation: And those who transgress the limits of Allah, it is they who are the wrongdoers.","The ultimate boundary that separates it from all other things.","Edge","حد","2:187-2:229-2:230-4:13-4:14-9:97-9:112-58:4-65:1",9
2305,498,"E","حَرْف","«حَرْفُ الْجَبَل» meaning the sharp edge of a mountain. The highest peak. They say «فُلَانٌ عَلٰی حَرْفٍ مِنْ اَمْرِہٖ», i.e., such a person is on the brink of a transaction. Meaning, if any contrary circumstance arises, he will withdraw from it (manjada). The farthest point of doubt and suspicion.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَنۡ یَّعۡبُدُ اللّٰہَ عَلٰی حَرۡفٍ ۚ فَاِنۡ  اَصَابَہٗ  خَیۡرُۨ  اطۡمَاَنَّ بِہٖ ۚ وَ اِنۡ اَصَابَتۡہُ فِتۡنَۃُۨ  انۡقَلَبَ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ» (22/11)\nTranslation: And among people is he who worships Allah on the edge (i.e., in a state of doubt). Then if good befalls him, he is content; but if a trial strikes him, he turns back on his face in loss.","«حَرْف» meaning a sharp edge.","Edge","حرف","22:11",1
2306,498,"E","اُفْق","The coming together or appearing to meet at the distant and ultimate limit of the surroundings of two things. And that meeting edge is called the horizon, as on one side of space is the earth and on the other is the sky. Thus, the horizon is where sight meets at the farthest limit. Its plural is «اٰفَاق». And «اٰفاق» means the vastness of the world, in which there is ample expanse and distance.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہُوَ  بِالۡاُفُقِ الۡاَعۡلٰی» (53:7)\nTranslation: And he (Prophet Gabriel ﷺ) was on the upper edge of the sky.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine declaration states:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (41:53)\nTranslation: Soon We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves.","«اُفْق» two round objects converging at their outermost limits.","Edge","افق","41:53-53:7-81:23",3
2307,498,"E","اَقْطَار","«قَطَرَ» means to stand in a row. It is said «قَطَرَ الْبَعِیْرُ اِلَی الْبَعِیْر» that the camels were made to stand in an orderly row (a line). And «اَقْطَارَ الدُّنْیَا» means the four corners/sides of the world. In the terminology of geometry, it refers to the straight line that passes through the center and divides the circle into two equal parts (a diameter). Thus, the concept of a straight line is also found in «قَطَرَ», as well as that of a circular shape. Moreover, there can be thousands of such diameters, encompassing all sides and directions. Right, left, forward, backward, up, down, straight and opposite directions—all are included.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ دُخِلَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ اَقۡطَارِہَا ثُمَّ سُئِلُوا الۡفِتۡنَۃَ  لَاٰتَوۡہَا وَ مَا تَلَبَّثُوۡا بِہَاۤ   اِلَّا  یَسِیۡرًا» (33:14)\nTranslation: And people would come to them (the hypocrites) from the outskirts of Medina, and they would be urged to cause trouble (conspiracy or mobilization against the Muslims), they would promptly do so, and they would hesitate but very little.\n\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» (55:33)\nTranslation: O company of jinn and humans! If you have the power to pass out of the boundaries of the heavens and the earth, then pass out.\n\nNote: (Geometry is the branch of mathematics that studies the size, shape, and relationships of figures, as well as the measurement of lines and angles. It also deals with numbers and numerals.)\n(A perfectly straight line is called a straight line, which in English is called a Straight Line. (Geometry) A straight line between two points.)","«اَقْطَار» the inner sides and aspects of something round.","Edge","اقطار","33:14-55:33",2
2308,498,"E","اَرْجَاء","«اَرْجَاء» is the plural form of «رَجَا». It means the edge of a circular object. «رَجَا الْبِئْر» means the edge of a well. And «رَجَا السَّمَاء» means the edge of the heaven (pl.).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ الۡمَلَکُ  عَلٰۤی  اَرۡجَآئِہَا ؕ وَ یَحۡمِلُ عَرۡشَ رَبِّکَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ یَوۡمَئِذٍ ثَمٰنِیَۃٌ» ( 69/17 )\nTranslation: And the angels will be on its edges, and on that Day eight [angels] will bear the Throne of your Lord above them.","«اَرْجَاء» a rounded form, such as the horizon or the edge of the sky.","Edge","ارجاء","69:17",1
2309,498,"E","شَفَا","«شَفَا» This word is a proverb for the brink of destruction. «شَفَا» They call the edge of anything that is hollow and empty inside, and where there is a danger of a person falling and perishing by standing on its edge. (m.f.)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی شَفَا حُفۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ فَاَنۡقَذَکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا» ( 3/103 )\nTranslation: And you had already come close to the brink of the Fire, and Allah saved you from it.\nAt another place, the Divine command states:\n«اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ» ( 9/109 )\nTranslation: Or [it is] like one who built upon the edge of a collapsing pit (Punjabi: *man* or *mani*).","The term refers to the edge of anything that is hollow and empty inside, and standing on which poses a risk of falling to one's death.","Edge","شفا","3:103-9:109",2
2310,498,"S","مَعْزل","«عَزَل» means to take refuge, to keep aloof and save oneself. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «تَدُلُّ عَلَیَّ تَنْجِیَۃُ وَ اَمَالَۃً وَ اَبْعَاداً» (m. l.) i.e., «مَعْزل» is that shore towards which going saves a person from a calamity. For example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated: «وَ نَادٰی نُوۡحُۨ  ابۡنَہٗ وَ کَانَ فِیۡ  مَعۡزِلٍ یّٰـبُنَیَّ ارۡکَبۡ مَّعَنَا» (11/42). Translation: And Noah called his son, who was standing on a shore. O my son, embark with us.","A shore that provides refuge.","side","معزل","11:42",1
2311,498,"S","شَاطِیء","«شَاطِیء» meaning one of the two sides of something (for example) one side or bank of a river or valley.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is: «فَلَمَّاۤ  اَتٰىہَا نُوۡدِیَ مِنۡ شَاطِیَٔ الۡوَادِ الۡاَیۡمَنِ» (28/30) Translation: When Moses arrived there, he heard a voice from the right side of the valley.","«شَاطِیء» any one side of a field or a river.","Side","شاطیء","28:30",1
2312,498,"E","سَاحِل","The word «سَاحِل» is specific to the bank of a river or sea (manjad).\nFor example: in the Quran it says:\n«فَلۡیُلۡقِہِ الۡیَمُّ بِالسَّاحِلِ» (20/39)\nTranslation: Then he will cast the (chest) onto the shore.","«سَاحِل» river or sea shore","Edge","ساحل","20:39",1
2313,498,"B","اَقْصَا","The concept of being distant and remaining far away is found in «قُصْوَی» (example), and «اَقْصٰی» means the far side, the outer edge.  \nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ جَآءَ مِنۡ اَقۡصَا الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  رَجُلٌ یَّسۡعٰی» (36:20)  \nTranslation: And a person came running from the farthest side of the city.","«اَقْصَا» the other side's edge.","Bank","اقصا","8:42-17:1-19:22-28:20-36:20",5
2314,498,"S","عُدْوَۃ","«عَدَا» means a distant traveler, and also means the edge of a valley. And «عُدْوَۃ» means a high place, the edge of a valley (manjad). That is, «عُدْوَۃ» refers to the edge of a valley or field that is both distant and elevated.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ اَنۡتُمۡ بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ ہُمۡ  بِالۡعُدۡوَۃِ الۡقُصۡوٰی» (8/42)\nTranslation: When you were on the near side and they were on the far side.","«عُدْوَۃ» the distant elevated shore.","side","عدوۃ","8:42",1
2315,498,"E","صَدَف","The open field between mountains is called a valley. And the boundaries of that valley along the edges of the mountains are termed «صَدَف». Therefore, the translation of «صَدَف» is also taken as the edge of the valley, but the edge of the mountain is its more equivalent translation. Hence, Imam Raghib states that its meaning is specifically the edge of the mountain (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا سَاوٰی بَیۡنَ الصَّدَفَیۡنِ» (18/96)\nTranslation: Until he (Dhul-Qarnayn) made the two mountains' edges (the middle part) equal.","«صَدَفُ» the side of the mountain","Edge","صدف","18:96",1
2316,499,"W","بِئر","«بِئر» means a well. It is a general term. It applies whether the well is inhabited or uninhabited (Fal 262). The term can also apply to a well that has no water (F. L 31).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ بِئۡرٍ  مُّعَطَّلَۃٍ   وَّ  قَصۡرٍ  مَّشِیۡدٍ» (22/45)\nTranslation: And many a well is abandoned, and many a grand palace lies in ruins.","«بِئر» meaning well.","well","بئر","22:45",1
2317,499,"W","جُبّ","«جُبّ» A well that has only been dug and not constructed with bricks or stones (cf. 262). An unlined well.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا ذَہَبُوۡا بِہٖ  وَ  اَجۡمَعُوۡۤا اَنۡ یَّجۡعَلُوۡہُ  فِیۡ غَیٰبَتِ  الۡجُبِّ» (12:15)\nTranslation: Then when they agreed to cast him (i.e., Yusuf) into the bottom of an unidentified well.","«جُبّ» an unlined well, i.e., a well that has only been dug and not constructed with bricks or stones.","Well","جب","12:10-12:15",2
2318,499,"W","رَسّ","«رَسّ» a very large well (cf. 39) containing a sufficient amount of water (cf. 262)\nFor example: It is mentioned in the Quran:\n«کَذَّبَتۡ قَبۡلَہُمۡ قَوۡمُ نُوۡحٍ وَّ اَصۡحٰبُ الرَّسِّ  وَ  ثَمُوۡدُ» (50/12)\nTranslation: The people of Noah, the companions of the well, and the Thamud had already denied.","«رَسّ» very large well.","Well","رس","25:38-50:12",2
2319,500,"G","سَوْط","«سَوْط» means tanned leather. Koṛa chabak (masc.) and «سَاطَ» mean to throw a scourge. And «سَوَّاط» means a soldier who carries a scourge or a whip. And «مِسْوَاط» refers to a horse that does not move without a whip (as per the source). For instance, the Quran states: «فَصَبَّ عَلَیۡہِمۡ رَبُّکَ سَوۡطَ عَذَابٍ» (89/13) Translation: So your Lord hurled at them a scourge of punishment.","«سَوْط» refers to a leather whip or scourge.","Garbage","سوط","89:13",1
2320,500,"G","جَلْدَۃ","«جِلْد» The skin of a living being is called 'khal.' And «جَلَدَ» means to strike someone on the skin in such a way that the effect of the strike does not go beyond the skin. And «جَلْدَۃ» is any thing with which one is struck on the skin, and it is hard but does not cause a wound, regardless of what it is. Durrah. «اَرْض جَلْدَۃ» means hard ground (muf) and «جَلَّاد» means the one who flogs with a whip.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ» (24/2)\nTranslation: Flog the adulteress and the adulterer, each of them, a hundred lashes.","«جَلْدَۃ» is general, whether it is made of leather or of something else, but it must be hard and not cause wounds, whereas what is called a whip refers specifically to leather strips or a scourge.","Garbage","جلدۃ","24:2-24:4",2
2321,501,"E","سَعٰی","«سَعِی» means to walk briskly. (Figuratively) to be vigorously engaged in completing a good or bad deed.  \nFor example, in the Quran: «وَ اَنۡ  لَّیۡسَ لِلۡاِنۡسَانِ  اِلَّا مَا سَعٰی» (53/39). Translation: And that man will receive only that for which he strives.","«سَعٰی» to strive for something.","Effort","سعی","2:114-2:205-17:19-20:15-20:20-20:66-28:20-36:20-53:39-57:12-66:8-79:22-79:35-80:8",14
2322,501,"E","جَھَدَ","To expend one's utmost efforts in completing a task. In the words of Ibn al-Faris «اَصْلُہُ الْمُشَقَّۃُ وَمَا یُقَارِبُہٗ» (m. l.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ جَاہَدُوۡا فِیۡنَا لَنَہۡدِیَنَّہُمۡ سُبُلَنَا» (29/69).\nTranslation: As for those who strive in Our cause, We will surely guide them to Our paths.","To bring all means into action for the completion of a task.","Effort","جھد","2:218-3:142-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:79-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-49:15-61:11-66:9",27
2323,501,"E","کَدَحَ","«اَلْکَدْح» means scratch or erosion, and «کَدَحَ» means to work very hard (manjad) and to toil through difficulties. For example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِنَّکَ کَادِحٌ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَدۡحًا  فَمُلٰقِیۡہِ» (84:6). Translation: O human, you must endure hardship in reaching your Lord, toiling, then you will meet Him.","To carry out duties with steadfast perseverance.","Effort","کدح","84:6",1
2325,502,"W","اَیُّ","«اَیُّ» When incorporated into pronouns in interrogative form, it conveys the meaning of who and requires an obligatory idafa construction (which at times carries conditional meanings), i.e., who among the mentioned things. This structure is also applicable for those of sound intellect.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«لِیَبۡلُوَکُمۡ  اَیُّکُمۡ  اَحۡسَنُ عَمَلًا» ( 67/2 )\nTranslation: So that He may test you [as to] which of you is best in deed.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n«لَا تَدۡرُوۡنَ اَیُّہُمۡ اَقۡرَبُ  لَکُمۡ نَفۡعًا» ( 4/11 )\nTranslation: You do not know which of you is nearest in benefit to you.","«اَیُّ», when entering into pronouns in an interrogative form, gives the meaning of who.","Who","ای","3:44-4:11-6:19-6:81-7:185-9:124-11:7-17:57-18:7-18:12-19:69-19:73-26:227-27:38-31:34-40:81-45:6-53:55-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77-67:2-68:6-68:40-77:12-77:50-80:18-81:9-82:8",57
2326,503,"S","اَحَد","«اَحَد» means peerless, having no equal. Non-dual. Unique. Alone, as in «قُلۡ ہُوَ اللّٰہُ  اَحَدٌ» (112/1). And in the sequence of numbers, it conveys the meaning of 'one', as «اَحَدَ» means 'one' and «عَشَرَ» means 'ten'. Its feminine form is «اِحْدٰی». Its third usage is to denote any single part of the whole. It is used in both affirmative and negative contexts. And generally, it applies to rational beings.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَخُذۡ اَحَدَنَا مَکَانَہٗ» (12/78)\nTranslation: So take any one of us instead of him.\n\nAnd when used in the negative, it imparts the meaning of 'anyone'.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَا مِنۡکُمۡ  مِّنۡ اَحَدٍ عَنۡہُ حٰجِزِیۡنَ» (69/47)\nTranslation: Then none of you could have prevented us from him.","The usage of «اَحَد» is as a part of the whole and generally for those of intellect.","some","احد","2:96-2:102-2:136-2:180-2:266-2:285-3:73-3:84-3:91-3:153-4:18-4:43-4:152-5:6-5:20-5:27-5:106-5:115-6:61-7:80-9:4-9:6-9:84-9:127-11:81-12:36-12:41-12:78-15:65-16:58-16:76-17:23-18:19-18:22-18:26-18:32-18:38-18:42-18:47-18:49-18:110-19:26-19:98-23:99-24:6-24:21-24:28-29:28-33:32-33:39-33:40-35:41-38:35-43:17-49:12-59:11-63:10-69:47-72:2-72:7-72:18-72:20-72:22-72:26-89:25-89:26-90:5-90:7-92:19-112:1-112:4",71
2328,504,"A","اَنْ","The phrase occurring within the sentence (meaning that - as if) conveys the meaning of...  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«اِنَّ اللّٰہَ لَا یَسۡتَحۡیٖۤ اَنۡ یَّضۡرِبَ مَثَلًا» (2/26)  \nTranslation: Allah is not ashamed to set forth any parable.","«اَنْ» refers to something inserted between sentences (e.g., 'that' or 'as if').","as if","ان","2:26-2:27-2:67-2:75-2:90-2:96-2:105-2:108-2:114-2:125-2:158-2:169-2:177-2:184-2:198-2:210-2:214-2:216-2:224-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:232-2:233-2:235-2:237-2:248-2:254-2:258-2:266-2:267-2:280-2:282-3:28-3:73-3:79-3:80-3:93-3:122-3:124-3:142-3:143-3:145-3:147-3:161-3:188-3:193-4:6-4:19-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:27-4:28-4:29-4:44-4:47-4:48-4:58-4:60-4:66-4:84-4:88-4:90-4:91-4:92-4:99-4:101-4:102-4:113-4:116-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:131-4:135-4:140-4:144-4:150-4:153-4:171-4:172-4:176-5:2-5:3-5:11-5:17-5:19-5:29-5:31-5:33-5:34-5:37-5:41-5:49-5:52-5:59-5:80-5:84-5:91-5:108-5:111-5:112-5:113-5:116-5:117-6:14-6:23-6:25-6:35-6:37-6:51-6:56-6:65-6:70-6:72-6:80-6:111-6:125-6:131-6:145-6:156-6:158-7:5-7:13-7:20-7:33-7:43-7:44-7:46-7:50-7:63-7:69-7:82-7:89-7:97-7:98-7:100-7:105-7:110-7:115-7:117-7:123-7:126-7:129-7:160-7:169-7:172-7:185-8:7-8:26-8:62-8:67-9:13-9:16-9:17-9:18-9:32-9:44-9:52-9:54-9:62-9:64-9:74-9:81-9:85-9:86-9:102-9:108-9:110-9:113-9:118-9:120-10:2-10:10-10:15-10:35-10:37-10:72-10:83-10:87-10:100-10:104-10:105-11:3-11:12-11:14-11:26-11:34-11:46-11:47-11:62-11:69-11:87-11:88-11:89-12:13-12:15-12:21-12:24-12:25-12:37-12:38-12:66-12:76-12:79-12:83-12:94-12:96-12:100-12:107-13:21-13:25-13:31-13:36-13:38-14:5-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:31-14:35-15:31-15:54-16:2-16:15-16:33-16:36-16:40-16:45-16:68-16:92-16:123-17:8-17:16-17:46-17:51-17:59-17:68-17:69-17:74-17:79-17:88-17:94-17:99-17:103-18:24-18:35-18:40-18:55-18:57-18:63-18:66-18:77-18:79-18:80-18:81-18:82-18:86-18:94-18:97-18:102-18:109-19:11-19:35-19:45-19:91-19:92-20:39-20:45-20:59-20:63-20:65-20:71-20:77-20:86-20:94-20:97-20:114-20:134-21:17-21:31-21:57-21:87-22:15-22:22-22:26-22:40-22:65-23:24-23:27-23:32-23:95-23:98-24:8-24:16-24:17-24:19-24:22-24:29-24:36-24:50-24:51-24:60-24:61-24:63-25:18-25:42-25:57-25:62-26:10-26:12-26:14-26:17-26:22-26:35-26:49-26:51-26:52-26:63-26:82-26:197-27:8-27:19-27:38-27:39-27:40-27:45-27:56-27:60-27:72-27:91-27:92-28:5-28:7-28:9-28:10-28:19-28:22-28:27-28:30-28:31-28:33-28:34-28:47-28:67-28:82-28:86-29:2-29:4-29:24-29:29-29:33-30:10-30:20-30:21-30:25-30:43-30:46-30:49-31:10-31:12-31:14-31:15-32:20-33:6-33:36-33:37-33:49-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:59-33:72-34:11-34:14-34:33-34:43-34:46-35:41-36:40-36:60-36:61-36:81-36:82-37:104-38:4-38:6-38:75-39:4-39:11-39:17-39:54-39:55-39:56-40:26-40:28-40:66-40:78-41:22-42:13-42:47-42:51-43:5-43:33-43:66-44:18-44:19-44:20-45:21-45:25-46:15-46:17-46:33-47:18-47:22-47:29-48:12-48:15-48:24-48:25-49:2-49:6-49:11-49:12-49:17-50:2-51:57-53:26-53:39-55:33-56:61-57:16-57:22-58:3-58:4-58:13-59:2-59:3-60:1-60:7-60:8-60:9-60:10-60:12-61:3-63:10-64:7-65:1-65:4-66:5-66:8-67:16-67:17-68:14-68:22-68:24-68:32-68:49-70:38-70:41-71:1-71:3-72:5-72:7-72:12-72:16-72:28-73:20-74:15-74:37-74:52-74:56-75:4-75:25-75:36-75:40-76:30-79:18-80:2-81:28-81:29-84:14-85:8-90:5-90:7-96:7",488
2329,504,"A","کَاَنْ ۔ کَاَنَّ ۔ کَاَنَّمَا","«کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا» All these letters are composed of «کَ» simile and «اَنْ» or «اَنَّ». And they convey the meaning of as if. For example: In the Quran it is: «کَاَنۡ  لَّمۡ یَسۡمَعۡہَا کَاَنَّ فِیۡۤ  اُذُنَیۡہِ  وَقۡرًا» (31/7) Translation: As if he had not heard, as if there were weights in his ears. «اَنْ» and «کَاَنْ» attach to the verb, while «اَنَّ» and «کَاَنَّ» attach to the noun, as is evident from the above verse. For example: In the Quran it is: «کَاَنَّمَا یُسَاقُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡمَوۡتِ» (8/6) Translation: As if they were being driven towards death.","These letters «کَاَنْ ، کَاَنَّ ، کَاَنَّمَا» convey the meaning of as if.","As if","کان ۔ کان ۔ کانما","2:101-4:73-5:32-6:125-7:92-7:171-7:187-8:6-10:12-10:24-10:27-10:45-11:68-11:95-22:31-24:35-27:10-27:42-28:31-31:7-37:49-37:65-41:34-45:8-46:35-52:24-54:7-54:20-55:58-61:4-63:4-69:7-70:43-74:50-77:33-79:46",36
2330,504,"A","اَلَّا","«اَلَّا» is essentially «اَنْ ۔ لَا». It means that not and is inserted between clauses to convey this meaning.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«تَتَنَزَّلُ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  اَلَّا تَخَافُوۡا وَ لَا تَحۡزَنُوۡا» (41/30)  \nTranslation: Angels descend upon them (and say), Fear not, nor grieve.","«اَلَّا» This is actually «اَنْ ۔ لَا», meaning that not.","as if","الا","2:229-2:246-2:282-3:41-3:64-3:170-3:176-3:183-4:3-5:8-5:71-6:119-6:151-7:12-8:34-9:92-9:97-11:2-12:40-14:12-15:32-17:2-17:23-19:10-19:24-19:48-20:89-20:93-20:118-26:3-27:25-27:31-41:14-41:30-46:21-53:38-55:8-57:10-57:29-80:7",40
2331,505,"W","اَیْنَ ۔ اَیْنَمَا","«اَیْن» is an adverb of place. It is used to ask about a location.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَیۡنَ شُرَکَآءِیَ الَّذِیۡنَ» (16/22)\nTranslation: Where are my partners?\n\n«اَیْنَمَا»: By adding «مَا» after «اَیْنَ», it gives the meaning of wherever. That is, the sentence becomes a conditional clause seeking a consequence.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ» (4/78)\nTranslation: Wherever you may be, death will overtake you.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the divine command states:\n«اَیۡنَمَا تُوَلُّوۡا فَثَمَّ وَجۡہُ اللّٰہِ» (2/115)\nTranslation: Wherever you may turn (whichever direction you face), there is the Face of Allah.\n\nAnd «ثَمَّ» is actually the answer to «اَیْنَ». «اَیْنَ» means where. And «ثَمَّ» means there, at that place.","«اَیْن» means where. It is used solely to inquire about a location. And «اَیْنَمَا» means wherever.","Where","این ۔ اینما","2:115-2:148-3:112-4:78-6:22-7:37-16:27-16:76-19:31-26:92-28:62-28:74-33:61-40:73-41:47-57:4-58:7-75:10-81:26",19
2332,505,"W","اَنّٰی","«اَنّٰی» comes to inquire about both place and condition (interrogative).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اَنّٰی لَکِ ہٰذَا» (3/37)\nTranslation: (Zachariah, upon seeing this circumstance,) said, O Mary! From where does this provision come to you?\nAnd when it comes solely for the purpose of spatial context, what meaning of 'which direction' or 'where' will it convey?\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«قٰتَلَہُمُ اللّٰہُ  ۚ ۫  اَنّٰی  یُؤۡفَکُوۡنَ» (9/30)\nTranslation: May Allah destroy them; where (or which way) are they wandering astray?","«اَنّٰی» is also used to inquire about both location and state/condition.","Where","انی","2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23",28
2333,506,"E","اَسَاطِیْر","«اَسْطُوْرَہ ، اَسَیْطَرۃ» and «اِسْطَار» are both unified in «اَسَاطِیْر». And «اِسْطَار» has emerged from «سَطَر». Meaning: every thing that is written in lines (i.e., such a phrase that is in a straight line) or has entered into a written record but in reality is nothing. Baseless and unfounded matters (myth): such stories or tales that are not based on reality.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡۤا اِنۡ ہٰذَاۤ  اِلَّاۤ  اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (6/25)\nTranslation: The disbelievers say, These are but the tales of the former people.","«اَسَاطِیْر» baseless incidents.","Events","اساطیر","6:25-8:31-16:24-23:83-25:5-27:68-46:17-68:15-83:13",9
2334,506,"E","اَحَادِیْث","«اَحَادِیْث» is a collective term for «حَدِیْث». It refers to any event that occurred and did not exist before; such a report is a Hadith. Then this term is also applied to incidents which people have forgotten due to the passage of a long time. Instructive historical events.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«کُلَّمَا جَآءَ اُمَّۃً  رَّسُوۡلُہَا کَذَّبُوۡہُ  فَاَتۡبَعۡنَا بَعۡضَہُمۡ بَعۡضًا وَّ جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ اَحَادِیۡثَ» (23/44)\nTranslation: Whenever a messenger came to them from their Lord, they denied him. So We punished them by making some follow others in succession, and thus We turned them into tales (by confounding them).","«اَحَادِیْث» Unheeded yet instructive events.","Events","احادیث","12:6-12:21-12:101-23:44-34:19",5
2335,506,"E","قَصَص","«قَصَص» is a collection of «قِصَّہ». «قَصَّ» means 'to follow in the footsteps' and also 'to narrate an event' (sing. and pl.). By «قَصَص» is meant those events that are famous among common people and have been passed down orally. Oral traditions, well-known and famous among all people.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n\n«نَحۡنُ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ اَحۡسَنَ الۡقَصَصِ» (12/3)\n\nTranslation: (O Prophet (ﷺ)!) We relate to you an excellent story.","«قَصَص» are incidents that have remained famous among common people and have been transmitted from person to person.","Events","قصص","3:62-4:164-7:176-12:3-12:5-12:111-16:118-18:64-28:25-40:78",10
2336,507,"S","جِلْد","«جِلْد» refers to the skin or hide of a living being, and the outer part of the entire body is its skin or hide (general); this term is used in a general sense.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«کُلَّمَا نَضِجَتۡ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ بَدَّلۡنٰہُمۡ جُلُوۡدًا غَیۡرَہَا» (4/56)  \nTranslation: Whenever their skins are burned (and melted), We shall replace them with other skins.","«جِلْد» the skin of any living being.","Skin","جلد","4:56-16:80-22:20-39:23-41:20-41:21-41:22",7
2337,507,"S","شَوٰی","«شَوٰی» refers to the outer parts of the body—the hands, feet, and those organs upon which a wound does not cause death. This is an idiomatic expression. «رَمَاہُ فَاَشْوَاہُ» means, for example, I shot an arrow, and it landed on its periphery, i.e., on a part where a wound would not be fatal (as explained). For instance, the Quran states:  \n«کَلَّا ؕ اِنَّہَا  لَظٰی نَزَّاعَۃً   لِّلشَّوٰی» (70:15-16)  \nTranslation: Never will it be! It is a raging fire, which will strip off the skin.","«شَوٰی» hands, feet, and other parts of the body.","Skin","شوی","18:29-70:16",2
2338,507,"S","سَلَخَ","«سَلَخَ الْحَیَّۃُ» means to strip off the skin (hide) of a snake. And «سَلَخُ الْحَیَّۃ» means the slough or cast-off skin of a snake. And «مِسْلَاخ» also means the skin of a snake. And «سَلَخَ الْمِرَاۃ» means for a woman to remove her own shift (undergarment). And «سَلَخَ الْخَرُوْف» means to remove the skin (membrane) of a young goat (kid), i.e., its caul. The word «سَلَخَ» comes to mean raw skin, raw hide, or a raw veil—it is used for removing something that is raw or fresh.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اٰیَۃٌ  لَّہُمُ الَّیۡلُ   ۚ ۖ نَسۡلَخُ مِنۡہُ النَّہَارَ» ( 36/37 )\nTranslation: And a sign for them is the night; We remove from it the day, and behold, they are in darkness.","«سَلَخَ» is used for the temporary removal of skin or a veil.","skin","سلخ","36:37",1
2339,507,"S","کَشَطَ","«کَشَطَ الْعَبِیْر » means to skin a camel. And «کِشَاط» means the removed skin, and «کَشَّاط» means butcher, slaughterer (manjad). For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ اِذَا  السَّمَآءُ کُشِطَتۡ» (81:11). Translation: And when the sky's skin is stripped away.","«کَشَطَ» is used for removing a tight membrane or covering.","skin","کشط","81:11",1
2340,508,"F","اَکَلَ","«اَکَلَ» This word is general and applies to every edible thing, whether it is food, bread, sweets, fruit, or any other item of consumption. It is used everywhere. It is used equally for humans and non-humans. It is an idiom: «اَکَلَتِ النَّارُ الْحَطَبَ», meaning fire has consumed the wood. (Example)\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَکَلَ السَّبُعُ اِلَّا مَا ذَکَّیۡتُمۡ» ( 5/3 )\nTranslation: And that which is killed by a wild animal (is also forbidden for you), unless you (first) slaughter it (while it is still alive).","«اَکَلَ» This word is general and is used everywhere for every kind of food item, whether it is a meal, bread, sweets, fruits, or any other edible thing.","Food","اکل","2:57-2:58-2:60-2:168-2:172-2:174-2:187-2:188-2:275-3:49-3:130-3:183-4:2-4:4-4:6-4:10-4:29-4:161-5:3-5:4-5:62-5:63-5:66-5:75-5:88-5:113-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:141-6:142-7:31-7:73-7:160-7:161-8:69-9:34-10:24-11:64-12:13-12:14-12:17-12:36-12:41-12:43-12:46-12:47-12:48-15:3-16:5-16:14-16:114-20:54-20:81-20:121-21:8-22:28-22:36-23:19-23:21-23:33-23:51-24:61-25:7-25:8-25:20-29:59-32:27-34:14-34:15-35:12-36:33-36:35-36:72-37:66-37:91-40:79-43:73-47:12-49:12-51:27-52:19-56:52-67:15-69:24-69:37-77:43-77:46-89:19",89
2341,508,"F","طَعَمَ","«طَعَمَ» is used in very limited meanings compared to «اکل». It means food, eating bread, eating (m.), and anything that is consumed as food. And this word is generally applied to humans. «طَعَامِیّ» means bread-seller. And «مَطْعَم» means hotel (m. q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«فَاِذَا طَعِمۡتُمۡ فَانۡتَشِرُوۡا وَ لَا مُسۡتَاۡنِسِیۡنَ لِحَدِیۡثٍ» (33/53)\nTranslation: Then when you have eaten, disperse, lingering in conversation out of courtesy.","«طَعَمَ» the food of humans","Food","طعم","2:61-2:184-2:249-2:259-3:93-5:5-5:75-5:93-5:95-5:96-6:145-12:37-18:19-18:77-21:8-25:7-25:20-33:53-44:44-69:34-69:36-73:13-76:8-80:24-88:6-89:18-107:3",27
2342,508,"F","رَتَعَ","The basic meaning of «رَتَعَ» is the grazing and feeding of animals. Then, metaphorically, this term is also used for humans eating and drinking to their heart's content. That is, to eat a lot like animals.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعَنَا غَدًا یَّرۡتَعۡ وَ یَلۡعَبۡ» (12/12)\nTranslation: (O my father!) Send him with us tomorrow so he may eat his fill of fruits and play.","«رَتَعَ» Eat heartily. Animals' grazing and nibbling.","Food","رتع","12:12",1
2343,509,"O","اَطْعَمَ","To feed a person.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ  یُطۡعِمُنِیۡ وَ  یَسۡقِیۡنِ» (26/79)\nTranslation: And He (Allah) is the one who feeds me and gives me drink.","«اَطْعَمَ» to feed a person.","Open!","اطعم","5:89-6:14-6:138-22:28-22:36-26:79-36:47-51:57-58:4-74:44-76:8-76:9-90:14-106:4",14
2344,509,"T","رِزْق ","«رِزْق» has a broad meaning and comes to provide all kinds of material and spiritual nourishment (for details, see Food).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ ارۡزُقُوۡہُمۡ فِیۡہَا وَ اکۡسُوۡہُمۡ» (4/5)\nTranslation: So feed and clothe them from it.","«رِزْق» has a broad meaning and is used to provide all kinds of material and spiritual nourishment.","to open","رزق","2:3-2:22-2:25-2:57-2:60-2:126-2:172-2:212-2:233-2:254-3:27-3:37-3:169-4:5-4:8-4:39-5:88-5:114-6:140-6:142-6:151-7:32-7:50-7:160-8:3-8:4-8:26-8:74-10:31-10:59-10:93-11:6-11:88-12:37-13:22-13:26-14:31-14:32-14:37-16:56-16:67-16:71-16:72-16:73-16:75-16:112-16:114-17:30-17:31-17:70-18:19-19:62-20:81-20:131-20:132-22:28-22:34-22:35-22:50-22:58-24:26-24:38-27:64-28:54-28:57-28:82-29:17-29:60-29:62-30:28-30:37-30:40-32:16-33:31-34:4-34:15-34:24-34:36-34:39-35:3-35:29-36:47-37:41-38:54-39:52-40:13-40:40-40:64-42:12-42:19-42:27-42:38-45:5-45:16-50:11-51:22-51:57-56:82-63:10-65:3-65:7-65:11-67:15-67:21-89:16",105
2345,510,"D","نَخْلَة","«نَخْلَة» meaning a date palm sapling or tree.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ» ( 19/25 )\nTranslation: (O Mary!) Shake the trunk of the date palm tree towards yourself.\nAnd «نَخْل» is the plural of «نَخْلَۃ». Date palm trees and their fruit. Dates. The fruit of the date palm.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«جَعَلۡنَا لِاَحَدِہِمَا جَنَّتَیۡنِ مِنۡ اَعۡنَابٍ وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ» ( 18/32 )\nTranslation: We granted one of them two gardens of grapes, and surrounded them both with date palm trees.\nAnd «نَخِیْل» refers to a garden or plantation in which date palm trees are abundant.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«اَیَوَدُّ اَحَدُکُمۡ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ لَہٗ جَنَّۃٌ مِّنۡ نَّخِیۡلٍ وَّ اَعۡنَابٍ» ( 2/266 )\nTranslation: Is there any among you who would like that his garden should be a garden of date palms and grapes?","«نَخْلَة» meaning date palm tree.","date","نخلۃ","2:266-6:99-6:141-13:4-16:11-16:67-17:91-18:32-19:23-19:25-20:71-23:19-26:148-36:34-50:10-54:20-55:11-55:68-69:7-80:29",20
2346,510,"D","لِیْنَۃ","«لِیْنَۃ» 'Ajwah (an excellent variety of dates). Besides that, every kind of date palm tree and its fruit (Munjid al-Furqan 116).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَا  قَطَعۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ  لِّیۡنَۃٍ  اَوۡ  تَرَکۡتُمُوۡہَا قَآئِمَۃً  عَلٰۤی  اُصُوۡلِہَا فَبِاِذۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (59:5)\nTranslation: Whatever date palms you cut down or left standing on their roots, it was all by Allah's command.","«لِیْنَۃ» Ajwa dates.","date","لینۃ","59:5",1
2347,510,"D","رُطَب","«رُطَب» meaning fresh dates (fruit) (Surah 47, verse 46)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«تُسٰقِطۡ عَلَیۡکِ  رُطَبًا جَنِیًّا» (19/25)\nTranslation: Fresh dates will fall upon you.","fresh dates","date","رطب","6:59-19:25",2
2348,511,"S","قَامَ","«قَامَ» means to stand, and its opposites are «قَعَدَ» and «جَلَسَ», which mean to sit. This is a well-known term.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا قَامُوۡۤا اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ قَامُوۡا کُسَالٰی» (4/142)\nTranslation: The hypocrites stand for prayer lazily and sluggishly.\n\nAnd «اَقَامَ» means to make someone or something stand, to establish, to make upright, or to set something in its proper, straight position. (m. l.)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» (18/77)\nTranslation: Then they found a wall that was about to collapse, and Khidr (peace be upon him) straightened it.","«قَامَ» signifies standing, and its antonyms are «قَعَدَ» and «جَلَسَ», which denote sitting.","Standing (in prayer)","قام","2:20-3:191-4:5-4:102-4:103-4:142-5:6-5:97-9:84-9:108-18:14-18:77-25:64-36:8-39:68-51:45-72:19-73:2-74:2",19
2349,511,"S","وَقَفَ","«وَقَف» means to stop for a while while working or walking; to stand motionless and still (transitive and intransitive). It can be used both transitively and intransitively.\n\nExample of the intransitive form: The divine command states:\n«وَ لَوۡ تَرٰۤی اِذۡ  وُقِفُوۡا عَلٰی رَبِّہِمۡ» (6:30)\nTranslation: And if you could but see when they will be made to stand before their Lord.\n\nExample of the transitive form: The divine command states:\n«وَ قِفُوۡہُمۡ   اِنَّہُمۡ  مَّسۡئُوۡلُوۡنَ» (37:24)\nTranslation: And detain them, for indeed, they will be questioned.","«وَقَف» to stun or to stop in one's tracks.","Standing","وقف","2:87-5:46-6:27-6:30-34:31-37:24-57:27",7
2350,511,"S","نَتَقَ","«نَتَقَ» meaning to shake, to raise, to spread (M) and meaning to make something loose by pulling (F), and meaning to shake something with such force that it remains rooted but tilts to one side (M.L.). In Punjabi, the specific word Alarna is used for this meaning, which accurately conveys its correct sense.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ» (7/171)\nTranslation: And when We raised the mountain above their heads as if it were a canopy, and they were certain that it would fall upon them.","«نَتَقَ» to shake something so forcefully that it remains rooted but tilts to one side.","Standing","نتق","7:171",1
2351,511,"S","نَشَزَ","«نَشَزَ» means to stand up. «نَشَزَ الرَّجُل» refers to a person who was sitting and then stood up. And «نَشَزَ عَنْ مَکَانِہٖ» means that he rose from his place and departed. For example, the Holy Quran states: «وَ اِذَا قِیۡلَ انۡشُزُوۡا فَانۡشُزُوۡا» (58:11) Translation: And when it is said, 'Rise up,' then rise up and proceed.","«نَشَزَ» meaning to stand up and leave. To get up and go.","Standing","نشز","2:259-58:11",2
2352,512,"T","اَنٰی ۔ یَانِیْ","«اَنٰی ، یَانِیْ» means for water or similar substances to reach their extreme limit in heat (i.e., for a liquid substance to begin boiling due to intense heat).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«تُسۡقٰی مِنۡ عَیۡنٍ  اٰنِیَۃٍ» (88/5)\nTranslation: It will be given to drink from a scalding hot spring.","«اَنٰی ، یَانِیْ» water and the like starting to boil due to intense heat.","to open","انی ۔ یانی","55:44-88:5",2
2353,512,"T","غَلٰی","«غَلٰی» The water boils and bubbles up due to intense heat. It comes to a boil. «غَلٰی الْقَدَر» Meaning: the pot boils and the contents rise up (figurative). For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَغۡلِیۡ  فِی الۡبُطُوۡنِ کَغَلۡیِ  الۡحَمِیۡمِ» (44/45,46)\nTranslation: He will cause it to boil within them like the boiling of hot water.","«غَلٰی» the boiling of water due to extreme heat.","to open","غلی","44:45-44:46",2
2354,512,"T","بَسَطَ","«بَسَطَ» means to open and spread something, and its opposite is «قبَضَ». And «قَدَر» means to spread and widen something, to make it vast (transitive).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ» (13/26)\nTranslation: Allah expands the provision for whom He wills and restricts it for whom He wills.","to open and spread","to open","بسط","2:245-2:247-5:11-5:28-6:93-7:69-13:14-13:26-17:29-17:30-18:18-28:82-29:62-30:37-30:48-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-42:27-60:2-71:19",22
2355,512,"T","فَتَحَ","«فَتَحَ» is to remove the complexity of a complicated matter, to open a tied package, and its opposite is «اَغْلَاق». (m.f.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65)\nTranslation: When Yusuf's brothers opened their baggage, they found their money returned to them.","«فَتَحَ» opening a sealed item or complex matter.","to open","فتح","2:76-6:44-7:40-7:96-12:65-15:14-21:96-23:77-35:2-38:50-39:71-39:73-54:11-78:19",14
2356,512,"T","حَلَّ","(al-'Uqdah) means to untie a knot, to unravel a tangle, to solve a difficulty. (M. R. Manj) Arbab-i-Hall wa 'Aqd is a well-known term (meaning the rulers of a country or region, experts in a field, a certified scholar, authorized officials, higher authorities, those in charge).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ احۡلُلۡ  عُقۡدَۃً   مِّنۡ  لِّسَانِیۡ یَفۡقَہُوۡا  قَوۡلِیۡ» (20:27,28)\nTranslation: And untie the knot from my tongue, so that they may understand my speech.","«حَلّ ، العُقْدَۃ» meaning to untie the knot.","to reveal","حل","20:27",1
2357,512,"T","شَرَحَ","«شَرَحَ» means unfolding the meanings of difficult speech (mufassal), and according to Ibn al-Faris, two things are fundamental in commentary (sharh): (1) unfolding (fath) and (2) elucidation (bayān). As for sharh al-sadr, it means opening the chest, i.e., comprehending a difficult and complex matter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«رَبِّ  اشۡرَحۡ  لِیۡ  صَدۡرِیۡ وَ  یَسِّرۡ لِیۡۤ   اَمۡرِیۡ» (20/25,26)\nTranslation: O my Lord! Open my chest for me, and make my task easy for me.","«شَرَحَ» meaning to open and clarify the meanings of difficult speech.","to open","شرح","6:125-16:106-20:25-39:22-94:1",5
2358,512,"T","کَشَفَ","«کَشَفَ» to uncover and remove. To unveil. To remove one thing from another. And the first thing becomes prominent and apparent.\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَتۡہُ حَسِبَتۡہُ  لُجَّۃً  وَّ کَشَفَتۡ عَنۡ سَاقَیۡہَا» (27/44)\nTranslation: When the Queen of Sheba saw it, she thought it was deep water. And (lifting her garment) she uncovered her legs.","«کَشَفَ» to remove one thing in order to unveil another.","To unveil","کشف","6:41-7:134-7:135-10:12-10:98-16:54-17:56-21:84-23:75-27:44-27:62-43:50-44:12-50:22-68:42",15
2359,512,"T","نَشَطَ","«نَشَطَ» This word is from the category of 'addad' (antonyms). «نَشَطَ الْحَبْلَ» means to tie a knot in a rope. And «نَشَطَ الْعُقْدَۃ» means to strengthen a knot. And «اَلْنَشْط» means a knot that opens easily. (Majid) And «نَشَطَ» means to untie a knot (Mufradat). Thus, this word is more specific than «حَلَّ». The meanings of «حَلَّ الْعُقٌدَۃ» are the same as the meanings of 'nashṭ' (i.e., to untie a knot). To loosen a fastening. To loosen a knot.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran it is mentioned:\n«وَ النّٰزِعٰتِ غَرۡقًا وَّ النّٰشِطٰتِ نَشۡطًا» (79:1,2)\nTranslation: By those (angels) who draw forth the soul from within the body, and by those who loosen the ties and fastenings.\n\nNote: (Lughat Addad refers to words that have two separate meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other).","to loosen a knot or joint, etc.","to open","نشط","79:2",1
2360,512,"T","فَرَجَ","The concept of expansiveness is found in «فَرْج». «فَرَجَ» means: to open, to widen, to throw open, to make spacious. (For further details, see cleft.)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  فُرِجَتۡ» (77/9)\nTranslation: And when the skies are split open.","«فَرَجَ» to open and expand.","to open","فرج","77:9",1
2361,513,"A","حَرَثَ","«حَرَثَ» means to prepare the earth by breaking it up for sowing seeds and cultivation (sing.), and «مِحْرَث» is the plural of it. «مَحَارِث» means the tools for tilling the earth, such as a plow, etc. (coll.). However, sometimes the cultivation itself is also called «حَرْث» (sing.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَنِ  اغۡدُوۡا عَلٰی حَرۡثِکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰرِمِیۡنَ» (68/22)\nTranslation: If you intend to harvest, then proceed to your crop early in the morning.","«حَرَثَ» meaning to plow and to sow seeds.","Agriculture","حرث","2:71-2:205-2:223-3:14-3:117-6:136-6:138-21:78-42:20-68:22",10
2362,513,"F","زَرَع","The original meaning of «زَرَعَ» is «اِنْبَات» or 'to grow.' It also includes placing a seed in the soil, irrigating it with water, and providing appropriate care and attention. The attribution of 'growing' to humans is metaphorical because they perform the duties of care and maintenance; otherwise, in reality, the actual growth of crops is solely the work of Allah. (Detailed explanation)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَفَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  مَّا  تَحۡرُثُوۡنَ ءَاَنۡتُمۡ تَزۡرَعُوۡنَہٗۤ  اَمۡ نَحۡنُ الزّٰرِعُوۡنَ» (56:63,64)\nTranslation: So have you considered what you sow? Do you cause it to grow, or is it We who cause it to grow?","meaning to irrigate and properly tend to it after sowing the seed.","Farming","زرع","6:141-12:47-13:4-14:37-16:11-18:32-32:27-39:21-48:29-56:64",10
2363,514,"T","مَدّ","meaning to stretch or extend something and to spread it while maintaining continuity, and duration refers to the length of time.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ اِخۡوَانُہُمۡ یَمُدُّوۡنَہُمۡ فِی الۡغَیِّ ثُمَّ لَا یُقۡصِرُوۡنَ» (7/202)  \nTranslation: And their brothers lead them into error, and they do not shorten [the path].  \n\nMoreover, «مَدَّدَ» serves as an additional emphasis.  \nFor instance, the Divine declaration says:  \n«فِیۡ  عَمَدٍ  مُّمَدَّدَۃٍ» (104/9)  \nTranslation: In long pillars.","Pulling and spreading, and elongating it in such a way that it remains unbroken.","to pull","مد","2:15-7:202-13:3-19:75-25:45-31:27-56:30-74:12-104:9",9
2364,514,"T","جَرَّ","«جَرَّ» meaning to pull and drag (m. l.) to pull on the ground. And «جَیْشٌ جَرَارٌ» meaning a very large army that spreads over a wide area and advances, being pulled along.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَخَذَ بِرَاۡسِ اَخِیۡہِ یَجُرُّہٗۤ اِلَیۡہِ» (7/150)\nTranslation: And Moses seized his brother by the head and began to pull him toward himself.","«جَرَّ» to drag someone on the ground.","to pull / to draw / to attract (in Islamic contexts: to draw towards Allah)","جر","7:150",1
2365,514,"T","اِضطَرَّ","«اِضطَرَّ» means to forcibly drag someone toward something; to compel and make someone helpless, then pull them into performing an action (m. l.).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ کَفَرَ فَاُمَتِّعُہٗ قَلِیۡلًا ثُمَّ  اَضۡطَرُّہٗۤ اِلٰی عَذَابِ النَّارِ» (2/126)\nTranslation: And whoever disbelieves, I will grant him a little enjoyment [in this world]; then I will drag him to the punishment of the Fire.","«اِضطَرَّ» to compel someone to do something by force or coercion.","to draw","اضطر","2:126-2:173-5:3-6:119-6:145-16:115-27:62-31:24",8
2366,514,"T","سَلَخَ","«سَلَخَ» To pull off and remove the skin of a living being (i.e., to shed skin), such as a snake shedding its slough. And in the words of Ibn al-Faris, to extract something from upon the skin (i.e., to peel off). And «سَلَخَتِ الشَّھْر» means to become the last day of the month (i.e., to conclude).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اٰیَۃٌ  لَّہُمُ الَّیۡلُ   ۚ ۖ نَسۡلَخُ مِنۡہُ النَّہَارَ  فَاِذَا ہُمۡ  مُّظۡلِمُوۡنَ» (36/37)\nTranslation: And the night is also a sign for them. We draw the day away from it, then they are left in darkness.","«سَلَخَ» to act rashly.","to pull; to draw; to attract","سلخ","36:37",1
2367,514,"T","نَزَعَ","meaning to pull something out from its place (transitive), as in extracting the soul from the body, or to pull out and take something. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ نَزَعۡنَا مَا فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ مِّنۡ غِلٍّ» (7/43) Translation: And We will remove from their breasts any sense of envy and the like.","«نَزَعَ» to pull something from its place.","to pull","نزع","3:26-7:27-7:43-7:108-11:9-15:47-19:69-26:33-28:75-54:20",10
2368,514,"T","سَفَع","«سَفَعَ» meaning to pull a horse by its forelock (detailed)\nFor example: In the Quran it is said:\n«لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ یَنۡتَہِ  ۬ ۙ  لَنَسۡفَعًۢا بِالنَّاصِیَۃِ» (96/15)\nTranslation: If he does not desist, we will drag him by the forelock.","«سَفَعَ» means 'to pull'. «سَفَعَ بالنّاصیۃ» to pull by grasping the hair on the forehead.","to draw","سفع","96:15",1
2369,515,"T","لَعَبَ","«لَعِبَ» means to play. To do something for recreation. To perform an action from which no benefit is derived. And «لُعْبَۃ» means play. A turn to play from which one plays. And «لاَعِب» and «لَعِب» mean player. And «مَلَاعِب» means playmate (companion in play).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَذَرۡہُمۡ  یَخُوۡضُوۡا وَ یَلۡعَبُوۡا حَتّٰی یُلٰقُوۡا یَوۡمَہُمُ  الَّذِیۡ یُوۡعَدُوۡنَ» ( 43/83 )\nTranslation: And let them amuse themselves and play until they see the Day which they are promised.","«لَعِبَ» meaning to play.","to play","لعب","5:57-5:58-6:32-6:70-6:91-7:51-7:98-9:65-12:12-21:2-29:64-43:83-44:9-47:36-52:12-57:20-70:42",17
2370,515,"T","لَھٰی","«لَھٰی» means amusement and every action done for the recreation of nature. And this is more general than «لَعَبَ». Playing is also included in «لَھْو». And watching play or amusement, etc., all are included. That is, every action that distracts attention from purposeful deeds and causes delight is «لَھْو». And «اَلْھٰی» means causing neglect of the original purposeful deeds through such delightful actions.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ مَا الۡحَیٰوۃُ  الدُّنۡیَاۤ  اِلَّا  لَعِبٌ وَّ لَہۡوٌ» (6/32)\nTranslation: But the life of this world is only play and amusement.","«لَھٰی» refers to every action that causes one to neglect the primary objective.","to play","لھی","4:135-6:32-6:70-7:51-21:17-29:64-31:6-38:26-47:36-53:3-57:20-62:11-79:40-102:1",14
2371,515,"T","عَبَثَ","«عَبَث» is even more common than «لَھْو». That is, work is performed with purpose, but it is treated as play. And through this admixture, that work is rendered purposeless and fruitless (Ma'f). Moreover, «عَبَث» also means to play and to mix one thing with another—«عَبَثَ الشَّیْء بِالشَّیْء» meaning to blend one thing into another. And «عَبَث» means to mock or jest (Manjad).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَفَحَسِبۡتُمۡ اَنَّمَا خَلَقۡنٰکُمۡ عَبَثًا» (23/115)\nTranslation: Do you then think that We created you in vain? (Jalandhari).\nYou were created only to play. (Usmani).","«عَبَث» To engage in aimless actions, or to intermix play with purposeful endeavors, thereby rendering them futile.","to play","عبث","23:115",1
2373,516,"W","ھَلْ","«ھَلْ» is an interrogative particle. It applies to nouns and verbs, but not to other particles.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ہَلۡ یَسۡتَوِی الۡاَعۡمٰی وَ الۡبَصِیۡرُ» (13/16)\nTranslation: Can the seeing and the blind be equal?","«ھَلْ» is an interrogative letter, meaning what.","What","ھل","2:210-2:246-3:154-5:59-5:60-5:91-5:112-6:47-6:50-6:148-6:158-7:44-7:53-7:147-9:52-9:127-10:34-10:35-10:52-10:102-11:14-11:24-12:64-12:89-13:16-14:21-16:33-16:35-16:75-16:76-17:93-18:66-18:94-18:103-19:65-19:98-20:9-20:40-20:120-21:3-21:80-21:108-22:15-26:39-26:72-26:93-26:203-26:221-27:90-28:12-30:28-30:40-34:7-34:17-34:33-35:3-35:43-37:54-39:9-39:29-39:38-40:11-40:47-42:44-43:66-46:35-47:18-47:22-50:30-50:36-51:24-54:15-54:17-54:22-54:32-54:40-54:51-55:60-61:10-67:3-69:8-76:1-79:15-79:18-83:36-85:17-88:1-89:5",88
2375,516,"W","مَاذَا","The addition of «مَا» ismiyah istihfamiyah with «ذَا» expands its meanings. It conveys both the concepts of what and which. It can also apply to those of sound intellect.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ مَا ذَا یُنۡفِقُوۡنَ» (2:219)\nTranslation: They ask you what [i.e., which wealth] to spend.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine command states:\n«مَاذَاۤ  اَجَبۡتُمُ الۡمُرۡسَلِیۡنَ» (28:65)\nTranslation: What answer did you give to the messengers?","«مَاذَا»’’ what and which ‘‘ both convey the meaning.","What","ماذا","2:26-2:215-2:219-4:39-5:4-5:109-7:110-10:32-10:50-10:101-12:71-16:24-16:30-26:35-27:28-27:33-27:84-28:65-31:11-31:34-34:23-35:40-37:85-37:102-46:4-47:16-74:31",27
2376,517,"H","کَیْف","«کَیْف» is used to inquire about the quality and nature of something. For example: In the Quran, it says: «اَفَلَا یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَی الۡاِبِلِ کَیۡفَ خُلِقَتۡ» (88/17). Translation: Do people not look at the camels—how wonderfully they are created?","«کَیْف» is used to inquire about the quality and essence of something.","How","کیف","2:28-2:259-2:260-3:6-3:25-3:86-3:101-3:137-4:21-4:41-4:50-4:62-5:31-5:43-5:64-5:75-6:11-6:24-6:46-6:65-6:81-7:84-7:86-7:93-7:103-7:129-9:7-9:8-10:14-10:35-10:39-10:73-12:109-13:32-14:24-14:45-16:36-17:21-17:48-18:68-19:29-22:44-25:9-25:45-27:14-27:51-27:69-28:40-29:19-29:20-30:9-30:42-30:48-30:50-34:45-35:26-35:44-37:73-37:154-40:5-40:21-40:82-43:25-47:10-47:27-50:6-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-67:17-67:18-68:36-71:15-73:17-74:19-74:20-88:17-88:18-88:19-88:20-89:6-105:1",83
2377,517,"H","اَنّٰی","«اَنّٰی» is used to inquire about the reason for something. How? For example, the Quran states:\n«اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لَہُ الۡمُلۡکُ عَلَیۡنَا» (2:247)\nTranslation: How can the right of sovereignty be upon us?","«اَنّٰی» comes to ask about the reason for something.","How","انی","2:223-2:247-2:259-3:37-3:40-3:47-3:165-5:75-6:95-6:101-9:30-10:32-10:34-19:8-19:20-23:89-29:61-34:52-35:3-36:66-39:6-40:62-40:69-43:87-44:13-47:18-63:4-89:23",28
2378,518,"W","لِمَ","«لِمَ» meaning: why? for what reason?\nFor example: in the Noble Quran it is:\n«رَبِّ  لِمَ حَشَرۡتَنِیۡۤ  اَعۡمٰی» (20/125)\nTranslation: O my Lord! Why have you raised me blind while I was seeing?","What does «لِمَ» mean?","Why","لم","2:91-3:65-3:66-3:70-3:71-3:98-3:99-3:183-4:77-5:18-7:164-9:43-19:42-20:125-27:46-41:21-61:2-61:5-66:1",19
2379,518,"W","لَوْلَا","«لَوْلَا» means why not. «ھَلَّا» is used in the sense of reproach—meaning scolding—and specification—meaning particularization—and it is necessary for a verb to follow it immediately. In the case of specification, it is specifically associated with the present tense verb. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «لَوۡ لَا تَسۡتَغۡفِرُوۡنَ اللّٰہَ» (27/46). Translation: Why do you not seek forgiveness from Allah? And in the case of reproach, it is specifically associated with the past tense verb. For example: The divine command states: «لَوۡ لَا جَآءُوۡ عَلَیۡہِ  بِاَرۡبَعَۃِ شُہَدَآءَ» (24/13). Translation: Why did they not bring four witnesses?","«لَوْلَا» meaning why not?","Why","لولا","2:118-4:77-5:63-6:8-6:37-6:43-7:203-9:122-10:20-10:98-11:12-11:116-13:7-13:27-18:15-18:39-20:133-20:134-24:12-24:13-24:16-25:7-25:21-25:32-27:46-28:47-28:48-29:50-41:44-43:31-43:53-46:28-47:20-56:57-56:62-56:70-56:83-56:86-58:8-63:10-68:28",41
2380,518,"W","لَوْمَا","«لَوْمَا» is a particle of specification. And upon entering the present tense, it conveys the meaning of «لَوْلَا». For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «لَوۡ مَا تَاۡتِیۡنَا بِالۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ» (15/7). Translation: Then why do you not bring the angels to us?","In Arabic grammar, this is called the particle of specification «لَوْمَا».","Why","لوما","15:7",1
2381,519,"T","نَصَبَ","«نَصَب» means to erect or plant something in such a way that part of it is embedded in the ground while the larger part stands upright in a straight direction, as in planting a flag or spear in the ground, or erecting a building or stone. The word nusb (نصب) is used for such an act (M. L. Maf), and «نَصَب» also refers to an idol that has been fixed in place. Its plural is «اَنْصَاب» and «نُصُب».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِلَی الۡجِبَالِ کَیۡفَ نُصِبَتۡ» (88/19)\nTranslation: (Do they not look at) how the mountains are set firm?\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ مَا ذُبِحَ عَلَی النُّصُبِ» (5/3)\nTranslation: And that which is slaughtered at the altars (is also forbidden to you).","«نَصَب» to plant something like a flag into the ground so that part of it remains underground and part above ground.","To plant / To implant","نصب","5:3-70:43-88:19",3
2382,519,"T","اَرْسٰی","«رَسُو» means firm or solid. And «اَرْسٰی» means to embed something in the earth such that most of it is inside and a little outside. It is said that «رَسَا الْوَتْدَ فِی الْاَرْضِ» means to drive a stake into the earth or to plant it firmly (manjada), and «رَاسِیَہ» means mountain. And its plural is «رَوَاسِی». «رَاسِیْۃ» refers to such mountains that are spread over a vast area on the earth, with most of them being underground. And «رَوَاسی» means mountain range. And for the embedding of mountains, Allah has used both words «نَصَب» and «رسو».\n\nFor example, in the Quran:\n«وَ الۡجِبَالَ  اَرۡسٰہَا» (79/32)\nTranslation: And He has embedded the mountains in the (earth).\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ ہُوَ الَّذِیۡ مَدَّ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ جَعَلَ  فِیۡہَا رَوَاسِیَ وَ اَنۡہٰرًا» (13/3)\nTranslation: And He it is who has spread out the earth and placed therein mountains and rivers.","To drive in like a stake so that more of it is inside the earth and less is outside.","to bury","ارسی","13:3-15:19-16:15-21:31-27:61-31:10-34:13-41:10-50:7-77:27-79:32",11
2383,519,"T","دَسَّ","«دَسّ» means to make something lost by burying it in the soil (Quranic usage), and also means to forcibly insert one thing into another (figurative), and also means to hide something under the soil, to bury. And «دَسَّ عَلَیْہ» means to conspire, to devise a secret scheme (according to Majma' al-Bayan).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ  قَدۡ خَابَ مَنۡ  دَسّٰىہَا» ( 91/10 )\nTranslation: And he who corrupts (or stains) the soul (with evil) has failed.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«اَیُمۡسِکُہٗ عَلٰی ہُوۡنٍ اَمۡ  یَدُسُّہٗ  فِی التُّرَابِ» ( 16/59 )\nTranslation: Either (the mother) should bear the disgrace and keep the child with herself, or (the child) should be buried in the earth.","«دَسّ» to bury something underground.","to bury","دس","16:59-91:10",2
2384,519,"T","وَأَدَ","«وَأَد» means to bury a living person under the weight of soil (i.e., to bury alive). This is more specific than «دَسَّ». For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِذَا الۡمَوۡءٗدَۃُ  سُئِلَتۡ بِاَیِّ ذَنۡۢبٍ قُتِلَتۡ» (81:8). Translation: And when the girl who was buried alive is asked for what sin she was killed.","«وَأَد» to press any creature into the ground.","to plant / to implant","وأد","81:8",1
2385,520,"T","رَیْب","«رَیْب» meaning doubt and suspicion, restlessness. (See detailed explanation under doubt and suspicion). Slander, circulation. And «مَنَی» meaning to test, to afflict. Also «مَنِیَّۃ» meaning death, intention, divine decree. And the plural forms of «مَنِیَّۃ» are «مَنَایَا» and «مَنُوْن». It (i.e., «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن») is used idiomatically when a person is waiting for the adverse outcome of another. And its translation is given as the turn of events (the accidents of time).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَمۡ  یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ  شَاعِرٌ  نَّتَرَبَّصُ بِہٖ  رَیۡبَ الۡمَنُوۡنِ» (52:30)\nTranslation: Or the disbelievers say, He is a poet, and we are waiting for the turn of events concerning him.","«رَیْب» means doubt, and «رَیْبَ الْمَنُوْن» is used idiomatically when one person anticipates negative outcomes from another. Its translation is given as the cycle of time (or events of time).","Time","ریب","52:30",1
2386,520,"E","دَائِرَۃ","«دَارَ» means to revolve, to move in a circle. And «دَائِرَۃ» is used in one sense as a well-known term. In the terminology of geometry, it refers to a round and flat line (curve) whose distance from the center is equal at every point. And in meaning, it signifies the rotation of days, the vicissitudes of time, and calamities (manjad). Thus, this word is also used in a negative sense. That is, to await the descent of calamities and afflictions upon someone, and the gathering of such (events) is its «دوائر».\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ مَنۡ یَّتَّخِذُ مَا یُنۡفِقُ مَغۡرَمًا وَّ یَتَرَبَّصُ بِکُمُ الدَّوَآئِرَ ؕ عَلَیۡہِمۡ دَآئِرَۃُ  السَّوۡءِ» ( 9/98 )\nTranslation: And some of the Bedouins are such that whatever they spend, they consider it a loss, and they await the rotations of fortune for you. The rotations of fortune (i.e., calamities) will befall them.\n\nNote: (Geometry is that branch of mathematics which expresses the shape, reality, and relationships of bodies, as well as the relationships or measurements of lines and angles, and is also the knowledge of numbers and numerals.)\nNote: (That round circle on which, no matter how many straight lines you draw, they all meet it at an equal distance from the center everywhere, with no depression or elevation.)","«دَائِرَۃ» meaning to revolve, to complete a cycle, the revolutions of days and times, and their afflictions and calamities.","Era","دائرۃ","5:52-9:98-48:6",3
2387,520,"T","دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً","«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً» is used in a positive sense, opposite to the literal meaning (i.e., circulation). «دَالَ الزَّمَان» signifies moving from one state to another in terms of time. It refers to the circulation of money, prosperous times, and the anticipation thereof. After detailing the distribution of wealth and the eligible recipients, Allah the Almighty says:\n«کَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ  دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» ( 59/7 )\nTranslation: So that wealth does not continue to circulate only among those among you who are rich.\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«وَ تِلۡکَ الۡاَیَّامُ نُدَاوِلُہَا بَیۡنَ النَّاسِ» ( 3/140 )\nTranslation: And these are the days in which We alternate them among the people.","«دُوْلَۃً ، دَوْلَۃً» is used in a positive sense, as in days of prosperity.","Time","دولۃً ، دولۃً","3:140-59:7",2
2388,521,"N","عُنُق","«عُنُق» refers to the neck or throat. It is a well-known human organ. Its usage is common, and its plural is «اَعْنَاق».  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ کُلَّ  اِنۡسَانٍ اَلۡزَمۡنٰہُ طٰٓئِرَہٗ  فِیۡ عُنُقِہٖ» (17:13)  \nTranslation: And We have made every person's record of deeds hang around his neck.","«عُنُق» is a common term for the neck.","neck","عنق","8:12-13:5-17:13-17:29-26:4-34:33-36:8-38:33-40:71",9
2389,521,"N","جِیْد","«جِیْد» a slender and long neck (f.l. 110), beautiful like a deer's neck.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ فِیۡ  جِیۡدِہَا حَبۡلٌ مِّنۡ مَّسَدٍ» (111:4-5)\nTranslation: And the wife of Abu Lahab will carry firewood. A rope of palm fiber will be around her neck.","«جِیْد» long and beautiful neck.","neck","جید","111:5",1
2390,521,"N","رَقَبَۃ","«رَقَبَۃ» means the neck or the part behind it (the nape), and «رَقَبَ» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. It also signifies to supervise and guard. Moreover, Arabs generally, by uttering «جُزْءُ اشَرَف», intend the entire meaning. Similarly, 'raqabah' (slave) is understood because a noose of slavery is around his neck, and its plural is «رِقَاب» (manajid, etc.). «تَحْرِیْرُ رَقَبَۃ» means to free the neck from the noose, i.e., to free a slave.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» (90:12-13)\nTranslation: And what will make you realize what the 'ravine' is? It is the freeing of a neck (from a noose).","«رَقَبَۃ» the neck and its posterior part, the nape. The noose of slavery.","neck","رقبۃ","4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13",4
2391,521,"N","وَتِیْن","«وَتِیْن» meaning the jugular vein. The major vein that travels from the heart to the head (note 114). That side of the neck where the jugular vein is located.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَاَخَذۡنَا مِنۡہُ  بِالۡیَمِیۡنِ ثُمَّ  لَقَطَعۡنَا مِنۡہُ  الۡوَتِیۡنَ» (69/45,46)\nTranslation: We would have seized him by his right hand and then severed his jugular vein (jalaandhri).","«وَتِیْن» the front part of the neck where the jugular vein is located.","neck","وتین","69:46",1
2392,522,"S","اٰخَذَ","«اَخَذَ» meaning to seize something, to acquire, to encompass. And «اٰخَذَ» meaning to question, to seize, to catch (verbal noun), whether this accountability is by word or by action. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «رَبَّنَا لَا تُؤَاخِذۡنَاۤ  اِنۡ نَّسِیۡنَاۤ  اَوۡ اَخۡطَاۡنَا» (2/286) Translation: O our Lord! If we have committed a mistake or oversight, then do not hold us accountable.","«اٰخَذَ» to take action against, interrogate, or arrest someone for an undesirable act.","Seizure","اخذ","2:225-2:286-5:89-16:61-18:58-18:73-35:45",7
2393,522,"G","ثَرَّبَ","«ثَرَبَ» and «ثَرَّبَ» mean to declare someone's action as ugly or bad (manjada) and to warn and scold for a mistake. (Muf) (Faq l 397)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ لَا تَثۡرِیۡبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡیَوۡمَ ؕ یَغۡفِرُ اللّٰہُ  لَکُمۡ» (12/92)\nTranslation: Joseph (peace be upon him) said to his brothers, Today there will be no reproach or blame upon you. May Allah forgive you.","«تَثْرِیْب» To admonish and scold someone for their mistake. It is harsher than reproach.","Grasp of Hell","ثرب","12:92",1
2394,522,"G","لاَمَه ","«لاَمَه» means to reproach someone for committing a bad deed. (To censure, transitive). It also means to warn someone about the consequence of their action (Faqih 39). And «لَوْم» means reproach and fear (Manjad). Thus, «لَامَ» is used when the doer of an action fears that they may be reproached for it, whether the action itself is good or bad.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یُجَاہِدُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا  یَخَافُوۡنَ لَوۡمَۃَ لَآئِمٍ» (5/54)\nTranslation: That they may strive in the way of Allah and not fear the reproach of any reproacher.","«لاَمَه ، لَوْمَ» To speak ill, whether the deed is bad or not, does not carry the same severity as «تَثْرِیْب».","Grasp","لام","5:54-14:22-17:29-17:39-23:6-37:142-51:40-51:54-68:30-70:30-75:2",11
2395,523,"H","صَیْف","«صَیْف» means the summer season, and «صَیِّف» means the rain of summer and the grass that grows from it. And «صَاف» and «صَیَّف بِالْمَکَان» mean spending the summer season in a place (manjadd).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اٖلٰفِہِمۡ  رِحۡلَۃَ  الشِّتَآءِ  وَ الصَّیۡفِ» (106/2)\nTranslation: To accustom them (the Quraysh) to the journeys of winter and summer.","«صَیْف» summer season.","Heat","صیف","106:2",1
2396,523,"H","حَرّ","«حَرّ» means heat or intensity. Whether it is from fire, or from the sun i.e., sunshine, or from any other cause, such as heat generated by the friction of two things. However, this word is generally applied to the intensity of the sun's heat. And «حَرُوْر» means scorching heat. Lo (also see heat).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡا لَا تَنۡفِرُوۡا فِی الۡحَرِّ ؕ قُلۡ نَارُ جَہَنَّمَ اَشَدُّ حَرًّا» (9/81)\n\nTranslation: And they (began to) say to one another, Do not go out in the heat. Say to them, The fire of Hell is even more intensely hot!","«حَرّ» The scorching heat of the sun.","heat","حر","9:81-16:81",2
2397,523,"H","حَمَّ ۔ حُمَّي","These two words are so close in meaning that it is difficult to distinguish between them. This is why scholars of language (lexicographers) include their original etymological roots under both root words. There are four sources for the acquisition of heat. Fire and sunlight are the material sources. And the heat of emotions and bodily warmth (ghazīzī) are the spiritual ones. Both of these root words are used across these four sources. If there is any difference, it is that «حَمَّ» is used transitively and «حَمِیَ» appears intransitively. However, when the passive form is used, then they become synonymous in meaning. For example, «حَمَّ الْمَاء» means 'to heat water'. And «حُمَّ الرَّجُل» means 'a person got a fever'. And «حُمّٰی» means 'fever'. Both have been listed by lexicographers under both root words. And «حَمَّ التَّنُوْر» means 'to heat an oven'. And «حُمّٰی النَّار» means 'the fire blazed up'. And «حَمِیْم» means both 'hot water' and 'cold water' (Lexicon of Antonyms. M.R. Manjad). And also a warm-hearted friend or relative. Its connection is with emotions. And «حَمَّ الظَّھِیْرَۃ» means 'the intense heat of midday'. And «حَمَّۃ» means 'a spring of hot water'. And «حُمَّۃ» means 'a furnace, embers, or anything burning in fire'. And «حَمَام» means 'a place for bathing with hot water' (Maf. Manjad). Now observe their examples:\n\nFor instance, the Divine Command states:\n(1) «لَہُمۡ شَرَابٌ مِّنۡ حَمِیۡمٍ  وَّ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌۢ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ» (6/70)\nTranslation: For them is a drink of boiling water and a painful torment, because they used to disbelieve.\n\nSimilarly, the Divine Command states:\n(2) «وَ لَا یَسۡئَلُ  حَمِیۡمٌ حَمِیۡمًا» (70/10)\nTranslation: And no friend will ask about his friend.\n\nSimilarly, at another place, the Divine Command states:\n(3) «وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا ہِیَہۡ نَارٌ حَامِیَۃٌ» (101/10,11)\nTranslation: And what will make you realize what the Hawiyah is? It is the blazing Fire.\n\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n(4) «اِذۡ جَعَلَ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ الۡحَمِیَّۃَ حَمِیَّۃَ  الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ» (48/26)\nTranslation: When the disbelievers had put in their hearts the defiance, the defiance of the Time of Ignorance...","«حَمَّ ۔ حُمَّي» are synonymous and are used in all forms in the context of warmth and fervor.","Heat","حم ۔ حمی","6:70-10:4-22:19-26:101-37:67-38:57-40:18-40:72-41:34-44:46-44:48-47:15-48:26-55:44-56:42-56:54-56:93-69:35-70:10-78:25-88:4-101:11",22
2398,523,"H","سَقَرَ","«سَقَرَ» meaning to scorch or burn with fire or heat. «سَقَرَتْہُ الشَّمْس» meaning the sun/heat scorched it. Then this word evolved into «عَلَم» (Hell). (m.f.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ذُوۡقُوۡا مَسَّ سَقَرَ» (54/48)\nTranslation: Now taste the fire.","meaning to scorch the body with fire or the intense heat of the sun.","Heat","سقر","54:48-74:26-74:27-74:42",4
2399,523,"I","سَمُوْم","«سَمّ» denotes a narrow hole, such as the eye of a needle or the piercing of an ear or nose. It also denotes deadly poison. And «سَمُوْم» denotes a scorching wind that penetrates the body like poison.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» (52:27)\nTranslation: So Allah bestowed favor upon us and saved us from the hot punishment.","«سَمُوْم» a scorching wind that penetrates the body.","Intense heat","سموم","15:27-52:27-56:42",3
2400,523,"H","دِفْءٌ ۔ دَفِیءَ","«دَفِئَ مِنَ الْبَرْدِ» To obtain warmth from the sun, blanket, etc., meaning to become warm. To gain heat or to feel warmth. To avoid cold and to be warm. (Punjabi: to feel warm). And «دَفَّاَ» means to heat. And «اَدْفَاَ» means to wear warm clothes. And «دِفْءٌ» means both intense heat and also the means to obtain warmth. And «اَلدِّفَاءُ» means warm clothes. The means to obtain warmth. (Source: Munjid)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡاَنۡعَامَ خَلَقَہَا ۚ لَکُمۡ فِیۡہَا دِفۡءٌ  وَّ  مَنَافِعُ وَ مِنۡہَا  تَاۡکُلُوۡنَ» (16/5)\nTranslation: And He has created the cattle. In them, you have warmth and other benefits too. Then some of them you also eat.","«دِفْءٌ ، دَفِیءَ ، دَفَاَ» is used to gain warmth from warm clothes.","heat","دفء ۔ دفیء","16:5",1
2401,523,"H","اِصْطَلٰی","«صَلَی» means to enter fire. And «اَصْلٰی» and «صَلّٰی» mean to cause to enter fire. And «اِصْطَلٰی» means to obtain heat from fire. To heat (oneself). To warm and to heat the body for protection from cold.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَوۡ اٰتِیۡکُمۡ بِشِہَابٍ قَبَسٍ لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَصۡطَلُوۡنَ» (27:7)\nTranslation: Or I will bring you a burning firebrand so that you may warm yourselves.","«اِصْطَلٰی» is used to generate heat from fire.","Heat","اصطلی","27:7-28:29",2
2402,524,"P","سُقِط","«سُقِط» refers to the falling of something from a height to the ground. Its usage is general, yet an aspect of contempt is found in it. For instance, «رَجُلٌ سَاقِط» means a contemptible person (lowly). For example, the Noble Quran states: «وَ مَا تَسۡقُطُ مِنۡ وَّرَقَۃٍ  اِلَّا یَعۡلَمُہَا» (6:59). Translation: And not even a leaf falls but Allah knows it. Then, just as this word is used in a physical sense, it is also used in a spiritual sense. For example, the Almighty Lord declares: «اَلَا فِی الۡفِتۡنَۃِ سَقَطُوۡا» (9:49). Translation: Look, these people have fallen into fitnah. And «سُقِطَ فِیْ یَدِہٖ» is used metaphorically, meaning someone becomes regretful and ashamed. Only by changing the pronoun does the form change. For example, the Almighty Lord declares: «وَ لَمَّا سُقِطَ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ رَاَوۡا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ ضَلُّوۡا» (7:149). Translation: And when they became regretful and saw that they had gone astray. And for to cause to fall, «اَسْقَطَ» is used. For example, the Noble Quran states: «فَاَسۡقِطۡ عَلَیۡنَا کِسَفًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  اِنۡ  کُنۡتَ مِنَ  الصّٰدِقِیۡنَ» (26:187). Translation: If you are truthful, then bring down upon us a piece from the sky.","Falling from above.","prostrate","سقط","6:59-7:149-9:49-17:92-26:187-34:9",6
2403,524,"T","خَرَّ","«خَرَّ» refers to falling with sound and agitation (i.e., restlessness and disturbance) (example word). That is, during the fall, there is restlessness or trembling, and a sound is produced upon falling. And «خَرِیْر» means the sound of water falling or dripping (example word).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا خَرَّ تَبَیَّنَتِ الۡجِنُّ اَنۡ لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا یَعۡلَمُوۡنَ الۡغَیۡبَ مَا لَبِثُوۡا فِی الۡعَذَابِ الۡمُہِیۡنِ» (34/14)\nTranslation: Then when Solomon fell (in death), it became clear to the jinn that if they had known the unseen, they would not have remained in the torment of humiliation.","«خَرَّ» distress (i.e., restlessness) and the falling of something with a sound.","to fall","خر","7:143-22:31-34:14-38:24",4
2404,524,"T","ھَدَمَ","«ھَدَمَ» means the falling of a building or structure (M. L.). And «ھَدَّم» means to demolish a building; to raze; to tear down. «اِنْھِدَام» is a famous word that is used only in the sense of «ھَدَم».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ لَّہُدِّمَتۡ صَوَامِعُ وَ بِیَعٌ» (22/40)\nTranslation: And if Allah did not repel people by means of others, these monasteries, churches, etc. would have been demolished.","«ھَدَمَ» The collapse of a building, wall, or structure.","to fall","ھدم","22:40",1
2405,524,"P","ھَدَّ","«ھَدَّ» The collapse of a building, etc., falling to the ground with a loud crash that produces sound (m. l.) and meaning 'shudduhu al-hadam' (f. l. 47)\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«تَکَادُ السَّمٰوٰتُ یَتَفَطَّرۡنَ مِنۡہُ وَ تَنۡشَقُّ الۡاَرۡضُ وَ تَخِرُّ الۡجِبَالُ ہَدًّا» (19/90)\nTranslation: Because of this fabrication, the sky would almost burst asunder, the earth split open, and the mountains crumble into pieces and fall.","«ھَدَّ» The sudden collapse of a building, wall, or structure.","prostration","ھد","19:90",1
2406,524,"T","اِنْقَضَّ","«اِنْقَضَّ» The cracking of a building or a wall. And being on the verge of collapsing (F L 297). «قَضَّ الْحَائِط» Meaning: to cause the wall to collapse. And «اِنْقَضَّ الْحَائِط» Meaning: the wall cracked and collapsed (M. Q).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَوَجَدَا فِیۡہَا جِدَارًا یُّرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یَّنۡقَضَّ فَاَقَامَہٗ» (18/77)\nTranslation: Then they saw a wall that was about to collapse, so he (Khidr, peace be upon him) set it upright.","«اِنْقَضَّ» the cracking open and collapsing of a wall or building, or being on the verge of collapse.","to fall","انقض","2:27-4:155-5:13-8:56-13:20-13:25-16:91-16:92-18:77-94:3",10
2407,524,"T","ھَبَطَ","«ھَبَطَ» meaning to fall, to descend, to come out. In this word, the aspects of wrath (qahr) and compulsion/idtarar (restlessness and agitation) are found (intransitive). «ھَبَطَ الثَّمَن» meaning the price has fallen. «ھَبَطَ الزَّمَان» Time has made him poor from rich. «ھَبَطَ الْمَرَض» Disease has eaten his flesh and made him thin and weak (transitive and intransitive both usages are found).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہَا لَمَا یَہۡبِطُ مِنۡ خَشۡیَۃِ اللّٰہِ» (2/74)\nTranslation: And among them are some stones that fall down due to the fear of Allah.\n\nThen in «ھَبَطَ», besides wrath and compulsion, sometimes the aspect of humiliation is also found. In this context, it gives the meaning of get out.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«قُلۡنَا اہۡبِطُوۡا مِنۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا» (2/38)\nTranslation: All of you get out together from this Paradise.\n\nA poet has expressed this meaning in these words:\nTo hear of Adam's expulsion from Paradise, we came,\nBut we left your neighborhood greatly disgraced!\n\nAnd the following verse:\n«قِیۡلَ یٰنُوۡحُ اہۡبِطۡ بِسَلٰمٍ مِّنَّا» (11/48)\nTranslation: It was commanded: O Noah, descend with peace and safety.\n\nI make the word «بِسَلٰمٍ» from «ھَبِطَ» by excluding all aspects of wrath, compulsion, or humiliation, leaving only the meaning of divine decree.","«ھَبَطَ» meaning to fall, to descend, to emerge. In this word, the aspect of wrath (قہر) and compulsion (اضطرار) — implying restlessness and unease — is found.","to fall","ھبط","2:36-2:38-2:61-2:74-7:13-7:24-11:48-20:123",8
2408,524,"T","وَقَعَ","«وَقَعَ» meaning to fall, to be established, to happen. This word is generally used to denote horror, intensity, and hardship. And by 'incident' is meant an event that involves severity (muf).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ نَتَقۡنَا الۡجَبَلَ فَوۡقَہُمۡ کَاَنَّہٗ ظُلَّۃٌ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ وَاقِعٌۢ بِہِمۡ» (7/171)\nTranslation: When We raised the mountain over them as if it were a canopy, and they thought it would fall upon them.","Something falling also involves hardship and severity.","to fall","وقع","4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7",19
2409,524,"T","ھَارَ ( ھور )","«ھَارَ» means the falling of something in such a way that some part of it falls upon another (for example). And «اِنْھَار» and «اِنْھِدَام» are close in meaning. «اِنْھِدَام» is used only for buildings, construction, or walls, whereas «اِنْھَار» has a wider scope.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ فَانۡہَارَ بِہٖ فِیۡ نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ» (9/109). Translation: Or he who built a structure on the edge of a collapsing pit, and it fell along with him into the fire of Hell.","«ھَارَ» the falling of some parts of something onto another.","to fall","ھار ( ھور )","9:109",1
2410,524,"P","ھَوٰی","«ھَوَا» is a famous term. It refers to the space between the heavens and the earth. And «ھَوٰی» means to fall from a great height or from the sky. It is also used for the falling of a star (see reference 297).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ النَّجۡمِ   اِذَا ہَوٰی» (53/1)\nTranslation: By the star when it falls.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine decree states:\n«فَکَاَنَّمَا خَرَّ  مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَتَخۡطَفُہُ الطَّیۡرُ  اَوۡ تَہۡوِیۡ بِہِ الرِّیۡحُ فِیۡ مَکَانٍ  سَحِیۡقٍ» (22/31)\nTranslation: So it is as if the polytheist is like one who falls from the sky, then the birds snatch him away, or the wind carries him to a far-off place.","«ھَوٰی» falling from a great height in the sky.","Prostration","ھوی","20:81-22:31-53:1-53:53",4
2411,524,"T","خَوٰی","«خَوٰی» and «ھَوٰی» are similar in meaning. The difference is only that «ھَوَا» refers to the empty space between the earth and the sky, whereas «خَوٰی» refers to any empty space between two things. For instance, for the falling of stars, the word «ھَوَی النَّجْم» is used, and similarly «خَوٰی النَّجْم» is also used (m. l). «تَخْوِیَۃ» means to leave an empty space between two things, and «خَوٰی الدَّار» means the falling of a place that is uninhabited and desolate.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ وَّ ہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا» (2/259) Translation: Or like the person who passed by a town, which had fallen upon its roofs.","«خَوٰی» falling into the void between two things.","to fall","خوی","2:259-18:42-22:45-27:52-69:7",5
2412,524,"T","وَجَبَ","«اَلْوَجَبَۃ» means the falling of something with an explosion (minjada), and the concept of death is also inherent in it. They say «ضَرَبَہٗ فَوَجَبَ». He struck it and it died (m. q.). For example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «فَاذۡکُرُوا اسۡمَ اللّٰہِ عَلَیۡہَا صَوَآفَّ ۚ فَاِذَا وَجَبَتۡ جُنُوۡبُہَا فَکُلُوۡا مِنۡہَا وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36). Translation: Thus, when the sacrificial animals are lined up, invoke Allah's name upon them. Then, once they have fallen (after being slaughtered) with their sides on the ground, eat from them and feed the needy—both those who are patient and those who ask.","«وَجَبَ» to fall and die suddenly, or to fall with a thud while dying.","to descend","وجب","22:36",1
2413,524,"T","رَدِيَ","«رَدِيَ ،  رَدًي» means causing something to fall from a height to the ground or into a pit so that it reaches near destruction.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  ہَوٰىہُ  فَتَرۡدٰی» (20:16)  \nTranslation: And if he follows his desires, then you too will be destroyed.  \n\n«اَرْدَی الرَّجُل» means causing someone to fall into a well. And «رَدَّی الرَّجُل» means causing a person to fall, to destroy.  \nFor example: The Divine declaration states:  \n«قَالَ تَاللّٰہِ   اِنۡ  کِدۡتَّ  لَتُرۡدِیۡنِ» (37:56)  \nTranslation: He will say, By Allah, you almost destroyed me. (Jalandhari) / You were about to cast me into the pit. (Othmani)  \n\n«تَرَدّٰی» means falling into a well or pit. And «مُتَرَدِّیَۃ» refers to the animal that falls into a well or pit and dies.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«وَ مَا یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُ  مَا لُہٗۤ  اِذَا تَرَدّٰی» (92:11)  \nTranslation: And when he falls into the pit of Hell, his wealth will be of no use to him.","«رَدِيَ ، رَدًي» to fall into a pit and perish.","to descend","ردی","5:3-20:16-37:56-92:11",4
2414,524,"T","صَرَعَ","«صَرَعَ» means to fall to the ground due to panic, agitation, and restlessness (Fall 130), and also to fall to the ground due to a head injury (stroke) (Manj). And «صَرع» means a patient, having lost consciousness due to a stroke, falls to the ground with a thud. And «صَرَعَ» also means to throw and pin one's opponent to the ground in a boat. (M. Q)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی ۙ کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اَعۡجَازُ نَخۡلٍ خَاوِیَۃٍ» (69:7)\nTranslation: So you would see the people lying overthrown as if they were hollowed-out trunks of date-palms.","«صَرَعَ» to capsize or be overturned, as in a boat, or from death, or from illness.","to fall","صرع","69:7",1
2415,524,"P","تَلّ","«تَلّ» meaning to make someone fall prostrate with their forehead on the ground (F L 189).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّاۤ اَسۡلَمَا وَ تَلَّہٗ  لِلۡجَبِیۡنِ» (37/103)\nTranslation: Then when both had submitted, and Prophet Abraham had laid his son Ishmael down on his forehead.","«تَلّ» meaning forehead to the ground.","Prostration","تل","37:103",1
2416,524,"T","تَعَسَ","«تَعَسَ» means to stumble and fall, and then not be able to get up. It also means to fall and break something (figurative), and to fall flat on one's face and perish (literal). And «تَعَسَ» also means to slip and fall flat on one's face. And «اَلتَّعْسَۃ» means destruction and (annihilation).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  فَتَعۡسًا لَّہُمۡ» (47/8)\nTranslation: And for those who disbelieved, there is destruction for them.\nThey fell flat on their faces (Uthmani).","«تَعَسَ» meaning to fall flat on one's face.","to fall","تعس","47:8",1
2417,524,"T","اِدّٰرَک","«دَرْک» means the meeting of one thing with another from behind and then joining with it (m. l). «دَرْک» also refers to the depth of the sea and to the rope that is tied to another rope to reach the bottom of the water (m.f). And in this manner, reaching the extremity of something through a means is called «اَدْرَکَ». In the Quran, the divine command of Allah regarding Pharaoh states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَاۤ  اَدۡرَکَہُ الۡغَرَقُ» (10/90)\nIts meaning is that Pharaoh's intended destination or end was drowning. Thus, causes came together that led him to drowning. And this same concept is found in «اِدّٰرَک» as well.\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«بَلِ ادّٰرَکَ عِلۡمُہُمۡ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (27/66)\nTranslation: Rather, their knowledge of the Hereafter has come to an end.\nIt is as if, even after gathering and collecting all means of knowledge, they will be exhausted and defeated, biting their fingers in frustration.\nAt another place, the divine command of Allah states:\n«کُلَّمَا دَخَلَتۡ اُمَّۃٌ  لَّعَنَتۡ اُخۡتَہَا ؕ حَتّٰۤی اِذَا ادَّارَکُوۡا فِیۡہَا جَمِیۡعًا» (7/38)\nTranslation: (Thus) whenever a group enters Hell, it will curse its own kind (20) until, when they have all entered it successively, one after another.\nIt is as if the end and culmination is reaching Hell. And the continuity and connection is the coming and going of one group after another, the second after the third.","«اِدّٰرَک» worn out and helpless, collapsing.","to fall","ادرک","7:38-10:90-27:66",3
2418,524,"T","اِنْھَمَرَ","«ھَمَرَ الْمَاء» means He caused water to fall which then flowed. And «اِنْھَمَرَ الْمَاء» means water fell and flowed. (Meaning of the Quran) means the falling and flowing of water or tears.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَفَتَحۡنَاۤ  اَبۡوَابَ السَّمَآءِ  بِمَآءٍ  مُّنۡہَمِرٍ» (54/11)\nTranslation: Thus We opened the gates of the sky with water pouring forth in bursts.","«اِنْھَمَرَ» meaning the falling and flowing of water.","to fall","انھمر","54:11",1
2419,524,"T","صَبَّ ( الماء )","«صَبَّ» means to pour or send down water from above in a single instance. (Ref. Fiqh Lamekani 257) And «صَبَّ عَلَیْہِ الْبَلَاء» means to send down a calamity upon it (Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَلۡیَنۡظُرِ الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِلٰی  طَعَامِہٖۤ اَنَّا صَبَبۡنَا  الۡمَآءَ صَبًّا» (80/24,25)\n\nTranslation: So let man look at his food. Indeed, We have sent down water.","«صَبَّ» meaning to pour water, spill, or flow (flowing once at a time)","to fall","صب ( الماء )","80:25",1
2420,524,"T","سَکَبَ","«سَکَبَ الْمَاء» means to pour or fall (water). And «اَسْکَبَ» means continuous rainfall. And «اَلْاَسْکُوْب» means continuous downpour. And «مَاءٍ مَّسْکُوْبٍ» means «جَارٍ دَائِمًا» (water that is always flowing) (M. Q.). It is as if in «سَکَبَ» there is the pouring of water, etc., from above. Flowing. And continuity or permanence—three things are found.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ ظِلٍّ  مَّمۡدُوۡدٍ وَّ مَآءٍ  مَّسۡکُوۡبٍ» (56/30,31)\nTranslation: And extended shade and flowing water.","«سَکَبَ» continuous falling and flowing of water.","to fall","سکب","56:31",1
2421,525,"E","رَھَنَ","«رَھَنَ» means to keep something as security with the creditor in exchange for a loan, etc. To keep a pledge. And «رَھْن» means the thing kept as a pledge. It is common. Whether it is inanimate or living. And «رِھَانٌ» also refers to the thing kept as a condition in a contest. And also to the thing kept under a loan or general circumstances. (Example)\nFor instance: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ» ( 2/283 )\nTranslation: And if you are on a journey and cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge or possession (by way of security for the loan).\nJust as this word is used in a physical sense, it is also used in a spiritual sense.\nFor instance: The command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍۭ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ رَہِیۡنَۃٌ» ( 74/38 )\nTranslation: Every person is a pledge for their deeds.","to keep something as collateral for a loan or the like","excessive uncertainty","رھن","2:283-52:21-74:38",3
2422,525,"G","اَبْسَلَ","«اَبْسَلَ» means to hand someone over to destruction. To take as a hostage (ransom). To keep as a captive. When the thing kept as a pledge is a living being, then «اَبْسَلَ» is used, whereas «رَھَنَ» is a general term and means «اَسْلَمَہٗ لِلْھَاکَ ۔ اَبْسَلَ نَفْسَہٗ لِلْمَوْت» (lit. bond, security).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is said:\n«وَ ذَکِّرۡ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ تُبۡسَلَ نَفۡسٌۢ بِمَا کَسَبَتۡ» (6/70)\nTranslation: Continue to admonish through this (Quran) so that no one may be cast into destruction as a recompense for their deeds on the Day of Resurrection.","«اَبْسَلَ» to hand over oneself or any living being to capture and destruction (as a slave).","Gharar","ابسل","6:70",1
2423,526,"P","حُفْرَۃ","«حُفْرَۃ ، حَفِیرَۃ» means a pit. «حَفَرَ» means to dig a pit. And «حَفْر» means the soil dug out from a pit, and «مِحْفَر» is the tool with which a pit is dug (a spade), for example.  \n«مَرْدُوْدٌ فِیْ الْحَافِرَۃ» is used in the proverb: He reached the very spot where the clay was.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی شَفَا حُفۡرَۃٍ مِّنَ النَّارِ فَاَنۡقَذَکُمۡ مِّنۡہَا» (3/103)  \nTranslation: And you were on the edge of the pit of Fire, and He saved you from it.","«حُفْرَۃ» meaning pit. A common word.","Pit of Hell","حفرۃ","3:103",1
2424,526,"P","جُرُف","«جُرُف» The bank of a river or stream that has been hollowed out by water from within (i.e., a cavity or hollow) — the Punjabi word *mun* or *muni* accurately conveys this meaning.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اَمۡ مَّنۡ اَسَّسَ بُنۡیَانَہٗ عَلٰی شَفَا جُرُفٍ ہَارٍ» (9/109)  \nTranslation: Or [it is] like the one who built his building on the edge of a precipice (a hollowed-out bank).","«جُرُف» An undercut bank, i.e., the bank of a river, stream, or sea that has been hollowed out by water washing away soil from below.","Pit of Hell","جرف","9:109",1
2425,526,"T","اُخْدُوْد","«اَلْخَدّ و اُخْدُوْد» denotes a long, deep, and square-shaped trench in the earth. Its plural form is «اَخَادِیْد» (mufrad), and «اَلْخَدّ» means a water canal, a long trench, and «اَلْخَدَّۃ وَ الْاُخْدُوْد» means a trench (manjad), i.e., «اُخْدُوْد» refers to a long, deep, and rectangular (i.e., square-shaped) trench that has been dug out. Trench. Ditch.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُتِلَ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡاُخۡدُوۡدِ» (85/4)\nTranslation: Those who dig the trenches (have been destroyed).\n\n(The word akhdūd is singular according to Ṣāḥib al-Munjad, whereas Jalandhari has translated it in the plural form.)","«اُخْدُوْد» a long, deep, self-dug trench or pit.","The Pit","اخدود","85:4",1
2426,526,"H","غَائِط","«غَوْط» means low ground, and «غَاطَ الْحُفْرَۃ» means to dig a pit. And «غَوَّطَ الْبِئْر» means to dig a well deep. And «اَلْغَائِط» means low ground. The place for relieving oneself (qaza-e-hajjat). The footrest (manjad) and this is a metaphor indicating that a modest person seeks a deep place for urination (m. q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَوۡ جَآءَ اَحَدٌ مِّنۡکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡغَآئِطِ» (4/43) (5/6)\nTranslation: Or any of you who has come from the place of relieving himself.","«غَائِط» Low ground, metaphorically, denotes a place for fulfilling necessities.","Hellfire","غائط","4:43-5:6",2
2427,527,"T","سَبَقَ","«سَبَقَ» means to leave others behind and move ahead, to surpass (sing./pl.). Indeed, «سَبَقَ» necessarily implies having one's masebooq (i.e., those who remain behind).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«رَبَّنَا  اغۡفِرۡ لَنَا وَ لِاِخۡوَانِنَا  الَّذِیۡنَ سَبَقُوۡنَا بِالۡاِیۡمَانِ» (59/10)\nTranslation: O our Lord! Forgive us our sins and the sins of our brothers who have preceded us in faith.\n\nAnd when it occurs in the sense of passing away, its meaning becomes to pass before. That is, many things have passed or occurred even after it.\n\nFor example: The Divine declaration states:\n«کَذٰلِکَ نَقُصُّ عَلَیۡکَ مِنۡ اَنۡۢبَآءِ مَا قَدۡ سَبَقَ» (20/99)\nTranslation: Thus, We relate to you some news of the events that have passed before.","«سَبَقَ» meaning to move ahead, leaving others behind.","to elapse","سبق","7:80-8:59-8:68-10:19-11:40-11:110-15:5-20:99-20:199-21:27-21:101-23:27-23:43-29:4-29:28-37:171-41:45-42:14-46:11-59:10-79:4",21
2428,527,"T","خَلَا","«خَلَا» means to be empty. It is the separation of one thing from another (as in the dictionary). It signifies passing through a state where no resistance is offered, applicable to both time and space (as in the usage). And «خَلّٰی» means to empty or vacate something.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ تَابُوۡا وَ اَقَامُوا الصَّلٰوۃَ وَ اٰتَوُا الزَّکٰوۃَ فَخَلُّوۡا سَبِیۡلَہُمۡ» ( 9/5 )\nTranslation: But if they repent, establish prayer, and give Zakat, then leave their way clear.\nMeaning: Clear their path. Move away from the path and let them go, or leave the path and do not oppose them. And «خَلَاء» refers to an empty house, and also to the empty space between the earth and the sky. Thus, in «خَلَا», the concept of a place or time becoming empty is also found alongside the idea of something passing through.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«تِلۡکَ اُمَّۃٌ  قَدۡ خَلَتۡ ۚ لَہَا مَا کَسَبَتۡ» ( 2/141 )\nTranslation: They were a community who passed away; for them is what they earned, and for you is what you have earned.","«خَلَا» meaning to be empty, to be distinct from one thing to another. Passing through a state where no resistance was encountered.","to pass","خلا","2:134-2:141-3:137-3:144-5:75-7:38-13:6-13:30-15:13-40:85-41:25-46:17-46:18-46:21-48:23",15
2429,527,"T","سَلَفَ","«سَلَفَ» means to advance. And «سَلَفَ الْقَوْم» means to surpass one's people (manjid). And «سَلْف» means preceding, i.e., one who has passed before (muf). And its opposite is «خَلْف». And the plural is «اَسْلَاف», meaning pious ancestors who have passed on. And «سَلَفِی» is the person who desires to be connected to them. And «خَلْف» means subsequent, i.e., unworthy successors who come after. Thus, when «سَلَفَ» is used in the sense of to pass away, it conveys the concept of later generations or similar events that follow.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَنۡ تَجۡمَعُوۡا بَیۡنَ الۡاُخۡتَیۡنِ اِلَّا مَا قَدۡ سَلَفَ» (4/23)\nTranslation: And that you take two sisters together in marriage (this is also forbidden for you) except those who have passed before.","When «سَلَفَ» is used in the sense of passing, it encompasses the concept of subsequent generations or similar events that follow.","To pass","سلف","2:275-4:22-4:23-5:95-8:38-10:30-43:56-69:24",8
2430,527,"T","مَرَّ","«مَرَّ» means to pass by something (figurative).  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ» (2:259)  \nTranslation: Or like the man who passed by a town.  \n\nAnd «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to pass by, to remain in a state or manner, to persist (Manjada).  \nAnd «مَرُوْر اَیَّام» means the passing of days.  \nMoreover, «مَرَّ» also appears in the Quran with the meanings of «اِسْتَمَرَّ».  \n\nFor instance, Allah, the Most High, says:  \n«حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا فَمَرَّتۡ بِہٖ» (7:189)  \nTranslation: Then its burden became light for her, and she moved about with it.  \n\nIn another instance, Allah, the Most High, says:  \n«وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54:2)  \nTranslation: And when the disbelievers see a sign, they turn away and say, This is just magic that has been continuing from old times.  \n\nSimilarly, in another instance, Allah, the Most High, says:  \n«یَمُرُّوۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا» (12:105)  \nTranslation: Meaning, their passing over those towns continues.  \n\nThus, it is evident that in «مَرَّ», the meaning of continuity (i.e., ongoing, uninterrupted) is also present.","«مَرَّ» meaning to pass by something.","to pass away","مر","2:259-7:189-10:12-11:38-12:105-25:72-27:88-37:137-83:30",9
2431,527,"T","مَضٰی","«مَضٰی» means to pass away and to move on (lexical), and the opposite of «مَضٰی» is «اِسْتَقْبَلَ», meaning to come from the front. And «مَضٰی» also means to depart from the front and to penetrate (Fiqh 252). And in the past tense, it means a time that has passed, and its opposite is the future, meaning the time to come. It is used for both incidents (i.e., something new or a thing) or an event (lexical). Whether it is a matter or an occurrence (lexical). And «مَضٰی عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to persist in doing something (as in Munjid).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّعُوۡدُوۡا فَقَدۡ مَضَتۡ سُنَّتُ  الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ» (8/38)\nTranslation: And if these people adopt similar actions, then the way of those who have passed before will be adopted with them.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ اَوۡ اَمۡضِیَ حُقُبًا» (18/60)\nTranslation: Until I reach the confluence of the two rivers or continue traveling for years on end.","«مَضٰی» denotes the accomplishment of a task in bygone eras.","to pass","مضی","8:38-15:65-18:60-36:67-43:8",5
2432,527,"T","اِنْسَلَخَ","«سَلَخَ» means to skin. And «سَلَخَ» and «اِنْسَلَخَ الشَّھْر» mean to become the last day of a lunar month. For example, the Quran states: «فَاِذَا انۡسَلَخَ الۡاَشۡہُرُ الۡحُرُمُ» (9:5). Translation: Then when the sacred months have passed.","the passing of any lunar month «اِنْسَلَخَ»","to pass","انسلخ","7:175-9:5",2
2433,528,"T","حُلْقُوْم","«حُلْقُوْم» means throat—the place where an animal is slaughtered (a well-known organ). There is no difference in meaning between «حُلْقُوْم» and «حَلَق». For example, the Quran states: «فَلَوۡ لَاۤ   اِذَا  بَلَغَتِ  الۡحُلۡقُوۡمَ» (56/83)  \nTranslation: Then why is it not that when the soul reaches the throat?","«حُلْقُوْم» meaning throat; the place where an animal is slaughtered.","throat","حلقوم","56:83",1
2434,528,"T","حَنَاجِر","«حَنَاجِر» is the plural of «حَنْجَرَہ», meaning the windpipe. Narakhara (Manjad). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ بَلَغَتِ الۡقُلُوۡبُ الۡحَنَاجِرَ وَ تَظُنُّوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ  الظُّنُوۡنَا» (33/10) Translation: And the hearts reached up to the throats, and you began to think various thoughts about Allah.","«حَنَاجِر» meaning windpipe. trachea.\nAnd «حَنْجَرَہ» in medical science, the part related to the food pipe in the throat is called the pharynx, and the part related to the windpipe is called the larynx.","Throat","حناجر","33:10-40:18",2
2435,529,"L","فَاتَ","«فَاتَ» the slipping away of something from one's hand  \n«فَاتَ الْاَمْر» meaning the time for action has slipped away and cannot return (m. q.)  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «لِّکَیۡلَا تَاۡسَوۡا عَلٰی مَا فَاتَکُمۡ وَ لَا تَفۡرَحُوۡا بِمَاۤ  اٰتٰىکُمۡ» (57/23) Translation: so that you do not grieve over what has escaped you, nor exult over what He has granted you.","«فَاتَ» to let an opportunity slip through one's fingers; to lose all hope of obtaining something.","Lost","فات","3:153-57:23-60:11",3
2436,529,"L","فَقَدَ","«فَقَدَ» The temporary non-availability of something; its non-existence (m. l.), even if it is found later. And it means that despite something existing, it is not found. And this is more specific than «عَدَم» (muf).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا وَ اَقۡبَلُوۡا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  مَّا ذَا  تَفۡقِدُوۡنَ» (12/71)\nTranslation: They turned towards them and said, What is it that you have lost?\n\nAnd the meaning of «تَفَقَّدَ» is to investigate whether something is lost. In the words of Imam Raghib, it is to ascertain that something is lost (muf); the search for a lost thing (minjadd).\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ تَفَقَّدَ الطَّیۡرَ فَقَالَ مَا لِیَ  لَاۤ  اَرَی الۡہُدۡہُدَ» (27/20)\nTranslation: And when Solomon reviewed the birds, he said, Why do I not see the hoopoe?","«فَقَدَ» being temporarily unavailable when needed, despite existing.","Lost","فقد","12:71-12:72",2
2437,529,"L","ضَلَّ","The word «ضَلَّ» originally comes to mean losing one's way or becoming lost, but sometimes it also conveys the meaning of a thing ceasing to exist by merging into something else.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it says:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤا ءَ اِذَا ضَلَلۡنَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ ءَ اِنَّا لَفِیۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (32/10)\n\nTranslation: And the disbelievers say, When we are lost in the earth, will we then be created anew?","The basic meaning of «ضَلَّ» is to lose one's way or to cause someone to go astray.","Lost","ضل","1:7-2:16-2:26-2:108-2:175-2:198-2:282-3:69-3:90-3:164-4:44-4:60-4:88-4:113-4:116-4:119-4:136-4:143-4:167-4:176-5:12-5:60-5:77-5:105-6:24-6:39-6:56-6:74-6:77-6:94-6:116-6:117-6:119-6:125-6:140-6:144-7:30-7:37-7:38-7:53-7:60-7:61-7:149-7:155-7:178-7:179-7:186-9:37-9:115-10:30-10:32-10:88-10:108-11:21-12:8-12:30-12:95-13:14-13:27-13:33-14:3-14:18-14:27-14:30-14:36-15:56-16:25-16:36-16:37-16:87-16:93-16:125-17:15-17:67-17:72-17:97-18:17-18:51-18:104-19:38-19:75-20:52-20:79-20:85-20:92-20:123-21:54-22:4-22:9-22:12-23:106-25:17-25:29-25:34-25:42-25:44-26:20-26:86-26:97-26:99-27:81-27:92-28:15-28:50-28:75-28:85-30:29-30:53-31:6-31:11-32:10-33:36-33:67-34:8-34:24-34:50-35:8-36:24-36:47-36:62-37:69-37:71-38:26-39:8-39:22-39:23-39:36-39:37-39:41-40:25-40:33-40:34-40:50-40:74-41:29-41:48-41:52-42:18-42:44-42:46-43:40-45:23-46:5-46:28-46:32-50:27-53:2-53:30-54:24-54:47-56:51-56:92-60:1-62:2-67:9-67:29-68:7-68:26-71:24-71:27-74:31-83:32-93:7",163
2438,530,"B","ظَنَّ","The conclusion derived from the signs of something is called «ظَنّ». If the signs are strong, «ظَنّ» conveys the meanings of knowledge and certainty. In this case, the words «اَنَّ» or «اَنْ» precede this term. (Example) Please observe the following examples:\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n(1) «الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ» (2/46)\nTranslation: Those who are certain that they will meet their Lord.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n(2) «وَّ  ظَنَّ  اَنَّہُ  الۡفِرَاقُ» (75/28)\nTranslation: And the dying person will be certain that this is the time of his departure.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states:\n(3) «بَلۡ ظَنَنۡتُمۡ  اَنۡ  لَّنۡ یَّنۡقَلِبَ الرَّسُوۡلُ» (48/12)\nTranslation: And you assumed that the Messenger would never return.\n\nAnd when the meaning of «ظَنّ» remains merely within the limits of conjecture and doubt, then «اِنّ» or «اِنْ» precede it. And its second sign is that in contrast to 'conjecture' (ظن), there exists a word as a sign that changes the meaning of conjecture to that of suspicion and doubt. (Example) Now observe their examples:\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n(1) «اِنَّ الظَّنَّ  لَا یُغۡنِیۡ مِنَ الۡحَقِّ شَیۡئًا» (53/28)\nTranslation: Indeed, conjecture avails nothing against the truth.\n\nIn this example, both 'truth' in contrast to «اِنَّ» and «ظَنّ» are generating the meanings of conjecture and doubt.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command states:\n(2) «اِنۡ  نَّظُنُّ   اِلَّا ظَنًّا وَّ مَا نَحۡنُ  بِمُسۡتَیۡقِنِیۡنَ» (45/32)\nTranslation: We only consider it as mere conjecture, and we are not certain about it.\n\nIn this example, the words of certainty in contrast to «اِنْ» and conjecture are generating the meanings of conjecture and doubt.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the Divine Command states:\n(3) «الظَّآنِّیۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ  ظَنَّ السَّوۡءِ» (48/6)\nTranslation: Those who harbor evil thoughts about Allah.\n\nIn this example, «ظَنَّ السَّوْء» in contrast to «ظَنّ» is specifically assigning the meanings of conjecture and doubt to it.\n\nThen between conjecture and certainty, there are also degrees of doubt and predominant supposition. And the word «ظَنّ» is used in all these meanings. (Example)","The scope of «ظَنَّ» is vast, and it applies to all kinds of thoughts and assumptions—including conjecture, suspicion, dominance, and certainty.","Baseless assumption","ظن","2:46-2:78-2:230-2:249-3:154-4:157-6:116-6:148-7:66-7:171-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:36-10:60-10:66-11:27-12:42-12:110-17:52-17:101-17:102-18:35-18:35-18:36-18:53-21:87-22:15-24:12-26:186-28:38-28:39-33:10-34:20-37:87-38:24-38:27-40:37-41:22-41:23-41:48-41:50-45:24-45:32-48:6-48:12-49:12-53:23-53:28-59:2-69:20-72:5-72:7-72:12-75:25-75:28-83:4-84:14",58
2439,530,"C","زَعَمَ","«زَعَمَ» is used for false conjecture (i.e., baseless suspicion and delusion). In the words of Ibn al-Faris, «اَلْقَوْلُ مِنْ غَیْرِ صِحَّۃٍ وَّلَا یَقِیْنٍ» (m. l) means a matter that is neither certain nor correct. In the Quran, wherever this word appears, it is solely to condemn the one who conjectures.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«زَعَمَ  الَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡۤا اَنۡ  لَّنۡ یُّبۡعَثُوۡا» (64/7)\nTranslation: The disbelievers suppose that they will never be resurrected.","«زَعَمَ» is used for false conjecture (i.e., baseless fancies and thoughts).","Conjecture","زعم","4:60-6:22-6:94-6:136-6:138-17:56-17:92-18:48-18:52-28:62-28:74-34:22-62:6-64:7",14
2440,530,"C","حَسِبَ","«حَسَب» means to calculate, count, or enumerate. «حَسُبَ» means to be honorable or respected. And «حَسِبَ» means to assume or think. This term is used for a supposition to which the heart clings with hope, even though it is not granted the status of certainty. Such a supposition is predominant.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبۡتُمۡ  اَنۡ تَدۡخُلُوا الۡجَنَّۃَ وَ لَمَّا یَاۡتِکُمۡ مَّثَلُ الَّذِیۡنَ خَلَوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِکُمۡ» (2/214)\nTranslation: Do you think that you will enter Paradise just like that, and that you will not be tested with the kind of difficulties that came to those before you?","«حَسِبَ» arises from a conjecture about which the one who conjectures is hopeful.","Conjecture","حسب","2:214-2:273-3:78-3:142-3:169-3:178-3:180-3:188-5:71-7:30-8:59-9:16-14:42-14:47-18:9-18:18-18:102-18:104-23:55-23:115-24:11-24:15-24:39-24:57-25:44-27:44-27:88-29:2-29:4-33:20-43:37-43:80-45:21-47:29-58:18-59:14-63:4-75:3-75:36-76:19-90:5-90:7-104:3",43
2441,531,"S","ذَنْب","«ذَنْب» refers to any action whose consequence is bad (lexical), and it also carries the meaning of what follows blame (jurisprudential 193). Its application is so general that it can apply to everything from minor slips to the greatest of sins. And its plural is «ذُنُوب».\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا فَتَحۡنَا لَکَ فَتۡحًا مُّبِیۡنًا لِّیَغۡفِرَ  لَکَ اللّٰہُ  مَا تَقَدَّمَ مِنۡ ذَنۡۢبِکَ وَ مَا تَاَخَّرَ» (48:1,2)\nTranslation: O Muhammad! We have granted you a clear victory so that Allah may forgive your past and future sins.\n\nAnd it is evident that these sins could only be the ijtihadi errors of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ; otherwise, a Muslim would not even conceptually attribute the occurrence of even the smallest sin to him intentionally.\n\nAs in another place, the Divine Command states:\n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ» (9:43)\nTranslation: May Allah forgive you! Why did you grant permission to the hypocrites?\n\nAnd even the greatest of sins—unjust killing—has the term «ذَنْب» applied to it.\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَہُمۡ عَلَیَّ  ذَنۡۢبٌ فَاَخَافُ اَنۡ یَّقۡتُلُوۡنِ» (20:14)\nTranslation: (Prophet Musa ﷺ says to Allah:) I have a sin (of killing) upon me, and I fear that they will kill me.","«ذَنْب» is commonly recited for all sins, whether minor or major.","Sin","ذنب","12:29-26:14-29:40-40:3-40:55-47:19-48:2-55:39-67:11-81:9-91:14",11
2442,531,"S","خَطَا","A sin whose commission a person does not intend, but occurs by chance or error. For example, a hunter aimed an arrow at game but it accidentally struck a person, causing their death. Such an error, if it is liable to a prescribed punishment or punishable, has its penalty reduced, and it is called «خِطْأ» or «خَطْأ». And if it is of another type, then Allah forgives in exchange for repentance and good deeds, and it is called «خَطَاء». Its plural is «خَطَایَا». And the plural of «خَطِیْءَ» is «خَطِیْئَات». And it is also used in the same sense.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ قَتَلَ مُؤۡمِنًا خَطَئًا فَتَحۡرِیۡرُ رَقَبَۃٍ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٍ وَّ دِیَۃٌ مُّسَلَّمَۃٌ اِلٰۤی اَہۡلِہٖۤ  اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ یَّصَّدَّقُوۡا» (4/92)\nTranslation: And whoever kills a believer by error should free a believing slave and pay blood money to the victim's heirs unless they remit it as charity.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n« وَّ ادۡخُلُوا الۡبَابَ سُجَّدًا وَّ قُوۡلُوۡا حِطَّۃٌ نَّغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ خَطٰیٰکُمۡ» (2/58)\nTranslation: And enter the gate humbly and say, 'O Allah, we seek Your forgiveness,' so We will forgive your errors.","«خَطَا» a sin that is committed unintentionally.","sin","خطا","2:58-2:81-2:286-4:92-4:112-7:161-17:31-20:73-26:51-26:82-29:12-33:5-71:25",13
2443,531,"S","حُوْب","«اَلْحُوْبَۃ» are terms used for mother, father, sister, and daughter. «اِنَّ لِیْ حُوْبَۃٌ اَعْوَلُھَا» means my dependents whom I support (manjīd). And «حَوْب» refers to the disobedience of children towards their parents or the parents' negligence in showing compassion and upbringing towards their children (m. l.). According to Imam Raghīb, «حُوْب» denotes the commission of acts from which one has been strictly prohibited (muf). Fundamentally, «حُوْب» means reprimand. And «حُوْب» is every sin for which the perpetrator deserves scolding and admonition (faq l 193).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَاۡکُلُوۡۤا اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ  اِلٰۤی اَمۡوَالِکُمۡ ؕ اِنَّہٗ کَانَ حُوۡبًا کَبِیۡرًا» (4/2)\nTranslation: And do not consume the orphans' wealth by mixing it with your own, for that is a great sin.","«حُوْب» major sins associated with gambling and family matters.","Sin","حوب","4:2",1
2444,531,"S","حِنْث","«حِنْث» means a false and untrue oath, sin and disobedience (m.f.), and «حَنَثَ فِی الْیَمِیْن» means to violate an oath (m.l.), and «حَنِثَ» means to incline towards falsehood, to be biased (manj). Thus, «حِنْث» refers to a sin related to breaking a covenant or oath. For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَانُوۡا یُصِرُّوۡنَ عَلَی الۡحِنۡثِ الۡعَظِیۡمِ» (56/46)\nTranslation: And they used to persist in a great sin.","«حِنْث» meaning the breaking of an oath. A major sin related to covenants and pledges.","sin","حنث","38:44-56:46",2
2445,531,"S","اِثْم","«اِثْم» refers to every action that hinders or obstructs the cause of goodness or reward (Mafatih al-Ghayb). Its plural is «اٰثَام». Its opposite is «بِرّ», meaning goodness. Furthermore, the lexical meaning of «اِثْم» is negligence (i.e., fault and error) (Fath al-Qadir 193).\n\nFor example, the Prophetic Hadith states: «اَلْبِرُّ مَا اطْمَاَنَّتْ اِلَیْہِ النَّفْسُ وَ الْاِثْمُ مَا حَاکَ فِیْ صَدْرِکَ»\nTranslation: That is, goodness is that which brings contentment to the heart, and «اِثْم», meaning sin, is that which causes unease in your heart.\n\nThus, «اِثْم» is the name for a state wherein a person's heart holds back from performing good deeds but inclines toward sinful ones, and when an opportunity arises, they do not refrain from that sin. That is, «اِثْم» relates more to the heart than to the action. A person in such a state is called «اَثِیْم», the opposite of whom is «سَلِیْم».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی ۪ وَ لَا تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ» (5:2)\nTranslation: And cooperate in righteousness and piety, but do not cooperate in sin and transgression.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«وَ لَا تَکۡتُمُوا الشَّہَادَۃَ ؕ وَ مَنۡ یَّکۡتُمۡہَا فَاِنَّہٗۤ اٰثِمٌ قَلۡبُہٗ» (2:283)\nTranslation: And do not conceal testimony. And whoever conceals it—then indeed, his heart is sinful.","«اِثْم» To remain naturally predisposed toward sin and not to refrain from committing it when the time comes.","sin","اثم","2:283-5:106-76:24",3
2446,531,"S","اِجْرَام","«جُرْم» is only considered [a crime] for which a punishment is prescribed by law. However, this is neither valid according to the Quran nor according to the language. «جُرْم ۔ جَرِیْمَۃ» means 'to be a major sinner.' And «اَجْرَمَ» means 'to be a criminal, to commit a crime.' And «اِجْرَام» means 'the consequence of sin' (manjad). The fundamental meaning of «جُرْم» is «القطع». And «جُرْم» is every act through which an obligatory command is not fulfilled or the obligatory is not performed; «جُرْم» is (Fiqh 93).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ  اِنِ افۡتَرَیۡتُہٗ فَعَلَیَّ  اِجۡرَامِیۡ وَ اَنَا بَرِیۡٓءٌ  مِّمَّا تُجۡرِمُوۡنَ» (11/35)\nTranslation: (O Prophet) say, If I have fabricated it, then its consequence is upon me, and whatever crime you are committing, I am not responsible for it.","«اِجْرَام» meaning the consequence of a major sin.","Sin","اجرام","11:35",1
2447,531,"S","جُنَاح","The meaning of «جُنَاح» is essentially not sin, but rather inclination or leaning towards sin. «جَنَحَ» means to incline, to be prone. (cited) It appears frequently in the Quran. «لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیْکُمْ ،» or «لَیْسَ عَلَیْکُمْ جُنَاحٌ» mean there is no blame, no grounds for reproach or accountability, etc. For example: In the Quran, it is: «لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ مَا لَمۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ» (2/236) Translation: For those women whom you have not touched, there is no blame upon you in divorcing them. And «جَنَاح» (meaning arm, on, side) this is used for inclination towards good. For example: The divine command states: «وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24) Translation: And lower to them both (parents) the wing of humility out of tenderness and need. At another instance, the divine command states: «وَ اخۡفِضۡ جَنَاحَکَ لِمَنِ اتَّبَعَکَ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (26/215) Translation: And for those believing men who follow you, lower the wing of your compassion with humility for them.","The meaning of «جُنَاح» is actually not sin, but rather an inclination toward sin.","sin","جناح","2:158-2:198-2:229-2:230-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:282-4:23-4:24-4:101-4:102-4:128-5:93-24:29-24:58-24:60-24:61-33:5-33:51-33:55-60:10",24
2448,531,"S","لَمَمْ","«لَمَمْ» refers to minor sins that lead one toward a major sin, and those who assist in such acts. «اَلَمَّ» refers to the commission of minor sins (such as visiting a non-mahram woman or engaging in free mixing with her before committing adultery, or conspiring and planning before theft). All these examples fall under the definition of 'minor sins'.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«اَلَّذِیۡنَ یَجۡتَنِبُوۡنَ کَبٰٓئِرَ الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡفَوَاحِشَ  اِلَّا اللَّمَمَ ؕ اِنَّ  رَبَّکَ وَاسِعُ  الۡمَغۡفِرَۃِ» (53/32)\nTranslation: Those who avoid great sins and shameful deeds, except for minor lapses—surely your Lord is vast in forgiveness, Most Merciful.","Minor sins that lead to major sins.","Sin","لمم","53:32",1
2449,532,"S","اٰثِمْ ، اَثِیْم ، خَاطِی","«اٰثِمْ» one who occasionally commits sinful acts.\n«اَثِیم» whose nature remains disposed toward committing sins at all times.\n«خَاطِیْ» a sinner who commits sin due to forgetfulness or error.\n«مُجْرِمْ» the perpetrator of a major sin. And the explanation of «مُجْرِم» has been elaborated upon in the context of sin.","«اٰثِمْ» One who occasionally commits sinful acts.\n«اَثِیم» One whose nature is always inclined to commit sins.\n«خَاطِیْ» A sinner who commits a sin out of forgetfulness or error.\n«مُجْرِمْ» One who commits a major sin.","Sinner","اثم ، اثیم ، خاطی","2:276-4:107-12:29-12:91-12:97-26:222-28:8-44:44-45:7-52:23-26:25-68:12-69:9-69:37-83:12-96:16",16
2450,532,"S","فَاسِق","«فَسَقَ» signifies deviating from the path of truth and rectitude, being wicked, stepping out of obedience (m. l), and not adhering to Shariah commands (muf).  \nThe word «فَاسِقٌ» is used for a habitual disobedient person—wicked. However, such an individual certainly considers sinful acts as both sin and disobedience.  \nFor example, the Quran states: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اِنۡ جَآءَکُمۡ فَاسِقٌۢ بِنَبَاٍ فَتَبَیَّنُوۡۤا» (49:6). Translation: O believers! If a wicked person brings you any news, then verify it.","«فَاسِق» There must be such a disobedient or sinner who regards sin as permissible.","Sinner","فاسق","2:26-2:99-3:82-3:110-5:25-5:26-5:47-5:49-5:59-5:81-5:108-7:102-7:145-9:8-9:24-9:53-9:67-9:80-9:84-9:96-21:74-24:4-24:55-27:12-28:32-32:18-43:54-46:35-49:6-51:46-57:16-57:26-57:27-59:5-59:19-61:5-63:6",37
2451,532,"S","فَاجِر","The plural of «فَاجِرْ» is «فُجَّار», and its opposite is «اَبْرَار». «فَجَرَ» means to tear something apart extensively. And «فَاجِر» means the concealment of religion and disobedience; a wicked person, an evil-doer who commits sins and does not repent (such an individual). And fajoor means being engrossed in sins; a fornicator (persistent). And «فَجَرَ» means to be stubborn; to become obstinate. And fajir is such a sinner who does not even regard sin as sin; immoral.\n\nFor example, in the Quran: «کَلَّاۤ  اِنَّ  کِتٰبَ الۡفُجَّارِ لَفِیۡ  سِجِّیۡنٍ» (83/7) Translation: Indeed, the record of the wicked is in Sijjin.","«فَاجِرْ» A sinner and wicked person who has become hardened and does not even regard sin as sin.","Sinner","فاجر","38:28-71:27-82:14-83:7",4
2452,533,"I","تَفَث","«تَفِثَ» means the accumulation of dirt/impurity on something. And «قَضٰی تَفِثَ» means to remove such dirt/impurity (mansaj). Abu Ubaidah says that it refers to cutting nails, trimming lips, applying perfume. Its application is for all things prohibited during Ihram except marriage (m. l.). It signifies bodily cleanliness, which includes cutting nails, shaving excess hair, bathing to cleanse off dirt, and then wearing clean clothes and applying perfume—all of which are encompassed by «قَضٰی تَفِثَ».\n\nFor instance, the Quran states: «ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ وَ لۡیَطَّوَّفُوۡا بِالۡبَیۡتِ الۡعَتِیۡقِ» (22/29). Translation: Then (the pilgrims, after the sacrifice) they should remove their dirt/impurity, fulfill their vows, and circumambulate the ancient House (Baytullah).","The body's ritual impurity.","impurity","تفث","22:29",1
2453,533,"U","رِجْز","«رَجَزَ» means to cause anxiety (uneasiness). And «رَجَزَ فُلَانٌ» means he recited poetry in the meter of *rajaz*. And *rajzi* verses are those recited during battle to incite fighting. And in «عَذَابٌ مِّنْ رِجْزٍ اَلِیْم», *rajaz* means that which causes anxiety (uneasiness) to be bestowed. And «رِجْز» refers to those satanic whispers which continuously generate anxiety (uneasiness) and evil desires in the heart (ref. *Munjid*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ یُغَشِّیۡکُمُ النُّعَاسَ اَمَنَۃً مِّنۡہُ وَ یُنَزِّلُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً  لِّیُطَہِّرَکُمۡ بِہٖ وَ یُذۡہِبَ عَنۡکُمۡ رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» (8/11)\nTranslation: When He (i.e., Allah) enveloped you in drowsiness from Himself as a security (or comfort), and sent down water upon you from the sky to purify you thereby and remove from you the impurity of Satan.\n\nHere, «رِجۡزَ الشَّیۡطٰنِ» refers to those satanic whispers which could have arisen in hearts in the event of defeat at the Battle of Badr.\n\n«رُجْز : رِجْز» is essentially the same word (*munjad*), and it carries the same connection (relation) that exists between «حَمْل» and «حِمْل» or «وَقْر» and «وِقْر» (for details, see *Bawjh*). This word is applied to all those satanic whispers that exist in the heart, whether they pertain to worship of other than Allah or to evil thoughts.\n\nFor example: The Command of Allah, the Exalted, states:\n«وَ  ثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ وَ الرُّجۡزَ  فَاہۡجُرۡ» (74/4,5)\nTranslation: And keep your garments clean. And avoid all impurity.","«رِجْز» Disturbing satanic whispers.","Uncleanliness","رجز","8:11-74:5",2
2454,533,"F","رِجْس","«رِجْس» refers to the impurity of such things that Shariah has declared filthy (impure) or forbidden (reprehensible). It is used in both material and spiritual senses.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنَ مَیۡتَۃً اَوۡ دَمًا مَّسۡفُوۡحًا اَوۡ لَحۡمَ  خِنۡزِیۡرٍ فَاِنَّہٗ رِجۡسٌ» (6/145)  \nTranslation: Except for that which is dead, or flowing blood, or the flesh of swine—for all that is impure.  \n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:  \n«وَ اَمَّا الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ فَزَادَتۡہُمۡ رِجۡسًا اِلٰی رِجۡسِہِمۡ» (9/125)  \nTranslation: And for those whose hearts are diseased, impurity has been added to their impurity.  \n\nHere, «رِجْس» signifies the impurity of disbelief and polytheism. This is the spiritual application of «رِجْس». (Also see “impure.”)","The «رِجْس» of forbidden and filthy things.","filth","رجس","5:90-6:125-6:145-7:71-9:95-9:125-10:100-22:30-33:33",9
2455,534,"T","عَدّ","«عَدَد» means to count, to enumerate, to number. It is a well-known word and its usage is widespread. 'Adad means enumeration, numeral.  \nFor example: In the Quran: «فَضَرَبۡنَا عَلٰۤی اٰذَانِہِمۡ فِی الۡکَہۡفِ سِنِیۡنَ عَدَدًا» (18:11).  \nTranslation: So We placed a veil over their ears in the cave for a number of years.","«عَدَد» merely counting and calculating.","to count","عد","10:5-17:12-18:11-23:112-72:24-72:28-104:2",7
2456,534,"T","حَسَبَ","«یَحْسَبُ ، حَسَابًا ، وَ حُسْبَانًا» means to count and to keep its account; to maintain order and discipline in counting, so that there is no discrepancy in the account.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ جَعَلَ الَّیۡلَ سَکَنًا وَّ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ حُسۡبَانًا» (6/96)  \nTranslation: He has made the night a thing of rest, and the sun and moon He has kept with account.","«حَسَبَ» To count and keep it in order so that there is no error.","to count","حسب","6:96-55:5",2
2457,534,"T","اَحْصٰی","«حَصٰی» means pebbles and «حَصٰی یَحْصِی» means to throw pebbles. Arabs generally used pebbles for counting because they were not accountants. Consequently, this word began to be used in the sense of counting. In «حَصٰی», two aspects are found: (1) counting, and (2) having power over it or maintaining a record of it. Remembering it (for example) — and this is more specific than «عَدَّ».\n\nFor instance, the divine command states:\n«اِنۡ تَعُدُّوۡا نِعۡمَتَ اللّٰہِ لَا تُحۡصُوۡہَا» (14/34)\nTranslation: If you seek to count God's favors, you will never be able to enumerate them.\n\nMoreover, this word is also employed to signify having control over the account.\nFor example, the Quran says:\n«عَلِمَ  اَنۡ  لَّنۡ تُحۡصُوۡہُ فَتَابَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ» (73/20)\nTranslation: He knew that you would not be able to endure it, so He showed mercy to you.","«اَحْصٰی» meaning to count and have power over; to record; to remember.","to count","احصی","14:34-16:18-18:12-18:49-19:94-36:12-58:6-65:1-72:28-73:20-78:29",11
2458,535,"L","مَھْد","«مَھْد» denotes a cradle. It refers to a child's swing and also to a mother's lap for a nursing infant. As long as the child nurses, the mother's lap serves as his cradle. This word also encompasses the concept of upbringing or the means of upbringing. (see 'cradle')\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ یُکَلِّمُ النَّاسَ فِی الۡمَہۡدِ وَ کَہۡلًا» (3/46)\nTranslation: He will speak to people even while in the cradle, and when he reaches old age, he will be of excellent character.","«مَھْد» The mother's lap for the nursing infant.","Lap","مھد","3:46-5:110-19:29-20:53-30:44-43:10-74:14",7
2459,535,"L","حُجُور","«حُجُور» is the plural of «حِجْر». And «حُجْر» means lap or shelter. They say «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ» refers to a person being raised and brought up in someone's lap or care (manjada), and «فُلَانٌ فِیْ حِجْرِ فُلَانٍ» also means that person is under the guardianship of so-and-so. That is, there is a restriction on their wealth and authority from that guardian's side (muf).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «وَ رَبَآئِبُکُمُ الّٰتِیۡ فِیۡ  حُجُوۡرِکُمۡ» (4/23). Translation: And the first daughters among your wives who have been raised under your care.","«حُجُور» Guardianship for older children. This refers to a guardian who can impose restrictions on the property and authority of a child under guardianship.","lap","حجور","4:23",1
2460,536,"D","لُجَّۃً","«لُجّ» meaning depth of water. The deep part of water where it is deepest. And «لُجُّ الْبَحْر» meaning the extreme depth of the sea (m. l.) «بَحۡرٍ لُّجِّیٍّ» (24/40) meaning deep river or sea. And «لُجَّۃ» meaning deep water.\nFor instance: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَتۡہُ حَسِبَتۡہُ  لُجَّۃً  وَّ کَشَفَتۡ عَنۡ سَاقَیۡہَا» (27/44)\nTranslation: When the Queen of Sheba saw it, she thought it was deep water and lifted her garment from her ankles.","«لُجَّۃ» deep water and «لُجّ» the depth of water.","Depth","لجۃً","27:44",1
2461,536,"D","غَوْر","«غَارَ» means to descend downwards towards the lower ground. غار (cave) is a well-known term for a cave. And «غَوْر» means the lower ground. It also signifies subterranean depth (muf), implying that the concept of a dwelling with depth is also found in it.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ  اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَصۡبَحَ مَآؤُکُمۡ غَوۡرًا فَمَنۡ یَّاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِمَآءٍ مَّعِیۡنٍ» (67:30)\nTranslation: Say, Have you considered: if your water were to sink into the ground (in depth), who would then bring you cool, clear water?","«غَوْر» subterranean depth. Depth from the earth's surface. Sloping ground.","depth","غور","18:41-67:30",2
2462,536,"P","عَمِیْق","«عُمْق» means the depth of anything, and its opposite is «اِرْتِفَاع», which means height. If a distance is horizontal (i.e., along the side), it is length or distance. And if it is vertical and upward from the ground, it is height or «اِرْتِفَاع»; if it is downward from the ground or if one is standing above, then that same height is «عُمْق» or depth. And «عَمِیْق» means deep.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَّاۡتِیۡنَ مِنۡ کُلِّ فَجٍّ عَمِیۡقٍ» (22/27)\nTranslation: They will come from every distant path.\n\nThus, in this context, the meaning of deep is distant due to its relation to «فَجّ». «فَجّ» refers to the path between two mountains that passes through valleys and peaks.","«عَمِیْق» signifies 'profound'. However, in common usage, it is understood in a general sense.","Profoundness","عمیق","22:27",1
2463,537,"R","مَشْرَب","«مَشْرَب» a place for drinking and drawing water. Ghaat. This word is common.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«قَدۡ عَلِمَ کُلُّ اُنَاسٍ مَّشۡرَبَہُمۡ» (2/60)  \nTranslation: All the people recognized their own watering place.","«مَشْرَب» a place for drinking and filling water; ghat.","riverbank","مشرب","2:60-7:160",2
2464,537,"R","وِرْد","«وَرَدَ» means to arrive at a place of water for drinking. And its opposite is «صَدَر», i.e., to return from there after drinking. And «وِرْد» is the term for water that has been prepared for travelers (detailed), such as the water troughs etc. prepared for livestock in our lands, and «وِرْد» also refers to a thirsty person (19/86).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«یَقۡدُمُ  قَوۡمَہٗ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ فَاَوۡرَدَہُمُ النَّارَ ؕ وَ بِئۡسَ الۡوِرۡدُ  الۡمَوۡرُوۡدُ» (11/98)\nTranslation: Pharaoh will lead his people on the Day of Judgment and will bring them to the Fire. wretched is the place to which they will be brought.","«وِرْد» meaning a place to drink water.","riverbank","ورد","11:98-19:86-21:99-28:23",4
2465,538,"V","نَجَد","«نَجَد» means a valley, elevated ground, land devoid of trees, a high road (Munjid), and also the road that ascends it or descends from it (Muf). In its original meaning, it also refers to a valley (Muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  النَّجۡدَیۡنِ» (90:10)\nTranslation: And We have shown man the two paths (Jalbandhari).\nWe have made clear to him two valleys (Uthmani).","«نَجَد» is a common word for valley.","valley","نجد","90:10",1
2466,538,"V","عَقَبَۃ","«عَقَبَۃ» means a difficult path for ascending a mountain (detailed), i.e., «عَقَبَۃ» refers specifically to a path that ascends a valley or a mountain.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَلَا  اقۡتَحَمَ الۡعَقَبَۃَ وَ مَاۤ  اَدۡرٰىکَ مَا الۡعَقَبَۃُ فَکُّ رَقَبَۃٍ» (90/11)  \nTranslation: But he has not attempted the steep path. And what will make you know what the steep path is? It is the freeing of a slave.  \n\nHowever, according to the commentator Manjīd, the meaning of «عَقَبَۃ» is a difficult-to-traverse valley, and also the arduous path of ascending it.","We call only that valley difficult to pass through.","valley","عقبۃ","90:11-90:12",2
2467,539,"H","بَیْت","«بَاتَ» To spend the night. To pass the night. And «بَیْت» refers to the place where one spends the night, i.e., where one passes the night. Then, terminologically, Bayt (house) refers to that place where a person can spend the night with his family and dependents in peace, and which is their dwelling and place of refuge. (Muf. M. L.) The plural of «بَیْت» is «بُیُوْت».\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَرۡنَ فِیۡ بُیُوۡتِکُنَّ وَ لَا تَبَرَّجۡنَ تَبَرُّجَ الۡجَاہِلِیَّۃِ  الۡاُوۡلٰی» (33:33)\nTranslation: (O wives of the Prophet ﷺ!) And remain in your homes. And do not display yourselves as in the former times of Jahiliyyah (ignorance).\n\nAnd for the Ka'bah as well, Allah the Exalted has used the words «بَیْت» and «اَلْبَیْت». In it too, the aforementioned relationship is found.\n\nFor instance: The Prophetic Hadith states:\n«اَلْخَلْقُ عَیَالُ اللہ» Meaning: All of creation is the family of Allah. And although the Ka'bah is not a place for spending the night, it is certainly a dwelling and a place of refuge.","«بَیْت» where people live with their families and also spend the night.","House","بیت","2:125-2:127-2:158-2:189-3:49-3:96-3:97-3:154-4:15-4:81-4:100-5:2-5:97-7:74-8:5-8:35-10:87-11:73-12:23-14:37-15:82-16:68-16:80-17:93-22:26-22:29-22:33-24:27-24:29-24:36-24:61-26:149-27:52-28:12-29:41-33:13-33:33-33:34-33:53-43:33-43:34-51:36-52:4-59:2-65:1-66:11-71:28-106:3",48
2468,539,"H","مَسْکَن","«سَکَنَ» means to be inhabited. Also, to rest after doing work. And «مَسْکَنْ» is the place where a person takes up residence and is given shelter without rent or the like, which is called «سُکْنٰی». And those living in a single house are called «سُکْن». The plural form is «سَاکِنٌ» (mufrad) and the word «مَسْکَن» solely implies the concept of residence. Thus, every house is a dwelling, but not every dwelling is a house.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَتِلۡکَ مَسٰکِنُہُمۡ لَمۡ تُسۡکَنۡ مِّنۡۢ  بَعۡدِہِمۡ  اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (28/58)\nTranslation: So these are the houses of those (destroyed people) which were inhabited by fewer after them.","«مَسْکَن» implies merely residence, whether it is a place for spending the night (i.e., spending the night) or not, as though this is more specific than «بَیْت».","House","مسکن","9:24-9:72-14:45-20:128-21:13-27:18-28:58-29:38-32:26-34:15-46:25-61:12",12
2469,539,"H","دَار","The plural of «دَار» is «دَوْر» and «دِیَار», meaning house, dwelling. The usage of «دَار» is very extensive. It can refer to a house, mansion, town, city, country, the entire world, and even the Hereafter (for details, see 'city'). And when «دَار» refers to a house, the external aspect of the house is intended. In English, the word 'home' is used for it. Moreover, when «دَار» is used in the meaning of house, its plural will also be «دَار».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is said:\n«فَقَالَ تَمَتَّعُوۡا فِیۡ  دَارِکُمۡ ثَلٰثَۃَ  اَیَّامٍ» (11/65)\nTranslation: So (Prophet Saleh ﷺ said to his people), You people, benefit from your homes for three days (and more).","The use of «دَار» is very common. When it means house, it refers to the external aspect of the house, as there can be several «بَیْت» inside a single «دَار» (haveli).","house","دار","2:94-6:32-6:127-6:135-7:78-7:91-7:145-7:169-10:25-11:65-12:109-13:22-13:24-13:25-13:31-13:42-14:28-16:30-28:37-28:77-28:83-29:37-29:64-33:29-35:35-38:46-40:39-40:52-41:28-59:9",30
2470,539,"H","اَھْل","The word «اَھْل» is also used in very broad meanings (for details and for the distinction between «اَھْل» and «اٰل», see first generation/offspring). In its common meanings, «اَہْلُ الرَّجُل» refers to the members of one's household and family, i.e., one's wife and children who are under one's guardianship and upbringing. Then, just as the word «قَرْیَۃ» is used for both a settlement and the inhabitants of that settlement, similarly the word «اَھْل» is used not only for the household members but also for the home itself.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ غَدَوۡتَ مِنۡ اَہۡلِکَ تُبَوِّئُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مَقَاعِدَ لِلۡقِتَالِ» (3/121)\nTranslation: And when you, [O Muhammad], left at dawn from your home to post the believers at their positions [for battle].","«اَھْل» encompasses the home and its inhabitants, as well as the family and dependents, within its meaning.","House","اھل","2:196-2:126-2:217-3:121-4:25-4:35-4:58-4:75-4:92-5:89-6:131-7:83-7:94-7:100-7:123-10:24-11:40-11:45-11:46-11:81-11:117-12:26-12:62-12:65-12:88-12:93-15:65-18:71-18:77-19:16-19:55-20:10-20:29-20:132-21:76-21:84-23:27-24:27-26:169-26:170-27:7-27:34-27:49-27:57-28:4-28:15-28:29-28:59-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-35:43-36:50-37:76-37:134-38:43-39:15-42:45-48:11-48:12-48:26-51:26-52:26-66:6-75:33-83:31-84:9-84:13",69
2471,540,"C","سَاعَۃ","«سَاعَۃ» is a specific portion of time. An hour. Its plural is «سَاعَات». The Arabs have proposed separate names for the twelve hours into which they divided the night and the day, the details of which have passed in the section Day and Night. Even today, the complete duration of night and day is divided into 24 hours. Thus, «سَاعَۃ» can also refer to a single hour.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَمۡ  یَلۡبَثُوۡۤا اِلَّا سَاعَۃً  مِّنۡ نَّہَارٍ» (46:35)\nTranslation: They (in the world) remained not but a single «سَاعَۃ» (hour).\n\nAnd for the timepiece which is called a watch in English, the word «سَاعَۃ» is also used. And «سَاعَاتِی» means a seller of watches and a watchmaker. Sometimes, «سَاعَۃ» is also taken to mean a period or durations, which can encompass not just a full day but also several days, months, and even years.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ تَّابَ اللّٰہُ عَلَی النَّبِیِّ وَ الۡمُہٰجِرِیۡنَ وَ الۡاَنۡصَارِ الَّذِیۡنَ اتَّبَعُوۡہُ فِیۡ سَاعَۃِ الۡعُسۡرَۃِ» (9:117)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah has shown mercy to the Prophet and also to the Muhajireen and the Ansar who followed him in a difficult «سَاعَۃ» (time).\n\nAnd generally, «اَلسَّاعَۃ» refers to the Day of Judgment.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«حَتّٰۤی  اِذَا جَآءَتۡہُمُ السَّاعَۃُ  بَغۡتَۃً» (6:31)\nTranslation: Until the Day of Judgment comes upon them unexpectedly.","«سَاعَۃ» any one of the hours of day and night. Time. Resurrection.","Clock","ساعۃ","7:34-9:117-10:45-10:49-16:61-30:55-34:30-46:35",8
2472,540,"C","اٰنَاء","«اٰن» means a part of time. «اٰنَاء» means the time for something arriving and reaching its end (see *Mufradat*). Furthermore, «اَنٰی» means a full day or a part of it (see *Majma' al-Bayan*). However, in the Noble Quran, the word «اٰنَاء» has been used three times: (3:113), (20:13), and (39:9). In all three instances, the word «لَیْل» (meaning 'night') appears alongside «اٰنَاء». This word is never used with 'day'. Therefore, it can only be understood that the term «اٰنَاء» is specific to the hours of the night.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یَّتۡلُوۡنَ اٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ اٰنَآءَ الَّیۡلِ  وَ ہُمۡ  یَسۡجُدُوۡنَ» (3:113)\nTranslation: They recite the verses of Allah during the night and prostrate.","«اٰنَاء» the watches of the night.","Clock","اناء","3:113-20:130-39:9-57:16",4
2473,540,"C","زُلْف","«زُلَف» means the early part of the night or the first hours (fn 34). The basic meanings of «زُلْف» are rank and nearness. The early part of the night is called «زُلْف» because it is the part of the entire night that is closest and most proximate.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَقِمِ الصَّلٰوۃَ طَرَفَیِ النَّہَارِ وَ زُلَفًا مِّنَ الَّیۡلِ» (11/114)\nTranslation: Establish prayer at the two ends of the day (i.e., morning and evening) and during the first hours of the night.","«زُلَف» the early part of the night or the early hours.","Clock","زلف","11:114",1
2474,541,"T","وَلَجَ","to enter a narrow place; to squeeze in (fig.)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا یَدۡخُلُوۡنَ الۡجَنَّۃَ حَتّٰی یَلِجَ الۡجَمَلُ فِیۡ سَمِّ الۡخِیَاطِ» (7/40)\nTranslation: And they will not enter Paradise until a camel enters the eye of a needle.","«وَلَجَ» is used for entering a tight space.","to rub","ولج","3:27-7:40-22:61-31:29-34:2-35:13-57:4-57:6",8
2475,541,"T","جَاسَ","«جَاسَ» meaning to reach between things (m. l.) and meaning to reach the utmost limit in seeking something (muf.), and «جَاسَ فِی الْبَیْت» meaning that corruption and plunder entered the house (m. q.), and «جَوَّاس» meaning one who infiltrates among a people to cause corruption (minjadd).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«بَعَثۡنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  عِبَادًا  لَّنَاۤ   اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ فَجَاسُوۡا خِلٰلَ الدِّیَارِ» (17/5)\nTranslation: We have made our mighty soldiers dominant over you, who entered your cities.","«جَاسَ» to break into a house or shop etc. for looting and rioting.","to penetrate","جاس","17:5",1
2476,542,"T","جَرَّ","«جَرّ» signifies pulling as the predominant action, with dragging being less prominent. It refers to pulling in a horizontal (i.e., sideways) direction, or pulling an upright object in such a way that it loses its footing and begins to drag—this is «جَرّ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَخَذَ بِرَاۡسِ اَخِیۡہِ یَجُرُّہٗۤ اِلَیۡہِ» (7:150)\nTranslation: And Moses seized his brother by the head and pulled him toward himself.\n\nAnd «جَیْشٌ جَرَّارٌ» refers to a large army that advances while spread over a wide area, as if being pulled or dragged forward.","To pull a standing object in such a way that it begins to scrape, and when such «جَرّ» involves harshness and mercilessness, it is «عَتَلَ»; whereas when a fallen object is pulled, it is «سَحْب».","to drag","جر","7:150",1
2477,542,"T","سَحَبَ","The aspect of «سَحَبَ» is prominent, while that of pulling (in another sense) is less so. According to Imam Raghīb, its meaning is to drag someone on their face (ref). When a thing is oriented in a lying down direction instead of standing, or in a horizontal (sideways) direction instead of upright, and it is pulled, then this is «سَحْب». And «سَحَاب» means cloud, and a cloud is called «سَحَاب» because the wind pulls and carries it forward, and it itself advances in such a manner as if it is being dragged along (ref).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ یُسۡحَبُوۡنَ فِی النَّارِ عَلٰی وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ» (54:48)\nTranslation: On the Day they will be dragged on their faces into the Fire.","«سَحَبَ» to drag along the ground, to snatch, to seize, to take back.","to pull","سحب","40:71-54:48",2
2478,542,"T","عَتَلَ","In «عَتَل» compared to «جَرّ», a concept of greater severity and ruthlessness is found (M. Q.). And according to the scholar of language and jurisprudence, it means to seize by the neck and pull forward with extreme severity (Fal 188).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خُذُوۡہُ فَاعۡتِلُوۡہُ  اِلٰی سَوَآءِ الۡجَحِیۡمِ» (44/47)\n\nTranslation: Seize him and drag him into the midst of Hell.","To place something around the neck and pull forward with extreme force.","to drag","عتل","44:47",1
2479,543,"H","خَیْل","«خَیْل» is a generic noun. That is, it applies to all types of horses, whether male or female (mare). Then its usage also extends to a group or herd of horses. For example, «غَنَم» means a herd of goats. And besides this, its usage also applies to a cavalryman or a combination of a cavalryman and his horse (manjad).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ الۡخَیۡلَ وَ الۡبِغَالَ وَ الۡحَمِیۡرَ لِتَرۡکَبُوۡہَا وَ زِیۡنَۃً» (16:8)\nTranslation: And horses, mules, and donkeys (are also created) for you to ride upon, and (they are also) a source of beauty for you.\n\nIn this verse, «خَیْل» is used as a generic noun. And in the following verse, the usage of «خَیْل» is occurring for a cavalryman or the combination of a cavalryman and his horse.\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» (17:64)\nTranslation: And mobilize against them your cavalry and your infantry.\n\nAnd the fundamental meaning of «خَیْل» is the movement of various concepts in the mind (m. l.). From this, the word khayal (imagination/thought) is derived. And «الخَیْلَاء» refers to that pride and arrogance which a cavalryman feels while mounted on his horse in comparison to a pedestrian. From this, the word takhayyul (conceit/fantasy) is derived. Meaning: to know something with keen insight (manjad). Lofty flight.","«خَیْل» is a common gender. Its usage is common for a horse, for a rider, and for a group as well.","Horse","خیل","3:14-8:60-16:8-59:6",4
2480,543,"H","صٰفِنٰت","«صٰفِنٰت» is the plural of «صافن». «صَفَنَ الْفَرَس» means a horse standing on three legs in such a way that only the tip of the fourth hoof touches the ground (manjada. mafu), and it refers to a swift and agile horse.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» (38/31). Translation: When excellent horses of noble breed were presented before them in the evening.","«صٰفِنٰت» a well-proportioned horse standing on three legs.","horse","صفنت","38:31",1
2481,543,"H","جِیَاد","«جِیَاد» is the plural form of «جَیَِّد». «جُوْد» means to be vast or extensive in something. And «جَوَّاد» refers to a generous man or woman. And «جَادَ الْفَرْس» means a horse being swift and fast-paced (m. l.). Furthermore, the word «جَیَِّد» also denotes the excellence or perfection of something. According to the author of 'Fiqh al-Lughah', «جِیَاد» means swift and excellent horses. (f. l. 56)\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِذۡ عُرِضَ عَلَیۡہِ بِالۡعَشِیِّ الصّٰفِنٰتُ الۡجِیَادُ» (38/31). Translation: When in the evening, swift and well-trained horses were presented before Solomon (peace be upon him).","«جِیَاد» swift and well-bred horses.","horse","جیاد","38:31",1
2482,543,"H","عَادِیَات","«عَادِیَات» is a plural form, the feminine of «عَادِیَۃ» and the masculine of «عَادِیَۃٌ ، عَادِی». And «عَادِی» means that group which is prepared for killing and fighting. Raiding horses. And «عَدَ الْفَرْس» means the horses raced. And «تَعَادَی الْقَوْم» means people competed in the race (mansaj). Thus, «عَادِیَات» refers to those horses that go to war and continue to participate in racing competitions.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1)\nTranslation: By those galloping horses that pant.","«عَادِیَات» Those horses that participate in races and are prepared for war.","horse","عادیات","100:1",1
2483,544,"T","حَفَّ","«حَفَّ» meaning to encircle something from both sides (مف) and «حَفَّہٗ بکذا» meaning to encompass completely (منجد) and «مَحِفَّۃ» meaning curtain. A portable throne over which a curtain has been draped on all sides (م.ق).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَّ حَفَفۡنٰہُمَا بِنَخۡلٍ وَّ جَعَلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمَا زَرۡعًا» (18/32) Translation: And We had surrounded both gardens with date-palm trees and placed fields between them.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is: «وَ تَرَی الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃَ  حَآفِّیۡنَ مِنۡ حَوۡلِ الۡعَرۡشِ» (39/75) Translation: And you will see the angels surrounding the Throne from all sides.","By this, «حَفَّ» is intended to mean only encircling or surrounding.","to encompass","حف","18:32-39:75",2
2484,544,"T","اَحَاط","«اَحَاطَ» meaning to encompass. To build a four-walled enclosure. To surround something in such a way that it is protected. (Figurative) In a manner where the thing itself cannot get out, nor can anyone else take it out. Just as a house is enclosed by building four walls around it.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10/22)\nTranslation: And waves come upon them from every side, and they think that they are encompassed by the waves.\n\nThe use of this word is also spiritual in nature.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«بَلٰی مَنۡ کَسَبَ سَیِّئَۃً وَّ اَحَاطَتۡ بِہٖ خَطِیۡٓئَتُہٗ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَصۡحٰبُ النَّارِ» (2/81)\nTranslation: Why not? He who has committed evil and whose sins have encompassed him—those are the companions of the Fire.","«اَحَاطَ» meaning to encircle with the purpose of protection.","to encompass","احاط","2:81-12:66-17:60-18:29-48:21-65:12-72:28",7
2485,544,"T","اَحْصَرَ","«اَحْصَرَ» meaning to besiege, to encircle. To surround something in such a way that it becomes trapped and cannot escape (as per the dictionary). To capture and prevent any supplies (food and drink provisions), reinforcements (military aid), or any other form of assistance from reaching them from outside.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ احۡصُرُوۡہُمۡ وَ اقۡعُدُوۡا لَہُمۡ کُلَّ مَرۡصَدٍ» (9/5)\nTranslation: And besiege them and lie in wait for them at every place of ambush.","«اَحْصَرَ» encirclement and confinement, meaning to confine or enclose something.","to encompass","احصر","2:196-2:273-4:90-9:5",4
2486,544,"T","حَاقَ","«حَاقَ» means the descending of something upon something (m.l.) and also means the descending of something upon something and thereby encircling it (m.f.). It is as if it is a siege that inherently surrounds the besieged. The coming down of a calamity, disaster, or punishment upon someone, causing them to be confined. And «حَیْق» means the recompense of deeds. The bad result of a bad action (minj.d). This word is used in a negative sense.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ حَاقَ بِہِمۡ  مَّا کَانُوۡا بِہٖ یَسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» (39/48)\nTranslation: And that (punishment) which they used to mock will encompass them.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا یَحِیۡقُ الۡمَکۡرُ السَّیِّیئُ  اِلَّا بِاَہۡلِہٖ» (35/43)\nTranslation: And the evil consequence of a bad deed befalls only its perpetrator.\n\nThis part of the mentioned verse is also used metaphorically; it is a Persian proverb: چاہ کن را چاہ درپیش meaning whoever plots harm for others ends up suffering that harm himself.","«حَاقَ» meaning to afflict someone with a calamity.","to encompass","حاق","6:10-11:8-16:34-21:41-35:43-39:48-40:45-40:83-45:33-46:26",10
2487,545,"C","عَصَا","«عَصَا» means a shepherd's staff or rod. Its plural is «عِصِیّ».\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَلۡقٰی عَصَاہُ  فَاِذَا ہِیَ ثُعۡبَانٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (7/107)\nTranslation: So (Moses ﷺ) threw his staff, and at once it became a real serpent.","«عَصَا» meaning a shepherd's staff.","club","عصا","2:60-7:107-7:117-7:160-20:18-20:66-26:32-26:44-26:45-26:63-27:10-28:31",12
2488,545,"C","مِنْسَأَۃ","«مِنْسَأَۃ» meaning the staff of a sick or weak person (F L 231)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضَیۡنَا عَلَیۡہِ الۡمَوۡتَ مَا دَلَّہُمۡ عَلٰی مَوۡتِہٖۤ اِلَّا دَآبَّۃُ الۡاَرۡضِ تَاۡکُلُ مِنۡسَاَتَہٗ» (34/14)\nTranslation: Then when We decreed the death of Solomon, nothing indicated his death to them except the creatures of the earth eating his staff. And a staff whose tip is curved is called «مِحْجَنْ» (F L 231). The tips of «عَصَا» and «مِنْسَاَۃ» are not curved. «عَصَا» is a thick and strong staff. And «مِنْسَاَۃ» is a relatively thinner and well-shaped type of staff.","«مِنْسَأَۃ» meaning the staff of a sick or weak person.","cane","منسأۃ","34:14",1
2489,546,"T","جَآءَبِ","«جَآءَبِ» meaning to bring, its usage is common.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَدۡ کُذِّبَ رُسُلٌ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِکَ جَآءُوۡ بِالۡبَیِّنٰتِ» (3:184)\nTranslation: So indeed, messengers were denied before you who brought clear proofs.","«جَآءَبِ» means to bring; its usage is common.","to bring","جآءب","2:87-2:92-3:183-3:184-4:170-5:32-5:70-6:91-6:160-7:43-7:53-7:101-7:116-10:13-10:74-11:69-12:18-12:72-12:100-14:9-19:23-23:70-24:11-24:13-25:4-27:89-27:90-28:37-28:84-28:85-29:39-30:9-30:47-35:25-37:37-37:84-39:33-40:25-40:28-40:34-40:83-43:47-43:63-49:6-50:19-50:21-50:33-51:26-61:6",49
2490,546,"T","اَتٰی بِہٖ","«اَتٰی بِہٖ» to bring forth as a result.  \nFor example: It is stated in the Quran: «فَاۡتُوۡا بِسُوۡرَۃٍ مِّنۡ مِّثۡلِہٖ» (2/23)  \nTranslation: Then produce a surah like it, if you are truthful.","to bring about","to bring","اتی بہٖ","2:23-2:25-2:106-2:109-2:145-2:148-2:258-3:93-3:161-3:183-4:133-5:52-5:54-5:108-6:35-6:46-7:70-7:112-7:132-7:169-7:203-9:24-9:70-10:38-10:39-11:13-11:32-11:33-12:60-12:66-12:83-12:93-13:38-14:10-14:11-14:19-15:7-15:64-16:76-17:88-17:92-18:15-18:33-18:62-18:96-19:27-19:80-20:10-20:58-20:133-21:5-21:47-21:61-23:71-23:90-24:4-24:13-25:33-26:31-26:37-27:7-27:21-27:37-27:38-27:39-27:40-28:29-28:49-28:71-28:72-31:16-35:16-37:157-40:78-44:10-44:19-44:36-46:22-52:34-52:38-67:30-68:41",82
2491,546,"T","ھَلُمَّ","«ھَلُمَّ» is a verbal noun. It means to call or to summon, i.e., to call someone repeatedly to come (as per lexicographers). This word is used in both intransitive (lazim) and transitive (mutaddi) forms.\n\nWhen used intransitively, it conveys the meaning of to come.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n« لِاِخۡوَانِہِمۡ ہَلُمَّ اِلَیۡنَا» (33:18)\nTranslation: They say to their brothers, Come to us.\n\nWhen used transitively, it conveys the meaning of to bring.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«قُلۡ ہَلُمَّ  شُہَدَآءَکُمُ» (6:150)\nTranslation: Then say, Bring your witnesses.","When the call to summon is made.","to bring","ھلم","6:150-33:18",2
2492,546,"T","ھَاتُوْا","According to lexicographers, this word originally is «اٰتُوْا», which is the form of the masculine plural present tense imperative from «اَتٰی». And this word is used as an imperative noun. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is also to shout or call out. «یَدُلُّ عَلَی الصَّیْحَۃ» (M L) However, according to some, its meanings are bring here or hurry up, bring it.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ ہَاتُوۡا بُرۡہَانَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2/111)\nTranslation: Say, If you are truthful, then produce your evidence.","«ھَاتُوْا» meaning bring it here.","to bring","ھاتوا","2:111-21:24-27:64-28:75",4
2493,546,"T","اَجَآءَ","«اَجَآءَ» The act of bringing something forcefully by compulsion, i.e., by making someone or something compelled and helpless.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَجَآءَہَا الۡمَخَاضُ  اِلٰی جِذۡعِ  النَّخۡلَۃِ» (19/23)\nTranslation: Then the pain of childbirth compelled Maryam (peace be upon her) to move towards the trunk of the palm tree.","«اَجَآءَ» To forcibly bring something in or cause it to be brought in out of necessity or compulsion.","to bring","اجآء","19:23",1
2494,546,"B","اَجْلَبَ","«جَلَبَ» means to drive something and urge it forward. And «اَجْلَبَ عَلَیْہِ» means to drive someone by urging them and forcefully advance them. (muf)\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَجۡلِبۡ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِخَیۡلِکَ وَ رَجِلِکَ» (17/64)\nTranslation: And mount upon them your cavalry and infantry.","«اَجْلَبَ» to forcefully pull someone from behind.","bring","اجلب","17:64",1
2495,547,"W","یَنْبَغِیْ","«اِنْبَغٰی» means to be easy and simple. And «ینبغی» means to be worthy, appropriate (manjada). This word is used for an action that is considered absurd. They say «اَلنَّارُ یَنْبَغِیْ اَنْ یُّحْرِقَ الثَّوْبَ», meaning that burning clothes is a special property of fire (muf). Only this singular masculine jussive form is employed. It also pertains to matters that are inherent or integral to nature. Lexically, it is used in both negation and affirmation.\n\nAn example of its negation is stated in the Holy Quran as follows:\n«لَا الشَّمۡسُ یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہَاۤ اَنۡ تُدۡرِکَ الۡقَمَرَ» (36/40)\nTranslation: It is not fitting for the sun to overtake the moon.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah Almighty states:\n«وَ مَا عَلَّمۡنٰہُ الشِّعۡرَ وَ مَا یَنۡۢبَغِیۡ لَہٗ» (36/69)\nTranslation: We have not taught the Prophet poetry, nor is it fitting for him.","«یَنْبَغِیْ» meaning 'to be worthy.' This word is used for an action (deed) that is subjected (i.e., controlled).","Worthy","ینبغی","19:92-25:18-26:211-36:40-36:69-38:35",6
2496,547,"B","اَجْدَر","«جَدَرَ» means to be worthy and appropriate. And «اَجْدَر» is an intensive form of the noun and is used for optional matters. «جَدِیْرُ الذِّکْر» means mentionable. And «جَدِیْرُ الثَّنَاء» means definable or praiseworthy. It is used when something is fitting to someone's condition and status.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَلۡاَعۡرَابُ اَشَدُّ کُفۡرًا وَّ نِفَاقًا وَّ اَجۡدَرُ اَلَّا یَعۡلَمُوۡا حُدُوۡدَ  مَاۤ  اَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ» (9:97)\nTranslation: The bedouins are very hard in disbelief and hypocrisy, and are exactly such that they should not understand the limits and commandments revealed by Allah.","«اَجْدَر» is an intensive form and it is used for optional matters.","Befitting","اجدر","9:97",1
2497,547,"D","اَوْلٰی","«وَلِی» means protector, friend, and one meaning of «مَوَالِی» is heir of the legacy. And «وَلَاء» means the legacy of a freed slave. And the right of guardianship. And «اَوْلٰی» means more worthy, more suitable, more deserving. It comes for optional matters. And it comes only for affirmation. And it is much stronger than «یَنْبَغِیْ» (مف); even for this, only this form is used. And its reward will come from «ب». And its meaning will be: He alone is capable of it, He alone is more suitable or deserving.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لَنَحۡنُ اَعۡلَمُ بِالَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِہَا صِلِیًّا» (19/70)\nTranslation: Then We are most knowing of those who are most worthy of entering Hell.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ» (33/6)\nTranslation: The Prophet has more right over the believers than they have over themselves.\n\nAnd if the reward of «اَوْلٰی» comes from «ل», then this word becomes one of rebuke, censure, and admonition. Meaning corruption, destruction, etc.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«اَوۡلٰی لَکَ  فَاَوۡلٰی» (75/35)\nTranslation: May you be destroyed, then may you be destroyed.","This term is used in a broader semantic range than «اَجْدَر» and appears only in affirmative constructions for optional matters.","Deserving","اولی","3:68-4:135-8:75-19:70-33:6",5
2498,547,"W","حُقَّ","«حَقَّ» means to be established and to be obligatory. And «حُقَّ اَنْ یَّفْعَل کَذَا» means that performing such an act is obligatory and deserving (mandatory) for it—that is, it was its very right to do so. Its usage is only in an affirmative sense.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «اِذَا السَّمَآءُ  انۡشَقَّتۡ وَ اَذِنَتۡ لِرَبِّہَا وَ حُقَّتۡ» (84/1,2). Translation: When the sky splits open and listens to its Lord's command, and it is also obligatory for it.","«حُقَّ» means that doing so is obligatory and fitting for him.","worthy","حق","2:228-2:247-5:107-6:81-9:13-9:62-9:108-10:35-10:53-33:37-48:26-84:2-84:5",13
2499,548,"T","طَوٰی","«طَوَی» means to roll up or fold. To roll up a bedding, mattress, carpet, etc. To fold a tablecloth. «طُوِیَتِ الثَّوْبُ وَ الْکِتَابُ» means as a cloth or a book is rolled up or tied (m. l.). They say «نَشَرْتُ الکِتابَ ثُمَّ طَوَیْتُہٗ», meaning I opened the book and then closed it again.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَوۡمَ نَطۡوِی السَّمَآءَ کَطَیِّ السِّجِلِّ لِلۡکُتُبِ» (21/104)\nTranslation: The Day when We will roll up the heavens like the rolling up of a scroll.","«طَوَی» meaning to fold something, such as folding a tablecloth.","to wrap","طوی","21:104-39:67",2
2500,548,"T","لَفَّ","«لَفَّ» means to mix one thing with another and blend them together (figuratively), to layer one thing. Then placing a second layer over it and mixing them. Then after that, placing a third layer over it (M. L.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ  جِئۡنَا بِکُمۡ  لَفِیۡفًا» (17/104)\nTranslation: Then when the promise of the Hereafter comes, We will gather you all together and bring you forth.\n\nAnd for the meaning of clinging, «اِلْتَفَّ» will be used. It means one thing sticking and clinging to another.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ الۡتَفَّتِ السَّاقُ بِالسَّاقِ . اِلٰی رَبِّکَ یَوۡمَئِذِ ۣ الۡمَسَاقُ» (75/29)\nTranslation: And leg will be clinging to leg. That Day you will have no recourse except to your Lord.","«لَفَّ» To place one thing upon another and then mix it, i.e., to combine.","to wrap","لف","17:104-75:29",2
2501,548,"T","کَوَّر","«کَوَّر» means to wrap something like a turban or pagri and to coil it over and under. And «اِکْتَارُ الْفَرَسِ», meaning a horse turning its own tail (muf), is also used for the purpose of wrapping like a pagri. One says «لَفَفْتُ عَمَامَتِیْ عَلٰی رَأسِیْ», i.e., I have wrapped a pagri on my head. It is in this sense that one layer is placed upon another. And the word «کَوَّر» is stronger for wrapping a pagri. Because «کَوَّر» embodies the concepts of both gathering and roundness, which are found in a pagri.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«یُکَوِّرُ الَّیۡلَ عَلَی النَّہَارِ وَ یُکَوِّرُ النَّہَارَ عَلَی» (39:5)\nTranslation: He it is Who wraps the night over the day and the day over the night.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«اِذَا  الشَّمۡسُ کُوِّرَتۡ» (81:1)\nTranslation: When the sun is wrapped up.","«کَوَّر» to wrap into a spherical shape and to keep gathering.","to wrap","کور","39:5-81:1",2
2502,549,"T","اَدْلٰی","«دَلٰی» meaning to approach something with ease and gentleness. «دَلَاہُ» meaning to treat someone with kindness and consideration. And «دَلْو» meaning to pull (a bucket) to lower it into the well and retrieve it. And «اَدْلٰی دَلْوَہٗ» meaning he let down his empty bucket to draw water from the well.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)\nTranslation: And a caravan came that had sent their man (to this well) to bring water. So he let down his bucket.\n\n«تَدَلّٰی» meaning to hang down oneself with ease and softness. They say «تَدَلَّی الثَّمَرُ مِنَ الشَّجَرِ» the fruit of the tree hung down (manjad).\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«ثُمَّ  دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی» (53/8)\nTranslation: Then Gabriel drew near, then he hung down.","«اَدْلٰی» to lower something gradually and gently.","to hang","ادلی","2:188-7:22-12:19-20:40-20:120-28:12-34:7-34:14-53:8-61:10",10
2503,549,"T","عَلَّقَ","«عَلِقَ» means to become stuck or entangled in something. «عَلِقَ الصَّیْدُ فِی الْجُعَالَۃِ» refers to the prey becoming caught in a trap. «عَلَّقَ» means to hang or suspend. «عَلَقٌ» denotes a suspended or hanging thing.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَا تَمِیۡلُوۡا کُلَّ الۡمَیۡلِ فَتَذَرُوۡہَا کَالۡمُعَلَّقَۃِ» (4/129)\nTranslation: So do not incline entirely toward one (wife) and leave the other suspended.","«عَلَّقَ» to keep something hanging and entangled.","to hang","علق","4:129",1
2504,549,"T","تَرَدَّدَ","«رَدَّ» meaning to return, to revert, to turn back. And «تَرَدَّد» meaning the coming of one thought, then another thought in its place, which also passes away, followed by yet another thought. And «تَرَدَّد فِی الْاَمْر» meaning to fall into doubt and perplexity (manjada), to remain bewildered, and to be unable to make a decision.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَہُمۡ  فِیۡ  رَیۡبِہِمۡ  یَتَرَدَّدُوۡنَ» (9/45)\nTranslation: They are wavering in their doubt.","«تَرَدَّد» To remain suspended and hesitant due to conflicting opinions; i.e., not arriving at a final decision.","to hang","تردد","9:45",1
2505,549,"T","ذَبْذَبَ ۔ اَلزآَبْذَبَۃ","«ذَبْذَبَ» originally refers to the sound of a swaying hanging object. Metaphorically, it is used to denote all kinds of movement and agitation (see *Mufradat*). And «اَلزَّبْذَبَۃ» means something that moves in the air, or an object hung for the adornment of a palanquin. And «ذَبْذَبَ الرَّجُل» means for a person to be perplexed and indecisive (see *Majid*). Thus, «ذَبْذَبَ» signifies remaining suspended in a state of agitation (restlessness and distress) between different paths, unable to make a decision.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«مُّذَبۡذَبِیۡنَ بَیۡنَ ذٰلِکَ ٭ۖ لَاۤ اِلٰی ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ وَ لَاۤ اِلٰی ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ» (4:143)\nTranslation: They are hanging between disbelief and faith, neither of this side nor that.","«ذَبْذَبَ» a hesitation characterized by anxiety and restlessness.","to hang","ذبذب ۔ الزآبذبۃ","4:143",1
2506,550,"D","رَقِبَ","«رَقِبَ» to keep a close watch on someone; to exercise strict vigilance (مف); to supervise; to guard; to wait (منجد); to protect.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it says: «لَا یَرۡقُبُوۡنَ فِیۡ مُؤۡمِنٍ اِلًّا وَّ لَا ذِمَّۃً» (9/10) Translation: These hypocrites do not respect familial ties or covenants with any Muslim.","The term «رَقِبَ» is used solely to refer to looking at something with a fixed stare or with aversion.","Deference","رقب","9:8-9:10-20:94",3
2507,550,"D","رَعٰی","«رَعٰی» means to protect something well and be mindful of it (figuratively: to fulfill a covenant or responsibility and to be concerned about it). And «رَاعِیْ» means a shepherd who is tasked with guarding his flock, and it also means to protect something and to take measures to ward off external threats. Its opposite is «اِهْمَالُ», i.e., grazing without a shepherd (Fiqh, 15). For example: The Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ ہُمۡ  لِاَمٰنٰتِہِمۡ وَ عَہۡدِہِمۡ رٰعُوۡنَ» (23/8)\nTranslation: And those who faithfully observe their trusts and their pledges.","«رَعٰی» meaning to protect something well and to pay attention to it.","deference","رعی","20:54-28:23",2
2508,551,"A","جُنْد","«جُنْد» is used for a military force and is the commonly employed term. «جُنْدِیْ» means military, and «جَنَّدَ» means to recruit into the army (its plural is «جُنُوْد»). Besides «جُنْد», another common word for an army is «جَیْش», whose plural is «جُیُوْش». Its usage does not occur in the Quran. The other word is «عَسْکَر», its plural is «عَسَاکَر». This also is not found in the Quran. «عَسَاکَر» and «جُیُوْش» generally refer to those armies that begin to gather from various directions upon the proclamation of jihad, whether they possess weapons or not. Whereas «جُنْد» refers specifically to an armed force.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا فَصَلَ طَالُوۡتُ بِالۡجُنُوۡدِ» (2:249)\nTranslation: When Talut set out with the armies.","«جُنْد» a contingent of recruited armed forces.","Army","جند","19:75-36:28-36:75-37:173-38:11-44:24-67:20",7
2509,551,"A","فَوْج","«فَوْج» means a group that passes by quickly. Its plural is «اَفْوَاج». And a larger group is called «طائفۃ» (Fal 205). However, in the Quran, this word has generally only appeared in the meanings of a group or a community. It has not appeared in the meanings of a military unit or squad. It seems that the concept which today arises from the word army does not emerge from the Quran.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ مِنۡ کُلِّ اُمَّۃٍ  فَوۡجًا مِّمَّنۡ یُّکَذِّبُ بِاٰیٰتِنَا» (27:83)\nTranslation: And on the Day We will gather from every nation a group of those who denied Our signs.","«فَوْج» The swiftly passing crowd.","army","فوج","27:83-38:59-67:8-78:18-110:2",5
2510,551,"A","حِزْب","«حِزْب» means a group, a party, a faction, a group of like-minded people. And «اَحْزَاب» refers to people whose hearts and actions are in harmony, even if they do not meet each other. And «حَازَبَ» means to enter into a party, to help, to provide strength. And «حَزَّب» means to gather the people into separate groups (from the root 'najada'). And «حِزْب» (in another context) means a group in which strictness and severity are found (from 'muf'). And «حِزْب» in essence refers to a political party. And according to the Quran, there are only two major parties: one is *Hizbullah* (the Party of Allah) and the other is *Hizbush-Shaitan* (the Party of Satan). Between them, the confrontation continues at all times. And the Party of Satan further divides into many smaller factions (i.e., groups), just as during the incident of the Trench, several factions of the disbelievers had gathered together to confront. Moreover, *hizb* also means people gathered under one banner (as cited in *al-Mufradat* and *al-Qamus*).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ الۡاَحۡزَابَ لَمۡ  یَذۡہَبُوۡا ۚ وَ اِنۡ یَّاۡتِ الۡاَحۡزَابُ یَوَدُّوۡا لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ بَادُوۡنَ فِی الۡاَعۡرَابِ یَسۡاَلُوۡنَ عَنۡ اَنۡۢبَآئِکُمۡ» (33/20)\nTranslation: They think that the enemy armies have not yet departed. And if those armies were to return, they would wish that they were in the deserts among the Bedouins, so they could keep tabs on your news from there.","«حِزْب» party. Political faction.","Army","حزب","5:56-11:17-13:36-18:12-19:37-23:53-30:32-33:20-33:22-35:6-38:11-38:13-40:5-40:30-43:65-58:19-58:22",17
2511,551,"A","فِئَۃ","«فَاَیَ الرَّاْسَ فُلَانٌ» means to cut off someone's head with a sword (manjad). «فِئَۃ» refers to a military unit whose members maintain mutual contact for cooperation (muf). For example, the Quran states: «کَمۡ مِّنۡ فِئَۃٍ قَلِیۡلَۃٍ غَلَبَتۡ فِئَۃً  کَثِیۡرَۃًۢ بِاِذۡنِ  اللّٰہِ» (2/249). Translation: Often, a small group, by Allah's command, has overcome a larger group.","«فِئَۃ» A militant faction that cooperates internally.","Army","فئۃ","2:249-3:13-4:88-8:16-8:19-8:45-8:48-18:43-28:81",9
2512,551,"A","نَفِیْر","«نَفَرَ» means war or to set out on a campaign. «نَفِیْر» has two meanings: (1) people who march toward battle, and (2) a group of fewer than ten people (munjaz).","«نَفِیْر» meaning people setting out on a campaign or war.","army","نفیر","4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-17:6-46:29-18:34-46:29-72:1",11
2513,551,"A","ثُبَاتٍ","meaning such brave warriors whose attack never goes astray (Manjad)\n\nFor example, it is in the Holy Quran: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا خُذُوۡا حِذۡرَکُمۡ فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71). Translation: O you who have believed! Take your precaution and your weapons, and then go forth in companies or all together.","A small contingent of brave horsemen.","Army","ثبات","4:71",1
2514,552,"W","حَطَب","«حَطَبَ» wood that is only fit for burning. Fuel (m. l.)\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«وَّ  امۡرَاَتُہٗ ؕ حَمَّالَۃَ  الۡحَطَبِ» (111/4)\nTranslation: And Abu Lahab's wife too, who carries firewood on her head.","«حَطَبَ» Wood that is only fit for burning.","wood","حطب","72:15-111:4",2
2515,552,"W","خَشَبَ","«خَشَبَ» is wood that is usable, wood suitable for building structures. In the words of Ibn al-Faris, it is hard and thick wood. Its plural is «خُشُب» (TIMBER) (m. l.). For example: in the Quran it is mentioned:\n«کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ» (63/4)\nTranslation: As if they were wooden planks propped against a wall.","«خَشَبَ» fruitful wood.","Wood","خشب","63:4",1
2516,553,"T","خَطَّ","«خَطَّ» means drawing lines, marking them, and extending them in length. «مُخَلَّط» means lined fabric, and «خَطَّاط» means a very prolific writer (ruled). Essentially, «خَطَّ» refers merely to writing something in a lengthy manner, regardless of the script.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتَ تَتۡلُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہٖ مِنۡ کِتٰبٍ وَّ لَا تَخُطُّہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِکَ» (29/48)\nTranslation: Before this, you could not read any book, nor could you write with your right hand.","«خَطَّ» meaning drawing lines, placing marks, and elongating them in length.","to write","خط","29:48",1
2517,553,"T","سَطَرَ","«سَطَرٌ» means line, row, line of writing (mansuj). And «سَطَرَ» means to write in lines, to form lines, or to write straight lines.  \nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:  \n«وَ الۡقَلَمِ وَ مَا یَسۡطُرُوۡنَ» (68/1)  \nTranslation: By the pen and what they write.","«سَطَرَ» meaning to write by forming a continuous line, to write in a single line.","to write","سطر","17:58-33:6-52:2-68:1",4
2518,553,"T","رَقَم","«رَقَم» means adding diacritics (i.e., zabar, zer, pesh) and dots to the text. It also means to write (on cloth) to create engravings or designs. And «مِرْقَمُ» means the tool for engraving. And «مَرْقُوم» means clearly written (mansuj). And «رَقَمَ» means to write in such a manner that it is clear and in a thick script (muqaffa). For example, in the Holy Quran: «کِتٰبٌ مَّرۡقُوۡمٌ یَّشۡہَدُہُ  الۡمُقَرَّبُوۡنَ» (83:20-21) Translation: It is a book inscribed, wherein the nearest angels are present.","«رَقَم» to write in such a way that the script is clear and bold.","to write","رقم","83:9-83:20",2
2519,553,"T","کَتَبَ","«کَتَبَ» Write in a manner that is complete in conveying its meaning (example).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! When you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down.","«کَتَبَ» such a text that expresses its own meaning completely.","to write","کتب","2:79-2:178-2:180-2:183-2:187-2:216-2:246-2:282-3:53-3:154-3:181-4:66-4:77-4:81-4:127-5:21-5:32-5:45-5:83-6:12-6:54-7:145-7:156-9:51-9:120-9:121-10:21-19:79-21:105-22:4-36:12-43:19-43:80-52:41-57:27-58:21-58:22-59:3-68:47-98:3",40
2520,554,"T","اِسْتَنْسَخَ","«نَسْخُ الْکِتَاب» means copying a book, and a copy is the book from which a transcription is made. A transcribed book and «اِسْتَنْسَخَ» mean to say writing or copying (manjud) to transcribe a book letter by letter. For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «ہٰذَا کِتٰبُنَا یَنۡطِقُ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  بِالۡحَقِّ ؕ اِنَّا کُنَّا نَسۡتَنۡسِخُ مَا کُنۡتُمۡ تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (45/29). Translation: This Our Book will speak about you in truth. Indeed, We used to record all that you used to do.","«اِسْتَنْسَخَ» to give something to someone to copy or to have something written.","to have written","استنسخ","45:29",1
2521,554,"T","اَمَلَّ","«اَمَلّ» means to have something written. In such a way that one person dictates and another writes. To have written. To read aloud after writing (see details in the explanation).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لۡیُمۡلِلِ الَّذِیۡ عَلَیۡہِ الۡحَقُّ» (2/282)\nTranslation: And it should be that the person who took the loan has it written [down].","«اَمَلّ» One person speaking and the other writing.","to have written","امل","2:282-25:5",2
2522,554,"T","اِکْتَتَبَ","«اِکْتَتَبَ» means to write, to have something written, to dictate, or to request something to be written (source: Manjad). The term «اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally used in reference to false and forged writings (mufradat).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَالُوۡۤا اَسَاطِیۡرُ الۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ اکۡتَتَبَہَا فَہِیَ تُمۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ  بُکۡرَۃً   وَّ اَصِیۡلًا» (25:5)\nTranslation: And they (the disbelievers) say, These are just tales of the former people which he has had written down, and they are dictated to him morning and evening.","«اِکْتَتَبَ» is generally used for false and forged imitation.","to have written","اکتتب","25:5",1
2523,555,"T","کَاتِب","«کَاتِب» Every person who writes something is a kātib (scribe). This term is well-known and its usage is common.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ عَلٰی سَفَرٍ وَّ لَمۡ تَجِدُوۡا کَاتِبًا فَرِہٰنٌ مَّقۡبُوۡضَۃٌ» (2/283)  \nTranslation: And if (you are on a journey and) cannot find a scribe, then take a pledge or hold in possession (while taking a loan).","General: Every person who writes anything is called a scribe.","to write","کاتب","2:282-2:283-21:94-24:33-82:11",5
2524,555,"T","سَفَرَۃ","«سَفَرَۃ» is plural. «سَافِر» means a book that unveils the facts (m. l.), and «اَسْفَار» means the exegeses and interpretations of the Torah. And «سَافِر» also means a person who writes or composes such a text. The angels who record the Book of Deeds. Those who write inspired scripture.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فِیۡ  صُحُفٍ مُّکَرَّمَۃٍ مَّرۡفُوۡعَۃٍ  مُّطَہَّرَۃٍۭ بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ  بَرَرَۃٍ» (80/13-16)\nTranslation: It (the admonition) is in honored pages, raised high and pure. Written by the hands of noble and most pious scribes.","«سَفَرَۃ» writers of blessed and pure texts.","to write","سفرۃ","80:15",1
2525,556,"C","تَتْرًا","«تَتْرًا» means the arrival of one after another without any interval in between (consecutive). Tawatur and Mutawatir are well-known terms. That is, multiple can coexist simultaneously, but it is impossible for there to be a time when none exist.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا رُسُلَنَا تَتۡرَا» (23/44)\nTranslation: Then We kept sending Our messengers successively.","«تَتْرًا» consecutive. Continuous, with one following immediately after the other, such that there is no interval or pause in between.","Continuous","تترًا","23:44",1
2526,556,"C","عَلٰی فَتْرَۃٍ","«فَتَرَ» denotes the decline in the performance of an action, resulting in weakness or deficiency. (م ۔ ل ۔ مف) For example, the Holy Quran states: «یٰۤاَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ قَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ  رَسُوۡلُنَا یُبَیِّنُ لَکُمۡ عَلٰی  فَتۡرَۃٍ  مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ» (5:19). The translation is: O People of the Book, Our Messenger has come to you when the chain of the teachings of the previous messengers had become ineffective. This Messenger (peace be upon him) clarifies the divine commands for you.","«عَلٰی فَتْرَۃٍ» refers to the decline in performance or efficiency of something through continuous work, resulting in actual weakness or debilitation.","continuously","علی فترۃٍ","5:19",1
2527,556,"C","حُسُوْمًا","«حَسَمَ» means to erase the sign of something and wipe it out. And «حَسْمُ الدَّاءِ» means to inflict continuous wounds and scars, thereby erasing the wound and its mark. And «نَاَلَہٗ حُسُوْمًا» means ill omen has erased its name and sign (interpretation). And «حَسَمَ» also means to cut out from the root. «حَسَمَ الْعِرْق» means to cut a vein and cauterize it so that the bleeding stops. And «حُسُوْم» means accursed, ill-omened (manjood). It seems that in «حُسُوْم», three concepts are found: (1) pain and ill omen, (2) continuity, (3) destruction and annihilation (i.e., to erase and demolish).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَمَّا عَادٌ  فَاُہۡلِکُوۡا بِرِیۡحٍ صَرۡصَرٍ عَاتِیَۃٍ . سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبۡعَ  لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69:6,7)\nTranslation: And the people of 'Ad were destroyed by a fierce, violent, and bitterly cold wind. Allah the Almighty subjected them to it continuously for seven nights and eight days. (Had you been there) you would have seen them lying prostrate as if they were hollow trunks of date palms.\n\nIn this verse, the word «حُسُوْم» has been used in all three of its meanings.","«حُسُوْمًا» relentless calamities and misfortunes that erase one's name and reputation.","Continuous","حسومًا","69:7",1
2528,556,"C","رَدِفَ","«رَدِفَ» means to ride behind someone. And «اَرْدَفَ» means to make someone ride behind you; to come one after another; to be consecutive. And «تَرَادَفَ» means to help each other; to ride behind each other (in a line). And «اِرْدَافُ الْمُلُوْک» means the successors of kings (heirs).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «اِذۡ تَسۡتَغِیۡثُوۡنَ رَبَّکُمۡ فَاسۡتَجَابَ لَکُمۡ اَنِّیۡ مُمِدُّکُمۡ بِاَلۡفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ  مُرۡدِفِیۡنَ» (8/9) Translation: When you called upon Allah, He answered your call (and said), I will assist you with a thousand angels coming in succession.","«رَدِفَ» one after the other, while also being mutually supportive.","Continuous","ردف","8:9-27:72",2
2529,556,"C","دَاَبَ","«دَاَبَ» meaning to continuously and without interruption pursue a task with equal effort and hardship (manjada). (singular)  \nFor example, in the Quran:  \n«وَ سَخَّرَ لَکُمُ الشَّمۡسَ وَ الۡقَمَرَ دَآئِبَیۡنِ» (14/33)  \nTranslation: And He has made the sun and the moon subservient for you, both steadily pursuing their courses.","«دَاَبَ» continuous striving and perseverance.","Continuous","داب","12:47-14:33",2
2530,556,"C","مُتَتَابِع","«مُتَتَابِع» means the coming or occurring of two things in such a consecutive manner that no third thing intervenes between them (detailed).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَمَنۡ لَّمۡ  یَجِدۡ فَصِیَامُ شَہۡرَیۡنِ مُتَتَابِعَیۡنِ» (4/92)\n\nTranslation: So whoever cannot afford to free a slave must observe two consecutive months of fasting.","«مُتَتَابِع» Two similar things positioned one in front of the other with no third thing intervening between them.","Continuous","متتابع","4:92-58:4",2
2531,556,"C","وَصَّلَ","«وَصَلَ» meaning to mix and join (m-l) i.e., to mix something in such a way that it becomes ingrained. And in «وَصَّلَ», exaggeration is found. And «وَاصِلُ الشَّیء» or «وَاصِلُ بِالشَّیء» means to do with persistence (manjada).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ وَصَّلۡنَا لَہُمُ الۡقَوۡلَ لَعَلَّہُمۡ یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (28/51)\nTranslation: And We repeatedly sent to them (words of) guidance so that they might take heed.","«وَصَّلَ» is to join one thing with another in such a way that they become intertwined so completely that no possibility of separation or pause remains.","Continuous","وصل","2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3",18
2532,557,"R","رَجَعَ","It means the return of something to its beginning, its origin. Whether that thing is living or non-living, a statement or an action. Moreover, in this return, the intention of the one returning may or may not be involved (detailed). A famous saying is «کُلُّ شَیْءٍ یَرْجِعْ اِلٰی اَصْلِہٖ», meaning Everything returns to its origin. Thus, the usage of this term is general in every respect.\n\nFor instance, the Holy Quran states: «الَّذِیۡنَ اِذَاۤ  اَصَابَتۡہُمۡ مُّصِیۡبَۃٌ   ۙ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا لِلّٰہِ وَ  اِنَّاۤ اِلَیۡہِ رٰجِعُوۡنَ» (2/156).  \nTranslation: These are the people who, when afflicted with a calamity, say, 'Indeed, we belong to Allah, and to Him we shall return.'\n\nAnd «اَرْجَعَ» means to return.\n\nFor example, the command of Allah, the Most High, is: «وَ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ تُرۡجَعُ  الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (2/210).  \nTranslation: And all matters are returned to Allah.","«رَجَعَ» the return of something to its origin.","Return","رجع","2:18-2:28-2:196-2:210-2:245-2:281-3:55-3:72-3:83-3:109-5:48-5:105-6:36-6:60-6:108-6:164-7:150-7:168-7:174-8:44-9:83-9:94-9:122-10:4-10:23-10:46-10:56-10:70-11:4-11:34-11:123-12:46-12:50-12:62-12:63-12:81-19:40-20:40-20:86-20:89-20:91-21:13-21:35-21:58-21:64-21:95-22:76-23:99-23:115-24:28-24:64-27:28-27:35-27:37-28:39-28:70-28:88-29:8-29:17-29:57-30:11-30:41-31:15-31:23-32:11-32:12-32:21-33:13-34:31-35:4-36:22-36:31-36:50-36:67-36:83-37:68-39:7-39:44-40:77-41:21-41:50-43:28-43:48-43:85-45:15-46:27-50:3-56:87-57:5-57:13-60:10-63:8-67:3-67:4-86:8-86:11-89:28-96:8",98
2533,557,"R","اٰبَ","«اٰبَ» This is more specific than «رَجَعَ». And it applies only to the living.  \n«مَاٰب» means 'reference', 'place of return', 'abode' (singular: 'manjad').  \nAnd «اَیَاب» means 'to return', 'to go back', or 'a return journey'.  \nAnd «ذِھَاب و اِیَاب» means 'to go and return'.  \n«اٰبَ» does not necessarily entail the intention of the one returning.  \n\nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اِنَّ  اِلَیۡنَاۤ  اِیَابَہُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِنَّ  عَلَیۡنَا حِسَابَہُمۡ» (88:25,26)  \nTranslation: Indeed, they will return to Us.  \n\nAnd when this verb takes the intensive form, such as «اٰوَبَ» and «اَوَّبَ», then the intention of the one returning is also included.  \n«اَوَّاب» means 'the one who returns', 'the one who turns back at every moment'.  \n\nFor example: The divine command states:  \n«فَاِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِلۡاَوَّابِیۡنَ غَفُوۡرًا» (17:25)  \nTranslation: Indeed, Allah is Forgiving to those who turn to Him.","«اٰبَ» is turning away from a living being, whether unintentionally or intentionally.\n«اَوَّبَ» is frequently resorting to a living being with one's own intention.","Return","اب","17:25-38:17-38:19-38:30-38:44-50:32-88:25",7
2534,557,"R","تَابَ","«تَابَ» meaning to turn away from sinful deeds. To confess one's sin and resolve not to repeat it. To repent (fig.), and if it is directed towards Allah, it means He accepts repentance. It also means forgiving sins or being merciful.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِلَّا الَّذِیۡنَ تَابُوۡا وَ اَصۡلَحُوۡا وَ بَیَّنُوۡا فَاُولٰٓئِکَ اَتُوۡبُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ۚ وَ اَنَا التَّوَّابُ الرَّحِیۡمُ» (2/160)\nTranslation: But those who repent and reform their conduct and clearly expound the truth, I will accept their repentance, and I am the Accepting of repentance, the Merciful.","«تَابَ» repentance from sinful deeds.","Return","تاب","2:37-2:54-2:128-2:160-2:187-2:222-3:89-3:90-3:128-4:16-4:17-4:18-4:26-4:27-4:64-4:92-4:146-5:34-5:39-5:71-5:74-6:54-7:153-9:5-9:11-9:15-9:27-9:74-9:102-9:104-9:106-9:117-9:118-9:126-11:3-11:52-11:61-11:90-11:112-13:30-16:119-19:60-20:82-20:122-24:5-24:10-24:31-25:70-25:71-28:67-33:24-33:73-40:3-40:7-42:25-49:12-58:13-66:4-66:8-73:20-85:10-110:3",62
2535,557,"R","اَنَاب","«نَابَ اِلَیْہِ»: meaning to repeatedly turn to someone. And «نَوْبَۃ» meaning turn, occasion, opportunity. And «اَنَاب» meaning to be a deputy, to stand in. And «اَنَابَ اِلَی اللہ» meaning to repeatedly turn to and return to Allah (source: Munjid).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«رَبَّنَا عَلَیۡکَ تَوَکَّلۡنَا وَ اِلَیۡکَ اَنَبۡنَا» (60/4)\nTranslation: Our Lord, we place our trust in You alone, and to You we turn.","to keep returning again and again","Return (to Allah)","اناب","13:27-31:15-38:24-38:34-39:17-60:4",6
2536,557,"R","بَاءَ","The basic meanings of «بَوْء» are two: (1) to return, and (2) to be equal (for example), i.e., to return in a state where the recompense of their deeds appears before them. This is generally used in a negative sense, meaning to return from a good state to a bad state.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it says: «وَ بَآءُوۡ بِغَضَبٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ  ؕ ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ کَانُوۡا یَکۡفُرُوۡنَ بِاٰیٰتِ اللّٰہِ وَ یَقۡتُلُوۡنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ بِغَیۡرِ الۡحَقِّ» (2:61). Translation: And they returned with the wrath of Allah upon them. This is because they used to deny the signs of Allah and kill the prophets unjustly. That is, their state was such that they became deserving of being seized in God's wrath.","«بَاءَ» to revert to a bad state.","Return to Allah","باء","2:61-2:90-3:112-3:162-8:16",5
2537,557,"R","فَاءَ","«فَاء» means to return to a good state (detailed explanation), i.e., to reform oneself. And to return from a bad state to a good one. And it also means to return from close proximity (jurisprudential interpretation 249). For example: in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَاتِلُوا الَّتِیۡ تَبۡغِیۡ  حَتّٰی تَفِیۡٓءَ  اِلٰۤی  اَمۡرِ اللّٰہِ» ( 49/9 )\nTranslation: Fight the group that commits aggression until they return to the command of Allah.","«فَاء» Returning to a favorable state. Returning from a state of nearness.","Return","فاء","2:226-33:50-49:9-59:6-59:7",5
2538,557,"R","صَدَرَ","«صَدَرَ» means to return after quenching one's thirst from a well or waterhole. And «اَصْدَر» means to return after drinking water. They say «صَدَرَتِ الْاِبِلُ مِنَ الْمَاءِ», i.e., the camel returns after drinking water.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23)  \nTranslation: Both girls said, We cannot give water until the shepherds have taken their turn and brought back their animals.  \n\nAnd the opposite of «صَدَرَ» is «وَرَدَ». That is, to arrive at the well to draw water (for drinking). And «وِرْدُ» means both the well itself and also a thirsty person. And «وَارِد» means the person who goes to the well or waterhole to fetch water.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ فَاَدۡلٰی دَلۡوَہٗ» (12/19)  \nTranslation: And a caravan came and sent their water-drawer. He let down his bucket (into the well).","«صَدَرَ» To return from a riverbank or well after quenching one's thirst.","reversion","صدر","28:23-99:6",2
2539,557,"R","صَارَ","There are two basic meanings of «صَیْر»: (1) return/reference, and (2) outcome/end (for details on the latter, see the explanation). It means to return for the last time, to go back, or to refer.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَلَاۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ  تَصِیۡرُ الۡاُمُوۡرُ» (42/53)\n\nTranslation: Observe, all matters return to Allah alone.","«صَارَ» the final return","Return","صار","2:126-2:285-3:28-3:162-4:97-4:115-5:18-8:16-9:73-14:30-22:48-22:72-24:42-24:57-25:15-31:14-35:18-40:3-42:15-42:53-48:6-50:43-57:15-58:8-60:4-64:3-64:10-66:9-67:6",29
2540,557,"R","رَدَّ ، اِرْتَدَّ","«رَدّ» means to return something because it is unacceptable. It also means rejected. For example, in the Quran: «وَ لَمَّا فَتَحُوۡا مَتَاعَہُمۡ وَجَدُوۡا بِضَاعَتَہُمۡ رُدَّتۡ  اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (12/65) Translation: And when they opened their baggage, they found their money returned to them.\n\nAnd «اِرْتَدَّ» means to step back or return oneself because something is unacceptable. For example, the divine declaration says: «اِنَّ  الَّذِیۡنَ ارۡتَدُّوۡا عَلٰۤی  اَدۡبَارِہِمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَعۡدِ مَا تَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمُ  الۡہُدَی» (47/25) Translation: Those who turned their backs and went away after the path of guidance became clear.\n\nThen the usage of «رَدّ» and «اَرْتَدّ» became common, so they also began to mean merely to return and to be returned. For example, the divine declaration says: «فَلَمَّاۤ  اَنۡ جَآءَ الۡبَشِیۡرُ اَلۡقٰىہُ عَلٰی وَجۡہِہٖ فَارۡتَدَّ بَصِیۡرًا» (12/96) Translation: When the bearer of good news came, he placed the shirt on Jacob's face, and he regained his sight.","«رَدَّ» To return (something) because it is unacceptable; to not accept.  \n«اِرْتَدَّ» To retreat from something on account of its being unacceptable.","reversion","رد ، ارتد","2:85-2:109-2:217-2:228-3:100-3:149-4:47-4:59-4:83-4:86-4:91-5:21-5:54-5:108-6:27-6:28-6:62-6:71-6:147-7:53-9:94-9:101-9:105-10:30-11:76-12:65-12:96-12:110-13:11-14:9-14:43-16:70-17:6-18:36-18:64-18:87-21:40-22:5-27:40-28:13-30:43-33:25-38:33-40:43-41:47-42:44-42:47-47:25-62:8-79:10-95:5",51
2541,557,"R","اِنْقَلَبَ","«قَلَبَ» means to reverse the direction or state. To turn the upper part down and the lower part up. To turn the outer part in and the inner part out. And «اِنْقَلَبَ» means to undergo such a change in one's state or direction that is opposite to the original form. To be reversed. To turn back. To revert (as in *manjad*).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«سَیَحۡلِفُوۡنَ بِاللّٰہِ لَکُمۡ اِذَا انۡقَلَبۡتُمۡ اِلَیۡہِمۡ» (9:95)\nTranslation: When you return to them, they will swear oaths to you by Allah.","«اِنْقَلَبَ» complete reversal of state or condition.","Return","انقلب","2:143-2:144-3:127-3:144-3:149-3:174-3:196-5:21-6:110-7:119-7:125-9:48-9:95-12:62-16:46-18:18-18:36-22:11-24:37-24:44-26:50-26:219-26:227-29:21-33:66-40:4-43:14-47:19-48:12-67:4-83:31-84:9",32
2542,557,"R","اَفَاضَ","«فَاضَ الْمَاءَ» means water gushing forth from a place. And «اَفَاضَ الْاِنَاءَ» means filling a vessel to the brim so that water begins to overflow from the top. By drawing a metaphor from this overflowing of water, this term is also applied to crowds of people flowing like the current of a river (detailed).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199)\nTranslation: Then depart from the place from whence the other people depart.","«اَفَاضَ» to be swept away swiftly. To come flowing continuously.","Return to Allah","افاض","2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8",6
2543,557,"R","ھَادَ ( ھَوَّد )","«ھَادَ» means to turn with gentleness. And «ھَوَّد» means to walk and crawl with slowness and gentleness (as in a metaphorical sense). And «ھَادَ» also means to turn towards the truth. And «ھَادَ فِی الْمَنْطِق» means to speak with gentleness and slowness, and ھَوَّدَ means to gradually raise the voice in the throat, to hum, to proceed slowly and with pauses (as in the context of recitation). Thus, the meaning of «ھَادَ» is to turn towards the truth with gentleness and gradually.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اکۡتُبۡ لَنَا فِیۡ ہٰذِہِ الدُّنۡیَا حَسَنَۃً  وَّ  فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ   اِنَّا ہُدۡنَاۤ   اِلَیۡکَ» (7/156)\nTranslation: And write for us [good] in this world and in the Hereafter. Indeed, we have turned to You.","Gradually and gently return.","reversion","ھاد ( ھود )","7:156",1
2544,558,"P","لَوْح مَحْفُوْظ","The literal meaning of «لَوْح مَحْفُوْظ» is only the Preserved Tablet. Its complete comprehension, that is, intellectual understanding, is beyond human capacity; however, through traditions, it is known that it is a tablet or book in which all matters concerning the destiny of the universe are written beforehand, and there is no alteration in them. In the Quranic verses, the illumination regarding its various names is as follows:\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«بَلۡ ہُوَ  قُرۡاٰنٌ  مَّجِیۡدٌ فِیۡ  لَوۡحٍ مَّحۡفُوۡظٍ» (85:21-22)\nTranslation: Rather, it is a Glorious Quran, (inscribed) in the Preserved Tablet.","«لَوْح مَحْفُوْظ» The Preserved Tablet is the tablet upon which the decree of the entire universe (divine knowledge) is inscribed. From this knowledge, Allah the Pure grants as much as He wills to whom He wills. The Preserved Tablet is protected from the interference of creation. Nothing can be stolen from it, nor can it be altered.","Preserved Tablet","لوح محفوظ","85:22",1
2545,558,"P","اُمُّ الْکِتَاب","«اُمُّ الْکِتَاب» refers to the Holy Quran, as it is the source of all divine commands, decrees, and words of God. For example, the Holy Quran states:\n\n«اِنَّا جَعَلۡنٰہُ  قُرۡءٰنًا عَرَبِیًّا  لَّعَلَّکُمۡ تَعۡقِلُوۡنَ وَ اِنَّہٗ  فِیۡۤ  اُمِّ الۡکِتٰبِ لَدَیۡنَا لَعَلِیٌّ حَکِیۡمٌ» (43:3,4)\n\nTranslation: Indeed, We have made it an Arabic Quran, so that you may understand. And indeed, it is, in the Mother of the Book, with Us, sublime and full of wisdom.\n\nBy stating that it is in the Mother of the Book, the Holy Quran clarifies an important truth: that for the guidance of different nations and peoples in various eras, Allah Almighty revealed different scriptures to different prophets. In all of them, the invitation to the same creed was given. The standard of good and evil is one, and the principles of morality and civilization are identical. That is, the religion has remained one.\n\nAs for the Shariah (divine law), the matter pertains to changes in the legal rulings according to circumstances and conditions, regarding which the following divine guidance is provided:\n\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ   ۚ ۖ وَ عِنۡدَہٗۤ   اُمُّ   الۡکِتٰبِ» (13:39)\n\nTranslation: Allah eliminates what He wills or confirms, and with Him is the Mother of the Book.\n\nThis verse indicates that the record of changes and alterations in divine rulings across different times is also preserved in that Book.","«اُمُّ الْکِتَاب» refers to the Noble Quran, as it is the source of all divine commands, decrees, and words.","Preserved Tablet","ام الکتاب","3:7-13:39-43:4",3
2546,558,"P","اِمَامٌ مُبِیْن","«اِمَامٌ مُبِیْن» It is called the Preserved Tablet because everything is already written in it beforehand.\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ اَحۡصَیۡنٰہُ  فِیۡۤ   اِمَامٍ  مُّبِیۡنٍ» (36:12)\nTranslation: And We have recorded everything in the Clear Record (the Preserved Tablet).","«اِمَامٌ مُبِیْن» is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that everything is already inscribed in it.","Preserved Tablet","امام مبین","36:12",1
2547,558,"P","کِتَابٌ مَّکْنُوْن","«کِتَابٌ مَّکْنُوْن» It is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that the details of what is inscribed in it are known to none except Allah Almighty.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّہٗ   لَقُرۡاٰنٌ   کَرِیۡمٌ فِیۡ  کِتٰبٍ مَّکۡنُوۡنٍ» (56/77,78)  \nTranslation: This is a highly exalted Quran, written in the Preserved Book.  \nFrom this verse, it is understood that the details of what is inscribed in it are known to none besides Allah, not even to Gabriel (peace be upon him), who is the means through which revelation is conveyed to the prophets.","«کِتَابٌ مَّکْنُوْن» This is the Preserved Tablet in the sense that no one besides Allah has any knowledge of the details of what is inscribed in it.","Preserved Tablet","کتاب مکنون","56:78",1
2548,559,"S","عَبْد","«عَبْد» means servant, slave, servitude; expressing humility and submission. And the word «عَبَادَۃ» is stronger than ‘abudiyat, meaning to express extreme humility and submission. And worship is solely for God. Although, in terms of subjugation, all creation is Allah’s ‘abd, i.e., servant and slave. However, Allah Almighty designates that servant as «عَبْد» who, by his own choice, becomes His sincere servant. And this choice is only for humans and jinn. The plural of «عَبْد» can be «عِبَاد» or «عَبِیْد». And another meaning of «عَبْد» is to become a slave of something. It is used metaphorically, such as ‘abdud-dirham and ‘abdud-dinar, meaning slave or devotee of wealth and money, or ‘abdut-taghut, and «عَبْد» also means to be someone’s slave, whether acquired by purchase, inheritance, or as spoils of war. And its opposite is «حُرّ», meaning free. And «عَبَّدَ» means to enslave another person.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَلۡحُرُّ بِالۡحُرِّ وَ الۡعَبۡدُ بِالۡعَبۡدِ وَ الۡاُنۡثٰی بِالۡاُنۡثٰی» (2/178)\nTranslation: Free for free (will be killed), slave for slave, and woman for woman.","«عَبْد» meaning slave.","slave","عبد","2:23-2:90-2:178-2:186-2:207-2:221-3:15-3:20-3:30-3:79-4:118-4:172-5:118-6:18-6:61-6:88-7:32-7:128-7:194-8:41-9:104-10:107-12:24-14:11-14:31-15:40-15:42-15:49-16:2-16:75-17:1-17:3-17:5-17:17-17:30-17:53-17:65-17:96-18:1-18:65-18:102-18:110-19:2-19:30-19:61-19:63-19:93-20:77-21:26-21:105-23:109-24:32-25:1-25:17-25:58-25:63-26:22-26:52-27:15-27:19-27:59-28:82-29:56-29:62-30:48-34:9-34:13-34:39-35:28-35:31-35:32-35:45-36:30-37:40-37:74-37:81-37:111-37:122-37:128-37:132-37:160-37:169-37:171-38:17-38:30-38:41-38:44-38:45-38:83-39:7-39:10-39:16-39:17-39:36-39:46-39:53-40:15-40:31-40:44-40:48-40:85-42:19-42:23-42:25-42:27-42:52-43:15-43:19-43:59-43:68-44:18-44:23-50:8-50:11-53:10-54:9-57:9-66:10-71:27-72:19-76:6-89:29-96:10",123
2549,559,"S","اَمَۃ","«اَمَۃ» is the feminine form of «عَبْد». It means 'concubine'. This word is also used in all the contexts in which «عَبْد» is used. And the plural of «اَمَۃ» is «اِمَاء».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَنۡکِحُوا الۡاَیَامٰی مِنۡکُمۡ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ مِنۡ عِبَادِکُمۡ وَ اِمَآئِکُمۡ» (24/32)\nTranslation: And marry the widows among you and the righteous among your male and female slaves...\nAnother instance where the Almighty says:\n«وَ لَاَمَۃٌ مُّؤۡمِنَۃٌ  خَیۡرٌ مِّنۡ مُّشۡرِکَۃٍ  وَّ لَوۡ اَعۡجَبَتۡکُمۡ» (2/221)\nTranslation: And a believing female slave is better than a polytheist woman, even if she pleases you.","«اَمَۃ» means slave girl.","Slave","امۃ","2:221-24:32",2
2550,559,"S","رَقَبَۃ","«رَقَبَۃ» means the neck or the back part of the body. And «رَقَبَ» means to put a rope or noose around someone's neck. Arabs generally, when they say «جُزْءُ اشَرْف», intend the general meaning of a slave. Thus, «رَقَبَۃ» is understood to mean a slave, because the noose of slavery is around his neck. Its plural is «رِقَاب». (Maf, Manjad) And the word «رَقَبَۃ» is used equally for both masculine and feminine, i.e., for both a male slave and a female slave.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ ذَوِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ  وَ ابۡنَ السَّبِیۡلِ  ۙ وَ السَّآئِلِیۡنَ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ» (2/177)\nTranslation: And those who spend their wealth, despite their love for it, on relatives, orphans, the needy, the traveler, and those who ask (for help), and (spend) in (the emancipation of) necks (i.e., freeing slaves). (Jalandhari)","«رَقَبَۃ» a male or female slave, by any means, may come into one's possession.","Servant","رقبۃ","4:92-5:89-58:3-90:13",4
2551,559,"S","مِلْک یمین","«یَمِیْن» means the right hand or the right side. Since strength and capability are generally manifested through the hands, and among the hands, the right hand is superior and better than the left, therefore, by uttering the word «یَمِیْن», a human being is specifically intended. Just as the Arabs, by saying «جُزْءُ اشَرْف», intend to refer to everything in general. And «مِلْک» means that thing over which someone has both possession and control. And «مِلْک یَمِیْن» is every thing over which someone has possession and control, but in common usage, this term is also mostly applied to a female slave or a male slave who is obtained as a share of war booty after a battle.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (4/24)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess...","A female or male slave acquired as war booty.","Slave","ملک یمین","4:3-4:24-4:25-4:36-16:71-23:6-24:31-24:33-24:58-30:28-33:50-33:52-33:55-70:30",14
2552,560,"T","اَخَذَ","«اَخَذَ» means to take something, to encompass, or to seize. Its usage is both sensory (i.e., something perceived through one of the five senses) and spiritual.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِذۡ اَخَذَ اللّٰہُ مِیۡثَاقَ النَّبِیّٖنَ» (3:81)\nTranslation: And when Allah, the Most High, took a covenant from the prophets.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«وَ لَمَّا سَکَتَ عَنۡ  مُّوۡسَی الۡغَضَبُ  اَخَذَ الۡاَلۡوَاحَ» (7:154)\nTranslation: And when the anger of Moses subsided a little, he took up the tablets.","«اَخَذَ» meaning to acquire something, to encompass, to catch.","to take","اخذ","2:48-2:55-2:63-2:83-2:84-2:93-2:206-2:229-2:255-2:260-2:267-3:11-3:81-3:160-3:187-4:20-4:21-4:71-4:89-4:91-4:102-4:118-4:153-4:154-4:161-5:12-5:14-5:41-5:70-6:42-6:44-6:46-6:70-7:31-7:73-7:78-7:91-7:94-7:95-7:96-7:130-7:144-7:145-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:169-7:171-7:172-7:199-8:52-8:68-8:70-9:5-9:50-9:103-9:104-10:24-11:56-11:64-11:67-11:94-11:102-12:76-12:78-12:79-12:80-13:32-15:73-15:83-16:46-16:47-16:113-18:77-18:79-19:12-19:78-19:87-20:21-20:39-20:94-22:44-22:48-23:41-23:64-23:76-24:2-26:189-28:40-29:14-29:37-29:40-33:7-33:61-34:51-35:26-36:49-38:44-40:5-40:21-40:22-41:17-43:48-44:47-48:15-48:19-48:20-51:16-51:40-51:44-54:42-55:41-57:8-57:15-59:7-69:10-69:30-69:45-73:16-79:25",121
2553,560,"T","تَلَقّٰی","«لَقِیَ» means to meet. «تَلَقَّی الشَّیْء» means to meet and to receive (as in 'to welcome'). That is, the meaning of «تَلَقّٰی» is to go and take something after meeting it.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«لَا یَحۡزُنُہُمُ الۡفَزَعُ الۡاَکۡبَرُ وَ تَتَلَقّٰہُمُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ» (21:103)  \nTranslation: On that day, the distress will not grieve the righteous, and the angels will come to receive them.","to take it after reaching","to take","تلقی","3:143-21:103-24:15-50:17",4
2554,560,"T","ھَاءُمْ ( ھوء )","«ھَاءُمْ» This is a verbal noun. Meaning «خُذْ» take or seize—only the imperative form is used. And its conjugation comes as follows: «ھَاءُمْ ۔ ھَاءُمَا ۔ ھَاءُ مُوْا» (sing.) And according to the author of Munjed, the word «ھَا» also means to take, «ھَا الْکِتَاب» meaning take the book. And «ھَاءَ ، ھَوء» also has this same meaning. And «ھَاءُ یَا رَجُل» meaning O man, take the book. (Munjed) It appears this word is used to call someone, bring them close, and demand that they take something.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «فَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ  بِیَمِیۡنِہٖ ۙ فَیَقُوۡلُ ہَآؤُمُ اقۡرَءُوۡا کِتٰبِیَہۡ» (69/19) Translation: So the one whose record of deeds will be given in his right hand will say, Take and read my record of deeds.","To summon a person and demand the taking of a thing.","to take","ھاءم ( ھوء )","69:19",1
2555,561,"F","تَدَایَنَ","«دَیْن» means a loan. Credit (see details under credit). And «تَدَایَنَ» means to borrow from one another. To engage in credit transactions (manjud).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا تَدَایَنۡتُمۡ بِدَیۡنٍ اِلٰۤی اَجَلٍ مُّسَمًّی فَاکۡتُبُوۡہُ» (2/282)\n\nTranslation: O you who have believed, when you contract a debt for a specified term, write it down.","«تَدَایَن» is used for hand-to-hand transactions, while «اَدَارَ» is used for credit transactions.","financial transactions","تداین","2:282",1
2556,561,"L","اَدَارَ","«دَوْر ، دَارَ» means to revolve or circulate. And «اَدَارَہٗ» means to cause to circulate or turn. And «اَدَارَ الشَّیْء» means to take and give something, i.e., to exchange.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تَکُوۡنَ تِجَارَۃً حَاضِرَۃً  تُدِیۡرُوۡنَہَا بَیۡنَکُمۡ» (2/282)\nTranslation: Yes, if the transaction is hand-to-hand, then you may exchange among yourselves (there is no need to write it down).","«اَدَارَ» meaning to rotate. to revolve.","Lending and borrowing","ادار","2:282",1
2557,562,"T","ضَرَبَ","Generally, its meaning «ب» is to strike someone with a hand or another object. And after 'silah' «ب», the thing mentioned is that with which one is struck, i.e., the instrument of striking. The word is commonly used for striking (f l 188). For example, in the Quran it says: «فَقُلۡنَا اضۡرِبۡ بِّعَصَاکَ الۡحَجَرَ» (2/60) Translation: So We said to Moses, Strike the rock with your staff.","«ضَرَبَ» to hit someone with a hand or some other thing.","to kill","ضرب","2:60-2:61-2:73-3:112-4:34-7:160-8:12-8:50-26:63-37:93-38:44-47:4-47:27",13
2558,562,"T","وَکَزَ","«وَکَزَ» To strike with the fist. And according to the master of linguistic jurisprudence, makka marna means to strike the chest or side with the palm of the hand (f.l 188).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَوَکَزَہٗ  مُوۡسٰی فَقَضٰی عَلَیۡہِ» (28/15)\nTranslation: So Moses (peace be upon him) punched him, which caused his death.","«وَکَزَ» conquering Mecca.","to strike","وکز","28:15",1
2559,562,"T","صَکَّ","«صَکَّ» means the forceful collision of two things, producing a sound. «صَکَّ الْبَابَ» means the collision of a door's valve (m. l.) and also means to strike on the face, to slap, to strike the face (f. l. 188).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَصَکَّتۡ وَجۡہَہَا وَ قَالَتۡ عَجُوۡزٌ  عَقِیۡمٌ» (51/29)\nTranslation: She (the woman) slapped her face and said, What! An old woman, and barren? (Shall I bear a son?)","«صَکَّ» Slapping one's hand over one's mouth.","to beat","صک","51:29",1
2560,562,"T","دَعَّ","«دَعَّ» to repulse. To repel forcefully (F L 188). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (107/2). Translation: Thus, such a man repulses the orphan.","«دَعَّ» to push and shove","to kill; to slay; to hit/strike","دع","52:13-107:2",2
2561,562,"T","دَمَغَ","«دَمَغَ» meaning to strike someone on the head or mind (figurative).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«بَلۡ نَقۡذِفُ بِالۡحَقِّ عَلَی الۡبَاطِلِ فَیَدۡمَغُہٗ» (21/18)\nTranslation: Rather, We hurl the truth against falsehood, and it destroys it.","«دَمَغَ» to deal a blow to","to hit","دمغ","21:18",1
2562,562,"T","رَجَمَ","«رَجَمَ» To throw stones or pebbles at someone from a distance. And to stone someone by throwing stones at them from a distance. Stoning. It is used in both meanings. And it is used in both material and spiritual senses. «رَجْمًا بِالْغَیْب» (18/22) Also means throwing stones without aiming, and also speaking on the basis of conjecture (suspicion) (m. q.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ لَا رَہۡطُکَ لَرَجَمۡنٰکَ» (11/91)\nTranslation: If it were not for the esteem of your tribe, we would have stoned you.","«رَجَمَ» to pelt with stones from a distance; to stone.","to kill","رجم","11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20",6
2563,562,"T","وَقَذَ","«وَقَذَ» meaning to strike severely with a stick or stone until one dies. And «وَقْذ» meaning a severe strike (مف). And «وَقَذَ» meaning lethal, i.e., a blow that causes destruction (منجد).","to deliver a severe blow with a stick or stone","to strike","وقذ","5:3",1
2564,562,"T","نَطَحَ ( الثور )","«نَطَحَ» to strike with a bull's horn. «تَنَاطَعَ الْکَبْشَان» rams butting each other. And «نَطِیْح» meaning struck by a horn. An animal that died from being gored (manjad), for example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ وَ الۡمُتَرَدِّیَۃُ وَ النَّطِیۡحَۃُ» (5/3)\nTranslation: Any animal that dies by strangulation, by a violent blow, by falling, or by being gored (all these are forbidden to you).","«نَطَحَ» to gore some animal.","to strike","نطح ( الثور )","5:3",1
2565,562,"T","جَلَدَ ۔ جِلْد","«جَلَدَ» collectively is «جُلُوْد». Meaning: skin. Leather. And «جَلَدَ» means to strike on leather. And «جَلْدَۃً» means refuse or garbage, whose striking effect is confined to the skin and does not cause a wound. To strike with lashes (detailed).  \nFor example: In the Quran it says:  \n«اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ» (24/2)  \nTranslation: Whether a man or a woman, strike each one of them with a hundred lashes.","meaning to litter","to beat","جلد ۔ جلد","24:2-24:4",2
2566,562,"T","مَاتَ","«مَاتَ» means death, and its opposite «حَیَات» means life. «مَاتَ» means the loss of soul or power from a living being (m. l.), the separation of soul from the body. To die. In any form that it may occur.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا وَ مَاتُوۡا وَ ہُمۡ کُفَّارٌ» (2/161)\nTranslation: Those who disbelieved and died while they were disbelievers.\n\nAnd «اَمَات» means to cause someone else to die; to end their life.\n\nFor example: The divine declaration is:\n«ثُمَّ یُمِیۡتُکُمۡ ثُمَّ یُحۡیِیۡکُمۡ ثُمَّ  اِلَیۡہِ تُرۡجَعُوۡنَ» (2/28)\nTranslation: Then He will cause you to die, then He will give you life, then to Him you will be returned.","«مَاتَ» signifies the soul's separation from the body. It is a common concept.","To strike","مات","2:28-2:161-2:258-2:259-3:91-3:144-3:156-6:122-6:162-7:158-9:84-9:116-9:125-10:56-15:23-17:75-22:58-22:66-23:80-26:81-30:40-40:68-44:8-45:21-45:26-47:34-50:43-53:44-57:2-80:21",30
2567,562,"T","قَتَلَ","«قَتَلَ» means to overpower one living being over another and end its life. And in the words of Ibn Faris, it means to kill someone in a state of humiliation (m. l).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ  اَقَتَلۡتَ نَفۡسًا  زَکِیَّۃًۢ بِغَیۡرِ  نَفۡسٍ» (18/74)\nTranslation: Moses (peace be upon him) said to Khidr, Have you killed a pure soul without retribution?\n\nAnd «قَتَّلَ» means to kill someone by inflicting pain and causing harm.\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ سَنُقَتِّلُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ نَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (7/127)\nTranslation: Pharaoh said, I will kill your sons and spare your women.","«قَتَلَ» to kill someone unjustly, and «قَتَّل» to strike down in a brutal manner.","to beat","قتل","2:54-2:61-2:72-2:85-2:87-2:91-2:154-2:178-2:191-2:217-2:251-3:21-3:112-3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:181-3:183-3:195-4:29-4:66-4:74-4:89-4:91-4:92-4:93-4:155-4:157-5:27-5:28-5:30-5:32-5:33-5:70-5:95-6:137-6:140-6:151-7:127-7:141-7:150-8:17-8:30-9:5-9:111-12:9-12:10-17:31-17:33-18:74-20:40-22:58-25:68-26:14-28:9-28:19-28:20-28:33-29:24-33:16-33:26-33:61-40:25-40:26-40:28-47:4-51:10-60:12-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4",77
2568,562,"T","ھَلَکَ","«ھَلَکَ» means to perish/annihilate. It applies to both living and non-living things. In the context of a living being, it signifies dying a helpless death. In the words of Ibn Faris, «یَدُلُّ عَلٰی کَسْرٍ وَّ سَقُوْطٍ ( م ل )» means to die a bad/tragic death; to die as a result of an accident.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ  وَلَدٌ» (4/176)\nTranslation: If a person dies and has no children...\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«کُلُّ  شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ  اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» (28/88)\nTranslation: Everything is perishable/annihilated except His Face/Being.\n\nAnd the meaning of «اَھْلَکَ» is to cause someone to meet such a bad or helpless death; to destroy; to annihilate.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ  اَہۡلَکَنِیَ  اللّٰہُ  وَ مَنۡ مَّعِیَ» (67/28)\nTranslation: Say, 'Have you seen: if Allah were to destroy me and those with me...'","«ھَلَکَ» (annihilation), to die a death of helplessness, also applies to non-living things.","to strike","ھلک","2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6",63
2569,562,"T","صَلَبَ","«صَلَبَ» means to hang on the cross or to crucify. And Salib (cross) refers to that wooden structure on which a criminal is crucified after being made to ascend it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا قَتَلُوۡہُ وَ مَا صَلَبُوۡہُ وَ لٰکِنۡ شُبِّہَ لَہُمۡ» (4:157)\nTranslation: They neither killed nor crucified him, but it was made to appear so to them.\n\nAnd «صَلَّبَ» means to hang someone upside down to inflict additional torment or to cause extra suffering during crucifixion.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«فَلَاُقَطِّعَنَّ  اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ وَ اَرۡجُلَکُمۡ مِّنۡ خِلَافٍ وَّ لَاُصَلِّبَنَّکُمۡ فِیۡ جُذُوۡعِ النَّخۡلِ» (20:71)\nTranslation: (Pharaoh said to the believing magicians) I will cut off your hands and feet from opposite sides and hang you on the trunks of palm trees.","«صَلَبَ» To hang on the cross and then strike/kill.\n«صَلَّبَ» To torture and then hang on the cross.","to strike","صلب","4:157-5:33-7:124-12:41-20:71-26:49",6
2570,562,"T","ذَبَّحَ","«ذَبَحَ» means to sacrifice an animal according to Shariah, to shed blood. And «ذَبَّحَ» means to kill by causing pain or to exaggerate in the act of killing (from *manjad*). In this sense, «ذَبَّحَ» and «قَتَّلَ» become synonymous terms.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یُذَبِّحُ اَبۡنَآءَہُمۡ وَ یَسۡتَحۡیٖ نِسَآءَہُمۡ» (28/4)\nTranslation: Pharaoh used to slaughter the sons of the Israelites and keep their daughters alive.","to harm bit by bit through intermittent injuries","to stone","ذبح","2:49-2:67-2:71-5:3-14:6-27:21-28:4-37:102-37:107",9
2571,562,"T","رَجَمَ","The meaning of «رَجَمَ» is to throw stones or similar objects from a distance, or to throw stones at someone and beat them to death. And «رَجَم» is one of Allah's prescribed limits, meaning that a married adulterer, whether male or female, is to be executed by stoning. This is known as stoning to death. For example, the Quran states: «لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ تَنۡتَہِ لَاَرۡجُمَنَّکَ» (19/46) Translation: (Azar said to Ibrahim) If you do not desist, I will stone you to death.","«رَجَمَ» to stone to death; to kill by repeatedly throwing stones.","to strike","رجم","11:91-18:20-18:22-19:46-36:18-44:20",6
2572,562,"T","اِنْخَنَقَ","«خَنَقَ» means to strangle or suffocate, and «خِنَاق» is the term for the rope or cord used for strangling. «خُنَّاق» refers to the disease in which the throat constricts and breathing becomes difficult (as mentioned in Munjid). «خَنَقَ» also means to strangle severely to the point of death (as cited in Maqata). «مُنْخَنِقٌ» denotes the animal that dies due to throat constriction.\n\nFor example: the Quran states:\n«وَ الۡمُنۡخَنِقَۃُ وَ الۡمَوۡقُوۡذَۃُ» (5:3)\nTranslation: And that which dies by strangulation, and that which is killed by a violent blow... (all of these are forbidden).","«اِنْخَنَقَ» suffocation of a living being.","to strike","انخنق","5:3",1
2573,562,"T","تَوَفّٰی","The word «وَفٰی» denotes the conclusion and completion of something (M. L.), and the meaning of «تَوَفّٰی» is to take the soul out of the body upon the completion of life's term, to seize it, and this act is performed by Allah or by His appointed angels. Therefore, in this sense, it cannot be attributed to a human being or any other living creature.\n\nFor example, the divine decree states:\n«تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ  بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (12/101)\n\nTranslation: (O Allah!) Cause me to die as a Muslim [in a state of submission], and join me with the righteous [in the Hereafter].","«تَوَفّٰی» to complete the term of life, to take the soul from the body, and this is solely the work of Allah, the Most High, or His angels.","to strike","توفی","2:234-2:240-2:281-3:55-3:161-3:185-3:193-4:15-4:97-5:117-6:60-6:61-7:37-7:126-8:50-10:46-10:104-12:101-13:40-16:28-16:32-16:70-16:111-22:5-32:11-39:42-40:67-40:77-47:27-83:2",30
2574,562,"T","شَھَادَت","«شَھِدَ» means to bear witness. This testimony may be 'ayni (i.e., eyewitness) or from the heart, and both «شَاھِدْ» and «شَھِیْد» come in the meanings of a witness. Furthermore, the word «شَھِیْد» is also used for one who gives his life for the exaltation of the Word of Truth in the path of Allah. And in this sense, martyrdom (shahadat) is also giving one's life in the path of Allah, because the belief in the Hereafter and reward and punishment becomes so firm that he gives his life to bear witness to it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاُولٰٓئِکَ مَعَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنَ النَّبِیّٖنَ وَ الصِّدِّیۡقِیۡنَ وَ الشُّہَدَآءِ وَ الصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (4/69)\nTranslation: So they will be with those upon whom Allah has bestowed favor, meaning the Prophets, the Siddiqeen (the truthful), the Shuhada (the martyrs), and the righteous.","to die in the cause of Allah «شَھَادَت»","to kill","شھادت","2:23-2:84-2:133-2:143-2:185-2:204-2:282-3:18-3:52-3:64-3:70-3:81-3:86-3:99-3:140-4:6-4:15-4:69-4:135-4:166-5:8-5:44-5:111-6:19-6:130-6:144-6:150-7:37-7:172-9:107-11:54-12:26-12:81-18:51-19:37-21:61-22:28-22:78-24:2-24:4-24:6-24:8-24:13-24:24-25:72-27:32-27:49-36:65-39:69-41:20-41:21-41:22-43:19-43:86-46:10-57:19-59:11-63:1-65:2-83:21",60
2575,563,"W","مَال ( مول )","Among the rural populace, this term is applied to livestock, as it constitutes their primary asset. They say «خَرَجَ اِلٰی مَالِہٖ», meaning he went towards his property or camels. And «رَجُلٌ مَالٌ» denotes a very wealthy person. And «مَالَ یَمُوْلُ» signifies being wealthy. And «تَمَوُّل» conveys the meaning of amassing wealth, acquiring it, or becoming extremely affluent. And «مَیِّل» denotes great wealth. And «مُوَیْل» signifies a modest amount of wealth (minimal). And «اَمْوَال», and in common parlance, the term 'مال' (mal) is applied either to cash, currency, tangible assets and wealth, or to merchandise that is capable of being bought and sold.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«اَنَّمَا الۡحَیٰوۃُ  الدُّنۡیَا لَعِبٌ وَّ لَہۡوٌ وَّ زِیۡنَۃٌ  وَّ تَفَاخُرٌۢ  بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ تَکَاثُرٌ فِی الۡاَمۡوَالِ وَ الۡاَوۡلَادِ» (57:20)\nTranslation: The life of this world is merely diversion and play, and an adornment, and a cause for boasting among you, and a rivalry in wealth and children.","«مَال» refers to cash, currency, liquid assets and wealth, and any item that can be converted into cash.","Wealth","مال ( مول )","2:155-2:177-2:188-2:247-2:261-2:262-2:264-2:265-2:274-2:279-3:10-3:116-3:186-4:2-4:5-4:6-4:10-4:24-4:29-4:34-4:38-4:95-4:161-6:152-8:28-8:36-8:72-9:20-9:24-9:34-9:41-9:44-9:55-9:69-9:81-9:85-9:88-9:103-9:111-10:88-11:29-11:87-17:6-17:34-17:64-18:34-18:39-18:46-19:77-23:55-24:33-26:88-27:36-30:39-33:27-34:35-34:37-47:36-48:11-49:15-51:19-57:20-58:17-59:8-61:11-63:9-64:15-68:14-69:28-70:24-71:12-71:21-74:12-89:20-90:6-92:11-92:18-104:2-104:3-111:2",80
2576,563,"W","دَوْلَۃ","« دَوْل ، دَالَ» is the opposite of «دَارَ ، دَوْر». And the words «دَوْر» and دائرہ refer to tight-fistedness, bad conditions, and the cycle of days. And «دَوْلَۃ» and «دُوْلَۃ» refer to the return of prosperous days after bad days (مف). And «دَاوَل» means bringing prosperous days to people alternately or repeatedly. And «دَوْلَۃ» is that thing which keeps coming to people in turns—today it may be for someone, and tomorrow for another (منجد). As the proverb goes: wealth flows like shade. And in the view of political masters, «دَوْلَۃ» means king, ministers, government, governance, state (منجد).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «کَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ  دُوۡلَۃًۢ  بَیۡنَ الۡاَغۡنِیَآءِ مِنۡکُمۡ» (59/7). Translation: So that (the wealth) does not circulate solely among the wealthy among you.","Return to the era of prosperity.","Wealth","دولۃ","59:7",1
2577,563,"W","رِزْق","The fundamental meaning of «رِزْق» is sustenance, or anything that serves as a means for the training and reform of a human being, whether from a spiritual or physical perspective. (مف) Materially, its meaning is that which reaches the stomach and becomes nourishment. «رِزْق» also signifies 'fortune' or 'destined lot'. Furthermore, «مَرْزُوْق» means 'fortunate' (منجد), and «رُزِقْتُ عِلْمًا» means 'knowledge was granted to me'. Then, «رِزْق» is also used for anything that becomes a cause of spiritual or physical nourishment for a person. In this sense, rain is also «رِزْق».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ فِی السَّمَآءِ  رِزۡقُکُمۡ» (51:22)\nTranslation: Meaning, Indeed, your provision is in the sky.\n\nAnd «رَزَقَ» means to provide sustenance or nourishment, to feed and sustain, or to give some wealth and property. «رَزَّاق» Ultimately, this is solely from the essence of Allah, but the act of feeding and sustaining can also be attributed to others.\n\nFor example, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِذَا حَضَرَ الۡقِسۡمَۃَ  اُولُوا الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنُ فَارۡزُقُوۡہُمۡ  مِّنۡہُ وَ قُوۡلُوۡا لَہُمۡ  قَوۡلًا مَّعۡرُوۡفًا» (4:8)\nTranslation: And when the distribution of inheritance takes place, if relatives, orphans, or the needy are present, give them something from it and speak to them in a kind manner.","«رِزْق» Every such thing that constitutes physical or spiritual provision, or its cause.","Wealth","رزق","2:3-2:22-2:25-2:57-2:60-2:126-2:172-2:212-2:233-2:254-3:27-3:37-3:169-4:5-4:8-4:39-5:88-5:114-6:140-6:142-6:151-7:32-7:50-7:160-8:3-8:4-8:26-8:74-10:31-10:59-10:93-11:6-11:88-12:37-13:22-13:26-14:31-14:32-14:37-16:56-16:67-16:71-16:72-16:73-16:75-16:112-16:114-17:30-17:31-17:70-18:19-19:62-20:81-20:131-20:132-22:28-22:34-22:35-22:50-22:58-24:26-24:38-27:64-28:54-28:57-28:82-29:17-29:60-29:62-30:28-30:37-30:40-32:16-33:31-34:4-34:15-34:24-34:36-34:39-35:3-35:29-36:47-37:41-38:54-39:52-40:13-40:40-40:64-42:12-42:19-42:27-42:38-45:5-45:16-50:11-51:22-51:57-56:82-63:10-65:3-65:7-65:11-67:15-67:21-89:16",105
2578,563,"W","خَیْر","«خَیْر» means goodness and everything that is considered good by all. Wealth, in its essence, is also good, and for Allah Almighty to bestow wealth upon someone is a tremendous blessing, because through its proper use and expenditure in accordance with Shariah injunctions, a person can acquire much goodness and virtue.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قُلۡ مَاۤ اَنۡفَقۡتُمۡ  مِّنۡ خَیۡرٍ فَلِلۡوَالِدَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبِیۡنَ وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ ابۡنِ‌السَّبِیۡلِ» (2/215)\nTranslation: Say, 'Whatever you spend in charity, it is for the parents, the near relatives, the orphans, the needy, and the travelers.'\n\nHowever, the love of wealth is deeply ingrained in human nature.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«وَ اِنَّہٗ  لِحُبِّ الۡخَیۡرِ  لَشَدِیۡدٌ» (100/8)\nTranslation: Indeed, man is ever greedy and clingy to wealth.\n\nThus, when a person neglects the distinction between lawful and unlawful earnings or fails to spend according to Shariah regulations, this very wealth—which is entirely good in itself—becomes a trial and a test for him.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَنَّمَاۤ اَمۡوَالُکُمۡ  وَ اَوۡلَادُکُمۡ  فِتۡنَۃٌ» (8/28)\nTranslation: And know that your wealth and your children are but a trial.","«خَیْر» the better aspect of wealth, meaning wealth that is acquired and spent in accordance with Islamic law.","Wealth","خیر","2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8",170
2579,563,"W","اَفَاء","«فیء» is the wealth that comes into the possession of Muslim mujahideen without fighting. That is, if the disbelievers opt for retreat before fighting, whatever is acquired from their properties is fay. And «اَفَاء» means to grant someone the fay wealth.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مَاۤ  اَفَآءَ  اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی رَسُوۡلِہٖ  مِنۡ  اَہۡلِ الۡقُرٰی  فَلِلّٰہِ  وَ لِلرَّسُوۡلِ وَ  لِذِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ ابۡنِ السَّبِیۡلِ» (59:7)\nTranslation: Whatever (wealth) the people of the towns have acquired without fighting, which Allah has bestowed upon His Messenger, is for Allah and His Messenger, and for the near relatives, the orphans, the needy, and the wayfarer.","«فَیء» wealth that comes into the possession of Muslim mujahideen without fighting.","Wealth","افاء","33:50-59:6-59:7",3
2580,563,"W","مَغَانِم","«غَنَم» means a flock of sheep. And «اَلْغَنَمُ» means acquiring or obtaining livestock from somewhere. Then this word began to be applied to any wealth obtained from an enemy or a non-enemy. And the plural of it is «مَغَانِم». It means spoils of war. And in the technical Islamic terminology, ghanimah or «مَغْنَم» refers specifically to wealth obtained as a result of achieving victory over an enemy. For previous nations, such wealth was considered unlawful, but in the Sharia of Muhammad ﷺ, Allah the Almighty has made it permissible.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَکُلُوۡا مِمَّا غَنِمۡتُمۡ حَلٰلًا طَیِّبًا» (8:69)\nTranslation: So consume whatever you have obtained as spoils of war, for it is lawful and good for you.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High states:\n«تَبۡتَغُوۡنَ عَرَضَ الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا ۫ فَعِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ مَغَانِمُ کَثِیۡرَۃٌ» (4:94)\nTranslation: You desire the goods of this world, while Allah has abundant spoils of war [in the Hereafter].","«مَغَانِم» wealth obtained after victory over the enemy.","Wealth","مغانم","4:94-6:146-8:41-8:69-20:18-21:78-48:15-48:19-48:20",9
2581,563,"P","اَنْفَال","«نَفَل» means spoils of war, gift, forgiveness, excess, and its plural is «اَنْفَال». And «نَفْل» means work beyond the obligatory and essential duties (manajid). The term «اَنْفَال» is also applied to the spoils of war and to the «اَنْفَال» properties. This word specifically indicates that these properties are an additional grant from Allah Almighty to the Ummah of Muhammad (peace be upon him), which was not permissible for the previous nations.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ عَنِ الۡاَنۡفَالِ ؕ قُلِ الۡاَنۡفَالُ لِلّٰہِ وَ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (8:1)\nTranslation: They ask you, [O Muhammad], about the spoils of war. Say, The spoils of war belong to Allah and the Messenger.","The term «اَنْفَال» refers to wealth and possessions acquired in battle against disbelievers, which is also known as war booty.","Possessions","انفال","8:1",1
2582,564,"M","مَالِک","«مِلْک» refers to anything that is in someone's possession, with no other party having the right to intervene or exercise authority over it (as defined in Islamic jurisprudence). And «مَالِک» denotes one who holds absolute possession and authority over something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«مٰلِکِ یَوۡمِ الدِّیۡنِ» (1/3)\nTranslation: He is the Owner of the Day of Judgment.","«مَالِک» the one vested with the authority of possession and disposal.","Master","مالک","1:3-3:26-36:71",3
2584,564,"M","اَھْل","«اَھْل» means family, relatives, and also means household, family members, wife and children. And «اَھْلَ الرَّجُل» means wife, and «اَھَلَ الرَّجُل» means to marry (contract marriage). And «اَھْل» also means people of the same lineage or faith (interpretation). And «اَھْل» also means household members as well as the house itself (see 'house'). And in the following verse, the Quran has used the word 'أَهْل' to refer to the master of the house. For example, in the Quran it is: «فَانۡکِحُوۡہُنَّ بِاِذۡنِ اَہۡلِہِنَّ» (4/25). Translation: Therefore, marry those slave women with the permission of their owners.","«اَھْل» the people of the house, the house, and the owner of the house.","Master","اھل","2:196-2:126-2:217-3:121-4:25-4:35-4:58-4:75-4:92-5:89-6:131-7:83-7:94-7:100-7:123-10:24-11:40-11:45-11:46-11:81-11:117-12:26-12:62-12:65-12:88-12:93-15:65-18:71-18:77-19:16-19:55-20:10-20:29-20:132-21:76-21:84-23:27-24:27-26:169-26:170-27:7-27:34-27:49-27:57-28:4-28:15-28:29-28:59-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-35:43-36:50-37:76-37:134-38:43-39:15-42:45-48:11-48:12-48:26-51:26-52:26-66:6-75:33-83:31-84:9-84:13",69
2585,565,"M","وَالِدَۃ","«وَالِدَۃ» The woman who has given birth is a mother. This word is used in a limited and specific sense. And when the mention of both mother and father is intended, the word walīdayn (parents, dual masculine) is used. Its plural is «وَالِدَات».\nFor example: In the Noble Qur'an it is stated:\n«وَ الۡوَالِدٰتُ یُرۡضِعۡنَ اَوۡلَادَہُنَّ حَوۡلَیۡنِ کَامِلَیۡنِ» (2/233)\nTranslation: And mothers should breastfeed their children for two full years.","«وَالِدَۃ» The woman who has given birth to a child.","Mother","والدۃ","2:233-5:110-19:32",3
2586,565,"M","اُمّ","The word «اُمّ» is used in a very broad sense. «اُمّ» means both a biological mother and every thing that becomes the cause for the existence, origination, or reform and upbringing of something else. The word «اُمّ» is used in the following contexts:\n\n(1) In the sense of a biological mother: For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَوۡحَیۡنَاۤ  اِلٰۤی اُمِّ مُوۡسٰۤی اَنۡ  اَرۡضِعِیۡہِ» (28/7)\nTranslation: And We inspired the mother of Moses, saying, Suckle him...\n\n(2) Just as the word «اَبْ» is used for a father, grandfather, and ancestors beyond, similarly the word «اُمّ» is also used. Just as Prophet Adam (peace be upon him) is the father of mankind, similarly Hawwa (Eve) is the mother of mankind.\n\n(3) Meaning 'origin' or 'root'. Such as *Umm al-Kitab* (13/39), meaning the Original Book or the Preserved Tablet. And «اُمُّ الْقُرٰی» (6/92), meaning the central city or, metaphorically, the city of Makkah. Also, «اُمّ الخبائث» meaning 'wine', and *Umm al-Amradh* meaning 'constipation'. *Umm al-Tariq* meaning 'the main road'. And *Umm al-Nujum* meaning 'the galaxy'.\n\n(4) And as a title of honor and respect. For example, the divine declaration states:\n«اَلنَّبِیُّ  اَوۡلٰی بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ مِنۡ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ وَ اَزۡوَاجُہٗۤ  اُمَّہٰتُہُمۡ» (33/6)\nTranslation: The Prophet is closer to the believers than themselves, and his wives are their mothers.\n\n(5) As a *kunya* (honorific nickname). Then in this *kunya*, sometimes there is a clear connection, like «اُم اَرْبَع وَ اَرْبَعِیْن», and sometimes there is not even a weak connection, like naming a newborn girl *Umm Kulthum*. However, the Quran does not mention such a *kunya*.","The term «اُمّ» signifies a biological mother.","Mother","ام","3:7-4:11-4:23-5:17-5:75-5:116-6:92-7:150-13:39-16:78-19:28-20:38-20:40-23:50-24:61-28:7-28:10-28:13-31:14-33:4-33:6-39:6-42:7-43:4-46:15-53:32-58:2-80:35-101:9",29
2587,566,"T","طَلَبَ","«طَلَبَ الشَّیْ» means to ask for something (m. q.) and also signifies to strive or make an effort for something (f. l. 239). «طِلْب» and «طِلْبَۃ» mean the thing that is asked for (manjud) and the act of searching and striving to obtain something (muf). This word is used in all the meanings of asking, desiring, and searching. And it represents the initial state of asking.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ضَعُفَ الطَّالِبُ وَ الۡمَطۡلُوۡبُ» (22/73)\n\nTranslation: Both the seeker and the sought are weak.","«طَلَبَ» being greedy for a particular need and seeking it.","to supplicate","طلب","7:54-18:41-22:73",3
2588,566,"T","سَاَلَ","The word «سَاَلَ» comes in two meanings: (1) to ask someone for something in order to receive an answer; (2) to request from someone a necessary thing, i.e., to make a request for wealth or some other necessity. And «سُؤْل» means a need for which the soul is eager and which is also expressed verbally (Mufradat).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِہۡبِطُوۡا مِصۡرًا فَاِنَّ لَکُمۡ مَّا سَاَلۡتُمۡ» (2/61)\nTranslation: Then go out to the city. Then whatever you have requested will be given to you there.","«سَاَلَ» The self's greed for some need and its expression to someone else.","to supplicate","سال","2:61-2:108-2:119-2:134-2:141-2:186-2:189-2:215-2:217-2:219-2:220-2:222-2:273-4:32-4:153-5:4-5:101-5:102-6:90-7:6-7:163-7:187-8:1-8:12-9:65-10:72-10:94-11:29-11:46-11:47-11:51-12:50-12:82-12:104-14:34-15:92-16:43-16:56-16:93-17:85-17:101-18:70-18:76-18:83-20:105-20:132-21:7-21:13-21:23-21:63-23:72-23:113-25:57-25:59-26:109-26:127-26:145-26:164-26:180-28:78-29:13-29:61-29:63-31:25-33:8-33:20-33:53-33:63-34:25-34:47-36:21-38:86-39:38-42:23-43:9-43:19-43:44-43:45-43:87-47:36-47:37-51:12-52:40-55:29-55:39-60:10-67:8-68:46-70:1-70:10-75:6-79:42-102:8",93
2589,566,"T","اِدَّعَ","«دَعَا» means to ask, to call upon, or to supplicate. And an emphasis (mubalagha) is found in «اِدَّعَ», meaning to call upon and ask for something (emphatically).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَہُمۡ فِیۡہَا فَاکِہَۃٌ  وَّ لَہُمۡ مَّا یَدَّعُوۡنَ» (36:57)\nTranslation: And for them in Paradise will be fruits, and whatever they ask for will also be available.","«اِدَّعَ» the nafs being covetous of a need and crying out for it.","to supplicate","ادع","36:57-41:31-67:27",3
2590,566,"T","حَفَا","«حَفَو» means to exert excessive effort in seeking something, to strive and search intensely (cf. m.l.).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنۡ  یَّسۡئَلۡکُمُوۡہَا  فَیُحۡفِکُمۡ  تَبۡخَلُوۡا» (47/37)\nTranslation: If the Prophet were to ask you for wealth and press you for it, you would become stingy.\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«یَسۡئَلُوۡنَکَ کَاَنَّکَ حَفِیٌّ عَنۡہَا» (7/187)\nTranslation: They ask you about the Hour as if you are constantly pursuing it.","«حَفَو» the self's greed for a need and demand for it.","to supplicate","حفا","7:187-19:47-47:37",3
2591,566,"T","اِعْتَرَّ","«عَرّ» and «اِعْتَرّ» both convey the same meaning, namely seeking forgiveness and presenting oneself for it (detailed). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اَطۡعِمُوا الۡقَانِعَ وَ الۡمُعۡتَرَّ» (22/36). Translation: And feed from the sacrifice's meat those who do not ask and those who ask.","«اِعْتَرَّ» meaning to come before people to ask for forgiveness.","to supplicate","اعتر","22:36",1
2592,567,"T","طَمَسَ","«طَمَسَ» To rub and erase in such a way that some effects remain. «طَمَس» The word is generally used for the eyes, stars, and the face. The «طَمَس» of the eyes and stars is that they become dim (lose their light), and the «طَمَس» of the face is that it becomes disfigured (i.e., deformed).  \nFor example: The Holy Quran states:  \n«اٰمِنُوۡا بِمَا نَزَّلۡنَا مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا مَعَکُمۡ مِّنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ نَّطۡمِسَ وُجُوۡہًا» (4/47)  \nTranslation: Believe in what We have sent down, confirming that which is with you, before We obliterate your faces (i.e., erase your eyes, noses, etc.) and turn them backwards.  \nAt another place, the Divine Command states:  \n«فَاِذَا النُّجُوۡمُ  طُمِسَتۡ» (77/8)  \nTranslation: When the stars are obliterated (lose their light).","«طَمَسَ» to erase in such a way that some traces remain.","to erase","طمس","4:47-10:88-36:66-54:37-77:8",5
2593,567,"T","مَحَقَ","«مَحَقَ» means to weaken and render something sluggish; to nullify; to make fruitless and lifeless (Majma‘ al-Bayan), and «مَحَقَ» also signifies to be inferior and to decrease (Mafatih al-Ghayb). Its opposite is « رَبْواً» or «رَبِّی», meaning to nurture, rear, and cause to grow.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَمۡحَقُ اللّٰہُ الرِّبٰوا وَ یُرۡبِی الصَّدَقٰتِ» (2/276)\n\nTranslation: Allah eradicates usury and increases charity.","«مَحَقَ» to extinguish the force of something and render it lifeless.","to erase / to wipe out","محق","2:276-3:141",2
2594,567,"E","مَحُو","«مَحُو» is to erase something in such a way that even its traces do not remain. They say «مَحَتِ الرِّیْحُ السَّحَابَ». The wind carried away the clouds, meaning even the name and trace of the clouds did not remain. And its opposite is «اَثْبَتَ», meaning to preserve.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَمۡحُوا اللّٰہُ مَا یَشَآءُ وَ یُثۡبِتُ» (13:39)\nTranslation: Allah (SWT) erases whatever He wills and preserves whatever He wills.","«مَحُو» to end so that no trace remains.","efface","محو","13:39-17:12",2
2595,567,"T","نَسَخَ","«نَسَخَ» means to annul, to invalidate, to abrogate, to erase (manjūd), and also means to replace one thing with another after eliminating the first (muf). The first thing that is eliminated or erased is called mansūkh (abrogated), and the second that replaces it is called nāsikh (abrogating). Sometimes this word is used merely in the sense of elimination or erasure.\n\nFor example, in the Noble Quran it is:\n«فَیَنۡسَخُ اللّٰہُ مَا یُلۡقِی الشَّیۡطٰنُ ثُمَّ  یُحۡکِمُ  اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ» (22:52)\nTranslation: So Allah eliminates what the Shaytan casts and establishes His verses.\n\nAnd sometimes it also comes in the sense of terminating or eliminating the first thing and bringing another in its place.\nFor example, the Divine proclamation states:\n«مَا نَنۡسَخۡ مِنۡ اٰیَۃٍ اَوۡ نُنۡسِہَا نَاۡتِ بِخَیۡرٍ مِّنۡہَاۤ  اَوۡ مِثۡلِہَا» (2:106)\nTranslation: Whatever verse We abrogate or cause to be forgotten, We replace it with a better or similar one.","«نَسَخَ» to erase something and replace it with another thing.","To erase; to efface; to wipe out.  \n\n(In Islamic/Quranic contexts, it often refers to Allah wiping away sins or errors.)","نسخ","2:106-22:52",2
2596,568,"S","تُرَاب","«تُرَاب» means dust. Dry soil without moisture (Surah 31:30) that is blown about by the wind. It is a common term for soil.\n\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«وَ یَقُوۡلُ الۡکٰفِرُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ  کُنۡتُ تُرٰبًا» (78/40)\nTranslation: And the disbeliever will say, Oh, I wish I had been dust.","«تُرَاب» is a general term for dry soil and all kinds of soil.","Soil","تراب","2:264-3:59-13:5-16:59-18:37-22:5-23:35-23:82-27:67-30:20-35:11-37:16-37:53-40:67-50:3-56:47-78:40",17
2597,568,"S","طِیْن","«طِیْن» means wet clay but without straw (Fussilat 31). Even if its moisture, i.e., wetness, is removed, this dry clay is still called «طِیْن». For example, the Noble Quran states:  \nTranslation: And Allah has created man from dry clay (like that of) pottery.","«طِیْن» meaning wet soil but without straw.","Soil","طین","3:49-5:110-6:2-7:12-17:61-23:12-28:38-32:7-37:11-38:71-38:76-51:33",12
2598,568,"S","لَازِب","«لَازِب» refers to soil that sticks to the hand (munjad), i.e., sticky and adhesive soil (F.L. 268).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ لَّازِبٍ» (37:11)  \nTranslation: We have created them from sticky clay.  \n\nIn the above verse, the term «لَازِب» does not appear merely as an attribute of «طِیْن». Rather, the meaning of «لَازِب» itself is sticky and adhesive soil, as the reference indicates.","«لَازِب» sticky and adhesive soil.","Soil","لازب","37:11",1
2599,568,"S","حَمَاٍ","«حَمَأ» means putrid mud. When the mud begins to turn blackish and emits a foul odor (fl 268). «حَمَا الْبِئْرَ» He took out rotten black soil from the well. And «حَمَاَ الْمَاء» means water mixed with black soil (m. q).","«حَمَأ» a black, rotten, fetid morass.","Soil","حماٍ","15:26-15:28-15:33",3
2600,568,"S","صَلْصَال","When black, foul-smelling mud becomes completely dry and emits a sound upon being struck or beaten, it is *salsal* (ف ل 168).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ مِّنۡ حَمَاٍ مَّسۡنُوۡنٍ» (15/26)\nTranslation: And We created man from a clay that rings when struck.\n\nIn another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)\nTranslation: He created man from clay like pottery that emits a sound.","«صَلْصَال» dry crackling hessian.","soil","صلصال","15:26-15:28-15:33-55:14",4
2601,568,"S","فَخَّار","«فَخَّار» means baked clay—clay that has been fired and rings when struck, or pottery made from such material. And «فَخَّارِی» means a potter, who forms clay vessels and then fires them in a kiln to finish or sell them. Human creation ultimately came from just such clay.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«خَلَقَ الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ صَلۡصَالٍ کَالۡفَخَّارِ» (55/14)  \nTranslation: He created man from sounding clay like pottery.","«فَخَّار» baked clay that clinks or rings.","soil","فخار","55:14",1
2602,568,"S","صَعِیْد","«صَعَدَ» means to ascend. And «صَعِیْد» means the upper part of the earth, i.e., the top portion and the dust/dirt that rises upon it (Muf). Every flat surface of the earth is «صَعِیْد» (Fal 16), and it also means «وَجْہُ الْاَرْض», i.e., the upper soil of the earth and the dust/dirt, etc. (M. L).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n« فَلَمۡ  تَجِدُوۡا مَآءً فَتَیَمَّمُوۡا صَعِیۡدًا طَیِّبًا» (5/6)\n\nTranslation: Then if you do not find water, perform tayammum with clean earth.","«صَعِیْد» meaning the upper part of the earth, i.e., the region above, and the dust and particles present on it that ascend.","Soil","صعید","4:43-5:6-18:8-18:40",4
2603,568,"S","سُلَالَۃ","«سُلَالَۃ» meaning: essence, extract, effective part, something extracted (from something).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ سُلٰلَۃٍ  مِّنۡ طِیۡنٍ» (23/12)\nTranslation: And We created man from an extract of clay.","«سُلَالَۃ» meaning summary, essence, useful part, something extracted from a thing.","Soil","سلالۃ","23:12-32:8",2
2604,568,"S","ثَرٰی","«ثَرٰی» the wet and sticky soil of the earth's deepest layer (pp. 31, 167)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَہٗ مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ  وَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ وَ مَا بَیۡنَہُمَا وَ مَا  تَحۡتَ الثَّرٰی» (20/6)\nTranslation: Owner of all things in the heavens and the earth, and what is between them, and what is beneath the soil.","«ثَرٰی» the wet and muddy soil of the earth's deepest stratum.","Soil","ثری","20:6",1
2605,569,"C","بَاشَر","«بَشَرَ» meaning to peel the skin. «بَشَرَۃ» meaning the outer side of the skin. And «بَاشَرَ» meaning one body's skin touching another body's skin. «بَاشَرَ الْمَرَاۃ» meaning to have intercourse (from 'manjad').\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تُبَاشِرُوۡہُنَّ وَ اَنۡتُمۡ عٰکِفُوۡنَ  ۙ فِی الۡمَسٰجِدِ» (2/187)\nTranslation: And do not have intercourse with women while you are in retreat in the mosques.","«بَاشَر» meaning the skin of one body touching the skin of another.","Congregational prayer","باشر","2:187",1
2606,569,"C","قَضٰی وَطَرًا","«وَطَر» means necessity and important requirement (abbr.), and «قَضٰی وَطَرًا» means fulfilling the need. For example, the Quran states: «فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا» (33:37). Translation: Then when Zaid had fulfilled his need.","«قَضٰی وَطَرًا» meaning to fulfill a need.","Compilation","قضی وطرًا","33:37",1
2607,569,"C","تَغَشّٰی","meaning to cover one thing with another. For example: In the Quran it is stated: «فَلَمَّا تَغَشّٰہَا حَمَلَتۡ حَمۡلًا خَفِیۡفًا» (7/189) Translation: Then when the man covered the woman, a faint trace of pregnancy remained with her.","«تَغَشّٰی» meaning covering one thing with another.","Congregation","تغشی","7:189",1
2608,569,"C","رَفَثَ","«رَفَثَ» Every such speech in the expression of which shame is felt (for example), meaning to be explicit. This includes talking about intercourse and matters related to that act.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اُحِلَّ لَکُمۡ لَیۡلَۃَ الصِّیَامِ الرَّفَثُ اِلٰی نِسَآئِکُمۡ» (2/187)\nTranslation: It has been made lawful for you to have sexual relations with your wives during the nights of Ramadan.","«رَفَثَ» Any speech that is shameful to express.","Compilation","رفث","2:187-2:197",2
2609,569,"C","مَسَّ","«مَسَّ» meaning to touch something or for something to come into bodily contact (figurative).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«قَالَتۡ رَبِّ اَنّٰی یَکُوۡنُ لِیۡ وَلَدٌ وَّ لَمۡ یَمۡسَسۡنِیۡ بَشَرٌ» (3/47)  \nTranslation: Maryam said, O my Lord! How shall I have a son when no man has touched me?","«مَسَّ» to touch something or to come into contact with something.","Congregation","مس","2:80-2:214-2:236-2:237-2:275-3:24-3:47-3:120-3:140-3:174-5:73-6:7-6:17-6:49-7:73-7:95-7:188-7:201-8:68-10:12-10:21-10:107-11:10-11:48-11:64-11:113-12:88-15:48-15:54-16:53-17:67-17:83-19:20-19:45-20:97-21:46-21:83-24:14-24:35-26:156-30:33-33:49-35:35-36:18-38:41-39:8-39:49-39:61-41:49-41:50-41:51-50:38-54:48-56:79-70:20-70:21",56
2610,569,"C","لَامَسَ","«لَمَسَ» means to touch something with the fingers, or to search with the fingers or another part of the body (detailed). For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «اَوۡ لٰمَسۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ» (4/43). Translation: Or you have had sexual relations with women.","«لَامَسَ» meaning to feel or examine something with the fingers.","Congregation","لامس","4:43-5:6",2
2611,569,"C","طَمَثَ","«طَمَث» means menstrual blood (Fall 115), and «طَمِثَ یَطْمِثُ» also signifies a woman being in her menstrual state (Manjad) and a man removing the barrier of a woman's private parts (Muf). It appears this term is specifically used for the first act of intimacy (intercourse) with someone.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«لَمۡ یَطۡمِثۡہُنَّ اِنۡسٌ قَبۡلَہُمۡ وَ لَا جَآنٌّ» (55/74)\nTranslation: Neither has any human touched them before, nor any jinn.","«طَمَثَ» refers to menstrual blood.","Congregation","طمث","55:56-55:74",2
2612,569,"C","قَرُبَ","«قَرُبَ» meaning: to be near, to go to.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ لَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» (2/222)  \nTranslation: Do not approach them until they are pure.  \n\nFor to force, see زبردستی کرنا.  \nFor to be compelled, see بے قرار ہونا.","«قَرُبَ» meaning to be near.","Congregation","قرب","2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28",36
2613,570,"C","مَجْلِس","«مَجْلِس» The gathering is its «مَجَالِس». Every place where several people sit together for some purpose. The term مجلس (majlis) is a well-known word for gatherings during events in homes. (F L 32. 272) For example: The Quran states:\n«اِذَا  قِیۡلَ  لَکُمۡ تَفَسَّحُوۡا فِی  الۡمَجٰلِسِ فَافۡسَحُوۡا» (58/11)\nTranslation: When you are asked to make room in the assemblies, then make room.","When the members of a household or close friends gather and sit together.","Council","مجلس","58:11",1
2614,570,"A","نَادِی","«نَادِی» gatherings of people where the occupation is conversation and storytelling (F 272): clubs, assemblies, places of amusement, centers of obscenity; and «اَلنَّدْوَۃ» meaning welfare and well-being: places for national or religious consultation. (F 32)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَاۡتُوۡنَ فِیۡ نَادِیۡکُمُ الۡمُنۡکَرَ» (29/29)\nTranslation: And you commit in your meetings what is disapproved of.","«نَادِی» specific venues such as clubs, gatherings, or entertainment spots where activities typically frowned upon in social settings are often pursued.","Assembly","نادی","29:29-96:17",2
2615,571,"L","حَبَّ ، مَحَبَۃً","«حُبّ» means to consider something good, intend it, desire it, and pursue its attainment with wisdom (Faq l 99), whether it be regarding women and children or wealth and property. And «حَبَّ» and «حَبَّۃ» refer to grain (such as wheat or barley, etc.). And «حَبَّۃُ الْقَلْب» means heartfelt love (Muf).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«فَقَالَ  اِنِّیۡۤ  اَحۡبَبۡتُ حُبَّ الۡخَیۡرِ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ  رَبِّیۡ ۚ حَتّٰی تَوَارَتۡ بِالۡحِجَابِ» (38/32)\nTranslation: Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him) said, I have preferred the love of wealth over the remembrance of my Lord, until the sun was veiled [or set].\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ اَلۡقَیۡتُ عَلَیۡکَ مَحَبَّۃً مِّنِّیۡ» (20/39)\nTranslation: And (O Moses, peace be upon him!) I have cast My love upon you.","«حُبّ» to intend and desire something.","Love","حب ، محبۃً","2:165-2:177-2:190-2:195-2:205-2:216-2:222-2:276-3:14-3:31-3:32-3:57-3:76-3:92-3:119-3:134-3:140-3:146-3:148-3:152-3:159-3:188-4:36-4:107-4:148-5:13-5:18-5:42-5:54-5:64-5:87-5:93-6:76-6:141-7:31-7:55-7:79-8:58-9:4-9:7-9:24-9:108-12:8-12:30-12:33-14:3-16:23-16:107-20:39-22:38-24:19-24:22-28:56-28:76-28:77-30:45-31:18-38:32-41:17-42:40-49:7-49:9-49:12-57:23-59:9-60:8-61:4-61:13-75:20-76:8-76:27-89:20-100:8",73
2616,571,"L","وَدَّ","«وَدَّ» means to desire something, to befriend, to love (manjada), and this word sometimes comes only in the meanings of desiring and wishing (faqal 99).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«رُبَمَا یَوَدُّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا لَوۡ کَانُوۡا مُسۡلِمِیۡنَ» (15/2)\nTranslation: At some time, the disbelievers will wish that they had been Muslims.\nAnd when it is used in the meanings of love, then the utmost love is intended.\n«مَؤَدَۃْ» means mutual love and affection, compassion. And «وَدُوْد» means one who loves much. And «وُدّ» comes in the meanings of love and affection (muf).\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ عَمِلُوا الصّٰلِحٰتِ سَیَجۡعَلُ  لَہُمُ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وُدًّا» (19/96)\nTranslation: And those who believe and do righteous deeds, Allah will create love for them (in the hearts of His creation).\nAt another instance, the command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«اِنَّ  رَبِّیۡ  رَحِیۡمٌ   وَّدُوۡدٌ» (11/90)\nTranslation: Indeed, my Lord is Merciful and Loving.\nThus, the word «وَدَّ» when it comes in the meanings of loving is stronger than «حَبَّ» (muf).","«وَدَّ» meaning to desire something. to befriend. to love.","Love","ود","2:96-2:105-2:109-2:266-3:30-3:69-3:118-4:42-4:73-4:89-4:102-5:82-11:90-15:2-19:96-29:25-30:21-33:20-42:23-60:1-60:2-60:7-68:9-70:11-85:14",25
2617,571,"L","اَلَّفَ","«اَلَّفَ» refers to combining the disparate elements of something. From this derives the word 'تالیف', meaning to create harmony. And «اُلْفَت» means the love that arises from such harmony (as in the following example). For instance, the Quran states:\n«لَوۡ اَنۡفَقۡتَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ جَمِیۡعًا مَّاۤ  اَلَّفۡتَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ» (8/63)\nTranslation: Even if you, [O Prophet], were to spend all the wealth in the world, you could not unite their [the believers'] hearts.","meaning a love that arises from harmony","Love","الف","3:103-8:63",2
2618,571,"L","شَغَفَ","«شَغَفَۃُ الْقَلْب» means the inner core of the heart (مف) and the outer layer/covering of the heart (م.ل). And «شَغَفَ» means to strike the veil over one's heart. And «شَغَفَ حُبًّا» means a love that has permeated the innermost core of the heart (مف) (ف ل 168). To be madly in love (م.ق).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قَدۡ شَغَفَہَا حُبًّا» (12:30)\nTranslation: The love (for Yusuf) had taken residence in her heart.","«شَغَفَ حُبًّا» a love that has permeated the innermost recesses of the heart.","Love","شغف","12:30",1
2619,571,"L","عُرُبَا","«عُرُبَ» is the plural form of «عَرُوْب». And the meaning of «عَرُوْب» is a woman who loves her husband (F L 146) and also means a cheerful, playful woman who laughs a lot (M. L Minj).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«فَجَعَلۡنٰہُنَّ  اَبۡکَارًا عُرُبًا  اَتۡرَابًا» (56/36,37)  \nTranslation: Then We made them [the houris] virgins, devoted to their husbands and of equal age.","«عُرُبَ» A woman who loves her husband.","Love","عربا","56:37",1
2620,572,"S","قَصْر","«قَصَرَ» The residence of the Roman kings, meaning palaces, was called 'qasr'. Subsequently, this term began to be used for every elevated and magnificent structure. Its plural is «قَصُوْر». For example, the Quran states: «فَہِیَ خَاوِیَۃٌ عَلٰی عُرُوۡشِہَا وَ بِئۡرٍ مُّعَطَّلَۃٍ  وَّ قَصۡرٍ مَّشِیۡدٍ» (22:45) Translation: And that city lay in ruins upon its roofs, and its wells and fortified palaces were all left desolate.","«قَصَرَ» any magnificent and lofty building.","Station","قصر","7:74-22:45-25:10-77:32",4
2621,572,"S","صَرْح","«صَرَحَ» meaning pure and unmixed (from *manjad*), and «صَرْحٌ» meaning a lofty edifice adorned with intricate decoration and free from all flaws. (Mufradat)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا رَاَتۡہُ حَسِبَتۡہُ  لُجَّۃً  وَّ کَشَفَتۡ عَنۡ سَاقَیۡہَا ؕ قَالَ  اِنَّہٗ  صَرۡحٌ مُّمَرَّدٌ مِّنۡ قَوَارِیۡرَ» (27/44)\nTranslation: When she saw it, she thought it was a deep pool of water, and she uncovered her legs. Solomon said, This is a palace with its floors made of glass.","«صَرَحَ» An edifice adorned with decoration and free from flaws and defects.","Station","صرح","27:44-28:38-40:36",3
2622,573,"S","عَمِلَ","«عَمْل» is every action that any living being performs with their free will and intention, whether that action is good or bad (detailed). And the word «عَمِلَ» is also used not only for any action but for labor, working for wages, or in other words, earning a livelihood.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «اَمَّا السَّفِیۡنَۃُ  فَکَانَتۡ لِمَسٰکِیۡنَ یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ فِی الۡبَحۡرِ» (18/79). Translation: And as for the ship, it belonged to poor people who earned their livelihood by labor (rowing the boat) on the sea.","«عَمِلَ» means to work hard for wages. This term is also common, and its usage is widespread.","Striving","عمل","2:25-2:62-2:74-2:82-2:85-2:96-2:110-2:134-2:139-2:140-2:141-2:144-2:149-2:167-2:217-2:233-2:234-2:237-2:265-2:271-2:277-2:283-3:22-3:30-3:57-3:98-3:99-3:120-3:153-3:156-3:163-3:180-3:195-4:17-4:18-4:57-4:94-4:108-4:110-4:122-4:123-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:173-5:5-5:8-5:9-5:53-5:62-5:66-5:69-5:71-5:90-5:93-5:105-6:43-6:54-6:60-6:88-6:108-6:122-6:127-6:132-6:135-7:42-7:43-7:53-7:118-7:129-7:139-7:147-7:153-7:180-8:39-8:47-8:48-8:72-9:9-9:16-9:17-9:37-9:69-9:94-9:102-9:105-9:120-9:121-10:4-10:9-10:12-10:14-10:23-10:41-10:61-10:81-11:7-11:11-11:15-11:16-11:23-11:46-11:78-11:92-11:93-11:111-11:112-11:121-11:123-12:19-12:69-13:29-14:18-14:23-14:42-15:93-16:28-16:32-16:34-16:63-16:93-16:96-16:97-16:111-16:119-17:9-17:84-18:2-18:7-18:30-18:49-18:79-18:88-18:103-18:105-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:27-21:74-21:82-21:94-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-22:68-23:51-23:63-23:100-24:24-24:28-24:38-24:39-24:53-24:55-24:64-25:23-25:70-25:71-26:112-26:168-26:169-26:188-26:216-26:227-27:4-27:19-27:24-27:84-27:90-27:93-28:15-28:55-28:67-28:80-28:84-29:4-29:7-29:8-29:9-29:38-29:55-29:58-30:15-30:41-30:44-30:45-31:8-31:15-31:23-31:29-32:12-32:14-32:17-32:19-33:2-33:9-33:19-33:31-33:71-34:4-34:11-34:12-34:13-34:25-34:33-34:37-35:7-35:8-35:10-35:37-36:35-36:54-36:71-37:39-37:61-37:96-38:24-38:28-39:7-39:35-39:39-39:65-39:70-40:37-40:40-40:58-41:5-41:8-41:20-41:22-41:27-41:33-41:40-41:46-41:50-42:15-42:22-42:23-42:26-43:72-45:15-45:21-45:28-45:29-45:30-45:33-46:14-46:15-46:16-46:19-47:1-47:2-47:4-47:8-47:9-47:12-47:14-47:28-47:30-47:32-47:33-47:35-48:11-48:24-48:29-49:2-49:14-49:18-52:16-52:19-52:21-53:31-56:24-57:4-57:10-58:3-58:6-58:7-58:11-58:13-58:15-59:18-60:3-62:8-63:2-63:11-64:2-64:7-64:8-64:9-65:11-66:7-66:11-67:2-77:43-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-99:6-99:7-99:8-103:3",309
2623,573,"S","جَھَدَ","«جَھَدَ» means utilizing all means and resources in carrying out a task. Sa'i-e-Baligh means to exert one's utmost effort. (m. l.)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ جَاہَدَ فَاِنَّمَا یُجَاہِدُ لِنَفۡسِہٖ» (29/6)\nTranslation: And whoever strives does so for his own benefit.\n\nAnd «جُھْد» means the effort that a human can possibly exert to the fullest.\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ لَا یَجِدُوۡنَ  اِلَّا جُہۡدَہُمۡ» (9/79)\nTranslation: And those who cannot earn except through their own effort.","to employ all available means in carrying out a task","Striving","جھد","2:218-3:142-5:35-5:54-8:72-8:74-8:75-9:16-9:19-9:20-9:41-9:44-9:73-9:79-9:81-9:86-9:88-16:110-22:78-25:52-29:6-29:8-29:69-31:15-49:15-61:11-66:9",27
2624,573,"S","نَصَبَ","«نَصَبَ» Such effort that exhausts a person (1) to toil, to labor (2) to become fatigued. This word is also used in different contexts.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لَقَدۡ لَقِیۡنَا مِنۡ سَفَرِنَا ہٰذَا نَصَبًا» (18:62)  \nTranslation: We have been greatly fatigued by this journey.  \n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:  \n«فَاِذَا  فَرَغۡتَ فَانۡصَبۡ وَ اِلٰی  رَبِّکَ فَارۡغَبۡ» (94:7-8)  \nTranslation: Then when you are free, strive [in worship] and turn to your Lord with longing.","«نَصَبَ» labor that exhausts or causes fatigue.","Striving","نصب","9:120-15:48-18:62-35:35-88:3-94:7",6
2625,573,"S","کَلَّفَ","«تَکْلِیْف» meaning to impose a burden. To command an effort that is bearable for someone and does not exceed their capacity and strength.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لَا یُکَلِّفُ اللّٰہُ نَفۡسًا اِلَّا وُسۡعَہَا» (2/286)  \nTranslation: Allah does not impose upon a person beyond his capacity.","«تَکْلِیْف» meaning to impose a duty. To prescribe an amount of effort that is bearable for a person and does not exceed their capacity and strength.","Striving","کلف","2:233-2:286-4:84-6:152-7:42-23:62-65:7",7
2626,573,"E","کَدَحَ","«کَدْح» to persistently endure hardship and toil while continuing one's work (meaning)\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «یٰۤاَیُّہَا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِنَّکَ کَادِحٌ  اِلٰی رَبِّکَ کَدۡحًا  فَمُلٰقِیۡہِ» (84/6) Translation: O human! You are toiling toward your Lord with toil, and you will meet Him.","«کَدْح», enduring pain time and again, one continues to do some work.","Earnest endeavor","کدح","84:6",1
2627,573,"D","کُرْہ","«کُرْہ» meaning forced hardship. Such hardship in which a person's own will and choice have no part, and which he dislikes. The opposite of this is «رَضَا  وَ الْمَحَبَۃ ». (detailed)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَمَلَتۡہُ  اُمُّہٗ  کُرۡہًا وَّ وَضَعَتۡہُ  کُرۡہًا» (46/15)\nTranslation: His mother carried him with hardship and gave birth to him with hardship.\n\nAnd «اَکْرَہَ» means forcing someone into a task or labor which he dislikes.\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ لَا تُکۡرِہُوۡا فَتَیٰتِکُمۡ عَلَی الۡبِغَآءِ» (24/33)\nTranslation: Do not compel your slave girls into prostitution.","«کُرْہ» meaning compelled hardship: such hardship in which a person's own will and choice have no part.","Diligence","کرہ","2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9",26
2628,573,"S","شِقّ","«شِقّ» A hardship or toil that causes physical or mental exhaustion or distress (expl.)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ تَحۡمِلُ اَثۡقَالَکُمۡ  اِلٰی بَلَدٍ لَّمۡ تَکُوۡنُوۡا بٰلِغِیۡہِ   اِلَّا بِشِقِّ الۡاَنۡفُسِ» (16:7)\nTranslation: And they carry your loads to cities which you could not have reached except by enduring great hardship.","The hardship and labor of toiling.","striving in the way of Allah","شق","13:34-16:7-20:2-20:117-20:123-28:27",6
2629,573,"S","شُقَّۃ","There is a difference between «شِقّ» and «شُقَّۃ» which is found in «حَمْل» and «حِمْل» or «وَقْر» and «وِقْر» (see 'Bojh' for details). That is, the stage which can be reached with difficulty (detailed).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ وَ لٰکِنۡۢ بَعُدَتۡ عَلَیۡہِمُ الشُّقَّۃُ» (9/42)\nTranslation: If there had been an easy gain and a short journey, they would have followed you. But the distance seemed long to them.","That destination which can only be reached with great difficulty.","striving","شقۃ","9:42",1
2630,574,"D","خَالَفَ","«خَالَفَ» means to oppose, to turn away, and to shun. It also signifies going against something, disagreeing, or doing something other than what has been instructed.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ مَاۤ  اُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ اُخَالِفَکُمۡ  اِلٰی مَاۤ اَنۡہٰکُمۡ عَنۡہُ» (11:88). Translation: I do not wish to do the very thing that I forbid you.","«خَالَفَ» meaning to oppose; to disregard.","Disobedience","خالف","9:83-11:88-24:63",3
2631,574,"O","ضَدَّ","«ضَدَّ» means to oppose. And «ضِدّ» means opponent, counterpart. Its plural is «اَضّدَاد». Two things that are counterparts are called «ضِدّین». According to Imam Raghib, the definition of «ضِدَّیْن» is that they are two things that are opposites of each other, belong to the same genus, and can never coexist, such as whiteness and blackness, whose genus is color or hue. And according to Ibn Faris, the definition of «ضِدَّیْن» is that they are two opposite things whose simultaneous existence at the same time is impossible, such as day and night (m.l.). Thus, this term «خِلَاف» is specific. That is, every opposite is certainly a contrary, but not every contrary is an opposite.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«کَلَّا ؕ سَیَکۡفُرُوۡنَ  بِعِبَادَتِہِمۡ وَ یَکُوۡنُوۡنَ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  ضِدًّا» (19/82)\nTranslation: Never! They will reject their worship and there they will become opponents of those people.\n\nAnd the word «ضِدّ» itself is from the linguistic term *addad* (words with opposite meanings). That is, «ضدّ» means opponent and counterpart. And «ضِدّ» also means similar and counterpart (m.q.).\n\nNote: (*Lughat addad* refers to words that have two distinct meanings, and those meanings are opposite and contradictory to each other.)","«ضَدَّ» two entities that are opposites, belong to the same genus, and can never coexist—such as whiteness and blackness, whose genus is color.","Opposition","ضد","19:82",1
2632,574,"D","شَاقَّ","«شَاقَّ» means to oppose, to bear enmity (manj) and «شَقّ» means rift, fissure, and «شِقَاق» means separation, distance, division, difference, opposition. Such opposition wherein each party adopts the stance opposite to that of the other (muf) i.e., whatever one party dislikes, the other party adopts it.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«ذٰلِکَ بِاَنَّہُمۡ  شَآقُّوا اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ ۚ وَ مَنۡ یُّشَآقِّ  اللّٰہَ  فَاِنَّ اللّٰہَ شَدِیۡدُ الۡعِقَابِ» (59/4)\nTranslation: This is because they opposed Allah and His Messenger. And whoever opposes Allah and His Messenger, then indeed Allah is severe in punishment.","«شَاقَّ» to be an adversary and an enemy.","Disobedience","شاق","4:115-8:13-16:27-47:32-59:4",5
2633,574,"O","حَآدَّ","«حَدّ النَّظَر» means to glare with sharp eyesight. And «حَدَّ السَّیْف» means the edge of a sword. And «حَدَّ السِّکِّیْن» means to sharpen a knife. And «حَادَّ» means to harbor enmity, to become angry (manjad). It appears that by «حَادَّ» is meant such opposition and enmity that a person becomes angry and resorts to confrontation and revenge.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ یَعۡلَمُوۡۤا اَنَّہٗ مَنۡ یُّحَادِدِ اللّٰہَ وَ رَسُوۡلَہٗ  فَاَنَّ لَہٗ  نَارَ جَہَنَّمَ خَالِدًا فِیۡہَا» (9:63)\nTranslation: Do they not know that whoever opposes Allah and His Messenger will have the fire of Hell prepared for him?","«حَادَّ» such enmity that causes someone to engage in confrontation.","Opposition / Contradiction","حآد","9:63-58:5-58:20-58:22",4
2634,574,"D","تَعَاسَرَ","«عُسْر» means constriction or tightness. And «عَسَّرَ الْاَمْر» means He made a matter difficult for someone, and He constricted him. And «تَعَاسَرَ» means to oppose one another in such a way that the matter becomes difficult for the other party (as cited). In «تَعَاسَرَ», there is no intensity in opposition and enmity; rather, one party adopts a course of action that causes constriction and distress to the other.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اۡتَمِرُوۡا  بَیۡنَکُمۡ بِمَعۡرُوۡفٍ ۚ وَ اِنۡ  تَعَاسَرۡتُمۡ فَسَتُرۡضِعُ  لَہٗۤ   اُخۡرٰی» (65:6)\nTranslation: And consult each other, O you who believe, in a fair manner. Then if they decide to wean the child, let another woman nurse him.","«تَعَاسَرَ» A scarcity in which one party imposes hardship upon another.","Defiance","تعاسر","65:6",1
2635,574,"O","عَنَدَ","«عَنَدَ» meaning to deliberately oppose the truth and the path of truth. «عَنِیْد» meaning a person who harbors enmity (hostility) toward the path of truth and opposes it. And «عَنُوْد» meaning a person who deviates from the correct path.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«اِنَّہٗ  کَانَ  لِاٰیٰتِنَا عَنِیۡدًا» (74/16)  \nTranslation: Indeed, he has been an opponent of Our verses.","«عَنَدَ» to oppose the Truth and the Path of Truth.","Opposition","عند","11:59-14:15-50:24-74:16",4
2636,575,"D","مُخْتَلِف","«اِخْتَلَاف» is the opposite of «اِتَّفَاق». «اِخْتَلَاف» means things being separate and distinct; being of various types or kinds; a species being different; having a difference (of opinion) in a matter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَخۡرُجُ مِنۡۢ بُطُوۡنِہَا شَرَابٌ مُّخۡتَلِفٌ اَلۡوَانُہٗ» (16/69)\nTranslation: A drink (honey) comes out of their (the bees') bellies, having different colors.\n\nAt another place, the command of Allah the Most High is:\n«وَّ النَّخۡلَ وَ الزَّرۡعَ مُخۡتَلِفًا اُکُلُہٗ» (6/141)\nTranslation: And date-palms and crops, (the fruits of) which are of various kinds.","«مُخْتَلِف» separate existence, diverse forms and types, distinct in nature.","different","مختلف","6:141-11:118-16:13-16:69-35:27-35:28-39:21-51:8-78:3",9
2637,575,"D","شَتّٰی","«شَتَّ» meaning the scattering of something's parts, i.e., the components becoming separate. Pragandah means being dispersed. Its opposite is «اَلَّفَ» (m. l.), meaning to gather the separate parts of something and arrange them. And «شَتِیْث» means dispersed. Its plural is «شَتّٰی». (m. q.)\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«تَحۡسَبُہُمۡ جَمِیۡعًا وَّ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ شَتّٰی» (59/14)\nTranslation: You (regarding those hypocrites) think that they are united (and of one mind), but their hearts are divided.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«یَوۡمَئِذٍ یَّصۡدُرُ  النَّاسُ اَشۡتَاتًا   ۬ ۙ لِّیُرَوۡا اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ » (99/6)\nTranslation: On that day, people will come in groups so that their deeds may be shown to them.","When the expression of scattered, i.e., separate parts of a single thing is intended.","Different","شتی","20:53-24:61-59:14-92:4-99:6",5
2638,575,"D","اَزْوَاج","«زَوْج» means a pair and every individual of a pair. For example, the husband is the zawj of the wife, and the wife is the zawj of the husband. And together, the husband and wife are also a single zawj. In any creation where male and female exist, the concept of zawj is also present. The concept of male and female in animals and plants is already known to humans, but this concept is also found in inanimate objects.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مِنۡ کُلِّ  شَیۡءٍ خَلَقۡنَا زَوۡجَیۡنِ» (51/49)\nTranslation: And We have created pairs of all things.\n\nSince the meaning of companionship or partnership is also present in «زَوْج», it is also applied when several important groups of living things gather together. In this case, the meaning of zawj becomes category, division, or sect.\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَّ کُنۡتُمۡ  اَزۡوَاجًا  ثَلٰثَۃً» (56/7)\nTranslation: And you will become three groups.\n\nAnd the word «اَزْوَاج» is also used for different categories of similar groups. Each such group, when considered as one, will have the meaning of zawj as multiple categories of such groups.\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَ لَا تَمُدَّنَّ عَیۡنَیۡکَ  اِلٰی مَا مَتَّعۡنَا بِہٖۤ اَزۡوَاجًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (20/131)\nTranslation: And do not turn your eyes toward the worldly provisions We have given to different groups of them.","«اَزْوَاج» meaning a pair and each individual of a pair. In common usage, it is used for husband and wife, and it is used for every same-gender pair.","different","ازواج","2:25-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:12-4:57-6:139-6:143-9:24-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:131-23:6-24:6-25:74-26:166-30:21-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-43:12-43:70-56:7-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-78:8",47
2639,576,"P","مُدّت","«مَدَّ» (meaning 'to draw out or lengthen') is a verbal noun indicating the extension of time. It is a well-known word and is commonly used. For example, in the Quran it says: «فَاَتِمُّوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِمۡ عَہۡدَہُمۡ اِلٰی مُدَّتِہِمۡ» (9/4). Translation: Fulfill the treaty with those polytheists until their appointed term.","«مُدَّت» the extension or lengthening of time and period. It is commonly used.","Period","مدت","9:4-84:3",2
2640,576,"T","اَمَدَ","The word «اَمَدَ» comes to denote a prolonged period and is used to indicate the extremity and purpose of a duration (lexicon). This word is used both as a temporal and spatial adverb. In the sense of space, it conveys the meaning of distance (fiqh 242).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«اَیُّ الۡحِزۡبَیۡنِ اَحۡصٰی  لِمَا  لَبِثُوۡۤا  اَمَدًا» (18/12)\nTranslation: Which of the two groups remembered best the longest period they had spent?\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty states:\n«تَوَدُّ لَوۡ اَنَّ بَیۡنَہَا وَ بَیۡنَہٗۤ اَمَدًۢا بَعِیۡدًا» (3/30)؎\nTranslation: He will wish, Oh, if only the distance between me and that evil were far!","«اَمَدَ» is used to denote a long period and its limit or distance.","term","امد","3:30-18:12-57:16-72:25",4
2641,576,"A","عِدَّت","«عَدَّ» is derived from the meaning to count. It refers to the period that is counted and the term is applied to that duration during which a divorced or widowed woman cannot marry another man and spends this time in the house of her former husband.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ الّٰٓـِٔىۡ یَئِسۡنَ مِنَ  الۡمَحِیۡضِ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِکُمۡ   اِنِ  ارۡتَبۡتُمۡ فَعِدَّتُہُنَّ  ثَلٰثَۃُ اَشۡہُرٍ» (65/4)\n\nTranslation: And for those of your women who have despaired of menstruation, if you are in doubt, then their waiting period is three months.","«عِدَّت» a duration whose reckoning is absolutely necessary. This is an Islamic legal term.","Appointed time","عدت","18:22-65:1-65:4-74:31",4
2642,576,"P","اُمَّۃ","«اُمّ» means mother and anything in which all its related elements are included (i.e., encompassed), and «اُمَّۃ» refers to the application of a period after it has elapsed.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ  بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And among the two prisoners, the one who had been released remembered after a period (a forgotten matter) and said.","«اُمَّۃ» the period that has passed.","Period","امۃ","2:143-2:213-3:104-3:110-3:113-4:41-5:48-5:66-6:38-6:42-6:108-7:34-7:38-7:159-7:160-7:164-7:168-7:181-10:19-10:47-10:49-11:8-11:48-11:118-12:45-13:30-15:5-16:36-16:63-16:84-16:89-16:92-16:93-16:120-21:92-22:34-22:67-23:43-23:44-23:52-27:83-28:23-28:75-29:18-35:24-35:42-40:5-41:25-42:8-43:22-43:23-43:33-45:28-46:18",54
2643,576,"T","مَلِیًّا","«مِلِّی» is understood to mean 'long and vast'. «مَلِیٌّ مِنَ الدَّھْر» means a long period (al-firru maqṣūrah), «مَلَاکُ اللہ» means 'may God grant you a long life' (munjad), and «مَلِیًّا» means 'for a long duration'.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ تَنۡتَہِ لَاَرۡجُمَنَّکَ وَ اہۡجُرۡنِیۡ  مَلِیًّا» (19/46)\nTranslation: (Azar said, O Abraham!) If you do not desist, I will certainly stone you, and for a long time keep you away from me.","«مَلِیَّا» is used in the meanings of long duration, eternity, and permanence.","Term","ملیًا","19:46",1
2644,576,"D","مَھَلَ","The Arabic terms «مُھْلَت», «اَمْھَل», and «مَھَّل» mean to postpone. It involves gradually and gently extending the period and not rushing. (detailed) For example: In the Quran, it says: «وَ ذَرۡنِیۡ وَ الۡمُکَذِّبِیۡنَ  اُولِی النَّعۡمَۃِ وَ مَہِّلۡہُمۡ  قَلِیۡلًا» (73/11). Translation: And leave to Me and those who deny, the possessors of wealth, and give them respite.","to gradually and gently extend the period","Duration","مھل","73:11-86:17",2
2645,576,"P","عُمُر","«عَمَرَ» meaning to inhabit and populate, and «عُمر» meaning the duration of the soul's residence within the body. The period from the birth of a living being to the present time.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لٰکِنَّاۤ  اَنۡشَاۡنَا قُرُوۡنًا فَتَطَاوَلَ عَلَیۡہِمُ الۡعُمُرُ» (28/45)\nTranslation: But we have (after Moses) created many generations, and long ages passed over them.","«عُمُر» the duration from the birth of a living being to the present time.","Period","عمر","2:96-10:16-15:72-16:70-21:44-22:5-26:18-28:45-35:11-35:37",10
2646,577,"H","اَعَانَ","«عَون» means a helper ( supporter ), and «اَعَان» means to give a hand, to assist. «تَعَاوَنَ» means to give each other a hand and to assist. This word is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاَعِیۡنُوۡنِیۡ بِقُوَّۃٍ  اَجۡعَلۡ بَیۡنَکُمۡ وَ بَیۡنَہُمۡ  رَدۡمًا» ( 18:95 )\nTranslation: Give me strength (power) to assist. I will erect between you and them a strong wall.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَعَان» means to seek help and cooperation from someone.\nFor example: The majestic command of Allah states:\n«اِیَّاکَ نَعۡبُدُ وَ اِیَّاکَ نَسۡتَعِیۡنُ» ( 1:4 )\nTranslation: ( O Lord! ) We worship only You, and we seek help only from You.","«اَعَانَ» to help someone. It is general, all forms of assistance.","Help","اعان","1:4-2:45-2:153-7:128-18:95-25:4",6
2647,577,"H","نَصَر","«نَصَر» means to help someone in order to remove their hardship or oppression (encompassing). And this is more specific than general assistance.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَ لَقَدۡ نَصَرَکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِبَدۡرٍ وَّ اَنۡتُمۡ اَذِلَّۃٌ» (3/123)\n\nTranslation: And without doubt, Allah the Almighty helped you in the field of Badr when you were weak.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَنْصَر» means to seek help from someone in order to remove oppression or injustice from oneself.\n\nFor example, the command of Allah the Almighty is: «وَ اِنِ اسۡتَنۡصَرُوۡکُمۡ فِی الدِّیۡنِ فَعَلَیۡکُمُ النَّصۡرُ» (8/72)\n\nTranslation: And if they (the Muslims who have not yet migrated) ask you for help in matters of religion, then helping them is obligatory upon you!","«نَصَر» To help someone eliminate their hardship or oppression.","Help","نصر","2:48-2:86-2:123-2:214-2:250-2:286-3:13-3:81-3:111-3:123-3:126-3:147-3:160-6:34-7:157-7:192-7:197-8:10-8:26-8:62-8:72-8:74-9:14-9:25-9:40-11:30-11:63-11:113-12:110-18:43-21:39-21:43-21:68-21:77-22:15-22:39-22:40-22:60-23:26-23:39-23:65-25:19-26:93-28:18-28:41-28:81-29:10-29:30-30:5-30:47-36:74-36:75-37:116-39:54-40:29-40:51-41:16-42:46-44:41-46:28-47:7-48:3-52:46-57:25-59:8-59:11-59:12-61:13-67:20-110:1",70
2648,577,"H","اَیَّد","«اَلْاَیَّد» meaning severe strength (fig.) and «اَیَّد» meaning to assist someone by imparting strength to them. To support.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاَنۡزَلَ اللّٰہُ سَکِیۡنَتَہٗ عَلَیۡہِ وَ اَیَّدَہٗ  بِجُنُوۡدٍ لَّمۡ تَرَوۡہَا» (9/40)\nTranslation: Then Allah sent down tranquility upon His Prophet and supported him with forces which you did not see.","to empower someone by helping them gain strength and power","Help","اید","2:87-2:253-5:110-8:26-8:62-9:40-38:17-58:22-61:14",9
2649,577,"H","عَزَّرَ","«عَزَّرَ» meaning to assist with a sense of reverence (meaning; example)\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«لِّتُؤۡمِنُوۡا بِاللّٰہِ وَ رَسُوۡلِہٖ  وَ تُعَزِّرُوۡہُ وَ تُوَقِّرُوۡہُ» (48/9)\nTranslation: that you may believe in Allah and His Messenger and support him and revere him.","to assist someone with reverence and zeal","Help","عزر","5:12-7:157-48:9",3
2650,577,"H","عَزَّزَ","«عَزَّز» means to help someone to such an extent that their weakness is removed. For details, see 'giving honor.' For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَاۤ  اِلَیۡہِمُ  اثۡنَیۡنِ  فَکَذَّبُوۡہُمَا فَعَزَّزۡنَا بِثَالِثٍ» (36:14). Translation: We sent two messengers to them, but they denied them. Then We strengthened them with a third.","«عَزَّز» to help someone to such an extent that their weakness ends.","Help","عزز","36:14",1
2651,577,"H","ظَاھَر","«ظَھَر» has two basic meanings: (1) to appear, to come forward, to be manifest. And «ظَھْر» means 'back' and «ظَاھَرَ» means 'to give such support that someone acts upon its foundation.' To back someone.  \nFor example, in the Quran it says:  \n«وَ اَنۡزَلَ الَّذِیۡنَ ظَاہَرُوۡہُمۡ مِّنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ مِنۡ صَیَاصِیۡہِمۡ» (33/26)  \nTranslation: And those from the People of the Book who had supported them, Allah brought them down from their fortresses.","«ظَاھَرَ» to seek refuge.","Help","ظاھر","9:4-28:48-33:26-60:9-66:4",5
2652,577,"H","رَفَدَ","«رَفَدَ» Giving aid to a poor and destitute person through gifts and charity (see the detailed explanation under giving).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اُتۡبِعُوۡا فِیۡ ہٰذِہٖ  لَعۡنَۃً وَّ یَوۡمَ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ ؕ بِئۡسَ الرِّفۡدُ  الۡمَرۡفُوۡدُ» (11/99)\nTranslation: And curse was made to follow them in this world as well, and on the Day of Resurrection. Evil is the reward that they will be given.","«رَفَدَ» to assist a poor person through gifts and charity and to persist in doing so.","Help","رفد","11:99",1
2653,577,"H","رَدَأَ ( الحائط )","«رَدَأَ» means to prop up a wall, and «رَدَاَ الرَجُل» means to become someone's helper and supporter. To be a protector. And «رِدْءٌ» means a helper and companion. (Manjadd. M Q) i.e., a helper who is always present.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اَخِیۡ ہٰرُوۡنُ ہُوَ اَفۡصَحُ مِنِّیۡ لِسَانًا فَاَرۡسِلۡہُ  مَعِیَ رِدۡاً  یُّصَدِّقُنِیۡۤ» (28/34)  \nTranslation: And appoint for me a helper from my brothers, Haroon, who is more fluent in speech than me, so that he may support me and confirm me.  \n\nNote: Pushta lagana (to prop up) means to build a support or foundation at the base of a wall to prevent it from collapsing and to strengthen it.","A helper who is ever-present.","Help","ردأ ( الحائط )","28:34",1
2654,577,"H","اَمَدَّ","«مَدَّ» means to extend something, to spread it, or to make it lengthy. In this manner, its connection remains established (interpretive meaning). And «اَمَدَّ» means to assist by increasing the amount or quantity of something, to provide help, or to bring aid.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ  بِاَمۡوَالٍ وَّ بَنِیۡنَ» (71/12)\nTranslation: And He will increase you in wealth and sons (Othmani) and He will assist you with wealth and sons (Jalandhari).\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«یُمۡدِدۡکُمۡ رَبُّکُمۡ بِخَمۡسَۃِ اٰلٰفٍ مِّنَ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃِ مُسَوِّمِیۡنَ» (3/125)\nTranslation: Then your Lord will send down to you five thousand angels, with marks [of distinction].","«اَمَدَّ» meaning to assist by increasing the quantity or number of something; to impart strength, to fortify.","Help","امد","3:124-3:125-17:6-26:132-26:133-52:22-71:12",7
2655,578,"H","نَاصِر ، نَصِیْر","«نَصَرَ» means to help someone in preventing excess or injustice against them. «مُحِیْط » and «نَاصِر» refer to a helper who assists in such a situation. Their plural forms are «نَصَر» and «اَنْصَار».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَہۡلَکۡنٰہُمۡ فَلَا  نَاصِرَ  لَہُمۡ» (47:13)\nTranslation: So when We destroyed them, no helper did they have.\n\nAnd «نَصِیْر» is one who brings help in every such situation. Its plural forms are «نُصَرَاء» and «اَنْصَار». This term is generally used in the Quran exclusively for Allah, the Exalted. And «نِصِیْر» means one who helps with strength (as in Fiqh 156).\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«وَّ کَفٰی  بِاللّٰہِ نَصِیۡرًا» (4:45)\nTranslation: And Allah is the best of helpers.","«نَاصِر» and «نَصِیْر», who help in times of oppression and transgression.","Helper","ناصر ، نَصِیْر","2:107-2:120-3:22-3:56-3:91-3:150-4:45-4:52-4:75-4:89-4:123-4:145-4:173-8:40-9:74-9:116-16:37-17:75-17:80-22:71-22:78-25:31-29:22-29:25-30:29-33:17-33:65-35:37-37:25-42:8-42:31-45:34-47:13-48:22-72:24-86:10",36
2656,578,"S","حَوَارِی","«حُوَارِی» meaning white cloth used for cleaning clothes, etc. (M. Q.) and also meaning an adviser, a relative, a helper. Hawari actually refers to the helpers of Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him) who supported him during difficult times. And the Messenger of Allah ﷺ said: Every prophet has a Hawari, and my Hawari is Zubair (may Allah be pleased with him).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ  مَرۡیَمَ لِلۡحَوَارِیّٖنَ مَنۡ  اَنۡصَارِیۡۤ  اِلَی اللّٰہِ ؕ قَالَ الۡحَوَارِیُّوۡنَ نَحۡنُ  اَنۡصَارُ اللّٰہِ» (61/14)\nTranslation: Jesus (peace be upon him) said to the Hawariyun, Who will be my helpers in the way of Allah? The Hawariyun said, We are helpers of Allah.","«حَوَارِی» the special group of helpers of the prophets.","Succorer","حواری","3:52-5:111-5:112-61:14",4
2657,578,"H","وَلِی ، مَوَالِی","«اَلْوِلَاءُ» means love, friendship, closeness, kinship (muf), and relationship (m. l). And «وِلَایَۃ» means inheritance, and «مَوَالِی» also means heir.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (4/33)\nTranslation: And if a man or woman leaves behind property or wealth, and has no direct heirs, We have appointed heirs for each one.\n\nIn Arabia, the custom of *wilayah* (guardianship/protectorship) was common, meaning people would take a friend other than their relatives as their *wali* (guardian). Then that *wali* was considered the heir of his estate and superior to the relatives (i.e., one holding a position of precedence). Islam initially upheld this practice. This chain existed among the Ansar and Muhajirin. After the conquest of Mecca, when Allah the Almighty prescribed shares for relatives in inheritance, this chain was terminated. Thus, in the words *wali* and *mawali*, there is greater comprehensiveness and breadth in many aspects than in the words *nasser* and *naseer*. Their meanings also include a supportive friend and helper. And «وَلِی» means one who helps with sincerity and love, not to show off or cause harm to people. (Fq 156)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ مِنۡ وَّلِیٍّ وَّ لَا نَصِیۡرٍ» (2/107)\nTranslation: And you have no protector or helper besides Allah.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ  اِنۡ تَوَلَّوۡا  فَاعۡلَمُوۡۤا  اَنَّ اللّٰہَ مَوۡلٰىکُمۡ ؕ نِعۡمَ  الۡمَوۡلٰی  وَ نِعۡمَ النَّصِیۡرُ» (8/40)\nTranslation: And if they turn away, then know that Allah is your Protector. And He is the best Protector and the best Helper.","and «مَولٰی» a supportive and close friend and helper","Helper","ولی ، موالی","2:107-2:120-2:257-2:286-3:68-3:150-4:33-6:51-6:62-6:70-8:40-9:51-9:74-9:116-10:30-13:37-16:76-17:111-18:26-19:5-22:13-22:78-29:22-32:4-33:5-41:34-42:8-42:31-42:44-44:41-45:19-47:11-57:15-66:2-66:4",35
2658,578,"H","شَھِیْد","«شَھِدَ» means to bear witness, whether this testimony is ocular (related to sight) or heartfelt (related to insight), meaning it may pertain to physical sight or spiritual perception; and it also means to be present (as cited in the lexical sources). And «شَھِیْد» is also used for a witness who appears before a judge to give testimony in someone's favor, and it serves as a means of support and proof for that person.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ادۡعُوۡا شُہَدَآءَکُمۡ مِّنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ  اِنۡ کُنۡتُمۡ صٰدِقِیۡنَ» (2/23)\nTranslation: And invoke besides Allah those who claim to be your helpers, if you are truthful.","«شَھِیْد» One who comes to a place to testify on behalf of someone and assist them.","Helper","شھید","2:143-2:282-3:98-4:33-4:41-4:72-4:79-4:159-4:166-5:117-6:19-10:29-10:46-13:43-16:84-16:89-17:96-22:17-22:78-28:75-29:52-33:55-34:47-41:47-41:53-46:8-48:28-50:21-50:37-58:6-85:9-100:7",32
2659,578,"H","ظَھِیْرٌ","«ظَھْرٌ» meaning 'back'; 'back'; and meaning 'riding'. 'Protector'; 'helper' (abbr.). «ظَھِیْرٌ» meaning 'helper'. Such a helper on whom a person relies. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «فَلَا تَکُوۡنَنَّ  ظَہِیۡرًا  لِّلۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (28/86) Translation: So do not ever be helpers of the disbelievers.","«ظَھِیْرٌ» A helper in whom one can place trust (reliance). Guardian. Protector, patron, supporter, helper.","Helper","ظھیر","17:88-25:55-28:17-28:86-34:22-66:4",6
2660,578,"H","وَزِیْر","«وِزْر» means 'to shoulder the burden,' and «اَوْزَار» carries the same meaning. And «وَزِیْر» is the person who helps and accompanies, who shares the burden in the difficulty of excessive work. For example: In the Quran, it is: «وَ اجۡعَلۡ  لِّیۡ  وَزِیۡرًا مِّنۡ  اَہۡلِیۡ» (20:29) Translation: And appoint for me a minister (helper) from my family (Jalandhari).","A meddler in excessive work.","Helper","وزیر","20:29-25:35",2
2661,578,"H","عَضُد","«عَضُد» means arm — the part from the shoulder to the elbow — and «عَضَدْتُہٗ» means to hold someone's arm and support them. In this sense, the word «عَضُد» is used metaphorically to mean helper (in the singular), and its plural is «اَعْضَاد» (as cited in Manj).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ مَا کُنۡتُ مُتَّخِذَ  الۡمُضِلِّیۡنَ  عَضُدًا» (18:51)\nTranslation: And I was never one to take those who lead astray as helpers.","«عَضُد» A steadfast helper.","Helper","عضد","18:51-28:35",2
2662,579,"D","اِسْتَھْزَاء","«اَلْھَزْءً» means to mock someone inwardly (i.e., in one's heart), and «اِسْتَھْزَاء» means to ridicule a person for an action they never even committed, considering it irrational (Faqih 212).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا خَلَوۡا اِلٰی شَیٰطِیۡنِہِمۡ  ۙ  قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّا مَعَکُمۡ  ۙ  اِنَّمَا نَحۡنُ مُسۡتَہۡزِءُوۡنَ» (2/14)\nTranslation: When these hypocrites converse privately with their evil associates, they say, We are only mocking them.","«اِسْتَھْزَاء» to mock something as irrational or absurd.","Discernment","استھزاء","2:14-2:15-4:140-6:5-6:10-9:64-9:65-11:8-13:32-15:11-15:95-16:34-21:41-26:6-30:10-36:30-39:48-40:83-43:7-45:33-46:26",21
2663,579,"T","سَخَّرَ","«مَسْخَر» carries the connotation of humiliation and degradation (M, L). «سَخَرَ» means to take labor from someone (i.e., work without wages) and «سَخَّرَ» means to humiliate someone, to overpower them (Munjid), and also means to mock someone by pointing out their faults, with the intention of ridiculing and degrading them (FQ 211).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا  الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا یَسۡخَرۡ قَوۡمٌ مِّنۡ قَوۡمٍ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ یَّکُوۡنُوۡا خَیۡرًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (49/11)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Let no group ridicule another group; perhaps they may be better than them.","to mock someone by pointing out their faults in a contemptuous manner.","Taste","سخر","2:212-6:10-9:79-11:38-21:41-23:110-37:12-37:14-38:63-49:11",10
2664,579,"T","فَنَّد","«فَنْد» meaning the weakness of opinion, and «فَنَّدَ» meaning to label someone as having a weak opinion or feeble-minded (i.e., of low intelligence, insane, crazy, foolish) (figurative), and «فَنِدَ» meaning to become senile. To become feeble-minded due to old age and to speak incoherently. And «فَنَّدَ» meaning to reproach someone for the talk of an elderly person. To deem someone erroneous. To censure.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالَ اَبُوۡہُمۡ اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ لَوۡ لَاۤ اَنۡ تُفَنِّدُوۡنِ» (12/94)\nTranslation: Their father (Prophet Ya'qub عليه السلام) said, If you do not tell me that the old man has become senile (then the truth is that) I sense the scent of Joseph.","«فَنَّد» to make fun of an elderly person by treating their words as jokes.","Taste","فند","12:94",1
2665,580,"M","رَجُلٌ","«رَجُلٌ» (meaning man) is used when the expression of strength, bravery, and masculinity is intended. «رَجُوْلِیَّۃ» is the root meaning strength, masculinity. The plural of masculine strength (manjada) is «رِجَالٌ». Its feminine forms are «نِسَاء» and «نِسْوَۃ».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلرِّجَالُ قَوّٰمُوۡنَ عَلَی النِّسَآءِ بِمَا فَضَّلَ اللّٰہُ بَعۡضَہُمۡ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ» (4/34)\nTranslation: Men are the protectors and maintainers of women, because Allah has given one of them a degree of excellence over the other.","«رَجُلٌ» is used when bravery and manly strength are intended to be expressed.","Man","رجل","2:228-2:282-4:1-4:7-4:12-4:32-4:34-4:75-4:98-4:176-5:23-6:9-7:46-7:48-7:63-7:69-7:81-7:155-9:108-10:2-11:78-12:109-16:43-16:76-17:47-18:32-18:37-21:7-23:25-23:38-24:31-24:37-25:8-27:55-28:15-28:20-29:29-33:4-33:23-33:40-34:7-34:43-36:20-38:62-39:29-40:28-43:31-48:25-72:6",49
2666,580,"M","اِمْرَءٌ","«مَرْءٌ» (meaning male) person. This term is employed when the intention is to refer to ethical matters concerning humanity. «مَرُوْءَتْ» or «مُرَرَّت» as a verbal noun means 'humanity' or 'human compassion.' Its feminine form is «اِمْرَاَۃٌ» or «اَلْمَرْءَۃُ». Its plural is also «رِجَالٌ» (Munjid). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «فَیَتَعَلَّمُوۡنَ مِنۡہُمَا مَا یُفَرِّقُوۡنَ بِہٖ بَیۡنَ الۡمَرۡءِ  وَ زَوۡجِہٖ» (2/102). Translation: People learn from both of them that which causes separation between husband and wife.","«اِمْرَءٌ» is used when one needs to demonstrate chivalry, humanity, and moral values.","man","امرء","2:102-8:24-78:40-80:34",4
2667,580,"M","ذَکَرَ","«ذَکَرَ» means male; its opposite is «اُنْثٰی». In every pair that gives birth, one is male, whether it be a human, animal, bird, tree, or the like. However, when this word refers to humans, it means a man, regardless of age. Its plural is «ذَكُوْر», and «ذَکْرَان» is its opposite, «اَنَاث». For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ ءٰٓالذَّکَرَیۡنِ حَرَّمَ  اَمِ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ» (6/144)\nTranslation: Ask them, Has Allah forbidden both males or both females?\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«لَیۡسَ الذَّکَرُ  کَالۡاُنۡثٰی» (3/36)\nTranslation: The son (i.e., the male) is not equal to the daughter (Maryam).","«ذَکَرَ» is used when the expression of a gender is intended.","Man","ذکر","3:36-3:195-4:11-4:124-4:176-6:143-6:144-16:97-26:165-40:40-42:50-49:13-53:21-53:45-75:39-92:3",16
2668,581,"T","ذَائِقَۃ","«ذَاقَ» means to taste. However, this word is generally used in the meanings of tasting with the tongue. «ذَائِقَۃ» also means the faculty of tasting which is in the tongue. And [maza] (pleasure) and «ذَوَاق» and «مَذَاق» come in the meanings of pleasure (manjad). The use of this word is common. It is used in every material and spiritual way.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is:\n«کُلُّ نَفۡسٍ ذَآئِقَۃُ الۡمَوۡتِ» (3/185)\nTranslation: Every soul is bound to taste death.","«ذَائِقَۃ» is a general term meaning 'to taste' or 'to savor.'","taste","ذائقۃ","3:185-21:35-29:57-37:31-37:38",5
2669,581,"T","طَعْم","«طَعَمَ» refers to food, bread, or eating, and the pleasure of eating is termed «طَعْم».  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«وَ اَنۡہٰرٌ مِّنۡ لَّبَنٍ لَّمۡ  یَتَغَیَّرۡ  طَعۡمُہٗ» (47/15)  \nTranslation: In it are rivers of milk whose taste will never change.","«طَعَمَ» meaning food, bread, or meal, and the pleasure of eating.","Taste","طعم","47:15",1
2670,581,"P","لَذَّۃ","«لَذَّ» means that something has a good taste or is delicious. And «لَذَّۃ» means the pleasantness of taste, or a taste that is agreeable to one's nature. Whether this taste is sweet or salty, sour, or even if it is bitter yet agreeable to one's nature, it is considered delicious. Its usage is applicable in both material and spiritual senses.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡہٰرٌ  مِّنۡ خَمۡرٍ  لَّذَّۃٍ   لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ» (47:15)\nTranslation: And in Paradise, there are rivers of wine, which will be delightful for those who drink.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَ فِیۡہَا مَا تَشۡتَہِیۡہِ  الۡاَنۡفُسُ وَ تَلَذُّ الۡاَعۡیُنُ» (43:71)\nTranslation: And in Paradise, there will be everything that souls desire and that which is delightful to the eyes.","«لَذَّت» affability, agreeableness.","Pleasure","لذۃ","37:46-43:71-47:15",3
2671,581,"P","ھَنَاَ","«اَلْھَنِیءُ» is that which is obtained without hardship and is pleasing in its results. This term is generally used for something that is enjoyable to eat (Mafatih al-Ghayb). And «ھَنَأ» means to be pleased. And «ھَنِیءَ الطَّعَام» means to find food delicious. And «ھَنُؤَ» means to be obtained without toil or hardship. And «ھَنَّاَ» means to congratulate. And «ھَنیئُ» means a thing obtained freely and joyfully without effort (Munjid). And «ھَنِئ» means food that is visually pleasing and contains no filth or defect whatsoever (Fiqh, 345). Then its usage began to apply to wealth acquired with ease.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4/4)\nTranslation: Then if the women, of their own accord, give you anything of it, consume it with pleasure and delight.","«ھَنَاَ» The delight in wealth that comes without effort. Something being visually appealing and rich.","Pleasure / Delight","ھنا","4:4-52:19-69:24-77:43",4
2672,582,"A","زَیَّنَ","«زَیَّن» meaning to adorn something, to decorate, to embellish, to make beautiful. This word is commonly used. It is employed in both material and spiritual senses.\nFor example, in the Noble Quran:\n«وَ لَقَدۡ  زَیَّنَّا السَّمَآءَ الدُّنۡیَا بِمَصَابِیۡحَ» (67:5)\nTranslation: And We have adorned the sky of the world with lamps (stars).\nAt another place, the Divine Command states:\n«وَ زَیَّنَ لَہُمُ الشَّیۡطٰنُ  مَا  کَانُوۡا  یَعۡمَلُوۡنَ» (6:43)\nTranslation: And whatever they used to do, Satan would adorn it for them and show it to them.","«زَیَّن» means to adorn or to decorate. This usage is common.","Adorned / Honorable","زین","2:212-3:14-6:43-6:108-6:122-6:137-8:48-9:37-10:12-13:33-15:16-15:39-16:63-27:4-27:24-29:38-35:8-37:6-40:37-41:12-41:25-47:14-48:12-49:7-50:6-67:5",26
2673,582,"D","زُخْرُف","«زُخْرُف» meaning gold (GOLD) and the adornment obtained from show and display. And «زُخْرُفَ الْقَوْل» meaning polished speech (muf) and «زُخْرُفَ الْکَلَام» meaning speech adorned with falsehood (manjad) and «زَخْرَفَ» and «تَزَخْرَفَ» meaning to make something attractive by polishing it (i.e., artificial and superficial embellishment) (manjad).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَذٰلِکَ جَعَلۡنَا لِکُلِّ نَبِیٍّ عَدُوًّا شَیٰطِیۡنَ الۡاِنۡسِ وَ  الۡجِنِّ  یُوۡحِیۡ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اِلٰی بَعۡضٍ زُخۡرُفَ الۡقَوۡلِ غُرُوۡرًا» (6/112)\nTranslation: And thus We have made for every prophet an enemy - devils from among mankind and jinn, inspiring one another with delusive speech through which they seek to deceive.","«زُخْرَفَ» To embellish something with falsehoods and fabrications. To adorn speech with lies.","Distinguished","زخرف","6:112-10:24-17:93-43:35",4
2674,582,"A","سَوَّلَ","«سَوِلَ» means laxity below the navel (metaphorical), and «سَوَّلَ» means (the nafs or Satan weakening and loosening the awareness of a sin so that one no longer perceives it as sinful, or adorning and beautifying a wrong act and presenting it enticingly so that a person becomes inclined to commit it rather than abstain). «اَلسَّوِیْل» means the nafs adorning a thing for which it also feels greed and presenting it in an attractive manner (metaphorical).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ جَآءُوۡ عَلٰی  قَمِیۡصِہٖ بِدَمٍ  کَذِبٍ ؕ قَالَ بَلۡ سَوَّلَتۡ لَکُمۡ اَنۡفُسُکُمۡ اَمۡرًا» (12/18). Translation: And the brothers of Joseph also smeared false blood on the shirt of Joseph (peace be upon him). Prophet Jacob (peace be upon him) said, Rather, you have fabricated this matter yourselves.","«سَوَّل» To present an evil act, which a person already covets, in an attractive light by Satan or the lower self (nafs).","Adorned","سول","12:18-12:83-20:96",3
2675,583,"T","اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل","«اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل» meaning (son of the road. This is a title for a traveler). A person remains a «اِبْنُ السّبِیل» until they return home, whether they are traveling or temporarily staying somewhere during the journey.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اٰتَی الۡمَالَ عَلٰی حُبِّہٖ ذَوِی الۡقُرۡبٰی وَ الۡیَتٰمٰی وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنَ  وَ ابۡنَ السَّبِیۡلِ» ( 2/177 )\nTranslation: And for the love of God, they give wealth to relatives, orphans, the poor, and travelers.","The traveler's «اِبْنُ السَّبِیْل» remains until he returns home.","Traveler","ابن السبیل","2:177-2:215-4:36-8:41-9:60-17:26-30:38-59:7",8
2676,583,"T","عَابِرِی السَّبِیْل","«عَابِرِ» meaning the One Who Causes to Pass; the One Who Decides. And «عَابِرِی السَّبِیْل» meaning the traveler, the wayfarer, one whose journey is ongoing. For example, the Quran states: «وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43). Translation: And neither the junub should approach the prayer except the traveler (for whom tayammum is permitted if water is unavailable) until you have bathed.","«عَابِرِی السَّبِیْل» wayfarer, travelers walking the path who are in a state of travel.","Traveler","عابری سبیل","4:43",1
2677,583,"T","مُقْوِیْن","«اَلْقَوٰی» means hunger, and «بَاتَ الْقَوٰی» means spending the night hungry, and «اَلْقَاوِیَۃ» means a year of scarce rain (Munjid), and «تَقَاوِی» means scarcity or excess of rain that destroys crops and causes famine (m. q.). Loans are those that the government gives to landlords on the condition of installment payments in such famine years. And «تَقَاوٰی» means spending the night hungry (Munjid), and «قُوَّتُ لَا یَمُوت» means such a small amount of food that a person can only stay alive, and «مُقْوِیْن» means people traveling in need of strength, i.e., nomads who keep moving in search of livelihood.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is said:\n«نَحۡنُ جَعَلۡنٰہَا تَذۡکِرَۃً  وَّ مَتَاعًا لِّلۡمُقۡوِیۡنَ» (56/73)\nTranslation: We have made it a means of admonition and a beneficial thing for desert travelers.","«مُقْوِیْن» those who wander about in search of livelihood.","Traveler","مقوین","56:73",1
2678,583,"T","سَیَّارَۃٌ","«سَارَ» means to travel, to walk. And «سیّار» is an intensive form meaning one who walks a lot. And «سَیَّارَہ» means a group of fellow travelers, things that are constantly moving: planets, celestial bodies, motor cars, etc. In the Quran, this word appears in the first meanings. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ جَآءَتۡ سَیَّارَۃٌ  فَاَرۡسَلُوۡا وَارِدَہُمۡ» (12/19). Translation: And a caravan arrived there, who sent their water-drawer.","«سَیَّارَۃٌ» the caravan of fellow travelers.","traveler","سیارۃ","5:96-12:10-12:19",3
2679,584,"S","سَخَّرَ","It refers to compulsory obedience, meaning that a thing performs the very function for which it was created. In this, the will, choice, and intention of the obedient (whether living or inanimate) have no part (for further details, see to force).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ تَقُوۡلُوۡا سُبۡحٰنَ الَّذِیۡ سَخَّرَ لَنَا ہٰذَا  وَ مَا کُنَّا لَہٗ  مُقۡرِنِیۡنَ» (43:13)\nTranslation: And (when you mount your rides) say, Pure is He who has subjugated this for us; otherwise we could not have brought it under our control.","«سَخَّرَ» highlights the aspect of restlessness and agitation associated with something.","Subjected (to human service)","سخر","2:164-7:54-13:2-14:32-14:33-16:12-16:14-16:79-21:79-22:36-22:37-22:65-29:61-31:20-31:29-35:13-38:18-38:36-39:5-43:13-43:32-45:12-45:13-69:7",24
2680,584,"R","ذَلَّلَ","«ذَلَّ» means to be weak and subservient. And «ذَلَّلَ» means to make someone powerless and feeble. Obedience that involves elements of humiliation and helplessness (as cited).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ ذَلَّلۡنٰہَا لَہُمۡ  فَمِنۡہَا رَکُوۡبُہُمۡ  وَ  مِنۡہَا یَاۡکُلُوۡنَ» (36/72)\nTranslation: And We have subjected these cattle to them, so some they ride and some they eat.\n\nAnd «ذَلُوْلٌ» means to willingly abandon rebellion and become obedient and compliant towards something (as cited).\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, states:\n«ہُوَ  الَّذِیۡ جَعَلَ  لَکُمُ  الۡاَرۡضَ ذَلُوۡلًا» (67/15)\nTranslation: It is He who has made the earth subservient and soft for you.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah, the Exalted, states:\n«اِنَّہَا بَقَرَۃٌ لَّا ذَلُوۡلٌ تُثِیۡرُ الۡاَرۡضَ وَ لَا تَسۡقِی الۡحَرۡثَ» (2/71)\nTranslation: An ox that is not employed for work, nor does it plow the land, nor does it water the crops.","The term «ذَلُوْل» conveys the sense of a person making something subservient and obedient through their own effort, as well as the state of that thing being subservient and obedient.","ridiculed","ذلل","36:72-76:14",2
2681,585,"A","سَلَّطَ","«سَلِطَ» means to be long-tongued or eloquent. And in «سَلَّطَ», two concepts are found: (1) power (qudrat) and (2) might (qahr) (i.e., supremacy and, along with it, pressure too). And «سُلْطان» means kingship, authority, and clear proof (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُسَلِّطُ رُسُلَہٗ  عَلٰی مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (59/6)\nTranslation: But Allah, the Exalted, grants dominance to His messengers over whom He wills.","«سَلَّطَ» encompasses two aspects: (1) Power and (2) Coercion, meaning dominance accompanied by pressure/compulsion.","authority","سلط","4:90-59:6",2
2682,585,"A","قَیَّضَ","«قَیْض» is called the egg's shell. And «قَیَّض» means to dominate and envelop something, or to become dominant and take possession, as the shell is over the egg's contents (meaning: to overpower someone and make them subservient).  \nFor example: In the Quran, «وَ مَنۡ یَّعۡشُ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ نُقَیِّضۡ لَہٗ  شَیۡطٰنًا» (43/36):  \nTranslation: And whoever turns away from the remembrance of God, We assign to him a devil as a companion.","To subjugate someone by prevailing over them.","Authority","قیض","41:25-43:36",2
2683,586,"B","شَغَلَ","A preoccupation that prevents a person from paying attention to other matters. And its opposite is «فَرَغَ».  \nFor example, the Quran states: «سَیَقُوۡلُ  لَکَ الۡمُخَلَّفُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡاَعۡرَابِ شَغَلَتۡنَاۤ  اَمۡوَالُنَا وَ اَہۡلُوۡنَا» (48/11).  \nTranslation: Those who remained behind will now say to you, We were preoccupied with our wealth and family matters.","«شَغَلَ» is common. To be occupied in some work.","Busy","شغل","36:55-48:11",2
2684,586,"B","خَاضَ","«خَاضَ» means to sink or to penetrate deep into something (m. l.). «خَاضَ فِی الْمَاء» means to plunge into water, and «خَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْث» means to become engrossed in conversations (manjada), i.e., to occupy oneself with complete absorption in a task or discussion. In the Quran, this word is generally used in a negative sense. That is, to remain engaged in idle talk or futile deeds.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ خُضۡتُمۡ کَالَّذِیۡ خَاضُوۡا ؕ اُولٰٓئِکَ حَبِطَتۡ اَعۡمَالُہُمۡ  فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (9:69)\nTranslation: And they (the earlier people) became engrossed in falsehood, so you (too) became engrossed. Those are the ones whose deeds have become worthless in this world and the Hereafter.\n\nAt another place, the divine command states:\n«وَ اِذَا  رَاَیۡتَ الَّذِیۡنَ  یَخُوۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡۤ  اٰیٰتِنَا فَاَعۡرِضۡ عَنۡہُمۡ» (6:68)\nTranslation: When you see those who engage in [idle] talk about Our verses, then turn away from them until they turn to another topic.","Being preoccupied with «خَاضَ» carries negative connotations.","busy","خاض","4:140-6:68-6:91-9:65-9:69-43:83-52:12-70:42-74:45",9
2685,586,"B","اَفَاضَ","«فَاضَ ، فَیْض» means something flowing easily (m. l.) or water gushing forth and flowing from a place (muf.). It also means something being abundant (as cited in Munjid). They say «فَاضَ السَّبیل», meaning water being abundant and flowing out from rivers and streams. And «فَاضَتْ عَیْنَہٗ» means tears began to flow from his eyes. And «اَفَاضَ اِنَاءَہٗ» means he filled his vessel so full that water began to spill over the edges.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  اَفِیۡضُوۡا مِنۡ حَیۡثُ اَفَاضَ النَّاسُ» (2/199)\nTranslation: Then return from where the people return.\nThe intended meaning here is to come along with the crowd and its flow. That is, flow along with that crowd's movement. And according to the author of Munjid, «اَفَاضَ الْقَوْمُ مِنْ مَکَان» means to become scattered and dispersed (Munjid), and «اَفَاضَ فِی الْحَدِیْثِ» means to remain intensely and completely engrossed in a matter for a long time.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَّ لَا تَعۡمَلُوۡنَ مِنۡ عَمَلٍ اِلَّا کُنَّا عَلَیۡکُمۡ شُہُوۡدًا  اِذۡ تُفِیۡضُوۡنَ فِیۡہِ» (10/61)\nTranslation: And whatever work you may be doing, We are present with you while you are engaged in it.\nAccording to Ibn al-Faris, the meaning of «تَفِیْضُوْنَ فِیْہِ» is «اِنْد فعوافیہ» (m. l.), meaning you become so engrossed that you forget everything else.","«اَفَاضَ» Such engrossment that makes one forget even themselves.","busy","افاض","2:199-5:83-7:50-9:92-10:61-46:8",6
2686,586,"B","سَبَحَ","«سَبَحَ» meaning to swim or float (i.e., to flow on water, to cross, to traverse, to pass over). And according to Imam Raghib, it signifies the swift passage of something through water or air, or its passage while swimming (detailed).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُلٌّ فِیۡ  فَلَکٍ  یَّسۡبَحُوۡنَ» ( 36/40 )\nTranslation: And all these celestial bodies are swimming/traversing in their orbits.\n\nThen the use of this word also began to signify the execution of a task with speed and vigor (detailed).\nFor example: the Divine declaration is:\n«اِنَّ  لَکَ فِی النَّہَارِ سَبۡحًا طَوِیۡلًا» ( 73/7 )\nTranslation: During the day, you will have much to occupy you.","«سَبَحَ» Such busyness where the fast-paced aspect becomes evident due to the overwhelming number of tasks.","Busy","سبح","21:33-36:40-73:7-79:3",4
2687,587,"H","اَعْنَتَ","«عَنَتَ» means a person becoming entangled in a matter wherein there is fear of their destruction (detailed), and «اَعْنَتَ» means causing someone else such trouble or calamity.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَوۡ شَآءَ اللّٰہُ  لَاَعۡنَتَکُمۡ» (2/220)\nTranslation: And if Allah had willed, He could have put you into hardship.","«اَعْنَتَ» means to throw someone else into a deadly and difficult task. And «اِقْتَحَمَ» means to throw oneself into a deadly and difficult task.","Hardship","اعنت","2:220-3:118-9:128",3
2688,587,"T","اِقْتَحَمَ","«قَحَمَ فِی الْاَمْر» means to enter into a matter without thinking or understanding. And «اِقْتَحَمَ الْاَمْر» means to entangle oneself in a matter with difficulty (manjada). And «اِقْتَحَمَ» means to plunge into a terrifying place (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«ہٰذَا فَوۡجٌ مُّقۡتَحِمٌ  مَّعَکُمۡ» (38/59)\nTranslation: This is an army that is coming towards you in haste.","«اِقْتَحَمَ» meaning to entangle oneself in something with difficulty.","Tribulation","اقتحم","38:59-90:11",2
2689,588,"C","شَاوَرَ","«شَاوَرَ» means to consult. It involves gathering several people regarding an issue, considering its various aspects, and taking each other's opinions (m. l. mf.). The use of this word is common.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is:\n«وَ شَاوِرۡہُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ ۚ فَاِذَا عَزَمۡتَ فَتَوَکَّلۡ عَلَی اللّٰہِ» (3/159)\nTranslation: And consult them in (important) matters. Then when you have made a firm decision after consultation, put your trust in Allah.","It is common to consult «شَاوَرَ».","Consultation","شاور","2:233-3:159",2
2690,588,"C","بَیَّتَ","«باتَ» means spending the night, passing the night. And «بَیَّتَ» means gathering at home after part of the night has passed to consult on a matter (M. L.). (Its other meaning is also 'night bloodshed').\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَاِذَا بَرَزُوۡا مِنۡ عِنۡدِکَ بَیَّتَ طَآئِفَۃٌ مِّنۡہُمۡ غَیۡرَ الَّذِیۡ تَقُوۡلُ» (4/81)\nTranslation: Then when they rise up from your presence, a group of them spends the night in consultation contrary to what they say to you.\n\nThe meaning of «بَیَّتَ» in the sense of 'night bloodshed' also occurs (27/49), but that meaning is not under discussion here.","The secret night counsel.","Consultation","بیت","4:81-4:108-27:49",3
2691,588,"C","تَنَاجٰی","«نَجَو» meaning a secret between two people (m. l. minjd) and «نَجْوٰی» meaning secret talk, mystery, confidant, sharing a secret. And «تَنَاجٰی» meaning to whisper, to dedicate for whispering, to make someone a confidant (minjd). And «نَجِیًّا» meaning advice of secrecy (12/80).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یَتَنٰجَوۡنَ بِالۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ وَ مَعۡصِیَتِ الرَّسُوۡلِ» (58/8)\nTranslation: They consult each other regarding sin, transgression, and disobedience to the Messenger.","«تَنَاجٰی» secret gossip or backbiting among a select few or just two individuals.","Consultation","تناجی","4:114-9:78-12:80-17:47-19:52-20:62-21:3-43:80-58:7-58:8-58:9-58:10-58:12-58:13",14
2692,588,"C","اِئْتَمَرَ","«اَمَرَ» meaning to command, and «اِئْتَمَرَ» meaning to agree upon something after mutual consultation and to carry out the command (detailed), and «اِئْتَمَرَ بِفُلَانٍ» meaning to conspire to kill someone (conspiracy).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated: «قَالَ یٰمُوۡسٰۤی  اِنَّ الۡمَلَاَ یَاۡتَمِرُوۡنَ بِکَ لِیَقۡتُلُوۡکَ» (28/20). Translation: That man said, O Moses! Indeed, the courtiers of Pharaoh are discussing you secretly, intending to kill you.","«اِئْتَمَرَ» to concur on a course of action or to conspire to kill someone.","Consultation","ائتمر","28:20-65:6",2
2693,589,"F","شَاعَ","«شَاعَ الْخَبْر» meaning: the news spread and gained strength. «شَاعَ الْقَوْم» meaning: the nation became dispersed and increased, and «اَلْشِیَاعَ» meaning: to disperse and to give strength (mufrad) as if «شَاعَ» the word comes for something good or bad spreading among people and becoming widespread at the same time. From this, the term Ash'aat (publication/spreading) is a well-known word.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُحِبُّوۡنَ اَنۡ تَشِیۡعَ الۡفَاحِشَۃُ فِی الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (24/19)  \nTranslation: Those who like to spread [such news]—that is, slander or immorality—among the believers will have a painful punishment in this world and the Hereafter.","«اَشَاعَ» To announce or publish any good or bad news.","Famous","شاع","24:19",1
2694,589,"F","اَذَاعَ","«ذَاعَ» meaning the manifestation and spread of something. And «ذَاعَ الْخَبْر» meaning the news became manifest and spread. And «رَجُلٌ لِذَاعٌ» meaning a person who cannot conceal a secret (as if). «اَزَاعَ» comes to reveal something that ought not to have been revealed. And «اِذَاعَۃ» it is also used for 'radio', since radio too broadcasts certain news that some countries find unwelcome. To spread news (خبر اڑانا).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِذَا جَآءَہُمۡ  اَمۡرٌ مِّنَ الۡاَمۡنِ اَوِ  الۡخَوۡفِ اَذَاعُوۡا بِہٖ» (4/83)\nTranslation: And when the hypocrites receive any news of danger or peace, they spread it abroad.","«اَذَاعَ» to spread rumors and disclose confidential matters.","famous","اذاع","4:83",1
2695,589,"F","اَرْجَفَ","«رَجْف» means severe anxiety, i.e., extreme restlessness (M. L.), and «رَجْفَۃ» means the most intense form of an earthquake. Powerful jolts, and «بَحْرٌ رِجَافٌ» means turbulent, i.e., a stormy sea (Munjad), and «اَرْجَفَ» means spreading false rumors, etc., to create unrest and commotion among people. And «اَرَاجِیْف» means baseless reports. Rumors (M. Q.).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَئِنۡ لَّمۡ  یَنۡتَہِ  الۡمُنٰفِقُوۡنَ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ  مَّرَضٌ وَّ الۡمُرۡجِفُوۡنَ فِی الۡمَدِیۡنَۃِ  لَنُغۡرِیَنَّکَ بِہِمۡ ثُمَّ لَا یُجَاوِرُوۡنَکَ  فِیۡہَاۤ   اِلَّا   قَلِیۡلًا» (33/60)\nTranslation: If the hypocrites and those in whose hearts is a disease and those who spread false rumors in the city do not desist from their actions, We will surely incite you against them, then they will not be your neighbors except for a short while.","spreading such a matter that causes anxiety and unrest «اَرْجَفَ»","Famous","ارجف","33:60",1
2696,589,"F","اَھَلَّ","«اَھَلَّ» means to raise one's voice while mentioning the name of something. And «ھِلَال» means the new moon, upon seeing which people call out to one another and raise their voices (m. l. maf). And «تَھْلِیْل» means to say aloud «لَا اِلٰہَ اِلَّا اللہُ».\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا حَرَّمَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡمَیۡتَۃَ وَ الدَّمَ وَ لَحۡمَ الۡخِنۡزِیۡرِ وَ مَاۤ  اُہِلَّ بِہٖ لِغَیۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (2/173)\nTranslation: He has only forbidden to you dead animals, blood, the flesh of swine, and that which has been dedicated to other than Allah, and those animals killed by strangling, a violent blow, a fall, or by the goring of horns, and those at which a wild animal has devoured, except what you [are able to] slaughter [before its death], and those which are sacrificed on stone altars [to idols], and [prohibited is] that you try to determine [fates] by divining arrows. That is grave disobedience. This day those who disbelieve have despaired of [defeating] your religion; so fear them not, but fear Me. This day I have perfected for you your religion and completed My favor upon you and have approved for you Islam as religion. But whoever is forced by severe hunger with no inclination to sin - then indeed, Allah is Forgiving and Merciful.","«اَھَلَّ» to raise one's voice while mentioning something and making it widely known.","Famous","اھل","2:173-5:3-6:145-16:105",4
2697,590,"S","ثَابِت","«ثَبَّتَ» means to remain firm, to establish. «ثَبَّتَ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to persist in something (from najm), and its opposite is «زَلّ», meaning not to remain firm on one's foundation, to slip.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«مَثَلًا کَلِمَۃً طَیِّبَۃً  کَشَجَرَۃٍ  طَیِّبَۃٍ اَصۡلُہَا ثَابِتٌ وَّ فَرۡعُہَا فِی  السَّمَآءِ» (14/24)\nTranslation: The example of a good word is that of a good tree, whose roots are firm and whose branches are in the sky.","«ثَابِت» meaning to remain firmly established on one's own foundation.","Strong","ثابت","14:24-14:27",2
2698,590,"F","راسِخ","«رَسَخَ» meaning to be firmly established in its place (firmly rooted) and meaning the firm and place-holding one of something, the one that remains established. (M.F.) «رَسَخَ الْحِبْر فِی الصَّحِیْفَۃ» meaning collected in the ink of a book. And «رَسَخَ الْعِلْمُ فِی الْقَلْبِ» meaning knowledge deeply rooted in the heart (firmly established). That is, in «رَسَخَ», with affirmation, firm establishment (i.e., taking root) is also found (M. Q.). And meaning to know something with many proofs or as needed, whose removal is not possible (Fiqh 65).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَا یَعۡلَمُ  تَاۡوِیۡلَہٗۤ  اِلَّا اللّٰہُ  ۘ ؔ وَ الرّٰسِخُوۡنَ فِی الۡعِلۡمِ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ اٰمَنَّا بِہٖ» (3:7)\nTranslation: Although none knows its true meaning except Allah, and those firm in knowledge say: We believe in it.","«رَاسِخ» meaning stable, firmly established, and unshakable. That is, to know something with numerous arguments or as required, the dispelling of which is not possible.","Firm","راسخ","3:7-4:162",2
2699,590,"S","مَتِیْن","«مَتِیْن» means that something is inherently strong and solid in itself, and that firmness and stability (i.e., strength and steadfastness) permeate it. (Ref. M. L.) «حَبْلٌ مَّتِیْنٌ» means a strong rope, and «رَأیَ مَتِیْنٌ» means a firm or resolved opinion. (Ref. M. L.)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اُمۡلِیۡ لَہُمۡ ؕ اِنَّ  کَیۡدِیۡ  مَتِیۡنٌ» (68/45)\nTranslation: And I give them respite. My plan is firm.","«مَتِیْن» denotes the self-subsistence of a thing.","Strong","متین","7:183-51:58-68:45",3
2700,590,"F","مُحْکَم","«اَحْکَمَ» meaning to make something firm with wisdom and experience (Munjad), and according to Imam Raghib, by 'muhkamat ayat' are meant those verses in which, in terms of wording and meaning, no kind of doubt or suspicion is found (Muf).  \nFor example, in the Holy Quran:  \n«ہُوَ الَّذِیۡۤ اَنۡزَلَ عَلَیۡکَ الۡکِتٰبَ مِنۡہُ اٰیٰتٌ مُّحۡکَمٰتٌ ہُنَّ اُمُّ  الۡکِتٰبِ وَ اُخَرُ مُتَشٰبِہٰتٌ» (3/7)  \nTranslation: He is the One who has sent down the Book upon you. In it are some clear verses, and they are the foundation of the Book, and some others are also ambiguous.","«مُحْکَم» Proven by wisdom and experience. Strong.","Firm","محکم","3:7-47:20",2
2701,590,"S","قَیِّمَۃٌ","«قَامَ» means to stand. And «قَامَ الْاَمْر» means for a matter to come to a just balance. And «اَقَامَ الْمَائِل» means to straighten the crooked (i.e., to set right). And «قَیَام» and «قَوَام» are also terms used for that thing upon which other things can remain established (i.e., a foundation or support).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا تُؤۡتُوا السُّفَہَآءَ اَمۡوَالَکُمُ الَّتِیۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ لَکُمۡ قِیٰمًا» (4/5)\nTranslation: And do not give the foolish your property which Allah has made a means of support for you.\n\nAnd «قَیِّمْ» its feminine form is «قَیِّمَۃ», meaning that thing upon which other things are established. That is, it is what maintains and upholds things. And it also refers to that which serves as a standard for distinguishing between truth and falsehood, or for making a clear distinction.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«رَسُوۡلٌ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ یَتۡلُوۡا صُحُفًا مُّطَہَّرَۃً فِیۡہَا کُتُبٌ قَیِّمَۃٌ» (98/2,3)\nTranslation: A Messenger from Allah, reciting purified scriptures wherein are firm (established) verses.","«قَیِّمَۃٌ» a strength that can support others or set a standard for them.","Strong","قیمۃ","98:3-98:5",2
2702,590,"F","وُثْقٰی","«وَثِقَ یَثِقُ ثِقَۃً» means to consider reliable, to trust. And «وَثُقَ یُوْثَقُ وَثَاقَۃً» means to be firm and strong, to be solid. And «اَوْثَقَ» means to tie firmly with a rope. And «ثِقَۃٌ» means trustworthy, reliable. And «اَوْثَقٌ» its feminine form is «وُثْقٰی», meaning a firm and trustworthy thing.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ ۚ فَمَنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِالطَّاغُوۡتِ وَ یُؤۡمِنۡۢ بِاللّٰہِ فَقَدِ اسۡتَمۡسَکَ بِالۡعُرۡوَۃِ الۡوُثۡقٰی ٭ لَا انۡفِصَامَ  لَہَا» (2/256)\nTranslation: The path of guidance has become clearly distinguished from error. Thereafter, whoever rejects taghut and believes in Allah has grasped the most firm handle, which has no possibility of breaking.","«وُثْقٰی» such strength on which one can rely.","Firm","وثقی","2:256-31:22",2
2703,590,"S","ثَبَّتَ","«ثَبَّتَ» means to firmly establish something in its place, to strengthen it, and to keep it steadfast.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«یُثَبِّتُ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا بِالۡقَوۡلِ الثَّابِتِ فِی الۡحَیٰوۃِ الدُّنۡیَا وَ فِی الۡاٰخِرَۃِ» (14/27)  \nTranslation: Allah strengthens the believers with a firm word in this world and the Hereafter.","to establish something firmly in its place","Strong","ثبت","2:250-3:147-8:11-8:12-8:45-11:120-13:39-14:24-14:27-16:102-17:74-25:32-47:7",13
2704,590,"F","اَحْکَم","«اَحْکَم» To make something strong and firm in its structure through wisdom, knowledge, and experience. And «حَکِیْم» meaning «اَلْعَالَمُ بِاِحْکَامِ الْاُمُورِ» (Faq l 77).\nFor example: The Holy Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ  یُحۡکِمُ  اللّٰہُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ» (22/52)\nTranslation: Then Allah the Almighty strengthens His verses.\nAnd the decisive verses are those in which there is no textual or semantic ambiguity.","To purify a matter from doubt and suspicion through wisdom and experience.","Firm","احکم","11:1-22:52",2
2705,590,"S","اَوْثَقَ","«اَوْثَقَ» means to make a covenant, pledge, etc., firm and reliable. Or to bind someone tightly with ropes, etc.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ لَا یُوۡثِقُ وَ ثَاقَہٗۤ  اَحَدٌ» (89/26)\nTranslation: And no one will be bound in such a manner.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ اذۡکُرُوۡا نِعۡمَۃَ اللّٰہِ عَلَیۡکُمۡ وَ مِیۡثَاقَہُ الَّذِیۡ وَاثَقَکُمۡ  بِہٖۤ» (5/7)\nTranslation: And remember the favors that Allah has bestowed upon you, and the firm covenant which He took from you.\n\nApart from these, the following words are also mentioned in the Quran: for example:\n«شَدَّ ، اَتْقَنَ ، رَبَطَ ، اٰزَرَ ، عَقَّدَ ، وَکَّدَ ، سَنَّدَ ، رَصَّ ، شَیَّد»\nThese words also appear with similar meanings.","to make something strong and trustworthy through something else","Strong","اوثق","12:66-12:80-89:26",3
2706,590,"S","شدّ","«شَدَّ» means something being inherently strong and robust (m. l.). It is used in both intransitive and transitive forms. And «اَشُدّ» refers to the age of youth when strength reaches its peak.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«نَحۡنُ خَلَقۡنٰہُمۡ وَ شَدَدۡنَاۤ  اَسۡرَہُمۡ» (76/28)\nTranslation: We have created them and strengthened their constitution.","To strengthen something by endowing it with power, making it inherently robust.","Strong","شد","10:88-20:31-28:35-38:20-47:4-66:6-76:28-78:12",8
2707,590,"S","اَتْقَنَ الْاَمْر","«اَتْقَنَ» means to build something firmly. And «تَقَّنَ الْاَرْضَ» means to make land powerful by irrigating it with muddy water. And «رَجُلٌ تَقِنٌ» means one who executes work with trust; an expert (manjidd) and wise in work, one who corrects work (m. q.). Essentially, the meaning of «اَتْقَنَ» is to skillfully strengthen something.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «صُنۡعَ اللّٰہِ  الَّذِیۡۤ اَتۡقَنَ کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ» (27:88). Translation: (All) creation is (a model of) Allah's craftsmanship, which has firmly built everything.","«اَتْقَنَ» to strengthen something with technical skill.","Steadfast","اتقن الامر","27:88",1
2708,590,"S","رَبَطَ","«رَبَطَ» means to bind firmly; it is an idiom. «رَبَطَ اللہُ عَلٰی قَلْبِہٖ» Allah the Almighty strengthened and fortified his heart with patience. And «رِبَاط» means that with which something is bound. And «رَابِطَہ» means connection, union (manjad). For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ  اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا ؕ اِنۡ کَادَتۡ لَتُبۡدِیۡ بِہٖ  لَوۡ لَاۤ  اَنۡ رَّبَطۡنَا عَلٰی قَلۡبِہَا» (28/10)\nTranslation: And the heart of Moses' (peace be upon him) mother became restless. Had We not strengthened her heart, she would almost have disclosed the truth.","«رَبَطَ» meaning to tie firmly.","Strong","ربط","8:11-18:14-28:10",3
2709,590,"F","اٰزَرَ","«اَلْاِزْر» meaning root, bandage. And «اَلْاَزَار» meaning shawl, bandage, veil, wall backing. And «اٰزَرَ الْنَبَات» meaning the sprouting of plants. And «اَزَّرَہ» meaning to give strength, to strengthen (manjad). As if «اٰزَرَ» comes to gradually strengthen someone by giving them strength.  \nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:  \n«کَزَرۡعٍ  اَخۡرَجَ  شَطۡئَہٗ  فَاٰزَرَہٗ» (48/29)  \nTranslation: Like a crop that draws out its sprout, then strengthens it.","«اٰزَرَ» gradually reinforcing after empowering.","Firm","ازر","48:29",1
2710,590,"F","وَکَّدَ","This is the rope used to tie the legs of cows etc. while milking. And «وَکَّد» or «اَکَّدَ» or «اَوْکَدَ السَّرْج اَوِالْعَھْد» means to tighten the saddle firmly or to strengthen a contract (as in the sources). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ لَا تَنۡقُضُوا الۡاَیۡمَانَ بَعۡدَ تَوۡکِیۡدِہَا» (16/91). Translation: When you have firmly established your oaths, then do not break them.","«اَکَّدَ» Strengthening covenants, agreements, and oaths.","Firm","وکد","16:91",1
2711,590,"F","عَقَّدَ","«عَقَدَ» means to tie a knot. And «عَقَدَۃ» means knot, tangle, complex matter. And «عَقَّدُ الْبَیْع وَ الْیَمِیْن» means to make a sale or oath firm (recorded). And «عَقْد» means covenant, pledge, acknowledgment. Its plural is «عَقُوْد».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«لَا یُؤَاخِذُکُمُ اللّٰہُ بِاللَّغۡوِ فِیۡۤ  اَیۡمَانِکُمۡ وَ لٰکِنۡ یُّؤَاخِذُکُمۡ بِمَا عَقَّدۡتُّمُ الۡاَیۡمَانَ» (5/89)\nTranslation: Allah does not hold you accountable for your frivolous oaths, but He will certainly hold you accountable for the oaths you have firmly made.","«عَقَّدَ» serves to strengthen all forms of contracts and agreements, including trade, marriage, and others.","Firm","عقد","2:235-2:237-4:33-5:1-5:89-20:27-113:4",7
2712,590,"F","سَنَّدَ","«سَنَدَ» means to trust, to rely on, and to take support. And «سَنَّدَ» means to give support and strengthen (reinforcement). For example, when the roof beams are weak, one places another timber under them to reinforce the roof.\n\nFor instance, the Holy Quran states: «کَاَنَّہُمۡ خُشُبٌ مُّسَنَّدَۃٌ ؕ یَحۡسَبُوۡنَ  کُلَّ صَیۡحَۃٍ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (63:4). Translation: It is as if they (the hypocrites) are planks (leaned against a wall). (So cowardly that) they think every loud sound is a summons upon them.","to strengthen by giving support","Firm","سند","63:4",1
2713,590,"S","رَصَّ","«رَصَّ» means to mix one thing with another, to join and connect. And «رَصَاص» also means lead (as in solder). Therefore, «رَصَّہٗ» means to strengthen something by applying lead/solder to it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states: «اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُحِبُّ الَّذِیۡنَ یُقَاتِلُوۡنَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِہٖ  صَفًّا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  بُنۡیَانٌ  مَّرۡصُوۡصٌ» (61/4). Translation: Allah Almighty loves those who fight in His cause in tight ranks, as though they are a solid structure, like a wall reinforced with lead.","«رَصَّ» to strengthen something by pouring lead.","Strong","رص","61:4",1
2714,590,"S","شَیَّدَ","«شَادَا الْحَائِط» means to plaster walls with lime (munaajjad), and «شَیَّدَ» means to strengthen a building by plastering it with lime or another mortar. To build. (Example)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَیۡنَ مَا تَکُوۡنُوۡا یُدۡرِکۡکُّمُ الۡمَوۡتُ وَ لَوۡ کُنۡتُمۡ  فِیۡ  بُرُوۡجٍ مُّشَیَّدَۃٍ» (4/78)\nTranslation: Wherever you may be, death will overtake you, even if you are in fortified and lofty castles.","«شَیَّد» strengthening the building by plastering it with lime and other materials.","Strong","شید","4:78-22:45",2
2715,591,"F","عَفَا","«عَفَا» To renounce punishment or retribution against someone (i.e., to let go of the right to punish a person who deserves punishment). Not taking requital for a fault, whether the fault is minor or major. (The second meaning of «َفْو» should be observed in the sense of 'excess').\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«عَفَا اللّٰہُ عَنۡکَ ۚ لِمَ اَذِنۡتَ لَہُمۡ» (9/43)\nTranslation: May Allah forgive you, [O Muhammad]. Why did you permit [the stay of] the hypocrites?","«عَفَا» To release the one who is deserving of punishment.","Forgiven","عفا","2:52-2:109-2:178-2:187-2:237-2:286-3:152-3:155-3:159-4:43-4:99-4:149-4:153-5:13-5:15-5:95-5:101-7:199-9:43-9:66-22:60-24:22-42:25-42:30-42:34-42:40-58:2-64:14",28
2716,591,"F","اَصْفَحَ","To forgive. To let go. Not making someone feel the weight of their fault. Not even reproaching them. This act is more difficult than forgiveness. And «اَصْفَحَ ، عَفَا» is more potent than «اَصْفَحَ». «عَفَا» is the abandonment of punishment, and «اَصْفَحَ» comes for the abandonment of reproach. (مف) (م ۔ ل)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاعۡفُوۡا وَ اصۡفَحُوۡا حَتّٰی یَاۡتِیَ اللّٰہُ بِاَمۡرِہٖ» (2/109)\nTranslation: So pardon them and overlook [their misdeeds] until Allah executes His command.","«اَصْفَحَ» To forgive someone without letting them even feel the guilt of their fault.","Forgiveness","اصفح","2:109-5:13-15:85-24:22-43:89-64:14",6
2717,591,"F","غَفَرَ","«غَفَرَ» means placing something over something else to protect it from dirt, harm, or loss (detailed). They say «غَفَرَ الشَّبَاب بِالْخِضَاب» — he covered the white hair with henna. And «مِغْفَر» means what soldiers wear on their heads during battle. It is also called «اَلْغَفَارَۃ». And «اَلْغَفَارَۃ» is sometimes used for the cloth that women place under their dupatta to protect it from oil, and also for the cloth used to wrap the bow's edges (a protective covering). And in Allah's context, «غُفْرَان» means that He covers humans from the punishment of sins. And «غَفَرَ» means Allah's saving His servants from the punishment of their sins; its reward comes from «ل». And «غُفْرَان» entails the removal of punishment and makes reward obligatory (fiqh 195). For example, the Quran states: «وَ مَنۡ یَّغۡفِرُ الذُّنُوۡبَ اِلَّا اللّٰہُ» (3:135) Translation: And who can forgive sins except Allah? And for seeking forgiveness for sins from Allah, «اِسْتَغْفر» will come, and its relation is to Allah alone, whether Allah's name is mentioned or not. For example, the divine command states: «سَوَآءٌ  عَلَیۡہِمۡ  اَسۡتَغۡفَرۡتَ لَہُمۡ  اَمۡ لَمۡ تَسۡتَغۡفِرۡ لَہُمۡ» (63:6) Translation: Whether you ask forgiveness for them or not, it is the same for them.","«غَفَرَ»: Allah Ta'ala's protection of His servants from the punishment for their sins, i.e., forgiveness.","Forgiveness","غفر","2:58-2:175-2:199-2:221-2:263-2:268-2:284-2:285-2:286-3:16-3:17-3:31-3:129-3:133-3:135-3:136-3:147-3:157-3:159-3:193-4:48-4:64-4:96-4:106-4:110-4:116-4:137-4:168-5:9-5:18-5:40-5:74-5:118-7:23-7:149-7:151-7:155-7:161-7:169-8:4-8:29-8:33-8:38-8:70-8:74-9:80-9:113-11:3-11:11-11:47-11:52-11:61-11:90-12:29-12:92-12:97-12:98-13:6-14:10-14:41-18:55-19:47-20:73-22:50-23:109-23:118-24:22-24:26-24:62-26:51-26:82-26:86-27:46-28:16-33:35-33:71-34:4-35:7-36:11-36:27-38:24-38:25-38:35-39:53-40:7-40:55-41:6-41:43-42:5-42:37-42:43-45:14-46:31-47:15-47:19-47:34-48:2-48:11-48:14-48:29-49:3-51:18-53:32-57:20-57:21-57:28-59:10-60:4-60:5-60:12-61:12-63:5-63:6-64:14-64:17-66:8-67:12-71:4-71:7-71:10-71:28-73:20-74:56-110:3",124
2718,591,"F","تَصَدَّقَ","«تَصَدَّقَ» meaning to give up one's right and to forgive the debt of another (muf). For example: it is in the Holy Quran: «وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ ؕ وَ اَنۡ تَصَدَّقُوۡا خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ» (2/280) Translation: If the debtor is in difficulty, then grant him respite until it becomes easy for him, and if you forgive the debt, it is better for you.","«تَصَدَّقَ» is used to waive one's right.","Forgiveness","تصدق","2:280-4:92-5:45",3
2719,591,"F","تَجَاوَزَ","«جَازَ» means something being permissible, not prohibited. «جَاوَزَ الْمَکَان» means to go beyond a place. «تَجَاوَزَ عَنْہُ» means to overlook or forgive. «تَجَاوَزَ فِی الْاَمْرِ» means to exceed limits in an action (i.e., going beyond the bounds of moderation) or to be at fault (i.e., negligence and error), but not to hold accountable out of grace and favor.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ نَتَقَبَّلُ عَنۡہُمۡ  اَحۡسَنَ مَا عَمِلُوۡا وَ نَتَجَاوَزُ عَنۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ» (46/16)\nTranslation: These are the ones whose good deeds We will accept and from whose faults We will overlook.","«تَجَاوَزَ» meaning to overlook, to forgive, and to pardon.","Forgiveness","تجاوز","46:16",1
2720,591,"F","کَفَّر ( عن ) کَفَرَ","«کَفَّر» means to conceal. And «کُفْرَۃ» means the darkness of the night. And «کَفَّارَۃ» is the act whose performance results in covering sins. And «کَفَّرَ عَنْہُ» means to remove evils. Not holding them accountable. «کَفَّرَ عَنْ اِثْمِہٖ» means to expiate sins (mansuj). And the meaning of «اِبْطَالُ السَّیِّأت بِالْحَسَنَاتِ» (faq l 196). For example: In the Noble Quran it is stated: «وَ لَوۡ  اَنَّ  اَہۡلَ الۡکِتٰبِ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ اتَّقَوۡا لَکَفَّرۡنَا عَنۡہُمۡ سَیِّاٰتِہِمۡ» (5/65) Translation: And if the People of the Book had believed and been pious, We would have removed their evils from them.","«کَفَّرَعَنْ سیئات» is used to abolish and forgive sins through means.","Forgiven","کفر ( عن ) کفر","2:271-3:193-3:195-4:31-5:12-5:45-5:65-5:89-5:95-8:29-29:7-39:35-47:2-48:5-64:9-65:5-66:8",17
2721,591,"F","حِطَّۃٌ","«حَطَّ» means to descend or to be revealed. «حَطَّ السَّعْر» means a drop in price. And «حَطُّ الْحَمْلَ» means removing a load from an animal's back. And «اِنْحِطَاط» means a fall in price or initiative (stagnation), and «حَطُّ» means to take something down from above. They say: «حَطَطْتُ الرَّحَل» I removed the saddle from the mount and placed it below. From this, «حِطَّۃٌ» means the request to remove the burden of sins (figuratively). For example: In the Quran it is stated: «وَّ قُوۡلُوۡا حِطَّۃٌ نَّغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ خَطٰیٰکُمۡ» (2/58). Translation: And if you ask for forgiveness of your sins, then We will forgive your sins.","«حِطَّۃٌ» is used to seek forgiveness for sins.","Forgiveness","حطۃ","2:58-7:161",2
2722,592,"L","وُجْد","«وَجَدَ» means to obtain. And «وُجْد» means present/existent. موجودات refers to the essentials of life that one has available.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«اَسۡکِنُوۡہُنَّ  مِنۡ حَیۡثُ سَکَنۡتُمۡ مِّنۡ وُّجۡدِکُمۡ» (65:6)  \nTranslation: (Divorced) women should be kept in their domiciles during their waiting period, according to your means, where you yourselves reside.","This «وُجْد» is common for existing items.","Legal status","وجد","12:75-65:6",2
2723,592,"S","سَعَۃ","«سَعَۃ» meaning abundance, capacity, prosperity. This term is used to determine the degree of a person's prosperity. The concept of poverty is not found within it.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لِیُنۡفِقۡ  ذُوۡ سَعَۃٍ  مِّنۡ سَعَتِہٖ» (65/7)  \nTranslation: The person of means should spend according to their capacity.","«سَعَۃ» is used to determine prosperity and its degree.","spiritual rank","سعۃ","2:247-4:130-24:22-65:7",4
2724,592,"S","قَدَر","This word, in terms of its origin, is used to denote the state of poverty and to determine its degree. For instance, in the Noble Quran: «اَللّٰہُ یَبۡسُطُ الرِّزۡقَ لِمَنۡ یَّشَآءُ  وَ یَقۡدِرُ» (13/26) Translation: Allah Almighty expands the provision for whom He wills and restricts it for whom He wills. However, this word has also been employed by the Noble Quran to determine the degrees of both poverty and affluence. For instance, the divine command is: «عَلَی الۡمُوۡسِعِ قَدَرُہٗ  وَ عَلَی الۡمُقۡتِرِ قَدَرُہٗ مَتَاعًۢا بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡف» (2/236) Translation: The wealthy person should give this gift in a good manner according to his means, and the poor person according to his means.","Generally, «قَدَرَ» denotes constriction, and it is used to determine its degree.","Standing","قدر","13:26-17:30-28:82-29:62-30:37-34:36-34:39-39:52-42:12-65:7-89:16",11
2725,593,"D","فَرَضَ","«فَرَضَ» meaning to cut something hard, to pierce, and to mark on something hard, a line on stone. (M. L. Maf) And «فَرَّضَ الْخَشْبَۃَ» meaning to bore a hole in wood. And «فَرَضَ الْاَمْر» meaning to make something necessary and obligatory. And «اَلْفَرْض» meaning a law decreed by Allah Almighty or a thing made obligatory upon oneself (mansuj). And «فَرِیْضَۃً» meaning a stipulated, prescribed, or settled matter. The dowry of women (mansuj).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا جُنَاحَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ  اِنۡ طَلَّقۡتُمُ النِّسَآءَ مَا لَمۡ تَمَسُّوۡہُنَّ اَوۡ تَفۡرِضُوۡا لَہُنَّ فَرِیۡضَۃً» (2/236)\nTranslation: If you divorce women before consummating the marriage or before fixing their dowry for them, there is no blame upon you.","«فَرَضَ» to make obligatory and prescribe.","Decreed","فرض","2:197-2:236-2:237-4:11-4:24-9:60-24:1-28:85-33:38-33:50-66:2",11
2726,593,"E","وَکَّلَ","«وَکَلَ» meaning to trust another in one's affair (M. L.) and «وَکَّل» meaning to entrust one's affair to another by relying on them. To appoint a lawyer or deputy (M. F. Manj).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَاِنۡ یَّکۡفُرۡ بِہَا ہٰۤؤُلَآءِ  فَقَدۡ وَکَّلۡنَا بِہَا قَوۡمًا لَّیۡسُوۡا بِہَا بِکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (6/89)\nTranslation: So if these people (the disbelievers of Mecca) deny this Quran, We have appointed for it those who will believe in it and not deny it.","«وَکَّلَ» to appoint someone as one's deputy.","Established","وکل","6:89-32:11",2
2727,593,"D","اَجَّلَ","«اَجَل» means a fixed term for something. Then, the term appointed for human life is also called «اَجَل». It is an idiom: «دَنَا اَجَلُہٗ» means his time of death has drawn near, and «اَجَّلَ» means to fix a term for something.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ بَلَغۡنَاۤ  اَجَلَنَا الَّذِیۡۤ  اَجَّلۡتَ لَنَا» (6/128)\nTranslation: And (finally) we have reached the appointed time (the time of death) which You had fixed for us.","to appoint a fixed term","Decreed","اجل","2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-2:282-4:77-6:2-6:60-6:128-7:34-7:135-7:185-10:11-10:49-11:3-11:104-13:2-13:38-14:10-14:44-15:5-16:61-17:99-20:129-22:5-22:33-23:43-28:28-28:29-29:5-29:53-30:8-31:29-35:13-35:45-39:5-39:42-40:67-42:14-46:3-63:10-63:11-65:2-65:4-71:4",45
2728,594,"F","ذُبَاب","«ذُبَاب» means small fly. And «ذَبَّ عَنْہُ» means to drive flies away from someone, or to ward off accusations. And «مَذِبَّۃ» means a fly whisk, with which flies are shooed away. Its plural is «ذُبٌّ و اَذِبَّۃ». For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ یَّسۡلُبۡہُمُ الذُّبَابُ شَیۡئًا لَّا یَسۡتَنۡقِذُوۡہُ  مِنۡہُ» (22/73). Translation: And if a fly were to snatch something from them, they would not be able to retrieve it from the fly.","«ذُبَاب» meaning fly.","fly","ذباب","22:73",1
2729,594,"F","نَحْل","«نَحْل» is the plural of «نَحْلَۃٌ», meaning honey bee. It is a common gender noun, applicable to both masculine and feminine. For example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «وَ اَوۡحٰی رَبُّکَ اِلَی النَّحۡلِ اَنِ اتَّخِذِیۡ مِنَ الۡجِبَالِ بُیُوۡتًا وَّ مِنَ الشَّجَرِ وَ مِمَّا یَعۡرِشُوۡنَ» (16/68). Translation: And your Lord has inspired the honey bees, saying: 'Build your homes in the mountains, in the trees, and in the elevated structures that people construct.'","«نَحْل» is the genus name for the honey bee.","fly","نحل","16:68",1
2730,595,"T","لَقِیَ","«لَقِیَ» The coming together of two things face to face, meeting each other. Meeting by coming face to face.  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ اِذَا لَقُوا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَالُوۡۤا اٰمَنَّا» (2/14)  \nTranslation: And when they meet those who believe, they say, We have believed.","«لَقِیَ» The face-to-face meeting of two things.","to meet (with Allah)","لقی","2:14-2:76",2
2731,595,"T","لَحَقَ","«لَحَقَ» The meeting or joining of a thing with its like from the first (م ۔ ل).  \n«لَاحِق» The thing that joins with the first; the fruit of the second time after the first (manjadd).  \n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ یَسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡنَ بِالَّذِیۡنَ لَمۡ یَلۡحَقُوۡا بِہِمۡ مِّنۡ خَلۡفِہِمۡ  ۙ اَلَّا خَوۡفٌ عَلَیۡہِمۡ وَ لَا ہُمۡ یَحۡزَنُوۡنَ» (3/170) Translation: And those who are behind them—the people who have not yet joined them [in martyrdom]—are also pleased about the matter that when they come to join them, there will be no fear upon them, nor will they be grieved.  \n\nAt another instance, the Almighty declares:  \n«وَّ اٰخَرِیۡنَ مِنۡہُمۡ  لَمَّا یَلۡحَقُوۡا بِہِمۡ» (62/3) Translation: And (these messengers who have been sent to them) among them there are also others who have not yet joined them. And He is the Exalted in Might, the Wise.","«لَحَقَ» encountering its own kind for the first time.","to meet","لحق","3:170-62:3",2
2732,595,"T","وَلِیَ","«وَلَی یَلیٰ وَلْیًا» Meaning: to be near and close. To be connected. To go behind without separation (mansuj). To be joined due to closeness. This word is used in both linguistic and spatial contexts. This proximity is also in terms of lineage, or in terms of religion and friendship. (Note) The example of spatial proximity is:\n\nIn the Quran it is:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا قَاتِلُوا الَّذِیۡنَ یَلُوۡنَکُمۡ مِّنَ الۡکُفَّارِ» (9/123)\nTranslation: O you who have believed! Fight the disbelievers near you (those residing with you).\n\nIts meaning is that you should first fight the disbelievers who are adjacent to you. Then, if they become Muslim or accept obedience, fight those who are with them, and then those who reside with them. An example of temporal proximity is probably not found in the Quran. However, it is clarified by the following Prophetic saying:\n\nThe Prophetic saying is:\n«خَیْرُ الْقُرُوْنِ قَرْنِیْ ثُمَّ الَّذِیْنَ یَلُوْنَھُمْ ثُمَّ الَّذِیْنَ یَلُوْنَھُمْ»\nTranslation: The best generation is mine, then those who follow them, then those who follow them!\n\nAnd by this is meant the generation of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ, then the generation of the Companions, and then the generation of the Successors.","«وَلِیَ» The state of being united or conjoined for two living things without any temporal or spatial separation.","to meet","ولی","9:123",1
2733,595,"T","اَصْنٰی ( النَخَل )","«اَصْنٰی النَخَل» refers to two date palm trees originating from a single root (m. l.), and «صِنْو» also denotes that deep place which lies between two mountains, where the water from both flows together. Furthermore, when two or more date palms grow from a single root, each is the «صِنْو» of the other (m. q). Similarly, true siblings are also each other's «صِنْو» (m. q). For example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ نَخِیۡلٌ صِنۡوَانٌ وَّ غَیۡرُ صِنۡوَانٍ یُّسۡقٰی بِمَآءٍ وَّاحِدٍ» (13/4)\nTranslation: And the date palms, from the same root and trunk, are irrigated by the same water.","«اَصْنٰی» Things that unite, all sharing a single root.","to meet","اصنی ( النخل )","13:4",1
2734,595,"T","اِخْتَلَطَ","«اَخْتَلَطَ» The coming together and mixing of various different things is called 'gud mud' (mixing/blending). The opposite of «خَلَطَ» is «خَلَصَ» (m. l.), meaning 'khalat milat' (gud mud) or the state of being mixed/blended. For example: In the Quran it is: «کَمَآءٍ اَنۡزَلۡنٰہُ مِنَ السَّمَآءِ فَاخۡتَلَطَ بِہٖ نَبَاتُ الۡاَرۡضِ» (18/45) Translation: Like the rain that We sent down from the sky. Then the earth's vegetation, mixed and blended with that water, sprouted forth.","«اَخْتَلَطَ» to become all mixed up.","to meet","اختلط","6:146-10:24-18:45",3
2735,595,"T","تَجَاوَرَ","«جَارَ» means companion. Neighbor, and «جَاوَرَ» and «تَجَاوَرَ» signify being connected due to closeness in distance. They imply being in proximity, living as neighbors, being adjacent, and being in the same vicinity. For instance, the Quran states: «وَ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ قِطَعٌ مُّتَجٰوِرٰتٌ» (13:4). Translation: And on the earth are tracts of land that are adjacent to one another.","the coming together of two things due to their proximity","To meet","تجاور","13:4",1
2736,595,"T","رَتَقَ","«رَتَقَ» means the merging, joining, or adhering together of two or more things (as cited). And «رَتْقَاء» refers to a woman whose labial edges are fused in such a way that intercourse becomes impossible (as cited).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ  یَرَ الَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡۤا  اَنَّ  السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ کَانَتَا رَتۡقًا فَفَتَقۡنٰہُمَا» (21/30)\nTranslation: Have the disbelievers not considered that the heavens and the earth were a joined entity, sealed shut, and then We parted them?","«رَتَقَ» to unite and become firmly established. to become silent.","to meet","رتق","21:30",1
2737,595,"T","تَحَیَّزَ","«تَحَیَّز» meaning the separation of something and then its reunion. This term is from 'Lughat-e-Izdad'. \n\nNote: (Lughat-e-Izdad refers to words that have two distinct meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other).","«تَحَیَّز» to separate and then reunite.","to meet","تحیز","8:16",1
2738,595,"T","اِشْتَمَلَ","«اَلشَّمْل» meaning: the collective matter. Dispersed matter (this word is from the lexical opposites). «جَمَعَ اللہُ شَمْلَھُمْ» meaning: May Allah gather their scattered deeds. And «فَرَّقَ اللہُ شَمْلَھُمْ» meaning: May Allah scatter their gathering. And «شَمِلَ» meaning: to wrap in a cloth. And «شَمَلَ» and «شَمِلَ» meaning: to include everything. To be general (in the lexicon). And «اِشْتَمَلَ» meaning: to incorporate the scattered parts of a thing back into the original thing. To include completely.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«قُلۡ ءٰٓالذَّکَرَیۡنِ حَرَّمَ اَمِ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ اَمَّا اشۡتَمَلَتۡ عَلَیۡہِ اَرۡحَامُ الۡاُنۡثَیَیۡنِ ؕ» (6/143)\nTranslation: Then ask them, Has Allah forbidden the two males, or the two females, or that which is in the wombs of the two females?\n\nNote: (Lexical opposites are words that have two separate meanings, and those meanings are contrary and opposite to each other.)","To reassemble the scattered parts into the original whole.","to meet","اشتمل","6:143-6:144",2
2739,596,"M","خَلَطَ","«خَلَطَ» is the act of mixing or blending together two or more different things. Its opposite is «خَلَصَ».\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ اٰخَرُوۡنَ اعۡتَرَفُوۡا بِذُنُوۡبِہِمۡ خَلَطُوۡا عَمَلًا صَالِحًا وَّ اٰخَرَ  سَیِّئًا» (9:102)\nTranslation: And there are others who have acknowledged their sins. They had mixed good deeds with bad ones.","«خَلَطَ» to jumble different things together.","Maulana","خلط","9:102-38:24",2
2740,596,"I","اَلْحَقَ","«اَلْحَقَ» meaning to meet from behind.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«تَوَفَّنِیۡ مُسۡلِمًا وَّ اَلۡحِقۡنِیۡ  بِالصّٰلِحِیۡنَ» (12/101)\nTranslation: (O Allah) grant me death in a state of obedience and unite me with the righteous servants in the Hereafter.","«اَلْحَقَ» to mix from behind.","Islamic scholar","الحق","12:101-26:83-34:27-52:21",4
2741,596,"T","وَصَلَ","To join two things in such a way that they become inseparable (as defined). Its opposite is «ھِجْرَان». And (the opposite of connection is disconnection) joining, connecting. This word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. In a material sense, it means reaching something. In a spiritual sense, it means to connect and bind relationships, etc.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «وَ یَقۡطَعُوۡنَ مَاۤ اَمَرَ اللّٰہُ بِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّوۡصَلَ» (2/27). Translation: And they break the bond concerning which Allah had commanded them to join.","«وَصَلَ» mixing and joining.","to mix","وصل","2:27-4:10-4:90-6:136-11:81-13:21-13:25-14:29-17:18-28:35-28:51-38:56-58:8-82:15-84:12-87:12-92:15-111:3",18
2742,596,"R","اَلَّفَ","«اَلَّفَ» means to merge the scattered components of a single entity. It is to correct and reunite a dispersed arrangement, and its opposite is «شَتَّ». That is, to be in agreement with others' thoughts and to eliminate differences of hearts, thereby uniting them and creating love. And «اُلْفَت» means heartfelt love. And تالیف (compilation) is the term used for a phrase whose various parts have been correctly assembled in their proper places, considering precedence and sequence. (Source: Maf)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَلَّفَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ ؕ لَوۡ اَنۡفَقۡتَ مَا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ جَمِیۡعًا مَّاۤ  اَلَّفۡتَ بَیۡنَ قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ» (8/63)\nTranslation: And Allah has put affection between the believers. Even if you had spent all that is in the earth, you could not have put affection between them.","«اَلَّفَ» The process of reintegrating the disseminated, scattered components of a single entity.","Respected Scholar","الف","3:103-8:63",2
2743,596,"M","لَبَسَ","«یَلْبَسُ» means to wear clothing and cover the body. And «لَبَسَ یَلْبِسُ» means to mix something with another, thereby making the original thing doubtful and suspicious. And «تَلْبِیْس» means to hide the truth and manifest falsehood (concealment). And «لَیْس» occurs in the meanings of doubt (see doubt and suspicion). The usage of «لَبِسَ» is confined only to *iʿrāḍ* (i.e., aversion, turning away) and only in speech, such as mixing truth with falsehood (in Fiqh, p. 249).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَلۡبِسُوا الۡحَقَّ بِالۡبَاطِلِ» (2/42)\nTranslation: And do not mix truth with falsehood.","«لَبِسَ» Mixing one thing with another in order to deceive. It is employed in contexts of denial and in the form of speech, such as mixing truth with falsehood.","Maulana","لبس","2:42-3:71-6:9-6:65-6:82-6:137-50:15",7
2744,596,"T","رَکَّبَ","«رَکَبَ» means to mount or ride, i.e., to sit on top of one thing upon another. And «تَرَاکَبَ» means to place one thing upon another and combine them. And «رَکَّبَ» means to combine one thing with another, then a third, then a fourth, and so on. In this manner, combining many things to form a single entity. Combination (ترکیب) is a well-known term.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡ خَلَقَکَ فَسَوّٰىکَ فَعَدَلَکَ فِیۡۤ  اَیِّ صُوۡرَۃٍ  مَّا شَآءَ  رَکَّبَکَ» (82:7,8)\nTranslation: That very Being created you, perfected your limbs, and established balance within you. Then, in whatever form He willed, He combined you.","«رَکّب» combining one thing with a second, then with a third, to merge them into one.","to mix","رکب","82:8",1
2745,596,"M","ضَمَّ","«ضَمّ» to attach a related part of a single thing to it; to include (manjad). «ضَمِیْمَۃُ الْکِتَاب» is a famous term. For example, the Quran states: «وَ اضۡمُمۡ یَدَکَ  اِلٰی جَنَاحِکَ تَخۡرُجۡ بَیۡضَآءَ» (20/22). Translation: And (O Moses) when you draw your hand from your bosom, it will emerge completely white. Note: («ضَمِیْمَۃُ الْکِتَاب»: meaning something extra added as an augmentation to the original or essential part, a superfluous element that is included alongside the original).","«ضَمّ» to combine the relevant part of a thing with that thing.","Maulana","ضم","20:22-28:32",2
2746,596,"M","مَشَجَ","«مَشَجَ» meaning 'to mix'. To blend thoroughly, and «مَشَجَ» and «مَشِیْج» meaning 'mixed, blended'. Its plural is «اَمْشَاج». (manjada) i.e., two similar things mixing together to become one.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّا خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ مِنۡ نُّطۡفَۃٍ  اَمۡشَاجٍ ٭ۖ  نَّبۡتَلِیۡہِ» (76/2)\nTranslation: And indeed, We created man from an extract (i.e., a mixture) of a male and female (i.e., the sperm of both), which We then made into a clinging clot. And We have made [the sperm] into a mixed, blended substance.","«مَشَجَ» the merging of two similar things into one.","Maulana","مشج","76:2",1
2747,596,"M","مَزَجَ","«مَزَجَ» means to mix something into a drink. And «اَلشَّرَاب» also means to mix something into a drink. And that which is mixed into a drink is called «مِزْج» and «مِزَاج» (see: Majma‘ al-Bayan, Munjid). And in the terminology of «اَطِبَّاء», the quality that results from the mixing of different humors of the body is called mizaj (temperament). Nature. State (see: Mu‘jam al-Qamus, Qamus).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُسۡقَوۡنَ  فِیۡہَا کَاۡسًا کَانَ مِزَاجُہَا زَنۡجَبِیۡلًا» (76:17)\nTranslation: And they will be given to drink there a cup [of wine] mixed with ginger.\n\nIn the Quran, two such mizaj (mixtures), Kafur and Tasnim, are also mentioned.","to mix something into a drink","Maulana","مزج","76:5-76:17-83:27",3
2748,596,"M","مَرَجَ","«مَرَجَ» The meeting of two things in such a way that their individual identities remain preserved. «غُصْنٌ مَرِیْجٌ» Mutually intertwined branches, i.e., things that have become intermingled. And «اَمْرٌ مَرَیْج» meaning a complex and mixed-up situation in which two or more theories are entangled with each other (conc.).  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«مَرَجَ  الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ یَلۡتَقِیٰنِ» (55:19)  \nTranslation: He has set free two seas (rivers) that meet. (Jalandhari) / Two rivers flowing together. (Osmani)","Blending two like entities while retaining their separate identities. «مَرَجَ»","Maulana","مرج","25:53-55:19",2
2749,596,"T","شَابَ","«شَوْب» meaning mixing, deceiving, betraying (manjada). «شَوْب» also means honey. And every edible thing that is mixed into another thing. Honey is also called «شَوْب» because it is generally mixed into every drink. From this, the word shaibah is famous, which is used in the meanings of mixing and adulteration (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «ثُمَّ  اِنَّ لَہُمۡ عَلَیۡہَا لَشَوۡبًا مِّنۡ حَمِیۡمٍ» (37/67)\nTranslation: Then their food will be given to them mixed with scalding water.","«شَوْب» anything that is eaten or drunk after being mixed with another.","to mix","شاب","37:67",1
2750,596,"M","ضَغَثَ ( الحدیث )","«ضَغَثَ الْحَدِیْث» to mix up. To confuse. And «ضَغَثَ مِنَ الْخَیْرِا وَالْاَمْر» meaning a mixed good or transaction that has no reality or basis. And «اَضْغَثَ الرُّؤْیَا» meaning to narrate dreams with doubt. And «اَضْغَاثُ اَحْلَام» meaning frightening dreams. Mixed-type dreams whose reality cannot be stated (manjood).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡۤا اَضۡغَاثُ اَحۡلَامٍ ۚ وَ مَا نَحۡنُ بِتَاۡوِیۡلِ  الۡاَحۡلَامِ  بِعٰلِمِیۡنَ» (12/44)\nTranslation: They said, These are mixed dreams, and we are not skilled in the interpretation of such dreams.","«ضَغَثَ» to muddle up the conversation. To jumble up.","Mawlana","ضغث ( الحدیث )","12:44-21:5",2
2751,597,"F","اَعْرَضَ (عَنْ) عَرَضَ","«عَرَضَ» means to present something before someone. And «عَرْض» means entreaty, petition (mansaj). «اَعْرَضَ عَنْ» means to turn away from the front, to turn one's face away.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ اَعۡرَضَ عَنۡ ذِکۡرِیۡ فَاِنَّ لَہٗ مَعِیۡشَۃً ضَنۡکًا» (20/124)\nTranslation: And whoever turns away from My admonition, his life will become constricted.","«اَعْرَضَ عَنْ» to turn away; to turn one's face away.","Face","اعرض ( عن )۔ عرض","4:16-4:63-4:81-5:42-6:68-6:106-7:199-9:95-11:76-12:29-15:94-18:57-20:100-20:124-28:55-32:22-32:30-53:29-66:3",19
2752,597,"F","تَوَلّٰی عَنْ","«تَوَلّٰی» means to make someone a friend. And «تَوَلّٰی عَن» means to abandon friendship, to turn away, to become distant, to leave (manjada).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ تَوَلَّ عَنۡہُمۡ حَتّٰی حِیۡنٍ» (37/178)\nTranslation: So turn away from them for a while.","«تَوَلّٰی عَنْ» is used to end friendly relations.","Face","تولی عن","7:79-7:93-8:20-12:84-27:28-37:90-37:174-37:178-44:14-51:54-53:29-54:6",12
2753,597,"F","صَدَفَ","«اَعْرَضَ عَنْہُ و صَدّ» means to turn away obstinately. And «صَدَف» means a shell, the edge of a mountain, and the crookedness in a camel's legs. And stiffness and crookedness are also found in all three (detailed). Its consequence sometimes comes from «عَنْ» (but it retains its meaning even without this consequence).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«سَنَجۡزِی الَّذِیۡنَ یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ عَنۡ اٰیٰتِنَا سُوۡٓءَ الۡعَذَابِ  بِمَا  کَانُوۡا  یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ» (6/157)\nTranslation: Those who turn away from Our signs (either by turning their faces or turning others away) — We will punish them with a severe punishment because of their turning away.\n\nAt another place, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«اُنۡظُرۡ  کَیۡفَ نُصَرِّفُ الۡاٰیٰتِ ثُمَّ ہُمۡ یَصۡدِفُوۡنَ» (6/46)\nTranslation: Look how We explain the signs, yet they turn away.","«صَدَفَ» comes to cause severe turning away.","Face","صدف","6:46-6:157",2
2754,598,"C","وَفَّقَ","«اَلْوَفْق» means agreement and harmony between two things. And «وَفَّقَ تَوْفِیْقًا» means Allah Almighty making circumstances suitable and conducive for a particular task. This word is not used in a negative sense.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنۡ یُّرِیۡدَاۤ  اِصۡلَاحًا یُّوَفِّقِ اللّٰہُ بَیۡنَہُمَا» (4/35)\nTranslation: If both spouses wish reconciliation, Allah will create harmony between them.","«وَفَّقَ» God making circumstances favorable for someone (carrying a positive connotation, implying it is for a good purpose).","Conformity","وفق","4:35",1
2755,598,"C","وَطَأ","The meaning of «وَطَأ» is to crush, grind, or trample something underfoot. And «وَطَأ عَلَی الْاَمْر» means to make an action easy or convenient according to one's own will (manjada), and this action is of human nature and is generally used in a negative sense.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا النَّسِیۡٓءُ زِیَادَۃٌ فِی الۡکُفۡرِ  یُضَلُّ بِہِ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا یُحِلُّوۡنَہٗ عَامًا وَّ یُحَرِّمُوۡنَہٗ عَامًا لِّیُوَاطِئُوۡا عِدَّۃَ مَا حَرَّمَ اللّٰہُ فَیُحِلُّوۡا مَا حَرَّمَ اللّٰہُ» (9/37)\n\nTranslation: (By) altering the sacred months is an increase in disbelief. Through this, those who disbelieve are led astray. They make a month lawful one year and unlawful another to make the number of months sacred by Allah seem consistent (or to fulfill their desires).","«وَطَأ عَلَی الْاَمْر» refers to tampering with something in a person's work and altering it to suit one's own desires (used in a negative sense).","Conformity","وطأ","9:37",1
2756,599,"T","ثَنٰی","«اِثْنِیْن» means two and «ثانی» means second or another, and «ثَنٰی ، یَثْنِیْ» means to double, to fold, or to layer (figurative: to conceal or hide).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«اَلَاۤ  اِنَّہُمۡ  یَثۡنُوۡنَ صُدُوۡرَہُمۡ» (11/5)  \nTranslation: Look! These people fold (or double) their chests.","«ثَنٰی» to turn something toward one side, even if it becomes dual.","to turn away","ثنی","11:5",1
2757,599,"T","لَوٰی","«لَوَی الْحَبَل» means to twist or turn something. And «لَوٰی یَدَہٗ» means he twisted or turned his hand (figurative). And «لِیًّا بِدَیْنِہٖ» means to delay or procrastinate in the repayment of a debt. And «لِوَاء» means a flag (which flutters sometimes here, sometimes there). And «اَلْاَلْوَاءِ» means a bend in the valley (a meander).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنَّ مِنۡہُمۡ لَفَرِیۡقًا یَّلۡوٗنَ اَلۡسِنَتَہُمۡ بِالۡکِتٰبِ» (3/78)\nTranslation: And among them (the People of the Book) are some who twist their tongues while reading the Book (the Torah).","«لَوٰی» to bend or twist something this way and that.","to turn away (in rejection)","لوی","3:78-3:153-4:135-63:5",4
2758,600,"M","رَحْمَان - رَحِیْم","«رَحْمَان ، رَحِیْم» These two words are intensive forms derived from the root rahm (mercy), conveying the meaning of One who shows exceedingly great mercy. Within the concept of mercy, three elements are found: tenderness, kindness, and compassion (m. l.). In Rahman, the intensity is greater. In other words, in it the attribute of mercy is found to a higher degree. Rahman means the One who bestows equal favor upon all His creation—whether they be disbelievers and polytheists, or other living beings or inanimate objects. And what is meant by this are the favors of Allah from which all creation uniformly benefits, such as the sun, the moon, the stars, the wind, light, water, the earth, and its power of productivity (i.e., the act of growth or causing growth), and so on. Moreover, all such favors can be attributed solely to Allah, the Most High. Therefore, Rahman is exclusively Allah, the Most High; no human or created being can be Rahman. However, «رَحِیْم» a human can also be described as Rahim. And this word has been used in the Noble Quran for the Messenger of Allah ﷺ and also for the Companions. As for Rahim, when attributed to Allah, its meaning, according to some, is the One who shows mercy to His righteous servants in this world and the Hereafter. But defining it with such a restriction (i.e., specification) is not appropriate, because Allah, the Most High, hears the call of every compelled and needy being and, out of mercy, removes their afflictions—whether the one calling is a believer or a disbeliever and polytheist.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«بِسۡمِ اللّٰہِ الرَّحۡمٰنِ الرَّحِیۡمِ» (1/0)\nTranslation: In the name of Allah, the Most Gracious and the Most Merciful.","«رَحْمَان» is The Most Gracious, and this attribute belongs solely to God.  \n«رَحِیْم» is The Most Merciful. This attribute is on the second level from «رَحْمَان».","Merciful","رحمن ۔ رحیم","1:2-2:37-2:54-2:128-2:143-2:160-2:163-2:173-2:182-2:192-2:199-2:218-2:226-3:31-3:89-3:129-4:16-4:23-4:25-4:29-4:64-4:96-4:100-4:106-4:110-4:129-4:152-5:3-5:34-5:39-5:74-5:98-6:54-6:145-6:165-7:153-7:167-8:69-8:70-9:5-9:27-9:91-9:99-9:102-9:104-9:117-9:118-9:128-10:107-11:41-11:90-12:53-12:98-13:30-14:36-15:49-16:7-16:18-16:47-16:110-16:115-16:119-17:66-17:110-19:18-19:26-19:44-19:45-19:58-19:61-19:69-19:75-19:78-19:85-19:87-19:88-19:91-19:92-19:93-19:96-20:5-20:90-20:108-20:109-21:26-21:36-21:42-21:112-22:65-24:5-24:20-24:22-24:33-24:62-25:6-25:26-25:59-25:60-25:63-25:70-26:5-26:9-26:68-26:104-26:122-26:140-26:159-26:175-26:191-26:217-27:11-27:30-28:16-30:5-32:6-33:5-33:24-33:43-33:50-33:59-33:73-34:2-36:5-36:11-36:15-36:23-36:52-36:58-39:53-41:2-41:32-42:5-43:17-43:19-43:20-43:33-43:36-43:45-43:81-44:42-46:8-48:14-49:5-49:12-49:14-50:33-52:28-55:1-57:9-57:28-58:12-59:10-59:22-60:7-60:12-64:14-66:1-67:3-67:19-67:20-67:29-73:20-78:37-78:38",164
2759,600,"M","رَءُوْف","«رَأفَۃ» means to be filled with tenderness and to feel compassion. To have one's heart overflow upon seeing someone's hardship.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلزَّانِیَۃُ وَ الزَّانِیۡ فَاجۡلِدُوۡا کُلَّ وَاحِدٍ مِّنۡہُمَا مِائَۃَ جَلۡدَۃٍ ۪ وَّ لَا  تَاۡخُذۡکُمۡ بِہِمَا رَاۡفَۃٌ  فِیۡ  دِیۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (24/2)\nTranslation: Flog the adulterer and the adulteress, each of them, with a hundred stripes, and let not pity for them overcome you in the matter of Allah's law.\n\nAnd «رَءُوْف» means tender-hearted (i.e., one who feels compassion, merciful) whose heart aches upon seeing another's suffering, and who is deeply concerned with alleviating that suffering.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَقَدۡ جَآءَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلٌ مِّنۡ اَنۡفُسِکُمۡ عَزِیۡزٌ عَلَیۡہِ مَا عَنِتُّمۡ حَرِیۡصٌ عَلَیۡکُمۡ بِالۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ رَءُوۡفٌ رَّحِیۡمٌ» (9/128)\nTranslation: O people! A Messenger has come to you from among yourselves; your hardship is grievous to him. He is full of concern for your well-being and is kind and merciful to the believers.","«رَءُوْف» to be moved to the heart by seeing someone in distress.","Merciful","رءوف","2:143-2:207-3:30-9:117-9:128-16:7-16:47-22:65-24:20-57:9-59:10",11
2760,600,"M","لُطْف","In the fundamental meanings of «لُطْف», two aspects are identified: (1) precision of perception (i.e., subtlety of sight) (2) gentleness (م ۔ ل) and in the sense of «دَقْ اور رَق», i.e., being thin and soft or small (م ق). At times, in the meaning of Latif, only one aspect is found, namely precision of perception—that is, acute discernment, profound insight, or awareness of minute, subtle details.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا تُدۡرِکُہُ  الۡاَبۡصَارُ ۫ وَ ہُوَ یُدۡرِکُ الۡاَبۡصَارَ ۚ وَ  ہُوَ  اللَّطِیۡفُ الۡخَبِیۡرُ» (6:103)\nTranslation: Eyes comprehend Him not, but He comprehends all eyes. He is the Subtle, the Acquainted.\n\nAt other times, both aspects are present. That is, having knowledge of the creation's slightest afflictions and then, out of benevolence, removing them. In this context, the meaning of Latif is understood as 'Most Kind'.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command declares:\n«اَللّٰہُ  لَطِیۡفٌۢ  بِعِبَادِہٖ  یَرۡزُقُ مَنۡ  یَّشَآءُ» (42:19)\nTranslation: Allah is Most Gracious to His servants. He provides for whom He wills.","One who is attentive to minor details and eliminates them.","Merciful","لطیف","6:103-12:100-22:63-31:16-33:34-42:19-67:14",7
2761,600,"M","حَنَّان","«اَلْحَنِیْن» meaning to be drawn compassionately toward something. They say «حَنَتِ المَرْاَۃُ اَوِ النَّاقَۃُ لِوَلَدِھَا», meaning a woman or a she-camel turned affectionately toward her young or became eager for it (interpretation). And «حَنَّ» meaning to be kind and compassionate, and «حَنَّان» meaning mercy, kindness, and the compassionate one. It is one of the Beautiful Names of Allah (source: Manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ حَنَانًا مِّنۡ لَّدُنَّا وَ زَکٰوۃً ؕ وَ کَانَ تَقِیًّا» (19:13)\nTranslation: And (We granted Yahya peace be upon him) compassion and purity from Ourselves, and he was ever dutiful.","«حَنَّان» such mercy and compassion as a mother has for her child.","Merciful","حنان","19:13",1
2762,601,"S","طَبَعَ","«طَبَعَ» meaning to reach the extreme limit of something and to fill up. «تَطَبَّعَ النَّھْر» meaning the river is filled (M. L.) and also «طَبَعَ» meaning to stamp/seal. And «طَبَعَ الدَّرَاھِم» meaning to mint a coin. And «مَطْبَع» meaning the machine for stamping/sealing. And «مَطْبُوْع» meaning the hidden thing (manjada) and «طَوَابِع» meaning postage stamp (Q. J.) — it is called «طَبَعَ» when, upon the completion or conclusion of something, a stamp or seal is affixed. And its relation is to the effectuality of something (i.e., to be affected, to have an impact) and its remaining established and necessary (Fiqh al-... 56).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is: «بَلۡ طَبَعَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡہَا بِکُفۡرِہِمۡ فَلَا یُؤۡمِنُوۡنَ  اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا» (4/155) Translation: Rather, because of their disbelief, Allah has sealed their hearts, so they believe little.","«طَبَعَ» to print. to imprint.","Seal of Prophethood, seal, ring","طبع","4:155-7:100-7:101-9:87-9:93-10:74-16:108-30:59-40:35-47:16-63:3",11
2763,601,"S","خَتَمَ","«خَتَمَ» means to stamp or seal. To seal something completely (i.e., to close it and then apply a seal) so that nothing can enter (even if there is capacity for entry) and nothing can exit.  \n«خَتَمَ الْاَنَاء» means to close the mouth of a vessel with soil, etc.  \n«خَتَام» means the instrument or thing used for sealing (i.e., a seal or stamp).  \n«خَتَمَ الْقُرآن» means 'he has completed the Quran.' Thus, 'completion' pertains to something being fulfilled and the cessation (i.e., conclusion) of an action or deed (Faqih 56).  \n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:  \n«خَتَمَ اللّٰہُ عَلٰی قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ وَ عَلٰی سَمۡعِہِمۡ» (2/7)  \nTranslation: Allah Ta'ala has placed a seal on their (the disbelievers') hearts and ears.","«خَتَمَ» To seal something completely once it is finished, so that nothing can enter it nor anything exit from it.","seal","ختم","2:7-6:46-33:40-36:65-42:24-45:23",6
2764,602,"R","مَھَّلَ","«مَھَّلَ» means to grant respite or to do something gradually. «سَارَ عَلٰی مَھْلٍ» means to walk slowly (majid). «مَھَّل» means to gradually and gently extend the term for someone, without rushing (muf), and this term is prolonged (faq l 59).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَمَہِّلِ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  اَمۡہِلۡہُمۡ رُوَیۡدًا» (86:17).  \nTranslation: So give the disbelievers respite. Just a few days of respite.  \nIn this verse, «مَھَّل» and «اَمْھَل» are used with the same meaning.","«مَھَّلَ» and «اَمْھَلَ»: Gradually and gently granting respite (for an unspecified period).","Respite","مھل","73:11-86:17",2
2765,602,"R","اَمْلٰی","«مَلَا» (from the curtailed alif) means to prolong life. It is said, «مَلَاکَ اللہ» May God prolong your life. And «مَلَا» also means a vast desert, and it means to continue deriving benefit for a long time. And «مَلِیٌّ مِنَ الدَّھْر» means a long period (mansaj). And «مَلِیًّا» means a long duration (19/46). Thus, in «مَلِیٌّ», both meanings of prolongation and vastness are found. And «اَمْلٰی» means to grant someone respite until a long time—to extend the rope (for the wrongdoer) for a long duration.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ  اُمۡلِیۡ   لَہُمۡ  اِنَّ  کَیۡدِیۡ مَتِیۡنٌ» (7/183)\nTranslation: And I grant them respite. My plan is most formidable.","to let the rope hang loose","Respite","املی","7:183-13:32-22:44-22:48-68:45",5
2766,602,"R","نَظِرَۃٌ","«نَظَرَ» means to see or to cast a glance. And «نَظَرَ فُلَانَا الْمَدِیْن» means opting for leniency toward a debtor and continually casting a glance for the repayment of the loan (manjad). And «اَنْظَار» means waiting until an appropriate time to request something, and this period is conditional (fiqh 59). For example, the Quran states: «وَ اِنۡ کَانَ ذُوۡ عُسۡرَۃٍ فَنَظِرَۃٌ اِلٰی مَیۡسَرَۃٍ» (2/280). Translation: Then, if the debtor is in hardship, grant him respite until ease is attained.","«نَظِرَۃٌ» is understood as waiting with gentleness for a specified period.","Respite","نظرۃ","2:280-37:88",2
2767,603,"G","ضَیْف","«ضَیْف» means guest. It is a well-known word. Its plural forms are «ضَیَاف» and «ضُیُوف». The word «ضَیْف» can be used in both singular and plural forms.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَاتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لَا تُخۡزُوۡنِ فِیۡ ضَیۡفِیۡ» (11/78)\nTranslation: Fear Allah and do not disgrace me among my guests.","«ضَیْف» meaning guest.","Guest","ضیف","11:78-15:51-15:68-18:77-51:24-54:37",6
2768,603,"G","وَفَدَ","«وَفَدَ» denotes going as a delegation to a king or ruler, and also means a royal guest. For example, the Quran states: «یَوۡمَ نَحۡشُرُ الۡمُتَّقِیۡنَ  اِلَی الرَّحۡمٰنِ وَفۡدًا» (19/85) Translation: On the Day when We will gather the righteous before Allah as guests.","A delegation, meaning a royal guest.","Guest","وفد","19:85",1
2769,604,"M","شُھُوْر","«شُھُوْر» meaning the total number of months. The maximum number of months.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اِنَّ عِدَّۃَ الشُّہُوۡرِ عِنۡدَ اللّٰہِ اثۡنَا عَشَرَ شَہۡرًا فِیۡ  کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ یَوۡمَ خَلَقَ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضَ» ( 9/36 )\nTranslation: Indeed, the number of months ordained by Allah is twelve in the record of Allah from the day He created the heavens and the earth.","«شُھُوْر» means the months of the year.","months","شھور","9:36",1
2770,604,"M","اَشْھُرُ","«اَشْھُرُ» means the months of a prescribed period. Their number will, in any case, be less than twelve. When the mentioned number is singular, «اَشْھُرُ» will be used. «اَشْھُر» is the plural of scarcity, which is applied from three to ten.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لِلَّذِیۡنَ یُؤۡلُوۡنَ مِنۡ نِّسَآئِہِمۡ تَرَبُّصُ اَرۡبَعَۃِ اَشۡہُرٍ» (2/226)  \nTranslation: For those who take an oath to abstain from their wives, there is a waiting period of four months.","meaning the prescribed months","months","اشھر","2:185-2:194-2:197-2:217-2:226-2:234-4:92-5:2-5:97-9:2-9:5-9:36-34:12-46:15-58:4-65:4-97:3",17
2771,605,"N","دُسُر","«دُسُر» is the plural form of «دِسَار», meaning a nail or peg. «دَسَر» means to spear or to drive in a peg. «دِسَار» refers to the small peg that is driven in to close a crack, fissure, or gap in something, or to make it firm. Also, «دِسَار» is the rope made from the bark of a date-palm, used to bind a ship. (Nail, from *manjad*)\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ  حَمَلۡنٰہُ  عَلٰی ذَاتِ اَلۡوَاحٍ  وَّ دُسُرٍ» (54/13)\nTranslation: And We carried Noah on a ship [made] from planks and nails.","«دُسُر» meaning nail, peg.","Nail","دسر","54:13",1
2772,605,"P","اَوْتَاد","«اَوْتَاد» is plural. «وَتَد» refers to a large peg or stake, part of which is outside and the greater part is inside the earth or something else. And «وَتَدَان» means the protruding parts of the shoulders (m.f. manajid), i.e., «وَتَد» is that thing of which some part has come out. And «وَتَدَ» means a strong, driven peg, and «وَتْد» means a wooden peg, and «اَوْتَادُ الْاَرْضِ» means a mountain (m.q).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَمۡ  نَجۡعَلِ الۡاَرۡضَ مِہٰدًا وَّ  الۡجِبَالَ  اَوۡتَادًا» (78/6,7)\nTranslation: Did We not make the earth a resting place? And the mountains as pegs?","«اَوْتَاد» meaning wooden pegs, stakes, pins, or dowels.","peg","اوتاد","38:12-78:7-89:10",3
2773,606,"H","یَأَسَ","«یَأَسَ» means qat'u al-raja (m. l.), i.e., to cease hoping or become despairing regarding a matter. This can occur either before or after the time of desire (fiqh 203).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (12:87)\nTranslation: It is only the disbelievers who despair of Allah's mercy.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَیْئَس» means gradually ceasing expectations regarding a matter. Ultimately becoming despairing after experience.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا اسۡتَیۡئَسَ الرُّسُلُ وَ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ قَدۡ کُذِبُوۡا جَآءَہُمۡ نَصۡرُنَا» (12:110)\nTranslation: Even when the messengers had lost hope and were convinced that they were not proven true (regarding victory and success), then at that moment Our help came to them.","«یَأَسَ» to despair. It is commonly used in the sense of hopelessness.\n«اِسْتَیْئَس» to gradually lose hope.","Hopeless","یأس","12:80-12:87-12:110-13:31",4
2774,606,"D","قَنَطَ","«قَنَطَ» means to despair of goodness, to lose hope and become despondent (figurative). And «قُنُوْط» means «اَشدُّ مُبَالِغَۃ إِِنَّ الْیَاس» (in Fiqh 283), i.e., it refers to extreme despair. And قُنُوْط describes a person or قنوطی describes someone who is accustomed to considering only the dark aspects and drawbacks of every matter and who rarely ponders the good sides.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَا یَسۡئَمُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِنۡ دُعَآءِ  الۡخَیۡرِ ۫ وَ اِنۡ مَّسَّہُ  الشَّرُّ  فَیَئُوۡسٌ قَنُوۡطٌ» (41/49)\nTranslation: Man does not tire of praying for good. But if evil touches him, he despairs and loses all hope.","«قَنَطَ» is to despair of goodness or to remain in that state. «یَأَسَ» is a more severe degree of despair.","Despair","قنط","15:56-30:36-39:53-41:49-42:28",5
2775,606,"H","اَبْلَسَ","«اَبْلَسَ» means to become sorrowful due to intense despair (figurative) and also means to become unaware. To be sorrowful and broken-hearted (mujnad). When grief befalls due to becoming hopeless, then this word is used. And Satan (Iblis) is also called Ablis for this very reason, that he became despairing and broken-hearted, having lost hope in Allah's mercy.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِنۡ کَانُوۡا مِنۡ قَبۡلِ اَنۡ یُّنَزَّلَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ مِّنۡ  قَبۡلِہٖ لَمُبۡلِسِیۡنَ» (30/49)\nTranslation: And before the rain fell, they had lost hope.","«اَبْلَسَ» a crushing hopelessness that plunges one into grief.","Hopeless","ابلس","6:44-23:77-30:12-30:49-43:75",5
2776,607,"R","رِجْس","«رِجْسٌ» It also conveys the meanings of 'impurity' and 'uncleanness'. (See details under 'impurity') And this refers to the impurity of such things that Shariah has declared haram or unclean, whether they are material or spiritual.\n\nFor example: In the Quran:\n«فَاَعۡرِضُوۡا عَنۡہُمۡ ؕ اِنَّہُمۡ  رِجۡسٌ ۫ وَّ مَاۡوٰىہُمۡ  جَہَنَّمُ» (9:95)\nTranslation: So do not turn towards the hypocrites; they are unclean people, and their abode is Hell.","«رِجْسٌ» the prohibited things as prescribed by Sharia.","ritually impure","رجس","5:90-6:125-6:145-7:71-9:95-9:125-10:100-22:30-33:33",9
2777,607,"R","خَبِیْث","«خَبِیْث» means impure and filthy. Its opposite is «طَیَّب», meaning pure. «خَبِیْث» is used in both material and spiritual contexts. In material terms, it refers to rubbish and worthless things. «خَبِثُ الْحَدِیْد» means the dross of iron. Additionally, this word is also used for things that are filthy, rotten, and foul-smelling.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَیَمَّمُوا الۡخَبِیۡثَ مِنۡہُ تُنۡفِقُوۡنَ وَ لَسۡتُمۡ بِاٰخِذِیۡہِ اِلَّاۤ اَنۡ تُغۡمِضُوۡا فِیۡہِ» (2/267)\nTranslation: And whatever you spend in the cause of Allah, do not intend to spend therein any filth or worthless thing which you would not accept yourself, except that you overlook it.\n\nWhen used in a spiritual sense, 'khabeeth' refers to a person whose nature is inclined to obscenity or who is mischievous.\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states:\n«اَلۡخَبِیۡثٰتُ لِلۡخَبِیۡثِیۡنَ وَ الۡخَبِیۡثُوۡنَ لِلۡخَبِیۡثٰتِ» (24/26)\nTranslation: Impure women are for impure men, and impure men are for impure women.","«خَبِیْث» garbage and filthy things, and people whose nature is prone to vulgarity.","Ritually impure","خبیث","2:267-3:179-4:2-5:100-7:58-8:37-14:26-24:26",8
2778,607,"R","نَجَسٌ","This term is also used for both external and internal impurity. Its antonyms are «طَاھِر» and «طَھُوْر». «دَاءٌ نَجِسٌ وَّ نَاجِسٌ» means an incurable disease. And «نَجَّسَ الصَّبِی» means to hang an amulet, etc., on a child's neck to protect it from the evil eye. And «نُجُس» refers to people who practice talismanic charms (manjad). The material use of this word does not occur in the Quran. However, when used in a spiritual sense, it refers to such a filth of disbelief and polytheism that assumes the form of an incurable disease.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِنَّمَا الۡمُشۡرِکُوۡنَ نَجَسٌ فَلَا یَقۡرَبُوا الۡمَسۡجِدَ الۡحَرَامَ بَعۡدَ عَامِہِمۡ ہٰذَا» (9/28)\nTranslation: O you who have believed, indeed the polytheists are impure. So let them not approach the Sacred Mosque after this, the final year of theirs.","«نَجَسَ» Those people who are deeply entrenched in the doctrines of disbelief and polytheism, whose malady has become incurable. And the things whose impurity has been explicitly declared by Sharia.","ritually impure","نجس","9:28",1
2779,608,"D","مَکْرُوْہ","«کَرِہَ» means to dislike something. And *makruh* (detestable) is every matter that a person of sound nature finds repulsive and from which their nature recoils (unacceptable).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَیُحِبُّ  اَحَدُکُمۡ  اَنۡ یَّاۡکُلَ  لَحۡمَ اَخِیۡہِ  مَیۡتًا فَکَرِہۡتُمُوۡہُ» (49/12)\nTranslation: Would any of you like to eat the flesh of his dead brother? You would surely detest it!\n\nThen there are matters which, on the surface, appear to be worthy of dislike but in reality are based on benefit. The Shariah has identified such matters.\n\nFor example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is:\n«کُتِبَ عَلَیۡکُمُ الۡقِتَالُ وَ ہُوَ کُرۡہٌ لَّکُمۡ ۚ وَ عَسٰۤی اَنۡ تَکۡرَہُوۡا شَیۡئًا وَّ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ لَّکُمۡ» (2/216)\nTranslation: Fighting has been enjoined upon you, though it is disliked by you. And perhaps you dislike a thing while it is good for you.\n\nThus, *makruh* is that thing which is disapproved of by both intellect and Shariah. (Source: *Mafatih al-Ghayb*)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُلُّ ذٰلِکَ کَانَ سَیِّئُہٗ عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ مَکۡرُوۡہًا» (17/38)\nTranslation: All of these (mentioned habits) are greatly detestable to your Lord.","«مَکْرُوْہ» that which a person of upright nature (i.e., composed, good-natured) dislikes.","Disapproved","مکروہ","2:216-3:83-4:19-8:8-9:32-9:33-9:46-9:53-9:81-10:82-10:99-13:15-16:62-16:106-17:38-20:73-24:33-40:14-41:11-46:15-47:9-47:26-47:28-49:7-49:12-61:8-61:9",27
2780,608,"D","اِدَّ","«اِدَّ» means an extremely detestable matter that causes an uproar. And «اَرِیْد» means commotion. Uproar (lit.) and «اَدَّ الْاَمْر» means to be burdensome and difficult (in work). «اَدِیْد» means commotion and «اِدّ» means calamity, terrible event, difficult task (manjad). That is, such a detestable matter that causes an uproar.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَ قَالُوا  اتَّخَذَ  الرَّحۡمٰنُ  وَلَدًا لَقَدۡ  جِئۡتُمۡ  شَیۡئًا  اِدًّا» (19/88,89). Translation: And they say, 'Allah has a son'; this is indeed a very evil statement that you utter.","«اِدَّ» A severely objectionable thing that causes an uproar.","disapproved","اد","19:89",1
2781,608,"D","مُنْکِر","«مُنْکِر» every strange and astonishing thing, every matter that is disapproved or forbidden by Sharia, evil words or evil deeds. And 'munkar' refers to every matter that society considers reprehensible and evil.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَلۡتَکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ اُمَّۃٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡخَیۡرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» ( 3/104 )\nTranslation: There should be a group among you who invite people to goodness, enjoin what is right, and forbid what is wrong.\n\nThus, Sharia has not left 'munkar' merely to the approval or disapproval of society; rather, wherever an incorrect or impermissible practice becomes prevalent in society and is not considered reprehensible by it, Sharia has rectified it as well.\n\nFor example: The Divine Command states:\n«وَ تَاۡتُوۡنَ فِیۡ نَادِیۡکُمُ الۡمُنۡکَرَ» ( 29/29 )\nTranslation: And you commit abominations in your gatherings.","«مُنْکِر» The matter that society deems reprehensible and evil.","Disapproved","منکر","3:104-3:110-3:114-5:79-7:157-9:67-9:71-9:112-12:58-16:90-22:41-22:72-24:21-29:29-29:45-31:17-58:2",17
2782,608,"D","اِمْر","«اِمْر» meaning every irrational and un-Islamic statement ( manjada ) meaning «مُنْکَرًا عَظِیْمًا» ( m. q ) «اَمِرَ الْاَمْر» exceeding the limit in any matter or statement ( maf ) an extremely unreasonable statement.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ اَخَرَقۡتَہَا لِتُغۡرِقَ اَہۡلَہَا ۚ لَقَدۡ جِئۡتَ شَیۡئًا اِمۡرًا» ( 18/71 )\nTranslation: Moses said, Have you broken it (the ship) so that you may drown its people? You have certainly done a grave wrong.","«اِمْر» An utterly unreasonable, irrational, and un-Islamic matter.","disapproved","امر","18:71",1
2783,608,"D","مَذْمُوْم ، مَذْءُوْم","«ذَمَّ» and «ذَءَمَ» both carry the same meaning: to consider something despicable and blameworthy. In «ذَءَمَ», two elements are fundamental: (1) aversion and (2) fault-finding. It also means to find fault, to show contempt, to disgrace. The opposite of «ذَمَّ» is «حَمَدَ» and «مَدَحَ», meaning praise and commendation. Furthermore, «ذَمَّ» means to point out someone's faults, whether they are optional (chosen) or necessary (compulsory), i.e., done under duress.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«قَالَ اخۡرُجۡ مِنۡہَا مَذۡءُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» (7:18)\nTranslation: Allah the Most High said, Then get out from here, humiliated and disgraced.","«مَذْمُوم» bad, evil, corrupt, ugly, something that is condemned.\n«مَذْءُوْم» meaning disliked due to some flaw.","Disapproved","مذموم ، مذءوم","7:18-17:18-17:22-68:49",4
2784,608,"D","اُفّ","Literally, it refers to every dirty and detestable thing, such as filth, grime, and nail clippings, etc. But figuratively, this word is used to express disgust toward something bad.  \nFor example, in the Quran, it says:  \n«اُفٍّ لَّکُمۡ وَ لِمَا تَعۡبُدُوۡنَ مِنۡ دُوۡنِ اللّٰہِ» (21/67)  \nTranslation: Taf upon you and upon those whom you worship besides Allah.","Figuratively, «اُفّ» is used to express hatred toward something bad.","disapproved","اف","17:23-21:67-46:17",3
2785,609,"I","جَاھِلْ","«جَاھِلْ» meaning ignorant, unaware. Its opposite is «عَالِم», also ignorant. «جَھَلَ» means a human mind devoid of knowledge. The reason for this could be anything (muf); this word is general. For example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَحۡسَبُہُمُ الۡجَاہِلُ اَغۡنِیَآءَ مِنَ التَّعَفُّفِ» (2/273)\nTranslation: Ignorant people consider them wealthy due to their lack of questioning.","«جَاھِلْ» meaning ignorant, unaware.","Ignorant","جاھل","2:67-2:273-6:35-7:199-11:46-12:33-12:89-25:63-28:55-39:64",10
2786,609,"I","سُفَھَاء","«سُفَھَاء» is «سَفِیْھَہ ، سَفّہ», meaning of low intellect and base character. Its opposite is «حِلم», meaning forbearance, patient temperament, and gentleness. In the meaning of «سُفَھَاء», two things are found: (1) low intellect and (2) being of base character (م. ل). And «سَفِیْہ» means an ignorant person who, due to a lack of intellect, remains incapable of learning or acquiring knowledge, and whose character is also base. That is, it is his habit to object without knowing or understanding—a fool (م. ق).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «سَیَقُوۡلُ السُّفَہَآءُ مِنَ النَّاسِ مَا وَلّٰىہُمۡ عَنۡ قِبۡلَتِہِمُ الَّتِیۡ کَانُوۡا عَلَیۡہَا» (2:142). Translation: Now these foolish people will say, What is this that has made these Muslims turn away from the Qiblah, the direction they used to face as they went?","«سُفَھَاء» denoting one of low intellect and base character.","ignorant","سفھاء","2:13-2:130-2:142-4:5-6:140-7:155",6
2787,610,"D","سَخَط","«سَخَطَ» means displeasure, dislike. Its opposite is «رِضْوَان», which means contentment and pleasure. And «سَخَطَ» also means being unhappy at acting against one's will, being angry. For example: the Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ اُعۡطُوۡا مِنۡہَا رَضُوۡا وَ اِنۡ لَّمۡ یُعۡطَوۡا مِنۡہَاۤ اِذَا ہُمۡ یَسۡخَطُوۡنَ» (9/58)\nTranslation: If they get (sufficient) from it, they become pleased, and if they do not get (enough), they become angry immediately.","«سَخَطَ» signifies displeasure.","Displeasure","سخط","3:162-5:80-9:58",3
2788,610,"D","ضِغْن","«ضِغْن» meaning deeply concealed enmity, overwhelming hatred—a resentment that one keeps hidden in the heart and does not expel from it.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَمۡ حَسِبَ الَّذِیۡنَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمۡ مَّرَضٌ اَنۡ  لَّنۡ یُّخۡرِجَ اللّٰہُ  اَضۡغَانَہُمۡ» (47/29)\n\nTranslation: Do those in whose hearts is disease think that Allah will never reveal their [malice]?","«ضِغْن» meaning hostility, rancor, hatred, spite.","Displeasure","ضغن","47:29-47:37",2
2789,610,"D","غِلّ","The meanings of غِلّ are found to be two-fold: (1) Intensity of envy, hidden hostility (figurative), and (2) To steal and betray; to secretly take something and keep it in one's belongings (lit. Quran). And «غِلّ» means envy. کھوٹ (from منجد).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ نَزَعۡنَا مَا فِیۡ صُدُوۡرِہِمۡ مِّنۡ غِلٍّ» (7/43)\nTranslation: And We will remove from their hearts whatever rancor (envy) there may be.","«غِلّ» meaning resentment, a displeasure that escalates to the point of enmity and is harbored in the heart.","Displeasure","غل","7:43-15:47-59:10",3
2790,611,"U","کَفُوْر","Two meanings are found for «کَفَرَ»: (1) denial of God, and (2) denial of God's blessings. To be ungrateful for a favor. The terms «کَافِر» are generally used for the one who denies God, and «کَفُوْر» or «کَفّار» for the one who denies His blessings. Its opposites are «شاکِر» and «شَکُوْر».\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  السَّبِیۡلَ  اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا» (76:3)\nTranslation: We have shown man the way; now whether he is grateful or ungrateful.","meaning 'forgotten favor'","Ungrateful","کفور","11:9-17:27-17:67-17:89-17:99-22:38-22:66-25:50-31:32-34:17-35:36-42:48-43:15-76:3-76:24",15
2791,611,"U","کَنُوْد","«کَنَدَ» means to be ungrateful, and «کَنُوْد» refers to one who constantly mentions trials and hardships yet never even alludes to God's bounties. Ungrateful, miserly, perfidious (Munjid, etc.).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«اِنَّ  الۡاِنۡسَانَ لِرَبِّہٖ  لَکَنُوۡدٌ» (100/6)  \nTranslation: Indeed, man is ungrateful (and thankless) to his Lord.","«کَنُوْد» Such an ungrateful person who is always mentioning trials and difficulties, yet never even mentions the blessings bestowed by Allah.","Ungrateful","کنود","100:6",1
2792,612,"D","عَصٰی","«عَاصِی» means not obeying the command. Disobeying (Munjid) means not implementing a good deed (Mufradat), whether done knowingly or by mistake. And «عِصْیَان» means disobedience (49:7). And «عَاصِی» means disobedient. And «عِصِیًّا» means extremely disobedient (19:44). For example, the Quran states: «وَعَصٰۤی اٰدَمُ  رَبَّہٗ  فَغَوٰی» (20:121). Translation: Adam (peace be upon him) disobeyed his Lord, so he became astray.","«عَاصِی» who occasionally does not implement a command, whether intentionally or by mistake.","Disobedience","عصی","2:61-2:93-3:112-3:152-4:14-4:42-4:46-5:78-6:15-10:15-10:91-11:59-11:63-14:36-18:69-19:14-19:44-20:93-20:121-26:216-33:36-39:13-49:7-58:8-58:9-60:12-66:6-69:10-71:21-72:23-73:16-79:21",32
2793,612,"D","فَسَقَ","«فَاسِق» means to deviate from the path of truth and rectitude; to become a sinner (manjada); to step out of obedience (m. l.). The word «فَاسِق» is used for a habitual disobedient person. Whereas the word fisq is used for the commission of any sin, major or minor. It refers to one who does not adhere to Shariah rulings (muf). However, such a person still considers sin to be sin (muf).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَفَمَنۡ کَانَ مُؤۡمِنًا کَمَنۡ کَانَ فَاسِقًا» (32/18)\nTranslation: Can one who is a believer be like one who is a sinner?","«فَاسِق» who makes a habit of sins and does not repent. However, he certainly regards sinful acts as sinful.","Defiance","فسق","2:59-5:3-6:49-6:121-6:145-7:163-7:165-10:33-17:16-18:50-29:34-32:20-46:20",13
2794,612,"D","فَجَرَ","«فَجَرَ» means to rip something apart widely, and «فَاجِر» refers to a person who is completely submerged in sins, does not even consider them as sins, and shows no inclination toward repentance. (Muf) Immoral. And «فُجُور» means engrossed in sins. Fornicator (manjad). And «فَجَرَ» means to act with insolence.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّکَ اِنۡ تَذَرۡہُمۡ یُضِلُّوۡا عِبَادَکَ وَ لَا یَلِدُوۡۤا  اِلَّا  فَاجِرًا کَفَّارًا» (71/27)\nTranslation: (O Allah) if You leave them, they will mislead Your servants, and those who are born to them will also be wicked and ungrateful.","«فَجَرَ» meaning to persist in sins heedlessly, to commit sins, and to engage in immoral acts.","Disobedience","فجر","38:28-71:27-75:5-80:42-82:14-83:7-",6
2795,613,"N","اَنْف","«اَنْف» means 'nose.' A well-known body part. Since the nose protrudes, any protruding part of something is also called «اَنْف». For example, «اَنْفُ الْجَبْل» means the protruding part of a mountain (figurative).\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it says: «وَ الۡعَیۡنَ بِالۡعَیۡنِ وَ الۡاَنۡفَ بِالۡاَنۡفِ» (5/45)\nTranslation: An eye for an eye and a nose for a nose.","The term «اَنْف» is used for the body organ (nose).","nose","انف","5:45",1
2796,613,"N","خُرْطُوْم","«خُرْطُوْم» means an elephant's trunk. And «اِنْخَرْطَمَ» means a long nose whose front part reaches down to the feet, and also means to raise one's nose (i.e., to be arrogant, to act haughtily). Its plural is «خَرَاطِیْم». And «خَرَاطِیْمُ الْقَوْم» means the leaders of a people and arrogant individuals (see *Minaj*, vol. ...).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِذَا تُتۡلٰی عَلَیۡہِ اٰیٰتُنَا قَالَ اَسَاطِیۡرُالۡاَوَّلِیۡنَ . سَنَسِمُہٗ عَلَی الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68:15-16)\nTranslation: When Our verses are recited to him, he says, These are just tales of the ancients. We will surely mark his nose.","«خُرْطُوْم» A long, downward-growing or hooked nose, or the nose of a proud and arrogant person.","nose","خرطوم","68:16",1
2797,614,"N","اِسْم ( سُمُو )","«اِسْم» means the name of a thing. «سُمُو» means elevation. And a word is called 'ism' (name) because through it, the knowledge of that thing is attained, and its mention is elevated. (Mufradat) Its plural is «اَسْمَاء».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ عَلَّمَ اٰدَمَ الۡاَسۡمَآءَ کُلَّہَا» (2/31)\nTranslation: And Allah taught Adam the names of all things.\n\nAnd «سَمَّی» means to name. And in this naming, it is not necessary to consider the attributes of the thing or for the name (ism) to correspond to the named thing (musamma).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَتُجَادِلُوۡنَنِیۡ فِیۡۤ  اَسۡمَآءٍ سَمَّیۡتُمُوۡہَاۤ  اَنۡتُمۡ  وَ اٰبَآؤُکُمۡ» (7/71)\nTranslation: Do you dispute with me over names which you and your fathers have named?\n\nAnd «سَمِیًّا» means homonym (same name).\n\nFor example: The Divine declaration states:\n«اسۡمُہٗ یَحۡیٰی ۙ لَمۡ  نَجۡعَلۡ  لَّہٗ  مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ  سَمِیًّا» (19/7)\nTranslation: His name will be John. We have not given this name to anyone before him.","«اِسْم» a name given for introduction and identification.","Name","اسم ( سمو )","2:31-2:33-2:114-3:45-5:4-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:138-7:71-7:180-12:40-17:110-19:7-20:8-22:28-22:34-22:36-22:40-22:78-24:36-49:11-53:23-55:78-56:74-56:96-59:24-61:6-69:52-73:8-76:25-87:1-87:15-96:1",34
2798,614,"N","لَقَب","«لَقَب» Attributive names are names, other than the original name, given to someone due to a particular attribute. For example, Messiah is a title for Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him), who spent his entire life traveling in preaching and chose a celibate (i.e., without a spouse and children) life.\n\nFor instance: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِذۡ قَالَتِ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ یٰمَرۡیَمُ اِنَّ اللّٰہَ یُبَشِّرُکِ بِکَلِمَۃٍ مِّنۡہُ ٭ۖ اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ» (3:45)\nTranslation: And when the angels said, O Mary, indeed Allah gives you good tidings of a word from Him, whose name will be the Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary.\n\nIn this verse, Messiah is a title. Jesus is the original name, and son of Mary denotes his lineage. Since he had no father, Allah the Exalted attributed him to his mother.","An attributive name: a name given due to a particular attribute, aside from the original name.","Name","لقب","49:11",1
2799,614,"N","نَبَز","«اَلنَّبْز» is also a type of epithet, but in it, the evil traits of a person are highlighted, whether they are actually present in them or not, and whether they pertain to lineage or character. And «نبز» means to give someone a bad name or epithet (as in the lexical sources).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَنَابَزُوۡا بِالۡاَلۡقَابِ» ( 49/11 )\nTranslation: And do not call each other by [bad] nicknames.","«نَبَز» A name that brings shame.","name","نبز","49:11",1
2800,614,"N","فُلَانٌ","«فُلَانٌ» Its feminine form is «فُلَانَۃٌ». It serves as a substitute for the noun. Therefore, when it comes for those of sound intellect, «ال» can be inserted. They say: «رَکَیْتُ الْفُلَانَ» I rode such-and-such a (male) animal, and «جَلَبْتُ الْفُلَانَۃَ» I milked such-and-such a (female) animal.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is: «یٰوَیۡلَتٰی لَیۡتَنِیۡ لَمۡ اَتَّخِذۡ فُلَانًا خَلِیۡلًا» (25/28)\n\nTranslation: Alas, would that I had not made so-and-so a friend!","«فُلَانٌ» to say 'so-and-so' instead of mentioning a person's name","Name","فلان","25:28",1
2801,615,"T","مَشْئَمَۃ","«شَئَم» means unfortunate and ominous, and «شَاءَمَ» means taking from the left side (manjad). «شَئَمَ» is the opposite of «یَمَنَ». «یمن» means the right side or right hand, and also signifies blessing. The root word for «شَأمَ» is shamat (misfortune). «شَامَت» refers to that misfortune or bad luck in which a person's own actions play a greater role. Misfortune of deeds is a well-known term. And «مَشْئَمَۃْ», meaning unfortunate and left-sided, is akin to «شَئَمَ»—that misfortune which manifests as a result of one's own deeds.\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا بِاٰیٰتِنَا ہُمۡ اَصۡحٰبُ الۡمَشۡئَمَۃِ» (90/19). Translation: And those who did not believe in Our verses, they are the unfortunate (destitute).","«مَشْئَمَۃ» meaning ill omen or misfortune.","the Blessed","مشئمۃ","56:9-90:19",2
2802,615,"B","نَحَسَ","«نَحَسَ» Its opposite is «سَعَد». And «سَعَد» means that divine matters are a helper and assistant to humans in attaining good fortune and goodness (Mufradat). And «نَحُوْسَت» is that in which the divine will has greater involvement. In the terminology of astronomers, «نَحْسَان» refers to Saturn and Mars, and «سَعْدَان» refers to Jupiter and Venus (Manjad).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡ یَوۡمِ  نَحۡسٍ  مُّسۡتَمِرٍّ» (54:19)\nTranslation: And We sent upon the people of 'Ad a fierce, bitter wind on a day of relentless calamity.","«نَحَسَ» means to be unfortunate or wretched.","Blessed be his name","نحس","41:16-54:19",2
2803,615,"T","حُسُوْم","«حُسُوْم» A persistent calamity that continues uninterrupted, to the point of wiping out all traces. (For details, see 'persistent').\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«سَخَّرَہَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ  سَبۡعَ  لَیَالٍ وَّ ثَمٰنِیَۃَ اَیَّامٍ ۙ حُسُوۡمًا ۙ فَتَرَی الۡقَوۡمَ فِیۡہَا صَرۡعٰی» (69/7)\nTranslation: Allah Almighty caused it (the furious wind) to continue uninterrupted for seven nights and eight days. So you would have seen the people lying prostrate as if they were hollow tree trunks.","«حُسُوْم» is a calamity that persists until it erases all traces.","the Blessed Name","حسوم","69:7",1
2804,616,"S","نَجٰی","The word «نَجَات» is used exclusively to denote attaining relief from a calamity. To gain release. In any manner whatsoever. Its usage is general.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ  بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And among the two prisoners, the one who had been released said, and he remembered [the matter] after a period of time.","«نَجٰی» meaning to get relief from some calamity.","Salvation","نجی","2:49-2:50-6:63-6:64-7:64-7:72-7:83-7:89-7:141-7:165-10:22-10:23-10:73-10:92-10:103-11:58-11:66-11:94-11:116-12:45-12:110-14:6-17:67-19:72-20:40-20:80-21:9-21:71-21:74-21:76-21:88-23:28-26:65-26:119-26:170-27:53-27:57-29:15-29:24-29:32-29:65-31:32-37:76-37:115-37:134-39:61-40:41-41:18-44:30-54:34-61:10-70:14",52
2805,616,"S","فَازَ","The word «فَازَ» is used to signify escaping a calamity and reaching the beloved object. (Fiqh, p. 273) Meaning: to attain good safely. (مف)\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» (3/185)\nTranslation: Whoever is kept far from the Fire (Hell) and is admitted to Paradise has attained salvation.\n\nFurthermore, the word «فَازَ» is also derived from an antonymous lexicon. «فَوْز» means both to attain salvation and to perish; «فَوَّزَ الرَّجُل» means the person died; and «مَفَازَۃ» means the cause of salvation, the place of success or the cause of success, the place of destruction or the cause of destruction. (Manjad, m. l.)\n\nFor instance, the divine command of Allah states:\n«فَلَا تَحۡسَبَنَّہُمۡ بِمَفَازَۃٍ مِّنَ الۡعَذَابِ ۚ وَ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ اَلِیۡمٌ» (3/188)\nTranslation: Do not think concerning them that they will escape the punishment; for them is a painful punishment.\n\nIn this verse, the word «مَفَازَۃ» conveys the meaning of the place of destruction and its cause.","«فَازَ» meaning to be saved from some calamity and to reach the beloved thing.","Salvation","فاز","3:185-4:13-4:73-5:119-6:16-9:72-9:89-9:100-9:111-10:64-33:71-37:60-40:9-44:57-45:30-48:5-57:12-61:12-64:9-85:11",20
2806,617,"V","نَذْر ( ج نذور )","«نَذْر» is a collective term for «نُذُورٌ», meaning to make a non-obligatory act obligatory upon oneself due to some incident. And «نَذَرَ» means to make a vow or pledge. Although such a vow is generally conditional upon circumstances, its fulfillment remains necessary and obligatory.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«ثُمَّ لۡیَقۡضُوۡا تَفَثَہُمۡ وَ لۡیُوۡفُوۡا نُذُوۡرَہُمۡ» (22:29)\nTranslation: (After the Hajj pilgrims have offered the sacrifice) they should remove their impurities and fulfill their vows.","«نَذْر» (vow or pledge) means voluntarily assuming a non-obligatory act as a result of some incident or event.","Vows and supplications","نذر ( ج نذور )","2:270-3:35-19:26-22:29",4
2807,617,"T","قُرْبَان","«قُرْبَانَ الْمَلَک» meaning the companion of the King. And a qurban is any thing through which attaining closeness to Allah, the Most High, is intended. Whether it is an animal sacrifice or something else (or any other thing). And all forms of vows, dedications, and sacrifices made for other than Allah are forbidden, because these too are forms of financial worship (but the polytheists also present vows, dedications, sacrifices, etc., to others besides Allah, whom they regard as worthy of reverence).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِذۡ قَرَّبَا قُرۡبَانًا فَتُقُبِّلَ مِنۡ اَحَدِہِمَا وَ لَمۡ یُتَقَبَّلۡ مِنَ الۡاٰخَرِ» (5/27)\nTranslation: When both (Abel and Cain) presented some offerings (to Allah), the offering of one was accepted while that of the other was not.","«قُرْبَان» All that a person gives solely to attain Allah's pleasure and closeness to Him in His path.","Total surrender to God; utter dependence on the Divine.","قربان","3:183-5:27",2
2808,618,"S","لَانَ","«لَانَ ، لِیْن» means to be soft, to be flexible. (e.g.) And «قَوْلًا لَّیِّنًا» means soft speech (20/44). It appears that this word is used in both material and spiritual contexts. And its opposite is «خَشُونَت», meaning roughness and harshness.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «ثُمَّ  تَلِیۡنُ جُلُوۡدُہُمۡ وَ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ  اِلٰی ذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (39/23) Translation: Then their haste and their hearts soften, turning towards the remembrance of Allah.\n\nAnd to denote softening, «اَلَان» is used. For example: The command of Allah, the Exalted, is: «وَ اَلَنَّا لَہُ  الۡحَدِیۡدَ اَنِ اعۡمَلۡ سٰبِغٰتٍ وَّ قَدِّرۡ فِی السَّرۡدِ» (34/11) Translation: And for David, We had softened iron, so make wide coats of mail and join the rings with precision.","«لَانَ» the softness and flexibility of something.","Soft / Gentle (often used in Islamic contexts to describe the gentle nature of the Quran or the attribute of Allah as being Most Gentle/Kind)","لان","39:23",1
2809,618,"G","اَدْھَنَ","«دُھْن» means oil, grease, fat. And «اَدْھَنَ» means to soften something by applying oil. When used in a spiritual or moral sense, it implies that while one's heart holds something else, they adopt a demeanor of gentleness and flattery with their speech to deceive the other person. To be lax. To flatter. To practice hypocrisy (M. Q).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَدُّوۡا  لَوۡ  تُدۡہِنُ  فَیُدۡہِنُوۡنَ» (68/9)\nTranslation: These people wish that you [O Prophet] adopt leniency, so they too would become lenient.","«اَدْھَنَ» meaning to soften something by applying oil.","Gentle","ادھن","23:20-68:9",2
2810,618,"G","اٰہَ","«اٰہَ» means sighing (in illness) and expressing sorrow. And «اَوَّاہٌ» means tender-hearted, soft-hearted, one who sighs and laments with prayer (Quranic usage).\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ اِبۡرٰہِیۡمَ  لَاَوَّاہٌ  حَلِیۡمٌ» (9/114)\nTranslation: Indeed, Abraham (peace be upon him) was most tender-hearted and forbearing.","Softness of the heart, meaning to have a tender heart.","Gentle","اہ","9:114-11:75",2
2811,618,"G","تَلَطَّفَ","«لَطْفَ» Two meanings are found in it: (1) to know and be mindful of small matters, and (2) to remove its harmful aspects (see Merciful). And «تَلَطّف» means to adopt the aspect of caution and gentleness in performing a task.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلۡیَاۡتِکُمۡ بِرِزۡقٍ مِّنۡہُ  وَ لۡـیَؔ‍‍‍تَلَطَّفۡ وَ لَا  یُشۡعِرَنَّ  بِکُمۡ  اَحَدًا» (18/19)\nTranslation: So that he may bring you food from it and come with gentleness, and not expose any of you to anyone.","«تَلَطَّفَ» to adopt a cautious and gentle approach in carrying out a task.","Gentle","تلطف","18:19",1
2812,619,"N","کَادَ","«کَادَ» meaning to be on the verge of doing something (lit.) and meaning to be prepared to do something but not necessarily doing it (fig.). This form is derived from the verbs of nearness and requires another verb with it. Only the past and present tenses are used.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«یَکَادُ الۡبَرۡقُ یَخۡطَفُ اَبۡصَارَہُمۡ» (2/20)\nTranslation: It is near that the lightning snatches away their sight.","«کَادَ» to be on the verge of doing something but not doing it.","near","کاد","2:20-2:71-4:78-7:150-9:117-14:17-17:73-17:76-18:93-19:90-20:15-22:72-24:35-24:43-25:42-28:10-42:5-43:52-67:8-68:51-72:19",21
2813,619,"N","قَرُبَ","«قَرُبَ» means to be near. Its opposite is «بَعُدَ», meaning to be far. The usage of «قَرُبَ» is general. That is, it is used for the nearness of distance, time, lineage, and status. Now, observe the examples:\n\n(1) For proximity in distance, in the Quran it is:\n«اَوۡ  تَحُلُّ قَرِیۡبًا مِّنۡ دَارِہِمۡ» (13/31)\nTranslation: Or (some calamity) will continue to befall near their homes.\n\n(2) Another example for proximity in distance in the Quran is:\n«وَ لَا تَقۡرَبُوۡہُنَّ حَتّٰی یَطۡہُرۡنَ» (2/222)\nTranslation: And do not approach them (your wives) until they are pure.\n\n(3) For proximity in lineage, in the Quran it is:\n«لَا نَشۡتَرِیۡ بِہٖ ثَمَنًا وَّ لَوۡ  کَانَ ذَا قُرۡبٰی» (5/106)\nTranslation: We will not accept any recompense from anyone, even if he is a close relative.\n\n(4) For proximity in status, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اَنۡ تَعۡفُوۡۤا اَقۡرَبُ لِلتَّقۡوٰی» (2/237)\nTranslation: But if you remit it as a charity, it is nearer to piety.\n\nThe word «اِقْتَرَبَ» is used more for proximity in time and status.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«وَ اسۡجُدۡ وَ اقۡتَرِبۡ» (96/19)\nTranslation: Prostrate and draw near.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ  وَ انۡشَقَّ  الۡقَمَرُ» (54/1)\nTranslation: The Hour has drawn near, and the moon has split.\n\nAnd for proximity in status, the word «قَرَّبَ» is used specifically. And it comes in the meanings of bringing someone near.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«اسۡمُہُ الۡمَسِیۡحُ عِیۡسَی ابۡنُ مَرۡیَمَ وَجِیۡہًا فِی الدُّنۡیَا وَ الۡاٰخِرَۃِ وَ مِنَ الۡمُقَرَّبِیۡنَ» (3/45)\nTranslation: Whose name is the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary, who will be honored in this world and the Hereafter, and he will be one of those near to Me.","«قَرُبَ» meaning to be near, this word is commonly used; that is, it is employed for the nearness of all things—distance, duration, lineage, and status.","Near","قرب","2:35-2:187-2:222-2:237-3:167-4:11-4:43-4:172-5:8-5:82-6:151-6:152-7:19-7:114-9:28-9:99-12:60-16:77-17:32-17:34-17:57-18:24-18:81-19:52-22:13-26:42-34:37-39:3-46:28-50:16-51:27-56:11-56:85-56:88-83:21-83:28",36
2814,619,"N","دَنٰی","«دَنٰی» is generally used for the proximity of distance (see page 353), and 'dunya' means the realm of the near, the present universe. And its opposite is «آخرت».\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states: «ثُمَّ  دَنَا فَتَدَلّٰی» (53/8). Translation: Then he drew near, then he paused.\n\nAnd sometimes it also comes to denote a fall in rank and status. «اَدْنٰی» means mean, insignificant. And its opposite is «اَعْلٰی».\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states: «اَتَسۡتَبۡدِلُوۡنَ الَّذِیۡ ہُوَ اَدۡنٰی بِالَّذِیۡ ہُوَ خَیۡرٌ» (2/61). Translation: Do you intend to exchange the better thing for the worse?\n\nAnd for the proximity of time, «اَدْنٰی» is used in the sense of approximately, nearly.\n\nFor example, the Divine Command states: «اِنَّ  رَبَّکَ یَعۡلَمُ  اَنَّکَ  تَقُوۡمُ  اَدۡنٰی مِنۡ ثُلُثَیِ الَّیۡلِ» (73/20). Translation: Your Lord knows that you stand [in prayer] nearly two-thirds of the night.","«دَنٰی» is used to indicate proximity in distance and a decline in value and status.","Near","دنی","2:61-2:282-4:3-5:108-7:169-30:3-32:21-33:51-33:59-53:8-53:9-58:7-73:20",13
2815,619,"N","اَزِفَ","«اَزِفَ» comes to signify the nearness of time, and within it the meaning of the constriction of time is found. It is said «اَزِفَتِ الشُّخُوْصُ», meaning 'the time of the Hour has drawn near' (muf.), and the Day of Judgment is named «اٰزِفۃ» because there is little time until its arrival.  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«وَ اَنۡذِرۡہُمۡ یَوۡمَ الۡاٰزِفَۃِ» (40/18)  \nTranslation: And warn them of the Day that is ever drawing near.","«اَزِفَ» is used to express time constraints.","Near","ازف","40:18-53:57",2
2816,619,"N","زَلَفَ","«زَلَفَ» is used to denote nearness in degree and rank.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اِنَّ لَہٗ عِنۡدَنَا لَزُلۡفٰی وَ حُسۡنَ مَاٰبٍ» (38/40)\nTranslation: And for Solomon, with Us is nearness and an excellent position.\nAnd to bring near, to cause to approach, to bring close, «اَزْلَفَ» is used, and in this usage, the meaning of honor and rank is not necessarily implied.\nFor example: The Divine declaration states:\n«وَ  اِذَا  الۡجَنَّۃُ   اُزۡلِفَتۡ» (81/13)\nTranslation: And when Paradise is brought near.","«زَلَفَ» comes for the sake of proximity in honor and status.","Near","زلف","26:64-26:90-34:37-38:25-38:40-39:3-50:31-67:27-81:13",9
2817,619,"N","قَابَ ( الارض )","«قَابَ» means digging the earth in a circular manner, and «قَاب» means quantity, estimate, the distance from the notch of a bow to its grip. «ھُوَ عَلیٰ قَابَ قَوْسَیْن» is a metaphor (منجد).  \nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«فَکَانَ قَابَ قَوۡسَیۡنِ  اَوۡ اَدۡنٰی» (53/9)  \nTranslation: So he remained at a distance of about two bow-lengths, or even less.","The interval of extreme proximity, such as the distance from one corner of a bow to the grip.","Near","قاب ( الارض )","53:9",1
2818,619,"N","اِقْتَرَنَ","«قَرَن» This is also said for the rope with which two camels are tied together. And «قَرِیْن» means companion (muf), and «قَرَنَ» means to place one thing near another, and «قَرَنَ الثَّوْرَیْن» means to join two oxen together in a Punjabi (style/plough). And «اِقْتَرَنَ» contains intensification, i.e., bringing them extremely close (m. q.). And in «اِقْتَرَن», after one comes immediately the second, then the third, then the fourth. In this way, the meaning of continuity, succession, or consecutiveness is also found due to this very nearness.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اَوۡ جَآءَ  مَعَہُ الۡمَلٰٓئِکَۃُ  مُقۡتَرِنِیۡنَ» ( 43/53 )\nTranslation: Or (it would be) that the angels gather together and come to him (Jalandhari)\nOr: The angels come to him, tied in a bundle (Othmani)","«اِقْتَرَنَ» such proximity in time or duration that the two things appear to be joined.","Near","اقترن","43:53",1
2819,620,"S","اَثر ( ج اٰثار )","«اَثَر» means obtaining something that indicates the existence of the original thing (meaning), and also means the traces left behind of something by which that thing is remembered (i.e., remnants). Ancient traces and the science of traces are well-known terms. That is, the knowledge of things by which the memory of great personages, to whom those things were related, is kept fresh. And the word «اٰثار» is sometimes also used for footprints or the traces left by someone passing by.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَارۡتَدَّا عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمَا قَصَصًا» (18:64)\nTranslation: So both of them turned back, recognizing the traces of their feet.","«اَثَر» refers to the vestiges or traces left by something that point to the existence of the original.","sign","اثر ( ج اثار )","5:46-18:6-18:64-20:84-20:96-30:50-36:12-37:70-40:21-40:82-43:22-43:23-46:4-48:29-57:27-100:4",16
2820,620,"S","علامت ( ج علامات )","«عَلَامَت» is the plural of «عَلَامَات». Every such sign that is not evident in itself but through which knowledge of another reality is obtained (e.g., determining time and direction by observing stars at night, or estimating time and direction from the sun and shadow, or diagnosing a disease from a patient's symptoms). The indication is of the desired thing, such as clouds are an indication of rain, whereas «اَثَر» is related to something that comes after it. (Faq l 55) For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ عَلٰمٰتٍ ؕ وَ  بِالنَّجۡمِ  ہُمۡ  یَہۡتَدُوۡنَ» (16/16) Translation: And signs are placed in the paths, and people also find their way by the stars.","«عَلَامَت» An indication that is not self-evident but elucidates another matter and precedes it.","Sign","علامت ( ج علامات )","16:16",1
2821,620,"S","اٰیَۃ","«اٰیَۃ» Any sign which, upon contemplation, grants knowledge of both the thing itself and its intricacies (for example, a person knowing that certain types of markers exist along a specific route). If those markers are then found, certainty will arise that the path has been found and one is proceeding correctly. In the Quran, the word 'āyah' (verse) is used in three meanings: (1) a sentence of the Quran; (2) in the sense of a 'sign'—as defined above; (3) a miracle granted to the prophets. Any sentence of the Quran, by virtue of its eloquence and rhetorical beauty, inherently indicates that it is the speech of a Being transcendent above humanity. In this sense too, every sentence is a sign. And in the other meanings, such verses naturally fall under the aforementioned categories.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«سَنُرِیۡہِمۡ  اٰیٰتِنَا فِی الۡاٰفَاقِ  وَ فِیۡۤ   اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ حَتّٰی یَتَبَیَّنَ  لَہُمۡ  اَنَّہُ  الۡحَقُّ» ( 41/53 )\nTranslation: They will show their signs within themselves until it becomes evident to them that the Quran is the truth.","«اٰیَۃ» a sign whose knowledge is attained through contemplation.","Sign","ایۃ","2:39-2:41-2:61-2:73-2:99-2:106-2:118-2:129-2:145-2:151-2:164-2:187-2:211-2:219-2:221-2:231-2:242-2:248-2:252-2:259-2:266-3:4-3:7-3:11-3:13-3:19-3:21-3:41-3:49-3:50-3:58-3:70-3:97-3:98-3:101-3:103-3:108-3:112-3:113-3:118-3:164-3:190-3:199-4:56-4:140-4:155-5:10-5:44-5:75-5:86-5:89-5:114-6:4-6:21-6:25-6:27-6:33-6:35-6:37-6:39-6:46-6:49-6:54-6:55-6:65-6:68-6:93-6:97-6:98-6:99-6:105-6:109-6:118-6:124-6:126-6:130-6:150-6:157-6:158-7:9-7:26-7:32-7:35-7:36-7:37-7:40-7:51-7:58-7:64-7:72-7:73-7:103-7:106-7:126-7:132-7:133-7:136-7:146-7:147-7:156-7:174-7:175-7:176-7:177-7:182-7:203-8:2-8:31-8:52-8:54-9:9-9:11-9:65-10:1-10:5-10:6-10:7-10:15-10:17-10:20-10:21-10:24-10:67-10:71-10:73-10:75-10:92-10:95-10:97-10:101-11:1-11:59-11:64-11:96-11:103-12:1-12:7-12:35-12:105-13:1-13:2-13:3-13:4-13:7-13:27-13:38-14:5-15:1-15:75-15:77-15:81-16:11-16:12-16:13-16:65-16:67-16:69-16:79-16:101-16:104-16:105-17:1-17:12-17:59-17:98-17:101-18:9-18:17-18:56-18:57-18:105-18:106-19:10-19:21-19:58-19:73-19:77-20:22-20:23-20:42-20:47-20:54-20:56-20:126-20:127-20:128-20:133-20:134-21:5-21:32-21:37-21:77-21:91-22:16-22:51-22:52-22:57-22:72-23:30-23:45-23:50-23:58-23:66-23:105-24:1-24:18-24:34-24:46-24:58-24:59-24:61-25:36-25:37-25:73-26:2-26:4-26:8-26:15-26:67-26:103-26:121-26:128-26:139-26:154-26:158-26:174-26:190-26:197-27:1-27:12-27:13-27:52-27:81-27:82-27:83-27:84-27:86-27:93-28:2-28:35-28:36-28:45-28:47-28:59-28:87-29:15-29:23-29:24-29:35-29:44-29:47-29:49-29:50-30:10-30:16-30:20-30:21-30:22-30:23-30:24-30:25-30:28-30:37-30:46-30:53-30:58-31:2-31:7-31:31-31:32-32:15-32:22-32:24-32:26-33:34-34:5-34:9-34:15-34:19-34:38-34:43-36:33-36:37-36:41-36:46-37:14-38:29-39:42-39:52-39:59-39:63-39:71-40:4-40:13-40:23-40:35-40:56-40:63-40:69-40:78-40:81-41:3-41:15-41:28-41:37-41:39-41:40-41:44-41:53-42:29-42:32-42:33-42:35-43:46-43:47-43:48-43:69-44:33-45:3-45:4-45:5-45:6-45:8-45:9-45:11-45:13-45:25-45:31-45:35-46:7-46:26-46:27-48:20-51:20-51:37-53:18-54:2-54:15-54:42-57:9-57:17-57:19-58:5-62:2-62:5-64:10-65:11-68:15-74:16-78:28-79:20-83:13-90:19",353
2822,620,"S","مُبْصِرَۃً","«مُبْصِرَۃ» means a clear and evident sign that opens one's eyes (i.e., makes the truth apparent), and this term is generally applied to a miracle.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَتۡہُمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا مُبۡصِرَۃً  قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا  سِحۡرٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ» (27:13)\nTranslation: When Our clear signs came to them, they said, This is indeed manifest sorcery.\n\nOn another occasion, the Almighty declares:\n«وَ اٰتَیۡنَا ثَمُوۡدَ النَّاقَۃَ  مُبۡصِرَۃً» (17:59)\nTranslation: And We gave to the people of Thamud the she-camel as a clear sign.\n\nFurthermore, if the rejection by disbelievers is repeated after the words of a verse, whether mentioned in the Quran or in Hadith, then the meaning of that verse also becomes a miracle.\n\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«اِقۡتَرَبَتِ السَّاعَۃُ  وَ انۡشَقَّ  الۡقَمَرُ وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54:1,2)\nTranslation: The Hour has drawn near, and the moon has split. And if they see a sign, they turn away and say, This is continuous magic.","«مُبْصِرَۃ» – a clear and evident sign that opens the eyes, a miracle.","Sign","مبصرۃً","17:12-17:59-27:13-50:8",4
2823,620,"S","شَرْط","«اَشْرَطَ الْاِبِلَ» means to mark a camel and separate it for sale, and the plural of «شرط» is «اشراط», meaning sign, mark. The beginning of everything (manjad) means a specific ruling whose occurrence or fulfillment is connected with another ruling. And the second matter serves as a sign for it, and «اَشْرَاطُ السَّاعَۃ» means signs of the Day of Judgment (muf).\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «فَہَلۡ یَنۡظُرُوۡنَ  اِلَّا السَّاعَۃَ  اَنۡ تَاۡتِیَہُمۡ بَغۡتَۃً ۚ فَقَدۡ جَآءَ  اَشۡرَاطُہَا» (47/18). Translation: Now these people are only awaiting that the Hour should come upon them unexpectedly. So its signs have already come (in occurrence).","«شَرْط» The existence or completion of something being contingent upon another thing; for example, wudu is a condition for prayer—without it, prayer is not valid.","Sign","شرط","47:18",1
2824,620,"S","نُصُب","«نَصَبَ الشَّیْءِ» means to make something stand upright; to erect. And «اَلنَّصْب» means a raised flag; an erected sign. And «نُصُب» and «نُصْب» mean an erected sign; a landmark. (See: Majid)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَخۡرُجُوۡنَ  مِنَ الۡاَجۡدَاثِ سِرَاعًا کَاَنَّہُمۡ  اِلٰی نُصُبٍ یُّوۡفِضُوۡنَ» (70:43)\nTranslation: On that Day they will rush forth from the graves as if they were racing towards a sign.","«نُصُب» a path marked by piles of stones or markers, etc.","Sign","نصب","5:3-70:43-88:19",3
2825,620,"M","سِیْمَا","«سِیْمَا» means sign or mark, and «سَوَّمَ» means to mark so as to be distinguished from others (detailed). Thus, «سِیْما» refers to a symbolic or distinguishing mark.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«سِیۡمَاہُمۡ  فِیۡ وُجُوۡہِہِمۡ  مِّنۡ  اَثَرِ السُّجُوۡدِ» (48/29)\n\nTranslation: Due to the abundance of prostration, marks are evident on their foreheads.","«سِیْمَا» meaning 'distinctive mark'.","miracle","سیما","2:273-7:46-7:48-47:30-48:29-55:41",6
2826,620,"D","شَعَائِر","«شَعَائِر» is the plural of «شَعِیْرَۃ», meaning public symbols. That is, such signs which, from a religious perspective, attain the status of sanctity. Objects of reverence, places, and symbols. Symbols of Hajj: meaning the pillars and stations of Hajj. Symbols of Allah: those signs which Allah has deemed worthy of respect. And by Symbols of Allah are also meant the sacrificial animals that were sent towards the House of Allah.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الصَّفَا وَ الۡمَرۡوَۃَ مِنۡ شَعَآئِرِ اللّٰہِ» (2/158)\nTranslation: Indeed, Safa and Marwah are among the symbols of Allah.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا لَا تُحِلُّوۡا شَعَآئِرَ اللّٰہِ وَ لَا الشَّہۡرَ الۡحَرَامَ وَ لَا الۡہَدۡیَ وَ لَا الۡقَلَآئِدَ» (5/2)\nTranslation: O you who believe! Do not violate the sanctity of Allah's name, nor the sacred months, nor the animals that have been offered in sacrifice, nor those with garlands around their necks.","«شَعَائِر» Worldly signs—those that pertain to religion.","Divine Sign","شعائر","2:158-5:2-22:32-22:36",4
2827,621,"S","سَوَّمَ","«سِیْمَاء» means a sign or a distinguishing mark. And «سَوَّمَ» means to mark, to put a sign, or to make a mark so as to be distinguished from others (detailed). For instance, the Quran states: «وَ اَمۡطَرۡنَا عَلَیۡہَا حِجَارَۃً  مِّنۡ سِجِّیۡلٍ   ۬ ۙ مَّنۡضُوۡدٍ مُّسَوَّمَۃً  عِنۡدَ رَبِّکَ» (11/83) Translation: And We rained upon it [the city of Lot] stones of baked clay, marked from your Lord.","«سَوَّم» is used to indicate distinction.","Sign","سوم","3:14-3:125-11:83-51:34",4
2828,621,"S","وَسَمَ","«وَسَمَ» meaning to mark or brand (figurative) and to inscribe or carve designs on the body (literal). And «وَسَّمَ» meaning to apply henna or dye. And «وِسَام» and «وَسْمَہ» are that with which a mark or dye is applied. And «وَسِیْم» meaning beautiful (lit.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«سَنَسِمُہٗ  عَلَی  الۡخُرۡطُوۡمِ» (68/16)\nTranslation: We will surely mark his nose (or snout) prominently.","«وَسَمَ» is used for designing or beautifying, or for marking or staining.","Sign","وسم","2:273-7:46-7:48-15:75-47:30-48:29-55:41-68:16",8
2829,622,"A","نَصَحَ","«نَصَحَ» To wish well for someone. And «نَصِیْحَۃ» every word or action wherein the goodwill of another is intended (detailed).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَا یَنۡفَعُکُمۡ نُصۡحِیۡۤ  اِنۡ  اَرَدۡتُّ اَنۡ اَنۡصَحَ لَکُمۡ  اِنۡ کَانَ اللّٰہُ یُرِیۡدُ اَنۡ یُّغۡوِیَکُمۡ» (11/34)\nTranslation: If I were to wish you well and Allah intends to misguide you, my benevolence cannot benefit you at all.","«نَصَحَ» to speak or act with sincere goodwill toward someone.","Advice","نصح","7:62-7:79-7:93-9:91-11:34",5
2830,622,"A","ذَکَّرَ","«ذَکَرَ» means to remember and to be reminded, and its opposite is «نَسِیَ», meaning to forget. And «ذِکْر» means something being present in the heart or on the tongue. And *tazkirah* (reminder) means every thing that causes one to recall a need or requirement—certificate, passport, ticket, etc. (*manjad*). The Noble Quran has also been referred to as «ذِکْر» and «تَذْکِرَہ», because it also reminds humans of the innate call to goodness and the covenant of Alast. And «ذِکْر» also refers to such admonition that becomes a means of remembering Allah, and every act that refreshes the remembrance of God is a reminder. And «ذَکَّرَ» comes in the meanings of admonishing and directing attention. «ذَکَّرَ الْقَوْم» means 'he admonished his people' (m. q.).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ  ذَکِّرۡ فَاِنَّ  الذِّکۡرٰی تَنۡفَعُ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ» (51:55)\nTranslation: And continue to admonish, for admonition benefits the believers.\n\nAnd «تَذَکَّر» comes in the context of accepting or obtaining admonition.\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ یُبَیِّنُ  اٰیٰتِہٖ لِلنَّاسِ لَعَلَّہُمۡ  یَتَذَکَّرُوۡنَ» (2:221)\nTranslation: And Allah explains His commandments in detail for the people so that they may receive admonition.","«ذَکَّرَ» such admonition through which the remembrance of God is renewed.","Admonition","ذکر","2:114-2:221-2:269-2:282-3:7-3:58-5:13-5:14-5:91-6:44-6:68-6:69-6:70-6:80-6:90-6:118-6:119-6:121-6:126-6:138-6:152-7:2-7:3-7:26-7:57-7:63-7:69-7:130-7:165-7:201-8:2-8:57-9:126-10:3-11:24-11:30-11:114-11:120-12:42-12:104-13:19-13:28-14:5-14:25-14:52-15:6-15:9-16:13-16:17-16:43-16:44-16:90-17:41-17:46-18:28-18:57-18:70-18:83-18:101-19:2-20:3-20:14-20:34-20:42-20:44-20:99-20:113-20:124-21:2-21:7-21:10-21:24-21:42-21:48-21:50-21:84-21:105-22:35-23:71-23:85-23:110-24:1-24:27-24:37-25:18-25:29-25:50-25:62-25:73-26:5-26:209-26:227-27:62-28:43-28:46-28:51-29:45-29:51-32:4-32:15-32:22-33:34-33:41-35:37-36:11-36:19-36:69-37:3-37:13-37:155-37:168-38:1-38:8-38:29-38:32-38:43-38:46-38:49-38:87-39:9-39:21-39:22-39:23-39:27-39:45-40:13-40:54-40:58-41:41-43:5-43:36-43:44-44:13-44:58-45:23-47:18-47:20-50:8-50:37-50:45-51:49-51:55-52:29-53:29-54:17-54:22-54:25-54:32-54:40-56:62-56:73-57:16-58:19-62:9-63:9-65:10-68:51-68:52-69:12-69:42-69:48-72:17-73:19-74:31-74:49-74:54-74:55-74:56-76:29-77:5-79:43-80:4-80:11-80:12-81:27-87:9-87:10-88:21-89:23-94:4-79:35",181
2831,622,"A","وَعَظَ","«وَعَظَ» signifies speaking of such goodness that softness enters the heart (م ۔ ل). Inclining toward piety through threats and promises. Admonition in which an element of fear is mixed. Stimulating the desire for reward and recompense by instilling fear of Allah's punishment (مف ۔ منجد).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا النَّاسُ قَدۡ جَآءَتۡکُمۡ  مَّوۡعِظَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّکُمۡ وَ شِفَآءٌ لِّمَا فِی الصُّدُوۡرِ» (10/57)\nTranslation: O mankind! There has come to you a reminder from your Lord and a cure for the diseases of the hearts.","«وَعَظَ» denotes admonition through targhib (instilling eagerness) and tarhib (instilling fear).","Admonition","وعظ","2:66-2:232-2:275-3:138-4:63-4:66-5:46-7:145-10:57-11:120-16:125-24:34-26:136-58:3-65:2",15
2832,622,"S","وَصّٰی","«اَلْوَصِیَّۃ» meaning to guide someone in an admonishing manner before an event occurs (detailed).\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«مِنۡۢ بَعۡدِ وَصِیَّۃٍ یُّوۡصٰی بِہَاۤ اَوۡ دَیۡنٍ» (4/12)\nTranslation: This distribution of inheritance will occur after the fulfillment of the will (that the deceased made) or after the repayment of debts.\nAnd when it is attributed to Allah, its meaning will be to emphasize or to command.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«یُوۡصِیۡکُمُ اللّٰہُ فِیۡۤ  اَوۡلَادِکُمۡ» (4/11)\nTranslation: Allah the Most High commands you regarding the distribution of inheritance among your children.","«وَصّٰی» To guide someone in an admonishing manner before an event occurs.","Sincere counsel","وصی","2:132-2:180-2:182-2:240-4:11-4:12-4:131-5:106-6:144-6:151-6:152-6:153-19:31-29:8-31:14-36:50-42:13-46:15",18
2833,622,"C","عِبْرَۃ ، اِعْتَبَرَ","«عَبُوْر» fundamentally denotes crossing water, whether by swimming, boat, animal, or bridge. And «عَبْرُ النَّھْرِ» is the place from which one descends into the water to cross the river. Maintaining a similar analogy, «عَبَرَ الْعَیْنُ» means tears flowing from the eye (figurative), and «عَبْرَۃ» means tears; its plural is «عَبَرَات». And «عَبَرَ» means to be sorrowful, to shed tears. And «عَبْرُ الْعَیْنُ» means an eye drenched with tears. And «عِبَرَۃ» means to reflect on an event and derive admonition. They say «لَکَ بِفُلَانٍ عِبْرَۃٌ», i.e., to ponder over someone's state of affairs and seek the root cause that is the actual reason for that event (mandaj).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یُقَلِّبُ اللّٰہُ الَّیۡلَ وَ النَّہَارَ ؕ اِنَّ فِیۡ ذٰلِکَ لَعِبۡرَۃً   لِّاُولِی  الۡاَبۡصَارِ» (24/44)\nTranslation: Allah alternates the night and the day. Indeed in that is a great lesson for those of insight.\nAnd «اِعْتَبَرَ» means to reflect on a tragic and sorrowful event and derive admonition from it.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قَذَفَ فِیۡ  قُلُوۡبِہِمُ  الرُّعۡبَ یُخۡرِبُوۡنَ بُیُوۡتَہُمۡ  بِاَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ  وَ اَیۡدِی الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ ٭  فَاعۡتَبِرُوۡا یٰۤاُولِی الۡاَبۡصَارِ» (59/2)\nTranslation: And He cast terror into their hearts, so they destroyed their houses by their own hands and the hands of the believers. Then take heed, O you who have eyes to see!","«عِبَرَۃ» meaning to derive admonition through contemplation of an occurrence.\n«اِعْتَبَرَ» meaning to derive admonition by reflecting on the causes of a tragic incident or event.","counsel","عبرۃ ، اعتبر","3:13-12:111-16:66-23:21-24:44-59:2-79:26",7
2834,623,"B","نِعْمَۃ","«نِعْمَۃ» means ihsān (beneficence), nu‘āzish (favor), meharbānī (kindness), faḍl (grace). (According to the lexicon) it refers to a favor bestowed upon another. Its plural is «نِعَمْ». And «اَنْعُمْ نِعْمَۃٌ» is a generic term, and this word is applied equally to all kinds of blessings, whether small or large, little or much.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یَسۡتَبۡشِرُوۡنَ بِنِعۡمَۃٍ مِّنَ اللّٰہِ وَ فَضۡلٍ» (3/171)\nTranslation: They rejoice in the bounties and grace of Allah.","«نِعْمَۃ» meaning favor or kindness shown to others.","Blessing","نعمۃ","2:211-3:171-3:174-5:7-5:20-8:53-14:6-16:18-16:53-16:71-26:22-29:67-33:9-37:57-39:8-39:49-43:13-49:8-54:35-68:2-68:49-92:19-93:11",23
2835,623,"B","نَعْمَۃ","«نَعْمَۃ» meaning every such thing that becomes a cause of improvement, abundance, and prosperity in livelihood. The means and requisites of comfort and ease.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ  نَعۡمَۃٍ  کَانُوۡا فِیۡہَا  فٰکِہِیۡنَ» (44/27)\nTranslation: And the things of comfort in which they used to indulge.","«نَعْمَۃ» The means and provisions for a life of comfort and ease, along with its necessities.","Blessing","نعمۃ","44:27-73:11",2
2836,623,"B","اٰلَا","«اٰلَاء» is the plural form of «اِلًی», meaning blessing (singular). «( اَلیٰ ۔ یَا لُوْ ۔» means to diminish, to bear a shortcoming, to fall short, to leave a deficiency (singular, collective).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is:\n«لَا یَاۡلُوۡنَکُمۡ خَبَالًا» (3/118)\nTranslation: Those people do not bear any shortcoming in your faults.\n\nAnd by «اَلَاء» are meant those blessings that provide for human needs and come consecutively, and one does not feel any deficiency in anything for living life (Fiqh 160). And generally, it is used in the plural because such a blessing is not singular. Therefore, «اٰلَاءِیْ» occurs.\n\nFor example, the divine command is:\n«ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ فَبِاَیِّ  اٰلَآءِ  رَبِّکُمَا تُکَذِّبٰنِ» (55/12,13)\nTranslation: There are fruit trees and date-palms with sheaths, and grain with its husk, and fragrant flowers. So which of the favors of your Lord will you deny?","«اٰلَاء» the basic necessities of life.","Blessing","الا","7:69-7:74-53:55-55:13-55:16-55:18-55:21-55:23-55:25-55:28-55:30-55:32-55:34-55:36-55:38-55:40-55:42-55:45-55:47-55:49-55:51-55:53-55:55-55:57-55:59-55:61-55:63-55:65-55:67-55:69-55:71-55:73-55:75-55:77",34
2837,623,"B","اَنْعَمَ","«اَنْعَمَ» means to do good; to bestow favors. This word is not used for non-human entities. «اَنْعَمَ عَلٰی فَرْسِہٖ» will never come (m. q.) nor can it be used for one's own self (faq l 158).\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِہۡدِ نَا الصِّرَاطَ الۡمُسۡتَقِیۡمَ صِرَاطَ الَّذِیۡنَ اَنۡعَمۡتَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ» (1/5,6)\nTranslation: Guide us to the straight path. The path of those upon whom You have bestowed Your favors and grace.\nAnd «نَعَّمَ» means to bestow blessings upon someone.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«فَاَمَّا الۡاِنۡسَانُ  اِذَا مَا ابۡتَلٰىہُ  رَبُّہٗ فَاَکۡرَمَہٗ  وَ نَعَّمَہٗ» (89/15)\nTranslation: But man is indeed ungrateful. When his Lord tests him and honors him and favors him.","«اَنْعَمَ» to show kindness and honor is customary (applies only to humans).","Blessing","انعم","1:6-2:40-2:47-2:122-2:150-2:211-2:231-3:103-3:171-3:174-4:69-4:72-5:3-5:6-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:23-5:110-8:53-11:10-12:6-14:6-14:28-14:34-16:18-16:53-16:71-16:72-16:81-16:83-16:112-16:114-16:121-17:83-19:58-26:22-27:19-28:17-29:67-31:20-31:31-33:9-33:37-35:3-37:57-39:8-39:49-41:51-43:13-43:59-44:27-46:15-48:2-49:8-52:29-54:35-68:2-68:49-73:11-89:15-92:19-93:11",63
2838,623,"B","خَوَّلَ","«خَوَّلَ» meaning to give, to forgive, to make owner (manjīd), and meaning to grant honor and service (muf).\nFor example: in the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ تَرَکۡتُمۡ مَّا خَوَّلۡنٰکُمۡ  وَرَآءَ  ظُہُوۡرِکُمۡ» (6/94)\nTranslation: And all the wealth and possessions We had granted you are now abandoned behind you.","«خَوَّلَ» to bestow. to forgive. to make master.","Blessing","خول","6:94-39:8-39:49",3
2839,623,"B","اَتْرَفَ","«اَلتَّرَفُّہ» meaning an abundance of luxury and comfort. The plenitude of blessings that can lead a person astray. And «مُتْرِفْ» meaning one who is prosperous and intoxicated by the abundance of wealth. (Mufradat)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  الَّذِیۡنَ  ظَلَمُوۡا مَاۤ اُتۡرِفُوۡا فِیۡہِ وَ کَانُوۡا مُجۡرِمِیۡنَ» (11/116)\nTranslation: And those who were wronged pursued the very things in which there was luxury and comfort, and they were immersed in sin.","«اَتْرَفَ» to become intoxicated with the abundance of comfort and ease.","Blessing","اترف","11:116-21:13-23:33",3
2840,623,"B","اَغْنَی ( اللّٰہ )","meaning Allah Almighty grants a person so much wealth and riches that they become free from the need of others. It is a common term.","«اَغْنَی» to give such wealth that makes one self-sufficient.","Blessing","اغنی ( اللہ )","9:74-53:48-93:8",3
2841,623,"B","اَقْنٰی","«اَقْنٰی» means to enrich and to satisfy (as in the lexicon *Mafradat* and *Manjad*). That is, to give such wealth and property that it fulfills the need and also makes one happy. And it also means to enrich further by increasing that wealth. To grant a treasure (as in *Mafradat* and *Qamus*). And according to some lexicographers, it is the opposite of «اَقْنٰی اَغْنٰی», meaning to make destitute. And «اَقْنٰی» is from the category of *al-iddad* (words with opposite meanings).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اَنَّہٗ  ہُوَ  اَغۡنٰی وَ  اَقۡنٰی» (53/48)\n\nTranslation: And that it is He (Allah) who grants wealth and bestows treasure (Ottoman translation).\nHe is the One who makes wealthy and makes destitute (Jalandhri translation).\n\nNote: (*Al-iddad* refers to words that have two separate meanings which are opposite and contradictory to each other).","«اَقْنٰی» to enrich and to satisfy, to grant a treasure, and, according to some, to impoverish.","Blessing","اقنی","53:48",1
2842,624,"D","ضَرّ","«ضَرًّا» means task, harm, or its opposite. «نَفَع» is a general term.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قُلۡ لَّاۤ  اَمۡلِکُ  لِنَفۡسِیۡ  نَفۡعًا وَّ لَا  ضَرًّا  اِلَّا مَا شَآءَ اللّٰہُ» ( 7/188 )\nTranslation: Say, I do not possess for myself any benefit or harm, except what Allah has willed.\nAnd the meaning of «ضَیْر» is also harm, calamity, and loss. And according to Imam Raghīb, «ضَارَہٗ» and «ضَرَّہٗ» have the same meaning (Mufradāt).\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا  لَا ضَیۡرَ ۫ اِنَّاۤ اِلٰی رَبِّنَا مُنۡقَلِبُوۡنَ» ( 26/50 )\nTranslation: The magicians said to Pharaoh, There will be no harm for us. Indeed, we will return to our Lord.","«ضَرًّا» means harm. It is general.","Deficiency","ضر","2:102-2:177-2:214-2:231-3:111-3:120-3:134-3:144-3:176-3:177-4:95-4:113-5:42-5:76-5:105-6:17-6:42-6:71-7:94-7:95-7:188-9:39-9:107-10:12-10:18-10:21-10:49-10:106-10:107-11:10-11:57-12:88-13:16-16:53-16:54-17:56-17:67-20:89-21:66-21:83-21:84-22:12-22:13-23:75-25:3-25:55-26:73-30:33-34:42-36:23-39:8-39:38-39:49-41:50-47:32-48:11-72:21",57
2843,624,"L","خَسَارًا","«خَسَارًا» means diminution in the principal amount (i.e., in a transaction, loss occurring instead of profit). Loss. Deficit. Its opposite is «رَبِحَ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ لَا یَزِیۡدُ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ  کُفۡرُہُمۡ اِلَّا خَسَارًا» (35/39)\nTranslation: And for the disbelievers, their disbelief only increases their loss.","«خَسَارًا» Incurring a loss in trade. Diminution of capital.","Loss; Deficiency; Diminution","خسارًا","17:82-35:39-71:21",3
2844,624,"L","کَسَاد","«کَسَاد» means not having the desire to purchase something. (M. L.) To be sluggish. For trade goods to not be sold. The famous phrase کساد بازاری means the market becoming stagnant or cold.\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ تِجَارَۃٌ تَخۡشَوۡنَ  کَسَادَہَا» (9/24)\nTranslation: ...and trade whose stagnation you fear.","«کَسَاد» Goods not selling. Market cooling down.","Loss","کساد","9:24",1
2845,624,"D","بَخْس","«بَخْس» meaning a trivial and deficient thing. And «یَبْخَس» to diminish something through injustice (meaning). For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «فَمَنۡ یُّؤۡمِنۡۢ  بِرَبِّہٖ  فَلَا یَخَافُ بَخۡسًا وَّ لَا رَہَقًا» (72/13) Translation: And whoever believes in Allah will fear no harm or compulsion.","«بَخْس» to receive a defective and worthless item in exchange for something good.","Deficiency","بخس","2:282-7:85-11:15-11:85-12:20-26:183-72:13",7
2846,624,"L","بَوَار","«بُوْر» and «بَوَار» mean to diminish greatly and approach ruin (i.e., the gradual erosion and eventual destruction of capital while incurring loss).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِمَّا رَزَقۡنٰہُمۡ سِرًّا وَّ عَلَانِیَۃً  یَّرۡجُوۡنَ  تِجَارَۃً  لَّنۡ تَبُوۡرَ» (35/29)\nTranslation: And those who spend of what We have provided them, both secretly and openly, hope for a commerce that will never fail.","«بَوَار» to be utterly destroyed while in a state of loss.","Loss","بوار","14:28-17:102-25:13-25:14-25:18-35:10-35:29-48:12-84:11",9
2847,624,"L","مَغْرَمْ","«اَلْغُرْم»: That financial loss which a person is forced to bear without having committed any betrayal or crime. Indemnity (compensation) and «غَرِم» meaning to repay someone's debt. And «غَرِیْم» meaning both the creditor and the debtor (from the root *najada*).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّمَا الصَّدَقٰتُ لِلۡفُقَرَآءِ وَ الۡمَسٰکِیۡنِ وَ الۡعٰمِلِیۡنَ عَلَیۡہَا وَ الۡمُؤَلَّفَۃِ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ وَ فِی الرِّقَابِ وَ الۡغٰرِمِیۡنَ وَ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ ابۡنِ السَّبِیۡلِ ؕ» (9/60)\nTranslation: Alms (Zakat) are meant only for the poor, the needy, those employed to collect them, those whose hearts are to be reconciled, for freeing slaves, for repaying debts, for the cause of Allah, and for the stranded traveler—an obligation imposed by Allah. And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.\n\nAnd «مَغْرَم» and «غُرْم» are synonymous. And «مُغْرَم» is the person upon whom indemnity is imposed.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَوۡ نَشَآءُ  لَجَعَلۡنٰہُ  حُطَامًا فَظَلۡتُمۡ تَفَکَّہُوۡنَ اِنَّا  لَمُغۡرَمُوۡنَ» (56/65,66)\nTranslation: If We willed, We could have made it (the vegetation) broken into pieces. Then you would be lamenting, We are laden with debt (or: We are in loss)!","«مَغْرَمْ» to be responsible for a non-obligatory matter, to take responsibility for payment on someone's behalf.","Loss","مغرم","9:60-9:98-52:40-56:66-68:46",5
2848,625,"M","نَکَحَ","«َالنِّکَاح» is the contract that is established between spouses (detailed) and it pertains only to accountable beings, i.e., humans and jinns. And «نَکَحَ» means to marry oneself. For example: The Noble Quran states: «فَانۡکِحُوۡا مَا طَابَ لَکُمۡ مِّنَ النِّسَآءِ» (4:3) Translation: Marry those among women who seem good to you. And «اَنْکَحَ» means to marry someone else or to give someone in marriage. For example: The Noble Quran states: «وَ لَا تُنۡکِحُوا الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یُؤۡمِنُوۡا» (2:221) Translation: Do not give Muslim women in marriage to polytheist men until they believe.","«نَکَحَ» refers to the marriage contract, which is exclusively for accountable beings among the jinn and humans.","Marriage","نکح","2:221-2:230-2:232-2:235-2:237-4:3-4:6-4:22-4:25-4:127-24:3-24:32-24:33-24:60-28:27-33:49-33:50-33:53-60:10",19
2849,625,"N","زَوَّجَ","«زَوْج» means pair, husband, wife, companion. And «زَوَّج» means to pair or to marry. Among animals where male and female are found, each is called the «زَوْج» of the other. And besides animals, in other things, a pair, i.e., a couple, is called «زَوْج» (detailed). And its second aspect is that even if there is no divorce after marriage, the correct meaning of «زَوَّج» is marriage and divorce or to marry and to pair. And similarly, its meaning is not to marry oneself but to give in marriage.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَمَّا قَضٰی زَیۡدٌ مِّنۡہَا وَطَرًا زَوَّجۡنٰکَہَا  لِکَیۡ لَا یَکُوۡنَ عَلَی  الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ حَرَجٌ  فِیۡۤ  اَزۡوَاجِ اَدۡعِیَآئِہِمۡ» (33/37)\nTranslation: Then when Zaid had accomplished his desire in her (Zainab), We gave her in marriage to you (O Prophet) so that there should be no restriction for the believers in regard to the wives of their adopted sons when they have accomplished their desire in them.\n\nImam Raghib says that if the reward of «زَوَّج» comes from «ب», then its meaning is merely to pair, not to establish sexual relations. And in «زَوَّجْنَا ھُمْ بِحُوْرٍ عِیْنٍ», this indication is found that they will be merely companions and partners; otherwise, the Quran would have said «زَوَّجْنٰھُمْ حُوْرًا» instead of «زَوَّجْنٰھُمْ بِحُوْرٍ». As the proverb «زَوَّجْتُہٗ اِمْرَأَۃً» says (detailed). And Allah knows best!","«زَوَّجَ» pairing is common. Moreover, within it, the concept of concession alongside marriage is also found.","Nikah","زوج","2:25-2:35-2:102-2:230-2:232-2:234-2:240-3:15-4:1-4:12-4:20-4:57-6:139-6:143-7:19-7:189-9:24-11:40-13:3-13:23-13:38-15:88-16:72-20:53-20:117-20:131-21:90-22:5-23:6-23:27-24:6-25:74-26:7-26:166-30:21-31:10-33:4-33:6-33:28-33:37-33:50-33:52-33:53-33:59-35:11-36:36-36:56-37:22-38:58-39:6-40:8-42:11-42:50-43:12-43:70-44:54-50:7-51:49-52:20-53:45-55:52-56:7-58:1-60:11-64:14-66:1-66:3-66:5-70:30-75:39-78:8-81:7",72
2850,626,"T","خَرَجَ","«خَرَجَ» means to exit, to come out, and its opposite is «دَخَلَ». It is a well-known word and its usage is also common.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:  \n«لَئِنۡ  اُخۡرِجۡتُمۡ  لَنَخۡرُجَنَّ مَعَکُمۡ» (59:11)  \nTranslation: If you go forth, we will go forth with you.","«خَرَجَ» meaning 'to exit' or 'to come out'. Commonly used.","To emerge","خرج","2:74-2:149-2:150-2:240-2:243-4:66-4:100-5:22-5:37-5:61-7:13-7:18-7:58-8:47-9:42-9:47-9:83-12:31-15:34-16:69-18:5-19:11-20:22-22:22-23:20-24:43-24:53-27:12-28:20-28:21-28:32-28:79-30:25-30:48-32:20-34:2-37:64-38:77-41:47-47:16-49:5-54:7-55:22-57:4-59:2-59:11-59:12-60:1-65:1-70:43-86:7-",51
2851,626,"T","بَرَزَ","«بَرَزَ» means to emerge into an open field, to come forward, to appear after obscurity and concealment (manjada). And «بَرْز» means space and an open field. And «دَعْوَتِ مُبَارِزَت» means in the battlefield, for a person to advance and challenge an enemy soldier to single combat.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا بَرَزُوۡا لِجَالُوۡتَ وَ جُنُوۡدِہٖ» (2/250)\nTranslation: And when they emerged to confront Jalut and his armies.","«بَرَزَ» to emerge into the field; to come before.","to emerge","برز","2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36",7
2852,626,"T","نَفَرَ","«نَفَرَ» means to set out on a campaign or battle. «اَلنَّفْر» refers to a group of warriors, a squad of three to ten. And «نَفِیْر» means people marching toward battle. «نَفِیْرُ الْعَام» signifies the public rising against an enemy (source: Manjad). For instance, the Quran states: «فَانۡفِرُوۡا ثُبَاتٍ اَوِ انۡفِرُوۡا جَمِیۡعًا» (4/71) Translation: Go forth in groups or all together.","«نَفَرَ» meaning war or to embark on a campaign.","to exit","نفر","4:71-9:38-9:39-9:41-9:81-9:122-46:29-18:34-46:29-72:1",10
2853,626,"T","غَزٰی ( غزو )","«غَزٰی» means to go out with the intention of fighting the enemy (in one sense) and to go out for battle. To launch an attack for plunder. And «غَزَّی» means to send or prepare for causing terror (preparation) and «غَزَّی» and «اَغْزٰی» mean to send for fighting and to supply war equipment (for fighting).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَوۡ کَانُوۡا غُزًّی لَّوۡ کَانُوۡا عِنۡدَنَا مَا مَاتُوۡا» (3:156)\nTranslation: Or go forth for jihad (and if they are killed, they say), If only they had remained with us, they would not have died.","«غَزٰی» This word is specifically used for embarking on jihad.","to exit","غزی ( غزو )","3:156",1
2854,626,"T","زَھَقَ","«زَھَقَ» means to flee or escape (m.f.) «زَھَقَ النَّفْس» means the departure of the soul from the body. And «زَھَقَ الْبَاطِل» means for falsehood to flee away (m.l.). And «زَاھِقْ» means defeated; one who comes to a contest, suffers defeat, and then flees. Furthermore, «زَھَقَ» is derived from the category of lexical antonyms. And «زَاھِق» also means a very fat animal, as well as a very thin and weak animal (m.r. manj). Therefore, «زھق» can apply in both senses: to defeat something and cause it to flee, or to make something weak, exhausted, and then cause it to flee.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ قُلۡ جَآءَ الۡحَقُّ وَ زَہَقَ الۡبَاطِلُ ؕ اِنَّ الۡبَاطِلَ  کَانَ  زَہُوۡقًا» (17/81)\nTranslation: And say, Truth has come, and falsehood has fled away. Indeed, falsehood is bound to flee.\n\nNote: (Lexical antonyms are words that have two distinct, opposite meanings.)","«زَھَقَ» to flee after defeat or in distress","to emerge","زھق","17:81",1
2855,626,"T","نَفَذَ","«نَفَذَ» means to break out or emerge beyond. And «نَفَاذ» means to complete and implement a decree with strength and power, and to enforce it. To burst into something with speed and cross beyond (figurative).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«یٰمَعۡشَرَ الۡجِنِّ وَ الۡاِنۡسِ  اِنِ اسۡتَطَعۡتُمۡ اَنۡ  تَنۡفُذُوۡا مِنۡ  اَقۡطَارِ السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ فَانۡفُذُوۡا» (55/33)\nTranslation: O assembly of jinn and humans! If you have the strength to break out from the boundaries of the heavens and the earth, then break out.","«نَفَذَ» meaning to come out or get through.","to exit","نفذ","55:33",1
2856,626,"T","سَلَّلَ","«سَلَّلَ» meaning to slip away calmly and stealthily (e.g.) to slide away.","«سَلَّلَ» meaning to slip away.","to emerge","سلل","24:63",1
2857,626,"T","لِوَاذًا","«لَاذَ» to set out in search of shelter. «لَاذَ بِالْجَبَل» meaning to take shelter in the mountain, to hide. And «لَوْذ» meaning the edge of the mountain, and «مَلَاذ» a place of refuge or fortress (Quranic example). «لِوَاذًا» to depart in search of shelter.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَدۡ یَعۡلَمُ  اللّٰہُ  الَّذِیۡنَ  یَتَسَلَّلُوۡنَ مِنۡکُمۡ  لِوَاذًا» (24/63)\nTranslation: Indeed, Allah knows those who slip away stealthily.","«لِوَاذًا» meaning to slip away unnoticed.","to emerge","لواذًا","24:63",1
2858,626,"T","دَفَقَ","«دَفَقَ» means: to move forward with force and strength, to leap out. For example:\n«فَلۡیَنۡظُرِ الۡاِنۡسَانُ مِمَّ خُلِقَ خُلِقَ مِنۡ مَّآءٍ  دَافِقٍ» (86/6) Translation: So let man consider from what he is created. He is created from gushing water.","«دَفَقَ» meaning to advance with strength and force; to leap forth.","to emerge","دفق","86:6",1
2859,626,"T","شَرَقَ","«شَرْق» means the sun, sunlight, the point of sunrise, and «شِرْق» means the light that emerges from a doorway's crack. And «شَرَقَتِ الشَّمْس» means the rising of the sun. And «مَشْرِق» means the place of the sun's rising (mindsad). It seems the word «شَرَقَ» is specific to the rising or dawning of the sun, or to something that is exceptionally bright and luminous compared to ordinary celestial bodies.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَشۡرَقَتِ  الۡاَرۡضُ بِنُوۡرِ رَبِّہَا» (39/69)\nTranslation: And the earth will shine with the light of its Lord.\n\nAnd «اَشْرَقَ» also signifies the time of sunrise in contexts of performing actions.\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«فَاَتۡبَعُوۡہُمۡ مُّشۡرِقِیۡنَ» (26/60)\nTranslation: So the Pharaoh's people pursued them at sunrise.","«شَرَقَ» meaning the rising of the sun.","to exit","شرق","2:115-2:142-2:177-2:258-15:73-19:16-24:35-26:28-26:60-38:18-39:69-43:38-55:17-73:9",14
2860,626,"T","طَلَعَ","«طَلَعَ» refers to the rising of general celestial bodies, such as planets, and includes the sun as well. So to speak, the word «طَلَعَ» is general. Whereas «شَرَقَ» is used specifically for the rising of the sun. The first verse of the song that the daughters of Banu Najjar were singing upon the arrival of the Messenger of Allah ﷺ was «طَلَعَ الْبَدْرُ عَلَیْنَا», meaning, The moon of the fourteenth night has risen upon us. In the Quran, the word «طَلَعَ» does not appear for the rising of planets. However, it does appear in relation to dawn (or perhaps the sun), and the light of dawn is, after all, much less than that of the sun.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«سَلٰم ٌ ۟ ۛ ہِیَ حَتّٰی مَطۡلَعِ  الۡفَجۡرِ» (97:5)\nTranslation: This (night) is safety and security until the coming of dawn.","«طَلَعَ» The rising of stars and planets, including the sun, is common.","to emerge","طلع","18:17-18:90-97:5",3
2861,626,"T","اَخْرَجَ","«اَخْرَجَ» meaning 'to take out' or 'to expel'. Its usage is common.\n«اِلَّا تَنۡصُرُوۡہُ فَقَدۡ  نَصَرَہُ  اللّٰہُ  اِذۡ اَخۡرَجَہُ الَّذِیۡنَ  کَفَرُوۡا» (9/40)\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it states:\nTranslation: If you do not support the Messenger, then Allah supported him at the time when the disbelievers had expelled him.","«اَخْرَجَ» is commonly used to extract.","to emerge","اخرج","2:22-2:36-2:61-2:72-2:84-2:85-2:191-2:240-2:246-2:257-2:267-3:27-3:110-3:195-4:75-5:16-5:110-6:93-6:95-6:99-6:148-7:25-7:27-7:32-7:57-7:82-7:88-7:110-7:123-8:5-8:30-9:40-10:31-12:76-12:100-14:1-14:5-14:13-14:32-15:48-16:14-16:78-17:13-17:76-17:80-18:82-19:66-20:53-20:55-20:57-20:63-20:88-20:117-22:5-22:40-23:35-23:107-24:40-26:35-26:57-26:167-27:25-27:37-27:56-27:67-27:82-30:19-32:27-33:43-35:12-35:27-35:37-36:33-39:21-40:67-43:11-45:35-46:17-47:13-47:29-47:37-48:29-51:35-57:9-59:2-59:8-59:11-59:12-60:1-60:8-60:9-63:8-65:1-65:2-65:11-71:18-78:15-79:29-79:31-87:4-99:2",101
2862,626,"T","بَرَّزَ","«بَرَّزَ» To bring something out and place it in an open space in front.\nFor example: In the Quran it is: «وَ بُرِّزَتِ الۡجَحِیۡمُ  لِمَنۡ یَّرٰی» (79/36)\nTranslation: And Hell will be placed in full view for those who see it.","«بَرَّزَ» meaning to bring forward.","To emerge","برز","2:250-3:154-4:81-14:21-14:48-26:91-79:36",7
2863,626,"T","طَرَد","«طَرَد» To regard someone as contemptible and degraded, and thus expel them; to dismiss. (Also: to firmly repel) (Mufradat, p. 188)\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَا تَطۡرُدِ الَّذِیۡنَ یَدۡعُوۡنَ رَبَّہُمۡ بِالۡغَدٰوۃِ  وَ الۡعَشِیِّ  یُرِیۡدُوۡنَ وَجۡہَہٗ» (6:52)\nTranslation: And do not drive away those who call upon their Lord morning and evening, seeking His pleasure.","to expel someone while considering them contemptible and despicable","to come out","طرد","6:52-11:30",2
2864,627,"G","بَصَر","«بَصَر» means the eye as well as the action of the eye, which is sight or gaze, and also to see. And from this word, only the action of seeing becomes evident.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَبَصَرُکَ الۡیَوۡمَ حَدِیۡدٌ» (50/22)\nTranslation: So today your sight is very sharp.","«بَصَر» is a term commonly used for sight or vision.","Gaze","بصر","2:7-2:17-2:20-3:13-6:46-6:103-6:104-6:110-7:47-7:179-7:195-7:198-7:201-10:31-10:43-10:67-11:20-14:42-15:15-16:77-16:78-16:108-17:12-17:36-17:59-18:26-19:38-19:42-20:96-21:3-21:97-22:46-23:78-24:30-24:31-24:37-24:43-24:44-27:13-27:54-27:86-28:11-28:72-29:38-32:9-32:12-32:27-33:10-36:9-36:66-37:175-37:179-38:45-38:63-40:61-41:20-41:22-43:51-45:23-46:26-47:23-50:8-50:22-51:21-52:15-53:17-54:7-54:50-56:85-59:2-67:3-67:4-67:23-68:5-68:43-68:51-69:38-69:39-70:11-70:44-75:7-79:9",82
2865,627,"V","طَرْف","The word «طَرْف» also denotes an extremely short duration, like the time it takes to blink an eye. Its original meaning is the edge or boundary of something. «طَرْفُ الْعَیْن» means the blinking of an eye, and «طَرْفَۃُ عَیْنٍ» means a period or interval of time as brief as a single blink. Thus, in «طَرْف», the reference is not to the act of seeing itself, but to an extremely short span of time.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«اَنَا اٰتِیۡکَ بِہٖ قَبۡلَ  اَنۡ یَّرۡتَدَّ اِلَیۡکَ طَرۡفُکَ» (27:40)\nTranslation: I can bring it [the throne of the Queen of Sheba] to you before your glance returns (or before you blink).\n\nLater, due to its frequent usage, this word became synonymous with «بَصَر». For instance, «طَرْفٌ خَفِیٌّ» means a piercing gaze, and «قٰصِرٰتُ الطَّرۡفِ» (37:48) means women with downcast glances.","«طَرْف» meaning the edge or boundary of something.","Vision","طرف","14:43-27:40-37:48-38:52-42:45-55:56",6
2866,628,"G","حَافِظ","«اَحْفَظ» means to save something from being lost or destroyed (to guard, to protect). It means to attempt to safeguard something from external dangers. Its opposite is «اَضَاع», meaning to cause loss or destruction. And «حَافِظْ» is the active participle, meaning 'the One who protects'. In «حَفِیْظ», there is an emphasis (intensification), meaning 'the One who protects at all times'.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَاللّٰہُ خَیۡرٌ حٰفِظًا» (12/64)\nTranslation: And Allah is the best of protectors.\n\nSimilarly, at another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ مَاۤ اَنَا عَلَیۡکُمۡ  بِحَفِیۡظٍ» (11/86)\nTranslation: And I am not a guardian over you.","«حَافِظ» Preserver, one who saves something from being lost and destroyed.","Guardian","حافظ","2:238-4:34-4:80-6:92-6:104-6:107-9:112-11:57-11:86-12:12-12:55-12:63-12:64-12:81-15:9-21:82-23:5-23:9-33:35-34:21-42:6-42:48-50:4-50:32-70:29-70:34-82:10-83:33-86:4",29
2867,628,"G","رَقِیْب","«رَقَبَۃ» means neck. And «رَقَبَ» means to keep one's eye on someone's neck, or to oversee and guard them (figurative). And «رَقْبَۃٌ» means caution, guardianship, protection, and fear (lexical). Therefore, «رَقِیْب» signifies a guardian who is himself constantly vigilant. And for the one over whom he is guardian, not a single action of theirs remains hidden from him (Fiqh 170).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کُنۡتُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ شَہِیۡدًا مَّا دُمۡتُ فِیۡہِمۡ ۚ فَلَمَّا تَوَفَّیۡتَنِیۡ کُنۡتَ اَنۡتَ الرَّقِیۡبَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ ؕ» (5:117)\nTranslation: And as long as I remained among them, I was aware of their state. Then when You raised me up, You Yourself were their Guardian.","«رَقِیْب» such a guardian who remains vigilant himself and is also aware of every single movement of the other entity.","Guardian","رقیب","4:1-5:117-11:93-33:52-50:18",5
2868,628,"G","مُقِیْت","«قُوَّۃ ، قَاتَ» means to provide sustenance, to give provision, and to undertake guardianship. And «اَقَاتَ» means to possess power, to protect, and to grant sustenance. And «مُقِیْت» means possessing authority, a guardian and protector (mujannad). It is as if «مُقِیْت» is a guardian who is also inherently possessing authority. According to Ibn Faris, «مُقِیْت» encompasses three elements: (1) power over something, (2) protection, and (3) restriction (m. l). That is, «مُقِیْت» refers to an entity possessing authority and control, which is fully capable of protection.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ کَانَ اللّٰہُ  عَلٰی کُلِّ  شَیۡءٍ  مُّقِیۡتًا» (4/85)\nTranslation: And Allah, the Most High, is Watchful over all things.","«مُقِیْت» a protector who possesses complete power over protection.","Guardian","مقیت","4:85",1
2869,628,"G","حَرَسَ","«حَرَس» means to take into custody, to guard, to keep watch, to supervise the accused. According to Ibn Faris, «حَرَس» encompasses two concepts: (1) protection, (2) time period (i.e., to supervise for a certain duration). And «حَرَسَ الْمَلِک» means royal guard, bodyguard (manjad).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَّ اَنَّا لَمَسۡنَا السَّمَآءَ  فَوَجَدۡنٰہَا مُلِئَتۡ حَرَسًا شَدِیۡدًا وَّ  شُہُبًا» (72/8)\nTranslation: And when we scanned the sky, we found it filled with strong guards and burning stars.","«حَرَس» meaning guard, sentinel, or one who takes into custody.","Guardian","حرس","72:8",1
2870,628,"G","مُھَیْمِن","Ibn al-Faris and some other lexicographers have derived it under the meaning of *aman* (safety/security), i.e., the One who grants safety (M. L.), and «ھَیْمَنَ الطَّائِرُ عَلٰی فَرَاخِہٖ» means: the bird has spread its wings over its chicks. And two meanings are found for «مُھَیْمِن»: (1) to grant someone safety from fear, (2) not allowing someone's right to be wasted (M. R.). This word appears twice in the Quran, and it has come with both these meanings.\n\n**Example 1** - Meaning: to take under protection. For example, the Holy Quran states:\n«اَلۡمَلِکُ الۡقُدُّوۡسُ السَّلٰمُ  الۡمُؤۡمِنُ الۡمُہَیۡمِنُ» (59:23)\n**Translation:** He is the King, the Most Holy, the Source of Peace and Safety, the Guardian.\n\n**Example 2** - Not allowing a right to be wasted. For example, the divine command of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَ اَنۡزَلۡنَاۤ اِلَیۡکَ الۡکِتٰبَ بِالۡحَقِّ مُصَدِّقًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہِ مِنَ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ مُہَیۡمِنًا عَلَیۡہِ» (5:48)\n**Translation:** And We have sent down to you, [O Muhammad], the Book in truth, confirming what was before it of the Scripture and as a criterion over it.","The Protector who takes «مُھَیْمِن» under His shelter.","Guardian","مھیمن","5:48-59:23",2
2871,629,"T","بَلَعَ","«بَلْعَم» or «بُلْعُوْم» means throat. It also refers to the sound or act of eating. And «بَلَعَ» means to swallow, i.e., to take something down from the throat. (Muf.) For example, the Quran states: «وَ قِیۡلَ یٰۤاَرۡضُ ابۡلَعِیۡ مَآءَکِ» (11/44). Translation: And the earth was commanded that it should swallow its water.","«بَلَعَ» meaning to swallow. To take down from the throat. It is in common usage.","to swallow","بلع","11:44",1
2872,629,"S","مَرَءَ","«اَلْمَرِئُ» This tube is called the one that extends from the throat to the stomach, through which food reaches the stomach. And «مَرَءَ» means food that has easily reached the stomach via this tube (muf). And «مَرِیْئًا» refers to food that easily reaches the stomach. (Ends with good, Fiqh 245)\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«فَاِنۡ طِبۡنَ لَکُمۡ عَنۡ شَیۡءٍ مِّنۡہُ نَفۡسًا فَکُلُوۡہُ ہَنِیۡٓئًا مَّرِیۡٓئًا» (4/4)\nTranslation: Yes, if women, of their own accord, remit any portion of the bridal money (mahr) to you, then consume it with pleasure and enjoyment.","«مَرَءَ» meaning something that effortlessly reaches the stomach.","Swallow","مرء","4:4",1
2873,629,"T","سَاغَ","«سَاغَ» means the smooth and pleasant descent of food or drink down the throat (as in *manjad*).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«لَّبَنًا خَالِصًا سَآئِغًا لِّلشّٰرِبِیۡنَ» (16/66)\nTranslation: (And We give you) pure milk, which is pleasant for those who drink it.\n\nAnd «اَسَاغَ» means to make food or drink descend from the throat.\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَ یُسۡقٰی مِنۡ مَّآءٍ صَدِیۡدٍ یَّتَجَرَّعُہٗ  وَ لَا یَکَادُ یُسِیۡغُہٗ» (14/16,17)\nTranslation: He will be given scalding water to gulp down, which he will be unable to swallow down his throat.","«سَاغَ» meaning that due to its delightful and pleasant taste, something passes easily into the stomach.","to swallow","ساغ","14:17-16:66-35:12",3
2874,629,"T","غَصَّ","«غَصَّ» meaning to get a knot in the throat from eating or drinking (mansaj) – food getting stuck in the throat and unable to be swallowed.  \nFor example: In the Quran it is:  \n«اِنَّ  لَدَیۡنَاۤ  اَنۡکَالًا وَّ  جَحِیۡمًا وَّ طَعَامًا ذَا غُصَّۃٍ» (73/12,13)  \nTranslation: No doubt, we have chains and a blazing fire and food that chokes.","«غَصَّ» meaning food getting stuck in the throat, i.e., food becoming lodged in the throat and unable to be swallowed.","to swallow","غص","73:13",1
2875,629,"T","لَقِفَ","«لَقِفَ» means to take something hastily. And «لَقِفَ الطَّعَام» means to eat hastily (munjad), or to take something with perfection and cleverness. It is used for taking with the hand and mouth. (m q) means to eat hastily; swallowing (m q).\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated: «وَ اَلۡقِ مَا فِیۡ یَمِیۡنِکَ تَلۡقَفۡ مَا صَنَعُوۡا» (20/69). Translation: And O Moses! Throw what is in your right hand (i.e., the staff); it will swallow whatever they have fabricated.","«لَقِفَ» meaning eating hastily, or swallowing without chewing.","to recite (the Quran)","لقف","7:117-20:69-26:45",3
2876,629,"T","اِلْتَقَمَ","«لَقَمَ» means to make a morsel. The amount of food that can fit in the mouth at once. To put into the mouth with the hand. (e.g.) And «اِلْتَقَمَ» means to swallow quickly (minjadd) and means to swallow by making large morsels (meaning). For instance: In the Quran it is said: «فَالۡتَقَمَہُ  الۡحُوۡتُ وَ ہُوَ  مُلِیۡمٌ» (37/142) Translation: Then the fish swallowed Jonah, and he had done a blameworthy deed.","«اِلْتَقَمَ» meaning to swallow greedily, to take large mouthfuls, or to swallow in one go.","to swallow","التقم","37:142",1
2877,630,"R","غَسَلَ","«غَسَلَ» means to wash something and remove dirt. For example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اِذَا قُمۡتُمۡ  اِلَی الصَّلٰوۃِ فَاغۡسِلُوۡا وُجُوۡہَکُمۡ وَ اَیۡدِیَکُمۡ» (5/6)\nTranslation: When you rise for prayer, wash your faces and your hands.\n\nAnd «اِغْتَسَلَ» means to clean the entire body from dirt or to bathe. For example: The commandment of Allah, the Most High, is:\n«وَ لَا جُنُبًا اِلَّا عَابِرِیۡ سَبِیۡلٍ حَتّٰی تَغۡتَسِلُوۡا» (4/43)\nTranslation: And the junub too, until he has bathed, may not approach the prayer, except for a traveler on the road (that if water is not available, then he should perform prayer with tayammum).","«غَسَلَ» and «اِغْتَسَلَ» mean to eliminate the blend of deception and impurity from something.","ritual washing of the deceased","غسل","5:6-4:43-38:42",3
2878,630,"T","طَھَّرَ","«طَھَرَتْ» Its opposite is «طَمَثَتْ», meaning a woman having menstruation. And «طَھْرَت» means being free from menstruation and becoming pure by bathing. Furthermore, the term «طَھَّر» is used in a much broader sense than «غَسَلَ». Purity (طہارت) is of three types: apparent, legal, and spiritual. Its example can be understood thus: if semen splashes onto clothing, the cloth does not become dirty but it certainly becomes impure.\n\nFor instance: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ  ثِیَابَکَ فَطَہِّرۡ» (74:4)\nTranslation: And keep your garments pure.\n\nThus, «طَھَّر» implies both cleaning clothes from dirt and removing impurities. And this very distinction exists between «اِطَّھَرَ» (meaning to bathe) and «اِغْتَسَلَ» (meaning to bathe).","«طَھَّرَ» and «اِطَّھَرَ» mean to also remove impurity, beyond mere physical dirt.","to perform wudu","طھر","2:25-2:125-2:222-2:232-3:15-3:42-3:55-4:57-5:6-5:41-7:82-8:11-9:103-9:108-11:78-22:26-25:48-27:56-33:33-33:53-56:79-58:12-74:4-76:21-80:14-98:2",26
2879,631,"N","لَیْسَ","«لَیْسَ» is an incomplete verb. It only appears in the past tense, and full forms are used, conveying both past and present meanings. For example, «لَسْتَ» means he did not or he was not, and «لَسْنَا» means they did not or they were not.\n\n« ب ، لَا ، لَمْ» and «لَنْ»: These three particles are such that when they enter the imperfect tense, they render it negative. «لَا»'s function is merely to create negation. For example, «لَا یَضْرِبُ» means he does not hit or he will not hit. And when «لَمْ» enters, it not only negates but also shifts the meaning to the past tense, as in «لَمْ یَضْرِبْ», meaning he did not hit. And «لَنْ», along with negating, first specifies it for the future and second emphasizes the negation. For example, «لَنْ یَّضْرِبَ» means he will absolutely never hit.\n\n« ج ، اِنْ ۔ مَا» and «ھَلْ»: These three particles have their own distinct meanings, but when «اِلَّا» follows them, they change their meaning to not or did not.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِنۡ  اَنۡتُمۡ  اِلَّا تَکۡذِبُوۡنَ» (36:15)\nMeaning: You are not except [a man] like us who lies, i.e., your only work is to lie.\n\nSimilarly, «مَا مِنْ اِلٰہٍ اِلَّا اللہ» i.e., There is no deity except Allah.\n\nAnd similarly, at another place, the Divine declaration states:\n«ہَلۡ کُنۡتُ  اِلَّا بَشَرًا رَّسُوۡلًا» (17:93)\nMeaning: I am not except a human messenger.\n\nAnd for or or nor, the following particles appear with standalone function: «لَا ۔ لَمَّا ۔ بَلٰی ۔ کَلَّا ، اِنَّمَا ، مَا ( نافیہ )» and «لَاتَ».","In Arabic grammar, this particle «لَیْسَ» is called an incomplete verb, meaning is not or was not.","No.","لیس","2:113-2:177-2:189-2:198-2:249-2:272-2:282-3:28-3:36-3:66-3:75-3:113-3:128-3:167-3:182-4:18-4:101-4:123-4:176-5:93-5:116-6:30-6:51-6:53-6:70-6:89-6:122-7:61-7:67-8:51-9:91-11:8-11:16-11:46-11:47-11:78-11:81-15:42-16:99-17:36-17:65-22:10-22:71-24:15-24:29-24:58-24:60-24:61-29:8-29:10-29:68-31:15-33:5-36:81-39:32-39:36-39:37-39:60-40:42-40:43-42:11-43:51-46:32-46:34-48:11-48:17-53:39-53:58-56:2-58:10-69:35-70:2-75:40-88:6-95:8",75
2880,631,"N","لَا","«لَا» is frequently used. It comes for answering in the negation of positive speech, for conjunction, and for repetition.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is:\n«فَلَا  صَدَّقَ  وَ لَا صَلّٰی» (75/31)\n\nTranslation: Neither did he believe (in Allah's word) nor did he pray.\n\n(For details, see any book on grammar.)","«لَا» does not mean no; it is used to give a response in the negation of a positive statement.","No","لا","1:7-2:2-2:6-2:11-2:12-2:13-2:17-2:18-2:22-2:26-2:30-2:32-2:35-2:38-2:41-2:42-2:48-2:60-2:62-2:68-2:71-2:78-2:80-2:83-2:84-2:86-2:87-2:100-2:101-2:102-2:104-2:105-2:107-2:112-2:113-2:118-2:119-2:120-2:123-2:124-2:132-2:134-2:136-2:141-2:147-2:150-2:152-2:154-2:158-2:162-2:163-2:168-2:169-2:170-2:171-2:173-2:174-2:182-2:185-2:187-2:188-2:190-2:191-2:193-2:195-2:196-2:197-2:203-2:205-2:208-2:216-2:217-2:221-2:222-2:224-2:225-2:228-2:229-2:230-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:237-2:240-2:243-2:249-2:254-2:255-2:256-2:258-2:262-2:264-2:267-2:272-2:273-2:274-2:275-2:276-2:277-2:279-2:281-2:282-2:283-2:285-2:286-3:2-3:5-3:6-3:8-3:9-3:10-3:18-3:25-3:28-3:32-3:57-3:60-3:64-3:66-3:67-3:73-3:75-3:77-3:80-3:84-3:86-3:88-3:102-3:103-3:105-3:111-3:116-3:118-3:119-3:120-3:130-3:139-3:140-3:153-3:154-3:156-3:160-3:161-3:169-3:170-3:171-3:175-3:176-3:178-3:180-3:187-3:188-3:194-3:195-3:196-3:199-4:2-4:5-4:6-4:11-4:18-4:19-4:20-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:25-4:29-4:32-4:34-4:36-4:38-4:40-4:42-4:43-4:46-4:48-4:49-4:53-4:65-4:75-4:77-4:78-4:84-4:87-4:89-4:94-4:95-4:98-4:102-4:104-4:105-4:107-4:108-4:114-4:116-4:121-4:123-4:124-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:135-4:137-4:140-4:142-4:143-4:144-4:148-4:154-4:155-4:168-4:171-4:172-4:173-5:2-5:3-5:5-5:8-5:13-5:19-5:21-5:25-5:26-5:41-5:44-5:48-5:49-5:51-5:54-5:57-5:58-5:64-5:67-5:68-5:69-5:70-5:76-5:77-5:79-5:82-5:84-5:87-5:89-5:95-5:100-5:101-5:103-5:104-5:105-5:106-5:108-5:109-5:115-5:116-6:8-6:12-6:14-6:17-6:19-6:20-6:21-6:25-6:27-6:33-6:34-6:35-6:37-6:38-6:48-6:50-6:51-6:52-6:56-6:59-6:61-6:68-6:70-6:71-6:76-6:80-6:81-6:90-6:91-6:102-6:103-6:106-6:108-6:109-6:113-6:114-6:115-6:121-6:125-6:135-6:136-6:138-6:141-6:142-6:144-6:145-6:147-6:148-6:150-6:151-6:152-6:153-6:158-6:160-6:163-6:164-7:2-7:3-7:17-7:19-7:27-7:28-7:31-7:33-7:34-7:35-7:38-7:40-7:42-7:47-7:49-7:55-7:56-7:58-7:62-7:73-7:74-7:79-7:85-7:86-7:95-7:99-7:100-7:105-7:131-7:142-7:146-7:148-7:150-7:158-7:163-7:169-7:170-7:179-7:182-7:186-7:187-7:188-7:191-7:192-7:193-7:195-7:197-7:198-7:202-7:205-7:206-8:15-8:20-8:21-8:22-8:25-8:27-8:34-8:39-8:46-8:47-8:48-8:55-8:56-8:58-8:59-8:60-8:65-9:6-9:8-9:10-9:12-9:16-9:19-9:23-9:24-9:28-9:29-9:31-9:34-9:36-9:37-9:39-9:40-9:44-9:45-9:49-9:54-9:55-9:66-9:74-9:79-9:80-9:81-9:84-9:85-9:87-9:91-9:92-9:93-9:94-9:96-9:101-9:108-9:109-9:110-9:116-9:118-9:120-9:121-9:126-9:127-9:129-10:7-10:11-10:15-10:16-10:17-10:18-10:26-10:33-10:35-10:36-10:37-10:40-10:42-10:43-10:44-10:47-10:49-10:54-10:55-10:60-10:61-10:62-10:64-10:65-10:68-10:69-10:71-10:77-10:81-10:85-10:88-10:89-10:90-10:94-10:95-10:96-10:100-10:101-10:104-10:105-10:106-10:107-11:14-11:15-11:17-11:22-11:26-11:29-11:31-11:34-11:36-11:37-11:42-11:43-11:46-11:49-11:51-11:52-11:55-11:57-11:64-11:70-11:78-11:81-11:84-11:85-11:89-11:105-11:109-11:112-11:113-11:115-11:118-11:121-12:5-12:10-12:11-12:15-12:21-12:23-12:37-12:38-12:40-12:52-12:56-12:60-12:67-12:68-12:69-12:86-12:87-12:90-12:92-12:96-12:107-12:110-13:1-13:11-13:14-13:16-13:20-13:30-13:31-13:33-13:36-13:37-13:41-14:9-14:17-14:18-14:22-14:31-14:34-14:38-14:42-14:43-14:47-15:13-15:48-15:53-15:55-15:65-15:68-15:69-15:88-16:1-16:2-16:8-16:17-16:18-16:20-16:22-16:23-16:26-16:35-16:37-16:38-16:43-16:45-16:49-16:51-16:56-16:60-16:61-16:62-16:70-16:73-16:74-16:75-16:76-16:78-16:84-16:85-16:91-16:92-16:94-16:95-16:101-16:104-16:105-16:107-16:109-16:111-16:115-16:116-16:127-17:10-17:15-17:22-17:23-17:26-17:29-17:31-17:32-17:33-17:34-17:36-17:37-17:39-17:44-17:45-17:48-17:56-17:68-17:69-17:71-17:75-17:76-17:77-17:82-17:86-17:88-17:99-17:107-17:110-18:5-18:19-18:21-18:22-18:23-18:26-18:27-1