:40-40:43-40:52-40:57-40:58-40:59-40:61-40:62-40:65-41:4-41:7-41:16-41:22-41:26-41:30-41:34-41:37-41:38-41:40-41:42-41:44-41:47-41:49-42:7-42:8-42:13-42:15-42:18-42:23-42:31-42:40-42:47-42:52-43:52-43:61-43:62-43:66-43:68-43:75-43:80-43:86-43:88-44:8-44:19-44:39-44:41-44:56-45:10-45:14-45:18-45:22-45:26-45:32-45:35-46:5-46:8-46:9-46:10-46:13-46:19-46:25-46:26-46:32-46:35-47:11-47:13-47:19-47:33-47:35-47:36-47:38-48:15-48:17-48:22-48:27-49:1-49:2-49:4-49:11-49:12-49:14-49:17-50:28-51:28-51:51-51:59-52:15-52:16-52:23-52:29-52:33-52:36-52:46-52:47-53:26-53:27-53:28-53:32-53:60-55:9-55:20-55:33-55:35-55:39-55:56-55:74-56:19-56:25-56:33-56:44-56:61-56:75-56:79-56:85-57:8-57:10-57:15-57:16-57:22-57:23-58:7-58:9-58:14-58:17-58:22-59:6-59:7-59:9-59:10-59:11-59:12-59:13-59:14-59:19-59:20-59:22-59:23-60:1-60:3-60:5-60:8-60:10-60:12-60:13-61:2-61:3-61:5-61:7-62:5-62:7-63:3-63:6-63:7-63:8-63:9-64:13-65:1-65:3-65:6-65:7-65:6-66:6-66:7-66:8-68:8-68:10-68:18-68:24-68:42-68:44-68:48-69:18-69:33-69:34-69:36-69:37-69:38-69:39-69:42-70:10-70:40-71:4-71:13-71:23-71:24-71:26-71:27-71:28-72:3-72:10-72:13-72:18-72:20-72:21-72:26-73:9-74:6-74:28-74:31-74:53-75:1-75:2-75:11-75:16-75:31-76:9-76:13-76:24-77:31-77:35-77:36-77:48-78:24-78:27-78:35-78:37-78:38-81:15-82:19-84:16-84:20-84:21-86:10-87:6-87:13-88:7-88:11-89:17-89:18-89:25-89:26-90:1-90:11-91:15-92:15-93:9-93:10-96:19-107:3-109-2-109:3-109:4-109:5",1204
2881,631,"N","لَمَّا","«لَمَّا» Generally, it is used for negating a past event (muf), meaning not yet or has not. For example: In the Quran: «وَ لَمَّا یَعۡلَمِ اللّٰہُ الَّذِیۡنَ جٰہَدُوۡا مِنۡکُمۡ» (9/16) Translation: And Allah has not yet known those who have striven from among you. (For further details, refer to a grammar book!)","«لَمَّا» is used to deny any past event.","No","لما","2:17-2:33-2:89-2:101-2:214-2:246-2:249-2:250-2:259-3:36-3:52-3:142-4:77-5:117-6:5-6:44-6:76-6:77-6:78-7:22-7:116-7:126-7:134-7:135-7:143-7:149-7:150-7:154-7:155-7:165-7:166-7:189-7:190-8:48-9:16-9:76-9:114-10:12-10:13-10:23-10:39-10:54-10:76-10:77-10:80-10:81-10:98-11:58-11:66-11:70-11:74-11:77-11:82-11:94-11:101-11:111-12:15-12:22-12:28-12:31-12:50-12:54-12:59-12:63-12:65-12:66-12:68-12:69-12:70-12:80-12:88-12:94-12:96-12:99-14:22-15:61-17:67-18:59-18:61-18:62-19:49-20:11-21:12-25:37-26:21-26:41-26:61-27:8-27:10-27:13-27:36-27:40-27:42-27:44-28:14-28:19-28:22-28:23-28:25-28:29-28:30-28:31-28:36-28:48-29:31-29:33-29:65-29:68-31:32-32:24-33:22-33:37-34:14-34:33-34:43-35:42-36:32-37:102-37:103-38:8-40:25-40:66-40:83-40:84-40:85-41:41-42:44-43:30-43:35-43:47-43:50-43:55-43:57-43:63-46:7-46:24-46:29-49:14-50:5-59:16-61:5-61:6-62:3-66:3-67:27-68:26-68:51-69:11-72:13-72:19-80:23-86:4",152
2882,631,"N","بَلٰی","«بَلٰی» is used when a question is phrased in the negative, but the intended answer is a positive affirmation, and the response is to be given in an affirmative manner. It means Why not? or Indeed yes.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اَلَسۡتُ بِرَبِّکُمۡ ؕ قَالُوۡا بَلٰی» (7/172)\nTranslation: (Allah asked) Am I not your Lord? And they replied: Yes indeed! (i.e., Of course You are).","«بَلٰی» meaning why not","No","بلی","2:81-2:112-2:260-3:76-3:125-6:30-7:172-16:28-16:38-34:3-36:81-39:59-39:71-40:50-43:80-46:33-46:34-57:14-64:7-67:9-75:4-84:15",22
2883,631,"N","کَلَّا","«کَلَّا» means 'by no means'. It is used exclusively to prevent or warn against the preceding speech, not to invalidate it. It serves to nullify the previous statement (M. Q) (Munjid).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«عَمَّ  یَتَسَآءَلُوۡنَ عَنِ النَّبَاِ  الۡعَظِیۡمِ الَّذِیۡ ہُمۡ  فِیۡہِ  مُخۡتَلِفُوۡنَ کَلَّا  سَیَعۡلَمُوۡنَ ثُمَّ  کَلَّا  سَیَعۡلَمُوۡنَ» (78/1-5)  \nTranslation: What are these people asking about? About the momentous news. Regarding which they are in disagreement. By no means! They will soon come to know. Then by no means! They will soon come to know.","«کَلَّا» meaning by no means.","No.","کلا","19:79-19:82-23:100-26:15-26:62-34:27-70:15-70:39-74:16-74:32-74:53-74:54-75:11-75:20-75:26-78:4-78:5-80:11-80:23-82:9-83:7-83:14-83:15-83:18-89:17-78:21-96:6-96:15-96:19-102:3-102:4-102:5-104:4",33
2884,631,"N","اِنَّمَا","In Arabic grammar, this term is known as 'hass.' It signifies 'nothing except it' or 'apart from it, there is no other thing.' The term 'hass' functions to restrict or confine a specific purpose. For example, the Quran states: «قُلۡ اِنَّمَاۤ  اَنَا بَشَرٌ  مِّثۡلُکُمۡ  یُوۡحٰۤی  اِلَیَّ» (18/110) Translation: 'Say, There is nothing except this: that I am a human just like you, yet revelation is conveyed to me.'","«اِنَّمَا» In Arabic grammar, it is called 'kalam hasr'. It means there is nothing else besides it.","No","انما","2:11-2:14-2:102-2:117-2:137-2:169-2:173-2:181-2:275-3:20-3:47-3:155-3:175-3:178-3:185-4:10-4:17-4:111-4:171-5:27-5:33-5:55-5:90-5:91-6:19-6:36-6:109-6:156-6:159-7:33-7:131-7:173-7:187-7:203-8:2-9:18-9:28-9:37-9:45-9:55-9:60-9:65-9:85-9:93-10:20-10:23-10:24-10:108-11:12-11:33-12:86-13:7-13:19-13:36-13:40-14:42-15:15-16:40-16:51-16:82-16:92-16:95-16:100-16:101-16:103-16:105-16:115-16:124-17:15-18:110-19:19-19:35-19:84-19:97-20:69-20:72-20:90-20:98-21:45-21:108-22:49-23:117-24:51-24:54-24:62-26:153-26:185-27:40-27:91-27:92-28:78-29:6-29:17-29:25-29:50-31:12-32:15-33:33-33:63-34:46-34:50-35:6-35:18-35:28-36:11-36:82-37:19-38:65-39:9-39:10-39:41-39:49-40:39-40:68-41:6-42:42-44:58-46:23-47:36-47:38-48:10-49:10-49:15-51:5-52:16-58:10-60:9-64:12-64:15-66:7-67:26-72:20-76:9-77:7-79:13-79:45-88:21",137
2886,631,"N","لَات","«لَات» comes in the meaning of «لَیْسَ» and is counted among the eloquence of the people of Yemen. After «لا», «ت» is extra, and its noun is elided (manjid).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَنَادَوۡا  وَّ  لَاتَ حِیۡنَ مَنَاصٍ» (38/3)  \nTranslation: (Upon seeing the punishment) they began to cry out, though there was no longer any chance of deliverance.  \nHere, «لَاتَ الْحِیْنَ حِینَ مَنَاص» was in place of «لَاتَ حِیْنَ مَنَاص». In this instance, the first «حِیْن» was elided (Jami' al-Bayan).","if «لَات» is not","No","لات","38:3",1
2887,632,"N","حَدَثَ","«حَدَثَ» is the opposite of «عَدَمَ». And «حَدَثَ» means the emergence of something new or a novel matter. And in the context of Hadith, it refers to any matter that did not exist before and has come into existence anew. It could be a new matter or thing, or something that is not new but which people had forgotten and has now been reintroduced as if anew.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n« لَا تَدۡرِیۡ لَعَلَّ اللّٰہَ یُحۡدِثُ بَعۡدَ ذٰلِکَ اَمۡرًا » (65/1)\nTranslation: You do not know; perhaps Allah will bring forth after that a new matter.\n\nFor further detail, see Various Names of the Quran.","«حَدَثَ» meaning the emergence or appearance of something new or novel. For example, all creation is accidental.","New","حدث","2:76-18:70-20:113-21:2-26:5-65:1-93:11-99:4",8
2888,632,"N","جَدّ","«جَدِیْد» means a new thing. And the word «جَدَّ» comes with several meanings: (1) to be majestic, (2) to be fortunate and blessed, (3) to be new. When its meaning is 'new', it refers to a thing that has no precedent or like it previously existing. And that thing is usable. But after use, it becomes old, worn out, and then unusable. For example, a new shirt.\n\nFor instance: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«بَلۡ ہُمۡ فِیۡ لَبۡسٍ مِّنۡ خَلۡقٍ جَدِیۡدٍ» (50/15)\nTranslation: But they are in doubt about a new creation.","Something that is new and its counterpart already exists.","New","جد","17:49-17:98-32:10-34:7-35:16-50:15",6
2889,632,"N","بَدَعَه","Two meanings are derived from it: (1) to initiate something, and (2) to create something for which no prior example or model exists (for example). From this perspective, the name of Allah Ta'ala is «بَدِیْع», meaning the One who brings into existence for the first time. And «بِدْعًا» means the One who initiates something or a sequence.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قُلۡ مَا کُنۡتُ بِدۡعًا مِّنَ الرُّسُلِ» (46/9)\nTranslation: Say, I am not a new messenger.","to create something new without precedent","New","بدع","2:117-6:101-46:9",3
2890,633,"B","تَحْت","«تَحْت» is an adverb meaning below. Its opposite is «فَوْق», meaning above. It is used in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ لَوۡ اَنَّہُمۡ اَقَامُوا التَّوۡرٰىۃَ وَ الۡاِنۡجِیۡلَ وَ مَاۤ  اُنۡزِلَ اِلَیۡہِمۡ  مِّنۡ رَّبِّہِمۡ لَاَکَلُوۡا مِنۡ فَوۡقِہِمۡ وَ مِنۡ تَحۡتِ اَرۡجُلِہِمۡ» (5:66)\nTranslation: And if they had upheld the Torah and the Gospel and what was revealed to them from their Lord, they would have surely been fed from above them and from beneath their feet.","«تَحْت» is an adverbial noun meaning 'below'.","Below","تحت","2:25-2:266-3:15-3:136-3:195-3:198-4:13-4:57-4:122-5:12-5:66-5:85-5:119-6:6-6:65-7:43-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:9-13:35-14:23-16:31-18:31-18:82-19:24-20:6-20:76-22:14-22:23-25:10-29:55-29:58-39:16-39:20-41:29-43:51-47:12-48:5-48:17-48:18-57:12-58:22-61:12-64:9-65:11-66:8-66:10-85:11-98:8",50
2891,633,"B","اَسْفَل","«اَسْفَلَ» means low, inferior, or lesser. Its opposite is «اعلٰی», meaning excellent, high, or exalted. This word is used in two ways: (1) The lower part of a single thing is called «اَسْفَل» and the upper part is called «اَعْلٰی», as in «اَسْفَلَہٗ اَغْلَظُ مِنْ اَعْلَاہُ», meaning the lower part of that thing is harder than its upper part.\n\nThe word «اَعْلٰی» is used for the height of rank and status. «اَسْفَلَ» is used for lowness and inferiority, and its feminine form is «سُفْلٰی».\n\nFor example: The Noble Prophet ﷺ said:\n«اَلْیَدُ الْعُلْیَا خَیْرٌ مِّنْ یَدِ السُّفْلٰی»\nMeaning: The upper hand is better than the lower hand.\n\nIn this Hadith, «عُلْیَا» and «سُفْلٰی» are used in a spiritual sense, meaning the hand that gives charity is better than the hand that receives.\n\nAnd in the Noble Quran, Almighty Allah says:\n«وَ جَعَلَ کَلِمَۃَ  الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوا السُّفۡلٰی ؕ وَ کَلِمَۃُ  اللّٰہِ ہِیَ الۡعُلۡیَا» (9:40)\nTranslation: And Allah exalted the word of the disbelievers and lowered the word of the believers. And the word of Allah is ever exalted.\n\nAnd «سَافِل» means inferior and contemptible in terms of status and rank. And «اَلسِّفْلَۃ» means lowly people (i.e., the contemptible ones).\n\nFor example: Almighty Allah says:\n«لَقَدۡ خَلَقۡنَا الۡاِنۡسَانَ فِیۡۤ  اَحۡسَنِ تَقۡوِیۡمٍ ۫ثُمَّ  رَدَدۡنٰہُ  اَسۡفَلَ سٰفِلِیۡنَ» (95:4-5)\nTranslation: We have certainly created man in the best of stature; Then We return him to the lowest of the low.","«اَسْفَلَ سَافِل» the lower part of something; or inferior in rank or status. Below. Low. Inferior. Lesser.","below","اسفل","4:145-8:42-9:40-33:10-37:98-41:29-95:5",7
2892,633,"B","خَفَضَ","«خَفَضَ» means to lower. Its opposite is «رَفَعَ», which means to raise. «خافِض» and «رافِع» are both names of Allah, meaning the One who lowers someone and the One who raises someone's status. «خَفَضَ الصَّوْت». He lowered the voice and «خَفَضَ الْجَنَاحَ» means to keep the arms down, to bow.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اخۡفِضۡ لَہُمَا جَنَاحَ الذُّلِّ مِنَ الرَّحۡمَۃِ» (17/24)\nTranslation: And lower unto them the wing of humility out of mercy.","«خَفَضَ» to be pressed down or to press down. to lower or tilt the eye, arm, or side.","Below","خفض","15:88-17:24-26:215-56:3",4
2893,633,"B","غَضَّ","«غَضَّ» refers to lowering or moderating the gaze or voice. «غَضَّ صَوْتُہٗ». He lowered his voice and «غَضَّ بَصَرُہٗ» he lowered his gaze or restrained his sight from unlawful things.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«قُلۡ  لِّلۡمُؤۡمِنٰتِ یَغۡضُضۡنَ مِنۡ اَبۡصَارِہِنَّ» (24:31)  \nTranslation: And tell the believing women to lower their gaze.  \nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is:  \n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ وَ اغۡضُضۡ مِنۡ صَوۡتِکَ» (31:19)  \nTranslation: And lower your voice; indeed, the most disagreeable of sounds is the voice of donkeys.","«غَضَّ» is used to lower or suppress the gaze or voice (in general).","below","غض","24:30-24:31-31:19-49:3",4
2894,633,"B","قَصَر","«قَصَرَ» meaning not reaching the length or extremity of something (muf, m, l) to shorten, to make small, to not do as much as should have been done. As in «صَلٰوۃُ الْقَصْر». And «قَصَرُ الطَّرْف» meaning a gaze as far as it can see. Not looking that far, but keeping the gaze only downwards. In these meanings, this word is specific for gazes.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ عِنۡدَہُمۡ  قٰصِرٰتُ الطَّرۡفِ عِیۡنٌ» (37/48)\nTranslation: And there will be with them large-eyed, restrained glances women.","«قَصَرَ» To lower one's gaze. Not to cast a full glance.","Below","قصر","37:48-38:52-55:56",3
2895,633,"B","خَشَعَ","«خَشَعَ» essentially denotes fear whose effects begin to manifest on the organs and limbs (meaning), and these effects can only become apparent on the face, voice, or eyes. Therefore, this term is employed to describe them. For gaze and voice, the term «غَضَّ» is also used. The distinction between the two is that if the state is general, «غَضَّ» is applied, whereas if it arises from fear, «خَشَعَ» is used.\n\nFor instance, regarding gaze: The Quran states:\n«خَاشِعَۃً  اَبۡصَارُہُمۡ تَرۡہَقُہُمۡ  ذِلَّۃٌ» (70/44)\nTranslation: Their eyes will be downcast, and humiliation will overwhelm them.\n\nAnd for voice: The Quran states:\n«وَ خَشَعَتِ الۡاَصۡوَاتُ لِلرَّحۡمٰنِ» (20/108)\nTranslation: And voices will be lowered before God (i.e., they will be subdued due to fear).\n\nAnd for faces: The Quran states:\n«وُجُوۡہٌ  یَّوۡمَئِذٍ خَاشِعَۃٌ» (88/2)\nTranslation: On that day, many faces will be downcast.","«خَشَعَ» a fear whose effects begin to manifest even on the organs and limbs.","below","خشع","2:45-3:199-20:108-21:90-23:2-33:35-41:39-42:45-54:7-57:16-59:21-68:43-70:44-79:9-88:2",15
2896,634,"R","صَالِح","«صَلَح» means to correct corruption and its opposite, «فَسَدَ» (lit.). And «صَالِح» means: one who reforms oneself; one who rectifies the soul (fig.); one who adopts good deeds and abandons bad ones; and one who persists in the effort of self-reformation.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کَانَ اَبُوۡہُمَا صَالِحًا» (18/82)\nTranslation: And their father was a righteous man.\n\nAt another instance, the divine decree states:\n«وَ لَا تُفۡسِدُوۡا فِی الۡاَرۡضِ بَعۡدَ اِصۡلَاحِہَا» (7/56)\nTranslation: And do not cause corruption in the land after its reformation.","«صَالِح» The One who reforms the self and corrects all corruption.","Righteous","صالح","2:25-2:62-2:82-2:130-2:277-3:39-3:46-3:57-3:114-4:34-4:57-4:69-4:122-4:124-4:173-5:9-5:69-5:84-5:93-6:85-7:42-7:168-7:189-7:190-7:196-9:75-9:102-9:120-10:4-10:9-11:11-11:23-11:46-12:9-12:101-13:29-14:23-16:97-16:122-17:9-17:25-18:2-18:30-18:46-18:82-18:88-18:107-18:110-19:60-19:76-19:96-20:75-20:82-20:112-21:72-21:75-21:86-21:94-21:105-22:14-22:23-22:50-22:56-23:51-23:100-24:32-24:55-25:70-25:71-26:83-26:227-27:19-28:27-28:67-28:80-29:7-29:9-29:27-29:58-30:15-30:44-30:45-31:8-32:12-32:19-33:31-34:4-34:11-34:37-35:7-35:10-35:37-37:100-37:112-38:24-38:28-40:40-40:58-41:8-41:33-41:46-42:22-42:23-42:26-45:15-45:21-45:30-46:15-47:2-47:12-48:29-63:10-64:9-65:11-66:4-66:10-68:50-72:11-84:25-85:11-95:6-98:7-103:3",123
2897,634,"R","اَبْرَار","This is the plural of «بَار». «بِرّ» means to do good on a large scale (detailed). In reality, «بِرّ» refers not merely to performing good deeds but to the innate character and nature that is constantly inclined towards goodness. Its opposite is «اِثْم», meaning sin and disobedience.\n\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«لَنۡ تَنَالُوا الۡبِرَّ حَتّٰی تُنۡفِقُوۡا مِمَّا تُحِبُّوۡنَ» (3:92)\nTranslation: You will never attain goodness until you spend from that which you love (in the way of Allah).\n\nAnd «بَرَّ» and «بَارّ» describe a person whose nature is always prepared to do good. When an opportunity arises, they perform a good deed. Hajj mabrur refers to a Hajj performed exactly in accordance with the Sunnah of the Prophet ﷺ, without any shortcomings.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَّ بَرًّۢا بِوَالِدَیۡہِ وَ لَمۡ یَکُنۡ جَبَّارًا عَصِیًّا» (19:14)\nTranslation: And Yahya (peace be upon him) was consistently kind to his parents. He was never rebellious or disobedient.","This «اَبْرَار» (the plural form) denotes a person who is always prepared to do good deeds and frequently performs them.","Righteous","ابرار","3:193-3:198-19:14-19:32-76:5-80:16-82:13-83:18-83:22",9
2898,634,"R","بَرَرَۃٌ","It is a collection of «بَرَّ» and this is stronger than «بَارّ», and more exaggeration is found in it. For example: In the Quran it is: «بِاَیۡدِیۡ سَفَرَۃٍ کِرَامٍۭ  بَرَرَۃٍ» (80/15-16). Translation: (Such ones) are written by the hands of scribes who are leaders and righteous.","«بَرَرَۃٌ» In it, there is more exaggeration than «بَار», such as a person who is always prepared to do far more good deeds than required.","Righteous","بررۃ","80:16",1
2899,634,"R","رَشِیْد","«رُشْد» means «اِسْتِقَامَۃُ الطَّرِیْق» (m. l.), i.e., to proceed correctly on the path or to remain steadfast on the straight path. Its opposite is «غَیّ», meaning to go astray on a wrong path.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَدۡ تَّبَیَّنَ الرُّشۡدُ مِنَ الۡغَیِّ» (2/256)\nTranslation: Guidance has become distinctly clear from misguidance.\n\nAnd «رَشِیْد» means one who is guided, possessing good habits and morals; righteous conduct.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«فَاتَّقُوا اللّٰہَ وَ لَا تُخۡزُوۡنِ فِیۡ ضَیۡفِیۡ ؕ اَلَـیۡسَ مِنۡکُمۡ  رَجُلٌ  رَّشِیۡدٌ» (11/78)\nTranslation: Fear Allah and do not disgrace me before my guests. Is there not among you a man of righteous conduct?","«رَشِیْد» of good habits and manners, and virtuous conduct.","Righteous","رشید","11:78-11:87-11:97",3
2900,634,"V","سَعِیْد","«سَعِیْد» A person who is innately righteous. Meaning: righteous and fortunate, and its opposite «شَقِیّ» means wicked, and «سَعَدَ» means blessed. And that divine matters are a helper and supporter for humans in attaining good (abbreviation: m. m. l).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَوۡمَ یَاۡتِ لَا تَکَلَّمُ نَفۡسٌ اِلَّا بِاِذۡنِہٖ ۚ فَمِنۡہُمۡ  شَقِیٌّ  وَّ سَعِیۡدٌ» (11/105)\nTranslation: When that Day arrives, no soul will speak except by His permission. Then some will be wretched and some will be blessed.","«سَعِیْد» such a person who is inherently good, of good character.","Virtuous","سعید","11:105",1
2901,634,"V","مُتَّقِیْنَ یا مُتَّقُوْنَ","The plural of «مُتَّقِی» is «وَقٰی», denoting to save something from a harmful thing (source), and «اِتَّقٰی ۔ تقوٰی» means to abstain from sinful acts out of fear of Allah's punishment or to be cautious. Its opposite is «عُدْوَان», meaning injustice and oppression. And «مُتَّقِیْ» means pious, one who, out of the fear of Allah, is mindful of His commands and prohibitions (source).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ صَدَقُوۡا ؕ وَ اُولٰٓئِکَ ہُمُ الۡمُتَّقُوۡنَ» (2/177)\nTranslation: It is these who are the true believers, and it is these who are the God-fearing.","«مُتَّقِی» the pious one who abstains from sinful acts out of the fear of God.","virtuous","متقین یا متقون","2:2-2:66-2:177-2:180-2:194-2:241-3:76-3:115-3:133-3:138-5:27-5:46-7:128-8:34-9:4-9:7-9:36-9:44-9:123-11:49-13:35-15:45-16:30-16:31-19:85-19:97-21:48-24:34-25:15-25:74-26:90-28:83-38:28-38:49-39:33-39:57-43:35-43:67-44:51-45:19-47:15-50:31-51:15-52:17-54:54-68:34-69:48-77:41-78:31",49
2902,634,"R","رَبَّانِی","«رَبَّانِی» Imam Raghhib has discussed this word at length. Some scholars write that its meaning is 'one who fosters knowledge'. Some others attribute it to «رَبّ», just as «جِسْمٌ» is from «جِسْمَانِیٌّ». Similarly, «رَبّ» is from «رَبَّانِیٌّ». And its meaning is, 'belonging to Allah'. Both Dervish and Sahib Munajid have recorded both meanings. 'The great scholar' and 'the people of Allah'. Also 'the one acquainted with Allah' (the gnostic of Allah), meaning 'one who knows Allah'. In any case, the second opinion seems to be the prevalent one. Because in the Quran, the word «اَحْبَار» (scholars) appears separately alongside «رَبَّانِیُّون» (5/44). Similarly, in the Quran, the word «رِبِّیُّوْن» also appears in one place (3/146); its meaning is also the same.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«لَوۡ لَا یَنۡہٰہُمُ الرَّبّٰنِیُّوۡنَ وَ الۡاَحۡبَارُ عَنۡ قَوۡلِہِمُ الۡاِثۡمَ وَ اَکۡلِہِمُ السُّحۡتَ» (5/63)\nTranslation: Why do their rabbis and scholars not forbid them from sinful speech and from [consuming] what is forbidden?","«رَبَّانِی» Darwesh. God-conscious people. Sheikhs of the worshipper-ascetic type.","Righteous","ربانی","3:79-5:44-5:63",3
2903,635,"R","عُرف ، مَعْرُوْف","«عَرَفَ» means to recognize something and its opposite «نَکَرَ». It means astonishment at something. And ma'roof (معروف) and 'urf (عرف) refer to any matter that the good people of society consider good. The good custom of society. The ways of good-natured people. The national custom that is considered praiseworthy. Such as sitting respectfully before elders and addressing them with honor, etc.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«خُذِ الۡعَفۡوَ وَ اۡمُرۡ بِالۡعُرۡفِ وَ اَعۡرِضۡ عَنِ  الۡجٰہِلِیۡنَ» (7/199)\nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ!) Practice forgiveness, enjoin what is good, and turn away from the ignorant.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَلۡتَکُنۡ مِّنۡکُمۡ اُمَّۃٌ یَّدۡعُوۡنَ اِلَی الۡخَیۡرِ وَ یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ» (3/104)\nTranslation: And there must be among you a group who invite people to goodness, enjoin what is right, and forbid what is wrong.","«عُرف ، مَعْرُوْف» every such thing that the good people of society think well of.","Righteousness","عرف ، معروف","2:89-2:146-2:178-2:180-2:228-2:229-2:231-2:232-2:233-2:234-2:235-2:236-2:240-2:241-2:263-2:273-3:104-3:110-3:114-4:5-4:6-4:8-4:19-4:25-4:114-5:83-6:20-7:46-7:48-7:157-7:199-9:67-9:71-9:112-12:58-12:62-16:83-22:41-22:72-23:69-24:53-27:93-31:15-31:17-33:6-33:32-33:59-47:6-47:21-47:30-55:41-60:12-65:2-65:6-83:24",55
2904,635,"R","حَسَنَۃٌ","The plural of «حَسَنَۃٌ» is «حَسَنَات». «حَسَنَات» denotes every pleasing and preferred action that conforms to reason and Shariah. Its opposite is «سَیِّئَۃً». And the plural of «سَیِّئَۃً» is «سَیِّئَات».\n\nFor example, the Quran states: «اِنَّ الۡحَسَنٰتِ یُذۡہِبۡنَ السَّیِّاٰتِ» (11/114).\n\nTranslation: Indeed, good deeds remove bad deeds.","«حَسَنَۃٌ» Every deed that aligns with both reason and Sharia.","Righteousness","حسنۃ","2:201-3:120-4:40-4:78-4:79-4:85-6:160-7:95-7:131-7:156-7:168-9:50-9:52-11:114-13:6-13:22-16:30-16:41-16:122-16:125-25:70-27:46-27:89-28:54-28:84-33:21-39:10-41:34-42:23-60:4-60:6",31
2905,635,"G","خَیْر","«خَیْر» refers to the perfection of any good deed. These are great virtuous acts that bring benefit to the general public (muf). Great, great deeds in goodness. Moreover, «خَیْر» also means an act that is desirable for all (muf), such as arranging water for travelers along the road, and so on.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَاۡمُرُوۡنَ بِالۡمَعۡرُوۡفِ وَ یَنۡہَوۡنَ عَنِ الۡمُنۡکَرِ وَ یُسَارِعُوۡنَ فِی الۡخَیۡرٰتِ» (3/114)\nTranslation: They enjoin what is right, forbid what is wrong, and hasten to do good deeds.","«خَیْر» Every action that is universally cherished or that brings benefit to the community.","goodness","خیر","2:54-2:61-2:103-2:105-2:106-2:110-2:148-2:158-2:180-2:184-2:197-2:215-2:216-2:220-2:221-2:263-2:269-2:271-2:272-2:273-2:280-3:15-3:26-3:30-3:54-3:104-3:110-3:114-3:115-3:150-3:157-3:178-3:180-3:198-4:19-4:25-4:46-4:59-4:66-4:77-4:114-4:127-4:128-4:149-4:170-4:171-5:48-5:114-6:17-6:32-6:57-6:158-7:12-7:26-7:85-7:87-7:89-7:155-7:169-7:188-8:19-8:23-8:30-8:70-9:3-9:41-9:61-9:74-9:88-9:109-10:11-10:58-10:107-10:109-11:31-11:84-11:86-12:39-12:57-12:59-12:64-12:80-12:109-16:30-16:76-16:95-16:126-17:11-17:35-18:36-18:40-18:44-18:46-18:81-18:95-19:73-19:76-20:73-20:131-21:35-21:73-21:89-21:90-22:11-22:30-22:36-22:58-22:77-23:29-23:56-23:61-23:72-23:109-23:118-24:11-24:12-24:27-24:33-24:60-25:10-25:15-25:24-27:36-27:59-27:89-28:24-28:26-28:60-28:80-28:84-29:16-30:38-33:19-33:25-34:39-35:32-37:62-38:32-38:76-41:40-41:49-42:36-43:32-43:52-43:58-44:37-46:11-47:21-49:5-49:11-50:25-54:43-55:70-58:12-61:11-62:9-62:11-64:16-66:5-68:12-68:32-70:21-70:41-73:20-87:17-93:4-97:3-98:7-99:7-100:8",170
2906,635,"R","بِرّ","«بِرّ» means an inherent tendency toward every good deed and carrying them out when the opportunity arises, and its opposite is «اِثْم», meaning sin, transgression, moral or religious offense (see details above under 'good deeds').\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡبِرِّ وَ التَّقۡوٰی ۪ وَ لَا تَعَاوَنُوۡا عَلَی الۡاِثۡمِ وَ الۡعُدۡوَانِ» (5/2)\n\nTranslation: Cooperate in righteousness and piety, but do not cooperate in sin and aggression.","An innate disposition to remain inclined toward goodness at all times.","righteousness","بر","2:44-2:177-2:189-2:224-3:92-5:2-52:28-58:9-60:8",9
2907,636,"M","کَثِیْر","«کَثِیْر» means more. It occurs in both contexts of quantity and number, and is used in both material and spiritual senses. Its usage is common. Its opposite is «قَلِیْل», meaning less and few.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ مَنۡ یُّؤۡتَ الۡحِکۡمَۃَ فَقَدۡ اُوۡتِیَ خَیۡرًا کَثِیۡرًا» (2/269)\nTranslation: And whoever is given wisdom has indeed been given abundant good.\n\nIn the aforementioned verse, «کَثِیْر» is used in a spiritual sense for quantity, and in the following verse fragment, its usage is physical and for number.\n\nFor example, The Command of Allah, the Most High states:\n«فَاٰتَیۡنَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا مِنۡہُمۡ اَجۡرَہُمۡ ۚ وَ کَثِیۡرٌ  مِّنۡہُمۡ  فٰسِقُوۡنَ» (57/27)\nTranslation: So those who believed among them, We will give them their reward. And most of them are defiantly disobedient.\n\nAnd in «کَوْثَر», hyperbolic usage is frequently encountered. «تَکَاثُرَ الشَّیْء» means something being extremely abundant. «رَجُلٌ کَاثِرٌ» means a wealthy person, and «کَوْثَر» also means a generous person as well as «خَیْرٌ کَثِیْر». Moreover, «کَوْثَر» is also the name of a river in Paradise. (Miftah)\n\nFor example, The Command of Allah, the Most High states:\n«اِنَّاۤ  اَعۡطَیۡنٰکَ  الۡکَوۡثَرَ» (108/1)\nTranslation: Indeed, We have granted you, [O Muhammad], al-Kawthar.","«کَثِیْر» is commonly used to denote an increase in the number or quantity of anything.","More","کثیر","2:26-2:109-2:245-2:249-2:269-3:41-3:146-3:186-4:1-4:19-4:82-4:94-4:100-4:114-4:160-5:15-5:32-5:49-5:62-5:64-5:66-5:68-5:71-5:77-5:80-5:81-5:91-6:119-6:137-7:179-8:43-8:45-9:25-9:34-9:82-10:92-11:91-14:36-17:70-20:33-20:34-22:18-22:40-23:19-23:21-25:14-25:38-25:49-26:227-27:15-30:8-33:21-33:35-33:41-36:62-38:24-38:51-41:22-42:30-42:34-43:73-48:19-48:20-49:7-49:12-56:32-57:16-57:26-57:27-62:10-71:24",71
2908,636,"M","جَمّ","«جَمّ» The gathering of a large quantity of something in one place (m. l.) «جَمَّ الْبِئْر» meaning a well having abundant water. And «جَمَّ الْمِکْیَال» meaning to fill the measure to the brim (manjadd). Its usage occurs in both material and spiritual contexts.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَّ  تُحِبُّوۡنَ الۡمَالَ حُبًّا جَمًّا» (89/20)\nTranslation: And you love wealth with intense love.","The concentration of a large quantity of something in one place.","more","جم","89:20",1
2909,636,"M","مَرْکُوْم","«رَکَمَ» means placing one layer over another of the same thing. Then a third layer is placed over that, which is «علٰی ہٰذا القیاس». And when something accumulates in a large quantity or forms a heap, it is called «رُکَام» and «مَرْکُوْم». And «رَکَمَ السَّحَاب» means the clouds became thick (M. Q.), and «سَحَابٌ مَرْکُوم» means thick clouds.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ یَجۡعَلَ الۡخَبِیۡثَ بَعۡضَہٗ عَلٰی بَعۡضٍ فَیَرۡکُمَہٗ جَمِیۡعًا» (8/37)\nTranslation: Then Allah will heap those impure people upon one another.","to pile up layer upon layer","more","مرکوم","8:37-52:44",2
2910,636,"M","لُبَد","«لِبْد» and «لِبْدَةُ » mean compressed layers of hair or wool. A thick woolen cloth. And «مَالٌ لُبْدٌ» means abundant wealth. And «لَبَّدَ شَعْرُہٗ» means to fashion (something) into symbolic forms by adhering hair, etc., with gum or resin. And «لُبَدَ الشَّیء» means to be in the form of a symbol (namdah), i.e., to gather scattered material and compact it densely.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«یَقُوۡلُ  اَہۡلَکۡتُ مَالًا  لُّبَدًا» ( 90/6 )\nTranslation: Man says, I have wasted heaps of wealth.\nAnd when its relation is to those of sound intellect, its meaning will be: to crowd together so densely that there is no space left to spread out a mat.\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah is:\n«وَّ اَنَّہٗ  لَمَّا قَامَ عَبۡدُ اللّٰہِ یَدۡعُوۡہُ کَادُوۡا یَکُوۡنُوۡنَ عَلَیۡہِ  لِبَدًا» ( 72/19 )\nTranslation: And when the servant of Allah (Muhammad ﷺ) stood up in worship, the disbelievers crowded around him, eager to press upon him.\n\nNote: Namdah refers to the thick cloth made by compressing the wool, hair, or fleece of sheep and goats with soap or similar agents, forming a dense, thick woolen cloth, also used for caps.","The gathering of scattered parts of something into a pile.","more","لبد","72:19-90:6",2
2911,636,"M","رَغَدَ","«رَغَدَ» comes only for sustenance or food. Eating without distraction or obtaining sustenance without distraction. (m. l)\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُلَا مِنۡہَا رَغَدًا حَیۡثُ شِئۡتُمَا» (2/35)\nTranslation: (O Adam and Eve) Eat from wherever you wish, to your heart's content from the fruits of Paradise.","«رَغَدَ» is used exclusively for the abundance of food and sustenance.","more","رغد","2:35-2:58-16:112",3
2912,636,"M","غَدَقَ","«غَدَقَ» means to rain abundantly and as a blessing. For example, in the Quran it is: «وَّ اَنۡ لَّوِ اسۡتَقَامُوۡا عَلَی الطَّرِیۡقَۃِ لَاَسۡقَیۡنٰہُمۡ  مَّآءً   غَدَقًا» (72/16) Translation: If they had remained steadfast on the straight path, We would have given them abundant water to drink.","«غَدَقَ» for the abundance of water, while it is also beneficial.","More","غدق","72:16",1
2913,636,"M","ثَجَّاج","«ثَجَّ» meaning to rain and flow heavily (sing.), and «ثَجَّاج» meaning a stream of water (m. q.).\nFor example, in the Quran it is: «وَّ اَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ الۡمُعۡصِرٰتِ مَآءً  ثَجَّاجًا» (78/14)\nTranslation: And We sent down a torrential rain from the overflowing clouds.","«ثَجَّاج» is used in large quantities of water for rainfall and flow in Musalla Dhar.","More","ثجاج","78:14",1
2914,636,"M","مَوْفُوْر","«وَفَر» comes for the completion (fulfillment) and abundance of a thing (m. l.) and «وَفَّرَ» means to complete. To increase (manj). And «وَفَرَ جَزَاءُہٗ» means to give it its full, complete recompense and some extra as well (muf).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ اذۡہَبۡ فَمَنۡ تَبِعَکَ مِنۡہُمۡ فَاِنَّ جَہَنَّمَ  جَزَآؤُکُمۡ  جَزَآءً  مَّوۡفُوۡرًا» (17/63)\nTranslation: Allah the Most High said (to Iblis): Go! Whoever among them follows you, for all of you the punishment is Hell, and it is a full recompense.","«مَوْفُوْر» is used to indicate the completeness and abundance of something.","More","موفور","17:63",1
2915,637,"T","اَصْحَاب","«اَصْحَاب» is plural. It means one who accompanies or stays with for a long duration, whether that companionship is with a human, an animal, a place, or a time. Although this word is used in a spiritual sense etymologically, generally its usage pertains to physical companionship. Such as أصحابِ کہف, أصحابُ الرَّس, أصحابُ السَّبْت, أصحابُ الْفیل, أصحابُ الْقبور, أصحابُ السَّفینۃ, etc.","«اَصْحَاب» one who remains with or accompanies over an extended period.","The Owner","اصحاب","2:39-2:81-2:82-2:119-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:116-4:47-5:10-5:29-5:86-6:71-7:36-7:42-7:44-7:46-7:47-7:48-7:50-9:70-9:113-10:26-10:27-11:23-13:5-15:78-15:80-18:9-20:135-22:44-22:51-25:24-25:38-26:61-26:176-29:15-35:6-36:13-36:55-38:13-39:8-40:6-40:43-46:14-46:16-50:12-50:14-51:59-56:8-56:9-56:27-56:38-56:41-56:90-56:91-57:19-58:17-59:20-60:13-64:10-67:10-67:11-68:17-74:31-74:39-85:4-90:18-90:19-105:1",70
2916,637,"I","اٰل","«اٰل» The word is used only as an epithet for a renowned personage and nobles. For example, one can say 'Al Muhammad', 'Al Ibrahim', 'Al Imran', 'Al Firon', but one cannot say 'Al Khayyat' (Mufradat, Manjad). And 'Al' includes all those people who hold that noble personage in high esteem and are in mental consensus and unity with him. In other words, 'Al Muhammad' does not refer only to the family of the Prophet ﷺ; rather, it also includes those who have a special connection with him in terms of knowledge and insight. Similarly, 'Al Firon' refers to all his adherents and those who are ideologically aligned with him.","«اٰل» This attribution is directed only toward a distinguished figure and noble families, such as the family of Muhammad (peace be upon him), the family of Abraham, and the family of Imran.","Indeed","ال","2:49-2:50-2:248-3:11-3:33-4:54-7:130-7:141-8:52-8:54-12:6-14:6-15:59-15:61-19:6-27:56-28:8-34:13-40:28-40:45-40:46-54:34-54:41",23
2917,637,"G","اَھْل","«اَھْل» This can also be a possessive construct referring to non-rational entities, such as the people of the city «اَھْلُ الْاَرْض» (the landowners) «اَھْلُ الْقُرٰی» (the villagers) «اھلِ البیت ، اھلَ الکتاب ، اَھْلُ الذِّکْر» and «اَھْلُ النَّار», etc. However, when it is a possessive construct referring to rational beings, its meaning will be the household, wife, children, clan, or family. For example, «اَھْلُ الْخَیَّاط» means the tailor's household—the people of his family and clan, which includes his wife. (For further clarification on the distinction between «اَھْل» and «اٰل», see the entry for offspring «اَھْل».)","«اَھْل» denotes something related to a family or clan, and this relation can be directed toward anything.","Guardian","اھل","2:105-2:109-3:64-3:65-3:69-3:70-3:71-3:72-3:75-3:98-3:99-3:110-3:113-3:199-4:123-4:153-4:159-4:171-5:15-5:19-5:47-5:59-5:65-5:68-5:77-7:96-7:97-7:98-9:101-9:120-11:73-12:109-15:67-16:43-18:77-20:40-21:7-28:12-28:45-29:46-33:13-33:26-33:33-38:64-57:29-59:2-59:7-59:11-74:56-98:1-98:6",51
2918,637,"G","ذُو ، اُولُوا","The word «ذُو» serves as a means to describe the excellence and types of things. As a noun, it is always in the genitive case. It does not function as a pronoun. In the genitive state, «ذُو» is used; in the nominative state, «ذَا»; and in the accusative state, «ذِی». Examples include «ذُوۡ مِرَّۃٍ» (53:6), «ذَا عَذَابٍ» (23:77), and «ذِی الۡعَرۡشِ» (17:42). Its dual form is «ذَوُوْن» or «ذَوِیْن», as in «ذَوَیۡ عَدۡلٍ  مِّنۡکُمۡ» (65:2) ('two just ones among you'). The plural forms are «اُوْلُو» and «اُوْلِی», as seen in «اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَامِ» (8:75) and «اُولِیۡ  بَاۡسٍ  شَدِیۡدٍ» (17:5). The feminine of «ذُوْ» is «ذَاتَ», exemplified by «ذَاتَ الْیَمِیْنِ». Its dual is «ذَوَاتَان», as in «ذَوَاتَاۤ اَفۡنَانٍ» (55:48) ('both gardens with long branches'). The feminine plural is both «ذَوَات» and «اُوْلَاتِ», though only «اُوْلَاتِ» appears in the Quran, as in «اُولَاتُ الۡاَحۡمَالِ» (65:4) ('pregnant women').","«ذُو» and «اُولُوا» are used as a means to define the name.","Guardian","ذو ، اولوا","2:105-2:177-2:179-2:197-2:243-2:251-2:269-2:280-3:4-3:7-3:13-3:18-3:74-3:152-3:174-3:190-4:8-4:36-4:59-4:83-4:95-5:95-5:100-5:106-6:133-6:146-6:147-8:29-8:75-9:86-9:113-10:60-11:3-11:116-12:68-12:76-12:111-13:6-13:19-14:37-14:47-14:52-16:90-17:5-17:42-18:58-18:83-20:54-20:128-24:22-24:31-24:44-27:33-27:73-28:76-28:79-33:6-35:1-38:1-38:12-38:29-38:43-38:45-39:9-39:18-39:21-39:28-39:37-40:3-40:15-40:54-40:61-41:35-41:43-41:51-46:35-48:16-51:58-53:6-55:12-55:27-55:78-57:21-57:29-59:2-62:4-65:2-65:4-65:6-65:7-65:10-70:3-73:11-77:30-81:20-85:15-89:10-90:14",98
2919,638,"I","وَلَایَۃ","«اَلْوَلَاء» means inheritance obtained from a freed slave (m.f.). The Prophetic saying ﷺ is «فَإِنَّ الْوَلَاءَ لِمَنْ أَعْتَقَ» (Muslim), i.e., the inheritance of a slave belongs to the one who freed him. Thus, the original meaning of «وَلاء» is purely inheritance or estate. Among the Arabs, there were several customs of inheritance. For example: they considered only male offspring as heirs, who were capable of bearing arms after them. And if there were no male offspring, they would appoint a close male relative as guardian or heir, and their order was: after offspring, the father. If no father, then the brother, and if no brother, then the uncle, etc. Then among them, there was also the custom of «وَلَاء», which meant that one person would make a covenant with another that they would help each other and be heirs to one another.\n\nIslam made women entitled along with men and initially recognized the contract of clientage (wala). However, it based it on Islam and Hijrah (migration).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ ہَاجَرُوۡا وَ جٰہَدُوۡا بِاَمۡوَالِہِمۡ وَ اَنۡفُسِہِمۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰوَوۡا وَّ نَصَرُوۡۤا اُولٰٓئِکَ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اَوۡلِیَآءُ بَعۡضٍ ؕ وَ الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡا وَ لَمۡ یُہَاجِرُوۡا مَا لَکُمۡ مِّنۡ وَّلَایَتِہِمۡ مِّنۡ شَیۡءٍ حَتّٰی یُہَاجِرُوۡا» (8/72)\nTranslation: Indeed, those who have believed and emigrated and fought with their wealth and lives in the cause of Allah, and those who gave shelter and aided - they are allies of one another. And those who believed but did not emigrate - you have no alliance with them until they emigrate.\n\nAnd «مَوْلٰی» its plural is «مَوَالی», meaning heir.\nFor example: The Divine declaration is:\n«وَ لِکُلٍّ جَعَلۡنَا مَوَالِیَ  مِمَّا تَرَکَ الۡوَالِدٰنِ وَ الۡاَقۡرَبُوۡنَ» (44/33)\nTranslation: And those who inherit from their parents and near relatives - We have made heirs for each.\n\nThis ruling of heirship was actually a link in the chain of mutual brotherhood (mu'akhat). Then, when the condition of the Muhajirin (emigrants) somewhat stabilized, the chain of clientage was terminated forever, and only the dhawu al-arham (blood relatives) were made heirs. However, guidance was also given to treat friends kindly and give them something.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اُولُوا الۡاَرۡحَامِ بَعۡضُہُمۡ اَوۡلٰی بِبَعۡضٍ فِیۡ کِتٰبِ اللّٰہِ مِنَ الۡمُؤۡمِنِیۡنَ وَ الۡمُہٰجِرِیۡنَ  اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ تَفۡعَلُوۡۤا  اِلٰۤی  اَوۡلِیٰٓئِکُمۡ مَّعۡرُوۡفًا» (33/6)\nTranslation: The Prophet is closer to the believers than themselves, and his wives are their mothers. And those of blood relationship are closer to one another in the decree of Allah than the [other] believers and the emigrants, except that you may do kindness to your friends. That is inscribed in the Book.\n\nNote: (Aqd al-Wala: The former master used to receive a share in the inheritance of the freed slave, which Sharia has abolished).","Under the contract of wala', the share in inheritance was later terminated.","Inheritance","ولایۃ","8:72-18:44",2
2920,638,"I","وَِرَاثَۃ","«وِرَاثَۃ» are the Shariah contracts or divine commandments through which the property of a deceased person transfers to another's ownership. This heir's connection is not only with wealth and property but also with customs and traits.\n\nThe Prophetic saying is:\n«اَلْعُلَمَآءُ وَرَثَۃُ الْاَنْبِیَاءَ».\nTranslation: The scholars are the heirs of the prophets.\n\nSo here, «وَرَثَۃ» refers to heirs of knowledge and propagation, not of wealth and riches. And «وَرِثَ» means to become the heir of a deceased person. And «اَوْرَثَ» means to make someone an heir. And «وَرِثَۃ» and «تُرَاث» mean inheritance.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ وَرِثَ سُلَیۡمٰنُ دَاوٗدَ وَ» (27:16)\nTranslation: And Solomon succeeded David.\n\nSo here, inheritance includes wealth and property, caliphate, prophethood, customs, and traits—everything.","«وِرَاثَۃ» The share of close relatives in inheritance under a Shariah contract.","Inheritance","وراثۃ","4:11-4:12-7:43-7:128-7:137-7:169-19:63-26:59-26:85-27:16-33:27-35:32-39:74-40:53-42:14-43:72-44:28",17
2921,639,"T","وَقْت","«وَقْت» is a well-known term (TIME) «اَلْوَقْت» meaning «زَمَانٌ مَّعْلُوْمٌ» (sing. & pl.) «وَقْت». Its plural is «اَوْقَات». And in the words of Imam Raghib, it refers to the final limit of time appointed for a matter (i.e., a fixed term).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«قُلۡ اِنَّمَا عِلۡمُہَا عِنۡدَ رَبِّیۡ ۚ لَا یُجَلِّیۡہَا لِوَقۡتِہَاۤ اِلَّا ہُوَ» (7/187)\nTranslation: Say, The knowledge of the Hour is only with my Lord. He will reveal it at its appointed time.\n\nAnd «مِیْقَات» is a noun of time (ظرف زمانہ). It is used in both temporal and spatial contexts. Its plural is «مواقیت». In the following verse, *miqat* is used in the sense of a temporal noun (ظرف زمانہ).\n\nFor example: The Divine declaration states:\n«وَ وٰعَدۡنَا  مُوۡسٰی ثَلٰثِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً وَّ اَتۡمَمۡنٰہَا بِعَشۡرٍ فَتَمَّ  مِیۡقَاتُ رَبِّہٖۤ اَرۡبَعِیۡنَ  لَیۡلَۃً» (7/142)\nTranslation: And We made an appointment with Moses for thirty nights and completed them with ten, so the term [miqat] of his Lord was fulfilled in forty nights.\n\nAnd in the following verse, the word *miqat* is used in both temporal and spatial senses. That is, both the time and the place are specified.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ لَمَّا جَآءَ مُوۡسٰی لِمِیۡقَاتِنَا وَ کَلَّمَہٗ رَبُّہٗ» (7/143)\nTranslation: Then when Moses arrived at his appointed time [miqat] at the mount and his Lord spoke to him...","«وَقْت ، مِیْقَات» fixed time or place.","Time","وقت","4:103-7:187-15:38-38:81",4
2922,639,"T","حِیْن","«حِیْن» refers to an indefinite time, meaning whenever news arrives or something is obtained. It is an ambiguous temporal adverb. (Linguistically) its plural forms are «اَحْیَان» and «اَحْیَانًا», meaning at times or occasionally.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَکُمۡ فِی الۡاَرۡضِ مُسۡتَقَرٌّ  وَّ مَتَاعٌ اِلٰی  حِیۡنٍ» (2:36)\nTranslation: And for you on the earth is a place of settlement and provision for a time.\n\nBy adding «اِذْ» after «حِیْن», the form «حِیْنَئِدٍ» is constructed, which points to a specific time, meaning at that time.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ اَنۡتُمۡ  حِیۡنَئِذٍ  تَنۡظُرُوۡنَ» (56:84)\nTranslation: And you are at that time looking on.","«حِیْن» unspecified time.","Time","حین","2:36-2:177-5:101-5:106-7:24-10:98-11:5-12:35-14:25-16:6-16:80-21:39-21:111-23:25-23:54-24:58-25:42-26:218-28:15-30:17-30:18-36:44-37:148-37:174-37:178-38:3-38:88-39:42-39:58-51:43-52:48-56:84-76:1",33
2923,639,"T","اٰن","«اٰنی» or «نِی» means the time has arrived. It signifies that something has reached its utmost limit or point of maturity.\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَمۡ یَاۡنِ  لِلَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا  اَنۡ  تَخۡشَعَ قُلُوۡبُہُمۡ  لِذِکۡرِ اللّٰہِ» (57:16)\nTranslation: Has the time not yet come for the believers that their hearts should become humbled by the remembrance of Allah?\n\nAnd «اٰن» means the time has gathered. Its «اٰناء» means clocks. The definite article is always prefixed to this term. That is, «ال» means the present time or now.\nFor example: The sublime command of Allah states:\n«اَلۡئٰنَ  خَفَّفَ اللّٰہُ عَنۡکُمۡ وَ عَلِمَ اَنَّ فِیۡکُمۡ ضَعۡفًا»\nTranslation: Now Allah has lightened your burden and has known that there is weakness in you.","«اٰن» and «اَلْئٰن» and the present time.","Time","ان","2:71-2:187-3:113-4:18-8:66-10:51-10:91-12:51-20:130-39:9-57:16-72:9",12
2924,639,"T","اٰنِفًا","«اَنْف» meaning the highest part of everything and the origin, i.e., the place of beginning. «اَنْفُ الْجَبْل» meaning the peak of a mountain. And «اَنْفُ الْلِحْیَۃ» meaning the edge of a beard. And «اِسْتَانَفُ الشَّیء» means to grasp the beginning and origin of something and to start (مف). And «اِسْتَانَفُ الْاَمْر» means to start a task anew (منجد). And «اٰنِفَا» means just now. At the beginning of this matter or task. A little while ago (مف. منجد).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا لِلَّذِیۡنَ اُوۡتُوا الۡعِلۡمَ  مَاذَا  قَالَ  اٰنِفًا» (47:16)\nTranslation: They say to those who have been given knowledge (of the religion), Well then, did he (the Prophet) say this just now (at the beginning)?","«اٰنِفا» meaning right at the beginning of this matter or work, just a moment ago.","time","انفًا","47:16",1
2925,639,"T","اَجَل","«اَجِلَ» means to delay. And «اٰجِل» and «اٰجِلَہ» mean delayed. Yawm al-Akhirat (the appointed Hereafter) «اٰجِل» its opposite is «عَاجِل», meaning prompt, hasty. Both terms are well-known. They are generally used in the context of marriage regarding the payment of the mahr. «عَاجِل» means to be paid immediately in cash, and «اٰجل» means on credit. And «اَجَل» means period, time, death (appointed). As if the word «اَجَل» includes meanings from the present time to the promised or appointed term, and sometimes up to death. Its usage is very extensive.\n\nFor instance, in the Quran it is said: «وَ جَعَلَ لَہُمۡ اَجَلًا  لَّا رَیۡبَ فِیۡہِ» (17/99). Translation: And He has appointed for them a term about which there is no doubt.\n\nNow in this verse, the translation of «اَجَل» should be taken as 'time' or 'period' or 'appointed term' or 'time of death'—all fit correctly here.","The intervening period between the appointed time and the present time.","Time","اجل","2:231-2:232-2:234-2:235-2:282-4:77-6:2-6:60-6:128-7:34-7:135-7:185-10:11-10:49-11:3-11:104-13:2-13:38-14:10-14:44-15:5-16:61-17:99-20:129-22:5-22:33-23:43-28:28-28:29-29:5-29:53-30:8-31:29-35:13-35:45-39:5-39:42-40:67-42:14-46:3-63:10-63:11-65:2-65:4-71:4",45
2926,640,"H","یَد","«یَد» means hand. This word is originally «یَدَی». Due to the deficiency of the waw (ناقصِ واوی), «ی» has fallen (i.e., the form is altered). Its dual is «یَدَان» and «یَدَیْن», and its plural is «اَیْدِی».\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«فَوَیۡلٌ لَّہُمۡ  مِّمَّا کَتَبَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ وَیۡلٌ لَّہُمۡ مِّمَّا یَکۡسِبُوۡنَ» (2/79)\nTranslation: Woe to them for what their hands write! And woe to them for what they earn.\n\nAnd since the hand, among all human organs, is the most noble and excellent in terms of strength and action, therefore the word «یَد» also comes in the meanings of strength, control, and ownership.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«اِلَّاۤ  اَنۡ یَّعۡفُوۡنَ اَوۡ یَعۡفُوَا الَّذِیۡ بِیَدِہٖ عُقۡدَۃُ النِّکَاحِ» (2/237)\nTranslation: But if women, with mutual agreement, remit anything of their due (mahr) or if men, in whose hands the marriage tie is (i.e., the husbands), remit (their right), then there is no blame on them.\n\nAnd «بَیْنَ یَدَی» and «بَیْنَ اَیْدِی» come metaphorically in the meanings of before and ahead or present.\n\nFor example: The divine command states:\n«یٰۤاَیُّہَا الَّذِیۡنَ اٰمَنُوۡۤا اِذَا نَاجَیۡتُمُ الرَّسُوۡلَ  فَقَدِّمُوۡا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡ نَجۡوٰىکُمۡ صَدَقَۃً» (58/12)\nTranslation: O you who believe! When you consult the Messenger in private, spend something in charity before your private consultation. That is better for you and purer.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ جَعَلۡنَا مِنۡۢ بَیۡنِ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ سَدًّا وَّ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہِمۡ سَدًّا» (36/9)\nTranslation: And We have put a barrier in front of them and a barrier behind them, and We have covered them up, so that they cannot see.\n\nMoreover, at another instance, the divine command states:\n«فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ . فَجَعَلۡنٰہَا نَکَالًا لِّمَا بَیۡنَ یَدَیۡہَا وَ مَا خَلۡفَہَا» (2/65-66)\nTranslation: And We said to them, Be apes, despised and hated. And We made this story a lesson for those present and for those who came after them.\n\nNote: (ناقصِ واوی: (A grammatical rule) In Arabic, a word whose original radical letter is waw instead of lam).","«یَد» meaning hand, power, and control.","hand","ید","2:79-2:95-2:195-2:237-2:249-3:26-3:73-3:182-4:43-4:62-4:77-4:91-5:6-5:11-5:28-5:33-5:38-5:64-5:94-6:7-6:93-7:108-7:124-7:149-7:195-8:51-8:70-9:14-9:29-9:52-9:67-11:70-12:31-12:50-14:9-17:29-18:57-20:22-20:71-22:10-23:88-24:24-24:40-25:27-26:33-26:49-27:12-28:32-28:47-30:36-30:41-36:35-36:65-36:71-36:83-38:44-38:45-38:75-42:30-42:48-48:10-48:20-48:24-51:47-57:29-59:2-60:2-62:7-67:1-78:40-80:15-111:1",72
2927,640,"H","یَمِیْن","«یَمِیْن» has three meanings: (1) «یَمِیْن» means the right hand. (2) «یَمِیْن» means the right side, and its opposite is the left. (3) «یَمِیْن» means an oath.\n\nNow let us look at examples for each:\n\nFor right hand, an example is from the Quran:\n«وَ مَا تِلۡکَ بِیَمِیۡنِکَ  یٰمُوۡسٰی» (20:17)\nTranslation: O Moses, what is that in your right hand?\n\nFor right side, an example is from the Quran:\n«لَقَدۡ کَانَ لِسَبَاٍ  فِیۡ مَسۡکَنِہِمۡ اٰیَۃٌ ۚ جَنَّتٰنِ عَنۡ یَّمِیۡنٍ وَّ شِمَالٍ» (34:15)\nTranslation: There was for the people of Saba a sign in their dwelling place: two gardens—one on the right and one on the left.\n\nThen, just as «ید» comes in the meanings of strength and authority, «یَمِیْن» comes in even broader meanings. This is because, in terms of strength and function, the right hand is superior and better than the left. And milk yamin (ملک یمین) refers to that over which one has full control and authority. Figuratively, this word is also used to mean a female slave or a male slave.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَّ الۡمُحۡصَنٰتُ مِنَ النِّسَآءِ  اِلَّا مَا مَلَکَتۡ اَیۡمَانُکُمۡ» (4:24)\nTranslation: And [also prohibited are] married women, except those whom your right hands possess...\n\nMoreover, it was the custom of the Arabs to place or strike their right hand against the right hand of the person they were addressing to strengthen their covenant and oath. Therefore, this word began to be used in the meaning of an oath. And «یَمِیْن» refers to an oath that is sworn to make a covenant more firm.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«اَلَا تُقَاتِلُوۡنَ قَوۡمًا نَّکَثُوۡۤا اَیۡمَانَہُمۡ» (9:13)\nTranslation: Will you not fight a people who broke their oaths...","«یَمِیْن» denotes right hand. It is also used to signify complete possession/authority and for taking oaths.","Hand","یمین","16:48-17:71-18:17-18:18-20:17-20:69-29:48-33:50-33:52-34:15-37:28-37:93-39:67-50:17-56:27-56:38-56:90-56:91-69:19-69:45-70:37-74:39-84:7",23
2928,640,"H","شِمَال","«شِمال» means left side, left hand. And its opposite is «یَمِیْن». Then, just as «یُمْن» is used in the meanings of blessing and good fortune, similarly «شِمَال» is also used in the meanings of misfortune (Munjid), and its plural is «شَمَائِل».\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَاَمَّا مَنۡ اُوۡتِیَ کِتٰبَہٗ بِشِمَالِہٖ ۬ ۙ فَیَقُوۡلُ یٰلَیۡتَنِیۡ لَمۡ اُوۡتَ کِتٰبِیَہۡ» (69/25). Translation: And the person whose record (of deeds) is given in his left hand will say, Oh, I wish my record (of deeds) had not been given to me.\n\nAt another instance, the command of Allah the Most High is: «ثُمَّ لَاٰتِیَنَّہُمۡ مِّنۡۢ بَیۡنِ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ وَ مِنۡ خَلۡفِہِمۡ  وَ عَنۡ اَیۡمَانِہِمۡ وَ عَنۡ شَمَآئِلِہِمۡ» (7/17). Translation: (Iblis said) Then I will come to them from before them, from behind them, from their right, and from their left (meaning from every direction) (and I will block their path).","«شِمال» right hand. left side.","Hand","شمال","18:17-18:18-34:15-50:17-56:41-69:25-70:37",7
2929,640,"H","ذِرَاع","«ذِرَاع» means hand. It refers to the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger. And «ذَرَعَ الثَّوَبَ» means measuring cloth with «ذِرَاع». And «ذَرْعُہٗ کَذَا» means its length or measurement is the same. And «ذِرَاع» is a measuring unit whose length ranges from 50 centimeters to 70 centimeters (i.e., approximately 20 inches to 28 inches). The reason for this difference is that in earlier times, people's heights were longer, which gradually decreased. And some translators also translate «ذِرَاع» as gaz. For example, in the Holy Quran it says: «ثُمَّ  فِیۡ سِلۡسِلَۃٍ  ذَرۡعُہَا سَبۡعُوۡنَ  ذِرَاعًا  فَاسۡلُکُوۡہُ» (69:32). Translation: Then tie him in a chain whose length is seventy hands.","«ذِرَاع» the part from the elbow to the tip of the middle finger.","hand","ذراع","18:51-28:35",2
2930,641,"Y","نَعَمْ","«نَعَمْ» meaning yes. The word *ijab* (affirmative) is used when both the question and the answer are in a positive sense.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ جَآءَ السَّحَرَۃُ فِرۡعَوۡنَ قَالُوۡۤا اِنَّ لَنَا لَاَجۡرًا اِنۡ کُنَّا نَحۡنُ الۡغٰلِبِیۡنَ . قَالَ نَعَمۡ وَ اِنَّکُمۡ لَمِنَ الۡمُقَرَّبِیۡنَ» (7/114)\nTranslation: The magicians came to Pharaoh and said, Will we have a reward if we are the victors? Pharaoh said, Yes, and you will be made close (to me).","«نَعَمْ» means 'yes.' It is the affirmative response to a positive question.","Yes","نعم","7:44-7:114-26:42-37:18",4
2931,641,"Y","اِیْ","«اِیْ» means yes, yes. certainly. it is the word of affirmation. when the answer to a question is positive and given in an emphatic and firm manner, this word is used (muf) so that no room for doubt remains. and after it an oath becomes necessary (m. q.).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَسۡتَنۡۢبِئُوۡنَکَ اَحَقٌّ ہُوَ  ؕ ؔ قُلۡ اِیۡ  وَ رَبِّیۡۤ  اِنَّہٗ  لَحَقٌّ» (10/53)\nTranslation: They ask you whether that matter (the Resurrection) is true? Say: Yes, yes, by my Lord's oath, it is a reality.\n\nNote: (The word of affirmation is the word that is spoken in affirming something or in responding to someone's call and question.)","The word «اِیْ» is used when giving a positive response in a firm, resolute manner. For example: Yes, yes, certainly.","Yes","ای","10:53",1
2932,641,"Y","بَلٰی","«بلٰی» This is also an affirmative expression. It is used when a question is posed in the negative, and the response intends to refute that negation—that is, to deny it—while also providing an affirmative answer. Its meaning is Why not? Indeed, it is.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«اَلَسۡتُ بِرَبِّکُمۡ ؕ قَالُوۡا بَلٰی» (7:172)\nTranslation: (Allah the Most High asked) Am I not your Lord? They said, Why not! (Indeed, He is.)\n\nNote: (The word of affirmation is the term used when acknowledging something or in responding to someone's call and question.)","When the question is in the negative and the answer is intended to deny that negation while also providing a positive response, then this word is used.","Yes.","بلی","2:81-2:112-2:260-3:76-3:125-6:30-7:172-16:28-16:38-34:3-36:81-39:59-39:71-40:50-43:80-46:33-46:34-57:14-64:7-67:9-75:4-84:15",22
2933,642,"T","ضَبَحَ","«ضَبَحَ الْفَرَس» The sound emitted from a horse's chest while running at full gallop (i.e., the warhorses).\nFor example, in the Holy Quran:\n«وَالۡعٰدِیٰتِ ضَبۡحًا» (100/1)\nTranslation: By the swift-running horses that pant!","«ضَبَحَ» panting from running too fast.","to pant","ضبح","100:1",1
2934,642,"T","لَھَثَ","«لَھَثَ» Due to extreme thirst, to protrude the tongue from the mouth and emit sounds from the chest cavity (detailed). Due to thirst or fatigue, a dog panting and sticking out its tongue (Munjad).\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَمَثَلُہٗ  کَمَثَلِ الۡکَلۡبِ ۚ اِنۡ  تَحۡمِلۡ عَلَیۡہِ یَلۡہَثۡ اَوۡ تَتۡرُکۡہُ یَلۡہَثۡ» (7/176)\nTranslation: The example of that person is like a dog: if you burden it, it pants; and if you leave it, it pants.\n\nNote: (Jauf is defined as: the inner cavity, the space that is hollow toward the inside of something, the hollow interior part of anything, a hole.)","«لَھَثَ» is called panting due to thirst or fatigue.","to pant","لھث","7:176",1
2935,643,"T","دَفَعَ","«دَفَعَ» means to ward off and remove external dangers or attacks in order to protect and support something. (Ref. Mafatih, Manhaj)  \n«دِفَاع» means to protect and support something, and «مُدافعَت» means to retaliate or respond.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ لَوۡ لَا دَفۡعُ اللّٰہِ النَّاسَ بَعۡضَہُمۡ بِبَعۡضٍ» (22:40)  \nTranslation: And if Allah did not repel people from one another (by preventing aggression and attack)...  \n\nAnd when this word is followed by «اِلٰی», its meaning is to entrust something to someone, to hand it over, or to give it.  \nFor example: The Divine Command states:  \n«فَادۡفَعُوۡۤا اِلَیۡہِمۡ اَمۡوَالَہُمۡ» (4:6)  \nTranslation: So hand over their property to them.","«دَفَعَ» To ward off and push away external threats or attacks in the protection and support of something.","to remove","دفع","2:251-22:40-23:96-41:34",4
2936,643,"T","جَنَّبَ","«جَانِب» meaning side, direction, and «جَنَبَ» and «جَنَّبَ» meaning to repel, to remove, to save by turning aside, to strike on the side (manjada).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ سَیُجَنَّبُہَا  الۡاَتۡقَی الَّذِیۡ یُؤۡتِیۡ مَالَہٗ یَتَزَکّٰی» (92/17)\nTranslation: And the most pious one will be turned away from it—he who gives wealth to become pure.","«جَنَّبَ» means to push someone aside or to remove. It is a common term.","to remove","جنب","87:11-92:17",2
2937,643,"T","زَحْزَحَ","«اَلْزَحْزَح» means distant or far-removed, and «زَحْزَحَ». To remove someone from a place. To dismiss. To discharge (figurative). And «زَحْزَحَ عَنْ» means to save someone from harm or loss.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنۡ زُحۡزِحَ عَنِ النَّارِ وَ اُدۡخِلَ الۡجَنَّۃَ فَقَدۡ فَازَ» ( 3/185 )\nTranslation: And whoever is removed far from the Fire (of Hell) and is admitted to Paradise, he has indeed attained success.","to save someone from harm by removing them from a place","to remove","زحزح","2:96-3:185",2
2938,643,"T","دَرَءَ","«دَرَءَ» means to save someone from harm by completely pushing it away (to protect from injury or loss). It also means to forcefully push away, to remove.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ یَدۡرَؤُا  عَنۡہَا الۡعَذَابَ اَنۡ تَشۡہَدَ اَرۡبَعَ شَہٰدٰتٍۭ بِاللّٰہِ» (24/8)\nTranslation: And if the (accused) woman swears four times by Allah that he is lying, this will save her from punishment.\n\nAnd «اِدَّرَءَ» means to shift one's blame onto another, so that one may avoid punishment oneself.\n\nFor example: The Almighty says:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَتَلۡتُمۡ نَفۡسًا فَادّٰرَءۡتُمۡ فِیۡہَا» (2/72)\nTranslation: And when you had killed a person, and then you began to shift the blame onto another.","«دَرَءَ» to ward off harm with all one's might and effort.","to remove","درء","3:168-13:22-24:8-28:54",4
2939,643,"T","دَعَّ","«دَعَّ» means to push out forcefully; to repel firmly (footnote 188). For example, in the Noble Quran, it says: «فَذٰلِکَ الَّذِیۡ یَدُعُّ  الۡیَتِیۡمَ» (107:2). Translation: The one who shoves the orphan.","to shove someone out","To take away","دع","52:13-107:2",2
2940,643,"T","دَحَرَ","«دَحَرَ» two fundamental meanings are found: (1) to drive away, (2) to banish (e.g., meaning to drive someone away and expel them from there).\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ اخۡرُجۡ مِنۡہَا مَذۡءُوۡمًا مَّدۡحُوۡرًا» (7/18)\nTranslation: Allah Almighty said (to Iblis), Get out of this (Paradise). You are accursed!","«دَحَرَ» To expel someone by pushing or shoving, regardless of the reason.","to remove","دحر","7:18-17:18-17:39-37:9",4
2941,643,"T","خَسَأ","«خَسَّاَ النَّظَر» meaning the fatigue and weakening of sight. And «خسَأَ الْکَلْب» meaning to drive away a dog. And «خَاسِیءُ مِنَ الْکِلاَبِ وَ الْخَنَازِیْر» meaning driven away and chased dogs and pigs who are not permitted to come near people (manjad).  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«فَقُلۡنَا لَہُمۡ کُوۡنُوۡا قِرَدَۃً خٰسِئِیۡنَ» (2/65)  \nTranslation: So We said to them, Be apes, despised.","«خَسَأَ» To revile someone by considering them degraded and contemptible, out of hatred.","To remove","خسأ","2:65-7:166-23:108-67:4",4
2942,644,"G","اِھْتَدَی","«هُدَى» means to guide someone with kindness and grace, to show the path of goodness (figurative). Its opposite is «ضَلَّ» and «اَضَلَّ». It also means to lead someone astray or cause them to lose their way; to cause the path of goodness to be lost or obscured is «ھِدَایَت», and its opposite is «ضَلَالَت». The word «ھِدَایَت» has three meanings:\n\n(1) Innate guidance that Allah has placed in everything from creation. For example, a newborn baby's instinctive movement toward the mother's breast.\nFor instance, the Quran states:\n«رَبُّنَا الَّذِیۡۤ اَعۡطٰی کُلَّ شَیۡءٍ خَلۡقَہٗ  ثُمَّ  ہَدٰی» (20/50)\nTranslation: Our Lord is He who gave everything its form and then guided it.\n\n(2) Turning the human mind from misguidance toward guidance, from disbelief toward Islam, or from disobedience toward obedience to Allah. This may occur through the mediation of prophets, messengers, and other people, but the actual turning of the heart is solely in Allah's power.\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«اِنَّکَ لَا تَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ  اَحۡبَبۡتَ وَ لٰکِنَّ اللّٰہَ یَہۡدِیۡ مَنۡ یَّشَآءُ» (28/56)\nTranslation: O Muhammad! You cannot guide whom you love, but Allah guides whom He wills.\n\n(3) To show the straight path to those who turn to Allah's obedience or Islam, and to keep them walking upon it. This is primarily the responsibility of the prophets and messengers, after which other Muslims also participate in it (though this too occurs under Allah's will).\nFor instance, the divine declaration states:\n«اَفَاَنۡتَ تَہۡدِی الۡعُمۡیَ وَ لَوۡ کَانُوۡا لَا یُبۡصِرُوۡنَ» (10/43)\nTranslation: Can you guide the blind even if they do not see?\nAt another instance, the divine declaration states:\n«وَ اِنَّکَ لَتَہۡدِیۡۤ  اِلٰی صِرَاطٍ مُّسۡتَقِیۡمٍ» (42/52)\nTranslation: And indeed, you guide to the straight path.\n\nAnd «اِھْتَدَی» means to attain guidance, to walk the straight path.\nFor example, the divine declaration states:\n«فَمَنِ اہۡتَدٰی فَاِنَّمَا یَہۡتَدِیۡ لِنَفۡسِہٖ» (10/108)\nTranslation: So whoever is guided is only guided for himself.","«اِھْتَدَی» to be on the straight path.","Guidance","اھتدی","2:16-2:53-2:70-2:135-2:137-2:150-2:157-2:170-3:20-3:103-4:98-5:104-5:105-6:56-6:82-6:97-6:117-6:140-7:30-7:43-7:158-7:178-9:18-10:45-10:108-16:15-16:16-16:125-17:15-17:97-18:17-18:57-19:76-20:82-20:135-21:31-23:49-24:54-27:24-27:41-27:92-28:56-28:64-32:3-34:50-36:21-39:41-43:10-43:22-43:37-43:49-46:11-47:17-53:30-57:26-68:7",56
2943,644,"G","رَشَدَ","«رَشَدَ» means a person who comes upon the straight path and also adopts righteous conduct. And its opposite is «غوٰی», meaning misguided, one who follows the wrong path. (Q. M) And «رُشْد» means firm establishment on the path of truth; adherence. And its opposite is «غَیّ». (Munjid)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَلَـیۡسَ مِنۡکُمۡ  رَجُلٌ  رَّشِیۡدٌ» (11/78)\nTranslation: Is there not even a single man among you who is righteous? (Uthmani)","After choosing the straight path, adopt good habits and manners and remain steadfast on it.","Guidance","رشد","2:186-2:256-4:6-7:146-18:10-18:17-18:24-18:66-21:51-72:2-72:10-72:14-72:21",13
2944,645,"D","تَبّ","«تَبّ» means to perish, to break, to cut, to sever; it applies in all contexts (manjada).  \nFor example: In the Quran it says: «تَبَّتۡ یَدَاۤ  اَبِیۡ  لَہَبٍ وَّ  تَبَّ» (111/1) Translation: May the hands of Abu Lahab be broken, and may he himself be ruined.","«تَبّ» meaning to be destroyed.","damnation","تب","7:139-11:101-17:7-18:35-25:39-35:29-40:37-111:1",8
2945,645,"D","تَعْسَ","«تَعْسَ» meaning to stumble and fall, then not be able to rise again. To fall into a pit and perish.\nFor example, in the Quran it says:\n«وَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا  فَتَعۡسًا لَّہُمۡ» (47/8)\nTranslation: Destroyed are those who disbelieve.","«تَعْسَ» meaning to perish by falling into a pit.","destruction","تعس","47:8",1
2946,645,"P","قُتِلَ","«قَتَلَ» means to kill someone or to separate the soul from the body. And «قُتِل» means to be killed or to perish.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says:\n«فَقُتِلَ  کَیۡفَ قَدَّرَ ثُمَّ  قُتِلَ  کَیۡفَ قَدَّرَ» (20/74)\nTranslation: Perish the one who made a (false) estimate. Then perish the one who made a (false) estimate.","«قُتِلَ» meaning to beat/kill someone, to destroy/annihilate.","Perdition","قتل","3:144-3:154-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:168-3:169-3:195-17:33-22:58-33:61-47:4-51:10-74:19-74:20-80:17-81:9-85:4",18
2947,645,"P","ثَبَرَ","«ثَبَرَ» means to be destroyed or (of a wound) to be corrupted (figurative), and «ثُبُوْر» means destruction. For example: In the Holy Quran it is: «لَا تَدۡعُوا الۡیَوۡمَ ثُبُوۡرًا وَّاحِدًا وَّ ادۡعُوۡا ثُبُوۡرًا کَثِیۡرًا» (25/14) Translation: Do not call one destruction today. Call many destructions.","«ثَبَرَ» meaning destruction.","Perdition","ثبر","17:102-25:13-25:14-84:11",4
2948,645,"D","اَوْلٰی","The reward of «اَوْلٰی», if it comes from «ب», means more worthy, more appropriate, and more deserving. And if it comes from «ل», it means destruction, ruin, doom, and regret. This word is a threat and intimidation (i.e., to frighten and intimidate), and it is used for someone who has reached the brink of destruction so that he may be warned. Moreover, this word generally comes with repetition so that the addressee may reflect on the consequence and strive to avoid it (Mufradat).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«فَلَا  صَدَّقَ  وَ لَا صَلّٰی وَ  لٰکِنۡ  کَذَّبَ وَ تَوَلّٰی ثُمَّ  ذَہَبَ  اِلٰۤی  اَہۡلِہٖ یَتَمَطّٰی اَوۡلٰی لَکَ فَاَوۡلٰی» (75/31-34)\nTranslation: So he (the one who does not contemplate the Hereafter) neither believed in the Words of Allah nor performed prayer. But he denied and turned away. Then he went to his people, swaggering. Woe to you, and woe to you again.","«اَوْلٰی» meaning more worthy, more suitable, and more deserving.","destruction","اولی","47:20-75:34-75:35",3
2949,645,"P","وَیْلٌ","«وَیْلٌ» — destruction, ruin, regret, perdition. This word is generally uttered on occasions of regret (m.f.). For example, the Quran states: «وَیۡلٌ   لِّکُلِّ   اَفَّاکٍ  اَثِیۡمٍ» (45/7). Translation: There is destruction for every liar and sinner.","«وَیْلٌ» This sentence is typically uttered when expressing regret.","Perdition","ویل","2:79-5:31-11:72-14:2-18:49-19:37-20:61-21:14-21:18-21:46-21:97-25:28-28:80-36:52-37:20-38:27-39:22-41:6-43:65-45:7-46:17-51:60-52:11-68:31-77:15-77:19-77:24-77:28-77:34-77:37-77:40-77:45-77:47-77:49-83:1-83:10-104:1-107:4",38
2950,646,"P","ھَلَکَ","«ھَلَکَ» signifies perishing or annihilation. It applies to all things, both living and non-living. In the context of living beings, it denotes dying in a state of helplessness or meeting an evil death.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«کُلُّ  شَیۡءٍ ہَالِکٌ  اِلَّا وَجۡہَہٗ» (28/88)\nTranslation: Everything besides Allah is bound to perish.\n\nAt another instance, the Divine Command declares:\n«اِنِ امۡرُؤٌا ہَلَکَ لَیۡسَ لَہٗ  وَلَدٌ» (4/176)\nTranslation: If a person dies without leaving any heirs,\n\nAnd «اَھْلَکَ» means to utterly destroy or eliminate something else.\nFor example, the Divine Command declares:\n«اَلَمۡ یَرَوۡا کَمۡ اَہۡلَکۡنَا مِنۡ قَبۡلِہِمۡ مِّنۡ قَرۡنٍ» (6/6)\nTranslation: Do they not see how many communities We have eradicated before them?","«ھَلَکَ» Perdition, ruin—it is common to all, living and inanimate.","Perdition","ھلک","2:195-2:205-3:117-4:176-5:17-6:6-6:26-6:47-6:131-7:4-7:129-7:155-7:164-7:173-8:42-8:54-9:42-10:13-11:117-12:85-14:13-15:4-17:16-17:17-17:58-18:59-19:74-19:98-20:128-20:134-21:6-21:9-21:95-22:45-23:48-26:139-26:208-27:49-28:43-28:58-28:59-28:78-28:88-29:31-32:26-36:31-38:3-40:34-43:8-44:37-45:24-46:27-46:35-47:13-50:36-53:50-54:51-67:28-69:5-69:6-69:29-77:16-90:6",63
2951,646,"P","بَادَ","«اَلْبَیْدَاء» means a barren and level wasteland, and its plural is «بِیْد». And «بَادَ» means for a field to become a desert after being ruined, to be utterly destroyed and ruined (figurative).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ مَاۤ اَظُنُّ اَنۡ تَبِیۡدَ ہٰذِہٖۤ  اَبَدًا» (18/35)\nTranslation: He said, I never thought that this garden would ever become a ruin.\n\nNote: (لق و وق صحرا: harsh and level land where there are no trees, no greenery, no inhabitants; desolate, barren).","«بَادَ» meaning: for a cultivated field to turn into a desert after being destroyed, to be completely ruined and devastated.","Perdition","باد","18:35",1
2952,646,"P","تَرَدّٰی","«رَدٰی» means to cast something down from a height to the ground or to hurl it into a pit so that it meets destruction.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ اتَّبَعَ  ہَوٰىہُ  فَتَرۡدٰی» (20:16)  \nTranslation: But if he (the man) follows his own desires, then you would perish.  \n\nAnd «اَرْدٰی» is transitive. That is, to destroy another in the same manner.  \nFor example: The Divine Command states:  \n«قَالَ تَاللّٰہِ  اِنۡ کِدۡتَّ  لَتُرۡدِیۡنِ» (37:56)  \nTranslation: He will say, By Allah! You were about to destroy me.  \n\nAnd «تَرَدّٰی» means to fall into a well or a pit oneself and meet destruction.  \nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«وَ مَا یُغۡنِیۡ عَنۡہُ  مَا لُہٗۤ  اِذَا تَرَدّٰی» (92:11)  \nTranslation: And when he falls into the pit of Hell, his wealth will be of no use to him.","perishing by falling into a well or pit","Perdition","تردی","20:16-37:56-92:11-",3
2953,646,"P","بَخَعَ","To waste away from grief or anger; to consume oneself in sorrow or rage.\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«فَلَعَلَّکَ بَاخِعٌ نَّفۡسَکَ عَلٰۤی اٰثَارِہِمۡ  اِنۡ لَّمۡ  یُؤۡمِنُوۡا بِہٰذَا  الۡحَدِیۡثِ  اَسَفًا» (18:6)\nTranslation: So if they do not believe in this, will you then destroy yourself in grief over them?","to be consumed by grief","Perdition","بخع","18:6-26:3",2
2954,646,"P","دَمَّرَ","«دَمَرَ» means entering someone's home without permission with bad intentions (manjada) and «دَمَّرَ» means causing sudden destruction to something (muf). For example: In the Quran, it says: «فَفَسَقُوۡا فِیۡہَا فَحَقَّ عَلَیۡہَا الۡقَوۡلُ  فَدَمَّرۡنٰہَا  تَدۡمِیۡرًا» (17/16). Translation: So when those people rebelled in that town, the decree of punishment became binding upon them. So We destroyed them, brick by brick.","«دَمَّرَ» Tit for tat. To crush/defeat someone.","Perdition","دمر","7:137-17:16-25:36-26:172-27:51-37:136-46:25-47:10",8
2955,646,"P","دَمْدَمَ","««دَمْدَمَ الشَیْء» means to stick something to the ground. And «دَمْدَمَ اللہُ عَلَیْھِم» means God destroyed them. He made them level (or flattened them).\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَدَمۡدَمَ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  رَبُّہُمۡ بِذَنۡۢبِہِمۡ  فَسَوّٰىہَا» (91/14)\nTranslation: So God sent a punishment upon them because of their sins and made them all level (by destroying them).","«دَمْدَمَ» to make someone bite the dust.","Perdition","دمدم","91:14",1
2956,646,"P","تَبَّب","The phrase «تَبَّ» is an imprecatory term. «تَبًّا لَکَ» means may destruction be upon you. Lexically, its meanings are to break, to cut, or to be destroyed. And in «تَبَّبَ», the verbal repetition is intended to convey semantic repetition, i.e., to step continuously toward ruin. (Ed.)\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَا زَادُوۡہُمۡ غَیۡرَ تَتۡبِیۡبٍ» (11/101)\nTranslation: And they (the false deities) did not add to them anything except continuous destruction.","«تَبَّبَ» gradually heading toward destruction.","Perdition","تبب","11:101",1
2957,646,"P","تَبَّرَ","«تَبَّرَّ» to utterly destroy, to smash to pieces, to annihilate completely. (figurative) And «تَبَار» meaning destruction, ruin.\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ کُلًّا ضَرَبۡنَا لَہُ  الۡاَمۡثَالَ ۫ وَ کُلًّا  تَبَّرۡنَا تَتۡبِیۡرًا» (25:39)\nTranslation: And We have presented for them all kinds of examples, and We have reduced them to complete ruin.","to utterly obliterate, erasing even the mark","Perdition","تبر","7:139-17:7-25:39",3
2958,646,"P","بَارَ","Its source is «بُوْر» and «بُوَار». Meaning: the excessive piling up of commercial goods and coming near to ruin. That is «کَسَدَ حَتّٰی فَسَدَ». Gradually moving towards destruction (detailed). Gradually, the original capital dwindling away and being utterly ruined.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اَنۡفَقُوۡا مِمَّا رَزَقۡنٰہُمۡ سِرًّا وَّ عَلَانِیَۃً  یَّرۡجُوۡنَ  تِجَارَۃً  لَّنۡ تَبُوۡرَ» (35/29)\nTranslation: And they spend from what We have provided them, both secretly and openly, and they hope for a trade (i.e., reward) that will never perish.","Ruination of commercial goods due to scarcity.","Perdition","بار","25:18-35:10-35:29-48:12-71:28",5
2959,646,"P","اَسْحَتَ","«سُحْت» meaning illicit earnings and bribery (interpretation)  \n«سَحَتَ» meaning illicit wealth earned. And  \n«اَسْحَتَتِ التِّجَارَۃ» meaning adulterated and illicit wealth mixing with trade capital. And  \n«اُسْحِتَ» meaning depletion of wealth. Ruin of wealth (interpretation). And  \n«اَسْحَتَ» meaning to uproot from the very foundation (interpretation). As if, due to «اَسْحَتَ» ruined condition and poverty (i.e., a degraded state and destitution), it will come to cause destruction.  \n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:  \n«لَا تَفۡتَرُوۡا عَلَی اللّٰہِ  کَذِبًا فَیُسۡحِتَکُمۡ  بِعَذَابٍ» (20/61)  \nTranslation: Do not fabricate lies against Allah, lest He destroy you with a punishment.","«اَسْحَتَ» To be ruined due to deplorable condition, poverty, and destitution.","Perdition","اسحت","20:61",1
2960,646,"P","اَوْبَقَ","«وَبَقَ» means to be destroyed. And «مَوْبِق» means a place of destruction; a prison; a thing that comes between two things (a barrier). Here is fire, there is a pit. For example, there is a Persian proverb: Neither can they go forward nor can they stay back. (Meaning: they can neither go nor remain.) And «اَوَبَقَ» means to arrive at a place where, ahead and behind, there is only destruction visible. And «اَوْبَقَ» means to cause someone to be destroyed in such a place.\n\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«وَ یَوۡمَ یَقُوۡلُ نَادُوۡا شُرَکَآءِیَ  الَّذِیۡنَ زَعَمۡتُمۡ فَدَعَوۡہُمۡ فَلَمۡ یَسۡتَجِیۡبُوۡا لَہُمۡ وَ جَعَلۡنَا بَیۡنَہُمۡ  مَّوۡبِقًا» (18/52)\nTranslation: And on the Day when Allah will say, Call upon My partners whom you claimed (as deities). They will call them, but they will not answer them, and We will place between them a barrier of destruction.","«اَوْبَق» a place of utter ruin, with fire on one side and a pit on the other.","Perdition","اوبق","18:52-42:34",2
2961,646,"P","قَصَمَ","«قَصَمَ» means to utterly destroy, to smash and break into pieces (as in total ruin).  \nFor example, in the Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ کَمۡ قَصَمۡنَا مِنۡ قَرۡیَۃٍ کَانَتۡ ظَالِمَۃً» (21/11)  \nTranslation: And We have destroyed many towns that were unjust.","«قَصَمَ» to twist and distort","Perdition","قصم","21:11",1
2962,646,"P","فَنٰی","«فَنٰی» means to lose one's existence, to have nothing remain, to pass into non-existence (detailed). It is more comprehensive than «ھلک». «ھلک» includes the corruption of something, slipping from one's grasp, dying a bad death—all are encompassed within it. Whereas «فنی» means to completely terminate the existence of something from the very beginning. And the opposite of «فَنٰی» is «بَقَا», meaning to remain.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«کُلُّ  مَنۡ  عَلَیۡہَا  فَانٍ» (55:26)\nTranslation: Everything on earth will perish.","Losing oneself is even more common than «فَنٰی», let alone «ھَلَکَ».","Perdition","فنی","55:26",1
2963,647,"L","خَفَّفَ","«خَفَّ» means lightness. Its opposite is «ثَقُلَ», meaning heaviness. Both are used in material and spiritual contexts. «خَفِیْف» means light in weight, and also swift in pace or pleasant/agreeable. Whereas «ثَقِیْل» means heavy in weight and also burdensome. «قَوۡلًا  ثَقِیۡلًا» (73/5) means burdensome to one's nature and a heavy load; a heavy responsibility.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ خَفَّتۡ مَوَازِیۡنُہٗ فَاُولٰٓئِکَ الَّذِیۡنَ خَسِرُوۡۤا اَنۡفُسَہُمۡ» (7/9)\nTranslation: And those whose scales are light—it is they who have lost their souls by wronging themselves.\n\nAnd «خَفَّفَ» means alleviation, i.e., to make less; to reduce a burden or responsibility; to lighten. This is also used in all contexts.\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَلَا یُخَفَّفُ عَنۡہُمُ الۡعَذَابُ وَ لَا ہُمۡ یُنۡصَرُوۡنَ» (2/86)\nTranslation: Neither will their punishment be lightened for them, nor will they be helped.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَخَفَّ» means to attempt to gradually diminish the value or status of something.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration is:\n«فَاسۡتَخَفَّ قَوۡمَہٗ  فَاَطَاعُوۡہُ» (43/54)\nTranslation: And Pharaoh persuaded his people, and they obeyed him. Indeed, they were a people defiantly disobedient [and thus] deluded.","«خَفَّف» meaning to ease by lessening a burden or responsibility.","Light","خفف","2:86-2:162-2:178-3:88-4:28-7:9-7:189-8:66-9:41-16:80-16:85-23:103-30:60-35:36-40:49-43:54-101:8",17
2964,647,"L","فَتَّرَ","«فَتَرَ» means a gradual decrease in the strength or pace of something. After strength comes weakness; after swiftness comes a gradual slowing down (figurative), and «فَتُور» means slowness or stagnation after speed. Softness after hardness, and becoming weak after strength (figurative), and «فَتَّرَ» means to gradually make a burden, pace, etc., lighter or less.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«ِیۡ عَذَابِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدُوۡنَ لَا یُفَتَّرُ عَنۡہُمۡ  وَ ہُمۡ فِیۡہِ مُبۡلِسُوۡنَ» ( 43/75 )\nTranslation: They will abide eternally in the punishment of Hell, which will not be lightened for them, and they will be in despair.","«فَتَّر» to gradually lighten or reduce a burden, behavior, etc.","Light","فتر","21:20-43:75",2
2965,647,"L","قَصَدَ","One meaning of «قَصَدَ» is also to adopt the middle path, thereby avoiding extremes and excesses. And «اِقْتِصَاد» refers to adopting the middle path in the use of wealth or other things.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اقۡصِدۡ فِیۡ  مَشۡیِکَ» ( 31/19 )\nTranslation: And adopt moderation in your gait.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«لَوۡ کَانَ عَرَضًا قَرِیۡبًا وَّ سَفَرًا قَاصِدًا لَّاتَّبَعُوۡکَ» ( 9/42 )\nTranslation: If the goods of the world were near at hand and the journey were of moderate length, they would have surely followed you.\n\nThus, here too the meaning of «قَاصِدًا» is of a moderate or necessary distance. That is, neither too far nor too near, but its translation is lightened to avoid comparison and excessive detail.","«قَصَدَ» meaning intermediate in type, moderate, difficult, lighter compared to difficult, and easy.","Light","قصد","9:42-16:9-31:19",3
2966,648,"T","حَرَّک","Meaning: to move, to shake. Its usage is general, regardless of the type of movement.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«لَا تُحَرِّکۡ بِہٖ لِسَانَکَ لِتَعۡجَلَ بِہٖ» (75/16)  \nTranslation: (O Muhammad ﷺ) Do not move your tongue hastily in order to memorize it.","To move, to shake, is commonly used.","to shake","حرک","75:16",1
2967,648,"T","ھَزَّ","«ھَزَّ» means to shake a tree in such a way that its fruit falls down (F 173). In Punjabi, there is a specific word for it: *jhonna* or *jhona marna* (to shake or strike).  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«وَ ہُزِّیۡۤ  اِلَیۡکِ بِجِذۡعِ النَّخۡلَۃِ» (19/25)  \nTranslation: And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards yourself.  \n\nAnd «اِھْتَزَّ» means something moving or shaking as if it has been given a jerk or is jerking.  \nFor example: The divine command states:  \n«فَلَمَّا رَاٰہَا تَہۡتَزُّ کَاَنَّہَا جَآنٌّ  وَّلّٰی مُدۡبِرًا» (28/31)  \nTranslation: When Moses saw it moving as if it were a snake, he turned back and fled.","«ھَزَّ» to jolt a large or heavy object.","to sway","ھز","19:25-27:10-28:31",3
2968,648,"T","ھَشَّ","«ھَشَّ» and «ھَزَّ» are both synonymous. The difference is only that «ھَشَّ» is used specifically for shaking something gentle or light. For example, «ھَشَّ الْوَرَق» means 'to shake leaves' (figurative), and «ھَشِیْش» means 'any soft thing'. A soft-natured man. «ھَشَّ» means 'to smile'. And «ھَشَّاش» refers to a man whose face lights up and becomes happy even on a minor matter (Figurative). 'Hashash Bashash' is a famous phrase.\n\nFor instance: In the Holy Quran it is stated:\n«قَالَ ہِیَ عَصَایَ ۚ اَتَوَکَّؤُا عَلَیۡہَا وَ اَہُشُّ بِہَا عَلٰی غَنَمِیۡ» (18 / 20)\nTranslation: Moses (peace be upon him) said, 'This is my staff; I lean on it and I shake down leaves from the trees with it for my sheep.'","«ھَشَّ» to give a quick, sharp shake to something light or soft.","to sway","ھش","20:18",1
2969,648,"T","لَوّٰی","«لَوَی الْحَبْل» meaning to twist a rope. And «لَوَیْتُ الْحَیَّۃُ» meaning to coil like a snake (to wind). And «لَوٰی لِسَانَہٗ» meaning to twist one's tongue while speaking in such a way that the meaning becomes distorted (equivocation). And «لَوّٰی» meaning to bend and twist something; to contort. It occurs in all these meanings. And «لَوّٰی رَأسَہٗ» meaning to move one's head in such a way as to show rejection of what is being said; to shake one's head in refusal.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اِذَا  قِیۡلَ لَہُمۡ  تَعَالَوۡا  یَسۡتَغۡفِرۡ لَکُمۡ رَسُوۡلُ  اللّٰہِ  لَوَّوۡا رُءُوۡسَہُمۡ» (63/5)\nTranslation: And when it is said to them, Come, let the Messenger of Allah ask forgiveness for you, they shake their heads.","to twist or jerk something","to bob","لوی","3:78-3:153-4:135-63:5",4
2970,648,"T","نَغَضَ","«نَغَضَ» meaning to tremble, to shake, to be restless; and «نَغَضَ رَأسَہٗ» meaning to shake one's head due to surprise, mockery, or astonishment, to nod (in disbelief); and «نَغْض» meaning one who nods/shakes his head while walking; and «اَلْاَنْغَاض» meaning to move one's head.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَسَیُنۡغِضُوۡنَ اِلَیۡکَ رُءُوۡسَہُمۡ وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡنَ مَتٰی ہُوَ ؕ  قُلۡ  عَسٰۤی  اَنۡ  یَّکُوۡنَ  قَرِیۡبًا» (17/51)\nTranslation: So they will shake their heads at you (in disbelief) and ask, When will that be? Say, Perhaps it will be soon.","«نَغَضَ» refers to shaking the head due to surprise, mockery, or blinking. This term is specifically used for the act of shaking the head.","to shake","نغض","17:51",1
2971,649,"H","قَرِیْن","«قُرُوْن» is the plural form of «قَرَن». And «قُرُوْن» also means 'time' (see details under 'زمانہ'). In this sense, «قَرِیْن» is taken to mean 'contemporary'. And «قَرَن» means a rope with which two camels are tied together. «قَرَنَ الثَّوْرَیْن» means to yoke two oxen in Punjabi. In this sense, «قَرِیْن» is taken to mean 'companion'—a partner who shares the same food and drink. And the plural of this « قُرَنَاء» is «قَرِیْن». Moreover, its usage is predominantly in a negative sense.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَ مَنۡ  یَّکُنِ  الشَّیۡطٰنُ  لَہٗ  قَرِیۡنًا فَسَآءَ  قَرِیۡنًا» (4/38)\nTranslation: And whoever has Satan as a companion—there is no doubt that he is an evil companion.","«قَرِیْن» a peer or close companion.","Harmony","قرین","4:38-37:51-43:36-43:38-50:23-50:27",6
2972,649,"H","اَتْرَاب","«تُرَاب» means dust, soil. And «تَرِبَ» also signifies being dust-covered as well as being needy and destitute. And «اَتْرَبَ» also means being wealthy as well as being healthy. And this (is from the lexicon of antonyms). (Munjid) And «تَارَبَ» means to play together in the mud, to be of the same age, to be friends. And the feminine form of «تَرِب» is «تَرِبَۃ». And its plural is «اَتْرَاب». And «صَدِیْقَہ» and a woman of the same age, co-womb, playmate. (M.Q.) The word «اَتْرَاب» frequently occurs for women. (Munjid) Thus, by 'Atrab' is meant such friends and women of the same age in whose natures there is complete harmony.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «فَجَعَلۡنٰہُنَّ  اَبۡکَارًا عُرُبًا  اَتۡرَابًا» (37/56) Translation: We have made those houris virgins, who will be intensely loving towards their husbands and of the same age as well.","«اَتْرَاب» peers or companions of the same age and disposition (or female companions).","Harmony","اتراب","38:52-56:37-78:33",3
2973,649,"H","سَمِیٌّ","«اِسْمٌ» means 'name' and «سَمِیٌّ» means 'homonym' (i.e., two or more persons having the same name).  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اسۡمُہٗ یَحۡیٰی ۙ لَمۡ  نَجۡعَلۡ  لَّہٗ  مِنۡ  قَبۡلُ  سَمِیًّا» (19/7)  \nTranslation: His name is Yahya. We have not assigned this name to anyone before him.","«سَمِیٌّ» meaning homonym.","Harmony","سمی","19:7-19:65",2
2974,649,"H","کُفْو","«کَفَأ ، کُفْو» and «کُفٰی» mean equal in rank and status. Barābar (from manjada) and «کِفَاءٌ» mean similar or counterpart. Jor (from mīm-qāf) means being the equal of another in rank and station. And «کُفْو» refers to that piece of cloth which, when joined with another similar piece, is thrown over the back of the tent. The word «فُلَانٌ کُفْوٌ لِفَلَانٍ» is generally uttered during marriage or kinship agreements or during battle. «فُلَانٌ کُفْوٌ لِفَلَانٍ», i.e., so-and-so is the counterpart or equal of so-and-so (muf).\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«وَ لَمۡ  یَکُنۡ  لَّہٗ   کُفُوًا  اَحَدٌ» (112:4)\nTranslation: And there is no counterpart to Him (Allah, the Most High).","Equal in status and rank.","Harmony","کفو","112:4",1
2975,649,"H","صَفَّ","«صَفّ» means to form a straight row. «صَفَّفَ» means to straighten and maintain a row (M. Q). «صَفّ» (masdar) means the straight row of everything; a class; a nation arranged in ranks (manjada).\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«وَّ جَآءَ رَبُّکَ وَ الۡمَلَکُ صَفًّا صَفًّا» (89:22)\nTranslation: And your Lord will come, and the angels will appear in ranks.\n\nThen, the state of harmony found in this rank is also applied in many other contexts. For example, «اَلصَّافَۃُ مِنَ الْاِبِلِ» means a camel that makes its feet move in a row. Its plural is «صافّات» and «صَوَّاف» is derived from it. And «صَافّ مِنَ الْاِبِل» means a camel with its legs placed in a single row. Similarly, «صَفَّ الطّیر» means birds have straightened their wings in flight like a row. And it also refers to birds spreading their wings in the air and holding them completely still, all in the same state.\n\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اَوَ لَمۡ  یَرَوۡا اِلَی الطَّیۡرِ فَوۡقَہُمۡ صٰٓفّٰتٍ وَّ یَقۡبِضۡنَ  ؔ ۘ  ؕ مَا یُمۡسِکُہُنَّ  اِلَّا الرَّحۡمٰنُ» (67:19)\nTranslation: Do they not see the birds above them, spreading their wings and then folding them? None holds them except the Most Merciful. Indeed, He is ever, of all things, Seeing.","«صَفّ» meaning to form a row; to form a straight line.","Harmony","صف","18:48-20:64-24:41-37:1-37:165-61:4-67:19-78:38-89:22",9
2976,649,"H","ضَاھٰی","«ضَاھَی الرَّجُل»: That is, for a person to resemble another or to be similar in habits and temperament. And «ضَھِیٌّ» means a similar person. (M. Q. Maf. Manjd)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«یُضَاہِئُوۡنَ  قَوۡلَ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا» (9/30)\n\nTranslation: The earlier disbelievers also used to say such things. (Jalandhari)","«ضَاھٰی» harmony in appearance or in customs and habits.","Harmony","ضاھی","9:30",1
2977,650,"C","فَشِلَ","«فَشِلَ» meaning to display cowardice and falter during battle and times of hardship (manjada), to lose courage, to give up, to show cowardice, to exhibit weakness and cowardice.  \nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is stated:  \n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا فَشِلۡتُمۡ وَ تَنَازَعۡتُمۡ فِی الۡاَمۡرِ» (3/152)  \nTranslation: to the extent that when you showed weakness and disputed among yourselves concerning the command.","«فَشِلَ» is used from the very beginning to denote losing heart and courage.","Courage","فشل","3:122-3:152-8:43-8:46",4
2978,650,"F","اِسْتَکَانَ","«اِسْتَکَانَ» means: after complete exertion, becoming weary and weak, ultimately losing heart; becoming helpless; showing contempt; becoming submissive; being crushed.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «فَمَا وَہَنُوۡا لِمَاۤ اَصَابَہُمۡ فِیۡ سَبِیۡلِ اللّٰہِ وَ مَا ضَعُفُوۡا وَ مَا اسۡتَکَانُوۡا» (3/146) Translation: So when calamities befell them in the way of Allah, they did not exhibit cowardice, nor did they display weakness, nor were they crushed by the disbelievers.","After giving it your all, «اِسْتَکَانَ» courage is wasted, so they say.","Fortitude","استکان","3:146-23:76",2
2979,651,"E","سَطَح","Two fundamental meanings are found for «سَطَحَ»: (1) to spread or lay out, and (2) then to level it. And «سَطَحَ الْبَیْت» means to level the roof of a house. And «مِسْطَحْ» means a tool or instrument for leveling. And «سَطَح» means the upper part of a roof's covering (the parapet). According to Imam Raghīb, «اَعْلَی الْبَیْتِ جُعِلَ سَوِیًّا» (مف).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran, it is stated:\n«وَ اِلَی الۡاَرۡضِ کَیۡفَ سُطِحَتۡ» (88/20)\nTranslation: And do they not look at the earth—how it is laid out?","«سَطَحَ» spreading and leveling.","Even-Tempered","سطح","88:20",1
2980,651,"T","دَکَّ","Two basic meanings of «دَکَّ»: (1) to cut, (2) then to level it. For example, in the Quran it is stated: «قَالَ ہٰذَا رَحۡمَۃٌ مِّنۡ رَّبِّیۡ ۚ فَاِذَا جَآءَ وَعۡدُ رَبِّیۡ جَعَلَہٗ دَکَّآءَ ۚ » (18/98). Translation: Dhul-Qarnayn said: This is a mercy from my Lord (that He granted me the ability to build such a wall). Then, when the time my Lord has promised arrives, He will level it (the wall) to the ground.","«دَکَّ» crush it into tiny fragments and level it completely flat.","the Straight Path","دک","7:143-18:98-89:21",3
2981,651,"E","مَرَّدَ","«مَرِدَ الْغُلَام» meaning to be beardless. And «مَرَّدَ الْغُصْن» meaning to prune the twig leaves. And «مَرَّدَ الْبَنَاء» meaning to make a building smooth and polished (as in the lexicon). For example: In the Quran, it is mentioned: «قَالَ  اِنَّہٗ  صَرۡحٌ مُّمَرَّدٌ مِّنۡ قَوَارِیۡرَ» (27/44). Translation: Solomon (peace be upon him) said, This is a palace made smooth due to the glass being embedded.","«مَرَّدَ» to smooth and polish.","Evenness","مرد","27:44",1
2982,652,"A","سَرْمَد","«سَرْمَد» meaning eternal. always (مف)  \n«سَرْمَدِیّ» meaning which has neither beginning nor end (منجد) always remaining in the same state of something and no change or alteration in it (فق ل 95)  \n\nFor example, the Quran states:  \n«قُلۡ اَرَءَیۡتُمۡ  اِنۡ جَعَلَ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡکُمُ الَّیۡلَ سَرۡمَدًا  اِلٰی یَوۡمِ الۡقِیٰمَۃِ مَنۡ اِلٰہٌ غَیۡرُ اللّٰہِ یَاۡتِیۡکُمۡ بِضِیَآءٍ» (28/71)  \nTranslation: Say, Consider if Allah were to make the night last over you until the Day of Resurrection, who else could provide you with light besides Him?","Remaining in a constant state without any change or variation.","Always","سرمد","28:71-28:72",2
2983,652,"A","اَبَدَ","«اَبَدًا» means prolonged duration. It is a continuous ongoing period (i.e.) a temporal particle used for emphasis in both negation and affirmation in the future tense. For example, in «اَفْعَلُہٗ اَبَدًا» it means I will certainly continue to do it, and in «لَا اَفْعَلُہٗ اَبَدًا» it means I will never do it (for emphasis). It is also used before «خَلَدَ» for additional emphasis. Its opposite is «زَل».\n\nFor example, the Quran states:\n«خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَبَدًا» (98/8)\nTranslation: They will abide therein forever.\n\nIn another instance, the divine command states:\n«وَ لَا یَتَمَنَّوۡنَہٗۤ  اَبَدًۢا  بِمَا قَدَّمَتۡ اَیۡدِیۡہِمۡ» (62/7)\nTranslation: The Jews, for the evil they have done, will never wish for death.","«اَبَدًا» is a temporal particle used for emphasis in future tense, both negative and affirmative.","Always","ابد","2:95-4:57-4:122-4:169-5:24-5:119-9:22-9:83-9:84-9:100-9:108-18:3-18:20-18:35-18:57-24:4-24:17-24:21-33:53-33:65-48:12-59:11-60:4-62:7-64:9-65:11-72:23-98:8",28
2984,652,"A","خَلَدَ","The word «خَلَدَ» does not come to mean forever in general, but rather for something to remain without any change or difference from its beginning for a long duration. This is because the word «خَلَدَ» comes for emphasis along with «اَبَد», and where only a long duration is intended, only «خَلَدَ» is used. The word «اَبَدَا» does not come with it.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«اِنَّ الَّذِیۡنَ کَفَرُوۡا مِنۡ اَہۡلِ الۡکِتٰبِ وَ الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ فِیۡ  نَارِ جَہَنَّمَ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَا» (98/6)\nTranslation: And those who disbelieved, namely the People of the Book and the polytheists, will be in the Hellfire; they will abide therein forever.\n\nAnd in the same Surah, where the reward of the believers is mentioned, it is stated:\nThe divine command says:\n«جَزَآؤُہُمۡ عِنۡدَ  رَبِّہِمۡ جَنّٰتُ عَدۡنٍ تَجۡرِیۡ مِنۡ تَحۡتِہَا الۡاَنۡہٰرُ خٰلِدِیۡنَ فِیۡہَاۤ  اَبَدًا» (98/8)\nTranslation: Their reward with their Lord is gardens beneath which rivers flow, wherein they will abide forever.\n\nAnd both «اَخْلَدَ» and «خَلَّدَ» are used in the meaning of remaining in a single state for a prolonged period or staying in one condition.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«یَحۡسَبُ اَنَّ مَالَہٗۤ  اَخۡلَدَہٗ» (104/3)\nTranslation: He thinks that his wealth will make him live forever.\n\nAt another place, the divine command says:\n«یَطُوۡفُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ  وِلۡدَانٌ   مُّخَلَّدُوۡنَ» (56/17)\nTranslation: Young men serving them, moving around them in a single state forever.","To remain in the same state without change or alteration for a long period.","Always","خلد","2:25-2:39-2:81-2:82-2:162-2:217-2:257-2:275-3:15-3:88-3:107-3:116-3:136-3:198-4:13-4:14-4:57-4:93-4:122-4:169-5:80-5:85-5:119-6:128-7:20-7:36-7:42-9:17-9:22-9:63-9:68-9:72-9:89-9:100-10:26-10:27-10:52-11:23-11:107-11:108-13:5-14:23-16:29-18:108-20:76-20:101-20:120-21:8-21:34-21:99-21:102-23:11-23:103-25:15-25:16-25:69-25:76-26:129-29:58-31:9-32:14-33:65-39:72-39:73-40:76-41:28-43:71-43:74-46:14-47:15-48:5-56:17-57:12-58:17-58:22-59:17-64:9-64:10-65:11-72:23-76:19-98:6-98:8-104:3",84
2985,652,"A","وَصَبَ","According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is merely the persistence of a thing in one state, i.e., perpetuity. (M. L.) And according to the expert in linguistic jurisprudence, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» (F. L. 48) means the intensity of pain. And according to the author of *al-Munjid*, «اَلْوَاصِب» means a vast desert stretching far and wide, and «وَصَبَ» means to be permanent and established. And «َدائِمُ الْمَرِیْض» means to be (as in *al-Munjid*).\n\nFor example, the Noble Quran states:\n«وَّ لَہُمۡ عَذَابٌ وَّاصِبٌ» (37:9)\nTranslation: And for them is everlasting punishment.\n\nHere, in the meaning of «واصِبٌ», all three concepts—perpetuity, «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع», and extension—are found. But later, this word abandoned the meaning of «شِدَّۃُ الْوَجْع» and began to be used only in the senses of intensity or strength, and in the senses of vastness and perpetuity.\n\nFor example, the Divine declaration states:\n«وَ لَہٗ  مَا فِی السَّمٰوٰتِ وَ الۡاَرۡضِ وَ لَہُ الدِّیۡنُ وَاصِبًا» (16:52)\nTranslation: And whatever is in the heavens and the earth is all His. And His dominion is everlasting.","«وَصَبَ» In it, vastness and strength are also found along with permanence (eternity).","Always","وصب","16:52-37:9",2
2986,652,"A","ظلّ","«ظَلَّ» meaning to remain forever. «ظَلَّ الْیَوْم». To be shady during the day. To remain in shade all day. «ظَلَلُ» meaning the water that remains under the shade of trees forever. And «ظَلِيْلُ» meaning shady, always having shade. And «ظَلَّۃٌ» is the intensive form. The word 'iqamat' (manjada) «ظَلْتُ» (with one lam) and «ظَلِلْتُ» (with two lams) is originally used in relation to an action performed during the day. But sometimes it also comes to mean «صِرْتُ», i.e., to become or to remain (m.f.), and «ظلّ» meaning to do something all day or to remain in the same state all day (m.q.). Thus, in «ظَلّ», continuity is found for the entire day or for some period.\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ فَیَظۡلَلۡنَ رَوَاکِدَ عَلٰی ظَہۡرِہٖ» (42/33) Translation: If Allah wills, He can calm the wind and the ships remain standing on the surface of the sea (Jalandhari) then they remain calm all day (Osmani).","«ظَلَّ» to spend the entire day engaged in some work, or to remain in the same condition throughout the day.","Always","ظل","2:57-2:210-7:160-31:32-39:16-42:33",6
2987,652,"A","اِسْتَمَرَّ","«مَرَّ» means to pass, to go, to pass by something (mufradat, manjad). And «اِسْتَمَرَّ» means to remain in a particular state or manner; to persist, to continue (manjad).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ اِنۡ یَّرَوۡا اٰیَۃً  یُّعۡرِضُوۡا وَ یَقُوۡلُوۡا سِحۡرٌ مُّسۡتَمِرٌّ» (54:2)\nTranslation: And when they see a sign, they turn their faces away and say, This is just ancient magic. (Jalandhari)\nIt is magic that has been handed down from old. (Usmani)","«اِسْتَمَرَّ» to remain in a state or on a path from the beginning.","Always","استمر","54:2-54:19",2
2988,652,"A","دَامَ","«دَوَام» means stillness, and «مَاءَ الدَّائِم» means standing (stagnant) water that has no movement. And «دَامَ الشَّیء» means the state of something remaining in one condition for a long duration without change (i.e., permanence), and دوام means perpetuity. This verb is often conditioned upon another state. That is, as long as this state continues, that state will also remain. At that point, the particle «مَا» enters (is used), and «مَا دَامَ» means as long as.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«قَالُوۡا یٰمُوۡسٰۤی اِنَّا لَنۡ  نَّدۡخُلَہَاۤ  اَبَدًا مَّا دَامُوۡا فِیۡہَا» (5/24)\n\nTranslation: The Israelites said, O Moses! We will never enter as long as they are present there.","«دَامَ» to remain forever, to be established and firm, to be enduring.","Always","دام","5:24-13:35-70:23",3
2989,652,"E","زَالَ","«زَالَ» means to vanish or to move away. And \"Zawaal\" means to decline or set. This word, when combined with the negative particles «لَا» and «مَا», gives the meaning of eternity or continuousness, and in these meanings, it is always used with «لَا» or «مَا» (Muffradat). It is used to denote temporal duration.\n\nFor example: It is stated in the Holy Quran:\n«وَ لَا تَزَالُ تَطَّلِعُ عَلٰی خَآئِنَۃٍ مِّنۡہُمۡ اِلَّا قَلِیۡلًا مِّنۡہُمۡ» (5/13)\nTranslation: And you will not cease to discover treachery from them, except for a few of them.\n\nAt another place, Allah the Almighty states:\n«فَمَا زَالَتۡ تِّلۡکَ دَعۡوٰىہُمۡ حَتّٰی جَعَلۡنٰہُمۡ حَصِیۡدًا خٰمِدِیۡنَ» (21/15)\nTranslation: So that cry of theirs did not cease until We made them like a harvested field, extinguished.","«زَالَ» means to vanish or move away, and \"Zawaal\" means to decline. This word, when used with negative particles «لَا» and «مَا», conveys the sense of eternity.","Eternal / Forever","زال","2:217-5:13-9:110-11:118-13:31-21:15-22:55",7
2990,652,"A","اَبْرَحَ","«بَرَحَ» is the opposite of «بَرَزَ». And «بَرَزَ» means to appear in an open field. And «بَرَحَ» means to withdraw from an open field (muf). Only the present tense form is used. With it, when the negation words «لَا» or «لَنْ» come, it is employed for spatial adverbs. And it is always conditional upon «حَتّٰی».\n\nFor example, in the Quran it is:\n«وَ اِذۡ قَالَ مُوۡسٰی لِفَتٰىہُ لَاۤ  اَبۡرَحُ حَتّٰۤی اَبۡلُغَ  مَجۡمَعَ الۡبَحۡرَیۡنِ» (18/60)\nTranslation: And when Moses pbuh said to his young companion, I will not withdraw until I reach the confluence of the two rivers.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n«قَالُوۡا لَنۡ نَّبۡرَحَ عَلَیۡہِ عٰکِفِیۡنَ حَتّٰی یَرۡجِعَ   اِلَیۡنَا مُوۡسٰی» (20/91)\nTranslation: The Children of Israel said to Aaron pbuh, We will remain seated in the same place until Moses pbuh returns to us.\n\nNote: (Present tense: A verb in which an action is found to be done or to occur in the present or future tense, such as: آئے [comes], جائے [goes], کرے [does], etc.)","«اَبْرَحَ» is used only with the jussive form «لَا» and negation «لَنْ», and is conditioned by «حَتّٰی» for an adverbial of place.","Always","ابرح","12:80-18:60-20:91",3
2991,652,"A","فَتَا","«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from doing something. When «لَا» and «مَا» Nafiyyah enter upon it, it conveys the meaning of continuously performing an action. They say «مَا فَتَاَ یَفْعَلُ ذٰلک»: he always kept doing that. Generally, it is conditional with «حَتّٰی». Only the past and present tenses are used (Manjada). It is employed for time adverbials. This word appears once in the Quran, but even there «لَا» is omitted, i.e., hidden (Jalaalin wa Jamaa' al-Bayaan). For example, in the Quran it is: «قَالُوۡا تَاللّٰہِ تَفۡتَؤُا تَذۡکُرُ  یُوۡسُفَ حَتّٰی تَکُوۡنَ حَرَضًا اَوۡ تَکُوۡنَ مِنَ الۡہٰلِکِیۡنَ» (12/85). Translation: The brothers of Yusuf began to say to their father, 'By Allah! You will keep remembering Yusuf (peace be upon him) in this way until you either become ill or die.'","«فَتَا» means to prevent someone from doing something, and when «لَا» and «مَا» (negative particles) are added to it, it means to continuously do something.","Always","فتا","12:85",1
2992,653,"T","ضَحِکَ","Laughing with an open mouth accompanied by sound, revealing the teeth (munajid).\nFor example: In the Holy Quran it is: «وَ امۡرَاَتُہٗ  قَآئِمَۃٌ  فَضَحِکَتۡ فَبَشَّرۡنٰہَا بِاِسۡحٰقَ» (11/71)\nTranslation: And the wife of Abraham (peace be upon him) was standing nearby. She laughed, so We gave her the glad tidings of Isaac (peace be upon him).","«ضَحِکَ» laughing aloud with an open mouth, causing the teeth to become visible.","to laugh","ضحک","9:82-11:71-23:110-43:47-53:43-53:60-83:29-83:34",8
2993,653,"T","تَبَسَّمَ","«بَسَمَ» and «تَبَسَّمَ» mean to smile (mansaj), to laugh a little without sound, from which signs of happiness become visible.\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«فَتَبَسَّمَ ضَاحِکًا مِّنۡ قَوۡلِہَا» (27:19)\nTranslation: Prophet Solomon (peace be upon him) smiled at that statement of the ant and then started laughing.","«تَبَسَّمَ» means to smile.","to laugh","تبسم","27:19",1
2994,654,"W","رِیْح","«رِیْح  ، رَوْح» is a well-known term for wind. According to Ibn al-Faris, its meaning is wind and to move (m. l.). However, it has been used in the Quran in a wider range of meanings. For example:\n\n(1) «رِیْح» meaning wind in the well-known sense, which moves (f. l. 172).\nFor instance, the divine declaration is:\n«اِنۡ یَّشَاۡ یُسۡکِنِ الرِّیۡحَ» (42/33)\nTranslation: If Allah wills, He can make the wind cease.\n\n(2) «رِیْح» meaning scent or fragrance.\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«اِنِّیۡ لَاَجِدُ رِیۡحَ یُوۡسُفَ» (12/94)\nTranslation: Indeed, I find the scent of Yusuf (Joseph) [here].\n\n(3) «رِیْح» meaning awe and terror.\nFor instance, the divine declaration is:\n«وَ لَا  تَنَازَعُوۡا فَتَفۡشَلُوۡا  وَ تَذۡہَبَ رِیۡحُکُمۡ» (8/46)\nTranslation: And do not dispute, lest you lose courage and your wind [i.e., morale] becomes disordered.\n\nAnd the plural of «رِیْح» is «رِیَاح». When «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیَاح» is mentioned, it refers to winds of mercy there. And if «اِرْسَالُ الرِّیْح» is mentioned—i.e., the singular form is used—then it refers to a punishing wind (muf). It is categorized differently accordingly.","«رِیْح» means wind.","Wind","ریح","3:117-8:46-10:22-12:94-14:18-17:69-21:81-22:31-30:51-33:9-34:12-38:36-41:16-42:33-46:24-51:41-54:19-69:6",18
2995,654,"W","رَوْح","«رَوْح» means gentle breeze, mercy, happiness, comfort, and help, and «یَوْمٌ رَوْحٌ» means joyful day (victory). According to Imam Raghb, «رُوْح» and «رَوْح» are essentially the same. «رُوْح» is applied to breathing, and «اَرَاحَ الْاِنْسَان» means the act of a person breathing. It also signifies attaining comfort (in detail). By contemplating the various meanings of «رُوْح», it becomes evident that its meaning is the continuous, ever-flowing wave of Allah's favors and bounties, which becomes a source of comfort and ease for humanity. For example: In the Quran, it is stated: «لَا تَایۡئَسُوۡا مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ ؕ اِنَّہٗ  لَا یَایۡئَسُ مِنۡ رَّوۡحِ اللّٰہِ  اِلَّا الۡقَوۡمُ  الۡکٰفِرُوۡنَ» (12/87). Translation: Do not despair of Allah's mercy, for only disbelieving people despair of Allah's mercy.","«رَوْح» meaning mercy. The continuous flowing waves of Allah's favors and bounties.","Wind","روح","12:87-56:89",2
2996,654,"W","رَیْحَان","«رَیْحَان» means every fragrant plant, sustenance, livelihood (mankind), and «رَائِحَۃ» means a pleasant fragrance, while «رَیْحَانَۃ» means a bouquet of flowers (mankind). Reflecting upon these meanings reveals that if «رَیْحَان» refers to rizq (provision) or edible items obtained from agriculture, then it denotes things whose fragrance and scent are delightful.\n\nFor instance, the Noble Quran states:\n«فَرَوۡحٌ وَّ رَیۡحَانٌ  ۬ ۙ وَّ جَنَّتُ نَعِیۡمٍ» (56:89)\nTranslation: For him will be comfort and fragrant flowers and gardens of bliss.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah states:\n«وَ الۡحَبُّ ذُو الۡعَصۡفِ وَ الرَّیۡحَانُ» (55:12)\nTranslation: And corn having (spikes) with grain, and fragrant flowers (jalendhri).","«رَیْحَان» fragrant flowering plants.","Wind","ریحان","55:12-56:89",2
2997,654,"W","مُبَشِّرَات","«مُبَشِّرَات» Winds that bring glad tidings of the descent of mercy or the rain of mercy. The moist and pleasant wind that precedes the rain (F. L. 254).\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is: «وَ مِنۡ اٰیٰتِہٖۤ  اَنۡ یُّرۡسِلَ الرِّیَاحَ مُبَشِّرٰتٍ وَّ  لِیُذِیۡقَکُمۡ  مِّنۡ  رَّحۡمَتِہٖ» (30/46) Translation: And of His signs is that He sends the glad-tidings-bearing winds so that you may taste His mercy!","«مُبَشِّرَات» winds that bring glad tidings of rain.","Wind","مبشرات","30:46",1
2998,654,"W","لَوَاقِح","«لَوَاقِح» is plural; «لَاقِحَہ ،  لَقِحَ» means became burden-bearing. This burden can be of two types: (1) the water burden that winds carry before rainfall, and (2) the pollen (i.e., seeds, kernels, grains, or sperm) of male trees, which they go and deposit on female trees. In the Quran, this word is used only in the first meaning. For example, in the Holy Quran it is: «وَ اَرۡسَلۡنَا الرِّیٰحَ لَوَاقِحَ فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا مِنَ السَّمَآءِ مَآءً» (15/22). Translation: We sent forth the burden-bearing winds, then caused rain to descend from the sky.","«لَوَاقِح» heavy-laden clouds, which are the clouds that carry the weight of water before it rains.","Wind","لواقح","15:22",1
2999,654,"D","عَاصِف","«عَصْف» means bhusi (dry, brittle vegetation that crumbles into fragments). «عَاصِفَۃ» refers to the violent wind or storm that carries away bhusi or similar lightweight debris.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«حَتّٰۤی اِذَا کُنۡتُمۡ فِی الۡفُلۡکِ ۚ وَ  جَرَیۡنَ بِہِمۡ بِرِیۡحٍ طَیِّبَۃٍ وَّ فَرِحُوۡا بِہَا جَآءَتۡہَا رِیۡحٌ عَاصِفٌ وَّ جَآءَہُمُ الۡمَوۡجُ مِنۡ کُلِّ مَکَانٍ وَّ ظَنُّوۡۤا اَنَّہُمۡ اُحِیۡطَ بِہِمۡ» (10/22)\nTranslation: Until, when you are aboard ships and they sail with them with a favorable wind, and they rejoice therein—a violent wind comes upon them from every direction, and they think that they are surrounded; then they supplicate Allah, sincere to Him in religion...","«عَاصِف» dust storm.","Divine wind","عاصف","10:22-14:18-21:81-77:2",4
3000,654,"W","حَاصِبٌ","«حَصَب» means a wind that carries stones and pebbles, and «حاصِبَۃ» refers to such a fierce wind that whirls stones and pebbles along (F L 253). And «اَحْصَبَ الْفَرْس» means a horse galloping so fast that stones fly from its hooves into the air (M. Q).\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«اَفَاَمِنۡتُمۡ اَنۡ یَّخۡسِفَ بِکُمۡ جَانِبَ الۡبَرِّ اَوۡ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ حَاصِبًا» (17/68)\nTranslation: So have you become secure that He will not cause you to be swallowed up by the earth when you are on land, or send upon you a storm of stones?","«حَاصِبٌ» a storm that hurls stones and pebbles.","Wind","حاصب","17:68-29:40-54:34-67:17",4
3001,654,"W","قَاصِف","«قَصَفَ» means to break and shatter (m. l.) and «قَاصِف» is that fierce and violent wind which breaks trees, etc. (m.) a storm. A thunderous wind.\n\nFor example, in the Quran it says: «فَیُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡکُمۡ قَاصِفًا مِّنَ الرِّیۡحِ فَیُغۡرِقَکُمۡ بِمَا کَفَرۡتُمۡ» (17/69). Translation: Then We sent upon you a fierce and violent wind because of your disbelief, which would destroy you.","«قَاصِف» the tree-breaking windstorm.","Wind","قاصف","17:69",1
3002,654,"W","سَمُوْم","«سَمُوْم» A fiercely hot wind that scorches bodies. (Fussilat 254)\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَمَنَّ اللّٰہُ عَلَیۡنَا وَ  وَقٰىنَا عَذَابَ السَّمُوۡمِ» (52/27)\nTranslation: Thus, Allah favored us and saved us from the punishment of the wind.","Lo! A scorching wind is blowing.","Wind","سموم","15:27-52:27-56:42",3
3003,654,"W","اِعْصَار","«اِعْصَار» A fierce, whirling wind that spins in the atmosphere (m.f.) and, meaning dust and debris, such a violent wind that heads straight for the sky (f.l. 253). A bagola (cyclonic windstorm).\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«فَاَصَابَہَاۤ اِعۡصَارٌ فِیۡہِ نَارٌ فَاحۡتَرَقَتۡ» (2/266)\nTranslation: Then a bagola, containing fire, reached that garden and turned it to ashes.","«اِعْصَار» a simoom. A dust-laden, fierce wind that blows straight toward the sky.","Wind","اعصار","2:266",1
3004,654,"W","حُسْبَان","«حَسَبَ» means to calculate, to count, to enumerate. And «حُسْبَان» means a punishment that is sufficient for the settlement of accounts. The meaning of «حُسْبَان» has been defined differently by various lexicographers. However, it pertains to the punishment of Hellfire.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ یُرۡسِلَ عَلَیۡہَا حُسۡبَانًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ  فَتُصۡبِحَ  صَعِیۡدًا  زَلَقًا» (18/40)\nTranslation: And Allah may send down upon your garden a calamity from the sky, and it becomes a smooth, empty plain.","«حُسْبَان» a wind-borne punishment that is sufficient to settle the account.","wind","حسبان","6:96-18:40-55:5",3
3005,654,"W","نَفْحَۃٌ","«نَفْحَۃٌ» means a cold blast, as when air emerges from a bellows in a single burst. Puff. Blast. The intense licking of cold wind and its opposite, «لَفْحَۃٌ», means the licking of hot breath. (F L 29)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«وَ لَئِنۡ مَّسَّتۡہُمۡ نَفۡحَۃٌ مِّنۡ عَذَابِ رَبِّکَ» (21/46)\nTranslation: If even a single puff of your Lord's punishment should reach them.\n\nNote: (Bellows: a leather bag or metal tube, etc., into which air is pumped and then released with force to stoke a fire).","«نَفْحَۃٌ» denoting a cold gust, just one wave of intensely cold wind.","Wind","نفحۃ","21:46",1
3006,654,"W","صَرْصَرْ","«صَرْصَر» A severely cold wind. A fierce and howling cold wind. A wind that brings a chill. (F. L 47, 254)\nFor example: The Quran states:\n«اِنَّاۤ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمۡ رِیۡحًا صَرۡصَرًا فِیۡ یَوۡمِ  نَحۡسٍ  مُّسۡتَمِرٍّ» (54/19)\nTranslation: We sent upon them a chilling wind on an ominous day.","The cool breeze of silence.","Wind","صرصر","41:16-54:19-69:6",3
3007,654,"W","رِیْحُ العَقِیْم","«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» meaning a wind that neither brings rain nor clouds nor is it for seeding, i.e., planting seeds (f l 254). A wind devoid of goodness, which causes harm. And its opposite is «لَا قِحَہ».\n\nFor example: In the Quran it says: «وَ فِیۡ عَادٍ  اِذۡ  اَرۡسَلۡنَا عَلَیۡہِمُ  الرِّیۡحَ الۡعَقِیۡمَ» (51/41). Translation: And in the people of 'Ad there is also a sign when We sent upon them a barren wind.","«رِیْحُ العَقِیْم» a wind that is devoid of goodness and in which there is nothing but harm.","Wind","ریح العقیم","51:41",1
3008,655,"T","کَانَ","«کَانَ» denotes past and present tenses, such as: is, became, and was. And its imperfect form is «یَکُون», which conveys both present and future meanings. According to Ibn al-Faris, the meaning of «کَانَ» is «اَخْبَار عَنِ الْحَدُوْثُ الشَّیء», i.e., to announce the existence of something new.\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«اِلَّاۤ اِبۡلِیۡسَ ؕ اَبٰی وَ اسۡتَکۡبَرَ ٭۫ وَ کَانَ مِنَ الۡکٰفِرِیۡنَ» (2/34)\nTranslation: But Iblis did not obey the command of Allah and became one of the disbelievers.\n\nAt another instance, the Almighty states:\n«وَ یَخَافُوۡنَ یَوۡمًا کَانَ شَرُّہٗ  مُسۡتَطِیۡرًا» (76/7)\nTranslation: And they fear the Day whose evil will be spreading.\n\nFurthermore, «کَانَ» also occurs in the form of an incomplete verb. When it enters the past tense, it changes it to the distant past (i.e., the meaning of 'distant past'). «کَانَ ذَھَبَ» means 'he had gone', and when it enters the imperfect, it changes it to the continuous past tense.\n\nFor example: The Almighty states:\n«فَاَنۡزَلۡنَا عَلَی الَّذِیۡنَ ظَلَمُوۡا رِجۡزًا مِّنَ السَّمَآءِ بِمَا کَانُوۡا یَفۡسُقُوۡنَ» (2/59)\nTranslation: So We sent down punishment upon those wrongdoers because they used to disobey.\n\nNote: (Continuous Past: It is the verb that indicates the repetition or continuity of an action, such as: he used to come).","«کَانَ» denotes the meaning of past and present, as in: ہے (is), ہو گیا (became/happened), and تھا (was).","to be","کان","2:10-2:16-2:34-2:36-2:57-2:59-2:61-2:75-2:89-2:94-2:97-2:98-2:102-2:103-2:111-2:113-2:114-2:134-2:135-2:140-2:141-2:142-2:143-2:170-2:184-2:185-2:196-2:213-2:232-2:280-2:282-3:13-3:24-3:67-3:79-3:93-3:95-3:97-3:110-3:112-3:137-3:145-3:147-3:154-3:156-3:161-3:164-3:179-4:1-4:2-4:6-4:11-4:12-4:16-4:17-4:22-4:23-4:24-4:29-4:30-4:32-4:33-4:34-4:35-4:36-4:39-4:43-4:46-4:47-4:56-4:58-4:66-4:76-4:82-4:85-4:86-4:92-4:94-4:96-4:99-4:100-4:101-4:102-4:103-4:104-4:106-4:107-4:108-4:111-4:113-4:126-4:127-4:128-4:129-4:130-4:131-4:133-4:134-4:135-4:141-4:147-4:148-4:149-4:152-4:158-4:165-4:169-4:170-4:176-5:14-5:44-5:61-5:62-5:63-5:75-5:78-5:79-5:81-5:104-5:106-6:4-6:5-6:10-6:11-6:24-6:28-6:35-6:43-6:49-6:70-6:88-6:108-6:111-6:120-6:122-6:124-6:127-6:129-6:130-6:136-6:138-6:140-6:152-6:157-6:159-6:161-7:5-7:9-7:37-7:39-7:51-7:53-7:64-7:70-7:72-7:82-7:83-7:84-7:86-7:87-7:92-7:96-7:101-7:103-7:118-7:133-7:136-7:137-7:139-7:146-7:147-7:148-7:157-7:160-7:162-7:163-7:165-7:175-7:177-7:180-8:32-8:33-8:34-8:35-8:42-8:44-8:54-8:67-9:9-9:17-9:24-9:42-9:62-9:66-9:69-9:70-9:77-9:81-9:82-9:95-9:113-9:114-9:115-9:120-9:121-9:122-10:2-10:4-10:8-10:12-10:13-10:19-10:30-10:37-10:39-10:42-10:43-10:45-10:63-10:70-10:71-10:73-10:74-10:75-10:93-10:98-10:100-11:7-11:8-11:15-11:16-11:17-11:20-11:21-11:34-11:36-11:42-11:43-11:78-11:116-11:117-12:7-12:20-12:26-12:27-12:38-12:57-12:68-12:69-12:76-12:109-12:111-13:32-13:38-14:10-14:11-14:22-14:46-15:2-15:8-15:11-15:63-15:78-15:81-15:82-15:84-15:93-16:33-16:34-16:36-16:39-16:41-16:87-16:88-16:96-16:97-16:112-16:118-16:120-16:123-16:124-17:3-17:5-17:11-17:18-17:19-17:20-17:25-17:27-17:30-17:31-17:32-17:33-17:34-17:36-17:38-17:42-17:44-17:53-17:57-17:58-17:66-17:67-17:72-17:78-17:81-17:83-17:87-17:88-17:95-17:96-17:100-17:108-18:9-18:28-18:34-18:43-18:45-18:50-18:54-18:79-18:80-18:82-18:98-18:101-18:107-18:109-18:110-19:5-19:8-19:13-19:21-19:28-19:29-19:35-19:41-19:44-19:47-19:51-19:54-19:55-19:56-19:61-19:63-19:64-19:71-19:75-20:129-21:8-21:11-21:22-21:30-21:41-21:47-21:63-21:73-21:74-21:77-21:90-21:99-22:15-22:44-23:46-23:48-23:66-23:91-23:109-24:7-24:9-24:24-24:51-24:62-25:6-25:15-25:16-25:18-25:20-25:26-25:29-25:40-25:54-25:55-25:65-25:67-25:70-26:5-26:6-26:8-26:40-26:63-26:67-26:86-26:103-26:112-26:121-26:139-26:158-26:174-26:189-26:190-26:199-26:206-26:207-27:12-27:14-27:20-27:43-27:48-27:51-27:53-27:56-27:60-27:69-27:82-28:4-28:6-28:8-28:32-28:40-28:59-28:63-28:64-28:68-28:75-28:76-28:81-28:84-29:5-29:7-29:13-29:24-29:29-29:31-29:32-29:33-29:34-29:38-29:39-29:40-29:41-29:64-30:9-30:10-30:13-30:32-30:35-30:42-30:47-30:49-30:55-31:21-32:5-32:17-32:18-32:19-32:24-32:25-33:1-33:2-33:5-33:6-33:9-33:15-33:19-33:20-33:21-33:24-33:35-33:27-33:30-33:34-33:36-33:37-33:38-33:40-33:43-33:50-33:51-33:52-33:53-33:54-33:55-33:59-33:69-33:72-33:73-34:14-34:15-34:21-34:33-34:40-34:41-34:43-34:45-34:54-35:10-35:18-35:26-35:41-35:44-35:45-36:29-36:30-36:46-36:53-36:65-36:70-37:22-37:30-37:35-37:51-37:73-37:116-37:141-37:143-37:167-38:69-38:74-39:8-39:26-39:35-39:43-39:46-39:48-39:50-40:5-40:21-40:22-40:63-40:78-40:82-40:83-41:15-41:17-41:18-41:20-41:25-41:27-41:28-41:48-41:52-42:20-42:46-42:51-43:7-43:25-43:40-43:54-43:69-43:76-43:81-44:27-44:29-44:31-44:37-45:14-45:17-45:25-45:33-46:6-46:10-46:11-46:14-46:16-46:18-46:26-46:28-47:10-47:14-47:21-48:4-48:5-48:7-48:11-48:14-48:15-48:19-48:21-48:24-48:26-49:5-50:27-50:37-51:16-51:17-51:35-51:45-51:46-52:34-53:9-53:52-54:14-54:16-54:18-54:21-54:30-54:31-55:37-56:6-56:24-56:45-56:46-56:47-56:88-56:90-56:92-58:7-58:15-58:22-59:9-59:17-60:4-60:6-62:2-63:2-64:6-65:2-65:9-66:10-66:12-67:18-68:14-68:33-68:41-68:43-69:27-69:33-70:4-70:44-71:10-72:4-72:6-72:15-73:14-73:18-74:16-75:38-76:5-76:7-76:15-76:17-76:22-76:30-77:39-78:17-78:19-78:20-78:21-78:27-83:14-83:29-83:36-84:13-84:15-90:17-96:11-110:3",657
3009,655,"T","اَصْبَحَ","«اَصْبَح» means 'it became' (used to indicate a change from one state to another or one attribute to another) (ref: M. Q.). «اَصْبَحَ الْحَقُّ» means 'the truth became manifest' (Munjid). For example: In the Quran, it says: «وَ اَصۡبَحَ فُؤَادُ  اُمِّ مُوۡسٰی فٰرِغًا» (28/10). Translation: The heart of Musa's (AS) mother became restless (deprived of patience).","«اَصْبَح» is used for changing from one state to another or from one attribute to another.","to be","اصبح","3:103-5:30-5:31-5:53-5:102-7:78-7:91-11:67-11:94-18:42-18:45-26:157-28:10-28:18-28:82-29:37-41:23-46:25-61:14-67:30-68:20",21
3010,655,"T","صَدَرَ","«صَدَرَ» signifies a transaction being executed, a ruling being issued or enacted. And its opposite is «وَرَدَ», which denotes the occurrence of annulment or reversal. And «صُدُوْر» refers to when a task is accomplished with goodness and excellence; then, after its completion, it is said upon return (detailed).\n\nFor example, in the Holy Quran it is stated: «یَوۡمَئِذٍ یَّصۡدُرُ  النَّاسُ اَشۡتَاتًا  ۬ ۙ لِّیُرَوۡا اَعۡمَالَہُمۡ» (99/6) Translation: On that day, people will come in groups so that their deeds may be shown to them.\n\nAt another instance, the sublime command of Allah is: «قَالَتَا لَا نَسۡقِیۡ حَتّٰی یُصۡدِرَ الرِّعَآءُ» (28/23) Translation: Both of them said, We will not water (our sheep) until the other shepherds have taken (their sheep) and left.","«صَدَرَ» for a contract or agreement to come into effect. For an order to be issued and enforced.","to be","صدر","28:23-99:6",2
3011,655,"T","وَقَعَ","The basic meanings of «وَقَعَ» are two: (1) the establishment of something, (2) to fall down. And generally, the term refers to an incident characterized by severity and hardship.\n\nIn the Quran, this word has been used for punishment, detestable things, and hardships (مف).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n\n«سَاَلَ  سَآئِلٌۢ  بِعَذَابٍ  وَّاقِعٍ» (70/1)\n\nTranslation: A seeker demanded a punishment that would descend and remain.\n\nAt another instance, the divine command states:\n\n«وَ وَقَعَ الۡقَوۡلُ عَلَیۡہِمۡ بِمَا ظَلَمُوۡا» (27/85)\n\nTranslation: And due to their oppression, the promised punishment for them will be fully executed and remain.","«وَقَعَ» The occurrence of an unpleasant act.","to be","وقع","4:100-5:91-7:71-7:118-7:134-7:171-10:51-18:53-27:82-27:85-42:22-51:6-52:7-56:1-56:2-56:75-69:15-70:1-77:7",19
3012,656,"O","اَوْ","«اَوْ» is used to denote one of two or more things.  \nFor example: The Quran states:  \n«اَوۡ کَالَّذِیۡ مَرَّ عَلٰی قَرۡیَۃٍ» (2/259)  \nTranslation: Or like the person who passed by a town.","«اَوْ» is used to indicate one thing among two or more.","or","او","2:19-2:74-2:106-2:111-2:118-2:135-2:140-2:158-2:182-2:184-2:185-2:196-2:200-2:229-2:231-2:235-2:236-2:237-2:239-2:259-2:270-2:282-2:284-2:286-3:29-3:73-3:127-3:128-3:135-3:144-3:156-3:157-3:158-3:167-3:195-4:3-4:7-4:11-4:12-4:15-4:43-4:47-4:66-4:71-4:74-4:77-4:83-4:86-4:90-4:102-4:110-4:112-4:114-4:124-4:128-4:135-4:149-5:6-5:32-5:33-5:42-5:52-5:89-5:95-5:106-5:108-6:21-6:35-6:40-6:47-6:65-6:93-6:145-6:146-6:157-6:158-7:4-7:20-7:37-7:50-7:53-7:88-7:164-7:173-7:176-8:16-8:30-8:32-9:52-9:53-9:57-9:80-9:126-10:12-10:15-10:17-10:24-10:46-10:50-11:12-11:80-11:87-11:89-12:9-12:21-12:25-12:80-12:85-12:107-13:17-13:31-13:40-14:13-16:33-16:45-16:46-16:47-16:77-16:97-17:23-17:50-17:51-17:54-17:58-17:68-17:91-17:92-17:93-17:107-17:110-18:19-18:20-18:41-18:55-18:60-19:98-20:10-20:44-20:45-20:113-22:31-22:46-22:55-22:58-23:6-23:113-24:3-24:31-24:40-24:61-24:63-25:8-25:21-25:44-25:62-26:73-26:93-27:7-27:21-28:9-28:29-29:24-29:68-31:16-33:16-33:17-33:24-33:54-34:9-34:24-37:147-38:39-39:38-39:57-39:58-40:26-40:40-40:77-41:11-42:34-42:50-42:51-43:40-43:42-43:53-46:4-48:11-48:16-50:37-51:39-51:52-52:16-53:9-58:22-59-5-59:14-62:11-65:2-67:10-67:13-67:28-70:30-73:3-73:4-74:37-76:24-77:6-79:46-80:4-83:3-90:14-90:16",211
3013,656,"O","اَمْ","«اَمْ» is called a conjunction in Arabic grammar. It comes after an interrogative hamzah to convey the meaning of equality.\nFor example: In the Quran, it appears as:\n«ءَاَنۡتُمۡ اَشَدُّ خَلۡقًا  اَمِ  السَّمَآءُ» (79/27)\nTranslation: Which is harder to create: you or the sky?","In Arabic grammar, this «اَمْ» is termed a conjunction. The hamzah follows the interrogative, expressing equality.","O","ام","2:6-2:80-2:108-2:133-2:140-2:214-3:142-4:53-4:54-4:109-6:143-6:144-7:193-7:195-9:16-9:109-10:38-10:59-11:13-11:35-12:39-13:16-13:33-14:21-16:59-17:69-18:9-19:78-20:86-21:21-21:24-21:43-21:55-21:109-23:68-23:69-23:70-23:72-24:50-25:15-25:17-25:44-26:136-27:20-27:27-27:40-27:41-29:4-30:35-32:3-34:8-35:40-36:10-37:11-37:62-37:150-37:156-38:9-38:10-38:28-38:63-38:75-39:43-41:40-42:9-42:21-42:24-43:16-43:21-43:52-43:58-43:79-43:80-44:37-45:21-46:4-46:8-47:24-47:29-52:15-52:30-52:32-52:33-52:35-52:36-52:37-52:38-52:39-52:40-52:41-52:42-52:43-53:24-53:36-54:43-54:44-56:59-56:64-56:69-56:72-63:6-67:17-68:37-68:39-68:41-68:46-68:47-72:10-72:25-79:27",110
3014,656,"O","اِمَّا","«اِمَّا» Each of the two things comes to teach and comes with repetition. For example: In the Quran it is: «اِنَّا ہَدَیۡنٰہُ  السَّبِیۡلَ  اِمَّا شَاکِرًا وَّ اِمَّا کَفُوۡرًا» (76/3) Translation: We have shown man the path. Now either be grateful or ungrateful.","«اِمَّا» each of the two matters is mentioned to inform and is repeated.","or","اما","2:38-6:68-7:35-7:115-7:200-8:57-8:58-9:106-10:46-17:23-17:28-18:86-19:26-19:75-20:65-20:123-23:93-40:77-41:36-43:41-47:4-76:3",22
3015,657,"R","ذَکَرَ","«ذَکَرَ» means something coming to mind on the tongue or in the heart, whether it is remembered or recalled after forgetting (fig.). Its usage is general.\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«اَوَلَا یَذۡکُرُ الۡاِنۡسَانُ اَنَّا خَلَقۡنٰہُ مِنۡ قَبۡلُ وَلَمۡ یَکُ شَیۡئًا» (19/67)\nTranslation: Does man not remember that We created him before, while he was nothing?\n\nAnd «اِدَّکَر» means the recollection of a forgotten matter.\nFor example: The Almighty Allah states:\n«وَ قَالَ الَّذِیۡ نَجَا مِنۡہُمَا وَ ادَّکَرَ  بَعۡدَ اُمَّۃٍ» (12/45)\nTranslation: And one of them who was freed said, after a time, I will inform you of its interpretation.","«ذَکَرَ» is used in all contexts—to remember, to keep, to come (to mind), to recall in the heart or on the tongue—and its usage is widespread.","Remembrance","ذکر","2:40-2:47-2:63-2:122-2:152-2:198-2:200-2:203-2:231-2:235-2:239-3:41-3:103-3:135-3:191-4:103-4:142-5:4-5:7-5:11-5:20-5:110-7:69-7:74-7:86-7:171-7:205-8:26-8:45-12:42-12:85-14:6-18:24-18:63-19:16-19:41-19:51-19:54-19:56-19:67-21:36-21:60-22:28-22:34-22:36-22:40-24:36-33:9-33:21-35:3-38:17-38:41-38:45-38:48-40:44-43:13-46:21-62:10-73:8-76:25-87:15",61
3016,657,"M","حَفِظَ","«حَفِظَ» To remember something and then to keep it in mind (M, L). To save something from being wasted and ruined. To keep it safe from corruption. (Muf)\n\nFor example: In the Quran it is stated:\n«حٰفِظُوۡا عَلَی الصَّلَوٰتِ وَ الصَّلٰوۃِ الۡوُسۡطٰی» (2/238)\nTranslation: Guard strictly (your) prayers, and (especially) the middle prayer.","«حَفِظَ» To commit something to memory verbally, to preserve it in the heart, then to remain mindful of it and never neglect it.","Memory","حفظ","2:238-2:255-4:34-5:44-5:89-6:61-6:92-9:112-12:12-12:63-12:64-12:65-12:81-13:11-15:9-15:17-21:82-23:5-23:9-24:30-24:31-33:35-37:7-41:12-70:29-70:34-82:10-83:33-86:4",29
3017,657,"R","وَعٰی","«وَعٰی» means to put something in a container, etc., and close its mouth. To protect it and not let anything come out (Mufradat, etc.). And «وِعَاء» means tied equipment or gear.  \nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:  \n«لِنَجۡعَلَہَا  لَکُمۡ  تَذۡکِرَۃً  وَّ تَعِیَہَاۤ  اُذُنٌ وَّاعِیَۃٌ» (69/12)  \nTranslation: So that it may become a reminder for you, and that every heart that remembers may take heed.","«وَعٰی» means to preserve and ensure there is no addition or subtraction in it.","Remembrance","وعی","69:12-70:18",2
3018,658,"C","اَیْقَنَ","«يَقِنُ» means that no room for doubt or suspicion remains (M. L.). According to Imam Raghib, «يَقِنُ» means to fully comprehend something and simultaneously reach the very foundation of its proof. Its degree is above that of knowledge and wisdom (M.F.). And according to Abu Al-Halal Asakari, the degree of certainty surpasses that of knowledge. He writes: Al-yaqīnu sukūnu an-nafsi wa nahju aṣ-ṣadri bimā 'ilm. (Faq L. 63) i.e., certainty is the name for the tranquility of the heart and coolness of the breast regarding a known matter.\n\nFor example: The Noble Quran states:\n«وَ بِالۡاٰخِرَۃِ ہُمۡ یُوۡقِنُوۡنَ» (2/4)\nTranslation: (One of the characteristics of the believers is that) they are certain of the Hereafter.\n\nAnd «اِسْتَیْقَنَ» means that certainty about something is attained gradually after experiencing it.\nFor example: The Divine declaration states:\n«فَلَمَّا جَآءَتۡہُمۡ اٰیٰتُنَا مُبۡصِرَۃً  قَالُوۡا ہٰذَا  سِحۡرٌ  مُّبِیۡنٌ . وَ جَحَدُوۡا بِہَا وَ اسۡتَیۡقَنَتۡہَاۤ  اَنۡفُسُہُمۡ» (27/13-14)\nTranslation: Then when Our clear signs came to them, they said, This is evident sorcery. And they denied them, while their hearts were convinced [of their truth].","«اَیْقَنَ» to comprehend something fully and to reach its foundational proof.","Conviction","ایقن","2:4-2:118-4:157-5:50-15:99-27:3-27:14-27:22-27:82-30:60-31:4-32:24-45:4-45:20-45:32-52:36-56:95-69:51-74:31-74:47-102:5-102:7",22
3019,658,"C","ظَنَّ","«ظَنَّ» essentially comes in the meanings of inferring and guessing from circumstantial evidence. Now, the weaker these signs and evidences are, the weaker «ظَن» will be. And the stronger they are, the stronger «ظَن» will be. In this context, «ظَن» signifies strong certainty, and its indication is that after «ظَنَّ», the word «اَنَّ» or «اَنْ» generally follows (see detailed explanation under گمان کرنا [guessing]).\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated:\n«الَّذِیۡنَ یَظُنُّوۡنَ اَنَّہُمۡ مُّلٰقُوۡا رَبِّہِمۡ» (2/46)\nTranslation: And give glad tidings to the believers who have certainty that they will meet their Lord.","Attaining certainty through signs and indications.","Conviction","ظن","2:46-2:78-2:230-2:249-3:154-4:157-6:116-6:148-7:66-7:171-9:118-10:22-10:24-10:36-10:60-10:66-11:27-12:42-12:110-17:52-17:101-17:102-18:35-18:35-18:36-18:53-21:87-22:15-24:12-26:186-28:38-28:39-33:10-34:20-37:87-38:24-38:27-40:37-41:22-41:23-41:48-41:50-45:24-45:32-48:6-48:12-49:12-53:23-53:28-59:2-69:20-72:5-72:7-72:12-75:25-75:28-83:4-84:14",58
3020,659,"F","حَنِیْف","«حَنَفَ» To abandon all false paths and incline towards steadfastness. (مف) And «حَنِیْف» (refers to) the one who, after abandoning all wrong paths, comes to only one straight path. And its opposite «جَنَفَ» means injustice and transgression.\n\nFor example: In the Quran, it is stated: «وَ اَنۡ اَقِمۡ  وَجۡہَکَ لِلدِّیۡنِ حَنِیۡفًا ۚ وَ لَا  تَکُوۡنَنَّ  مِنَ  الۡمُشۡرِکِیۡنَ» (10/105) Translation: And that you (O Muhammad ﷺ) turn away from all (false paths) and adopt the religion of Islam exclusively, and be not among the polytheists.","Abandoning the false paths, turning away from them, and turning singly toward the straight path.","Focused / Single-minded","حنیف","2:135-3:67-3:95-4:125-6:79-6:161-10:105-16:120-16:123-22:31-30:30-98:5",12
3021,659,"F","تَبْتِیْل","«بَتَلَ» meaning to cut off something and separate it (from something else) (seclusion), and «بَتَّل» and «تَبَتَّل» meaning to turn attention away from all kinds of distractions and confusions, attain tranquility, and turn toward God. To be occupied in the worship of God with sincere intention. (muf)\n\nFor example: In the Noble Quran it is stated:\n«وَ اذۡکُرِ اسۡمَ رَبِّکَ وَ تَبَتَّلۡ  اِلَیۡہِ تَبۡتِیۡلًا» (73/8)\nTranslation: And remember the name of your Lord, and detach from everything and turn toward Him.","«تَبَتَّل» turning away from worldly allurements and illusions and turning towards Allah.","Focused / Single-minded","تبتیل","73:8",1